	(3923, 4, 7, 72, 'On the eleventh day Pagiel the son of Ochran, prince of the children of Asher\n'),
	(3924, 4, 7, 73, 'gave his offering:\none silver platter, the weight of which was one hundred thirty shekels,\none silver bowl of seventy shekels, after the shekel of the sanctuary; both of them full of fine flour mixed with oil for a meal offering;\n'),
	(3925, 4, 7, 74, 'one golden ladle of ten shekels, full of incense;\n'),
	(3926, 4, 7, 75, 'one young bull,\none ram,\none male lamb a year old, for a burnt offering;\n'),
	(3927, 4, 7, 76, 'one male goat for a sin offering;\n'),
	(3928, 4, 7, 77, 'and for the sacrifice of peace offerings, two head of cattle, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs a year old. This was the offering of Pagiel the son of Ochran.\n'),
	(3929, 4, 7, 78, 'On the twelfth day Ahira the son of Enan, prince of the children of Naphtali\n'),
	(3930, 4, 7, 79, 'gave his offering:\none silver platter, the weight of which was one hundred thirty shekels,\none silver bowl of seventy shekels, after the shekel of the sanctuary; both of them full of fine flour mixed with oil for a meal offering;\n'),
	(3931, 4, 7, 80, 'one golden spoon of ten shekels, full of incense;\n'),
	(3932, 4, 7, 81, 'one young bull,\none ram,\none male lamb a year old, for a burnt offering;\n'),
	(3933, 4, 7, 82, 'one male goat for a sin offering;\n'),
	(3934, 4, 7, 83, 'and for the sacrifice of peace offerings, two head of cattle, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs a year old. This was the offering of Ahira the son of Enan.\n'),
	(3935, 4, 7, 84, 'This was the dedication of the altar, on the day when it was anointed, by the princes of Israel: twelve silver platters, twelve silver bowls, twelve golden ladles;\n'),
	(3936, 4, 7, 85, 'each silver platter weighing one hundred thirty shekels, and each bowl seventy; all the silver of the vessels two thousand four hundred shekels, after the shekel of the sanctuary;\n'),
	(3937, 4, 7, 86, 'the twelve golden ladles, full of incense, weighing ten shekels apiece, after the shekel of the sanctuary; all the gold of the ladles weighed one hundred twenty shekels;\n'),
	(3938, 4, 7, 87, 'all the cattle for the burnt offering twelve bulls, the rams twelve, the male lambs a year old twelve, and their meal offering; and the male goats for a sin offering twelve;\n'),
	(3939, 4, 7, 88, 'and all the cattle for the sacrifice of peace offerings twenty-four bulls, the rams sixty, the male goats sixty, the male lambs a year old sixty. This was the dedication of the altar, after it was anointed.\n'),
	(3940, 4, 7, 89, 'When Moses went into the Tent of Meeting to speak with Yahweh, he heard his voice speaking to him from above the mercy seat that was on the ark of the Testimony, from between the two cherubim: and he spoke to him.\n'),
	(3941, 4, 8, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(3942, 4, 8, 2, '“Speak to Aaron, and tell him, ‘When you light the lamps, the seven lamps shall give light in front of the lamp stand.’”\n'),
	(3943, 4, 8, 3, 'Aaron did so. He lit its lamps to light the area in front of the lamp stand, as Yahweh commanded Moses.\n'),
	(3944, 4, 8, 4, 'This was the workmanship of the lamp stand, beaten work of gold. From its base to its flowers, it was beaten work: according to the pattern which Yahweh had shown Moses, so he made the lamp stand.\n'),
	(3945, 4, 8, 5, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(3946, 4, 8, 6, '“Take the Levites from among the children of Israel, and cleanse them.\n'),
	(3947, 4, 8, 7, 'You shall do this to them, to cleanse them: sprinkle the water of cleansing on them, let them shave their whole bodies with a razor, and let them wash their clothes, and cleanse themselves.\n'),
	(3948, 4, 8, 8, 'Then let them take a young bull, and its meal offering, fine flour mixed with oil; and another young bull you shall take for a sin offering.\n'),
	(3949, 4, 8, 9, 'You shall present the Levites before the Tent of Meeting. You shall assemble the whole congregation of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(3950, 4, 8, 10, 'You shall present the Levites before Yahweh. The children of Israel shall lay their hands on the Levites,\n'),
	(3951, 4, 8, 11, 'and Aaron shall offer the Levites before Yahweh for a wave offering, on the behalf of the children of Israel, that it may be theirs to do the service of Yahweh.\n'),
	(3952, 4, 8, 12, '“The Levites shall lay their hands on the heads of the bulls, and you shall offer the one for a sin offering, and the other for a burnt offering to Yahweh, to make atonement for the Levites.\n'),
	(3953, 4, 8, 13, 'You shall set the Levites before Aaron, and before his sons, and offer them as a wave offering to Yahweh.\n'),
	(3954, 4, 8, 14, 'Thus you shall separate the Levites from among the children of Israel, and the Levites shall be mine.\n'),
	(3955, 4, 8, 15, '“After that, the Levites shall go in to do the service of the Tent of Meeting: and you shall cleanse them, and offer them as a wave offering.\n'),
	(3956, 4, 8, 16, 'For they are wholly given to me from among the children of Israel; instead of all who open the womb, even the firstborn of all the children of Israel, I have taken them to me.\n'),
	(3957, 4, 8, 17, 'For all the firstborn among the children of Israel are mine, both man and animal. On the day that I struck all the firstborn in the land of Egypt, I sanctified them for myself.\n'),
	(3958, 4, 8, 18, 'I have taken the Levites instead of all the firstborn among the children of Israel.\n'),
	(3959, 4, 8, 19, 'I have given the Levites as a gift to Aaron and to his sons from among the children of Israel, to do the service of the children of Israel in the Tent of Meeting, and to make atonement for the children of Israel; that there be no plague among the children of Israel, when the children of Israel come near to the sanctuary.”\n'),
	(3960, 4, 8, 20, 'Moses, and Aaron, and all the congregation of the children of Israel did so to the Levites. According to all that Yahweh commanded Moses concerning the Levites, so the children of Israel did to them.\n'),
	(3961, 4, 8, 21, 'The Levites purified themselves from sin, and they washed their clothes; and Aaron offered them for a wave offering before Yahweh; and Aaron made atonement for them to cleanse them.\n'),
	(3962, 4, 8, 22, 'After that, the Levites went in to do their service in the Tent of Meeting before Aaron, and before his sons: as Yahweh had commanded Moses concerning the Levites, so they did to them.\n'),
	(3963, 4, 8, 23, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(3964, 4, 8, 24, '“This is that which belongs to the Levites: from twenty-five years old and upward they shall go in to wait on the service in the work of the Tent of Meeting;\n'),
	(3965, 4, 8, 25, 'and from the age of fifty years they shall cease waiting on the work, and shall serve no more,\n'),
	(3966, 4, 8, 26, 'but shall minister with their brothers in the Tent of Meeting, to perform the duty, and shall perform no service. You shall do thus to the Levites concerning their duties.”\n'),
	(3967, 4, 9, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses in the wilderness of Sinai, in the first month of the second year after they had come out of the land of Egypt, saying,\n'),
	(3968, 4, 9, 2, '“Moreover let the children of Israel keep the Passover in its appointed season.\n'),
	(3969, 4, 9, 3, 'On the fourteenth day of this month, at evening, you shall keep it in its appointed season—according to all its statutes, and according to all its ordinances, you shall keep it.”\n'),
	(3970, 4, 9, 4, 'Moses spoke to the children of Israel, that they should keep the Passover.\n'),
	(3971, 4, 9, 5, 'They kept the Passover in the first month, on the fourteenth day of the month, at evening, in the wilderness of Sinai. According to all that Yahweh commanded Moses, so the children of Israel did.\n'),
	(3972, 4, 9, 6, 'There were certain men, who were unclean because of the dead body of a man, so that they could not keep the Passover on that day, and they came before Moses and before Aaron on that day.\n'),
	(3973, 4, 9, 7, 'Those men said to him, “We are unclean because of the dead body of a man. Why are we kept back, that we may not offer the offering of Yahweh in its appointed season among the children of Israel?”\n'),
	(3974, 4, 9, 8, 'Moses answered them, “Wait, that I may hear what Yahweh will command concerning you.”\n'),
	(3975, 4, 9, 9, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(3976, 4, 9, 10, '“Say to the children of Israel, ‘If any man of you or of your generations is unclean by reason of a dead body, or is on a journey far away, he shall still keep the Passover to Yahweh.\n'),
	(3977, 4, 9, 11, 'In the second month, on the fourteenth day at evening they shall keep it; they shall eat it with unleavened bread and bitter herbs.\n'),
	(3978, 4, 9, 12, 'They shall leave none of it until the morning, nor break a bone of it. According to all the statute of the Passover they shall keep it.\n'),
	(3979, 4, 9, 13, 'But the man who is clean, and is not on a journey, and fails to keep the Passover, that soul shall be cut off from his people. Because he didn’t offer the offering of Yahweh in its appointed season, that man shall bear his sin.\n'),
	(3980, 4, 9, 14, '“‘If a foreigner lives among you, and desires to keep the Passover to Yahweh; according to the statute of the Passover, and according to its ordinance, so shall he do. You shall have one statute, both for the foreigner, and for him who is born in the land.’”\n'),
	(3981, 4, 9, 15, 'On the day that the tabernacle was raised up, the cloud covered the tabernacle, even the Tent of the Testimony: and at evening it was over the tabernacle, as it were the appearance of fire, until morning.\n'),
	(3982, 4, 9, 16, 'So it was continually. The cloud covered it, and the appearance of fire by night.\n'),
	(3983, 4, 9, 17, 'Whenever the cloud was taken up from over the Tent, then after that the children of Israel traveled; and in the place where the cloud remained, there the children of Israel encamped.\n'),
	(3984, 4, 9, 18, 'At the commandment of Yahweh, the children of Israel traveled, and at the commandment of Yahweh they encamped. As long as the cloud remained on the tabernacle they remained encamped.\n'),
	(3985, 4, 9, 19, 'When the cloud stayed on the tabernacle many days, then the children of Israel kept Yahweh’s command, and didn’t travel.\n'),
	(3986, 4, 9, 20, 'Sometimes the cloud was a few days on the tabernacle; then according to the commandment of Yahweh they remained encamped, and according to the commandment of Yahweh they traveled.\n'),
	(3987, 4, 9, 21, 'Sometimes the cloud was from evening until morning; and when the cloud was taken up in the morning, they traveled: or by day and by night, when the cloud was taken up, they traveled.\n'),
	(3988, 4, 9, 22, 'Whether it was two days, or a month, or a year that the cloud stayed on the tabernacle, remaining on it, the children of Israel remained encamped, and didn’t travel; but when it was taken up, they traveled.\n'),
	(3989, 4, 9, 23, 'At the commandment of Yahweh they encamped, and at the commandment of Yahweh they traveled. They kept Yahweh’s command, at the commandment of Yahweh by Moses.\n'),
	(3990, 4, 10, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(3991, 4, 10, 2, '“Make two trumpets of silver. You shall make them of beaten work. You shall use them for the calling of the congregation, and for the journeying of the camps.\n'),
	(3992, 4, 10, 3, 'When they blow them, all the congregation shall gather themselves to you at the door of the Tent of Meeting.\n'),
	(3993, 4, 10, 4, 'If they blow just one, then the princes, the heads of the thousands of Israel, shall gather themselves to you.\n'),
	(3994, 4, 10, 5, 'When you blow an alarm, the camps that lie on the east side shall go forward.\n'),
	(3995, 4, 10, 6, 'When you blow an alarm the second time, the camps that lie on the south side shall go forward. They shall blow an alarm for their journeys.\n'),
	(3996, 4, 10, 7, 'But when the assembly is to be gathered together, you shall blow, but you shall not sound an alarm.\n'),
	(3997, 4, 10, 8, '“The sons of Aaron, the priests, shall blow the trumpets. This shall be to you for a statute forever throughout your generations.\n'),
	(3998, 4, 10, 9, 'When you go to war in your land against the adversary who oppresses you, then you shall sound an alarm with the trumpets. Then you will be remembered before Yahweh your God, and you will be saved from your enemies.\n'),
	(3999, 4, 10, 10, '“Also in the day of your gladness, and in your set feasts, and in the beginnings of your months, you shall blow the trumpets over your burnt offerings, and over the sacrifices of your peace offerings; and they shall be to you for a memorial before your God. I am Yahweh your God.”\n'),
	(4000, 4, 10, 11, 'In the second year, in the second month, on the twentieth day of the month, the cloud was taken up from over the tabernacle of the testimony.\n'),
	(4001, 4, 10, 12, 'The children of Israel went forward according to their journeys out of the wilderness of Sinai; and the cloud stayed in the wilderness of Paran.\n'),
	(4002, 4, 10, 13, 'They first went forward according to the commandment of Yahweh by Moses.\n'),
	(4003, 4, 10, 14, 'First, the standard of the camp of the children of Judah went forward according to their armies. Nahshon the son of Amminadab was over his army.\n'),
	(4004, 4, 10, 15, 'Nethanel the son of Zuar was over the army of the tribe of the children of Issachar.\n'),
	(4005, 4, 10, 16, 'Eliab the son of Helon was over the army of the tribe of the children of Zebulun.\n'),
	(4006, 4, 10, 17, 'The tabernacle was taken down; and the sons of Gershon and the sons of Merari, who bore the tabernacle, went forward.\n'),
	(4007, 4, 10, 18, 'The standard of the camp of Reuben went forward according to their armies. Elizur the son of Shedeur was over his army.\n'),
	(4008, 4, 10, 19, 'Shelumiel the son of Zurishaddai was over the army of the tribe of the children of Simeon.\n'),
	(4009, 4, 10, 20, 'Eliasaph the son of Deuel was over the army of the tribe of the children of Gad.\n'),
	(4010, 4, 10, 21, 'The Kohathites set forward, bearing the sanctuary. The others set up the tabernacle before they arrived.\n'),
	(4011, 4, 10, 22, 'The standard of the camp of the children of Ephraim set forward according to their armies. Elishama the son of Ammihud was over his army.\n'),
	(4012, 4, 10, 23, 'Gamaliel the son of Pedahzur was over the army of the tribe of the children of Manasseh.\n'),
	(4013, 4, 10, 24, 'Abidan the son of Gideoni was over the army of the tribe of the children of Benjamin.\n'),
	(4014, 4, 10, 25, 'The standard of the camp of the children of Dan, which was the rear guard of all the camps, set forward according to their armies. Ahiezer the son of Ammishaddai was over his army.\n'),
	(4015, 4, 10, 26, 'Pagiel the son of Ochran was over the army of the tribe of the children of Asher.\n'),
	(4016, 4, 10, 27, 'Ahira the son of Enan was over the army of the tribe of the children of Naphtali.\n'),
	(4017, 4, 10, 28, 'Thus were the travels of the children of Israel according to their armies; and they went forward.\n'),
	(4018, 4, 10, 29, 'Moses said to Hobab, the son of Reuel the Midianite, Moses’ father-in-law, “We are journeying to the place of which Yahweh said, ‘I will give it to you.’ Come with us, and we will treat you well; for Yahweh has spoken good concerning Israel.”\n'),
	(4019, 4, 10, 30, 'He said to him, “I will not go; but I will depart to my own land, and to my relatives.”\n'),
	(4020, 4, 10, 31, 'He said, “Don’t leave us, please; because you know how we are to encamp in the wilderness, and you can be our eyes.\n'),
	(4021, 4, 10, 32, 'It shall be, if you go with us, yes, it shall be, that whatever good Yahweh does to us, we will do the same to you.”\n'),
	(4022, 4, 10, 33, 'They set forward from the Mount of Yahweh three days’ journey. The ark of Yahweh’s covenant went before them three days’ journey, to seek out a resting place for them.\n'),
	(4023, 4, 10, 34, 'The cloud of Yahweh was over them by day, when they set forward from the camp.\n'),
	(4024, 4, 10, 35, 'When the ark went forward, Moses said, “Rise up, Yahweh, and let your enemies be scattered! Let those who hate you flee before you!”\n'),
	(4025, 4, 10, 36, 'When it rested, he said, “Return, Yahweh, to the ten thousands of the thousands of Israel.”\n'),
	(4026, 4, 11, 1, 'The people were complaining in the ears of Yahweh. When Yahweh heard it, his anger burned; and Yahweh’s fire burned among them, and consumed some of the outskirts of the camp.\n'),
	(4027, 4, 11, 2, 'The people cried to Moses; and Moses prayed to Yahweh, and the fire abated.\n'),
	(4028, 4, 11, 3, 'The name of that place was called Taberah, because Yahweh’s fire burned among them.\n'),
	(4029, 4, 11, 4, 'The mixed multitude that was among them lusted exceedingly: and the children of Israel also wept again, and said, “Who will give us meat to eat?\n'),
	(4030, 4, 11, 5, 'We remember the fish, which we ate in Egypt for nothing; the cucumbers, and the melons, and the leeks, and the onions, and the garlic;\n'),
	(4031, 4, 11, 6, 'but now we have lost our appetite. There is nothing at all except this manna to look at.”\n'),
	(4032, 4, 11, 7, 'The manna was like coriander seed, and its appearance like the appearance of bdellium.\n'),
	(4033, 4, 11, 8, 'The people went around, gathered it, and ground it in mills, or beat it in mortars, and boiled it in pots, and made cakes of it. Its taste was like the taste of fresh oil.\n'),
	(4034, 4, 11, 9, 'When the dew fell on the camp in the night, the manna fell on it.\n'),
	(4035, 4, 11, 10, 'Moses heard the people weeping throughout their families, every man at the door of his tent; and Yahweh’s anger burned greatly; and Moses was displeased.\n'),
	(4036, 4, 11, 11, 'Moses said to Yahweh, “Why have you treated your servant so badly? Why haven’t I found favor in your sight, that you lay the burden of all this people on me?\n'),
	(4037, 4, 11, 12, 'Have I conceived all this people? Have I brought them out, that you should tell me, ‘Carry them in your bosom, as a nurse carries a nursing infant, to the land which you swore to their fathers?’\n'),
	(4038, 4, 11, 13, 'Where could I get meat to give all these people? For they weep before me, saying, ‘Give us meat, that we may eat.’\n'),
	(4039, 4, 11, 14, 'I am not able to bear all this people alone, because it is too heavy for me.\n'),
	(4040, 4, 11, 15, 'If you treat me this way, please kill me right now, if I have found favor in your sight; and don’t let me see my wretchedness.”\n'),
	(4041, 4, 11, 16, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Gather to me seventy men of the elders of Israel, whom you know to be the elders of the people, and officers over them; and bring them to the Tent of Meeting, that they may stand there with you.\n'),
	(4042, 4, 11, 17, 'I will come down and talk with you there. I will take of the Spirit which is on you, and will put it on them; and they shall bear the burden of the people with you, that you don’t bear it yourself alone.\n'),
	(4043, 4, 11, 18, '“Say to the people, ‘Sanctify yourselves in preparation for tomorrow, and you will eat meat; for you have wept in the ears of Yahweh, saying, “Who will give us meat to eat? For it was well with us in Egypt.” Therefore Yahweh will give you meat, and you will eat.\n'),
	(4044, 4, 11, 19, 'You will not eat one day, nor two days, nor five days, neither ten days, nor twenty days,\n'),
	(4045, 4, 11, 20, 'but a whole month, until it comes out at your nostrils, and it is loathsome to you; because you have rejected Yahweh who is among you, and have wept before him, saying, “Why did we come out of Egypt?”’”\n'),
	(4046, 4, 11, 21, 'Moses said, “The people, among whom I am, are six hundred thousand men on foot; and you have said, ‘I will give them meat, that they may eat a whole month.’\n'),
	(4047, 4, 11, 22, 'Shall flocks and herds be slaughtered for them, to be sufficient for them? Shall all the fish of the sea be gathered together for them, to be sufficient for them?”\n'),
	(4048, 4, 11, 23, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Has Yahweh’s hand grown short? Now you will see whether my word will happen to you or not.”\n'),
	(4049, 4, 11, 24, 'Moses went out, and told the people Yahweh’s words; and he gathered seventy men of the elders of the people, and set them around the Tent.\n'),
	(4050, 4, 11, 25, 'Yahweh came down in the cloud, and spoke to him, and took of the Spirit that was on him, and put it on the seventy elders. When the Spirit rested on them, they prophesied, but they did so no more.\n'),
	(4051, 4, 11, 26, 'But two men remained in the camp. The name of one was Eldad, and the name of the other Medad: and the Spirit rested on them; and they were of those who were written, but had not gone out to the Tent; and they prophesied in the camp.\n'),
	(4052, 4, 11, 27, 'A young man ran, and told Moses, and said, “Eldad and Medad are prophesying in the camp!”\n'),
	(4053, 4, 11, 28, 'Joshua the son of Nun, the servant of Moses, one of his chosen men, answered, “My lord Moses, forbid them!”\n'),
	(4054, 4, 11, 29, 'Moses said to him, “Are you jealous for my sake? I wish that all Yahweh’s people were prophets, that Yahweh would put his Spirit on them!”\n'),
	(4055, 4, 11, 30, 'Moses went into the camp, he and the elders of Israel.\n'),
	(4056, 4, 11, 31, 'A wind from Yahweh went out and brought quails from the sea, and let them fall by the camp, about a day’s journey on this side, and a day’s journey on the other side, around the camp, and about two cubits above the surface of the earth.\n'),
	(4057, 4, 11, 32, 'The people rose up all that day, and all of that night, and all the next day, and gathered the quails. He who gathered least gathered ten homers;\n and they spread them all out for themselves around the camp.\n'),
	(4058, 4, 11, 33, 'While the meat was still between their teeth, before it was chewed, Yahweh’s anger burned against the people, and Yahweh struck the people with a very great plague.\n'),
	(4059, 4, 11, 34, 'The name of that place was called Kibroth Hattaavah, because there they buried the people who lusted.\n'),
	(4060, 4, 11, 35, 'From Kibroth Hattaavah the people traveled to Hazeroth; and they stayed at Hazeroth.\n'),
	(4061, 4, 12, 1, 'Miriam and Aaron spoke against Moses because of the Cushite woman whom he had married; for he had married a Cushite woman.\n'),
	(4062, 4, 12, 2, 'They said, “Has Yahweh indeed spoken only with Moses? Hasn’t he spoken also with us?” And Yahweh heard it.\n'),
	(4063, 4, 12, 3, 'Now the man Moses was very humble, more than all the men who were on the surface of the earth.\n'),
	(4064, 4, 12, 4, 'Yahweh spoke suddenly to Moses, to Aaron, and to Miriam, “You three come out to the Tent of Meeting!”\nThe three of them came out.\n'),
	(4065, 4, 12, 5, 'Yahweh came down in a pillar of cloud, and stood at the door of the Tent, and called Aaron and Miriam; and they both came forward.\n'),
	(4066, 4, 12, 6, 'He said, “Now hear my words. If there is a prophet among you, I, Yahweh, will make myself known to him in a vision. I will speak with him in a dream.\n'),
	(4067, 4, 12, 7, 'My servant Moses is not so. He is faithful in all my house.\n'),
	(4068, 4, 12, 8, 'With him, I will speak mouth to mouth, even plainly, and not in riddles; and he shall see Yahweh’s form. Why then were you not afraid to speak against my servant, against Moses?”\n'),
	(4069, 4, 12, 9, 'Yahweh’s anger burned against them; and he departed.\n'),
	(4070, 4, 12, 10, 'The cloud departed from over the Tent; and behold, Miriam was leprous, as white as snow. Aaron looked at Miriam, and behold, she was leprous.\n'),
	(4071, 4, 12, 11, 'Aaron said to Moses, “Oh, my lord, please don’t count this sin against us, in which we have done foolishly, and in which we have sinned.\n'),
	(4072, 4, 12, 12, 'Let her not, I pray, be as one dead, of whom the flesh is half consumed when he comes out of his mother’s womb.”\n'),
	(4073, 4, 12, 13, 'Moses cried to Yahweh, saying, “Heal her, God, I beg you!”\n'),
	(4074, 4, 12, 14, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “If her father had but spit in her face, shouldn’t she be ashamed seven days? Let her be shut up outside of the camp seven days, and after that she shall be brought in again.”\n'),
	(4075, 4, 12, 15, 'Miriam was shut up outside of the camp seven days, and the people didn’t travel until Miriam was brought in again.\n'),
	(4076, 4, 12, 16, 'Afterward the people traveled from Hazeroth, and encamped in the wilderness of Paran.\n'),
	(4077, 4, 13, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4078, 4, 13, 2, '“Send men, that they may spy out the land of Canaan, which I give to the children of Israel. Of every tribe of their fathers, you shall send a man, every one a prince among them.”\n'),
	(4079, 4, 13, 3, 'Moses sent them from the wilderness of Paran according to the commandment of Yahweh. All of them were men who were heads of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4080, 4, 13, 4, 'These were their names:\nOf the tribe of Reuben, Shammua the son of Zaccur.\n'),
	(4081, 4, 13, 5, 'Of the tribe of Simeon, Shaphat the son of Hori.\n'),
	(4082, 4, 13, 6, 'Of the tribe of Judah, Caleb the son of Jephunneh.\n'),
	(4083, 4, 13, 7, 'Of the tribe of Issachar, Igal the son of Joseph.\n'),
	(4084, 4, 13, 8, 'Of the tribe of Ephraim, Hoshea the son of Nun.\n'),
	(4085, 4, 13, 9, 'Of the tribe of Benjamin, Palti the son of Raphu.\n'),
	(4086, 4, 13, 10, 'Of the tribe of Zebulun, Gaddiel the son of Sodi.\n'),
	(4087, 4, 13, 11, 'Of the tribe of Joseph, of the tribe of Manasseh, Gaddi the son of Susi.\n'),
	(4088, 4, 13, 12, 'Of the tribe of Dan, Ammiel the son of Gemalli.\n'),
	(4089, 4, 13, 13, 'Of the tribe of Asher, Sethur the son of Michael.\n'),
	(4090, 4, 13, 14, 'Of the tribe of Naphtali, Nahbi the son of Vophsi.\n'),
	(4091, 4, 13, 15, 'Of the tribe of Gad, Geuel the son of Machi.\n'),
	(4092, 4, 13, 16, 'These are the names of the men who Moses sent to spy out the land. Moses called Hoshea the son of Nun Joshua.\n'),
	(4093, 4, 13, 17, 'Moses sent them to spy out the land of Canaan, and said to them, “Go up this way by the South, and go up into the hill country.\n'),
	(4094, 4, 13, 18, 'See the land, what it is; and the people who dwell therein, whether they are strong or weak, whether they are few or many;\n'),
	(4095, 4, 13, 19, 'and what the land is that they dwell in, whether it is good or bad; and what cities they are that they dwell in, whether in camps, or in strongholds;\n'),
	(4096, 4, 13, 20, 'and what the land is, whether it is fat or lean, whether there is wood therein, or not. Be courageous, and bring some of the fruit of the land.” Now the time was the time of the first-ripe grapes.\n'),
	(4097, 4, 13, 21, 'So they went up, and spied out the land from the wilderness of Zin to Rehob, to the entrance of Hamath.\n'),
	(4098, 4, 13, 22, 'They went up by the South, and came to Hebron; and Ahiman, Sheshai, and Talmai, the children of Anak, were there. (Now Hebron was built seven years before Zoan in Egypt.)\n'),
	(4099, 4, 13, 23, 'They came to the valley of Eshcol, and cut down from there a branch with one cluster of grapes, and they bore it on a staff between two. They also brought some of the pomegranates and figs.\n'),
	(4100, 4, 13, 24, 'That place was called the valley of Eshcol, because of the cluster which the children of Israel cut down from there.\n'),
	(4101, 4, 13, 25, 'They returned from spying out the land at the end of forty days.\n'),
	(4102, 4, 13, 26, 'They went and came to Moses, to Aaron, and to all the congregation of the children of Israel, to the wilderness of Paran, to Kadesh; and brought back word to them and to all the congregation. They showed them the fruit of the land.\n'),
	(4103, 4, 13, 27, 'They told him, and said, “We came to the land where you sent us. Surely it flows with milk and honey, and this is its fruit.\n'),
	(4104, 4, 13, 28, 'However the people who dwell in the land are strong, and the cities are fortified and very large. Moreover, we saw the children of Anak there.\n'),
	(4105, 4, 13, 29, 'Amalek dwells in the land of the South. The Hittite, the Jebusite, and the Amorite dwell in the hill country. The Canaanite dwells by the sea, and along the side of the Jordan.”\n'),
	(4106, 4, 13, 30, 'Caleb stilled the people before Moses, and said, “Let us go up at once, and possess it; for we are well able to overcome it!”\n'),
	(4107, 4, 13, 31, 'But the men who went up with him said, “We aren’t able to go up against the people; for they are stronger than we.”\n'),
	(4108, 4, 13, 32, 'They brought up an evil report of the land which they had spied out to the children of Israel, saying, “The land, through which we have gone to spy it out, is a land that eats up its inhabitants; and all the people who we saw in it are men of great stature.\n'),
	(4109, 4, 13, 33, 'There we saw the Nephilim, the sons of Anak, who come from the Nephilim. We were in our own sight as grasshoppers, and so we were in their sight.”\n'),
	(4110, 4, 14, 1, 'All the congregation lifted up their voice, and cried; and the people wept that night.\n'),
	(4111, 4, 14, 2, 'All the children of Israel murmured against Moses and against Aaron. The whole congregation said to them, “We wish that we had died in the land of Egypt, or that we had died in this wilderness!\n'),
	(4112, 4, 14, 3, 'Why does Yahweh bring us to this land, to fall by the sword? Our wives and our little ones will be captured or killed! Wouldn’t it be better for us to return into Egypt?”\n'),
	(4113, 4, 14, 4, 'They said to one another, “Let us make a captain, and let us return into Egypt.”\n'),
	(4114, 4, 14, 5, 'Then Moses and Aaron fell on their faces before all the assembly of the congregation of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4115, 4, 14, 6, 'Joshua the son of Nun and Caleb the son of Jephunneh, who were of those who spied out the land, tore their clothes.\n'),
	(4116, 4, 14, 7, 'They spoke to all the congregation of the children of Israel, saying, “The land, which we passed through to spy it out, is an exceeding good land.\n'),
	(4117, 4, 14, 8, 'If Yahweh delights in us, then he will bring us into this land, and give it to us; a land which flows with milk and honey.\n'),
	(4118, 4, 14, 9, 'Only don’t rebel against Yahweh, neither fear the people of the land; for they are bread for us. Their defense is removed from over them, and Yahweh is with us. Don’t fear them.”\n'),
	(4119, 4, 14, 10, 'But all the congregation threatened to stone them with stones.\nYahweh’s glory appeared in the Tent of Meeting to all the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4120, 4, 14, 11, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “How long will this people despise me? and how long will they not believe in me, for all the signs which I have worked among them?\n'),
	(4121, 4, 14, 12, 'I will strike them with the pestilence, and disinherit them, and will make of you a nation greater and mightier than they.”\n'),
	(4122, 4, 14, 13, 'Moses said to Yahweh, “Then the Egyptians will hear it; for you brought up this people in your might from among them.\n'),
	(4123, 4, 14, 14, 'They will tell it to the inhabitants of this land. They have heard that you Yahweh are among this people; for you Yahweh are seen face to face, and your cloud stands over them, and you go before them, in a pillar of cloud by day, and in a pillar of fire by night.\n'),
	(4124, 4, 14, 15, 'Now if you killed this people as one man, then the nations which have heard the fame of you will speak, saying,\n'),
	(4125, 4, 14, 16, '‘Because Yahweh was not able to bring this people into the land which he swore to them, therefore he has slain them in the wilderness.’\n'),
	(4126, 4, 14, 17, 'Now please let the power of the Lord be great, according as you have spoken, saying,\n'),
	(4127, 4, 14, 18, '‘Yahweh is slow to anger, and abundant in loving kindness, forgiving iniquity and disobedience; and he will by no means clear the guilty, visiting the iniquity of the fathers on the children, on the third and on the fourth generation.’\n'),
	(4128, 4, 14, 19, 'Please pardon the iniquity of this people according to the greatness of your loving kindness, and just as you have forgiven this people, from Egypt even until now.”\n'),
	(4129, 4, 14, 20, 'Yahweh said, “I have pardoned according to your word:\n'),
	(4130, 4, 14, 21, 'but in very deed, as I live, and as all the earth shall be filled with Yahweh’s glory;\n'),
	(4131, 4, 14, 22, 'because all those men who have seen my glory, and my signs, which I worked in Egypt and in the wilderness, yet have tempted me these ten times, and have not listened to my voice;\n'),
	(4132, 4, 14, 23, 'surely they shall not see the land which I swore to their fathers, neither shall any of those who despised me see it.\n'),
	(4133, 4, 14, 24, 'But my servant Caleb, because he had another spirit with him, and has followed me fully, him I will bring into the land into which he went. His offspring shall possess it.\n'),
	(4134, 4, 14, 25, 'Since the Amalekite and the Canaanite dwell in the valley, tomorrow turn, and go into the wilderness by the way to the Red Sea.”\n'),
	(4135, 4, 14, 26, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses and to Aaron, saying,\n'),
	(4136, 4, 14, 27, '“How long shall I bear with this evil congregation, that murmur against me? I have heard the murmurings of the children of Israel, which they murmur against me.\n'),
	(4137, 4, 14, 28, 'Tell them, ‘As I live, says Yahweh, surely as you have spoken in my ears, so will I do to you.\n'),
	(4138, 4, 14, 29, 'Your dead bodies shall fall in this wilderness; and all who were counted of you, according to your whole number, from twenty years old and upward, who have murmured against me,\n'),
	(4139, 4, 14, 30, 'surely you shall not come into the land, concerning which I swore that I would make you dwell therein, except Caleb the son of Jephunneh, and Joshua the son of Nun.\n'),
	(4140, 4, 14, 31, 'But your little ones, that you said should be captured or killed, them I will bring in, and they shall know the land which you have rejected.\n'),
	(4141, 4, 14, 32, 'But as for you, your dead bodies shall fall in this wilderness.\n'),
	(4142, 4, 14, 33, 'Your children shall be wanderers in the wilderness forty years, and shall bear your prostitution, until your dead bodies are consumed in the wilderness.\n'),
	(4143, 4, 14, 34, 'After the number of the days in which you spied out the land, even forty days, for every day a year, you will bear your iniquities, even forty years, and you will know my alienation.’\n'),
	(4144, 4, 14, 35, 'I, Yahweh, have spoken. I will surely do this to all this evil congregation, who are gathered together against me. In this wilderness they shall be consumed, and there they shall die.”\n'),
	(4145, 4, 14, 36, 'The men, whom Moses sent to spy out the land, who returned, and made all the congregation to murmur against him, by bringing up an evil report against the land,\n'),
	(4146, 4, 14, 37, 'even those men who brought up an evil report of the land, died by the plague before Yahweh.\n'),
	(4147, 4, 14, 38, 'But Joshua the son of Nun, and Caleb the son of Jephunneh, remained alive of those men who went to spy out the land.\n'),
	(4148, 4, 14, 39, 'Moses told these words to all the children of Israel, and the people mourned greatly.\n'),
	(4149, 4, 14, 40, 'They rose up early in the morning, and went up to the top of the mountain, saying, “Behold, we are here, and will go up to the place which Yahweh has promised: for we have sinned.”\n'),
	(4150, 4, 14, 41, 'Moses said, “Why now do you disobey the commandment of Yahweh, since it shall not prosper?\n'),
	(4151, 4, 14, 42, 'Don’t go up, for Yahweh isn’t among you; that way you won’t be struck down before your enemies.\n'),
	(4152, 4, 14, 43, 'For there the Amalekite and the Canaanite are before you, and you will fall by the sword, because you turned back from following Yahweh, therefore Yahweh will not be with you.”\n'),
	(4153, 4, 14, 44, 'But they presumed to go up to the top of the mountain. Nevertheless, the ark of Yahweh’s covenant and Moses didn’t depart out of the camp.\n'),
	(4154, 4, 14, 45, 'Then the Amalekites came down, and the Canaanites who lived in that mountain, and struck them and beat them down, even to Hormah.\n'),
	(4155, 4, 15, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4156, 4, 15, 2, '“Speak to the children of Israel, and tell them, ‘When you have come into the land of your habitations, which I give to you,\n'),
	(4157, 4, 15, 3, 'and will make an offering by fire to Yahweh, a burnt offering, or a sacrifice, to accomplish a vow, or as a freewill offering, or in your set feasts, to make a pleasant aroma to Yahweh, of the herd, or of the flock;\n'),
	(4158, 4, 15, 4, 'then he who offers his offering shall offer to Yahweh a meal offering of one tenth of an ephah of fine flour mixed with the fourth part of a hin of oil.\n'),
	(4159, 4, 15, 5, 'You shall prepare wine for the drink offering, the fourth part of a hin, with the burnt offering, or for the sacrifice, for each lamb.\n'),
	(4160, 4, 15, 6, '“‘Or for a ram, you shall prepare for a meal offering two tenths of an ephah of fine flour mixed with the third part of a hin of oil;\n'),
	(4161, 4, 15, 7, 'and for the drink offering you shall offer the third part of a hin of wine, of a pleasant aroma to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4162, 4, 15, 8, 'When you prepare a bull for a burnt offering, or for a sacrifice, to accomplish a vow, or for peace offerings to Yahweh;\n'),
	(4163, 4, 15, 9, 'then shall he offer with the bull a meal offering of three tenths of an ephah of fine flour mixed with half a hin of oil:\n'),
	(4164, 4, 15, 10, 'and you shall offer for the drink offering half a hin of wine, for an offering made by fire, of a pleasant aroma to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4165, 4, 15, 11, 'Thus shall it be done for each bull, or for each ram, or for each of the male lambs, or of the young goats.\n'),
	(4166, 4, 15, 12, 'According to the number that you shall prepare, so you shall do to everyone according to their number.\n'),
	(4167, 4, 15, 13, '“‘All who are native-born shall do these things in this way, in offering an offering made by fire, of a pleasant aroma to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4168, 4, 15, 14, 'If a stranger lives as a foreigner with you, or whoever may be among you throughout your generations, and will offer an offering made by fire, of a pleasant aroma to Yahweh; as you do, so he shall do.\n'),
	(4169, 4, 15, 15, 'For the assembly, there shall be one statute for you and for the stranger who lives as a foreigner, a statute forever throughout your generations. As you are, so shall the foreigner be before Yahweh.\n'),
	(4170, 4, 15, 16, 'One law and one ordinance shall be for you, and for the stranger who lives as a foreigner with you.’”\n'),
	(4171, 4, 15, 17, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4172, 4, 15, 18, '“Speak to the children of Israel, and tell them, ‘When you come into the land where I bring you,\n'),
	(4173, 4, 15, 19, 'then it shall be that when you eat of the bread of the land, you shall offer up a wave offering to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4174, 4, 15, 20, 'Of the first of your dough you shall offer up a cake for a wave offering. As the wave offering of the threshing floor, so you shall heave it.\n'),
	(4175, 4, 15, 21, 'Of the first of your dough, you shall give to Yahweh a wave offering throughout your generations.\n'),
	(4176, 4, 15, 22, '“‘When you err, and don’t observe all these commandments, which Yahweh has spoken to Moses,\n'),
	(4177, 4, 15, 23, 'even all that Yahweh has commanded you by Moses, from the day that Yahweh gave commandment, and onward throughout your generations;\n'),
	(4178, 4, 15, 24, 'then it shall be, if it was done unwittingly, without the knowledge of the congregation, that all the congregation shall offer one young bull for a burnt offering, for a pleasant aroma to Yahweh, with its meal offering, and its drink offering, according to the ordinance, and one male goat for a sin offering.\n'),
	(4179, 4, 15, 25, 'The priest shall make atonement for all the congregation of the children of Israel, and they shall be forgiven; for it was an error, and they have brought their offering, an offering made by fire to Yahweh, and their sin offering before Yahweh, for their error.\n'),
	(4180, 4, 15, 26, 'All the congregation of the children of Israel shall be forgiven, as well as the stranger who lives as a foreigner among them; for with regard to all the people, it was done unwittingly.\n'),
	(4181, 4, 15, 27, '“‘If one person sins unwittingly, then he shall offer a female goat a year old for a sin offering.\n'),
	(4182, 4, 15, 28, 'The priest shall make atonement for the soul who errs, when he sins unwittingly before Yahweh, to make atonement for him; and he shall be forgiven.\n'),
	(4183, 4, 15, 29, 'You shall have one law for him who does anything unwittingly, for him who is native-born among the children of Israel, and for the stranger who lives as a foreigner among them.\n'),
	(4184, 4, 15, 30, '“‘But the soul who does anything with a high hand, whether he is native-born or a foreigner, the same blasphemes Yahweh. That soul shall be cut off from among his people.\n'),
	(4185, 4, 15, 31, 'Because he has despised Yahweh’s word, and has broken his commandment, that soul shall utterly be cut off. His iniquity shall be on him.’”\n'),
	(4186, 4, 15, 32, 'While the children of Israel were in the wilderness, they found a man gathering sticks on the Sabbath day.\n'),
	(4187, 4, 15, 33, 'Those who found him gathering sticks brought him to Moses and Aaron, and to all the congregation.\n'),
	(4188, 4, 15, 34, 'They put him in custody, because it had not been declared what should be done to him.\n'),
	(4189, 4, 15, 35, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “The man shall surely be put to death. All the congregation shall stone him with stones outside of the camp.”\n'),
	(4190, 4, 15, 36, 'All the congregation brought him outside of the camp, and stoned him to death with stones, as Yahweh commanded Moses.\n'),
	(4191, 4, 15, 37, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4192, 4, 15, 38, '“Speak to the children of Israel, and tell them that they should make themselves fringes in the borders of their garments throughout their generations, and that they put on the fringe\n of each border a cord of blue:\n'),
	(4193, 4, 15, 39, 'and it shall be to you for a fringe, that you may look on it, and remember all Yahweh’s commandments, and do them; and that you don’ t follow your own heart and your own eyes, after which you use to play the prostitute;\n'),
	(4194, 4, 15, 40, 'so that you may remember and do all my commandments, and be holy to your God.\n'),
	(4195, 4, 15, 41, 'I am Yahweh your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, to be your God: I am Yahweh your God.”\n'),
	(4196, 4, 16, 1, 'Now Korah, the son of Izhar, the son of Kohath, the son of Levi, with Dathan and Abiram, the sons of Eliab, and On, the son of Peleth, sons of Reuben, took some men.\n'),
	(4197, 4, 16, 2, 'They rose up before Moses, with some of the children of Israel, two hundred fifty princes of the congregation, called to the assembly, men of renown.\n'),
	(4198, 4, 16, 3, 'They assembled themselves together against Moses and against Aaron, and said to them, “You take too much on yourself, since all the congregation are holy, everyone of them, and Yahweh is among them! Why do you lift yourselves up above Yahweh’s assembly?”\n'),
	(4199, 4, 16, 4, 'When Moses heard it, he fell on his face.\n'),
	(4200, 4, 16, 5, 'He said to Korah and to all his company, “In the morning, Yahweh will show who are his, and who is holy, and will cause him to come near to him. Even him whom he shall choose, he will cause to come near to him.\n'),
	(4201, 4, 16, 6, 'Do this: take censers, Korah, and all his company;\n'),
	(4202, 4, 16, 7, 'and put fire in them, and put incense on them before Yahweh tomorrow. It shall be that the man whom Yahweh chooses, he shall be holy. You have gone too far, you sons of Levi!”\n'),
	(4203, 4, 16, 8, 'Moses said to Korah, “Hear now, you sons of Levi!\n'),
	(4204, 4, 16, 9, 'Is it a small thing to you, that the God of Israel has separated you from the congregation of Israel, to bring you near to himself, to do the service of Yahweh’s tabernacle, and to stand before the congregation to minister to them;\n'),
	(4205, 4, 16, 10, 'and that he has brought you near, and all your brothers the sons of Levi with you? Do you seek the priesthood also?\n'),
	(4206, 4, 16, 11, 'Therefore you and all your company have gathered together against Yahweh! What is Aaron that you murmur against him?”\n'),
	(4207, 4, 16, 12, 'Moses sent to call Dathan and Abiram, the sons of Eliab; and they said, “We won’t come up!\n'),
	(4208, 4, 16, 13, 'Is it a small thing that you have brought us up out of a land flowing with milk and honey, to kill us in the wilderness, but you must also make yourself a prince over us?\n'),
	(4209, 4, 16, 14, 'Moreover you haven’t brought us into a land flowing with milk and honey, nor given us inheritance of fields and vineyards. Will you put out the eyes of these men? We won’t come up.”\n'),
	(4210, 4, 16, 15, 'Moses was very angry, and said to Yahweh, “Don’t respect their offering. I have not taken one donkey from them, neither have I hurt one of them.”\n'),
	(4211, 4, 16, 16, 'Moses said to Korah, “You and all your company go before Yahweh, you, and they, and Aaron, tomorrow.\n'),
	(4212, 4, 16, 17, 'Each man take his censer, and put incense on them, and each man bring before Yahweh his censer, two hundred fifty censers; you also, and Aaron, each his censer.”\n'),
	(4213, 4, 16, 18, 'They each took his censer, and put fire in them, and laid incense on it, and stood at the door of the Tent of Meeting with Moses and Aaron.\n'),
	(4214, 4, 16, 19, 'Korah assembled all the congregation opposite them to the door of the Tent of Meeting.\nYahweh’s glory appeared to all the congregation.\n'),
	(4215, 4, 16, 20, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses and to Aaron, saying,\n'),
	(4216, 4, 16, 21, '“Separate yourselves from among this congregation, that I may consume them in a moment!”\n'),
	(4217, 4, 16, 22, 'They fell on their faces, and said, “God, the God of the spirits of all flesh, shall one man sin, and will you be angry with all the congregation?”\n'),
	(4218, 4, 16, 23, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4219, 4, 16, 24, '“Speak to the congregation, saying, ‘Get away from around the tent of Korah, Dathan, and Abiram!’”\n'),
	(4220, 4, 16, 25, 'Moses rose up and went to Dathan and Abiram; and the elders of Israel followed him.\n'),
	(4221, 4, 16, 26, 'He spoke to the congregation, saying, “Depart, please, from the tents of these wicked men, and touch nothing of theirs, lest you be consumed in all their sins!”\n'),
	(4222, 4, 16, 27, 'So they went away from the tent of Korah, Dathan, and Abiram, on every side. Dathan and Abiram came out, and stood at the door of their tents, with their wives, their sons, and their little ones.\n'),
	(4223, 4, 16, 28, 'Moses said, “Hereby you shall know that Yahweh has sent me to do all these works; for they are not from my own mind.\n'),
	(4224, 4, 16, 29, 'If these men die the common death of all men, or if they experience what all men experience, then Yahweh hasn’t sent me.\n'),
	(4225, 4, 16, 30, 'But if Yahweh makes a new thing, and the ground opens its mouth, and swallows them up, with all that belong to them, and they go down alive into Sheol; then you shall understand that these men have despised Yahweh.”\n'),
	(4226, 4, 16, 31, 'As he finished speaking all these words, the ground that was under them split apart.\n'),
	(4227, 4, 16, 32, 'The earth opened its mouth and swallowed them up, with their households, all of Korah’s men, and all their goods.\n'),
	(4228, 4, 16, 33, 'So they, and all that belonged to them went down alive into Sheol.\n The earth closed on them, and they perished from among the assembly.\n'),
	(4229, 4, 16, 34, 'All Israel that were around them fled at their cry; for they said, “Lest the earth swallow us up!”\n'),
	(4230, 4, 16, 35, 'Fire came out from Yahweh, and devoured the two hundred fifty men who offered the incense.\n'),
	(4231, 4, 16, 36, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4232, 4, 16, 37, '“Speak to Eleazar the son of Aaron the priest, that he take up the censers out of the burning, and scatter the fire away from the camp; for they are holy,\n'),
	(4233, 4, 16, 38, 'even the censers of those who sinned against their own lives. Let them be beaten into plates for a covering of the altar, for they offered them before Yahweh. Therefore they are holy. They shall be a sign to the children of Israel.”\n'),
	(4234, 4, 16, 39, 'Eleazar the priest took the bronze censers, which those who were burned had offered; and they beat them out for a covering of the altar,\n'),
	(4235, 4, 16, 40, 'to be a memorial to the children of Israel, to the end that no stranger, who isn’t of the offspring of Aaron, would come near to burn incense before Yahweh, that he not be as Korah, and as his company; as Yahweh spoke to him by Moses.\n'),
	(4236, 4, 16, 41, 'But on the next day all the congregation of the children of Israel murmured against Moses and against Aaron, saying, “You have killed Yahweh’s people!”\n'),
	(4237, 4, 16, 42, 'When the congregation was assembled against Moses and against Aaron, They looked toward the Tent of Meeting. Behold, the cloud covered it, and Yahweh’s glory appeared.\n'),
	(4238, 4, 16, 43, 'Moses and Aaron came to the front of the Tent of Meeting.\n'),
	(4239, 4, 16, 44, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4240, 4, 16, 45, '“Get away from among this congregation, that I may consume them in a moment!” They fell on their faces.\n'),
	(4241, 4, 16, 46, 'Moses said to Aaron, “Take your censer, and put fire from off the altar in it, and lay incense on it, and carry it quickly to the congregation, and make atonement for them; for wrath has gone out from Yahweh! The plague has begun.”\n'),
	(4242, 4, 16, 47, 'Aaron did as Moses said, and ran into the middle of the assembly. The plague had already begun among the people. He put on the incense, and made atonement for the people.\n'),
	(4243, 4, 16, 48, 'He stood between the dead and the living; and the plague was stayed.\n'),
	(4244, 4, 16, 49, 'Now those who died by the plague were fourteen thousand and seven hundred, besides those who died about the matter of Korah.\n'),
	(4245, 4, 16, 50, 'Aaron returned to Moses to the door of the Tent of Meeting, and the plague was stopped.\n'),
	(4246, 4, 17, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4247, 4, 17, 2, '“Speak to the children of Israel, and take rods from them, one for each fathers’ house, of all their princes according to their fathers’ houses, twelve rods. Write each man’s name on his rod.\n'),
	(4248, 4, 17, 3, 'You shall write Aaron’s name on the rod of Levi; for there shall be one rod for each head of their fathers’ houses.\n'),
	(4249, 4, 17, 4, 'You shall lay them up in the Tent of Meeting before the testimony, where I meet with you.\n'),
	(4250, 4, 17, 5, 'It shall happen, that the rod of the man whom I shall choose shall bud. I will make the murmurings of the children of Israel, which they murmur against you, cease from me.”\n'),
	(4251, 4, 17, 6, 'Moses spoke to the children of Israel; and all their princes gave him rods, for each prince one, according to their fathers’ houses, a total of twelve rods. Aaron’s rod was among their rods.\n'),
	(4252, 4, 17, 7, 'Moses laid up the rods before Yahweh in the Tent of the Testimony.\n'),
	(4253, 4, 17, 8, 'On the next day, Moses went into the Tent of the Testimony; and behold, Aaron’s rod for the house of Levi had sprouted, budded, produced blossoms, and bore ripe almonds.\n'),
	(4254, 4, 17, 9, 'Moses brought out all the rods from before Yahweh to all the children of Israel. They looked, and each man took his rod.\n'),
	(4255, 4, 17, 10, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Put back the rod of Aaron before the testimony, to be kept for a token against the children of rebellion; that you may make an end of their murmurings against me, that they not die.”\n'),
	(4256, 4, 17, 11, 'Moses did so. As Yahweh commanded him, so he did.\n'),
	(4257, 4, 17, 12, 'The children of Israel spoke to Moses, saying, “Behold, we perish! We are undone! We are all undone!\n'),
	(4258, 4, 17, 13, 'Everyone who keeps approaching Yahweh’s tabernacle, dies! Will we all perish?”\n'),
	(4259, 4, 18, 1, 'Yahweh said to Aaron, “You and your sons and your fathers’ house with you shall bear the iniquity of the sanctuary; and you and your sons with you shall bear the iniquity of your priesthood.\n'),
	(4260, 4, 18, 2, 'Bring your brothers also, the tribe of Levi, the tribe of your father, near with you, that they may be joined to you, and minister to you; but you and your sons with you shall be before the Tent of the Testimony.\n'),
	(4261, 4, 18, 3, 'They shall keep your commands, and the duty of the whole Tent; only they shall not come near to the vessels of the sanctuary and to the altar, that they not die, neither they, nor you.\n'),
	(4262, 4, 18, 4, 'They shall be joined to you, and keep the responsibility of the Tent of Meeting, for all the service of the Tent. A stranger shall not come near to you.\n'),
	(4263, 4, 18, 5, '“You shall perform the duty of the sanctuary and the duty of the altar, that there be no more wrath on the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4264, 4, 18, 6, 'Behold, I myself have taken your brothers the Levites from among the children of Israel. They are a gift to you, dedicated to Yahweh, to do the service of the Tent of Meeting.\n'),
	(4265, 4, 18, 7, 'You and your sons with you shall keep your priesthood for everything of the altar, and for that within the veil. You shall serve. I give you the service of the priesthood as a gift. The stranger who comes near shall be put to death.”\n'),
	(4266, 4, 18, 8, 'Yahweh spoke to Aaron, “Behold, I myself have given you the command of my wave offerings, even all the holy things of the children of Israel. I have given them to you by reason of the anointing, and to your sons, as a portion forever.\n'),
	(4267, 4, 18, 9, 'This shall be yours of the most holy things from the fire: every offering of theirs, even every meal offering of theirs, and every sin offering of theirs, and every trespass offering of theirs, which they shall render to me, shall be most holy for you and for your sons.\n'),
	(4268, 4, 18, 10, 'You shall eat of it like the most holy things. Every male shall eat of it. It shall be holy to you.\n'),
	(4269, 4, 18, 11, '“This is yours, too: the wave offering of their gift, even all the wave offerings of the children of Israel. I have given them to you, and to your sons and to your daughters with you, as a portion forever. Everyone who is clean in your house shall eat of it.\n'),
	(4270, 4, 18, 12, '“I have given to you all the best of the oil, and all the best of the vintage, and of the grain, the first fruits of them which they give to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4271, 4, 18, 13, 'The first-ripe fruits of all that is in their land, which they bring to Yahweh, shall be yours. Everyone who is clean in your house shall eat of it.\n'),
	(4272, 4, 18, 14, '“Everything devoted in Israel shall be yours.\n'),
	(4273, 4, 18, 15, 'Everything that opens the womb, of all flesh which they offer to Yahweh, both of man and animal shall be yours. Nevertheless, you shall surely redeem the firstborn of man, and you shall redeem the firstborn of unclean animals.\n'),
	(4274, 4, 18, 16, 'You shall redeem those who are to be redeemed of them from a month old, according to your estimation, for five shekels of money, after the shekel of the sanctuary, which weighs twenty gerahs.\n'),
	(4275, 4, 18, 17, '“But you shall not redeem the firstborn of a cow, or the firstborn of a sheep, or the firstborn of a goat. They are holy. You shall sprinkle their blood on the altar, and shall burn their fat for an offering made by fire, for a pleasant aroma to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4276, 4, 18, 18, 'Their meat shall be yours, as the wave offering breast and as the right thigh, it shall be yours.\n'),
	(4277, 4, 18, 19, 'All the wave offerings of the holy things, which the children of Israel offer to Yahweh, I have given you, and your sons and your daughters with you, as a portion forever. It is a covenant of salt forever before Yahweh to you and to your offspring with you.”\n'),
	(4278, 4, 18, 20, 'Yahweh said to Aaron, “You shall have no inheritance in their land, neither shall you have any portion among them. I am your portion and your inheritance among the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4279, 4, 18, 21, '“To the children of Levi, behold, I have given all the tithe in Israel for an inheritance, in return for their service which they serve, even the service of the Tent of Meeting.\n'),
	(4280, 4, 18, 22, 'Henceforth the children of Israel shall not come near the Tent of Meeting, lest they bear sin, and die.\n'),
	(4281, 4, 18, 23, 'But the Levites shall do the service of the Tent of Meeting, and they shall bear their iniquity. It shall be a statute forever throughout your generations. Among the children of Israel, they shall have no inheritance.\n'),
	(4282, 4, 18, 24, 'For the tithe of the children of Israel, which they offer as a wave offering to Yahweh, I have given to the Levites for an inheritance. Therefore I have said to them, ‘Among the children of Israel they shall have no inheritance.’”\n'),
	(4283, 4, 18, 25, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4284, 4, 18, 26, '“Moreover you shall speak to the Levites, and tell them, ‘When you take of the children of Israel the tithe which I have given you from them for your inheritance, then you shall offer up a wave offering of it for Yahweh, a tithe of the tithe.\n'),
	(4285, 4, 18, 27, 'Your wave offering shall be credited to you, as though it were the grain of the threshing floor, and as the fullness of the wine press.\n'),
	(4286, 4, 18, 28, 'Thus you also shall offer a wave offering to Yahweh of all your tithes, which you receive of the children of Israel; and of it you shall give Yahweh’s wave offering to Aaron the priest.\n'),
	(4287, 4, 18, 29, 'Out of all your gifts, you shall offer every wave offering of Yahweh, of all its best parts, even the holy part of it.’\n'),
	(4288, 4, 18, 30, '“Therefore you shall tell them, ‘When you heave its best from it, then it shall be credited to the Levites as the increase of the threshing floor, and as the increase of the wine press.\n'),
	(4289, 4, 18, 31, 'You may eat it anywhere, you and your households, for it is your reward in return for your service in the Tent of Meeting.\n'),
	(4290, 4, 18, 32, 'You shall bear no sin by reason of it, when you have heaved from it its best. You shall not profane the holy things of the children of Israel, that you not die.’”\n'),
	(4291, 4, 19, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses and to Aaron, saying,\n'),
	(4292, 4, 19, 2, '“This is the statute of the law which Yahweh has commanded. Tell the children of Israel to bring you a red heifer without spot, in which is no defect, and which was never yoked.\n'),
	(4293, 4, 19, 3, 'You shall give her to Eleazar the priest, and he shall bring her outside of the camp, and one shall kill her before his face.\n'),
	(4294, 4, 19, 4, 'Eleazar the priest shall take some of her blood with his finger, and sprinkle her blood toward the front of the Tent of Meeting seven times.\n'),
	(4295, 4, 19, 5, 'One shall burn the heifer in his sight; her skin, and her meat, and her blood, with her dung, shall he burn.\n'),
	(4296, 4, 19, 6, 'The priest shall take cedar wood, hyssop, and scarlet, and cast it into the middle of the burning of the heifer.\n'),
	(4297, 4, 19, 7, 'Then the priest shall wash his clothes, and he shall bathe his flesh in water, and afterward he shall come into the camp, and the priest shall be unclean until the evening.\n'),
	(4298, 4, 19, 8, 'He who burns her shall wash his clothes in water, and bathe his flesh in water, and shall be unclean until the evening.\n'),
	(4299, 4, 19, 9, '“A man who is clean shall gather up the ashes of the heifer, and lay them up outside of the camp in a clean place; and it shall be kept for the congregation of the children of Israel for use in water for cleansing impurity. It is a sin offering.\n'),
	(4300, 4, 19, 10, 'He who gathers the ashes of the heifer shall wash his clothes, and be unclean until the evening. It shall be to the children of Israel, and to the stranger who lives as a foreigner among them, for a statute forever.\n'),
	(4301, 4, 19, 11, '“He who touches the dead body of any man shall be unclean seven days.\n'),
	(4302, 4, 19, 12, 'He shall purify himself with water on the third day, and on the seventh day he shall be clean; but if he doesn’t purify himself the third day, then the seventh day he shall not be clean.\n'),
	(4303, 4, 19, 13, 'Whoever touches a dead person, the body of a man who has died, and doesn’t purify himself, defiles Yahweh’s tabernacle; and that soul shall be cut off from Israel; because the water for impurity was not sprinkled on him, he shall be unclean. His uncleanness is yet on him.\n'),
	(4304, 4, 19, 14, '“This is the law when a man dies in a tent: everyone who comes into the tent, and everyone who is in the tent, shall be unclean seven days.\n'),
	(4305, 4, 19, 15, 'Every open vessel, which has no covering bound on it, is unclean.\n'),
	(4306, 4, 19, 16, '“Whoever in the open field touches one who is slain with a sword, or a dead body, or a bone of a man, or a grave, shall be unclean seven days.\n'),
	(4307, 4, 19, 17, '“For the unclean, they shall take of the ashes of the burning of the sin offering; and running water shall be poured into a vessel.\n'),
	(4308, 4, 19, 18, 'A clean person shall take hyssop, dip it in the water, and sprinkle it on the tent, on all the vessels, on the persons who were there, and on him who touched the bone, or the slain, or the dead, or the grave.\n'),
	(4309, 4, 19, 19, 'The clean person shall sprinkle on the unclean on the third day, and on the seventh day. On the seventh day, he shall purify him. He shall wash his clothes and bathe himself in water, and shall be clean at evening.\n'),
	(4310, 4, 19, 20, 'But the man who shall be unclean, and shall not purify himself, that soul shall be cut off from among the assembly, because he has defiled the sanctuary of Yahweh. The water for impurity has not been sprinkled on him. He is unclean.\n'),
	(4311, 4, 19, 21, 'It shall be a perpetual statute to them. He who sprinkles the water for impurity shall wash his clothes, and he who touches the water for impurity shall be unclean until evening.\n'),
	(4312, 4, 19, 22, '“Whatever the unclean person touches shall be unclean; and the soul that touches it shall be unclean until evening.”\n'),
	(4313, 4, 20, 1, 'The children of Israel, even the whole congregation, came into the wilderness of Zin in the first month. The people stayed in Kadesh. Miriam died there, and was buried there.\n'),
	(4314, 4, 20, 2, 'There was no water for the congregation; and they assembled themselves together against Moses and against Aaron.\n'),
	(4315, 4, 20, 3, 'The people quarreled with Moses, and spoke, saying, “We wish that we had died when our brothers died before Yahweh!\n'),
	(4316, 4, 20, 4, 'Why have you brought Yahweh’s assembly into this wilderness, that we should die there, we and our animals?\n'),
	(4317, 4, 20, 5, 'Why have you made us to come up out of Egypt, to bring us in to this evil place? It is no place of seed, or of figs, or of vines, or of pomegranates; neither is there any water to drink.”\n'),
	(4318, 4, 20, 6, 'Moses and Aaron went from the presence of the assembly to the door of the Tent of Meeting, and fell on their faces. Yahweh’s glory appeared to them.\n'),
	(4319, 4, 20, 7, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4320, 4, 20, 8, '“Take the rod, and assemble the congregation, you, and Aaron your brother, and speak to the rock before their eyes, that it pour out its water. You shall bring water to them out of the rock; so you shall give the congregation and their livestock drink.”\n'),
	(4321, 4, 20, 9, 'Moses took the rod from before Yahweh, as he commanded him.\n'),
	(4322, 4, 20, 10, 'Moses and Aaron gathered the assembly together before the rock, and he said to them, “Hear now, you rebels! Shall we bring water out of this rock for you?”\n'),
	(4323, 4, 20, 11, 'Moses lifted up his hand, and struck the rock with his rod twice, and water came out abundantly. The congregation and their livestock drank.\n'),
	(4324, 4, 20, 12, 'Yahweh said to Moses and Aaron, “Because you didn’t believe in me, to sanctify me in the eyes of the children of Israel, therefore you shall not bring this assembly into the land which I have given them.”\n'),
	(4325, 4, 20, 13, 'These are the waters of Meribah; because the children of Israel strove with Yahweh, and he was sanctified in them.\n'),
	(4326, 4, 20, 14, 'Moses sent messengers from Kadesh to the king of Edom, saying:\n“Thus says your brother Israel: You know all the travail that has happened to us;\n'),
	(4327, 4, 20, 15, 'how our fathers went down into Egypt, and we lived in Egypt a long time. The Egyptians mistreated us and our fathers.\n'),
	(4328, 4, 20, 16, 'When we cried to Yahweh, he heard our voice, sent an angel, and brought us out of Egypt. Behold, we are in Kadesh, a city in the edge of your border.\n'),
	(4329, 4, 20, 17, '“Please let us pass through your land. We will not pass through field or through vineyard, neither will we drink from the water of the wells. We will go along the king’s highway. We will not turn away to the right hand nor to the left, until we have passed your border.”\n'),
	(4330, 4, 20, 18, 'Edom said to him, “You shall not pass through me, lest I come out with the sword against you.”\n'),
	(4331, 4, 20, 19, 'The children of Israel said to him, “We will go up by the highway; and if we drink your water, I and my livestock, then I will give its price. Only let me, without doing anything else, pass through on my feet.”\n'),
	(4332, 4, 20, 20, 'He said, “You shall not pass through.” Edom came out against him with many people, and with a strong hand.\n'),
	(4333, 4, 20, 21, 'Thus Edom refused to give Israel passage through his border, so Israel turned away from him.\n'),
	(4334, 4, 20, 22, 'They traveled from Kadesh: and the children of Israel, even the whole congregation, came to Mount Hor.\n'),
	(4335, 4, 20, 23, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses and Aaron in Mount Hor, by the border of the land of Edom, saying,\n'),
	(4336, 4, 20, 24, '“Aaron shall be gathered to his people; for he shall not enter into the land which I have given to the children of Israel, because you rebelled against my word at the waters of Meribah.\n'),
	(4337, 4, 20, 25, 'Take Aaron and Eleazar his son, and bring them up to Mount Hor;\n'),
	(4338, 4, 20, 26, 'and strip Aaron of his garments, and put them on Eleazar his son. Aaron shall be gathered, and shall die there.”\n'),
	(4339, 4, 20, 27, 'Moses did as Yahweh commanded. They went up into Mount Hor in the sight of all the congregation.\n'),
	(4340, 4, 20, 28, 'Moses stripped Aaron of his garments, and put them on Eleazar his son. Aaron died there on the top of the mountain, and Moses and Eleazar came down from the mountain.\n'),
	(4341, 4, 20, 29, 'When all the congregation saw that Aaron was dead, they wept for Aaron thirty days, even all the house of Israel.\n'),
	(4342, 4, 21, 1, 'The Canaanite, the king of Arad, who lived in the South, heard that Israel came by the way of Atharim. He fought against Israel, and took some of them captive.\n'),
	(4343, 4, 21, 2, 'Israel vowed a vow to Yahweh, and said, “If you will indeed deliver this people into my hand, then I will utterly destroy their cities.”\n'),
	(4344, 4, 21, 3, 'Yahweh listened to the voice of Israel, and delivered up the Canaanites; and they utterly destroyed them and their cities. The name of the place was called Hormah.\n'),
	(4345, 4, 21, 4, 'They traveled from Mount Hor by the way to the Red Sea, to go around the land of Edom The soul of the people was very discouraged because of the journey.\n'),
	(4346, 4, 21, 5, 'The people spoke against God, and against Moses, “Why have you brought us up out of Egypt to die in the wilderness? For there is no bread, and there is no water; and our soul loathes this disgusting bread.”\n'),
	(4347, 4, 21, 6, 'Yahweh sent venomous snakes among the people, and they bit the people. Many people of Israel died.\n'),
	(4348, 4, 21, 7, 'The people came to Moses, and said, “We have sinned, because we have spoken against Yahweh, and against you. Pray to Yahweh, that he take away the serpents from us.” Moses prayed for the people.\n'),
	(4349, 4, 21, 8, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Make a venomous snake, and set it on a pole. It shall happen, that everyone who is bitten, when he sees it, shall live.”\n'),
	(4350, 4, 21, 9, 'Moses made a serpent of brass, and set it on the pole. If a serpent had bitten any man, when he looked at the serpent of brass, he lived.\n'),
	(4351, 4, 21, 10, 'The children of Israel traveled, and encamped in Oboth.\n'),
	(4352, 4, 21, 11, 'They traveled from Oboth, and encamped at Iyeabarim, in the wilderness which is before Moab, toward the sunrise.\n'),
	(4353, 4, 21, 12, 'From there they traveled, and encamped in the valley of Zered.\n'),
	(4354, 4, 21, 13, 'From there they traveled, and encamped on the other side of the Arnon, which is in the wilderness, that comes out of the border of the Amorites: for the Arnon is the border of Moab, between Moab and the Amorites.\n'),
	(4355, 4, 21, 14, 'Therefore it is said in the book of the Wars of Yahweh, “Vaheb in Suphah, the valleys of the Arnon,\n'),
	(4356, 4, 21, 15, 'the slope of the valleys that incline toward the dwelling of Ar, leans on the border of Moab.”\n'),
	(4357, 4, 21, 16, 'From there they traveled to Beer; that is the well of which Yahweh said to Moses, “Gather the people together, and I will give them water.”\n'),
	(4358, 4, 21, 17, 'Then Israel sang this song:\n“Spring up, well! Sing to it,\n'),
	(4359, 4, 21, 18, 'the well, which the princes dug,\nwhich the nobles of the people dug,\nwith the scepter, and with their poles.”\nFrom the wilderness they traveled to Mattanah;\n'),
	(4360, 4, 21, 19, 'and from Mattanah to Nahaliel; and from Nahaliel to Bamoth;\n'),
	(4361, 4, 21, 20, 'and from Bamoth to the valley that is in the field of Moab, to the top of Pisgah, which looks down on the desert.\n'),
	(4362, 4, 21, 21, 'Israel sent messengers to Sihon king of the Amorites, saying,\n'),
	(4363, 4, 21, 22, '“Let me pass through your land. We will not turn away into field or vineyard. We will not drink of the water of the wells. We will go by the king’s highway, until we have passed your border.”\n'),
	(4364, 4, 21, 23, 'Sihon would not allow Israel to pass through his border, but Sihon gathered all his people together, and went out against Israel into the wilderness, and came to Jahaz. He fought against Israel.\n'),
	(4365, 4, 21, 24, 'Israel struck him with the edge of the sword, and possessed his land from the Arnon to the Jabbok, even to the children of Ammon; for the border of the children of Ammon was strong.\n'),
	(4366, 4, 21, 25, 'Israel took all these cities. Israel lived in all the cities of the Amorites, in Heshbon, and in all its villages.\n'),
	(4367, 4, 21, 26, 'For Heshbon was the city of Sihon the king of the Amorites, who had fought against the former king of Moab, and taken all his land out of his hand, even to the Arnon.\n'),
	(4368, 4, 21, 27, 'Therefore those who speak in proverbs say,\n“Come to Heshbon.\nLet the city of Sihon be built and established;\n'),
	(4369, 4, 21, 28, 'for a fire has gone out of Heshbon,\na flame from the city of Sihon.\nIt has devoured Ar of Moab,\nThe lords of the high places of the Arnon.\n'),
	(4370, 4, 21, 29, 'Woe to you, Moab!\nYou are undone, people of Chemosh!\nHe has given his sons as fugitives,\nand his daughters into captivity,\nto Sihon king of the Amorites.\n'),
	(4371, 4, 21, 30, 'We have shot at them.\nHeshbon has perished even to Dibon.\nWe have laid waste even to Nophah,\nWhich reaches to Medeba.”\n'),
	(4372, 4, 21, 31, 'Thus Israel lived in the land of the Amorites.\n'),
	(4373, 4, 21, 32, 'Moses sent to spy out Jazer. They took its villages, and drove out the Amorites who were there.\n'),
	(4374, 4, 21, 33, 'They turned and went up by the way of Bashan. Og the king of Bashan went out against them, he and all his people, to battle at Edrei.\n'),
	(4375, 4, 21, 34, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Don’t fear him, for I have delivered him into your hand, with all his people, and his land. You shall do to him as you did to Sihon king of the Amorites, who lived at Heshbon.”\n'),
	(4376, 4, 21, 35, 'So they struck him, with his sons and all his people, until there were no survivors; and they possessed his land.\n'),
	(4377, 4, 22, 1, 'The children of Israel traveled, and encamped in the plains of Moab beyond the Jordan at Jericho.\n'),
	(4378, 4, 22, 2, 'Balak the son of Zippor saw all that Israel had done to the Amorites.\n'),
	(4379, 4, 22, 3, 'Moab was very afraid of the people, because they were many. Moab was distressed because of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4380, 4, 22, 4, 'Moab said to the elders of Midian, “Now this multitude will lick up all that is around us, as the ox licks up the grass of the field.”\nBalak the son of Zippor was king of Moab at that time.\n'),
	(4381, 4, 22, 5, 'He sent messengers to Balaam the son of Beor, to Pethor, which is by the River, to the land of the children of his people, to call him, saying, “Behold, there is a people who came out of Egypt. Behold, they cover the surface of the earth, and they are staying opposite me.\n'),
	(4382, 4, 22, 6, 'Please come now therefore curse me this people; for they are too mighty for me. Perhaps I shall prevail, that we may strike them, and that I may drive them out of the land; for I know that he whom you bless is blessed, and he whom you curse is cursed.”\n'),
	(4383, 4, 22, 7, 'The elders of Moab and the elders of Midian departed with the rewards of divination in their hand. They came to Balaam, and spoke to him the words of Balak.\n'),
	(4384, 4, 22, 8, 'He said to them, “Lodge here this night, and I will bring you word again, as Yahweh shall speak to me.” The princes of Moab stayed with Balaam.\n'),
	(4385, 4, 22, 9, 'God came to Balaam, and said, “Who are these men with you?”\n'),
	(4386, 4, 22, 10, 'Balaam said to God, “Balak the son of Zippor, king of Moab, has said to me,\n'),
	(4387, 4, 22, 11, '‘Behold, the people that has come out of Egypt covers the surface of the earth. Now, come curse me them. Perhaps I shall be able to fight against them, and shall drive them out.’”\n'),
	(4388, 4, 22, 12, 'God said to Balaam, “You shall not go with them. You shall not curse the people; for they are blessed.”\n'),
	(4389, 4, 22, 13, 'Balaam rose up in the morning, and said to the princes of Balak, “Go to your land; for Yahweh refuses to permit me to go with you.”\n'),
	(4390, 4, 22, 14, 'The princes of Moab rose up, and they went to Balak, and said, “Balaam refuses to come with us.”\n'),
	(4391, 4, 22, 15, 'Balak again sent princes, more, and more honorable than they.\n'),
	(4392, 4, 22, 16, 'They came to Balaam, and said to him, “Thus says Balak the son of Zippor, ‘Please let nothing hinder you from coming to me,\n'),
	(4393, 4, 22, 17, 'for I will promote you to very great honor, and whatever you say to me I will do. Please come therefore, and curse this people for me.’”\n'),
	(4394, 4, 22, 18, 'Balaam answered the servants of Balak, “If Balak would give me his house full of silver and gold, I can’t go beyond the word of Yahweh my God, to do less or more.\n'),
	(4395, 4, 22, 19, 'Now therefore please stay here tonight as well, that I may know what else Yahweh will speak to me.”\n'),
	(4396, 4, 22, 20, 'God came to Balaam at night, and said to him, “If the men have come to call you, rise up, go with them; but only the word which I speak to you, that you shall do.”\n'),
	(4397, 4, 22, 21, 'Balaam rose up in the morning, and saddled his donkey, and went with the princes of Moab.\n'),
	(4398, 4, 22, 22, 'God’s anger burned because he went; and Yahweh’s angel placed himself in the way for an adversary against him. Now he was riding on his donkey, and his two servants were with him.\n'),
	(4399, 4, 22, 23, 'The donkey saw Yahweh’s angel standing in the way, with his sword drawn in his hand; and the donkey turned out of the path, and went into the field. Balaam struck the donkey, to turn her into the path.\n'),
	(4400, 4, 22, 24, 'Then Yahweh’s angel stood in a narrow path between the vineyards, a wall being on this side, and a wall on that side.\n'),
	(4401, 4, 22, 25, 'The donkey saw Yahweh’s angel, and she thrust herself to the wall, and crushed Balaam’s foot against the wall. He struck her again.\n'),
	(4402, 4, 22, 26, 'Yahweh’s angel went further, and stood in a narrow place, where there was no way to turn either to the right hand or to the left.\n'),
	(4403, 4, 22, 27, 'The donkey saw Yahweh’s angel, and she lay down under Balaam. Balaam’s anger burned, and he struck the donkey with his staff.\n'),
	(4404, 4, 22, 28, 'Yahweh opened the mouth of the donkey, and she said to Balaam, “What have I done to you, that you have struck me these three times?”\n'),
	(4405, 4, 22, 29, 'Balaam said to the donkey, “Because you have mocked me, I wish there were a sword in my hand, for now I would have killed you.”\n'),
	(4406, 4, 22, 30, 'The donkey said to Balaam, “Am I not your donkey, on which you have ridden all your life long until today? Was I ever in the habit of doing so to you?”\nHe said, “No.”\n'),
	(4407, 4, 22, 31, 'Then Yahweh opened the eyes of Balaam, and he saw Yahweh’s angel standing in the way, with his sword drawn in his hand; and he bowed his head, and fell on his face.\n'),
	(4408, 4, 22, 32, 'Yahweh’s angel said to him, “Why have you struck your donkey these three times? Behold, I have come out as an adversary, because your way is perverse before me.\n'),
	(4409, 4, 22, 33, 'The donkey saw me, and turned away before me these three times. Unless she had turned away from me, surely now I would have killed you, and saved her alive.”\n'),
	(4410, 4, 22, 34, 'Balaam said to Yahweh’s angel, “I have sinned; for I didn’t know that you stood in the way against me. Now therefore, if it displeases you, I will go back again.”\n'),
	(4411, 4, 22, 35, 'Yahweh’s angel said to Balaam, “Go with the men; but only the word that I shall speak to you, that you shall speak.”\nSo Balaam went with the princes of Balak.\n'),
	(4412, 4, 22, 36, 'When Balak heard that Balaam had come, he went out to meet him to the City of Moab, which is on the border of the Arnon, which is in the utmost part of the border.\n'),
	(4413, 4, 22, 37, 'Balak said to Balaam, “Didn’t I earnestly send for you to summon you? Why didn’t you come to me? Am I not able indeed to promote you to honor?”\n'),
	(4414, 4, 22, 38, 'Balaam said to Balak, “Behold, I have come to you. Have I now any power at all to speak anything? The word that God puts in my mouth, that shall I speak.”\n'),
	(4415, 4, 22, 39, 'Balaam went with Balak, and they came to Kiriath Huzoth.\n'),
	(4416, 4, 22, 40, 'Balak sacrificed cattle and sheep, and sent to Balaam, and to the princes who were with him.\n'),
	(4417, 4, 22, 41, 'In the morning, Balak took Balaam, and brought him up into the high places of Baal; and he saw from there part of the people.\n'),
	(4418, 4, 23, 1, 'Balaam said to Balak, “Build here seven altars for me, and prepare here seven bulls and seven rams for me.”\n'),
	(4419, 4, 23, 2, 'Balak did as Balaam had spoken; and Balak and Balaam offered on every altar a bull and a ram.\n'),
	(4420, 4, 23, 3, 'Balaam said to Balak, “Stand by your burnt offering, and I will go. Perhaps Yahweh will come to meet me. Whatever he shows me I will tell you.”\nHe went to a bare height.\n'),
	(4421, 4, 23, 4, 'God met Balaam, and he said to him, “I have prepared the seven altars, and I have offered up a bull and a ram on every altar.”\n'),
	(4422, 4, 23, 5, 'Yahweh put a word in Balaam’s mouth, and said, “Return to Balak, and thus you shall speak.”\n'),
	(4423, 4, 23, 6, 'He returned to him, and behold, he was standing by his burnt offering, he, and all the princes of Moab.\n'),
	(4424, 4, 23, 7, 'He took up his parable, and said,\n“From Aram has Balak brought me,\nthe king of Moab from the mountains of the East.\nCome, curse Jacob for me.\nCome, defy Israel.\n'),
	(4425, 4, 23, 8, 'How shall I curse whom God has not cursed?\nHow shall I defy whom Yahweh has not defied?\n'),
	(4426, 4, 23, 9, 'For from the top of the rocks I see him.\nFrom the hills I see him.\nBehold, it is a people that dwells alone,\nand shall not be listed among the nations.\n'),
	(4427, 4, 23, 10, 'Who can count the dust of Jacob,\nor count the fourth part of Israel?\nLet me die the death of the righteous!\nLet my last end be like his!”\n'),
	(4428, 4, 23, 11, 'Balak said to Balaam, “What have you done to me? I took you to curse my enemies, and behold, you have blessed them altogether.”\n'),
	(4429, 4, 23, 12, 'He answered and said, “Must I not take heed to speak that which Yahweh puts in my mouth?”\n'),
	(4430, 4, 23, 13, 'Balak said to him, “Please come with me to another place, where you may see them. You shall see just part of them, and shall not see them all. Curse them from there for me.”\n'),
	(4431, 4, 23, 14, 'He took him into the field of Zophim, to the top of Pisgah, and built seven altars, and offered up a bull and a ram on every altar.\n'),
	(4432, 4, 23, 15, 'He said to Balak, “Stand here by your burnt offering, while I meet God over there.”\n'),
	(4433, 4, 23, 16, 'Yahweh met Balaam, and put a word in his mouth, and said, “Return to Balak, and say this.”\n'),
	(4434, 4, 23, 17, 'He came to him, and behold, he was standing by his burnt offering, and the princes of Moab with him. Balak said to him, “What has Yahweh spoken?”\n'),
	(4435, 4, 23, 18, 'He took up his parable, and said,\n“Rise up, Balak, and hear!\nListen to me, you son of Zippor.\n'),
	(4436, 4, 23, 19, 'God is not a man, that he should lie,\nnor a son of man, that he should repent.\nHas he said, and will he not do it?\nOr has he spoken, and will he not make it good?\n'),
	(4437, 4, 23, 20, 'Behold, I have received a command to bless.\nHe has blessed, and I can’t reverse it.\n'),
	(4438, 4, 23, 21, 'He has not seen iniquity in Jacob.\nNeither has he seen perverseness in Israel.\nYahweh his God is with him.\nThe shout of a king is among them.\n'),
	(4439, 4, 23, 22, 'God brings them out of Egypt.\nHe has as it were the strength of the wild ox.\n'),
	(4440, 4, 23, 23, 'Surely there is no enchantment with Jacob;\nNeither is there any divination with Israel.\nNow it shall be said of Jacob and of Israel,\n‘What has God done!’\n'),
	(4441, 4, 23, 24, 'Behold, the people rises up as a lioness.\nAs a lion he lifts himself up.\nHe shall not lie down until he eats of the prey,\nand drinks the blood of the slain.”\n'),
	(4442, 4, 23, 25, 'Balak said to Balaam, “Neither curse them at all, nor bless them at all.”\n'),
	(4443, 4, 23, 26, 'But Balaam answered Balak, “Didn’t I tell you, saying, ‘All that Yahweh speaks, that I must do?’”\n'),
	(4444, 4, 23, 27, 'Balak said to Balaam, “Come now, I will take you to another place; perhaps it will please God that you may curse them for me from there.”\n'),
	(4445, 4, 23, 28, 'Balak took Balaam to the top of Peor, that looks down on the desert.\n'),
	(4446, 4, 23, 29, 'Balaam said to Balak, “Build seven altars for me here, and prepare seven bulls and seven rams for me here.”\n'),
	(4447, 4, 23, 30, 'Balak did as Balaam had said, and offered up a bull and a ram on every altar.\n'),
	(4448, 4, 24, 1, 'When Balaam saw that it pleased Yahweh to bless Israel, he didn’t go, as at the other times, to meet with enchantments, but he set his face toward the wilderness.\n'),
	(4449, 4, 24, 2, 'Balaam lifted up his eyes, and he saw Israel dwelling according to their tribes; and the Spirit of God came on him.\n'),
	(4450, 4, 24, 3, 'He took up his parable, and said,\n“Balaam the son of Beor says,\nthe man whose eyes are open says;\n'),
	(4451, 4, 24, 4, 'he says, who hears the words of God,\nwho sees the vision of the Almighty,\nfalling down, and having his eyes open:\n'),
	(4452, 4, 24, 5, 'How goodly are your tents, Jacob,\nand your tents, Israel!\n'),
	(4453, 4, 24, 6, 'As valleys they are spread out,\nas gardens by the riverside,\nas aloes which Yahweh has planted,\nas cedar trees beside the waters.\n'),
	(4454, 4, 24, 7, 'Water shall flow from his buckets.\nHis seed shall be in many waters.\nHis king shall be higher than Agag.\nHis kingdom shall be exalted.\n'),
	(4455, 4, 24, 8, 'God brings him out of Egypt.\nHe has as it were the strength of the wild ox.\nHe shall eat up the nations his adversaries,\nshall break their bones in pieces,\nand pierce them with his arrows.\n'),
	(4456, 4, 24, 9, 'He couched, he lay down as a lion,\nas a lioness; who shall rouse him up?\nEveryone who blesses you is blessed.\nEveryone who curses you is cursed.”\n'),
	(4457, 4, 24, 10, 'Balak’s anger burned against Balaam, and he struck his hands together. Balak said to Balaam, “I called you to curse my enemies, and, behold, you have altogether blessed them these three times.\n'),
	(4458, 4, 24, 11, 'Therefore, flee to your place, now! I thought to promote you to great honor; but, behold, Yahweh has kept you back from honor.”\n'),
	(4459, 4, 24, 12, 'Balaam said to Balak, “Didn’t I also tell your messengers whom you sent to me, saying,\n'),
	(4460, 4, 24, 13, '‘If Balak would give me his house full of silver and gold, I can’t go beyond Yahweh’s word, to do either good or bad from my own mind. I will say what Yahweh says’?\n'),
	(4461, 4, 24, 14, 'Now, behold, I go to my people. Come, I will inform you what this people shall do to your people in the latter days.”\n'),
	(4462, 4, 24, 15, 'He took up his parable, and said,\n“Balaam the son of Beor says,\nthe man whose eyes are open says;\n'),
	(4463, 4, 24, 16, 'he says, who hears the words of God,\nknows the knowledge of the Most High,\nand who sees the vision of the Almighty,\nFalling down, and having his eyes open:\n'),
	(4464, 4, 24, 17, 'I see him, but not now.\nI see him, but not near.\nA star will come out of Jacob.\nA scepter will rise out of Israel,\nand shall strike through the corners of Moab,\nand break down all the sons of Sheth.\n'),
	(4465, 4, 24, 18, 'Edom shall be a possession.\nSeir, his enemies, also shall be a possession,\nwhile Israel does valiantly.\n'),
	(4466, 4, 24, 19, 'Out of Jacob shall one have dominion,\nand shall destroy the remnant from the city.”\n'),
	(4467, 4, 24, 20, 'He looked at Amalek, and took up his parable, and said,\n“Amalek was the first of the nations,\nBut his latter end shall come to destruction.”\n'),
	(4468, 4, 24, 21, 'He looked at the Kenite, and took up his parable, and said,\n“Your dwelling place is strong.\nYour nest is set in the rock.\n'),
	(4469, 4, 24, 22, 'Nevertheless Kain shall be wasted,\nuntil Asshur carries you away captive.”\n'),
	(4470, 4, 24, 23, 'He took up his parable, and said,\n“Alas, who shall live when God does this?\n'),
	(4471, 4, 24, 24, 'But ships shall come from the coast of Kittim.\nThey shall afflict Asshur, and shall afflict Eber.\nHe also shall come to destruction.”\n'),
	(4472, 4, 24, 25, 'Balaam rose up, and went and returned to his place; and Balak also went his way.\n'),
	(4473, 4, 25, 1, 'Israel stayed in Shittim; and the people began to play the prostitute with the daughters of Moab;\n'),
	(4474, 4, 25, 2, 'for they called the people to the sacrifices of their gods. The people ate and bowed down to their gods.\n'),
	(4475, 4, 25, 3, 'Israel joined himself to Baal Peor. Yahweh’s anger burned against Israel.\n'),
	(4476, 4, 25, 4, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Take all the chiefs of the people, and hang them up to Yahweh before the sun, that the fierce anger of Yahweh may turn away from Israel.”\n'),
	(4477, 4, 25, 5, 'Moses said to the judges of Israel, “Everyone kill his men who have joined themselves to Baal Peor.”\n'),
	(4478, 4, 25, 6, 'Behold, one of the children of Israel came and brought to his brothers a Midianite woman in the sight of Moses, and in the sight of all the congregation of the children of Israel, while they were weeping at the door of the Tent of Meeting.\n'),
	(4479, 4, 25, 7, 'When Phinehas, the son of Eleazar, the son of Aaron the priest, saw it, he rose up from the middle of the congregation, and took a spear in his hand.\n'),
	(4480, 4, 25, 8, 'He went after the man of Israel into the pavilion, and thrust both of them through, the man of Israel, and the woman through her body. So the plague was stayed from the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4481, 4, 25, 9, 'Those who died by the plague were twenty-four thousand.\n'),
	(4482, 4, 25, 10, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4483, 4, 25, 11, '“Phinehas, the son of Eleazar, the son of Aaron the priest, has turned my wrath away from the children of Israel, in that he was jealous with my jealousy among them, so that I didn’t consume the children of Israel in my jealousy.\n'),
	(4484, 4, 25, 12, 'Therefore say, ‘Behold, I give to him my covenant of peace.\n'),
	(4485, 4, 25, 13, 'It shall be to him, and to his offspring after him, the covenant of an everlasting priesthood, because he was jealous for his God, and made atonement for the children of Israel.’”\n'),
	(4486, 4, 25, 14, 'Now the name of the man of Israel that was slain, who was slain with the Midianite woman, was Zimri, the son of Salu, a prince of a fathers’ house among the Simeonites.\n'),
	(4487, 4, 25, 15, 'The name of the Midianite woman who was slain was Cozbi, the daughter of Zur. He was head of the people of a fathers’ house in Midian.\n'),
	(4488, 4, 25, 16, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4489, 4, 25, 17, '“Harass the Midianites, and strike them,\n'),
	(4490, 4, 25, 18, 'for they harassed you with their wiles, wherein they have deceived you in the matter of Peor, and in the incident regarding Cozbi, the daughter of the prince of Midian, their sister, who was slain on the day of the plague in the matter of Peor.”\n'),
	(4491, 4, 26, 1, 'After the plague, Yahweh spoke to Moses and to Eleazar the son of Aaron the priest, saying,\n'),
	(4492, 4, 26, 2, '“Take a census of all the congregation of the children of Israel, from twenty years old and upward, by their fathers’ houses, all who are able to go out to war in Israel.”\n'),
	(4493, 4, 26, 3, 'Moses and Eleazar the priest spoke with them in the plains of Moab by the Jordan at Jericho, saying,\n'),
	(4494, 4, 26, 4, '“Take a census, from twenty years old and upward; as Yahweh commanded Moses and the children of Israel.”\nThese are those that came out of the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(4495, 4, 26, 5, 'Reuben, the firstborn of Israel; the sons of Reuben: of Hanoch, the family of the Hanochites; of Pallu, the family of the Palluites;\n'),
	(4496, 4, 26, 6, 'of Hezron, the family of the Hezronites; of Carmi, the family of the Carmites.\n'),
	(4497, 4, 26, 7, 'These are the families of the Reubenites; and those who were counted of them were forty-three thousand seven hundred thirty.\n'),
	(4498, 4, 26, 8, 'The sons of Pallu: Eliab.\n'),
	(4499, 4, 26, 9, 'The sons of Eliab: Nemuel, and Dathan, and Abiram. These are that Dathan and Abiram, who were called by the congregation, who rebelled against Moses and against Aaron in the company of Korah, when they rebelled against Yahweh,\n'),
	(4500, 4, 26, 10, 'and the earth opened its mouth, and swallowed them up together with Korah, when that company died; at the time the fire devoured two hundred fifty men, and they became a sign.\n'),
	(4501, 4, 26, 11, 'Notwithstanding, the sons of Korah didn’t die.\n'),
	(4502, 4, 26, 12, 'The sons of Simeon after their families: of Nemuel, the family of the Nemuelites; of Jamin, the family of the Jaminites; of Jachin, the family of the Jachinites;\n'),
	(4503, 4, 26, 13, 'of Zerah, the family of the Zerahites; of Shaul, the family of the Shaulites.\n'),
	(4504, 4, 26, 14, 'These are the families of the Simeonites, twenty-two thousand two hundred.\n'),
	(4505, 4, 26, 15, 'The sons of Gad after their families: of Zephon, the family of the Zephonites; of Haggi, the family of the Haggites; of Shuni, the family of the Shunites;\n'),
	(4506, 4, 26, 16, 'of Ozni, the family of the Oznites; of Eri, the family of the Erites;\n'),
	(4507, 4, 26, 17, 'of Arod, the family of the Arodites; of Areli, the family of the Arelites.\n'),
	(4508, 4, 26, 18, 'These are the families of the sons of Gad according to those who were counted of them, forty thousand and five hundred.\n'),
	(4509, 4, 26, 19, 'The sons of Judah: Er and Onan. Er and Onan died in the land of Canaan.\n'),
	(4510, 4, 26, 20, 'The sons of Judah after their families were: of Shelah, the family of the Shelanites; of Perez, the family of the Perezites; of Zerah, the family of the Zerahites.\n'),
	(4511, 4, 26, 21, 'The sons of Perez were: of Hezron, the family of the Hezronites; of Hamul, the family of the Hamulites.\n'),
	(4512, 4, 26, 22, 'These are the families of Judah according to those who were counted of them, seventy-six thousand five hundred.\n'),
	(4513, 4, 26, 23, 'The sons of Issachar after their families: of Tola, the family of the Tolaites; of Puvah, the family of the Punites;\n'),
	(4514, 4, 26, 24, 'of Jashub, the family of the Jashubites; of Shimron, the family of the Shimronites.\n'),
	(4515, 4, 26, 25, 'These are the families of Issachar according to those who were counted of them, sixty-four thousand three hundred.\n'),
	(4516, 4, 26, 26, 'The sons of Zebulun after their families: of Sered, the family of the Seredites; of Elon, the family of the Elonites; of Jahleel, the family of the Jahleelites.\n'),
	(4517, 4, 26, 27, 'These are the families of the Zebulunites according to those who were counted of them, sixty thousand five hundred.\n'),
	(4518, 4, 26, 28, 'The sons of Joseph after their families: Manasseh and Ephraim.\n'),
	(4519, 4, 26, 29, 'The sons of Manasseh: of Machir, the family of the Machirites; and Machir became the father of Gilead; of Gilead, the family of the Gileadites.\n'),
	(4520, 4, 26, 30, 'These are the sons of Gilead: of Iezer, the family of the Iezerites; of Helek, the family of the Helekites;\n'),
	(4521, 4, 26, 31, 'and Asriel, the family of the Asrielites; and Shechem, the family of the Shechemites;\n'),
	(4522, 4, 26, 32, 'and Shemida, the family of the Shemidaites; and Hepher, the family of the Hepherites.\n'),
	(4523, 4, 26, 33, 'Zelophehad the son of Hepher had no sons, but daughters: and the names of the daughters of Zelophehad were Mahlah, and Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah.\n'),
	(4524, 4, 26, 34, 'These are the families of Manasseh. Those who were counted of them were fifty-two thousand seven hundred.\n'),
	(4525, 4, 26, 35, 'These are the sons of Ephraim after their families: of Shuthelah, the family of the Shuthelahites; of Becher, the family of the Becherites; of Tahan, the family of the Tahanites.\n'),
	(4526, 4, 26, 36, 'These are the sons of Shuthelah: of Eran, the family of the Eranites.\n'),
	(4527, 4, 26, 37, 'These are the families of the sons of Ephraim according to those who were counted of them, thirty-two thousand five hundred. These are the sons of Joseph after their families.\n'),
	(4528, 4, 26, 38, 'The sons of Benjamin after their families: of Bela, the family of the Belaites; of Ashbel, the family of the Ashbelites; of Ahiram, the family of the Ahiramites;\n'),
	(4529, 4, 26, 39, 'of Shephupham, the family of the Shuphamites; of Hupham, the family of the Huphamites.\n'),
	(4530, 4, 26, 40, 'The sons of Bela were Ard and Naaman: the family of the Ardites; of Naaman, the family of the Naamites.\n'),
	(4531, 4, 26, 41, 'These are the sons of Benjamin after their families; and those who were counted of them were forty-five thousand six hundred.\n'),
	(4532, 4, 26, 42, 'These are the sons of Dan after their families: of Shuham, the family of the Shuhamites. These are the families of Dan after their families.\n'),
	(4533, 4, 26, 43, 'All the families of the Shuhamites, according to those who were counted of them, were sixty-four thousand four hundred.\n'),
	(4534, 4, 26, 44, 'The sons of Asher after their families: of Imnah, the family of the Imnites; of Ishvi, the family of the Ishvites; of Beriah, the family of the Berites.\n'),
	(4535, 4, 26, 45, 'Of the sons of Beriah: of Heber, the family of the Heberites; of Malchiel, the family of the Malchielites.\n'),
	(4536, 4, 26, 46, 'The name of the daughter of Asher was Serah.\n'),
	(4537, 4, 26, 47, 'These are the families of the sons of Asher according to those who were counted of them, fifty-three thousand and four hundred.\n'),
	(4538, 4, 26, 48, 'The sons of Naphtali after their families: of Jahzeel, the family of the Jahzeelites; of Guni, the family of the Gunites;\n'),
	(4539, 4, 26, 49, 'of Jezer, the family of the Jezerites; of Shillem, the family of the Shillemites.\n'),
	(4540, 4, 26, 50, 'These are the families of Naphtali according to their families; and those who were counted of them were forty-five thousand four hundred.\n'),
	(4541, 4, 26, 51, 'These are those who were counted of the children of Israel, six hundred one thousand seven hundred thirty.\n'),
	(4542, 4, 26, 52, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4543, 4, 26, 53, '“To these the land shall be divided for an inheritance according to the number of names.\n'),
	(4544, 4, 26, 54, 'To the more you shall give the more inheritance, and to the fewer you shall give the less inheritance. To everyone according to those who were counted of him shall his inheritance be given.\n'),
	(4545, 4, 26, 55, 'Notwithstanding, the land shall be divided by lot. According to the names of the tribes of their fathers they shall inherit.\n'),
	(4546, 4, 26, 56, 'According to the lot shall their inheritance be divided between the more and the fewer.”\n'),
	(4547, 4, 26, 57, 'These are those who were counted of the Levites after their families: of Gershon, the family of the Gershonites; of Kohath, the family of the Kohathites; of Merari, the family of the Merarites.\n'),
	(4548, 4, 26, 58, 'These are the families of Levi: the family of the Libnites, the family of the Hebronites, the family of the Mahlites, the family of the Mushites, the family of the Korahites. Kohath became the father of Amram.\n'),
	(4549, 4, 26, 59, 'The name of Amram’s wife was Jochebed, the daughter of Levi, who was born to Levi in Egypt. She bore to Amram Aaron and Moses, and Miriam their sister.\n'),
	(4550, 4, 26, 60, 'To Aaron were born Nadab and Abihu, Eleazar and Ithamar.\n'),
	(4551, 4, 26, 61, 'Nadab and Abihu died when they offered strange fire before Yahweh.\n'),
	(4552, 4, 26, 62, 'Those who were counted of them were twenty-three thousand, every male from a month old and upward; for they were not counted among the children of Israel, because there was no inheritance given them among the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4553, 4, 26, 63, 'These are those who were counted by Moses and Eleazar the priest, who counted the children of Israel in the plains of Moab by the Jordan at Jericho.\n'),
	(4554, 4, 26, 64, 'But among these there was not a man of them who were counted by Moses and Aaron the priest, who counted the children of Israel in the wilderness of Sinai.\n'),
	(4555, 4, 26, 65, 'For Yahweh had said of them, “They shall surely die in the wilderness.” There was not a man left of them, except Caleb the son of Jephunneh, and Joshua the son of Nun.\n'),
	(4556, 4, 27, 1, 'Then the daughters of Zelophehad, the son of Hepher, the son of Gilead, the son of Machir, the son of Manasseh, of the families of Manasseh the son of Joseph came near. These are the names of his daughters: Mahlah, Noah, and Hoglah, and Milcah, and Tirzah.\n'),
	(4557, 4, 27, 2, 'They stood before Moses, and before Eleazar the priest, and before the princes and all the congregation, at the door of the Tent of Meeting, saying,\n'),
	(4558, 4, 27, 3, '“Our father died in the wilderness. He was not among the company of those who gathered themselves together against Yahweh in the company of Korah, but he died in his own sin. He had no sons.\n'),
	(4559, 4, 27, 4, 'Why should the name of our father be taken away from among his family, because he had no son? Give to us a possession among the brothers of our father.”\n'),
	(4560, 4, 27, 5, 'Moses brought their cause before Yahweh.\n'),
	(4561, 4, 27, 6, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4562, 4, 27, 7, '“The daughters of Zelophehad speak right. You shall surely give them a possession of an inheritance among their father’s brothers. You shall cause the inheritance of their father to pass to them.\n'),
	(4563, 4, 27, 8, 'You shall speak to the children of Israel, saying, ‘If a man dies, and has no son, then you shall cause his inheritance to pass to his daughter.\n'),
	(4564, 4, 27, 9, 'If he has no daughter, then you shall give his inheritance to his brothers.\n'),
	(4565, 4, 27, 10, 'If he has no brothers, then you shall give his inheritance to his father’s brothers.\n'),
	(4566, 4, 27, 11, 'If his father has no brothers, then you shall give his inheritance to his kinsman who is next to him of his family, and he shall possess it. This shall be a statute and ordinance for the children of Israel, as Yahweh commanded Moses.’”\n'),
	(4567, 4, 27, 12, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Go up into this mountain of Abarim, and see the land which I have given to the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4568, 4, 27, 13, 'When you have seen it, you also shall be gathered to your people, as Aaron your brother was gathered;\n'),
	(4569, 4, 27, 14, 'because in the strife of the congregation, you rebelled against my word in the wilderness of Zin, to honor me as holy at the waters before their eyes.” (These are the waters of Meribah of Kadesh in the wilderness of Zin.)\n'),
	(4570, 4, 27, 15, 'Moses spoke to Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(4571, 4, 27, 16, '“Let Yahweh, the God of the spirits of all flesh, appoint a man over the congregation,\n'),
	(4572, 4, 27, 17, 'who may go out before them, and who may come in before them, and who may lead them out, and who may bring them in; that the congregation of Yahweh may not be as sheep which have no shepherd.”\n'),
	(4573, 4, 27, 18, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Take Joshua the son of Nun, a man in whom is the Spirit, and lay your hand on him.\n'),
	(4574, 4, 27, 19, 'Set him before Eleazar the priest, and before all the congregation; and commission him in their sight.\n'),
	(4575, 4, 27, 20, 'You shall give authority to him, that all the congregation of the children of Israel may obey.\n'),
	(4576, 4, 27, 21, 'He shall stand before Eleazar the priest, who shall inquire for him by the judgment of the Urim before Yahweh. At his word they shall go out, and at his word they shall come in, both he, and all the children of Israel with him, even all the congregation.”\n'),
	(4577, 4, 27, 22, 'Moses did as Yahweh commanded him. He took Joshua, and set him before Eleazar the priest, and before all the congregation.\n'),
	(4578, 4, 27, 23, 'He laid his hands on him, and commissioned him, as Yahweh spoke by Moses.\n'),
	(4579, 4, 28, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4580, 4, 28, 2, '“Command the children of Israel, and tell them, ‘See that you present my offering, my food for my offerings made by fire, of a pleasant aroma to me, in their due season.’\n'),
	(4581, 4, 28, 3, 'You shall tell them, ‘This is the offering made by fire which you shall offer to Yahweh: male lambs a year old without defect, two day by day, for a continual burnt offering.\n'),
	(4582, 4, 28, 4, 'You shall offer the one lamb in the morning, and you shall offer the other lamb at evening;\n'),
	(4583, 4, 28, 5, 'with one tenth of an ephah of fine flour for a meal offering, mixed with the fourth part of a hin of beaten oil.\n'),
	(4584, 4, 28, 6, 'It is a continual burnt offering, which was ordained in Mount Sinai for a pleasant aroma, an offering made by fire to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4585, 4, 28, 7, 'Its drink offering shall be the fourth part of a hin for the one lamb. You shall pour out a drink offering of strong drink to Yahweh in the holy place.\n'),
	(4586, 4, 28, 8, 'The other lamb you shall offer at evening. As the meal offering of the morning, and as its drink offering, you shall offer it, an offering made by fire, for a pleasant aroma to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4587, 4, 28, 9, '“‘On the Sabbath day, you shall offer two male lambs a year old without defect, and two tenths of an ephah of fine flour for a meal offering, mixed with oil, and its drink offering:\n'),
	(4588, 4, 28, 10, 'this is the burnt offering of every Sabbath, besides the continual burnt offering, and its drink offering.\n'),
	(4589, 4, 28, 11, '“‘In the beginnings of your months, you shall offer a burnt offering to Yahweh: two young bulls, and one ram, seven male lambs a year old without defect;\n'),
	(4590, 4, 28, 12, 'and three tenths of an ephah of fine flour for a meal offering, mixed with oil, for each bull; and two tenth parts of fine flour for a meal offering, mixed with oil, for the one ram;\n'),
	(4591, 4, 28, 13, 'and one tenth part of fine flour mixed with oil for a meal offering to every lamb; for a burnt offering of a pleasant aroma, an offering made by fire to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4592, 4, 28, 14, 'Their drink offerings shall be half a hin of wine for a bull, and the third part of a hin for the ram, and the fourth part of a hin for a lamb. This is the burnt offering of every month throughout the months of the year.\n'),
	(4593, 4, 28, 15, 'One male goat for a sin offering to Yahweh; it shall be offered besides the continual burnt offering, and its drink offering.\n'),
	(4594, 4, 28, 16, '“‘In the first month, on the fourteenth day of the month, is Yahweh’s Passover.\n'),
	(4595, 4, 28, 17, 'On the fifteenth day of this month shall be a feast. Unleavened bread shall be eaten for seven days.\n'),
	(4596, 4, 28, 18, 'In the first day shall be a holy convocation. You shall do no regular work;\n'),
	(4597, 4, 28, 19, 'but you shall offer an offering made by fire, a burnt offering to Yahweh: two young bulls, and one ram, and seven male lambs a year old; they shall be to you without defect;\n'),
	(4598, 4, 28, 20, 'and their meal offering, fine flour mixed with oil. You shall offer three tenths for a bull, and two tenths for the ram.\n'),
	(4599, 4, 28, 21, 'You shall offer one tenth for every lamb of the seven lambs;\n'),
	(4600, 4, 28, 22, 'and one male goat for a sin offering, to make atonement for you.\n'),
	(4601, 4, 28, 23, 'You shall offer these besides the burnt offering of the morning, which is for a continual burnt offering.\n'),
	(4602, 4, 28, 24, 'In this way you shall offer daily, for seven days, the food of the offering made by fire, of a pleasant aroma to Yahweh. It shall be offered in addition to the continual burnt offering, and its drink offering.\n'),
	(4603, 4, 28, 25, 'On the seventh day you shall have a holy convocation. You shall do no regular work.\n'),
	(4604, 4, 28, 26, '“‘Also in the day of the first fruits, when you offer a new meal offering to Yahweh in your feast of weeks, you shall have a holy convocation. You shall do no regular work;\n'),
	(4605, 4, 28, 27, 'but you shall offer a burnt offering for a pleasant aroma to Yahweh: two young bulls, one ram, seven male lambs a year old;\n'),
	(4606, 4, 28, 28, 'and their meal offering, fine flour mixed with oil, three tenths for each bull, two tenths for the one ram,\n'),
	(4607, 4, 28, 29, 'one tenth for every lamb of the seven lambs;\n'),
	(4608, 4, 28, 30, 'one male goat, to make atonement for you.\n'),
	(4609, 4, 28, 31, 'Besides the continual burnt offering, and its meal offering, you shall offer them and their drink offerings. See that they are without defect.\n'),
	(4610, 4, 29, 1, '“‘In the seventh month, on the first day of the month, you shall have a holy convocation; you shall do no regular work: it is a day of blowing of trumpets to you.\n'),
	(4611, 4, 29, 2, 'You shall offer a burnt offering for a pleasant aroma to Yahweh: one young bull, one ram, seven male lambs a year old without defect;\n'),
	(4612, 4, 29, 3, 'and their meal offering, fine flour mixed with oil, three tenths for the bull, two tenths for the ram,\n'),
	(4613, 4, 29, 4, 'and one tenth for every lamb of the seven lambs;\n'),
	(4614, 4, 29, 5, 'and one male goat for a sin offering, to make atonement for you;\n'),
	(4615, 4, 29, 6, 'besides the burnt offering of the new moon, and its meal offering, and the continual burnt offering and its meal offering, and their drink offerings, according to their ordinance, for a pleasant aroma, an offering made by fire to Yahweh.\n'),
	(4616, 4, 29, 7, '“‘On the tenth day of this seventh month you shall have a holy convocation. You shall afflict your souls. You shall do no kind of work;\n'),
	(4617, 4, 29, 8, 'but you shall offer a burnt offering to Yahweh for a pleasant aroma: one young bull, one ram, seven male lambs a year old; all without defect;\n'),
	(4618, 4, 29, 9, 'and their meal offering, fine flour mixed with oil, three tenths for the bull, two tenths for the one ram,\n'),
	(4619, 4, 29, 10, 'one tenth for every lamb of the seven lambs:\n'),
	(4620, 4, 29, 11, 'one male goat for a sin offering; besides the sin offering of atonement, and the continual burnt offering, and its meal offering, and their drink offerings.\n'),
	(4621, 4, 29, 12, '“‘On the fifteenth day of the seventh month you shall have a holy convocation. You shall do no regular work. You shall keep a feast to Yahweh seven days.\n'),
	(4622, 4, 29, 13, 'You shall offer a burnt offering, an offering made by fire, of a pleasant aroma to Yahweh: thirteen young bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs a year old; all without defect;\n'),
	(4623, 4, 29, 14, 'and their meal offering, fine flour mixed with oil, three tenths for every bull of the thirteen bulls, two tenths for each ram of the two rams,\n'),
	(4624, 4, 29, 15, 'and one tenth for every lamb of the fourteen lambs;\n'),
	(4625, 4, 29, 16, 'and one male goat for a sin offering, besides the continual burnt offering, its meal offering, and its drink offering.\n'),
	(4626, 4, 29, 17, '“‘On the second day you shall offer twelve young bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs a year old without defect;\n'),
	(4627, 4, 29, 18, 'and their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, according to their number, after the ordinance;\n'),
	(4628, 4, 29, 19, 'and one male goat for a sin offering; besides the continual burnt offering, with its meal offering and their drink offerings.\n'),
	(4629, 4, 29, 20, '“‘On the third day eleven bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs a year old without defect;\n'),
	(4630, 4, 29, 21, 'and their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, according to their number, after the ordinance;\n'),
	(4631, 4, 29, 22, 'and one male goat for a sin offering; besides the continual burnt offering, and its meal offering, and its drink offering.\n'),
	(4632, 4, 29, 23, '“‘On the fourth day ten bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs a year old without defect;\n'),
	(4633, 4, 29, 24, 'their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, according to their number, after the ordinance;\n'),
	(4634, 4, 29, 25, 'and one male goat for a sin offering; besides the continual burnt offering, its meal offering, and its drink offering.\n'),
	(4635, 4, 29, 26, '“‘On the fifth day nine bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs a year old without defect;\n'),
	(4636, 4, 29, 27, 'and their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, according to their number, after the ordinance;\n'),
	(4637, 4, 29, 28, 'and one male goat for a sin offering, besides the continual burnt offering, and its meal offering, and its drink offering.\n'),
	(4638, 4, 29, 29, '“‘On the sixth day eight bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs a year old without defect;\n'),
	(4639, 4, 29, 30, 'and their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, according to their number, after the ordinance;\n'),
	(4640, 4, 29, 31, 'and one male goat for a sin offering; besides the continual burnt offering, its meal offering, and the drink offerings of it.\n'),
	(4641, 4, 29, 32, '“‘On the seventh day seven bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs a year old without defect;\n'),
	(4642, 4, 29, 33, 'and their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, according to their number, after the ordinance;\n'),
	(4643, 4, 29, 34, 'and one male goat for a sin offering; besides the continual burnt offering, its meal offering, and its drink offering.\n'),
	(4644, 4, 29, 35, '“‘On the eighth day you shall have a solemn assembly: you shall do no regular work;\n'),
	(4645, 4, 29, 36, 'but you shall offer a burnt offering, an offering made by fire, of a pleasant aroma to Yahweh: one bull, one ram, seven male lambs a year old without defect;\n'),
	(4646, 4, 29, 37, 'their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bull, for the ram, and for the lambs, shall be according to their number, after the ordinance:\n'),
	(4647, 4, 29, 38, 'and one male goat for a sin offering, besides the continual burnt offering, with its meal offering, and its drink offering.\n'),
	(4648, 4, 29, 39, '“‘You shall offer these to Yahweh in your set feasts, besides your vows, and your freewill offerings, for your burnt offerings, and for your meal offerings, and for your drink offerings, and for your peace offerings.’”\n'),
	(4649, 4, 29, 40, 'Moses told the children of Israel according to all that Yahweh commanded Moses.\n'),
	(4650, 4, 30, 1, 'Moses spoke to the heads of the tribes of the children of Israel, saying, “This is the thing which Yahweh has commanded.\n'),
	(4651, 4, 30, 2, 'When a man vows a vow to Yahweh, or swears an oath to bind his soul with a bond, he shall not break his word. He shall do according to all that proceeds out of his mouth.\n'),
	(4652, 4, 30, 3, '“Also when a woman vows a vow to Yahweh, and binds herself by a bond, being in her father’s house, in her youth,\n'),
	(4653, 4, 30, 4, 'and her father hears her vow, and her bond with which she has bound her soul, and her father holds his peace at her; then all her vows shall stand, and every bond with which she has bound her soul shall stand.\n'),
	(4654, 4, 30, 5, 'But if her father forbids her in the day that he hears, none of her vows, or of her bonds with which she has bound her soul, shall stand. Yahweh will forgive her, because her father has forbidden her.\n'),
	(4655, 4, 30, 6, '“If she has a husband, while her vows are on her, or the rash utterance of her lips, with which she has bound her soul,\n'),
	(4656, 4, 30, 7, 'and her husband hears it, and hold his peace at her in the day that he hears it; then her vows shall stand, and her bonds with which she has bound her soul shall stand.\n'),
	(4657, 4, 30, 8, 'But if her husband forbids her in the day that he hears it, then he shall make void her vow which is on her, and the rash utterance of her lips, with which she has bound her soul. Yahweh will forgive her.\n'),
	(4658, 4, 30, 9, '“But the vow of a widow, or of her who is divorced, everything with which she has bound her soul, shall stand against her.\n'),
	(4659, 4, 30, 10, '“If she vowed in her husband’s house, or bound her soul by a bond with an oath,\n'),
	(4660, 4, 30, 11, 'and her husband heard it, and held his peace at her, and didn’t disallow her; then all her vows shall stand, and every bond with which she bound her soul shall stand.\n'),
	(4661, 4, 30, 12, 'But if her husband made them null and void in the day that he heard them, then whatever proceeded out of her lips concerning her vows, or concerning the bond of her soul, shall not stand. Her husband has made them void. Yahweh will forgive her.\n'),
	(4662, 4, 30, 13, 'Every vow, and every binding oath to afflict the soul, her husband may establish it, or her husband may make it void.\n'),
	(4663, 4, 30, 14, 'But if her husband altogether hold his peace at her from day to day, then he establishes all her vows, or all her bonds, which are on her. He has established them, because he held his peace at her in the day that he heard them.\n'),
	(4664, 4, 30, 15, 'But if he shall make them null and void after that he has heard them, then he shall bear her iniquity.”\n'),
	(4665, 4, 30, 16, 'These are the statutes which Yahweh commanded Moses, between a man and his wife, between a father and his daughter, being in her youth, in her father’s house.\n'),
	(4666, 4, 31, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4667, 4, 31, 2, '“Avenge the children of Israel for the Midianites. Afterward you shall be gathered to your people.”\n'),
	(4668, 4, 31, 3, 'Moses spoke to the people, saying, “Arm men from among you for the war, that they may go against Midian, to execute Yahweh’s vengeance on Midian.\n'),
	(4669, 4, 31, 4, 'Of every tribe one thousand, throughout all the tribes of Israel, you shall send to the war.”\n'),
	(4670, 4, 31, 5, 'So there were delivered, out of the thousands of Israel, a thousand of every tribe, twelve thousand armed for war.\n'),
	(4671, 4, 31, 6, 'Moses sent them, one thousand of every tribe, to the war, them and Phinehas the son of Eleazar the priest, to the war, with the vessels of the sanctuary and the trumpets for the alarm in his hand.\n'),
	(4672, 4, 31, 7, 'They fought against Midian, as Yahweh commanded Moses. They killed every male.\n'),
	(4673, 4, 31, 8, 'They killed the kings of Midian with the rest of their slain: Evi, Rekem, Zur, Hur, and Reba, the five kings of Midian. They also killed Balaam the son of Beor with the sword.\n'),
	(4674, 4, 31, 9, 'The children of Israel took the women of Midian captive with their little ones; and all their livestock, all their flocks, and all their goods, they took as plunder.\n'),
	(4675, 4, 31, 10, 'All their cities in the places in which they lived, and all their encampments, they burned with fire.\n'),
	(4676, 4, 31, 11, 'They took all the captives, and all the plunder, both of man and of animal.\n'),
	(4677, 4, 31, 12, 'They brought the captives, and the prey, and the plunder, to Moses, and to Eleazar the priest, and to the congregation of the children of Israel, to the camp at the plains of Moab, which are by the Jordan at Jericho.\n'),
	(4678, 4, 31, 13, 'Moses, and Eleazar the priest, and all the princes of the congregation, went out to meet them outside of the camp.\n'),
	(4679, 4, 31, 14, 'Moses was angry with the officers of the army, the captains of thousands and the captains of hundreds, who came from the service of the war.\n'),
	(4680, 4, 31, 15, 'Moses said to them, “Have you saved all the women alive?\n'),
	(4681, 4, 31, 16, 'Behold, these caused the children of Israel, through the counsel of Balaam, to commit trespass against Yahweh in the matter of Peor, and so the plague was among the congregation of Yahweh.\n'),
	(4682, 4, 31, 17, 'Now therefore kill every male among the little ones, and kill every woman who has known man by lying with him.\n'),
	(4683, 4, 31, 18, 'But all the girls, who have not known man by lying with him, keep alive for yourselves.\n'),
	(4684, 4, 31, 19, '“Encamp outside of the camp seven days. Whoever has killed any person, and whoever has touched any slain, purify yourselves on the third day and on the seventh day, you and your captives.\n'),
	(4685, 4, 31, 20, 'As to every garment, and all that is made of skin, and all work of goats’ hair, and all things made of wood, you shall purify yourselves.”\n'),
	(4686, 4, 31, 21, 'Eleazar the priest said to the men of war who went to the battle, “This is the statute of the law which Yahweh has commanded Moses:\n'),
	(4687, 4, 31, 22, 'however the gold, and the silver, the brass, the iron, the tin, and the lead,\n'),
	(4688, 4, 31, 23, 'everything that may withstand the fire, you shall make to go through the fire, and it shall be clean; nevertheless it shall be purified with the water for impurity. All that doesn’t withstand the fire you shall make to go through the water.\n'),
	(4689, 4, 31, 24, 'You shall wash your clothes on the seventh day, and you shall be clean. Afterward you shall come into the camp.”\n'),
	(4690, 4, 31, 25, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4691, 4, 31, 26, '“Count the plunder that was taken, both of man and of animal, you, and Eleazar the priest, and the heads of the fathers’ households of the congregation;\n'),
	(4692, 4, 31, 27, 'and divide the plunder into two parts: between the men skilled in war, who went out to battle, and all the congregation.\n'),
	(4693, 4, 31, 28, 'Levy a tribute to Yahweh of the men of war who went out to battle: one soul of five hundred; of the persons, of the cattle, of the donkeys, and of the flocks.\n'),
	(4694, 4, 31, 29, 'Take it from their half, and give it to Eleazar the priest, for Yahweh’s wave offering.\n'),
	(4695, 4, 31, 30, 'Of the children of Israel’s half, you shall take one drawn out of every fifty, of the persons, of the cattle, of the donkeys, and of the flocks, of all the livestock, and give them to the Levites, who perform the duty of Yahweh’s tabernacle.”\n'),
	(4696, 4, 31, 31, 'Moses and Eleazar the priest did as Yahweh commanded Moses.\n'),
	(4697, 4, 31, 32, 'Now the plunder, over and above the booty which the men of war took, was six hundred seventy-five thousand sheep,\n'),
	(4698, 4, 31, 33, 'and seventy-two thousand head of cattle,\n'),
	(4699, 4, 31, 34, 'and sixty-one thousand donkeys,\n'),
	(4700, 4, 31, 35, 'and thirty-two thousand persons in all, of the women who had not known man by lying with him.\n'),
	(4701, 4, 31, 36, 'The half, which was the portion of those who went out to war, was in number three hundred thirty-seven thousand five hundred sheep:\n'),
	(4702, 4, 31, 37, 'and Yahweh’s tribute of the sheep was six hundred seventy-five.\n'),
	(4703, 4, 31, 38, 'The cattle were thirty-six thousand; of which Yahweh’s tribute was seventy-two.\n'),
	(4704, 4, 31, 39, 'The donkeys were thirty thousand five hundred; of which Yahweh’s tribute was sixty-one.\n'),
	(4705, 4, 31, 40, 'The persons were sixteen thousand; of whom Yahweh’s tribute was thirty-two persons.\n'),
	(4706, 4, 31, 41, 'Moses gave the tribute, which was Yahweh’s wave offering, to Eleazar the priest, as Yahweh commanded Moses.\n'),
	(4707, 4, 31, 42, 'Of the children of Israel’s half, which Moses divided off from the men who fought\n'),
	(4708, 4, 31, 43, '(now the congregation’s half was three hundred thirty-seven thousand five hundred sheep,\n'),
	(4709, 4, 31, 44, 'and thirty-six thousand head of cattle,\n'),
	(4710, 4, 31, 45, 'and thirty thousand five hundred donkeys,\n'),
	(4711, 4, 31, 46, 'and sixteen thousand persons),\n'),
	(4712, 4, 31, 47, 'even of the children of Israel’s half, Moses took one drawn out of every fifty, both of man and of animal, and gave them to the Levites, who performed the duty of Yahweh’s tabernacle; as Yahweh commanded Moses.\n'),
	(4713, 4, 31, 48, 'The officers who were over the thousands of the army, the captains of thousands, and the captains of hundreds, came near to Moses.\n'),
	(4714, 4, 31, 49, 'They said to Moses, “Your servants have taken the sum of the men of war who are under our command, and there lacks not one man of us.\n'),
	(4715, 4, 31, 50, 'We have brought Yahweh’s offering, what every man has gotten, of jewels of gold, armlets, and bracelets, signet rings, earrings, and necklaces, to make atonement for our souls before Yahweh.”\n'),
	(4716, 4, 31, 51, 'Moses and Eleazar the priest took their gold, even all worked jewels.\n'),
	(4717, 4, 31, 52, 'All the gold of the wave offering that they offered up to Yahweh, of the captains of thousands, and of the captains of hundreds, was sixteen thousand seven hundred fifty shekels.\n'),
	(4718, 4, 31, 53, 'The men of war had taken booty, every man for himself.\n'),
	(4719, 4, 31, 54, 'Moses and Eleazar the priest took the gold of the captains of thousands and of hundreds, and brought it into the Tent of Meeting, for a memorial for the children of Israel before Yahweh.\n'),
	(4720, 4, 32, 1, 'Now the children of Reuben and the children of Gad had a very great multitude of livestock. When they saw the land of Jazer, and the land of Gilead, that behold, the place was a place for livestock;\n'),
	(4721, 4, 32, 2, 'the children of Gad and the children of Reuben came and spoke to Moses, and to Eleazar the priest, and to the princes of the congregation, saying,\n'),
	(4722, 4, 32, 3, '“Ataroth, Dibon, Jazer, Nimrah, Heshbon, Elealeh, Sebam, Nebo, and Beon,\n'),
	(4723, 4, 32, 4, 'the land which Yahweh struck before the congregation of Israel, is a land for livestock; and your servants have livestock.”\n'),
	(4724, 4, 32, 5, 'They said, “If we have found favor in your sight, let this land be given to your servants for a possession. Don’t bring us over the Jordan.”\n'),
	(4725, 4, 32, 6, 'Moses said to the children of Gad, and to the children of Reuben, “Shall your brothers go to the war, and shall you sit here?\n'),
	(4726, 4, 32, 7, 'Why do you discourage the heart of the children of Israel from going over into the land which Yahweh has given them?\n'),
	(4727, 4, 32, 8, 'Your fathers did so when I sent them from Kadesh Barnea to see the land.\n'),
	(4728, 4, 32, 9, 'For when they went up to the valley of Eshcol, and saw the land, they discouraged the heart of the children of Israel, that they should not go into the land which Yahweh had given them.\n'),
	(4729, 4, 32, 10, 'Yahweh’s anger burned in that day, and he swore, saying,\n'),
	(4730, 4, 32, 11, '‘Surely none of the men who came up out of Egypt, from twenty years old and upward, shall see the land which I swore to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob; because they have not wholly followed me,\n'),
	(4731, 4, 32, 12, 'except Caleb the son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite, and Joshua the son of Nun; because they have followed Yahweh completely.’\n'),
	(4732, 4, 32, 13, 'Yahweh’s anger burned against Israel, and he made them wander back and forth in the wilderness forty years, until all the generation, who had done evil in Yahweh’s sight, was consumed.\n'),
	(4733, 4, 32, 14, '“Behold, you have risen up in your fathers’ place, an increase of sinful men, to increase the fierce anger of Yahweh toward Israel.\n'),
	(4734, 4, 32, 15, 'For if you turn away from after him, he will yet again leave them in the wilderness; and you will destroy all these people.”\n'),
	(4735, 4, 32, 16, 'They came near to him, and said, “We will build sheepfolds here for our livestock, and cities for our little ones;\n'),
	(4736, 4, 32, 17, 'but we ourselves will be ready armed to go before the children of Israel, until we have brought them to their place. Our little ones shall dwell in the fortified cities because of the inhabitants of the land.\n'),
	(4737, 4, 32, 18, 'We will not return to our houses, until the children of Israel have each inherited their inheritance.\n'),
	(4738, 4, 32, 19, 'For we will not inherit with them on the other side of the Jordan, and forward; because our inheritance has come to us on this side of the Jordan eastward.”\n'),
	(4739, 4, 32, 20, 'Moses said to them, “If you will do this thing, if you will arm yourselves to go before Yahweh to the war,\n'),
	(4740, 4, 32, 21, 'and every armed man of you will pass over the Jordan before Yahweh, until he has driven out his enemies from before him,\n'),
	(4741, 4, 32, 22, 'and the land is subdued before Yahweh; then afterward you shall return, and be guiltless towards Yahweh, and towards Israel; and this land shall be to you for a possession before Yahweh.\n'),
	(4742, 4, 32, 23, '“But if you will not do so, behold, you have sinned against Yahweh; and be sure your sin will find you out.\n'),
	(4743, 4, 32, 24, 'Build cities for your little ones, and folds for your sheep; and do that which has proceeded out of your mouth.”\n'),
	(4744, 4, 32, 25, 'The children of Gad and the children of Reuben spoke to Moses, saying, “Your servants will do as my lord commands.\n'),
	(4745, 4, 32, 26, 'Our little ones, our wives, our flocks, and all our livestock, shall be there in the cities of Gilead;\n'),
	(4746, 4, 32, 27, 'but your servants will pass over, every man who is armed for war, before Yahweh to battle, as my lord says.”\n'),
	(4747, 4, 32, 28, 'So Moses commanded concerning them to Eleazar the priest, and to Joshua the son of Nun, and to the heads of the fathers’ households of the tribes of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4748, 4, 32, 29, 'Moses said to them, “If the children of Gad and the children of Reuben will pass with you over the Jordan, every man who is armed to battle, before Yahweh, and the land is subdued before you, then you shall give them the land of Gilead for a possession;\n'),
	(4749, 4, 32, 30, 'but if they will not pass over with you armed, they shall have possessions among you in the land of Canaan.”\n'),
	(4750, 4, 32, 31, 'The children of Gad and the children of Reuben answered, saying, “As Yahweh has said to your servants, so will we do.\n'),
	(4751, 4, 32, 32, 'We will pass over armed before Yahweh into the land of Canaan, and the possession of our inheritance shall remain with us beyond the Jordan.”\n'),
	(4752, 4, 32, 33, 'Moses gave to them, even to the children of Gad, and to the children of Reuben, and to the half-tribe of Manasseh the son of Joseph, the kingdom of Sihon king of the Amorites, and the kingdom of Og king of Bashan, the land, according to its cities and borders, even the cities of the surrounding land.\n'),
	(4753, 4, 32, 34, 'The children of Gad built Dibon, Ataroth, Aroer,\n'),
	(4754, 4, 32, 35, 'Atrothshophan, Jazer, Jogbehah,\n'),
	(4755, 4, 32, 36, 'Beth Nimrah, and Beth Haran: fortified cities, and folds for sheep.\n'),
	(4756, 4, 32, 37, 'The children of Reuben built Heshbon, Elealeh, Kiriathaim,\n'),
	(4757, 4, 32, 38, 'Nebo, and Baal Meon, (their names being changed), and Sibmah. They gave other names to the cities which they built.\n'),
	(4758, 4, 32, 39, 'The children of Machir the son of Manasseh went to Gilead, took it, and dispossessed the Amorites who were therein.\n'),
	(4759, 4, 32, 40, 'Moses gave Gilead to Machir the son of Manasseh; and he lived therein.\n'),
	(4760, 4, 32, 41, 'Jair the son of Manasseh went and took its villages, and called them Havvoth Jair.\n'),
	(4761, 4, 32, 42, 'Nobah went and took Kenath, and its villages, and called it Nobah, after his own name.\n'),
	(4762, 4, 33, 1, 'These are the journeys of the children of Israel, when they went out of the land of Egypt by their armies under the hand of Moses and Aaron.\n'),
	(4763, 4, 33, 2, 'Moses wrote their goings out according to their journeys by the commandment of Yahweh. These are their journeys according to their goings out.\n'),
	(4764, 4, 33, 3, 'They traveled from Rameses in the first month, on the fifteenth day of the first month; on the next day after the Passover, the children of Israel went out with a high hand in the sight of all the Egyptians,\n'),
	(4765, 4, 33, 4, 'while the Egyptians were burying all their firstborn, whom Yahweh had struck among them. Yahweh also executed judgments on their gods.\n'),
	(4766, 4, 33, 5, 'The children of Israel traveled from Rameses, and encamped in Succoth.\n'),
	(4767, 4, 33, 6, 'They traveled from Succoth, and encamped in Etham, which is in the edge of the wilderness.\n'),
	(4768, 4, 33, 7, 'They traveled from Etham, and turned back to Pihahiroth, which is before Baal Zephon: and they encamped before Migdol.\n'),
	(4769, 4, 33, 8, 'They traveled from before Hahiroth, and crossed through the middle of the sea into the wilderness. They went three days’ journey in the wilderness of Etham, and encamped in Marah.\n'),
	(4770, 4, 33, 9, 'They traveled from Marah, and came to Elim. In Elim, there were twelve springs of water, and seventy palm trees; and they encamped there.\n'),
	(4771, 4, 33, 10, 'They traveled from Elim, and encamped by the Red Sea.\n'),
	(4772, 4, 33, 11, 'They traveled from the Red Sea, and encamped in the wilderness of Sin.\n'),
	(4773, 4, 33, 12, 'They traveled from the wilderness of Sin, and encamped in Dophkah.\n'),
	(4774, 4, 33, 13, 'They traveled from Dophkah, and encamped in Alush.\n'),
	(4775, 4, 33, 14, 'They traveled from Alush, and encamped in Rephidim, where there was no water for the people to drink.\n'),
	(4776, 4, 33, 15, 'They traveled from Rephidim, and encamped in the wilderness of Sinai.\n'),
	(4777, 4, 33, 16, 'They traveled from the wilderness of Sinai, and encamped in Kibroth Hattaavah.\n'),
	(4778, 4, 33, 17, 'They traveled from Kibroth Hattaavah, and encamped in Hazeroth.\n'),
	(4779, 4, 33, 18, 'They traveled from Hazeroth, and encamped in Rithmah.\n'),
	(4780, 4, 33, 19, 'They traveled from Rithmah, and encamped in Rimmon Perez.\n'),
	(4781, 4, 33, 20, 'They traveled from Rimmon Perez, and encamped in Libnah.\n'),
	(4782, 4, 33, 21, 'They traveled from Libnah, and encamped in Rissah.\n'),
	(4783, 4, 33, 22, 'They traveled from Rissah, and encamped in Kehelathah.\n'),
	(4784, 4, 33, 23, 'They traveled from Kehelathah, and encamped in Mount Shepher.\n'),
	(4785, 4, 33, 24, 'They traveled from Mount Shepher, and encamped in Haradah.\n'),
	(4786, 4, 33, 25, 'They traveled from Haradah, and encamped in Makheloth.\n'),
	(4787, 4, 33, 26, 'They traveled from Makheloth, and encamped in Tahath.\n'),
	(4788, 4, 33, 27, 'They traveled from Tahath, and encamped in Terah.\n'),
	(4789, 4, 33, 28, 'They traveled from Terah, and encamped in Mithkah.\n'),
	(4790, 4, 33, 29, 'They traveled from Mithkah, and encamped in Hashmonah.\n'),
	(4791, 4, 33, 30, 'They traveled from Hashmonah, and encamped in Moseroth.\n'),
	(4792, 4, 33, 31, 'They traveled from Moseroth, and encamped in Bene Jaakan.\n'),
	(4793, 4, 33, 32, 'They traveled from Bene Jaakan, and encamped in Hor Haggidgad.\n'),
	(4794, 4, 33, 33, 'They traveled from Hor Haggidgad, and encamped in Jotbathah.\n'),
	(4795, 4, 33, 34, 'They traveled from Jotbathah, and encamped in Abronah.\n'),
	(4796, 4, 33, 35, 'They traveled from Abronah, and encamped in Ezion Geber.\n'),
	(4797, 4, 33, 36, 'They traveled from Ezion Geber, and encamped at Kadesh in the wilderness of Zin.\n'),
	(4798, 4, 33, 37, 'They traveled from Kadesh, and encamped in Mount Hor, in the edge of the land of Edom.\n'),
	(4799, 4, 33, 38, 'Aaron the priest went up into Mount Hor at the commandment of Yahweh, and died there, in the fortieth year after the children of Israel had come out of the land of Egypt, in the fifth month, on the first day of the month.\n'),
	(4800, 4, 33, 39, 'Aaron was one hundred twenty-three years old when he died in Mount Hor.\n'),
	(4801, 4, 33, 40, 'The Canaanite, the king of Arad, who lived in the South in the land of Canaan, heard of the coming of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4802, 4, 33, 41, 'They traveled from Mount Hor, and encamped in Zalmonah.\n'),
	(4803, 4, 33, 42, 'They traveled from Zalmonah, and encamped in Punon.\n'),
	(4804, 4, 33, 43, 'They traveled from Punon, and encamped in Oboth.\n'),
	(4805, 4, 33, 44, 'They traveled from Oboth, and encamped in Iye Abarim, in the border of Moab.\n'),
	(4806, 4, 33, 45, 'They traveled from Iyim, and encamped in Dibon Gad.\n'),
	(4807, 4, 33, 46, 'They traveled from Dibon Gad, and encamped in Almon Diblathaim.\n'),
	(4808, 4, 33, 47, 'They traveled from Almon Diblathaim, and encamped in the mountains of Abarim, before Nebo.\n'),
	(4809, 4, 33, 48, 'They traveled from the mountains of Abarim, and encamped in the plains of Moab by the Jordan at Jericho.\n'),
	(4810, 4, 33, 49, 'They encamped by the Jordan, from Beth Jeshimoth even to Abel Shittim in the plains of Moab.\n'),
	(4811, 4, 33, 50, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses in the plains of Moab by the Jordan at Jericho, saying,\n'),
	(4812, 4, 33, 51, 'Speak to the children of Israel, and tell them, “When you pass over the Jordan into the land of Canaan,\n'),
	(4813, 4, 33, 52, 'then you shall drive out all the inhabitants of the land from before you, destroy all their stone idols, destroy all their molten images, and demolish all their high places.\n'),
	(4814, 4, 33, 53, 'You shall take possession of the land, and dwell therein; for I have given the land to you to possess it.\n'),
	(4815, 4, 33, 54, 'You shall inherit the land by lot according to your families; to the more you shall give the more inheritance, and to the fewer you shall give the less inheritance. Wherever the lot falls to any man, that shall be his. You shall inherit according to the tribes of your fathers.\n'),
	(4816, 4, 33, 55, '“But if you do not drive out the inhabitants of the land from before you, then those you let remain of them will be as pricks in your eyes and as thorns in your sides, and they will harass you in the land in which you dwell.\n'),
	(4817, 4, 33, 56, 'It shall happen that as I thought to do to them, so will I do to you.”\n'),
	(4818, 4, 34, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4819, 4, 34, 2, '“Command the children of Israel, and tell them, ‘When you come into the land of Canaan (this is the land that shall fall to you for an inheritance, even the land of Canaan according to its borders),\n'),
	(4820, 4, 34, 3, 'then your south quarter shall be from the wilderness of Zin along by the side of Edom, and your south border shall be from the end of the Salt Sea eastward.\n'),
	(4821, 4, 34, 4, 'Your border shall turn about southward of the ascent of Akrabbim, and pass along to Zin; and it shall pass southward of Kadesh Barnea; and it shall go from there to Hazar Addar, and pass along to Azmon.\n'),
	(4822, 4, 34, 5, 'The border shall turn about from Azmon to the brook of Egypt, and it shall end at the sea.\n'),
	(4823, 4, 34, 6, '“‘For the western border, you shall have the great sea and its border. This shall be your west border.\n'),
	(4824, 4, 34, 7, '“‘This shall be your north border: from the great sea you shall mark out for yourselves Mount Hor.\n'),
	(4825, 4, 34, 8, 'From Mount Hor you shall mark out to the entrance of Hamath; and the border shall pass by Zedad.\n'),
	(4826, 4, 34, 9, 'Then the border shall go to Ziphron, and it shall end at Hazar Enan. This shall be your north border.\n'),
	(4827, 4, 34, 10, '“‘You shall mark out your east border from Hazar Enan to Shepham.\n'),
	(4828, 4, 34, 11, 'The border shall go down from Shepham to Riblah, on the east side of Ain. The border shall go down, and shall reach to the side of the sea of Chinnereth eastward.\n'),
	(4829, 4, 34, 12, 'The border shall go down to the Jordan, and end at the Salt Sea. This shall be your land according to its borders around it.’”\n'),
	(4830, 4, 34, 13, 'Moses commanded the children of Israel, saying, “This is the land which you shall inherit by lot, which Yahweh has commanded to give to the nine tribes, and to the half-tribe;\n'),
	(4831, 4, 34, 14, 'for the tribe of the children of Reuben according to their fathers’ houses, and the tribe of the children of Gad according to their fathers’ houses, have received, and the half-tribe of Manasseh have received, their inheritance.\n'),
	(4832, 4, 34, 15, 'The two tribes and the half-tribe have received their inheritance beyond the Jordan at Jericho eastward, toward the sunrise.”\n'),
	(4833, 4, 34, 16, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4834, 4, 34, 17, '“These are the names of the men who shall divide the land to you for inheritance: Eleazar the priest, and Joshua the son of Nun.\n'),
	(4835, 4, 34, 18, 'You shall take one prince of every tribe, to divide the land for inheritance.\n'),
	(4836, 4, 34, 19, 'These are the names of the men: Of the tribe of Judah, Caleb the son of Jephunneh.\n'),
	(4837, 4, 34, 20, 'Of the tribe of the children of Simeon, Shemuel the son of Ammihud.\n'),
	(4838, 4, 34, 21, 'Of the tribe of Benjamin, Elidad the son of Chislon.\n'),
	(4839, 4, 34, 22, 'Of the tribe of the children of Dan a prince, Bukki the son of Jogli.\n'),
	(4840, 4, 34, 23, 'Of the children of Joseph: of the tribe of the children of Manasseh a prince, Hanniel the son of Ephod.\n'),
	(4841, 4, 34, 24, 'Of the tribe of the children of Ephraim a prince, Kemuel the son of Shiphtan.\n'),
	(4842, 4, 34, 25, 'Of the tribe of the children of Zebulun a prince, Elizaphan the son of Parnach.\n'),
	(4843, 4, 34, 26, 'Of the tribe of the children of Issachar a prince, Paltiel the son of Azzan.\n'),
	(4844, 4, 34, 27, 'Of the tribe of the children of Asher a prince, Ahihud the son of Shelomi.\n'),
	(4845, 4, 34, 28, 'Of the tribe of the children of Naphtali a prince, Pedahel the son of Ammihud.”\n'),
	(4846, 4, 34, 29, 'These are they whom Yahweh commanded to divide the inheritance to the children of Israel in the land of Canaan.\n'),
	(4847, 4, 35, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses in the plains of Moab by the Jordan at Jericho, saying,\n'),
	(4848, 4, 35, 2, '“Command the children of Israel to give to the Levites of the inheritance of their possession cities to dwell in. You shall give suburbs for the cities around them to the Levites.\n'),
	(4849, 4, 35, 3, 'They shall have the cities to dwell in. Their suburbs shall be for their livestock, and for their possessions, and for all their animals.\n'),
	(4850, 4, 35, 4, '“The suburbs of the cities, which you shall give to the Levites, shall be from the wall of the city and outward one thousand cubits around it.\n'),
	(4851, 4, 35, 5, 'You shall measure outside of the city for the east side two thousand cubits, and for the south side two thousand cubits, and for the west side two thousand cubits, and for the north side two thousand cubits, the city being in the middle. This shall be the suburbs of their cities.\n'),
	(4852, 4, 35, 6, '“The cities which you shall give to the Levites, they shall be the six cities of refuge, which you shall give for the man slayer to flee to. Besides them you shall give forty-two cities.\n'),
	(4853, 4, 35, 7, 'All the cities which you shall give to the Levites shall be forty-eight cities together with their suburbs.\n'),
	(4854, 4, 35, 8, 'Concerning the cities which you shall give of the possession of the children of Israel, from the many you shall take many; and from the few you shall take few. Everyone according to his inheritance which he inherits shall give some of his cities to the Levites.”\n'),
	(4855, 4, 35, 9, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses, saying,\n'),
	(4856, 4, 35, 10, '“Speak to the children of Israel, and tell them, ‘When you pass over the Jordan into the land of Canaan,\n'),
	(4857, 4, 35, 11, 'then you shall appoint for yourselves cities to be cities of refuge for you, that the man slayer who kills any person unwittingly may flee there.\n'),
	(4858, 4, 35, 12, 'The cities shall be to you for refuge from the avenger, that the man slayer not die, until he stands before the congregation for judgment.\n'),
	(4859, 4, 35, 13, 'The cities which you shall give shall be for you six cities of refuge.\n'),
	(4860, 4, 35, 14, 'You shall give three cities beyond the Jordan, and you shall give three cities in the land of Canaan. They shall be cities of refuge.\n'),
	(4861, 4, 35, 15, 'For the children of Israel, and for the stranger and for the foreigner living among them, shall these six cities be for refuge; that everyone who kills any person unwittingly may flee there.\n'),
	(4862, 4, 35, 16, '“‘But if he struck him with an instrument of iron, so that he died, he is a murderer. The murderer shall surely be put to death.\n'),
	(4863, 4, 35, 17, 'If he struck him with a stone in the hand, by which a man may die, and he died, he is a murderer. The murderer shall surely be put to death.\n'),
	(4864, 4, 35, 18, 'Or if he struck him with a weapon of wood in the hand, by which a man may die, and he died, he is a murderer. The murderer shall surely be put to death.\n'),
	(4865, 4, 35, 19, 'The avenger of blood shall himself put the murderer to death. When he meets him, he shall put him to death.\n'),
	(4866, 4, 35, 20, 'If he shoved him out of hatred, or hurled at him, lying in wait, so that he died,\n'),
	(4867, 4, 35, 21, 'or in hostility struck him with his hand, so that he died, he who struck him shall surely be put to death. He is a murderer. The avenger of blood shall put the murderer to death, when he meets him.\n'),
	(4868, 4, 35, 22, '“‘But if he shoved him suddenly without hostility, or hurled on him anything without lying in wait,\n'),
	(4869, 4, 35, 23, 'or with any stone, by which a man may die, not seeing him, and cast it on him, so that he died, and he was not his enemy, neither sought his harm;\n'),
	(4870, 4, 35, 24, 'then the congregation shall judge between the striker and the avenger of blood according to these ordinances.\n'),
	(4871, 4, 35, 25, 'The congregation shall deliver the man slayer out of the hand of the avenger of blood, and the congregation shall restore him to his city of refuge, where he had fled. He shall dwell therein until the death of the high priest, who was anointed with the holy oil.\n'),
	(4872, 4, 35, 26, '“‘But if the man slayer shall at any time go beyond the border of his city of refuge, where he flees,\n'),
	(4873, 4, 35, 27, 'and the avenger of blood finds him outside of the border of his city of refuge, and the avenger of blood kills the man slayer; he shall not be guilty of blood,\n'),
	(4874, 4, 35, 28, 'because he should have remained in his city of refuge until the death of the high priest. But after the death of the high priest, the man slayer shall return into the land of his possession.\n'),
	(4875, 4, 35, 29, '“‘These things shall be for a statute and ordinance to you throughout your generations in all your dwellings.\n'),
	(4876, 4, 35, 30, '“‘Whoever kills any person, the murderer shall be slain at the mouth of witnesses; but one witness shall not testify against any person that he die.\n'),
	(4877, 4, 35, 31, '“‘Moreover you shall take no ransom for the life of a murderer who is guilty of death; but he shall surely be put to death.\n'),
	(4878, 4, 35, 32, '“‘You shall take no ransom for him who is fled to his city of refuge, that he may come again to dwell in the land, until the death of the priest.\n'),
	(4879, 4, 35, 33, '“‘So you shall not pollute the land in which you are; for blood pollutes the land. No atonement can be made for the land for the blood that is shed in it, but by the blood of him who shed it.\n'),
	(4880, 4, 35, 34, 'You shall not defile the land which you inhabit, in the middle of which I dwell; for I, Yahweh, dwell in the middle of the children of Israel.’”\n'),
	(4881, 4, 36, 1, 'The heads of the fathers’ households of the family of the children of Gilead, the son of Machir, the son of Manasseh, of the families of the sons of Joseph, came near, and spoke before Moses, and before the princes, the heads of the fathers’ households of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(4882, 4, 36, 2, 'They said, “Yahweh commanded my lord to give the land for inheritance by lot to the children of Israel. My lord was commanded by Yahweh to give the inheritance of Zelophehad our brother to his daughters.\n'),
	(4883, 4, 36, 3, 'If they are married to any of the sons of the other tribes of the children of Israel, then will their inheritance be taken away from the inheritance of our fathers, and will be added to the inheritance of the tribe to which they shall belong. So will it be taken away from the lot of our inheritance.\n'),
	(4884, 4, 36, 4, 'When the jubilee of the children of Israel shall be, then will their inheritance be added to the inheritance of the tribe to which they shall belong. So their inheritance will be taken away from the inheritance of the tribe of our fathers.”\n'),
	(4885, 4, 36, 5, 'Moses commanded the children of Israel according to Yahweh’s word, saying, “The tribe of the sons of Joseph speaks right.\n'),
	(4886, 4, 36, 6, 'This is the thing which Yahweh does command concerning the daughters of Zelophehad, saying, ‘Let them be married to whom they think best; only they shall marry into the family of the tribe of their father.\n'),
	(4887, 4, 36, 7, 'So shall no inheritance of the children of Israel move from tribe to tribe; for the children of Israel shall all keep the inheritance of the tribe of his fathers.\n'),
	(4888, 4, 36, 8, 'Every daughter who possesses an inheritance in any tribe of the children of Israel shall be wife to one of the family of the tribe of her father, that the children of Israel may each possess the inheritance of his fathers.\n'),
	(4889, 4, 36, 9, 'So shall no inheritance move from one tribe to another tribe; for the tribes of the children of Israel shall each keep his own inheritance.’”\n'),
	(4890, 4, 36, 10, 'The daughters of Zelophehad did as Yahweh commanded Moses:\n'),
	(4891, 4, 36, 11, 'for Mahlah, Tirzah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Noah, the daughters of Zelophehad, were married to their father’s brothers’ sons.\n'),
	(4892, 4, 36, 12, 'They were married into the families of the sons of Manasseh the son of Joseph. Their inheritance remained in the tribe of the family of their father.\n'),
	(4893, 4, 36, 13, 'These are the commandments and the ordinances which Yahweh commanded by Moses to the children of Israel in the plains of Moab by the Jordan at Jericho.\n'),
	(4894, 5, 1, 1, 'These are the words which Moses spoke to all Israel beyond the Jordan in the wilderness, in the Arabah over against Suf, between Paran, Tophel, Laban, Hazeroth, and Dizahab.\n'),
	(4895, 5, 1, 2, 'It is eleven days’ journey from Horeb by the way of Mount Seir to Kadesh Barnea.\n'),
	(4896, 5, 1, 3, 'In the fortieth year, in the eleventh month, on the first day of the month, Moses spoke to the children of Israel, according to all that Yahweh had given him in commandment to them;\n'),
	(4897, 5, 1, 4, 'after he had struck Sihon the king of the Amorites, who lived in Heshbon, and Og the king of Bashan, who lived in Ashtaroth, at Edrei.\n'),
	(4898, 5, 1, 5, 'Beyond the Jordan, in the land of Moab, Moses began to declare this law, saying,\n'),
	(4899, 5, 1, 6, '“Yahweh our God spoke to us in Horeb, saying, ‘You have lived long enough at this mountain.\n'),
	(4900, 5, 1, 7, 'Turn, and take your journey, and go to the hill country of the Amorites, and to all the places near there, in the Arabah, in the hill country, in the lowland, in the South, by the seashore, in the land of the Canaanites, and in Lebanon, as far as the great river, the river Euphrates.\n'),
	(4901, 5, 1, 8, 'Behold, I have set the land before you. Go in and possess the land which Yahweh swore to your fathers, to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob, to give to them and to their offspring after them.’”\n'),
	(4902, 5, 1, 9, 'I spoke to you at that time, saying, “I am not able to bear you myself alone.\n'),
	(4903, 5, 1, 10, 'Yahweh your God has multiplied you, and behold, you are today as the stars of the sky for multitude.\n'),
	(4904, 5, 1, 11, 'Yahweh, the God of your fathers, make you a thousand times as many as you are, and bless you, as he has promised you!\n'),
	(4905, 5, 1, 12, 'How can I myself alone bear your problems, your burdens, and your strife?\n'),
	(4906, 5, 1, 13, 'Take wise men of understanding and well known according to your tribes, and I will make them heads over you.”\n'),
	(4907, 5, 1, 14, 'You answered me, and said, “The thing which you have spoken is good to do.”\n'),
	(4908, 5, 1, 15, 'So I took the heads of your tribes, wise men, and known, and made them heads over you, captains of thousands, and captains of hundreds, and captains of fifties, and captains of tens, and officers, according to your tribes.\n'),
	(4909, 5, 1, 16, 'I commanded your judges at that time, saying, “Hear cases between your brothers, and judge righteously between a man and his brother, and the foreigner who is living with him.\n'),
	(4910, 5, 1, 17, 'You shall not show partiality in judgment; you shall hear the small and the great alike. You shall not be afraid of the face of man, for the judgment is God’s. The case that is too hard for you, you shall bring to me, and I will hear it.”\n'),
	(4911, 5, 1, 18, 'I commanded you at that time all the things which you should do.\n'),
	(4912, 5, 1, 19, 'We traveled from Horeb, and went through all that great and terrible wilderness which you saw, by the way to the hill country of the Amorites, as Yahweh our God commanded us; and we came to Kadesh Barnea.\n'),
	(4913, 5, 1, 20, 'I said to you, “You have come to the hill country of the Amorites, which Yahweh our God gives to us.\n'),
	(4914, 5, 1, 21, 'Behold, Yahweh your God has set the land before you. Go up, take possession, as Yahweh, the God of your fathers, has spoken to you. Don’t be afraid, neither be dismayed.”\n'),
	(4915, 5, 1, 22, 'You came near to me, everyone of you, and said, “Let us send men before us, that they may search the land for us, and bring us word again of the way by which we must go up, and the cities to which we shall come.”\n'),
	(4916, 5, 1, 23, 'The thing pleased me well. I took twelve men of you, one man for every tribe.\n'),
	(4917, 5, 1, 24, 'They turned and went up into the hill country, and came to the valley of Eshcol, and spied it out.\n'),
	(4918, 5, 1, 25, 'They took some of the fruit of the land in their hands, and brought it down to us, and brought us word again, and said, “It is a good land which Yahweh our God gives to us.”\n'),
	(4919, 5, 1, 26, 'Yet you wouldn’t go up, but rebelled against the commandment of Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(4920, 5, 1, 27, 'You murmured in your tents, and said, “Because Yahweh hated us, he has brought us out of the land of Egypt, to deliver us into the hand of the Amorites, to destroy us.\n'),
	(4921, 5, 1, 28, 'Where are we going up? Our brothers have made our heart melt, saying, ‘The people are greater and taller than we. The cities are great and fortified up to the sky. Moreover we have seen the sons of the Anakim there!’”\n'),
	(4922, 5, 1, 29, 'Then I said to you, “Don’t dread, neither be afraid of them.\n'),
	(4923, 5, 1, 30, 'Yahweh your God who goes before you, he will fight for you, according to all that he did for you in Egypt before your eyes,\n'),
	(4924, 5, 1, 31, 'and in the wilderness, where you have seen how that Yahweh your God bore you, as a man does bear his son, in all the way that you went, until you came to this place.”\n'),
	(4925, 5, 1, 32, 'Yet in this thing you didn’t believe Yahweh your God,\n'),
	(4926, 5, 1, 33, 'who went before you on the way, to seek out a place for you to pitch your tents in, in fire by night, to show you by what way you should go, and in the cloud by day.\n'),
	(4927, 5, 1, 34, 'Yahweh heard the voice of your words, and was angry, and swore, saying,\n'),
	(4928, 5, 1, 35, '“Surely not one of these men of this evil generation shall see the good land, which I swore to give to your fathers,\n'),
	(4929, 5, 1, 36, 'except Caleb the son of Jephunneh. He shall see it. I will give the land that he has trodden on to him, and to his children, because he has wholly followed Yahweh.”\n'),
	(4930, 5, 1, 37, 'Also Yahweh was angry with me for your sakes, saying, “You also shall not go in there.\n'),
	(4931, 5, 1, 38, 'Joshua the son of Nun, who stands before you, shall go in there. Encourage him, for he shall cause Israel to inherit it.\n'),
	(4932, 5, 1, 39, 'Moreover your little ones, whom you said would be captured or killed, and your children, who today have no knowledge of good or evil, shall go in there. I will give it to them, and they shall possess it.\n'),
	(4933, 5, 1, 40, 'But as for you, turn, and take your journey into the wilderness by the way to the Red Sea.”\n'),
	(4934, 5, 1, 41, 'Then you answered and said to me, “We have sinned against Yahweh, we will go up and fight, according to all that Yahweh our God commanded us.” Every man of you put on his weapons of war, and presumed to go up into the hill country.\n'),
	(4935, 5, 1, 42, 'Yahweh said to me, “Tell them, ‘Don’t go up and don’t fight; for I am not among you; lest you be struck before your enemies.’”\n'),
	(4936, 5, 1, 43, 'So I spoke to you, and you didn’t listen; but you rebelled against the commandment of Yahweh, and were presumptuous, and went up into the hill country.\n'),
	(4937, 5, 1, 44, 'The Amorites, who lived in that hill country, came out against you, and chased you, as bees do, and beat you down in Seir, even to Hormah.\n'),
	(4938, 5, 1, 45, 'You returned and wept before Yahweh; but Yahweh didn’t listen to your voice, nor turn his ear to you.\n'),
	(4939, 5, 1, 46, 'So you stayed in Kadesh many days, according to the days that you remained.\n'),
	(4940, 5, 2, 1, 'Then we turned, and took our journey into the wilderness by the way to the Red Sea, as Yahweh spoke to me; and we encircled Mount Seir many days.\n'),
	(4941, 5, 2, 2, 'Yahweh spoke to me, saying,\n'),
	(4942, 5, 2, 3, '“You have encircled this mountain long enough. Turn northward.\n'),
	(4943, 5, 2, 4, 'Command the people, saying, ‘You are to pass through the border of your brothers the children of Esau, who dwell in Seir; and they will be afraid of you. Therefore be careful.\n'),
	(4944, 5, 2, 5, 'Don’t contend with them; for I will not give you any of their land, no, not so much as for the sole of the foot to tread on; because I have given Mount Seir to Esau for a possession.\n'),
	(4945, 5, 2, 6, 'You shall purchase food from them for money, that you may eat. You shall also buy water from them for money, that you may drink.’”\n'),
	(4946, 5, 2, 7, 'For Yahweh your God has blessed you in all the work of your hand. He has known your walking through this great wilderness. These forty years, Yahweh your God has been with you. You have lacked nothing.\n'),
	(4947, 5, 2, 8, 'So we passed by from our brothers the children of Esau, who dwell in Seir, from the way of the Arabah from Elath and from Ezion Geber. We turned and passed by the way of the wilderness of Moab.\n'),
	(4948, 5, 2, 9, 'Yahweh said to me, “Don’t bother Moab, neither contend with them in battle; for I will not give you any of his land for a possession; because I have given Ar to the children of Lot for a possession.”\n'),
	(4949, 5, 2, 10, '(The Emim lived therein before, a people great, and many, and tall, as the Anakim.\n'),
	(4950, 5, 2, 11, 'These also are considered to be Rephaim, as the Anakim; but the Moabites call them Emim.\n'),
	(4951, 5, 2, 12, 'The Horites also lived in Seir before, but the children of Esau succeeded them. They destroyed them from before them, and lived in their place; as Israel did to the land of his possession, which Yahweh gave to them.)\n'),
	(4952, 5, 2, 13, '“Now rise up, and cross over the brook Zered.” We went over the brook Zered.\n'),
	(4953, 5, 2, 14, 'The days in which we came from Kadesh Barnea, until we had come over the brook Zered, were thirty-eight years; until all the generation of the men of war were consumed from the middle of the camp, as Yahweh swore to them.\n'),
	(4954, 5, 2, 15, 'Moreover Yahweh’s hand was against them, to destroy them from the middle of the camp, until they were consumed.\n'),
	(4955, 5, 2, 16, 'So, when all the men of war were consumed and dead from among the people,\n'),
	(4956, 5, 2, 17, 'Yahweh spoke to me, saying,\n'),
	(4957, 5, 2, 18, '“You are to pass over Ar, the border of Moab, today.\n'),
	(4958, 5, 2, 19, 'When you come near the border of the children of Ammon, don’t bother them, nor contend with them; for I will not give you any of the land of the children of Ammon for a possession; because I have given it to the children of Lot for a possession.”\n'),
	(4959, 5, 2, 20, '(That also is considered a land of Rephaim: Rephaim lived there before; but the Ammonites call them Zamzummim,\n'),
	(4960, 5, 2, 21, 'a great people, many, and tall, as the Anakim; but Yahweh destroyed them before them; and they succeeded them, and lived in their place;\n'),
	(4961, 5, 2, 22, 'as he did for the children of Esau, who dwell in Seir, when he destroyed the Horites from before them; and they succeeded them, and lived in their place even to this day:\n'),
	(4962, 5, 2, 23, 'and the Avvim, who lived in villages as far as Gaza, the Caphtorim, who came out of Caphtor, destroyed them, and lived in their place.)\n'),
	(4963, 5, 2, 24, '“Rise up, take your journey, and pass over the valley of the Arnon: behold, I have given into your hand Sihon the Amorite, king of Heshbon, and his land; begin to possess it, and contend with him in battle.\n'),
	(4964, 5, 2, 25, 'Today I will begin to put the dread of you and the fear of you on the peoples who are under the whole sky, who shall hear the report of you, and shall tremble, and be in anguish because of you.”\n'),
	(4965, 5, 2, 26, 'I sent messengers out of the wilderness of Kedemoth to Sihon king of Heshbon with words of peace, saying,\n'),
	(4966, 5, 2, 27, '“Let me pass through your land. I will go along by the highway, I will turn neither to the right hand nor to the left.\n'),
	(4967, 5, 2, 28, 'You shall sell me food for money, that I may eat; and give me water for money, that I may drink. Just let me pass through on my feet,\n'),
	(4968, 5, 2, 29, 'as the children of Esau who dwell in Seir, and the Moabites who dwell in Ar, did to me; until I pass over the Jordan into the land which Yahweh our God gives us.”\n'),
	(4969, 5, 2, 30, 'But Sihon king of Heshbon would not let us pass by him; for Yahweh your God hardened his spirit, and made his heart obstinate, that he might deliver him into your hand, as it is today.\n'),
	(4970, 5, 2, 31, 'Yahweh said to me, “Behold, I have begun to deliver up Sihon and his land before you. Begin to possess, that you may inherit his land.”\n'),
	(4971, 5, 2, 32, 'Then Sihon came out against us, he and all his people, to battle at Jahaz.\n'),
	(4972, 5, 2, 33, 'Yahweh our God delivered him up before us; and we struck him, his sons, and all his people.\n'),
	(4973, 5, 2, 34, 'We took all his cities at that time, and utterly destroyed every inhabited city, with the women and the little ones. We left no one remaining.\n'),
	(4974, 5, 2, 35, 'Only the livestock we took for plunder for ourselves, with the plunder of the cities which we had taken.\n'),
	(4975, 5, 2, 36, 'From Aroer, which is on the edge of the valley of the Arnon, and the city that is in the valley, even to Gilead, there was not a city too high for us. Yahweh our God delivered up all before us.\n'),
	(4976, 5, 2, 37, 'Only to the land of the children of Ammon you didn’t come near; all the banks of the river Jabbok, and the cities of the hill country, and wherever Yahweh our God forbade us.\n'),
	(4977, 5, 3, 1, 'Then we turned, and went up the way to Bashan. Og the king of Bashan came out against us, he and all his people, to battle at Edrei.\n'),
	(4978, 5, 3, 2, 'Yahweh said to me, “Don’t fear him; for I have delivered him, with all his people, and his land, into your hand. You shall do to him as you did to Sihon king of the Amorites, who lived at Heshbon.”\n'),
	(4979, 5, 3, 3, 'So Yahweh our God delivered into our hand Og also, the king of Bashan, and all his people. We struck him until no one was left to him remaining.\n'),
	(4980, 5, 3, 4, 'We took all his cities at that time. There was not a city which we didn’t take from them; sixty cities, all the region of Argob, the kingdom of Og in Bashan.\n'),
	(4981, 5, 3, 5, 'All these were cities fortified with high walls, gates, and bars; besides a great many villages without walls.\n'),
	(4982, 5, 3, 6, 'We utterly destroyed them, as we did to Sihon king of Heshbon, utterly destroying every inhabited city, with the women and the little ones.\n'),
	(4983, 5, 3, 7, 'But all the livestock, and the plunder of the cities, we took for plunder for ourselves.\n'),
	(4984, 5, 3, 8, 'We took the land at that time out of the hand of the two kings of the Amorites who were beyond the Jordan, from the valley of the Arnon to Mount Hermon.\n'),
	(4985, 5, 3, 9, '(The Sidonians call Hermon Sirion, and the Amorites call it Senir.)\n'),
	(4986, 5, 3, 10, 'We took all the cities of the plain, and all Gilead, and all Bashan, to Salecah and Edrei, cities of the kingdom of Og in Bashan.\n'),
	(4987, 5, 3, 11, '(For only Og king of Bashan remained of the remnant of the Rephaim. Behold, his bedstead was a bedstead of iron. Isn’t it in Rabbah of the children of Ammon? Nine cubits was its length, and four cubits its width, after the cubit of a man.)\n'),
	(4988, 5, 3, 12, 'This land we took in possession at that time: from Aroer, which is by the valley of the Arnon, and half the hill country of Gilead, and its cities, I gave to the Reubenites and to the Gadites:\n'),
	(4989, 5, 3, 13, 'and the rest of Gilead, and all Bashan, the kingdom of Og, I gave to the half-tribe of Manasseh; all the region of Argob, even all Bashan. (The same is called the land of Rephaim.\n'),
	(4990, 5, 3, 14, 'Jair the son of Manasseh took all the region of Argob, to the border of the Geshurites and the Maacathites, and called them, even Bashan, after his own name, Havvoth Jair, to this day.)\n'),
	(4991, 5, 3, 15, 'I gave Gilead to Machir.\n'),
	(4992, 5, 3, 16, 'To the Reubenites and to the Gadites I gave from Gilead even to the valley of the Arnon, the middle of the valley, and its border, even to the river Jabbok, which is the border of the children of Ammon;\n'),
	(4993, 5, 3, 17, 'the Arabah also, and the Jordan and its border, from Chinnereth even to the sea of the Arabah, the Salt Sea, under the slopes of Pisgah eastward.\n'),
	(4994, 5, 3, 18, 'I commanded you at that time, saying, “Yahweh your God has given you this land to possess it. You shall pass over armed before your brothers the children of Israel, all the men of valor.\n'),
	(4995, 5, 3, 19, 'But your wives, and your little ones, and your livestock, (I know that you have much livestock), shall live in your cities which I have given you,\n'),
	(4996, 5, 3, 20, 'until Yahweh gives rest to your brothers, as to you, and they also possess the land which Yahweh your God gives them beyond the Jordan. Then you shall each return to his own possession, which I have given you.”\n'),
	(4997, 5, 3, 21, 'I commanded Joshua at that time, saying, “Your eyes have seen all that Yahweh your God has done to these two kings. So shall Yahweh do to all the kingdoms where you go over.\n'),
	(4998, 5, 3, 22, 'You shall not fear them; for Yahweh your God himself fights for you.”\n'),
	(4999, 5, 3, 23, 'I begged Yahweh at that time, saying,\n'),
	(5000, 5, 3, 24, '“Lord Yahweh, you have begun to show your servant your greatness, and your strong hand. For what god is there in heaven or in earth that can do works like yours, and mighty acts like yours?\n'),
	(5001, 5, 3, 25, 'Please let me go over and see the good land that is beyond the Jordan, that fine mountain, and Lebanon.”\n'),
	(5002, 5, 3, 26, 'But Yahweh was angry with me for your sakes, and didn’t listen to me. Yahweh said to me, “Let this satisfy you. Speak no more to me of this matter.\n'),
	(5003, 5, 3, 27, 'Go up to the top of Pisgah, and lift up your eyes westward, and northward, and southward, and eastward, and see with your eyes; for you shall not go over this Jordan.\n'),
	(5004, 5, 3, 28, 'But commission Joshua, and encourage him, and strengthen him; for he shall go over before this people, and he shall cause them to inherit the land which you shall see.”\n'),
	(5005, 5, 3, 29, 'So we stayed in the valley near Beth Peor.\n'),
	(5006, 5, 4, 1, 'Now, Israel, listen to the statutes and to the ordinances, which I teach you, to do them; that you may live, and go in and possess the land which Yahweh, the God of your fathers, gives you.\n'),
	(5007, 5, 4, 2, 'You shall not add to the word which I command you, neither shall you take away from it, that you may keep the commandments of Yahweh your God which I command you.\n'),
	(5008, 5, 4, 3, 'Your eyes have seen what Yahweh did because of Baal Peor; for all the men who followed Baal Peor, Yahweh your God has destroyed them from among you.\n'),
	(5009, 5, 4, 4, 'But you who were faithful to Yahweh your God are all alive today.\n'),
	(5010, 5, 4, 5, 'Behold, I have taught you statutes and ordinances, even as Yahweh my God commanded me, that you should do so in the middle of the land where you go in to possess it.\n'),
	(5011, 5, 4, 6, 'Keep therefore and do them; for this is your wisdom and your understanding in the sight of the peoples who shall hear all these statutes and say, “Surely this great nation is a wise and understanding people.”\n'),
	(5012, 5, 4, 7, 'For what great nation is there, that has a god so near to them, as Yahweh our God is whenever we call on him?\n'),
	(5013, 5, 4, 8, 'What great nation is there, that has statutes and ordinances so righteous as all this law, which I set before you today?\n'),
	(5014, 5, 4, 9, 'Only be careful, and keep your soul diligently, lest you forget the things which your eyes saw, and lest they depart from your heart all the days of your life; but make them known to your children and your children’s children;\n'),
	(5015, 5, 4, 10, 'the day that you stood before Yahweh your God in Horeb, when Yahweh said to me, “Assemble the people to me, and I will make them hear my words, that they may learn to fear me all the days that they live on the earth, and that they may teach their children.”\n'),
	(5016, 5, 4, 11, 'You came near and stood under the mountain. The mountain burned with fire to the heart of the sky, with darkness, cloud, and thick darkness.\n'),
	(5017, 5, 4, 12, 'Yahweh spoke to you out of the middle of the fire: you heard the voice of words, but you saw no form; you only heard a voice.\n'),
	(5018, 5, 4, 13, 'He declared to you his covenant, which he commanded you to perform, even the ten commandments. He wrote them on two stone tablets.\n'),
	(5019, 5, 4, 14, 'Yahweh commanded me at that time to teach you statutes and ordinances, that you might do them in the land where you go over to possess it.\n'),
	(5020, 5, 4, 15, 'Be very careful, for you saw no kind of form on the day that Yahweh spoke to you in Horeb out of the middle of the fire,\n'),
	(5021, 5, 4, 16, 'lest you corrupt yourselves, and make yourself a carved image in the form of any figure, the likeness of male or female,\n'),
	(5022, 5, 4, 17, 'the likeness of any animal that is on the earth, the likeness of any winged bird that flies in the sky,\n'),
	(5023, 5, 4, 18, 'the likeness of anything that creeps on the ground, the likeness of any fish that is in the water under the earth;\n'),
	(5024, 5, 4, 19, 'and lest you lift up your eyes to the sky, and when you see the sun and the moon and the stars, even all the army of the sky, you are drawn away and worship them, and serve them, which Yahweh your God has allotted to all the peoples under the whole sky.\n'),
	(5025, 5, 4, 20, 'But Yahweh has taken you, and brought you out of the iron furnace, out of Egypt, to be to him a people of inheritance, as it is today.\n'),
	(5026, 5, 4, 21, 'Furthermore Yahweh was angry with me for your sakes, and swore that I should not go over the Jordan, and that I should not go in to that good land, which Yahweh your God gives you for an inheritance;\n'),
	(5027, 5, 4, 22, 'but I must die in this land. I must not go over the Jordan; but you shall go over, and possess that good land.\n'),
	(5028, 5, 4, 23, 'Be careful, lest you forget the covenant of Yahweh your God, which he made with you, and make yourselves a carved image in the form of anything which Yahweh your God has forbidden you.\n'),
	(5029, 5, 4, 24, 'For Yahweh your God is a devouring fire, a jealous God.\n'),
	(5030, 5, 4, 25, 'When you shall father children, and children’s children, and you shall have been long in the land, and shall corrupt yourselves, and make a carved image in the form of anything, and shall do that which is evil in Yahweh your God’s sight, to provoke him to anger;\n'),
	(5031, 5, 4, 26, 'I call heaven and earth to witness against you today, that you will soon utterly perish from off the land which you go over the Jordan to possess it. You will not prolong your days on it, but will utterly be destroyed.\n'),
	(5032, 5, 4, 27, 'Yahweh will scatter you among the peoples, and you will be left few in number among the nations, where Yahweh will lead you away.\n'),
	(5033, 5, 4, 28, 'There you shall serve gods, the work of men’s hands, wood and stone, which neither see, nor hear, nor eat, nor smell.\n'),
	(5034, 5, 4, 29, 'But from there you shall seek Yahweh your God, and you shall find him, when you search after him with all your heart and with all your soul.\n'),
	(5035, 5, 4, 30, 'When you are in oppression, and all these things have come on you, in the latter days you shall return to Yahweh your God, and listen to his voice.\n'),
	(5036, 5, 4, 31, 'For Yahweh your God is a merciful God. He will not fail you, neither destroy you, nor forget the covenant of your fathers which he swore to them.\n'),
	(5037, 5, 4, 32, 'For ask now of the days that are past, which were before you, since the day that God created man on the earth, and from the one end of the sky to the other, whether there has been anything as this great thing is, or has been heard like it?\n'),
	(5038, 5, 4, 33, 'Did a people ever hear the voice of God speaking out of the middle of the fire, as you have heard, and live?\n'),
	(5039, 5, 4, 34, 'Or has God tried to go and take a nation for himself from among another nation, by trials, by signs, by wonders, by war, by a mighty hand, by an outstretched arm, and by great terrors, according to all that Yahweh your God did for you in Egypt before your eyes?\n'),
	(5040, 5, 4, 35, 'It was shown to you so that you might know that Yahweh is God. There is no one else besides him.\n'),
	(5041, 5, 4, 36, 'Out of heaven he made you to hear his voice, that he might instruct you. On earth he made you to see his great fire; and you heard his words out of the middle of the fire.\n'),
	(5042, 5, 4, 37, 'Because he loved your fathers, therefore he chose their offspring after them, and brought you out with his presence, with his great power, out of Egypt;\n'),
	(5043, 5, 4, 38, 'to drive out nations from before you greater and mightier than you, to bring you in, to give you their land for an inheritance, as it is today.\n'),
	(5044, 5, 4, 39, 'Know therefore today, and take it to heart, that Yahweh himself is God in heaven above and on the earth beneath. There is no one else.\n'),
	(5045, 5, 4, 40, 'You shall keep his statutes, and his commandments, which I command you today, that it may go well with you, and with your children after you, and that you may prolong your days in the land, which Yahweh your God gives you, forever.\n'),
	(5046, 5, 4, 41, 'Then Moses set apart three cities beyond the Jordan toward the sunrise;\n'),
	(5047, 5, 4, 42, 'that the man slayer might flee there, who kills his neighbor unawares, and didn’t hate him in time past; and that fleeing to one of these cities he might live:\n'),
	(5048, 5, 4, 43, 'Bezer in the wilderness, in the plain country, for the Reubenites; and Ramoth in Gilead, for the Gadites; and Golan in Bashan, for the Manassites.\n'),
	(5049, 5, 4, 44, 'This is the law which Moses set before the children of Israel.\n'),
	(5050, 5, 4, 45, 'These are the testimonies, and the statutes, and the ordinances, which Moses spoke to the children of Israel, when they came out of Egypt,\n'),
	(5051, 5, 4, 46, 'beyond the Jordan, in the valley over against Beth Peor, in the land of Sihon king of the Amorites, who lived at Heshbon, whom Moses and the children of Israel struck, when they came out of Egypt.\n'),
	(5052, 5, 4, 47, 'They took his land in possession, and the land of Og king of Bashan, the two kings of the Amorites, who were beyond the Jordan toward the sunrise;\n'),
	(5053, 5, 4, 48, 'from Aroer, which is on the edge of the valley of the Arnon, even to Mount Sion (also called Hermon),\n'),
	(5054, 5, 4, 49, 'and all the Arabah beyond the Jordan eastward, even to the sea of the Arabah, under the slopes of Pisgah.\n'),
	(5055, 5, 5, 1, 'Moses called to all Israel, and said to them, “Hear, Israel, the statutes and the ordinances which I speak in your ears today, that you may learn them, and observe to do them.”\n'),
	(5056, 5, 5, 2, 'Yahweh our God made a covenant with us in Horeb.\n'),
	(5057, 5, 5, 3, 'Yahweh didn’t make this covenant with our fathers, but with us, even us, who are all of us here alive today.\n'),
	(5058, 5, 5, 4, 'Yahweh spoke with you face to face on the mountain out of the middle of the fire,\n'),
	(5059, 5, 5, 5, '(I stood between Yahweh and you at that time, to show you Yahweh’s word: for you were afraid because of the fire, and didn’t go up onto the mountain;) saying,\n'),
	(5060, 5, 5, 6, '“I am Yahweh your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, out of the house of bondage.\n'),
	(5061, 5, 5, 7, '“You shall have no other gods before me.\n'),
	(5062, 5, 5, 8, '“You shall not make a carved image for yourself, any likeness of what is in heaven above, or what is in the earth beneath, or that is in the water under the earth.\n'),
	(5063, 5, 5, 9, 'You shall not bow yourself down to them, nor serve them; for I, Yahweh, your God, am a jealous God, visiting the iniquity of the fathers on the children, and on the third and on the fourth generation of those who hate me;\n'),
	(5064, 5, 5, 10, 'and showing loving kindness to thousands of those who love me and keep my commandments.\n'),
	(5065, 5, 5, 11, '“You shall not take the name of Yahweh your God in vain: for Yahweh will not hold him guiltless who takes his name in vain.\n'),
	(5066, 5, 5, 12, '“Observe the Sabbath day, to keep it holy, as Yahweh your God commanded you.\n'),
	(5067, 5, 5, 13, 'You shall labor six days, and do all your work;\n'),
	(5068, 5, 5, 14, 'but the seventh day is a Sabbath to Yahweh your God, in which you shall not do any work, you, nor your son, nor your daughter, nor your male servant, nor your female servant, nor your ox, nor your donkey, nor any of your livestock, nor your stranger who is within your gates; that your male servant and your female servant may rest as well as you.\n'),
	(5069, 5, 5, 15, 'You shall remember that you were a servant in the land of Egypt, and Yahweh your God brought you out of there by a mighty hand and by an outstretched arm. Therefore Yahweh your God commanded you to keep the Sabbath day.\n'),
	(5070, 5, 5, 16, '“Honor your father and your mother, as Yahweh your God commanded you; that your days may be long, and that it may go well with you, in the land which Yahweh your God gives you.\n'),
	(5071, 5, 5, 17, '“You shall not murder.\n'),
	(5072, 5, 5, 18, '“You shall not commit adultery.\n'),
	(5073, 5, 5, 19, '“You shall not steal.\n'),
	(5074, 5, 5, 20, '“You shall not give false testimony against your neighbor.\n'),
	(5075, 5, 5, 21, '“You shall not covet your neighbor’s wife. Neither shall you desire your neighbor’s house, his field, or his male servant, or his female servant, his ox, or his donkey, or anything that is your neighbor’s.”\n'),
	(5076, 5, 5, 22, 'Yahweh spoke these words to all your assembly on the mountain out of the middle of the fire, of the cloud, and of the thick darkness, with a great voice. He added no more. He wrote them on two stone tablets, and gave them to me.\n'),
	(5077, 5, 5, 23, 'When you heard the voice out of the middle of the darkness, while the mountain was burning with fire, you came near to me, even all the heads of your tribes, and your elders;\n'),
	(5078, 5, 5, 24, 'and you said, “Behold, Yahweh our God has shown us his glory and his greatness, and we have heard his voice out of the middle of the fire. We have seen today that God does speak with man, and he lives.\n'),
	(5079, 5, 5, 25, 'Now therefore why should we die? For this great fire will consume us. If we hear Yahweh our God’s voice any more, then we shall die.\n'),
	(5080, 5, 5, 26, 'For who is there of all flesh, that has heard the voice of the living God speaking out of the middle of the fire, as we have, and lived?\n'),
	(5081, 5, 5, 27, 'Go near, and hear all that Yahweh our God shall say, and tell us all that Yahweh our God tells you; and we will hear it, and do it.”\n'),
	(5082, 5, 5, 28, 'Yahweh heard the voice of your words, when you spoke to me; and Yahweh said to me, “I have heard the voice of the words of this people, which they have spoken to you. They have well said all that they have spoken.\n'),
	(5083, 5, 5, 29, 'Oh that there were such a heart in them, that they would fear me, and keep all my commandments always, that it might be well with them, and with their children forever!\n'),
	(5084, 5, 5, 30, '“Go tell them, ‘Return to your tents.’\n'),
	(5085, 5, 5, 31, 'But as for you, stand here by me, and I will tell you all the commandment, and the statutes, and the ordinances, which you shall teach them, that they may do them in the land which I give them to possess it.”\n'),
	(5086, 5, 5, 32, 'You shall observe to do therefore as Yahweh your God has commanded you. You shall not turn away to the right hand or to the left.\n'),
	(5087, 5, 5, 33, 'You shall walk in all the way which Yahweh your God has commanded you, that you may live, and that it may be well with you, and that you may prolong your days in the land which you shall possess.\n'),
	(5088, 5, 6, 1, 'Now this is the commandment, the statutes, and the ordinances, which Yahweh your God commanded to teach you, that you might do them in the land where you go over to possess it;\n'),
	(5089, 5, 6, 2, 'that you might fear Yahweh your God, to keep all his statutes and his commandments, which I command you; you, and your son, and your son’s son, all the days of your life; and that your days may be prolonged.\n'),
	(5090, 5, 6, 3, 'Hear therefore, Israel, and observe to do it; that it may be well with you, and that you may increase mightily, as Yahweh, the God of your fathers, has promised to you, in a land flowing with milk and honey.\n'),
	(5091, 5, 6, 4, 'Hear, Israel: Yahweh is our God. Yahweh is one.\n'),
	(5092, 5, 6, 5, 'You shall love Yahweh your God with all your heart, with all your soul, and with all your might.\n'),
	(5093, 5, 6, 6, 'These words, which I command you today, shall be on your heart;\n'),
	(5094, 5, 6, 7, 'and you shall teach them diligently to your children, and shall talk of them when you sit in your house, and when you walk by the way, and when you lie down, and when you rise up.\n'),
	(5095, 5, 6, 8, 'You shall bind them for a sign on your hand, and they shall be for frontlets between your eyes.\n'),
	(5096, 5, 6, 9, 'You shall write them on the door posts of your house, and on your gates.\n'),
	(5097, 5, 6, 10, 'It shall be, when Yahweh your God brings you into the land which he swore to your fathers, to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob, to give you, great and goodly cities, which you didn’t build,\n'),
	(5098, 5, 6, 11, 'and houses full of all good things, which you didn’t fill, and cisterns dug out, which you didn’t dig, vineyards and olive trees, which you didn’t plant, and you shall eat and be full;\n'),
	(5099, 5, 6, 12, 'then beware lest you forget Yahweh, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, out of the house of bondage.\n'),
	(5100, 5, 6, 13, 'You shall fear Yahweh your God; and you shall serve him, and shall swear by his name.\n'),
	(5101, 5, 6, 14, 'You shall not go after other gods, of the gods of the peoples who are around you;\n'),
	(5102, 5, 6, 15, 'for Yahweh your God among you is a jealous God; lest the anger of Yahweh your God be kindled against you, and he destroy you from off the face of the earth.\n'),
	(5103, 5, 6, 16, 'You shall not tempt Yahweh your God, as you tempted him in Massah.\n'),
	(5104, 5, 6, 17, 'You shall diligently keep the commandments of Yahweh your God, and his testimonies, and his statutes, which he has commanded you.\n'),
	(5105, 5, 6, 18, 'You shall do that which is right and good in Yahweh’s sight; that it may be well with you, and that you may go in and possess the good land which Yahweh swore to your fathers,\n'),
	(5106, 5, 6, 19, 'to thrust out all your enemies from before you, as Yahweh has spoken.\n'),
	(5107, 5, 6, 20, 'When your son asks you in time to come, saying, “What do the testimonies, the statutes, and the ordinances, which Yahweh our God has commanded you mean?”\n'),
	(5108, 5, 6, 21, 'then you shall tell your son, “We were Pharaoh’s slaves in Egypt. Yahweh brought us out of Egypt with a mighty hand;\n'),
	(5109, 5, 6, 22, 'and Yahweh showed great and awesome signs and wonders on Egypt, on Pharaoh, and on all his house, before our eyes;\n'),
	(5110, 5, 6, 23, 'and he brought us out from there, that he might bring us in, to give us the land which he swore to our fathers.\n'),
	(5111, 5, 6, 24, 'Yahweh commanded us to do all these statutes, to fear Yahweh our God, for our good always, that he might preserve us alive, as we are today.\n'),
	(5112, 5, 6, 25, 'It shall be righteousness to us, if we observe to do all this commandment before Yahweh our God, as he has commanded us.”\n'),
	(5113, 5, 7, 1, 'When Yahweh your God brings you into the land where you go to possess it, and casts out many nations before you, the Hittite, the Girgashite, the Amorite, the Canaanite, the Perizzite, the Hivite, and the Jebusite, seven nations greater and mightier than you;\n'),
	(5114, 5, 7, 2, 'and when Yahweh your God delivers them up before you, and you strike them; then you shall utterly destroy them. You shall make no covenant with them, nor show mercy to them.\n'),
	(5115, 5, 7, 3, 'You shall not make marriages with them. You shall not give your daughter to his son, nor shall you take his daughter for your son.\n'),
	(5116, 5, 7, 4, 'For he will turn away your son from following me, that they may serve other gods. So Yahweh’s anger would be kindled against you, and he would destroy you quickly.\n'),
	(5117, 5, 7, 5, 'But you shall deal with them like this. You shall break down their altars, dash their pillars in pieces, cut down their Asherah poles, and burn their engraved images with fire.\n'),
	(5118, 5, 7, 6, 'For you are a holy people to Yahweh your God. Yahweh your God has chosen you to be a people for his own possession, above all peoples who are on the face of the earth.\n'),
	(5119, 5, 7, 7, 'Yahweh didn’t set his love on you, nor choose you, because you were more in number than any people; for you were the fewest of all peoples:\n'),
	(5120, 5, 7, 8, 'but because Yahweh loves you, and because he desires to keep the oath which he swore to your fathers, Yahweh has brought you out with a mighty hand, and redeemed you out of the house of bondage, from the hand of Pharaoh king of Egypt.\n'),
	(5121, 5, 7, 9, 'Know therefore that Yahweh your God himself is God, the faithful God, who keeps covenant and loving kindness with them who love him and keep his commandments to a thousand generations,\n'),
	(5122, 5, 7, 10, 'and repays those who hate him to their face, to destroy them. He will not be slack to him who hates him. He will repay him to his face.\n'),
	(5123, 5, 7, 11, 'You shall therefore keep the commandments, the statutes, and the ordinances, which I command you today, to do them.\n'),
	(5124, 5, 7, 12, 'It shall happen, because you listen to these ordinances, and keep and do them, that Yahweh your God will keep with you the covenant and the loving kindness which he swore to your fathers.\n'),
	(5125, 5, 7, 13, 'He will love you, bless you, and multiply you. He will also bless the fruit of your body and the fruit of your ground, your grain and your new wine and your oil, the increase of your livestock and the young of your flock, in the land which he swore to your fathers to give you.\n'),
	(5126, 5, 7, 14, 'You will be blessed above all peoples. There won’t be male or female barren among you, or among your livestock.\n'),
	(5127, 5, 7, 15, 'Yahweh will take away from you all sickness; and he will put none of the evil diseases of Egypt, which you know, on you, but will lay them on all those who hate you.\n'),
	(5128, 5, 7, 16, 'You shall consume all the peoples whom Yahweh your God shall deliver to you. Your eye shall not pity them. You shall not serve their gods; for that would be a snare to you.\n'),
	(5129, 5, 7, 17, 'If you shall say in your heart, “These nations are more than I; how can I dispossess them?”\n'),
	(5130, 5, 7, 18, 'you shall not be afraid of them. You shall remember well what Yahweh your God did to Pharaoh, and to all Egypt:\n'),
	(5131, 5, 7, 19, 'the great trials which your eyes saw, the signs, the wonders, the mighty hand, and the outstretched arm, by which Yahweh your God brought you out. So shall Yahweh your God do to all the peoples of whom you are afraid.\n'),
	(5132, 5, 7, 20, 'Moreover Yahweh your God will send the hornet among them, until those who are left, and hide themselves, perish from before you.\n'),
	(5133, 5, 7, 21, 'You shall not be scared of them; for Yahweh your God is among you, a great and awesome God.\n'),
	(5134, 5, 7, 22, 'Yahweh your God will cast out those nations before you little by little. You may not consume them at once, lest the animals of the field increase on you.\n'),
	(5135, 5, 7, 23, 'But Yahweh your God will deliver them up before you, and will confuse them with a great confusion, until they are destroyed.\n'),
	(5136, 5, 7, 24, 'He will deliver their kings into your hand, and you shall make their name perish from under the sky. No one will be able to stand before you, until you have destroyed them.\n'),
	(5137, 5, 7, 25, 'You shall burn the engraved images of their gods with fire. You shall not covet the silver or the gold that is on them, nor take it for yourself, lest you be snared in it; for it is an abomination to Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5138, 5, 7, 26, 'You shall not bring an abomination into your house, and become a devoted thing like it. You shall utterly detest it, and you shall utterly abhor it; for it is a devoted thing.\n'),
	(5139, 5, 8, 1, 'You shall observe to do all the commandments which I command you today, that you may live, and multiply, and go in and possess the land which Yahweh swore to your fathers.\n'),
	(5140, 5, 8, 2, 'You shall remember all the way which Yahweh your God has led you these forty years in the wilderness, that he might humble you, to prove you, to know what was in your heart, whether you would keep his commandments, or not.\n'),
	(5141, 5, 8, 3, 'He humbled you, and allowed you to be hungry, and fed you with manna, which you didn’t know, neither did your fathers know; that he might teach you that man does not live by bread only, but man lives by every word that proceeds out of Yahweh’s mouth.\n'),
	(5142, 5, 8, 4, 'Your clothing didn’t grow old on you, neither did your foot swell, these forty years.\n'),
	(5143, 5, 8, 5, 'You shall consider in your heart that as a man disciplines his son, so Yahweh your God disciplines you.\n'),
	(5144, 5, 8, 6, 'You shall keep the commandments of Yahweh your God, to walk in his ways, and to fear him.\n'),
	(5145, 5, 8, 7, 'For Yahweh your God brings you into a good land, a land of brooks of water, of springs, and underground water flowing into valleys and hills;\n'),
	(5146, 5, 8, 8, 'a land of wheat and barley, and vines and fig trees and pomegranates; a land of olive trees and honey;\n'),
	(5147, 5, 8, 9, 'a land in which you shall eat bread without scarceness, you shall not lack anything in it; a land whose stones are iron, and out of whose hills you may dig copper.\n'),
	(5148, 5, 8, 10, 'You shall eat and be full, and you shall bless Yahweh your God for the good land which he has given you.\n'),
	(5149, 5, 8, 11, 'Beware lest you forget Yahweh your God, in not keeping his commandments, and his ordinances, and his statutes, which I command you today;\n'),
	(5150, 5, 8, 12, 'lest, when you have eaten and are full, and have built fine houses, and lived in them;\n'),
	(5151, 5, 8, 13, 'and when your herds and your flocks multiply, and your silver and your gold is multiplied, and all that you have is multiplied;\n'),
	(5152, 5, 8, 14, 'then your heart might be lifted up, and you forget Yahweh your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, out of the house of bondage;\n'),
	(5153, 5, 8, 15, 'who led you through the great and terrible wilderness, with venomous snakes and scorpions, and thirsty ground where there was no water; who poured water for you out of the rock of flint;\n'),
	(5154, 5, 8, 16, 'who fed you in the wilderness with manna, which your fathers didn’t know; that he might humble you, and that he might prove you, to do you good at your latter end:\n'),
	(5155, 5, 8, 17, 'and lest you say in your heart, “My power and the might of my hand has gotten me this wealth.”\n'),
	(5156, 5, 8, 18, 'But you shall remember Yahweh your God, for it is he who gives you power to get wealth; that he may establish his covenant which he swore to your fathers, as it is today.\n'),
	(5157, 5, 8, 19, 'It shall be, if you shall forget Yahweh your God, and walk after other gods, and serve them, and worship them, I testify against you today that you shall surely perish.\n'),
	(5158, 5, 8, 20, 'As the nations that Yahweh makes to perish before you, so you shall perish; because you wouldn’t listen to Yahweh your God’s voice.\n'),
	(5159, 5, 9, 1, 'Hear, Israel! You are to pass over the Jordan today, to go in to dispossess nations greater and mightier than yourself, cities great and fortified up to the sky,\n'),
	(5160, 5, 9, 2, 'a people great and tall, the sons of the Anakim, whom you know, and of whom you have heard say, “Who can stand before the sons of Anak?”\n'),
	(5161, 5, 9, 3, 'Know therefore today, that Yahweh your God is he who goes over before you as a devouring fire. He will destroy them, and he will bring them down before you. So you shall drive them out, and make them perish quickly, as Yahweh has spoken to you.\n'),
	(5162, 5, 9, 4, 'Don’t say in your heart, after Yahweh your God has thrust them out from before you, saying, “For my righteousness Yahweh has brought me in to possess this land”; because Yahweh drives them out before you because of the wickedness of these nations.\n'),
	(5163, 5, 9, 5, 'Not for your righteousness, or for the uprightness of your heart, do you go in to possess their land; but for the wickedness of these nations Yahweh your God does drive them out from before you, and that he may establish the word which Yahweh swore to your fathers, to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob.\n'),
	(5164, 5, 9, 6, 'Know therefore, that Yahweh your God doesn’t give you this good land to possess for your righteousness; for you are a stiff-necked people.\n'),
	(5165, 5, 9, 7, 'Remember, and don’t forget, how you provoked Yahweh your God to wrath in the wilderness. From the day that you left the land of Egypt, until you came to this place, you have been rebellious against Yahweh.\n'),
	(5166, 5, 9, 8, 'Also in Horeb you provoked Yahweh to wrath, and Yahweh was angry with you to destroy you.\n'),
	(5167, 5, 9, 9, 'When I had gone up onto the mountain to receive the stone tablets, even the tablets of the covenant which Yahweh made with you, then I stayed on the mountain forty days and forty nights. I neither ate bread nor drank water.\n'),
	(5168, 5, 9, 10, 'Yahweh delivered to me the two stone tablets written with God’s finger. On them were all the words which Yahweh spoke with you on the mountain out of the middle of the fire in the day of the assembly.\n'),
	(5169, 5, 9, 11, 'It came to pass at the end of forty days and forty nights, that Yahweh gave me the two stone tablets, even the tablets of the covenant.\n'),
	(5170, 5, 9, 12, 'Yahweh said to me, “Arise, get down quickly from here; for your people whom you have brought out of Egypt have corrupted themselves. They have quickly turned away from the way which I commanded them. They have made a molten image for themselves!”\n'),
	(5171, 5, 9, 13, 'Furthermore Yahweh spoke to me, saying, “I have seen this people, and behold, it is a stiff-necked people.\n'),
	(5172, 5, 9, 14, 'Leave me alone, that I may destroy them, and blot out their name from under the sky; and I will make of you a nation mightier and greater than they.”\n'),
	(5173, 5, 9, 15, 'So I turned and came down from the mountain, and the mountain was burning with fire. The two tablets of the covenant were in my two hands.\n'),
	(5174, 5, 9, 16, 'I looked, and behold, you had sinned against Yahweh your God. You had made yourselves a molten calf. You had quickly turned away from the way which Yahweh had commanded you.\n'),
	(5175, 5, 9, 17, 'I took hold of the two tablets, and threw them out of my two hands, and broke them before your eyes.\n'),
	(5176, 5, 9, 18, 'I fell down before Yahweh, as at the first, forty days and forty nights. I neither ate bread nor drank water, because of all your sin which you sinned, in doing that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight, to provoke him to anger.\n'),
	(5177, 5, 9, 19, 'For I was afraid of the anger and hot displeasure with which Yahweh was angry against you to destroy you. But Yahweh listened to me that time also.\n'),
	(5178, 5, 9, 20, 'Yahweh was angry enough with Aaron to destroy him. I prayed for Aaron also at the same time.\n'),
	(5179, 5, 9, 21, 'I took your sin, the calf which you had made, and burned it with fire, and crushed it, grinding it very small, until it was as fine as dust. I threw its dust into the brook that descended out of the mountain.\n'),
	(5180, 5, 9, 22, 'At Taberah, and at Massah, and at Kibroth Hattaavah, you provoked Yahweh to wrath.\n'),
	(5181, 5, 9, 23, 'When Yahweh sent you from Kadesh Barnea, saying, “Go up and possess the land which I have given you,” you rebelled against the commandment of Yahweh your God, and you didn’t believe him, nor listen to his voice.\n'),
	(5182, 5, 9, 24, 'You have been rebellious against Yahweh from the day that I knew you.\n'),
	(5183, 5, 9, 25, 'So I fell down before Yahweh the forty days and forty nights that I fell down, because Yahweh had said he would destroy you.\n'),
	(5184, 5, 9, 26, 'I prayed to Yahweh, and said, “Lord Yahweh, don’t destroy your people and your inheritance, that you have redeemed through your greatness, that you have brought out of Egypt with a mighty hand.\n'),
	(5185, 5, 9, 27, 'Remember your servants, Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. Don’t look at the stubbornness of this people, nor at their wickedness, nor at their sin,\n'),
	(5186, 5, 9, 28, 'lest the land you brought us out from say, ‘Because Yahweh was not able to bring them into the land which he promised to them, and because he hated them, he has brought them out to kill them in the wilderness.’\n'),
	(5187, 5, 9, 29, 'Yet they are your people and your inheritance, which you brought out by your great power and by your outstretched arm.”\n'),
	(5188, 5, 10, 1, 'At that time Yahweh said to me, “Cut two stone tablets like the first, and come up to me onto the mountain, and make an ark of wood.\n'),
	(5189, 5, 10, 2, 'I will write on the tablets the words that were on the first tablets which you broke, and you shall put them in the ark.”\n'),
	(5190, 5, 10, 3, 'So I made an ark of acacia wood, and cut two stone tablets like the first, and went up onto the mountain, having the two tablets in my hand.\n'),
	(5191, 5, 10, 4, 'He wrote on the tablets, according to the first writing, the ten commandments, which Yahweh spoke to you on the mountain out of the middle of the fire in the day of the assembly: and Yahweh gave them to me.\n'),
	(5192, 5, 10, 5, 'I turned and came down from the mountain, and put the tablets in the ark which I had made; and there they are as Yahweh commanded me.\n'),
	(5193, 5, 10, 6, '(The children of Israel traveled from Beeroth Bene Jaakan to Moserah. There Aaron died, and there he was buried; and Eleazar his son ministered in the priest’s office in his place.\n'),
	(5194, 5, 10, 7, 'From there they traveled to Gudgodah; and from Gudgodah to Jotbathah, a land of brooks of water.\n'),
	(5195, 5, 10, 8, 'At that time Yahweh set apart the tribe of Levi, to bear the ark of Yahweh’s covenant, to stand before Yahweh to minister to him, and to bless in his name, to this day.\n'),
	(5196, 5, 10, 9, 'Therefore Levi has no portion nor inheritance with his brothers; Yahweh is his inheritance, according as Yahweh your God spoke to him.)\n'),
	(5197, 5, 10, 10, 'I stayed on the mountain, as at the first time, forty days and forty nights: and Yahweh listened to me that time also; Yahweh would not destroy you.\n'),
	(5198, 5, 10, 11, 'Yahweh said to me, “Arise, take your journey before the people; and they shall go in and possess the land, which I swore to their fathers to give to them.”\n'),
	(5199, 5, 10, 12, 'Now, Israel, what does Yahweh your God require of you, but to fear Yahweh your God, to walk in all his ways, and to love him, and to serve Yahweh your God with all your heart and with all your soul,\n'),
	(5200, 5, 10, 13, 'to keep Yahweh’s commandments and statutes, which I command you today for your good?\n'),
	(5201, 5, 10, 14, 'Behold, to Yahweh your God belongs heaven and the heaven of heavens, the earth, with all that is therein.\n'),
	(5202, 5, 10, 15, 'Only Yahweh had a delight in your fathers to love them, and he chose their offspring after them, even you above all peoples, as it is today.\n'),
	(5203, 5, 10, 16, 'Circumcise therefore the foreskin of your heart, and be no more stiff-necked.\n'),
	(5204, 5, 10, 17, 'For Yahweh your God, he is God of gods, and Lord of lords, the great God, the mighty, and the awesome, who doesn’t respect persons, nor takes reward.\n'),
	(5205, 5, 10, 18, 'He does execute justice for the fatherless and widow, and loves the foreigner, in giving him food and clothing.\n'),
	(5206, 5, 10, 19, 'Therefore love the foreigner; for you were foreigners in the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(5207, 5, 10, 20, 'You shall fear Yahweh your God; you shall serve him; and you shall cling to him, and you shall swear by his name.\n'),
	(5208, 5, 10, 21, 'He is your praise, and he is your God, who has done for you these great and awesome things, which your eyes have seen.\n'),
	(5209, 5, 10, 22, 'Your fathers went down into Egypt with seventy persons; and now Yahweh your God has made you as the stars of the sky for multitude.\n'),
	(5210, 5, 11, 1, 'Therefore you shall love Yahweh your God, and keep his instructions, his statutes, his ordinances, and his commandments, always.\n'),
	(5211, 5, 11, 2, 'Know this day—for I don’t speak with your children who have not known, and who have not seen the chastisement of Yahweh your God, his greatness, his mighty hand, his outstretched arm,\n'),
	(5212, 5, 11, 3, 'his signs, and his works, which he did in the middle of Egypt to Pharaoh the king of Egypt, and to all his land;\n'),
	(5213, 5, 11, 4, 'and what he did to the army of Egypt, to their horses, and to their chariots; how he made the water of the Red Sea to overflow them as they pursued you, and how Yahweh has destroyed them to this day;\n'),
	(5214, 5, 11, 5, 'and what he did to you in the wilderness, until you came to this place;\n'),
	(5215, 5, 11, 6, 'and what he did to Dathan and Abiram, the sons of Eliab, the son of Reuben; how the earth opened its mouth, and swallowed them up, with their households, their tents, and every living thing that followed them, in the middle of all Israel;\n'),
	(5216, 5, 11, 7, 'but your eyes have seen all of Yahweh’s great work which he did.\n'),
	(5217, 5, 11, 8, 'Therefore you shall keep all the commandment which I command you today, that you may be strong, and go in and possess the land, where you go over to possess it;\n'),
	(5218, 5, 11, 9, 'and that you may prolong your days in the land, which Yahweh swore to your fathers to give to them and to their offspring, a land flowing with milk and honey.\n'),
	(5219, 5, 11, 10, 'For the land, where you go in to possess, isn’t like the land of Egypt, that you came out of, where you sowed your seed, and watered it with your foot, as a garden of herbs;\n'),
	(5220, 5, 11, 11, 'but the land, where you go over to possess it, is a land of hills and valleys which drinks water from the rain of the sky,\n'),
	(5221, 5, 11, 12, 'a land which Yahweh your God cares for. Yahweh your God’s eyes are always on it, from the beginning of the year even to the end of the year.\n'),
	(5222, 5, 11, 13, 'It shall happen, if you shall listen diligently to my commandments which I command you today, to love Yahweh your God, and to serve him with all your heart and with all your soul,\n'),
	(5223, 5, 11, 14, 'that I will give the rain of your land in its season, the former rain and the latter rain, that you may gather in your grain, your new wine, and your oil.\n'),
	(5224, 5, 11, 15, 'I will give grass in your fields for your livestock, and you shall eat and be full.\n'),
	(5225, 5, 11, 16, 'Be careful, lest your heart be deceived, and you turn away, and serve other gods, and worship them;\n'),
	(5226, 5, 11, 17, 'and Yahweh’s anger be kindled against you, and he shut up the sky, so that there is no rain, and the land doesn’t yield its fruit; and you perish quickly from off the good land which Yahweh gives you.\n'),
	(5227, 5, 11, 18, 'Therefore you shall lay up these my words in your heart and in your soul. You shall bind them for a sign on your hand, and they shall be for frontlets between your eyes.\n'),
	(5228, 5, 11, 19, 'You shall teach them to your children, talking of them, when you sit in your house, and when you walk by the way, and when you lie down, and when you rise up.\n'),
	(5229, 5, 11, 20, 'You shall write them on the door posts of your house, and on your gates;\n'),
	(5230, 5, 11, 21, 'that your days may be multiplied, and the days of your children, in the land which Yahweh swore to your fathers to give them, as the days of the heavens above the earth.\n'),
	(5231, 5, 11, 22, 'For if you shall diligently keep all these commandments which I command you, to do them, to love Yahweh your God, to walk in all his ways, and to cling to him;\n'),
	(5232, 5, 11, 23, 'then Yahweh will drive out all these nations from before you, and you shall dispossess nations greater and mightier than yourselves.\n'),
	(5233, 5, 11, 24, 'Every place on which the sole of your foot treads shall be yours: from the wilderness, and Lebanon, from the river, the river Euphrates, even to the western sea shall be your border.\n'),
	(5234, 5, 11, 25, 'No man will be able to stand before you. Yahweh your God will lay the fear of you and the dread of you on all the land that you tread on, as he has spoken to you.\n'),
	(5235, 5, 11, 26, 'Behold, I set before you today a blessing and a curse:\n'),
	(5236, 5, 11, 27, 'the blessing, if you listen to the commandments of Yahweh your God, which I command you today;\n'),
	(5237, 5, 11, 28, 'and the curse, if you do not listen to the commandments of Yahweh your God, but turn away out of the way which I command you today, to go after other gods, which you have not known.\n'),
	(5238, 5, 11, 29, 'It shall happen, when Yahweh your God brings you into the land where you go to possess it, that you shall set the blessing on Mount Gerizim, and the curse on Mount Ebal.\n'),
	(5239, 5, 11, 30, 'Aren’t they beyond the Jordan, behind the way of the going down of the sun, in the land of the Canaanites who dwell in the Arabah, near Gilgal, beside the oaks of Moreh?\n'),
	(5240, 5, 11, 31, 'For you are to pass over the Jordan to go in to possess the land which Yahweh your God gives you, and you shall possess it, and dwell therein.\n'),
	(5241, 5, 11, 32, 'You shall observe to do all the statutes and the ordinances which I set before you today.\n'),
	(5242, 5, 12, 1, 'These are the statutes and the ordinances which you shall observe to do in the land which Yahweh, the God of your fathers, has given you to possess it, all the days that you live on the earth.\n'),
	(5243, 5, 12, 2, 'You shall surely destroy all the places in which the nations that you shall dispossess served their gods, on the high mountains, and on the hills, and under every green tree.\n'),
	(5244, 5, 12, 3, 'You shall break down their altars, and dash their pillars in pieces, and burn their Asherah poles with fire. You shall cut down the engraved images of their gods. You shall destroy their name out of that place.\n'),
	(5245, 5, 12, 4, 'You shall not do so to Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5246, 5, 12, 5, 'But to the place which Yahweh your God shall choose out of all your tribes, to put his name there, you shall seek his habitation, and there you shall come.\n'),
	(5247, 5, 12, 6, 'There you shall bring your burnt offerings, your sacrifices, your tithes, the wave offering of your hand, your vows, your freewill offerings, and the firstborn of your herd and of your flock.\n'),
	(5248, 5, 12, 7, 'There you shall eat before Yahweh your God, and you shall rejoice in all that you put your hand to, you and your households, in which Yahweh your God has blessed you.\n'),
	(5249, 5, 12, 8, 'You shall not do all the things that we do here today, every man whatever is right in his own eyes;\n'),
	(5250, 5, 12, 9, 'for you haven’t yet come to the rest and to the inheritance, which Yahweh your God gives you.\n'),
	(5251, 5, 12, 10, 'But when you go over the Jordan, and dwell in the land which Yahweh your God causes you to inherit, and he gives you rest from all your enemies around you, so that you dwell in safety;\n'),
	(5252, 5, 12, 11, 'then it shall happen that to the place which Yahweh your God shall choose, to cause his name to dwell there, there you shall bring all that I command you: your burnt offerings, your sacrifices, your tithes, the wave offering of your hand, and all your choice vows which you vow to Yahweh.\n'),
	(5253, 5, 12, 12, 'You shall rejoice before Yahweh your God: you, and your sons, your daughters, your male servants, your female servants, and the Levite who is within your gates, because he has no portion nor inheritance with you.\n'),
	(5254, 5, 12, 13, 'Be careful that you don’t offer your burnt offerings in every place that you see;\n'),
	(5255, 5, 12, 14, 'but in the place which Yahweh chooses in one of your tribes, there you shall offer your burnt offerings, and there you shall do all that I command you.\n'),
	(5256, 5, 12, 15, 'Notwithstanding, you may kill and eat meat within all your gates, after all the desire of your soul, according to Yahweh your God’s blessing which he has given you. The unclean and the clean may eat of it, as of the gazelle, and as of the deer.\n'),
	(5257, 5, 12, 16, 'Only you shall not eat the blood. You shall pour it out on the earth like water.\n'),
	(5258, 5, 12, 17, 'You may not eat within your gates the tithe of your grain, or of your new wine, or of your oil, or the firstborn of your herd or of your flock, nor any of your vows which you vow, nor your freewill offerings, nor the wave offering of your hand;\n'),
	(5259, 5, 12, 18, 'but you shall eat them before Yahweh your God in the place which Yahweh your God shall choose: you, your son, your daughter, your male servant, your female servant, and the Levite who is within your gates. You shall rejoice before Yahweh your God in all that you put your hand to.\n'),
	(5260, 5, 12, 19, 'Be careful that you don’t forsake the Levite as long as you live in your land.\n'),
	(5261, 5, 12, 20, 'When Yahweh your God enlarges your border, as he has promised you, and you say, “I want to eat meat,” because your soul desires to eat meat; you may eat meat, after all the desire of your soul.\n'),
	(5262, 5, 12, 21, 'If the place which Yahweh your God shall choose, to put his name there, is too far from you, then you shall kill of your herd and of your flock, which Yahweh has given you, as I have commanded you; and you may eat within your gates, after all the desire of your soul.\n'),
	(5263, 5, 12, 22, 'Even as the gazelle and as the deer is eaten, so you shall eat of it. The unclean and the clean may eat of it alike.\n'),
	(5264, 5, 12, 23, 'Only be sure that you don’t eat the blood; for the blood is the life. You shall not eat the life with the meat.\n'),
	(5265, 5, 12, 24, 'You shall not eat it. You shall pour it out on the earth like water.\n'),
	(5266, 5, 12, 25, 'You shall not eat it; that it may go well with you, and with your children after you, when you shall do that which is right in Yahweh’s eyes.\n'),
	(5267, 5, 12, 26, 'Only your holy things which you have, and your vows, you shall take, and go to the place which Yahweh shall choose.\n'),
	(5268, 5, 12, 27, 'You shall offer your burnt offerings, the meat and the blood, on Yahweh your God’s altar; and the blood of your sacrifices shall be poured out on Yahweh your God’s altar; and you shall eat the meat.\n'),
	(5269, 5, 12, 28, 'Observe and hear all these words which I command you, that it may go well with you, and with your children after you forever, when you do that which is good and right in Yahweh your God’s eyes.\n'),
	(5270, 5, 12, 29, 'When Yahweh your God cuts off the nations from before you, where you go in to dispossess them, and you dispossess them, and dwell in their land;\n'),
	(5271, 5, 12, 30, 'be careful that you are not ensnared to follow them, after that they are destroyed from before you; and that you not inquire after their gods, saying, “How do these nations serve their gods? I will do likewise.”\n'),
	(5272, 5, 12, 31, 'You shall not do so to Yahweh your God; for every abomination to Yahweh, which he hates, they have done to their gods; for they even burn their sons and their daughters in the fire to their gods.\n'),
	(5273, 5, 12, 32, 'Whatever thing I command you, that you shall observe to do. You shall not add to it, nor take away from it.\n'),
	(5274, 5, 13, 1, 'If a prophet or a dreamer of dreams arises among you, and he gives you a sign or a wonder,\n'),
	(5275, 5, 13, 2, 'and the sign or the wonder comes to pass, of which he spoke to you, saying, “Let us go after other gods” (which you have not known) “and let us serve them”;\n'),
	(5276, 5, 13, 3, 'you shall not listen to the words of that prophet, or to that dreamer of dreams; for Yahweh your God is testing you, to know whether you love Yahweh your God with all your heart and with all your soul.\n'),
	(5277, 5, 13, 4, 'You shall walk after Yahweh your God, fear him, keep his commandments, and obey his voice, and you shall serve him, and cling to him.\n'),
	(5278, 5, 13, 5, 'That prophet, or that dreamer of dreams, shall be put to death, because he has spoken rebellion against Yahweh your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, and redeemed you out of the house of bondage, to draw you aside out of the way which Yahweh your God commanded you to walk in. So you shall remove the evil from among you.\n'),
	(5279, 5, 13, 6, 'If your brother, the son of your mother, or your son, or your daughter, or the wife of your bosom, or your friend, who is as your own soul, entices you secretly, saying, “Let us go and serve other gods,” which you have not known, you, nor your fathers;\n'),
	(5280, 5, 13, 7, 'of the gods of the peoples who are around you, near to you, or far off from you, from the one end of the earth even to the other end of the earth;\n'),
	(5281, 5, 13, 8, 'you shall not consent to him, nor listen to him; neither shall your eye pity him, neither shall you spare, neither shall you conceal him;\n'),
	(5282, 5, 13, 9, 'but you shall surely kill him. Your hand shall be first on him to put him to death, and afterwards the hands of all the people.\n'),
	(5283, 5, 13, 10, 'You shall stone him to death with stones, because he has sought to draw you away from Yahweh your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, out of the house of bondage.\n'),
	(5284, 5, 13, 11, 'All Israel shall hear, and fear, and shall not do any more wickedness like this among you.\n'),
	(5285, 5, 13, 12, 'If you shall hear about one of your cities, which Yahweh your God gives you to dwell there, that\n'),
	(5286, 5, 13, 13, 'certain wicked fellows have gone out from among you, and have drawn away the inhabitants of their city, saying, “Let us go and serve other gods,” which you have not known;\n'),
	(5287, 5, 13, 14, 'then you shall inquire, and make search, and ask diligently. Behold, if it is true, and the thing certain, that such abomination was done among you,\n'),
	(5288, 5, 13, 15, 'you shall surely strike the inhabitants of that city with the edge of the sword, destroying it utterly, with all that is therein and its livestock, with the edge of the sword.\n'),
	(5289, 5, 13, 16, 'You shall gather all its plunder into the middle of its street, and shall burn with fire the city, and all of its plunder, to Yahweh your God. It shall be a heap forever. It shall not be built again.\n'),
	(5290, 5, 13, 17, 'Nothing of the devoted thing shall cling to your hand, that Yahweh may turn from the fierceness of his anger, and show you mercy, and have compassion on you, and multiply you, as he has sworn to your fathers;\n'),
	(5291, 5, 13, 18, 'when you listen to Yahweh your God’s voice, to keep all his commandments which I command you today, to do that which is right in Yahweh your God’s eyes.\n'),
	(5292, 5, 14, 1, 'You are the children of Yahweh your God. You shall not cut yourselves, nor make any baldness between your eyes for the dead.\n'),
	(5293, 5, 14, 2, 'For you are a holy people to Yahweh your God, and Yahweh has chosen you to be a people for his own possession, above all peoples who are on the face of the earth.\n'),
	(5294, 5, 14, 3, 'You shall not eat any abominable thing.\n'),
	(5295, 5, 14, 4, 'These are the animals which you may eat: the ox, the sheep, the goat,\n'),
	(5296, 5, 14, 5, 'the deer, the gazelle, the roebuck, the wild goat, the ibex, the antelope, and the chamois.\n'),
	(5297, 5, 14, 6, 'Every animal that parts the hoof, and has the hoof cloven in two and chews the cud, among the animals, that may you eat.\n'),
	(5298, 5, 14, 7, 'Nevertheless these you shall not eat of them that chew the cud, or of those who have the hoof cloven: the camel, the hare, and the rabbit. Because they chew the cud but don’t part the hoof, they are unclean to you.\n'),
	(5299, 5, 14, 8, 'The pig, because it has a split hoof but doesn’t chew the cud, is unclean to you. You shall not eat their meat, and you shall not touch their carcasses.\n'),
	(5300, 5, 14, 9, 'These you may eat of all that are in the waters: whatever has fins and scales may you eat.\n'),
	(5301, 5, 14, 10, 'You shall not eat whatever doesn’t have fins and scales. It is unclean to you.\n'),
	(5302, 5, 14, 11, 'Of all clean birds you may eat.\n'),
	(5303, 5, 14, 12, 'But these are they of which you shall not eat: the eagle, the vulture, the osprey,\n'),
	(5304, 5, 14, 13, 'the red kite, the falcon, the kite after its kind,\n'),
	(5305, 5, 14, 14, 'every raven after its kind,\n'),
	(5306, 5, 14, 15, 'the ostrich, the owl, the seagull, the hawk after its kind,\n'),
	(5307, 5, 14, 16, 'the little owl, the great owl, the horned owl,\n'),
	(5308, 5, 14, 17, 'the pelican, the vulture, the cormorant,\n'),
	(5309, 5, 14, 18, 'the stork, the heron after its kind, the hoopoe, and the bat.\n'),
	(5310, 5, 14, 19, 'All winged creeping things are unclean to you. They shall not be eaten.\n'),
	(5311, 5, 14, 20, 'Of all clean birds you may eat.\n'),
	(5312, 5, 14, 21, 'You shall not eat of anything that dies of itself. You may give it to the foreigner living among you who is within your gates, that he may eat it; or you may sell it to a foreigner; for you are a holy people to Yahweh your God. You shall not boil a young goat in its mother’s milk.\n'),
	(5313, 5, 14, 22, 'You shall surely tithe all the increase of your seed, that which comes out of the field year by year.\n'),
	(5314, 5, 14, 23, 'You shall eat before Yahweh your God, in the place which he chooses, to cause his name to dwell there, the tithe of your grain, of your new wine, and of your oil, and the firstborn of your herd and of your flock; that you may learn to fear Yahweh your God always.\n'),
	(5315, 5, 14, 24, 'If the way is too long for you, so that you are not able to carry it, because the place is too far from you, which Yahweh your God shall choose, to set his name there, when Yahweh your God shall bless you;\n'),
	(5316, 5, 14, 25, 'then you shall turn it into money, and bind up the money in your hand, and shall go to the place which Yahweh your God shall choose.\n'),
	(5317, 5, 14, 26, 'You shall trade the money for whatever your soul desires, for cattle, or for sheep, or for wine, or for strong drink, or for whatever your soul asks of you; and you shall eat there before Yahweh your God, and you shall rejoice, you and your household.\n'),
	(5318, 5, 14, 27, 'You shall not forsake the Levite who is within your gates, for he has no portion nor inheritance with you.\n'),
	(5319, 5, 14, 28, 'At the end of every three years you shall bring all the tithe of your increase in the same year, and shall store it within your gates.\n'),
	(5320, 5, 14, 29, 'The Levite, because he has no portion nor inheritance with you, and the foreigner living among you, and the fatherless, and the widow, who are within your gates, shall come, and shall eat and be satisfied; that Yahweh your God may bless you in all the work of your hand which you do.\n'),
	(5321, 5, 15, 1, 'At the end of every seven years, you shall cancel debts.\n'),
	(5322, 5, 15, 2, 'This is the way it shall be done: every creditor shall release that which he has lent to his neighbor. He shall not require payment from his neighbor and his brother; because Yahweh’s release has been proclaimed.\n'),
	(5323, 5, 15, 3, 'Of a foreigner you may require it; but whatever of yours is with your brother, your hand shall release.\n'),
	(5324, 5, 15, 4, 'However there shall be no poor with you (for Yahweh will surely bless you in the land which Yahweh your God gives you for an inheritance to possess it)\n'),
	(5325, 5, 15, 5, 'if only you diligently listen to Yahweh your God’s voice, to observe to do all this commandment which I command you today.\n'),
	(5326, 5, 15, 6, 'For Yahweh your God will bless you, as he promised you. You will lend to many nations, but you will not borrow. You will rule over many nations, but they will not rule over you.\n'),
	(5327, 5, 15, 7, 'If a poor man, one of your brothers, is with you within any of your gates in your land which Yahweh your God gives you, you shall not harden your heart, nor shut your hand from your poor brother;\n'),
	(5328, 5, 15, 8, 'but you shall surely open your hand to him, and shall surely lend him sufficient for his need, which he lacks.\n'),
	(5329, 5, 15, 9, 'Beware that there not be a wicked thought in your heart, saying, “The seventh year, the year of release, is at hand”; and your eye be evil against your poor brother, and you give him nothing; and he cry to Yahweh against you, and it be sin to you.\n'),
	(5330, 5, 15, 10, 'You shall surely give, and your heart shall not be grieved when you give to him; because that for this thing Yahweh your God will bless you in all your work, and in all that you put your hand to.\n'),
	(5331, 5, 15, 11, 'For the poor will never cease out of the land. Therefore I command you to surely open your hand to your brother, to your needy, and to your poor, in your land.\n'),
	(5332, 5, 15, 12, 'If your brother, a Hebrew man, or a Hebrew woman, is sold to you, and serves you six years; then in the seventh year you shall let him go free from you.\n'),
	(5333, 5, 15, 13, 'When you let him go free from you, you shall not let him go empty.\n'),
	(5334, 5, 15, 14, 'You shall furnish him liberally out of your flock, out of your threshing floor, and out of your wine press. As Yahweh your God has blessed you, you shall give to him.\n'),
	(5335, 5, 15, 15, 'You shall remember that you were a slave in the land of Egypt, and Yahweh your God redeemed you. Therefore I command you this thing today.\n'),
	(5336, 5, 15, 16, 'It shall be, if he tells you, “I will not go out from you,” because he loves you and your house, because he is well with you;\n'),
	(5337, 5, 15, 17, 'then you shall take an awl, and thrust it through his ear to the door, and he shall be your servant forever. Also to your female servant you shall do likewise.\n'),
	(5338, 5, 15, 18, 'It shall not seem hard to you, when you let him go free from you; for he has been double value of a hired hand as he served you six years. Yahweh your God will bless you in all that you do.\n'),
	(5339, 5, 15, 19, 'You shall dedicate all the firstborn males that are born of your herd and of your flock to Yahweh your God. You shall do no work with the firstborn of your herd, nor shear the firstborn of your flock.\n'),
	(5340, 5, 15, 20, 'You shall eat it before Yahweh your God year by year in the place which Yahweh shall choose, you and your household.\n'),
	(5341, 5, 15, 21, 'If it has any defect, is lame or blind, or has any defect whatever, you shall not sacrifice it to Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5342, 5, 15, 22, 'You shall eat it within your gates. The unclean and the clean shall eat it alike, as the gazelle, and as the deer.\n'),
	(5343, 5, 15, 23, 'Only you shall not eat its blood. You shall pour it out on the ground like water.\n'),
	(5344, 5, 16, 1, 'Observe the month of Abib, and keep the Passover to Yahweh your God; for in the month of Abib Yahweh your God brought you out of Egypt by night.\n'),
	(5345, 5, 16, 2, 'You shall sacrifice the Passover to Yahweh your God, of the flock and the herd, in the place which Yahweh shall choose, to cause his name to dwell there.\n'),
	(5346, 5, 16, 3, 'You shall eat no leavened bread with it. You shall eat unleavened bread with it seven days, even the bread of affliction; for you came out of the land of Egypt in haste; that you may remember the day when you came out of the land of Egypt all the days of your life.\n'),
	(5347, 5, 16, 4, 'No yeast shall be seen with you in all your borders seven days; neither shall any of the meat, which you sacrifice the first day at evening, remain all night until the morning.\n'),
	(5348, 5, 16, 5, 'You may not sacrifice the Passover within any of your gates, which Yahweh your God gives you;\n'),
	(5349, 5, 16, 6, 'but at the place which Yahweh your God shall choose, to cause his name to dwell in, there you shall sacrifice the Passover at evening, at the going down of the sun, at the season that you came out of Egypt.\n'),
	(5350, 5, 16, 7, 'You shall roast and eat it in the place which Yahweh your God chooses. In the morning you shall return to your tents.\n'),
	(5351, 5, 16, 8, 'Six days you shall eat unleavened bread. On the seventh day shall be a solemn assembly to Yahweh your God. You shall do no work.\n'),
	(5352, 5, 16, 9, 'You shall count for yourselves seven weeks. From the time you begin to put the sickle to the standing grain you shall begin to count seven weeks.\n'),
	(5353, 5, 16, 10, 'You shall keep the feast of weeks to Yahweh your God with a tribute of a freewill offering of your hand, which you shall give, according as Yahweh your God blesses you.\n'),
	(5354, 5, 16, 11, 'You shall rejoice before Yahweh your God: you, your son, your daughter, your male servant, your female servant, the Levite who is within your gates, the foreigner, the fatherless, and the widow, who are among you, in the place which Yahweh your God shall choose to cause his name to dwell there.\n'),
	(5355, 5, 16, 12, 'You shall remember that you were a slave in Egypt. You shall observe and do these statutes.\n'),
	(5356, 5, 16, 13, 'You shall keep the feast of tents seven days, after you have gathered in from your threshing floor and from your wine press.\n'),
	(5357, 5, 16, 14, 'You shall rejoice in your feast, you, your son, your daughter, your male servant, your female servant, the Levite, the foreigner, the fatherless, and the widow, who are within your gates.\n'),
	(5358, 5, 16, 15, 'You shall keep a feast to Yahweh your God seven days in the place which Yahweh chooses; because Yahweh your God will bless you in all your increase, and in all the work of your hands, and you shall be altogether joyful.\n'),
	(5359, 5, 16, 16, 'Three times in a year all of your males shall appear before Yahweh your God in the place which he chooses: in the feast of unleavened bread, in the feast of weeks, and in the feast of tents. They shall not appear before Yahweh empty.\n'),
	(5360, 5, 16, 17, 'Every man shall give as he is able, according to Yahweh your God’s blessing which he has given you.\n'),
	(5361, 5, 16, 18, 'You shall make judges and officers in all your gates, which Yahweh your God gives you, according to your tribes; and they shall judge the people with righteous judgment.\n'),
	(5362, 5, 16, 19, 'You shall not pervert justice. You shall not show partiality. You shall not take a bribe, for a bribe blinds the eyes of the wise, and perverts the words of the righteous.\n'),
	(5363, 5, 16, 20, 'You shall follow that which is altogether just, that you may live, and inherit the land which Yahweh your God gives you.\n'),
	(5364, 5, 16, 21, 'You shall not plant for yourselves an Asherah of any kind of tree beside Yahweh your God’s altar, which you shall make for yourselves.\n'),
	(5365, 5, 16, 22, 'Neither shall you set yourself up a sacred stone which Yahweh your God hates.\n'),
	(5366, 5, 17, 1, 'You shall not sacrifice to Yahweh your God an ox, or a sheep, in which is a defect, or anything evil; for that is an abomination to Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5367, 5, 17, 2, 'If there is found among you, within any of your gates which Yahweh your God gives you, a man or woman who does that which is evil in Yahweh your God’s sight, in transgressing his covenant,\n'),
	(5368, 5, 17, 3, 'and has gone and served other gods, and worshiped them, or the sun, or the moon, or any of the stars of the sky, which I have not commanded;\n'),
	(5369, 5, 17, 4, 'and you are told, and you have heard of it, then you shall inquire diligently. Behold, if it is true, and the thing certain, that such abomination is done in Israel,\n'),
	(5370, 5, 17, 5, 'then you shall bring out that man or that woman, who has done this evil thing, to your gates, even that same man or woman; and you shall stone them to death with stones.\n'),
	(5371, 5, 17, 6, 'At the mouth of two witnesses, or three witnesses, he who is to die shall be put to death. At the mouth of one witness he shall not be put to death.\n'),
	(5372, 5, 17, 7, 'The hand of the witnesses shall be first on him to put him to death, and afterward the hand of all the people. So you shall remove the evil from among you.\n'),
	(5373, 5, 17, 8, 'If there arises a matter too hard for you in judgment, between blood and blood, between plea and plea, and between stroke and stroke, being matters of controversy within your gates; then you shall arise, and go up to the place which Yahweh your God chooses.\n'),
	(5374, 5, 17, 9, 'You shall come to the priests who are Levites, and to the judge who shall be in those days. You shall inquire, and they shall give you the verdict.\n'),
	(5375, 5, 17, 10, 'You shall do according to the decisions of the verdict which they shall give you from that place which Yahweh chooses. You shall observe to do according to all that they shall teach you:\n'),
	(5376, 5, 17, 11, 'according to the decisions of the law which they shall teach you, and according to the judgment which they shall tell you, you shall do. You shall not turn away from the sentence which they shall show you, to the right hand, nor to the left.\n'),
	(5377, 5, 17, 12, 'The man who does presumptuously, in not listening to the priest who stands to minister there before Yahweh your God, or to the judge, even that man shall die. You shall put away the evil from Israel.\n'),
	(5378, 5, 17, 13, 'All the people shall hear, and fear, and do no more presumptuously.\n'),
	(5379, 5, 17, 14, 'When you have come to the land which Yahweh your God gives you, and possess it, and dwell in it, and say, “I will set a king over me, like all the nations that are around me”;\n'),
	(5380, 5, 17, 15, 'you shall surely set him king over yourselves, whom Yahweh your God chooses. You shall set as king over you one from among your brothers. You may not put a foreigner over you, who is not your brother.\n'),
	(5381, 5, 17, 16, 'Only he shall not multiply horses to himself, nor cause the people to return to Egypt, to the end that he may multiply horses; because Yahweh has said to you, “You shall not go back that way again.”\n'),
	(5382, 5, 17, 17, 'He shall not multiply wives to himself, that his heart not turn away. He shall not greatly multiply to himself silver and gold.\n'),
	(5383, 5, 17, 18, 'It shall be, when he sits on the throne of his kingdom, that he shall write himself a copy of this law in a book, out of that which is before the priests the Levites.\n'),
	(5384, 5, 17, 19, 'It shall be with him, and he shall read from it all the days of his life; that he may learn to fear Yahweh his God, to keep all the words of this law and these statutes, to do them;\n'),
	(5385, 5, 17, 20, 'that his heart not be lifted up above his brothers, and that he not turn away from the commandment, to the right hand, or to the left; to the end that he may prolong his days in his kingdom, he and his children, in the middle of Israel.\n'),
	(5386, 5, 18, 1, 'The priests the Levites, all the tribe of Levi, shall have no portion nor inheritance with Israel. They shall eat the offerings of Yahweh made by fire and his portion.\n'),
	(5387, 5, 18, 2, 'They shall have no inheritance among their brothers. Yahweh is their inheritance, as he has spoken to them.\n'),
	(5388, 5, 18, 3, 'This shall be the priests’ due from the people, from those who offer a sacrifice, whether it be ox or sheep, that they shall give to the priest the shoulder, the two cheeks, and the inner parts.\n'),
	(5389, 5, 18, 4, 'The first fruits of your grain, of your new wine, and of your oil, and the first of the fleece of your sheep, you shall give him.\n'),
	(5390, 5, 18, 5, 'For Yahweh your God has chosen him out of all your tribes, to stand to minister in Yahweh’s name, him and his sons for ever.\n'),
	(5391, 5, 18, 6, 'If a Levite comes from any of your gates out of all Israel, where he lives as a foreigner, and comes with all the desire of his soul to the place which Yahweh shall choose;\n'),
	(5392, 5, 18, 7, 'then he shall minister in the name of Yahweh his God, as all his brothers the Levites do, who stand there before Yahweh.\n'),
	(5393, 5, 18, 8, 'They shall have like portions to eat, in addition to that which comes from the sale of his family possessions.\n'),
	(5394, 5, 18, 9, 'When you have come into the land which Yahweh your God gives you, you shall not learn to imitate the abominations of those nations.\n'),
	(5395, 5, 18, 10, 'There shall not be found with you anyone who makes his son or his daughter to pass through the fire, one who uses divination, one who practices sorcery, or an enchanter, or a sorcerer,\n'),
	(5396, 5, 18, 11, 'or a charmer, or a consulter with a familiar spirit, or a wizard, or a necromancer.\n'),
	(5397, 5, 18, 12, 'For whoever does these things is an abomination to Yahweh. Because of these abominations, Yahweh your God drives them out from before you.\n'),
	(5398, 5, 18, 13, 'You shall be perfect with Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5399, 5, 18, 14, 'For these nations that you shall dispossess listen to those who practice sorcery and to diviners; but as for you, Yahweh your God has not allowed you so to do.\n'),
	(5400, 5, 18, 15, 'Yahweh your God will raise up to you a prophet from among you, of your brothers, like me. You shall listen to him.\n'),
	(5401, 5, 18, 16, 'This is according to all that you desired of Yahweh your God in Horeb in the day of the assembly, saying, “Let me not hear again Yahweh my God’s voice, neither let me see this great fire any more, that I not die.”\n'),
	(5402, 5, 18, 17, 'Yahweh said to me, “They have well said that which they have spoken.\n'),
	(5403, 5, 18, 18, 'I will raise them up a prophet from among their brothers, like you. I will put my words in his mouth, and he shall speak to them all that I shall command him.\n'),
	(5404, 5, 18, 19, 'It shall happen, that whoever will not listen to my words which he shall speak in my name, I will require it of him.\n'),
	(5405, 5, 18, 20, 'But the prophet who speaks a word presumptuously in my name, which I have not commanded him to speak, or who speaks in the name of other gods, that same prophet shall die.”\n'),
	(5406, 5, 18, 21, 'You may say in your heart, “How shall we know the word which Yahweh has not spoken?”\n'),
	(5407, 5, 18, 22, 'When a prophet speaks in Yahweh’s name, if the thing doesn’t follow, nor happen, that is the thing which Yahweh has not spoken. The prophet has spoken it presumptuously. You shall not be afraid of him.\n'),
	(5408, 5, 19, 1, 'When Yahweh your God cuts off the nations whose land Yahweh your God gives you, and you succeed them and dwell in their cities and in their houses;\n'),
	(5409, 5, 19, 2, 'you shall set apart three cities for yourselves in the middle of your land, which Yahweh your God gives you to possess it.\n'),
	(5410, 5, 19, 3, 'You shall prepare the way, and divide the borders of your land which Yahweh your God causes you to inherit into three parts, that every man slayer may flee there.\n'),
	(5411, 5, 19, 4, 'This is the case of the man slayer who shall flee there and live. Whoever kills his neighbor unawares, and didn’t hate him in time past;\n'),
	(5412, 5, 19, 5, 'as when a man goes into the forest with his neighbor to chop wood and his hand swings the ax to cut down the tree, and the head slips from the handle and hits his neighbor so that he dies, he shall flee to one of these cities and live.\n'),
	(5413, 5, 19, 6, 'Otherwise, the avenger of blood might pursue the man slayer while his heart is hot and overtake him, because the way is long, and strike him mortally; even though he was not worthy of death, because he didn’t hate him in time past.\n'),
	(5414, 5, 19, 7, 'Therefore I command you to set apart three cities for yourselves.\n'),
	(5415, 5, 19, 8, 'If Yahweh your God enlarges your border, as he has sworn to your fathers, and gives you all the land which he promised to give to your fathers;\n'),
	(5416, 5, 19, 9, 'if you keep all this commandment to do it, which I command you today, to love Yahweh your God, and to walk ever in his ways; then you shall add three cities more for yourselves, besides these three.\n'),
	(5417, 5, 19, 10, 'This is so that innocent blood will not be shed in the middle of your land which Yahweh your God gives you for an inheritance, leaving blood guilt on you.\n'),
	(5418, 5, 19, 11, 'But if any man hates his neighbor, lies in wait for him, rises up against him, strikes him mortally so that he dies, and he flees into one of these cities;\n'),
	(5419, 5, 19, 12, 'then the elders of his city shall send and bring him there, and deliver him into the hand of the avenger of blood, that he may die.\n'),
	(5420, 5, 19, 13, 'Your eye shall not pity him, but you shall purge the innocent blood from Israel that it may go well with you.\n'),
	(5421, 5, 19, 14, 'You shall not remove your neighbor’s landmark, which they of old time have set, in your inheritance which you shall inherit, in the land that Yahweh your God gives you to possess.\n'),
	(5422, 5, 19, 15, 'One witness shall not rise up against a man for any iniquity, or for any sin, in any sin that he sins. At the mouth of two witnesses, or at the mouth of three witnesses, shall a matter be established.\n'),
	(5423, 5, 19, 16, 'If an unrighteous witness rises up against any man to testify against him of wrongdoing,\n'),
	(5424, 5, 19, 17, 'then both the men, between whom the controversy is, shall stand before Yahweh, before the priests and the judges who shall be in those days;\n'),
	(5425, 5, 19, 18, 'and the judges shall make diligent inquisition: and behold, if the witness is a false witness, and has testified falsely against his brother;\n'),
	(5426, 5, 19, 19, 'then you shall do to him as he had thought to do to his brother. So you shall remove the evil from among you.\n'),
	(5427, 5, 19, 20, 'Those who remain shall hear, and fear, and will never again commit any such evil among you.\n'),
	(5428, 5, 19, 21, 'Your eyes shall not pity: life for life, eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot.\n'),
	(5429, 5, 20, 1, 'When you go out to battle against your enemies, and see horses, chariots, and a people more than you, you shall not be afraid of them; for Yahweh your God is with you, who brought you up out of the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(5430, 5, 20, 2, 'It shall be, when you draw near to the battle, that the priest shall approach and speak to the people,\n'),
	(5431, 5, 20, 3, 'and shall tell them, “Hear, Israel, you draw near today to battle against your enemies. Don’t let your heart faint! Don’t be afraid, nor tremble, neither be scared of them;\n'),
	(5432, 5, 20, 4, 'for Yahweh your God is he who goes with you, to fight for you against your enemies, to save you.”\n'),
	(5433, 5, 20, 5, 'The officers shall speak to the people, saying, “What man is there who has built a new house, and has not dedicated it? Let him go and return to his house, lest he die in the battle, and another man dedicate it.\n'),
	(5434, 5, 20, 6, 'What man is there who has planted a vineyard, and has not used its fruit? Let him go and return to his house, lest he die in the battle, and another man use its fruit.\n'),
	(5435, 5, 20, 7, 'What man is there who has pledged to be married a wife, and has not taken her? Let him go and return to his house, lest he die in the battle, and another man take her.”\n'),
	(5436, 5, 20, 8, 'The officers shall speak further to the people, and they shall say, “What man is there who is fearful and faint-hearted? Let him go and return to his house, lest his brother’s heart melt as his heart.”\n'),
	(5437, 5, 20, 9, 'It shall be, when the officers have finished speaking to the people, that they shall appoint captains of armies at the head of the people.\n'),
	(5438, 5, 20, 10, 'When you draw near to a city to fight against it, then proclaim peace to it.\n'),
	(5439, 5, 20, 11, 'It shall be, if it makes you answer of peace, and opens to you, then it shall be, that all the people who are found therein shall become forced laborers to you, and shall serve you.\n'),
	(5440, 5, 20, 12, 'If it will make no peace with you, but will make war against you, then you shall besiege it.\n'),
	(5441, 5, 20, 13, 'When Yahweh your God delivers it into your hand, you shall strike every male of it with the edge of the sword;\n'),
	(5442, 5, 20, 14, 'but the women, the little ones, the livestock, and all that is in the city, even all its plunder, you shall take for plunder for yourself. You may use the plunder of your enemies, which Yahweh your God has given you.\n'),
	(5443, 5, 20, 15, 'Thus you shall do to all the cities which are very far off from you, which are not of the cities of these nations.\n'),
	(5444, 5, 20, 16, 'But of the cities of these peoples, that Yahweh your God gives you for an inheritance, you shall save alive nothing that breathes;\n'),
	(5445, 5, 20, 17, 'but you shall utterly destroy them: the Hittite, the Amorite, the Canaanite, the Perizzite, the Hivite, and the Jebusite; as Yahweh your God has commanded you;\n'),
	(5446, 5, 20, 18, 'that they not teach you to follow all their abominations, which they have done to their gods; so would you sin against Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5447, 5, 20, 19, 'When you shall besiege a city a long time, in making war against it to take it, you shall not destroy its trees by wielding an ax against them; for you may eat of them. You shall not cut them down; for is the tree of the field man, that it should be besieged by you?\n'),
	(5448, 5, 20, 20, 'Only the trees that you know are not trees for food, you shall destroy and cut them down. You shall build bulwarks against the city that makes war with you, until it falls.\n'),
	(5449, 5, 21, 1, 'If someone is found slain in the land which Yahweh your God gives you to possess, lying in the field, and it isn’t known who has struck him;\n'),
	(5450, 5, 21, 2, 'then your elders and your judges shall come out, and they shall measure to the cities which are around him who is slain.\n'),
	(5451, 5, 21, 3, 'It shall be that the elders of the city which is nearest to the slain man shall take a heifer of the herd, which hasn’t been worked with, and which has not drawn in the yoke.\n'),
	(5452, 5, 21, 4, 'The elders of that city shall bring the heifer down to a valley with running water, which is neither plowed nor sown, and shall break the heifer’s neck there in the valley.\n'),
	(5453, 5, 21, 5, 'The priests the sons of Levi shall come near; for them Yahweh your God has chosen to minister to him, and to bless in Yahweh’s name; and according to their word shall every controversy and every assault be decided.\n'),
	(5454, 5, 21, 6, 'All the elders of that city, who are nearest to the slain man, shall wash their hands over the heifer whose neck was broken in the valley.\n'),
	(5455, 5, 21, 7, 'They shall answer and say, “Our hands have not shed this blood, neither have our eyes seen it.\n'),
	(5456, 5, 21, 8, 'Forgive, Yahweh, your people Israel, whom you have redeemed, and don’t allow innocent blood among your people Israel.” The blood shall be forgiven them.\n'),
	(5457, 5, 21, 9, 'So you shall put away the innocent blood from among you, when you shall do that which is right in Yahweh’s eyes.\n'),
	(5458, 5, 21, 10, 'When you go out to battle against your enemies, and Yahweh your God delivers them into your hands, and you carry them away captive,\n'),
	(5459, 5, 21, 11, 'and see among the captives a beautiful woman, and you have a desire to her, and desire to take her as your wife;\n'),
	(5460, 5, 21, 12, 'then you shall bring her home to your house. She shall shave her head and trim her nails.\n'),
	(5461, 5, 21, 13, 'She shall take off the clothing of her captivity, and shall remain in your house, and bewail her father and her mother a full month. After that you shall go in to her and be her husband, and she shall be your wife.\n'),
	(5462, 5, 21, 14, 'It shall be, if you have no delight in her, then you shall let her go where she desires; but you shall not sell her at all for money. You shall not deal with her as a slave, because you have humbled her.\n'),
	(5463, 5, 21, 15, 'If a man has two wives, the one beloved, and the other hated, and they have borne him children, both the beloved and the hated; and if the firstborn son is hers who was hated;\n'),
	(5464, 5, 21, 16, 'then it shall be, in the day that he causes his sons to inherit that which he has, that he may not give the son of the beloved the rights of the firstborn before the son of the hated, who is the firstborn;\n'),
	(5465, 5, 21, 17, 'but he shall acknowledge the firstborn, the son of the hated, by giving him a double portion of all that he has; for he is the beginning of his strength. The right of the firstborn is his.\n'),
	(5466, 5, 21, 18, 'If a man has a stubborn and rebellious son, who will not obey the voice of his father or the voice of his mother, and though they chasten him, will not listen to them;\n'),
	(5467, 5, 21, 19, 'then his father and his mother shall take hold of him and bring him out to the elders of his city, and to the gate of his place.\n'),
	(5468, 5, 21, 20, 'They shall tell the elders of his city, “This our son is stubborn and rebellious. He will not obey our voice. He is a glutton and a drunkard.”\n'),
	(5469, 5, 21, 21, 'All the men of his city shall stone him to death with stones. So you shall remove the evil from among you. All Israel shall hear, and fear.\n'),
	(5470, 5, 21, 22, 'If a man has committed a sin worthy of death, and he is put to death, and you hang him on a tree;\n'),
	(5471, 5, 21, 23, 'his body shall not remain all night on the tree, but you shall surely bury him the same day; for he who is hanged is accursed of God; that you don’t defile your land which Yahweh your God gives you for an inheritance.\n'),
	(5472, 5, 22, 1, 'You shall not see your brother’s ox or his sheep go astray, and hide yourself from them. You shall surely bring them again to your brother.\n'),
	(5473, 5, 22, 2, 'If your brother isn’t near to you, or if you don’t know him, then you shall bring it home to your house, and it shall be with you until your brother comes looking for it, and you shall restore it to him.\n'),
	(5474, 5, 22, 3, 'So you shall do with his donkey. So you shall do with his garment. So you shall do with every lost thing of your brother’s, which he has lost, and you have found. You may not hide yourself.\n'),
	(5475, 5, 22, 4, 'You shall not see your brother’s donkey or his ox fallen down by the way, and hide yourself from them. You shall surely help him to lift them up again.\n'),
	(5476, 5, 22, 5, 'A woman shall not wear men’s clothing, neither shall a man put on women’s clothing; for whoever does these things is an abomination to Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5477, 5, 22, 6, 'If you come across a bird’s nest on the way, in any tree or on the ground, with young ones or eggs, and the hen sitting on the young, or on the eggs, you shall not take the hen with the young.\n'),
	(5478, 5, 22, 7, 'You shall surely let the hen go, but the young you may take for yourself; that it may be well with you, and that you may prolong your days.\n'),
	(5479, 5, 22, 8, 'When you build a new house, then you shall make a railing around your roof, so that you don’t bring blood on your house if anyone falls from there.\n'),
	(5480, 5, 22, 9, 'You shall not sow your vineyard with two kinds of seed, lest all the fruit be defiled, the seed which you have sown, and the increase of the vineyard.\n'),
	(5481, 5, 22, 10, 'You shall not plow with an ox and a donkey together.\n'),
	(5482, 5, 22, 11, 'You shall not wear clothes of wool and linen woven together.\n'),
	(5483, 5, 22, 12, 'You shall make yourselves fringes on the four corners of your cloak with which you cover yourself.\n'),
	(5484, 5, 22, 13, 'If any man takes a wife, and goes in to her, hates her,\n'),
	(5485, 5, 22, 14, 'accuses her of shameful things, and gives her a bad name, and says, “I took this woman, and when I came near to her, I didn’t find in her the tokens of virginity”;\n'),
	(5486, 5, 22, 15, 'then the young lady’s father and mother shall take and bring the tokens of the young lady’s virginity to the elders of the city in the gate.\n'),
	(5487, 5, 22, 16, 'The young lady’s father shall tell the elders, “I gave my daughter to this man as his wife, and he hates her.\n'),
	(5488, 5, 22, 17, 'Behold, he has accused her of shameful things, saying, ‘I didn’t find in your daughter the tokens of virginity;’ and yet these are the tokens of my daughter’s virginity.” They shall spread the cloth before the elders of the city.\n'),
	(5489, 5, 22, 18, 'The elders of that city shall take the man and chastise him.\n'),
	(5490, 5, 22, 19, 'They shall fine him one hundred shekels of silver, and give them to the father of the young lady, because he has given a bad name to a virgin of Israel. She shall be his wife. He may not put her away all his days.\n'),
	(5491, 5, 22, 20, 'But if this thing is true, that the tokens of virginity were not found in the young lady;\n'),
	(5492, 5, 22, 21, 'then they shall bring out the young lady to the door of her father’s house, and the men of her city shall stone her to death with stones, because she has done folly in Israel, to play the prostitute in her father’s house. So you shall remove the evil from among you.\n'),
	(5493, 5, 22, 22, 'If a man is found lying with a woman married to a husband, then they shall both die, the man who lay with the woman and the woman. So you shall remove the evil from Israel.\n'),
	(5494, 5, 22, 23, 'If there is a young lady who is a virgin pledged to be married to a husband, and a man finds her in the city, and lies with her;\n'),
	(5495, 5, 22, 24, 'then you shall bring them both out to the gate of that city, and you shall stone them to death with stones; the lady, because she didn’t cry, being in the city; and the man, because he has humbled his neighbor’s wife. So you shall remove the evil from among you.\n'),
	(5496, 5, 22, 25, 'But if the man finds the lady who is pledged to be married in the field, and the man forces her, and lies with her; then only the man who lay with her shall die;\n'),
	(5497, 5, 22, 26, 'but to the lady you shall do nothing. There is in the lady no sin worthy of death; for as when a man rises against his neighbor, and kills him, even so is this matter;\n'),
	(5498, 5, 22, 27, 'for he found her in the field, the pledged to be married lady cried, and there was no one to save her.\n'),
	(5499, 5, 22, 28, 'If a man finds a lady who is a virgin, who is not pledged to be married, grabs her, and lies with her, and they are found;\n'),
	(5500, 5, 22, 29, 'then the man who lay with her shall give to the lady’s father fifty shekels of silver. She shall be his wife, because he has humbled her. He may not put her away all his days.\n'),
	(5501, 5, 22, 30, 'A man shall not take his father’s wife, and shall not uncover his father’s skirt.\n'),
	(5502, 5, 23, 1, 'He who is emasculated by crushing or cutting shall not enter into Yahweh’s assembly.\n'),
	(5503, 5, 23, 2, 'A person born of a forbidden union shall not enter into Yahweh’s assembly; even to the tenth generation shall no one of his enter into Yahweh’s assembly.\n'),
	(5504, 5, 23, 3, 'An Ammonite or a Moabite shall not enter into Yahweh’s assembly; even to the tenth generation shall no one belonging to them enter into Yahweh’s assembly forever;\n'),
	(5505, 5, 23, 4, 'because they didn’t meet you with bread and with water on the way, when you came out of Egypt, and because they hired against you Balaam the son of Beor from Pethor of Mesopotamia, to curse you.\n'),
	(5506, 5, 23, 5, 'Nevertheless Yahweh your God wouldn’t listen to Balaam; but Yahweh your God turned the curse into a blessing to you, because Yahweh your God loved you.\n'),
	(5507, 5, 23, 6, 'You shall not seek their peace nor their prosperity all your days forever.\n'),
	(5508, 5, 23, 7, 'You shall not abhor an Edomite; for he is your brother. You shall not abhor an Egyptian, because you lived as a foreigner in his land.\n'),
	(5509, 5, 23, 8, 'The children of the third generation who are born to them may enter into Yahweh’s assembly.\n'),
	(5510, 5, 23, 9, 'When you go out and camp against your enemies, then you shall keep yourselves from every evil thing.\n'),
	(5511, 5, 23, 10, 'If there is among you any man who is not clean by reason of that which happens him by night, then shall he go outside of the camp. He shall not come within the camp;\n'),
	(5512, 5, 23, 11, 'but it shall be, when evening comes, he shall bathe himself in water. When the sun is down, he shall come within the camp.\n'),
	(5513, 5, 23, 12, 'You shall have a place also outside of the camp where you go relieve yourself.\n'),
	(5514, 5, 23, 13, 'You shall have a trowel among your weapons. It shall be, when you relieve yourself, you shall dig with it, and shall turn back and cover your excrement;\n'),
	(5515, 5, 23, 14, 'for Yahweh your God walks in the middle of your camp, to deliver you, and to give up your enemies before you. Therefore your camp shall be holy, that he may not see an unclean thing in you, and turn away from you.\n'),
	(5516, 5, 23, 15, 'You shall not deliver to his master a servant who has escaped from his master to you.\n'),
	(5517, 5, 23, 16, 'He shall dwell with you, among you, in the place which he shall choose within one of your gates, where it pleases him best. You shall not oppress him.\n'),
	(5518, 5, 23, 17, 'There shall be no prostitute of the daughters of Israel, neither shall there be a sodomite of the sons of Israel.\n'),
	(5519, 5, 23, 18, 'You shall not bring the hire of a prostitute, or the wages of a male prostitute, into the house of Yahweh your God for any vow; for both of these are an abomination to Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5520, 5, 23, 19, 'You shall not lend on interest to your brother; interest of money, interest of food, interest of anything that is lent on interest.\n'),
	(5521, 5, 23, 20, 'You may lend on interest to a foreigner; but to your brother you shall not lend on interest, that Yahweh your God may bless you in all that you put your hand to, in the land where you go in to possess it.\n'),
	(5522, 5, 23, 21, 'When you vow a vow to Yahweh your God, you shall not be slack to pay it; for Yahweh your God will surely require it of you; and it would be sin in you.\n'),
	(5523, 5, 23, 22, 'But if you refrain from making a vow, it shall be no sin in you.\n'),
	(5524, 5, 23, 23, 'You shall observe and do that which has gone out of your lips. Whatever you have vowed to Yahweh your God as a freewill offering, which you have promised with your mouth, you must do.\n'),
	(5525, 5, 23, 24, 'When you come into your neighbor’s vineyard, then you may eat of grapes your fill at your own pleasure; but you shall not put any in your container.\n'),
	(5526, 5, 23, 25, 'When you come into your neighbor’s standing grain, then you may pluck the ears with your hand; but you shall not move a sickle to your neighbor’s standing grain.\n'),
	(5527, 5, 24, 1, 'When a man takes a wife and marries her, then it shall be, if she finds no favor in his eyes, because he has found some unseemly thing in her, that he shall write her a bill of divorce, and put it in her hand, and send her out of his house.\n'),
	(5528, 5, 24, 2, 'When she has departed out of his house, she may go and be another man’s wife.\n'),
	(5529, 5, 24, 3, 'If the latter husband hates her, and write her a bill of divorce, and puts it in her hand, and sends her out of his house; or if the latter husband die, who took her to be his wife;\n'),
	(5530, 5, 24, 4, 'her former husband, who sent her away, may not take her again to be his wife, after that she is defiled; for that is abomination before Yahweh. You shall not cause the land to sin, which Yahweh your God gives you for an inheritance.\n'),
	(5531, 5, 24, 5, 'When a man takes a new wife, he shall not go out in the army, neither shall he be assigned any business. He shall be free at home one year, and shall cheer his wife whom he has taken.\n'),
	(5532, 5, 24, 6, 'No man shall take the mill or the upper millstone as a pledge; for he takes a life in pledge.\n'),
	(5533, 5, 24, 7, 'If a man is found stealing any of his brothers of the children of Israel, and he deals with him as a slave, or sells him; then that thief shall die. So you shall remove the evil from among you.\n'),
	(5534, 5, 24, 8, 'Be careful in the plague of leprosy, that you observe diligently, and do according to all that the priests the Levites teach you. As I commanded them, so you shall observe to do.\n'),
	(5535, 5, 24, 9, 'Remember what Yahweh your God did to Miriam, by the way as you came out of Egypt.\n'),
	(5536, 5, 24, 10, 'When you lend your neighbor any kind of loan, you shall not go into his house to get his pledge.\n'),
	(5537, 5, 24, 11, 'You shall stand outside, and the man to whom you lend shall bring the pledge outside to you.\n'),
	(5538, 5, 24, 12, 'If he is a poor man, you shall not sleep with his pledge.\n'),
	(5539, 5, 24, 13, 'You shall surely restore to him the pledge when the sun goes down, that he may sleep in his garment, and bless you. It shall be righteousness to you before Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5540, 5, 24, 14, 'You shall not oppress a hired servant who is poor and needy, whether he is one of your brothers, or one of the foreigners who are in your land within your gates.\n'),
	(5541, 5, 24, 15, 'In his day you shall give him his hire, neither shall the sun go down on it; for he is poor, and sets his heart on it; lest he cry against you to Yahweh, and it be sin to you.\n'),
	(5542, 5, 24, 16, 'The fathers shall not be put to death for the children, neither shall the children be put to death for the fathers. Every man shall be put to death for his own sin.\n'),
	(5543, 5, 24, 17, 'You shall not deprive the foreigner or the fatherless of justice, nor take a widow’s clothing in pledge;\n'),
	(5544, 5, 24, 18, 'but you shall remember that you were a slave in Egypt, and Yahweh your God redeemed you there. Therefore I command you to do this thing.\n'),
	(5545, 5, 24, 19, 'When you reap your harvest in your field, and have forgotten a sheaf in the field, you shall not go again to get it. It shall be for the foreigner, for the fatherless, and for the widow; that Yahweh your God may bless you in all the work of your hands.\n'),
	(5546, 5, 24, 20, 'When you beat your olive tree, you shall not go over the boughs again. It shall be for the foreigner, for the fatherless, and for the widow.\n'),
	(5547, 5, 24, 21, 'When you harvest your vineyard, you shall not glean it after yourselves. It shall be for the foreigner, for the fatherless, and for the widow.\n'),
	(5548, 5, 24, 22, 'You shall remember that you were a slave in the land of Egypt. Therefore I command you to do this thing.\n'),
	(5549, 5, 25, 1, 'If there is a controversy between men, and they come to judgment, and the judges judge them; then they shall justify the righteous, and condemn the wicked.\n'),
	(5550, 5, 25, 2, 'It shall be, if the wicked man is worthy to be beaten, that the judge shall cause him to lie down, and to be beaten before his face, according to his wickedness, by number.\n'),
	(5551, 5, 25, 3, 'He may sentence him to no more than forty stripes. He shall not give more; lest, if he should give more, and beat him more than that many stripes, then your brother will be degraded in your sight.\n'),
	(5552, 5, 25, 4, 'You shall not muzzle the ox when he treads out the grain.\n'),
	(5553, 5, 25, 5, 'If brothers dwell together, and one of them dies, and has no son, the wife of the dead shall not be married outside to a stranger. Her husband’s brother shall go in to her, and take her as his wife, and perform the duty of a husband’s brother to her.\n'),
	(5554, 5, 25, 6, 'It shall be that the firstborn whom she bears shall succeed in the name of his brother who is dead, that his name not be blotted out of Israel.\n'),
	(5555, 5, 25, 7, 'If the man doesn’t want to take his brother’s wife, then his brother’s wife shall go up to the gate to the elders, and say, “My husband’s brother refuses to raise up to his brother a name in Israel. He will not perform the duty of a husband’s brother to me.”\n'),
	(5556, 5, 25, 8, 'Then the elders of his city shall call him, and speak to him: and if he stands and says, “I don’t want to take her”;\n'),
	(5557, 5, 25, 9, 'then his brother’s wife shall come to him in the presence of the elders, and loose his shoe from off his foot, and spit in his face. She shall answer and say, “So shall it be done to the man who does not build up his brother’s house.”\n'),
	(5558, 5, 25, 10, 'His name shall be called in Israel, “The house of him who had his shoe removed.”\n'),
	(5559, 5, 25, 11, 'When men strive against each other, and the wife of one draws near to deliver her husband out of the hand of him who strikes him, and puts out her hand, and takes him by his private parts,\n'),
	(5560, 5, 25, 12, 'then you shall cut off her hand. Your eye shall have no pity.\n'),
	(5561, 5, 25, 13, 'You shall not have in your bag diverse weights, one heavy and one light.\n'),
	(5562, 5, 25, 14, 'You shall not have in your house diverse measures, one large and one small.\n'),
	(5563, 5, 25, 15, 'You shall have a perfect and just weight. You shall have a perfect and just measure, that your days may be long in the land which Yahweh your God gives you.\n'),
	(5564, 5, 25, 16, 'For all who do such things, all who do unrighteously, are an abomination to Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5565, 5, 25, 17, 'Remember what Amalek did to you by the way as you came out of Egypt;\n'),
	(5566, 5, 25, 18, 'how he met you by the way, and struck the rearmost of you, all who were feeble behind you, when you were faint and weary; and he didn’t fear God.\n'),
	(5567, 5, 25, 19, 'Therefore it shall be, when Yahweh your God has given you rest from all your enemies all around, in the land which Yahweh your God gives you for an inheritance to possess it, that you shall blot out the memory of Amalek from under the sky. You shall not forget.\n'),
	(5568, 5, 26, 1, 'It shall be, when you have come in to the land which Yahweh your God gives you for an inheritance, possess it, and dwell in it,\n'),
	(5569, 5, 26, 2, 'that you shall take some of the first of all the fruit of the ground, which you shall bring in from your land that Yahweh your God gives you. You shall put it in a basket, and shall go to the place which Yahweh your God shall choose, to cause his name to dwell there.\n'),
	(5570, 5, 26, 3, 'You shall come to the priest who shall be in those days, and tell him, “I profess today to Yahweh your God, that I have come to the land which Yahweh swore to our fathers to give us.”\n'),
	(5571, 5, 26, 4, 'The priest shall take the basket out of your hand, and set it down before Yahweh your God’s altar.\n'),
	(5572, 5, 26, 5, 'You shall answer and say before Yahweh your God, “My father was a Syrian ready to perish. He went down into Egypt, and lived there, few in number. There he became a great, mighty, and populous nation.\n'),
	(5573, 5, 26, 6, 'The Egyptians mistreated us, afflicted us, and imposed hard labor on us.\n'),
	(5574, 5, 26, 7, 'Then we cried to Yahweh, the God of our fathers. Yahweh heard our voice, and saw our affliction, our toil, and our oppression.\n'),
	(5575, 5, 26, 8, 'Yahweh brought us out of Egypt with a mighty hand, with an outstretched arm, with great terror, with signs, and with wonders;\n'),
	(5576, 5, 26, 9, 'and he has brought us into this place, and has given us this land, a land flowing with milk and honey.\n'),
	(5577, 5, 26, 10, 'Now, behold, I have brought the first of the fruit of the ground, which you, Yahweh, have given me.” You shall set it down before Yahweh your God, and worship before Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5578, 5, 26, 11, 'You shall rejoice in all the good which Yahweh your God has given to you, and to your house, you, and the Levite, and the foreigner who is among you.\n'),
	(5579, 5, 26, 12, 'When you have finished tithing all the tithe of your increase in the third year, which is the year of tithing, then you shall give it to the Levite, to the foreigner, to the fatherless, and to the widow, that they may eat within your gates, and be filled.\n'),
	(5580, 5, 26, 13, 'You shall say before Yahweh your God, “I have put away the holy things out of my house, and also have given them to the Levite, to the foreigner, to the fatherless, and to the widow, according to all your commandment which you have commanded me. I have not transgressed any of your commandments, neither have I forgotten them.\n'),
	(5581, 5, 26, 14, 'I have not eaten of it in my mourning, neither have I removed any of it while I was unclean, nor given of it for the dead. I have listened to Yahweh my God’s voice. I have done according to all that you have commanded me.\n'),
	(5582, 5, 26, 15, 'Look down from your holy habitation, from heaven, and bless your people Israel, and the ground which you have given us, as you swore to our fathers, a land flowing with milk and honey.”\n'),
	(5583, 5, 26, 16, 'Today Yahweh your God commands you to do these statutes and ordinances. You shall therefore keep and do them with all your heart and with all your soul.\n'),
	(5584, 5, 26, 17, 'You have declared today that Yahweh is your God, and that you would walk in his ways, and keep his statutes, and his commandments, and his ordinances, and listen to his voice.\n'),
	(5585, 5, 26, 18, 'Yahweh has declared today that you are a people for his own possession, as he has promised you, and that you should keep all his commandments.\n'),
	(5586, 5, 26, 19, 'He will make you high above all nations that he has made, in praise, in name, and in honor; and that you may be a holy people to Yahweh your God, as he has spoken.\n'),
	(5587, 5, 27, 1, 'Moses and the elders of Israel commanded the people, saying, “Keep all the commandment which I command you today.\n'),
	(5588, 5, 27, 2, 'It shall be on the day when you shall pass over the Jordan to the land which Yahweh your God gives you, that you shall set yourself up great stones, and coat them with plaster.\n'),
	(5589, 5, 27, 3, 'You shall write on them all the words of this law, when you have passed over; that you may go in to the land which Yahweh your God gives you, a land flowing with milk and honey, as Yahweh, the God of your fathers, has promised you.\n'),
	(5590, 5, 27, 4, 'It shall be, when you have crossed over the Jordan, that you shall set up these stones, which I command you today, on Mount Ebal, and you shall coat them with plaster.\n'),
	(5591, 5, 27, 5, 'There you shall build an altar to Yahweh your God, an altar of stones. You shall not use any iron tool on them.\n'),
	(5592, 5, 27, 6, 'You shall build Yahweh your God’s altar of uncut stones. You shall offer burnt offerings on it to Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5593, 5, 27, 7, 'You shall sacrifice peace offerings, and shall eat there. You shall rejoice before Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5594, 5, 27, 8, 'You shall write on the stones all the words of this law very plainly.”\n'),
	(5595, 5, 27, 9, 'Moses and the priests the Levites spoke to all Israel, saying, “Be silent, and listen, Israel! Today you have become the people of Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5596, 5, 27, 10, 'You shall therefore obey Yahweh your God’s voice, and do his commandments and his statutes, which I command you today.”\n'),
	(5597, 5, 27, 11, 'Moses commanded the people the same day, saying,\n'),
	(5598, 5, 27, 12, '“These shall stand on Mount Gerizim to bless the people, when you have crossed over the Jordan: Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, Joseph, and Benjamin.\n'),
	(5599, 5, 27, 13, 'These shall stand on Mount Ebal for the curse: Reuben, Gad, Asher, Zebulun, Dan, and Naphtali.\n'),
	(5600, 5, 27, 14, 'With a loud voice, the Levites shall say to all the men of Israel,\n'),
	(5601, 5, 27, 15, '‘Cursed is the man who makes an engraved or molten image, an abomination to Yahweh, the work of the hands of the craftsman, and sets it up in secret.’\nAll the people shall answer and say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5602, 5, 27, 16, '‘Cursed is he who dishonors his father or his mother.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5603, 5, 27, 17, '‘Cursed is he who removes his neighbor’s landmark.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5604, 5, 27, 18, '‘Cursed is he who leads the blind astray on the road.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5605, 5, 27, 19, '‘Cursed is he who withholds justice from the foreigner, fatherless, and widow.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5606, 5, 27, 20, '‘Cursed is he who lies with his father’s wife, because he dishonors his father’s bed.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5607, 5, 27, 21, '‘Cursed is he who lies with any kind of animal.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5608, 5, 27, 22, '‘Cursed is he who lies with his sister, his father’s daughter or his mother’s daughter.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5609, 5, 27, 23, '‘Cursed is he who lies with his mother-in-law.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5610, 5, 27, 24, '‘Cursed is he who secretly kills his neighbor.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5611, 5, 27, 25, '‘Cursed is he who takes a bribe to kill an innocent person.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’\n'),
	(5612, 5, 27, 26, '‘Cursed is he who doesn’t uphold the words of this law by doing them.’\nAll the people shall say, ‘Amen.’”\n'),
	(5613, 5, 28, 1, 'It shall happen, if you shall listen diligently to Yahweh your God’s voice, to observe to do all his commandments which I command you today, that Yahweh your God will set you high above all the nations of the earth.\n'),
	(5614, 5, 28, 2, 'All these blessings will come upon you, and overtake you, if you listen to Yahweh your God’s voice.\n'),
	(5615, 5, 28, 3, 'You shall be blessed in the city, and you shall be blessed in the field.\n'),
	(5616, 5, 28, 4, 'You shall be blessed in the fruit of your body, the fruit of your ground, the fruit of your animals, the increase of your livestock, and the young of your flock.\n'),
	(5617, 5, 28, 5, 'Your basket and your kneading trough shall be blessed.\n'),
	(5618, 5, 28, 6, 'You shall be blessed when you come in, and you shall be blessed when you go out.\n'),
	(5619, 5, 28, 7, 'Yahweh will cause your enemies who rise up against you to be struck before you. They will come out against you one way, and will flee before you seven ways.\n'),
	(5620, 5, 28, 8, 'Yahweh will command the blessing on you in your barns, and in all that you put your hand to. He will bless you in the land which Yahweh your God gives you.\n'),
	(5621, 5, 28, 9, 'Yahweh will establish you for a holy people to himself, as he has sworn to you, if you shall keep the commandments of Yahweh your God, and walk in his ways.\n'),
	(5622, 5, 28, 10, 'All the peoples of the earth shall see that you are called by Yahweh’s name, and they will be afraid of you.\n'),
	(5623, 5, 28, 11, 'Yahweh will grant you abundant prosperity, in the fruit of your body, in the fruit of your livestock, and in the fruit of your ground, in the land which Yahweh swore to your fathers to give you.\n'),
	(5624, 5, 28, 12, 'Yahweh will open to you his good treasure in the sky, to give the rain of your land in its season, and to bless all the work of your hand. You will lend to many nations, and you will not borrow.\n'),
	(5625, 5, 28, 13, 'Yahweh will make you the head, and not the tail. You will be above only, and you will not be beneath; if you listen to the commandments of Yahweh your God, which I command you today, to observe and to do,\n'),
	(5626, 5, 28, 14, 'and shall not turn away from any of the words which I command you today, to the right hand, or to the left, to go after other gods to serve them.\n'),
	(5627, 5, 28, 15, 'But it shall come to pass, if you will not listen to Yahweh your God’s voice, to observe to do all his commandments and his statutes which I command you today, that all these curses will come on you, and overtake you.\n'),
	(5628, 5, 28, 16, 'You will be cursed in the city, and you will be cursed in the field.\n'),
	(5629, 5, 28, 17, 'Your basket and your kneading trough will be cursed.\n'),
	(5630, 5, 28, 18, 'The fruit of your body, the fruit of your ground, the increase of your livestock, and the young of your flock will be cursed.\n'),
	(5631, 5, 28, 19, 'You will be cursed when you come in, and you will be cursed when you go out.\n'),
	(5632, 5, 28, 20, 'Yahweh will send on you cursing, confusion, and rebuke, in all that you put your hand to do, until you are destroyed, and until you perish quickly; because of the evil of your doings, by which you have forsaken me.\n'),
	(5633, 5, 28, 21, 'Yahweh will make the pestilence cling to you, until he has consumed you from off the land, where you go in to possess it.\n'),
	(5634, 5, 28, 22, 'Yahweh will strike you with consumption, with fever, with inflammation, with fiery heat, with the sword, with blight, and with mildew. They will pursue you until you perish.\n'),
	(5635, 5, 28, 23, 'Your sky that is over your head will be brass, and the earth that is under you will be iron.\n'),
	(5636, 5, 28, 24, 'Yahweh will make the rain of your land powder and dust. It will come down on you from the sky, until you are destroyed.\n'),
	(5637, 5, 28, 25, 'Yahweh will cause you to be struck before your enemies. You will go out one way against them, and will flee seven ways before them. You will be tossed back and forth among all the kingdoms of the earth.\n'),
	(5638, 5, 28, 26, 'Your dead body will be food to all birds of the sky, and to the animals of the earth; and there will be no one to frighten them away.\n'),
	(5639, 5, 28, 27, 'Yahweh will strike you with the boils of Egypt, with the tumors, with the scurvy, and with the itch, of which you can not be healed.\n'),
	(5640, 5, 28, 28, 'Yahweh will strike you with madness, with blindness, and with astonishment of heart.\n'),
	(5641, 5, 28, 29, 'You will grope at noonday, as the blind gropes in darkness, and you shall not prosper in your ways. You will only be oppressed and robbed always, and there will be no one to save you.\n'),
	(5642, 5, 28, 30, 'You will betroth a wife, and another man shall lie with her. You will build a house, and you won’t dwell in it. You will plant a vineyard, and not use its fruit.\n'),
	(5643, 5, 28, 31, 'Your ox will be slain before your eyes, and you will not eat any of it. Your donkey will be violently taken away from before your face, and will not be restored to you. Your sheep will be given to your enemies, and you will have no one to save you.\n'),
	(5644, 5, 28, 32, 'Your sons and your daughters will be given to another people. Your eyes will look, and fail with longing for them all day long. There will be no power in your hand.\n'),
	(5645, 5, 28, 33, 'A nation which you don’t know will eat the fruit of your ground and all of your work. You will only be oppressed and crushed always;\n'),
	(5646, 5, 28, 34, 'so that the sights that you see with your eyes will drive you mad.\n'),
	(5647, 5, 28, 35, 'Yahweh will strike you in the knees and in the legs with a sore boil, of which you can not be healed, from the sole of your foot to the crown of your head.\n'),
	(5648, 5, 28, 36, 'Yahweh will bring you, and your king whom you will set over yourselves, to a nation that you have not known, you nor your fathers. There you will serve other gods of wood and stone.\n'),
	(5649, 5, 28, 37, 'You will become an astonishment, a proverb, and a byword among all the peoples where Yahweh will lead you away.\n'),
	(5650, 5, 28, 38, 'You will carry much seed out into the field, and will gather little in; for the locust will consume it.\n'),
	(5651, 5, 28, 39, 'You will plant vineyards and dress them, but you will neither drink of the wine, nor harvest, because worms will eat them.\n'),
	(5652, 5, 28, 40, 'You will have olive trees throughout all your borders, but you won’t anoint yourself with the oil; for your olives will drop off.\n'),
	(5653, 5, 28, 41, 'You will father sons and daughters, but they will not be yours; for they will go into captivity.\n'),
	(5654, 5, 28, 42, 'Locusts will consume all of your trees and the fruit of your ground.\n'),
	(5655, 5, 28, 43, 'The foreigner who is among you will mount up above you higher and higher, and you will come down lower and lower.\n'),
	(5656, 5, 28, 44, 'He will lend to you, and you won’t lend to him. He will be the head, and you will be the tail.\n'),
	(5657, 5, 28, 45, 'All these curses will come on you, and will pursue you, and overtake you, until you are destroyed; because you didn’t listen to Yahweh your God’s voice, to keep his commandments and his statutes which he commanded you.\n'),
	(5658, 5, 28, 46, 'They will be for a sign and for a wonder to you and to your offspring forever.\n'),
	(5659, 5, 28, 47, 'Because you didn’t serve Yahweh your God with joyfulness, and with gladness of heart, by reason of the abundance of all things;\n'),
	(5660, 5, 28, 48, 'therefore you will serve your enemies whom Yahweh sends against you, in hunger, in thirst, in nakedness, and in lack of all things. He will put an iron yoke on your neck, until he has destroyed you.\n'),
	(5661, 5, 28, 49, 'Yahweh will bring a nation against you from far, from the end of the earth, as the eagle flies; a nation whose language you will not understand;\n'),
	(5662, 5, 28, 50, 'a nation of fierce facial expressions, that doesn’t respect the elderly, nor show favor to the young,\n'),
	(5663, 5, 28, 51, 'and they will eat the fruit of your livestock, and the fruit of your ground, until you are destroyed. They also won’t leave you grain, new wine, or oil, the increase of your livestock, or the young of your flock, until they have caused you to perish.\n'),
	(5664, 5, 28, 52, 'They will besiege you in all your gates, until your high and fortified walls come down, in which you trusted, throughout all your land. They will besiege you in all your gates throughout all your land, which Yahweh your God has given you.\n'),
	(5665, 5, 28, 53, 'You will eat the fruit of your own body, the flesh of your sons and of your daughters, whom Yahweh your God has given you, in the siege and in the distress with which your enemies will distress you.\n'),
	(5666, 5, 28, 54, 'The man who is tender among you, and very delicate, his eye will be evil toward his brother, toward the wife whom he loves, and toward the remnant of his children whom he has remaining;\n'),
	(5667, 5, 28, 55, 'so that he will not give to any of them of the flesh of his children whom he will eat, because he has nothing left to him, in the siege and in the distress with which your enemy will distress you in all your gates.\n'),
	(5668, 5, 28, 56, 'The tender and delicate woman among you, who would not venture to set the sole of her foot on the ground for delicateness and tenderness, her eye will be evil toward the husband that she loves, toward her son, toward her daughter,\n'),
	(5669, 5, 28, 57, 'toward her young one who comes out from between her feet, and toward her children whom she bears; for she will eat them secretly for lack of all things, in the siege and in the distress with which your enemy will distress you in your gates.\n'),
	(5670, 5, 28, 58, 'If you will not observe to do all the words of this law that are written in this book, that you may fear this glorious and fearful name, YAHWEH YOUR GOD;\n'),
	(5671, 5, 28, 59, 'then Yahweh will make your plagues fearful, and the plagues of your offspring, even great plagues, and of long duration, and severe sicknesses, and of long duration.\n'),
	(5672, 5, 28, 60, 'He will bring on you again all the diseases of Egypt, which you were afraid of; and they will cling to you.\n'),
	(5673, 5, 28, 61, 'Also every sickness and every plague, which is not written in the book of this law, Yahweh will bring them on you, until you are destroyed.\n'),
	(5674, 5, 28, 62, 'You will be left few in number, even though you were as the stars of the sky for multitude; because you didn’t listen to Yahweh your God’s voice.\n'),
	(5675, 5, 28, 63, 'It will happen that as Yahweh rejoiced over you to do you good, and to multiply you, so Yahweh will rejoice over you to cause you to perish, and to destroy you. You will be plucked from the land that you are going in to possess.\n'),
	(5676, 5, 28, 64, 'Yahweh will scatter you among all peoples, from one end of the earth to the other end of the earth. There you will serve other gods, which you have not known, you nor your fathers, even wood and stone.\n'),
	(5677, 5, 28, 65, 'Among these nations you will find no ease, and there will be no rest for the sole of your foot; but Yahweh will give you there a trembling heart, failing of eyes, and pining of soul.\n'),
	(5678, 5, 28, 66, 'Your life will hang in doubt before you. You will be afraid night and day, and will have no assurance of your life.\n'),
	(5679, 5, 28, 67, 'In the morning you will say, “I wish it were evening!” and at evening you will say, “I wish it were morning!” for the fear of your heart which you will fear, and for the sights which your eyes will see.\n'),
	(5680, 5, 28, 68, 'Yahweh will bring you into Egypt again with ships, by the way of which I told to you that you would never see it again. There you will sell yourselves to your enemies for male and female slaves, and nobody will buy you.\n'),
	(5681, 5, 29, 1, 'These are the words of the covenant which Yahweh commanded Moses to make with the children of Israel in the land of Moab, in addition to the covenant which he made with them in Horeb.\n'),
	(5682, 5, 29, 2, 'Moses called to all Israel, and said to them:\nYour eyes have seen all that Yahweh did in the land of Egypt to Pharaoh, and to all his servants, and to all his land;\n'),
	(5683, 5, 29, 3, 'the great trials which your eyes saw, the signs, and those great wonders.\n'),
	(5684, 5, 29, 4, 'But Yahweh has not given you a heart to know, eyes to see, and ears to hear, to this day.\n'),
	(5685, 5, 29, 5, 'I have led you forty years in the wilderness. Your clothes have not grown old on you, and your shoes have not grown old on your feet.\n'),
	(5686, 5, 29, 6, 'You have not eaten bread, neither have you drunk wine or strong drink; that you may know that I am Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(5687, 5, 29, 7, 'When you came to this place, Sihon the king of Heshbon, and Og the king of Bashan, came out against us to battle, and we struck them.\n'),
	(5688, 5, 29, 8, 'We took their land, and gave it for an inheritance to the Reubenites, and to the Gadites, and to the half-tribe of the Manassites.\n'),
	(5689, 5, 29, 9, 'Therefore keep the words of this covenant and do them, that you may prosper in all that you do.\n'),
	(5690, 5, 29, 10, 'All of you stand today in the presence of Yahweh your God; your heads, your tribes, your elders, and your officers, even all the men of Israel,\n'),
	(5691, 5, 29, 11, 'your little ones, your wives, and the foreigners who are in the middle of your camps, from the one who cuts your wood to the one who draws your water;\n'),
	(5692, 5, 29, 12, 'that you may enter into the covenant of Yahweh your God, and into his oath, which Yahweh your God makes with you today;\n'),
	(5693, 5, 29, 13, 'that he may establish you today as his people, and that he may be your God, as he spoke to you, and as he swore to your fathers, to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob.\n'),
	(5694, 5, 29, 14, 'Neither do I make this covenant and this oath with you only,\n'),
	(5695, 5, 29, 15, 'but with those who stand here with us today before Yahweh our God, and also with those who are not here with us today\n'),
	(5696, 5, 29, 16, '(for you know how we lived in the land of Egypt, and how we came through the middle of the nations through which you passed;\n'),
	(5697, 5, 29, 17, 'and you have seen their abominations, and their idols, wood and stone, silver and gold, which were among them);\n'),
	(5698, 5, 29, 18, 'lest there should be among you man, woman, family, or tribe whose heart turns away today from Yahweh our God, to go to serve the gods of those nations; lest there should be among you a root that produces bitter poison;\n'),
	(5699, 5, 29, 19, 'and it happen, when he hears the words of this curse, that he bless himself in his heart, saying, “I shall have peace, though I walk in the stubbornness of my heart, to destroy the moist with the dry.”\n'),
	(5700, 5, 29, 20, 'Yahweh will not pardon him, but then Yahweh’s anger and his jealousy will smoke against that man, and all the curse that is written in this book will fall on him, and Yahweh will blot out his name from under the sky.\n'),
	(5701, 5, 29, 21, 'Yahweh will set him apart for evil out of all the tribes of Israel, according to all the curses of the covenant that is written in this book of the law.\n'),
	(5702, 5, 29, 22, 'The generation to come, your children who will rise up after you, and the foreigner who will come from a far land, will say, when they see the plagues of that land, and the sicknesses with which Yahweh has made it sick;\n'),
	(5703, 5, 29, 23, 'and that all of its land is sulfur, salt, and burning, that it is not sown, doesn’t produce, nor does any grass grow in it, like the overthrow of Sodom, Gomorrah, Admah, and Zeboiim, which Yahweh overthrew in his anger, and in his wrath;\n'),
	(5704, 5, 29, 24, 'even all the nations will say, “Why has Yahweh done thus to this land? What does the heat of this great anger mean?”\n'),
	(5705, 5, 29, 25, 'Then men will say, “Because they abandoned the covenant of Yahweh, the God of their fathers, which he made with them when he brought them out of the land of Egypt,\n'),
	(5706, 5, 29, 26, 'and went and served other gods, and worshiped them, gods that they didn’t know, and that he had not given to them.\n'),
	(5707, 5, 29, 27, 'Therefore Yahweh’s anger burned against this land, to bring on it all the curses that are written in this book.\n'),
	(5708, 5, 29, 28, 'Yahweh rooted them out of their land in anger, in wrath, and in great indignation, and thrust them into another land, as it is today.”\n'),
	(5709, 5, 29, 29, 'The secret things belong to Yahweh our God; but the things that are revealed belong to us and to our children forever, that we may do all the words of this law.\n'),
	(5710, 5, 30, 1, 'It shall happen, when all these things have come on you, the blessing and the curse, which I have set before you, and you shall call them to mind among all the nations, where Yahweh your God has driven you,\n'),
	(5711, 5, 30, 2, 'and return to Yahweh your God, and obey his voice according to all that I command you today, you and your children, with all your heart, and with all your soul;\n'),
	(5712, 5, 30, 3, 'that then Yahweh your God will release you from captivity, have compassion on you, and will return and gather you from all the peoples where Yahweh your God has scattered you.\n'),
	(5713, 5, 30, 4, 'If your outcasts are in the uttermost parts of the heavens, from there Yahweh your God will gather you, and from there he will bring you back.\n'),
	(5714, 5, 30, 5, 'Yahweh your God will bring you into the land which your fathers possessed, and you will possess it. He will do you good, and increase your numbers more than your fathers.\n'),
	(5715, 5, 30, 6, 'Yahweh your God will circumcise your heart, and the heart of your offspring, to love Yahweh your God with all your heart, and with all your soul, that you may live.\n'),
	(5716, 5, 30, 7, 'Yahweh your God will put all these curses on your enemies, and on those who hate you, who persecuted you.\n'),
	(5717, 5, 30, 8, 'You shall return and obey Yahweh’s voice, and do all his commandments which I command you today.\n'),
	(5718, 5, 30, 9, 'Yahweh your God will make you plenteous in all the work of your hand, in the fruit of your body, in the fruit of your livestock, and in the fruit of your ground, for good; for Yahweh will again rejoice over you for good, as he rejoiced over your fathers;\n'),
	(5719, 5, 30, 10, 'if you will obey Yahweh your God’s voice, to keep his commandments and his statutes which are written in this book of the law; if you turn to Yahweh your God with all your heart, and with all your soul.\n'),
	(5720, 5, 30, 11, 'For this commandment which I command you today is not too hard for you or too distant.\n'),
	(5721, 5, 30, 12, 'It is not in heaven, that you should say, “Who will go up for us to heaven, and bring it to us, and proclaim it to us, that we may do it?”\n'),
	(5722, 5, 30, 13, 'Neither is it beyond the sea, that you should say, “Who will go over the sea for us, and bring it to us, and proclaim it to us, that we may do it?”\n'),
	(5723, 5, 30, 14, 'But the word is very near to you, in your mouth and in your heart, that you may do it.\n'),
	(5724, 5, 30, 15, 'Behold, I have set before you today life and prosperity, and death and evil.\n'),
	(5725, 5, 30, 16, 'For I command you today to love Yahweh your God, to walk in his ways, and to keep his commandments, his statutes, and his ordinances, that you may live and multiply, and that Yahweh your God may bless you in the land where you go in to possess it.\n'),
	(5726, 5, 30, 17, 'But if your heart turns away, and you will not hear, but are drawn away, and worship other gods, and serve them;\n'),
	(5727, 5, 30, 18, 'I denounce to you today, that you will surely perish. You will not prolong your days in the land where you pass over the Jordan to go in to possess it.\n'),
	(5728, 5, 30, 19, 'I call heaven and earth to witness against you today, that I have set before you life and death, the blessing and the curse. Therefore choose life, that you may live, you and your descendants;\n'),
	(5729, 5, 30, 20, 'to love Yahweh your God, to obey his voice, and to cling to him; for he is your life, and the length of your days; that you may dwell in the land which Yahweh swore to your fathers, to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob, to give them.\n'),
	(5730, 5, 31, 1, 'Moses went and spoke these words to all Israel.\n'),
	(5731, 5, 31, 2, 'He said to them, “I am one hundred twenty years old today. I can no more go out and come in. Yahweh has said to me, ‘You shall not go over this Jordan.’\n'),
	(5732, 5, 31, 3, 'Yahweh your God himself will go over before you. He will destroy these nations from before you, and you shall dispossess them. Joshua will go over before you, as Yahweh has spoken.\n'),
	(5733, 5, 31, 4, 'Yahweh will do to them as he did to Sihon and to Og, the kings of the Amorites, and to their land; whom he destroyed.\n'),
	(5734, 5, 31, 5, 'Yahweh will deliver them up before you, and you shall do to them according to all the commandment which I have commanded you.\n'),
	(5735, 5, 31, 6, 'Be strong and courageous. Don’t be afraid or scared of them; for Yahweh your God himself is who goes with you. He will not fail you nor forsake you.”\n'),
	(5736, 5, 31, 7, 'Moses called to Joshua, and said to him in the sight of all Israel, “Be strong and courageous, for you shall go with this people into the land which Yahweh has sworn to their fathers to give them; and you shall cause them to inherit it.\n'),
	(5737, 5, 31, 8, 'Yahweh himself is who goes before you. He will be with you. He will not fail you nor forsake you. Don’t be afraid. Don’t be discouraged.”\n'),
	(5738, 5, 31, 9, 'Moses wrote this law, and delivered it to the priests the sons of Levi, who bore the ark of Yahweh’s covenant, and to all the elders of Israel.\n'),
	(5739, 5, 31, 10, 'Moses commanded them, saying, “At the end of every seven years, in the set time of the year of release, in the feast of tents,\n'),
	(5740, 5, 31, 11, 'when all Israel has come to appear before Yahweh your God in the place which he will choose, you shall read this law before all Israel in their hearing.\n'),
	(5741, 5, 31, 12, 'Assemble the people, the men and the women and the little ones, and the foreigners who are within your gates, that they may hear, and that they may learn, and fear Yahweh your God, and observe to do all the words of this law;\n'),
	(5742, 5, 31, 13, 'and that their children, who have not known, may hear, and learn to fear Yahweh your God, as long as you live in the land where you go over the Jordan to possess it.”\n'),
	(5743, 5, 31, 14, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Behold, your days approach that you must die. Call Joshua, and present yourselves in the Tent of Meeting, that I may commission him.”\nMoses and Joshua went, and presented themselves in the Tent of Meeting.\n'),
	(5744, 5, 31, 15, 'Yahweh appeared in the Tent in a pillar of cloud, and the pillar of cloud stood over the Tent’s door.\n'),
	(5745, 5, 31, 16, 'Yahweh said to Moses, “Behold, you shall sleep with your fathers. This people will rise up, and play the prostitute after the strange gods of the land, where they go to be among them, and will forsake me, and break my covenant which I have made with them.\n'),
	(5746, 5, 31, 17, 'Then my anger shall be kindled against them in that day, and I will forsake them, and I will hide my face from them, and they shall be devoured, and many evils and troubles shall come on them; so that they will say in that day, ‘Haven’t these evils come on us because our God is not among us?’\n'),
	(5747, 5, 31, 18, 'I will surely hide my face in that day for all the evil which they have done, in that they have turned to other gods.\n'),
	(5748, 5, 31, 19, '“Now therefore write this song for yourselves, and teach it to the children of Israel. Put it in their mouths, that this song may be a witness for me against the children of Israel.\n'),
	(5749, 5, 31, 20, 'For when I have brought them into the land which I swore to their fathers, flowing with milk and honey, and they have eaten and filled themselves, and grown fat; then they will turn to other gods, and serve them, and despise me, and break my covenant.\n'),
	(5750, 5, 31, 21, 'It will happen, when many evils and troubles have come on them, that this song will testify before them as a witness; for it will not be forgotten out of the mouths of their descendants; for I know their ways and what they are doing today, before I have brought them into the land which I swore.”\n'),
	(5751, 5, 31, 22, 'So Moses wrote this song the same day, and taught it to the children of Israel.\n'),
	(5752, 5, 31, 23, 'He commissioned Joshua the son of Nun, and said, “Be strong and courageous; for you shall bring the children of Israel into the land which I swore to them. I will be with you.”\n'),
	(5753, 5, 31, 24, 'When Moses had finished writing the words of this law in a book, until they were finished,\n'),
	(5754, 5, 31, 25, 'Moses commanded the Levites, who bore the ark of Yahweh’s covenant, saying,\n'),
	(5755, 5, 31, 26, '“Take this book of the law, and put it by the side of the ark of Yahweh your God’s covenant, that it may be there for a witness against you.\n'),
	(5756, 5, 31, 27, 'For I know your rebellion, and your stiff neck. Behold, while I am yet alive with you today, you have been rebellious against Yahweh. How much more after my death?\n'),
	(5757, 5, 31, 28, 'Assemble to me all the elders of your tribes, and your officers, that I may speak these words in their ears, and call heaven and earth to witness against them.\n'),
	(5758, 5, 31, 29, 'For I know that after my death you will utterly corrupt yourselves, and turn away from the way which I have commanded you; and evil will happen to you in the latter days; because you will do that which is evil in Yahweh’s sight, to provoke him to anger through the work of your hands.”\n'),
	(5759, 5, 31, 30, 'Moses spoke in the ears of all the assembly of Israel the words of this song, until they were finished.\n'),
	(5760, 5, 32, 1, 'Give ear, you heavens, and I will speak.\nLet the earth hear the words of my mouth.\n'),
	(5761, 5, 32, 2, 'My doctrine will drop as the rain.\nMy speech will condense as the dew,\nas the misty rain on the tender grass,\nas the showers on the herb.\n'),
	(5762, 5, 32, 3, 'For I will proclaim Yahweh’s name.\nAscribe greatness to our God!\n'),
	(5763, 5, 32, 4, 'The Rock, his work is perfect,\nfor all his ways are just.\nA God of faithfulness who does no wrong,\njust and right is he.\n'),
	(5764, 5, 32, 5, 'They have dealt corruptly with him.\nThey are not his children, because of their defect.\nThey are a perverse and crooked generation.\n'),
	(5765, 5, 32, 6, 'Is this the way you repay Yahweh,\nfoolish and unwise people?\nIsn’t he your father who has bought you?\nHe has made you and established you.\n'),
	(5766, 5, 32, 7, 'Remember the days of old.\nConsider the years of many generations.\nAsk your father, and he will show you;\nyour elders, and they will tell you.\n'),
	(5767, 5, 32, 8, 'When the Most High gave to the nations their inheritance,\nwhen he separated the children of men,\nhe set the bounds of the peoples\naccording to the number of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(5768, 5, 32, 9, 'For Yahweh’s portion is his people.\nJacob is the lot of his inheritance.\n'),
	(5769, 5, 32, 10, 'He found him in a desert land,\nin the waste howling wilderness.\nHe surrounded him.\nHe cared for him.\nHe kept him as the apple of his eye.\n'),
	(5770, 5, 32, 11, 'As an eagle that stirs up her nest,\nthat flutters over her young,\nhe spread abroad his wings,\nhe took them,\nhe bore them on his feathers.\n'),
	(5771, 5, 32, 12, 'Yahweh alone led him.\nThere was no foreign god with him.\n'),
	(5772, 5, 32, 13, 'He made him ride on the high places of the earth.\nHe ate the increase of the field.\nHe caused him to suck honey out of the rock,\noil out of the flinty rock;\n'),
	(5773, 5, 32, 14, 'butter from the herd, and milk from the flock,\nwith fat of lambs,\nrams of the breed of Bashan, and goats,\nwith the finest of the wheat.\nFrom the blood of the grape, you drank wine.\n'),
	(5774, 5, 32, 15, 'But Jeshurun grew fat, and kicked.\nYou have grown fat.\nYou have grown thick.\nYou have become sleek.\nThen he abandoned God who made him,\nand rejected the Rock of his salvation.\n'),
	(5775, 5, 32, 16, 'They moved him to jealousy with strange gods.\nThey provoked him to anger with abominations.\n'),
	(5776, 5, 32, 17, 'They sacrificed to demons, not God,\nto gods that they didn’t know,\nto new gods that came up recently,\nwhich your fathers didn’t dread.\n'),
	(5777, 5, 32, 18, 'Of the Rock who became your father, you are unmindful,\nand have forgotten God who gave you birth.\n'),
	(5778, 5, 32, 19, 'Yahweh saw and abhorred,\nbecause of the provocation of his sons and his daughters.\n'),
	(5779, 5, 32, 20, 'He said, “I will hide my face from them.\nI will see what their end will be;\nfor they are a very perverse generation,\nchildren in whom is no faithfulness.\n'),
	(5780, 5, 32, 21, 'They have moved me to jealousy with that which is not God.\nThey have provoked me to anger with their vanities.\nI will move them to jealousy with those who are not a people.\nI will provoke them to anger with a foolish nation.\n'),
	(5781, 5, 32, 22, 'For a fire is kindled in my anger,\nthat burns to the lowest Sheol,\ndevours the earth with its increase,\nand sets the foundations of the mountains on fire.\n'),
	(5782, 5, 32, 23, '“I will heap evils on them.\nI will spend my arrows on them.\n'),
	(5783, 5, 32, 24, 'They shall be wasted with hunger,\nand devoured with burning heat\nand bitter destruction.\nI will send the teeth of animals on them,\nwith the venom of vipers that glide in the dust.\n'),
	(5784, 5, 32, 25, 'Outside the sword will bereave,\nand in the rooms, terror;\non both young man and virgin,\nthe nursing infant with the gray-haired man.\n'),
	(5785, 5, 32, 26, 'I said that I would scatter them afar.\nI would make their memory to cease from among men;\n'),
	(5786, 5, 32, 27, 'were it not that I feared the provocation of the enemy,\nlest their adversaries should judge wrongly,\nlest they should say, ‘Our hand is exalted,\nYahweh has not done all this.’”\n'),
	(5787, 5, 32, 28, 'For they are a nation void of counsel.\nThere is no understanding in them.\n'),
	(5788, 5, 32, 29, 'Oh that they were wise, that they understood this,\nthat they would consider their latter end!\n'),
	(5789, 5, 32, 30, 'How could one chase a thousand,\nand two put ten thousand to flight,\nunless their Rock had sold them,\nand Yahweh had delivered them up?\n'),
	(5790, 5, 32, 31, 'For their rock is not as our Rock,\neven our enemies themselves concede.\n'),
	(5791, 5, 32, 32, 'For their vine is of the vine of Sodom,\nof the fields of Gomorrah.\nTheir grapes are poison grapes.\nTheir clusters are bitter.\n'),
	(5792, 5, 32, 33, 'Their wine is the poison of serpents,\nthe cruel venom of asps.\n'),
	(5793, 5, 32, 34, '“Isn’t this laid up in store with me,\nsealed up among my treasures?\n'),
	(5794, 5, 32, 35, 'Vengeance is mine, and recompense,\nat the time when their foot slides;\nfor the day of their calamity is at hand.\nTheir doom rushes at them.”\n'),
	(5795, 5, 32, 36, 'For Yahweh will judge his people,\nand have compassion on his servants,\nwhen he sees that their power is gone;\nthat there is no one remaining, shut up or left at large.\n'),
	(5796, 5, 32, 37, 'He will say, “Where are their gods,\nthe rock in which they took refuge;\n'),
	(5797, 5, 32, 38, 'which ate the fat of their sacrifices,\nand drank the wine of their drink offering?\nLet them rise up and help you!\nLet them be your protection.\n'),
	(5798, 5, 32, 39, '“See now that I myself am he.\nThere is no god with me.\nI kill and I make alive.\nI wound and I heal.\nThere is no one who can deliver out of my hand.\n'),
	(5799, 5, 32, 40, 'For I lift up my hand to heaven and declare,\nas I live forever,\n'),
	(5800, 5, 32, 41, 'if I sharpen my glittering sword,\nmy hand grasps it in judgment;\nI will take vengeance on my adversaries,\nand will repay those who hate me.\n'),
	(5801, 5, 32, 42, 'I will make my arrows drunk with blood.\nMy sword shall devour flesh with the blood of the slain and the captives,\nfrom the head of the leaders of the enemy.”\n'),
	(5802, 5, 32, 43, 'Rejoice, you nations, with his people,\nfor he will avenge the blood of his servants.\nHe will take vengeance on his adversaries,\nand will make atonement for his land and for his people.\n'),
	(5803, 5, 32, 44, 'Moses came and spoke all the words of this song in the ears of the people, he and Joshua the son of Nun.\n'),
	(5804, 5, 32, 45, 'Moses finished reciting all these words to all Israel.\n'),
	(5805, 5, 32, 46, 'He said to them, “Set your heart to all the words which I testify to you today, which you shall command your children to observe to do, all the words of this law.\n'),
	(5806, 5, 32, 47, 'For it is no vain thing for you; because it is your life, and through this thing you shall prolong your days in the land, where you go over the Jordan to possess it.”\n'),
	(5807, 5, 32, 48, 'Yahweh spoke to Moses that same day, saying,\n'),
	(5808, 5, 32, 49, '“Go up into this mountain of Abarim, to Mount Nebo, which is in the land of Moab, that is across from Jericho; and see the land of Canaan, which I give to the children of Israel for a possession.\n'),
	(5809, 5, 32, 50, 'Die on the mountain where you go up, and be gathered to your people, as Aaron your brother died on Mount Hor, and was gathered to his people;\n'),
	(5810, 5, 32, 51, 'because you trespassed against me among the children of Israel at the waters of Meribah of Kadesh, in the wilderness of Zin; because you didn’t uphold my holiness among the children of Israel.\n'),
	(5811, 5, 32, 52, 'For you shall see the land from a distance; but you shall not go there into the land which I give the children of Israel.”\n'),
	(5812, 5, 33, 1, 'This is the blessing with which Moses the man of God blessed the children of Israel before his death.\n'),
	(5813, 5, 33, 2, 'He said,\n“Yahweh came from Sinai,\nand rose from Seir to them.\nHe shone from Mount Paran.\nHe came from the ten thousands of holy ones.\nAt his right hand was a fiery law for them.\n'),
	(5814, 5, 33, 3, 'Yes, he loves the people.\nAll his saints are in your hand.\nThey sat down at your feet.\nEach receives your words.\n'),
	(5815, 5, 33, 4, 'Moses commanded us a law,\nan inheritance for the assembly of Jacob.\n'),
	(5816, 5, 33, 5, 'He was king in Jeshurun,\nwhen the heads of the people were gathered,\nall the tribes of Israel together.\n'),
	(5817, 5, 33, 6, '“Let Reuben live, and not die;\nNor let his men be few.”\n'),
	(5818, 5, 33, 7, 'This is for Judah. He said,\n“Hear, Yahweh, the voice of Judah.\nBring him in to his people.\nWith his hands he contended for himself.\nYou shall be a help against his adversaries.”\n'),
	(5819, 5, 33, 8, 'About Levi he said,\n“Your Thummim and your Urim are with your godly one,\nwhom you proved at Massah,\nwith whom you contended at the waters of Meribah.\n'),
	(5820, 5, 33, 9, 'He said of his father, and of his mother, ‘I have not seen him.’\nHe didn’t acknowledge his brothers,\nnor did he know his own children;\nfor they have observed your word,\nand keep your covenant.\n'),
	(5821, 5, 33, 10, 'They shall teach Jacob your ordinances,\nand Israel your law.\nThey shall put incense before you,\nand whole burnt offering on your altar.\n'),
	(5822, 5, 33, 11, 'Yahweh, bless his skills.\nAccept the work of his hands.\nStrike through the hips of those who rise up against him,\nof those who hate him, that they not rise again.”\n'),
	(5823, 5, 33, 12, 'About Benjamin he said,\n“The beloved of Yahweh will dwell in safety by him.\nHe covers him all day long.\nHe dwells between his shoulders.”\n'),
	(5824, 5, 33, 13, 'About Joseph he said,\n“His land is blessed by Yahweh,\nfor the precious things of the heavens, for the dew,\nfor the deep that couches beneath,\n'),
	(5825, 5, 33, 14, 'for the precious things of the fruits of the sun,\nfor the precious things that the moon can yield,\n'),
	(5826, 5, 33, 15, 'for the best things of the ancient mountains,\nfor the precious things of the everlasting hills,\n'),
	(5827, 5, 33, 16, 'for the precious things of the earth and its fullness,\nthe good will of him who lived in the bush.\nLet this come on the head of Joseph,\non the crown of the head of him who was separated from his brothers.\n'),
	(5828, 5, 33, 17, 'The firstborn of his herd, majesty is his.\nHis horns are the horns of the wild ox.\nWith them he will push all the peoples, to the ends of the earth.\nThey are the ten thousands of Ephraim.\nThey are the thousands of Manasseh.”\n'),
	(5829, 5, 33, 18, 'About Zebulun he said,\n“Rejoice, Zebulun, in your going out;\nand Issachar, in your tents.\n'),
	(5830, 5, 33, 19, 'They will call the peoples to the mountain.\nThere they will offer sacrifices of righteousness,\nfor they will draw out the abundance of the seas,\nthe hidden treasures of the sand.”\n'),
	(5831, 5, 33, 20, 'About Gad he said,\n“He who enlarges Gad is blessed.\nHe dwells as a lioness,\nand tears the arm, yes, the crown of the head.\n'),
	(5832, 5, 33, 21, 'He provided the first part for himself,\nfor the lawgiver’s portion reserved was reserved for him.\nHe came with the heads of the people.\nHe executed the righteousness of Yahweh,\nHis ordinances with Israel.”\n'),
	(5833, 5, 33, 22, 'About Dan he said,\n“Dan is a lion’s cub\nthat leaps out of Bashan.”\n'),
	(5834, 5, 33, 23, 'About Naphtali he said,\n“Naphtali, satisfied with favor,\nfull of Yahweh’s blessing,\nPossess the west and the south.”\n'),
	(5835, 5, 33, 24, 'About Asher he said,\n“Asher is blessed with children.\nLet him be acceptable to his brothers.\nLet him dip his foot in oil.\n'),
	(5836, 5, 33, 25, 'Your bars will be iron and brass.\nAs your days, so your strength will be.\n'),
	(5837, 5, 33, 26, '“There is no one like God, Jeshurun,\nwho rides on the heavens for your help,\nin his excellency on the skies.\n'),
	(5838, 5, 33, 27, 'The eternal God is your dwelling place.\nUnderneath are the everlasting arms.\nHe thrust out the enemy from before you,\nand said, ‘Destroy!’\n'),
	(5839, 5, 33, 28, 'Israel dwells in safety;\nthe fountain of Jacob alone,\nIn a land of grain and new wine.\nYes, his heavens drop down dew.\n'),
	(5840, 5, 33, 29, 'You are happy, Israel!\nWho is like you, a people saved by Yahweh,\nthe shield of your help,\nthe sword of your excellency?\nYour enemies will submit themselves to you.\nYou will tread on their high places.”\n'),
	(5841, 5, 34, 1, 'Moses went up from the plains of Moab to Mount Nebo, to the top of Pisgah, that is over against Jericho. Yahweh showed him all the land of Gilead, to Dan,\n'),
	(5842, 5, 34, 2, 'and all Naphtali, and the land of Ephraim and Manasseh, and all the land of Judah, to the western sea,\n'),
	(5843, 5, 34, 3, 'and the south, and the Plain of the valley of Jericho the city of palm trees, to Zoar.\n'),
	(5844, 5, 34, 4, 'Yahweh said to him, “This is the land which I swore to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob, saying, ‘I will give it to your offspring.’ I have caused you to see it with your eyes, but you shall not go over there.”\n'),
	(5845, 5, 34, 5, 'So Moses the servant of Yahweh died there in the land of Moab, according to Yahweh’s word.\n'),
	(5846, 5, 34, 6, 'He buried him in the valley in the land of Moab opposite Beth Peor, but no man knows where his tomb is to this day.\n'),
	(5847, 5, 34, 7, 'Moses was one hundred twenty years old when he died. His eye was not dim, nor his strength gone.\n'),
	(5848, 5, 34, 8, 'The children of Israel wept for Moses in the plains of Moab thirty days, until the days of weeping in the mourning for Moses were ended.\n'),
	(5849, 5, 34, 9, 'Joshua the son of Nun was full of the spirit of wisdom; for Moses had laid his hands on him. The children of Israel listened to him, and did as Yahweh commanded Moses.\n'),
	(5850, 5, 34, 10, 'Since then, there has not arisen a prophet in Israel like Moses, whom Yahweh knew face to face,\n'),
	(5851, 5, 34, 11, 'in all the signs and the wonders, which Yahweh sent him to do in the land of Egypt, to Pharaoh, and to all his servants, and to all his land,\n'),
	(5852, 5, 34, 12, 'and in all the mighty hand, and in all the awesome deeds, which Moses did in the sight of all Israel.\n'),
	(5853, 6, 1, 1, 'Now after the death of Moses the servant of Yahweh, Yahweh spoke to Joshua the son of Nun, Moses’ servant, saying,\n'),
	(5854, 6, 1, 2, '“Moses my servant is dead. Now therefore arise, go across this Jordan, you, and all these people, to the land which I am giving to them, even to the children of Israel.\n'),
	(5855, 6, 1, 3, 'I have given you every place that the sole of your foot will tread on, as I told Moses.\n'),
	(5856, 6, 1, 4, 'From the wilderness, and this Lebanon, even to the great river, the river Euphrates, all the land of the Hittites, and to the great sea toward the going down of the sun, shall be your border.\n'),
	(5857, 6, 1, 5, 'No man will be able to stand before you all the days of your life. As I was with Moses, so I will be with you. I will not fail you nor forsake you.\n'),
	(5858, 6, 1, 6, '“Be strong and courageous; for you shall cause this people to inherit the land which I swore to their fathers to give them.\n'),
	(5859, 6, 1, 7, 'Only be strong and very courageous. Be careful to observe to do according to all the law, which Moses my servant commanded you. Don’t turn from it to the right hand or to the left, that you may have good success wherever you go.\n'),
	(5860, 6, 1, 8, 'This book of the law shall not depart from your mouth, but you shall meditate on it day and night, that you may observe to do according to all that is written in it; for then you shall make your way prosperous, and then you shall have good success.\n'),
	(5861, 6, 1, 9, 'Haven’t I commanded you? Be strong and courageous. Don’t be afraid. Don’t be dismayed, for Yahweh your God is with you wherever you go.”\n'),
	(5862, 6, 1, 10, 'Then Joshua commanded the officers of the people, saying,\n'),
	(5863, 6, 1, 11, '“Pass through the middle of the camp, and command the people, saying, ‘Prepare food; for within three days you are to pass over this Jordan, to go in to possess the land, which Yahweh your God gives you to possess it.’”\n'),
	(5864, 6, 1, 12, 'Joshua spoke to the Reubenites, and to the Gadites, and to the half-tribe of Manasseh, saying,\n'),
	(5865, 6, 1, 13, '“Remember the word which Moses the servant of Yahweh commanded you, saying, ‘Yahweh your God gives you rest, and will give you this land.\n'),
	(5866, 6, 1, 14, 'Your wives, your little ones, and your livestock, shall live in the land which Moses gave you beyond the Jordan; but you shall pass over before your brothers armed, all the mighty men of valor, and shall help them\n'),
	(5867, 6, 1, 15, 'until Yahweh has given your brothers rest, as he has given you, and they have also possessed the land which Yahweh your God gives them. Then you shall return to the land of your possession, and possess it, which Moses the servant of Yahweh gave you beyond the Jordan toward the sunrise.’”\n'),
	(5868, 6, 1, 16, 'They answered Joshua, saying, “All that you have commanded us we will do, and wherever you send us we will go.\n'),
	(5869, 6, 1, 17, 'Just as we listened to Moses in all things, so will we listen to you. Only may Yahweh your God be with you, as he was with Moses.\n'),
	(5870, 6, 1, 18, 'Whoever rebels against your commandment, and doesn’t listen to your words in all that you command him shall himself be put to death. Only be strong and courageous.”\n'),
	(5871, 6, 2, 1, 'Joshua the son of Nun secretly sent two men out of Shittim as spies, saying, “Go, view the land, including Jericho.” They went and came into the house of a prostitute whose name was Rahab, and slept there.\n'),
	(5872, 6, 2, 2, 'The king of Jericho was told, “Behold, men of the children of Israel came in here tonight to spy out the land.”\n'),
	(5873, 6, 2, 3, 'Jericho’s king sent to Rahab, saying, “Bring out the men who have come to you, who have entered into your house; for they have come to spy out all the land.”\n'),
	(5874, 6, 2, 4, 'The woman took the two men and hid them. Then she said, “Yes, the men came to me, but I didn’t know where they came from.\n'),
	(5875, 6, 2, 5, 'About the time of the shutting of the gate, when it was dark, the men went out. Where the men went, I don’t know. Pursue them quickly. You may catch up with them.”\n'),
	(5876, 6, 2, 6, 'But she had brought them up to the roof, and hidden them under the stalks of flax which she had laid in order on the roof.\n'),
	(5877, 6, 2, 7, 'The men pursued them along the way to the fords of the Jordan River. As soon as those who pursued them had gone out, they shut the gate.\n'),
	(5878, 6, 2, 8, 'Before they had lain down, she came up to them on the roof.\n'),
	(5879, 6, 2, 9, 'She said to the men, “I know that Yahweh has given you the land, and that the fear of you has fallen upon us, and that all the inhabitants of the land melt away before you.\n'),
	(5880, 6, 2, 10, 'For we have heard how Yahweh dried up the water of the Red Sea before you, when you came out of Egypt; and what you did to the two kings of the Amorites, who were beyond the Jordan, to Sihon and to Og, whom you utterly destroyed.\n'),
	(5881, 6, 2, 11, 'As soon as we had heard it, our hearts melted, and there wasn’t any more spirit in any man, because of you: for Yahweh your God, he is God in heaven above, and on earth beneath.\n'),
	(5882, 6, 2, 12, 'Now therefore, please swear to me by Yahweh, since I have dealt kindly with you, that you also will deal kindly with my father’s house, and give me a true sign;\n'),
	(5883, 6, 2, 13, 'and that you will save alive my father, my mother, my brothers, and my sisters, and all that they have, and will deliver our lives from death.”\n'),
	(5884, 6, 2, 14, 'The men said to her, “Our life for yours, if you don’t talk about this business of ours; and it shall be, when Yahweh gives us the land, that we will deal kindly and truly with you.”\n'),
	(5885, 6, 2, 15, 'Then she let them down by a cord through the window; for her house was on the side of the wall, and she lived on the wall.\n'),
	(5886, 6, 2, 16, 'She said to them, “Go to the mountain, lest the pursuers find you. Hide yourselves there three days, until the pursuers have returned. Afterward, you may go your way.”\n'),
	(5887, 6, 2, 17, 'The men said to her, “We will be guiltless of this your oath which you’ve made us to swear.\n'),
	(5888, 6, 2, 18, 'Behold, when we come into the land, tie this line of scarlet thread in the window which you used to let us down. Gather to yourself into the house your father, your mother, your brothers, and all your father’s household.\n'),
	(5889, 6, 2, 19, 'It shall be that whoever goes out of the doors of your house into the street, his blood will be on his head, and we will be guiltless. Whoever is with you in the house, his blood shall be on our head, if any hand is on him.\n'),
	(5890, 6, 2, 20, 'But if you talk about this business of ours, then we shall be guiltless of your oath which you’ve made us to swear.”\n'),
	(5891, 6, 2, 21, 'She said, “Let it be as you have said.” She sent them away, and they departed. Then she tied the scarlet line in the window.\n'),
	(5892, 6, 2, 22, 'They went, and came to the mountain, and stayed there three days, until the pursuers had returned. The pursuers sought them all along the way, but didn’t find them.\n'),
	(5893, 6, 2, 23, 'Then the two men returned, descended from the mountain, crossed the river, and came to Joshua the son of Nun. They told him all that had happened to them.\n'),
	(5894, 6, 2, 24, 'They said to Joshua, “Truly Yahweh has delivered all the land into our hands. Moreover, all the inhabitants of the land melt away before us.”\n'),
	(5895, 6, 3, 1, 'Joshua got up early in the morning; and they moved from Shittim, and came to the Jordan, he and all the children of Israel. They camped there before they crossed over.\n'),
	(5896, 6, 3, 2, 'After three days, the officers went through the middle of the camp;\n'),
	(5897, 6, 3, 3, 'and they commanded the people, saying, “When you see the ark of Yahweh your God’s covenant, and the priests the Levites bearing it, then leave your place, and follow it.\n'),
	(5898, 6, 3, 4, 'Yet there shall be a space between you and it of about two thousand cubits by measure—don’t come closer to it—that you may know the way by which you must go; for you have not passed this way before.”\n'),
	(5899, 6, 3, 5, 'Joshua said to the people, “Sanctify yourselves; for tomorrow Yahweh will do wonders among you.”\n'),
	(5900, 6, 3, 6, 'Joshua spoke to the priests, saying, “Take up the ark of the covenant, and cross over before the people.” They took up the ark of the covenant, and went before the people.\n'),
	(5901, 6, 3, 7, 'Yahweh said to Joshua, “Today I will begin to magnify you in the sight of all Israel, that they may know that as I was with Moses, so I will be with you.\n'),
	(5902, 6, 3, 8, 'You shall command the priests who bear the ark of the covenant, saying, ‘When you come to the brink of the waters of the Jordan, you shall stand still in the Jordan.’”\n'),
	(5903, 6, 3, 9, 'Joshua said to the children of Israel, “Come here, and hear the words of Yahweh your God.”\n'),
	(5904, 6, 3, 10, 'Joshua said, “By this you shall know that the living God is among you, and that he will without fail drive the Canaanite, and the Hittite, and the Hivite, and the Perizzite, and the Girgashite, and the Amorite, and the Jebusite out from before you.\n'),
	(5905, 6, 3, 11, 'Behold, the ark of the covenant of the Lord of all the earth passes over before you into the Jordan.\n'),
	(5906, 6, 3, 12, 'Now therefore take twelve men out of the tribes of Israel, for every tribe a man.\n'),
	(5907, 6, 3, 13, 'It shall be that when the soles of the feet of the priests who bear the ark of Yahweh, the Lord of all the earth, rest in the waters of the Jordan, that the waters of the Jordan will be cut off. The waters that come down from above shall stand in one heap.”\n'),
	(5908, 6, 3, 14, 'When the people moved from their tents to pass over the Jordan, the priests who bore the ark of the covenant being before the people,\n'),
	(5909, 6, 3, 15, 'and when those who bore the ark had come to the Jordan, and the feet of the priests who bore the ark had dipped in the edge of the water (for the Jordan overflows all its banks all the time of harvest),\n'),
	(5910, 6, 3, 16, 'the waters which came down from above stood, and rose up in one heap, a great way off, at Adam, the city that is beside Zarethan; and those that went down toward the sea of the Arabah, even the Salt Sea, were wholly cut off. Then the people passed over near Jericho.\n'),
	(5911, 6, 3, 17, 'The priests who bore the ark of Yahweh’s covenant stood firm on dry ground in the middle of the Jordan; and all Israel crossed over on dry ground, until all the nation had passed completely over the Jordan.\n'),
	(5912, 6, 4, 1, 'When all the nation had completely crossed over the Jordan, Yahweh spoke to Joshua, saying,\n'),
	(5913, 6, 4, 2, '“Take twelve men out of the people, a man out of every tribe,\n'),
	(5914, 6, 4, 3, 'and command them, saying, ‘Take from out of the middle of the Jordan, out of the place where the priests’ feet stood firm, twelve stones, and carry them over with you, and lay them down in the place where you’ll camp tonight.’”\n');
REPLACE INTO `verses` (`id`, `book_id`, `chapter_number`, `verse_number`, `text`) VALUES
	(5915, 6, 4, 4, 'Then Joshua called the twelve men, whom he had prepared of the children of Israel, a man out of every tribe.\n'),
	(5916, 6, 4, 5, 'Joshua said to them, “Cross before the ark of Yahweh your God into the middle of the Jordan, and each of you pick up a stone and put it on your shoulder, according to the number of the tribes of the children of Israel;\n'),
	(5917, 6, 4, 6, 'that this may be a sign among you, that when your children ask in the future, saying, ‘What do you mean by these stones?’\n'),
	(5918, 6, 4, 7, 'then you shall tell them, ‘Because the waters of the Jordan were cut off before the ark of Yahweh’s covenant. When it crossed over the Jordan, the waters of the Jordan were cut off. These stones shall be for a memorial to the children of Israel forever.’”\n'),
	(5919, 6, 4, 8, 'The children of Israel did as Joshua commanded, and took up twelve stones out of the middle of the Jordan, as Yahweh spoke to Joshua, according to the number of the tribes of the children of Israel. They carried them over with them to the place where they camped, and laid them down there.\n'),
	(5920, 6, 4, 9, 'Joshua set up twelve stones in the middle of the Jordan, in the place where the feet of the priests who bore the ark of the covenant stood; and they are there to this day.\n'),
	(5921, 6, 4, 10, 'For the priests who bore the ark stood in the middle of the Jordan, until everything was finished that Yahweh commanded Joshua to speak to the people, according to all that Moses commanded Joshua; and the people hurried and passed over.\n'),
	(5922, 6, 4, 11, 'When all the people had completely crossed over, Yahweh’s ark crossed over, with the priests, in the presence of the people.\n'),
	(5923, 6, 4, 12, 'The children of Reuben, and the children of Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh, crossed over armed before the children of Israel, as Moses spoke to them.\n'),
	(5924, 6, 4, 13, 'About forty thousand men, ready and armed for war passed over before Yahweh to battle, to the plains of Jericho.\n'),
	(5925, 6, 4, 14, 'On that day, Yahweh magnified Joshua in the sight of all Israel; and they feared him, as they feared Moses, all the days of his life.\n'),
	(5926, 6, 4, 15, 'Yahweh spoke to Joshua, saying,\n'),
	(5927, 6, 4, 16, '“Command the priests who bear the ark of the testimony, that they come up out of the Jordan.”\n'),
	(5928, 6, 4, 17, 'Joshua therefore commanded the priests, saying, “Come up out of the Jordan!”\n'),
	(5929, 6, 4, 18, 'When the priests who bore the ark of Yahweh’s covenant had come up out of the middle of the Jordan, and the soles of the priests’ feet had been lifted up to the dry ground, the waters of the Jordan returned to their place, and went over all its banks, as before.\n'),
	(5930, 6, 4, 19, 'The people came up out of the Jordan on the tenth day of the first month, and encamped in Gilgal, on the east border of Jericho.\n'),
	(5931, 6, 4, 20, 'Joshua set up those twelve stones, which they took out of the Jordan, in Gilgal.\n'),
	(5932, 6, 4, 21, 'He spoke to the children of Israel, saying, “When your children ask their fathers in time to come, saying, ‘What do these stones mean?’\n'),
	(5933, 6, 4, 22, 'Then you shall let your children know, saying, ‘Israel came over this Jordan on dry land.\n'),
	(5934, 6, 4, 23, 'For Yahweh your God dried up the waters of the Jordan from before you, until you had crossed over, as Yahweh your God did to the Red Sea, which he dried up from before us, until we had crossed over;\n'),
	(5935, 6, 4, 24, 'that all the peoples of the earth may know that Yahweh’s hand is mighty; that you may fear Yahweh your God forever.’”\n'),
	(5936, 6, 5, 1, 'When all the kings of the Amorites, who were beyond the Jordan westward, and all the kings of the Canaanites, who were by the sea, heard how Yahweh had dried up the waters of the Jordan from before the children of Israel, until we had crossed over, their heart melted, and there was no more spirit in them, because of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(5937, 6, 5, 2, 'At that time, Yahweh said to Joshua, “Make flint knives, and circumcise again the sons of Israel the second time.”\n'),
	(5938, 6, 5, 3, 'Joshua made himself flint knives, and circumcised the sons of Israel at the hill of the foreskins.\n'),
	(5939, 6, 5, 4, 'This is the reason Joshua circumcised them: all the people who came out of Egypt, who were males, even all the men of war, died in the wilderness along the way, after they came out of Egypt.\n'),
	(5940, 6, 5, 5, 'For all the people who came out were circumcised; but all the people who were born in the wilderness along the way as they came out of Egypt had not been circumcised.\n'),
	(5941, 6, 5, 6, 'For the children of Israel walked forty years in the wilderness, until all the nation, even the men of war who came out of Egypt, were consumed, because they didn’t listen to Yahweh’s voice. Yahweh swore to them that he wouldn’t let them see the land which Yahweh swore to their fathers that he would give us, a land flowing with milk and honey.\n'),
	(5942, 6, 5, 7, 'Their children, whom he raised up in their place, were circumcised by Joshua; for they were uncircumcised, because they had not circumcised them on the way.\n'),
	(5943, 6, 5, 8, 'When they were done circumcising the whole nation, they stayed in their places in the camp until they were healed.\n'),
	(5944, 6, 5, 9, 'Yahweh said to Joshua, “Today I have rolled away the reproach of Egypt from you.” Therefore the name of that place was called Gilgal, to this day.\n'),
	(5945, 6, 5, 10, 'The children of Israel encamped in Gilgal. They kept the Passover on the fourteenth day of the month at evening in the plains of Jericho.\n'),
	(5946, 6, 5, 11, 'They ate unleavened cakes and parched grain of the produce of the land on the next day after the Passover, in the same day.\n'),
	(5947, 6, 5, 12, 'The manna ceased on the next day, after they had eaten of the produce of the land. The children of Israel didn’t have manna any more; but they ate of the fruit of the land of Canaan that year.\n'),
	(5948, 6, 5, 13, 'When Joshua was by Jericho, he lifted up his eyes and looked, and behold, a man stood in front of him with his sword drawn in his hand. Joshua went to him and said to him, “Are you for us, or for our enemies?”\n'),
	(5949, 6, 5, 14, 'He said, “No; but I have come now as commander of Yahweh’s army.”\nJoshua fell on his face to the earth, and worshiped, and asked him, “What does my lord say to his servant?”\n'),
	(5950, 6, 5, 15, 'The prince of Yahweh’s army said to Joshua, “Take off your shoes; for the place on which you stand is holy.” Joshua did so.\n'),
	(5951, 6, 6, 1, 'Now Jericho was tightly shut up because of the children of Israel. No one went out, and no one came in.\n'),
	(5952, 6, 6, 2, 'Yahweh said to Joshua, “Behold, I have given Jericho into your hand, with its king and the mighty men of valor.\n'),
	(5953, 6, 6, 3, 'All of your men of war shall march around the city, going around the city once. You shall do this six days.\n'),
	(5954, 6, 6, 4, 'Seven priests shall bear seven trumpets of rams’ horns before the ark. On the seventh day, you shall march around the city seven times, and the priests shall blow the trumpets.\n'),
	(5955, 6, 6, 5, 'It shall be that when they make a long blast with the ram’s horn, and when you hear the sound of the trumpet, all the people shall shout with a great shout; and the city wall shall fall down flat, and the people shall go up, every man straight in front of him.”\n'),
	(5956, 6, 6, 6, 'Joshua the son of Nun called the priests, and said to them, “Take up the ark of the covenant, and let seven priests bear seven trumpets of rams’ horns before Yahweh’s ark.”\n'),
	(5957, 6, 6, 7, 'They said to the people, “Advance! March around the city, and let the armed men pass on before Yahweh’s ark.”\n'),
	(5958, 6, 6, 8, 'It was so, that when Joshua had spoken to the people, the seven priests bearing the seven trumpets of rams’ horns before Yahweh advanced and blew the trumpets, and the ark of Yahweh’s covenant followed them.\n'),
	(5959, 6, 6, 9, 'The armed men went before the priests who blew the trumpets, and the ark went after them. The trumpets sounded as they went.\n'),
	(5960, 6, 6, 10, 'Joshua commanded the people, saying, “You shall not shout, nor let your voice be heard, neither shall any word proceed out of your mouth, until the day I tell you to shout. Then you shall shout.”\n'),
	(5961, 6, 6, 11, 'So he caused Yahweh’s ark to go around the city, going about it once. Then they came into the camp, and stayed in the camp.\n'),
	(5962, 6, 6, 12, 'Joshua rose early in the morning, and the priests took up Yahweh’s ark.\n'),
	(5963, 6, 6, 13, 'The seven priests bearing the seven trumpets of rams’ horns in front of Yahweh’s ark went on continually, and blew the trumpets. The armed men went in front of them. The rear guard came after Yahweh’s ark. The trumpets sounded as they went.\n'),
	(5964, 6, 6, 14, 'The second day they marched around the city once, and returned into the camp. They did this six days.\n'),
	(5965, 6, 6, 15, 'On the seventh day, they rose early at the dawning of the day, and marched around the city in the same way seven times. Only on this day they marched around the city seven times.\n'),
	(5966, 6, 6, 16, 'At the seventh time, when the priests blew the trumpets, Joshua said to the people, “Shout, for Yahweh has given you the city!\n'),
	(5967, 6, 6, 17, 'The city shall be devoted, even it and all that is in it, to Yahweh. Only Rahab the prostitute shall live, she and all who are with her in the house, because she hid the messengers that we sent.\n'),
	(5968, 6, 6, 18, 'But as for you, only keep yourselves from what is devoted to destruction, lest when you have devoted it, you take of the devoted thing; so you would make the camp of Israel accursed, and trouble it.\n'),
	(5969, 6, 6, 19, 'But all the silver, gold, and vessels of brass and iron, are holy to Yahweh. They shall come into Yahweh’s treasury.”\n'),
	(5970, 6, 6, 20, 'So the people shouted and the priests blew the trumpets. When the people heard the sound of the trumpet, the people shouted with a great shout, and the wall fell down flat, so that the people went up into the city, every man straight in front of him, and they took the city.\n'),
	(5971, 6, 6, 21, 'They utterly destroyed all that was in the city, both man and woman, both young and old, and ox, sheep, and donkey, with the edge of the sword.\n'),
	(5972, 6, 6, 22, 'Joshua said to the two men who had spied out the land, “Go into the prostitute’s house, and bring the woman and all that she has out from there, as you swore to her.”\n'),
	(5973, 6, 6, 23, 'The young men who were spies went in, and brought out Rahab with her father, her mother, her brothers, and all that she had. They also brought out all of her relatives, and they set them outside of the camp of Israel.\n'),
	(5974, 6, 6, 24, 'They burned the city with fire, and all that was in it. Only they put the silver, the gold, and the vessels of brass and of iron into the treasury of Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(5975, 6, 6, 25, 'But Rahab the prostitute, her father’s household, and all that she had, Joshua saved alive. She lives in the middle of Israel to this day, because she hid the messengers, whom Joshua sent to spy out Jericho.\n'),
	(5976, 6, 6, 26, 'Joshua commanded them with an oath at that time, saying, “Cursed is the man before Yahweh, who rises up and builds this city Jericho. With the loss of his firstborn he will lay its foundation, and with the loss of his youngest son he will set up its gates.”\n'),
	(5977, 6, 6, 27, 'So Yahweh was with Joshua; and his fame was in all the land.\n'),
	(5978, 6, 7, 1, 'But the children of Israel committed a trespass in the devoted things; for Achan, the son of Carmi, the son of Zabdi, the son of Zerah, of the tribe of Judah, took some of the devoted things. Therefore Yahweh’s anger burned against the children of Israel.\n'),
	(5979, 6, 7, 2, 'Joshua sent men from Jericho to Ai, which is beside Beth Aven, on the east side of Bethel, and spoke to them, saying, “Go up and spy out the land.”\nThe men went up and spied out Ai.\n'),
	(5980, 6, 7, 3, 'They returned to Joshua, and said to him, “Don’t let all the people go up; but let about two or three thousand men go up and strike Ai. Don’t make all the people to toil there, for there are only a few of them.”\n'),
	(5981, 6, 7, 4, 'So about three thousand men of the people went up there, and they fled before the men of Ai.\n'),
	(5982, 6, 7, 5, 'The men of Ai struck about thirty-six men of them, and they chased them from before the gate even to Shebarim, and struck them at the descent. The hearts of the people melted, and became like water.\n'),
	(5983, 6, 7, 6, 'Joshua tore his clothes, and fell to the earth on his face before Yahweh’s ark until the evening, he and the elders of Israel; and they put dust on their heads.\n'),
	(5984, 6, 7, 7, 'Joshua said, “Alas, Lord Yahweh, why have you brought this people over the Jordan at all, to deliver us into the hand of the Amorites, to cause us to perish? I wish that we had been content and lived beyond the Jordan!\n'),
	(5985, 6, 7, 8, 'Oh, Lord, what shall I say, after Israel has turned their backs before their enemies!\n'),
	(5986, 6, 7, 9, 'For the Canaanites and all the inhabitants of the land will hear of it, and will surround us, and cut off our name from the earth. What will you do for your great name?”\n'),
	(5987, 6, 7, 10, 'Yahweh said to Joshua, “Get up! Why have you fallen on your face like that?\n'),
	(5988, 6, 7, 11, 'Israel has sinned. Yes, they have even transgressed my covenant which I commanded them. Yes, they have even taken some of the devoted things, and have also stolen, and also deceived. They have even put it among their own stuff.\n'),
	(5989, 6, 7, 12, 'Therefore the children of Israel can’t stand before their enemies. They turn their backs before their enemies, because they have become devoted for destruction. I will not be with you any more, unless you destroy the devoted things from among you.\n'),
	(5990, 6, 7, 13, '“Get up! Sanctify the people, and say, ‘Sanctify yourselves for tomorrow, for Yahweh, the God of Israel, says, “There is a devoted thing among you, Israel. You cannot stand before your enemies until you take away the devoted thing from among you.”\n'),
	(5991, 6, 7, 14, '“‘In the morning therefore you shall be brought near by your tribes. It shall be that the tribe which Yahweh selects shall come near by families. The family which Yahweh selects shall come near by households. The household which Yahweh selects shall come near man by man.\n'),
	(5992, 6, 7, 15, 'It shall be, that he who is taken with the devoted thing shall be burned with fire, he and all that he has, because he has transgressed Yahweh’s covenant, and because he has done a disgraceful thing in Israel.’”\n'),
	(5993, 6, 7, 16, 'So Joshua rose up early in the morning and brought Israel near by their tribes. The tribe of Judah was selected.\n'),
	(5994, 6, 7, 17, 'He brought near the family of Judah; and he selected the family of the Zerahites. He brought near the family of the Zerahites man by man, and Zabdi was selected.\n'),
	(5995, 6, 7, 18, 'He brought near his household man by man, and Achan, the son of Carmi, the son of Zabdi, the son of Zerah, of the tribe of Judah, was selected.\n'),
	(5996, 6, 7, 19, 'Joshua said to Achan, “My son, please give glory to Yahweh, the God of Israel, and make confession to him. Tell me now what you have done! Don’t hide it from me!”\n'),
	(5997, 6, 7, 20, 'Achan answered Joshua, and said, “I have truly sinned against Yahweh, the God of Israel, and this is what I have done.\n'),
	(5998, 6, 7, 21, 'When I saw among the plunder a beautiful Babylonian robe, two hundred shekels of silver, and a wedge of gold weighing fifty shekels, then I coveted them and took them. Behold, they are hidden in the ground in the middle of my tent, with the silver under it.”\n'),
	(5999, 6, 7, 22, 'So Joshua sent messengers, and they ran to the tent. Behold, it was hidden in his tent, with the silver under it.\n'),
	(6000, 6, 7, 23, 'They took them from the middle of the tent, and brought them to Joshua and to all the children of Israel. They laid them down before Yahweh.\n'),
	(6001, 6, 7, 24, 'Joshua, and all Israel with him, took Achan the son of Zerah, the silver, the robe, the wedge of gold, his sons, his daughters, his cattle, his donkeys, his sheep, his tent, and all that he had; and they brought them up to the valley of Achor.\n'),
	(6002, 6, 7, 25, 'Joshua said, “Why have you troubled us? Yahweh will trouble you today.” All Israel stoned him with stones, and they burned them with fire and stoned them with stones.\n'),
	(6003, 6, 7, 26, 'They raised over him a great heap of stones that remains to this day. Yahweh turned from the fierceness of his anger. Therefore the name of that place was called “The valley of Achor” to this day.\n'),
	(6004, 6, 8, 1, 'Yahweh said to Joshua, “Don’t be afraid, and don’t be dismayed. Take all the warriors with you, and arise, go up to Ai. Behold, I have given into your hand the king of Ai, with his people, his city, and his land.\n'),
	(6005, 6, 8, 2, 'You shall do to Ai and her king as you did to Jericho and her king, except you shall take its goods and its livestock for yourselves. Set an ambush for the city behind it.”\n'),
	(6006, 6, 8, 3, 'So Joshua arose, with all the warriors, to go up to Ai. Joshua chose thirty thousand men, the mighty men of valor, and sent them out by night.\n'),
	(6007, 6, 8, 4, 'He commanded them, saying, “Behold, you shall lie in ambush against the city, behind the city. Don’t go very far from the city, but all of you be ready.\n'),
	(6008, 6, 8, 5, 'I and all the people who are with me will approach to the city. It shall happen, when they come out against us, as at the first, that we will flee before them.\n'),
	(6009, 6, 8, 6, 'They will come out after us, until we have drawn them away from the city; for they will say, ‘They flee before us, like the first time.’ So we will flee before them,\n'),
	(6010, 6, 8, 7, 'and you shall rise up from the ambush, and take possession of the city; for Yahweh your God will deliver it into your hand.\n'),
	(6011, 6, 8, 8, 'It shall be, when you have seized the city, that you shall set the city on fire. You shall do this according to Yahweh’s word. Behold, I have commanded you.”\n'),
	(6012, 6, 8, 9, 'Joshua sent them out; and they went to set up the ambush, and stayed between Bethel and Ai, on the west side of Ai; but Joshua stayed among the people that night.\n'),
	(6013, 6, 8, 10, 'Joshua rose up early in the morning, mustered the people, and went up, he and the elders of Israel, before the people to Ai.\n'),
	(6014, 6, 8, 11, 'All the people, even the men of war who were with him, went up, and came near, and came before the city, and encamped on the north side of Ai. Now there was a valley between him and Ai.\n'),
	(6015, 6, 8, 12, 'He took about five thousand men, and set them in ambush between Bethel and Ai, on the west side of the city.\n'),
	(6016, 6, 8, 13, 'So they set the people, even all the army who was on the north of the city, and their ambush on the west of the city; and Joshua went that night into the middle of the valley.\n'),
	(6017, 6, 8, 14, 'When the king of Ai saw it, they hurried and rose up early, and the men of the city went out against Israel to battle, he and all his people, at the time appointed, before the Arabah; but he didn’t know that there was an ambush against him behind the city.\n'),
	(6018, 6, 8, 15, 'Joshua and all Israel made as if they were beaten before them, and fled by the way of the wilderness.\n'),
	(6019, 6, 8, 16, 'All the people who were in the city were called together to pursue after them. They pursued Joshua, and were drawn away from the city.\n'),
	(6020, 6, 8, 17, 'There was not a man left in Ai or Beth El who didn’t go out after Israel. They left the city open, and pursued Israel.\n'),
	(6021, 6, 8, 18, 'Yahweh said to Joshua, “Stretch out the javelin that is in your hand toward Ai, for I will give it into your hand.”\nJoshua stretched out the javelin that was in his hand toward the city.\n'),
	(6022, 6, 8, 19, 'The ambush arose quickly out of their place, and they ran as soon as he had stretched out his hand, and entered into the city, and took it. They hurried and set the city on fire.\n'),
	(6023, 6, 8, 20, 'When the men of Ai looked behind them, they saw, and behold, the smoke of the city ascended up to heaven, and they had no power to flee this way or that way. The people who fled to the wilderness turned back on the pursuers.\n'),
	(6024, 6, 8, 21, 'When Joshua and all Israel saw that the ambush had taken the city, and that the smoke of the city ascended, then they turned again, and killed the men of Ai.\n'),
	(6025, 6, 8, 22, 'The others came out of the city against them, so they were in the middle of Israel, some on this side, and some on that side. They struck them, so that they let none of them remain or escape.\n'),
	(6026, 6, 8, 23, 'They captured the king of Ai alive, and brought him to Joshua.\n'),
	(6027, 6, 8, 24, 'When Israel had finished killing all the inhabitants of Ai in the field, in the wilderness in which they pursued them, and they had all fallen by the edge of the sword, until they were consumed, all Israel returned to Ai, and struck it with the edge of the sword.\n'),
	(6028, 6, 8, 25, 'All that fell that day, both of men and women, were twelve thousand, even all the men of Ai.\n'),
	(6029, 6, 8, 26, 'For Joshua didn’t draw back his hand, with which he stretched out the javelin, until he had utterly destroyed all the inhabitants of Ai.\n'),
	(6030, 6, 8, 27, 'Israel took for themselves only the livestock and the goods of that city, according to Yahweh’s word which he commanded Joshua.\n'),
	(6031, 6, 8, 28, 'So Joshua burned Ai, and made it a heap forever, even a desolation, to this day.\n'),
	(6032, 6, 8, 29, 'He hanged the king of Ai on a tree until the evening, and at sundown Joshua commanded, and they took his body down from the tree, and threw it at the entrance of the gate of the city, and raised a great heap of stones on it that remains to this day.\n'),
	(6033, 6, 8, 30, 'Then Joshua built an altar to Yahweh, the God of Israel, on Mount Ebal,\n'),
	(6034, 6, 8, 31, 'as Moses the servant of Yahweh commanded the children of Israel, as it is written in the book of the law of Moses, an altar of uncut stones, on which no one had lifted up any iron. They offered burnt offerings on it to Yahweh and sacrificed peace offerings.\n'),
	(6035, 6, 8, 32, 'He wrote there on the stones a copy of Moses’ law, which he wrote in the presence of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(6036, 6, 8, 33, 'All Israel, their elders and officers, and their judges, stood on both sides of the ark before the priests the Levites, who carried the ark of Yahweh’s covenant, the foreigner as well as the native; half of them in front of Mount Gerizim, and half of them in front of Mount Ebal, as Moses the servant of Yahweh had commanded at the first, that they should bless the people of Israel.\n'),
	(6037, 6, 8, 34, 'Afterward he read all the words of the law, the blessing and the curse, according to all that is written in the book of the law.\n'),
	(6038, 6, 8, 35, 'There was not a word of all that Moses commanded, which Joshua didn’t read before all the assembly of Israel, with the women, the little ones, and the foreigners who were among them.\n'),
	(6039, 6, 9, 1, 'When all the kings who were beyond the Jordan, in the hill country, and in the lowland, and on all the shore of the great sea in front of Lebanon, the Hittite, the Amorite, the Canaanite, the Perizzite, the Hivite, and the Jebusite, heard of it\n'),
	(6040, 6, 9, 2, 'they gathered themselves together to fight with Joshua and with Israel, with one accord.\n'),
	(6041, 6, 9, 3, 'But when the inhabitants of Gibeon heard what Joshua had done to Jericho and to Ai,\n'),
	(6042, 6, 9, 4, 'they also resorted to a ruse, and went and made as if they had been ambassadors, and took old sacks on their donkeys, and old, torn-up and bound up wine skins,\n'),
	(6043, 6, 9, 5, 'and old and patched shoes on their feet, and wore old garments. All the bread of their food supply was dry and moldy.\n'),
	(6044, 6, 9, 6, 'They went to Joshua at the camp at Gilgal, and said to him and to the men of Israel, “We have come from a far country. Now therefore make a covenant with us.”\n'),
	(6045, 6, 9, 7, 'The men of Israel said to the Hivites, “What if you live among us? How could we make a covenant with you?”\n'),
	(6046, 6, 9, 8, 'They said to Joshua, “We are your servants.”\nJoshua said to them, “Who are you? Where do you come from?”\n'),
	(6047, 6, 9, 9, 'They said to him, “Your servants have come from a very far country because of the name of Yahweh your God; for we have heard of his fame, all that he did in Egypt,\n'),
	(6048, 6, 9, 10, 'and all that he did to the two kings of the Amorites who were beyond the Jordan, to Sihon king of Heshbon and to Og king of Bashan, who was at Ashtaroth.\n'),
	(6049, 6, 9, 11, 'Our elders and all the inhabitants of our country spoke to us, saying, ‘Take supplies in your hand for the journey, and go to meet them. Tell them, “We are your servants. Now make a covenant with us.”’\n'),
	(6050, 6, 9, 12, 'This our bread we took hot for our supplies out of our houses on the day we went out to go to you; but now, behold, it is dry, and has become moldy.\n'),
	(6051, 6, 9, 13, 'These wine skins, which we filled, were new; and behold, they are torn. These our garments and our shoes have become old because of the very long journey.”\n'),
	(6052, 6, 9, 14, 'The men sampled their provisions, and didn’t ask counsel from Yahweh’s mouth.\n'),
	(6053, 6, 9, 15, 'Joshua made peace with them, and made a covenant with them, to let them live. The princes of the congregation swore to them.\n'),
	(6054, 6, 9, 16, 'At the end of three days after they had made a covenant with them, they heard that they were their neighbors, and that they lived among them.\n'),
	(6055, 6, 9, 17, 'The children of Israel traveled and came to their cities on the third day. Now their cities were Gibeon, Chephirah, Beeroth, and Kiriath Jearim.\n'),
	(6056, 6, 9, 18, 'The children of Israel didn’t strike them, because the princes of the congregation had sworn to them by Yahweh, the God of Israel. All the congregation murmured against the princes.\n'),
	(6057, 6, 9, 19, 'But all the princes said to all the congregation, “We have sworn to them by Yahweh, the God of Israel. Now therefore we may not touch them.\n'),
	(6058, 6, 9, 20, 'We will do this to them, and let them live; lest wrath be on us, because of the oath which we swore to them.”\n'),
	(6059, 6, 9, 21, 'The princes said to them, “Let them live, so they became wood cutters and drawers of water for all the congregation, as the princes had spoken to them.”\n'),
	(6060, 6, 9, 22, 'Joshua called for them, and he spoke to them, saying, “Why have you deceived us, saying, ‘We are very far from you,’ when you live among us?\n'),
	(6061, 6, 9, 23, 'Now therefore you are cursed, and some of you will never fail to be slaves, both wood cutters and drawers of water for the house of my God.”\n'),
	(6062, 6, 9, 24, 'They answered Joshua, and said, “Because your servants were certainly told how Yahweh your God commanded his servant Moses to give you all the land, and to destroy all the inhabitants of the land from before you. Therefore we were very afraid for our lives because of you, and have done this thing.\n'),
	(6063, 6, 9, 25, 'Now, behold, we are in your hand. Do to us as it seems good and right to you to do.”\n'),
	(6064, 6, 9, 26, 'He did so to them, and delivered them out of the hand of the children of Israel, so that they didn’t kill them.\n'),
	(6065, 6, 9, 27, 'That day Joshua made them wood cutters and drawers of water for the congregation and for Yahweh’s altar to this day, in the place which he should choose.\n'),
	(6066, 6, 10, 1, 'Now when Adoni-Zedek king of Jerusalem heard how Joshua had taken Ai, and had utterly destroyed it; as he had done to Jericho and her king, so he had done to Ai and her king; and how the inhabitants of Gibeon had made peace with Israel, and were among them,\n'),
	(6067, 6, 10, 2, 'they were very afraid, because Gibeon was a great city, as one of the royal cities, and because it was greater than Ai, and all its men were mighty.\n'),
	(6068, 6, 10, 3, 'Therefore Adoni-Zedek king of Jerusalem sent to Hoham king of Hebron, Piram king of Jarmuth, Japhia king of Lachish, and Debir king of Eglon, saying,\n'),
	(6069, 6, 10, 4, '“Come up to me and help me. Let us strike Gibeon; for they have made peace with Joshua and with the children of Israel.”\n'),
	(6070, 6, 10, 5, 'Therefore the five kings of the Amorites, the king of Jerusalem, the king of Hebron, the king of Jarmuth, the king of Lachish, and the king of Eglon, gathered themselves together and went up, they and all their armies, and encamped against Gibeon, and made war against it.\n'),
	(6071, 6, 10, 6, 'The men of Gibeon sent to Joshua at the camp at Gilgal, saying, “Don’t abandon your servants! Come up to us quickly and save us! Help us; for all the kings of the Amorites that dwell in the hill country have gathered together against us.”\n'),
	(6072, 6, 10, 7, 'So Joshua went up from Gilgal, he, and the whole army with him, including all the mighty men of valor.\n'),
	(6073, 6, 10, 8, 'Yahweh said to Joshua, “Don’t fear them, for I have delivered them into your hands. Not a man of them will stand before you.”\n'),
	(6074, 6, 10, 9, 'Joshua therefore came to them suddenly. He marched from Gilgal all night.\n'),
	(6075, 6, 10, 10, 'Yahweh confused them before Israel. He killed them with a great slaughter at Gibeon, and chased them by the way of the ascent of Beth Horon, and struck them to Azekah and to Makkedah.\n'),
	(6076, 6, 10, 11, 'As they fled from before Israel, while they were at the descent of Beth Horon, Yahweh hurled down great stones from the sky on them to Azekah, and they died. There were more who died from the hailstones than those whom the children of Israel killed with the sword.\n'),
	(6077, 6, 10, 12, 'Then Joshua spoke to Yahweh in the day when Yahweh delivered up the Amorites before the children of Israel. He said in the sight of Israel, “Sun, stand still on Gibeon! You, moon, stop in the valley of Aijalon!”\n'),
	(6078, 6, 10, 13, 'The sun stood still, and the moon stayed, until the nation had avenged themselves of their enemies. Isn’t this written in the book of Jashar? The sun stayed in the middle of the sky, and didn’t hurry to go down about a whole day.\n'),
	(6079, 6, 10, 14, 'There was no day like that before it or after it, that Yahweh listened to the voice of a man; for Yahweh fought for Israel.\n'),
	(6080, 6, 10, 15, 'Joshua returned, and all Israel with him, to the camp to Gilgal.\n'),
	(6081, 6, 10, 16, 'These five kings fled, and hid themselves in the cave at Makkedah.\n'),
	(6082, 6, 10, 17, 'Joshua was told, saying, “The five kings have been found, hidden in the cave at Makkedah.”\n'),
	(6083, 6, 10, 18, 'Joshua said, “Roll large stones to cover the cave’s entrance, and set men by it to guard them;\n'),
	(6084, 6, 10, 19, 'but don’t stay there. Pursue your enemies, and attack them from the rear. Don’t allow them to enter into their cities; for Yahweh your God has delivered them into your hand.”\n'),
	(6085, 6, 10, 20, 'When Joshua and the children of Israel had finished killing them with a very great slaughter until they were consumed, and the remnant which remained of them had entered into the fortified cities,\n'),
	(6086, 6, 10, 21, 'all the people returned to the camp to Joshua at Makkedah in peace. None moved his tongue against any of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(6087, 6, 10, 22, 'Then Joshua said, “Open the cave entrance, and bring those five kings out of the cave to me.”\n'),
	(6088, 6, 10, 23, 'They did so, and brought those five kings out of the cave to him: the king of Jerusalem, the king of Hebron, the king of Jarmuth, the king of Lachish, and the king of Eglon.\n'),
	(6089, 6, 10, 24, 'When they brought those kings out to Joshua, Joshua called for all the men of Israel, and said to the chiefs of the men of war who went with him, “Come near. Put your feet on the necks of these kings.”\nThey came near, and put their feet on their necks.\n'),
	(6090, 6, 10, 25, 'Joshua said to them, “Don’t be afraid, nor be dismayed. Be strong and courageous, for Yahweh will do this to all your enemies against whom you fight.”\n'),
	(6091, 6, 10, 26, 'Afterward Joshua struck them, put them to death, and hanged them on five trees. They were hanging on the trees until the evening.\n'),
	(6092, 6, 10, 27, 'At the time of the going down of the sun, Joshua commanded, and they took them down off the trees, and threw them into the cave in which they had hidden themselves, and laid great stones on the mouth of the cave, which remain to this very day.\n'),
	(6093, 6, 10, 28, 'Joshua took Makkedah on that day, and struck it with the edge of the sword, with its king. He utterly destroyed it and all the souls who were in it. He left no one remaining. He did to the king of Makkedah as he had done to the king of Jericho.\n'),
	(6094, 6, 10, 29, 'Joshua passed from Makkedah, and all Israel with him, to Libnah, and fought against Libnah.\n'),
	(6095, 6, 10, 30, 'Yahweh delivered it also, with its king, into the hand of Israel. He struck it with the edge of the sword, and all the souls who were in it. He left no one remaining in it. He did to its king as he had done to the king of Jericho.\n'),
	(6096, 6, 10, 31, 'Joshua passed from Libnah, and all Israel with him, to Lachish, and encamped against it, and fought against it.\n'),
	(6097, 6, 10, 32, 'Yahweh delivered Lachish into the hand of Israel. He took it on the second day, and struck it with the edge of the sword, with all the souls who were in it, according to all that he had done to Libnah.\n'),
	(6098, 6, 10, 33, 'Then Horam king of Gezer came up to help Lachish; and Joshua struck him and his people, until he had left him no one remaining.\n'),
	(6099, 6, 10, 34, 'Joshua passed from Lachish, and all Israel with him, to Eglon; and they encamped against it and fought against it.\n'),
	(6100, 6, 10, 35, 'They took it on that day, and struck it with the edge of the sword. He utterly destroyed all the souls who were in it that day, according to all that he had done to Lachish.\n'),
	(6101, 6, 10, 36, 'Joshua went up from Eglon, and all Israel with him, to Hebron; and they fought against it.\n'),
	(6102, 6, 10, 37, 'They took it, and struck it with the edge of the sword, with its king and all its cities, and all the souls who were in it. He left no one remaining, according to all that he had done to Eglon; but he utterly destroyed it, and all the souls who were in it.\n'),
	(6103, 6, 10, 38, 'Joshua returned, and all Israel with him, to Debir, and fought against it.\n'),
	(6104, 6, 10, 39, 'He took it, with its king and all its cities. They struck them with the edge of the sword, and utterly destroyed all the souls who were in it. He left no one remaining. As he had done to Hebron, so he did to Debir, and to its king; as he had done also to Libnah, and to its king.\n'),
	(6105, 6, 10, 40, 'So Joshua struck all the land, the hill country, the South, the lowland, the slopes, and all their kings. He left no one remaining, but he utterly destroyed all that breathed, as Yahweh, the God of Israel, commanded.\n'),
	(6106, 6, 10, 41, 'Joshua struck them from Kadesh Barnea even to Gaza, and all the country of Goshen, even to Gibeon.\n'),
	(6107, 6, 10, 42, 'Joshua took all these kings and their land at one time because Yahweh, the God of Israel, fought for Israel.\n'),
	(6108, 6, 10, 43, 'Joshua returned, and all Israel with him, to the camp to Gilgal.\n'),
	(6109, 6, 11, 1, 'When Jabin king of Hazor heard of it, he sent to Jobab king of Madon, to the king of Shimron, to the king of Achshaph,\n'),
	(6110, 6, 11, 2, 'and to the kings who were on the north, in the hill country, in the Arabah south of Chinneroth, in the lowland, and in the heights of Dor on the west,\n'),
	(6111, 6, 11, 3, 'to the Canaanite on the east and on the west, the Amorite, the Hittite, the Perizzite, the Jebusite in the hill country, and the Hivite under Hermon in the land of Mizpah.\n'),
	(6112, 6, 11, 4, 'They went out, they and all their armies with them, many people, even as the sand that is on the seashore in multitude, with very many horses and chariots.\n'),
	(6113, 6, 11, 5, 'All these kings met together; and they came and encamped together at the waters of Merom, to fight with Israel.\n'),
	(6114, 6, 11, 6, 'Yahweh said to Joshua, “Don’t be afraid because of them; for tomorrow at this time, I will deliver them up all slain before Israel. You shall hamstring their horses and burn their chariots with fire.”\n'),
	(6115, 6, 11, 7, 'So Joshua came suddenly, with all the warriors, against them by the waters of Merom, and attacked them.\n'),
	(6116, 6, 11, 8, 'Yahweh delivered them into the hand of Israel, and they struck them, and chased them to great Sidon, and to Misrephoth Maim, and to the valley of Mizpah eastward. They struck them until they left them no one remaining.\n'),
	(6117, 6, 11, 9, 'Joshua did to them as Yahweh told him. He hamstrung their horses and burned their chariots with fire.\n'),
	(6118, 6, 11, 10, 'Joshua turned back at that time, and took Hazor, and struck its king with the sword: for Hazor used to be the head of all those kingdoms.\n'),
	(6119, 6, 11, 11, 'They struck all the souls who were in it with the edge of the sword, utterly destroying them. There was no one left who breathed. He burned Hazor with fire.\n'),
	(6120, 6, 11, 12, 'Joshua captured all the cities of those kings, with their kings, and he struck them with the edge of the sword, and utterly destroyed them; as Moses the servant of Yahweh commanded.\n'),
	(6121, 6, 11, 13, 'But as for the cities that stood on their mounds, Israel burned none of them, except Hazor only. Joshua burned that.\n'),
	(6122, 6, 11, 14, 'The children of Israel took all the plunder of these cities, with the livestock, as plunder for themselves; but every man they struck with the edge of the sword, until they had destroyed them. They didn’t leave any who breathed.\n'),
	(6123, 6, 11, 15, 'As Yahweh commanded Moses his servant, so Moses commanded Joshua. Joshua did so. He left nothing undone of all that Yahweh commanded Moses.\n'),
	(6124, 6, 11, 16, 'So Joshua captured all that land, the hill country, all the South, all the land of Goshen, the lowland, the Arabah, the hill country of Israel, and the lowland of the same;\n'),
	(6125, 6, 11, 17, 'from Mount Halak, that goes up to Seir, even to Baal Gad in the valley of Lebanon under Mount Hermon. He took all their kings, struck them, and put them to death.\n'),
	(6126, 6, 11, 18, 'Joshua made war a long time with all those kings.\n'),
	(6127, 6, 11, 19, 'There was not a city that made peace with the children of Israel, except the Hivites, the inhabitants of Gibeon. They took all in battle.\n'),
	(6128, 6, 11, 20, 'For it was of Yahweh to harden their hearts, to come against Israel in battle, that he might utterly destroy them, that they might have no favor, but that he might destroy them, as Yahweh commanded Moses.\n'),
	(6129, 6, 11, 21, 'Joshua came at that time, and cut off the Anakim from the hill country, from Hebron, from Debir, from Anab, and from all the hill country of Judah, and from all the hill country of Israel: Joshua utterly destroyed them with their cities.\n'),
	(6130, 6, 11, 22, 'There were none of the Anakim left in the land of the children of Israel. Only in Gaza, in Gath, and in Ashdod, did some remain.\n'),
	(6131, 6, 11, 23, 'So Joshua took the whole land, according to all that Yahweh spoke to Moses; and Joshua gave it for an inheritance to Israel according to their divisions by their tribes. The land had rest from war.\n'),
	(6132, 6, 12, 1, 'Now these are the kings of the land, whom the children of Israel struck, and possessed their land beyond the Jordan toward the sunrise, from the valley of the Arnon to Mount Hermon, and all the Arabah eastward:\n'),
	(6133, 6, 12, 2, 'Sihon king of the Amorites, who lived in Heshbon, and ruled from Aroer, which is on the edge of the valley of the Arnon, and the middle of the valley, and half Gilead, even to the river Jabbok, the border of the children of Ammon;\n'),
	(6134, 6, 12, 3, 'and the Arabah to the sea of Chinneroth, eastward, and to the sea of the Arabah, even the Salt Sea, eastward, the way to Beth Jeshimoth; and on the south, under the slopes of Pisgah:\n'),
	(6135, 6, 12, 4, 'and the border of Og king of Bashan, of the remnant of the Rephaim, who lived at Ashtaroth and at Edrei,\n'),
	(6136, 6, 12, 5, 'and ruled in Mount Hermon, and in Salecah, and in all Bashan, to the border of the Geshurites and the Maacathites, and half Gilead, the border of Sihon king of Heshbon.\n'),
	(6137, 6, 12, 6, 'Moses the servant of Yahweh and the children of Israel struck them. Moses the servant of Yahweh gave it for a possession to the Reubenites, and the Gadites, and the half-tribe of Manasseh.\n'),
	(6138, 6, 12, 7, 'These are the kings of the land whom Joshua and the children of Israel struck beyond the Jordan westward, from Baal Gad in the valley of Lebanon even to Mount Halak, that goes up to Seir. Joshua gave it to the tribes of Israel for a possession according to their divisions;\n'),
	(6139, 6, 12, 8, 'in the hill country, and in the lowland, and in the Arabah, and in the slopes, and in the wilderness, and in the South; the Hittite, the Amorite, and the Canaanite, the Perizzite, the Hivite, and the Jebusite:\n'),
	(6140, 6, 12, 9, 'the king of Jericho, one;\nthe king of Ai, which is beside Bethel, one;\n'),
	(6141, 6, 12, 10, 'the king of Jerusalem, one;\nthe king of Hebron, one;\n'),
	(6142, 6, 12, 11, 'the king of Jarmuth, one;\nthe king of Lachish, one;\n'),
	(6143, 6, 12, 12, 'the king of Eglon, one;\nthe king of Gezer, one;\n'),
	(6144, 6, 12, 13, 'the king of Debir, one;\nthe king of Geder, one;\n'),
	(6145, 6, 12, 14, 'the king of Hormah, one;\nthe king of Arad, one;\n'),
	(6146, 6, 12, 15, 'the king of Libnah, one;\nthe king of Adullam, one;\n'),
	(6147, 6, 12, 16, 'the king of Makkedah, one;\nthe king of Bethel, one;\n'),
	(6148, 6, 12, 17, 'the king of Tappuah, one;\nthe king of Hepher, one;\n'),
	(6149, 6, 12, 18, 'the king of Aphek, one;\nthe king of Lassharon, one;\n'),
	(6150, 6, 12, 19, 'the king of Madon, one;\nthe king of Hazor, one;\n'),
	(6151, 6, 12, 20, 'the king of Shimron Meron, one;\nthe king of Achshaph, one;\n'),
	(6152, 6, 12, 21, 'the king of Taanach, one;\nthe king of Megiddo, one;\n'),
	(6153, 6, 12, 22, 'the king of Kedesh, one;\nthe king of Jokneam in Carmel, one;\n'),
	(6154, 6, 12, 23, 'the king of Dor in the height of Dor, one;\nthe king of Goiim in Gilgal, one;\n'),
	(6155, 6, 12, 24, 'the king of Tirzah, one:\nall the kings thirty-one.\n'),
	(6156, 6, 13, 1, 'Now Joshua was old and well advanced in years. Yahweh said to him, “You are old and advanced in years, and there remains yet very much land to be possessed.\n'),
	(6157, 6, 13, 2, '“This is the land that still remains: all the regions of the Philistines, and all the Geshurites;\n'),
	(6158, 6, 13, 3, 'from the Shihor, which is before Egypt, even to the border of Ekron northward, which is counted as Canaanite; the five lords of the Philistines; the Gazites, and the Ashdodites, the Ashkelonites, the Gittites, and the Ekronites; also the Avvim,\n'),
	(6159, 6, 13, 4, 'on the south; all the land of the Canaanites, and Mearah that belongs to the Sidonians, to Aphek, to the border of the Amorites;\n'),
	(6160, 6, 13, 5, 'and the land of the Gebalites, and all Lebanon, toward the sunrise, from Baal Gad under Mount Hermon to the entrance of Hamath;\n'),
	(6161, 6, 13, 6, 'all the inhabitants of the hill country from Lebanon to Misrephoth Maim, even all the Sidonians. I will drive them out from before the children of Israel. Just allocate it to Israel for an inheritance, as I have commanded you.\n'),
	(6162, 6, 13, 7, 'Now therefore divide this land for an inheritance to the nine tribes and the half-tribe of Manasseh.”\n'),
	(6163, 6, 13, 8, 'With him the Reubenites and the Gadites received their inheritance, which Moses gave them, beyond the Jordan eastward, even as Moses the servant of Yahweh gave them:\n'),
	(6164, 6, 13, 9, 'from Aroer, that is on the edge of the valley of the Arnon, and the city that is in the middle of the valley, and all the plain of Medeba to Dibon;\n'),
	(6165, 6, 13, 10, 'and all the cities of Sihon king of the Amorites, who reigned in Heshbon, to the border of the children of Ammon;\n'),
	(6166, 6, 13, 11, 'and Gilead, and the border of the Geshurites and Maacathites, and all Mount Hermon, and all Bashan to Salecah;\n'),
	(6167, 6, 13, 12, 'all the kingdom of Og in Bashan, who reigned in Ashtaroth and in Edrei (the same was left of the remnant of the Rephaim); for Moses attacked these, and drove them out.\n'),
	(6168, 6, 13, 13, 'Nevertheless the children of Israel didn’t drive out the Geshurites, nor the Maacathites: but Geshur and Maacath live within Israel to this day.\n'),
	(6169, 6, 13, 14, 'Only he gave no inheritance to the tribe of Levi. The offerings of Yahweh, the God of Israel, made by fire are his inheritance, as he spoke to him.\n'),
	(6170, 6, 13, 15, 'Moses gave to the tribe of the children of Reuben according to their families.\n'),
	(6171, 6, 13, 16, 'Their border was from Aroer, that is on the edge of the valley of the Arnon, and the city that is in the middle of the valley, and all the plain by Medeba;\n'),
	(6172, 6, 13, 17, 'Heshbon, and all its cities that are in the plain; Dibon, Bamoth Baal, Beth Baal Meon,\n'),
	(6173, 6, 13, 18, 'Jahaz, Kedemoth, Mephaath,\n'),
	(6174, 6, 13, 19, 'Kiriathaim, Sibmah, Zereth Shahar in the mount of the valley,\n'),
	(6175, 6, 13, 20, 'Beth Peor, the slopes of Pisgah, Beth Jeshimoth,\n'),
	(6176, 6, 13, 21, 'all the cities of the plain, and all the kingdom of Sihon king of the Amorites, who reigned in Heshbon, whom Moses struck with the chiefs of Midian, Evi, Rekem, Zur, Hur, and Reba, the princes of Sihon, who lived in the land.\n'),
	(6177, 6, 13, 22, 'The children of Israel also killed Balaam the son of Beor, the soothsayer, with the sword, among the rest of their slain.\n'),
	(6178, 6, 13, 23, 'The border of the children of Reuben was the bank of the Jordan. This was the inheritance of the children of Reuben according to their families, the cities and its villages.\n'),
	(6179, 6, 13, 24, 'Moses gave to the tribe of Gad, to the children of Gad, according to their families.\n'),
	(6180, 6, 13, 25, 'Their border was Jazer, and all the cities of Gilead, and half the land of the children of Ammon, to Aroer that is near Rabbah;\n'),
	(6181, 6, 13, 26, 'and from Heshbon to Ramath Mizpeh, and Betonim; and from Mahanaim to the border of Debir;\n'),
	(6182, 6, 13, 27, 'and in the valley, Beth Haram, Beth Nimrah, Succoth, and Zaphon, the rest of the kingdom of Sihon king of Heshbon, the Jordan’s bank, to the uttermost part of the sea of Chinnereth beyond the Jordan eastward.\n'),
	(6183, 6, 13, 28, 'This is the inheritance of the children of Gad according to their families, the cities and its villages.\n'),
	(6184, 6, 13, 29, 'Moses gave an inheritance to the half-tribe of Manasseh. It was for the half-tribe of the children of Manasseh according to their families.\n'),
	(6185, 6, 13, 30, 'Their border was from Mahanaim, all Bashan, all the kingdom of Og king of Bashan, and all the villages of Jair, which are in Bashan, sixty cities.\n'),
	(6186, 6, 13, 31, 'Half Gilead, Ashtaroth, and Edrei, the cities of the kingdom of Og in Bashan, were for the children of Machir the son of Manasseh, even for the half of the children of Machir according to their families.\n'),
	(6187, 6, 13, 32, 'These are the inheritances which Moses distributed in the plains of Moab, beyond the Jordan at Jericho, eastward.\n'),
	(6188, 6, 13, 33, 'But Moses gave no inheritance to the tribe of Levi. Yahweh, the God of Israel, is their inheritance, as he spoke to them.\n'),
	(6189, 6, 14, 1, 'These are the inheritances which the children of Israel took in the land of Canaan, which Eleazar the priest, Joshua the son of Nun, and the heads of the fathers’ houses of the tribes of the children of Israel, distributed to them,\n'),
	(6190, 6, 14, 2, 'by the lot of their inheritance, as Yahweh commanded by Moses, for the nine tribes, and for the half-tribe.\n'),
	(6191, 6, 14, 3, 'For Moses had given the inheritance of the two tribes and the half-tribe beyond the Jordan; but to the Levites he gave no inheritance among them.\n'),
	(6192, 6, 14, 4, 'For the children of Joseph were two tribes, Manasseh and Ephraim. They gave no portion to the Levites in the land, except cities to dwell in, with their suburbs for their livestock and for their property.\n'),
	(6193, 6, 14, 5, 'The children of Israel did as Yahweh commanded Moses, and they divided the land.\n'),
	(6194, 6, 14, 6, 'Then the children of Judah came near to Joshua in Gilgal. Caleb the son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite said to him, “You know the thing that Yahweh spoke to Moses the man of God concerning me and concerning you in Kadesh Barnea.\n'),
	(6195, 6, 14, 7, 'I was forty years old when Moses the servant of Yahweh sent me from Kadesh Barnea to spy out the land. I brought him word again as it was in my heart.\n'),
	(6196, 6, 14, 8, 'Nevertheless, my brothers who went up with me made the heart of the people melt; but I wholly followed Yahweh my God.\n'),
	(6197, 6, 14, 9, 'Moses swore on that day, saying, ‘Surely the land where you walked shall be an inheritance to you and to your children forever, because you have wholly followed Yahweh my God.’\n'),
	(6198, 6, 14, 10, '“Now, behold, Yahweh has kept me alive, as he spoke, these forty-five years, from the time that Yahweh spoke this word to Moses, while Israel walked in the wilderness. Now, behold, I am eighty-five years old, today.\n'),
	(6199, 6, 14, 11, 'As yet I am as strong today as I was in the day that Moses sent me. As my strength was then, even so is my strength now for war, to go out and to come in.\n'),
	(6200, 6, 14, 12, 'Now therefore give me this hill country, of which Yahweh spoke in that day; for you heard in that day how the Anakim were there, and great and fortified cities. It may be that Yahweh will be with me, and I shall drive them out, as Yahweh said.”\n'),
	(6201, 6, 14, 13, 'Joshua blessed him; and he gave Hebron to Caleb the son of Jephunneh for an inheritance.\n'),
	(6202, 6, 14, 14, 'Therefore Hebron became the inheritance of Caleb the son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite to this day, because he followed Yahweh, the God of Israel wholeheartedly.\n'),
	(6203, 6, 14, 15, 'Now the name of Hebron before was Kiriath Arba, after the greatest man among the Anakim. Then the land had rest from war.\n'),
	(6204, 6, 15, 1, 'The lot for the tribe of the children of Judah according to their families was to the border of Edom, even to the wilderness of Zin southward, at the uttermost part of the south.\n'),
	(6205, 6, 15, 2, 'Their south border was from the uttermost part of the Salt Sea, from the bay that looks southward;\n'),
	(6206, 6, 15, 3, 'and it went out southward of the ascent of Akrabbim, and passed along to Zin, and went up by the south of Kadesh Barnea, and passed along by Hezron, went up to Addar, and turned towards Karka;\n'),
	(6207, 6, 15, 4, 'and it passed along to Azmon, went out at the brook of Egypt; and the border ended at the sea. This shall be your south border.\n'),
	(6208, 6, 15, 5, 'The east border was the Salt Sea, even to the end of the Jordan. The border of the north quarter was from the bay of the sea at the end of the Jordan.\n'),
	(6209, 6, 15, 6, 'The border went up to Beth Hoglah, and passed along by the north of Beth Arabah; and the border went up to the stone of Bohan the son of Reuben.\n'),
	(6210, 6, 15, 7, 'The border went up to Debir from the valley of Achor, and so northward, looking toward Gilgal, that faces the ascent of Adummim, which is on the south side of the river. The border passed along to the waters of En Shemesh, and ended at En Rogel.\n'),
	(6211, 6, 15, 8, 'The border went up by the valley of the son of Hinnom to the side of the Jebusite (also called Jerusalem) southward; and the border went up to the top of the mountain that lies before the valley of Hinnom westward, which is at the farthest part of the valley of Rephaim northward.\n'),
	(6212, 6, 15, 9, 'The border extended from the top of the mountain to the spring of the waters of Nephtoah, and went out to the cities of Mount Ephron; and the border extended to Baalah (also called Kiriath Jearim);\n'),
	(6213, 6, 15, 10, 'and the border turned about from Baalah westward to Mount Seir, and passed along to the side of Mount Jearim (also called Chesalon) on the north, and went down to Beth Shemesh, and passed along by Timnah;\n'),
	(6214, 6, 15, 11, 'and the border went out to the side of Ekron northward; and the border extended to Shikkeron, and passed along to Mount Baalah, and went out at Jabneel; and the goings out of the border were at the sea.\n'),
	(6215, 6, 15, 12, 'The west border was to the shore of the great sea. This is the border of the children of Judah according to their families.\n'),
	(6216, 6, 15, 13, 'He gave to Caleb the son of Jephunneh a portion among the children of Judah, according to the commandment of Yahweh to Joshua, even Kiriath Arba, named after the father of Anak (also called Hebron).\n'),
	(6217, 6, 15, 14, 'Caleb drove out the three sons of Anak: Sheshai, and Ahiman, and Talmai, the children of Anak.\n'),
	(6218, 6, 15, 15, 'He went up against the inhabitants of Debir: now the name of Debir before was Kiriath Sepher.\n'),
	(6219, 6, 15, 16, 'Caleb said, “He who strikes Kiriath Sepher, and takes it, to him I will give Achsah my daughter as wife.”\n'),
	(6220, 6, 15, 17, 'Othniel the son of Kenaz, the brother of Caleb, took it: and he gave him Achsah his daughter as wife.\n'),
	(6221, 6, 15, 18, 'When she came, she had him ask her father for a field. She got off her donkey, and Caleb said, “What do you want?”\n'),
	(6222, 6, 15, 19, 'She said, “Give me a blessing. Because you have set me in the land of the South, give me also springs of water.”\nSo he gave her the upper springs and the lower springs.\n'),
	(6223, 6, 15, 20, 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the children of Judah according to their families.\n'),
	(6224, 6, 15, 21, 'The farthest cities of the tribe of the children of Judah toward the border of Edom in the South were Kabzeel, Eder, Jagur,\n'),
	(6225, 6, 15, 22, 'Kinah, Dimonah, Adadah,\n'),
	(6226, 6, 15, 23, 'Kedesh, Hazor, Ithnan,\n'),
	(6227, 6, 15, 24, 'Ziph, Telem, Bealoth,\n'),
	(6228, 6, 15, 25, 'Hazor Hadattah, Kerioth Hezron (also called Hazor),\n'),
	(6229, 6, 15, 26, 'Amam, Shema, Moladah,\n'),
	(6230, 6, 15, 27, 'Hazar Gaddah, Heshmon, Beth Pelet,\n'),
	(6231, 6, 15, 28, 'Hazar Shual, Beersheba, Biziothiah,\n'),
	(6232, 6, 15, 29, 'Baalah, Iim, Ezem,\n'),
	(6233, 6, 15, 30, 'Eltolad, Chesil, Hormah,\n'),
	(6234, 6, 15, 31, 'Ziklag, Madmannah, Sansannah,\n'),
	(6235, 6, 15, 32, 'Lebaoth, Shilhim, Ain, and Rimmon. All the cities are twenty-nine, with their villages.\n'),
	(6236, 6, 15, 33, 'In the lowland, Eshtaol, Zorah, Ashnah,\n'),
	(6237, 6, 15, 34, 'Zanoah, En Gannim, Tappuah, Enam,\n'),
	(6238, 6, 15, 35, 'Jarmuth, Adullam, Socoh, Azekah,\n'),
	(6239, 6, 15, 36, 'Shaaraim, Adithaim and Gederah (or Gederothaim); fourteen cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6240, 6, 15, 37, 'Zenan, Hadashah, Migdal Gad,\n'),
	(6241, 6, 15, 38, 'Dilean, Mizpah, Joktheel,\n'),
	(6242, 6, 15, 39, 'Lachish, Bozkath, Eglon,\n'),
	(6243, 6, 15, 40, 'Cabbon, Lahmam, Chitlish,\n'),
	(6244, 6, 15, 41, 'Gederoth, Beth Dagon, Naamah, and Makkedah; sixteen cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6245, 6, 15, 42, 'Libnah, Ether, Ashan,\n'),
	(6246, 6, 15, 43, 'Iphtah, Ashnah, Nezib,\n'),
	(6247, 6, 15, 44, 'Keilah, Achzib, and Mareshah; nine cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6248, 6, 15, 45, 'Ekron, with its towns and its villages;\n'),
	(6249, 6, 15, 46, 'from Ekron even to the sea, all that were by the side of Ashdod, with their villages.\n'),
	(6250, 6, 15, 47, 'Ashdod, its towns and its villages; Gaza, its towns and its villages; to the brook of Egypt, and the great sea with its coastline.\n'),
	(6251, 6, 15, 48, 'In the hill country, Shamir, Jattir, Socoh,\n'),
	(6252, 6, 15, 49, 'Dannah, Kiriath Sannah (which is Debir),\n'),
	(6253, 6, 15, 50, 'Anab, Eshtemoh, Anim,\n'),
	(6254, 6, 15, 51, 'Goshen, Holon, and Giloh; eleven cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6255, 6, 15, 52, 'Arab, Dumah, Eshan,\n'),
	(6256, 6, 15, 53, 'Janim, Beth Tappuah, Aphekah,\n'),
	(6257, 6, 15, 54, 'Humtah, Kiriath Arba (also called Hebron), and Zior; nine cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6258, 6, 15, 55, 'Maon, Carmel, Ziph, Jutah,\n'),
	(6259, 6, 15, 56, 'Jezreel, Jokdeam, Zanoah,\n'),
	(6260, 6, 15, 57, 'Kain, Gibeah, and Timnah; ten cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6261, 6, 15, 58, 'Halhul, Beth Zur, Gedor,\n'),
	(6262, 6, 15, 59, 'Maarath, Beth Anoth, and Eltekon; six cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6263, 6, 15, 60, 'Kiriath Baal (also called Kiriath Jearim), and Rabbah; two cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6264, 6, 15, 61, 'In the wilderness, Beth Arabah, Middin, Secacah,\n'),
	(6265, 6, 15, 62, 'Nibshan, the City of Salt, and En Gedi; six cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6266, 6, 15, 63, 'As for the Jebusites, the inhabitants of Jerusalem, the children of Judah couldn’t drive them out; but the Jebusites live with the children of Judah at Jerusalem to this day.\n'),
	(6267, 6, 16, 1, 'The lot came out for the children of Joseph from the Jordan at Jericho, at the waters of Jericho on the east, even the wilderness, going up from Jericho through the hill country to Bethel.\n'),
	(6268, 6, 16, 2, 'It went out from Bethel to Luz, and passed along to the border of the Archites to Ataroth;\n'),
	(6269, 6, 16, 3, 'and it went down westward to the border of the Japhletites, to the border of Beth Horon the lower, and on to Gezer; and ended at the sea.\n'),
	(6270, 6, 16, 4, 'The children of Joseph, Manasseh and Ephraim, took their inheritance.\n'),
	(6271, 6, 16, 5, 'This was the border of the children of Ephraim according to their families. The border of their inheritance eastward was Ataroth Addar, to Beth Horon the upper.\n'),
	(6272, 6, 16, 6, 'The border went out westward at Michmethath on the north. The border turned about eastward to Taanath Shiloh, and passed along it on the east of Janoah.\n'),
	(6273, 6, 16, 7, 'It went down from Janoah to Ataroth, to Naarah, reached to Jericho, and went out at the Jordan.\n'),
	(6274, 6, 16, 8, 'From Tappuah the border went along westward to the brook of Kanah; and ended at the sea. This is the inheritance of the tribe of the children of Ephraim according to their families;\n'),
	(6275, 6, 16, 9, 'together with the cities which were set apart for the children of Ephraim in the middle of the inheritance of the children of Manasseh, all the cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6276, 6, 16, 10, 'They didn’t drive out the Canaanites who lived in Gezer; but the Canaanites dwell in the territory of Ephraim to this day, and have become servants to do forced labor.\n'),
	(6277, 6, 17, 1, 'This was the lot for the tribe of Manasseh, for he was the firstborn of Joseph. As for Machir the firstborn of Manasseh, the father of Gilead, because he was a man of war, therefore he had Gilead and Bashan.\n'),
	(6278, 6, 17, 2, 'So this was for the rest of the children of Manasseh according to their families: for the children of Abiezer, for the children of Helek, for the children of Asriel, for the children of Shechem, for the children of Hepher, and for the children of Shemida. These were the male children of Manasseh the son of Joseph according to their families.\n'),
	(6279, 6, 17, 3, 'But Zelophehad, the son of Hepher, the son of Gilead, the son of Machir, the son of Manasseh, had no sons, but daughters. These are the names of his daughters: Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah.\n'),
	(6280, 6, 17, 4, 'They came to Eleazar the priest, and to Joshua the son of Nun, and to the princes, saying, “Yahweh commanded Moses to give us an inheritance among our brothers.” Therefore according to the commandment of Yahweh he gave them an inheritance among the brothers of their father.\n'),
	(6281, 6, 17, 5, 'Ten parts fell to Manasseh, besides the land of Gilead and Bashan, which is beyond the Jordan;\n'),
	(6282, 6, 17, 6, 'because the daughters of Manasseh had an inheritance among his sons. The land of Gilead belonged to the rest of the sons of Manasseh.\n'),
	(6283, 6, 17, 7, 'The border of Manasseh was from Asher to Michmethath, which is before Shechem. The border went along to the right hand, to the inhabitants of En Tappuah.\n'),
	(6284, 6, 17, 8, 'The land of Tappuah belonged to Manasseh; but Tappuah on the border of Manasseh belonged to the children of Ephraim.\n'),
	(6285, 6, 17, 9, 'The border went down to the brook of Kanah, southward of the brook. These cities belonged to Ephraim among the cities of Manasseh. The border of Manasseh was on the north side of the brook, and ended at the sea.\n'),
	(6286, 6, 17, 10, 'Southward it was Ephraim’s, and northward it was Manasseh’s, and the sea was his border. They reached to Asher on the north, and to Issachar on the east.\n'),
	(6287, 6, 17, 11, 'Manasseh had three heights in Issachar, in Asher Beth Shean and its towns, and Ibleam and its towns, and the inhabitants of Dor and its towns, and the inhabitants of Endor and its towns, and the inhabitants of Taanach and its towns, and the inhabitants of Megiddo and its towns.\n'),
	(6288, 6, 17, 12, 'Yet the children of Manasseh couldn’t drive out the inhabitants of those cities; but the Canaanites would dwell in that land.\n'),
	(6289, 6, 17, 13, 'When the children of Israel had grown strong, they put the Canaanites to forced labor, and didn’t utterly drive them out.\n'),
	(6290, 6, 17, 14, 'The children of Joseph spoke to Joshua, saying, “Why have you given me just one lot and one part for an inheritance, since we are a numerous people, because Yahweh has blessed us so far?”\n'),
	(6291, 6, 17, 15, 'Joshua said to them, “If you are a numerous people, go up to the forest, and clear land for yourself there in the land of the Perizzites and of the Rephaim; since the hill country of Ephraim is too narrow for you.”\n'),
	(6292, 6, 17, 16, 'The children of Joseph said, “The hill country is not enough for us. All the Canaanites who dwell in the land of the valley have chariots of iron, both those who are in Beth Shean and its towns, and those who are in the valley of Jezreel.”\n'),
	(6293, 6, 17, 17, 'Joshua spoke to the house of Joseph, that is, to Ephraim and to Manasseh, saying, “You are a numerous people, and have great power. You shall not have one lot only;\n'),
	(6294, 6, 17, 18, 'but the hill country shall be yours. Although it is a forest, you shall cut it down, and it’s farthest extent shall be yours; for you shall drive out the Canaanites, though they have chariots of iron, and though they are strong.”\n'),
	(6295, 6, 18, 1, 'The whole congregation of the children of Israel assembled themselves together at Shiloh, and set up the Tent of Meeting there. The land was subdued before them.\n'),
	(6296, 6, 18, 2, 'Seven tribes remained among the children of Israel, which had not yet divided their inheritance.\n'),
	(6297, 6, 18, 3, 'Joshua said to the children of Israel, “How long will you neglect to go in to possess the land, which Yahweh, the God of your fathers, has given you?\n'),
	(6298, 6, 18, 4, 'Appoint for yourselves three men from each tribe. I will send them, and they shall arise, walk through the land, and describe it according to their inheritance; and they shall come to me.\n'),
	(6299, 6, 18, 5, 'They shall divide it into seven portions. Judah shall live in his borders on the south, and the house of Joseph shall live in their borders on the north.\n'),
	(6300, 6, 18, 6, 'You shall survey the land into seven parts, and bring the description here to me; and I will cast lots for you here before Yahweh our God.\n'),
	(6301, 6, 18, 7, 'However, the Levites have no portion among you; for the priesthood of Yahweh is their inheritance. Gad, Reuben, and the half-tribe of Manasseh have received their inheritance east of the Jordan, which Moses the servant of Yahweh gave them.”\n'),
	(6302, 6, 18, 8, 'The men arose and went. Joshua commanded those who went to survey the land, saying, “Go walk through the land, survey it, and come again to me. I will cast lots for you here before Yahweh in Shiloh.”\n'),
	(6303, 6, 18, 9, 'The men went and passed through the land, and surveyed it by cities into seven portions in a book. They came to Joshua to the camp at Shiloh.\n'),
	(6304, 6, 18, 10, 'Joshua cast lots for them in Shiloh before Yahweh. There Joshua divided the land to the children of Israel according to their divisions.\n'),
	(6305, 6, 18, 11, 'The lot of the tribe of the children of Benjamin came up according to their families. The border of their lot went out between the children of Judah and the children of Joseph.\n'),
	(6306, 6, 18, 12, 'Their border on the north quarter was from the Jordan. The border went up to the side of Jericho on the north, and went up through the hill country westward. It ended at the wilderness of Beth Aven.\n'),
	(6307, 6, 18, 13, 'The border passed along from there to Luz, to the side of Luz (also called Bethel), southward. The border went down to Ataroth Addar, by the mountain that lies on the south of Beth Horon the lower.\n'),
	(6308, 6, 18, 14, 'The border extended, and turned around on the west quarter southward, from the mountain that lies before Beth Horon southward; and ended at Kiriath Baal (also called Kiriath Jearim), a city of the children of Judah. This was the west quarter.\n'),
	(6309, 6, 18, 15, 'The south quarter was from the farthest part of Kiriath Jearim. The border went out westward, and went out to the spring of the waters of Nephtoah.\n'),
	(6310, 6, 18, 16, 'The border went down to the farthest part of the mountain that lies before the valley of the son of Hinnom, which is in the valley of Rephaim northward. It went down to the valley of Hinnom, to the side of the Jebusite southward, and went down to En Rogel.\n'),
	(6311, 6, 18, 17, 'It extended northward, went out at En Shemesh, and went out to Geliloth, which is over against the ascent of Adummim. It went down to the stone of Bohan the son of Reuben.\n'),
	(6312, 6, 18, 18, 'It passed along to the side over against the Arabah northward, and went down to the Arabah.\n'),
	(6313, 6, 18, 19, 'The border passed along to the side of Beth Hoglah northward; and the border ended at the north bay of the Salt Sea, at the south end of the Jordan. This was the south border.\n'),
	(6314, 6, 18, 20, 'The Jordan was its border on the east quarter. This was the inheritance of the children of Benjamin, by the borders around it, according to their families.\n'),
	(6315, 6, 18, 21, 'Now the cities of the tribe of the children of Benjamin according to their families were Jericho, Beth Hoglah, Emek Keziz,\n'),
	(6316, 6, 18, 22, 'Beth Arabah, Zemaraim, Bethel,\n'),
	(6317, 6, 18, 23, 'Avvim, Parah, Ophrah,\n'),
	(6318, 6, 18, 24, 'Chephar Ammoni, Ophni, and Geba; twelve cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6319, 6, 18, 25, 'Gibeon, Ramah, Beeroth,\n'),
	(6320, 6, 18, 26, 'Mizpeh, Chephirah, Mozah,\n'),
	(6321, 6, 18, 27, 'Rekem, Irpeel, Taralah,\n'),
	(6322, 6, 18, 28, 'Zelah, Eleph, the Jebusite (also called Jerusalem), Gibeath, and Kiriath; fourteen cities with their villages. This is the inheritance of the children of Benjamin according to their families.\n'),
	(6323, 6, 19, 1, 'The second lot came out for Simeon, even for the tribe of the children of Simeon according to their families. Their inheritance was in the middle of the inheritance of the children of Judah.\n'),
	(6324, 6, 19, 2, 'They had for their inheritance Beersheba (or Sheba), Moladah,\n'),
	(6325, 6, 19, 3, 'Hazar Shual, Balah, Ezem,\n'),
	(6326, 6, 19, 4, 'Eltolad, Bethul, Hormah,\n'),
	(6327, 6, 19, 5, 'Ziklag, Beth Marcaboth, Hazar Susah,\n'),
	(6328, 6, 19, 6, 'Beth Lebaoth, and Sharuhen; thirteen cities with their villages;\n'),
	(6329, 6, 19, 7, 'Ain, Rimmon, Ether, and Ashan; four cities with their villages;\n'),
	(6330, 6, 19, 8, 'and all the villages that were around these cities to Baalath Beer, Ramah of the South. This is the inheritance of the tribe of the children of Simeon according to their families.\n'),
	(6331, 6, 19, 9, 'Out of the part of the children of Judah was the inheritance of the children of Simeon; for the portion of the children of Judah was too much for them. Therefore the children of Simeon had inheritance in the middle of their inheritance.\n'),
	(6332, 6, 19, 10, 'The third lot came up for the children of Zebulun according to their families. The border of their inheritance was to Sarid.\n'),
	(6333, 6, 19, 11, 'Their border went up westward, even to Maralah, and reached to Dabbesheth. It reached to the brook that is before Jokneam.\n'),
	(6334, 6, 19, 12, 'It turned from Sarid eastward toward the sunrise to the border of Chisloth Tabor. It went out to Daberath, and went up to Japhia.\n'),
	(6335, 6, 19, 13, 'From there it passed along eastward to Gath Hepher, to Ethkazin; and it went out at Rimmon which stretches to Neah.\n'),
	(6336, 6, 19, 14, 'The border turned around it on the north to Hannathon; and it ended at the valley of Iphtah El;\n'),
	(6337, 6, 19, 15, 'Kattath, Nahalal, Shimron, Idalah, and Bethlehem: twelve cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6338, 6, 19, 16, 'This is the inheritance of the children of Zebulun according to their families, these cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6339, 6, 19, 17, 'The fourth lot came out for Issachar, even for the children of Issachar according to their families.\n'),
	(6340, 6, 19, 18, 'Their border was to Jezreel, Chesulloth, Shunem,\n'),
	(6341, 6, 19, 19, 'Hapharaim, Shion, Anaharath,\n'),
	(6342, 6, 19, 20, 'Rabbith, Kishion, Ebez,\n'),
	(6343, 6, 19, 21, 'Remeth, Engannim, En Haddah, and Beth Pazzez.\n'),
	(6344, 6, 19, 22, 'The border reached to Tabor, Shahazumah, and Beth Shemesh. Their border ended at the Jordan: sixteen cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6345, 6, 19, 23, 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the children of Issachar according to their families, the cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6346, 6, 19, 24, 'The fifth lot came out for the tribe of the children of Asher according to their families.\n'),
	(6347, 6, 19, 25, 'Their border was Helkath, Hali, Beten, Achshaph,\n'),
	(6348, 6, 19, 26, 'Allammelech, Amad, Mishal. It reached to Carmel westward, and to Shihorlibnath.\n'),
	(6349, 6, 19, 27, 'It turned toward the sunrise to Beth Dagon, and reached to Zebulun, and to the valley of Iphtah El northward to Beth Emek and Neiel. It went out to Cabul on the left hand,\n'),
	(6350, 6, 19, 28, 'and Ebron, Rehob, Hammon, and Kanah, even to great Sidon.\n'),
	(6351, 6, 19, 29, 'The border turned to Ramah, to the fortified city of Tyre; and the border turned to Hosah. It ended at the sea by the region of Achzib;\n'),
	(6352, 6, 19, 30, 'Ummah also, and Aphek, and Rehob: twenty-two cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6353, 6, 19, 31, 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the children of Asher according to their families, these cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6354, 6, 19, 32, 'The sixth lot came out for the children of Naphtali, even for the children of Naphtali according to their families.\n'),
	(6355, 6, 19, 33, 'Their border was from Heleph, from the oak in Zaanannim, Adami-nekeb, and Jabneel, to Lakkum. It ended at the Jordan.\n'),
	(6356, 6, 19, 34, 'The border turned westward to Aznoth Tabor, and went out from there to Hukkok. It reached to Zebulun on the south, and reached to Asher on the west, and to Judah at the Jordan toward the sunrise.\n'),
	(6357, 6, 19, 35, 'The fortified cities were Ziddim, Zer, Hammath, Rakkath, Chinnereth,\n'),
	(6358, 6, 19, 36, 'Adamah, Ramah, Hazor,\n'),
	(6359, 6, 19, 37, 'Kedesh, Edrei, En Hazor,\n'),
	(6360, 6, 19, 38, 'Iron, Migdal El, Horem, Beth Anath, and Beth Shemesh; nineteen cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6361, 6, 19, 39, 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the children of Naphtali according to their families, the cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6362, 6, 19, 40, 'The seventh lot came out for the tribe of the children of Dan according to their families.\n'),
	(6363, 6, 19, 41, 'The border of their inheritance was Zorah, Eshtaol, Irshemesh,\n'),
	(6364, 6, 19, 42, 'Shaalabbin, Aijalon, Ithlah,\n'),
	(6365, 6, 19, 43, 'Elon, Timnah, Ekron,\n'),
	(6366, 6, 19, 44, 'Eltekeh, Gibbethon, Baalath,\n'),
	(6367, 6, 19, 45, 'Jehud, Bene Berak, Gath Rimmon,\n'),
	(6368, 6, 19, 46, 'Me Jarkon, and Rakkon, with the border over against Joppa.\n'),
	(6369, 6, 19, 47, 'The border of the children of Dan went out beyond them; for the children of Dan went up and fought against Leshem, and took it, and struck it with the edge of the sword, and possessed it, and lived therein, and called Leshem, Dan, after the name of Dan their forefather.\n'),
	(6370, 6, 19, 48, 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the children of Dan according to their families, these cities with their villages.\n'),
	(6371, 6, 19, 49, 'So they finished distributing the land for inheritance by its borders. The children of Israel gave an inheritance to Joshua the son of Nun among them.\n'),
	(6372, 6, 19, 50, 'According to Yahweh’s commandment, they gave him the city which he asked, even Timnathserah in the hill country of Ephraim; and he built the city, and lived there.\n'),
	(6373, 6, 19, 51, 'These are the inheritances, which Eleazar the priest, Joshua the son of Nun, and the heads of the fathers’ houses of the tribes of the children of Israel, distributed for inheritance by lot in Shiloh before Yahweh, at the door of the Tent of Meeting. So they finished dividing the land.\n'),
	(6374, 6, 20, 1, 'Yahweh spoke to Joshua, saying,\n'),
	(6375, 6, 20, 2, '“Speak to the children of Israel, saying, ‘Assign the cities of refuge, of which I spoke to you by Moses,\n'),
	(6376, 6, 20, 3, 'that the man slayer who kills any person accidentally or unintentionally may flee there. They shall be to you for a refuge from the avenger of blood.\n'),
	(6377, 6, 20, 4, 'He shall flee to one of those cities, and shall stand at the entrance of the gate of the city, and declare his case in the ears of the elders of that city. They shall take him into the city with them, and give him a place, that he may live among them.\n'),
	(6378, 6, 20, 5, 'If the avenger of blood pursues him, then they shall not deliver up the man slayer into his hand; because he struck his neighbor unintentionally, and didn’t hate him before.\n'),
	(6379, 6, 20, 6, 'He shall dwell in that city until he stands before the congregation for judgment, until the death of the high priest that shall be in those days. Then the man slayer shall return, and come to his own city, and to his own house, to the city he fled from.’”\n'),
	(6380, 6, 20, 7, 'They set apart Kedesh in Galilee in the hill country of Naphtali, Shechem in the hill country of Ephraim, and Kiriath Arba (also called Hebron) in the hill country of Judah.\n'),
	(6381, 6, 20, 8, 'Beyond the Jordan at Jericho eastward, they assigned Bezer in the wilderness in the plain out of the tribe of Reuben, Ramoth in Gilead out of the tribe of Gad, and Golan in Bashan out of the tribe of Manasseh.\n'),
	(6382, 6, 20, 9, 'These were the appointed cities for all the children of Israel, and for the alien who lives among them, that whoever kills any person unintentionally might flee there, and not die by the hand of the avenger of blood, until he stands trial before the congregation.\n'),
	(6383, 6, 21, 1, 'Then the heads of fathers’ houses of the Levites came near to Eleazar the priest, and to Joshua the son of Nun, and to the heads of fathers’ houses of the tribes of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(6384, 6, 21, 2, 'They spoke to them at Shiloh in the land of Canaan, saying, “Yahweh commanded through Moses to give us cities to dwell in, with their suburbs for our livestock.”\n'),
	(6385, 6, 21, 3, 'The children of Israel gave to the Levites out of their inheritance, according to the commandment of Yahweh, these cities with their suburbs.\n'),
	(6386, 6, 21, 4, 'The lot came out for the families of the Kohathites. The children of Aaron the priest, who were of the Levites, had thirteen cities by lot out of the tribe of Judah, out of the tribe of the Simeonites, and out of the tribe of Benjamin.\n'),
	(6387, 6, 21, 5, 'The rest of the children of Kohath had ten cities by lot out of the families of the tribe of Ephraim, out of the tribe of Dan, and out of the half-tribe of Manasseh.\n'),
	(6388, 6, 21, 6, 'The children of Gershon had thirteen cities by lot out of the families of the tribe of Issachar, out of the tribe of Asher, out of the tribe of Naphtali, and out of the half-tribe of Manasseh in Bashan.\n'),
	(6389, 6, 21, 7, 'The children of Merari according to their families had twelve cities out of the tribe of Reuben, out of the tribe of Gad, and out of the tribe of Zebulun.\n'),
	(6390, 6, 21, 8, 'The children of Israel gave these cities with their suburbs by lot to the Levites, as Yahweh commanded by Moses.\n'),
	(6391, 6, 21, 9, 'They gave out of the tribe of the children of Judah, and out of the tribe of the children of Simeon, these cities which are mentioned by name:\n'),
	(6392, 6, 21, 10, 'and they were for the children of Aaron, of the families of the Kohathites, who were of the children of Levi; for theirs was the first lot.\n'),
	(6393, 6, 21, 11, 'They gave them Kiriath Arba, named after the father of Anak (also called Hebron), in the hill country of Judah, with its suburbs around it.\n'),
	(6394, 6, 21, 12, 'But they gave the fields of the city and its villages to Caleb the son of Jephunneh for his possession.\n'),
	(6395, 6, 21, 13, 'To the children of Aaron the priest they gave Hebron with its suburbs, the city of refuge for the man slayer, Libnah with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6396, 6, 21, 14, 'Jattir with its suburbs, Eshtemoa with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6397, 6, 21, 15, 'Holon with its suburbs, Debir with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6398, 6, 21, 16, 'Ain with its suburbs, Juttah with its suburbs, and Beth Shemesh with its suburbs: nine cities out of those two tribes.\n'),
	(6399, 6, 21, 17, 'Out of the tribe of Benjamin, Gibeon with its suburbs, Geba with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6400, 6, 21, 18, 'Anathoth with its suburbs, and Almon with its suburbs: four cities.\n'),
	(6401, 6, 21, 19, 'All the cities of the children of Aaron, the priests, were thirteen cities with their suburbs.\n'),
	(6402, 6, 21, 20, 'The families of the children of Kohath, the Levites, even the rest of the children of Kohath, had the cities of their lot out of the tribe of Ephraim.\n'),
	(6403, 6, 21, 21, 'They gave them Shechem with its suburbs in the hill country of Ephraim, the city of refuge for the man slayer, and Gezer with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6404, 6, 21, 22, 'Kibzaim with its suburbs, and Beth Horon with its suburbs: four cities.\n'),
	(6405, 6, 21, 23, 'Out of the tribe of Dan, Elteke with its suburbs, Gibbethon with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6406, 6, 21, 24, 'Aijalon with its suburbs, Gath Rimmon with its suburbs: four cities.\n'),
	(6407, 6, 21, 25, 'Out of the half-tribe of Manasseh, Taanach with its suburbs, and Gath Rimmon with its suburbs: two cities.\n'),
	(6408, 6, 21, 26, 'All the cities of the families of the rest of the children of Kohath were ten with their suburbs.\n'),
	(6409, 6, 21, 27, 'They gave to the children of Gershon, of the families of the Levites, out of the half-tribe of Manasseh Golan in Bashan with its suburbs, the city of refuge for the man slayer, and Be Eshterah with its suburbs: two cities.\n'),
	(6410, 6, 21, 28, 'Out of the tribe of Issachar, Kishion with its suburbs, Daberath with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6411, 6, 21, 29, 'Jarmuth with its suburbs, En Gannim with its suburbs: four cities.\n'),
	(6412, 6, 21, 30, 'Out of the tribe of Asher, Mishal with its suburbs, Abdon with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6413, 6, 21, 31, 'Helkath with its suburbs, and Rehob with its suburbs: four cities.\n'),
	(6414, 6, 21, 32, 'Out of the tribe of Naphtali, Kedesh in Galilee with its suburbs, the city of refuge for the man slayer, Hammothdor with its suburbs, and Kartan with its suburbs: three cities.\n'),
	(6415, 6, 21, 33, 'All the cities of the Gershonites according to their families were thirteen cities with their suburbs.\n'),
	(6416, 6, 21, 34, 'To the families of the children of Merari, the rest of the Levites, out of the tribe of Zebulun, Jokneam with its suburbs, Kartah with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6417, 6, 21, 35, 'Dimnah with its suburbs, and Nahalal with its suburbs: four cities.\n'),
	(6418, 6, 21, 36, 'Out of the tribe of Reuben, Bezer with its suburbs, Jahaz with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6419, 6, 21, 37, 'Kedemoth with its suburbs, and Mephaath with its suburbs: four cities.\n'),
	(6420, 6, 21, 38, 'Out of the tribe of Gad, Ramoth in Gilead with its suburbs, the city of refuge for the man slayer, and Mahanaim with its suburbs,\n'),
	(6421, 6, 21, 39, 'Heshbon with its suburbs, Jazer with its suburbs: four cities in all.\n'),
	(6422, 6, 21, 40, 'All these were the cities of the children of Merari according to their families, even the rest of the families of the Levites. Their lot was twelve cities.\n'),
	(6423, 6, 21, 41, 'All the cities of the Levites among the possessions of the children of Israel were forty-eight cities with their suburbs.\n'),
	(6424, 6, 21, 42, 'Each of these cities included their suburbs around them. It was this way with all these cities.\n'),
	(6425, 6, 21, 43, 'So Yahweh gave to Israel all the land which he swore to give to their fathers. They possessed it, and lived in it.\n'),
	(6426, 6, 21, 44, 'Yahweh gave them rest all around, according to all that he swore to their fathers. Not a man of all their enemies stood before them. Yahweh delivered all their enemies into their hand.\n'),
	(6427, 6, 21, 45, 'Nothing failed of any good thing which Yahweh had spoken to the house of Israel. All came to pass.\n'),
	(6428, 6, 22, 1, 'Then Joshua called the Reubenites, the Gadites, and the half-tribe of Manasseh,\n'),
	(6429, 6, 22, 2, 'and said to them, “You have kept all that Moses the servant of Yahweh commanded you, and have listened to my voice in all that I commanded you.\n'),
	(6430, 6, 22, 3, 'You have not left your brothers these many days to this day, but have performed the duty of the commandment of Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(6431, 6, 22, 4, 'Now Yahweh your God has given rest to your brothers, as he spoke to them. Therefore now return and go to your tents, to the land of your possession, which Moses the servant of Yahweh gave you beyond the Jordan.\n'),
	(6432, 6, 22, 5, 'Only take diligent heed to do the commandment and the law which Moses the servant of Yahweh commanded you, to love Yahweh your God, to walk in all his ways, to keep his commandments, to hold fast to him, and to serve him with all your heart and with all your soul.”\n'),
	(6433, 6, 22, 6, 'So Joshua blessed them, and sent them away; and they went to their tents.\n'),
	(6434, 6, 22, 7, 'Now to the one half-tribe of Manasseh Moses had given inheritance in Bashan; but to the other half gave Joshua among their brothers beyond the Jordan westward. Moreover when Joshua sent them away to their tents, he blessed them,\n'),
	(6435, 6, 22, 8, 'and spoke to them, saying, “Return with much wealth to your tents, with very much livestock, with silver, with gold, with brass, with iron, and with very much clothing. Divide the plunder of your enemies with your brothers.”\n'),
	(6436, 6, 22, 9, 'The children of Reuben and the children of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh returned, and departed from the children of Israel out of Shiloh, which is in the land of Canaan, to go to the land of Gilead, to the land of their possession, which they owned, according to the commandment of Yahweh by Moses.\n'),
	(6437, 6, 22, 10, 'When they came to the region about the Jordan, that is in the land of Canaan, the children of Reuben and the children of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh built there an altar by the Jordan, a great altar to look at.\n'),
	(6438, 6, 22, 11, 'The children of Israel heard this, “Behold, the children of Reuben and the children of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh have built an altar in the border of the land of Canaan, in the region around the Jordan, on the side that belongs to the children of Israel.”\n'),
	(6439, 6, 22, 12, 'When the children of Israel heard of it, the whole congregation of the children of Israel gathered themselves together at Shiloh, to go up against them to war.\n'),
	(6440, 6, 22, 13, 'The children of Israel sent to the children of Reuben, and to the children of Gad, and to the half-tribe of Manasseh, into the land of Gilead, Phinehas the son of Eleazar the priest.\n'),
	(6441, 6, 22, 14, 'With him were ten princes, one prince of a fathers’ house for each of the tribes of Israel; and they were each head of their fathers’ houses among the thousands of Israel.\n'),
	(6442, 6, 22, 15, 'They came to the children of Reuben, and to the children of Gad, and to the half-tribe of Manasseh, to the land of Gilead, and they spoke with them, saying,\n'),
	(6443, 6, 22, 16, '“Thus says the whole congregation of Yahweh, ‘What trespass is this that you have committed against the God of Israel, to turn away today from following Yahweh, in that you have built yourselves an altar, to rebel today against Yahweh?\n'),
	(6444, 6, 22, 17, 'Is the iniquity of Peor too little for us, from which we have not cleansed ourselves to this day, although there came a plague on the congregation of Yahweh,\n'),
	(6445, 6, 22, 18, 'that you must turn away today from following Yahweh? It will be, since you rebel today against Yahweh, that tomorrow he will be angry with the whole congregation of Israel.\n'),
	(6446, 6, 22, 19, 'However, if the land of your possession is unclean, then pass over to the land of the possession of Yahweh, in which Yahweh’s tabernacle dwells, and take possession among us; but don’t rebel against Yahweh, nor rebel against us, in building an altar other than Yahweh our God’s altar.\n'),
	(6447, 6, 22, 20, 'Didn’t Achan the son of Zerah commit a trespass in the devoted thing, and wrath fell on all the congregation of Israel? That man didn’t perish alone in his iniquity.’”\n'),
	(6448, 6, 22, 21, 'Then the children of Reuben and the children of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh answered, and spoke to the heads of the thousands of Israel,\n'),
	(6449, 6, 22, 22, '“The Mighty One, God, Yahweh, the Mighty One, God, Yahweh, he knows; and Israel shall know: if it was in rebellion, or if in trespass against Yahweh (don’t save us today),\n'),
	(6450, 6, 22, 23, 'that we have built us an altar to turn away from following Yahweh; or if to offer burnt offering or meal offering, or if to offer sacrifices of peace offerings, let Yahweh himself require it.\n'),
	(6451, 6, 22, 24, '“If we have not out of concern done this, and for a reason, saying, ‘In time to come your children might speak to our children, saying, “What have you to do with Yahweh, the God of Israel?\n'),
	(6452, 6, 22, 25, 'For Yahweh has made the Jordan a border between us and you, you children of Reuben and children of Gad. You have no portion in Yahweh.”’ So your children might make our children cease from fearing Yahweh.\n'),
	(6453, 6, 22, 26, '“Therefore we said, ‘Let’s now prepare to build ourselves an altar, not for burnt offering, nor for sacrifice;\n'),
	(6454, 6, 22, 27, 'but it will be a witness between us and you, and between our generations after us, that we may perform the service of Yahweh before him with our burnt offerings, with our sacrifices, and with our peace offerings;’ that your children may not tell our children in time to come, ‘You have no portion in Yahweh.’\n'),
	(6455, 6, 22, 28, '“Therefore we said, ‘It shall be, when they tell us or our generations this in time to come, that we shall say, “Behold the pattern of Yahweh’s altar, which our fathers made, not for burnt offering, nor for sacrifice; but it is a witness between us and you.”’\n'),
	(6456, 6, 22, 29, '“Far be it from us that we should rebel against Yahweh, and turn away today from following Yahweh, to build an altar for burnt offering, for meal offering, or for sacrifice, besides Yahweh our God’s altar that is before his tabernacle!”\n'),
	(6457, 6, 22, 30, 'When Phinehas the priest, and the princes of the congregation, even the heads of the thousands of Israel that were with him, heard the words that the children of Reuben and the children of Gad and the children of Manasseh spoke, it pleased them well.\n'),
	(6458, 6, 22, 31, 'Phinehas the son of Eleazar the priest said to the children of Reuben, to the children of Gad, and to the children of Manasseh, “Today we know that Yahweh is among us, because you have not committed this trespass against Yahweh. Now you have delivered the children of Israel out of Yahweh’s hand.”\n'),
	(6459, 6, 22, 32, 'Phinehas the son of Eleazar the priest, and the princes, returned from the children of Reuben, and from the children of Gad, out of the land of Gilead, to the land of Canaan, to the children of Israel, and brought them word again.\n'),
	(6460, 6, 22, 33, 'The thing pleased the children of Israel; and the children of Israel blessed God, and spoke no more of going up against them to war, to destroy the land in which the children of Reuben and the children of Gad lived.\n'),
	(6461, 6, 22, 34, 'The children of Reuben and the children of Gad named the altar “A Witness Between Us that Yahweh is God.”\n'),
	(6462, 6, 23, 1, 'After many days, when Yahweh had given rest to Israel from their enemies all around, and Joshua was old and well advanced in years,\n'),
	(6463, 6, 23, 2, 'Joshua called for all Israel, for their elders and for their heads, and for their judges and for their officers, and said to them, “I am old and well advanced in years.\n'),
	(6464, 6, 23, 3, 'You have seen all that Yahweh your God has done to all these nations because of you; for it is Yahweh your God who has fought for you.\n'),
	(6465, 6, 23, 4, 'Behold, I have allotted to you these nations that remain, to be an inheritance for your tribes, from the Jordan, with all the nations that I have cut off, even to the great sea toward the going down of the sun.\n'),
	(6466, 6, 23, 5, 'Yahweh your God will thrust them out from before you, and drive them from out of your sight. You shall possess their land, as Yahweh your God spoke to you.\n'),
	(6467, 6, 23, 6, '“Therefore be very courageous to keep and to do all that is written in the book of the law of Moses, that you not turn away from it to the right hand or to the left;\n'),
	(6468, 6, 23, 7, 'that you not come among these nations, these that remain among you; neither make mention of the name of their gods, nor cause to swear by them, neither serve them, nor bow down yourselves to them;\n'),
	(6469, 6, 23, 8, 'but hold fast to Yahweh your God, as you have done to this day.\n'),
	(6470, 6, 23, 9, '“For Yahweh has driven great and strong nations out from before you. But as for you, no man has stood before you to this day.\n'),
	(6471, 6, 23, 10, 'One man of you shall chase a thousand; for it is Yahweh your God who fights for you, as he spoke to you.\n'),
	(6472, 6, 23, 11, 'Take good heed therefore to yourselves, that you love Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(6473, 6, 23, 12, '“But if you do at all go back, and hold fast to the remnant of these nations, even these who remain among you, and make marriages with them, and go in to them, and they to you;\n'),
	(6474, 6, 23, 13, 'know for a certainty that Yahweh your God will no longer drive these nations from out of your sight; but they shall be a snare and a trap to you, a scourge in your sides, and thorns in your eyes, until you perish from off this good land which Yahweh your God has given you.\n'),
	(6475, 6, 23, 14, '“Behold, today I am going the way of all the earth. You know in all your hearts and in all your souls that not one thing has failed of all the good things which Yahweh your God spoke concerning you. All have happened to you. Not one thing has failed of it.\n'),
	(6476, 6, 23, 15, 'It shall happen that as all the good things have come on you of which Yahweh your God spoke to you, so Yahweh will bring on you all the evil things, until he has destroyed you from off this good land which Yahweh your God has given you,\n'),
	(6477, 6, 23, 16, 'when you disobey the covenant of Yahweh your God, which he commanded you, and go and serve other gods, and bow down yourselves to them. Then Yahweh’s anger will be kindled against you, and you will perish quickly from off the good land which he has given to you.”\n'),
	(6478, 6, 24, 1, 'Joshua gathered all the tribes of Israel to Shechem, and called for the elders of Israel, for their heads, for their judges, and for their officers; and they presented themselves before God.\n'),
	(6479, 6, 24, 2, 'Joshua said to all the people, “Yahweh says, the God of Israel, ‘Your fathers lived of old time beyond the River, even Terah, the father of Abraham, and the father of Nahor: and they served other gods.\n'),
	(6480, 6, 24, 3, 'I took your father Abraham from beyond the River, and led him throughout all the land of Canaan, and multiplied his offspring, and gave him Isaac.\n'),
	(6481, 6, 24, 4, 'I gave to Isaac Jacob and Esau: and I gave to Esau Mount Seir, to possess it. Jacob and his children went down into Egypt.\n'),
	(6482, 6, 24, 5, '“‘I sent Moses and Aaron, and I plagued Egypt, according to that which I did among them: and afterward I brought you out.\n'),
	(6483, 6, 24, 6, 'I brought your fathers out of Egypt: and you came to the sea. The Egyptians pursued your fathers with chariots and with horsemen to the Red Sea.\n'),
	(6484, 6, 24, 7, 'When they cried out to Yahweh, he put darkness between you and the Egyptians, and brought the sea on them, and covered them; and your eyes saw what I did in Egypt. You lived in the wilderness many days.\n'),
	(6485, 6, 24, 8, '“‘I brought you into the land of the Amorites, that lived beyond the Jordan. They fought with you, and I gave them into your hand. You possessed their land, and I destroyed them from before you.\n'),
	(6486, 6, 24, 9, 'Then Balak the son of Zippor, king of Moab, arose and fought against Israel. He sent and called Balaam the son of Beor to curse you,\n'),
	(6487, 6, 24, 10, 'but I would not listen to Balaam; therefore he blessed you still. So I delivered you out of his hand.\n'),
	(6488, 6, 24, 11, '“‘You went over the Jordan, and came to Jericho. The men of Jericho fought against you, the Amorite, the Perizzite, the Canaanite, the Hittite, the Girgashite, the Hivite, and the Jebusite; and I delivered them into your hand.\n'),
	(6489, 6, 24, 12, 'I sent the hornet before you, which drove them out from before you, even the two kings of the Amorites; not with your sword, nor with your bow.\n'),
	(6490, 6, 24, 13, 'I gave you a land whereon you had not labored, and cities which you didn’t build, and you live in them. You eat of vineyards and olive groves which you didn’t plant.’\n'),
	(6491, 6, 24, 14, '“Now therefore fear Yahweh, and serve him in sincerity and in truth. Put away the gods which your fathers served beyond the River, in Egypt; and serve Yahweh.\n'),
	(6492, 6, 24, 15, 'If it seems evil to you to serve Yahweh, choose today whom you will serve; whether the gods which your fathers served that were beyond the River, or the gods of the Amorites, in whose land you dwell; but as for me and my house, we will serve Yahweh.”\n'),
	(6493, 6, 24, 16, 'The people answered, “Far be it from us that we should forsake Yahweh, to serve other gods;\n'),
	(6494, 6, 24, 17, 'for it is Yahweh our God who brought us and our fathers up out of the land of Egypt, from the house of bondage, and who did those great signs in our sight, and preserved us in all the way in which we went, and among all the peoples through the middle of whom we passed.\n'),
	(6495, 6, 24, 18, 'Yahweh drove out from before us all the peoples, even the Amorites who lived in the land. Therefore we also will serve Yahweh; for he is our God.”\n'),
	(6496, 6, 24, 19, 'Joshua said to the people, “You can’t serve Yahweh, for he is a holy God. He is a jealous God. He will not forgive your disobedience nor your sins.\n'),
	(6497, 6, 24, 20, 'If you forsake Yahweh, and serve foreign gods, then he will turn and do you evil, and consume you, after he has done you good.”\n'),
	(6498, 6, 24, 21, 'The people said to Joshua, “No, but we will serve Yahweh.”\n'),
	(6499, 6, 24, 22, 'Joshua said to the people, “You are witnesses against yourselves that you have chosen Yahweh yourselves, to serve him.”\nThey said, “We are witnesses.”\n'),
	(6500, 6, 24, 23, '“Now therefore put away the foreign gods which are among you, and incline your heart to Yahweh, the God of Israel.”\n'),
	(6501, 6, 24, 24, 'The people said to Joshua, “We will serve Yahweh our God, and we will listen to his voice.”\n'),
	(6502, 6, 24, 25, 'So Joshua made a covenant with the people that day, and made for them a statute and an ordinance in Shechem.\n'),
	(6503, 6, 24, 26, 'Joshua wrote these words in the book of the law of God; and he took a great stone, and set it up there under the oak that was by the sanctuary of Yahweh.\n'),
	(6504, 6, 24, 27, 'Joshua said to all the people, “Behold, this stone shall be a witness against us, for it has heard all Yahweh’s words which he spoke to us. It shall be therefore a witness against you, lest you deny your God.”\n'),
	(6505, 6, 24, 28, 'So Joshua sent the people away, each to his own inheritance.\n'),
	(6506, 6, 24, 29, 'After these things, Joshua the son of Nun, the servant of Yahweh, died, being one hundred ten years old.\n'),
	(6507, 6, 24, 30, 'They buried him in the border of his inheritance in Timnathserah, which is in the hill country of Ephraim, on the north of the mountain of Gaash.\n'),
	(6508, 6, 24, 31, 'Israel served Yahweh all the days of Joshua, and all the days of the elders who outlived Joshua, and had known all the work of Yahweh, that he had worked for Israel.\n'),
	(6509, 6, 24, 32, 'They buried the bones of Joseph, which the children of Israel brought up out of Egypt, in Shechem, in the parcel of ground which Jacob bought from the sons of Hamor the father of Shechem for a hundred pieces of silver. They became the inheritance of the children of Joseph.\n'),
	(6510, 6, 24, 33, 'Eleazar the son of Aaron died. They buried him in the hill of Phinehas his son, which was given him in the hill country of Ephraim.\n'),
	(6511, 7, 1, 1, 'After the death of Joshua, the children of Israel asked of Yahweh,\n saying, “Who should go up for us first against the Canaanites, to fight against them?”\n'),
	(6512, 7, 1, 2, 'Yahweh said, “Judah shall go up. Behold, I have delivered the land into his hand.”\n'),
	(6513, 7, 1, 3, 'Judah said to Simeon his brother, “Come up with me into my lot, that we may fight against the Canaanites; and I likewise will go with you into your lot.” So Simeon went with him.\n'),
	(6514, 7, 1, 4, 'Judah went up, and Yahweh delivered the Canaanites and the Perizzites into their hand. They struck ten thousand men in Bezek.\n'),
	(6515, 7, 1, 5, 'They found Adoni-Bezek in Bezek, and they fought against him. They struck the Canaanites and the Perizzites.\n'),
	(6516, 7, 1, 6, 'But Adoni-Bezek fled. They pursued him, caught him, and cut off his thumbs and his big toes.\n'),
	(6517, 7, 1, 7, 'Adoni-Bezek said, “Seventy kings, having their thumbs and their big toes cut off, scavenged under my table. As I have done, so God has done to me.” They brought him to Jerusalem, and he died there.\n'),
	(6518, 7, 1, 8, 'The children of Judah fought against Jerusalem, took it, struck it with the edge of the sword, and set the city on fire.\n'),
	(6519, 7, 1, 9, 'After that, the children of Judah went down to fight against the Canaanites who lived in the hill country, and in the South, and in the lowland.\n'),
	(6520, 7, 1, 10, 'Judah went against the Canaanites who lived in Hebron. (The name of Hebron before that was Kiriath Arba.) They struck Sheshai, Ahiman, and Talmai.\n'),
	(6521, 7, 1, 11, 'From there he went against the inhabitants of Debir. (The name of Debir before that was Kiriath Sepher.)\n'),
	(6522, 7, 1, 12, 'Caleb said, “I will give Achsah my daughter as wife to the man who strikes Kiriath Sepher, and takes it.”\n'),
	(6523, 7, 1, 13, 'Othniel the son of Kenaz, Caleb’s younger brother, took it, so he gave him Achsah his daughter as his wife.\n'),
	(6524, 7, 1, 14, 'When she came, she got him to ask her father for a field. She got off her donkey; and Caleb said to her, “What would you like?”\n'),
	(6525, 7, 1, 15, 'She said to him, “Give me a blessing; because you have set me in the land of the South, give me also springs of water.” Then Caleb gave her the upper springs and the lower springs.\n'),
	(6526, 7, 1, 16, 'The children of the Kenite, Moses’ brother-in-law, went up out of the city of palm trees with the children of Judah into the wilderness of Judah, which is in the south of Arad; and they went and lived with the people.\n'),
	(6527, 7, 1, 17, 'Judah went with Simeon his brother, and they struck the Canaanites who inhabited Zephath, and utterly destroyed it. The name of the city was called Hormah.\n'),
	(6528, 7, 1, 18, 'Also Judah took Gaza with its border, and Ashkelon with its border, and Ekron with its border.\n'),
	(6529, 7, 1, 19, 'Yahweh was with Judah; and drove out the inhabitants of the hill country; for he could not drive out the inhabitants of the valley, because they had chariots of iron.\n'),
	(6530, 7, 1, 20, 'They gave Hebron to Caleb, as Moses had said, and he drove the three sons of Anak out of there.\n'),
	(6531, 7, 1, 21, 'The children of Benjamin did not drive out the Jebusites who inhabited Jerusalem, but the Jebusites dwell with the children of Benjamin in Jerusalem to this day.\n'),
	(6532, 7, 1, 22, 'The house of Joseph also went up against Bethel, and Yahweh was with them.\n'),
	(6533, 7, 1, 23, 'The house of Joseph sent to spy out Bethel. (The name of the city before that was Luz.)\n'),
	(6534, 7, 1, 24, 'The watchers saw a man come out of the city, and they said to him, “Please show us the entrance into the city, and we will deal kindly with you.”\n'),
	(6535, 7, 1, 25, 'He showed them the entrance into the city, and they struck the city with the edge of the sword; but they let the man and all his family go.\n'),
	(6536, 7, 1, 26, 'The man went into the land of the Hittites, built a city, and called its name Luz, which is its name to this day.\n'),
	(6537, 7, 1, 27, 'Manasseh did not drive out the inhabitants of Beth Shean and its towns, nor Taanach and its towns, nor the inhabitants of Dor and its towns, nor the inhabitants of Ibleam and its towns, nor the inhabitants of Megiddo and its towns; but the Canaanites would dwell in that land.\n'),
	(6538, 7, 1, 28, 'When Israel had grown strong, they put the Canaanites to forced labor, and did not utterly drive them out.\n'),
	(6539, 7, 1, 29, 'Ephraim didn’t drive out the Canaanites who lived in Gezer, but the Canaanites lived in Gezer among them.\n'),
	(6540, 7, 1, 30, 'Zebulun didn’t drive out the inhabitants of Kitron, nor the inhabitants of Nahalol; but the Canaanites lived among them, and became subject to forced labor.\n'),
	(6541, 7, 1, 31, 'Asher didn’t drive out the inhabitants of Acco, nor the inhabitants of Sidon, nor of Ahlab, nor of Achzib, nor of Helbah, nor of Aphik, nor of Rehob;\n'),
	(6542, 7, 1, 32, 'but the Asherites lived among the Canaanites, the inhabitants of the land; for they did not drive them out.\n'),
	(6543, 7, 1, 33, 'Naphtali didn’t drive out the inhabitants of Beth Shemesh, nor the inhabitants of Beth Anath; but he lived among the Canaanites, the inhabitants of the land. Nevertheless the inhabitants of Beth Shemesh and of Beth Anath became subject to forced labor.\n'),
	(6544, 7, 1, 34, 'The Amorites forced the children of Dan into the hill country, for they would not allow them to come down to the valley;\n'),
	(6545, 7, 1, 35, 'but the Amorites would dwell in Mount Heres, in Aijalon, and in Shaalbim. Yet the hand of the house of Joseph prevailed, so that they became subject to forced labor.\n'),
	(6546, 7, 1, 36, 'The border of the Amorites was from the ascent of Akrabbim, from the rock, and upward.\n'),
	(6547, 7, 2, 1, 'Yahweh’s angel came up from Gilgal to Bochim. He said, “I brought you out of Egypt, and have brought you to the land which I swore to give your fathers. I said, ‘I will never break my covenant with you.\n'),
	(6548, 7, 2, 2, 'You shall make no covenant with the inhabitants of this land. You shall break down their altars.’ But you have not listened to my voice. Why have you done this?\n'),
	(6549, 7, 2, 3, 'Therefore I also said, ‘I will not drive them out from before you; but they shall be in your sides, and their gods will be a snare to you.’”\n'),
	(6550, 7, 2, 4, 'When Yahweh’s angel spoke these words to all the children of Israel, the people lifted up their voice, and wept.\n'),
	(6551, 7, 2, 5, 'They called the name of that place Bochim, and they sacrificed there to Yahweh.\n'),
	(6552, 7, 2, 6, 'Now when Joshua had sent the people away, the children of Israel each went to his inheritance to possess the land.\n'),
	(6553, 7, 2, 7, 'The people served Yahweh all the days of Joshua, and all the days of the elders who outlived Joshua, who had seen all the great work of Yahweh that he had worked for Israel.\n'),
	(6554, 7, 2, 8, 'Joshua the son of Nun, the servant of Yahweh, died, being one hundred ten years old.\n'),
	(6555, 7, 2, 9, 'They buried him in the border of his inheritance in Timnath Heres, in the hill country of Ephraim, on the north of the mountain of Gaash.\n'),
	(6556, 7, 2, 10, 'After all that generation were gathered to their fathers, another generation arose after them, who didn’t know Yahweh, nor the work which he had done for Israel.\n'),
	(6557, 7, 2, 11, 'The children of Israel did that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight, and served the Baals.\n'),
	(6558, 7, 2, 12, 'They abandoned Yahweh, the God of their fathers, who brought them out of the land of Egypt, and followed other gods, of the gods of the peoples who were around them, and bowed themselves down to them; and they provoked Yahweh to anger.\n'),
	(6559, 7, 2, 13, 'They abandoned Yahweh, and served Baal and the Ashtaroth.\n'),
	(6560, 7, 2, 14, 'Yahweh’s anger burned against Israel, and he delivered them into the hands of raiders who plundered them. He sold them into the hands of their enemies all around, so that they could no longer stand before their enemies.\n'),
	(6561, 7, 2, 15, 'Wherever they went out, Yahweh’s hand was against them for evil, as Yahweh had spoken, and as Yahweh had sworn to them; and they were very distressed.\n'),
	(6562, 7, 2, 16, 'Yahweh raised up judges, who saved them out of the hand of those who plundered them.\n'),
	(6563, 7, 2, 17, 'Yet they didn’t listen to their judges; for they prostituted themselves to other gods, and bowed themselves down to them. They quickly turned away from the way in which their fathers walked, obeying Yahweh’s commandments. They didn’t do so.\n'),
	(6564, 7, 2, 18, 'When Yahweh raised up judges for them, then Yahweh was with the judge, and saved them out of the hand of their enemies all the days of the judge; for it grieved Yahweh because of their groaning by reason of those who oppressed them and troubled them.\n'),
	(6565, 7, 2, 19, 'But when the judge was dead, they turned back, and dealt more corruptly than their fathers in following other gods to serve them, and to bow down to them. They didn’t cease what they were doing, or give up their stubborn ways.\n'),
	(6566, 7, 2, 20, 'Yahweh’s anger burned against Israel; and he said, “Because this nation transgressed my covenant which I commanded their fathers, and has not listened to my voice,\n'),
	(6567, 7, 2, 21, 'I also will no longer drive out any of the nations that Joshua left when he died from before them;\n'),
	(6568, 7, 2, 22, 'that by them I may test Israel, to see if they will keep Yahweh’s way to walk therein, as their fathers kept it, or not.”\n'),
	(6569, 7, 2, 23, 'So Yahweh left those nations, without driving them out hastily. He didn’t deliver them into Joshua’s hand.\n'),
	(6570, 7, 3, 1, 'Now these are the nations which Yahweh left, to test Israel by them, even as many as had not known all the wars of Canaan;\n'),
	(6571, 7, 3, 2, 'only that the generations of the children of Israel might know, to teach them war, at least those who knew nothing of it before:\n'),
	(6572, 7, 3, 3, 'the five lords of the Philistines, all the Canaanites, the Sidonians, and the Hivites who lived on Mount Lebanon, from Mount Baal Hermon to the entrance of Hamath.\n'),
	(6573, 7, 3, 4, 'They were left to test Israel by them, to know whether they would listen to Yahweh’s commandments, which he commanded their fathers by Moses.\n'),
	(6574, 7, 3, 5, 'The children of Israel lived among the Canaanites, the Hittites, the Amorites, the Perizzites, the Hivites, and the Jebusites.\n'),
	(6575, 7, 3, 6, 'They took their daughters to be their wives, and gave their own daughters to their sons and served their gods.\n'),
	(6576, 7, 3, 7, 'The children of Israel did that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight, and forgot Yahweh their God, and served the Baals and the Asheroth.\n'),
	(6577, 7, 3, 8, 'Therefore Yahweh’s anger burned against Israel, and he sold them into the hand of Cushan Rishathaim king of Mesopotamia; and the children of Israel served Cushan Rishathaim eight years.\n'),
	(6578, 7, 3, 9, 'When the children of Israel cried to Yahweh, Yahweh raised up a savior to the children of Israel, who saved them, even Othniel the son of Kenaz, Caleb’s younger brother.\n'),
	(6579, 7, 3, 10, 'Yahweh’s Spirit came on him, and he judged Israel; and he went out to war, and Yahweh delivered Cushan Rishathaim king of Mesopotamia into his hand. His hand prevailed against Cushan Rishathaim.\n'),
	(6580, 7, 3, 11, 'The land had rest forty years, then Othniel the son of Kenaz died.\n'),
	(6581, 7, 3, 12, 'The children of Israel again did that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight, and Yahweh strengthened Eglon the king of Moab against Israel, because they had done that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight.\n'),
	(6582, 7, 3, 13, 'He gathered the children of Ammon and Amalek to himself; and he went and struck Israel, and they possessed the city of palm trees.\n'),
	(6583, 7, 3, 14, 'The children of Israel served Eglon the king of Moab eighteen years.\n'),
	(6584, 7, 3, 15, 'But when the children of Israel cried to Yahweh, Yahweh raised up a savior for them, Ehud the son of Gera, the Benjamite, a left-handed man. The children of Israel sent tribute by him to Eglon the king of Moab.\n'),
	(6585, 7, 3, 16, 'Ehud made himself a sword which had two edges, a cubit in length; and he wore it under his clothing on his right thigh.\n'),
	(6586, 7, 3, 17, 'He offered the tribute to Eglon king of Moab. Now Eglon was a very fat man.\n'),
	(6587, 7, 3, 18, 'When he had finished offering the tribute, he sent away the people who carried the tribute.\n'),
	(6588, 7, 3, 19, 'But he himself turned back from the stone idols that were by Gilgal, and said, “I have a secret message for you, O king.”\nThe king said, “Keep silence!” All who stood by him left him.\n'),
	(6589, 7, 3, 20, 'Ehud came to him; and he was sitting by himself alone in the cool upper room. Ehud said, “I have a message from God to you.” He arose out of his seat.\n'),
	(6590, 7, 3, 21, 'Ehud put out his left hand, and took the sword from his right thigh, and thrust it into his body:\n'),
	(6591, 7, 3, 22, 'and the handle also went in after the blade; and the fat closed on the blade, for he didn’t draw the sword out of his body; and it came out behind.\n'),
	(6592, 7, 3, 23, 'Then Ehud went out onto the porch, and shut the doors of the upper room on him, and locked them.\n'),
	(6593, 7, 3, 24, 'After he had gone, his servants came and saw that the doors of the upper room were locked. They said, “Surely he is covering his feet in the upper room.”\n'),
	(6594, 7, 3, 25, 'They waited until they were ashamed; and behold, he didn’t open the doors of the upper room. Therefore they took the key and opened them, and behold, their lord had fallen down dead on the floor.\n'),
	(6595, 7, 3, 26, 'Ehud escaped while they waited, passed beyond the stone idols, and escaped to Seirah.\n'),
	(6596, 7, 3, 27, 'When he had come, he blew a trumpet in the hill country of Ephraim; and the children of Israel went down with him from the hill country, and he led them.\n'),
	(6597, 7, 3, 28, 'He said to them, “Follow me; for Yahweh has delivered your enemies the Moabites into your hand.” They followed him, and took the fords of the Jordan against the Moabites, and didn’t allow any man to pass over.\n'),
	(6598, 7, 3, 29, 'They struck at that time about ten thousand men of Moab, every strong man, and every man of valor. No man escaped.\n'),
	(6599, 7, 3, 30, 'So Moab was subdued that day under the hand of Israel. Then the land had rest eighty years.\n'),
	(6600, 7, 3, 31, 'After him was Shamgar the son of Anath, who struck six hundred men of the Philistines with an ox goad. He also saved Israel.\n'),
	(6601, 7, 4, 1, 'The children of Israel again did that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight, when Ehud was dead.\n'),
	(6602, 7, 4, 2, 'Yahweh sold them into the hand of Jabin king of Canaan, who reigned in Hazor; the captain of whose army was Sisera, who lived in Harosheth of the Gentiles.\n'),
	(6603, 7, 4, 3, 'The children of Israel cried to Yahweh, for he had nine hundred chariots of iron; and he mightily oppressed the children of Israel for twenty years.\n'),
	(6604, 7, 4, 4, 'Now Deborah, a prophetess, the wife of Lappidoth, judged Israel at that time.\n'),
	(6605, 7, 4, 5, 'She lived under Deborah’s palm tree between Ramah and Bethel in the hill country of Ephraim; and the children of Israel came up to her for judgment.\n'),
	(6606, 7, 4, 6, 'She sent and called Barak the son of Abinoam out of Kedesh Naphtali, and said to him, “Hasn’t Yahweh, the God of Israel, commanded, ‘Go and lead the way to Mount Tabor, and take with you ten thousand men of the children of Naphtali and of the children of Zebulun?\n'),
	(6607, 7, 4, 7, 'I will draw to you, to the river Kishon, Sisera, the captain of Jabin’s army, with his chariots and his multitude; and I will deliver him into your hand.’”\n'),
	(6608, 7, 4, 8, 'Barak said to her, “If you will go with me, then I will go; but if you will not go with me, I will not go.”\n'),
	(6609, 7, 4, 9, 'She said, “I will surely go with you. Nevertheless, the journey that you take won’t be for your honor; for Yahweh will sell Sisera into a woman’s hand.” Deborah arose, and went with Barak to Kedesh.\n'),
	(6610, 7, 4, 10, 'Barak called Zebulun and Naphtali together to Kedesh; and ten thousand men followed him; and Deborah went up with him.\n'),
	(6611, 7, 4, 11, 'Now Heber the Kenite had separated himself from the Kenites, even from the children of Hobab, Moses’ brother-in-law, and had pitched his tent as far as the oak in Zaanannim, which is by Kedesh.\n'),
	(6612, 7, 4, 12, 'They told Sisera that Barak the son of Abinoam was gone up to Mount Tabor.\n'),
	(6613, 7, 4, 13, 'Sisera gathered together all his chariots, even nine hundred chariots of iron, and all the people who were with him, from Harosheth of the Gentiles, to the river Kishon.\n'),
	(6614, 7, 4, 14, 'Deborah said to Barak, “Go; for this is the day in which Yahweh has delivered Sisera into your hand. Hasn’t Yahweh gone out before you?” So Barak went down from Mount Tabor, and ten thousand men after him.\n'),
	(6615, 7, 4, 15, 'Yahweh confused Sisera, all his chariots, and all his army, with the edge of the sword before Barak. Sisera abandoned his chariot and fled away on his feet.\n'),
	(6616, 7, 4, 16, 'But Barak pursued the chariots and the army to Harosheth of the Gentiles; and all the army of Sisera fell by the edge of the sword. There was not a man left.\n'),
	(6617, 7, 4, 17, 'However Sisera fled away on his feet to the tent of Jael the wife of Heber the Kenite; for there was peace between Jabin the king of Hazor and the house of Heber the Kenite.\n'),
	(6618, 7, 4, 18, 'Jael went out to meet Sisera, and said to him, “Turn in, my lord, turn in to me; don’t be afraid.” He came in to her into the tent, and she covered him with a rug.\n'),
	(6619, 7, 4, 19, 'He said to her, “Please give me a little water to drink; for I am thirsty.”\nShe opened a bottle of milk, and gave him a drink, and covered him.\n'),
	(6620, 7, 4, 20, 'He said to her, “Stand in the door of the tent, and if any man comes and inquires of you, and says, ‘Is there any man here?’ you shall say, ‘No.’”\n'),
	(6621, 7, 4, 21, 'Then Jael Heber’s wife took a tent peg, and took a hammer in her hand, and went softly to him, and struck the pin into his temples, and it pierced through into the ground; for he was in a deep sleep; so he fainted and died.\n'),
	(6622, 7, 4, 22, 'Behold, as Barak pursued Sisera, Jael came out to meet him, and said to him, “Come, and I will show you the man whom you seek.” He came to her; and behold, Sisera lay dead, and the tent peg was in his temples.\n'),
	(6623, 7, 4, 23, 'So God subdued Jabin the king of Canaan before the children of Israel on that day.\n'),
	(6624, 7, 4, 24, 'The hand of the children of Israel prevailed more and more against Jabin the king of Canaan, until they had destroyed Jabin king of Canaan.\n'),
	(6625, 7, 5, 1, 'Then Deborah and Barak the son of Abinoam sang on that day, saying,\n'),
	(6626, 7, 5, 2, '“Because the leaders took the lead in Israel,\nbecause the people offered themselves willingly,\nbe blessed, Yahweh!\n'),
	(6627, 7, 5, 3, '“Hear, you kings!\nGive ear, you princes!\nI, even I, will sing to Yahweh.\nI will sing praise to Yahweh, the God of Israel.\n'),
	(6628, 7, 5, 4, '“Yahweh, when you went out of Seir,\nwhen you marched out of the field of Edom,\nthe earth trembled, the sky also dropped.\nYes, the clouds dropped water.\n'),
	(6629, 7, 5, 5, 'The mountains quaked Yahweh’s presence,\neven Sinai at the presence of Yahweh, the God of Israel.\n'),
	(6630, 7, 5, 6, '“In the days of Shamgar the son of Anath,\nin the days of Jael, the highways were unoccupied.\nThe travelers walked through byways.\n'),
	(6631, 7, 5, 7, 'The rulers ceased in Israel.\nThey ceased until I, Deborah, arose;\nUntil I arose a mother in Israel.\n'),
	(6632, 7, 5, 8, 'They chose new gods.\nThen war was in the gates.\nWas there a shield or spear seen among forty thousand in Israel?\n'),
	(6633, 7, 5, 9, 'My heart is toward the governors of Israel,\nwho offered themselves willingly among the people.\nBless Yahweh!\n'),
	(6634, 7, 5, 10, '“Speak, you who ride on white donkeys,\nyou who sit on rich carpets,\nand you who walk by the way.\n'),
	(6635, 7, 5, 11, 'Far from the noise of archers, in the places of drawing water,\nthere they will rehearse Yahweh’s righteous acts,\nthe righteous acts of his rule in Israel.\n“Then Yahweh’s people went down to the gates.\n'),
	(6636, 7, 5, 12, '‘Awake, awake, Deborah!\nAwake, awake, utter a song!\nArise, Barak, and lead away your captives, you son of Abinoam.’\n'),
	(6637, 7, 5, 13, '“Then a remnant of the nobles and the people came down.\nYahweh came down for me against the mighty.\n'),
	(6638, 7, 5, 14, 'Those whose root is in Amalek came out of Ephraim,\nafter you, Benjamin, among your peoples.\nGovernors come down out of Machir.\nThose who handle the marshal’s staff came out of Zebulun.\n'),
	(6639, 7, 5, 15, 'The princes of Issachar were with Deborah.\nAs was Issachar, so was Barak.\nThey rushed into the valley at his feet.\nBy the watercourses of Reuben,\nthere were great resolves of heart.\n'),
	(6640, 7, 5, 16, 'Why did you sit among the sheepfolds?\nTo hear the whistling for the flocks?\nAt the watercourses of Reuben,\nthere were great searchings of heart.\n'),
	(6641, 7, 5, 17, 'Gilead lived beyond the Jordan.\nWhy did Dan remain in ships?\nAsher sat still at the haven of the sea,\nand lived by his creeks.\n'),
	(6642, 7, 5, 18, 'Zebulun was a people that jeopardized their lives to the death;\nNaphtali also, on the high places of the field.\n'),
	(6643, 7, 5, 19, '“The kings came and fought,\nthen the kings of Canaan fought at Taanach by the waters of Megiddo.\nThey took no plunder of silver.\n'),
	(6644, 7, 5, 20, 'From the sky the stars fought.\nFrom their courses, they fought against Sisera.\n'),
	(6645, 7, 5, 21, 'The river Kishon swept them away,\nthat ancient river, the river Kishon.\nMy soul, march on with strength.\n'),
	(6646, 7, 5, 22, 'Then the horse hoofs stamped because of the prancing,\nthe prancing of their strong ones.\n'),
	(6647, 7, 5, 23, '‘Curse Meroz,’ said Yahweh’s angel.\n‘Curse bitterly its inhabitants,\nbecause they didn’t come to help Yahweh,\nto help Yahweh against the mighty.’\n'),
	(6648, 7, 5, 24, '“Jael shall be blessed above women,\nthe wife of Heber the Kenite;\nblessed shall she be above women in the tent.\n'),
	(6649, 7, 5, 25, 'He asked for water.\nShe gave him milk.\nShe brought him butter in a lordly dish.\n'),
	(6650, 7, 5, 26, 'She put her hand to the tent peg,\nand her right hand to the workmen’s hammer.\nWith the hammer she struck Sisera.\nShe struck through his head.\nYes, she pierced and struck through his temples.\n'),
	(6651, 7, 5, 27, 'At her feet he bowed, he fell, he lay.\nAt her feet he bowed, he fell.\nWhere he bowed, there he fell down dead.\n'),
	(6652, 7, 5, 28, '“Through the window she looked out, and cried:\nSisera’s mother looked through the lattice.\n‘Why is his chariot so long in coming?\nWhy do the wheels of his chariots wait?’\n'),
	(6653, 7, 5, 29, 'Her wise ladies answered her,\nYes, she returned answer to herself,\n'),
	(6654, 7, 5, 30, '‘Have they not found, have they not divided the plunder?\nA lady, two ladies to every man;\nto Sisera a plunder of dyed garments,\na plunder of dyed garments embroidered,\nof dyed garments embroidered on both sides, on the necks of the plunder?’\n'),
	(6655, 7, 5, 31, '“So let all your enemies perish, Yahweh,\nbut let those who love him be as the sun when it rises in its strength.”\nThen the land had rest forty years.\n'),
	(6656, 7, 6, 1, 'The children of Israel did that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight: and Yahweh delivered them into the hand of Midian seven years.\n'),
	(6657, 7, 6, 2, 'The hand of Midian prevailed against Israel; and because of Midian the children of Israel made themselves the dens which are in the mountains, and the caves, and the strongholds.\n'),
	(6658, 7, 6, 3, 'So it was, when Israel had sown, that the Midianites, the Amalekites, and the children of the east came up against them.\n'),
	(6659, 7, 6, 4, 'They encamped against them, and destroyed the increase of the earth, until you come to Gaza. They left no sustenance in Israel, and no sheep, ox, or donkey.\n'),
	(6660, 7, 6, 5, 'For they came up with their livestock and their tents. They came in as locusts for multitude. Both they and their camels were without number; and they came into the land to destroy it.\n'),
	(6661, 7, 6, 6, 'Israel was brought very low because of Midian; and the children of Israel cried to Yahweh.\n'),
	(6662, 7, 6, 7, 'When the children of Israel cried to Yahweh because of Midian,\n'),
	(6663, 7, 6, 8, 'Yahweh sent a prophet to the children of Israel; and he said to them, “Yahweh says, the God of Israel, ‘I brought you up from Egypt, and brought you out of the house of bondage.\n'),
	(6664, 7, 6, 9, 'I delivered you out of the hand of the Egyptians, and out of the hand of all who oppressed you, and drove them out from before you, and gave you their land.\n'),
	(6665, 7, 6, 10, 'I said to you, “I am Yahweh your God. You shall not fear the gods of the Amorites, in whose land you dwell.” But you have not listened to my voice.’”\n'),
	(6666, 7, 6, 11, 'Yahweh’s angel came, and sat under the oak which was in Ophrah, that belonged to Joash the Abiezrite. His son Gideon was beating out wheat in the wine press, to hide it from the Midianites.\n'),
	(6667, 7, 6, 12, 'Yahweh’s angel appeared to him, and said to him, “Yahweh is with you, you mighty man of valor!”\n'),
	(6668, 7, 6, 13, 'Gideon said to him, “Oh, my lord, if Yahweh is with us, why then has all this happened to us? Where are all his wondrous works which our fathers told us of, saying, ‘Didn’t Yahweh bring us up from Egypt?’ But now Yahweh has cast us off, and delivered us into the hand of Midian.”\n'),
	(6669, 7, 6, 14, 'Yahweh looked at him, and said, “Go in this your might, and save Israel from the hand of Midian. Haven’t I sent you?”\n'),
	(6670, 7, 6, 15, 'He said to him, “O Lord, how shall I save Israel? Behold, my family is the poorest in Manasseh, and I am the least in my father’s house.”\n'),
	(6671, 7, 6, 16, 'Yahweh said to him, “Surely I will be with you, and you shall strike the Midianites as one man.”\n'),
	(6672, 7, 6, 17, 'He said to him, “If now I have found favor in your sight, then show me a sign that it is you who talk with me.\n'),
	(6673, 7, 6, 18, 'Please don’t go away, until I come to you, and bring out my present, and lay it before you.”\nHe said, “I will wait until you come back.”\n'),
	(6674, 7, 6, 19, 'Gideon went in and prepared a young goat and unleavened cakes of an ephah\n of meal. He put the meat in a basket and he put the broth in a pot, and brought it out to him under the oak, and presented it.\n'),
	(6675, 7, 6, 20, 'The angel of God said to him, “Take the meat and the unleavened cakes, and lay them on this rock, and pour out the broth.”\nHe did so.\n'),
	(6676, 7, 6, 21, 'Then Yahweh’s angel stretched out the end of the staff that was in his hand, and touched the meat and the unleavened cakes; and fire went up out of the rock, and consumed the meat and the unleavened cakes. Then Yahweh’s angel departed out of his sight.\n'),
	(6677, 7, 6, 22, 'Gideon saw that he was Yahweh’s angel; and Gideon said, “Alas, Lord Yahweh! Because I have seen Yahweh’s angel face to face!”\n'),
	(6678, 7, 6, 23, 'Yahweh said to him, “Peace be to you! Don’t be afraid. You shall not die.”\n'),
	(6679, 7, 6, 24, 'Then Gideon built an altar there to Yahweh, and called it “Yahweh is Peace.” To this day it is still in Ophrah of the Abiezrites.\n'),
	(6680, 7, 6, 25, 'That same night, Yahweh said to him, “Take your father’s bull, even the second bull seven years old, and throw down the altar of Baal that your father has, and cut down the Asherah that is by it.\n'),
	(6681, 7, 6, 26, 'Then build an altar to Yahweh your God on the top of this stronghold, in an orderly way, and take the second bull, and offer a burnt offering with the wood of the Asherah which you shall cut down.”\n'),
	(6682, 7, 6, 27, 'Then Gideon took ten men of his servants, and did as Yahweh had spoken to him. Because he feared his father’s household and the men of the city, he could not do it by day, but he did it by night.\n'),
	(6683, 7, 6, 28, 'When the men of the city arose early in the morning, behold, the altar of Baal was broken down, and the Asherah was cut down that was by it, and the second bull was offered on the altar that was built.\n'),
	(6684, 7, 6, 29, 'They said to one another, “Who has done this thing?”\nWhen they inquired and asked, they said, “Gideon the son of Joash has done this thing.”\n'),
	(6685, 7, 6, 30, 'Then the men of the city said to Joash, “Bring out your son, that he may die, because he has broken down the altar of Baal, and because he has cut down the Asherah that was by it.”\n'),
	(6686, 7, 6, 31, 'Joash said to all who stood against him, “Will you contend for Baal? Or will you save him? He who will contend for him, let him be put to death by morning! If he is a god, let him contend for himself, because someone has broken down his altar!”\n'),
	(6687, 7, 6, 32, 'Therefore on that day he named him Jerub-Baal, saying, “Let Baal contend against him, because he has broken down his altar.”\n'),
	(6688, 7, 6, 33, 'Then all the Midianites and the Amalekites and the children of the east assembled themselves together; and they passed over, and encamped in the valley of Jezreel.\n'),
	(6689, 7, 6, 34, 'But Yahweh’s Spirit came on Gideon, and he blew a trumpet; and Abiezer was gathered together to follow him.\n'),
	(6690, 7, 6, 35, 'He sent messengers throughout all Manasseh; and they also were gathered together to follow him. He sent messengers to Asher, and to Zebulun, and to Naphtali; and they came up to meet them.\n'),
	(6691, 7, 6, 36, 'Gideon said to God, “If you will save Israel by my hand, as you have spoken,\n'),
	(6692, 7, 6, 37, 'behold, I will put a fleece of wool on the threshing floor; if there is dew on the fleece only, and it is dry on all the ground, then shall I know that you will save Israel by my hand, as you have spoken.”\n'),
	(6693, 7, 6, 38, 'It was so; for he rose up early on the next day, and pressed the fleece together, and wrung the dew out of the fleece, a bowl full of water.\n'),
	(6694, 7, 6, 39, 'Gideon said to God, “Don’t let your anger be kindled against me, and I will speak but this once. Please let me make a trial just this once with the fleece. Let it now be dry only on the fleece, and on all the ground let there be dew.”\n'),
	(6695, 7, 6, 40, 'God did so that night; for it was dry on the fleece only, and there was dew on all the ground.\n'),
	(6696, 7, 7, 1, 'Then Jerubbaal, who is Gideon, and all the people who were with him, rose up early, and encamped beside the spring of Harod. Midian’s camp was on the north side of them, by the hill of Moreh, in the valley.\n'),
	(6697, 7, 7, 2, 'Yahweh said to Gideon, “The people who are with you are too many for me to give the Midianites into their hand, lest Israel brag against me, saying, ‘My own hand has saved me.’\n'),
	(6698, 7, 7, 3, 'Now therefore proclaim in the ears of the people, saying, ‘Whoever is fearful and trembling, let him return and depart from Mount Gilead.’” So twenty-two thousand of the people returned, and ten thousand remained.\n'),
	(6699, 7, 7, 4, 'Yahweh said to Gideon, “There are still too many people. Bring them down to the water, and I will test them for you there. It shall be, that those whom I tell you, ‘This shall go with you,’ the same shall go with you; and whoever I tell you, ‘This shall not go with you,’ the same shall not go.”\n'),
	(6700, 7, 7, 5, 'So he brought down the people to the water; and Yahweh said to Gideon, “Everyone who laps of the water with his tongue, like a dog laps, you shall set him by himself; likewise everyone who bows down on his knees to drink.”\n'),
	(6701, 7, 7, 6, 'The number of those who lapped, putting their hand to their mouth, was three hundred men; but all the rest of the people bowed down on their knees to drink water.\n'),
	(6702, 7, 7, 7, 'Yahweh said to Gideon, “By the three hundred men who lapped will I save you, and deliver the Midianites into your hand. Let all the other people go, each to his own place.”\n'),
	(6703, 7, 7, 8, 'So the people took food in their hand, and their trumpets; and he sent all the men of Israel every man to his tent, but retained the three hundred men; and the camp of Midian was beneath him in the valley.\n'),
	(6704, 7, 7, 9, 'That same night, Yahweh said to him, “Arise, go down into the camp; for I have delivered it into your hand.\n'),
	(6705, 7, 7, 10, 'But if you are afraid to go down, go with Purah your servant down to the camp.\n'),
	(6706, 7, 7, 11, 'You will hear what they say; and afterward your hands will be strengthened to go down into the camp.” Then went he down with Purah his servant to the outermost part of the armed men who were in the camp.\n'),
	(6707, 7, 7, 12, 'The Midianites and the Amalekites and all the children of the east lay along in the valley like locusts for multitude; and their camels were without number, as the sand which is on the seashore for multitude.\n'),
	(6708, 7, 7, 13, 'When Gideon had come, behold, there was a man telling a dream to his fellow. He said, “Behold, I dreamed a dream; and behold, a cake of barley bread tumbled into the camp of Midian, and came to the tent, and struck it so that it fell, and turned it upside down, so that the tent lay flat.”\n'),
	(6709, 7, 7, 14, 'His fellow answered, “This is nothing other than the sword of Gideon the son of Joash, a man of Israel. God has delivered Midian into his hand, with all the army.”\n'),
	(6710, 7, 7, 15, 'It was so, when Gideon heard the telling of the dream, and its interpretation, that he worshiped. Then he returned into the camp of Israel, and said, “Arise; for Yahweh has delivered the army of Midian into your hand!”\n'),
	(6711, 7, 7, 16, 'He divided the three hundred men into three companies, and he put into the hands of all them trumpets, and empty pitchers, with torches within the pitchers.\n'),
	(6712, 7, 7, 17, 'He said to them, “Watch me, and do likewise. Behold, when I come to the outermost part of the camp, it shall be that, as I do, so you shall do.\n'),
	(6713, 7, 7, 18, 'When I blow the trumpet, I and all who are with me, then blow the trumpets also on every side of all the camp, and shout, ‘For Yahweh and for Gideon!’”\n'),
	(6714, 7, 7, 19, 'So Gideon, and the hundred men who were with him, came to the outermost part of the camp in the beginning of the middle watch, when they had but newly set the watch. Then they blew the trumpets, and broke in pieces the pitchers that were in their hands.\n'),
	(6715, 7, 7, 20, 'The three companies blew the trumpets, broke the pitchers, and held the torches in their left hands, and the trumpets in their right hands with which to blow; and they shouted, “The sword of Yahweh and of Gideon!”\n'),
	(6716, 7, 7, 21, 'They each stood in his place around the camp; and all the army ran; and they shouted, and put them to flight.\n'),
	(6717, 7, 7, 22, 'They blew the three hundred trumpets, and Yahweh set every man’s sword against his fellow, and against all the army; and the army fled as far as Beth Shittah toward Zererah, as far as the border of Abel Meholah, by Tabbath.\n'),
	(6718, 7, 7, 23, 'The men of Israel were gathered together out of Naphtali, and out of Asher, and out of all Manasseh, and pursued Midian.\n'),
	(6719, 7, 7, 24, 'Gideon sent messengers throughout all the hill country of Ephraim, saying, “Come down against Midian, and take before them the waters, as far as Beth Barah, even the Jordan!” So all the men of Ephraim were gathered together, and took the waters as far as Beth Barah, even the Jordan.\n'),
	(6720, 7, 7, 25, 'They took the two princes of Midian, Oreb and Zeeb. They killed Oreb at Oreb’s rock, and Zeeb they killed at Zeeb’s wine press; and pursued Midian. Then they brought the heads of Oreb and Zeeb to Gideon beyond the Jordan.\n'),
	(6721, 7, 8, 1, 'The men of Ephraim said to him, “Why have you treated us this way, that you didn’t call us when you went to fight with Midian?” They rebuked him sharply.\n'),
	(6722, 7, 8, 2, 'He said to them, “What have I now done in comparison with you? Isn’t the gleaning of the grapes of Ephraim better than the vintage of Abiezer?\n'),
	(6723, 7, 8, 3, 'God has delivered into your hand the princes of Midian, Oreb and Zeeb! What was I able to do in comparison with you?” Then their anger was abated toward him, when he had said that.\n'),
	(6724, 7, 8, 4, 'Gideon came to the Jordan, and passed over, he, and the three hundred men who were with him, faint, yet pursuing.\n'),
	(6725, 7, 8, 5, 'He said to the men of Succoth, “Please give loaves of bread to the people who follow me; for they are faint, and I am pursuing after Zebah and Zalmunna, the kings of Midian.”\n'),
	(6726, 7, 8, 6, 'The princes of Succoth said, “Are the hands of Zebah and Zalmunna now in your hand, that we should give bread to your army?”\n'),
	(6727, 7, 8, 7, 'Gideon said, “Therefore when Yahweh has delivered Zebah and Zalmunna into my hand, then I will tear your flesh with the thorns of the wilderness and with briers.”\n'),
	(6728, 7, 8, 8, 'He went up there to Penuel, and spoke to them in the same way; and the men of Penuel answered him as the men of Succoth had answered.\n'),
	(6729, 7, 8, 9, 'He spoke also to the men of Penuel, saying, “When I come again in peace, I will break down this tower.”\n'),
	(6730, 7, 8, 10, 'Now Zebah and Zalmunna were in Karkor, and their armies with them, about fifteen thousand men, all who were left of all the army of the children of the east; for there fell one hundred twenty thousand men who drew sword.\n'),
	(6731, 7, 8, 11, 'Gideon went up by the way of those who lived in tents on the east of Nobah and Jogbehah, and struck the army; for the army was secure.\n'),
	(6732, 7, 8, 12, 'Zebah and Zalmunna fled; and he pursued them. He took the two kings of Midian, Zebah and Zalmunna, and confused all the army.\n'),
	(6733, 7, 8, 13, 'Gideon the son of Joash returned from the battle from the ascent of Heres.\n'),
	(6734, 7, 8, 14, 'He caught a young man of the men of Succoth, and inquired of him: and he described for him the princes of Succoth, and its elders, seventy-seven men.\n'),
	(6735, 7, 8, 15, 'He came to the men of Succoth, and said, “See Zebah and Zalmunna, concerning whom you taunted me, saying, ‘Are the hands of Zebah and Zalmunna now in your hand, that we should give bread to your men who are weary?’”\n'),
	(6736, 7, 8, 16, 'He took the elders of the city, and thorns of the wilderness and briers, and with them he taught the men of Succoth.\n'),
	(6737, 7, 8, 17, 'He broke down the tower of Penuel, and killed the men of the city.\n'),
	(6738, 7, 8, 18, 'Then he said to Zebah and Zalmunna, “What kind of men were they whom you killed at Tabor?”\nThey answered, “They were like you. Each one resembled the children of a king.”\n'),
	(6739, 7, 8, 19, 'He said, “They were my brothers, the sons of my mother. As Yahweh lives, if you had saved them alive, I would not kill you.”\n'),
	(6740, 7, 8, 20, 'He said to Jether his firstborn, “Get up, and kill them!” But the youth didn’t draw his sword; for he was afraid, because he was yet a youth.\n'),
	(6741, 7, 8, 21, 'Then Zebah and Zalmunna said, “Rise and fall on us; for as the man is, so is his strength.” Gideon arose, and killed Zebah and Zalmunna, and took the crescents that were on their camels’ necks.\n'),
	(6742, 7, 8, 22, 'Then the men of Israel said to Gideon, “Rule over us, both you, and your son, and your son’s son also; for you have saved us out of the hand of Midian.”\n'),
	(6743, 7, 8, 23, 'Gideon said to them, “I will not rule over you, neither shall my son rule over you. Yahweh shall rule over you.”\n'),
	(6744, 7, 8, 24, 'Gideon said to them, “I do have a request, that you would each give me the earrings of his plunder.” (For they had golden earrings, because they were Ishmaelites.)\n'),
	(6745, 7, 8, 25, 'They answered, “We will willingly give them.” They spread a garment, and every man threw the earrings of his plunder into it.\n'),
	(6746, 7, 8, 26, 'The weight of the golden earrings that he requested was one thousand and seven hundred shekels of gold, besides the crescents, and the pendants, and the purple clothing that was on the kings of Midian, and besides the chains that were about their camels’ necks.\n'),
	(6747, 7, 8, 27, 'Gideon made an ephod out of it, and put it in Ophrah, his city. Then all Israel played the prostitute with it there; and it became a snare to Gideon, and to his house.\n'),
	(6748, 7, 8, 28, 'So Midian was subdued before the children of Israel, and they lifted up their heads no more. The land had rest forty years in the days of Gideon.\n'),
	(6749, 7, 8, 29, 'Jerubbaal the son of Joash went and lived in his own house.\n'),
	(6750, 7, 8, 30, 'Gideon had seventy sons conceived from his body, for he had many wives.\n'),
	(6751, 7, 8, 31, 'His concubine who was in Shechem also bore him a son, and he named him Abimelech.\n'),
	(6752, 7, 8, 32, 'Gideon the son of Joash died in a good old age, and was buried in the tomb of Joash his father, in Ophrah of the Abiezrites.\n'),
	(6753, 7, 8, 33, 'As soon as Gideon was dead, the children of Israel turned again, and played the prostitute following the Baals, and made Baal Berith their god.\n'),
	(6754, 7, 8, 34, 'The children of Israel didn’t remember Yahweh their God, who had delivered them out of the hand of all their enemies on every side;\n'),
	(6755, 7, 8, 35, 'neither did they show kindness to the house of Jerubbaal, that is, Gideon, according to all the goodness which he had shown to Israel.\n'),
	(6756, 7, 9, 1, 'Abimelech the son of Jerubbaal went to Shechem to his mother’s brothers, and spoke with them, and with all the family of the house of his mother’s father, saying,\n'),
	(6757, 7, 9, 2, '“Please speak in the ears of all the men of Shechem, ‘Is it better for you that all the sons of Jerubbaal, who are seventy persons, rule over you, or that one rule over you?’ Remember also that I am your bone and your flesh.”\n'),
	(6758, 7, 9, 3, 'His mother’s brothers spoke of him in the ears of all the men of Shechem all these words. Their hearts inclined to follow Abimelech; for they said, “He is our brother.”\n'),
	(6759, 7, 9, 4, 'They gave him seventy pieces of silver out of the house of Baal Berith, with which Abimelech hired vain and light fellows, who followed him.\n'),
	(6760, 7, 9, 5, 'He went to his father’s house at Ophrah, and killed his brothers the sons of Jerubbaal, being seventy persons, on one stone: but Jotham the youngest son of Jerubbaal was left; for he hid himself.\n'),
	(6761, 7, 9, 6, 'All the men of Shechem assembled themselves together, and all the house of Millo, and went and made Abimelech king, by the oak of the pillar that was in Shechem.\n'),
	(6762, 7, 9, 7, 'When they told it to Jotham, he went and stood on the top of Mount Gerizim, and lifted up his voice, cried out, and said to them, “Listen to me, you men of Shechem, that God may listen to you.\n'),
	(6763, 7, 9, 8, 'The trees set out to anoint a king over themselves. They said to the olive tree, ‘Reign over us.’\n'),
	(6764, 7, 9, 9, '“But the olive tree said to them, ‘Should I stop producing my oil, with which they honor God and man by me, and go to wave back and forth over the trees?’\n'),
	(6765, 7, 9, 10, '“The trees said to the fig tree, ‘Come and reign over us.’\n'),
	(6766, 7, 9, 11, '“But the fig tree said to them, ‘Should I leave my sweetness, and my good fruit, and go to wave back and forth over the trees?’\n'),
	(6767, 7, 9, 12, '“The trees said to the vine, ‘Come and reign over us.’\n'),
	(6768, 7, 9, 13, '“The vine said to them, ‘Should I leave my new wine, which cheers God and man, and go to wave back and forth over the trees?’\n'),
	(6769, 7, 9, 14, '“Then all the trees said to the bramble, ‘Come and reign over us.’\n'),
	(6770, 7, 9, 15, '“The bramble said to the trees, ‘If in truth you anoint me king over you, then come and take refuge in my shade; and if not, let fire come out of the bramble, and devour the cedars of Lebanon.’\n'),
	(6771, 7, 9, 16, '“Now therefore, if you have dealt truly and righteously, in that you have made Abimelech king, and if you have dealt well with Jerubbaal and his house, and have done to him according to the deserving of his hands\n'),
	(6772, 7, 9, 17, '(for my father fought for you, and risked his life, and delivered you out of the hand of Midian;\n'),
	(6773, 7, 9, 18, 'and you have risen up against my father’s house today, and have slain his sons, seventy persons, on one stone, and have made Abimelech, the son of his female servant, king over the men of Shechem, because he is your brother);\n'),
	(6774, 7, 9, 19, 'if you then have dealt truly and righteously with Jerubbaal and with his house today, then rejoice in Abimelech, and let him also rejoice in you;\n'),
	(6775, 7, 9, 20, 'but if not, let fire come out from Abimelech, and devour the men of Shechem, and the house of Millo; and let fire come out from the men of Shechem, and from the house of Millo, and devour Abimelech.”\n'),
	(6776, 7, 9, 21, 'Jotham ran away, and fled, and went to Beer, and lived there, for fear of Abimelech his brother.\n'),
	(6777, 7, 9, 22, 'Abimelech was prince over Israel three years.\n'),
	(6778, 7, 9, 23, 'Then God sent an evil spirit between Abimelech and the men of Shechem; and the men of Shechem dealt treacherously with Abimelech,\n'),
	(6779, 7, 9, 24, 'that the violence done to the seventy sons of Jerubbaal might come, and that their blood might be laid on Abimelech their brother, who killed them, and on the men of Shechem, who strengthened his hands to kill his brothers.\n'),
	(6780, 7, 9, 25, 'The men of Shechem set an ambush for him on the tops of the mountains, and they robbed all who came along that way by them, and Abimelech was told about it.\n'),
	(6781, 7, 9, 26, 'Gaal the son of Ebed came with his brothers, and went over to Shechem; and the men of Shechem put their trust in him.\n'),
	(6782, 7, 9, 27, 'They went out into the field, harvested their vineyards, trod the grapes, held festival, and went into the house of their god, and ate and drank, and cursed Abimelech.\n'),
	(6783, 7, 9, 28, 'Gaal the son of Ebed said, “Who is Abimelech, and who is Shechem, that we should serve him? Isn’t he the son of Jerubbaal? Isn’t Zebul his officer? Serve the men of Hamor the father of Shechem, but why should we serve him?\n'),
	(6784, 7, 9, 29, 'I wish that this people were under my hand! Then I would remove Abimelech.” He said to Abimelech, “Increase your army, and come out!”\n'),
	(6785, 7, 9, 30, 'When Zebul the ruler of the city heard the words of Gaal the son of Ebed, his anger burned.\n'),
	(6786, 7, 9, 31, 'He sent messengers to Abimelech craftily, saying, “Behold, Gaal the son of Ebed and his brothers have come to Shechem; and behold, they incite the city against you.\n'),
	(6787, 7, 9, 32, 'Now therefore, go up by night, you and the people who are with you, and lie in wait in the field.\n'),
	(6788, 7, 9, 33, 'It shall be that in the morning, as soon as the sun is up, you shall rise early, and rush on the city. Behold, when he and the people who are with him come out against you, then may you do to them as you shall find occasion.”\n'),
	(6789, 7, 9, 34, 'Abimelech rose up, and all the people who were with him, by night, and they laid wait against Shechem in four companies.\n'),
	(6790, 7, 9, 35, 'Gaal the son of Ebed went out, and stood in the entrance of the gate of the city. Abimelech rose up, and the people who were with him, from the ambush.\n'),
	(6791, 7, 9, 36, 'When Gaal saw the people, he said to Zebul, “Behold, people are coming down from the tops of the mountains.”\nZebul said to him, “You see the shadow of the mountains as if they were men.”\n'),
	(6792, 7, 9, 37, 'Gaal spoke again and said, “Behold, people are coming down by the middle of the land, and one company comes by the way of the oak of Meonenim.”\n'),
	(6793, 7, 9, 38, 'Then Zebul said to him, “Now where is your mouth, that you said, ‘Who is Abimelech, that we should serve him?’ Isn’t this the people that you have despised? Please go out now and fight with them.”\n'),
	(6794, 7, 9, 39, 'Gaal went out before the men of Shechem, and fought with Abimelech.\n'),
	(6795, 7, 9, 40, 'Abimelech chased him, and he fled before him, and many fell wounded, even to the entrance of the gate.\n'),
	(6796, 7, 9, 41, 'Abimelech lived at Arumah; and Zebul drove out Gaal and his brothers, that they should not dwell in Shechem.\n'),
	(6797, 7, 9, 42, 'On the next day, the people went out into the field; and they told Abimelech.\n'),
	(6798, 7, 9, 43, 'He took the people, and divided them into three companies, and laid wait in the field; and he looked, and behold, the people came out of the city. So, he rose up against them, and struck them.\n'),
	(6799, 7, 9, 44, 'Abimelech and the companies that were with him rushed forward, and stood in the entrance of the gate of the city; and the two companies rushed on all who were in the field, and struck them.\n'),
	(6800, 7, 9, 45, 'Abimelech fought against the city all that day; and he took the city, and killed the people in it. He beat down the city, and sowed it with salt.\n'),
	(6801, 7, 9, 46, 'When all the men of the tower of Shechem heard of it, they entered into the stronghold of the house of Elberith.\n'),
	(6802, 7, 9, 47, 'Abimelech was told that all the men of the tower of Shechem were gathered together.\n'),
	(6803, 7, 9, 48, 'Abimelech went up to Mount Zalmon, he and all the people who were with him; and Abimelech took an ax in his hand, and cut down a bough from the trees, and took it up, and laid it on his shoulder. Then he said to the people who were with him, “What you have seen me do, make haste, and do as I have done!”\n'),
	(6804, 7, 9, 49, 'All the people likewise each cut down his bough, and followed Abimelech, and put them at the base of the stronghold, and set the stronghold on fire on them; so that all the people of the tower of Shechem died also, about a thousand men and women.\n'),
	(6805, 7, 9, 50, 'Then Abimelech went to Thebez, and encamped against Thebez, and took it.\n'),
	(6806, 7, 9, 51, 'But there was a strong tower within the city, and all the men and women of the city fled there, and shut themselves in, and went up to the roof of the tower.\n'),
	(6807, 7, 9, 52, 'Abimelech came to the tower, and fought against it, and came near to the door of the tower to burn it with fire.\n'),
	(6808, 7, 9, 53, 'A certain woman cast an upper millstone on Abimelech’s head, and broke his skull.\n'),
	(6809, 7, 9, 54, 'Then he called hastily to the young man his armor bearer, and said to him, “Draw your sword, and kill me, that men not say of me, ‘A woman killed him.’ His young man thrust him through, and he died.”\n'),
	(6810, 7, 9, 55, 'When the men of Israel saw that Abimelech was dead, they each departed to his place.\n'),
	(6811, 7, 9, 56, 'Thus God repaid the wickedness of Abimelech, which he did to his father, in killing his seventy brothers;\n'),
	(6812, 7, 9, 57, 'and God repaid all the wickedness of the men of Shechem on their heads; and the curse of Jotham the son of Jerubbaal came on them.\n'),
	(6813, 7, 10, 1, 'After Abimelech, Tola the son of Puah, the son of Dodo, a man of Issachar, arose to save Israel. He lived in Shamir in the hill country of Ephraim.\n'),
	(6814, 7, 10, 2, 'He judged Israel twenty-three years, and died, and was buried in Shamir.\n'),
	(6815, 7, 10, 3, 'After him Jair, the Gileadite arose, and he judged Israel twenty-two years.\n'),
	(6816, 7, 10, 4, 'He had thirty sons who rode on thirty donkey colts, and they had thirty cities, which are called Havvoth Jair to this day, which are in the land of Gilead.\n'),
	(6817, 7, 10, 5, 'Jair died, and was buried in Kamon.\n'),
	(6818, 7, 10, 6, 'The children of Israel again did that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight, and served the Baals, the Ashtaroth, the gods of Syria, the gods of Sidon, the gods of Moab, the gods of the children of Ammon, and the gods of the Philistines. They abandoned Yahweh, and didn’t serve him.\n'),
	(6819, 7, 10, 7, 'Yahweh’s anger burned against Israel, and he sold them into the hand of the Philistines, and into the hand of the children of Ammon.\n'),
	(6820, 7, 10, 8, 'They troubled and oppressed the children of Israel that year. For eighteen years, they oppressed all the children of Israel that were beyond the Jordan in the land of the Amorites, which is in Gilead.\n'),
	(6821, 7, 10, 9, 'The children of Ammon passed over the Jordan to fight also against Judah, and against Benjamin, and against the house of Ephraim, so that Israel was very distressed.\n'),
	(6822, 7, 10, 10, 'The children of Israel cried to Yahweh, saying, “We have sinned against you, even because we have forsaken our God, and have served the Baals.”\n'),
	(6823, 7, 10, 11, 'Yahweh said to the children of Israel, “Didn’t I save you from the Egyptians, and from the Amorites, from the children of Ammon, and from the Philistines?\n'),
	(6824, 7, 10, 12, 'The Sidonians also, and the Amalekites, and the Maonites, oppressed you; and you cried to me, and I saved you out of their hand.\n'),
	(6825, 7, 10, 13, 'Yet you have forsaken me, and served other gods. Therefore I will save you no more.\n'),
	(6826, 7, 10, 14, 'Go and cry to the gods which you have chosen. Let them save you in the time of your distress!”\n'),
	(6827, 7, 10, 15, 'The children of Israel said to Yahweh, “We have sinned! Do you to us whatever seems good to you; only deliver us, please, today.”\n'),
	(6828, 7, 10, 16, 'They put away the foreign gods from among them, and served Yahweh; and his soul was grieved for the misery of Israel.\n'),
	(6829, 7, 10, 17, 'Then the children of Ammon were gathered together and encamped in Gilead. The children of Israel assembled themselves together and encamped in Mizpah.\n'),
	(6830, 7, 10, 18, 'The people, the princes of Gilead, said to one another, “Who is the man who will begin to fight against the children of Ammon? He shall be head over all the inhabitants of Gilead.”\n'),
	(6831, 7, 11, 1, 'Now Jephthah the Gileadite was a mighty man of valor, and he was the son of a prostitute. Gilead became the father of Jephthah.\n'),
	(6832, 7, 11, 2, 'Gilead’s wife bore him sons. When his wife’s sons grew up, they drove Jephthah out, and said to him, “You will not inherit in our father’s house, for you are the son of another woman.”\n'),
	(6833, 7, 11, 3, 'Then Jephthah fled from his brothers, and lived in the land of Tob. Outlaws joined up with Jephthah, and they went out with him.\n'),
	(6834, 7, 11, 4, 'After a while, the children of Ammon made war against Israel.\n'),
	(6835, 7, 11, 5, 'When the children of Ammon made war against Israel, the elders of Gilead went to get Jephthah out of the land of Tob.\n'),
	(6836, 7, 11, 6, 'They said to Jephthah, “Come and be our chief, that we may fight with the children of Ammon.”\n'),
	(6837, 7, 11, 7, 'Jephthah said to the elders of Gilead, “Didn’t you hate me, and drive me out of my father’s house? Why have you come to me now when you are in distress?”\n'),
	(6838, 7, 11, 8, 'The elders of Gilead said to Jephthah, “Therefore we have turned again to you now, that you may go with us, and fight with the children of Ammon. You will be our head over all the inhabitants of Gilead.”\n'),
	(6839, 7, 11, 9, 'Jephthah said to the elders of Gilead, “If you bring me home again to fight with the children of Ammon, and Yahweh delivers them before me, will I be your head?”\n'),
	(6840, 7, 11, 10, 'The elders of Gilead said to Jephthah, “Yahweh will be witness between us. Surely we will do what you say.”\n'),
	(6841, 7, 11, 11, 'Then Jephthah went with the elders of Gilead, and the people made him head and chief over them. Jephthah spoke all his words before Yahweh in Mizpah.\n'),
	(6842, 7, 11, 12, 'Jephthah sent messengers to the king of the children of Ammon, saying, “What have you to do with me, that you have come to me to fight against my land?”\n'),
	(6843, 7, 11, 13, 'The king of the children of Ammon answered to the messengers of Jephthah, “Because Israel took away my land, when he came up out of Egypt, from the Arnon even to the Jabbok, and to the Jordan. Now therefore restore that territory again peaceably.”\n'),
	(6844, 7, 11, 14, 'Jephthah sent messengers again to the king of the children of Ammon;\n'),
	(6845, 7, 11, 15, 'and he said to him, “Thus says Jephthah: Israel didn’t take away the land of Moab, nor the land of the children of Ammon,\n'),
	(6846, 7, 11, 16, 'but when they came up from Egypt, and Israel went through the wilderness to the Red Sea, and came to Kadesh;\n'),
	(6847, 7, 11, 17, 'then Israel sent messengers to the king of Edom, saying, ‘Please let me pass through your land;’ but the king of Edom didn’t listen. In the same way, he sent to the king of Moab; but he would not: and Israel stayed in Kadesh.\n'),
	(6848, 7, 11, 18, 'Then they went through the wilderness, and went around the land of Edom, and the land of Moab, and came by the east side of the land of Moab, and they encamped on the other side of the Arnon; but they didn’t come within the border of Moab, for the Arnon was the border of Moab.\n'),
	(6849, 7, 11, 19, 'Israel sent messengers to Sihon king of the Amorites, the king of Heshbon; and Israel said to him, ‘Please let us pass through your land to my place.’\n'),
	(6850, 7, 11, 20, 'But Sihon didn’t trust Israel to pass through his border; but Sihon gathered all his people together, and encamped in Jahaz, and fought against Israel.\n'),
	(6851, 7, 11, 21, 'Yahweh, the God of Israel, delivered Sihon and all his people into the hand of Israel, and they struck them. So Israel possessed all the land of the Amorites, the inhabitants of that country.\n'),
	(6852, 7, 11, 22, 'They possessed all the border of the Amorites, from the Arnon even to the Jabbok, and from the wilderness even to the Jordan.\n'),
	(6853, 7, 11, 23, 'So now Yahweh, the God of Israel, has dispossessed the Amorites from before his people Israel, and should you possess them?\n'),
	(6854, 7, 11, 24, 'Won’t you possess that which Chemosh your god gives you to possess? So whoever Yahweh our God has dispossessed from before us, them will we possess.\n'),
	(6855, 7, 11, 25, 'Now are you anything better than Balak the son of Zippor, king of Moab? Did he ever strive against Israel, or did he ever fight against them?\n'),
	(6856, 7, 11, 26, 'While Israel lived in Heshbon and its towns, and in Aroer and its towns, and in all the cities that are along by the side of the Arnon, three hundred years; why didn’t you recover them within that time?\n'),
	(6857, 7, 11, 27, 'I therefore have not sinned against you, but you do me wrong to war against me. May Yahweh the Judge be judge today between the children of Israel and the children of Ammon.”\n'),
	(6858, 7, 11, 28, 'However the king of the children of Ammon didn’t listen to the words of Jephthah which he sent him.\n'),
	(6859, 7, 11, 29, 'Then Yahweh’s Spirit came on Jephthah, and he passed over Gilead and Manasseh, and passed over Mizpah of Gilead, and from Mizpah of Gilead he passed over to the children of Ammon.\n'),
	(6860, 7, 11, 30, 'Jephthah vowed a vow to Yahweh, and said, “If you will indeed deliver the children of Ammon into my hand,\n'),
	(6861, 7, 11, 31, 'then it shall be, that whatever comes out of the doors of my house to meet me, when I return in peace from the children of Ammon, it shall be Yahweh’s, and I will offer it up for a burnt offering.”\n'),
	(6862, 7, 11, 32, 'So Jephthah passed over to the children of Ammon to fight against them; and Yahweh delivered them into his hand.\n'),
	(6863, 7, 11, 33, 'He struck them from Aroer until you come to Minnith, even twenty cities, and to Abelcheramim, with a very great slaughter. So the children of Ammon were subdued before the children of Israel.\n'),
	(6864, 7, 11, 34, 'Jephthah came to Mizpah to his house; and behold, his daughter came out to meet him with tambourines and with dances. She was his only child. Besides her he had neither son nor daughter.\n'),
	(6865, 7, 11, 35, 'When he saw her, he tore his clothes, and said, “Alas, my daughter! You have brought me very low, and you are one of those who trouble me; for I have opened my mouth to Yahweh, and I can’t go back.”\n'),
	(6866, 7, 11, 36, 'She said to him, “My father, you have opened your mouth to Yahweh; do to me according to that which has proceeded out of your mouth, because Yahweh has taken vengeance for you on your enemies, even on the children of Ammon.”\n'),
	(6867, 7, 11, 37, 'She said to her father, “Let this thing be done for me. Leave me alone two months, that I may depart and go down on the mountains, and bewail my virginity, I and my companions.”\n'),
	(6868, 7, 11, 38, 'He said, “Go.” He sent her away for two months: and she departed, she and her companions, and mourned her virginity on the mountains.\n'),
	(6869, 7, 11, 39, 'At the end of two months, she returned to her father, who did with her according to his vow which he had vowed. She was a virgin. It was a custom in Israel\n'),
	(6870, 7, 11, 40, 'that the daughters of Israel went yearly to celebrate the daughter of Jephthah the Gileadite four days in a year.\n'),
	(6871, 7, 12, 1, 'The men of Ephraim were gathered together, and passed northward; and they said to Jephthah, “Why did you pass over to fight against the children of Ammon, and didn’t call us to go with you? We will burn your house around you with fire!”\n'),
	(6872, 7, 12, 2, 'Jephthah said to them, “I and my people were at great strife with the children of Ammon; and when I called you, you didn’t save me out of their hand.\n'),
	(6873, 7, 12, 3, 'When I saw that you didn’t save me, I put my life in my hand, and passed over against the children of Ammon, and Yahweh delivered them into my hand. Why then have you come up to me today, to fight against me?”\n'),
	(6874, 7, 12, 4, 'Then Jephthah gathered together all the men of Gilead, and fought with Ephraim. The men of Gilead struck Ephraim, because they said, “You are fugitives of Ephraim, you Gileadites, in the middle of Ephraim, and in the middle of Manasseh.”\n'),
	(6875, 7, 12, 5, 'The Gileadites took the fords of the Jordan against the Ephraimites. When the fugitives of Ephraim said, “Let me go over,” the men of Gilead said to him, “Are you an Ephraimite?” If he said, “No”;\n'),
	(6876, 7, 12, 6, 'then they said to him, “Now say ‘Shibboleth;’” and he said “Sibboleth”; for he couldn’t manage to pronounce it right: then they seized him, and killed him at the fords of the Jordan. At that time, forty-two thousand of Ephraim fell.\n'),
	(6877, 7, 12, 7, 'Jephthah judged Israel six years. Then Jephthah the Gileadite died, and was buried in the cities of Gilead.\n'),
	(6878, 7, 12, 8, 'After him Ibzan of Bethlehem judged Israel.\n'),
	(6879, 7, 12, 9, 'He had thirty sons; and thirty daughters he sent outside his clan, and thirty daughters he brought in from outside his clan for his sons. He judged Israel seven years.\n'),
	(6880, 7, 12, 10, 'Ibzan died, and was buried at Bethlehem.\n'),
	(6881, 7, 12, 11, 'After him Elon the Zebulunite judged Israel; and he judged Israel ten years.\n'),
	(6882, 7, 12, 12, 'Elon the Zebulunite died, and was buried in Aijalon in the land of Zebulun.\n'),
	(6883, 7, 12, 13, 'After him Abdon the son of Hillel the Pirathonite judged Israel.\n'),
	(6884, 7, 12, 14, 'He had forty sons and thirty sons’ sons, who rode on seventy donkey colts. He judged Israel eight years.\n'),
	(6885, 7, 12, 15, 'Abdon the son of Hillel the Pirathonite died, and was buried in Pirathon in the land of Ephraim, in the hill country of the Amalekites.\n'),
	(6886, 7, 13, 1, 'The children of Israel again did that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight; and Yahweh delivered them into the hand of the Philistines forty years.\n'),
	(6887, 7, 13, 2, 'There was a certain man of Zorah, of the family of the Danites, whose name was Manoah; and his wife was barren, and childless.\n'),
	(6888, 7, 13, 3, 'Yahweh’s angel appeared to the woman, and said to her, “See now, you are barren and childless; but you shall conceive, and bear a son.\n'),
	(6889, 7, 13, 4, 'Now therefore please beware and drink no wine nor strong drink, and don’t eat any unclean thing:\n'),
	(6890, 7, 13, 5, 'for, behold, you shall conceive, and give birth to a son. No razor shall come on his head; for the child shall be a Nazirite to God from the womb. He shall begin to save Israel out of the hand of the Philistines.”\n'),
	(6891, 7, 13, 6, 'Then the woman came and told her husband, saying, “A man of God came to me, and his face was like the face of the angel of God, very awesome. I didn’t ask him where he was from, neither did he tell me his name;\n'),
	(6892, 7, 13, 7, 'but he said to me, ‘Behold, you shall conceive, and bear a son; and now drink no wine nor strong drink. Don’t eat any unclean thing; for the child shall be a Nazirite to God from the womb to the day of his death.’”\n'),
	(6893, 7, 13, 8, 'Then Manoah entreated Yahweh, and said, “Oh, Lord, please let the man of God whom you sent come again to us, and teach us what we should do to the child who shall be born.”\n'),
	(6894, 7, 13, 9, 'God listened to the voice of Manoah, and the angel of God came again to the woman as she sat in the field, but Manoah, her husband, wasn’t with her.\n'),
	(6895, 7, 13, 10, 'The woman hurried and ran, and told her husband, and said to him, “Behold, the man who came to me that day has appeared to me,”\n'),
	(6896, 7, 13, 11, 'Manoah arose, and followed his wife, and came to the man, and said to him, “Are you the man who spoke to my wife?”\nHe said, “I am.”\n'),
	(6897, 7, 13, 12, 'Manoah said, “Now let your words happen. What shall the child’s way of life and mission be?”\n'),
	(6898, 7, 13, 13, 'Yahweh’s angel said to Manoah, “Of all that I said to the woman let her beware.\n'),
	(6899, 7, 13, 14, 'She may not eat of anything that comes of the vine, neither let her drink wine or strong drink, nor eat any unclean thing. Let her observe all that I commanded her.”\n'),
	(6900, 7, 13, 15, 'Manoah said to Yahweh’s angel, “Please stay with us, that we may make a young goat ready for you.”\n'),
	(6901, 7, 13, 16, 'Yahweh’s angel said to Manoah, “Though you detain me, I won’t eat your bread. If you will prepare a burnt offering, you must offer it to Yahweh.” For Manoah didn’t know that he was Yahweh’s angel.\n'),
	(6902, 7, 13, 17, 'Manoah said to Yahweh’s angel, “What is your name, that when your words happen, we may honor you?”\n'),
	(6903, 7, 13, 18, 'Yahweh’s angel said to him, “Why do you ask about my name, since it is incomprehensible?”\n'),
	(6904, 7, 13, 19, 'So Manoah took the young goat with the meal offering, and offered it on the rock to Yahweh. Then the angel did an amazing thing as Manoah and his wife watched.\n'),
	(6905, 7, 13, 20, 'For when the flame went up toward the sky from off the altar, Yahweh’s angel ascended in the flame of the altar. Manoah and his wife watched; and they fell on their faces to the ground.\n'),
	(6906, 7, 13, 21, 'But Yahweh’s angel didn’t appear to Manoah or to his wife any more. Then Manoah knew that he was Yahweh’s angel.\n'),
	(6907, 7, 13, 22, 'Manoah said to his wife, “We shall surely die, because we have seen God.”\n'),
	(6908, 7, 13, 23, 'But his wife said to him, “If Yahweh were pleased to kill us, he wouldn’t have received a burnt offering and a meal offering at our hand, and he wouldn’t have shown us all these things, nor would he have told us such things as these at this time.”\n'),
	(6909, 7, 13, 24, 'The woman bore a son, and named him Samson. The child grew, and Yahweh blessed him.\n'),
	(6910, 7, 13, 25, 'Yahweh’s Spirit began to move him in Mahaneh Dan, between Zorah and Eshtaol.\n'),
	(6911, 7, 14, 1, 'Samson went down to Timnah, and saw a woman in Timnah of the daughters of the Philistines.\n'),
	(6912, 7, 14, 2, 'He came up, and told his father and his mother, and said, “I have seen a woman in Timnah of the daughters of the Philistines. Now therefore get her for me as my wife.”\n'),
	(6913, 7, 14, 3, 'Then his father and his mother said to him, “Isn’t there a woman among your brothers’ daughters, or among all my people, that you go to take a wife of the uncircumcised Philistines?”\nSamson said to his father, “Get her for me, for she pleases me well.”\n'),
	(6914, 7, 14, 4, 'But his father and his mother didn’t know that it was of Yahweh; for he sought an occasion against the Philistines. Now at that time the Philistines ruled over Israel.\n'),
	(6915, 7, 14, 5, 'Then went Samson down with his father and his mother to Timnah, and came to the vineyards of Timnah; and behold, a young lion roared against him.\n'),
	(6916, 7, 14, 6, 'Yahweh’s Spirit came mightily on him, and he tore him as he would have torn a young goat; and he had nothing in his hand, but he didn’t tell his father or his mother what he had done.\n'),
	(6917, 7, 14, 7, 'He went down, and talked with the woman, and she pleased Samson well.\n'),
	(6918, 7, 14, 8, 'After a while he returned to take her; and he went over to see the carcass of the lion; and behold, there was a swarm of bees in the body of the lion, and honey.\n'),
	(6919, 7, 14, 9, 'He took it into his hands, and went on, eating as he went. He came to his father and mother, and gave to them, and they ate, but he didn’t tell them that he had taken the honey out of the lion’s body.\n'),
	(6920, 7, 14, 10, 'His father went down to the woman; and Samson made a feast there, for the young men used to do so.\n'),
	(6921, 7, 14, 11, 'When they saw him, they brought thirty companions to be with him.\n'),
	(6922, 7, 14, 12, 'Samson said to them, “Let me tell you a riddle now. If you can declare it to me within the seven days of the feast, and find it out, then I will give you thirty linen garments and thirty changes of clothing;\n'),
	(6923, 7, 14, 13, 'but if you can’t declare it to me, then you shall give me thirty linen garments and thirty changes of clothing.”\nThey said to him, “Tell us your riddle, that we may hear it.”\n'),
	(6924, 7, 14, 14, 'He said to them,\n“Out of the eater came out food.\nOut of the strong came out sweetness.”\nThey couldn’t in three days declare the riddle.\n'),
	(6925, 7, 14, 15, 'On the seventh day, they said to Samson’s wife, “Entice your husband, that he may declare to us the riddle, lest we burn you and your father’s house with fire. Have you called us to impoverish us? Isn’t that so?”\n'),
	(6926, 7, 14, 16, 'Samson’s wife wept before him, and said, “You just hate me, and don’t love me. You’ve told a riddle to the children of my people, and haven’t told it to me.”\nHe said to her, “Behold, I haven’t told my father or my mother, so why should I tell you?”\n'),
	(6927, 7, 14, 17, 'She wept before him the seven days, while their feast lasted; and on the seventh day, he told her, because she pressed him severely; and she told the riddle to the children of her people.\n'),
	(6928, 7, 14, 18, 'The men of the city said to him on the seventh day before the sun went down, “What is sweeter than honey? What is stronger than a lion?”\nHe said to them,\n“If you hadn’t plowed with my heifer,\nyou wouldn’t have found out my riddle.”\n'),
	(6929, 7, 14, 19, 'Yahweh’s Spirit came mightily on him, and he went down to Ashkelon, and struck thirty men of them, and took their plunder, then gave the changes of clothing to those who declared the riddle. His anger burned, and he went up to his father’s house.\n'),
	(6930, 7, 14, 20, 'But Samson’s wife was given to his companion who had been his friend.\n'),
	(6931, 7, 15, 1, 'But after a while, in the time of wheat harvest, Samson visited his wife with a young goat. He said, “I will go in to my wife’s room.”\nBut her father wouldn’t allow him to go in.\n'),
	(6932, 7, 15, 2, 'Her father said, “I most certainly thought that you utterly hated her; therefore I gave her to your companion. Isn’t her younger sister more beautiful than she? Please take her, instead.”\n'),
	(6933, 7, 15, 3, 'Samson said to them, “This time I will be blameless in the case of the Philistines, when I harm them.”\n'),
	(6934, 7, 15, 4, 'Samson went and caught three hundred foxes, and took torches, and turned tail to tail, and put a torch in the middle between every two tails.\n'),
	(6935, 7, 15, 5, 'When he had set the torches on fire, he let them go into the standing grain of the Philistines, and burned up both the shocks and the standing grain, and also the olive groves.\n'),
	(6936, 7, 15, 6, 'Then the Philistines said, “Who has done this?”\nThey said, “Samson, the son-in-law of the Timnite, because he has taken his wife, and given her to his companion.” The Philistines came up, and burned her and her father with fire.\n'),
	(6937, 7, 15, 7, 'Samson said to them, “If you behave like this, surely I will take revenge on you, and after that I will cease.”\n'),
	(6938, 7, 15, 8, 'He struck them hip and thigh with a great slaughter; and he went down and lived in the cave in Etam’s rock.\n'),
	(6939, 7, 15, 9, 'Then the Philistines went up, encamped in Judah, and spread themselves in Lehi.\n'),
	(6940, 7, 15, 10, 'The men of Judah said, “Why have you come up against us?”\nThey said, “We have come up to bind Samson, to do to him as he has done to us.”\n'),
	(6941, 7, 15, 11, 'Then three thousand men of Judah went down to the cave in Etam’s rock, and said to Samson, “Don’t you know that the Philistines are rulers over us? What then is this that you have done to us?”\nHe said to them, “As they did to me, so I have done to them.”\n'),
	(6942, 7, 15, 12, 'They said to him, “We have come down to bind you, that we may deliver you into the hand of the Philistines.”\nSamson said to them, “Swear to me that you will not attack me yourselves.”\n'),
	(6943, 7, 15, 13, 'They spoke to him, saying, “No; but we will bind you securely, and deliver you into their hands; but surely we will not kill you.” They bound him with two new ropes, and brought him up from the rock.\n'),
	(6944, 7, 15, 14, 'When he came to Lehi, the Philistines shouted as they met him. Then Yahweh’s Spirit came mightily on him, and the ropes that were on his arms became as flax that was burned with fire, and his bands dropped from off his hands.\n'),
	(6945, 7, 15, 15, 'He found a fresh jawbone of a donkey, put out his hand, took it, and struck a thousand men with it.\n'),
	(6946, 7, 15, 16, 'Samson said, “With the jawbone of a donkey, heaps on heaps; with the jawbone of a donkey I have struck a thousand men.”\n'),
	(6947, 7, 15, 17, 'When he had finished speaking, he threw the jawbone out of his hand; and that place was called Ramath Lehi.\n'),
	(6948, 7, 15, 18, 'He was very thirsty, and called on Yahweh, and said, “You have given this great deliverance by the hand of your servant; and now shall I die of thirst, and fall into the hands of the uncircumcised?”\n'),
	(6949, 7, 15, 19, 'But God split the hollow place that is in Lehi, and water came out of it. When he had drunk, his spirit came again, and he revived. Therefore its name was called En Hakkore, which is in Lehi, to this day.\n'),
	(6950, 7, 15, 20, 'He judged Israel twenty years in the days of the Philistines.\n'),
	(6951, 7, 16, 1, 'Samson went to Gaza, and saw there a prostitute, and went in to her.\n'),
	(6952, 7, 16, 2, 'The Gazites were told, “Samson is here!” They surrounded him, and laid wait for him all night in the gate of the city, and were quiet all the night, saying, “Wait until morning light, then we will kill him.”\n'),
	(6953, 7, 16, 3, 'Samson lay until midnight, and arose at midnight, and laid hold of the doors of the gate of the city, and the two posts, and plucked them up, bar and all, and put them on his shoulders, and carried them up to the top of the mountain that is before Hebron.\n'),
	(6954, 7, 16, 4, 'It came to pass afterward, that he loved a woman in the valley of Sorek, whose name was Delilah.\n'),
	(6955, 7, 16, 5, 'The lords of the Philistines came up to her, and said to her, “Entice him, and see in which his great strength lies, and by what means we may prevail against him, that we may bind him to afflict him; and we will each give you eleven hundred pieces of silver.”\n'),
	(6956, 7, 16, 6, 'Delilah said to Samson, “Please tell me where your great strength lies, and what you might be bound to afflict you.”\n'),
	(6957, 7, 16, 7, 'Samson said to her, “If they bind me with seven green cords that were never dried, then shall I become weak, and be as another man.”\n'),
	(6958, 7, 16, 8, 'Then the lords of the Philistines brought up to her seven green cords which had not been dried, and she bound him with them.\n'),
	(6959, 7, 16, 9, 'Now she had an ambush waiting in the inner room. She said to him, “The Philistines are on you, Samson!” He broke the cords, as a string of tow is broken when it touches the fire. So his strength was not known.\n'),
	(6960, 7, 16, 10, 'Delilah said to Samson, “Behold, you have mocked me, and told me lies: now please tell me with which you might be bound.”\n'),
	(6961, 7, 16, 11, 'He said to her, “If they only bind me with new ropes with which no work has been done, then shall I become weak, and be as another man.”\n'),
	(6962, 7, 16, 12, 'So Delilah took new ropes, and bound him therewith, and said to him, “The Philistines are on you, Samson!” The ambush was waiting in the inner room. He broke them off his arms like a thread.\n'),
	(6963, 7, 16, 13, 'Delilah said to Samson, “Until now, you have mocked me and told me lies. Tell me with what you might be bound.”\nHe said to her, “If you weave the seven locks of my head with the web.”\n'),
	(6964, 7, 16, 14, 'She fastened it with the pin, and said to him, “The Philistines are on you, Samson!” He awakened out of his sleep, and plucked away the pin of the beam, and the web.\n'),
	(6965, 7, 16, 15, 'She said to him, “How can you say, ‘I love you,’ when your heart is not with me? You have mocked me these three times, and have not told me where your great strength lies.”\n'),
	(6966, 7, 16, 16, 'When she pressed him daily with her words, and urged him, his soul was troubled to death.\n'),
	(6967, 7, 16, 17, 'He told her all his heart, and said to her, “No razor has ever come on my head; for I have been a Nazirite to God from my mother’s womb. If I am shaved, then my strength will go from me, and I will become weak, and be like any other man.”\n'),
	(6968, 7, 16, 18, 'When Delilah saw that he had told her all his heart, she sent and called for the lords of the Philistines, saying, “Come up this once, for he has told me all his heart.” Then the lords of the Philistines came up to her, and brought the money in their hand.\n'),
	(6969, 7, 16, 19, 'She made him sleep on her knees; and she called for a man, and shaved off the seven locks of his head; and she began to afflict him, and his strength went from him.\n'),
	(6970, 7, 16, 20, 'She said, “The Philistines are upon you, Samson!”\nHe awoke out of his sleep, and said, “I will go out as at other times, and shake myself free.” But he didn’t know that Yahweh had departed from him.\n'),
	(6971, 7, 16, 21, 'The Philistines laid hold on him, and put out his eyes; and they brought him down to Gaza, and bound him with fetters of brass; and he ground at the mill in the prison.\n'),
	(6972, 7, 16, 22, 'However the hair of his head began to grow again after he was shaved.\n'),
	(6973, 7, 16, 23, 'The lords of the Philistines gathered them together to offer a great sacrifice to Dagon their god, and to rejoice; for they said, “Our god has delivered Samson our enemy into our hand.”\n'),
	(6974, 7, 16, 24, 'When the people saw him, they praised their god; for they said, “Our god has delivered our enemy and the destroyer of our country, who has slain many of us, into our hand.”\n'),
	(6975, 7, 16, 25, 'When their hearts were merry, they said, “Call for Samson, that he may entertain us.” They called for Samson out of the prison; and he performed before them. They set him between the pillars;\n'),
	(6976, 7, 16, 26, 'and Samson said to the boy who held him by the hand, “Allow me to feel the pillars whereupon the house rests, that I may lean on them.”\n'),
	(6977, 7, 16, 27, 'Now the house was full of men and women; and all the lords of the Philistines were there; and there were on the roof about three thousand men and women, who saw while Samson performed.\n'),
	(6978, 7, 16, 28, 'Samson called to Yahweh, and said, “Lord Yahweh, remember me, please, and strengthen me, please, only this once, God, that I may be at once avenged of the Philistines for my two eyes.”\n'),
	(6979, 7, 16, 29, 'Samson took hold of the two middle pillars on which the house rested, and leaned on them, the one with his right hand, and the other with his left.\n'),
	(6980, 7, 16, 30, 'Samson said, “Let me die with the Philistines!” He bowed himself with all his might; and the house fell on the lords, and on all the people who were therein. So the dead that he killed at his death were more than those who he killed in his life.\n'),
	(6981, 7, 16, 31, 'Then his brothers and all the house of his father came down, and took him, and brought him up, and buried him between Zorah and Eshtaol in the burial site of Manoah his father. He judged Israel twenty years.\n'),
	(6982, 7, 17, 1, 'There was a man of the hill country of Ephraim, whose name was Micah.\n'),
	(6983, 7, 17, 2, 'He said to his mother, “The eleven hundred pieces of silver that were taken from you, about which you uttered a curse, and also spoke it in my ears, behold, the silver is with me. I took it.”\nHis mother said, “May Yahweh bless my son!”\n'),
	(6984, 7, 17, 3, 'He restored the eleven hundred pieces of silver to his mother, then his mother said, “I most certainly dedicate the silver to Yahweh from my hand for my son, to make a carved image and a molten image. Now therefore I will restore it to you.”\n'),
	(6985, 7, 17, 4, 'When he restored the money to his mother, his mother took two hundred pieces of silver, and gave them to a silversmith, who made a carved image and a molten image out of it. It was in the house of Micah.\n'),
	(6986, 7, 17, 5, 'The man Micah had a house of gods, and he made an ephod, and teraphim, and consecrated one of his sons, who became his priest.\n'),
	(6987, 7, 17, 6, 'In those days there was no king in Israel. Everyone did that which was right in his own eyes.\n'),
	(6988, 7, 17, 7, 'There was a young man out of Bethlehem Judah, of the family of Judah, who was a Levite; and he lived there.\n'),
	(6989, 7, 17, 8, 'The man departed out of the city, out of Bethlehem Judah, to live where he could find a place, and he came to the hill country of Ephraim, to the house of Micah, as he traveled.\n'),
	(6990, 7, 17, 9, 'Micah said to him, “Where did you come from?”\nHe said to him, “I am a Levite of Bethlehem Judah, and I am looking for a place to live.”\n'),
	(6991, 7, 17, 10, 'Micah said to him, “Dwell with me, and be to me a father and a priest, and I will give you ten pieces of silver per year, a suit of clothing, and your food.” So the Levite went in.\n'),
	(6992, 7, 17, 11, 'The Levite was content to dwell with the man; and the young man was to him as one of his sons.\n'),
	(6993, 7, 17, 12, 'Micah consecrated the Levite, and the young man became his priest, and was in the house of Micah.\n'),
	(6994, 7, 17, 13, 'Then Micah said, “Now know I that Yahweh will do good to me, since I have a Levite as my priest.”\n'),
	(6995, 7, 18, 1, 'In those days there was no king in Israel. In those days the tribe of the Danites sought an inheritance to dwell in; for to that day, their inheritance had not fallen to them among the tribes of Israel.\n'),
	(6996, 7, 18, 2, 'The children of Dan sent five men of their family from their whole number, men of valor, from Zorah, and from Eshtaol, to spy out the land, and to search it. They said to them, “Go, explore the land!”\nThey came to the hill country of Ephraim, to the house of Micah, and lodged there.\n'),
	(6997, 7, 18, 3, 'When they were by the house of Micah, they knew the voice of the young man the Levite; so they went over there, and said to him, “Who brought you here? What do you do in this place? What do you have here?”\n'),
	(6998, 7, 18, 4, 'He said to them, “Thus and thus has Micah dealt with me, and he has hired me, and I am become his priest.”\n'),
	(6999, 7, 18, 5, 'They said to him, “Please ask counsel of God, that we may know whether our way which we go shall be prosperous.”\n'),
	(7000, 7, 18, 6, 'The priest said to them, “Go in peace. Your way in which you go is before Yahweh.”\n'),
	(7001, 7, 18, 7, 'Then the five men departed, and came to Laish, and saw the people who were there, how they lived in safety, in the way of the Sidonians, quiet and secure; for there was no one in the land, possessing authority, that might put them to shame in anything, and they were far from the Sidonians, and had no dealings with anyone else.\n'),
	(7002, 7, 18, 8, 'They came to their brothers at Zorah and Eshtaol; and their brothers asked them, “What do you say?”\n'),
	(7003, 7, 18, 9, 'They said, “Arise, and let us go up against them; for we have seen the land, and behold, it is very good. Do you stand still? Don’t be slothful to go and to enter in to possess the land.\n'),
	(7004, 7, 18, 10, 'When you go, you will come to an unsuspecting people, and the land is large; for God has given it into your hand, a place where there is no lack of anything that is in the earth.”\n'),
	(7005, 7, 18, 11, 'The family of the Danites set out from Zorah and Eshtaol, with six hundred men armed with weapons of war.\n'),
	(7006, 7, 18, 12, 'They went up and encamped in Kiriath Jearim, in Judah. Therefore they called that place Mahaneh Dan, to this day. Behold, it is behind Kiriath Jearim.\n'),
	(7007, 7, 18, 13, 'They passed from there to the hill country of Ephraim, and came to the house of Micah.\n'),
	(7008, 7, 18, 14, 'Then the five men who went to spy out the country of Laish answered, and said to their brothers, “Do you know that there is in these houses an ephod, and teraphim, and a carved image, and a molten image? Now therefore consider what you have to do.”\n'),
	(7009, 7, 18, 15, 'They went over there, and came to the house of the young Levite man, even to the house of Micah, and asked him how he was doing.\n'),
	(7010, 7, 18, 16, 'The six hundred men armed with their weapons of war, who were of the children of Dan, stood by the entrance of the gate.\n'),
	(7011, 7, 18, 17, 'The five men who went to spy out the land went up, and came in there, and took the engraved image, the ephod, the teraphim, and the molten image; and the priest stood by the entrance of the gate with the six hundred men armed with weapons of war.\n'),
	(7012, 7, 18, 18, 'When these went into Micah’s house, and took the engraved image, the ephod, the teraphim, and the molten image, the priest said to them, “What are you doing?”\n'),
	(7013, 7, 18, 19, 'They said to him, “Hold your peace, put your hand on your mouth, and go with us, and be to us a father and a priest. Is it better for you to be priest to the house of one man, or to be priest to a tribe and a family in Israel?”\n'),
	(7014, 7, 18, 20, 'The priest’s heart was glad, and he took the ephod, the teraphim, and the engraved image, and went with the people.\n'),
	(7015, 7, 18, 21, 'So they turned and departed, and put the little ones, the livestock, and the goods before them.\n'),
	(7016, 7, 18, 22, 'When they were a good way from the house of Micah, the men who were in the houses near Micah’s house gathered together and overtook the children of Dan.\n'),
	(7017, 7, 18, 23, 'As they cried to the children of Dan, they turned their faces, and said to Micah, “What ails you, that you come with such a company?”\n'),
	(7018, 7, 18, 24, 'He said, “You have taken away my gods which I made, and the priest, and have gone away! What more do I have? How can you ask me, ‘What ails you?’”\n'),
	(7019, 7, 18, 25, 'The children of Dan said to him, “Don’t let your voice be heard among us, lest angry fellows fall on you, and you lose your life, with the lives of your household.”\n'),
	(7020, 7, 18, 26, 'The children of Dan went their way; and when Micah saw that they were too strong for him, he turned and went back to his house.\n'),
	(7021, 7, 18, 27, 'They took that which Micah had made, and the priest whom he had, and came to Laish, to a people quiet and unsuspecting, and struck them with the edge of the sword; then they burned the city with fire.\n'),
	(7022, 7, 18, 28, 'There was no deliverer, because it was far from Sidon, and they had no dealings with anyone else; and it was in the valley that lies by Beth Rehob. They built the city, and lived in it.\n'),
	(7023, 7, 18, 29, 'They called the name of the city Dan, after the name of Dan their father, who was born to Israel; however the name of the city used to be Laish.\n'),
	(7024, 7, 18, 30, 'The children of Dan set up for themselves the engraved image; and Jonathan, the son of Gershom, the son of Moses, and his sons were priests to the tribe of the Danites until the day of the captivity of the land.\n'),
	(7025, 7, 18, 31, 'So they set up for themselves Micah’s engraved image which he made, and it remained all the time that God’s house was in Shiloh.\n'),
	(7026, 7, 19, 1, 'In those days, when there was no king in Israel, there was a certain Levite living on the farther side of the hill country of Ephraim, who took for himself a concubine out of Bethlehem Judah.\n'),
	(7027, 7, 19, 2, 'His concubine played the prostitute against him, and went away from him to her father’s house to Bethlehem Judah, and was there for four months.\n'),
	(7028, 7, 19, 3, 'Her husband arose, and went after her, to speak kindly to her, to bring her again, having his servant with him, and a couple of donkeys. She brought him into her father’s house; and when the father of the young lady saw him, he rejoiced to meet him.\n'),
	(7029, 7, 19, 4, 'His father-in-law, the young lady’s father, kept him there; and he stayed with him three days. So they ate and drank, and stayed there.\n'),
	(7030, 7, 19, 5, 'On the fourth day, they got up early in the morning, and he rose up to depart. The young lady’s father said to his son-in-law, “Strengthen your heart with a morsel of bread, and afterward you shall go your way.”\n'),
	(7031, 7, 19, 6, 'So they sat down, ate, and drank, both of them together. Then the young lady’s father said to the man, “Please be pleased to stay all night, and let your heart be merry.”\n'),
	(7032, 7, 19, 7, 'The man rose up to depart; but his father-in-law urged him, and he stayed there again.\n'),
	(7033, 7, 19, 8, 'He arose early in the morning on the fifth day to depart; and the young lady’s father said, “Please strengthen your heart and stay until the day declines”; and they both ate.\n'),
	(7034, 7, 19, 9, 'When the man rose up to depart, he, and his concubine, and his servant, his father-in-law, the young lady’s father, said to him, “Behold, now the day draws toward evening, please stay all night. Behold, the day is ending. Stay here, that your heart may be merry; and tomorrow go on your way early, that you may go home.”\n'),
	(7035, 7, 19, 10, 'But the man wouldn’t stay that night, but he rose up and departed, and toward Jebus (also called Jerusalem). With him were a couple of saddled donkeys. His concubine also was with him.\n'),
	(7036, 7, 19, 11, 'When they were by Jebus, the day was far spent; and the servant said to his master, “Please come and let us enter into this city of the Jebusites, and stay in it.”\n'),
	(7037, 7, 19, 12, 'His master said to him, “We won’t enter into the city of a foreigner that is not of the children of Israel; but we will pass over to Gibeah.”\n'),
	(7038, 7, 19, 13, 'He said to his servant, “Come and let us draw near to one of these places; and we will lodge in Gibeah, or in Ramah.”\n'),
	(7039, 7, 19, 14, 'So they passed on and went their way; and the sun went down on them near Gibeah, which belongs to Benjamin.\n'),
	(7040, 7, 19, 15, 'They went over there, to go in to stay in Gibeah. He went in, and sat down in the street of the city; for there was no one who took them into his house to stay.\n'),
	(7041, 7, 19, 16, 'Behold, an old man came from his work out of the field at evening. Now the man was from the hill country of Ephraim, and he lived in Gibeah; but the men of the place were Benjamites.\n'),
	(7042, 7, 19, 17, 'He lifted up his eyes, and saw the wayfaring man in the street of the city; and the old man said, “Where are you going? Where did you come from?”\n'),
	(7043, 7, 19, 18, 'He said to him, “We are passing from Bethlehem Judah to the farther side of the hill country of Ephraim. I am from there, and I went to Bethlehem Judah. I am going to Yahweh’s house; and there is no one who has taken me into his house.\n'),
	(7044, 7, 19, 19, 'Yet there is both straw and feed for our donkeys; and there is bread and wine also for me, and for your servant, and for the young man who is with your servants. There is no lack of anything.”\n'),
	(7045, 7, 19, 20, 'The old man said, “Peace be to you; how ever let me supply all your needs. Just don’t sleep in the street.”\n'),
	(7046, 7, 19, 21, 'So he brought him into his house, and gave the donkeys fodder. Then they washed their feet, and ate and drank.\n'),
	(7047, 7, 19, 22, 'As they were making their hearts merry, behold, the men of the city, certain wicked fellows, surrounded the house, beating at the door; and they spoke to the master of the house, the old man, saying, “Bring out the man who came into your house, that we can have sex with him!”\n'),
	(7048, 7, 19, 23, 'The man, the master of the house, went out to them, and said to them, “No, my brothers, please don’t act so wickedly; since this man has come into my house, don’t do this folly.\n'),
	(7049, 7, 19, 24, 'Behold, here is my virgin daughter and his concubine. I will bring them out now. Humble them, and do with them what seems good to you; but to this man don’t do any such folly.”\n'),
	(7050, 7, 19, 25, 'But the men wouldn’t listen to him: so the man laid hold of his concubine, and brought her out to them; and they had sex with her, and abused her all night until the morning. When the day began to dawn, they let her go.\n'),
	(7051, 7, 19, 26, 'Then the woman came in the dawning of the day, and fell down at the door of the man’s house where her lord was, until it was light.\n'),
	(7052, 7, 19, 27, 'Her lord rose up in the morning, and opened the doors of the house, and went out to go his way; and behold, the woman his concubine had fallen down at the door of the house, with her hands on the threshold.\n'),
	(7053, 7, 19, 28, 'He said to her, “Get up, and let us be going!” but no one answered. Then he took her up on the donkey; and the man rose up, and went to his place.\n'),
	(7054, 7, 19, 29, 'When he had come into his house, he took a knife, and cut up his concubine, and divided her, limb by limb, into twelve pieces, and sent her throughout all the borders of Israel.\n'),
	(7055, 7, 19, 30, 'It was so, that all who saw it said, “Such a deed has not been done or seen from the day that the children of Israel came up out of the land of Egypt to this day! Consider it, take counsel, and speak.”\n'),
	(7056, 7, 20, 1, 'Then all the children of Israel went out, and the congregation was assembled as one man, from Dan even to Beersheba, with the land of Gilead, to Yahweh at Mizpah.\n'),
	(7057, 7, 20, 2, 'The chiefs of all the people, even of all the tribes of Israel, presented themselves in the assembly of the people of God, four hundred thousand footmen who drew sword.\n'),
	(7058, 7, 20, 3, '(Now the children of Benjamin heard that the children of Israel had gone up to Mizpah.) The children of Israel said, “Tell us, how did this wickedness happen?”\n'),
	(7059, 7, 20, 4, 'The Levite, the husband of the woman who was murdered, answered, “I came into Gibeah that belongs to Benjamin, I and my concubine, to spend the night.\n'),
	(7060, 7, 20, 5, 'The men of Gibeah rose against me, and surrounded the house by night. They intended to kill me, and they raped my concubine, and she is dead.\n'),
	(7061, 7, 20, 6, 'I took my concubine, and cut her in pieces, and sent her throughout all the country of the inheritance of Israel; for they have committed lewdness and folly in Israel.\n'),
	(7062, 7, 20, 7, 'Behold, you children of Israel, all of you, give here your advice and counsel.”\n'),
	(7063, 7, 20, 8, 'All the people arose as one man, saying, “None of us will go to his tent, neither will any of us turn to his house.\n'),
	(7064, 7, 20, 9, 'But now this is the thing which we will do to Gibeah: we will go up against it by lot;\n'),
	(7065, 7, 20, 10, 'and we will take ten men of one hundred throughout all the tribes of Israel, and one hundred of one thousand, and a thousand out of ten thousand, to get food for the people, that they may do, when they come to Gibeah of Benjamin, according to all the folly that they have worked in Israel.”\n'),
	(7066, 7, 20, 11, 'So all the men of Israel were gathered against the city, knit together as one man.\n'),
	(7067, 7, 20, 12, 'The tribes of Israel sent men through all the tribe of Benjamin, saying, “What wickedness is this that has happened among you?\n'),
	(7068, 7, 20, 13, 'Now therefore deliver up the men, the wicked fellows, who are in Gibeah, that we may put them to death, and put away evil from Israel.”\nBut Benjamin would not listen to the voice of their brothers the children of Israel.\n'),
	(7069, 7, 20, 14, 'The children of Benjamin gathered themselves together out of the cities to Gibeah, to go out to battle against the children of Israel.\n'),
	(7070, 7, 20, 15, 'The children of Benjamin were counted on that day out of the cities twenty-six thousand men who drew the sword, besides the inhabitants of Gibeah, who were counted seven hundred chosen men.\n'),
	(7071, 7, 20, 16, 'Among all these soldiers there were seven hundred chosen men who were left-handed. Every one of them could sling a stone at a hair and not miss.\n'),
	(7072, 7, 20, 17, 'The men of Israel, besides Benjamin, were counted four hundred thousand men who drew sword. All these were men of war.\n'),
	(7073, 7, 20, 18, 'The children of Israel arose, went up to Bethel, and asked counsel of God. They asked, “Who shall go up for us first to battle against the children of Benjamin?”\nYahweh said, “Judah first.”\n'),
	(7074, 7, 20, 19, 'The children of Israel rose up in the morning, and encamped against Gibeah.\n'),
	(7075, 7, 20, 20, 'The men of Israel went out to battle against Benjamin; and the men of Israel set the battle in array against them at Gibeah.\n'),
	(7076, 7, 20, 21, 'The children of Benjamin came out of Gibeah, and on that day destroyed twenty-two thousand of the Israelite men down to the ground.\n'),
	(7077, 7, 20, 22, 'The people, the men of Israel, encouraged themselves, and set the battle again in array in the place where they set themselves in array the first day.\n'),
	(7078, 7, 20, 23, 'The children of Israel went up and wept before Yahweh until evening; and they asked of Yahweh, saying, “Shall I again draw near to battle against the children of Benjamin my brother?”\nYahweh said, “Go up against him.”\n'),
	(7079, 7, 20, 24, 'The children of Israel came near against the children of Benjamin the second day.\n'),
	(7080, 7, 20, 25, 'Benjamin went out against them out of Gibeah the second day, and destroyed down to the ground of the children of Israel again eighteen thousand men. All these drew the sword.\n'),
	(7081, 7, 20, 26, 'Then all the children of Israel, and all the people, went up, and came to Bethel, and wept, and sat there before Yahweh, and fasted that day until evening; then they offered burnt offerings and peace offerings before Yahweh.\n'),
	(7082, 7, 20, 27, 'The children of Israel asked Yahweh (for the ark of the covenant of God was there in those days,\n'),
	(7083, 7, 20, 28, 'and Phinehas, the son of Eleazar, the son of Aaron, stood before it in those days), saying, “Shall I yet again go out to battle against the children of Benjamin my brother, or shall I cease?”\nYahweh said, “Go up; for tomorrow I will deliver him into your hand.”\n'),
	(7084, 7, 20, 29, 'Israel set ambushes all around Gibeah.\n'),
	(7085, 7, 20, 30, 'The children of Israel went up against the children of Benjamin on the third day, and set themselves in array against Gibeah, as at other times.\n'),
	(7086, 7, 20, 31, 'The children of Benjamin went out against the people, and were drawn away from the city; and they began to strike and kill of the people, as at other times, in the highways, of which one goes up to Bethel, and the other to Gibeah, in the field, about thirty men of Israel.\n'),
	(7087, 7, 20, 32, 'The children of Benjamin said, “They are struck down before us, as at the first.” But the children of Israel said, “Let us flee, and draw them away from the city to the highways.”\n'),
	(7088, 7, 20, 33, 'All the men of Israel rose up out of their place, and set themselves in array at Baal Tamar. Then the ambushers of Israel broke out of their place, even out of Maareh Geba.\n'),
	(7089, 7, 20, 34, 'Ten thousand chosen men out of all Israel came over against Gibeah, and the battle was severe; but they didn’t know that disaster was close to them.\n'),
	(7090, 7, 20, 35, 'Yahweh struck Benjamin before Israel; and the children of Israel destroyed of Benjamin that day twenty-five thousand one hundred men. All these drew the sword.\n'),
	(7091, 7, 20, 36, 'So the children of Benjamin saw that they were struck; for the men of Israel yielded to Benjamin, because they trusted the ambushers whom they had set against Gibeah.\n'),
	(7092, 7, 20, 37, 'The ambushers hurried, and rushed on Gibeah; then the ambushers spread out, and struck all the city with the edge of the sword.\n'),
	(7093, 7, 20, 38, 'Now the appointed sign between the men of Israel and the ambushers was that they should make a great cloud of smoke rise up out of the city.\n'),
	(7094, 7, 20, 39, 'The men of Israel turned in the battle, and Benjamin began to strike and kill of the men of Israel about thirty persons; for they said, “Surely they are struck down before us, as in the first battle.”\n'),
	(7095, 7, 20, 40, 'But when the cloud began to arise up out of the city in a pillar of smoke, the Benjamites looked behind them; and behold, the whole city went up in smoke to the sky.\n'),
	(7096, 7, 20, 41, 'The men of Israel turned, and the men of Benjamin were dismayed; for they saw that disaster had come on them.\n'),
	(7097, 7, 20, 42, 'Therefore they turned their backs before the men of Israel to the way of the wilderness; but the battle followed hard after them; and those who came out of the cities destroyed them in the middle of it.\n'),
	(7098, 7, 20, 43, 'They surrounded the Benjamites, chased them, and trod them down at their resting place, as far as near Gibeah toward the sunrise.\n'),
	(7099, 7, 20, 44, 'Eighteen thousand men of Benjamin fell; all these were men of valor.\n'),
	(7100, 7, 20, 45, 'They turned and fled toward the wilderness to the rock of Rimmon; and they gleaned five thousand men of them in the highways, and followed hard after them to Gidom, and struck two thousand men of them.\n'),
	(7101, 7, 20, 46, 'So that all who fell that day of Benjamin were twenty-five thousand men who drew the sword. All these were men of valor.\n'),
	(7102, 7, 20, 47, 'But six hundred men turned and fled toward the wilderness to the rock of Rimmon, and stayed in the rock of Rimmon four months.\n'),
	(7103, 7, 20, 48, 'The men of Israel turned again on the children of Benjamin, and struck them with the edge of the sword, both the entire city, and the livestock, and all that they found. Moreover all the cities which they found they set on fire.\n'),
	(7104, 7, 21, 1, 'Now the men of Israel had sworn in Mizpah, saying, “None of us will give his daughter to Benjamin as a wife.”\n'),
	(7105, 7, 21, 2, 'The people came to Bethel, and sat there until evening before God, and lifted up their voices, and wept severely.\n'),
	(7106, 7, 21, 3, 'They said, “Yahweh, the God of Israel, why has this happened in Israel, that there should be one tribe lacking in Israel today?”\n'),
	(7107, 7, 21, 4, 'On the next day, the people rose early, and built an altar there, and offered burnt offerings and peace offerings.\n'),
	(7108, 7, 21, 5, 'The children of Israel said, “Who is there among all the tribes of Israel who didn’t come up in the assembly to Yahweh?” For they had made a great oath concerning him who didn’t come up to Yahweh to Mizpah, saying, “He shall surely be put to death.”\n'),
	(7109, 7, 21, 6, 'The children of Israel grieved for Benjamin their brother, and said, “There is one tribe cut off from Israel today.\n'),
	(7110, 7, 21, 7, 'How shall we provide wives for those who remain, since we have sworn by Yahweh that we will not give them of our daughters to wives?”\n'),
	(7111, 7, 21, 8, 'They said, “What one is there of the tribes of Israel who didn’t come up to Yahweh to Mizpah?” Behold, no one came from Jabesh Gilead to the camp to the assembly.\n'),
	(7112, 7, 21, 9, 'For when the people were counted, behold, there were none of the inhabitants of Jabesh Gilead there.\n'),
	(7113, 7, 21, 10, 'The congregation sent twelve thousand of the most valiant men there, and commanded them, saying, “Go and strike the inhabitants of Jabesh Gilead with the edge of the sword, with the women and the little ones.\n'),
	(7114, 7, 21, 11, 'This is the thing that you shall do: you shall utterly destroy every male, and every woman who has lain with a man.”\n'),
	(7115, 7, 21, 12, 'They found among the inhabitants of Jabesh Gilead four hundred young virgins, who had not known man by lying with him; and they brought them to the camp to Shiloh, which is in the land of Canaan.\n'),
	(7116, 7, 21, 13, 'The whole congregation sent and spoke to the children of Benjamin who were in the rock of Rimmon, and proclaimed peace to them.\n'),
	(7117, 7, 21, 14, 'Benjamin returned at that time; and they gave them the women whom they had saved alive of the women of Jabesh Gilead. There still weren’t enough for them.\n'),
	(7118, 7, 21, 15, 'The people grieved for Benjamin, because Yahweh had made a breach in the tribes of Israel.\n'),
	(7119, 7, 21, 16, 'Then the elders of the congregation said, “How shall we provide wives for those who remain, since the women are destroyed out of Benjamin?”\n'),
	(7120, 7, 21, 17, 'They said, “There must be an inheritance for those who are escaped of Benjamin, that a tribe not be blotted out from Israel.\n'),
	(7121, 7, 21, 18, 'However we may not give them wives of our daughters, for the children of Israel had sworn, saying, ‘Cursed is he who gives a wife to Benjamin.’”\n'),
	(7122, 7, 21, 19, 'They said, “Behold, there is a feast of Yahweh from year to year in Shiloh, which is on the north of Bethel, on the east side of the highway that goes up from Bethel to Shechem, and on the south of Lebonah.”\n'),
	(7123, 7, 21, 20, 'They commanded the children of Benjamin, saying, “Go and lie in wait in the vineyards,\n'),
	(7124, 7, 21, 21, 'and see, and behold, if the daughters of Shiloh come out to dance in the dances, then come out of the vineyards, and each man catch his wife of the daughters of Shiloh, and go to the land of Benjamin.\n'),
	(7125, 7, 21, 22, 'It shall be, when their fathers or their brothers come to complain to us, that we will say to them, ‘Grant them graciously to us, because we didn’t take for each man his wife in battle, neither did you give them to them, otherwise you would now be guilty.’”\n'),
	(7126, 7, 21, 23, 'The children of Benjamin did so, and took wives for themselves, according to their number, of those who danced, whom they carried off. They went and returned to their inheritance, built the cities, and lived in them.\n'),
	(7127, 7, 21, 24, 'The children of Israel departed from there at that time, every man to his tribe and to his family, and they each went out from there to his own inheritance.\n'),
	(7128, 7, 21, 25, 'In those days there was no king in Israel. Everyone did that which was right in his own eyes.\n'),
	(7129, 8, 1, 1, 'In the days when the judges judged, there was a famine in the land. A certain man of Bethlehem Judah went to live in the country of Moab, he, and his wife, and his two sons.\n'),
	(7130, 8, 1, 2, 'The name of the man was Elimelech, and the name of his wife Naomi. The names of his two sons were Mahlon and Chilion, Ephrathites of Bethlehem Judah. They came into the country of Moab, and lived there.\n'),
	(7131, 8, 1, 3, 'Elimelech, Naomi’s husband, died; and she was left with her two sons.\n'),
	(7132, 8, 1, 4, 'They took for themselves wives of the women of Moab. The name of the one was Orpah, and the name of the other was Ruth. They lived there about ten years.\n'),
	(7133, 8, 1, 5, 'Mahlon and Chilion both died, and the woman was bereaved of her two children and of her husband.\n'),
	(7134, 8, 1, 6, 'Then she arose with her daughters-in-law, that she might return from the country of Moab; for she had heard in the country of Moab how Yahweh\n had visited his people in giving them bread.\n'),
	(7135, 8, 1, 7, 'She went out of the place where she was, and her two daughters-in-law with her. They went on the way to return to the land of Judah.\n'),
	(7136, 8, 1, 8, 'Naomi said to her two daughters-in-law, “Go, return each of you to her mother’s house. May Yahweh deal kindly with you, as you have dealt with the dead, and with me.\n'),
	(7137, 8, 1, 9, 'May Yahweh grant you that you may find rest, each of you in the house of her husband.”\nThen she kissed them, and they lifted up their voices, and wept.\n'),
	(7138, 8, 1, 10, 'They said to her, “No, but we will return with you to your people.”\n'),
	(7139, 8, 1, 11, 'Naomi said, “Go back, my daughters. Why do you want to go with me? Do I still have sons in my womb, that they may be your husbands?\n'),
	(7140, 8, 1, 12, 'Go back, my daughters, go your way; for I am too old to have a husband. If I should say, ‘I have hope,’ if I should even have a husband tonight, and should also bear sons;\n'),
	(7141, 8, 1, 13, 'would you then wait until they were grown? Would you then refrain from having husbands? No, my daughters, for it grieves me seriously for your sakes, for Yahweh’s hand has gone out against me.”\n'),
	(7142, 8, 1, 14, 'They lifted up their voices, and wept again; then Orpah kissed her mother-in-law, but Ruth joined with her.\n'),
	(7143, 8, 1, 15, 'She said, “Behold, your sister-in-law has gone back to her people, and to her god. Follow your sister-in-law.”\n'),
	(7144, 8, 1, 16, 'Ruth said, “Don’t urge me to leave you, and to return from following you, for where you go, I will go; and where you stay, I will stay. Your people will be my people, and your God my God.\n'),
	(7145, 8, 1, 17, 'Where you die, I will die, and there I will be buried. May Yahweh do so to me, and more also, if anything but death parts you and me.”\n'),
	(7146, 8, 1, 18, 'When she saw that she was determined to go with her, she stopped urging her.\n'),
	(7147, 8, 1, 19, 'So they both went until they came to Bethlehem. When they had come to Bethlehem, all the city was excited about them, and they asked, “Is this Naomi?”\n'),
	(7148, 8, 1, 20, 'She said to them, “Don’t call me Naomi. Call me Mara; for the Almighty has dealt very bitterly with me.\n'),
	(7149, 8, 1, 21, 'I went out full, and Yahweh has brought me home again empty. Why do you call me Naomi, since Yahweh has testified against me, and the Almighty has afflicted me?”\n'),
	(7150, 8, 1, 22, 'So Naomi returned, and Ruth the Moabitess, her daughter-in-law, with her, who returned out of the country of Moab. They came to Bethlehem in the beginning of barley harvest.\n'),
	(7151, 8, 2, 1, 'Naomi had a relative of her husband’s, a mighty man of wealth, of the family of Elimelech, and his name was Boaz.\n'),
	(7152, 8, 2, 2, 'Ruth the Moabitess said to Naomi, “Let me now go to the field, and glean among the ears of grain after him in whose sight I find favor.”\nShe said to her, “Go, my daughter.”\n'),
	(7153, 8, 2, 3, 'She went, and came and gleaned in the field after the reapers; and she happened to come to the portion of the field belonging to Boaz, who was of the family of Elimelech.\n'),
	(7154, 8, 2, 4, 'Behold, Boaz came from Bethlehem, and said to the reapers, “May Yahweh be with you.”\nThey answered him, “May Yahweh bless you.”\n'),
	(7155, 8, 2, 5, 'Then Boaz said to his servant who was set over the reapers, “Whose young lady is this?”\n'),
	(7156, 8, 2, 6, 'The servant who was set over the reapers answered, “It is the Moabite lady who came back with Naomi out of the country of Moab.\n'),
	(7157, 8, 2, 7, 'She said, ‘Please let me glean and gather after the reapers among the sheaves.’ So she came, and has continued even from the morning until now, except that she rested a little in the house.”\n'),
	(7158, 8, 2, 8, 'Then Boaz said to Ruth, “Listen, my daughter. Don’t go to glean in another field, and don’t go from here, but stay here close to my maidens.\n'),
	(7159, 8, 2, 9, 'Let your eyes be on the field that they reap, and go after them. Haven’t I commanded the young men not to touch you? When you are thirsty, go to the vessels, and drink from that which the young men have drawn.”\n'),
	(7160, 8, 2, 10, 'Then she fell on her face, and bowed herself to the ground, and said to him, “Why have I found favor in your sight, that you should take knowledge of me, since I am a foreigner?”\n'),
	(7161, 8, 2, 11, 'Boaz answered her, “I have been told all about what you have done for your mother-in-law since the death of your husband, and how you have left your father and your mother, and the land of your birth, and have come to a people that you didn’t know before.\n'),
	(7162, 8, 2, 12, 'May Yahweh repay your work, and a full reward be given to you from Yahweh, the God of Israel, under whose wings you have come to take refuge.”\n'),
	(7163, 8, 2, 13, 'Then she said, “Let me find favor in your sight, my lord, because you have comforted me, and because you have spoken kindly to your servant, though I am not as one of your servants.”\n'),
	(7164, 8, 2, 14, 'At meal time Boaz said to her, “Come here, and eat some bread, and dip your morsel in the vinegar.”\nShe sat beside the reapers, and they passed her parched grain, and she ate, and was satisfied, and left some of it.\n'),
	(7165, 8, 2, 15, 'When she had risen up to glean, Boaz commanded his young men, saying, “Let her glean even among the sheaves, and don’t reproach her.\n'),
	(7166, 8, 2, 16, 'Also pull out some for her from the bundles, and leave it. Let her glean, and don’t rebuke her.”\n'),
	(7167, 8, 2, 17, 'So she gleaned in the field until evening; and she beat out that which she had gleaned, and it was about an ephah of barley.\n'),
	(7168, 8, 2, 18, 'She took it up, and went into the city. Then her mother-in-law saw what she had gleaned; and she brought out and gave to her that which she had left after she had enough.\n'),
	(7169, 8, 2, 19, 'Her mother-in-law said to her, “Where have you gleaned today? Where have you worked? Blessed be he who noticed you.”\nShe told her mother-in-law with whom she had worked, “The man’s name with whom I worked today is Boaz.”\n'),
	(7170, 8, 2, 20, 'Naomi said to her daughter-in-law, “May he be blessed by Yahweh, who has not abandoned his kindness to the living and to the dead.” Naomi said to her, “The man is a close relative to us, one of our near kinsmen.”\n'),
	(7171, 8, 2, 21, 'Ruth the Moabitess said, “Yes, he said to me, ‘You shall stay close to my young men, until they have finished all my harvest.’”\n'),
	(7172, 8, 2, 22, 'Naomi said to Ruth her daughter-in-law, “It is good, my daughter, that you go out with his maidens, and that they not meet you in any other field.”\n'),
	(7173, 8, 2, 23, 'So she stayed close to the maidens of Boaz, to glean to the end of barley harvest and of wheat harvest; and she lived with her mother-in-law.\n'),
	(7174, 8, 3, 1, 'Naomi her mother-in-law said to her, “My daughter, shall I not seek rest for you, that it may be well with you?\n'),
	(7175, 8, 3, 2, 'Now isn’t Boaz our kinsman, with whose maidens you were? Behold, he will be winnowing barley tonight on the threshing floor.\n'),
	(7176, 8, 3, 3, 'Therefore wash yourself, anoint yourself, get dressed, and go down to the threshing floor, but don’t make yourself known to the man until he has finished eating and drinking.\n'),
	(7177, 8, 3, 4, 'It shall be, when he lies down, that you shall note the place where he is lying. Then you shall go in, uncover his feet, and lay down. Then he will tell you what to do.”\n'),
	(7178, 8, 3, 5, 'She said to her, “All that you say, I will do.”\n'),
	(7179, 8, 3, 6, 'She went down to the threshing floor, and did everything that her mother-in-law told her.\n'),
	(7180, 8, 3, 7, 'When Boaz had eaten and drunk, and his heart was merry, he went to lie down at the end of the heap of grain. She came softly, uncovered his feet, and laid down.\n'),
	(7181, 8, 3, 8, 'At midnight, the man was startled and turned himself; and behold, a woman lay at his feet.\n'),
	(7182, 8, 3, 9, 'He said, “Who are you?”\nShe answered, “I am Ruth your servant. Therefore spread the corner of your garment over your servant; for you are a near kinsman.”\n'),
	(7183, 8, 3, 10, 'He said, “You are blessed by Yahweh, my daughter. You have shown more kindness in the latter end than at the beginning, because you didn’t follow young men, whether poor or rich.\n'),
	(7184, 8, 3, 11, 'Now, my daughter, don’t be afraid. I will do to you all that you say; for all the city of my people knows that you are a worthy woman.\n'),
	(7185, 8, 3, 12, 'Now it is true that I am a near kinsman. However, there is a kinsman nearer than I.\n'),
	(7186, 8, 3, 13, 'Stay this night, and in the morning, if he will perform for you the part of a kinsman, good. Let him do the kinsman’s duty. But if he will not do the duty of a kinsman for you, then I will do the duty of a kinsman for you, as Yahweh lives. Lie down until the morning.”\n'),
	(7187, 8, 3, 14, 'She lay at his feet until the morning, then she rose up before one could discern another. For he said, “Let it not be known that the woman came to the threshing floor.”\n'),
	(7188, 8, 3, 15, 'He said, “Bring the mantle that is on you, and hold it.” She held it; and he measured six measures of barley, and laid it on her; then he went into the city.\n'),
	(7189, 8, 3, 16, 'When she came to her mother-in-law, she said, “How did it go, my daughter?”\nShe told her all that the man had done for her.\n'),
	(7190, 8, 3, 17, 'She said, “He gave me these six measures of barley; for he said, ‘Don’t go empty to your mother-in-law.’”\n'),
	(7191, 8, 3, 18, 'Then she said, “Wait, my daughter, until you know what will happen; for the man will not rest until he has settled this today.”\n'),
	(7192, 8, 4, 1, 'Now Boaz went up to the gate, and sat down there. Behold, the near kinsman of whom Boaz spoke came by. He said to him, “Come over here, friend, and sit down!” He came over, and sat down.\n'),
	(7193, 8, 4, 2, 'He took ten men of the elders of the city, and said, “Sit down here,” and they sat down.\n'),
	(7194, 8, 4, 3, 'He said to the near kinsman, “Naomi, who has come back out of the country of Moab, is selling the parcel of land, which was our brother Elimelech’s.\n'),
	(7195, 8, 4, 4, 'I thought I should tell you, saying, ‘Buy it before those who sit here, and before the elders of my people.’ If you will redeem it, redeem it; but if you will not redeem it, then tell me, that I may know. For there is no one to redeem it besides you; and I am after you.”\nHe said, “I will redeem it.”\n'),
	(7196, 8, 4, 5, 'Then Boaz said, “On the day you buy the field from the hand of Naomi, you must buy it also from Ruth the Moabitess, the wife of the dead, to raise up the name of the dead on his inheritance.”\n'),
	(7197, 8, 4, 6, 'The near kinsman said, “I can’t redeem it for myself, lest I endanger my own inheritance. Take my right of redemption for yourself; for I can’t redeem it.”\n'),
	(7198, 8, 4, 7, 'Now this was the custom in former time in Israel concerning redeeming and concerning exchanging, to confirm all things: a man took off his shoe, and gave it to his neighbor; and this was the way of formalizing transactions in Israel.\n'),
	(7199, 8, 4, 8, 'So the near kinsman said to Boaz, “Buy it for yourself,” then he took off his shoe.\n'),
	(7200, 8, 4, 9, 'Boaz said to the elders, and to all the people, “You are witnesses today, that I have bought all that was Elimelech’s, and all that was Chilion’s and Mahlon’s, from the hand of Naomi.\n'),
	(7201, 8, 4, 10, 'Moreover Ruth the Moabitess, the wife of Mahlon, I have purchased to be my wife, to raise up the name of the dead on his inheritance, that the name of the dead may not be cut off from among his brothers, and from the gate of his place. You are witnesses today.”\n'),
	(7202, 8, 4, 11, 'All the people who were in the gate, and the elders, said, “We are witnesses. May Yahweh make the woman who has come into your house like Rachel and like Leah, which both built the house of Israel; and treat you worthily in Ephrathah, and be famous in Bethlehem.\n'),
	(7203, 8, 4, 12, 'Let your house be like the house of Perez, whom Tamar bore to Judah, of the offspring which Yahweh will give you by this young woman.”\n'),
	(7204, 8, 4, 13, 'So Boaz took Ruth, and she became his wife; and he went in to her, and Yahweh enabled her to conceive, and she bore a son.\n'),
	(7205, 8, 4, 14, 'The women said to Naomi, “Blessed be Yahweh, who has not left you today without a near kinsman. Let his name be famous in Israel.\n'),
	(7206, 8, 4, 15, 'He shall be to you a restorer of life, and sustain you in your old age, for your daughter-in-law, who loves you, who is better to you than seven sons, has given birth to him.”\n'),
	(7207, 8, 4, 16, 'Naomi took the child, and laid him in her bosom, and became nurse to it.\n'),
	(7208, 8, 4, 17, 'The women, her neighbors, gave him a name, saying, “A son is born to Naomi”. They named him Obed. He is the father of Jesse, the father of David.\n'),
	(7209, 8, 4, 18, 'Now this is the history of the generations of Perez: Perez became the father of Hezron,\n'),
	(7210, 8, 4, 19, 'and Hezron became the father of Ram, and Ram became the father of Amminadab,\n'),
	(7211, 8, 4, 20, 'and Amminadab became the father of Nahshon, and Nahshon became the father of Salmon,\n'),
	(7212, 8, 4, 21, 'and Salmon became the father of Boaz, and Boaz became the father of Obed,\n'),
	(7213, 8, 4, 22, 'and Obed became the father of Jesse, and Jesse became the father of David.\n'),
	(7214, 12, 1, 1, 'Now in the first year of Cyrus king of Persia, that Yahweh’s word\n by Jeremiah’s mouth might be accomplished, Yahweh stirred up the spirit of Cyrus king of Persia, so that he made a proclamation throughout all his kingdom, and put it also in writing, saying,\n'),
	(7215, 12, 1, 2, '“Thus says Cyrus king of Persia, ‘Yahweh, the God of heaven, has given me all the kingdoms of the earth; and he has commanded me to build him a house in Jerusalem, which is in Judah.\n'),
	(7216, 12, 1, 3, 'Whoever there is among you of all his people, may his God be with him, and let him go up to Jerusalem, which is in Judah, and build the house of Yahweh, the God of Israel (he is God), which is in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7217, 12, 1, 4, 'Whoever is left, in any place where he lives, let the men of his place help him with silver, with gold, with goods, and with animals, besides the freewill offering for God’s house which is in Jerusalem.’”\n'),
	(7218, 12, 1, 5, 'Then the heads of fathers’ households of Judah and Benjamin, the priests, and the Levites, all whose spirit God had stirred to go up rose up to build Yahweh’s house which is in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7219, 12, 1, 6, 'All those who were around them strengthened their hands with vessels of silver, with gold, with goods, with animals, and with precious things, besides all that was willingly offered.\n'),
	(7220, 12, 1, 7, 'Also Cyrus the king brought out the vessels of Yahweh’s house, which Nebuchadnezzar had brought out of Jerusalem, and had put in the house of his gods;\n'),
	(7221, 12, 1, 8, 'even those, Cyrus king of Persia brought out by the hand of Mithredath the treasurer, and counted them out to Sheshbazzar, the prince of Judah.\n'),
	(7222, 12, 1, 9, 'This is the number of them: thirty platters of gold, one thousand platters of silver, twenty-nine knives,\n'),
	(7223, 12, 1, 10, 'thirty bowls of gold, four hundred ten silver bowls of a second sort, and one thousand other vessels.\n'),
	(7224, 12, 1, 11, 'All the vessels of gold and of silver were five thousand four hundred. Sheshbazzar brought all these up when the captives were brought up from Babylon to Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7225, 12, 2, 1, 'Now these are the children of the province, who went up out of the captivity of those who had been carried away, whom Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon had carried away to Babylon, and who returned to Jerusalem and Judah, everyone to his city;\n'),
	(7226, 12, 2, 2, 'who came with Zerubbabel, Jeshua, Nehemiah, Seraiah, Reelaiah, Mordecai, Bilshan, Mispar, Bigvai, Rehum, and Baanah.\nThe number of the men of the people of Israel:\n'),
	(7227, 12, 2, 3, 'The children of Parosh, two thousand one hundred seventy-two.\n'),
	(7228, 12, 2, 4, 'The children of Shephatiah, three hundred seventy-two.\n'),
	(7229, 12, 2, 5, 'The children of Arah, seven hundred seventy-five.\n'),
	(7230, 12, 2, 6, 'The children of Pahathmoab, of the children of Jeshua and Joab, two thousand eight hundred twelve.\n'),
	(7231, 12, 2, 7, 'The children of Elam, one thousand two hundred fifty-four.\n'),
	(7232, 12, 2, 8, 'The children of Zattu, nine hundred forty-five.\n'),
	(7233, 12, 2, 9, 'The children of Zaccai, seven hundred sixty.\n'),
	(7234, 12, 2, 10, 'The children of Bani, six hundred forty-two.\n'),
	(7235, 12, 2, 11, 'The children of Bebai, six hundred twenty-three.\n'),
	(7236, 12, 2, 12, 'The children of Azgad, one thousand two hundred twenty-two.\n'),
	(7237, 12, 2, 13, 'The children of Adonikam, six hundred sixty-six.\n'),
	(7238, 12, 2, 14, 'The children of Bigvai, two thousand fifty-six.\n'),
	(7239, 12, 2, 15, 'The children of Adin, four hundred fifty-four.\n'),
	(7240, 12, 2, 16, 'The children of Ater, of Hezekiah, ninety-eight.\n'),
	(7241, 12, 2, 17, 'The children of Bezai, three hundred twenty-three.\n'),
	(7242, 12, 2, 18, 'The children of Jorah, one hundred twelve.\n'),
	(7243, 12, 2, 19, 'The children of Hashum, two hundred twenty-three.\n'),
	(7244, 12, 2, 20, 'The children of Gibbar, ninety-five.\n'),
	(7245, 12, 2, 21, 'The children of Bethlehem, one hundred twenty-three.\n'),
	(7246, 12, 2, 22, 'The men of Netophah, fifty-six.\n'),
	(7247, 12, 2, 23, 'The men of Anathoth, one hundred twenty-eight.\n'),
	(7248, 12, 2, 24, 'The children of Azmaveth, forty-two.\n'),
	(7249, 12, 2, 25, 'The children of Kiriath Arim, Chephirah, and Beeroth, seven hundred forty-three.\n'),
	(7250, 12, 2, 26, 'The children of Ramah and Geba, six hundred twenty-one.\n'),
	(7251, 12, 2, 27, 'The men of Michmas, one hundred twenty-two.\n'),
	(7252, 12, 2, 28, 'The men of Bethel and Ai, two hundred twenty-three.\n'),
	(7253, 12, 2, 29, 'The children of Nebo, fifty-two.\n'),
	(7254, 12, 2, 30, 'The children of Magbish, one hundred fifty-six.\n'),
	(7255, 12, 2, 31, 'The children of the other Elam, one thousand two hundred fifty-four.\n'),
	(7256, 12, 2, 32, 'The children of Harim, three hundred twenty.\n'),
	(7257, 12, 2, 33, 'The children of Lod, Hadid, and Ono, seven hundred twenty-five.\n'),
	(7258, 12, 2, 34, 'The children of Jericho, three hundred forty-five.\n'),
	(7259, 12, 2, 35, 'The children of Senaah, three thousand six hundred thirty.\n'),
	(7260, 12, 2, 36, 'The priests: the children of Jedaiah, of the house of Jeshua, nine hundred seventy-three.\n'),
	(7261, 12, 2, 37, 'The children of Immer, one thousand fifty-two.\n'),
	(7262, 12, 2, 38, 'The children of Pashhur, one thousand two hundred forty-seven.\n'),
	(7263, 12, 2, 39, 'The children of Harim, one thousand seventeen.\n'),
	(7264, 12, 2, 40, 'The Levites: the children of Jeshua and Kadmiel, of the children of Hodaviah, seventy-four.\n'),
	(7265, 12, 2, 41, 'The singers: the children of Asaph, one hundred twenty-eight.\n'),
	(7266, 12, 2, 42, 'The children of the gatekeepers: the children of Shallum, the children of Ater, the children of Talmon, the children of Akkub, the children of Hatita, the children of Shobai, in all one hundred thirty-nine.\n'),
	(7267, 12, 2, 43, 'The temple servants: the children of Ziha, the children of Hasupha, the children of Tabbaoth,\n'),
	(7268, 12, 2, 44, 'the children of Keros, the children of Siaha, the children of Padon,\n'),
	(7269, 12, 2, 45, 'the children of Lebanah, the children of Hagabah, the children of Akkub,\n'),
	(7270, 12, 2, 46, 'the children of Hagab, the children of Shamlai, the children of Hanan,\n'),
	(7271, 12, 2, 47, 'the children of Giddel, the children of Gahar, the children of Reaiah,\n'),
	(7272, 12, 2, 48, 'the children of Rezin, the children of Nekoda, the children of Gazzam,\n'),
	(7273, 12, 2, 49, 'the children of Uzza, the children of Paseah, the children of Besai,\n'),
	(7274, 12, 2, 50, 'the children of Asnah, the children of Meunim, the children of Nephisim,\n'),
	(7275, 12, 2, 51, 'the children of Bakbuk, the children of Hakupha, the children of Harhur,\n'),
	(7276, 12, 2, 52, 'the children of Bazluth, the children of Mehida, the children of Harsha,\n'),
	(7277, 12, 2, 53, 'the children of Barkos, the children of Sisera, the children of Temah,\n'),
	(7278, 12, 2, 54, 'the children of Neziah, the children of Hatipha.\n'),
	(7279, 12, 2, 55, 'The children of Solomon’s servants: the children of Sotai, the children of Hassophereth, the children of Peruda,\n'),
	(7280, 12, 2, 56, 'the children of Jaalah, the children of Darkon, the children of Giddel,\n'),
	(7281, 12, 2, 57, 'the children of Shephatiah, the children of Hattil, the children of Pochereth Hazzebaim, the children of Ami.\n'),
	(7282, 12, 2, 58, 'All the temple servants, and the children of Solomon’s servants, were three hundred ninety-two.\n'),
	(7283, 12, 2, 59, 'These were those who went up from Tel Melah, Tel Harsha, Cherub, Addan, and Immer; but they could not show their fathers’ houses, and their offspring, whether they were of Israel:\n'),
	(7284, 12, 2, 60, 'the children of Delaiah, the children of Tobiah, the children of Nekoda, six hundred fifty-two.\n'),
	(7285, 12, 2, 61, 'Of the children of the priests: the children of Habaiah, the children of Hakkoz, and the children of Barzillai, who took a wife of the daughters of Barzillai the Gileadite, and was called after their name.\n'),
	(7286, 12, 2, 62, 'These sought their place among those who were registered by genealogy, but they were not found: therefore were they deemed disqualified and removed from the priesthood.\n'),
	(7287, 12, 2, 63, 'The governor told them that they should not eat of the most holy things until a priest stood up to serve with Urim and with Thummim.\n'),
	(7288, 12, 2, 64, 'The whole assembly together was forty-two thousand three hundred sixty,\n'),
	(7289, 12, 2, 65, 'besides their male servants and their female servants, of whom there were seven thousand three hundred thirty-seven; and they had two hundred singing men and singing women.\n'),
	(7290, 12, 2, 66, 'Their horses were seven hundred thirty-six; their mules, two hundred forty-five;\n'),
	(7291, 12, 2, 67, 'their camels, four hundred thirty-five; their donkeys, six thousand seven hundred twenty.\n'),
	(7292, 12, 2, 68, 'Some of the heads of fathers’ households, when they came to Yahweh’s house which is in Jerusalem, offered willingly for God’s house to set it up in its place.\n'),
	(7293, 12, 2, 69, 'They gave according to their ability into the treasury of the work sixty-one thousand darics of gold, and five thousand minas of silver, and one hundred priests’ garments.\n'),
	(7294, 12, 2, 70, 'So the priests, and the Levites, and some of the people, the singers, the gatekeepers, and the temple servants, lived in their cities, and all Israel in their cities.\n'),
	(7295, 12, 3, 1, 'When the seventh month had come, and the children of Israel were in the cities, the people gathered themselves together as one man to Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7296, 12, 3, 2, 'Then Jeshua the son of Jozadak stood up with his brothers the priests, and Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel and his brothers, and built the altar of the God of Israel, to offer burnt offerings on it, as it is written in the law of Moses the man of God.\n'),
	(7297, 12, 3, 3, 'In spite of their fear because of the peoples of the surrounding lands, they set the altar on its base; and they offered burnt offerings on it to Yahweh, even burnt offerings morning and evening.\n'),
	(7298, 12, 3, 4, 'They kept the feast of tents, as it is written, and offered the daily burnt offerings by number, according to the ordinance, as the duty of every day required;\n'),
	(7299, 12, 3, 5, 'and afterward the continual burnt offering, the offerings of the new moons, of all the set feasts of Yahweh that were consecrated, and of everyone who willingly offered a freewill offering to Yahweh.\n'),
	(7300, 12, 3, 6, 'From the first day of the seventh month, they began to offer burnt offerings to Yahweh; but the foundation of Yahweh’s temple was not yet laid.\n'),
	(7301, 12, 3, 7, 'They also gave money to the masons, and to the carpenters. They also gave food, drink, and oil to the people of Sidon and Tyre, to bring cedar trees from Lebanon to the sea, to Joppa, according to the grant that they had from Cyrus King of Persia.\n'),
	(7302, 12, 3, 8, 'Now in the second year of their coming to God’s house at Jerusalem, in the second month, Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel, and Jeshua the son of Jozadak, and the rest of their brothers the priests and the Levites, and all those who had come out of the captivity to Jerusalem, began the work and appointed the Levites, from twenty years old and upward, to have the oversight of the work of Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(7303, 12, 3, 9, 'Then Jeshua stood with his sons and his brothers, Kadmiel and his sons, the sons of Judah, together, to have the oversight of the workmen in God’s house: the sons of Henadad, with their sons and their brothers the Levites.\n'),
	(7304, 12, 3, 10, 'When the builders laid the foundation of Yahweh’s temple, they set the priests in their clothing with trumpets, with the Levites the sons of Asaph with cymbals, to praise Yahweh, according to the directions of David king of Israel.\n'),
	(7305, 12, 3, 11, 'They sang to one another in praising and giving thanks to Yahweh, “For he is good, for his loving kindness endures forever toward Israel.” All the people shouted with a great shout, when they praised Yahweh, because the foundation of Yahweh’s house had been laid.\n'),
	(7306, 12, 3, 12, 'But many of the priests and Levites and heads of fathers’ households, the old men who had seen the first house, when the foundation of this house was laid before their eyes, wept with a loud voice. Many also shouted aloud for joy,\n'),
	(7307, 12, 3, 13, 'so that the people could not discern the noise of the shout of joy from the noise of the weeping of the people; for the people shouted with a loud shout, and the noise was heard far away.\n'),
	(7308, 12, 4, 1, 'Now when the adversaries of Judah and Benjamin heard that the children of the captivity were building a temple to Yahweh, the God of Israel;\n'),
	(7309, 12, 4, 2, 'they came near to Zerubbabel, and to the heads of fathers’ households, and said to them, “Let us build with you; for we seek your God, as you do; and we have been sacrificing to him since the days of Esar Haddon king of Assyria, who brought us up here.”\n'),
	(7310, 12, 4, 3, 'But Zerubbabel, and Jeshua, and the rest of the heads of fathers’ households of Israel, said to them, “You have nothing to do with us in building a house to our God; but we ourselves together will build to Yahweh, the God of Israel, as king Cyrus the king of Persia has commanded us.”\n'),
	(7311, 12, 4, 4, 'Then the people of the land weakened the hands of the people of Judah, and troubled them in building.\n'),
	(7312, 12, 4, 5, 'They hired counselors against them, to frustrate their purpose, all the days of Cyrus king of Persia, even until the reign of Darius king of Persia.\n'),
	(7313, 12, 4, 6, 'In the reign of Ahasuerus, in the beginning of his reign, they wrote an accusation against the inhabitants of Judah and Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7314, 12, 4, 7, 'In the days of Artaxerxes, Bishlam, Mithredath, Tabeel, and the rest of his companions, wrote to Artaxerxes king of Persia; and the writing of the letter was written in Syrian, and delivered in the Syrian language.\n'),
	(7315, 12, 4, 8, 'Rehum the chancellor and Shimshai the scribe wrote a letter against Jerusalem to Artaxerxes the king as follows,\n'),
	(7316, 12, 4, 9, 'then Rehum the chancellor, Shimshai the scribe, and the rest of their companions, the Dinaites, and the Apharsathchites, the Tarpelites, the Apharsites, the Archevites, the Babylonians, the Shushanchites, the Dehaites, the Elamites,\n'),
	(7317, 12, 4, 10, 'and the rest of the nations whom the great and noble Osnappar brought over, and set in the city of Samaria, and in the rest of the country beyond the River, and so forth, wrote.\n'),
	(7318, 12, 4, 11, 'This is the copy of the letter that they sent:\nTo King Artaxerxes,\nFrom your servants the men beyond the River.\n'),
	(7319, 12, 4, 12, 'Be it known to the king that the Jews who came up from you have come to us to Jerusalem. They are building the rebellious and bad city, and have finished the walls, and repaired the foundations.\n'),
	(7320, 12, 4, 13, 'Be it known now to the king that if this city is built and the walls finished, they will not pay tribute, custom, or toll, and in the end it will be hurtful to the kings.\n'),
	(7321, 12, 4, 14, 'Now because we eat the salt of the palace, and it is not appropriate for us to see the king’s dishonor, therefore we have sent and informed the king,\n'),
	(7322, 12, 4, 15, 'that search may be made in the book of the records of your fathers. You will see in the book of the records, and know that this city is a rebellious city, and hurtful to kings and provinces, and that they have started rebellions within it in the past. That is why this city was destroyed.\n'),
	(7323, 12, 4, 16, 'We inform the king that, if this city is built and the walls finished, then you will have no possession beyond the River.\n'),
	(7324, 12, 4, 17, 'Then the king sent an answer to Rehum the chancellor, and to Shimshai the scribe, and to the rest of their companions who live in Samaria, and in the rest of the country beyond the River:\nPeace.\n'),
	(7325, 12, 4, 18, 'The letter which you sent to us has been plainly read before me.\n'),
	(7326, 12, 4, 19, 'I decreed, and search has been made, and it was found that this city has made insurrection against kings in the past, and that rebellion and revolts have been made in it.\n'),
	(7327, 12, 4, 20, 'There have also been mighty kings over Jerusalem, who have ruled over all the country beyond the River; and tribute, custom, and toll, was paid to them.\n'),
	(7328, 12, 4, 21, 'Make a decree now to cause these men to cease, and that this city not be built, until a decree is made by me.\n'),
	(7329, 12, 4, 22, 'Be careful that you not be slack doing so. Why should damage grow to the hurt of the kings?\n'),
	(7330, 12, 4, 23, 'Then when the copy of king Artaxerxes’ letter was read before Rehum, Shimshai the scribe, and their companions, they went in haste to Jerusalem to the Jews, and made them to cease by force of arms.\n'),
	(7331, 12, 4, 24, 'Then work stopped on God’s house which is at Jerusalem. It stopped until the second year of the reign of Darius king of Persia.\n'),
	(7332, 12, 5, 1, 'Now the prophets, Haggai the prophet and Zechariah the son of Iddo, prophesied to the Jews who were in Judah and Jerusalem. They prophesied to them in the name of the God of Israel.\n'),
	(7333, 12, 5, 2, 'Then Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel, and Jeshua the son of Jozadak rose up and began to build God’s house which is at Jerusalem; and with them were the prophets of God, helping them.\n'),
	(7334, 12, 5, 3, 'At the same time Tattenai, the governor beyond the River came to them, with Shetharbozenai, and their companions, and asked them, “Who gave you a decree to build this house, and to finish this wall?”\n'),
	(7335, 12, 5, 4, 'They also asked for the names of the men were who were making this building.\n'),
	(7336, 12, 5, 5, 'But the eye of their God was on the elders of the Jews, and they did not make them cease, until the matter should come to Darius, and an answer should be returned by letter concerning it.\n'),
	(7337, 12, 5, 6, 'The copy of the letter that Tattenai, the governor beyond the River, and Shetharbozenai, and his companions the Apharsachites, who were beyond the River, sent to Darius the king follows.\n'),
	(7338, 12, 5, 7, 'They sent a letter to him, in which was written:\nTo Darius the king, all peace.\n'),
	(7339, 12, 5, 8, 'Be it known to the king that we went into the province of Judah, to the house of the great God, which is built with great stones, and timber is laid in the walls. This work goes on with diligence and prospers in their hands.\n'),
	(7340, 12, 5, 9, 'Then we asked those elders, and said to them thus, “Who gave you a decree to build this house, and to finish this wall?”\n'),
	(7341, 12, 5, 10, 'We asked them their names also, to inform you that we might write the names of the men who were at their head.\n'),
	(7342, 12, 5, 11, 'Thus they returned us answer, saying, “We are the servants of the God of heaven and earth, and are building the house that was built these many years ago, which a great king of Israel built and finished.\n'),
	(7343, 12, 5, 12, 'But after that our fathers had provoked the God of heaven to wrath, he gave them into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, the Chaldean, who destroyed this house, and carried the people away into Babylon.\n'),
	(7344, 12, 5, 13, 'But in the first year of Cyrus king of Babylon, Cyrus the king made a decree to build this house of God.\n'),
	(7345, 12, 5, 14, 'The gold and silver vessels of God’s house, which Nebuchadnezzar took out of the temple that was in Jerusalem, and brought into the temple of Babylon, those Cyrus the king also took out of the temple of Babylon, and they were delivered to one whose name was Sheshbazzar, whom he had made governor.\n'),
	(7346, 12, 5, 15, 'He said to him, ‘Take these vessels, go, put them in the temple that is in Jerusalem, and let God’s house be built in its place.’\n'),
	(7347, 12, 5, 16, 'Then the same Sheshbazzar came and laid the foundations of God’s house which is in Jerusalem. Since that time even until now has it been in building, and yet it is not completed.\n'),
	(7348, 12, 5, 17, 'Now therefore, if it seems good to the king, let a search be made in the king’s treasure house, which is there at Babylon, whether it is so, that a decree was made of Cyrus the king to build this house of God at Jerusalem; and let the king send his pleasure to us concerning this matter.”\n'),
	(7349, 12, 6, 1, 'Then Darius the king made a decree, and the house of the archives, where the treasures were laid up in Babylon, was searched.\n'),
	(7350, 12, 6, 2, 'A scroll was found at Achmetha, in the palace that is in the province of Media, and in it this was written for a record:\n'),
	(7351, 12, 6, 3, 'In the first year of Cyrus the king, Cyrus the king made a decree: Concerning God’s house at Jerusalem, let the house be built, the place where they offer sacrifices, and let its foundations be strongly laid; with its height sixty cubits, and its width sixty cubits;\n'),
	(7352, 12, 6, 4, 'with three courses of great stones and a course of new timber. Let the expenses be given out of the king’s house.\n'),
	(7353, 12, 6, 5, 'Also let the gold and silver vessels of God’s house, which Nebuchadnezzar took out of the temple which is at Jerusalem, and brought to Babylon, be restored and brought again to the temple which is at Jerusalem, everything to its place. You shall put them in God’s house.\n'),
	(7354, 12, 6, 6, 'Now therefore, Tattenai, governor beyond the River, Shetharbozenai, and your companions the Apharsachites, who are beyond the River, you must stay far from there.\n'),
	(7355, 12, 6, 7, 'Leave the work of this house of God alone; let the governor of the Jews and the elders of the Jews build this house of God in its place.\n'),
	(7356, 12, 6, 8, 'Moreover I make a decree what you shall do for these elders of the Jews for the building of this house of God: that of the king’s goods, even of the tribute beyond the River, expenses must be given with all diligence to these men, that they not be hindered.\n'),
	(7357, 12, 6, 9, 'That which they have need of, including young bulls, rams, and lambs, for burnt offerings to the God of heaven; also wheat, salt, wine, and oil, according to the word of the priests who are at Jerusalem, let it be given them day by day without fail;\n'),
	(7358, 12, 6, 10, 'that they may offer sacrifices of pleasant aroma to the God of heaven, and pray for the life of the king, and of his sons.\n'),
	(7359, 12, 6, 11, 'I have also made a decree that whoever alters this message, let a beam be pulled out from his house, and let him be lifted up and fastened on it; and let his house be made a dunghill for this.\n'),
	(7360, 12, 6, 12, 'May the God who has caused his name to dwell there overthrow all kings and peoples who stretch out their hand to alter the same, to destroy this house of God which is at Jerusalem. I Darius have made a decree. Let it be done with all diligence.\n'),
	(7361, 12, 6, 13, 'Then Tattenai, the governor beyond the River, Shetharbozenai, and their companions did accordingly with all diligence, because Darius the king had sent a decree.\n'),
	(7362, 12, 6, 14, 'The elders of the Jews built and prospered, through the prophesying of Haggai the prophet and Zechariah the son of Iddo. They built and finished it, according to the commandment of the God of Israel, and according to the decree of Cyrus, Darius, and Artaxerxes king of Persia.\n'),
	(7363, 12, 6, 15, 'This house was finished on the third day of the month Adar, which was in the sixth year of the reign of Darius the king.\n'),
	(7364, 12, 6, 16, 'The children of Israel, the priests, the Levites, and the rest of the children of the captivity, kept the dedication of this house of God with joy.\n'),
	(7365, 12, 6, 17, 'They offered at the dedication of this house of God one hundred bulls, two hundred rams, four hundred lambs; and for a sin offering for all Israel, twelve male goats, according to the number of the tribes of Israel.\n'),
	(7366, 12, 6, 18, 'They set the priests in their divisions, and the Levites in their courses, for the service of God, which is at Jerusalem, as it is written in the book of Moses.\n'),
	(7367, 12, 6, 19, 'The children of the captivity kept the Passover on the fourteenth day of the first month.\n'),
	(7368, 12, 6, 20, 'Because the priests and the Levites had purified themselves together, all of them were pure. They killed the Passover for all the children of the captivity, for their brothers the priests, and for themselves.\n'),
	(7369, 12, 6, 21, 'The children of Israel who had returned out of the captivity, and all who had separated themselves to them from the filthiness of the nations of the land, to seek Yahweh, the God of Israel, ate,\n'),
	(7370, 12, 6, 22, 'and kept the feast of unleavened bread seven days with joy; because Yahweh had made them joyful, and had turned the heart of the king of Assyria to them, to strengthen their hands in the work of God, the God of Israel’s house.\n'),
	(7371, 12, 7, 1, 'Now after these things, in the reign of Artaxerxes king of Persia, Ezra the son of Seraiah, the son of Azariah, the son of Hilkiah,\n'),
	(7372, 12, 7, 2, 'the son of Shallum, the son of Zadok, the son of Ahitub,\n'),
	(7373, 12, 7, 3, 'the son of Amariah, the son of Azariah, the son of Meraioth,\n'),
	(7374, 12, 7, 4, 'the son of Zerahiah, the son of Uzzi, the son of Bukki,\n'),
	(7375, 12, 7, 5, 'the son of Abishua, the son of Phinehas, the son of Eleazar, the son of Aaron the chief priest—\n'),
	(7376, 12, 7, 6, 'this Ezra went up from Babylon. He was a skilled scribe in the law of Moses, which Yahweh, the God of Israel, had given; and the king granted him all his request, according to Yahweh his God’s hand on him.\n'),
	(7377, 12, 7, 7, 'Some of the children of Israel, including some of the priests, the Levites, the singers, the gatekeepers, and the temple servants went up to Jerusalem in the seventh year of Artaxerxes the king.\n'),
	(7378, 12, 7, 8, 'He came to Jerusalem in the fifth month, which was in the seventh year of the king.\n'),
	(7379, 12, 7, 9, 'For on the first day of the first month he began to go up from Babylon; and on the first day of the fifth month he came to Jerusalem, according to the good hand of his God on him.\n'),
	(7380, 12, 7, 10, 'For Ezra had set his heart to seek Yahweh’s law, and to do it, and to teach statutes and ordinances in Israel.\n'),
	(7381, 12, 7, 11, 'Now this is the copy of the letter that the king Artaxerxes gave to Ezra the priest, the scribe, even the scribe of the words of Yahweh’s commandments, and of his statutes to Israel:\n'),
	(7382, 12, 7, 12, 'Artaxerxes, king of kings,\nTo Ezra the priest, the scribe of the law of the perfect God of heaven.\nNow\n'),
	(7383, 12, 7, 13, 'I make a decree, that all those of the people of Israel, and their priests and the Levites, in my realm, who intend of their own free will to go to Jerusalem, go with you.\n'),
	(7384, 12, 7, 14, 'Because you are sent by the king and his seven counselors, to inquire concerning Judah and Jerusalem, according to the law of your God which is in your hand,\n'),
	(7385, 12, 7, 15, 'and to carry the silver and gold, which the king and his counselors have freely offered to the God of Israel, whose habitation is in Jerusalem,\n'),
	(7386, 12, 7, 16, 'and all the silver and gold that you will find in all the province of Babylon, with the freewill offering of the people, and of the priests, offering willingly for the house of their God which is in Jerusalem;\n'),
	(7387, 12, 7, 17, 'therefore you shall with all diligence buy with this money bulls, rams, lambs, with their meal offerings and their drink offerings, and shall offer them on the altar of the house of your God which is in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7388, 12, 7, 18, 'Whatever seems good to you and to your brothers to do with the rest of the silver and the gold, do that according to the will of your God.\n'),
	(7389, 12, 7, 19, 'The vessels that are given to you for the service of the house of your God, deliver before the God of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7390, 12, 7, 20, 'Whatever more will be needed for the house of your God, which you may have occasion to give, give it out of the king’s treasure house.\n'),
	(7391, 12, 7, 21, 'I, even I Artaxerxes the king, make a decree to all the treasurers who are beyond the River, that whatever Ezra the priest, the scribe of the law of the God of heaven, requires of you, it shall be done with all diligence,\n'),
	(7392, 12, 7, 22, 'up to one hundred talents of silver, and to one hundred cors of wheat, and to one hundred baths of wine, and to one hundred baths of oil, and salt without prescribing how much.\n'),
	(7393, 12, 7, 23, 'Whatever is commanded by the God of heaven, let it be done exactly for the house of the God of heaven; for why should there be wrath against the realm of the king and his sons?\n'),
	(7394, 12, 7, 24, 'Also we inform you that it shall not be lawful to impose tribute, custom, or toll, on any of the priests, Levites, singers, gatekeepers, temple servants, or laborers of this house of God.\n'),
	(7395, 12, 7, 25, 'You, Ezra, according to the wisdom of your God that is in your hand, appoint magistrates and judges, who may judge all the people who are beyond the River, who all know the laws of your God; and teach him who doesn’t know them.\n'),
	(7396, 12, 7, 26, 'Whoever will not do the law of your God and the law of the king, let judgment be executed on him with all diligence, whether it is to death, or to banishment, or to confiscation of goods, or to imprisonment.\n'),
	(7397, 12, 7, 27, 'Blessed be Yahweh, the God of our fathers, who has put such a thing as this in the king’s heart, to beautify Yahweh’s house which is in Jerusalem;\n'),
	(7398, 12, 7, 28, 'and has extended loving kindness to me before the king and his counselors, and before all the king’s mighty princes. I was strengthened according to Yahweh my God’s hand on me, and I gathered together chief men out of Israel to go up with me.\n'),
	(7399, 12, 8, 1, 'Now these are the heads of their fathers’ households, and this is the genealogy of those who went up with me from Babylon, in the reign of Artaxerxes the king:\n'),
	(7400, 12, 8, 2, 'Of the sons of Phinehas, Gershom.\nOf the sons of Ithamar, Daniel.\nOf the sons of David, Hattush.\n'),
	(7401, 12, 8, 3, 'Of the sons of Shecaniah, of the sons of Parosh, Zechariah; and with him were listed by genealogy of the males one hundred fifty.\n'),
	(7402, 12, 8, 4, 'Of the sons of Pahathmoab, Eliehoenai the son of Zerahiah; and with him two hundred males.\n'),
	(7403, 12, 8, 5, 'Of the sons of Shecaniah, the son of Jahaziel; and with him three hundred males.\n'),
	(7404, 12, 8, 6, 'Of the sons of Adin, Ebed the son of Jonathan; and with him fifty males.\n'),
	(7405, 12, 8, 7, 'Of the sons of Elam, Jeshaiah the son of Athaliah; and with him seventy males.\n'),
	(7406, 12, 8, 8, 'Of the sons of Shephatiah, Zebadiah the son of Michael; and with him eighty males.\n'),
	(7407, 12, 8, 9, 'Of the sons of Joab, Obadiah the son of Jehiel; and with him two hundred eighteen males.\n'),
	(7408, 12, 8, 10, 'Of the sons of Shelomith, the son of Josiphiah; and with him one hundred sixty males.\n'),
	(7409, 12, 8, 11, 'Of the sons of Bebai, Zechariah the son of Bebai; and with him twenty-eight males.\n'),
	(7410, 12, 8, 12, 'Of the sons of Azgad, Johanan the son of Hakkatan; and with him one hundred ten males.\n'),
	(7411, 12, 8, 13, 'Of the sons of Adonikam, who were the last; and these are their names: Eliphelet, Jeuel, and Shemaiah; and with them sixty males.\n'),
	(7412, 12, 8, 14, 'Of the sons of Bigvai, Uthai and Zabbud; and with them seventy males.\n'),
	(7413, 12, 8, 15, 'I gathered them together to the river that runs to Ahava; and there we encamped three days: and I looked around at the people the priests, and found there were none of the sons of Levi.\n'),
	(7414, 12, 8, 16, 'Then sent I for Eliezer, for Ariel, for Shemaiah, for Elnathan, for Jarib, for Elnathan, for Nathan, for Zechariah, and for Meshullam, chief men; also for Joiarib and for Elnathan, who were teachers.\n'),
	(7415, 12, 8, 17, 'I sent them out to Iddo the chief at the place Casiphia; and I told them what they should tell Iddo, and his brothers the temple servants, at the place Casiphia, that they should bring to us ministers for the house of our God.\n'),
	(7416, 12, 8, 18, 'According to the good hand of our God on us they brought us a man of discretion, of the sons of Mahli, the son of Levi, the son of Israel; and Sherebiah, with his sons and his brothers, eighteen;\n'),
	(7417, 12, 8, 19, 'and Hashabiah, and with him Jeshaiah of the sons of Merari, his brothers and their sons, twenty;\n'),
	(7418, 12, 8, 20, 'and of the temple servants, whom David and the princes had given for the service of the Levites, two hundred twenty temple servants. All of them were mentioned by name.\n'),
	(7419, 12, 8, 21, 'Then I proclaimed a fast there, at the river Ahava, that we might humble ourselves before our God, to seek from him a straight way for us, and for our little ones, and for all our possessions.\n'),
	(7420, 12, 8, 22, 'For I was ashamed to ask of the king a band of soldiers and horsemen to help us against the enemy on the way, because we had spoken to the king, saying, “The hand of our God is on all those who seek him, for good; but his power and his wrath is against all those who forsake him.”\n'),
	(7421, 12, 8, 23, 'So we fasted and begged our God for this: and he granted our request.\n'),
	(7422, 12, 8, 24, 'Then I set apart twelve of the chiefs of the priests, even Sherebiah, Hashabiah, and ten of their brothers with them,\n'),
	(7423, 12, 8, 25, 'and weighed to them the silver, the gold, and the vessels, even the offering for the house of our God, which the king, his counselors, his princes, and all Israel there present, had offered.\n'),
	(7424, 12, 8, 26, 'I weighed into their hand six hundred fifty talents of silver, one hundred talents of silver vessels; one hundred talents of gold,\n'),
	(7425, 12, 8, 27, 'twenty bowls of gold weighing one thousand darics; and two vessels of fine bright brass, precious as gold.\n'),
	(7426, 12, 8, 28, 'I said to them, “You are holy to Yahweh, and the vessels are holy. The silver and the gold are a freewill offering to Yahweh, the God of your fathers.\n'),
	(7427, 12, 8, 29, 'Watch and keep them, until you weigh them before the chiefs of the priests and the Levites, and the princes of the fathers’ households of Israel, at Jerusalem, in the rooms of Yahweh’s house.”\n'),
	(7428, 12, 8, 30, 'So the priests and the Levites received the weight of the silver and the gold, and the vessels, to bring them to Jerusalem to the house of our God.\n'),
	(7429, 12, 8, 31, 'Then we departed from the river Ahava on the twelfth day of the first month, to go to Jerusalem. The hand of our God was on us, and he delivered us from the hand of the enemy and the bandit by the way.\n'),
	(7430, 12, 8, 32, 'We came to Jerusalem, and stayed there three days.\n'),
	(7431, 12, 8, 33, 'On the fourth day the silver and the gold and the vessels were weighed in the house of our God into the hand of Meremoth the son of Uriah the priest; and with him was Eleazar the son of Phinehas; and with them was Jozabad the son of Jeshua, and Noadiah the son of Binnui, the Levite;\n'),
	(7432, 12, 8, 34, 'everything by number and by weight; and all the weight was written at that time.\n'),
	(7433, 12, 8, 35, 'The children of the captivity, who had come out of exile, offered burnt offerings to the God of Israel, twelve bulls for all Israel, ninety-six rams, seventy-seven lambs, and twelve male goats for a sin offering. All this was a burnt offering to Yahweh.\n'),
	(7434, 12, 8, 36, 'They delivered the king’s commissions to the king’s satraps, and to the governors beyond the River. So they supported the people and God’s house.\n'),
	(7435, 12, 9, 1, 'Now when these things were done, the princes came near to me, saying, “The people of Israel, the priests, and the Levites, have not separated themselves from the peoples of the lands, following their abominations, even those of the Canaanites, the Hittites, the Perizzites, the Jebusites, the Ammonites, the Moabites, the Egyptians, and the Amorites.\n'),
	(7436, 12, 9, 2, 'For they have taken of their daughters for themselves and for their sons, so that the holy offspring have mixed themselves with the peoples of the lands. Yes, the hand of the princes and rulers has been chief in this trespass.”\n'),
	(7437, 12, 9, 3, 'When I heard this thing, I tore my garment and my robe, and pulled the hair out of my head and of my beard, and sat down confounded.\n'),
	(7438, 12, 9, 4, 'Then everyone who trembled at the words of the God of Israel were assembled to me, because of their trespass of the captivity; and I sat confounded until the evening offering.\n'),
	(7439, 12, 9, 5, 'At the evening offering I arose up from my humiliation, even with my garment and my robe torn; and I fell on my knees, and spread out my hands to Yahweh my God;\n'),
	(7440, 12, 9, 6, 'and I said, “My God, I am ashamed and blush to lift up my face to you, my God; for our iniquities have increased over our head, and our guiltiness has grown up to the heavens.\n'),
	(7441, 12, 9, 7, 'Since the days of our fathers we have been exceeding guilty to this day; and for our iniquities we, our kings, and our priests, have been delivered into the hand of the kings of the lands, to the sword, to captivity, to plunder, and to confusion of face, as it is this day.\n'),
	(7442, 12, 9, 8, 'Now for a little moment grace has been shown from Yahweh our God, to leave us a remnant to escape, and to give us a nail in his holy place, that our God may lighten our eyes, and revived us a little in our bondage.\n'),
	(7443, 12, 9, 9, 'For we are bondservants; yet our God has not forsaken us in our bondage, but has extended loving kindness to us in the sight of the kings of Persia, to revive us, to set up the house of our God, and to repair its ruins, and to give us a wall in Judah and in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7444, 12, 9, 10, '“Now, our God, what shall we say after this? For we have forsaken your commandments,\n'),
	(7445, 12, 9, 11, 'which you have commanded by your servants the prophets, saying, ‘The land, to which you go to possess it, is an unclean land through the uncleanness of the peoples of the lands, through their abominations, which have filled it from one end to another with their filthiness.\n'),
	(7446, 12, 9, 12, 'Now therefore don’t give your daughters to their sons. Don’t take their daughters to your sons, nor seek their peace or their prosperity forever; that you may be strong, and eat the good of the land, and leave it for an inheritance to your children forever.’\n'),
	(7447, 12, 9, 13, '“After all that has come on us for our evil deeds, and for our great guilt, since you, our God, have punished us less than our iniquities deserve, and have given us such a remnant,\n'),
	(7448, 12, 9, 14, 'shall we again break your commandments, and join in affinity with the peoples that do these abominations? Wouldn’t you be angry with us until you had consumed us, so that there would be no remnant, nor any to escape?\n'),
	(7449, 12, 9, 15, 'Yahweh, the God of Israel, you are righteous; for we are left a remnant that has escaped, as it is today. Behold, we are before you in our guiltiness; for no one can stand before you because of this.”\n'),
	(7450, 12, 10, 1, 'Now while Ezra prayed and made confession, weeping and casting himself down before God’s house, there was gathered together to him out of Israel a very great assembly of men and women and children; for the people wept very bitterly.\n'),
	(7451, 12, 10, 2, 'Shecaniah the son of Jehiel, one of the sons of Elam, answered Ezra, “We have trespassed against our God, and have married foreign women of the peoples of the land. Yet now there is hope for Israel concerning this thing.\n'),
	(7452, 12, 10, 3, 'Now therefore let us make a covenant with our God to put away all the wives, and those who as are born of them, according to the counsel of my lord, and of those who tremble at the commandment of our God. Let it be done according to the law.\n'),
	(7453, 12, 10, 4, 'Arise; for the matter belongs to you, and we are with you. Be courageous, and do it.”\n'),
	(7454, 12, 10, 5, 'Then Ezra arose, and made the chiefs of the priests, the Levites, and all Israel, to swear that they would do according to this word. So they swore.\n'),
	(7455, 12, 10, 6, 'Then Ezra rose up from before God’s house, and went into the room of Jehohanan the son of Eliashib. When he came there, he ate no bread, nor drank water; for he mourned because of their trespass of the captivity.\n'),
	(7456, 12, 10, 7, 'They made a proclamation throughout Judah and Jerusalem to all the children of the captivity, that they should gather themselves together to Jerusalem;\n'),
	(7457, 12, 10, 8, 'and that whoever didn’t come within three days, according to the counsel of the princes and the elders, all his possessions should be forfeited, and himself separated from the assembly of the captivity.\n'),
	(7458, 12, 10, 9, 'Then all the men of Judah and Benjamin gathered themselves together to Jerusalem within the three days. It was the ninth month, on the twentieth day of the month; and all the people sat in the wide place in front of God’s house, trembling because of this matter, and because of the great rain.\n'),
	(7459, 12, 10, 10, 'Ezra the priest stood up and said to them, “You have trespassed, and have married foreign women, to increase the guilt of Israel.\n'),
	(7460, 12, 10, 11, 'Now therefore make confession to Yahweh, the God of your fathers, and do his pleasure; and separate yourselves from the peoples of the land, and from the foreign women.”\n'),
	(7461, 12, 10, 12, 'Then all the assembly answered with a loud voice, “As you have said concerning us, so must we do.\n'),
	(7462, 12, 10, 13, 'But the people are many, and it is a time of much rain, and we are not able to stand outside. This is not a work of one day or two, for we have greatly transgressed in this matter.\n'),
	(7463, 12, 10, 14, 'Now let our princes be appointed for all the assembly, and let all those who are in our cities who have married foreign women come at appointed times, and with them the elders of every city, and its judges, until the fierce wrath of our God is turned from us, until this matter is resolved.”\n'),
	(7464, 12, 10, 15, 'Only Jonathan the son of Asahel and Jahzeiah the son of Tikvah stood up against this; and Meshullam and Shabbethai the Levite helped them.\n'),
	(7465, 12, 10, 16, 'The children of the captivity did so. Ezra the priest, with certain heads of fathers’ households, after their fathers’ houses, and all of them by their names, were set apart; and they sat down in the first day of the tenth month to examine the matter.\n'),
	(7466, 12, 10, 17, 'They finished with all the men who had married foreign women by the first day of the first month.\n'),
	(7467, 12, 10, 18, 'Among the sons of the priests there were found who had married foreign women:\nof the sons of Jeshua, the son of Jozadak, and his brothers, Maaseiah, and Eliezer, and Jarib, and Gedaliah.\n'),
	(7468, 12, 10, 19, 'They gave their hand that they would put away their wives; and being guilty, they offered a ram of the flock for their guilt.\n'),
	(7469, 12, 10, 20, 'Of the sons of Immer: Hanani and Zebadiah.\n'),
	(7470, 12, 10, 21, 'Of the sons of Harim: Maaseiah, and Elijah, and Shemaiah, and Jehiel, and Uzziah.\n'),
	(7471, 12, 10, 22, 'Of the sons of Pashhur: Elioenai, Maaseiah, Ishmael, Nethanel, Jozabad, and Elasah.\n'),
	(7472, 12, 10, 23, 'Of the Levites: Jozabad, and Shimei, and Kelaiah (also called Kelita), Pethahiah, Judah, and Eliezer.\n'),
	(7473, 12, 10, 24, 'Of the singers: Eliashib. Of the gatekeepers: Shallum, and Telem, and Uri.\n'),
	(7474, 12, 10, 25, 'Of Israel: Of the sons of Parosh: Ramiah, and Izziah, and Malchijah, and Mijamin, and Eleazar, and Malchijah, and Benaiah.\n'),
	(7475, 12, 10, 26, 'Of the sons of Elam: Mattaniah, Zechariah, and Jehiel, and Abdi, and Jeremoth, and Elijah.\n'),
	(7476, 12, 10, 27, 'Of the sons of Zattu: Elioenai, Eliashib, Mattaniah, and Jeremoth, and Zabad, and Aziza.\n'),
	(7477, 12, 10, 28, 'Of the sons of Bebai: Jehohanan, Hananiah, Zabbai, Athlai.\n'),
	(7478, 12, 10, 29, 'Of the sons of Bani: Meshullam, Malluch, and Adaiah, Jashub, and Sheal, Jeremoth.\n'),
	(7479, 12, 10, 30, 'Of the sons of Pahathmoab: Adna, and Chelal, Benaiah, Maaseiah, Mattaniah, Bezalel, and Binnui, and Manasseh.\n'),
	(7480, 12, 10, 31, 'Of the sons of Harim: Eliezer, Isshijah, Malchijah, Shemaiah, Shimeon,\n'),
	(7481, 12, 10, 32, 'Benjamin, Malluch, Shemariah.\n'),
	(7482, 12, 10, 33, 'Of the sons of Hashum: Mattenai, Mattattah, Zabad, Eliphelet, Jeremai, Manasseh, Shimei.\n'),
	(7483, 12, 10, 34, 'Of the sons of Bani: Maadai, Amram, and Uel,\n'),
	(7484, 12, 10, 35, 'Benaiah, Bedeiah, Cheluhi,\n'),
	(7485, 12, 10, 36, 'Vaniah, Meremoth, Eliashib,\n'),
	(7486, 12, 10, 37, 'Mattaniah, Mattenai, and Jaasu,\n'),
	(7487, 12, 10, 38, 'and Bani, and Binnui, Shimei,\n'),
	(7488, 12, 10, 39, 'and Shelemiah, and Nathan, and Adaiah,\n'),
	(7489, 12, 10, 40, 'Machnadebai, Shashai, Sharai,\n'),
	(7490, 12, 10, 41, 'Azarel, and Shelemiah, Shemariah,\n'),
	(7491, 12, 10, 42, 'Shallum, Amariah, Joseph.\n'),
	(7492, 12, 10, 43, 'Of the sons of Nebo: Jeiel, Mattithiah, Zabad, Zebina, Iddo, and Joel, Benaiah.\n'),
	(7493, 12, 10, 44, 'All these had taken foreign wives; and some of them had wives by whom they had children.\n'),
	(7494, 13, 1, 1, 'The words of Nehemiah the son of Hacaliah.\nNow in the month Chislev, in the twentieth year, as I was in Shushan the palace,\n'),
	(7495, 13, 1, 2, 'Hanani, one of my brothers, came, he and certain men out of Judah; and I asked them about the Jews who had escaped, who were left of the captivity, and concerning Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7496, 13, 1, 3, 'They said to me, “The remnant who are left of the captivity there in the province are in great affliction and reproach. The wall of Jerusalem is also broken down, and its gates are burned with fire.”\n'),
	(7497, 13, 1, 4, 'When I heard these words, I sat down and wept, and mourned several days; and I fasted and prayed before the God of heaven,\n'),
	(7498, 13, 1, 5, 'and said, “I beg you, Yahweh, the God of heaven, the great and awesome God, who keeps covenant and loving kindness with those who love him and keep his commandments:\n'),
	(7499, 13, 1, 6, 'Let your ear now be attentive, and your eyes open, that you may listen to the prayer of your servant, which I pray before you at this time, day and night, for the children of Israel your servants, while I confess the sins of the children of Israel, which we have sinned against you. Yes, I and my father’s house have sinned.\n'),
	(7500, 13, 1, 7, 'We have dealt very corruptly against you, and have not kept the commandments, nor the statutes, nor the ordinances, which you commanded your servant Moses.\n'),
	(7501, 13, 1, 8, '“Remember, I beg you, the word that you commanded your servant Moses, saying, ‘If you trespass, I will scatter you among the peoples;\n'),
	(7502, 13, 1, 9, 'but if you return to me, and keep my commandments and do them, though your outcasts were in the uttermost part of the heavens, yet I will gather them from there, and will bring them to the place that I have chosen, to cause my name to dwell there.’\n'),
	(7503, 13, 1, 10, '“Now these are your servants and your people, whom you have redeemed by your great power, and by your strong hand.\n'),
	(7504, 13, 1, 11, 'Lord, I beg you, let your ear be attentive now to the prayer of your servant, and to the prayer of your servants, who delight to fear your name; and please prosper your servant today, and grant him mercy in the sight of this man.”\nNow I was cup bearer to the king.\n'),
	(7505, 13, 2, 1, 'In the month Nisan, in the twentieth year of Artaxerxes the king, when wine was before him, I picked up the wine, and gave it to the king. Now I had not been sad before in his presence.\n'),
	(7506, 13, 2, 2, 'The king said to me, “Why is your face sad, since you are not sick? This is nothing else but sorrow of heart.”\nThen I was very much afraid.\n'),
	(7507, 13, 2, 3, 'I said to the king, “Let the king live forever! Why shouldn’t my face be sad, when the city, the place of my fathers’ tombs, lies waste, and its gates have been consumed with fire?”\n'),
	(7508, 13, 2, 4, 'Then the king said to me, “What is your request?”\nSo I prayed to the God of heaven.\n'),
	(7509, 13, 2, 5, 'I said to the king, “If it pleases the king, and if your servant has found favor in your sight, that you would send me to Judah, to the city of my fathers’ tombs, that I may build it.”\n'),
	(7510, 13, 2, 6, 'The king said to me (the queen was also sitting by him), “How long will your journey be? When will you return?”\nSo it pleased the king to send me, and I set a time for him.\n'),
	(7511, 13, 2, 7, 'Moreover I said to the king, “If it pleases the king, let letters be given me to the governors beyond the River, that they may let me pass through until I come to Judah;\n'),
	(7512, 13, 2, 8, 'and a letter to Asaph the keeper of the king’s forest, that he may give me timber to make beams for the gates of the citadel by the temple, for the wall of the city, and for the house that I will occupy.”\nThe king granted my requests, because of the good hand of my God on me.\n'),
	(7513, 13, 2, 9, 'Then I came to the governors beyond the River, and gave them the king’s letters. Now the king had sent captains of the army and horsemen with me.\n'),
	(7514, 13, 2, 10, 'When Sanballat the Horonite, and Tobiah the servant, the Ammonite, heard of it, it grieved them exceedingly, because a man had come to seek the welfare of the children of Israel.\n'),
	(7515, 13, 2, 11, 'So I came to Jerusalem, and was there three days.\n'),
	(7516, 13, 2, 12, 'I arose in the night, I and a few men with me. I didn’t tell anyone what my God put into my heart to do for Jerusalem. There wasn’t any animal with me, except the animal that I rode on.\n'),
	(7517, 13, 2, 13, 'I went out by night by the valley gate, even toward the jackal’s well, then to the dung gate, and inspected the walls of Jerusalem, which were broken down, and its gates were consumed with fire.\n'),
	(7518, 13, 2, 14, 'Then I went on to the spring gate and to the king’s pool, but there was no place for the animal that was under me to pass.\n'),
	(7519, 13, 2, 15, 'Then went I up in the night by the brook, and inspected the wall; and I turned back, and entered by the valley gate, and so returned.\n'),
	(7520, 13, 2, 16, 'The rulers didn’t know where I went, or what I did. I had not as yet told it to the Jews, nor to the priests, nor to the nobles, nor to the rulers, nor to the rest who did the work.\n'),
	(7521, 13, 2, 17, 'Then I said to them, “You see the bad situation that we are in, how Jerusalem lies waste, and its gates are burned with fire. Come, let us build up the wall of Jerusalem, that we won’t be disgraced.”\n'),
	(7522, 13, 2, 18, 'I told them of the hand of my God which was good on me, as also of the king’s words that he had spoken to me.\nThey said, “Let’s rise up and build.” So they strengthened their hands for the good work.\n'),
	(7523, 13, 2, 19, 'But when Sanballat the Horonite, Tobiah the Ammontite servant, and Geshem the Arabian, heard it, they ridiculed us, and despised us, and said, “What is this thing that you are doing? Will you rebel against the king?”\n'),
	(7524, 13, 2, 20, 'Then I answered them, and said to them, “The God of heaven will prosper us. Therefore we, his servants, will arise and build; but you have no portion, nor right, nor memorial, in Jerusalem.”\n'),
	(7525, 13, 3, 1, 'Then Eliashib the high priest rose up with his brothers the priests, and they built the sheep gate. They sanctified it, and set up its doors. They sanctified it even to the tower of Hammeah, to the tower of Hananel.\n'),
	(7526, 13, 3, 2, 'Next to him the men of Jericho built. Next to them Zaccur the son of Imri built.\n'),
	(7527, 13, 3, 3, 'The sons of Hassenaah built the fish gate. They laid its beams, and set up its doors, its bolts, and its bars.\n'),
	(7528, 13, 3, 4, 'Next to them, Meremoth the son of Uriah, the son of Hakkoz made repairs. Next to them, Meshullam the son of Berechiah, the son of Meshezabel made repairs. Next to them, Zadok the son of Baana made repairs.\n'),
	(7529, 13, 3, 5, 'Next to them, the Tekoites made repairs; but their nobles didn’t put their necks to the Lord’s work.\n'),
	(7530, 13, 3, 6, 'Joiada the son of Paseah and Meshullam the son of Besodeiah repaired the old gate. They laid its beams, and set up its doors, and its bolts, and its bars.\n'),
	(7531, 13, 3, 7, 'Next to them, Melatiah the Gibeonite, and Jadon the Meronothite, the men of Gibeon and of Mizpah, repaired the residence of the governor beyond the River.\n'),
	(7532, 13, 3, 8, 'Next to him, Uzziel the son of Harhaiah, goldsmiths, made repairs. Next to him, Hananiah, one of the perfumers, made repairs, and they fortified Jerusalem even to the wide wall.\n'),
	(7533, 13, 3, 9, 'Next to them, Rephaiah the son of Hur, the ruler of half the district of Jerusalem, made repairs.\n'),
	(7534, 13, 3, 10, 'Next to them, Jedaiah the son of Harumaph made repairs across from his house. Next to him, Hattush the son of Hashabneiah made repairs.\n'),
	(7535, 13, 3, 11, 'Malchijah the son of Harim, and Hasshub the son of Pahathmoab, repaired another portion, and the tower of the furnaces.\n'),
	(7536, 13, 3, 12, 'Next to him, Shallum the son of Hallohesh, the ruler of half the district of Jerusalem, he and his daughters, made repairs.\n'),
	(7537, 13, 3, 13, 'Hanun and the inhabitants of Zanoah repaired the valley gate. They built it, and set up its doors, its bolts, and its bars, and one thousand cubits of the wall to the dung gate.\n'),
	(7538, 13, 3, 14, 'Malchijah the son of Rechab, the ruler of the district of Beth Haccherem repaired the dung gate. He built it, and set up its doors, its bolts, and its bars.\n'),
	(7539, 13, 3, 15, 'Shallun the son of Colhozeh, the ruler of the district of Mizpah repaired the spring gate. He built it, and covered it, and set up its doors, its bolts, and its bars, and the wall of the pool of Shelah by the king’s garden, even to the stairs that go down from David’s city.\n'),
	(7540, 13, 3, 16, 'After him, Nehemiah the son of Azbuk, the ruler of half the district of Beth Zur, made repairs to the place opposite the tombs of David, and to the pool that was made, and to the house of the mighty men.\n'),
	(7541, 13, 3, 17, 'After him, the Levites, Rehum the son of Bani made repairs. Next to him, Hashabiah, the ruler of half the district of Keilah, made repairs for his district.\n'),
	(7542, 13, 3, 18, 'After him, their brothers, Bavvai the son of Henadad, the ruler of half the district of Keilah made repairs.\n'),
	(7543, 13, 3, 19, 'Next to him, Ezer the son of Jeshua, the ruler of Mizpah, repaired another portion, across from the ascent to the armory at the turning of the wall.\n'),
	(7544, 13, 3, 20, 'After him, Baruch the son of Zabbai earnestly repaired another portion, from the turning of the wall to the door of the house of Eliashib the high priest.\n'),
	(7545, 13, 3, 21, 'After him, Meremoth the son of Uriah the son of Hakkoz repaired another portion, from the door of the house of Eliashib even to the end of the house of Eliashib.\n'),
	(7546, 13, 3, 22, 'After him, the priests, the men of the Plain made repairs.\n'),
	(7547, 13, 3, 23, 'After them, Benjamin and Hasshub made repairs across from their house. After them, Azariah the son of Maaseiah the son of Ananiah made repairs beside his own house.\n'),
	(7548, 13, 3, 24, 'After him, Binnui the son of Henadad repaired another portion, from the house of Azariah to the turning of the wall, and to the corner.\n'),
	(7549, 13, 3, 25, 'Palal the son of Uzai made repairs opposite the turning of the wall, and the tower that stands out from the upper house of the king, which is by the court of the guard. After him Pedaiah the son of Parosh made repairs.\n'),
	(7550, 13, 3, 26, '(Now the temple servants lived in Ophel, to the place over against the water gate toward the east, and the tower that stands out.)\n'),
	(7551, 13, 3, 27, 'After him the Tekoites repaired another portion, over against the great tower that stands out, and to the wall of Ophel.\n'),
	(7552, 13, 3, 28, 'Above the horse gate, the priests made repairs, everyone across from his own house.\n'),
	(7553, 13, 3, 29, 'After them, Zadok the son of Immer made repairs across from his own house. After him, Shemaiah the son of Shecaniah, the keeper of the east gate made repairs.\n'),
	(7554, 13, 3, 30, 'After him, Hananiah the son of Shelemiah, and Hanun the sixth son of Zalaph, repaired another portion. After him, Meshullam the son of Berechiah made repairs across from his room.\n'),
	(7555, 13, 3, 31, 'After him, Malchijah, one of the goldsmiths to the house of the temple servants, and of the merchants, made repairs opposite the gate of Hammiphkad, and to the ascent of the corner.\n'),
	(7556, 13, 3, 32, 'Between the ascent of the corner and the sheep gate, the goldsmiths and the merchants made repairs.\n'),
	(7557, 13, 4, 1, 'But when Sanballat heard that we were building the wall, he was angry, and was very indignant, and mocked the Jews.\n'),
	(7558, 13, 4, 2, 'He spoke before his brothers and the army of Samaria, and said, “What are these feeble Jews doing? Will they fortify themselves? Will they sacrifice? Will they finish in a day? Will they revive the stones out of the heaps of rubbish, since they are burned?”\n'),
	(7559, 13, 4, 3, 'Now Tobiah the Ammonite was by him, and he said, “What they are building, if a fox climbed up it, he would break down their stone wall.”\n'),
	(7560, 13, 4, 4, '“Hear, our God; for we are despised; and turn back their reproach on their own head, give them up for a plunder in a land of captivity;\n'),
	(7561, 13, 4, 5, 'don’t cover their iniquity, and don’t let their sin be blotted out from before you; for they have insulted the builders.”\n'),
	(7562, 13, 4, 6, 'So we built the wall; and all the wall was joined together to half its height: for the people had a mind to work.\n'),
	(7563, 13, 4, 7, 'But when Sanballat, Tobiah, the Arabians, the Ammonites, and the Ashdodites heard that the repairing of the walls of Jerusalem went forward, and that the breaches began to be filled, they were very angry;\n'),
	(7564, 13, 4, 8, 'and they all conspired together to come and fight against Jerusalem, and to cause confusion among us.\n'),
	(7565, 13, 4, 9, 'But we made our prayer to our God, and set a watch against them day and night, because of them.\n'),
	(7566, 13, 4, 10, 'Judah said, “The strength of the bearers of burdens is fading, and there is much rubble; so that we are not able to build the wall.”\n'),
	(7567, 13, 4, 11, 'Our adversaries said, “They will not know or see, until we come in among them and kill them, and cause the work to cease.”\n'),
	(7568, 13, 4, 12, 'When the Jews who lived by them came, they said to us ten times from all places, “Wherever you turn, they will attack us.”\n'),
	(7569, 13, 4, 13, 'Therefore I set guards in the lowest parts of the space behind the wall, in the open places. I set the people by family groups with their swords, their spears, and their bows.\n'),
	(7570, 13, 4, 14, 'I looked, and rose up, and said to the nobles, to the rulers, and to the rest of the people, “Don’t be afraid of them! Remember the Lord, who is great and awesome, and fight for your brothers, your sons, your daughters, your wives, and your houses.”\n'),
	(7571, 13, 4, 15, 'When our enemies heard that it was known to us, and God had brought their counsel to nothing, all of us returned to the wall, everyone to his work.\n'),
	(7572, 13, 4, 16, 'From that time forth, half of my servants did the work, and half of them held the spears, the shields, the bows, and the coats of mail; and the rulers were behind all the house of Judah.\n'),
	(7573, 13, 4, 17, 'Those who built the wall, and those who bore burdens loaded themselves; everyone with one of his hands did the work, and with the other held his weapon.\n'),
	(7574, 13, 4, 18, 'Among the builders, everyone wore his sword at his side, and so built. He who sounded the trumpet was by me.\n'),
	(7575, 13, 4, 19, 'I said to the nobles, and to the rulers and to the rest of the people, “The work is great and large, and we are separated on the wall, far from one another.\n'),
	(7576, 13, 4, 20, 'Wherever you hear the sound of the trumpet, rally there to us. Our God will fight for us.”\n'),
	(7577, 13, 4, 21, 'So we did the work. Half of the people held the spears from the rising of the morning until the stars appeared.\n'),
	(7578, 13, 4, 22, 'Likewise at the same time said I to the people, “Let everyone with his servant lodge within Jerusalem, that in the night they may be a guard to us, and may labor in the day.”\n'),
	(7579, 13, 4, 23, 'So neither I, nor my brothers, nor my servants, nor the men of the guard who followed me, none of us took off our clothes. Everyone took his weapon to the water.\n'),
	(7580, 13, 5, 1, 'Then there arose a great cry of the people and of their wives against their brothers the Jews.\n'),
	(7581, 13, 5, 2, 'For there were that said, “We, our sons and our daughters, are many. Let us get grain, that we may eat and live.”\n'),
	(7582, 13, 5, 3, 'There were also some that said, “We are mortgaging our fields, and our vineyards, and our houses. Let us get grain, because of the famine.”\n'),
	(7583, 13, 5, 4, 'There were also some who said, “We have borrowed money for the king’s tribute using our fields and our vineyards as collateral.\n'),
	(7584, 13, 5, 5, 'Yet now our flesh is as the flesh of our brothers, our children as their children. Behold, we bring our sons and our daughters into bondage to be servants, and some of our daughters have been brought into bondage. It is also not in our power to help it, because other men have our fields and our vineyards.”\n'),
	(7585, 13, 5, 6, 'I was very angry when I heard their cry and these words.\n'),
	(7586, 13, 5, 7, 'Then I consulted with myself, and contended with the nobles and the rulers, and said to them, “You exact usury, everyone of his brother.” I held a great assembly against them.\n'),
	(7587, 13, 5, 8, 'I said to them, “We, after our ability, have redeemed our brothers the Jews that were sold to the nations; and would you even sell your brothers, and should they be sold to us?” Then they held their peace, and found not a word to say.\n'),
	(7588, 13, 5, 9, 'Also I said, “The thing that you do is not good. Shouldn’t you walk in the fear of our God, because of the reproach of the nations our enemies?\n'),
	(7589, 13, 5, 10, 'I likewise, my brothers and my servants, lend them money and grain. Please let us stop this usury.\n'),
	(7590, 13, 5, 11, 'Please restore to them, even today, their fields, their vineyards, their olive groves, and their houses, also the hundredth part of the money, and of the grain, the new wine, and the oil, that you are charging them.”\n'),
	(7591, 13, 5, 12, 'Then they said, “We will restore them, and will require nothing of them. We will do so, even as you say.”\nThen I called the priests, and took an oath of them, that they would do according to this promise.\n'),
	(7592, 13, 5, 13, 'Also I shook out my lap, and said, “So may God shake out every man from his house, and from his labor, that doesn’t perform this promise; even be he shaken out, and emptied like this.”\nAll the assembly said, “Amen,” and praised Yahweh. The people did according to this promise.\n'),
	(7593, 13, 5, 14, 'Moreover from the time that I was appointed to be their governor in the land of Judah, from the twentieth year even to the thirty-second year of Artaxerxes the king, that is, twelve years, I and my brothers have not eaten the bread of the governor.\n'),
	(7594, 13, 5, 15, 'But the former governors who were before me were supported by the people, and took bread and wine from them, plus forty shekels of silver; yes, even their servants ruled over the people; but I didn’t do so, because of the fear of God.\n'),
	(7595, 13, 5, 16, 'Yes, I also continued in the work of this wall. We didn’t buy any land. All my servants were gathered there to the work.\n'),
	(7596, 13, 5, 17, 'Moreover there were at my table, of the Jews and the rulers, one hundred fifty men, besides those who came to us from among the nations that were around us.\n'),
	(7597, 13, 5, 18, 'Now that which was prepared for one day was one ox and six choice sheep. Also fowls were prepared for me, and once in ten days a store of all sorts of wine. Yet for all this, I didn’t demand the governor’s pay, because the bondage was heavy on this people.\n'),
	(7598, 13, 5, 19, 'Remember to me, my God, for good, all that I have done for this people.\n'),
	(7599, 13, 6, 1, 'Now when it was reported to Sanballat, Tobiah, and to Geshem the Arabian, and to the rest of our enemies, that I had built the wall, and that there was no breach left in it (though even to that time I had not set up the doors in the gates)\n'),
	(7600, 13, 6, 2, 'Sanballat and Geshem sent to me, saying, “Come, let us meet together in the villages in the plain of Ono.” But they intended to harm me.\n'),
	(7601, 13, 6, 3, 'I sent messengers to them, saying, “I am doing a great work, so that I can’t come down. Why should the work cease, while I leave it, and come down to you?”\n'),
	(7602, 13, 6, 4, 'They sent to me four times like this; and I answered them the same way.\n'),
	(7603, 13, 6, 5, 'Then Sanballat sent his servant to me the same way the fifth time with an open letter in his hand,\n'),
	(7604, 13, 6, 6, 'in which was written, “It is reported among the nations, and Gashmu says it, that you and the Jews intend to rebel. Because of that, you are building the wall. You would be their king, according to these words.\n'),
	(7605, 13, 6, 7, 'You have also appointed prophets to proclaim of you at Jerusalem, saying, ‘There is a king in Judah!’ Now it will be reported to the king according to these words. Come now therefore, and let us take counsel together.”\n'),
	(7606, 13, 6, 8, 'Then I sent to him, saying, “There are no such things done as you say, but you imagine them out of your own heart.”\n'),
	(7607, 13, 6, 9, 'For they all would have made us afraid, saying, “Their hands will be weakened from the work, that it not be done.” But now, strengthen my hands.\n'),
	(7608, 13, 6, 10, 'I went to the house of Shemaiah the son of Delaiah the son of Mehetabel, who was shut in at his home; and he said, “Let us meet together in God’s house, within the temple, and let us shut the doors of the temple; for they will come to kill you. Yes, in the night will they come to kill you.”\n'),
	(7609, 13, 6, 11, 'I said, “Should a man like me flee? Who is there that, being such as I, would go into the temple to save his life? I will not go in.”\n'),
	(7610, 13, 6, 12, 'I discerned, and behold, God had not sent him; but he pronounced this prophecy against me. Tobiah and Sanballat had hired him.\n'),
	(7611, 13, 6, 13, 'He hired so that I would be afraid, do so, and sin, and that they might have material for an evil report, that they might reproach me.\n'),
	(7612, 13, 6, 14, '“Remember, my God, Tobiah and Sanballat according to these their works, and also the prophetess Noadiah, and the rest of the prophets, that would have put me in fear.”\n'),
	(7613, 13, 6, 15, 'So the wall was finished in the twenty-fifth day of Elul, in fifty-two days.\n'),
	(7614, 13, 6, 16, 'When all our enemies heard of it, all the nations that were around us were afraid, and they lost their confidence; for they perceived that this work was done by our God.\n'),
	(7615, 13, 6, 17, 'Moreover in those days the nobles of Judah sent many letters to Tobiah, and Tobiah’s letters came to them.\n'),
	(7616, 13, 6, 18, 'For there were many in Judah sworn to him, because he was the son-in-law of Shecaniah the son of Arah; and his son Jehohanan had taken the daughter of Meshullam the son of Berechiah as wife.\n'),
	(7617, 13, 6, 19, 'Also they spoke of his good deeds before me, and reported my words to him. Tobiah sent letters to put me in fear.\n'),
	(7618, 13, 7, 1, 'Now when the wall was built, and I had set up the doors, and the gatekeepers and the singers and the Levites were appointed,\n'),
	(7619, 13, 7, 2, 'I put my brother Hanani, and Hananiah the governor of the fortress, in charge of Jerusalem; for he was a faithful man, and feared God above many.\n'),
	(7620, 13, 7, 3, 'I said to them, “Don’t let the gates of Jerusalem be opened until the sun is hot; and while they stand guard, let them shut the doors, and you bar them: and appoint watches of the inhabitants of Jerusalem, everyone in his watch, with everyone near his house.”\n'),
	(7621, 13, 7, 4, 'Now the city was wide and large; but the people were few therein, and the houses were not built.\n'),
	(7622, 13, 7, 5, 'My God put into my heart to gather together the nobles, and the rulers, and the people, that they might be listed by genealogy. I found the book of the genealogy of those who came up at the first, and I found this written in it:\n'),
	(7623, 13, 7, 6, 'These are the children of the province, who went up out of the captivity of those who had been carried away, whom Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon had carried away, and who returned to Jerusalem and to Judah, everyone to his city;\n'),
	(7624, 13, 7, 7, 'who came with Zerubbabel, Jeshua, Nehemiah, Azariah, Raamiah, Nahamani, Mordecai, Bilshan, Mispereth, Bigvai, Nehum, Baanah.\nThe number of the men of the people of Israel:\n'),
	(7625, 13, 7, 8, 'The children of Parosh, two thousand one hundred seventy-two.\n'),
	(7626, 13, 7, 9, 'The children of Shephatiah, three hundred seventy-two.\n'),
	(7627, 13, 7, 10, 'The children of Arah, six hundred fifty-two.\n'),
	(7628, 13, 7, 11, 'The children of Pahathmoab, of the children of Jeshua and Joab, two thousand eight hundred eighteen.\n'),
	(7629, 13, 7, 12, 'The children of Elam, one thousand two hundred fifty-four.\n'),
	(7630, 13, 7, 13, 'The children of Zattu, eight hundred forty-five.\n'),
	(7631, 13, 7, 14, 'The children of Zaccai, seven hundred sixty.\n'),
	(7632, 13, 7, 15, 'The children of Binnui, six hundred forty-eight.\n'),
	(7633, 13, 7, 16, 'The children of Bebai, six hundred twenty-eight.\n'),
	(7634, 13, 7, 17, 'The children of Azgad, two thousand three hundred twenty-two.\n'),
	(7635, 13, 7, 18, 'The children of Adonikam, six hundred sixty-seven.\n'),
	(7636, 13, 7, 19, 'The children of Bigvai, two thousand sixty-seven.\n'),
	(7637, 13, 7, 20, 'The children of Adin, six hundred fifty-five.\n'),
	(7638, 13, 7, 21, 'The children of Ater, of Hezekiah, ninety-eight.\n'),
	(7639, 13, 7, 22, 'The children of Hashum, three hundred twenty-eight.\n'),
	(7640, 13, 7, 23, 'The children of Bezai, three hundred twenty-four.\n'),
	(7641, 13, 7, 24, 'The children of Hariph, one hundred twelve.\n'),
	(7642, 13, 7, 25, 'The children of Gibeon, ninety-five.\n'),
	(7643, 13, 7, 26, 'The men of Bethlehem and Netophah, one hundred eighty-eight.\n'),
	(7644, 13, 7, 27, 'The men of Anathoth, one hundred twenty-eight.\n'),
	(7645, 13, 7, 28, 'The men of Beth Azmaveth, forty-two.\n'),
	(7646, 13, 7, 29, 'The men of Kiriath Jearim, Chephirah, and Beeroth, seven hundred forty-three.\n'),
	(7647, 13, 7, 30, 'The men of Ramah and Geba, six hundred twenty-one.\n'),
	(7648, 13, 7, 31, 'The men of Michmas, one hundred twenty-two.\n'),
	(7649, 13, 7, 32, 'The men of Bethel and Ai, one hundred twenty-three.\n'),
	(7650, 13, 7, 33, 'The men of the other Nebo, fifty-two.\n'),
	(7651, 13, 7, 34, 'The children of the other Elam, one thousand two hundred fifty-four.\n'),
	(7652, 13, 7, 35, 'The children of Harim, three hundred twenty.\n'),
	(7653, 13, 7, 36, 'The children of Jericho, three hundred forty-five.\n'),
	(7654, 13, 7, 37, 'The children of Lod, Hadid, and Ono, seven hundred twenty-one.\n'),
	(7655, 13, 7, 38, 'The children of Senaah, three thousand nine hundred thirty.\n'),
	(7656, 13, 7, 39, 'The priests: The children of Jedaiah, of the house of Jeshua, nine hundred seventy-three.\n'),
	(7657, 13, 7, 40, 'The children of Immer, one thousand fifty-two.\n'),
	(7658, 13, 7, 41, 'The children of Pashhur, one thousand two hundred forty-seven.\n'),
	(7659, 13, 7, 42, 'The children of Harim, one thousand seventeen.\n'),
	(7660, 13, 7, 43, 'The Levites: the children of Jeshua, of Kadmiel, of the children of Hodevah, seventy-four.\n'),
	(7661, 13, 7, 44, 'The singers: the children of Asaph, one hundred forty-eight.\n'),
	(7662, 13, 7, 45, 'The gatekeepers: the children of Shallum, the children of Ater, the children of Talmon, the children of Akkub, the children of Hatita, the children of Shobai, one hundred thirty-eight.\n'),
	(7663, 13, 7, 46, 'The temple servants: the children of Ziha, the children of Hasupha, the children of Tabbaoth,\n'),
	(7664, 13, 7, 47, 'the children of Keros, the children of Sia, the children of Padon,\n'),
	(7665, 13, 7, 48, 'the children of Lebana, the children of Hagaba, the children of Salmai,\n'),
	(7666, 13, 7, 49, 'the children of Hanan, the children of Giddel, the children of Gahar,\n'),
	(7667, 13, 7, 50, 'the children of Reaiah, the children of Rezin, the children of Nekoda,\n'),
	(7668, 13, 7, 51, 'the children of Gazzam, the children of Uzza, the children of Paseah.\n'),
	(7669, 13, 7, 52, 'The children of Besai, the children of Meunim, the children of Nephushesim,\n'),
	(7670, 13, 7, 53, 'the children of Bakbuk, the children of Hakupha, the children of Harhur,\n'),
	(7671, 13, 7, 54, 'the children of Bazlith, the children of Mehida, the children of Harsha,\n'),
	(7672, 13, 7, 55, 'the children of Barkos, the children of Sisera, the children of Temah,\n'),
	(7673, 13, 7, 56, 'the children of Neziah, the children of Hatipha.\n'),
	(7674, 13, 7, 57, 'The children of Solomon’s servants: the children of Sotai, the children of Sophereth, the children of Perida,\n'),
	(7675, 13, 7, 58, 'the children of Jaala, the children of Darkon, the children of Giddel,\n'),
	(7676, 13, 7, 59, 'the children of Shephatiah, the children of Hattil, the children of Pochereth Hazzebaim, the children of Amon.\n'),
	(7677, 13, 7, 60, 'All the temple servants, and the children of Solomon’s servants, were three hundred ninety-two.\n'),
	(7678, 13, 7, 61, 'These were those who went up from Tel Melah, Tel Harsha, Cherub, Addon, and Immer; but they could not show their fathers’ houses, nor their offspring, whether they were of Israel:\n'),
	(7679, 13, 7, 62, 'The children of Delaiah, the children of Tobiah, the children of Nekoda, six hundred forty-two.\n'),
	(7680, 13, 7, 63, 'Of the priests: the children of Hobaiah, the children of Hakkoz, the children of Barzillai, who took a wife of the daughters of Barzillai the Gileadite, and was called after their name.\n'),
	(7681, 13, 7, 64, 'These searched for their genealogical records, but couldn’t find them. Therefore were they deemed disqualified and removed from the priesthood.\n'),
	(7682, 13, 7, 65, 'The governor told that they should not eat of the most holy things until a priest stood up to minister with Urim and Thummim.\n'),
	(7683, 13, 7, 66, 'The whole assembly together was forty-two thousand three hundred sixty,\n'),
	(7684, 13, 7, 67, 'besides their male servants and their female servants, of whom there were seven thousand three hundred thirty-seven; and they had two hundred forty-five singing men and singing women.\n'),
	(7685, 13, 7, 68, 'Their horses were seven hundred thirty-six; their mules, two hundred forty-five;\n'),
	(7686, 13, 7, 69, 'their camels, four hundred thirty-five; their donkeys, six thousand seven hundred twenty.\n'),
	(7687, 13, 7, 70, 'Some from among the heads of fathers’ households gave to the work. The governor gave to the treasury one thousand darics of gold, fifty basins, and five hundred thirty priests’ garments.\n'),
	(7688, 13, 7, 71, 'Some of the heads of fathers’ households gave into the treasury of the work twenty thousand darics of gold, and two thousand two hundred minas of silver.\n'),
	(7689, 13, 7, 72, 'That which the rest of the people gave was twenty thousand darics of gold, plus two thousand minas of silver, and sixty-seven priests’ garments.\n'),
	(7690, 13, 7, 73, 'So the priests, the Levites, the gatekeepers, the singers, some of the people, the temple servants, and all Israel, lived in their cities.\nWhen the seventh month had come, the children of Israel were in their cities.\n'),
	(7691, 13, 8, 1, 'All the people gathered themselves together as one man into the wide place that was in front of the water gate; and they spoke to Ezra the scribe to bring the book of the law of Moses, which Yahweh had commanded to Israel.\n'),
	(7692, 13, 8, 2, 'Ezra the priest brought the law before the assembly, both men and women, and all who could hear with understanding, on the first day of the seventh month.\n'),
	(7693, 13, 8, 3, 'He read from it before the wide place that was in front of the water gate from early morning until midday, in the presence of the men and the women, and of those who could understand. The ears of all the people were attentive to the book of the law.\n'),
	(7694, 13, 8, 4, 'Ezra the scribe stood on a pulpit of wood, which they had made for the purpose; and beside him stood Mattithiah, Shema, Anaiah, Uriah, Hilkiah, and Maaseiah, on his right hand; and on his left hand, Pedaiah, Mishael, Malchijah, Hashum, Hashbaddanah, Zechariah, and Meshullam.\n'),
	(7695, 13, 8, 5, 'Ezra opened the book in the sight of all the people (for he was above all the people), and when he opened it, all the people stood up.\n'),
	(7696, 13, 8, 6, 'Then Ezra blessed Yahweh, the great God.\nAll the people answered, “Amen, Amen,” with the lifting up of their hands. They bowed their heads, and worshiped Yahweh with their faces to the ground.\n'),
	(7697, 13, 8, 7, 'Also Jeshua, Bani, Sherebiah, Jamin, Akkub, Shabbethai, Hodiah, Maaseiah, Kelita, Azariah, Jozabad, Hanan, Pelaiah, and the Levites, caused the people to understand the law; and the people stayed in their place.\n'),
	(7698, 13, 8, 8, 'They read in the book, in the law of God, distinctly; and they gave the sense, so that they understood the reading.\n'),
	(7699, 13, 8, 9, 'Nehemiah, who was the governor, and Ezra the priest and scribe, and the Levites who taught the people, said to all the people, “Today is holy to Yahweh your God. Don’t mourn, nor weep.” For all the people wept when they heard the words of the law.\n'),
	(7700, 13, 8, 10, 'Then he said to them, “Go your way. Eat the fat, drink the sweet, and send portions to him for whom nothing is prepared, for today is holy to our Lord. Don’t be grieved, for the joy of Yahweh is your strength.”\n'),
	(7701, 13, 8, 11, 'So the Levites calmed all the people, saying, “Hold your peace, for the day is holy. Don’t be grieved.”\n'),
	(7702, 13, 8, 12, 'All the people went their way to eat, to drink, to send portions, and to celebrate, because they had understood the words that were declared to them.\n'),
	(7703, 13, 8, 13, 'On the second day, the heads of fathers’ households of all the people, the priests, and the Levites were gathered together to Ezra the scribe, to study the words of the law.\n'),
	(7704, 13, 8, 14, 'They found written in the law how Yahweh had commanded by Moses that the children of Israel should dwell in booths in the feast of the seventh month;\n'),
	(7705, 13, 8, 15, 'and that they should publish and proclaim in all their cities, and in Jerusalem, saying, “Go out to the mountain, and get olive branches, branches of wild olive, myrtle branches, palm branches, and branches of thick trees, to make temporary shelters, as it is written.”\n'),
	(7706, 13, 8, 16, 'So the people went out, and brought them, and made themselves temporary shelters, everyone on the roof of his house, in their courts, in the courts of God’s house, in the wide place of the water gate, and in the wide place of Ephraim’s gate.\n'),
	(7707, 13, 8, 17, 'All the assembly of those who had come back out of the captivity made temporary shelters, and lived in the booths; for since the days of Jeshua the son of Nun to that day the children of Israel had not done so. There was very great gladness.\n'),
	(7708, 13, 8, 18, 'Also day by day, from the first day to the last day, he read in the book of the law of God. They kept the feast seven days; and on the eighth day was a solemn assembly, according to the ordinance.\n'),
	(7709, 13, 9, 1, 'Now in the twenty-fourth day of this month the children of Israel were assembled with fasting, with sackcloth, and dirt on them.\n'),
	(7710, 13, 9, 2, 'The offspring of Israel separated themselves from all foreigners, and stood and confessed their sins, and the iniquities of their fathers.\n'),
	(7711, 13, 9, 3, 'They stood up in their place, and read in the book of the law of Yahweh their God a fourth part of the day; and a fourth part they confessed, and worshiped Yahweh their God.\n'),
	(7712, 13, 9, 4, 'Then Jeshua, Bani, Kadmiel, Shebaniah, Bunni, Sherebiah, Bani, and Chenani of the Levites stood up on the stairs, and cried with a loud voice to Yahweh their God.\n'),
	(7713, 13, 9, 5, 'Then the Levites, Jeshua, and Kadmiel, Bani, Hashabneiah, Sherebiah, Hodiah, Shebaniah, and Pethahiah, said, “Stand up and bless Yahweh your God from everlasting to everlasting! Blessed be your glorious name, which is exalted above all blessing and praise!\n'),
	(7714, 13, 9, 6, 'You are Yahweh, even you alone. You have made heaven, the heaven of heavens, with all their army, the earth and all things that are on it, the seas and all that is in them, and you preserve them all. The army of heaven worships you.\n'),
	(7715, 13, 9, 7, 'You are Yahweh, the God who chose Abram, brought him out of Ur of the Chaldees, gave him the name of Abraham,\n'),
	(7716, 13, 9, 8, 'found his heart faithful before you, and made a covenant with him to give the land of the Canaanite, the Hittite, the Amorite, the Perizzite, the Jebusite, and the Girgashite, to give it to his offspring, and have performed your words; for you are righteous.\n'),
	(7717, 13, 9, 9, '“You saw the affliction of our fathers in Egypt, and heard their cry by the Red Sea,\n'),
	(7718, 13, 9, 10, 'and showed signs and wonders against Pharaoh, and against all his servants, and against all the people of his land; for you knew that they dealt proudly against them, and made a name for yourself, as it is today.\n'),
	(7719, 13, 9, 11, 'You divided the sea before them, so that they went through the middle of the sea on the dry land; and you cast their pursuers into the depths, as a stone into the mighty waters.\n'),
	(7720, 13, 9, 12, 'Moreover, in a pillar of cloud you led them by day; and in a pillar of fire by night, to give them light in the way in which they should go.\n'),
	(7721, 13, 9, 13, '“You also came down on Mount Sinai, and spoke with them from heaven, and gave them right ordinances and true laws, good statutes and commandments,\n'),
	(7722, 13, 9, 14, 'and made known to them your holy Sabbath, and commanded them commandments, statutes, and a law, by Moses your servant,\n'),
	(7723, 13, 9, 15, 'and gave them bread from the sky for their hunger, and brought water out of the rock for them for their thirst, and commanded them that they should go in to possess the land which you had sworn to give them.\n'),
	(7724, 13, 9, 16, '“But they and our fathers behaved proudly, hardened their neck, didn’t listen to your commandments,\n'),
	(7725, 13, 9, 17, 'and refused to obey. They weren’t mindful of your wonders that you did among them, but hardened their neck, and in their rebellion appointed a captain to return to their bondage. But you are a God ready to pardon, gracious and merciful, slow to anger, and abundant in loving kindness, and didn’t forsake them.\n'),
	(7726, 13, 9, 18, 'Yes, when they had made themselves a molten calf, and said, ‘This is your God who brought you up out of Egypt,’ and had committed awful blasphemies;\n'),
	(7727, 13, 9, 19, 'yet you in your manifold mercies didn’t forsake them in the wilderness. The pillar of cloud didn’t depart from over them by day, to lead them in the way; neither did the pillar of fire by night, to show them light, and the way in which they should go.\n'),
	(7728, 13, 9, 20, 'You gave also your good Spirit to instruct them, and didn’t withhold your manna from their mouth, and gave them water for their thirst.\n'),
	(7729, 13, 9, 21, '“Yes, forty years you sustained them in the wilderness. They lacked nothing. Their clothes didn’t grow old, and their feet didn’t swell.\n'),
	(7730, 13, 9, 22, 'Moreover you gave them kingdoms and peoples, which you allotted according to their portions. So they possessed the land of Sihon, even the land of the king of Heshbon, and the land of Og king of Bashan.\n'),
	(7731, 13, 9, 23, 'You also multiplied their children as the stars of the sky, and brought them into the land concerning which you said to their fathers, that they should go in to possess it.\n'),
	(7732, 13, 9, 24, '“So the children went in and possessed the land, and you subdued before them the inhabitants of the land, the Canaanites, and gave them into their hands, with their kings and the peoples of the land, that they might do with them as they pleased.\n'),
	(7733, 13, 9, 25, 'They took fortified cities and a rich land, and possessed houses full of all good things, cisterns dug out, vineyards, and olive groves, and fruit trees in abundance. So they ate, were filled, became fat, and delighted themselves in your great goodness.\n'),
	(7734, 13, 9, 26, '“Nevertheless they were disobedient, and rebelled against you, cast your law behind their back, killed your prophets that testified against them to turn them again to you, and they committed awful blasphemies.\n'),
	(7735, 13, 9, 27, 'Therefore you delivered them into the hand of their adversaries, who distressed them. In the time of their trouble, when they cried to you, you heard from heaven; and according to your manifold mercies you gave them saviors who saved them out of the hands of their adversaries.\n'),
	(7736, 13, 9, 28, 'But after they had rest, they did evil again before you; therefore left you them in the hands of their enemies, so that they had the dominion over them; yet when they returned, and cried to you, you heard from heaven; and many times you delivered them according to your mercies,\n'),
	(7737, 13, 9, 29, 'and testified against them, that you might bring them again to your law. Yet they were arrogant, and didn’t listen to your commandments, but sinned against your ordinances (which if a man does, he shall live in them), turned their backs, stiffened their neck, and would not hear.\n'),
	(7738, 13, 9, 30, 'Yet many years you put up with them, and testified against them by your Spirit through your prophets. Yet would they not give ear. Therefore you gave them into the hand of the peoples of the lands.\n'),
	(7739, 13, 9, 31, '“Nevertheless in your manifold mercies you did not make a full end of them, nor forsake them; for you are a gracious and merciful God.\n'),
	(7740, 13, 9, 32, 'Now therefore, our God, the great, the mighty, and the awesome God, who keeps covenant and loving kindness, don’t let all the travail seem little before you, that has come on us, on our kings, on our princes, on our priests, on our prophets, on our fathers, and on all your people, since the time of the kings of Assyria to this day.\n'),
	(7741, 13, 9, 33, 'However you are just in all that has come on us; for you have dealt truly, but we have done wickedly.\n'),
	(7742, 13, 9, 34, 'Also our kings, our princes, our priests, and our fathers have not kept your law, nor listened to your commandments and your testimonies with which you testified against them.\n'),
	(7743, 13, 9, 35, 'For they have not served you in their kingdom, and in your great goodness that you gave them, and in the large and rich land which you gave before them. They did not turn from their wicked works.\n'),
	(7744, 13, 9, 36, '“Behold, we are servants today, and as for the land that you gave to our fathers to eat its fruit and its good, behold, we are servants in it.\n'),
	(7745, 13, 9, 37, 'It yields much increase to the kings whom you have set over us because of our sins. Also they have power over our bodies and over our livestock, at their pleasure, and we are in great distress.\n'),
	(7746, 13, 9, 38, 'Yet for all this, we make a sure covenant, and write it; and our princes, our Levites, and our priests, seal it.”\n'),
	(7747, 13, 10, 1, 'Now those who sealed were: Nehemiah the governor, the son of Hacaliah, and Zedekiah,\n'),
	(7748, 13, 10, 2, 'Seraiah, Azariah, Jeremiah,\n'),
	(7749, 13, 10, 3, 'Pashhur, Amariah, Malchijah,\n'),
	(7750, 13, 10, 4, 'Hattush, Shebaniah, Malluch,\n'),
	(7751, 13, 10, 5, 'Harim, Meremoth, Obadiah,\n'),
	(7752, 13, 10, 6, 'Daniel, Ginnethon, Baruch,\n'),
	(7753, 13, 10, 7, 'Meshullam, Abijah, Mijamin,\n'),
	(7754, 13, 10, 8, 'Maaziah, Bilgai, and Shemaiah. These were the priests.\n'),
	(7755, 13, 10, 9, 'The Levites: namely, Jeshua the son of Azaniah, Binnui of the sons of Henadad, Kadmiel;\n'),
	(7756, 13, 10, 10, 'and their brothers, Shebaniah, Hodiah, Kelita, Pelaiah, Hanan,\n'),
	(7757, 13, 10, 11, 'Mica, Rehob, Hashabiah,\n'),
	(7758, 13, 10, 12, 'Zaccur, Sherebiah, Shebaniah,\n'),
	(7759, 13, 10, 13, 'Hodiah, Bani, and Beninu.\n'),
	(7760, 13, 10, 14, 'The chiefs of the people: Parosh, Pahathmoab, Elam, Zattu, Bani,\n'),
	(7761, 13, 10, 15, 'Bunni, Azgad, Bebai,\n'),
	(7762, 13, 10, 16, 'Adonijah, Bigvai, Adin,\n'),
	(7763, 13, 10, 17, 'Ater, Hezekiah, Azzur,\n'),
	(7764, 13, 10, 18, 'Hodiah, Hashum, Bezai,\n'),
	(7765, 13, 10, 19, 'Hariph, Anathoth, Nobai,\n'),
	(7766, 13, 10, 20, 'Magpiash, Meshullam, Hezir,\n'),
	(7767, 13, 10, 21, 'Meshezabel, Zadok, Jaddua,\n'),
	(7768, 13, 10, 22, 'Pelatiah, Hanan, Anaiah,\n'),
	(7769, 13, 10, 23, 'Hoshea, Hananiah, Hasshub,\n'),
	(7770, 13, 10, 24, 'Hallohesh, Pilha, Shobek,\n'),
	(7771, 13, 10, 25, 'Rehum, Hashabnah, Maaseiah,\n'),
	(7772, 13, 10, 26, 'and Ahiah, Hanan, Anan,\n'),
	(7773, 13, 10, 27, 'Malluch, Harim, and Baanah.\n'),
	(7774, 13, 10, 28, 'The rest of the people, the priests, the Levites, the gatekeepers, the singers, the temple servants, and all those who had separated themselves from the peoples of the lands to the law of God, their wives, their sons, and their daughters, everyone who had knowledge, and understanding—\n'),
	(7775, 13, 10, 29, 'they joined with their brothers, their nobles, and entered into a curse, and into an oath, to walk in God’s law, which was given by Moses the servant of God, and to observe and do all the commandments of Yahweh our Lord, and his ordinances and his statutes;\n'),
	(7776, 13, 10, 30, 'and that we would not give our daughters to the peoples of the land, nor take their daughters for our sons;\n'),
	(7777, 13, 10, 31, 'and if the peoples of the land bring wares or any grain on the Sabbath day to sell, that we would not buy from them on the Sabbath, or on a holy day; and that we would forego the seventh year, and the exaction of every debt.\n'),
	(7778, 13, 10, 32, 'Also we made ordinances for ourselves, to charge ourselves yearly with the third part of a shekel for the service of the house of our God;\n'),
	(7779, 13, 10, 33, 'for the show bread, for the continual meal offering, for the continual burnt offering, for the Sabbaths, for the new moons, for the set feasts, and for the holy things, and for the sin offerings to make atonement for Israel, and for all the work of the house of our God.\n'),
	(7780, 13, 10, 34, 'We cast lots, the priests, the Levites, and the people, for the wood offering, to bring it into the house of our God, according to our fathers’ houses, at times appointed, year by year, to burn on Yahweh our God’s altar, as it is written in the law;\n'),
	(7781, 13, 10, 35, 'and to bring the first fruits of our ground, and the first fruits of all fruit of all kinds of trees, year by year, to Yahweh’s house;\n'),
	(7782, 13, 10, 36, 'also the firstborn of our sons, and of our livestock, as it is written in the law, and the firstborn of our herds and of our flocks, to bring to the house of our God, to the priests who minister in the house of our God;\n'),
	(7783, 13, 10, 37, 'and that we should bring the first fruits of our dough, our wave offerings, the fruit of all kinds of trees, and the new wine and the oil, to the priests, to the rooms of the house of our God; and the tithes of our ground to the Levites; for they, the Levites, take the tithes in all the cities of our tillage.\n'),
	(7784, 13, 10, 38, 'The priest the son of Aaron shall be with the Levites, when the Levites take tithes. The Levites shall bring up the tithe of the tithes to the house of our God, to the rooms, into the treasure house.\n'),
	(7785, 13, 10, 39, 'For the children of Israel and the children of Levi shall bring the wave offering of the grain, of the new wine, and of the oil, to the rooms, where the vessels of the sanctuary are, and the priests who minister, with the gatekeepers and the singers. We will not forsake the house of our God.\n'),
	(7786, 13, 11, 1, 'The princes of the people lived in Jerusalem. The rest of the people also cast lots, to bring one of ten to dwell in Jerusalem the holy city, and nine parts in the other cities.\n'),
	(7787, 13, 11, 2, 'The people blessed all the men who willingly offered themselves to dwell in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7788, 13, 11, 3, 'Now these are the chiefs of the province who lived in Jerusalem; but in the cities of Judah everyone lived in his possession in their cities: Israel, the priests, the Levites, the temple servants, and the children of Solomon’s servants.\n'),
	(7789, 13, 11, 4, 'Some of the children of Judah and of the children of Benjamin lived in Jerusalem. Of the children of Judah: Athaiah the son of Uzziah, the son of Zechariah, the son of Amariah, the son of Shephatiah, the son of Mahalalel, of the children of Perez;\n'),
	(7790, 13, 11, 5, 'and Maaseiah the son of Baruch, the son of Colhozeh, the son of Hazaiah, the son of Adaiah, the son of Joiarib, the son of Zechariah, the son of the Shilonite.\n'),
	(7791, 13, 11, 6, 'All the sons of Perez who lived in Jerusalem were four hundred sixty-eight valiant men.\n'),
	(7792, 13, 11, 7, 'These are the sons of Benjamin: Sallu the son of Meshullam, the son of Joed, the son of Pedaiah, the son of Kolaiah, the son of Maaseiah, the son of Ithiel, the son of Jeshaiah.\n'),
	(7793, 13, 11, 8, 'After him Gabbai, Sallai, nine hundred twenty-eight.\n'),
	(7794, 13, 11, 9, 'Joel the son of Zichri was their overseer; and Judah the son of Hassenuah was second over the city.\n'),
	(7795, 13, 11, 10, 'Of the priests: Jedaiah the son of Joiarib, Jachin,\n'),
	(7796, 13, 11, 11, 'Seraiah the son of Hilkiah, the son of Meshullam, the son of Zadok, the son of Meraioth, the son of Ahitub, the ruler of God’s house,\n'),
	(7797, 13, 11, 12, 'and their brothers who did the work of the house, eight hundred twenty-two; and Adaiah the son of Jeroham, the son of Pelaliah, the son of Amzi, the son of Zechariah, the son of Pashhur, the son of Malchijah,\n'),
	(7798, 13, 11, 13, 'and his brothers, chiefs of fathers’ households, two hundred forty-two; and Amashsai the son of Azarel, the son of Ahzai, the son of Meshillemoth, the son of Immer,\n'),
	(7799, 13, 11, 14, 'and their brothers, mighty men of valor, one hundred twenty-eight; and their overseer was Zabdiel, the son of Haggedolim.\n'),
	(7800, 13, 11, 15, 'Of the Levites: Shemaiah the son of Hasshub, the son of Azrikam, the son of Hashabiah, the son of Bunni;\n'),
	(7801, 13, 11, 16, 'and Shabbethai and Jozabad, of the chiefs of the Levites, who had the oversight of the outward business of God’s house;\n'),
	(7802, 13, 11, 17, 'and Mattaniah the son of Mica, the son of Zabdi, the son of Asaph, who was the chief to begin the thanksgiving in prayer, and Bakbukiah, the second among his brothers; and Abda the son of Shammua, the son of Galal, the son of Jeduthun.\n'),
	(7803, 13, 11, 18, 'All the Levites in the holy city were two hundred eighty-four.\n'),
	(7804, 13, 11, 19, 'Moreover the gatekeepers, Akkub, Talmon, and their brothers, who kept watch at the gates, were one hundred seventy-two.\n'),
	(7805, 13, 11, 20, 'The residue of Israel, of the priests, the Levites, were in all the cities of Judah, everyone in his inheritance.\n'),
	(7806, 13, 11, 21, 'But the temple servants lived in Ophel: and Ziha and Gishpa were over the temple servants.\n'),
	(7807, 13, 11, 22, 'The overseer also of the Levites at Jerusalem was Uzzi the son of Bani, the son of Hashabiah, the son of Mattaniah, the son of Mica, of the sons of Asaph, the singers, over the business of God’s house.\n'),
	(7808, 13, 11, 23, 'For there was a commandment from the king concerning them, and a settled provision for the singers, as every day required.\n'),
	(7809, 13, 11, 24, 'Pethahiah the son of Meshezabel, of the children of Zerah the son of Judah, was at the king’s hand in all matters concerning the people.\n'),
	(7810, 13, 11, 25, 'As for the villages, with their fields, some of the children of Judah lived in Kiriath Arba and its towns, in Dibon and its towns, in Jekabzeel and its villages,\n'),
	(7811, 13, 11, 26, 'in Jeshua, in Moladah, Beth Pelet,\n'),
	(7812, 13, 11, 27, 'in Hazar Shual, in Beersheba and its towns,\n'),
	(7813, 13, 11, 28, 'in Ziklag, in Meconah and in its towns,\n'),
	(7814, 13, 11, 29, 'in En Rimmon, in Zorah, in Jarmuth,\n'),
	(7815, 13, 11, 30, 'Zanoah, Adullam, and their villages, Lachish and its fields, and Azekah and its towns. So they encamped from Beersheba to the valley of Hinnom.\n'),
	(7816, 13, 11, 31, 'The children of Benjamin also lived from Geba onward, at Michmash and Aija, and at Bethel and its towns,\n'),
	(7817, 13, 11, 32, 'at Anathoth, Nob, Ananiah,\n'),
	(7818, 13, 11, 33, 'Hazor, Ramah, Gittaim,\n'),
	(7819, 13, 11, 34, 'Hadid, Zeboim, Neballat,\n'),
	(7820, 13, 11, 35, 'Lod, and Ono, the valley of craftsmen.\n'),
	(7821, 13, 11, 36, 'Of the Levites, certain divisions in Judah settled in Benjamin’s territory.\n'),
	(7822, 13, 12, 1, 'Now these are the priests and the Levites who went up with Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel, and Jeshua: Seraiah, Jeremiah, Ezra,\n'),
	(7823, 13, 12, 2, 'Amariah, Malluch, Hattush,\n'),
	(7824, 13, 12, 3, 'Shecaniah, Rehum, Meremoth,\n'),
	(7825, 13, 12, 4, 'Iddo, Ginnethoi, Abijah,\n'),
	(7826, 13, 12, 5, 'Mijamin, Maadiah, Bilgah,\n'),
	(7827, 13, 12, 6, 'Shemaiah, and Joiarib, Jedaiah.\n'),
	(7828, 13, 12, 7, 'Sallu, Amok, Hilkiah, and Jedaiah. These were the chiefs of the priests and of their brothers in the days of Jeshua.\n'),
	(7829, 13, 12, 8, 'Moreover the Levites: Jeshua, Binnui, Kadmiel, Sherebiah, Judah, and Mattaniah, who was over the thanksgiving, he and his brothers.\n'),
	(7830, 13, 12, 9, 'Also Bakbukiah and Unno, their brothers, were close to them according to their offices.\n'),
	(7831, 13, 12, 10, 'Jeshua became the father of Joiakim, and Joiakim became the father of Eliashib, and Eliashib became the father of Joiada,\n'),
	(7832, 13, 12, 11, 'and Joiada became the father of Jonathan, and Jonathan became the father of Jaddua.\n'),
	(7833, 13, 12, 12, 'In the days of Joiakim were priests, heads of fathers’ households: of Seraiah, Meraiah; of Jeremiah, Hananiah;\n'),
	(7834, 13, 12, 13, 'of Ezra, Meshullam; of Amariah, Jehohanan;\n'),
	(7835, 13, 12, 14, 'of Malluchi, Jonathan; of Shebaniah, Joseph;\n'),
	(7836, 13, 12, 15, 'of Harim, Adna; of Meraioth, Helkai;\n'),
	(7837, 13, 12, 16, 'of Iddo, Zechariah; of Ginnethon, Meshullam;\n'),
	(7838, 13, 12, 17, 'of Abijah, Zichri; of Miniamin, of Moadiah, Piltai;\n'),
	(7839, 13, 12, 18, 'of Bilgah, Shammua; of Shemaiah, Jehonathan;\n'),
	(7840, 13, 12, 19, 'and of Joiarib, Mattenai; of Jedaiah, Uzzi;\n'),
	(7841, 13, 12, 20, 'of Sallai, Kallai; of Amok, Eber;\n'),
	(7842, 13, 12, 21, 'of Hilkiah, Hashabiah; of Jedaiah, Nethanel.\n'),
	(7843, 13, 12, 22, 'As for the Levites, in the days of Eliashib, Joiada, and Johanan, and Jaddua, there were recorded the heads of fathers’ households; also the priests, in the reign of Darius the Persian.\n'),
	(7844, 13, 12, 23, 'The sons of Levi, heads of fathers’ households, were written in the book of the chronicles, even until the days of Johanan the son of Eliashib.\n'),
	(7845, 13, 12, 24, 'The chiefs of the Levites: Hashabiah, Sherebiah, and Jeshua the son of Kadmiel, with their brothers close to them, to praise and give thanks, according to the commandment of David the man of God, watch next to watch.\n'),
	(7846, 13, 12, 25, 'Mattaniah, and Bakbukiah, Obadiah, Meshullam, Talmon, Akkub, were gatekeepers keeping the watch at the storehouses of the gates.\n'),
	(7847, 13, 12, 26, 'These were in the days of Joiakim the son of Jeshua, the son of Jozadak, and in the days of Nehemiah the governor, and of Ezra the priest and scribe.\n'),
	(7848, 13, 12, 27, 'At the dedication of the wall of Jerusalem, they sought the Levites out of all their places, to bring them to Jerusalem, to keep the dedication with gladness, both with giving thanks, and with singing, with cymbals, stringed instruments, and with harps.\n'),
	(7849, 13, 12, 28, 'The sons of the singers gathered themselves together, both out of the plain around Jerusalem and from the villages of the Netophathites;\n'),
	(7850, 13, 12, 29, 'also from Beth Gilgal, and out of the fields of Geba and Azmaveth: for the singers had built themselves villages around Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7851, 13, 12, 30, 'The priests and the Levites purified themselves; and they purified the people, and the gates, and the wall.\n'),
	(7852, 13, 12, 31, 'Then I brought up the princes of Judah on the wall, and appointed two great companies who gave thanks and went in procession. One went on the right hand on the wall toward the dung gate;\n'),
	(7853, 13, 12, 32, 'and after them went Hoshaiah, with half of the princes of Judah,\n'),
	(7854, 13, 12, 33, 'and Azariah, Ezra, and Meshullam,\n'),
	(7855, 13, 12, 34, 'Judah, Benjamin, Shemaiah, Jeremiah,\n'),
	(7856, 13, 12, 35, 'and some of the priests’ sons with trumpets: Zechariah the son of Jonathan, the son of Shemaiah, the son of Mattaniah, the son of Micaiah, the son of Zaccur, the son of Asaph;\n'),
	(7857, 13, 12, 36, 'and his brothers, Shemaiah, Azarel, Milalai, Gilalai, Maai, Nethanel, Judah, and Hanani, with the musical instruments of David the man of God; and Ezra the scribe was before them.\n'),
	(7858, 13, 12, 37, 'By the spring gate, and straight before them, they went up by the stairs of David’s city, at the ascent of the wall, above David’s house, even to the water gate eastward.\n'),
	(7859, 13, 12, 38, 'The other company of those who gave thanks went to meet them, and I after them, with the half of the people, on the wall, above the tower of the furnaces, even to the wide wall,\n'),
	(7860, 13, 12, 39, 'and above the gate of Ephraim, and by the old gate, and by the fish gate, and the tower of Hananel, and the tower of Hammeah, even to the sheep gate: and they stood still in the gate of the guard.\n'),
	(7861, 13, 12, 40, 'So the two companies of those who gave thanks in God’s house stood, and I, and the half of the rulers with me;\n'),
	(7862, 13, 12, 41, 'and the priests, Eliakim, Maaseiah, Miniamin, Micaiah, Elioenai, Zechariah, and Hananiah, with trumpets;\n'),
	(7863, 13, 12, 42, 'and Maaseiah, Shemaiah, Eleazar, Uzzi, Jehohanan, Malchijah, Elam, and Ezer. The singers sang loud, with Jezrahiah their overseer.\n'),
	(7864, 13, 12, 43, 'They offered great sacrifices that day, and rejoiced; for God had made them rejoice with great joy; and the women and the children also rejoiced; so that the joy of Jerusalem was heard even far away.\n'),
	(7865, 13, 12, 44, 'On that day were men appointed over the rooms for the treasures, for the wave offerings, for the first fruits, and for the tithes, to gather into them, according to the fields of the cities, the portions appointed by the law for the priests and Levites; for Judah rejoiced for the priests and for the Levites who waited.\n'),
	(7866, 13, 12, 45, 'They performed the duty of their God, and the duty of the purification, and so did the singers and the gatekeepers, according to the commandment of David, and of Solomon his son.\n'),
	(7867, 13, 12, 46, 'For in the days of David and Asaph of old there was a chief of the singers, and songs of praise and thanksgiving to God.\n'),
	(7868, 13, 12, 47, 'All Israel in the days of Zerubbabel, and in the days of Nehemiah, gave the portions of the singers and the gatekeepers, as every day required; and they set apart that which was for the Levites; and the Levites set apart that which was for the sons of Aaron.\n'),
	(7869, 13, 13, 1, 'On that day they read in the book of Moses in the hearing of the people; and it was found written in it that an Ammonite and a Moabite should not enter into the assembly of God forever,\n'),
	(7870, 13, 13, 2, 'because they didn’t meet the children of Israel with bread and with water, but hired Balaam against them, to curse them; however our God turned the curse into a blessing.\n'),
	(7871, 13, 13, 3, 'It came to pass, when they had heard the law, that they separated all the mixed multitude from Israel.\n'),
	(7872, 13, 13, 4, 'Now before this, Eliashib the priest, who was appointed over the rooms of the house of our God, being allied to Tobiah,\n'),
	(7873, 13, 13, 5, 'had prepared for him a great room, where before they laid the meal offerings, the frankincense, the vessels, and the tithes of the grain, the new wine, and the oil, which were given by commandment to the Levites, the singers, and the gatekeepers; and the wave offerings for the priests.\n'),
	(7874, 13, 13, 6, 'But in all this, I was not at Jerusalem; for in the thirty-second year of Artaxerxes king of Babylon I went to the king; and after some days I asked leave of the king,\n'),
	(7875, 13, 13, 7, 'and I came to Jerusalem, and understood the evil that Eliashib had done for Tobiah, in preparing him a room in the courts of God’s house.\n'),
	(7876, 13, 13, 8, 'It grieved me severely. Therefore I threw all Tobiah’s household stuff out of the room.\n'),
	(7877, 13, 13, 9, 'Then I commanded, and they cleansed the rooms. I brought into them the vessels of God’s house, with the meal offerings and the frankincense again.\n'),
	(7878, 13, 13, 10, 'I perceived that the portions of the Levites had not been given them; so that the Levites and the singers, who did the work, had each fled to his field.\n'),
	(7879, 13, 13, 11, 'Then I contended with the rulers, and said, “Why is God’s house forsaken?” I gathered them together, and set them in their place.\n'),
	(7880, 13, 13, 12, 'Then all Judah brought the tithe of the grain, the new wine, and the oil to the treasuries.\n'),
	(7881, 13, 13, 13, 'I made treasurers over the treasuries, Shelemiah the priest, and Zadok the scribe, and of the Levites, Pedaiah: and next to them was Hanan the son of Zaccur, the son of Mattaniah; for they were counted faithful, and their business was to distribute to their brothers.\n'),
	(7882, 13, 13, 14, 'Remember me, my God, concerning this, and don’t wipe out my good deeds that I have done for the house of my God, and for its observances.\n'),
	(7883, 13, 13, 15, 'In those days saw I in Judah some men treading wine presses on the Sabbath, bringing in sheaves, and loading donkeys; also with wine, grapes, figs, and all kinds of burdens, which they brought into Jerusalem on the Sabbath day; and I testified against them in the day in which they sold food.\n'),
	(7884, 13, 13, 16, 'Some men of Tyre also lived there, who brought in fish and all kinds of wares, and sold on the Sabbath to the children of Judah, and in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(7885, 13, 13, 17, 'Then I contended with the nobles of Judah, and said to them, “What evil thing is this that you do, and profane the Sabbath day?\n'),
	(7886, 13, 13, 18, 'Didn’t your fathers do thus, and didn’t our God bring all this evil on us, and on this city? Yet you bring more wrath on Israel by profaning the Sabbath.”\n'),
	(7887, 13, 13, 19, 'It came to pass that when the gates of Jerusalem began to be dark before the Sabbath, I commanded that the doors should be shut, and commanded that they should not be opened until after the Sabbath. I set some of my servants over the gates, so that no burden should be brought in on the Sabbath day.\n'),
	(7888, 13, 13, 20, 'So the merchants and sellers of all kinds of wares camped outside of Jerusalem once or twice.\n'),
	(7889, 13, 13, 21, 'Then I testified against them, and said to them, “Why do you stay around the wall? If you do so again, I will lay hands on you.” From that time on, they didn’t come on the Sabbath.\n'),
	(7890, 13, 13, 22, 'I commanded the Levites that they should purify themselves, and that they should come and keep the gates, to sanctify the Sabbath day. Remember to me, my God, this also, and spare me according to the greatness of your loving kindness.\n'),
	(7891, 13, 13, 23, 'In those days I also saw the Jews who had married women of Ashdod, of Ammon, and of Moab;\n'),
	(7892, 13, 13, 24, 'and their children spoke half in the speech of Ashdod, and could not speak in the Jews’ language, but according to the language of each people.\n'),
	(7893, 13, 13, 25, 'I contended with them, and cursed them, and struck certain of them, and plucked off their hair, and made them swear by God, “You shall not give your daughters to their sons, nor take their daughters for your sons, or for yourselves.\n'),
	(7894, 13, 13, 26, 'Didn’t Solomon king of Israel sin by these things? Yet among many nations was there no king like him, and he was beloved of his God, and God made him king over all Israel. Nevertheless foreign women caused even him to sin.\n'),
	(7895, 13, 13, 27, 'Shall we then listen to you to do all this great evil, to trespass against our God in marrying foreign women?”\n'),
	(7896, 13, 13, 28, 'One of the sons of Joiada, the son of Eliashib the high priest, was son-in-law to Sanballat the Horonite; therefore I chased him from me.\n'),
	(7897, 13, 13, 29, 'Remember them, my God, because they have defiled the priesthood, and the covenant of the priesthood and of the Levites.\n'),
	(7898, 13, 13, 30, 'Thus I cleansed them from all foreigners, and appointed duties for the priests and for the Levites, everyone in his work;\n'),
	(7899, 13, 13, 31, 'and for the wood offering, at times appointed, and for the first fruits. Remember me, my God, for good.\n'),
	(7900, 14, 1, 1, 'Now in the days of Ahasuerus (this is Ahasuerus who reigned from India even to Ethiopia, over one hundred twenty-seven provinces),\n'),
	(7901, 14, 1, 2, 'in those days, when the King Ahasuerus sat on the throne of his kingdom, which was in Shushan the palace,\n'),
	(7902, 14, 1, 3, 'in the third year of his reign, he made a feast for all his princes and his servants; the power of Persia and Media, the nobles and princes of the provinces, being before him.\n'),
	(7903, 14, 1, 4, 'He displayed the riches of his glorious kingdom and the honor of his excellent majesty many days, even one hundred eighty days.\n'),
	(7904, 14, 1, 5, 'When these days were fulfilled, the king made a seven day feast for all the people who were present in Shushan the palace, both great and small, in the court of the garden of the king’s palace.\n'),
	(7905, 14, 1, 6, 'There were hangings of white, green, and blue material, fastened with cords of fine linen and purple to silver rings and marble pillars. The couches were of gold and silver, on a pavement of red, white, yellow, and black marble.\n'),
	(7906, 14, 1, 7, 'They gave them drinks in golden vessels of various kinds, including royal wine in abundance, according to the bounty of the king.\n'),
	(7907, 14, 1, 8, 'In accordance with the law, the drinking was not compulsory; for so the king had instructed all the officials of his house, that they should do according to every man’s pleasure.\n'),
	(7908, 14, 1, 9, 'Also Vashti the queen made a feast for the women in the royal house which belonged to King Ahasuerus.\n'),
	(7909, 14, 1, 10, 'On the seventh day, when the heart of the king was merry with wine, he commanded Mehuman, Biztha, Harbona, Bigtha, and Abagtha, Zethar, and Carcass, the seven eunuchs who served in the presence of Ahasuerus the king,\n'),
	(7910, 14, 1, 11, 'to bring Vashti the queen before the king with the royal crown, to show the people and the princes her beauty; for she was beautiful.\n'),
	(7911, 14, 1, 12, 'But the queen Vashti refused to come at the king’s commandment by the eunuchs. Therefore the king was very angry, and his anger burned in him.\n'),
	(7912, 14, 1, 13, 'Then the king said to the wise men, who knew the times (for it was the king’s custom to consult those who knew law and judgment;\n'),
	(7913, 14, 1, 14, 'and the next to him were Carshena, Shethar, Admatha, Tarshish, Meres, Marsena, and Memucan, the seven princes of Persia and Media, who saw the king’s face, and sat first in the kingdom),\n'),
	(7914, 14, 1, 15, '“What shall we do to the queen Vashti according to law, because she has not done the bidding of the King Ahasuerus by the eunuchs?”\n'),
	(7915, 14, 1, 16, 'Memucan answered before the king and the princes, “Vashti the queen has not done wrong to just the king, but also to all the princes, and to all the people who are in all the provinces of the King Ahasuerus.\n'),
	(7916, 14, 1, 17, 'For this deed of the queen will become known to all women, causing them to show contempt for their husbands, when it is reported, ‘King Ahasuerus commanded Vashti the queen to be brought in before him, but she didn’t come.’\n'),
	(7917, 14, 1, 18, 'Today, the princesses of Persia and Media who have heard of the queen’s deed will tell all the king’s princes. This will cause much contempt and wrath.\n'),
	(7918, 14, 1, 19, '“If it pleases the king, let a royal commandment go from him, and let it be written among the laws of the Persians and the Medes, so that it cannot be altered, that Vashti may never again come before King Ahasuerus; and let the king give her royal estate to another who is better than she.\n'),
	(7919, 14, 1, 20, 'When the king’s decree which he shall make is published throughout all his kingdom (for it is great), all the wives will give their husbands honor, both great and small.”\n'),
	(7920, 14, 1, 21, 'This advice pleased the king and the princes, and the king did according to the word of Memucan:\n'),
	(7921, 14, 1, 22, 'for he sent letters into all the king’s provinces, into every province according to its writing, and to every people in their language, that every man should rule his own house, speaking in the language of his own people.\n'),
	(7922, 14, 2, 1, 'After these things, when the wrath of King Ahasuerus was pacified, he remembered Vashti, and what she had done, and what was decreed against her.\n'),
	(7923, 14, 2, 2, 'Then the king’s servants who served him said, “Let beautiful young virgins be sought for the king.\n'),
	(7924, 14, 2, 3, 'Let the king appoint officers in all the provinces of his kingdom, that they may gather together all the beautiful young virgins to the citadel of Susa, to the women’s house, to the custody of Hegai the king’s eunuch, keeper of the women. Let cosmetics be given them;\n'),
	(7925, 14, 2, 4, 'and let the maiden who pleases the king be queen instead of Vashti.” The thing pleased the king, and he did so.\n'),
	(7926, 14, 2, 5, 'There was a certain Jew in the citadel of Susa, whose name was Mordecai, the son of Jair, the son of Shimei, the son of Kish, a Benjamite,\n'),
	(7927, 14, 2, 6, 'who had been carried away from Jerusalem with the captives who had been carried away with Jeconiah king of Judah, whom Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon had carried away.\n'),
	(7928, 14, 2, 7, 'He brought up Hadassah, that is, Esther, his uncle’s daughter; for she had neither father nor mother. The maiden was fair and beautiful; and when her father and mother were dead, Mordecai took her for his own daughter.\n'),
	(7929, 14, 2, 8, 'So, when the king’s commandment and his decree was heard, and when many maidens were gathered together to the citadel of Susa, to the custody of Hegai, Esther was taken into the king’s house, to the custody of Hegai, keeper of the women.\n'),
	(7930, 14, 2, 9, 'The maiden pleased him, and she obtained kindness from him. He quickly gave her cosmetics and her portions of food, and the seven choice maidens who were to be given her out of the king’s house. He moved her and her maidens to the best place in the women’s house.\n'),
	(7931, 14, 2, 10, 'Esther had not made known her people nor her relatives, because Mordecai had instructed her that she should not make it known.\n'),
	(7932, 14, 2, 11, 'Mordecai walked every day in front of the court of the women’s house, to find out how Esther was doing, and what would become of her.\n'),
	(7933, 14, 2, 12, 'Each young woman’s turn came to go in to King Ahasuerus after her purification for twelve months (for so were the days of their purification accomplished, six months with oil of myrrh, and six months with sweet fragrances and with preparations for beautifying women).\n'),
	(7934, 14, 2, 13, 'The young woman then came to the king like this: whatever she desired was given her to go with her out of the women’s house to the king’s house.\n'),
	(7935, 14, 2, 14, 'In the evening she went, and on the next day she returned into the second women’s house, to the custody of Shaashgaz, the king’s eunuch, who kept the concubines. She came in to the king no more, unless the king delighted in her, and she was called by name.\n'),
	(7936, 14, 2, 15, 'Now when the turn of Esther, the daughter of Abihail the uncle of Mordecai, who had taken her for his daughter, came to go in to the king, she required nothing but what Hegai the king’s eunuch, the keeper of the women, advised. Esther obtained favor in the sight of all those who looked at her.\n'),
	(7937, 14, 2, 16, 'So Esther was taken to King Ahasuerus into his royal house in the tenth month, which is the month Tebeth, in the seventh year of his reign.\n'),
	(7938, 14, 2, 17, 'The king loved Esther more than all the women, and she obtained favor and kindness in his sight more than all the virgins; so that he set the royal crown on her head, and made her queen instead of Vashti.\n'),
	(7939, 14, 2, 18, 'Then the king made a great feast for all his princes and his servants, even Esther’s feast; and he proclaimed a holiday in the provinces, and gave gifts according to the king’s bounty.\n'),
	(7940, 14, 2, 19, 'When the virgins were gathered together the second time, Mordecai was sitting in the king’s gate.\n'),
	(7941, 14, 2, 20, 'Esther had not yet made known her relatives nor her people, as Mordecai had commanded her; for Esther obeyed Mordecai, like she did when she was brought up by him.\n'),
	(7942, 14, 2, 21, 'In those days, while Mordecai was sitting in the king’s gate, two of the king’s eunuchs, Bigthan and Teresh, who were doorkeepers, were angry, and sought to lay hands on the King Ahasuerus.\n'),
	(7943, 14, 2, 22, 'This thing became known to Mordecai, who informed Esther the queen; and Esther informed the king in Mordecai’s name.\n'),
	(7944, 14, 2, 23, 'When this matter was investigated, and it was found to be so, they were both hanged on a tree; and it was written in the book of the chronicles in the king’s presence.\n'),
	(7945, 14, 3, 1, 'After these things King Ahasuerus promoted Haman the son of Hammedatha the Agagite, and advanced him, and set his seat above all the princes who were with him.\n'),
	(7946, 14, 3, 2, 'All the king’s servants who were in the king’s gate bowed down, and paid homage to Haman; for the king had so commanded concerning him. But Mordecai didn’t bow down or pay him homage.\n'),
	(7947, 14, 3, 3, 'Then the king’s servants, who were in the king’s gate, said to Mordecai, “Why do you disobey the king’s commandment?”\n'),
	(7948, 14, 3, 4, 'Now it came to pass, when they spoke daily to him, and he didn’t listen to them, that they told Haman, to see whether Mordecai’s reason would stand; for he had told them that he was a Jew.\n'),
	(7949, 14, 3, 5, 'When Haman saw that Mordecai didn’t bow down, nor pay him homage, Haman was full of wrath.\n'),
	(7950, 14, 3, 6, 'But he scorned the thought of laying hands on Mordecai alone, for they had made known to him Mordecai’s people. Therefore Haman sought to destroy all the Jews who were throughout the whole kingdom of Ahasuerus, even Mordecai’s people.\n'),
	(7951, 14, 3, 7, 'In the first month, which is the month Nisan, in the twelfth year of King Ahasuerus, they cast Pur, that is, the lot, before Haman from day to day, and from month to month, and chose the twelfth month, which is the month Adar.\n'),
	(7952, 14, 3, 8, 'Haman said to King Ahasuerus, “There is a certain people scattered abroad and dispersed among the peoples in all the provinces of your kingdom, and their laws are different than other people’s. They don’t keep the king’s laws. Therefore it is not for the king’s profit to allow them to remain.\n'),
	(7953, 14, 3, 9, 'If it pleases the king, let it be written that they be destroyed; and I will pay ten thousand talents of silver into the hands of those who are in charge of the king’s business, to bring it into the king’s treasuries.”\n'),
	(7954, 14, 3, 10, 'The king took his ring from his hand, and gave it to Haman the son of Hammedatha the Agagite, the Jews’ enemy.\n'),
	(7955, 14, 3, 11, 'The king said to Haman, “The silver is given to you, the people also, to do with them as it seems good to you.”\n'),
	(7956, 14, 3, 12, 'Then the king’s scribes were called in on the first month, on the thirteenth day of the month; and all that Haman commanded was written to the king’s satraps, and to the governors who were over every province, and to the princes of every people, to every province according to its writing, and to every people in their language. It was written in the name of King Ahasuerus, and it was sealed with the king’s ring.\n'),
	(7957, 14, 3, 13, 'Letters were sent by couriers into all the king’s provinces, to destroy, to kill, and to cause to perish, all Jews, both young and old, little children and women, in one day, even on the thirteenth day of the twelfth month, which is the month Adar, and to plunder their possessions.\n'),
	(7958, 14, 3, 14, 'A copy of the letter, that the decree should be given out in every province, was published to all the peoples, that they should be ready against that day.\n'),
	(7959, 14, 3, 15, 'The couriers went out in haste by the king’s commandment, and the decree was given out in the citadel of Susa. The king and Haman sat down to drink; but the city of Shushan was perplexed.\n'),
	(7960, 14, 4, 1, 'Now when Mordecai found out all that was done, Mordecai tore his clothes, and put on sackcloth with ashes, and went out into the middle of the city, and wailed loudly and bitterly.\n'),
	(7961, 14, 4, 2, 'He came even before the king’s gate, for no one is allowed inside the king’s gate clothed with sackcloth.\n'),
	(7962, 14, 4, 3, 'In every province, wherever the king’s commandment and his decree came, there was great mourning among the Jews, and fasting, and weeping, and wailing; and many lay in sackcloth and ashes.\n'),
	(7963, 14, 4, 4, 'Esther’s maidens and her eunuchs came and told her this, and the queen was exceedingly grieved. She sent clothing to Mordecai, to replace his sackcloth; but he didn’t receive it.\n'),
	(7964, 14, 4, 5, 'Then Esther called for Hathach, one of the king’s eunuchs, whom he had appointed to attend her, and commanded him to go to Mordecai, to find out what this was, and why it was.\n'),
	(7965, 14, 4, 6, 'So Hathach went out to Mordecai, to city square which was before the king’s gate.\n'),
	(7966, 14, 4, 7, 'Mordecai told him of all that had happened to him, and the exact sum of the money that Haman had promised to pay to the king’s treasuries for the destruction of the Jews.\n'),
	(7967, 14, 4, 8, 'He also gave him the copy of the writing of the decree that was given out in Shushan to destroy them, to show it to Esther, and to declare it to her, and to urge her to go in to the king, to make supplication to him, and to make request before him, for her people.\n'),
	(7968, 14, 4, 9, 'Hathach came and told Esther the words of Mordecai.\n'),
	(7969, 14, 4, 10, 'Then Esther spoke to Hathach, and gave him a message to Mordecai:\n'),
	(7970, 14, 4, 11, '“All the king’s servants, and the people of the king’s provinces, know, that whoever, whether man or woman, comes to the king into the inner court without being called, there is one law for him, that he be put to death, except those to whom the king might hold out the golden scepter, that he may live. I have not been called to come in to the king these thirty days.”\n'),
	(7971, 14, 4, 12, 'They told to Mordecai Esther’s words.\n'),
	(7972, 14, 4, 13, 'Then Mordecai asked them to return this answer to Esther: “Don’t think to yourself that you will escape in the king’s house any more than all the Jews.\n'),
	(7973, 14, 4, 14, 'For if you remain silent now, then relief and deliverance will come to the Jews from another place, but you and your father’s house will perish. Who knows if you haven’t come to the kingdom for such a time as this?”\n'),
	(7974, 14, 4, 15, 'Then Esther asked them to answer Mordecai,\n'),
	(7975, 14, 4, 16, '“Go, gather together all the Jews who are present in Shushan, and fast for me, and neither eat nor drink three days, night or day. I and my maidens will also fast the same way. Then I will go in to the king, which is against the law; and if I perish, I perish.”\n'),
	(7976, 14, 4, 17, 'So Mordecai went his way, and did according to all that Esther had commanded him.\n'),
	(7977, 14, 5, 1, 'Now on the third day, Esther put on her royal clothing, and stood in the inner court of the king’s house, next to the king’s house. The king sat on his royal throne in the royal house, next to the entrance of the house.\n'),
	(7978, 14, 5, 2, 'When the king saw Esther the queen standing in the court, she obtained favor in his sight; and the king held out to Esther the golden scepter that was in his hand. So Esther came near, and touched the top of the scepter.\n'),
	(7979, 14, 5, 3, 'Then the king asked her, “What would you like, queen Esther? What is your request? It shall be given you even to the half of the kingdom.”\n'),
	(7980, 14, 5, 4, 'Esther said, “If it seems good to the king, let the king and Haman come today to the banquet that I have prepared for him.”\n'),
	(7981, 14, 5, 5, 'Then the king said, “Bring Haman quickly, so that it may be done as Esther has said.” So the king and Haman came to the banquet that Esther had prepared.\n'),
	(7982, 14, 5, 6, 'The king said to Esther at the banquet of wine, “What is your petition? It shall be granted you. What is your request? Even to the half of the kingdom it shall be performed.”\n'),
	(7983, 14, 5, 7, 'Then Esther answered and said, “My petition and my request is this.\n'),
	(7984, 14, 5, 8, 'If I have found favor in the sight of the king, and if it pleases the king to grant my petition and to perform my request, let the king and Haman come to the banquet that I will prepare for them, and I will do tomorrow as the king has said.”\n'),
	(7985, 14, 5, 9, 'Then Haman went out that day joyful and glad of heart, but when Haman saw Mordecai in the king’s gate, that he didn’t stand up nor move for him, he was filled with wrath against Mordecai.\n'),
	(7986, 14, 5, 10, 'Nevertheless Haman restrained himself, and went home. There, he sent and called for his friends and Zeresh his wife.\n'),
	(7987, 14, 5, 11, 'Haman recounted to them the glory of his riches, the multitude of his children, all the things in which the king had promoted him, and how he had advanced him above the princes and servants of the king.\n'),
	(7988, 14, 5, 12, 'Haman also said, “Yes, Esther the queen let no man come in with the king to the banquet that she had prepared but myself; and tomorrow I am also invited by her together with the king.\n'),
	(7989, 14, 5, 13, 'Yet all this avails me nothing, so long as I see Mordecai the Jew sitting at the king’s gate.”\n'),
	(7990, 14, 5, 14, 'Then Zeresh his wife and all his friends said to him, “Let a gallows be made fifty cubits high, and in the morning speak to the king about hanging Mordecai on it. Then go in merrily with the king to the banquet.” This pleased Haman, so he had the gallows made.\n'),
	(7991, 14, 6, 1, 'On that night, the king couldn’t sleep. He commanded the book of records of the chronicles to be brought, and they were read to the king.\n'),
	(7992, 14, 6, 2, 'It was found written that Mordecai had told of Bigthana and Teresh, two of the king’s eunuchs, who were doorkeepers, who had tried to lay hands on the King Ahasuerus.\n'),
	(7993, 14, 6, 3, 'The king said, “What honor and dignity has been given to Mordecai for this?”\nThen the king’s servants who attended him said, “Nothing has been done for him.”\n'),
	(7994, 14, 6, 4, 'The king said, “Who is in the court?” Now Haman had come into the outer court of the king’s house, to speak to the king about hanging Mordecai on the gallows that he had prepared for him.\n'),
	(7995, 14, 6, 5, 'The king’s servants said to him, “Behold, Haman stands in the court.”\nThe king said, “Let him come in.”\n'),
	(7996, 14, 6, 6, 'So Haman came in. The king said to him, “What shall be done to the man whom the king delights to honor?”\nNow Haman said in his heart, “Who would the king delight to honor more than myself?”\n'),
	(7997, 14, 6, 7, 'Haman said to the king, “For the man whom the king delights to honor,\n'),
	(7998, 14, 6, 8, 'let royal clothing be brought which the king uses to wear, and the horse that the king rides on, and on the head of which a crown royal is set.\n'),
	(7999, 14, 6, 9, 'Let the clothing and the horse be delivered to the hand of one of the king’s most noble princes, that they may array the man whom the king delights to honor with them, and have him ride on horseback through the city square, and proclaim before him, ‘Thus shall it be done to the man whom the king delights to honor!’”\n'),
	(8000, 14, 6, 10, 'Then the king said to Haman, “Hurry and take the clothing and the horse, as you have said, and do this for Mordecai the Jew, who sits at the king’s gate. Let nothing fail of all that you have spoken.”\n'),
	(8001, 14, 6, 11, 'Then Haman took the clothing and the horse, and arrayed Mordecai, and had him ride through the city square, and proclaimed before him, “Thus shall it be done to the man whom the king delights to honor!”\n'),
	(8002, 14, 6, 12, 'Mordecai came back to the king’s gate, but Haman hurried to his house, mourning and having his head covered.\n'),
	(8003, 14, 6, 13, 'Haman recounted to Zeresh his wife and all his friends everything that had happened to him. Then his wise men and Zeresh his wife said to him, “If Mordecai, before whom you have begun to fall, is of Jewish descent, you will not prevail against him, but you will surely fall before him.”\n'),
	(8004, 14, 6, 14, 'While they were yet talking with him, the king’s eunuchs came, and hurried to bring Haman to the banquet that Esther had prepared.\n'),
	(8005, 14, 7, 1, 'So the king and Haman came to banquet with Esther the queen.\n'),
	(8006, 14, 7, 2, 'The king said again to Esther on the second day at the banquet of wine, “What is your petition, queen Esther? It shall be granted you. What is your request? Even to the half of the kingdom it shall be performed.”\n'),
	(8007, 14, 7, 3, 'Then Esther the queen answered, “If I have found favor in your sight, O king, and if it pleases the king, let my life be given me at my petition, and my people at my request.\n'),
	(8008, 14, 7, 4, 'For we are sold, I and my people, to be destroyed, to be slain, and to perish. But if we had been sold for male and female slaves, I would have held my peace, although the adversary could not have compensated for the king’s loss.”\n'),
	(8009, 14, 7, 5, 'Then King Ahasuerus said to Esther the queen, “Who is he, and where is he who dared presume in his heart to do so?”\n'),
	(8010, 14, 7, 6, 'Esther said, “An adversary and an enemy, even this wicked Haman!”\nThen Haman was afraid before the king and the queen.\n'),
	(8011, 14, 7, 7, 'The king arose in his wrath from the banquet of wine and went into the palace garden. Haman stood up to make request for his life to Esther the queen; for he saw that there was evil determined against him by the king.\n'),
	(8012, 14, 7, 8, 'Then the king returned out of the palace garden into the place of the banquet of wine; and Haman had fallen on the couch where Esther was. Then the king said, “Will he even assault the queen in front of me in the house?” As the word went out of the king’s mouth, they covered Haman’s face.\n'),
	(8013, 14, 7, 9, 'Then Harbonah, one of the eunuchs who were with the king said, “Behold, the gallows fifty cubits high, which Haman has made for Mordecai, who spoke good for the king, is standing at Haman’s house.”\nThe king said, “Hang him on it!”\n'),
	(8014, 14, 7, 10, 'So they hanged Haman on the gallows that he had prepared for Mordecai. Then was the king’s wrath pacified.\n'),
	(8015, 14, 8, 1, 'On that day, King Ahasuerus gave the house of Haman, the Jews’ enemy, to Esther the queen. Mordecai came before the king; for Esther had told what he was to her.\n'),
	(8016, 14, 8, 2, 'The king took off his ring, which he had taken from Haman, and gave it to Mordecai. Esther set Mordecai over the house of Haman.\n'),
	(8017, 14, 8, 3, 'Esther spoke yet again before the king, and fell down at his feet, and begged him with tears to put away the mischief of Haman the Agagite, and his plan that he had planned against the Jews.\n'),
	(8018, 14, 8, 4, 'Then the king held out to Esther the golden scepter. So Esther arose, and stood before the king.\n'),
	(8019, 14, 8, 5, 'She said, “If it pleases the king, and if I have found favor in his sight, and the thing seem right to the king, and I am pleasing in his eyes, let it be written to reverse the letters devised by Haman, the son of Hammedatha the Agagite, which he wrote to destroy the Jews who are in all the king’s provinces.\n'),
	(8020, 14, 8, 6, 'For how can I endure to see the evil that would come to my people? How can I endure to see the destruction of my relatives?”\n'),
	(8021, 14, 8, 7, 'Then King Ahasuerus said to Esther the queen and to Mordecai the Jew, “See, I have given Esther the house of Haman, and him they have hanged on the gallows, because he laid his hand on the Jews.\n'),
	(8022, 14, 8, 8, 'Write also to the Jews, as it pleases you, in the king’s name, and seal it with the king’s ring; for the writing which is written in the king’s name, and sealed with the king’s ring, may not be reversed by any man.”\n'),
	(8023, 14, 8, 9, 'Then the king’s scribes were called at that time, in the third month, which is the month Sivan, on the twenty-third day of the month; and it was written according to all that Mordecai commanded to the Jews, and to the satraps, and the governors and princes of the provinces which are from India to Ethiopia, one hundred twenty-seven provinces, to every province according to its writing, and to every people in their language, and to the Jews in their writing, and in their language.\n'),
	(8024, 14, 8, 10, 'He wrote in the name of King Ahasuerus, and sealed it with the king’s ring, and sent letters by courier on horseback, riding on royal horses that were bred from swift steeds.\n'),
	(8025, 14, 8, 11, 'In those letters, the king granted the Jews who were in every city to gather themselves together, and to defend their life, to destroy, to kill, and to cause to perish, all the power of the people and province that would assault them, their little ones and women, and to plunder their possessions,\n'),
	(8026, 14, 8, 12, 'on one day in all the provinces of King Ahasuerus, on the thirteenth day of the twelfth month, which is the month Adar.\n'),
	(8027, 14, 8, 13, 'A copy of the letter, that the decree should be given out in every province, was published to all the peoples, that the Jews should be ready for that day to avenge themselves on their enemies.\n'),
	(8028, 14, 8, 14, 'So the couriers who rode on royal horses went out, hastened and pressed on by the king’s commandment. The decree was given out in the citadel of Susa.\n'),
	(8029, 14, 8, 15, 'Mordecai went out of the presence of the king in royal clothing of blue and white, and with a great crown of gold, and with a robe of fine linen and purple; and the city of Susa shouted and was glad.\n'),
	(8030, 14, 8, 16, 'The Jews had light, gladness, joy, and honor.\n'),
	(8031, 14, 8, 17, 'In every province, and in every city, wherever the king’s commandment and his decree came, the Jews had gladness, joy, a feast, and a good day. Many from among the peoples of the land became Jews; for the fear of the Jews was fallen on them.\n'),
	(8032, 14, 9, 1, 'Now in the twelfth month, which is the month Adar, on the thirteenth day of the month, when the king’s commandment and his decree came near to be put in execution, on the day that the enemies of the Jews hoped to conquer them, (but it was turned out the opposite happened, that the Jews conquered those who hated them),\n'),
	(8033, 14, 9, 2, 'the Jews gathered themselves together in their cities throughout all the provinces of the King Ahasuerus, to lay hands on those who wanted to harm them. No one could withstand them, because the fear of them had fallen on all the people.\n'),
	(8034, 14, 9, 3, 'All the princes of the provinces, the satraps, the governors, and those who did the king’s business helped the Jews, because the fear of Mordecai had fallen on them.\n'),
	(8035, 14, 9, 4, 'For Mordecai was great in the king’s house, and his fame went out throughout all the provinces; for the man Mordecai grew greater and greater.\n'),
	(8036, 14, 9, 5, 'The Jews struck all their enemies with the stroke of the sword, and with slaughter and destruction, and did what they wanted to those who hated them.\n'),
	(8037, 14, 9, 6, 'In the citadel of Susa, the Jews killed and destroyed five hundred men.\n'),
	(8038, 14, 9, 7, 'They killed Parshandatha, Dalphon, Aspatha,\n'),
	(8039, 14, 9, 8, 'Poratha, Adalia, Aridatha,\n'),
	(8040, 14, 9, 9, 'Parmashta, Arisai, Aridai, and Vaizatha,\n'),
	(8041, 14, 9, 10, 'the ten sons of Haman the son of Hammedatha, the Jews’ enemy, but they didn’t lay their hand on the plunder.\n'),
	(8042, 14, 9, 11, 'On that day, the number of those who were slain in the citadel of Susa was brought before the king.\n'),
	(8043, 14, 9, 12, 'The king said to Esther the queen, “The Jews have slain and destroyed five hundred men in the citadel of Susa, including the ten sons of Haman; what then have they done in the rest of the king’s provinces! Now what is your petition? It shall be granted you. What is your further request? It shall be done.”\n'),
	(8044, 14, 9, 13, 'Then Esther said, “If it pleases the king, let it be granted to the Jews who are in Shushan to do tomorrow also according to today’s decree, and let Haman’s ten sons be hanged on the gallows.”\n'),
	(8045, 14, 9, 14, 'The king commanded this to be done. A decree was given out in Shushan; and they hanged Haman’s ten sons.\n'),
	(8046, 14, 9, 15, 'The Jews who were in Shushan gathered themselves together on the fourteenth day also of the month Adar, and killed three hundred men in Shushan; but they didn’t lay their hand on the plunder.\n'),
	(8047, 14, 9, 16, 'The other Jews who were in the king’s provinces gathered themselves together, defended their lives, had rest from their enemies, and killed seventy-five thousand of those who hated them; but they didn’t lay their hand on the plunder.\n'),
	(8048, 14, 9, 17, 'This was done on the thirteenth day of the month Adar; and on the fourteenth day of that month they rested and made it a day of feasting and gladness.\n'),
	(8049, 14, 9, 18, 'But the Jews who were in Shushan assembled together on the thirteenth and on the fourteenth days of the month; and on the fifteenth day of that month, they rested, and made it a day of feasting and gladness.\n'),
	(8050, 14, 9, 19, 'Therefore the Jews of the villages, who live in the unwalled towns, make the fourteenth day of the month Adar a day of gladness and feasting, a good day, and a day of sending presents of food to one another.\n'),
	(8051, 14, 9, 20, 'Mordecai wrote these things, and sent letters to all the Jews who were in all the provinces of the king Ahasuerus, both near and far,\n'),
	(8052, 14, 9, 21, 'to enjoin them that they should keep the fourteenth and fifteenth days of the month Adar yearly,\n'),
	(8053, 14, 9, 22, 'as the days in which the Jews had rest from their enemies, and the month which was turned to them from sorrow to gladness, and from mourning into a good day; that they should make them days of feasting and gladness, and of sending presents of food to one another, and gifts to the needy.\n'),
	(8054, 14, 9, 23, 'The Jews accepted the custom that they had begun, as Mordecai had written to them;\n'),
	(8055, 14, 9, 24, 'because Haman the son of Hammedatha, the Agagite, the enemy of all the Jews, had plotted against the Jews to destroy them, and had cast “Pur”, that is the lot, to consume them, and to destroy them;\n'),
	(8056, 14, 9, 25, 'but when this became known to the king, he commanded by letters that his wicked plan, which he had planned against the Jews, should return on his own head, and that he and his sons should be hanged on the gallows.\n'),
	(8057, 14, 9, 26, 'Therefore they called these days “Purim”, from the word “Pur.” Therefore because of all the words of this letter, and of that which they had seen concerning this matter, and that which had come to them,\n'),
	(8058, 14, 9, 27, 'the Jews established, and imposed on themselves, and on their descendants, and on all those who joined themselves to them, so that it should not fail, that they would keep these two days according to what was written, and according to its appointed time, every year;\n'),
	(8059, 14, 9, 28, 'and that these days should be remembered and kept throughout every generation, every family, every province, and every city; and that these days of Purim should not fail from among the Jews, nor their memory perish from their offspring,\n'),
	(8060, 14, 9, 29, 'Then Esther the queen, the daughter of Abihail, and Mordecai the Jew, wrote with all authority to confirm this second letter of Purim.\n'),
	(8061, 14, 9, 30, 'He sent letters to all the Jews, to the hundred twenty-seven provinces of the kingdom of Ahasuerus, with words of peace and truth,\n'),
	(8062, 14, 9, 31, 'to confirm these days of Purim in their appointed times, as Mordecai the Jew and Esther the queen had decreed, and as they had imposed upon themselves and their descendants, in the matter of the fastings and their cry.\n'),
	(8063, 14, 9, 32, 'The commandment of Esther confirmed these matters of Purim; and it was written in the book.\n'),
	(8064, 14, 10, 1, 'King Ahasuerus laid a tribute on the land, and on the islands of the sea.\n'),
	(8065, 14, 10, 2, 'All the acts of his power and of his might, and the full account of the greatness of Mordecai, to which the king advanced him, aren’t they written in the book of the chronicles of the kings of Media and Persia?\n'),
	(8066, 14, 10, 3, 'For Mordecai the Jew was next to King Ahasuerus, and great among the Jews, and accepted by the multitude of his brothers, seeking the good of his people, and speaking peace to all his descendants.\n'),
	(8067, 15, 1, 1, 'There was a man in the land of Uz, whose name was Job. That man was blameless and upright, and one who feared God, and turned away from evil.\n'),
	(8068, 15, 1, 2, 'There were born to him seven sons and three daughters.\n'),
	(8069, 15, 1, 3, 'His possessions also were seven thousand sheep, three thousand camels, five hundred yoke of oxen, five hundred female donkeys, and a very great household; so that this man was the greatest of all the children of the east.\n'),
	(8070, 15, 1, 4, 'His sons went and held a feast in the house of each one on his birthday; and they sent and called for their three sisters to eat and to drink with them.\n'),
	(8071, 15, 1, 5, 'It was so, when the days of their feasting had run their course, that Job sent and sanctified them, and rose up early in the morning, and offered burnt offerings according to the number of them all. For Job said, “It may be that my sons have sinned, and renounced God in their hearts.” Job did so continually.\n'),
	(8072, 15, 1, 6, 'Now on the day when God’s sons came to present themselves before Yahweh, Satan also came among them.\n'),
	(8073, 15, 1, 7, 'Yahweh said to Satan, “Where have you come from?”\nThen Satan answered Yahweh, and said, “From going back and forth in the earth, and from walking up and down in it.”\n'),
	(8074, 15, 1, 8, 'Yahweh said to Satan, “Have you considered my servant, Job? For there is no one like him in the earth, a blameless and an upright man, one who fears God, and turns away from evil.”\n'),
	(8075, 15, 1, 9, 'Then Satan answered Yahweh, and said, “Does Job fear God for nothing?\n'),
	(8076, 15, 1, 10, 'Haven’t you made a hedge around him, and around his house, and around all that he has, on every side? You have blessed the work of his hands, and his substance is increased in the land.\n'),
	(8077, 15, 1, 11, 'But stretch out your hand now, and touch all that he has, and he will renounce you to your face.”\n'),
	(8078, 15, 1, 12, 'Yahweh said to Satan, “Behold, all that he has is in your power. Only on himself don’t stretch out your hand.”\nSo Satan went out from the presence of Yahweh.\n'),
	(8079, 15, 1, 13, 'It fell on a day when his sons and his daughters were eating and drinking wine in their oldest brother’s house,\n'),
	(8080, 15, 1, 14, 'that there came a messenger to Job, and said, “The oxen were plowing, and the donkeys feeding beside them,\n'),
	(8081, 15, 1, 15, 'and the Sabeans attacked, and took them away. Yes, they have killed the servants with the edge of the sword, and I alone have escaped to tell you.”\n'),
	(8082, 15, 1, 16, 'While he was still speaking, there also came another, and said, “The fire of God has fallen from the sky, and has burned up the sheep and the servants, and consumed them, and I alone have escaped to tell you.”\n'),
	(8083, 15, 1, 17, 'While he was still speaking, there came also another, and said, “The Chaldeans made three bands, and swept down on the camels, and have taken them away, yes, and killed the servants with the edge of the sword; and I alone have escaped to tell you.”\n'),
	(8084, 15, 1, 18, 'While he was still speaking, there came also another, and said, “Your sons and your daughters were eating and drinking wine in their oldest brother’s house,\n'),
	(8085, 15, 1, 19, 'and behold, there came a great wind from the wilderness, and struck the four corners of the house, and it fell on the young men, and they are dead. I alone have escaped to tell you.”\n'),
	(8086, 15, 1, 20, 'Then Job arose, and tore his robe, and shaved his head, and fell down on the ground, and worshiped.\n'),
	(8087, 15, 1, 21, 'He said, “Naked I came out of my mother’s womb, and naked shall I return there. Yahweh gave, and Yahweh has taken away. Blessed be Yahweh’s name.”\n'),
	(8088, 15, 1, 22, 'In all this, Job did not sin, nor charge God with wrongdoing.\n'),
	(8089, 15, 2, 1, 'Again, on the day when the God’s sons came to present themselves before Yahweh, Satan came also among them to present himself before Yahweh.\n'),
	(8090, 15, 2, 2, 'Yahweh said to Satan, “Where have you come from?”\nSatan answered Yahweh, and said, “From going back and forth in the earth, and from walking up and down in it.”\n'),
	(8091, 15, 2, 3, 'Yahweh said to Satan, “Have you considered my servant Job? For there is no one like him in the earth, a blameless and an upright man, one who fears God, and turns away from evil. He still maintains his integrity, although you incited me against him, to ruin him without cause.”\n'),
	(8092, 15, 2, 4, 'Satan answered Yahweh, and said, “Skin for skin. Yes, all that a man has he will give for his life.\n'),
	(8093, 15, 2, 5, 'But stretch out your hand now, and touch his bone and his flesh, and he will renounce you to your face.”\n'),
	(8094, 15, 2, 6, 'Yahweh said to Satan, “Behold, he is in your hand. Only spare his life.”\n'),
	(8095, 15, 2, 7, 'So Satan went out from the presence of Yahweh, and struck Job with painful sores from the sole of his foot to his head.\n'),
	(8096, 15, 2, 8, 'He took for himself a potsherd to scrape himself with, and he sat among the ashes.\n'),
	(8097, 15, 2, 9, 'Then his wife said to him, “Do you still maintain your integrity? Renounce God, and die.”\n'),
	(8098, 15, 2, 10, 'But he said to her, “You speak as one of the foolish women would speak. What? Shall we receive good at the hand of God, and shall we not receive evil?”\nIn all this Job didn’t sin with his lips.\n'),
	(8099, 15, 2, 11, 'Now when Job’s three friends heard of all this evil that had come on him, they each came from his own place: Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad the Shuhite, and Zophar the Naamathite; and they made an appointment together to come to sympathize with him and to comfort him.\n'),
	(8100, 15, 2, 12, 'When they lifted up their eyes from a distance, and didn’t recognize him, they raised their voices, and wept; and they each tore his robe, and sprinkled dust on their heads toward the sky.\n'),
	(8101, 15, 2, 13, 'So they sat down with him on the ground seven days and seven nights, and no one spoke a word to him, for they saw that his grief was very great.\n'),
	(8102, 15, 3, 1, 'After this Job opened his mouth, and cursed the day of his birth.\n'),
	(8103, 15, 3, 2, 'Job answered:\n'),
	(8104, 15, 3, 3, '“Let the day perish in which I was born,\nthe night which said, ‘There is a boy conceived.’\n'),
	(8105, 15, 3, 4, 'Let that day be darkness.\nDon’t let God from above seek for it,\nneither let the light shine on it.\n'),
	(8106, 15, 3, 5, 'Let darkness and the shadow of death claim it for their own.\nLet a cloud dwell on it.\nLet all that makes black the day terrify it.\n'),
	(8107, 15, 3, 6, 'As for that night, let thick darkness seize on it.\nLet it not rejoice among the days of the year.\nLet it not come into the number of the months.\n'),
	(8108, 15, 3, 7, 'Behold, let that night be barren.\nLet no joyful voice come therein.\n'),
	(8109, 15, 3, 8, 'Let them curse it who curse the day,\nwho are ready to rouse up leviathan.\n'),
	(8110, 15, 3, 9, 'Let the stars of its twilight be dark.\nLet it look for light, but have none,\nneither let it see the eyelids of the morning,\n'),
	(8111, 15, 3, 10, 'because it didn’t shut up the doors of my mother’s womb,\nnor did it hide trouble from my eyes.\n'),
	(8112, 15, 3, 11, '“Why didn’t I die from the womb?\nWhy didn’t I give up the spirit when my mother bore me?\n'),
	(8113, 15, 3, 12, 'Why did the knees receive me?\nOr why the breast, that I should nurse?\n'),
	(8114, 15, 3, 13, 'For now should I have lain down and been quiet.\nI should have slept, then I would have been at rest,\n'),
	(8115, 15, 3, 14, 'with kings and counselors of the earth,\nwho built up waste places for themselves;\n'),
	(8116, 15, 3, 15, 'or with princes who had gold,\nwho filled their houses with silver:\n'),
	(8117, 15, 3, 16, 'or as a hidden untimely birth I had not been,\nas infants who never saw light.\n'),
	(8118, 15, 3, 17, 'There the wicked cease from troubling.\nThere the weary are at rest.\n'),
	(8119, 15, 3, 18, 'There the prisoners are at ease together.\nThey don’t hear the voice of the taskmaster.\n'),
	(8120, 15, 3, 19, 'The small and the great are there.\nThe servant is free from his master.\n'),
	(8121, 15, 3, 20, '“Why is light given to him who is in misery,\nlife to the bitter in soul,\n'),
	(8122, 15, 3, 21, 'Who long for death, but it doesn’t come;\nand dig for it more than for hidden treasures,\n'),
	(8123, 15, 3, 22, 'who rejoice exceedingly,\nand are glad, when they can find the grave?\n'),
	(8124, 15, 3, 23, 'Why is light given to a man whose way is hidden,\nwhom God has hedged in?\n'),
	(8125, 15, 3, 24, 'For my sighing comes before I eat.\nMy groanings are poured out like water.\n'),
	(8126, 15, 3, 25, 'For the thing which I fear comes on me,\nThat which I am afraid of comes to me.\n'),
	(8127, 15, 3, 26, 'I am not at ease, neither am I quiet, neither have I rest;\nbut trouble comes.”\n'),
	(8128, 15, 4, 1, 'Then Eliphaz the Temanite answered,\n'),
	(8129, 15, 4, 2, '“If someone ventures to talk with you, will you be grieved?\nBut who can withhold himself from speaking?\n'),
	(8130, 15, 4, 3, 'Behold, you have instructed many,\nyou have strengthened the weak hands.\n'),
	(8131, 15, 4, 4, 'Your words have supported him who was falling,\nYou have made firm the feeble knees.\n'),
	(8132, 15, 4, 5, 'But now it has come to you, and you faint.\nIt touches you, and you are troubled.\n'),
	(8133, 15, 4, 6, 'Isn’t your piety your confidence?\nIsn’t the integrity of your ways your hope?\n'),
	(8134, 15, 4, 7, '“Remember, now, whoever perished, being innocent?\nOr where were the upright cut off?\n'),
	(8135, 15, 4, 8, 'According to what I have seen, those who plow iniquity,\nand sow trouble,\nreap the same.\n'),
	(8136, 15, 4, 9, 'By the breath of God they perish.\nBy the blast of his anger are they consumed.\n'),
	(8137, 15, 4, 10, 'The roaring of the lion,\nand the voice of the fierce lion,\nthe teeth of the young lions, are broken.\n'),
	(8138, 15, 4, 11, 'The old lion perishes for lack of prey.\nThe cubs of the lioness are scattered abroad.\n'),
	(8139, 15, 4, 12, '“Now a thing was secretly brought to me.\nMy ear received a whisper of it.\n'),
	(8140, 15, 4, 13, 'In thoughts from the visions of the night,\nwhen deep sleep falls on men,\n'),
	(8141, 15, 4, 14, 'fear came on me, and trembling,\nwhich made all my bones shake.\n'),
	(8142, 15, 4, 15, 'Then a spirit passed before my face.\nThe hair of my flesh stood up.\n'),
	(8143, 15, 4, 16, 'It stood still, but I couldn’t discern its appearance.\nA form was before my eyes.\nSilence, then I heard a voice, saying,\n'),
	(8144, 15, 4, 17, '‘Shall mortal man be more just than God?\nShall a man be more pure than his Maker?\n'),
	(8145, 15, 4, 18, 'Behold, he puts no trust in his servants.\nHe charges his angels with error.\n'),
	(8146, 15, 4, 19, 'How much more, those who dwell in houses of clay,\nwhose foundation is in the dust,\nwho are crushed before the moth!\n'),
	(8147, 15, 4, 20, 'Between morning and evening they are destroyed.\nThey perish forever without any regarding it.\n'),
	(8148, 15, 4, 21, 'Isn’t their tent cord plucked up within them?\nThey die, and that without wisdom.’\n'),
	(8149, 15, 5, 1, '“Call now; is there any who will answer you?\nTo which of the holy ones will you turn?\n'),
	(8150, 15, 5, 2, 'For resentment kills the foolish man,\nand jealousy kills the simple.\n'),
	(8151, 15, 5, 3, 'I have seen the foolish taking root,\nbut suddenly I cursed his habitation.\n'),
	(8152, 15, 5, 4, 'His children are far from safety.\nThey are crushed in the gate.\nNeither is there any to deliver them,\n'),
	(8153, 15, 5, 5, 'whose harvest the hungry eats up,\nand take it even out of the thorns.\nThe snare gapes for their substance.\n'),
	(8154, 15, 5, 6, 'For affliction doesn’t come out of the dust,\nneither does trouble spring out of the ground;\n'),
	(8155, 15, 5, 7, 'but man is born to trouble,\nas the sparks fly upward.\n'),
	(8156, 15, 5, 8, '“But as for me, I would seek God.\nI would commit my cause to God,\n'),
	(8157, 15, 5, 9, 'who does great things that can’t be fathomed,\nmarvelous things without number;\n'),
	(8158, 15, 5, 10, 'who gives rain on the earth,\nand sends waters on the fields;\n'),
	(8159, 15, 5, 11, 'so that he sets up on high those who are low,\nthose who mourn are exalted to safety.\n'),
	(8160, 15, 5, 12, 'He frustrates the plans of the crafty,\nSo that their hands can’t perform their enterprise.\n'),
	(8161, 15, 5, 13, 'He takes the wise in their own craftiness;\nthe counsel of the cunning is carried headlong.\n'),
	(8162, 15, 5, 14, 'They meet with darkness in the day time,\nand grope at noonday as in the night.\n'),
	(8163, 15, 5, 15, 'But he saves from the sword of their mouth,\neven the needy from the hand of the mighty.\n'),
	(8164, 15, 5, 16, 'So the poor has hope,\nand injustice shuts her mouth.\n'),
	(8165, 15, 5, 17, '“Behold, happy is the man whom God corrects.\nTherefore do not despise the chastening of the Almighty.\n'),
	(8166, 15, 5, 18, 'For he wounds, and binds up.\nHe injures, and his hands make whole.\n'),
	(8167, 15, 5, 19, 'He will deliver you in six troubles;\nyes, in seven no evil shall touch you.\n'),
	(8168, 15, 5, 20, 'In famine he will redeem you from death;\nin war, from the power of the sword.\n'),
	(8169, 15, 5, 21, 'You shall be hidden from the scourge of the tongue,\nneither shall you be afraid of destruction when it comes.\n'),
	(8170, 15, 5, 22, 'At destruction and famine you shall laugh,\nneither shall you be afraid of the animals of the earth.\n'),
	(8171, 15, 5, 23, 'For you shall be allied with the stones of the field.\nThe animals of the field shall be at peace with you.\n'),
	(8172, 15, 5, 24, 'You shall know that your tent is in peace.\nYou shall visit your fold, and shall miss nothing.\n'),
	(8173, 15, 5, 25, 'You shall know also that your offspring shall be great,\nYour offspring as the grass of the earth.\n'),
	(8174, 15, 5, 26, 'You shall come to your grave in a full age,\nlike a shock of grain comes in its season.\n'),
	(8175, 15, 5, 27, 'Look this, we have searched it, so it is.\nHear it, and know it for your good.”\n'),
	(8176, 15, 6, 1, 'Then Job answered,\n'),
	(8177, 15, 6, 2, '“Oh that my anguish were weighed,\nand all my calamity laid in the balances!\n'),
	(8178, 15, 6, 3, 'For now it would be heavier than the sand of the seas,\ntherefore have my words been rash.\n'),
	(8179, 15, 6, 4, 'For the arrows of the Almighty are within me.\nMy spirit drinks up their poison.\nThe terrors of God set themselves in array against me.\n'),
	(8180, 15, 6, 5, 'Does the wild donkey bray when he has grass?\nOr does the ox low over his fodder?\n'),
	(8181, 15, 6, 6, 'Can that which has no flavor be eaten without salt?\nOr is there any taste in the white of an egg?\n'),
	(8182, 15, 6, 7, 'My soul refuses to touch them.\nThey are as loathsome food to me.\n'),
	(8183, 15, 6, 8, '“Oh that I might have my request,\nthat God would grant the thing that I long for,\n'),
	(8184, 15, 6, 9, 'even that it would please God to crush me;\nthat he would let loose his hand, and cut me off!\n'),
	(8185, 15, 6, 10, 'Be it still my consolation,\nyes, let me exult in pain that doesn’t spare,\nthat I have not denied the words of the Holy One.\n'),
	(8186, 15, 6, 11, 'What is my strength, that I should wait?\nWhat is my end, that I should be patient?\n'),
	(8187, 15, 6, 12, 'Is my strength the strength of stones?\nOr is my flesh of brass?\n'),
	(8188, 15, 6, 13, 'Isn’t it that I have no help in me,\nThat wisdom is driven quite from me?\n'),
	(8189, 15, 6, 14, '“To him who is ready to faint, kindness should be shown from his friend;\neven to him who forsakes the fear of the Almighty.\n'),
	(8190, 15, 6, 15, 'My brothers have dealt deceitfully as a brook,\nas the channel of brooks that pass away;\n'),
	(8191, 15, 6, 16, 'Which are black by reason of the ice,\nin which the snow hides itself.\n'),
	(8192, 15, 6, 17, 'In the dry season, they vanish.\nWhen it is hot, they are consumed out of their place.\n'),
	(8193, 15, 6, 18, 'The caravans that travel beside them turn away.\nThey go up into the waste, and perish.\n'),
	(8194, 15, 6, 19, 'The caravans of Tema looked.\nThe companies of Sheba waited for them.\n'),
	(8195, 15, 6, 20, 'They were distressed because they were confident.\nThey came there, and were confounded.\n'),
	(8196, 15, 6, 21, 'For now you are nothing.\nYou see a terror, and are afraid.\n'),
	(8197, 15, 6, 22, 'Did I say, ‘Give to me?’\nor, ‘Offer a present for me from your substance?’\n'),
	(8198, 15, 6, 23, 'or, ‘Deliver me from the adversary’s hand?’\nor, ‘Redeem me from the hand of the oppressors?’\n'),
	(8199, 15, 6, 24, '“Teach me, and I will hold my peace.\nCause me to understand wherein I have erred.\n'),
	(8200, 15, 6, 25, 'How forcible are words of uprightness!\nBut your reproof, what does it reprove?\n'),
	(8201, 15, 6, 26, 'Do you intend to reprove words,\nsince the speeches of one who is desperate are as wind?\n'),
	(8202, 15, 6, 27, 'Yes, you would even cast lots for the fatherless,\nand make merchandise of your friend.\n'),
	(8203, 15, 6, 28, 'Now therefore be pleased to look at me,\nfor surely I shall not lie to your face.\n'),
	(8204, 15, 6, 29, 'Please return.\nLet there be no injustice.\nYes, return again.\nMy cause is righteous.\n'),
	(8205, 15, 6, 30, 'Is there injustice on my tongue?\nCan’t my taste discern mischievous things?\n'),
	(8206, 15, 7, 1, '“Isn’t a man forced to labor on earth?\nAren’t his days like the days of a hired hand?\n'),
	(8207, 15, 7, 2, 'As a servant who earnestly desires the shadow,\nas a hireling who looks for his wages,\n'),
	(8208, 15, 7, 3, 'so am I made to possess months of misery,\nwearisome nights are appointed to me.\n'),
	(8209, 15, 7, 4, 'When I lie down, I say,\n‘When shall I arise, and the night be gone?’\nI toss and turn until the dawning of the day.\n'),
	(8210, 15, 7, 5, 'My flesh is clothed with worms and clods of dust.\nMy skin closes up, and breaks out afresh.\n'),
	(8211, 15, 7, 6, 'My days are swifter than a weaver’s shuttle,\nand are spent without hope.\n'),
	(8212, 15, 7, 7, 'Oh remember that my life is a breath.\nMy eye shall no more see good.\n'),
	(8213, 15, 7, 8, 'The eye of him who sees me shall see me no more.\nYour eyes shall be on me, but I shall not be.\n'),
	(8214, 15, 7, 9, 'As the cloud is consumed and vanishes away,\nso he who goes down to Sheol shall come up no more.\n'),
	(8215, 15, 7, 10, 'He shall return no more to his house,\nneither shall his place know him any more.\n'),
	(8216, 15, 7, 11, '“Therefore I will not keep silent.\nI will speak in the anguish of my spirit.\nI will complain in the bitterness of my soul.\n'),
	(8217, 15, 7, 12, 'Am I a sea, or a sea monster,\nthat you put a guard over me?\n'),
	(8218, 15, 7, 13, 'When I say, ‘My bed shall comfort me.\nMy couch shall ease my complaint;’\n'),
	(8219, 15, 7, 14, 'then you scare me with dreams,\nand terrify me through visions:\n'),
	(8220, 15, 7, 15, 'so that my soul chooses strangling,\ndeath rather than my bones.\n'),
	(8221, 15, 7, 16, 'I loathe my life.\nI don’t want to live forever.\nLeave me alone, for my days are but a breath.\n'),
	(8222, 15, 7, 17, 'What is man, that you should magnify him,\nthat you should set your mind on him,\n'),
	(8223, 15, 7, 18, 'that you should visit him every morning,\nand test him every moment?\n'),
	(8224, 15, 7, 19, 'How long will you not look away from me,\nnor leave me alone until I swallow down my spittle?\n'),
	(8225, 15, 7, 20, 'If I have sinned, what do I do to you, you watcher of men?\nWhy have you set me as a mark for you,\nso that I am a burden to myself?\n'),
	(8226, 15, 7, 21, 'Why do you not pardon my disobedience, and take away my iniquity?\nFor now shall I lie down in the dust.\nYou will seek me diligently, but I shall not be.”\n'),
	(8227, 15, 8, 1, 'Then Bildad the Shuhite answered,\n'),
	(8228, 15, 8, 2, '“How long will you speak these things?\nShall the words of your mouth be a mighty wind?\n'),
	(8229, 15, 8, 3, 'Does God pervert justice?\nOr does the Almighty pervert righteousness?\n'),
	(8230, 15, 8, 4, 'If your children have sinned against him,\nHe has delivered them into the hand of their disobedience.\n'),
	(8231, 15, 8, 5, 'If you want to seek God diligently,\nmake your supplication to the Almighty.\n'),
	(8232, 15, 8, 6, 'If you were pure and upright,\nsurely now he would awaken for you,\nand make the habitation of your righteousness prosperous.\n'),
	(8233, 15, 8, 7, 'Though your beginning was small,\nyet your latter end would greatly increase.\n'),
	(8234, 15, 8, 8, '“Please inquire of past generations.\nFind out about the learning of their fathers.\n'),
	(8235, 15, 8, 9, '(For we are but of yesterday, and know nothing,\nbecause our days on earth are a shadow.)\n'),
	(8236, 15, 8, 10, 'Shall they not teach you, tell you,\nand utter words out of their heart?\n'),
	(8237, 15, 8, 11, '“Can the papyrus grow up without mire?\nCan the rushes grow without water?\n'),
	(8238, 15, 8, 12, 'While it is yet in its greenness, not cut down,\nit withers before any other reed.\n'),
	(8239, 15, 8, 13, 'So are the paths of all who forget God.\nThe hope of the godless man shall perish,\n'),
	(8240, 15, 8, 14, 'Whose confidence shall break apart,\nWhose trust is a spider’s web.\n'),
	(8241, 15, 8, 15, 'He shall lean on his house, but it shall not stand.\nHe shall cling to it, but it shall not endure.\n'),
	(8242, 15, 8, 16, 'He is green before the sun.\nHis shoots go out along his garden.\n'),
	(8243, 15, 8, 17, 'His roots are wrapped around the rock pile.\nHe sees the place of stones.\n'),
	(8244, 15, 8, 18, 'If he is destroyed from his place,\nthen it shall deny him, saying, ‘I have not seen you.’\n'),
	(8245, 15, 8, 19, 'Behold, this is the joy of his way:\nout of the earth, others shall spring.\n'),
	(8246, 15, 8, 20, '“Behold, God will not cast away a blameless man,\nneither will he uphold the evildoers.\n'),
	(8247, 15, 8, 21, 'He will still fill your mouth with laughter,\nyour lips with shouting.\n'),
	(8248, 15, 8, 22, 'Those who hate you shall be clothed with shame.\nThe tent of the wicked shall be no more.”\n'),
	(8249, 15, 9, 1, 'Then Job answered,\n'),
	(8250, 15, 9, 2, '“Truly I know that it is so,\nbut how can man be just with God?\n'),
	(8251, 15, 9, 3, 'If he is pleased to contend with him,\nhe can’t answer him one time in a thousand.\n'),
	(8252, 15, 9, 4, 'God who is wise in heart, and mighty in strength:\nwho has hardened himself against him, and prospered?\n'),
	(8253, 15, 9, 5, 'He removes the mountains, and they don’t know it,\nwhen he overturns them in his anger.\n'),
	(8254, 15, 9, 6, 'He shakes the earth out of its place.\nIts pillars tremble.\n'),
	(8255, 15, 9, 7, 'He commands the sun, and it doesn’t rise,\nand seals up the stars.\n'),
	(8256, 15, 9, 8, 'He alone stretches out the heavens,\nand treads on the waves of the sea.\n'),
	(8257, 15, 9, 9, 'He makes the Bear, Orion, and the Pleiades,\nand the rooms of the south.\n'),
	(8258, 15, 9, 10, 'He does great things past finding out;\nyes, marvelous things without number.\n'),
	(8259, 15, 9, 11, 'Behold, he goes by me, and I don’t see him.\nHe passes on also, but I don’t perceive him.\n'),
	(8260, 15, 9, 12, 'Behold, he snatches away.\nWho can hinder him?\nWho will ask him, ‘What are you doing?’\n'),
	(8261, 15, 9, 13, '“God will not withdraw his anger.\nThe helpers of Rahab stoop under him.\n'),
	(8262, 15, 9, 14, 'How much less shall I answer him,\nAnd choose my words to argue with him?\n'),
	(8263, 15, 9, 15, 'Though I were righteous, yet I wouldn’t answer him.\nI would make supplication to my judge.\n'),
	(8264, 15, 9, 16, 'If I had called, and he had answered me,\nyet I wouldn’t believe that he listened to my voice.\n'),
	(8265, 15, 9, 17, 'For he breaks me with a storm,\nand multiplies my wounds without cause.\n'),
	(8266, 15, 9, 18, 'He will not allow me to catch my breath,\nbut fills me with bitterness.\n'),
	(8267, 15, 9, 19, 'If it is a matter of strength, behold, he is mighty!\nIf of justice, ‘Who,’ says he, ‘will summon me?’\n'),
	(8268, 15, 9, 20, 'Though I am righteous, my own mouth shall condemn me.\nThough I am blameless, it shall prove me perverse.\n'),
	(8269, 15, 9, 21, 'I am blameless.\nI don’t respect myself.\nI despise my life.\n'),
	(8270, 15, 9, 22, '“It is all the same.\nTherefore I say he destroys the blameless and the wicked.\n'),
	(8271, 15, 9, 23, 'If the scourge kills suddenly,\nhe will mock at the trial of the innocent.\n'),
	(8272, 15, 9, 24, 'The earth is given into the hand of the wicked.\nHe covers the faces of its judges.\nIf not he, then who is it?\n'),
	(8273, 15, 9, 25, '“Now my days are swifter than a runner.\nThey flee away, they see no good.\n'),
	(8274, 15, 9, 26, 'They have passed away as the swift ships,\nas the eagle that swoops on the prey.\n'),
	(8275, 15, 9, 27, 'If I say, ‘I will forget my complaint,\nI will put off my sad face, and cheer up;’\n'),
	(8276, 15, 9, 28, 'I am afraid of all my sorrows,\nI know that you will not hold me innocent.\n'),
	(8277, 15, 9, 29, 'I shall be condemned.\nWhy then do I labor in vain?\n'),
	(8278, 15, 9, 30, 'If I wash myself with snow,\nand cleanse my hands with lye,\n'),
	(8279, 15, 9, 31, 'yet you will plunge me in the ditch.\nMy own clothes shall abhor me.\n'),
	(8280, 15, 9, 32, 'For he is not a man, as I am, that I should answer him,\nthat we should come together in judgment.\n'),
	(8281, 15, 9, 33, 'There is no umpire between us,\nthat might lay his hand on us both.\n'),
	(8282, 15, 9, 34, 'Let him take his rod away from me.\nLet his terror not make me afraid;\n'),
	(8283, 15, 9, 35, 'then I would speak, and not fear him,\nfor I am not so in myself.\n'),
	(8284, 15, 10, 1, '“My soul is weary of my life.\nI will give free course to my complaint.\nI will speak in the bitterness of my soul.\n'),
	(8285, 15, 10, 2, 'I will tell God, ‘Do not condemn me.\nShow me why you contend with me.\n'),
	(8286, 15, 10, 3, 'Is it good to you that you should oppress,\nthat you should despise the work of your hands,\nand smile on the counsel of the wicked?\n'),
	(8287, 15, 10, 4, 'Do you have eyes of flesh?\nOr do you see as man sees?\n'),
	(8288, 15, 10, 5, 'Are your days as the days of mortals,\nor your years as man’s years,\n'),
	(8289, 15, 10, 6, 'that you inquire after my iniquity,\nand search after my sin?\n'),
	(8290, 15, 10, 7, 'Although you know that I am not wicked,\nthere is no one who can deliver out of your hand.\n'),
	(8291, 15, 10, 8, '“‘Your hands have framed me and fashioned me altogether,\nyet you destroy me.\n'),
	(8292, 15, 10, 9, 'Remember, I beg you, that you have fashioned me as clay.\nWill you bring me into dust again?\n'),
	(8293, 15, 10, 10, 'Haven’t you poured me out like milk,\nand curdled me like cheese?\n'),
	(8294, 15, 10, 11, 'You have clothed me with skin and flesh,\nand knit me together with bones and sinews.\n'),
	(8295, 15, 10, 12, 'You have granted me life and loving kindness.\nYour visitation has preserved my spirit.\n'),
	(8296, 15, 10, 13, 'Yet you hid these things in your heart.\nI know that this is with you:\n'),
	(8297, 15, 10, 14, 'if I sin, then you mark me.\nYou will not acquit me from my iniquity.\n'),
	(8298, 15, 10, 15, 'If I am wicked, woe to me.\nIf I am righteous, I still shall not lift up my head,\nbeing filled with disgrace,\nand conscious of my affliction.\n'),
	(8299, 15, 10, 16, 'If my head is held high, you hunt me like a lion.\nAgain you show yourself powerful to me.\n'),
	(8300, 15, 10, 17, 'You renew your witnesses against me,\nand increase your indignation on me.\nChanges and warfare are with me.\n'),
	(8301, 15, 10, 18, '“‘Why, then, have you brought me out of the womb?\nI wish I had given up the spirit, and no eye had seen me.\n'),
	(8302, 15, 10, 19, 'I should have been as though I had not been.\nI should have been carried from the womb to the grave.\n'),
	(8303, 15, 10, 20, 'Aren’t my days few?\nCease then.\nLeave me alone, that I may find a little comfort,\n'),
	(8304, 15, 10, 21, 'before I go where I shall not return from,\nto the land of darkness and of the shadow of death;\n'),
	(8305, 15, 10, 22, 'the land dark as midnight,\nof the shadow of death,\nwithout any order,\nwhere the light is as midnight.’”\n'),
	(8306, 15, 11, 1, 'Then Zophar, the Naamathite, answered,\n'),
	(8307, 15, 11, 2, '“Shouldn’t the multitude of words be answered?\nShould a man full of talk be justified?\n'),
	(8308, 15, 11, 3, 'Should your boastings make men hold their peace?\nWhen you mock, shall no man make you ashamed?\n'),
	(8309, 15, 11, 4, 'For you say, ‘My doctrine is pure.\nI am clean in your eyes.’\n'),
	(8310, 15, 11, 5, 'But oh that God would speak,\nand open his lips against you,\n'),
	(8311, 15, 11, 6, 'that he would show you the secrets of wisdom!\nFor true wisdom has two sides.\nKnow therefore that God exacts of you less than your iniquity deserves.\n'),
	(8312, 15, 11, 7, '“Can you fathom the mystery of God?\nOr can you probe the limits of the Almighty?\n'),
	(8313, 15, 11, 8, 'They are high as heaven. What can you do?\nThey are deeper than Sheol. What can you know?\n'),
	(8314, 15, 11, 9, 'Its measure is longer than the earth,\nand broader than the sea.\n'),
	(8315, 15, 11, 10, 'If he passes by, or confines,\nor convenes a court, then who can oppose him?\n'),
	(8316, 15, 11, 11, 'For he knows false men.\nHe sees iniquity also, even though he doesn’t consider it.\n'),
	(8317, 15, 11, 12, 'An empty-headed man becomes wise\nwhen a man is born as a wild donkey’s colt.\n'),
	(8318, 15, 11, 13, '“If you set your heart aright,\nstretch out your hands toward him.\n'),
	(8319, 15, 11, 14, 'If iniquity is in your hand, put it far away.\nDon’t let unrighteousness dwell in your tents.\n'),
	(8320, 15, 11, 15, 'Surely then you shall lift up your face without spot;\nYes, you shall be steadfast, and shall not fear:\n'),
	(8321, 15, 11, 16, 'for you shall forget your misery.\nYou shall remember it like waters that have passed away.\n'),
	(8322, 15, 11, 17, 'Life shall be clearer than the noonday.\nThough there is darkness, it shall be as the morning.\n'),
	(8323, 15, 11, 18, 'You shall be secure, because there is hope.\nYes, you shall search, and shall take your rest in safety.\n'),
	(8324, 15, 11, 19, 'Also you shall lie down, and no one shall make you afraid.\nYes, many shall court your favor.\n'),
	(8325, 15, 11, 20, 'But the eyes of the wicked shall fail.\nThey shall have no way to flee.\nTheir hope shall be the giving up of the spirit.”\n'),
	(8326, 15, 12, 1, 'Then Job answered,\n'),
	(8327, 15, 12, 2, '“No doubt, but you are the people,\nand wisdom shall die with you.\n'),
	(8328, 15, 12, 3, 'But I have understanding as well as you;\nI am not inferior to you.\nYes, who doesn’t know such things as these?\n'),
	(8329, 15, 12, 4, 'I am like one who is a joke to his neighbor,\nI, who called on God, and he answered.\nThe just, the blameless man is a joke.\n'),
	(8330, 15, 12, 5, 'In the thought of him who is at ease there is contempt for misfortune.\nIt is ready for them whose foot slips.\n'),
	(8331, 15, 12, 6, 'The tents of robbers prosper.\nThose who provoke God are secure,\nwho carry their God in their hands.\n'),
	(8332, 15, 12, 7, '“But ask the animals, now, and they shall teach you;\nthe birds of the sky, and they shall tell you.\n'),
	(8333, 15, 12, 8, 'Or speak to the earth, and it shall teach you.\nThe fish of the sea shall declare to you.\n'),
	(8334, 15, 12, 9, 'Who doesn’t know that in all these,\nYahweh’s hand has done this,\n'),
	(8335, 15, 12, 10, 'in whose hand is the life of every living thing,\nand the breath of all mankind?\n'),
	(8336, 15, 12, 11, 'Doesn’t the ear try words,\neven as the palate tastes its food?\n'),
	(8337, 15, 12, 12, 'With aged men is wisdom,\nin length of days understanding.\n'),
	(8338, 15, 12, 13, '“With God is wisdom and might.\nHe has counsel and understanding.\n'),
	(8339, 15, 12, 14, 'Behold, he breaks down, and it can’t be built again.\nHe imprisons a man, and there can be no release.\n'),
	(8340, 15, 12, 15, 'Behold, he withholds the waters, and they dry up.\nAgain, he sends them out, and they overturn the earth.\n'),
	(8341, 15, 12, 16, 'With him is strength and wisdom.\nThe deceived and the deceiver are his.\n'),
	(8342, 15, 12, 17, 'He leads counselors away stripped.\nHe makes judges fools.\n'),
	(8343, 15, 12, 18, 'He loosens the bond of kings.\nHe binds their waist with a belt.\n'),
	(8344, 15, 12, 19, 'He leads priests away stripped,\nand overthrows the mighty.\n'),
	(8345, 15, 12, 20, 'He removes the speech of those who are trusted,\nand takes away the understanding of the elders.\n'),
	(8346, 15, 12, 21, 'He pours contempt on princes,\nand loosens the belt of the strong.\n'),
	(8347, 15, 12, 22, 'He uncovers deep things out of darkness,\nand brings out to light the shadow of death.\n'),
	(8348, 15, 12, 23, 'He increases the nations, and he destroys them.\nHe enlarges the nations, and he leads them captive.\n'),
	(8349, 15, 12, 24, 'He takes away understanding from the chiefs of the people of the earth,\nand causes them to wander in a wilderness where there is no way.\n'),
	(8350, 15, 12, 25, 'They grope in the dark without light.\nHe makes them stagger like a drunken man.\n'),
	(8351, 15, 13, 1, '“Behold, my eye has seen all this.\nMy ear has heard and understood it.\n'),
	(8352, 15, 13, 2, 'What you know, I know also.\nI am not inferior to you.\n'),
	(8353, 15, 13, 3, '“Surely I would speak to the Almighty.\nI desire to reason with God.\n'),
	(8354, 15, 13, 4, 'But you are forgers of lies.\nYou are all physicians of no value.\n'),
	(8355, 15, 13, 5, 'Oh that you would be completely silent!\nThen you would be wise.\n'),
	(8356, 15, 13, 6, 'Hear now my reasoning.\nListen to the pleadings of my lips.\n'),
	(8357, 15, 13, 7, 'Will you speak unrighteously for God,\nand talk deceitfully for him?\n'),
	(8358, 15, 13, 8, 'Will you show partiality to him?\nWill you contend for God?\n'),
	(8359, 15, 13, 9, 'Is it good that he should search you out?\nOr as one deceives a man, will you deceive him?\n'),
	(8360, 15, 13, 10, 'He will surely reprove you,\nif you secretly show partiality.\n'),
	(8361, 15, 13, 11, 'Shall not his majesty make you afraid,\nAnd his dread fall on you?\n'),
	(8362, 15, 13, 12, 'Your memorable sayings are proverbs of ashes,\nYour defenses are defenses of clay.\n'),
	(8363, 15, 13, 13, '“Be silent, leave me alone, that I may speak.\nLet come on me what will.\n'),
	(8364, 15, 13, 14, 'Why should I take my flesh in my teeth,\nand put my life in my hand?\n'),
	(8365, 15, 13, 15, 'Behold, he will kill me.\nI have no hope.\nNevertheless, I will maintain my ways before him.\n'),
	(8366, 15, 13, 16, 'This also shall be my salvation,\nthat a godless man shall not come before him.\n'),
	(8367, 15, 13, 17, 'Hear diligently my speech.\nLet my declaration be in your ears.\n'),
	(8368, 15, 13, 18, 'See now, I have set my cause in order.\nI know that I am righteous.\n'),
	(8369, 15, 13, 19, 'Who is he who will contend with me?\nFor then would I hold my peace and give up the spirit.\n'),
	(8370, 15, 13, 20, '“Only don’t do two things to me;\nthen I will not hide myself from your face:\n'),
	(8371, 15, 13, 21, 'withdraw your hand far from me;\nand don’t let your terror make me afraid.\n'),
	(8372, 15, 13, 22, 'Then call, and I will answer;\nor let me speak, and you answer me.\n'),
	(8373, 15, 13, 23, 'How many are my iniquities and sins?\nMake me know my disobedience and my sin.\n'),
	(8374, 15, 13, 24, 'Why hide you your face,\nand hold me for your enemy?\n'),
	(8375, 15, 13, 25, 'Will you harass a driven leaf?\nWill you pursue the dry stubble?\n'),
	(8376, 15, 13, 26, 'For you write bitter things against me,\nand make me inherit the iniquities of my youth:\n'),
	(8377, 15, 13, 27, 'You also put my feet in the stocks,\nand mark all my paths.\nYou set a bound to the soles of my feet,\n'),
	(8378, 15, 13, 28, 'though I am decaying like a rotten thing,\nlike a garment that is moth-eaten.\n'),
	(8379, 15, 14, 1, '“Man, who is born of a woman,\nis of few days, and full of trouble.\n'),
	(8380, 15, 14, 2, 'He grows up like a flower, and is cut down.\nHe also flees like a shadow, and doesn’t continue.\n'),
	(8381, 15, 14, 3, 'Do you open your eyes on such a one,\nand bring me into judgment with you?\n'),
	(8382, 15, 14, 4, 'Who can bring a clean thing out of an unclean?\nNot one.\n'),
	(8383, 15, 14, 5, 'Seeing his days are determined,\nthe number of his months is with you,\nand you have appointed his bounds that he can’t pass;\n'),
	(8384, 15, 14, 6, 'Look away from him, that he may rest,\nuntil he shall accomplish, as a hireling, his day.\n'),
	(8385, 15, 14, 7, '“For there is hope for a tree,\nIf it is cut down, that it will sprout again,\nthat the tender branch of it will not cease.\n'),
	(8386, 15, 14, 8, 'Though its root grows old in the earth,\nand its stock dies in the ground,\n'),
	(8387, 15, 14, 9, 'yet through the scent of water it will bud,\nand sprout boughs like a plant.\n'),
	(8388, 15, 14, 10, 'But man dies, and is laid low.\nYes, man gives up the spirit, and where is he?\n'),
	(8389, 15, 14, 11, 'As the waters fail from the sea,\nand the river wastes and dries up,\n'),
	(8390, 15, 14, 12, 'so man lies down and doesn’t rise.\nUntil the heavens are no more, they shall not awake,\nnor be roused out of their sleep.\n'),
	(8391, 15, 14, 13, '“Oh that you would hide me in Sheol,\nthat you would keep me secret, until your wrath is past,\nthat you would appoint me a set time, and remember me!\n'),
	(8392, 15, 14, 14, 'If a man dies, shall he live again?\nAll the days of my warfare would I wait,\nuntil my release should come.\n'),
	(8393, 15, 14, 15, 'You would call, and I would answer you.\nYou would have a desire to the work of your hands.\n'),
	(8394, 15, 14, 16, 'But now you count my steps.\nDon’t you watch over my sin?\n'),
	(8395, 15, 14, 17, 'My disobedience is sealed up in a bag.\nYou fasten up my iniquity.\n'),
	(8396, 15, 14, 18, '“But the mountain falling comes to nothing.\nThe rock is removed out of its place;\n'),
	(8397, 15, 14, 19, 'The waters wear the stones.\nThe torrents of it wash away the dust of the earth.\nSo you destroy the hope of man.\n'),
	(8398, 15, 14, 20, 'You forever prevail against him, and he departs.\nYou change his face, and send him away.\n'),
	(8399, 15, 14, 21, 'His sons come to honor, and he doesn’t know it.\nThey are brought low, but he doesn’t perceive it of them.\n'),
	(8400, 15, 14, 22, 'But his flesh on him has pain,\nand his soul within him mourns.”\n'),
	(8401, 15, 15, 1, 'Then Eliphaz the Temanite answered,\n'),
	(8402, 15, 15, 2, '“Should a wise man answer with vain knowledge,\nand fill himself with the east wind?\n'),
	(8403, 15, 15, 3, 'Should he reason with unprofitable talk,\nor with speeches with which he can do no good?\n'),
	(8404, 15, 15, 4, 'Yes, you do away with fear,\nand hinder devotion before God.\n'),
	(8405, 15, 15, 5, 'For your iniquity teaches your mouth,\nand you choose the language of the crafty.\n'),
	(8406, 15, 15, 6, 'Your own mouth condemns you, and not I.\nYes, your own lips testify against you.\n'),
	(8407, 15, 15, 7, '“Are you the first man who was born?\nOr were you brought out before the hills?\n'),
	(8408, 15, 15, 8, 'Have you heard the secret counsel of God?\nDo you limit wisdom to yourself?\n'),
	(8409, 15, 15, 9, 'What do you know, that we don’t know?\nWhat do you understand, which is not in us?\n'),
	(8410, 15, 15, 10, 'With us are both the gray-headed and the very aged men,\nmuch elder than your father.\n'),
	(8411, 15, 15, 11, 'Are the consolations of God too small for you,\neven the word that is gentle toward you?\n'),
	(8412, 15, 15, 12, 'Why does your heart carry you away?\nWhy do your eyes flash,\n'),
	(8413, 15, 15, 13, 'That you turn your spirit against God,\nand let such words go out of your mouth?\n'),
	(8414, 15, 15, 14, 'What is man, that he should be clean?\nWhat is he who is born of a woman, that he should be righteous?\n'),
	(8415, 15, 15, 15, 'Behold, he puts no trust in his holy ones.\nYes, the heavens are not clean in his sight;\n'),
	(8416, 15, 15, 16, 'how much less one who is abominable and corrupt,\na man who drinks iniquity like water!\n'),
	(8417, 15, 15, 17, '“I will show you, listen to me;\nthat which I have seen I will declare\n'),
	(8418, 15, 15, 18, '(which wise men have told by their fathers,\nand have not hidden it;\n'),
	(8419, 15, 15, 19, 'to whom alone the land was given,\nand no stranger passed among them):\n'),
	(8420, 15, 15, 20, 'the wicked man writhes in pain all his days,\neven the number of years that are laid up for the oppressor.\n'),
	(8421, 15, 15, 21, 'A sound of terrors is in his ears.\nIn prosperity the destroyer shall come on him.\n'),
	(8422, 15, 15, 22, 'He doesn’t believe that he shall return out of darkness.\nHe is waited for by the sword.\n'),
	(8423, 15, 15, 23, 'He wanders abroad for bread, saying, ‘Where is it?’\nHe knows that the day of darkness is ready at his hand.\n'),
	(8424, 15, 15, 24, 'Distress and anguish make him afraid.\nThey prevail against him, as a king ready to the battle.\n'),
	(8425, 15, 15, 25, 'Because he has stretched out his hand against God,\nand behaves himself proudly against the Almighty;\n'),
	(8426, 15, 15, 26, 'he runs at him with a stiff neck,\nwith the thick shields of his bucklers;\n'),
	(8427, 15, 15, 27, 'because he has covered his face with his fatness,\nand gathered fat on his thighs.\n'),
	(8428, 15, 15, 28, 'He has lived in desolate cities,\nin houses which no one inhabited,\nwhich were ready to become heaps.\n'),
	(8429, 15, 15, 29, 'He shall not be rich, neither shall his substance continue,\nneither shall their possessions be extended on the earth.\n'),
	(8430, 15, 15, 30, 'He shall not depart out of darkness.\nThe flame shall dry up his branches.\nBy the breath of God’s mouth shall he go away.\n'),
	(8431, 15, 15, 31, 'Let him not trust in emptiness, deceiving himself;\nfor emptiness shall be his reward.\n'),
	(8432, 15, 15, 32, 'It shall be accomplished before his time.\nHis branch shall not be green.\n'),
	(8433, 15, 15, 33, 'He shall shake off his unripe grape as the vine,\nand shall cast off his flower as the olive tree.\n'),
	(8434, 15, 15, 34, 'For the company of the godless shall be barren,\nand fire shall consume the tents of bribery.\n'),
	(8435, 15, 15, 35, 'They conceive mischief, and produce iniquity.\nTheir heart prepares deceit.”\n'),
	(8436, 15, 16, 1, 'Then Job answered,\n'),
	(8437, 15, 16, 2, '“I have heard many such things.\nYou are all miserable comforters!\n'),
	(8438, 15, 16, 3, 'Shall vain words have an end?\nOr what provokes you that you answer?\n'),
	(8439, 15, 16, 4, 'I also could speak as you do.\nIf your soul were in my soul’s place,\nI could join words together against you,\nand shake my head at you,\n'),
	(8440, 15, 16, 5, 'but I would strengthen you with my mouth.\nThe solace of my lips would relieve you.\n'),
	(8441, 15, 16, 6, '“Though I speak, my grief is not subsided.\nThough I forbear, what am I eased?\n'),
	(8442, 15, 16, 7, 'But now, God, you have surely worn me out.\nYou have made desolate all my company.\n'),
	(8443, 15, 16, 8, 'You have shriveled me up. This is a witness against me.\nMy leanness rises up against me.\nIt testifies to my face.\n'),
	(8444, 15, 16, 9, 'He has torn me in his wrath, and persecuted me.\nHe has gnashed on me with his teeth.\nMy adversary sharpens his eyes on me.\n'),
	(8445, 15, 16, 10, 'They have gaped on me with their mouth.\nThey have struck me on the cheek reproachfully.\nThey gather themselves together against me.\n'),
	(8446, 15, 16, 11, 'God delivers me to the ungodly,\nand casts me into the hands of the wicked.\n'),
	(8447, 15, 16, 12, 'I was at ease, and he broke me apart.\nYes, he has taken me by the neck, and dashed me to pieces.\nHe has also set me up for his target.\n'),
	(8448, 15, 16, 13, 'His archers surround me.\nHe splits my kidneys apart, and does not spare.\nHe pours out my gall on the ground.\n'),
	(8449, 15, 16, 14, 'He breaks me with breach on breach.\nHe runs on me like a giant.\n'),
	(8450, 15, 16, 15, 'I have sewed sackcloth on my skin,\nand have thrust my horn in the dust.\n'),
	(8451, 15, 16, 16, 'My face is red with weeping.\nDeep darkness is on my eyelids.\n'),
	(8452, 15, 16, 17, 'Although there is no violence in my hands,\nand my prayer is pure.\n'),
	(8453, 15, 16, 18, '“Earth, don’t cover my blood.\nLet my cry have no place to rest.\n'),
	(8454, 15, 16, 19, 'Even now, behold, my witness is in heaven.\nHe who vouches for me is on high.\n'),
	(8455, 15, 16, 20, 'My friends scoff at me.\nMy eyes pour out tears to God,\n'),
	(8456, 15, 16, 21, 'that he would maintain the right of a man with God,\nof a son of man with his neighbor!\n'),
	(8457, 15, 16, 22, 'For when a few years have come,\nI shall go the way of no return.\n'),
	(8458, 15, 17, 1, '“My spirit is consumed.\nMy days are extinct,\nAnd the grave is ready for me.\n'),
	(8459, 15, 17, 2, 'Surely there are mockers with me.\nMy eye dwells on their provocation.\n'),
	(8460, 15, 17, 3, '“Now give a pledge, be collateral for me with yourself.\nWho is there who will strike hands with me?\n'),
	(8461, 15, 17, 4, 'For you have hidden their heart from understanding,\nTherefore you shall not exalt them.\n'),
	(8462, 15, 17, 5, 'He who denounces his friends for plunder,\nEven the eyes of his children shall fail.\n'),
	(8463, 15, 17, 6, '“But he has made me a byword of the people.\nThey spit in my face.\n'),
	(8464, 15, 17, 7, 'My eye also is dim by reason of sorrow.\nAll my members are as a shadow.\n'),
	(8465, 15, 17, 8, 'Upright men shall be astonished at this.\nThe innocent shall stir up himself against the godless.\n'),
	(8466, 15, 17, 9, 'Yet shall the righteous hold on his way.\nHe who has clean hands shall grow stronger and stronger.\n'),
	(8467, 15, 17, 10, 'But as for you all, come on now again;\nI shall not find a wise man among you.\n'),
	(8468, 15, 17, 11, 'My days are past, my plans are broken off,\nas are the thoughts of my heart.\n'),
	(8469, 15, 17, 12, 'They change the night into day,\nsaying ‘The light is near’ in the presence of darkness.\n'),
	(8470, 15, 17, 13, 'If I look for Sheol as my house,\nif I have spread my couch in the darkness,\n'),
	(8471, 15, 17, 14, 'If I have said to corruption, ‘You are my father;’\nto the worm, ‘My mother,’ and ‘my sister;’\n'),
	(8472, 15, 17, 15, 'where then is my hope?\nas for my hope, who shall see it?\n'),
	(8473, 15, 17, 16, 'Shall it go down with me to the gates of Sheol,\nor descend together into the dust?”\n'),
	(8474, 15, 18, 1, 'Then Bildad the Shuhite answered,\n'),
	(8475, 15, 18, 2, '“How long will you hunt for words?\nConsider, and afterwards we will speak.\n'),
	(8476, 15, 18, 3, 'Why are we counted as animals,\nwhich have become unclean in your sight?\n'),
	(8477, 15, 18, 4, 'You who tear yourself in your anger,\nshall the earth be forsaken for you?\nOr shall the rock be removed out of its place?\n'),
	(8478, 15, 18, 5, '“Yes, the light of the wicked shall be put out,\nThe spark of his fire shall not shine.\n'),
	(8479, 15, 18, 6, 'The light shall be dark in his tent.\nHis lamp above him shall be put out.\n'),
	(8480, 15, 18, 7, 'The steps of his strength shall be shortened.\nHis own counsel shall cast him down.\n'),
	(8481, 15, 18, 8, 'For he is cast into a net by his own feet,\nand he wanders into its mesh.\n'),
	(8482, 15, 18, 9, 'A snare will take him by the heel.\nA trap will catch him.\n'),
	(8483, 15, 18, 10, 'A noose is hidden for him in the ground,\na trap for him on the path.\n'),
	(8484, 15, 18, 11, 'Terrors shall make him afraid on every side,\nand shall chase him at his heels.\n'),
	(8485, 15, 18, 12, 'His strength shall be famished.\nCalamity shall be ready at his side.\n'),
	(8486, 15, 18, 13, 'The members of his body shall be devoured.\nThe firstborn of death shall devour his members.\n'),
	(8487, 15, 18, 14, 'He shall be rooted out of the security of his tent.\nHe shall be brought to the king of terrors.\n'),
	(8488, 15, 18, 15, 'There shall dwell in his tent that which is none of his.\nSulfur shall be scattered on his habitation.\n'),
	(8489, 15, 18, 16, 'His roots shall be dried up beneath.\nAbove shall his branch be cut off.\n'),
	(8490, 15, 18, 17, 'His memory shall perish from the earth.\nHe shall have no name in the street.\n'),
	(8491, 15, 18, 18, 'He shall be driven from light into darkness,\nand chased out of the world.\n'),
	(8492, 15, 18, 19, 'He shall have neither son nor grandson among his people,\nnor any remaining where he lived.\n'),
	(8493, 15, 18, 20, 'Those who come after shall be astonished at his day,\nas those who went before were frightened.\n'),
	(8494, 15, 18, 21, 'Surely such are the dwellings of the unrighteous.\nThis is the place of him who doesn’t know God.”\n'),
	(8495, 15, 19, 1, 'Then Job answered,\n'),
	(8496, 15, 19, 2, '“How long will you torment me,\nand crush me with words?\n'),
	(8497, 15, 19, 3, 'You have reproached me ten times.\nYou aren’t ashamed that you attack me.\n'),
	(8498, 15, 19, 4, 'If it is true that I have erred,\nmy error remains with myself.\n'),
	(8499, 15, 19, 5, 'If indeed you will magnify yourselves against me,\nand plead against me my reproach;\n'),
	(8500, 15, 19, 6, 'know now that God has subverted me,\nand has surrounded me with his net.\n'),
	(8501, 15, 19, 7, '“Behold, I cry out of wrong, but I am not heard.\nI cry for help, but there is no justice.\n'),
	(8502, 15, 19, 8, 'He has walled up my way so that I can’t pass,\nand has set darkness in my paths.\n'),
	(8503, 15, 19, 9, 'He has stripped me of my glory,\nand taken the crown from my head.\n'),
	(8504, 15, 19, 10, 'He has broken me down on every side, and I am gone.\nMy hope he has plucked up like a tree.\n'),
	(8505, 15, 19, 11, 'He has also kindled his wrath against me.\nHe counts me among his adversaries.\n'),
	(8506, 15, 19, 12, 'His troops come on together,\nbuild a siege ramp against me,\nand encamp around my tent.\n'),
	(8507, 15, 19, 13, '“He has put my brothers far from me.\nMy acquaintances are wholly estranged from me.\n'),
	(8508, 15, 19, 14, 'My relatives have gone away.\nMy familiar friends have forgotten me.\n'),
	(8509, 15, 19, 15, 'Those who dwell in my house and my maids consider me a stranger.\nI am an alien in their sight.\n'),
	(8510, 15, 19, 16, 'I call to my servant, and he gives me no answer.\nI beg him with my mouth.\n'),
	(8511, 15, 19, 17, 'My breath is offensive to my wife.\nI am loathsome to the children of my own mother.\n'),
	(8512, 15, 19, 18, 'Even young children despise me.\nIf I arise, they speak against me.\n'),
	(8513, 15, 19, 19, 'All my familiar friends abhor me.\nThey whom I loved have turned against me.\n'),
	(8514, 15, 19, 20, 'My bones stick to my skin and to my flesh.\nI have escaped by the skin of my teeth.\n'),
	(8515, 15, 19, 21, '“Have pity on me, have pity on me, you my friends;\nfor the hand of God has touched me.\n'),
	(8516, 15, 19, 22, 'Why do you persecute me as God,\nand are not satisfied with my flesh?\n'),
	(8517, 15, 19, 23, '“Oh that my words were now written!\nOh that they were inscribed in a book!\n'),
	(8518, 15, 19, 24, 'That with an iron pen and lead\nthey were engraved in the rock forever!\n'),
	(8519, 15, 19, 25, 'But as for me, I know that my Redeemer lives.\nIn the end, he will stand upon the earth.\n'),
	(8520, 15, 19, 26, 'After my skin is destroyed,\nthen in my flesh shall I see God,\n'),
	(8521, 15, 19, 27, 'Whom I, even I, shall see on my side.\nMy eyes shall see, and not as a stranger.\n“My heart is consumed within me.\n'),
	(8522, 15, 19, 28, 'If you say, ‘How we will persecute him!’\nbecause the root of the matter is found in me,\n'),
	(8523, 15, 19, 29, 'be afraid of the sword,\nfor wrath brings the punishments of the sword,\nthat you may know there is a judgment.”\n'),
	(8524, 15, 20, 1, 'Then Zophar the Naamathite answered,\n'),
	(8525, 15, 20, 2, '“Therefore do my thoughts give answer to me,\neven by reason of my haste that is in me.\n'),
	(8526, 15, 20, 3, 'I have heard the reproof which puts me to shame.\nThe spirit of my understanding answers me.\n'),
	(8527, 15, 20, 4, 'Don’t you know this from old time,\nsince man was placed on earth,\n'),
	(8528, 15, 20, 5, 'that the triumphing of the wicked is short,\nthe joy of the godless but for a moment?\n'),
	(8529, 15, 20, 6, 'Though his height mount up to the heavens,\nand his head reach to the clouds,\n'),
	(8530, 15, 20, 7, 'yet he shall perish forever like his own dung.\nThose who have seen him shall say, ‘Where is he?’\n'),
	(8531, 15, 20, 8, 'He shall fly away as a dream, and shall not be found.\nYes, he shall be chased away like a vision of the night.\n'),
	(8532, 15, 20, 9, 'The eye which saw him shall see him no more,\nneither shall his place any more see him.\n'),
	(8533, 15, 20, 10, 'His children shall seek the favor of the poor.\nHis hands shall give back his wealth.\n'),
	(8534, 15, 20, 11, 'His bones are full of his youth,\nbut youth shall lie down with him in the dust.\n'),
	(8535, 15, 20, 12, '“Though wickedness is sweet in his mouth,\nthough he hide it under his tongue,\n'),
	(8536, 15, 20, 13, 'though he spare it, and will not let it go,\nbut keep it still within his mouth;\n'),
	(8537, 15, 20, 14, 'yet his food in his bowels is turned.\nIt is cobra venom within him.\n'),
	(8538, 15, 20, 15, 'He has swallowed down riches, and he shall vomit them up again.\nGod will cast them out of his belly.\n'),
	(8539, 15, 20, 16, 'He shall suck cobra venom.\nThe viper’s tongue shall kill him.\n'),
	(8540, 15, 20, 17, 'He shall not look at the rivers,\nthe flowing streams of honey and butter.\n'),
	(8541, 15, 20, 18, 'That for which he labored he shall restore, and shall not swallow it down.\nAccording to the substance that he has gotten, he shall not rejoice.\n'),
	(8542, 15, 20, 19, 'For he has oppressed and forsaken the poor.\nHe has violently taken away a house, and he shall not build it up.\n'),
	(8543, 15, 20, 20, '“Because he knew no quietness within him,\nhe shall not save anything of that in which he delights.\n'),
	(8544, 15, 20, 21, 'There was nothing left that he didn’t devour,\ntherefore his prosperity shall not endure.\n'),
	(8545, 15, 20, 22, 'In the fullness of his sufficiency, distress shall overtake him.\nThe hand of everyone who is in misery shall come on him.\n'),
	(8546, 15, 20, 23, 'When he is about to fill his belly, God will cast the fierceness of his wrath on him.\nIt will rain on him while he is eating.\n'),
	(8547, 15, 20, 24, 'He shall flee from the iron weapon.\nThe bronze arrow shall strike him through.\n'),
	(8548, 15, 20, 25, 'He draws it out, and it comes out of his body.\nYes, the glittering point comes out of his liver.\nTerrors are on him.\n'),
	(8549, 15, 20, 26, 'All darkness is laid up for his treasures.\nAn unfanned fire shall devour him.\nIt shall consume that which is left in his tent.\n'),
	(8550, 15, 20, 27, 'The heavens shall reveal his iniquity.\nThe earth shall rise up against him.\n'),
	(8551, 15, 20, 28, 'The increase of his house shall depart.\nThey shall rush away in the day of his wrath.\n'),
	(8552, 15, 20, 29, 'This is the portion of a wicked man from God,\nthe heritage appointed to him by God.”\n'),
	(8553, 15, 21, 1, 'Then Job answered,\n'),
	(8554, 15, 21, 2, '“Listen diligently to my speech.\nLet this be your consolation.\n'),
	(8555, 15, 21, 3, 'Allow me, and I also will speak;\nAfter I have spoken, mock on.\n'),
	(8556, 15, 21, 4, 'As for me, is my complaint to man?\nWhy shouldn’t I be impatient?\n'),
	(8557, 15, 21, 5, 'Look at me, and be astonished.\nLay your hand on your mouth.\n'),
	(8558, 15, 21, 6, 'When I remember, I am troubled.\nHorror takes hold of my flesh.\n'),
	(8559, 15, 21, 7, '“Why do the wicked live,\nbecome old, yes, and grow mighty in power?\n'),
	(8560, 15, 21, 8, 'Their child is established with them in their sight,\ntheir offspring before their eyes.\n'),
	(8561, 15, 21, 9, 'Their houses are safe from fear,\nneither is the rod of God upon them.\n'),
	(8562, 15, 21, 10, 'Their bulls breed without fail.\nTheir cows calve, and don’t miscarry.\n'),
	(8563, 15, 21, 11, 'They send out their little ones like a flock.\nTheir children dance.\n'),
	(8564, 15, 21, 12, 'They sing to the tambourine and harp,\nand rejoice at the sound of the pipe.\n'),
	(8565, 15, 21, 13, 'They spend their days in prosperity.\nIn an instant they go down to Sheol.\n'),
	(8566, 15, 21, 14, 'They tell God, ‘Depart from us,\nfor we don’t want to know about your ways.\n'),
	(8567, 15, 21, 15, 'What is the Almighty, that we should serve him?\nWhat profit should we have, if we pray to him?’\n'),
	(8568, 15, 21, 16, 'Behold, their prosperity is not in their hand.\nThe counsel of the wicked is far from me.\n'),
	(8569, 15, 21, 17, '“How often is it that the lamp of the wicked is put out,\nthat their calamity comes on them,\nthat God distributes sorrows in his anger?\n'),
	(8570, 15, 21, 18, 'How often is it that they are as stubble before the wind,\nas chaff that the storm carries away?\n'),
	(8571, 15, 21, 19, 'You say, ‘God lays up his iniquity for his children.’\nLet him recompense it to himself, that he may know it.\n'),
	(8572, 15, 21, 20, 'Let his own eyes see his destruction.\nLet him drink of the wrath of the Almighty.\n'),
	(8573, 15, 21, 21, 'For what does he care for his house after him,\nwhen the number of his months is cut off?\n'),
	(8574, 15, 21, 22, '“Shall any teach God knowledge,\nsince he judges those who are high?\n'),
	(8575, 15, 21, 23, 'One dies in his full strength,\nbeing wholly at ease and quiet.\n'),
	(8576, 15, 21, 24, 'His pails are full of milk.\nThe marrow of his bones is moistened.\n'),
	(8577, 15, 21, 25, 'Another dies in bitterness of soul,\nand never tastes of good.\n'),
	(8578, 15, 21, 26, 'They lie down alike in the dust.\nThe worm covers them.\n'),
	(8579, 15, 21, 27, '“Behold, I know your thoughts,\nthe plans with which you would wrong me.\n'),
	(8580, 15, 21, 28, 'For you say, ‘Where is the house of the prince?\nWhere is the tent in which the wicked lived?’\n'),
	(8581, 15, 21, 29, 'Haven’t you asked wayfaring men?\nDon’t you know their evidences,\n'),
	(8582, 15, 21, 30, 'that the evil man is reserved to the day of calamity,\nThat they are led out to the day of wrath?\n'),
	(8583, 15, 21, 31, 'Who shall declare his way to his face?\nWho shall repay him what he has done?\n'),
	(8584, 15, 21, 32, 'Yet he will be borne to the grave.\nMen shall keep watch over the tomb.\n'),
	(8585, 15, 21, 33, 'The clods of the valley shall be sweet to him.\nAll men shall draw after him,\nas there were innumerable before him.\n'),
	(8586, 15, 21, 34, 'So how can you comfort me with nonsense,\nbecause in your answers there remains only falsehood?”\n'),
	(8587, 15, 22, 1, 'Then Eliphaz the Temanite answered,\n'),
	(8588, 15, 22, 2, '“Can a man be profitable to God?\nSurely he who is wise is profitable to himself.\n'),
	(8589, 15, 22, 3, 'Is it any pleasure to the Almighty, that you are righteous?\nOr does it benefit him, that you make your ways perfect?\n'),
	(8590, 15, 22, 4, 'Is it for your piety that he reproves you,\nthat he enters with you into judgment?\n'),
	(8591, 15, 22, 5, 'Isn’t your wickedness great?\nNeither is there any end to your iniquities.\n'),
	(8592, 15, 22, 6, 'For you have taken pledges from your brother for nothing,\nand stripped the naked of their clothing.\n'),
	(8593, 15, 22, 7, 'You haven’t given water to the weary to drink,\nand you have withheld bread from the hungry.\n'),
	(8594, 15, 22, 8, 'But as for the mighty man, he had the earth.\nThe honorable man, he lived in it.\n'),
	(8595, 15, 22, 9, 'You have sent widows away empty,\nand the arms of the fatherless have been broken.\n'),
	(8596, 15, 22, 10, 'Therefore snares are around you.\nSudden fear troubles you,\n'),
	(8597, 15, 22, 11, 'or darkness, so that you can not see,\nand floods of waters cover you.\n'),
	(8598, 15, 22, 12, '“Isn’t God in the heights of heaven?\nSee the height of the stars, how high they are!\n'),
	(8599, 15, 22, 13, 'You say, ‘What does God know?\nCan he judge through the thick darkness?\n'),
	(8600, 15, 22, 14, 'Thick clouds are a covering to him, so that he doesn’t see.\nHe walks on the vault of the sky.’\n'),
	(8601, 15, 22, 15, 'Will you keep the old way,\nwhich wicked men have trodden,\n'),
	(8602, 15, 22, 16, 'who were snatched away before their time,\nwhose foundation was poured out as a stream,\n'),
	(8603, 15, 22, 17, 'who said to God, ‘Depart from us;’\nand, ‘What can the Almighty do for us?’\n'),
	(8604, 15, 22, 18, 'Yet he filled their houses with good things,\nbut the counsel of the wicked is far from me.\n'),
	(8605, 15, 22, 19, 'The righteous see it, and are glad.\nThe innocent ridicule them,\n'),
	(8606, 15, 22, 20, 'saying, ‘Surely those who rose up against us are cut off.\nThe fire has consumed their remnant.’\n'),
	(8607, 15, 22, 21, '“Acquaint yourself with him, now, and be at peace.\nThereby good shall come to you.\n'),
	(8608, 15, 22, 22, 'Please receive instruction from his mouth,\nand lay up his words in your heart.\n'),
	(8609, 15, 22, 23, 'If you return to the Almighty, you shall be built up,\nif you put away unrighteousness far from your tents.\n'),
	(8610, 15, 22, 24, 'Lay your treasure in the dust,\nthe gold of Ophir among the stones of the brooks.\n'),
	(8611, 15, 22, 25, 'The Almighty will be your treasure,\nand precious silver to you.\n'),
	(8612, 15, 22, 26, 'For then you will delight yourself in the Almighty,\nand shall lift up your face to God.\n'),
	(8613, 15, 22, 27, 'You shall make your prayer to him, and he will hear you.\nYou shall pay your vows.\n'),
	(8614, 15, 22, 28, 'You shall also decree a thing, and it shall be established to you.\nLight shall shine on your ways.\n'),
	(8615, 15, 22, 29, 'When they cast down, you shall say, ‘be lifted up.’\nHe will save the humble person.\n'),
	(8616, 15, 22, 30, 'He will even deliver him who is not innocent.\nYes, he shall be delivered through the cleanness of your hands.”\n'),
	(8617, 15, 23, 1, 'Then Job answered,\n'),
	(8618, 15, 23, 2, '“Even today my complaint is rebellious.\nHis hand is heavy in spite of my groaning.\n'),
	(8619, 15, 23, 3, 'Oh that I knew where I might find him!\nThat I might come even to his seat!\n'),
	(8620, 15, 23, 4, 'I would set my cause in order before him,\nand fill my mouth with arguments.\n'),
	(8621, 15, 23, 5, 'I would know the words which he would answer me,\nand understand what he would tell me.\n'),
	(8622, 15, 23, 6, 'Would he contend with me in the greatness of his power?\nNo, but he would listen to me.\n'),
	(8623, 15, 23, 7, 'There the upright might reason with him,\nso I should be delivered forever from my judge.\n'),
	(8624, 15, 23, 8, '“If I go east, he is not there;\nif west, I can’t find him;\n'),
	(8625, 15, 23, 9, 'He works to the north, but I can’t see him.\nHe turns south, but I can’t catch a glimpse of him.\n'),
	(8626, 15, 23, 10, 'But he knows the way that I take.\nWhen he has tried me, I shall come out like gold.\n'),
	(8627, 15, 23, 11, 'My foot has held fast to his steps.\nI have kept his way, and not turned away.\n'),
	(8628, 15, 23, 12, 'I haven’t gone back from the commandment of his lips.\nI have treasured up the words of his mouth more than my necessary food.\n'),
	(8629, 15, 23, 13, 'But he stands alone, and who can oppose him?\nWhat his soul desires, even that he does.\n'),
	(8630, 15, 23, 14, 'For he performs that which is appointed for me.\nMany such things are with him.\n'),
	(8631, 15, 23, 15, 'Therefore I am terrified at his presence.\nWhen I consider, I am afraid of him.\n'),
	(8632, 15, 23, 16, 'For God has made my heart faint.\nThe Almighty has terrified me.\n'),
	(8633, 15, 23, 17, 'Because I was not cut off before the darkness,\nneither did he cover the thick darkness from my face.\n'),
	(8634, 15, 24, 1, '“Why aren’t times laid up by the Almighty?\nWhy don’t those who know him see his days?\n'),
	(8635, 15, 24, 2, 'There are people who remove the landmarks.\nThey violently take away flocks, and feed them.\n'),
	(8636, 15, 24, 3, 'They drive away the donkey of the fatherless,\nand they take the widow’s ox for a pledge.\n'),
	(8637, 15, 24, 4, 'They turn the needy out of the way.\nThe poor of the earth all hide themselves.\n'),
	(8638, 15, 24, 5, 'Behold, as wild donkeys in the desert,\nthey go out to their work, seeking diligently for food.\nThe wilderness yields them bread for their children.\n'),
	(8639, 15, 24, 6, 'They cut their food in the field.\nThey glean the vineyard of the wicked.\n'),
	(8640, 15, 24, 7, 'They lie all night naked without clothing,\nand have no covering in the cold.\n'),
	(8641, 15, 24, 8, 'They are wet with the showers of the mountains,\nand embrace the rock for lack of a shelter.\n'),
	(8642, 15, 24, 9, 'There are those who pluck the fatherless from the breast,\nand take a pledge of the poor,\n'),
	(8643, 15, 24, 10, 'So that they go around naked without clothing.\nBeing hungry, they carry the sheaves.\n'),
	(8644, 15, 24, 11, 'They make oil within the walls of these men.\nThey tread wine presses, and suffer thirst.\n'),
	(8645, 15, 24, 12, 'From out of the populous city, men groan.\nThe soul of the wounded cries out,\nyet God doesn’t regard the folly.\n'),
	(8646, 15, 24, 13, '“These are of those who rebel against the light.\nThey don’t know its ways,\nnor stay in its paths.\n'),
	(8647, 15, 24, 14, 'The murderer rises with the light.\nHe kills the poor and needy.\nIn the night he is like a thief.\n'),
	(8648, 15, 24, 15, 'The eye also of the adulterer waits for the twilight,\nsaying, ‘No eye shall see me.’\nHe disguises his face.\n'),
	(8649, 15, 24, 16, 'In the dark they dig through houses.\nThey shut themselves up in the daytime.\nThey don’t know the light.\n'),
	(8650, 15, 24, 17, 'For the morning is to all of them like thick darkness,\nfor they know the terrors of the thick darkness.\n'),
	(8651, 15, 24, 18, '“They are foam on the surface of the waters.\nTheir portion is cursed in the earth.\nThey don’t turn into the way of the vineyards.\n'),
	(8652, 15, 24, 19, 'Drought and heat consume the snow waters,\nso does Sheol those who have sinned.\n'),
	(8653, 15, 24, 20, 'The womb shall forget him.\nThe worm shall feed sweetly on him.\nHe shall be no more remembered.\nUnrighteousness shall be broken as a tree.\n'),
	(8654, 15, 24, 21, 'He devours the barren who don’t bear.\nHe shows no kindness to the widow.\n'),
	(8655, 15, 24, 22, 'Yet God preserves the mighty by his power.\nHe rises up who has no assurance of life.\n'),
	(8656, 15, 24, 23, 'God gives them security, and they rest in it.\nHis eyes are on their ways.\n'),
	(8657, 15, 24, 24, 'They are exalted; yet a little while, and they are gone.\nYes, they are brought low, they are taken out of the way as all others,\nand are cut off as the tops of the ears of grain.\n'),
	(8658, 15, 24, 25, 'If it isn’t so now, who will prove me a liar,\nand make my speech worth nothing?”\n'),
	(8659, 15, 25, 1, 'Then Bildad the Shuhite answered,\n'),
	(8660, 15, 25, 2, '“Dominion and fear are with him.\nHe makes peace in his high places.\n'),
	(8661, 15, 25, 3, 'Can his armies be counted?\nOn whom does his light not arise?\n'),
	(8662, 15, 25, 4, 'How then can man be just with God?\nOr how can he who is born of a woman be clean?\n'),
	(8663, 15, 25, 5, 'Behold, even the moon has no brightness,\nand the stars are not pure in his sight;\n'),
	(8664, 15, 25, 6, 'How much less man, who is a worm,\nthe son of man, who is a worm!”\n'),
	(8665, 15, 26, 1, 'Then Job answered,\n'),
	(8666, 15, 26, 2, '“How have you helped him who is without power!\nHow have you saved the arm that has no strength!\n'),
	(8667, 15, 26, 3, 'How have you counseled him who has no wisdom,\nand plentifully declared sound knowledge!\n'),
	(8668, 15, 26, 4, 'To whom have you uttered words?\nWhose spirit came out of you?\n'),
	(8669, 15, 26, 5, '“The departed spirits tremble,\nthose beneath the waters and all that live in them.\n'),
	(8670, 15, 26, 6, 'Sheol is naked before God,\nand Abaddon has no covering.\n'),
	(8671, 15, 26, 7, 'He stretches out the north over empty space,\nand hangs the earth on nothing.\n'),
	(8672, 15, 26, 8, 'He binds up the waters in his thick clouds,\nand the cloud is not burst under them.\n'),
	(8673, 15, 26, 9, 'He encloses the face of his throne,\nand spreads his cloud on it.\n'),
	(8674, 15, 26, 10, 'He has described a boundary on the surface of the waters,\nand to the confines of light and darkness.\n'),
	(8675, 15, 26, 11, 'The pillars of heaven tremble\nand are astonished at his rebuke.\n'),
	(8676, 15, 26, 12, 'He stirs up the sea with his power,\nand by his understanding he strikes through Rahab.\n'),
	(8677, 15, 26, 13, 'By his Spirit the heavens are garnished.\nHis hand has pierced the swift serpent.\n'),
	(8678, 15, 26, 14, 'Behold, these are but the outskirts of his ways.\nHow small a whisper do we hear of him!\nBut the thunder of his power who can understand?”\n'),
	(8679, 15, 27, 1, 'Job again took up his parable, and said,\n'),
	(8680, 15, 27, 2, '“As God lives, who has taken away my right,\nthe Almighty, who has made my soul bitter\n'),
	(8681, 15, 27, 3, '(for the length of my life is still in me,\nand the spirit of God is in my nostrils);\n'),
	(8682, 15, 27, 4, 'surely my lips shall not speak unrighteousness,\nneither shall my tongue utter deceit.\n'),
	(8683, 15, 27, 5, 'Far be it from me that I should justify you.\nUntil I die I will not put away my integrity from me.\n'),
	(8684, 15, 27, 6, 'I hold fast to my righteousness, and will not let it go.\nMy heart shall not reproach me so long as I live.\n'),
	(8685, 15, 27, 7, '“Let my enemy be as the wicked.\nLet him who rises up against me be as the unrighteous.\n'),
	(8686, 15, 27, 8, 'For what is the hope of the godless, when he is cut off, when God takes away his life?\n'),
	(8687, 15, 27, 9, 'Will God hear his cry when trouble comes on him?\n'),
	(8688, 15, 27, 10, 'Will he delight himself in the Almighty,\nand call on God at all times?\n'),
	(8689, 15, 27, 11, 'I will teach you about the hand of God.\nThat which is with the Almighty will I not conceal.\n'),
	(8690, 15, 27, 12, 'Behold, all of you have seen it yourselves;\nwhy then have you become altogether vain?\n'),
	(8691, 15, 27, 13, '“This is the portion of a wicked man with God,\nthe heritage of oppressors, which they receive from the Almighty.\n'),
	(8692, 15, 27, 14, 'If his children are multiplied, it is for the sword.\nHis offspring shall not be satisfied with bread.\n'),
	(8693, 15, 27, 15, 'Those who remain of him shall be buried in death.\nHis widows shall make no lamentation.\n'),
	(8694, 15, 27, 16, 'Though he heap up silver as the dust,\nand prepare clothing as the clay;\n'),
	(8695, 15, 27, 17, 'he may prepare it, but the just shall put it on,\nand the innocent shall divide the silver.\n'),
	(8696, 15, 27, 18, 'He builds his house as the moth,\nas a booth which the watchman makes.\n'),
	(8697, 15, 27, 19, 'He lies down rich, but he shall not do so again.\nHe opens his eyes, and he is not.\n'),
	(8698, 15, 27, 20, 'Terrors overtake him like waters.\nA storm steals him away in the night.\n'),
	(8699, 15, 27, 21, 'The east wind carries him away, and he departs.\nIt sweeps him out of his place.\n'),
	(8700, 15, 27, 22, 'For it hurls at him, and does not spare,\nas he flees away from his hand.\n'),
	(8701, 15, 27, 23, 'Men shall clap their hands at him,\nand shall hiss him out of his place.\n'),
	(8702, 15, 28, 1, '“Surely there is a mine for silver,\nand a place for gold which they refine.\n'),
	(8703, 15, 28, 2, 'Iron is taken out of the earth,\nand copper is smelted out of the ore.\n'),
	(8704, 15, 28, 3, 'Man sets an end to darkness,\nand searches out, to the furthest bound,\nthe stones of obscurity and of thick darkness.\n'),
	(8705, 15, 28, 4, 'He breaks open a shaft away from where people live.\nThey are forgotten by the foot.\nThey hang far from men, they swing back and forth.\n'),
	(8706, 15, 28, 5, 'As for the earth, out of it comes bread;\nUnderneath it is turned up as it were by fire.\n'),
	(8707, 15, 28, 6, 'Sapphires come from its rocks.\nIt has dust of gold.\n'),
	(8708, 15, 28, 7, 'That path no bird of prey knows,\nneither has the falcon’s eye seen it.\n'),
	(8709, 15, 28, 8, 'The proud animals have not trodden it,\nnor has the fierce lion passed by there.\n'),
	(8710, 15, 28, 9, 'He puts his hand on the flinty rock,\nand he overturns the mountains by the roots.\n'),
	(8711, 15, 28, 10, 'He cuts out channels among the rocks.\nHis eye sees every precious thing.\n'),
	(8712, 15, 28, 11, 'He binds the streams that they don’t trickle.\nThe thing that is hidden he brings out to light.\n'),
	(8713, 15, 28, 12, '“But where shall wisdom be found?\nWhere is the place of understanding?\n'),
	(8714, 15, 28, 13, 'Man doesn’t know its price;\nNeither is it found in the land of the living.\n'),
	(8715, 15, 28, 14, 'The deep says, ‘It isn’t in me.’\nThe sea says, ‘It isn’t with me.’\n'),
	(8716, 15, 28, 15, 'It can’t be gotten for gold,\nneither shall silver be weighed for its price.\n'),
	(8717, 15, 28, 16, 'It can’t be valued with the gold of Ophir,\nwith the precious onyx, or the sapphire.\n'),
	(8718, 15, 28, 17, 'Gold and glass can’t equal it,\nneither shall it be exchanged for jewels of fine gold.\n'),
	(8719, 15, 28, 18, 'No mention shall be made of coral or of crystal.\nYes, the price of wisdom is above rubies.\n'),
	(8720, 15, 28, 19, 'The topaz of Ethiopia shall not equal it,\nNeither shall it be valued with pure gold.\n'),
	(8721, 15, 28, 20, 'Where then does wisdom come from?\nWhere is the place of understanding?\n'),
	(8722, 15, 28, 21, 'Seeing it is hidden from the eyes of all living,\nand kept close from the birds of the sky.\n'),
	(8723, 15, 28, 22, 'Destruction and Death say,\n‘We have heard a rumor of it with our ears.’\n'),
	(8724, 15, 28, 23, '“God understands its way,\nand he knows its place.\n'),
	(8725, 15, 28, 24, 'For he looks to the ends of the earth,\nand sees under the whole sky.\n'),
	(8726, 15, 28, 25, 'He establishes the force of the wind.\nYes, he measures out the waters by measure.\n'),
	(8727, 15, 28, 26, 'When he made a decree for the rain,\nand a way for the lightning of the thunder;\n'),
	(8728, 15, 28, 27, 'then he saw it, and declared it.\nHe established it, yes, and searched it out.\n'),
	(8729, 15, 28, 28, 'To man he said,\n‘Behold, the fear of the Lord, that is wisdom.\nTo depart from evil is understanding.’”\n'),
	(8730, 15, 29, 1, 'Job again took up his parable, and said,\n'),
	(8731, 15, 29, 2, '“Oh that I were as in the months of old,\nas in the days when God watched over me;\n'),
	(8732, 15, 29, 3, 'when his lamp shone on my head,\nand by his light I walked through darkness,\n'),
	(8733, 15, 29, 4, 'as I was in the ripeness of my days,\nwhen the friendship of God was in my tent,\n'),
	(8734, 15, 29, 5, 'when the Almighty was yet with me,\nand my children were around me,\n'),
	(8735, 15, 29, 6, 'when my steps were washed with butter,\nand the rock poured out streams of oil for me,\n'),
	(8736, 15, 29, 7, 'when I went out to the city gate,\nwhen I prepared my seat in the street.\n'),
	(8737, 15, 29, 8, 'The young men saw me and hid themselves.\nThe aged rose up and stood.\n'),
	(8738, 15, 29, 9, 'The princes refrained from talking,\nand laid their hand on their mouth.\n'),
	(8739, 15, 29, 10, 'The voice of the nobles was hushed,\nand their tongue stuck to the roof of their mouth.\n'),
	(8740, 15, 29, 11, 'For when the ear heard me, then it blessed me;\nand when the eye saw me, it commended me:\n'),
	(8741, 15, 29, 12, 'Because I delivered the poor who cried,\nand the fatherless also, who had no one to help him,\n'),
	(8742, 15, 29, 13, 'the blessing of him who was ready to perish came on me,\nand I caused the widow’s heart to sing for joy.\n'),
	(8743, 15, 29, 14, 'I put on righteousness, and it clothed me.\nMy justice was as a robe and a diadem.\n'),
	(8744, 15, 29, 15, 'I was eyes to the blind,\nand feet to the lame.\n'),
	(8745, 15, 29, 16, 'I was a father to the needy.\nThe cause of him who I didn’t know, I searched out.\n'),
	(8746, 15, 29, 17, 'I broke the jaws of the unrighteous,\nand plucked the prey out of his teeth.\n'),
	(8747, 15, 29, 18, 'Then I said, ‘I shall die in my own house,\nI shall count my days as the sand.\n'),
	(8748, 15, 29, 19, 'My root is spread out to the waters.\nThe dew lies all night on my branch.\n'),
	(8749, 15, 29, 20, 'My glory is fresh in me.\nMy bow is renewed in my hand.’\n'),
	(8750, 15, 29, 21, '“Men listened to me, waited,\nand kept silence for my counsel.\n'),
	(8751, 15, 29, 22, 'After my words they didn’t speak again.\nMy speech fell on them.\n'),
	(8752, 15, 29, 23, 'They waited for me as for the rain.\nTheir mouths drank as with the spring rain.\n'),
	(8753, 15, 29, 24, 'I smiled on them when they had no confidence.\nThey didn’t reject the light of my face.\n'),
	(8754, 15, 29, 25, 'I chose out their way, and sat as chief.\nI lived as a king in the army,\nas one who comforts the mourners.\n'),
	(8755, 15, 30, 1, '“But now those who are younger than I have me in derision,\nwhose fathers I would have disdained to put with my sheep dogs.\n'),
	(8756, 15, 30, 2, 'Of what use is the strength of their hands to me,\nmen in whom ripe age has perished?\n'),
	(8757, 15, 30, 3, 'They are gaunt from lack and famine.\nThey gnaw the dry ground, in the gloom of waste and desolation.\n'),
	(8758, 15, 30, 4, 'They pluck salt herbs by the bushes.\nThe roots of the broom are their food.\n'),
	(8759, 15, 30, 5, 'They are driven out from among men.\nThey cry after them as after a thief;\n'),
	(8760, 15, 30, 6, 'So that they dwell in frightful valleys,\nand in holes of the earth and of the rocks.\n'),
	(8761, 15, 30, 7, 'Among the bushes they bray;\nand under the nettles they are gathered together.\n'),
	(8762, 15, 30, 8, 'They are children of fools, yes, children of wicked men.\nThey were flogged out of the land.\n'),
	(8763, 15, 30, 9, '“Now I have become their song.\nYes, I am a byword to them.\n'),
	(8764, 15, 30, 10, 'They abhor me, they stand aloof from me,\nand don’t hesitate to spit in my face.\n'),
	(8765, 15, 30, 11, 'For he has untied his cord, and afflicted me;\nand they have thrown off restraint before me.\n'),
	(8766, 15, 30, 12, 'On my right hand rise the rabble.\nThey thrust aside my feet,\nThey cast up against me their ways of destruction.\n'),
	(8767, 15, 30, 13, 'They mar my path,\nThey set forward my calamity,\nwithout anyone’s help.\n'),
	(8768, 15, 30, 14, 'As through a wide breach they come,\nin the middle of the ruin they roll themselves in.\n'),
	(8769, 15, 30, 15, 'Terrors have turned on me.\nThey chase my honor as the wind.\nMy welfare has passed away as a cloud.\n'),
	(8770, 15, 30, 16, '“Now my soul is poured out within me.\nDays of affliction have taken hold on me.\n'),
	(8771, 15, 30, 17, 'In the night season my bones are pierced in me,\nand the pains that gnaw me take no rest.\n'),
	(8772, 15, 30, 18, 'By great force is my garment disfigured.\nIt binds me about as the collar of my coat.\n'),
	(8773, 15, 30, 19, 'He has cast me into the mire.\nI have become like dust and ashes.\n'),
	(8774, 15, 30, 20, 'I cry to you, and you do not answer me.\nI stand up, and you gaze at me.\n'),
	(8775, 15, 30, 21, 'You have turned to be cruel to me.\nWith the might of your hand you persecute me.\n'),
	(8776, 15, 30, 22, 'You lift me up to the wind, and drive me with it.\nYou dissolve me in the storm.\n'),
	(8777, 15, 30, 23, 'For I know that you will bring me to death,\nTo the house appointed for all living.\n'),
	(8778, 15, 30, 24, '“However doesn’t one stretch out a hand in his fall?\nOr in his calamity therefore cry for help?\n'),
	(8779, 15, 30, 25, 'Didn’t I weep for him who was in trouble?\nWasn’t my soul grieved for the needy?\n'),
	(8780, 15, 30, 26, 'When I looked for good, then evil came;\nWhen I waited for light, there came darkness.\n'),
	(8781, 15, 30, 27, 'My heart is troubled, and doesn’t rest.\nDays of affliction have come on me.\n'),
	(8782, 15, 30, 28, 'I go mourning without the sun.\nI stand up in the assembly, and cry for help.\n'),
	(8783, 15, 30, 29, 'I am a brother to jackals,\nand a companion to ostriches.\n'),
	(8784, 15, 30, 30, 'My skin grows black and peels from me.\nMy bones are burned with heat.\n'),
	(8785, 15, 30, 31, 'Therefore my harp has turned to mourning,\nand my pipe into the voice of those who weep.\n'),
	(8786, 15, 31, 1, '“I made a covenant with my eyes,\nhow then should I look lustfully at a young woman?\n'),
	(8787, 15, 31, 2, 'For what is the portion from God above,\nand the heritage from the Almighty on high?\n'),
	(8788, 15, 31, 3, 'Is it not calamity to the unrighteous,\nand disaster to the workers of iniquity?\n'),
	(8789, 15, 31, 4, 'Doesn’t he see my ways,\nand count all my steps?\n'),
	(8790, 15, 31, 5, '“If I have walked with falsehood,\nand my foot has hurried to deceit\n'),
	(8791, 15, 31, 6, '(let me be weighed in an even balance,\nthat God may know my integrity);\n'),
	(8792, 15, 31, 7, 'if my step has turned out of the way,\nif my heart walked after my eyes,\nif any defilement has stuck to my hands,\n'),
	(8793, 15, 31, 8, 'then let me sow, and let another eat.\nYes, let the produce of my field be rooted out.\n'),
	(8794, 15, 31, 9, '“If my heart has been enticed to a woman,\nand I have laid wait at my neighbor’s door,\n'),
	(8795, 15, 31, 10, 'then let my wife grind for another,\nand let others sleep with her.\n'),
	(8796, 15, 31, 11, 'For that would be a heinous crime.\nYes, it would be an iniquity to be punished by the judges:\n'),
	(8797, 15, 31, 12, 'For it is a fire that consumes to destruction,\nand would root out all my increase.\n'),
	(8798, 15, 31, 13, '“If I have despised the cause of my male servant\nor of my female servant,\nwhen they contended with me;\n'),
	(8799, 15, 31, 14, 'What then shall I do when God rises up?\nWhen he visits, what shall I answer him?\n'),
	(8800, 15, 31, 15, 'Didn’t he who made me in the womb make him?\nDidn’t one fashion us in the womb?\n'),
	(8801, 15, 31, 16, '“If I have withheld the poor from their desire,\nor have caused the eyes of the widow to fail,\n'),
	(8802, 15, 31, 17, 'or have eaten my morsel alone,\nand the fatherless has not eaten of it\n'),
	(8803, 15, 31, 18, '(no, from my youth he grew up with me as with a father,\nher I have guided from my mother’s womb);\n'),
	(8804, 15, 31, 19, 'if I have seen any perish for want of clothing,\nor that the needy had no covering;\n'),
	(8805, 15, 31, 20, 'if his heart hasn’t blessed me,\nif he hasn’t been warmed with my sheep’s fleece;\n'),
	(8806, 15, 31, 21, 'if I have lifted up my hand against the fatherless,\nbecause I saw my help in the gate,\n'),
	(8807, 15, 31, 22, 'then let my shoulder fall from the shoulder blade,\nand my arm be broken from the bone.\n'),
	(8808, 15, 31, 23, 'For calamity from God is a terror to me.\nBecause his majesty, I can do nothing.\n'),
	(8809, 15, 31, 24, '“If I have made gold my hope,\nand have said to the fine gold, ‘You are my confidence;’\n'),
	(8810, 15, 31, 25, 'If I have rejoiced because my wealth was great,\nand because my hand had gotten much;\n'),
	(8811, 15, 31, 26, 'if I have seen the sun when it shined,\nor the moon moving in splendor,\n'),
	(8812, 15, 31, 27, 'and my heart has been secretly enticed,\nand my hand threw a kiss from my mouth,\n'),
	(8813, 15, 31, 28, 'this also would be an iniquity to be punished by the judges;\nfor I should have denied the God who is above.\n'),
	(8814, 15, 31, 29, '“If I have rejoiced at the destruction of him who hated me,\nor lifted up myself when evil found him\n'),
	(8815, 15, 31, 30, '(yes, I have not allowed my mouth to sin\nby asking his life with a curse);\n'),
	(8816, 15, 31, 31, 'if the men of my tent have not said,\n‘Who can find one who has not been filled with his meat?’\n'),
	(8817, 15, 31, 32, '(the foreigner has not camped in the street,\nbut I have opened my doors to the traveler);\n'),
	(8818, 15, 31, 33, 'if like Adam I have covered my transgressions,\nby hiding my iniquity in my heart,\n'),
	(8819, 15, 31, 34, 'because I feared the great multitude,\nand the contempt of families terrified me,\nso that I kept silence, and didn’t go out of the door—\n'),
	(8820, 15, 31, 35, 'oh that I had one to hear me!\nBehold, here is my signature! Let the Almighty answer me!\nLet the accuser write my indictment!\n'),
	(8821, 15, 31, 36, 'Surely I would carry it on my shoulder;\nand I would bind it to me as a crown.\n'),
	(8822, 15, 31, 37, 'I would declare to him the number of my steps.\nas a prince would I go near to him.\n'),
	(8823, 15, 31, 38, 'If my land cries out against me,\nand its furrows weep together;\n'),
	(8824, 15, 31, 39, 'if I have eaten its fruits without money,\nor have caused its owners to lose their life,\n'),
	(8825, 15, 31, 40, 'let briers grow instead of wheat,\nand stinkweed instead of barley.”\nThe words of Job are ended.\n'),
	(8826, 15, 32, 1, 'So these three men ceased to answer Job, because he was righteous in his own eyes.\n'),
	(8827, 15, 32, 2, 'Then the wrath of Elihu the son of Barachel, the Buzite, of the family of Ram, was kindled against Job. His wrath was kindled because he justified himself rather than God.\n'),
	(8828, 15, 32, 3, 'Also his wrath was kindled against his three friends, because they had found no answer, and yet had condemned Job.\n'),
	(8829, 15, 32, 4, 'Now Elihu had waited to speak to Job, because they were elder than he.\n'),
	(8830, 15, 32, 5, 'When Elihu saw that there was no answer in the mouth of these three men, his wrath was kindled.\n'),
	(8831, 15, 32, 6, 'Elihu the son of Barachel the Buzite answered,\n“I am young, and you are very old;\nTherefore I held back, and didn’t dare show you my opinion.\n'),
	(8832, 15, 32, 7, 'I said, ‘Days should speak,\nand multitude of years should teach wisdom.’\n'),
	(8833, 15, 32, 8, 'But there is a spirit in man,\nand the breath of the Almighty gives them understanding.\n'),
	(8834, 15, 32, 9, 'It is not the great who are wise,\nnor the aged who understand justice.\n'),
	(8835, 15, 32, 10, 'Therefore I said, ‘Listen to me;\nI also will show my opinion.’\n'),
	(8836, 15, 32, 11, '“Behold, I waited for your words,\nand I listened for your reasoning,\nwhile you searched out what to say.\n'),
	(8837, 15, 32, 12, 'Yes, I gave you my full attention,\nbut there was no one who convinced Job,\nor who answered his words, among you.\n'),
	(8838, 15, 32, 13, 'Beware lest you say, ‘We have found wisdom,\nGod may refute him, not man;’\n'),
	(8839, 15, 32, 14, 'for he has not directed his words against me;\nneither will I answer him with your speeches.\n'),
	(8840, 15, 32, 15, '“They are amazed. They answer no more.\nThey don’t have a word to say.\n'),
	(8841, 15, 32, 16, 'Shall I wait, because they don’t speak,\nbecause they stand still, and answer no more?\n'),
	(8842, 15, 32, 17, 'I also will answer my part,\nand I also will show my opinion.\n'),
	(8843, 15, 32, 18, 'For I am full of words.\nThe spirit within me constrains me.\n'),
	(8844, 15, 32, 19, 'Behold, my breast is as wine which has no vent;\nlike new wineskins it is ready to burst.\n'),
	(8845, 15, 32, 20, 'I will speak, that I may be refreshed.\nI will open my lips and answer.\n'),
	(8846, 15, 32, 21, 'Please don’t let me respect any man’s person,\nneither will I give flattering titles to any man.\n'),
	(8847, 15, 32, 22, 'For I don’t know how to give flattering titles;\nor else my Maker would soon take me away.\n'),
	(8848, 15, 33, 1, '“However, Job, please hear my speech,\nand listen to all my words.\n'),
	(8849, 15, 33, 2, 'See now, I have opened my mouth.\nMy tongue has spoken in my mouth.\n'),
	(8850, 15, 33, 3, 'My words shall utter the uprightness of my heart.\nThat which my lips know they shall speak sincerely.\n'),
	(8851, 15, 33, 4, 'The Spirit of God has made me,\nand the breath of the Almighty gives me life.\n'),
	(8852, 15, 33, 5, 'If you can, answer me.\nSet your words in order before me, and stand up.\n'),
	(8853, 15, 33, 6, 'Behold, I am toward God even as you are.\nI am also formed out of the clay.\n'),
	(8854, 15, 33, 7, 'Behold, my terror shall not make you afraid,\nneither shall my pressure be heavy on you.\n'),
	(8855, 15, 33, 8, '“Surely you have spoken in my hearing,\nI have heard the voice of your words, saying,\n'),
	(8856, 15, 33, 9, '‘I am clean, without disobedience.\nI am innocent, neither is there iniquity in me.\n'),
	(8857, 15, 33, 10, 'Behold, he finds occasions against me.\nHe counts me for his enemy.\n'),
	(8858, 15, 33, 11, 'He puts my feet in the stocks.\nHe marks all my paths.’\n'),
	(8859, 15, 33, 12, '“Behold, I will answer you. In this you are not just,\nfor God is greater than man.\n'),
	(8860, 15, 33, 13, 'Why do you strive against him,\nbecause he doesn’t give account of any of his matters?\n'),
	(8861, 15, 33, 14, 'For God speaks once,\nyes twice, though man pays no attention.\n'),
	(8862, 15, 33, 15, 'In a dream, in a vision of the night,\nwhen deep sleep falls on men,\nin slumbering on the bed;\n'),
	(8863, 15, 33, 16, 'Then he opens the ears of men,\nand seals their instruction,\n'),
	(8864, 15, 33, 17, 'That he may withdraw man from his purpose,\nand hide pride from man.\n'),
	(8865, 15, 33, 18, 'He keeps back his soul from the pit,\nand his life from perishing by the sword.\n'),
	(8866, 15, 33, 19, 'He is chastened also with pain on his bed,\nwith continual strife in his bones;\n'),
	(8867, 15, 33, 20, 'So that his life abhors bread,\nand his soul dainty food.\n'),
	(8868, 15, 33, 21, 'His flesh is so consumed away, that it can’t be seen.\nHis bones that were not seen stick out.\n'),
	(8869, 15, 33, 22, 'Yes, his soul draws near to the pit,\nand his life to the destroyers.\n'),
	(8870, 15, 33, 23, '“If there is beside him an angel,\nan interpreter, one among a thousand,\nto show to man what is right for him;\n'),
	(8871, 15, 33, 24, 'then God is gracious to him, and says,\n‘Deliver him from going down to the pit,\nI have found a ransom.’\n'),
	(8872, 15, 33, 25, 'His flesh shall be fresher than a child’s.\nHe returns to the days of his youth.\n'),
	(8873, 15, 33, 26, 'He prays to God, and he is favorable to him,\nso that he sees his face with joy.\nHe restores to man his righteousness.\n'),
	(8874, 15, 33, 27, 'He sings before men, and says,\n‘I have sinned, and perverted that which was right,\nand it didn’t profit me.\n'),
	(8875, 15, 33, 28, 'He has redeemed my soul from going into the pit.\nMy life shall see the light.’\n'),
	(8876, 15, 33, 29, '“Behold, God does all these things,\ntwice, yes three times, with a man,\n'),
	(8877, 15, 33, 30, 'to bring back his soul from the pit,\nthat he may be enlightened with the light of the living.\n'),
	(8878, 15, 33, 31, 'Mark well, Job, and listen to me.\nHold your peace, and I will speak.\n'),
	(8879, 15, 33, 32, 'If you have anything to say, answer me.\nSpeak, for I desire to justify you.\n'),
	(8880, 15, 33, 33, 'If not, listen to me.\nHold your peace, and I will teach you wisdom.”\n'),
	(8881, 15, 34, 1, 'Moreover Elihu answered,\n'),
	(8882, 15, 34, 2, '“Hear my words, you wise men.\nGive ear to me, you who have knowledge.\n'),
	(8883, 15, 34, 3, 'For the ear tries words,\nas the palate tastes food.\n'),
	(8884, 15, 34, 4, 'Let us choose for us that which is right.\nLet us know among ourselves what is good.\n'),
	(8885, 15, 34, 5, 'For Job has said, ‘I am righteous,\nGod has taken away my right:\n'),
	(8886, 15, 34, 6, 'Notwithstanding my right I am considered a liar.\nMy wound is incurable, though I am without disobedience.’\n'),
	(8887, 15, 34, 7, 'What man is like Job,\nwho drinks scorn like water,\n'),
	(8888, 15, 34, 8, 'Who goes in company with the workers of iniquity,\nand walks with wicked men?\n'),
	(8889, 15, 34, 9, 'For he has said, ‘It profits a man nothing\nthat he should delight himself with God.’\n'),
	(8890, 15, 34, 10, '“Therefore listen to me, you men of understanding:\nfar be it from God, that he should do wickedness,\nfrom the Almighty, that he should commit iniquity.\n'),
	(8891, 15, 34, 11, 'For the work of a man he will render to him,\nand cause every man to find according to his ways.\n'),
	(8892, 15, 34, 12, 'Yes surely, God will not do wickedly,\nneither will the Almighty pervert justice.\n'),
	(8893, 15, 34, 13, 'Who put him in charge of the earth?\nor who has appointed him over the whole world?\n'),
	(8894, 15, 34, 14, 'If he set his heart on himself,\nIf he gathered to himself his spirit and his breath,\n'),
	(8895, 15, 34, 15, 'all flesh would perish together,\nand man would turn again to dust.\n'),
	(8896, 15, 34, 16, '“If now you have understanding, hear this.\nListen to the voice of my words.\n'),
	(8897, 15, 34, 17, 'Shall even one who hates justice govern?\nWill you condemn him who is righteous and mighty?—\n'),
	(8898, 15, 34, 18, 'Who says to a king, ‘Vile!’\nor to nobles, ‘Wicked!’?\n'),
	(8899, 15, 34, 19, 'Who doesn’t respect the persons of princes,\nnor respects the rich more than the poor;\nfor they all are the work of his hands.\n'),
	(8900, 15, 34, 20, 'In a moment they die, even at midnight.\nThe people are shaken and pass away.\nThe mighty are taken away without a hand.\n'),
	(8901, 15, 34, 21, '“For his eyes are on the ways of a man.\nHe sees all his goings.\n'),
	(8902, 15, 34, 22, 'There is no darkness, nor thick gloom,\nwhere the workers of iniquity may hide themselves.\n'),
	(8903, 15, 34, 23, 'For he doesn’t need to consider a man further,\nthat he should go before God in judgment.\n'),
	(8904, 15, 34, 24, 'He breaks in pieces mighty men in ways past finding out,\nand sets others in their place.\n'),
	(8905, 15, 34, 25, 'Therefore he takes knowledge of their works.\nHe overturns them in the night, so that they are destroyed.\n'),
	(8906, 15, 34, 26, 'He strikes them as wicked men\nin the open sight of others;\n'),
	(8907, 15, 34, 27, 'because they turned away from following him,\nand wouldn’t pay attention to any of his ways,\n'),
	(8908, 15, 34, 28, 'so that they caused the cry of the poor to come to him.\nHe heard the cry of the afflicted.\n'),
	(8909, 15, 34, 29, 'When he gives quietness, who then can condemn?\nWhen he hides his face, who then can see him?\nAlike whether to a nation, or to a man,\n'),
	(8910, 15, 34, 30, 'that the godless man may not reign,\nthat there be no one to ensnare the people.\n'),
	(8911, 15, 34, 31, '“For has any said to God,\n‘I am guilty, but I will not offend any more.\n'),
	(8912, 15, 34, 32, 'Teach me that which I don’t see.\nIf I have done iniquity, I will do it no more’?\n'),
	(8913, 15, 34, 33, 'Shall his recompense be as you desire, that you refuse it?\nFor you must choose, and not I.\nTherefore speak what you know.\n'),
	(8914, 15, 34, 34, 'Men of understanding will tell me,\nyes, every wise man who hears me:\n'),
	(8915, 15, 34, 35, '‘Job speaks without knowledge.\nHis words are without wisdom.’\n'),
	(8916, 15, 34, 36, 'I wish that Job were tried to the end,\nbecause of his answering like wicked men.\n'),
	(8917, 15, 34, 37, 'For he adds rebellion to his sin.\nHe claps his hands among us,\nand multiplies his words against God.”\n'),
	(8918, 15, 35, 1, 'Moreover Elihu answered,\n'),
	(8919, 15, 35, 2, '“Do you think this to be your right,\nor do you say, ‘My righteousness is more than God’s,’\n'),
	(8920, 15, 35, 3, 'That you ask, ‘What advantage will it be to you?\nWhat profit shall I have, more than if I had sinned?’\n'),
	(8921, 15, 35, 4, 'I will answer you,\nand your companions with you.\n'),
	(8922, 15, 35, 5, 'Look to the heavens, and see.\nSee the skies, which are higher than you.\n'),
	(8923, 15, 35, 6, 'If you have sinned, what effect do you have against him?\nIf your transgressions are multiplied, what do you do to him?\n'),
	(8924, 15, 35, 7, 'If you are righteous, what do you give him?\nOr what does he receive from your hand?\n'),
	(8925, 15, 35, 8, 'Your wickedness may hurt a man as you are,\nand your righteousness may profit a son of man.\n'),
	(8926, 15, 35, 9, '“By reason of the multitude of oppressions they cry out.\nThey cry for help by reason of the arm of the mighty.\n'),
	(8927, 15, 35, 10, 'But no one says, ‘Where is God my Maker,\nwho gives songs in the night,\n'),
	(8928, 15, 35, 11, 'who teaches us more than the animals of the earth,\nand makes us wiser than the birds of the sky?’\n'),
	(8929, 15, 35, 12, 'There they cry, but no one gives answer,\nbecause of the pride of evil men.\n'),
	(8930, 15, 35, 13, 'Surely God will not hear an empty cry,\nneither will the Almighty regard it.\n'),
	(8931, 15, 35, 14, 'How much less when you say you don’t see him.\nThe cause is before him, and you wait for him!\n'),
	(8932, 15, 35, 15, 'But now, because he has not visited in his anger,\nneither does he greatly regard arrogance.\n'),
	(8933, 15, 35, 16, 'Therefore Job opens his mouth with empty talk,\nand he multiplies words without knowledge.”\n'),
	(8934, 15, 36, 1, 'Elihu also continued, and said,\n'),
	(8935, 15, 36, 2, '“Bear with me a little, and I will show you;\nfor I still have something to say on God’s behalf.\n'),
	(8936, 15, 36, 3, 'I will get my knowledge from afar,\nand will ascribe righteousness to my Maker.\n'),
	(8937, 15, 36, 4, 'For truly my words are not false.\nOne who is perfect in knowledge is with you.\n'),
	(8938, 15, 36, 5, '“Behold, God is mighty, and doesn’t despise anyone.\nHe is mighty in strength of understanding.\n'),
	(8939, 15, 36, 6, 'He doesn’t preserve the life of the wicked,\nbut gives to the afflicted their right.\n'),
	(8940, 15, 36, 7, 'He doesn’t withdraw his eyes from the righteous,\nbut with kings on the throne,\nhe sets them forever, and they are exalted.\n'),
	(8941, 15, 36, 8, 'If they are bound in fetters,\nand are taken in the cords of afflictions,\n'),
	(8942, 15, 36, 9, 'then he shows them their work,\nand their transgressions, that they have behaved themselves proudly.\n'),
	(8943, 15, 36, 10, 'He also opens their ears to instruction,\nand commands that they return from iniquity.\n'),
	(8944, 15, 36, 11, 'If they listen and serve him,\nthey shall spend their days in prosperity,\nand their years in pleasures.\n'),
	(8945, 15, 36, 12, 'But if they don’t listen, they shall perish by the sword;\nthey shall die without knowledge.\n'),
	(8946, 15, 36, 13, '“But those who are godless in heart lay up anger.\nThey don’t cry for help when he binds them.\n'),
	(8947, 15, 36, 14, 'They die in youth.\nTheir life perishes among the unclean.\n'),
	(8948, 15, 36, 15, 'He delivers the afflicted by their affliction,\nand opens their ear in oppression.\n'),
	(8949, 15, 36, 16, 'Yes, he would have allured you out of distress,\ninto a wide place, where there is no restriction.\nThat which is set on your table would be full of fatness.\n'),
	(8950, 15, 36, 17, '“But you are full of the judgment of the wicked.\nJudgment and justice take hold of you.\n'),
	(8951, 15, 36, 18, 'Don’t let riches entice you to wrath,\nneither let the great size of a bribe turn you aside.\n'),
	(8952, 15, 36, 19, 'Would your wealth sustain you in distress,\nor all the might of your strength?\n'),
	(8953, 15, 36, 20, 'Don’t desire the night,\nwhen people are cut off in their place.\n'),
	(8954, 15, 36, 21, 'Take heed, don’t regard iniquity;\nfor you have chosen this rather than affliction.\n'),
	(8955, 15, 36, 22, 'Behold, God is exalted in his power.\nWho is a teacher like him?\n'),
	(8956, 15, 36, 23, 'Who has prescribed his way for him?\nOr who can say, ‘You have committed unrighteousness?’\n'),
	(8957, 15, 36, 24, '“Remember that you magnify his work,\nwhereof men have sung.\n'),
	(8958, 15, 36, 25, 'All men have looked on it.\nMan sees it afar off.\n'),
	(8959, 15, 36, 26, 'Behold, God is great, and we don’t know him.\nThe number of his years is unsearchable.\n'),
	(8960, 15, 36, 27, 'For he draws up the drops of water,\nwhich distill in rain from his vapor,\n'),
	(8961, 15, 36, 28, 'Which the skies pour down\nand which drop on man abundantly.\n'),
	(8962, 15, 36, 29, 'Yes, can any understand the spreading of the clouds,\nand the thunderings of his pavilion?\n'),
	(8963, 15, 36, 30, 'Behold, he spreads his light around him.\nHe covers the bottom of the sea.\n'),
	(8964, 15, 36, 31, 'For by these he judges the people.\nHe gives food in abundance.\n'),
	(8965, 15, 36, 32, 'He covers his hands with the lightning,\nand commands it to strike the mark.\n'),
	(8966, 15, 36, 33, 'Its noise tells about him,\nand the livestock also concerning the storm that comes up.\n'),
	(8967, 15, 37, 1, '“Yes, at this my heart trembles,\nand is moved out of its place.\n'),
	(8968, 15, 37, 2, 'Hear, oh, hear the noise of his voice,\nthe sound that goes out of his mouth.\n'),
	(8969, 15, 37, 3, 'He sends it out under the whole sky,\nand his lightning to the ends of the earth.\n'),
	(8970, 15, 37, 4, 'After it a voice roars.\nHe thunders with the voice of his majesty.\nHe doesn’t hold back anything when his voice is heard.\n'),
	(8971, 15, 37, 5, 'God thunders marvelously with his voice.\nHe does great things, which we can’t comprehend.\n'),
	(8972, 15, 37, 6, 'For he says to the snow, ‘Fall on the earth;’\nlikewise to the shower of rain,\nand to the showers of his mighty rain.\n'),
	(8973, 15, 37, 7, 'He seals up the hand of every man,\nthat all men whom he has made may know it.\n'),
	(8974, 15, 37, 8, 'Then the animals take cover,\nand remain in their dens.\n'),
	(8975, 15, 37, 9, 'Out of its room comes the storm,\nand cold out of the north.\n'),
	(8976, 15, 37, 10, 'By the breath of God, ice is given,\nand the width of the waters is frozen.\n'),
	(8977, 15, 37, 11, 'Yes, he loads the thick cloud with moisture.\nHe spreads abroad the cloud of his lightning.\n'),
	(8978, 15, 37, 12, 'It is turned around by his guidance,\nthat they may do whatever he commands them\non the surface of the habitable world,\n'),
	(8979, 15, 37, 13, 'Whether it is for correction, or for his land,\nor for loving kindness, that he causes it to come.\n'),
	(8980, 15, 37, 14, '“Listen to this, Job.\nStand still, and consider the wondrous works of God.\n'),
	(8981, 15, 37, 15, 'Do you know how God controls them,\nand causes the lightning of his cloud to shine?\n'),
	(8982, 15, 37, 16, 'Do you know the workings of the clouds,\nthe wondrous works of him who is perfect in knowledge?\n'),
	(8983, 15, 37, 17, 'You whose clothing is warm,\nwhen the earth is still by reason of the south wind?\n'),
	(8984, 15, 37, 18, 'Can you, with him, spread out the sky,\nwhich is strong as a cast metal mirror?\n'),
	(8985, 15, 37, 19, 'Teach us what we shall tell him,\nfor we can’t make our case by reason of darkness.\n'),
	(8986, 15, 37, 20, 'Will it be told him that I would speak?\nOr should a man wish that he were swallowed up?\n'),
	(8987, 15, 37, 21, 'Now men don’t see the light which is bright in the skies,\nbut the wind passes, and clears them.\n'),
	(8988, 15, 37, 22, 'Out of the north comes golden splendor.\nWith God is awesome majesty.\n'),
	(8989, 15, 37, 23, 'We can’t reach the Almighty.\nHe is exalted in power.\nIn justice and great righteousness, he will not oppress.\n'),
	(8990, 15, 37, 24, 'Therefore men revere him.\nHe doesn’t regard any who are wise of heart.”\n'),
	(8991, 15, 38, 1, 'Then Yahweh answered Job out of the whirlwind,\n'),
	(8992, 15, 38, 2, '“Who is this who darkens counsel\nby words without knowledge?\n'),
	(8993, 15, 38, 3, 'Brace yourself like a man,\nfor I will question you, then you answer me!\n'),
	(8994, 15, 38, 4, '“Where were you when I laid the foundations of the earth?\nDeclare, if you have understanding.\n'),
	(8995, 15, 38, 5, 'Who determined its measures, if you know?\nOr who stretched the line on it?\n'),
	(8996, 15, 38, 6, 'Whereupon were its foundations fastened?\nOr who laid its cornerstone,\n'),
	(8997, 15, 38, 7, 'when the morning stars sang together,\nand all the sons of God shouted for joy?\n'),
	(8998, 15, 38, 8, '“Or who shut up the sea with doors,\nwhen it broke out of the womb,\n'),
	(8999, 15, 38, 9, 'when I made clouds its garment,\nand wrapped it in thick darkness,\n'),
	(9000, 15, 38, 10, 'marked out for it my bound,\nset bars and doors,\n'),
	(9001, 15, 38, 11, 'and said, ‘Here you may come, but no further.\nHere your proud waves shall be stayed?’\n'),
	(9002, 15, 38, 12, '“Have you commanded the morning in your days,\nand caused the dawn to know its place;\n'),
	(9003, 15, 38, 13, 'that it might take hold of the ends of the earth,\nand shake the wicked out of it?\n'),
	(9004, 15, 38, 14, 'It is changed as clay under the seal,\nand presented as a garment.\n'),
	(9005, 15, 38, 15, 'From the wicked, their light is withheld.\nThe high arm is broken.\n'),
	(9006, 15, 38, 16, '“Have you entered into the springs of the sea?\nOr have you walked in the recesses of the deep?\n'),
	(9007, 15, 38, 17, 'Have the gates of death been revealed to you?\nOr have you seen the gates of the shadow of death?\n'),
	(9008, 15, 38, 18, 'Have you comprehended the earth in its width?\nDeclare, if you know it all.\n'),
	(9009, 15, 38, 19, '“What is the way to the dwelling of light?\nAs for darkness, where is its place,\n'),
	(9010, 15, 38, 20, 'that you should take it to its bound,\nthat you should discern the paths to its house?\n'),
	(9011, 15, 38, 21, 'Surely you know, for you were born then,\nand the number of your days is great!\n'),
	(9012, 15, 38, 22, 'Have you entered the treasuries of the snow,\nor have you seen the treasures of the hail,\n'),
	(9013, 15, 38, 23, 'which I have reserved against the time of trouble,\nagainst the day of battle and war?\n'),
	(9014, 15, 38, 24, 'By what way is the lightning distributed,\nor the east wind scattered on the earth?\n'),
	(9015, 15, 38, 25, 'Who has cut a channel for the flood water,\nor the path for the thunderstorm;\n'),
	(9016, 15, 38, 26, 'To cause it to rain on a land where no man is;\non the wilderness, in which there is no man;\n'),
	(9017, 15, 38, 27, 'to satisfy the waste and desolate ground,\nto cause the tender grass to grow?\n'),
	(9018, 15, 38, 28, 'Does the rain have a father?\nOr who fathers the drops of dew?\n'),
	(9019, 15, 38, 29, 'Out of whose womb came the ice?\nThe gray frost of the sky, who has given birth to it?\n'),
	(9020, 15, 38, 30, 'The waters become hard like stone,\nwhen the surface of the deep is frozen.\n'),
	(9021, 15, 38, 31, '“Can you bind the cluster of the Pleiades,\nor loosen the cords of Orion?\n'),
	(9022, 15, 38, 32, 'Can you lead the constellations out in their season?\nOr can you guide the Bear with her cubs?\n'),
	(9023, 15, 38, 33, 'Do you know the laws of the heavens?\nCan you establish its dominion over the earth?\n'),
	(9024, 15, 38, 34, '“Can you lift up your voice to the clouds,\nThat abundance of waters may cover you?\n'),
	(9025, 15, 38, 35, 'Can you send out lightnings, that they may go?\nDo they report to you, ‘Here we are?’\n'),
	(9026, 15, 38, 36, 'Who has put wisdom in the inward parts?\nOr who has given understanding to the mind?\n'),
	(9027, 15, 38, 37, 'Who can count the clouds by wisdom?\nOr who can pour out the bottles of the sky,\n'),
	(9028, 15, 38, 38, 'when the dust runs into a mass,\nand the clods of earth stick together?\n'),
	(9029, 15, 38, 39, '“Can you hunt the prey for the lioness,\nor satisfy the appetite of the young lions,\n'),
	(9030, 15, 38, 40, 'when they crouch in their dens,\nand lie in wait in the thicket?\n'),
	(9031, 15, 38, 41, 'Who provides for the raven his prey,\nwhen his young ones cry to God,\nand wander for lack of food?\n'),
	(9032, 15, 39, 1, '“Do you know the time when the mountain goats give birth?\nDo you watch when the doe bears fawns?\n'),
	(9033, 15, 39, 2, 'Can you count the months that they fulfill?\nOr do you know the time when they give birth?\n'),
	(9034, 15, 39, 3, 'They bow themselves, they bear their young.\nThey end their labor pains.\n'),
	(9035, 15, 39, 4, 'Their young ones become strong.\nThey grow up in the open field.\nThey go out, and don’t return again.\n'),
	(9036, 15, 39, 5, '“Who has set the wild donkey free?\nOr who has loosened the bonds of the swift donkey,\n'),
	(9037, 15, 39, 6, 'Whose home I have made the wilderness,\nand the salt land his dwelling place?\n'),
	(9038, 15, 39, 7, 'He scorns the tumult of the city,\nneither does he hear the shouting of the driver.\n'),
	(9039, 15, 39, 8, 'The range of the mountains is his pasture,\nHe searches after every green thing.\n'),
	(9040, 15, 39, 9, '“Will the wild ox be content to serve you?\nOr will he stay by your feeding trough?\n'),
	(9041, 15, 39, 10, 'Can you hold the wild ox in the furrow with his harness?\nOr will he till the valleys after you?\n'),
	(9042, 15, 39, 11, 'Will you trust him, because his strength is great?\nOr will you leave to him your labor?\n'),
	(9043, 15, 39, 12, 'Will you confide in him, that he will bring home your seed,\nand gather the grain of your threshing floor?\n'),
	(9044, 15, 39, 13, '“The wings of the ostrich wave proudly;\nbut are they the feathers and plumage of love?\n'),
	(9045, 15, 39, 14, 'For she leaves her eggs on the earth,\nwarms them in the dust,\n'),
	(9046, 15, 39, 15, 'and forgets that the foot may crush them,\nor that the wild animal may trample them.\n'),
	(9047, 15, 39, 16, 'She deals harshly with her young ones, as if they were not hers.\nThough her labor is in vain, she is without fear,\n'),
	(9048, 15, 39, 17, 'because God has deprived her of wisdom,\nneither has he imparted to her understanding.\n'),
	(9049, 15, 39, 18, 'When she lifts up herself on high,\nshe scorns the horse and his rider.\n'),
	(9050, 15, 39, 19, '“Have you given the horse might?\nHave you clothed his neck with a quivering mane?\n'),
	(9051, 15, 39, 20, 'Have you made him to leap as a locust?\nThe glory of his snorting is awesome.\n'),
	(9052, 15, 39, 21, 'He paws in the valley, and rejoices in his strength.\nHe goes out to meet the armed men.\n'),
	(9053, 15, 39, 22, 'He mocks at fear, and is not dismayed,\nneither does he turn back from the sword.\n'),
	(9054, 15, 39, 23, 'The quiver rattles against him,\nthe flashing spear and the javelin.\n'),
	(9055, 15, 39, 24, 'He eats up the ground with fierceness and rage,\nneither does he stand still at the sound of the trumpet.\n'),
	(9056, 15, 39, 25, 'As often as the trumpet sounds he snorts, ‘Aha!’\nHe smells the battle afar off,\nthe thunder of the captains, and the shouting.\n'),
	(9057, 15, 39, 26, '“Is it by your wisdom that the hawk soars,\nand stretches her wings toward the south?\n'),
	(9058, 15, 39, 27, 'Is it at your command that the eagle mounts up,\nand makes his nest on high?\n'),
	(9059, 15, 39, 28, 'On the cliff he dwells, and makes his home,\non the point of the cliff, and the stronghold.\n'),
	(9060, 15, 39, 29, 'From there he spies out the prey.\nHis eyes see it afar off.\n'),
	(9061, 15, 39, 30, 'His young ones also suck up blood.\nWhere the slain are, there he is.”\n'),
	(9062, 15, 40, 1, 'Moreover Yahweh answered Job,\n'),
	(9063, 15, 40, 2, '“Shall he who argues contend with the Almighty?\nHe who argues with God, let him answer it.”\n'),
	(9064, 15, 40, 3, 'Then Job answered Yahweh,\n'),
	(9065, 15, 40, 4, '“Behold, I am of small account. What shall I answer you?\nI lay my hand on my mouth.\n'),
	(9066, 15, 40, 5, 'I have spoken once, and I will not answer;\nYes, twice, but I will proceed no further.”\n'),
	(9067, 15, 40, 6, 'Then Yahweh answered Job out of the whirlwind,\n'),
	(9068, 15, 40, 7, '“Now brace yourself like a man.\nI will question you, and you will answer me.\n'),
	(9069, 15, 40, 8, 'Will you even annul my judgment?\nWill you condemn me, that you may be justified?\n'),
	(9070, 15, 40, 9, 'Or do you have an arm like God?\nCan you thunder with a voice like him?\n'),
	(9071, 15, 40, 10, '“Now deck yourself with excellency and dignity.\nArray yourself with honor and majesty.\n'),
	(9072, 15, 40, 11, 'Pour out the fury of your anger.\nLook at everyone who is proud, and bring him low.\n'),
	(9073, 15, 40, 12, 'Look at everyone who is proud, and humble him.\nCrush the wicked in their place.\n'),
	(9074, 15, 40, 13, 'Hide them in the dust together.\nBind their faces in the hidden place.\n'),
	(9075, 15, 40, 14, 'Then I will also admit to you\nthat your own right hand can save you.\n'),
	(9076, 15, 40, 15, '“See now, behemoth, which I made as well as you.\nHe eats grass as an ox.\n'),
	(9077, 15, 40, 16, 'Look now, his strength is in his thighs.\nHis force is in the muscles of his belly.\n'),
	(9078, 15, 40, 17, 'He moves his tail like a cedar.\nThe sinews of his thighs are knit together.\n'),
	(9079, 15, 40, 18, 'His bones are like tubes of brass.\nHis limbs are like bars of iron.\n'),
	(9080, 15, 40, 19, 'He is the chief of the ways of God.\nHe who made him gives him his sword.\n'),
	(9081, 15, 40, 20, 'Surely the mountains produce food for him,\nwhere all the animals of the field play.\n'),
	(9082, 15, 40, 21, 'He lies under the lotus trees,\nin the covert of the reed, and the marsh.\n'),
	(9083, 15, 40, 22, 'The lotuses cover him with their shade.\nThe willows of the brook surround him.\n'),
	(9084, 15, 40, 23, 'Behold, if a river overflows, he doesn’t tremble.\nHe is confident, though the Jordan swells even to his mouth.\n'),
	(9085, 15, 40, 24, 'Shall any take him when he is on the watch,\nor pierce through his nose with a snare?\n'),
	(9086, 15, 41, 1, '“Can you draw out Leviathan with a fish hook,\nor press down his tongue with a cord?\n'),
	(9087, 15, 41, 2, 'Can you put a rope into his nose,\nor pierce his jaw through with a hook?\n'),
	(9088, 15, 41, 3, 'Will he make many petitions to you,\nor will he speak soft words to you?\n'),
	(9089, 15, 41, 4, 'Will he make a covenant with you,\nthat you should take him for a servant forever?\n'),
	(9090, 15, 41, 5, 'Will you play with him as with a bird?\nOr will you bind him for your girls?\n'),
	(9091, 15, 41, 6, 'Will traders barter for him?\nWill they part him among the merchants?\n'),
	(9092, 15, 41, 7, 'Can you fill his skin with barbed irons,\nor his head with fish spears?\n'),
	(9093, 15, 41, 8, 'Lay your hand on him.\nRemember the battle, and do so no more.\n'),
	(9094, 15, 41, 9, 'Behold, the hope of him is in vain.\nWon’t one be cast down even at the sight of him?\n'),
	(9095, 15, 41, 10, 'None is so fierce that he dare stir him up.\nWho then is he who can stand before me?\n'),
	(9096, 15, 41, 11, 'Who has first given to me, that I should repay him?\nEverything under the heavens is mine.\n'),
	(9097, 15, 41, 12, '“I will not keep silence concerning his limbs,\nnor his mighty strength, nor his goodly frame.\n'),
	(9098, 15, 41, 13, 'Who can strip off his outer garment?\nWho shall come within his jaws?\n'),
	(9099, 15, 41, 14, 'Who can open the doors of his face?\nAround his teeth is terror.\n'),
	(9100, 15, 41, 15, 'Strong scales are his pride,\nshut up together with a close seal.\n'),
	(9101, 15, 41, 16, 'One is so near to another,\nthat no air can come between them.\n'),
	(9102, 15, 41, 17, 'They are joined to one another.\nThey stick together, so that they can’t be pulled apart.\n'),
	(9103, 15, 41, 18, 'His sneezing flashes out light.\nHis eyes are like the eyelids of the morning.\n'),
	(9104, 15, 41, 19, 'Out of his mouth go burning torches.\nSparks of fire leap out.\n'),
	(9105, 15, 41, 20, 'Out of his nostrils a smoke goes,\nas of a boiling pot over a fire of reeds.\n'),
	(9106, 15, 41, 21, 'His breath kindles coals.\nA flame goes out of his mouth.\n'),
	(9107, 15, 41, 22, 'There is strength in his neck.\nTerror dances before him.\n'),
	(9108, 15, 41, 23, 'The flakes of his flesh are joined together.\nThey are firm on him.\nThey can’t be moved.\n'),
	(9109, 15, 41, 24, 'His heart is as firm as a stone,\nyes, firm as the lower millstone.\n'),
	(9110, 15, 41, 25, 'When he raises himself up, the mighty are afraid.\nThey retreat before his thrashing.\n'),
	(9111, 15, 41, 26, 'If one attacks him with the sword, it can’t prevail;\nnor the spear, the dart, nor the pointed shaft.\n'),
	(9112, 15, 41, 27, 'He counts iron as straw;\nand brass as rotten wood.\n'),
	(9113, 15, 41, 28, 'The arrow can’t make him flee.\nSling stones are like chaff to him.\n'),
	(9114, 15, 41, 29, 'Clubs are counted as stubble.\nHe laughs at the rushing of the javelin.\n'),
	(9115, 15, 41, 30, 'His undersides are like sharp potsherds,\nleaving a trail in the mud like a threshing sledge.\n'),
	(9116, 15, 41, 31, 'He makes the deep to boil like a pot.\nHe makes the sea like a pot of ointment.\n'),
	(9117, 15, 41, 32, 'He makes a path shine after him.\nOne would think the deep had white hair.\n'),
	(9118, 15, 41, 33, 'On earth there is not his equal,\nthat is made without fear.\n'),
	(9119, 15, 41, 34, 'He sees everything that is high.\nHe is king over all the sons of pride.”\n'),
	(9120, 15, 42, 1, 'Then Job answered Yahweh,\n'),
	(9121, 15, 42, 2, '“I know that you can do all things,\nand that no purpose of yours can be restrained.\n'),
	(9122, 15, 42, 3, 'You asked, ‘Who is this who hides counsel without knowledge?’\ntherefore I have uttered that which I did not understand,\nthings too wonderful for me, which I didn’t know.\n'),
	(9123, 15, 42, 4, 'You said, ‘Listen, now, and I will speak;\nI will question you, and you will answer me.’\n'),
	(9124, 15, 42, 5, 'I had heard of you by the hearing of the ear,\nbut now my eye sees you.\n'),
	(9125, 15, 42, 6, 'Therefore I abhor myself,\nand repent in dust and ashes.”\n'),
	(9126, 15, 42, 7, 'It was so, that after Yahweh had spoken these words to Job, Yahweh said to Eliphaz the Temanite, “My wrath is kindled against you, and against your two friends; for you have not spoken of me the thing that is right, as my servant Job has.\n'),
	(9127, 15, 42, 8, 'Now therefore, take to yourselves seven bulls and seven rams, and go to my servant Job, and offer up for yourselves a burnt offering; and my servant Job shall pray for you, for I will accept him, that I not deal with you according to your folly. For you have not spoken of me the thing that is right, as my servant Job has.”\n'),
	(9128, 15, 42, 9, 'So Eliphaz the Temanite and Bildad the Shuhite and Zophar the Naamathite went, and did what Yahweh commanded them, and Yahweh accepted Job.\n'),
	(9129, 15, 42, 10, 'Yahweh turned the captivity of Job, when he prayed for his friends. Yahweh gave Job twice as much as he had before.\n'),
	(9130, 15, 42, 11, 'Then came there to him all his brothers, and all his sisters, and all those who had been of his acquaintance before, and ate bread with him in his house. They comforted him, and consoled him concerning all the evil that Yahweh had brought on him. Everyone also gave him a piece of money, and everyone a ring of gold.\n'),
	(9131, 15, 42, 12, 'So Yahweh blessed the latter end of Job more than his beginning. He had fourteen thousand sheep, six thousand camels, one thousand yoke of oxen, and a thousand female donkeys.\n'),
	(9132, 15, 42, 13, 'He had also seven sons and three daughters.\n'),
	(9133, 15, 42, 14, 'He called the name of the first, Jemimah; and the name of the second, Keziah; and the name of the third, Keren Happuch.\n'),
	(9134, 15, 42, 15, 'In all the land were no women found so beautiful as the daughters of Job. Their father gave them an inheritance among their brothers.\n'),
	(9135, 15, 42, 16, 'After this Job lived one hundred forty years, and saw his sons, and his sons’ sons, to four generations.\n'),
	(9136, 15, 42, 17, 'So Job died, being old and full of days.\n'),
	(9137, 16, 1, 1, 'Blessed is the man who doesn’t walk in the counsel of the wicked,\nnor stand on the path of sinners,\nnor sit in the seat of scoffers;\n'),
	(9138, 16, 1, 2, 'but his delight is in Yahweh’s law.\nOn his law he meditates day and night.\n'),
	(9139, 16, 1, 3, 'He will be like a tree planted by the streams of water,\nthat produces its fruit in its season,\nwhose leaf also does not wither.\nWhatever he does shall prosper.\n'),
	(9140, 16, 1, 4, 'The wicked are not so,\nbut are like the chaff which the wind drives away.\n'),
	(9141, 16, 1, 5, 'Therefore the wicked shall not stand in the judgment,\nnor sinners in the congregation of the righteous.\n'),
	(9142, 16, 1, 6, 'For Yahweh knows the way of the righteous,\nbut the way of the wicked shall perish.\n'),
	(9143, 16, 2, 1, 'Why do the nations rage,\nand the peoples plot a vain thing?\n'),
	(9144, 16, 2, 2, 'The kings of the earth take a stand,\nand the rulers take counsel together,\nagainst Yahweh, and against his Anointed, saying,\n'),
	(9145, 16, 2, 3, '“Let’s break their bonds apart,\nand cast their cords from us.”\n'),
	(9146, 16, 2, 4, 'He who sits in the heavens will laugh.\nThe Lord will have them in derision.\n'),
	(9147, 16, 2, 5, 'Then he will speak to them in his anger,\nand terrify them in his wrath:\n'),
	(9148, 16, 2, 6, '“Yet I have set my King on my holy hill of Zion.”\n'),
	(9149, 16, 2, 7, 'I will tell of the decree.\nYahweh said to me, “You are my son.\nToday I have become your father.\n'),
	(9150, 16, 2, 8, 'Ask of me, and I will give the nations for your inheritance,\nthe uttermost parts of the earth for your possession.\n'),
	(9151, 16, 2, 9, 'You shall break them with a rod of iron.\nYou shall dash them in pieces like a potter’s vessel.”\n'),
	(9152, 16, 2, 10, 'Now therefore be wise, you kings.\nBe instructed, you judges of the earth.\n'),
	(9153, 16, 2, 11, 'Serve Yahweh with fear,\nand rejoice with trembling.\n'),
	(9154, 16, 2, 12, 'Give sincere homage to the Son, lest he be angry, and you perish on the way,\nfor his wrath will soon be kindled.\nBlessed are all those who take refuge in him.\n'),
	(9155, 16, 3, 1, 'Yahweh, how my adversaries have increased!\nMany are those who rise up against me.\n'),
	(9156, 16, 3, 2, 'Many there are who say of my soul,\n“There is no help for him in God.”\nSelah.\n'),
	(9157, 16, 3, 3, 'But you, Yahweh, are a shield around me,\nmy glory, and the one who lifts up my head.\n'),
	(9158, 16, 3, 4, 'I cry to Yahweh with my voice,\nand he answers me out of his holy hill.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9159, 16, 3, 5, 'I laid myself down and slept.\nI awakened; for Yahweh sustains me.\n'),
	(9160, 16, 3, 6, 'I will not be afraid of tens of thousands of people\nwho have set themselves against me on every side.\n'),
	(9161, 16, 3, 7, 'Arise, Yahweh!\nSave me, my God!\nFor you have struck all of my enemies on the cheek bone.\nYou have broken the teeth of the wicked.\n'),
	(9162, 16, 3, 8, 'Salvation belongs to Yahweh.\nYour blessing be on your people.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9163, 16, 4, 1, 'Answer me when I call, God of my righteousness.\nGive me relief from my distress.\nHave mercy on me, and hear my prayer.\n'),
	(9164, 16, 4, 2, 'You sons of men, how long shall my glory be turned into dishonor?\nWill you love vanity, and seek after falsehood?\nSelah.\n'),
	(9165, 16, 4, 3, 'But know that Yahweh has set apart for himself him who is godly:\nYahweh will hear when I call to him.\n'),
	(9166, 16, 4, 4, 'Stand in awe, and don’t sin.\nSearch your own heart on your bed, and be still.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9167, 16, 4, 5, 'Offer the sacrifices of righteousness.\nPut your trust in Yahweh.\n'),
	(9168, 16, 4, 6, 'Many say, “Who will show us any good?”\nYahweh, let the light of your face shine on us.\n'),
	(9169, 16, 4, 7, 'You have put gladness in my heart,\nmore than when their grain and their new wine are increased.\n'),
	(9170, 16, 4, 8, 'In peace I will both lay myself down and sleep,\nfor you, Yahweh alone, make me live in safety.\n'),
	(9171, 16, 5, 1, 'Give ear to my words, Yahweh.\nConsider my meditation.\n'),
	(9172, 16, 5, 2, 'Listen to the voice of my cry, my King and my God;\nfor to you do I pray.\n'),
	(9173, 16, 5, 3, 'Yahweh, in the morning you shall hear my voice.\nIn the morning I will lay my requests before you, and will watch expectantly.\n'),
	(9174, 16, 5, 4, 'For you are not a God who has pleasure in wickedness.\nEvil can’t live with you.\n'),
	(9175, 16, 5, 5, 'The arrogant shall not stand in your sight.\nYou hate all workers of iniquity.\n'),
	(9176, 16, 5, 6, 'You will destroy those who speak lies.\nYahweh abhors the bloodthirsty and deceitful man.\n'),
	(9177, 16, 5, 7, 'But as for me, in the abundance of your loving kindness I will come into your house.\nI will bow toward your holy temple in reverence of you.\n'),
	(9178, 16, 5, 8, 'Lead me, Yahweh, in your righteousness because of my enemies.\nMake your way straight before my face.\n'),
	(9179, 16, 5, 9, 'For there is no faithfulness in their mouth.\nTheir heart is destruction.\nTheir throat is an open tomb.\nThey flatter with their tongue.\n'),
	(9180, 16, 5, 10, 'Hold them guilty, God.\nLet them fall by their own counsels;\nThrust them out in the multitude of their transgressions,\nfor they have rebelled against you.\n'),
	(9181, 16, 5, 11, 'But let all those who take refuge in you rejoice,\nLet them always shout for joy, because you defend them.\nLet them also who love your name be joyful in you.\n'),
	(9182, 16, 5, 12, 'For you will bless the righteous.\nYahweh, you will surround him with favor as with a shield.\n'),
	(9183, 16, 6, 1, 'Yahweh, don’t rebuke me in your anger,\nneither discipline me in your wrath.\n'),
	(9184, 16, 6, 2, 'Have mercy on me, Yahweh, for I am faint.\nYahweh, heal me, for my bones are troubled.\n'),
	(9185, 16, 6, 3, 'My soul is also in great anguish.\nBut you, Yahweh—how long?\n'),
	(9186, 16, 6, 4, 'Return, Yahweh. Deliver my soul,\nand save me for your loving kindness’ sake.\n'),
	(9187, 16, 6, 5, 'For in death there is no memory of you.\nIn Sheol, who shall give you thanks?\n'),
	(9188, 16, 6, 6, 'I am weary with my groaning.\nEvery night I flood my bed.\nI drench my couch with my tears.\n'),
	(9189, 16, 6, 7, 'My eye wastes away because of grief.\nIt grows old because of all my adversaries.\n'),
	(9190, 16, 6, 8, 'Depart from me, all you workers of iniquity,\nfor Yahweh has heard the voice of my weeping.\n'),
	(9191, 16, 6, 9, 'Yahweh has heard my supplication.\nYahweh accepts my prayer.\n'),
	(9192, 16, 6, 10, 'May all my enemies be ashamed and dismayed.\nThey shall turn back, they shall be disgraced suddenly.\n'),
	(9193, 16, 7, 1, 'Yahweh, my God, I take refuge in you.\nSave me from all those who pursue me, and deliver me,\n'),
	(9194, 16, 7, 2, 'lest they tear apart my soul like a lion,\nripping it in pieces, while there is no one to deliver.\n'),
	(9195, 16, 7, 3, 'Yahweh, my God, if I have done this,\nif there is iniquity in my hands,\n'),
	(9196, 16, 7, 4, 'if I have rewarded evil to him who was at peace with me\n(yes, I have delivered him who without cause was my adversary),\n'),
	(9197, 16, 7, 5, 'let the enemy pursue my soul, and overtake it;\nyes, let him tread my life down to the earth,\nand lay my glory in the dust.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9198, 16, 7, 6, 'Arise, Yahweh, in your anger.\nLift up yourself against the rage of my adversaries.\nAwake for me. You have commanded judgment.\n'),
	(9199, 16, 7, 7, 'Let the congregation of the peoples surround you.\nRule over them on high.\n'),
	(9200, 16, 7, 8, 'Yahweh administers judgment to the peoples.\nJudge me, Yahweh, according to my righteousness,\nand to my integrity that is in me.\n'),
	(9201, 16, 7, 9, 'Oh let the wickedness of the wicked come to an end,\nbut establish the righteous;\ntheir minds and hearts are searched by the righteous God.\n'),
	(9202, 16, 7, 10, 'My shield is with God,\nwho saves the upright in heart.\n'),
	(9203, 16, 7, 11, 'God is a righteous judge,\nyes, a God who has indignation every day.\n'),
	(9204, 16, 7, 12, 'If a man doesn’t relent, he will sharpen his sword;\nhe has bent and strung his bow.\n'),
	(9205, 16, 7, 13, 'He has also prepared for himself the instruments of death.\nHe makes ready his flaming arrows.\n'),
	(9206, 16, 7, 14, 'Behold, he travails with iniquity.\nYes, he has conceived mischief,\nand brought out falsehood.\n'),
	(9207, 16, 7, 15, 'He has dug a hole,\nand has fallen into the pit which he made.\n'),
	(9208, 16, 7, 16, 'The trouble he causes shall return to his own head.\nHis violence shall come down on the crown of his own head.\n'),
	(9209, 16, 7, 17, 'I will give thanks to Yahweh according to his righteousness,\nand will sing praise to the name of Yahweh Most High.\n'),
	(9210, 16, 8, 1, 'Yahweh, our Lord, how majestic is your name in all the earth,\nwho has set your glory above the heavens!\n'),
	(9211, 16, 8, 2, 'From the lips of babes and infants you have established strength,\nbecause of your adversaries, that you might silence the enemy and the avenger.\n'),
	(9212, 16, 8, 3, 'When I consider your heavens, the work of your fingers,\nthe moon and the stars, which you have ordained;\n'),
	(9213, 16, 8, 4, 'what is man, that you think of him?\nWhat is the son of man, that you care for him?\n'),
	(9214, 16, 8, 5, 'For you have made him a little lower than the angels,\nand crowned him with glory and honor.\n'),
	(9215, 16, 8, 6, 'You make him ruler over the works of your hands.\nYou have put all things under his feet:\n'),
	(9216, 16, 8, 7, 'All sheep and cattle,\nyes, and the animals of the field,\n'),
	(9217, 16, 8, 8, 'The birds of the sky, the fish of the sea,\nand whatever passes through the paths of the seas.\n'),
	(9218, 16, 8, 9, 'Yahweh, our Lord,\nhow majestic is your name in all the earth!\n'),
	(9219, 16, 9, 1, 'I will give thanks to Yahweh with my whole heart.\nI will tell of all your marvelous works.\n'),
	(9220, 16, 9, 2, 'I will be glad and rejoice in you.\nI will sing praise to your name, O Most High.\n'),
	(9221, 16, 9, 3, 'When my enemies turn back,\nthey stumble and perish in your presence.\n'),
	(9222, 16, 9, 4, 'For you have maintained my just cause.\nYou sit on the throne judging righteously.\n'),
	(9223, 16, 9, 5, 'You have rebuked the nations.\nYou have destroyed the wicked.\nYou have blotted out their name forever and ever.\n'),
	(9224, 16, 9, 6, 'The enemy is overtaken by endless ruin.\nThe very memory of the cities which you have overthrown has perished.\n'),
	(9225, 16, 9, 7, 'But Yahweh reigns forever.\nHe has prepared his throne for judgment.\n'),
	(9226, 16, 9, 8, 'He will judge the world in righteousness.\nHe will administer judgment to the peoples in uprightness.\n'),
	(9227, 16, 9, 9, 'Yahweh will also be a high tower for the oppressed;\na high tower in times of trouble.\n'),
	(9228, 16, 9, 10, 'Those who know your name will put their trust in you,\nfor you, Yahweh, have not forsaken those who seek you.\n'),
	(9229, 16, 9, 11, 'Sing praises to Yahweh, who dwells in Zion,\nand declare among the people what he has done.\n'),
	(9230, 16, 9, 12, 'For he who avenges blood remembers them.\nHe doesn’t forget the cry of the afflicted.\n'),
	(9231, 16, 9, 13, 'Have mercy on me, Yahweh.\nSee my affliction by those who hate me,\nand lift me up from the gates of death;\n'),
	(9232, 16, 9, 14, 'that I may show all of your praise.\nIn the gates of the daughter of Zion, I will rejoice in your salvation.\n'),
	(9233, 16, 9, 15, 'The nations have sunk down in the pit that they made.\nIn the net which they hid, their own foot is taken.\n'),
	(9234, 16, 9, 16, 'Yahweh has made himself known.\nHe has executed judgment.\nThe wicked is snared by the work of his own hands.\nMeditation. Selah.\n'),
	(9235, 16, 9, 17, 'The wicked shall be turned back to Sheol,\neven all the nations that forget God.\n'),
	(9236, 16, 9, 18, 'For the needy shall not always be forgotten,\nnor the hope of the poor perish forever.\n'),
	(9237, 16, 9, 19, 'Arise, Yahweh! Don’t let man prevail.\nLet the nations be judged in your sight.\n'),
	(9238, 16, 9, 20, 'Put them in fear, Yahweh.\nLet the nations know that they are only men.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9239, 16, 10, 1, 'Why do you stand far off, Yahweh?\nWhy do you hide yourself in times of trouble?\n'),
	(9240, 16, 10, 2, 'In arrogance, the wicked hunt down the weak.\nThey are caught in the schemes that they devise.\n'),
	(9241, 16, 10, 3, 'For the wicked boasts of his heart’s cravings.\nHe blesses the greedy, and condemns Yahweh.\n'),
	(9242, 16, 10, 4, 'The wicked, in the pride of his face,\nhas no room in his thoughts for God.\n'),
	(9243, 16, 10, 5, 'His ways are prosperous at all times.\nHe is haughty, and your laws are far from his sight.\nAs for all his adversaries, he sneers at them.\n'),
	(9244, 16, 10, 6, 'He says in his heart, “I shall not be shaken.\nFor generations I shall have no trouble.”\n'),
	(9245, 16, 10, 7, 'His mouth is full of cursing, deceit, and oppression.\nUnder his tongue is mischief and iniquity.\n'),
	(9246, 16, 10, 8, 'He lies in wait near the villages.\nFrom ambushes, he murders the innocent.\nHis eyes are secretly set against the helpless.\n'),
	(9247, 16, 10, 9, 'He lurks in secret as a lion in his ambush.\nHe lies in wait to catch the helpless.\nHe catches the helpless, when he draws him in his net.\n'),
	(9248, 16, 10, 10, 'The helpless are crushed.\nThey collapse.\nThey fall under his strength.\n'),
	(9249, 16, 10, 11, 'He says in his heart, “God has forgotten.\nHe hides his face.\nHe will never see it.”\n'),
	(9250, 16, 10, 12, 'Arise, Yahweh!\nGod, lift up your hand!\nDon’t forget the helpless.\n'),
	(9251, 16, 10, 13, 'Why does the wicked person condemn God,\nand say in his heart, “God won’t call me into account?”\n'),
	(9252, 16, 10, 14, 'But you do see trouble and grief.\nYou consider it to take it into your hand.\nYou help the victim and the fatherless.\n'),
	(9253, 16, 10, 15, 'Break the arm of the wicked.\nAs for the evil man, seek out his wickedness until you find none.\n'),
	(9254, 16, 10, 16, 'Yahweh is King forever and ever!\nThe nations will perish out of his land.\n'),
	(9255, 16, 10, 17, 'Yahweh, you have heard the desire of the humble.\nYou will prepare their heart.\nYou will cause your ear to hear,\n'),
	(9256, 16, 10, 18, 'to judge the fatherless and the oppressed,\nthat man who is of the earth may terrify no more.\n'),
	(9257, 16, 11, 1, 'In Yahweh, I take refuge.\nHow can you say to my soul, “Flee as a bird to your mountain!”\n'),
	(9258, 16, 11, 2, 'For, behold, the wicked bend their bows.\nThey set their arrows on the strings,\nthat they may shoot in darkness at the upright in heart.\n'),
	(9259, 16, 11, 3, 'If the foundations are destroyed,\nwhat can the righteous do?\n'),
	(9260, 16, 11, 4, 'Yahweh is in his holy temple.\nYahweh is on his throne in heaven.\nHis eyes observe.\nHis eyes examine the children of men.\n'),
	(9261, 16, 11, 5, 'Yahweh examines the righteous,\nbut the wicked and him who loves violence his soul hates.\n'),
	(9262, 16, 11, 6, 'On the wicked he will rain blazing coals;\nfire, sulfur, and scorching wind shall be the portion of their cup.\n'),
	(9263, 16, 11, 7, 'For Yahweh is righteous.\nHe loves righteousness.\nThe upright shall see his face.\n'),
	(9264, 16, 12, 1, 'Help, Yahweh; for the godly man ceases.\nFor the faithful fail from among the children of men.\n'),
	(9265, 16, 12, 2, 'Everyone lies to his neighbor.\nThey speak with flattering lips, and with a double heart.\n'),
	(9266, 16, 12, 3, 'May Yahweh cut off all flattering lips,\nand the tongue that boasts,\n'),
	(9267, 16, 12, 4, 'who have said, “With our tongue we will prevail.\nOur lips are our own.\nWho is lord over us?”\n'),
	(9268, 16, 12, 5, '“Because of the oppression of the weak and because of the groaning of the needy,\nI will now arise,” says Yahweh;\n“I will set him in safety from those who malign him.”\n'),
	(9269, 16, 12, 6, 'Yahweh’s words are flawless words,\nas silver refined in a clay furnace, purified seven times.\n'),
	(9270, 16, 12, 7, 'You will keep them, Yahweh.\nYou will preserve them from this generation forever.\n'),
	(9271, 16, 12, 8, 'The wicked walk on every side,\nwhen what is vile is exalted among the sons of men.\n'),
	(9272, 16, 13, 1, 'How long, Yahweh?\nWill you forget me forever?\nHow long will you hide your face from me?\n'),
	(9273, 16, 13, 2, 'How long shall I take counsel in my soul,\nhaving sorrow in my heart every day?\nHow long shall my enemy triumph over me?\n'),
	(9274, 16, 13, 3, 'Behold, and answer me, Yahweh, my God.\nGive light to my eyes, lest I sleep in death;\n'),
	(9275, 16, 13, 4, 'Lest my enemy say, “I have prevailed against him”;\nLest my adversaries rejoice when I fall.\n'),
	(9276, 16, 13, 5, 'But I trust in your loving kindness.\nMy heart rejoices in your salvation.\n'),
	(9277, 16, 13, 6, 'I will sing to Yahweh,\nbecause he has been good to me.\n'),
	(9278, 16, 14, 1, 'The fool has said in his heart, “There is no God.”\nThey are corrupt.\nThey have done abominable deeds.\nThere is no one who does good.\n'),
	(9279, 16, 14, 2, 'Yahweh looked down from heaven on the children of men,\nto see if there were any who understood,\nwho sought after God.\n'),
	(9280, 16, 14, 3, 'They have all gone aside.\nThey have together become corrupt.\nThere is no one who does good, no, not one.\n'),
	(9281, 16, 14, 4, 'Have all the workers of iniquity no knowledge,\nwho eat up my people as they eat bread,\nand don’t call on Yahweh?\n'),
	(9282, 16, 14, 5, 'There they were in great fear,\nfor God is in the generation of the righteous.\n'),
	(9283, 16, 14, 6, 'You frustrate the plan of the poor,\nbecause Yahweh is his refuge.\n'),
	(9284, 16, 14, 7, 'Oh that the salvation of Israel would come out of Zion!\nWhen Yahweh restores the fortunes of his people,\nthen Jacob shall rejoice, and Israel shall be glad.\n'),
	(9285, 16, 15, 1, 'Yahweh, who shall dwell in your sanctuary?\nWho shall live on your holy hill?\n'),
	(9286, 16, 15, 2, 'He who walks blamelessly does what is right,\nand speaks truth in his heart;\n'),
	(9287, 16, 15, 3, 'He who doesn’t slander with his tongue,\nnor does evil to his friend,\nnor casts slurs against his fellow man;\n'),
	(9288, 16, 15, 4, 'In whose eyes a vile man is despised,\nbut who honors those who fear Yahweh;\nhe who keeps an oath even when it hurts, and doesn’t change;\n'),
	(9289, 16, 15, 5, 'he who doesn’t lend out his money for usury,\nnor take a bribe against the innocent.\nHe who does these things shall never be shaken.\n'),
	(9290, 16, 16, 1, 'Preserve me, God, for in you do I take refuge.\n'),
	(9291, 16, 16, 2, 'My soul, you have said to Yahweh, “You are my Lord.\nApart from you I have no good thing.”\n'),
	(9292, 16, 16, 3, 'As for the saints who are in the earth,\nthey are the excellent ones in whom is all my delight.\n'),
	(9293, 16, 16, 4, 'Their sorrows shall be multiplied who give gifts to another god.\nTheir drink offerings of blood I will not offer,\nnor take their names on my lips.\n'),
	(9294, 16, 16, 5, 'Yahweh assigned my portion and my cup.\nYou made my lot secure.\n'),
	(9295, 16, 16, 6, 'The lines have fallen to me in pleasant places.\nYes, I have a good inheritance.\n'),
	(9296, 16, 16, 7, 'I will bless Yahweh, who has given me counsel.\nYes, my heart instructs me in the night seasons.\n'),
	(9297, 16, 16, 8, 'I have set Yahweh always before me.\nBecause he is at my right hand, I shall not be moved.\n'),
	(9298, 16, 16, 9, 'Therefore my heart is glad, and my tongue rejoices.\nMy body shall also dwell in safety.\n'),
	(9299, 16, 16, 10, 'For you will not leave my soul in Sheol,\nneither will you allow your holy one to see corruption.\n'),
	(9300, 16, 16, 11, 'You will show me the path of life.\nIn your presence is fullness of joy.\nIn your right hand there are pleasures forever more.\n'),
	(9301, 16, 17, 1, 'Hear, Yahweh, my righteous plea;\nGive ear to my prayer, that doesn’t go out of deceitful lips.\n'),
	(9302, 16, 17, 2, 'Let my sentence come out of your presence.\nLet your eyes look on equity.\n'),
	(9303, 16, 17, 3, 'You have proved my heart.\nYou have visited me in the night.\nYou have tried me, and found nothing.\nI have resolved that my mouth shall not disobey.\n'),
	(9304, 16, 17, 4, 'As for the deeds of men, by the word of your lips,\nI have kept myself from the ways of the violent.\n'),
	(9305, 16, 17, 5, 'My steps have held fast to your paths.\nMy feet have not slipped.\n'),
	(9306, 16, 17, 6, 'I have called on you, for you will answer me, God.\nTurn your ear to me.\nHear my speech.\n'),
	(9307, 16, 17, 7, 'Show your marvelous loving kindness,\nyou who save those who take refuge by your right hand from their enemies.\n'),
	(9308, 16, 17, 8, 'Keep me as the apple of your eye.\nHide me under the shadow of your wings,\n'),
	(9309, 16, 17, 9, 'from the wicked who oppress me,\nmy deadly enemies, who surround me.\n'),
	(9310, 16, 17, 10, 'They close up their callous hearts.\nWith their mouth they speak proudly.\n'),
	(9311, 16, 17, 11, 'They have now surrounded us in our steps.\nThey set their eyes to cast us down to the earth.\n'),
	(9312, 16, 17, 12, 'He is like a lion that is greedy of his prey,\nas it were a young lion lurking in secret places.\n'),
	(9313, 16, 17, 13, 'Arise, Yahweh, confront him.\nCast him down.\nDeliver my soul from the wicked by your sword;\n'),
	(9314, 16, 17, 14, 'from men by your hand, Yahweh,\nfrom men of the world, whose portion is in this life.\nYou fill the belly of your cherished ones.\nYour sons have plenty,\nand they store up wealth for their children.\n'),
	(9315, 16, 17, 15, 'As for me, I shall see your face in righteousness.\nI shall be satisfied, when I awake, with seeing your form.\n'),
	(9316, 16, 18, 1, 'I love you, Yahweh, my strength.\n'),
	(9317, 16, 18, 2, 'Yahweh is my rock, my fortress, and my deliverer;\nmy God, my rock, in whom I take refuge;\nmy shield, and the horn of my salvation, my high tower.\n'),
	(9318, 16, 18, 3, 'I call on Yahweh, who is worthy to be praised;\nand I am saved from my enemies.\n'),
	(9319, 16, 18, 4, 'The cords of death surrounded me.\nThe floods of ungodliness made me afraid.\n'),
	(9320, 16, 18, 5, 'The cords of Sheol were around me.\nThe snares of death came on me.\n'),
	(9321, 16, 18, 6, 'In my distress I called on Yahweh,\nand cried to my God.\nHe heard my voice out of his temple.\nMy cry before him came into his ears.\n'),
	(9322, 16, 18, 7, 'Then the earth shook and trembled.\nThe foundations also of the mountains quaked and were shaken,\nbecause he was angry.\n'),
	(9323, 16, 18, 8, 'Smoke went out of his nostrils.\nConsuming fire came out of his mouth.\nCoals were kindled by it.\n'),
	(9324, 16, 18, 9, 'He bowed the heavens also, and came down.\nThick darkness was under his feet.\n'),
	(9325, 16, 18, 10, 'He rode on a cherub, and flew.\nYes, he soared on the wings of the wind.\n'),
	(9326, 16, 18, 11, 'He made darkness his hiding place, his pavilion around him,\ndarkness of waters, thick clouds of the skies.\n'),
	(9327, 16, 18, 12, 'At the brightness before him his thick clouds passed,\nhailstones and coals of fire.\n'),
	(9328, 16, 18, 13, 'Yahweh also thundered in the sky.\nThe Most High uttered his voice:\nhailstones and coals of fire.\n'),
	(9329, 16, 18, 14, 'He sent out his arrows, and scattered them;\nYes, great lightning bolts, and routed them.\n'),
	(9330, 16, 18, 15, 'Then the channels of waters appeared.\nThe foundations of the world were laid bare at your rebuke, Yahweh,\nat the blast of the breath of your nostrils.\n'),
	(9331, 16, 18, 16, 'He sent from on high.\nHe took me.\nHe drew me out of many waters.\n'),
	(9332, 16, 18, 17, 'He delivered me from my strong enemy,\nfrom those who hated me; for they were too mighty for me.\n'),
	(9333, 16, 18, 18, 'They came on me in the day of my calamity,\nbut Yahweh was my support.\n'),
	(9334, 16, 18, 19, 'He brought me out also into a large place.\nHe delivered me, because he delighted in me.\n'),
	(9335, 16, 18, 20, 'Yahweh has rewarded me according to my righteousness.\nAccording to the cleanness of my hands has he recompensed me.\n'),
	(9336, 16, 18, 21, 'For I have kept the ways of Yahweh,\nand have not wickedly departed from my God.\n'),
	(9337, 16, 18, 22, 'For all his ordinances were before me.\nI didn’t put away his statutes from me.\n'),
	(9338, 16, 18, 23, 'I was also blameless with him.\nI kept myself from my iniquity.\n'),
	(9339, 16, 18, 24, 'Therefore Yahweh has rewarded me according to my righteousness,\naccording to the cleanness of my hands in his eyesight.\n'),
	(9340, 16, 18, 25, 'With the merciful you will show yourself merciful.\nWith the perfect man, you will show yourself perfect.\n'),
	(9341, 16, 18, 26, 'With the pure, you will show yourself pure.\nWith the crooked you will show yourself shrewd.\n'),
	(9342, 16, 18, 27, 'For you will save the afflicted people,\nbut the haughty eyes you will bring down.\n'),
	(9343, 16, 18, 28, 'For you will light my lamp, Yahweh.\nMy God will light up my darkness.\n'),
	(9344, 16, 18, 29, 'For by you, I advance through a troop.\nBy my God, I leap over a wall.\n'),
	(9345, 16, 18, 30, 'As for God, his way is perfect.\nYahweh’s word is tried.\nHe is a shield to all those who take refuge in him.\n'),
	(9346, 16, 18, 31, 'For who is God, except Yahweh?\nWho is a rock, besides our God,\n'),
	(9347, 16, 18, 32, 'the God who arms me with strength, and makes my way perfect?\n'),
	(9348, 16, 18, 33, 'He makes my feet like deer’s feet,\nand sets me on my high places.\n'),
	(9349, 16, 18, 34, 'He teaches my hands to war,\nso that my arms bend a bow of bronze.\n'),
	(9350, 16, 18, 35, 'You have also given me the shield of your salvation.\nYour right hand sustains me.\nYour gentleness has made me great.\n'),
	(9351, 16, 18, 36, 'You have enlarged my steps under me,\nMy feet have not slipped.\n'),
	(9352, 16, 18, 37, 'I will pursue my enemies, and overtake them.\nNeither will I turn again until they are consumed.\n'),
	(9353, 16, 18, 38, 'I will strike them through, so that they will not be able to rise.\nThey shall fall under my feet.\n'),
	(9354, 16, 18, 39, 'For you have armed me with strength to the battle.\nYou have subdued under me those who rose up against me.\n'),
	(9355, 16, 18, 40, 'You have also made my enemies turn their backs to me,\nthat I might cut off those who hate me.\n'),
	(9356, 16, 18, 41, 'They cried, but there was no one to save;\neven to Yahweh, but he didn’t answer them.\n'),
	(9357, 16, 18, 42, 'Then I beat them small as the dust before the wind.\nI cast them out as the mire of the streets.\n'),
	(9358, 16, 18, 43, 'You have delivered me from the strivings of the people.\nYou have made me the head of the nations.\nA people whom I have not known shall serve me.\n'),
	(9359, 16, 18, 44, 'As soon as they hear of me they shall obey me.\nThe foreigners shall submit themselves to me.\n'),
	(9360, 16, 18, 45, 'The foreigners shall fade away,\nand shall come trembling out of their close places.\n'),
	(9361, 16, 18, 46, 'Yahweh lives; and blessed be my rock.\nExalted be the God of my salvation,\n'),
	(9362, 16, 18, 47, 'even the God who executes vengeance for me,\nand subdues peoples under me.\n'),
	(9363, 16, 18, 48, 'He rescues me from my enemies.\nYes, you lift me up above those who rise up against me.\nYou deliver me from the violent man.\n'),
	(9364, 16, 18, 49, 'Therefore I will give thanks to you, Yahweh, among the nations,\nand will sing praises to your name.\n'),
	(9365, 16, 18, 50, 'He gives great deliverance to his king,\nand shows loving kindness to his anointed,\nto David and to his offspring, forever more.\n'),
	(9366, 16, 19, 1, 'The heavens declare the glory of God.\nThe expanse shows his handiwork.\n'),
	(9367, 16, 19, 2, 'Day after day they pour out speech,\nand night after night they display knowledge.\n'),
	(9368, 16, 19, 3, 'There is no speech nor language,\nwhere their voice is not heard.\n'),
	(9369, 16, 19, 4, 'Their voice has gone out through all the earth,\ntheir words to the end of the world.\nIn them he has set a tent for the sun,\n'),
	(9370, 16, 19, 5, 'which is as a bridegroom coming out of his room,\nlike a strong man rejoicing to run his course.\n'),
	(9371, 16, 19, 6, 'His going out is from the end of the heavens,\nhis circuit to its ends;\nThere is nothing hidden from its heat.\n'),
	(9372, 16, 19, 7, 'Yahweh’s law is perfect, restoring the soul.\nYahweh’s testimony is sure, making wise the simple.\n'),
	(9373, 16, 19, 8, 'Yahweh’s precepts are right, rejoicing the heart.\nYahweh’s commandment is pure, enlightening the eyes.\n'),
	(9374, 16, 19, 9, 'The fear of Yahweh is clean, enduring forever.\nYahweh’s ordinances are true, and righteous altogether.\n'),
	(9375, 16, 19, 10, 'More to be desired are they than gold, yes, than much fine gold;\nsweeter also than honey and the extract of the honeycomb.\n'),
	(9376, 16, 19, 11, 'Moreover by them is your servant warned.\nIn keeping them there is great reward.\n'),
	(9377, 16, 19, 12, 'Who can discern his errors?\nForgive me from hidden errors.\n'),
	(9378, 16, 19, 13, 'Keep back your servant also from presumptuous sins.\nLet them not have dominion over me.\nThen I will be upright.\nI will be blameless and innocent of great transgression.\n'),
	(9379, 16, 19, 14, 'Let the words of my mouth and the meditation of my heart\nbe acceptable in your sight,\nYahweh, my rock, and my redeemer.\n'),
	(9380, 16, 20, 1, 'May Yahweh answer you in the day of trouble.\nMay the name of the God of Jacob set you up on high,\n'),
	(9381, 16, 20, 2, 'send you help from the sanctuary,\ngrant you support from Zion,\n'),
	(9382, 16, 20, 3, 'remember all your offerings,\nand accept your burned sacrifice.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9383, 16, 20, 4, 'May He grant you your heart’s desire,\nand fulfill all your counsel.\n'),
	(9384, 16, 20, 5, 'We will triumph in your salvation.\nIn the name of our God, we will set up our banners.\nMay Yahweh grant all your requests.\n'),
	(9385, 16, 20, 6, 'Now I know that Yahweh saves his anointed.\nHe will answer him from his holy heaven,\nwith the saving strength of his right hand.\n'),
	(9386, 16, 20, 7, 'Some trust in chariots, and some in horses,\nbut we trust the name of Yahweh our God.\n'),
	(9387, 16, 20, 8, 'They are bowed down and fallen,\nbut we rise up, and stand upright.\n'),
	(9388, 16, 20, 9, 'Save, Yahweh!\nLet the King answer us when we call!\n'),
	(9389, 16, 21, 1, 'The king rejoices in your strength, Yahweh!\nHow greatly he rejoices in your salvation!\n'),
	(9390, 16, 21, 2, 'You have given him his heart’s desire,\nand have not withheld the request of his lips.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9391, 16, 21, 3, 'For you meet him with the blessings of goodness.\nYou set a crown of fine gold on his head.\n'),
	(9392, 16, 21, 4, 'He asked life of you, you gave it to him,\neven length of days forever and ever.\n'),
	(9393, 16, 21, 5, 'His glory is great in your salvation.\nYou lay honor and majesty on him.\n'),
	(9394, 16, 21, 6, 'For you make him most blessed forever.\nYou make him glad with joy in your presence.\n'),
	(9395, 16, 21, 7, 'For the king trusts in Yahweh.\nThrough the loving kindness of the Most High, he shall not be moved.\n'),
	(9396, 16, 21, 8, 'Your hand will find out all of your enemies.\nYour right hand will find out those who hate you.\n'),
	(9397, 16, 21, 9, 'You will make them as a fiery furnace in the time of your anger.\nYahweh will swallow them up in his wrath.\nThe fire shall devour them.\n'),
	(9398, 16, 21, 10, 'You will destroy their descendants from the earth,\ntheir posterity from among the children of men.\n'),
	(9399, 16, 21, 11, 'For they intended evil against you.\nThey plotted evil against you which cannot succeed.\n'),
	(9400, 16, 21, 12, 'For you will make them turn their back,\nwhen you aim drawn bows at their face.\n'),
	(9401, 16, 21, 13, 'Be exalted, Yahweh, in your strength,\nso we will sing and praise your power.\n'),
	(9402, 16, 22, 1, 'My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?\nWhy are you so far from helping me, and from the words of my groaning?\n'),
	(9403, 16, 22, 2, 'My God, I cry in the daytime, but you don’t answer;\nin the night season, and am not silent.\n'),
	(9404, 16, 22, 3, 'But you are holy,\nyou who inhabit the praises of Israel.\n'),
	(9405, 16, 22, 4, 'Our fathers trusted in you.\nThey trusted, and you delivered them.\n'),
	(9406, 16, 22, 5, 'They cried to you, and were delivered.\nThey trusted in you, and were not disappointed.\n'),
	(9407, 16, 22, 6, 'But I am a worm, and no man;\na reproach of men, and despised by the people.\n'),
	(9408, 16, 22, 7, 'All those who see me mock me.\nThey insult me with their lips. They shake their heads, saying,\n'),
	(9409, 16, 22, 8, '“He trusts in Yahweh.\nLet him deliver him.\nLet him rescue him, since he delights in him.”\n'),
	(9410, 16, 22, 9, 'But you brought me out of the womb.\nYou made me trust while at my mother’s breasts.\n'),
	(9411, 16, 22, 10, 'I was thrown on you from my mother’s womb.\nYou are my God since my mother bore me.\n'),
	(9412, 16, 22, 11, 'Don’t be far from me, for trouble is near.\nFor there is no one to help.\n'),
	(9413, 16, 22, 12, 'Many bulls have surrounded me.\nStrong bulls of Bashan have encircled me.\n'),
	(9414, 16, 22, 13, 'They open their mouths wide against me,\nlions tearing prey and roaring.\n'),
	(9415, 16, 22, 14, 'I am poured out like water.\nAll my bones are out of joint.\nMy heart is like wax;\nit is melted within me.\n'),
	(9416, 16, 22, 15, 'My strength is dried up like a potsherd.\nMy tongue sticks to the roof of my mouth.\nYou have brought me into the dust of death.\n'),
	(9417, 16, 22, 16, 'For dogs have surrounded me.\nA company of evildoers have enclosed me.\nThey have pierced my hands and feet.\n'),
	(9418, 16, 22, 17, 'I can count all of my bones.\nThey look and stare at me.\n'),
	(9419, 16, 22, 18, 'They divide my garments among them.\nThey cast lots for my clothing.\n'),
	(9420, 16, 22, 19, 'But don’t be far off, Yahweh.\nYou are my help: hurry to help me.\n'),
	(9421, 16, 22, 20, 'Deliver my soul from the sword,\nmy precious life from the power of the dog.\n'),
	(9422, 16, 22, 21, 'Save me from the lion’s mouth!\nYes, from the horns of the wild oxen, you have answered me.\n'),
	(9423, 16, 22, 22, 'I will declare your name to my brothers.\nAmong the assembly, I will praise you.\n'),
	(9424, 16, 22, 23, 'You who fear Yahweh, praise him!\nAll you descendants of Jacob, glorify him!\nStand in awe of him, all you descendants of Israel!\n'),
	(9425, 16, 22, 24, 'For he has not despised nor abhorred the affliction of the afflicted,\nNeither has he hidden his face from him;\nbut when he cried to him, he heard.\n'),
	(9426, 16, 22, 25, 'Of you comes my praise in the great assembly.\nI will pay my vows before those who fear him.\n'),
	(9427, 16, 22, 26, 'The humble shall eat and be satisfied.\nThey shall praise Yahweh who seek after him.\nLet your hearts live forever.\n'),
	(9428, 16, 22, 27, 'All the ends of the earth shall remember and turn to Yahweh.\nAll the relatives of the nations shall worship before you.\n'),
	(9429, 16, 22, 28, 'For the kingdom is Yahweh’s.\nHe is the ruler over the nations.\n'),
	(9430, 16, 22, 29, 'All the rich ones of the earth shall eat and worship.\nAll those who go down to the dust shall bow before him,\neven he who can’t keep his soul alive.\n'),
	(9431, 16, 22, 30, 'Posterity shall serve him.\nFuture generations shall be told about the Lord.\n'),
	(9432, 16, 22, 31, 'They shall come and shall declare his righteousness to a people that shall be born,\nfor he has done it.\n'),
	(9433, 16, 23, 1, 'Yahweh is my shepherd:\nI shall lack nothing.\n'),
	(9434, 16, 23, 2, 'He makes me lie down in green pastures.\nHe leads me beside still waters.\n'),
	(9435, 16, 23, 3, 'He restores my soul.\nHe guides me in the paths of righteousness for his name’s sake.\n'),
	(9436, 16, 23, 4, 'Even though I walk through the valley of the shadow of death,\nI will fear no evil, for you are with me.\nYour rod and your staff,\nthey comfort me.\n'),
	(9437, 16, 23, 5, 'You prepare a table before me\nin the presence of my enemies.\nYou anoint my head with oil.\nMy cup runs over.\n'),
	(9438, 16, 23, 6, 'Surely goodness and loving kindness shall follow me all the days of my life,\nand I will dwell in Yahweh’s house forever.\n'),
	(9439, 16, 24, 1, 'The earth is Yahweh’s, with its fullness;\nthe world, and those who dwell therein.\n'),
	(9440, 16, 24, 2, 'For he has founded it on the seas,\nand established it on the floods.\n'),
	(9441, 16, 24, 3, 'Who may ascend to Yahweh’s hill?\nWho may stand in his holy place?\n'),
	(9442, 16, 24, 4, 'He who has clean hands and a pure heart;\nwho has not lifted up his soul to falsehood,\nand has not sworn deceitfully.\n'),
	(9443, 16, 24, 5, 'He shall receive a blessing from Yahweh,\nrighteousness from the God of his salvation.\n'),
	(9444, 16, 24, 6, 'This is the generation of those who seek Him,\nwho seek your face—even Jacob.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9445, 16, 24, 7, 'Lift up your heads, you gates!\nBe lifted up, you everlasting doors,\nand the King of glory will come in.\n'),
	(9446, 16, 24, 8, 'Who is the King of glory?\nYahweh strong and mighty,\nYahweh mighty in battle.\n'),
	(9447, 16, 24, 9, 'Lift up your heads, you gates;\nyes, lift them up, you everlasting doors,\nand the King of glory will come in.\n'),
	(9448, 16, 24, 10, 'Who is this King of glory?\nYahweh of Armies is the King of glory!\nSelah.\n'),
	(9449, 16, 25, 1, 'To you, Yahweh, do I lift up my soul.\n'),
	(9450, 16, 25, 2, 'My God, I have trusted in you.\nDon’t let me be shamed.\nDon’t let my enemies triumph over me.\n'),
	(9451, 16, 25, 3, 'Yes, no one who waits for you shall be shamed.\nThey shall be shamed who deal treacherously without cause.\n'),
	(9452, 16, 25, 4, 'Show me your ways, Yahweh.\nTeach me your paths.\n'),
	(9453, 16, 25, 5, 'Guide me in your truth, and teach me,\nFor you are the God of my salvation,\nI wait for you all day long.\n'),
	(9454, 16, 25, 6, 'Yahweh, remember your tender mercies and your loving kindness,\nfor they are from old times.\n'),
	(9455, 16, 25, 7, 'Don’t remember the sins of my youth, nor my transgressions.\nRemember me according to your loving kindness,\nfor your goodness’ sake, Yahweh.\n'),
	(9456, 16, 25, 8, 'Good and upright is Yahweh,\ntherefore he will instruct sinners in the way.\n'),
	(9457, 16, 25, 9, 'He will guide the humble in justice.\nHe will teach the humble his way.\n'),
	(9458, 16, 25, 10, 'All the paths of Yahweh are loving kindness and truth\nto such as keep his covenant and his testimonies.\n'),
	(9459, 16, 25, 11, 'For your name’s sake, Yahweh,\npardon my iniquity, for it is great.\n'),
	(9460, 16, 25, 12, 'What man is he who fears Yahweh?\nHe shall instruct him in the way that he shall choose.\n'),
	(9461, 16, 25, 13, 'His soul shall dwell at ease.\nHis offspring shall inherit the land.\n'),
	(9462, 16, 25, 14, 'The friendship of Yahweh is with those who fear him.\nHe will show them his covenant.\n'),
	(9463, 16, 25, 15, 'My eyes are ever on Yahweh,\nfor he will pluck my feet out of the net.\n'),
	(9464, 16, 25, 16, 'Turn to me, and have mercy on me,\nfor I am desolate and afflicted.\n'),
	(9465, 16, 25, 17, 'The troubles of my heart are enlarged.\nOh bring me out of my distresses.\n'),
	(9466, 16, 25, 18, 'Consider my affliction and my travail.\nForgive all my sins.\n'),
	(9467, 16, 25, 19, 'Consider my enemies, for they are many.\nThey hate me with cruel hatred.\n'),
	(9468, 16, 25, 20, 'Oh keep my soul, and deliver me.\nLet me not be disappointed, for I take refuge in you.\n'),
	(9469, 16, 25, 21, 'Let integrity and uprightness preserve me,\nfor I wait for you.\n'),
	(9470, 16, 25, 22, 'Redeem Israel, God,\nout of all his troubles.\n'),
	(9471, 16, 26, 1, 'Judge me, Yahweh, for I have walked in my integrity.\nI have trusted also in Yahweh without wavering.\n'),
	(9472, 16, 26, 2, 'Examine me, Yahweh, and prove me.\nTry my heart and my mind.\n'),
	(9473, 16, 26, 3, 'For your loving kindness is before my eyes.\nI have walked in your truth.\n'),
	(9474, 16, 26, 4, 'I have not sat with deceitful men,\nneither will I go in with hypocrites.\n'),
	(9475, 16, 26, 5, 'I hate the assembly of evildoers,\nand will not sit with the wicked.\n'),
	(9476, 16, 26, 6, 'I will wash my hands in innocence,\nso I will go about your altar, Yahweh;\n'),
	(9477, 16, 26, 7, 'that I may make the voice of thanksgiving to be heard,\nand tell of all your wondrous deeds.\n'),
	(9478, 16, 26, 8, 'Yahweh, I love the habitation of your house,\nthe place where your glory dwells.\n'),
	(9479, 16, 26, 9, 'Don’t gather my soul with sinners,\nnor my life with bloodthirsty men;\n'),
	(9480, 16, 26, 10, 'in whose hands is wickedness,\ntheir right hand is full of bribes.\n'),
	(9481, 16, 26, 11, 'But as for me, I will walk in my integrity.\nRedeem me, and be merciful to me.\n'),
	(9482, 16, 26, 12, 'My foot stands in an even place.\nIn the congregations I will bless Yahweh.\n'),
	(9483, 16, 27, 1, 'Yahweh is my light and my salvation.\nWhom shall I fear?\nYahweh is the strength of my life.\nOf whom shall I be afraid?\n'),
	(9484, 16, 27, 2, 'When evildoers came at me to eat up my flesh,\neven my adversaries and my foes, they stumbled and fell.\n'),
	(9485, 16, 27, 3, 'Though an army should encamp against me,\nmy heart shall not fear.\nThough war should rise against me,\neven then I will be confident.\n'),
	(9486, 16, 27, 4, 'One thing I have asked of Yahweh, that I will seek after:\nthat I may dwell in Yahweh’s house all the days of my life,\nto see Yahweh’s beauty,\nand to inquire in his temple.\n'),
	(9487, 16, 27, 5, 'For in the day of trouble, he will keep me secretly in his pavilion.\nIn the secret place of his tabernacle, he will hide me.\nHe will lift me up on a rock.\n'),
	(9488, 16, 27, 6, 'Now my head will be lifted up above my enemies around me;\nI will offer sacrifices of joy in his tent.\nI will sing, yes, I will sing praises to Yahweh.\n'),
	(9489, 16, 27, 7, 'Hear, Yahweh, when I cry with my voice.\nHave mercy also on me, and answer me.\n'),
	(9490, 16, 27, 8, 'When you said, “Seek my face,”\nmy heart said to you, “I will seek your face, Yahweh.”\n'),
	(9491, 16, 27, 9, 'Don’t hide your face from me.\nDon’t put your servant away in anger.\nYou have been my help.\nDon’t abandon me,\nneither forsake me, God of my salvation.\n'),
	(9492, 16, 27, 10, 'When my father and my mother forsake me,\nthen Yahweh will take me up.\n'),
	(9493, 16, 27, 11, 'Teach me your way, Yahweh.\nLead me in a straight path, because of my enemies.\n'),
	(9494, 16, 27, 12, 'Don’t deliver me over to the desire of my adversaries,\nfor false witnesses have risen up against me,\nsuch as breathe out cruelty.\n'),
	(9495, 16, 27, 13, 'I am still confident of this:\nI will see the goodness of Yahweh in the land of the living.\n'),
	(9496, 16, 27, 14, 'Wait for Yahweh.\nBe strong, and let your heart take courage.\nYes, wait for Yahweh.\n'),
	(9497, 16, 28, 1, 'To you, Yahweh, I call.\nMy rock, don’t be deaf to me;\nlest, if you are silent to me,\nI would become like those who go down into the pit.\n'),
	(9498, 16, 28, 2, 'Hear the voice of my petitions, when I cry to you,\nwhen I lift up my hands toward your Most Holy Place.\n'),
	(9499, 16, 28, 3, 'Don’t draw me away with the wicked,\nwith the workers of iniquity who speak peace with their neighbors,\nbut mischief is in their hearts.\n'),
	(9500, 16, 28, 4, 'Give them according to their work, and according to the wickedness of their doings.\nGive them according to the operation of their hands.\nBring back on them what they deserve.\n'),
	(9501, 16, 28, 5, 'Because they don’t respect the works of Yahweh,\nnor the operation of his hands,\nhe will break them down and not build them up.\n'),
	(9502, 16, 28, 6, 'Blessed be Yahweh,\nbecause he has heard the voice of my petitions.\n'),
	(9503, 16, 28, 7, 'Yahweh is my strength and my shield.\nMy heart has trusted in him, and I am helped.\nTherefore my heart greatly rejoices.\nWith my song I will thank him.\n'),
	(9504, 16, 28, 8, 'Yahweh is their strength.\nHe is a stronghold of salvation to his anointed.\n'),
	(9505, 16, 28, 9, 'Save your people,\nand bless your inheritance.\nBe their shepherd also,\nand bear them up forever.\n'),
	(9506, 16, 29, 1, 'Ascribe to Yahweh, you sons of the mighty,\nascribe to Yahweh glory and strength.\n'),
	(9507, 16, 29, 2, 'Ascribe to Yahweh the glory due to his name.\nWorship Yahweh in holy array.\n'),
	(9508, 16, 29, 3, 'Yahweh’s voice is on the waters.\nThe God of glory thunders, even Yahweh on many waters.\n'),
	(9509, 16, 29, 4, 'Yahweh’s voice is powerful.\nYahweh’s voice is full of majesty.\n'),
	(9510, 16, 29, 5, 'Yahweh’s voice breaks the cedars.\nYes, Yahweh breaks in pieces the cedars of Lebanon.\n'),
	(9511, 16, 29, 6, 'He makes them also to skip like a calf;\nLebanon and Sirion like a young, wild ox.\n'),
	(9512, 16, 29, 7, 'Yahweh’s voice strikes with flashes of lightning.\n'),
	(9513, 16, 29, 8, 'Yahweh’s voice shakes the wilderness.\nYahweh shakes the wilderness of Kadesh.\n'),
	(9514, 16, 29, 9, 'Yahweh’s voice makes the deer calve,\nand strips the forests bare.\nIn his temple everything says, “Glory!”\n'),
	(9515, 16, 29, 10, 'Yahweh sat enthroned at the Flood.\nYes, Yahweh sits as King forever.\n'),
	(9516, 16, 29, 11, 'Yahweh will give strength to his people.\nYahweh will bless his people with peace.\n'),
	(9517, 16, 30, 1, 'I will extol you, Yahweh, for you have raised me up,\nand have not made my foes to rejoice over me.\n'),
	(9518, 16, 30, 2, 'Yahweh my God, I cried to you,\nand you have healed me.\n'),
	(9519, 16, 30, 3, 'Yahweh, you have brought up my soul from Sheol.\nYou have kept me alive, that I should not go down to the pit.\n'),
	(9520, 16, 30, 4, 'Sing praise to Yahweh, you saints of his.\nGive thanks to his holy name.\n'),
	(9521, 16, 30, 5, 'For his anger is but for a moment.\nHis favor is for a lifetime.\nWeeping may stay for the night,\nbut joy comes in the morning.\n'),
	(9522, 16, 30, 6, 'As for me, I said in my prosperity,\n“I shall never be moved.”\n'),
	(9523, 16, 30, 7, 'You, Yahweh, when you favored me, made my mountain stand strong;\nbut when you hid your face, I was troubled.\n'),
	(9524, 16, 30, 8, 'I cried to you, Yahweh.\nI made supplication to the Lord:\n'),
	(9525, 16, 30, 9, '“What profit is there in my destruction, if I go down to the pit?\nShall the dust praise you?\nShall it declare your truth?\n'),
	(9526, 16, 30, 10, 'Hear, Yahweh, and have mercy on me.\nYahweh, be my helper.”\n'),
	(9527, 16, 30, 11, 'You have turned my mourning into dancing for me.\nYou have removed my sackcloth, and clothed me with gladness,\n'),
	(9528, 16, 30, 12, 'To the end that my heart may sing praise to you, and not be silent.\nYahweh my God, I will give thanks to you forever!\n'),
	(9529, 16, 31, 1, 'In you, Yahweh, I take refuge.\nLet me never be disappointed.\nDeliver me in your righteousness.\n'),
	(9530, 16, 31, 2, 'Bow down your ear to me.\nDeliver me speedily.\nBe to me a strong rock,\na house of defense to save me.\n'),
	(9531, 16, 31, 3, 'For you are my rock and my fortress,\ntherefore for your name’s sake lead me and guide me.\n'),
	(9532, 16, 31, 4, 'Pluck me out of the net that they have laid secretly for me,\nfor you are my stronghold.\n'),
	(9533, 16, 31, 5, 'Into your hand I commend my spirit.\nYou redeem me, Yahweh, God of truth.\n'),
	(9534, 16, 31, 6, 'I hate those who regard lying vanities,\nbut I trust in Yahweh.\n'),
	(9535, 16, 31, 7, 'I will be glad and rejoice in your loving kindness,\nfor you have seen my affliction.\nYou have known my soul in adversities.\n'),
	(9536, 16, 31, 8, 'You have not shut me up into the hand of the enemy.\nYou have set my feet in a large place.\n'),
	(9537, 16, 31, 9, 'Have mercy on me, Yahweh, for I am in distress.\nMy eye, my soul, and my body waste away with grief.\n'),
	(9538, 16, 31, 10, 'For my life is spent with sorrow,\nmy years with sighing.\nMy strength fails because of my iniquity.\nMy bones are wasted away.\n'),
	(9539, 16, 31, 11, 'Because of all my adversaries I have become utterly contemptible to my neighbors,\nA fear to my acquaintances.\nThose who saw me on the street fled from me.\n'),
	(9540, 16, 31, 12, 'I am forgotten from their hearts like a dead man.\nI am like broken pottery.\n'),
	(9541, 16, 31, 13, 'For I have heard the slander of many, terror on every side,\nwhile they conspire together against me,\nthey plot to take away my life.\n'),
	(9542, 16, 31, 14, 'But I trust in you, Yahweh.\nI said, “You are my God.”\n'),
	(9543, 16, 31, 15, 'My times are in your hand.\nDeliver me from the hand of my enemies, and from those who persecute me.\n'),
	(9544, 16, 31, 16, 'Make your face to shine on your servant.\nSave me in your loving kindness.\n'),
	(9545, 16, 31, 17, 'Let me not be disappointed, Yahweh, for I have called on you.\nLet the wicked be disappointed.\nLet them be silent in Sheol.\n'),
	(9546, 16, 31, 18, 'Let the lying lips be mute,\nwhich speak against the righteous insolently, with pride and contempt.\n'),
	(9547, 16, 31, 19, 'Oh how great is your goodness,\nwhich you have laid up for those who fear you,\nwhich you have worked for those who take refuge in you,\nbefore the sons of men!\n'),
	(9548, 16, 31, 20, 'In the shelter of your presence you will hide them from the plotting of man.\nYou will keep them secretly in a dwelling away from the strife of tongues.\n'),
	(9549, 16, 31, 21, 'Praise be to Yahweh,\nfor he has shown me his marvelous loving kindness in a strong city.\n'),
	(9550, 16, 31, 22, 'As for me, I said in my haste, “I am cut off from before your eyes.”\nNevertheless you heard the voice of my petitions when I cried to you.\n'),
	(9551, 16, 31, 23, 'Oh love Yahweh, all you his saints!\nYahweh preserves the faithful,\nand fully recompenses him who behaves arrogantly.\n'),
	(9552, 16, 31, 24, 'Be strong, and let your heart take courage,\nall you who hope in Yahweh.\n'),
	(9553, 16, 32, 1, 'Blessed is he whose disobedience is forgiven,\nwhose sin is covered.\n'),
	(9554, 16, 32, 2, 'Blessed is the man to whom Yahweh doesn’t impute iniquity,\nin whose spirit there is no deceit.\n'),
	(9555, 16, 32, 3, 'When I kept silence, my bones wasted away through my groaning all day long.\n'),
	(9556, 16, 32, 4, 'For day and night your hand was heavy on me.\nMy strength was sapped in the heat of summer.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9557, 16, 32, 5, 'I acknowledged my sin to you.\nI didn’t hide my iniquity.\nI said, I will confess my transgressions to Yahweh,\nand you forgave the iniquity of my sin.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9558, 16, 32, 6, 'For this, let everyone who is godly pray to you in a time when you may be found.\nSurely when the great waters overflow, they shall not reach to him.\n'),
	(9559, 16, 32, 7, 'You are my hiding place.\nYou will preserve me from trouble.\nYou will surround me with songs of deliverance.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9560, 16, 32, 8, 'I will instruct you and teach you in the way which you shall go.\nI will counsel you with my eye on you.\n'),
	(9561, 16, 32, 9, 'Don’t be like the horse, or like the mule, which have no understanding,\nwho are controlled by bit and bridle, or else they will not come near to you.\n'),
	(9562, 16, 32, 10, 'Many sorrows come to the wicked,\nbut loving kindness shall surround him who trusts in Yahweh.\n'),
	(9563, 16, 32, 11, 'Be glad in Yahweh, and rejoice, you righteous!\nShout for joy, all you who are upright in heart!\n'),
	(9564, 16, 33, 1, 'Rejoice in Yahweh, you righteous!\nPraise is fitting for the upright.\n'),
	(9565, 16, 33, 2, 'Give thanks to Yahweh with the lyre.\nSing praises to him with the harp of ten strings.\n'),
	(9566, 16, 33, 3, 'Sing to him a new song.\nPlay skillfully with a shout of joy!\n'),
	(9567, 16, 33, 4, 'For Yahweh’s word is right.\nAll his work is done in faithfulness.\n'),
	(9568, 16, 33, 5, 'He loves righteousness and justice.\nThe earth is full of the loving kindness of Yahweh.\n'),
	(9569, 16, 33, 6, 'By Yahweh’s word, the heavens were made;\nall their army by the breath of his mouth.\n'),
	(9570, 16, 33, 7, 'He gathers the waters of the sea together as a heap.\nHe lays up the deeps in storehouses.\n'),
	(9571, 16, 33, 8, 'Let all the earth fear Yahweh.\nLet all the inhabitants of the world stand in awe of him.\n'),
	(9572, 16, 33, 9, 'For he spoke, and it was done.\nHe commanded, and it stood firm.\n'),
	(9573, 16, 33, 10, 'Yahweh brings the counsel of the nations to nothing.\nHe makes the thoughts of the peoples to be of no effect.\n'),
	(9574, 16, 33, 11, 'The counsel of Yahweh stands fast forever,\nthe thoughts of his heart to all generations.\n'),
	(9575, 16, 33, 12, 'Blessed is the nation whose God is Yahweh,\nthe people whom he has chosen for his own inheritance.\n'),
	(9576, 16, 33, 13, 'Yahweh looks from heaven.\nHe sees all the sons of men.\n'),
	(9577, 16, 33, 14, 'From the place of his habitation he looks out on all the inhabitants of the earth,\n'),
	(9578, 16, 33, 15, 'he who fashions all of their hearts;\nand he considers all of their works.\n'),
	(9579, 16, 33, 16, 'There is no king saved by the multitude of an army.\nA mighty man is not delivered by great strength.\n'),
	(9580, 16, 33, 17, 'A horse is a vain thing for safety,\nneither does he deliver any by his great power.\n'),
	(9581, 16, 33, 18, 'Behold, Yahweh’s eye is on those who fear him,\non those who hope in his loving kindness;\n'),
	(9582, 16, 33, 19, 'to deliver their soul from death,\nto keep them alive in famine.\n'),
	(9583, 16, 33, 20, 'Our soul has waited for Yahweh.\nHe is our help and our shield.\n'),
	(9584, 16, 33, 21, 'For our heart rejoices in him,\nbecause we have trusted in his holy name.\n'),
	(9585, 16, 33, 22, 'Let your loving kindness be on us, Yahweh,\nsince we have hoped in you.\n'),
	(9586, 16, 34, 1, '\n I will bless Yahweh at all times.\nHis praise will always be in my mouth.\n'),
	(9587, 16, 34, 2, 'My soul shall boast in Yahweh.\nThe humble shall hear of it, and be glad.\n'),
	(9588, 16, 34, 3, 'Oh magnify Yahweh with me.\nLet us exalt his name together.\n'),
	(9589, 16, 34, 4, 'I sought Yahweh, and he answered me,\nand delivered me from all my fears.\n'),
	(9590, 16, 34, 5, 'They looked to him, and were radiant.\nTheir faces shall never be covered with shame.\n'),
	(9591, 16, 34, 6, 'This poor man cried, and Yahweh heard him,\nand saved him out of all his troubles.\n'),
	(9592, 16, 34, 7, 'Yahweh’s angel encamps around those who fear him,\nand delivers them.\n'),
	(9593, 16, 34, 8, 'Oh taste and see that Yahweh is good.\nBlessed is the man who takes refuge in him.\n'),
	(9594, 16, 34, 9, 'Oh fear Yahweh, you his saints,\nfor there is no lack with those who fear him.\n'),
	(9595, 16, 34, 10, 'The young lions do lack, and suffer hunger,\nbut those who seek Yahweh shall not lack any good thing.\n'),
	(9596, 16, 34, 11, 'Come, you children, listen to me.\nI will teach you the fear of Yahweh.\n'),
	(9597, 16, 34, 12, 'Who is someone who desires life,\nand loves many days, that he may see good?\n'),
	(9598, 16, 34, 13, 'Keep your tongue from evil,\nand your lips from speaking lies.\n'),
	(9599, 16, 34, 14, 'Depart from evil, and do good.\nseek peace, and pursue it.\n'),
	(9600, 16, 34, 15, 'Yahweh’s eyes are toward the righteous.\nHis ears listen to their cry.\n'),
	(9601, 16, 34, 16, 'Yahweh’s face is against those who do evil,\nto cut off their memory from the earth.\n'),
	(9602, 16, 34, 17, 'The righteous cry, and Yahweh hears,\nand delivers them out of all their troubles.\n'),
	(9603, 16, 34, 18, 'Yahweh is near to those who have a broken heart,\nand saves those who have a crushed spirit.\n'),
	(9604, 16, 34, 19, 'Many are the afflictions of the righteous,\nbut Yahweh delivers him out of them all.\n'),
	(9605, 16, 34, 20, 'He protects all of his bones.\nNot one of them is broken.\n'),
	(9606, 16, 34, 21, 'Evil shall kill the wicked.\nThose who hate the righteous shall be condemned.\n'),
	(9607, 16, 34, 22, 'Yahweh redeems the soul of his servants.\nNone of those who take refuge in him shall be condemned.\n'),
	(9608, 16, 35, 1, 'Contend, Yahweh, with those who contend with me.\nFight against those who fight against me.\n'),
	(9609, 16, 35, 2, 'Take hold of shield and buckler,\nand stand up for my help.\n'),
	(9610, 16, 35, 3, 'Brandish the spear and block those who pursue me.\nTell my soul, “I am your salvation.”\n'),
	(9611, 16, 35, 4, 'Let those who seek after my soul be disappointed and brought to dishonor.\nLet those who plot my ruin be turned back and confounded.\n'),
	(9612, 16, 35, 5, 'Let them be as chaff before the wind,\nYahweh’s angel driving them on.\n'),
	(9613, 16, 35, 6, 'Let their way be dark and slippery,\nYahweh’s angel pursuing them.\n'),
	(9614, 16, 35, 7, 'For without cause they have hidden their net in a pit for me.\nWithout cause they have dug a pit for my soul.\n'),
	(9615, 16, 35, 8, 'Let destruction come on him unawares.\nLet his net that he has hidden catch himself.\nLet him fall into that destruction.\n'),
	(9616, 16, 35, 9, 'My soul shall be joyful in Yahweh.\nIt shall rejoice in his salvation.\n'),
	(9617, 16, 35, 10, 'All my bones shall say, “Yahweh, who is like you,\nwho delivers the poor from him who is too strong for him;\nyes, the poor and the needy from him who robs him?”\n'),
	(9618, 16, 35, 11, 'Unrighteous witnesses rise up.\nThey ask me about things that I don’t know about.\n'),
	(9619, 16, 35, 12, 'They reward me evil for good,\nto the bereaving of my soul.\n'),
	(9620, 16, 35, 13, 'But as for me, when they were sick, my clothing was sackcloth.\nI afflicted my soul with fasting.\nMy prayer returned into my own bosom.\n'),
	(9621, 16, 35, 14, 'I behaved myself as though it had been my friend or my brother.\nI bowed down mourning, as one who mourns his mother.\n'),
	(9622, 16, 35, 15, 'But in my adversity, they rejoiced, and gathered themselves together.\nThe attackers gathered themselves together against me, and I didn’t know it.\nThey tore at me, and didn’t cease.\n'),
	(9623, 16, 35, 16, 'Like the profane mockers in feasts,\nthey gnashed their teeth at me.\n'),
	(9624, 16, 35, 17, 'Lord, how long will you look on?\nRescue my soul from their destruction,\nmy precious life from the lions.\n'),
	(9625, 16, 35, 18, 'I will give you thanks in the great assembly.\nI will praise you among many people.\n'),
	(9626, 16, 35, 19, 'Don’t let those who are my enemies wrongfully rejoice over me;\nneither let those who hate me without a cause wink their eyes.\n'),
	(9627, 16, 35, 20, 'For they don’t speak peace,\nbut they devise deceitful words against those who are quiet in the land.\n'),
	(9628, 16, 35, 21, 'Yes, they opened their mouth wide against me.\nThey said, “Aha! Aha! Our eye has seen it!”\n'),
	(9629, 16, 35, 22, 'You have seen it, Yahweh. Don’t keep silent.\nLord, don’t be far from me.\n'),
	(9630, 16, 35, 23, 'Wake up! Rise up to defend me, my God!\nMy Lord, contend for me!\n'),
	(9631, 16, 35, 24, 'Vindicate me, Yahweh my God, according to your righteousness.\nDon’t let them gloat over me.\n'),
	(9632, 16, 35, 25, 'Don’t let them say in their heart, “Aha! That’s the way we want it!”\nDon’t let them say, “We have swallowed him up!”\n'),
	(9633, 16, 35, 26, 'Let them be disappointed and confounded together who rejoice at my calamity.\nLet them be clothed with shame and dishonor who magnify themselves against me.\n'),
	(9634, 16, 35, 27, 'Let them shout for joy and be glad, who favor my righteous cause.\nYes, let them say continually, “Yahweh be magnified,\nwho has pleasure in the prosperity of his servant!”\n'),
	(9635, 16, 35, 28, 'My tongue shall talk about your righteousness and about your praise all day long.\n'),
	(9636, 16, 36, 1, 'An inner sanctuary is within my heart about the disobedience of the wicked:\n“There is no fear of God before his eyes.”\n'),
	(9637, 16, 36, 2, 'For he flatters himself in his own eyes,\ntoo much to detect and hate his sin.\n'),
	(9638, 16, 36, 3, 'The words of his mouth are iniquity and deceit.\nHe has ceased to be wise and to do good.\n'),
	(9639, 16, 36, 4, 'He plots iniquity on his bed.\nHe sets himself in a way that is not good.\nHe doesn’t abhor evil.\n'),
	(9640, 16, 36, 5, 'Your loving kindness, Yahweh, is in the heavens.\nYour faithfulness reaches to the skies.\n'),
	(9641, 16, 36, 6, 'Your righteousness is like the mountains of God.\nYour judgments are like a great deep.\nYahweh, you preserve man and animal.\n'),
	(9642, 16, 36, 7, 'How precious is your loving kindness, God!\nThe children of men take refuge under the shadow of your wings.\n'),
	(9643, 16, 36, 8, 'They shall be abundantly satisfied with the abundance of your house.\nYou will make them drink of the river of your pleasures.\n'),
	(9644, 16, 36, 9, 'For with you is the spring of life.\nIn your light shall we see light.\n'),
	(9645, 16, 36, 10, 'Oh continue your loving kindness to those who know you,\nyour righteousness to the upright in heart.\n'),
	(9646, 16, 36, 11, 'Don’t let the foot of pride come against me.\nDon’t let the hand of the wicked drive me away.\n'),
	(9647, 16, 36, 12, 'There the workers of iniquity are fallen.\nThey are thrust down, and shall not be able to rise.\n'),
	(9648, 16, 37, 1, 'Don’t fret because of evildoers,\nneither be envious against those who work unrighteousness.\n'),
	(9649, 16, 37, 2, 'For they shall soon be cut down like the grass,\nand wither like the green herb.\n'),
	(9650, 16, 37, 3, 'Trust in Yahweh, and do good.\nDwell in the land, and enjoy safe pasture.\n'),
	(9651, 16, 37, 4, 'Also delight yourself in Yahweh,\nand he will give you the desires of your heart.\n'),
	(9652, 16, 37, 5, 'Commit your way to Yahweh.\nTrust also in him, and he will do this:\n'),
	(9653, 16, 37, 6, 'he will make your righteousness go out as the light,\nand your justice as the noon day sun.\n'),
	(9654, 16, 37, 7, 'Rest in Yahweh, and wait patiently for him.\nDon’t fret because of him who prospers in his way,\nbecause of the man who makes wicked plots happen.\n'),
	(9655, 16, 37, 8, 'Cease from anger, and forsake wrath.\nDon’t fret, it leads only to evildoing.\n'),
	(9656, 16, 37, 9, 'For evildoers shall be cut off,\nbut those who wait for Yahweh shall inherit the land.\n'),
	(9657, 16, 37, 10, 'For yet a little while, and the wicked will be no more.\nYes, though you look for his place, he isn’t there.\n'),
	(9658, 16, 37, 11, 'But the humble shall inherit the land,\nand shall delight themselves in the abundance of peace.\n'),
	(9659, 16, 37, 12, 'The wicked plots against the just,\nand gnashes at him with his teeth.\n'),
	(9660, 16, 37, 13, 'The Lord will laugh at him,\nfor he sees that his day is coming.\n'),
	(9661, 16, 37, 14, 'The wicked have drawn out the sword, and have bent their bow,\nto cast down the poor and needy,\nto kill those who are upright on the path.\n'),
	(9662, 16, 37, 15, 'Their sword shall enter into their own heart.\nTheir bows shall be broken.\n'),
	(9663, 16, 37, 16, 'Better is a little that the righteous has,\nthan the abundance of many wicked.\n'),
	(9664, 16, 37, 17, 'For the arms of the wicked shall be broken,\nbut Yahweh upholds the righteous.\n'),
	(9665, 16, 37, 18, 'Yahweh knows the days of the perfect.\nTheir inheritance shall be forever.\n'),
	(9666, 16, 37, 19, 'They shall not be disappointed in the time of evil.\nIn the days of famine they shall be satisfied.\n'),
	(9667, 16, 37, 20, 'But the wicked shall perish.\nThe enemies of Yahweh shall be like the beauty of the fields.\nThey will vanish—\nvanish like smoke.\n'),
	(9668, 16, 37, 21, 'The wicked borrow, and don’t pay back,\nbut the righteous give generously.\n'),
	(9669, 16, 37, 22, 'For such as are blessed by him shall inherit the land.\nThose who are cursed by him shall be cut off.\n'),
	(9670, 16, 37, 23, 'A man’s goings are established by Yahweh.\nHe delights in his way.\n'),
	(9671, 16, 37, 24, 'Though he stumble, he shall not fall,\nfor Yahweh holds him up with his hand.\n'),
	(9672, 16, 37, 25, 'I have been young, and now am old,\nyet I have not seen the righteous forsaken,\nnor his children begging for bread.\n'),
	(9673, 16, 37, 26, 'All day long he deals graciously, and lends.\nHis offspring is blessed.\n'),
	(9674, 16, 37, 27, 'Depart from evil, and do good.\nLive securely forever.\n'),
	(9675, 16, 37, 28, 'For Yahweh loves justice,\nand doesn’t forsake his saints.\nThey are preserved forever,\nbut the children of the wicked shall be cut off.\n'),
	(9676, 16, 37, 29, 'The righteous shall inherit the land,\nand live in it forever.\n'),
	(9677, 16, 37, 30, 'The mouth of the righteous talks of wisdom.\nHis tongue speaks justice.\n'),
	(9678, 16, 37, 31, 'The law of his God is in his heart.\nNone of his steps shall slide.\n'),
	(9679, 16, 37, 32, 'The wicked watches the righteous,\nand seeks to kill him.\n'),
	(9680, 16, 37, 33, 'Yahweh will not leave him in his hand,\nnor condemn him when he is judged.\n'),
	(9681, 16, 37, 34, 'Wait for Yahweh, and keep his way,\nand he will exalt you to inherit the land.\nWhen the wicked are cut off, you shall see it.\n'),
	(9682, 16, 37, 35, 'I have seen the wicked in great power,\nspreading himself like a green tree in its native soil.\n'),
	(9683, 16, 37, 36, 'But he passed away, and behold, he was not.\nYes, I sought him, but he could not be found.\n'),
	(9684, 16, 37, 37, 'Mark the perfect man, and see the upright,\nfor there is a future for the man of peace.\n'),
	(9685, 16, 37, 38, 'As for transgressors, they shall be destroyed together.\nThe future of the wicked shall be cut off.\n'),
	(9686, 16, 37, 39, 'But the salvation of the righteous is from Yahweh.\nHe is their stronghold in the time of trouble.\n'),
	(9687, 16, 37, 40, 'Yahweh helps them, and rescues them.\nHe rescues them from the wicked, and saves them,\nBecause they have taken refuge in him.\n'),
	(9688, 16, 38, 1, 'Yahweh, don’t rebuke me in your wrath,\nneither chasten me in your hot displeasure.\n'),
	(9689, 16, 38, 2, 'For your arrows have pierced me,\nyour hand presses hard on me.\n'),
	(9690, 16, 38, 3, 'There is no soundness in my flesh because of your indignation,\nneither is there any health in my bones because of my sin.\n'),
	(9691, 16, 38, 4, 'For my iniquities have gone over my head.\nAs a heavy burden, they are too heavy for me.\n'),
	(9692, 16, 38, 5, 'My wounds are loathsome and corrupt,\nbecause of my foolishness.\n'),
	(9693, 16, 38, 6, 'I am pained and bowed down greatly.\nI go mourning all day long.\n'),
	(9694, 16, 38, 7, 'For my waist is filled with burning.\nThere is no soundness in my flesh.\n'),
	(9695, 16, 38, 8, 'I am faint and severely bruised.\nI have groaned by reason of the anguish of my heart.\n'),
	(9696, 16, 38, 9, 'Lord, all my desire is before you.\nMy groaning is not hidden from you.\n'),
	(9697, 16, 38, 10, 'My heart throbs.\nMy strength fails me.\nAs for the light of my eyes, it has also left me.\n'),
	(9698, 16, 38, 11, 'My lovers and my friends stand aloof from my plague.\nMy kinsmen stand far away.\n'),
	(9699, 16, 38, 12, 'They also who seek after my life lay snares.\nThose who seek my hurt speak mischievous things,\nand meditate deceits all day long.\n'),
	(9700, 16, 38, 13, 'But I, as a deaf man, don’t hear.\nI am as a mute man who doesn’t open his mouth.\n'),
	(9701, 16, 38, 14, 'Yes, I am as a man who doesn’t hear,\nin whose mouth are no reproofs.\n'),
	(9702, 16, 38, 15, 'For in you, Yahweh, do I hope.\nYou will answer, Lord my God.\n'),
	(9703, 16, 38, 16, 'For I said, “Don’t let them gloat over me,\nor exalt themselves over me when my foot slips.”\n'),
	(9704, 16, 38, 17, 'For I am ready to fall.\nMy pain is continually before me.\n'),
	(9705, 16, 38, 18, 'For I will declare my iniquity.\nI will be sorry for my sin.\n'),
	(9706, 16, 38, 19, 'But my enemies are vigorous and many.\nThose who hate me without reason are numerous.\n'),
	(9707, 16, 38, 20, 'They who also render evil for good are adversaries to me,\nbecause I follow what is good.\n'),
	(9708, 16, 38, 21, 'Don’t forsake me, Yahweh.\nMy God, don’t be far from me.\n'),
	(9709, 16, 38, 22, 'Hurry to help me,\nLord, my salvation.\n'),
	(9710, 16, 39, 1, 'I said, “I will watch my ways, so that I don’t sin with my tongue.\nI will keep my mouth with a bridle while the wicked is before me.”\n'),
	(9711, 16, 39, 2, 'I was mute with silence.\nI held my peace, even from good.\nMy sorrow was stirred.\n'),
	(9712, 16, 39, 3, 'My heart was hot within me.\nWhile I meditated, the fire burned.\nI spoke with my tongue:\n'),
	(9713, 16, 39, 4, '“Yahweh, show me my end,\nwhat is the measure of my days.\nLet me know how frail I am.\n'),
	(9714, 16, 39, 5, 'Behold, you have made my days hand widths.\nMy lifetime is as nothing before you.\nSurely every man stands as a breath.”\nSelah.\n'),
	(9715, 16, 39, 6, '“Surely every man walks like a shadow.\nSurely they busy themselves in vain.\nHe heaps up, and doesn’t know who shall gather.\n'),
	(9716, 16, 39, 7, 'Now, Lord, what do I wait for?\nMy hope is in you.\n'),
	(9717, 16, 39, 8, 'Deliver me from all my transgressions.\nDon’t make me the reproach of the foolish.\n'),
	(9718, 16, 39, 9, 'I was mute.\nI didn’t open my mouth,\nbecause you did it.\n'),
	(9719, 16, 39, 10, 'Remove your scourge away from me.\nI am overcome by the blow of your hand.\n'),
	(9720, 16, 39, 11, 'When you rebuke and correct man for iniquity,\nYou consume his wealth like a moth.\nSurely every man is but a breath.”\nSelah.\n'),
	(9721, 16, 39, 12, '“Hear my prayer, Yahweh, and give ear to my cry.\nDon’t be silent at my tears.\nFor I am a stranger with you,\na foreigner, as all my fathers were.\n'),
	(9722, 16, 39, 13, 'Oh spare me, that I may recover strength,\nbefore I go away, and exist no more.”\n'),
	(9723, 16, 40, 1, 'I waited patiently for Yahweh.\nHe turned to me, and heard my cry.\n'),
	(9724, 16, 40, 2, 'He brought me up also out of a horrible pit,\nout of the miry clay.\nHe set my feet on a rock,\nand gave me a firm place to stand.\n'),
	(9725, 16, 40, 3, 'He has put a new song in my mouth, even praise to our God.\nMany shall see it, and fear, and shall trust in Yahweh.\n'),
	(9726, 16, 40, 4, 'Blessed is the man who makes Yahweh his trust,\nand doesn’t respect the proud, nor such as turn away to lies.\n'),
	(9727, 16, 40, 5, 'Many, Yahweh, my God, are the wonderful works which you have done,\nand your thoughts which are toward us.\nThey can’t be declared back to you.\nIf I would declare and speak of them, they are more than can be counted.\n'),
	(9728, 16, 40, 6, 'Sacrifice and offering you didn’t desire.\nYou have opened my ears.\nYou have not required burnt offering and sin offering.\n'),
	(9729, 16, 40, 7, 'Then I said, “Behold, I have come.\nIt is written about me in the book in the scroll.\n'),
	(9730, 16, 40, 8, 'I delight to do your will, my God.\nYes, your law is within my heart.”\n'),
	(9731, 16, 40, 9, 'I have proclaimed glad news of righteousness in the great assembly.\nBehold, I will not seal my lips, Yahweh, you know.\n'),
	(9732, 16, 40, 10, 'I have not hidden your righteousness within my heart.\nI have declared your faithfulness and your salvation.\nI have not concealed your loving kindness and your truth from the great assembly.\n'),
	(9733, 16, 40, 11, 'Don’t withhold your tender mercies from me, Yahweh.\nLet your loving kindness and your truth continually preserve me.\n'),
	(9734, 16, 40, 12, 'For innumerable evils have surrounded me.\nMy iniquities have overtaken me, so that I am not able to look up.\nThey are more than the hairs of my head.\nMy heart has failed me.\n'),
	(9735, 16, 40, 13, 'Be pleased, Yahweh, to deliver me.\nHurry to help me, Yahweh.\n'),
	(9736, 16, 40, 14, 'Let them be disappointed and confounded together who seek after my soul to destroy it.\nLet them be turned backward and brought to dishonor who delight in my hurt.\n'),
	(9737, 16, 40, 15, 'Let them be desolate by reason of their shame that tell me, “Aha! Aha!”\n'),
	(9738, 16, 40, 16, 'Let all those who seek you rejoice and be glad in you.\nLet such as love your salvation say continually, “Let Yahweh be exalted!”\n'),
	(9739, 16, 40, 17, 'But I am poor and needy.\nMay the Lord think about me.\nYou are my help and my deliverer.\nDon’t delay, my God.\n'),
	(9740, 16, 41, 1, 'Blessed is he who considers the poor.\nYahweh will deliver him in the day of evil.\n'),
	(9741, 16, 41, 2, 'Yahweh will preserve him, and keep him alive.\nHe shall be blessed on the earth,\nand he will not surrender him to the will of his enemies.\n'),
	(9742, 16, 41, 3, 'Yahweh will sustain him on his sickbed,\nand restore him from his bed of illness.\n'),
	(9743, 16, 41, 4, 'I said, “Yahweh, have mercy on me!\nHeal me, for I have sinned against you.”\n'),
	(9744, 16, 41, 5, 'My enemies speak evil against me:\n“When will he die, and his name perish?”\n'),
	(9745, 16, 41, 6, 'If he comes to see me, he speaks falsehood.\nHis heart gathers iniquity to itself.\nWhen he goes abroad, he tells it.\n'),
	(9746, 16, 41, 7, 'All who hate me whisper together against me.\nThey imagine the worst for me.\n'),
	(9747, 16, 41, 8, '“An evil disease”, they say, “has afflicted him.\nNow that he lies he shall rise up no more.”\n'),
	(9748, 16, 41, 9, 'Yes, my own familiar friend, in whom I trusted,\nwho ate bread with me,\nhas lifted up his heel against me.\n'),
	(9749, 16, 41, 10, 'But you, Yahweh, have mercy on me, and raise me up,\nthat I may repay them.\n'),
	(9750, 16, 41, 11, 'By this I know that you delight in me,\nbecause my enemy doesn’t triumph over me.\n'),
	(9751, 16, 41, 12, 'As for me, you uphold me in my integrity,\nand set me in your presence forever.\n'),
	(9752, 16, 41, 13, 'Blessed be Yahweh, the God of Israel,\nfrom everlasting and to everlasting!\nAmen and amen.\n'),
	(9753, 16, 42, 1, 'As the deer pants for the water brooks,\nso my soul pants after you, God.\n'),
	(9754, 16, 42, 2, 'My soul thirsts for God, for the living God.\nWhen shall I come and appear before God?\n'),
	(9755, 16, 42, 3, 'My tears have been my food day and night,\nwhile they continually ask me, “Where is your God?”\n'),
	(9756, 16, 42, 4, 'These things I remember, and pour out my soul within me,\nhow I used to go with the crowd, and led them to God’s house,\nwith the voice of joy and praise, a multitude keeping a holy day.\n'),
	(9757, 16, 42, 5, 'Why are you in despair, my soul?\nWhy are you disturbed within me?\nHope in God!\nFor I shall still praise him for the saving help of his presence.\n'),
	(9758, 16, 42, 6, 'My God, my soul is in despair within me.\nTherefore I remember you from the land of the Jordan,\nthe heights of Hermon, from the hill Mizar.\n'),
	(9759, 16, 42, 7, 'Deep calls to deep at the noise of your waterfalls.\nAll your waves and your billows have swept over me.\n'),
	(9760, 16, 42, 8, 'Yahweh will command his loving kindness in the daytime.\nIn the night his song shall be with me:\na prayer to the God of my life.\n'),
	(9761, 16, 42, 9, 'I will ask God, my rock, “Why have you forgotten me?\nWhy do I go mourning because of the oppression of the enemy?”\n'),
	(9762, 16, 42, 10, 'As with a sword in my bones, my adversaries reproach me,\nwhile they continually ask me, “Where is your God?”\n'),
	(9763, 16, 42, 11, 'Why are you in despair, my soul?\nWhy are you disturbed within me?\nHope in God! For I shall still praise him,\nthe saving help of my countenance, and my God.\n'),
	(9764, 16, 43, 1, 'Vindicate me, God, and plead my cause against an ungodly nation.\nOh, deliver me from deceitful and wicked men.\n'),
	(9765, 16, 43, 2, 'For you are the God of my strength. Why have you rejected me?\nWhy do I go mourning because of the oppression of the enemy?\n'),
	(9766, 16, 43, 3, 'Oh, send out your light and your truth.\nLet them lead me.\nLet them bring me to your holy hill,\nTo your tents.\n'),
	(9767, 16, 43, 4, 'Then I will go to the altar of God,\nto God, my exceeding joy.\nI will praise you on the harp, God, my God.\n'),
	(9768, 16, 43, 5, 'Why are you in despair, my soul?\nWhy are you disturbed within me?\nHope in God!\nFor I shall still praise him:\nmy Savior, my helper, and my God.\n'),
	(9769, 16, 44, 1, 'We have heard with our ears, God;\nour fathers have told us,\nwhat work you did in their days,\nin the days of old.\n'),
	(9770, 16, 44, 2, 'You drove out the nations with your hand,\nbut you planted them.\nYou afflicted the peoples,\nbut you spread them abroad.\n'),
	(9771, 16, 44, 3, 'For they didn’t get the land in possession by their own sword,\nneither did their own arm save them;\nbut your right hand, and your arm, and the light of your face,\nbecause you were favorable to them.\n'),
	(9772, 16, 44, 4, 'You are my King, God.\nCommand victories for Jacob!\n'),
	(9773, 16, 44, 5, 'Through you, will we push down our adversaries.\nThrough your name, will we tread them under who rise up against us.\n'),
	(9774, 16, 44, 6, 'For I will not trust in my bow,\nneither shall my sword save me.\n'),
	(9775, 16, 44, 7, 'But you have saved us from our adversaries,\nand have shamed those who hate us.\n'),
	(9776, 16, 44, 8, 'In God we have made our boast all day long,\nwe will give thanks to your name forever.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9777, 16, 44, 9, 'But now you rejected us, and brought us to dishonor,\nand don’t go out with our armies.\n'),
	(9778, 16, 44, 10, 'You make us turn back from the adversary.\nThose who hate us take plunder for themselves.\n'),
	(9779, 16, 44, 11, 'You have made us like sheep for food,\nand have scattered us among the nations.\n'),
	(9780, 16, 44, 12, 'You sell your people for nothing,\nand have gained nothing from their sale.\n'),
	(9781, 16, 44, 13, 'You make us a reproach to our neighbors,\na scoffing and a derision to those who are around us.\n'),
	(9782, 16, 44, 14, 'You make us a byword among the nations,\na shaking of the head among the peoples.\n'),
	(9783, 16, 44, 15, 'All day long my dishonor is before me,\nand shame covers my face,\n'),
	(9784, 16, 44, 16, 'At the taunt of one who reproaches and verbally abuses,\nbecause of the enemy and the avenger.\n'),
	(9785, 16, 44, 17, 'All this has come on us,\nyet have we not forgotten you,\nNeither have we been false to your covenant.\n'),
	(9786, 16, 44, 18, 'Our heart has not turned back,\nneither have our steps strayed from your path,\n'),
	(9787, 16, 44, 19, 'Though you have crushed us in the haunt of jackals,\nand covered us with the shadow of death.\n'),
	(9788, 16, 44, 20, 'If we have forgotten the name of our God,\nor spread out our hands to a strange god;\n'),
	(9789, 16, 44, 21, 'won’t God search this out?\nFor he knows the secrets of the heart.\n'),
	(9790, 16, 44, 22, 'Yes, for your sake we are killed all day long.\nWe are regarded as sheep for the slaughter.\n'),
	(9791, 16, 44, 23, 'Wake up!\nWhy do you sleep, Lord?\nArise!\nDon’t reject us forever.\n'),
	(9792, 16, 44, 24, 'Why do you hide your face,\nand forget our affliction and our oppression?\n'),
	(9793, 16, 44, 25, 'For our soul is bowed down to the dust.\nOur body clings to the earth.\n'),
	(9794, 16, 44, 26, 'Rise up to help us.\nRedeem us for your loving kindness’ sake.\n'),
	(9795, 16, 45, 1, 'My heart overflows with a noble theme.\nI recite my verses for the king.\nMy tongue is like the pen of a skillful writer.\n'),
	(9796, 16, 45, 2, 'You are the most excellent of the sons of men.\nGrace has anointed your lips,\ntherefore God has blessed you forever.\n'),
	(9797, 16, 45, 3, 'Strap your sword on your thigh, mighty one:\nyour splendor and your majesty.\n'),
	(9798, 16, 45, 4, 'In your majesty ride on victoriously on behalf of truth, humility, and righteousness.\nLet your right hand display awesome deeds.\n'),
	(9799, 16, 45, 5, 'Your arrows are sharp.\nThe nations fall under you, with arrows in the heart of the king’s enemies.\n'),
	(9800, 16, 45, 6, 'Your throne, God, is forever and ever.\nA scepter of equity is the scepter of your kingdom.\n'),
	(9801, 16, 45, 7, 'You have loved righteousness, and hated wickedness.\nTherefore God, your God, has anointed you with the oil of gladness above your fellows.\n'),
	(9802, 16, 45, 8, 'All your garments smell like myrrh, aloes, and cassia.\nOut of ivory palaces stringed instruments have made you glad.\n'),
	(9803, 16, 45, 9, 'Kings’ daughters are among your honorable women.\nAt your right hand the queen stands in gold of Ophir.\n'),
	(9804, 16, 45, 10, 'Listen, daughter, consider, and turn your ear.\nForget your own people, and also your father’s house.\n'),
	(9805, 16, 45, 11, 'So the king will desire your beauty,\nhonor him, for he is your lord.\n'),
	(9806, 16, 45, 12, 'The daughter of Tyre comes with a gift.\nThe rich among the people entreat your favor.\n'),
	(9807, 16, 45, 13, 'The princess inside is all glorious.\nHer clothing is interwoven with gold.\n'),
	(9808, 16, 45, 14, 'She shall be led to the king in embroidered work.\nThe virgins, her companions who follow her, shall be brought to you.\n'),
	(9809, 16, 45, 15, 'With gladness and rejoicing they shall be led.\nThey shall enter into the king’s palace.\n'),
	(9810, 16, 45, 16, 'Your sons will take the place of your fathers.\nYou shall make them princes in all the earth.\n'),
	(9811, 16, 45, 17, 'I will make your name to be remembered in all generations.\nTherefore the peoples shall give you thanks forever and ever.\n'),
	(9812, 16, 46, 1, 'God is our refuge and strength,\na very present help in trouble.\n'),
	(9813, 16, 46, 2, 'Therefore we won’t be afraid, though the earth changes,\nthough the mountains are shaken into the heart of the seas;\n'),
	(9814, 16, 46, 3, 'though its waters roar and are troubled,\nthough the mountains tremble with their swelling.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9815, 16, 46, 4, 'There is a river, the streams of which make the city of God glad,\nthe holy place of the tents of the Most High.\n'),
	(9816, 16, 46, 5, 'God is within her. She shall not be moved.\nGod will help her at dawn.\n'),
	(9817, 16, 46, 6, 'The nations raged. The kingdoms were moved.\nHe lifted his voice, and the earth melted.\n'),
	(9818, 16, 46, 7, 'Yahweh of Armies is with us.\nThe God of Jacob is our refuge.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9819, 16, 46, 8, 'Come, see Yahweh’s works,\nwhat desolations he has made in the earth.\n'),
	(9820, 16, 46, 9, 'He makes wars cease to the end of the earth.\nHe breaks the bow, and shatters the spear.\nHe burns the chariots in the fire.\n'),
	(9821, 16, 46, 10, '“Be still, and know that I am God.\nI will be exalted among the nations.\nI will be exalted in the earth.”\n'),
	(9822, 16, 46, 11, 'Yahweh of Armies is with us.\nThe God of Jacob is our refuge.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9823, 16, 47, 1, 'Oh clap your hands, all you nations.\nShout to God with the voice of triumph!\n'),
	(9824, 16, 47, 2, 'For Yahweh Most High is awesome.\nHe is a great King over all the earth.\n'),
	(9825, 16, 47, 3, 'He subdues nations under us,\nand peoples under our feet.\n'),
	(9826, 16, 47, 4, 'He chooses our inheritance for us,\nthe glory of Jacob whom he loved.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9827, 16, 47, 5, 'God has gone up with a shout,\nYahweh with the sound of a trumpet.\n'),
	(9828, 16, 47, 6, 'Sing praises to God, sing praises.\nSing praises to our King, sing praises.\n'),
	(9829, 16, 47, 7, 'For God is the King of all the earth.\nSing praises with understanding.\n'),
	(9830, 16, 47, 8, 'God reigns over the nations.\nGod sits on his holy throne.\n'),
	(9831, 16, 47, 9, 'The princes of the peoples are gathered together,\nthe people of the God of Abraham.\nFor the shields of the earth belong to God.\nHe is greatly exalted!\n'),
	(9832, 16, 48, 1, 'Great is Yahweh, and greatly to be praised,\nin the city of our God, in his holy mountain.\n'),
	(9833, 16, 48, 2, 'Beautiful in elevation, the joy of the whole earth,\nis Mount Zion, on the north sides,\nthe city of the great King.\n'),
	(9834, 16, 48, 3, 'God has shown himself in her citadels as a refuge.\n'),
	(9835, 16, 48, 4, 'For, behold, the kings assembled themselves,\nthey passed by together.\n'),
	(9836, 16, 48, 5, 'They saw it, then they were amazed.\nThey were dismayed.\nThey hurried away.\n'),
	(9837, 16, 48, 6, 'Trembling took hold of them there,\npain, as of a woman in travail.\n'),
	(9838, 16, 48, 7, 'With the east wind, you break the ships of Tarshish.\n'),
	(9839, 16, 48, 8, 'As we have heard, so we have seen,\nin the city of Yahweh of Armies, in the city of our God.\nGod will establish it forever.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9840, 16, 48, 9, 'We have thought about your loving kindness, God,\nin the middle of your temple.\n'),
	(9841, 16, 48, 10, 'As is your name, God,\nso is your praise to the ends of the earth.\nYour right hand is full of righteousness.\n'),
	(9842, 16, 48, 11, 'Let Mount Zion be glad!\nLet the daughters of Judah rejoice,\nBecause of your judgments.\n'),
	(9843, 16, 48, 12, 'Walk about Zion, and go around her.\nNumber its towers.\n'),
	(9844, 16, 48, 13, 'Mark well her bulwarks.\nConsider her palaces,\nthat you may tell it to the next generation.\n'),
	(9845, 16, 48, 14, 'For this God is our God forever and ever.\nHe will be our guide even to death.\n'),
	(9846, 16, 49, 1, 'Hear this, all you peoples.\nListen, all you inhabitants of the world,\n'),
	(9847, 16, 49, 2, 'both low and high,\nrich and poor together.\n'),
	(9848, 16, 49, 3, 'My mouth will speak words of wisdom.\nMy heart shall utter understanding.\n'),
	(9849, 16, 49, 4, 'I will incline my ear to a proverb.\nI will open my riddle on the harp.\n'),
	(9850, 16, 49, 5, 'Why should I fear in the days of evil,\nwhen iniquity at my heels surrounds me?\n'),
	(9851, 16, 49, 6, 'Those who trust in their wealth,\nand boast in the multitude of their riches—\n'),
	(9852, 16, 49, 7, 'none of them can by any means redeem his brother,\nnor give God a ransom for him.\n'),
	(9853, 16, 49, 8, 'For the redemption of their life is costly,\nno payment is ever enough,\n'),
	(9854, 16, 49, 9, 'that he should live on forever,\nthat he should not see corruption.\n'),
	(9855, 16, 49, 10, 'For he sees that wise men die;\nlikewise the fool and the senseless perish,\nand leave their wealth to others.\n'),
	(9856, 16, 49, 11, 'Their inward thought is that their houses will endure forever,\nand their dwelling places to all generations.\nThey name their lands after themselves.\n'),
	(9857, 16, 49, 12, 'But man, despite his riches, doesn’t endure.\nHe is like the animals that perish.\n'),
	(9858, 16, 49, 13, 'This is the destiny of those who are foolish,\nand of those who approve their sayings.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9859, 16, 49, 14, 'They are appointed as a flock for Sheol.\nDeath shall be their shepherd.\nThe upright shall have dominion over them in the morning.\nTheir beauty shall decay in Sheol,\nfar from their mansion.\n'),
	(9860, 16, 49, 15, 'But God will redeem my soul from the power of Sheol,\nfor he will receive me.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9861, 16, 49, 16, 'Don’t be afraid when a man is made rich,\nwhen the glory of his house is increased;\n'),
	(9862, 16, 49, 17, 'for when he dies he will carry nothing away.\nHis glory won’t descend after him.\n'),
	(9863, 16, 49, 18, 'Though while he lived he blessed his soul—\nand men praise you when you do well for yourself—\n'),
	(9864, 16, 49, 19, 'he shall go to the generation of his fathers.\nThey shall never see the light.\n'),
	(9865, 16, 49, 20, 'A man who has riches without understanding,\nis like the animals that perish.\n'),
	(9866, 16, 50, 1, 'The Mighty One, God, Yahweh, speaks,\nand calls the earth from sunrise to sunset.\n'),
	(9867, 16, 50, 2, 'Out of Zion, the perfection of beauty,\nGod shines out.\n'),
	(9868, 16, 50, 3, 'Our God comes, and does not keep silent.\nA fire devours before him.\nIt is very stormy around him.\n'),
	(9869, 16, 50, 4, 'He calls to the heavens above,\nto the earth, that he may judge his people:\n'),
	(9870, 16, 50, 5, '“Gather my saints together to me,\nthose who have made a covenant with me by sacrifice.”\n'),
	(9871, 16, 50, 6, 'The heavens shall declare his righteousness,\nfor God himself is judge.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9872, 16, 50, 7, '“Hear, my people, and I will speak;\nIsrael, and I will testify against you.\nI am God, your God.\n'),
	(9873, 16, 50, 8, 'I don’t rebuke you for your sacrifices.\nYour burnt offerings are continually before me.\n'),
	(9874, 16, 50, 9, 'I have no need for a bull from your stall,\nnor male goats from your pens.\n'),
	(9875, 16, 50, 10, 'For every animal of the forest is mine,\nand the livestock on a thousand hills.\n'),
	(9876, 16, 50, 11, 'I know all the birds of the mountains.\nThe wild animals of the field are mine.\n'),
	(9877, 16, 50, 12, 'If I were hungry, I would not tell you,\nfor the world is mine, and all that is in it.\n'),
	(9878, 16, 50, 13, 'Will I eat the meat of bulls,\nor drink the blood of goats?\n'),
	(9879, 16, 50, 14, 'Offer to God the sacrifice of thanksgiving.\nPay your vows to the Most High.\n'),
	(9880, 16, 50, 15, 'Call on me in the day of trouble.\nI will deliver you, and you will honor me.”\n'),
	(9881, 16, 50, 16, 'But to the wicked God says,\n“What right do you have to declare my statutes,\nthat you have taken my covenant on your lips,\n'),
	(9882, 16, 50, 17, 'since you hate instruction,\nand throw my words behind you?\n'),
	(9883, 16, 50, 18, 'When you saw a thief, you consented with him,\nand have participated with adulterers.\n'),
	(9884, 16, 50, 19, '“You give your mouth to evil.\nYour tongue frames deceit.\n'),
	(9885, 16, 50, 20, 'You sit and speak against your brother.\nYou slander your own mother’s son.\n'),
	(9886, 16, 50, 21, 'You have done these things, and I kept silent.\nYou thought that I was just like you.\nI will rebuke you, and accuse you in front of your eyes.\n'),
	(9887, 16, 50, 22, '“Now consider this, you who forget God,\nlest I tear you into pieces, and there be no one to deliver.\n'),
	(9888, 16, 50, 23, 'Whoever offers the sacrifice of thanksgiving glorifies me,\nand prepares his way so that I will show God’s salvation to him.”\n'),
	(9889, 16, 51, 1, 'Have mercy on me, God, according to your loving kindness.\nAccording to the multitude of your tender mercies, blot out my transgressions.\n'),
	(9890, 16, 51, 2, 'Wash me thoroughly from my iniquity.\nCleanse me from my sin.\n'),
	(9891, 16, 51, 3, 'For I know my transgressions.\nMy sin is constantly before me.\n'),
	(9892, 16, 51, 4, 'Against you, and you only, I have sinned,\nand done that which is evil in your sight;\nthat you may be proved right when you speak,\nand justified when you judge.\n'),
	(9893, 16, 51, 5, 'Behold, I was born in iniquity.\nIn sin my mother conceived me.\n'),
	(9894, 16, 51, 6, 'Behold, you desire truth in the inward parts.\nYou teach me wisdom in the inmost place.\n'),
	(9895, 16, 51, 7, 'Purify me with hyssop, and I will be clean.\nWash me, and I will be whiter than snow.\n'),
	(9896, 16, 51, 8, 'Let me hear joy and gladness,\nThat the bones which you have broken may rejoice.\n'),
	(9897, 16, 51, 9, 'Hide your face from my sins,\nand blot out all of my iniquities.\n'),
	(9898, 16, 51, 10, 'Create in me a clean heart, O God.\nRenew a right spirit within me.\n'),
	(9899, 16, 51, 11, 'Don’t throw me from your presence,\nand don’t take your holy Spirit from me.\n'),
	(9900, 16, 51, 12, 'Restore to me the joy of your salvation.\nUphold me with a willing spirit.\n'),
	(9901, 16, 51, 13, 'Then I will teach transgressors your ways.\nSinners shall be converted to you.\n'),
	(9902, 16, 51, 14, 'Deliver me from the guilt of bloodshed, O God, the God of my salvation.\nMy tongue shall sing aloud of your righteousness.\n'),
	(9903, 16, 51, 15, 'Lord, open my lips.\nMy mouth shall declare your praise.\n'),
	(9904, 16, 51, 16, 'For you don’t delight in sacrifice, or else I would give it.\nYou have no pleasure in burnt offering.\n'),
	(9905, 16, 51, 17, 'The sacrifices of God are a broken spirit.\nA broken and contrite heart, O God, you will not despise.\n'),
	(9906, 16, 51, 18, 'Do well in your good pleasure to Zion.\nBuild the walls of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(9907, 16, 51, 19, 'Then you will delight in the sacrifices of righteousness,\nin burnt offerings and in whole burnt offerings.\nThen they will offer bulls on your altar.\n'),
	(9908, 16, 52, 1, 'Why do you boast of mischief, mighty man?\nGod’s loving kindness endures continually.\n'),
	(9909, 16, 52, 2, 'Your tongue plots destruction,\nlike a sharp razor, working deceitfully.\n'),
	(9910, 16, 52, 3, 'You love evil more than good,\nlying rather than speaking the truth.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9911, 16, 52, 4, 'You love all devouring words,\nyou deceitful tongue.\n'),
	(9912, 16, 52, 5, 'God will likewise destroy you forever.\nHe will take you up, and pluck you out of your tent,\nand root you out of the land of the living.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9913, 16, 52, 6, 'The righteous also will see it, and fear,\nand laugh at him, saying,\n'),
	(9914, 16, 52, 7, '“Behold, this is the man who didn’t make God his strength,\nbut trusted in the abundance of his riches,\nand strengthened himself in his wickedness.”\n'),
	(9915, 16, 52, 8, 'But as for me, I am like a green olive tree in God’s house.\nI trust in God’s loving kindness forever and ever.\n'),
	(9916, 16, 52, 9, 'I will give you thanks forever, because you have done it.\nI will hope in your name, for it is good,\nin the presence of your saints.\n'),
	(9917, 16, 53, 1, 'The fool has said in his heart, “There is no God.”\nThey are corrupt, and have done abominable iniquity.\nThere is no one who does good.\n'),
	(9918, 16, 53, 2, 'God looks down from heaven on the children of men,\nto see if there are any who understood,\nwho seek after God.\n'),
	(9919, 16, 53, 3, 'Every one of them has gone back.\nThey have become filthy together.\nThere is no one who does good, no, not one.\n'),
	(9920, 16, 53, 4, 'Have the workers of iniquity no knowledge,\nwho eat up my people as they eat bread,\nand don’t call on God?\n'),
	(9921, 16, 53, 5, 'There they were in great fear, where no fear was,\nfor God has scattered the bones of him who encamps against you.\nYou have put them to shame,\nbecause God has rejected them.\n'),
	(9922, 16, 53, 6, 'Oh that the salvation of Israel would come out of Zion!\nWhen God brings back his people from captivity,\nthen Jacob shall rejoice,\nand Israel shall be glad.\n'),
	(9923, 16, 54, 1, 'Save me, God, by your name.\nVindicate me in your might.\n'),
	(9924, 16, 54, 2, 'Hear my prayer, God.\nListen to the words of my mouth.\n'),
	(9925, 16, 54, 3, 'For strangers have risen up against me.\nViolent men have sought after my soul.\nThey haven’t set God before them.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9926, 16, 54, 4, 'Behold, God is my helper.\nThe Lord is the one who sustains my soul.\n'),
	(9927, 16, 54, 5, 'He will repay the evil to my enemies.\nDestroy them in your truth.\n'),
	(9928, 16, 54, 6, 'With a free will offering, I will sacrifice to you.\nI will give thanks to your name, Yahweh, for it is good.\n'),
	(9929, 16, 54, 7, 'For he has delivered me out of all trouble.\nMy eye has seen triumph over my enemies.\n'),
	(9930, 16, 55, 1, 'Listen to my prayer, God.\nDon’t hide yourself from my supplication.\n'),
	(9931, 16, 55, 2, 'Attend to me, and answer me.\nI am restless in my complaint, and moan,\n'),
	(9932, 16, 55, 3, 'Because of the voice of the enemy,\nBecause of the oppression of the wicked.\nFor they bring suffering on me.\nIn anger they hold a grudge against me.\n'),
	(9933, 16, 55, 4, 'My heart is severely pained within me.\nThe terrors of death have fallen on me.\n'),
	(9934, 16, 55, 5, 'Fearfulness and trembling have come on me.\nHorror has overwhelmed me.\n'),
	(9935, 16, 55, 6, 'I said, “Oh that I had wings like a dove!\nThen I would fly away, and be at rest.\n'),
	(9936, 16, 55, 7, 'Behold, then I would wander far off.\nI would lodge in the wilderness.”\nSelah.\n'),
	(9937, 16, 55, 8, '“I would hurry to a shelter from the stormy wind and storm.”\n'),
	(9938, 16, 55, 9, 'Confuse them, Lord, and confound their language,\nfor I have seen violence and strife in the city.\n'),
	(9939, 16, 55, 10, 'Day and night they prowl around on its walls.\nMalice and abuse are also within her.\n'),
	(9940, 16, 55, 11, 'Destructive forces are within her.\nThreats and lies don’t depart from her streets.\n'),
	(9941, 16, 55, 12, 'For it was not an enemy who insulted me,\nthen I could have endured it.\nNeither was it he who hated me who raised himself up against me,\nthen I would have hidden myself from him.\n'),
	(9942, 16, 55, 13, 'But it was you, a man like me,\nmy companion, and my familiar friend.\n'),
	(9943, 16, 55, 14, 'We took sweet fellowship together.\nWe walked in God’s house with company.\n'),
	(9944, 16, 55, 15, 'Let death come suddenly on them.\nLet them go down alive into Sheol.\nFor wickedness is among them, in their dwelling.\n'),
	(9945, 16, 55, 16, 'As for me, I will call on God.\nYahweh will save me.\n'),
	(9946, 16, 55, 17, 'Evening, morning, and at noon, I will cry out in distress.\nHe will hear my voice.\n'),
	(9947, 16, 55, 18, 'He has redeemed my soul in peace from the battle that was against me,\nalthough there are many who oppose me.\n'),
	(9948, 16, 55, 19, 'God, who is enthroned forever,\nwill hear, and answer them.\nSelah.\nThey never change,\nwho don’t fear God.\n'),
	(9949, 16, 55, 20, 'He raises his hands against his friends.\nHe has violated his covenant.\n'),
	(9950, 16, 55, 21, 'His mouth was smooth as butter,\nbut his heart was war.\nHis words were softer than oil,\nyet they were drawn swords.\n'),
	(9951, 16, 55, 22, 'Cast your burden on Yahweh, and he will sustain you.\nHe will never allow the righteous to be moved.\n'),
	(9952, 16, 55, 23, 'But you, God, will bring them down into the pit of destruction.\nBloodthirsty and deceitful men shall not live out half their days,\nbut I will trust in you.\n'),
	(9953, 16, 56, 1, 'Be merciful to me, God, for man wants to swallow me up.\nAll day long, he attacks and oppresses me.\n'),
	(9954, 16, 56, 2, 'My enemies want to swallow me up all day long,\nfor they are many who fight proudly against me.\n'),
	(9955, 16, 56, 3, 'When I am afraid,\nI will put my trust in you.\n'),
	(9956, 16, 56, 4, 'In God, I praise his word.\nIn God, I put my trust.\nI will not be afraid.\nWhat can flesh do to me?\n'),
	(9957, 16, 56, 5, 'All day long they twist my words.\nAll their thoughts are against me for evil.\n'),
	(9958, 16, 56, 6, 'They conspire and lurk,\nwatching my steps, they are eager to take my life.\n'),
	(9959, 16, 56, 7, 'Shall they escape by iniquity?\nIn anger cast down the peoples, God.\n'),
	(9960, 16, 56, 8, 'You count my wanderings.\nYou put my tears into your bottle.\nAren’t they in your book?\n'),
	(9961, 16, 56, 9, 'Then my enemies shall turn back in the day that I call.\nI know this, that God is for me.\n'),
	(9962, 16, 56, 10, 'In God, I will praise his word.\nIn Yahweh, I will praise his word.\n'),
	(9963, 16, 56, 11, 'I have put my trust in God.\nI will not be afraid.\nWhat can man do to me?\n'),
	(9964, 16, 56, 12, 'Your vows are on me, God.\nI will give thank offerings to you.\n'),
	(9965, 16, 56, 13, 'For you have delivered my soul from death,\nand prevented my feet from falling,\nthat I may walk before God in the light of the living.\n'),
	(9966, 16, 57, 1, 'Be merciful to me, God, be merciful to me,\nfor my soul takes refuge in you.\nYes, in the shadow of your wings, I will take refuge,\nuntil disaster has passed.\n'),
	(9967, 16, 57, 2, 'I cry out to God Most High,\nto God who accomplishes my requests for me.\n'),
	(9968, 16, 57, 3, 'He will send from heaven, and save me,\nhe rebukes the one who is pursuing me.\nSelah.\nGod will send out his loving kindness and his truth.\n'),
	(9969, 16, 57, 4, 'My soul is among lions.\nI lie among those who are set on fire,\neven the sons of men, whose teeth are spears and arrows,\nand their tongue a sharp sword.\n'),
	(9970, 16, 57, 5, 'Be exalted, God, above the heavens!\nLet your glory be above all the earth!\n'),
	(9971, 16, 57, 6, 'They have prepared a net for my steps.\nMy soul is bowed down.\nThey dig a pit before me.\nThey fall into the middle of it themselves.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9972, 16, 57, 7, 'My heart is steadfast, God, my heart is steadfast.\nI will sing, yes, I will sing praises.\n'),
	(9973, 16, 57, 8, 'Wake up, my glory! Wake up, lute and harp!\nI will wake up the dawn.\n'),
	(9974, 16, 57, 9, 'I will give thanks to you, Lord, among the peoples.\nI will sing praises to you among the nations.\n'),
	(9975, 16, 57, 10, 'For your great loving kindness reaches to the heavens,\nand your truth to the skies.\n'),
	(9976, 16, 57, 11, 'Be exalted, God, above the heavens.\nLet your glory be over all the earth.\n'),
	(9977, 16, 58, 1, 'Do you indeed speak righteousness, silent ones?\nDo you judge blamelessly, you sons of men?\n'),
	(9978, 16, 58, 2, 'No, in your heart you plot injustice.\nYou measure out the violence of your hands in the earth.\n'),
	(9979, 16, 58, 3, 'The wicked go astray from the womb.\nThey are wayward as soon as they are born, speaking lies.\n'),
	(9980, 16, 58, 4, 'Their poison is like the poison of a snake;\nlike a deaf cobra that stops its ear,\n'),
	(9981, 16, 58, 5, 'which doesn’t listen to the voice of charmers,\nno matter how skillful the charmer may be.\n'),
	(9982, 16, 58, 6, 'Break their teeth, God, in their mouth.\nBreak out the great teeth of the young lions, Yahweh.\n'),
	(9983, 16, 58, 7, 'Let them vanish like water that flows away.\nWhen they draw the bow, let their arrows be made blunt.\n'),
	(9984, 16, 58, 8, 'Let them be like a snail which melts and passes away,\nlike the stillborn child, who has not seen the sun.\n'),
	(9985, 16, 58, 9, 'Before your pots can feel the heat of the thorns,\nhe will sweep away the green and the burning alike.\n'),
	(9986, 16, 58, 10, 'The righteous shall rejoice when he sees the vengeance.\nHe shall wash his feet in the blood of the wicked;\n'),
	(9987, 16, 58, 11, 'so that men shall say, “Most certainly there is a reward for the righteous.\nMost certainly there is a God who judges the earth.”\n'),
	(9988, 16, 59, 1, 'Deliver me from my enemies, my God.\nSet me on high from those who rise up against me.\n'),
	(9989, 16, 59, 2, 'Deliver me from the workers of iniquity.\nSave me from the bloodthirsty men.\n'),
	(9990, 16, 59, 3, 'For, behold, they lie in wait for my soul.\nThe mighty gather themselves together against me,\nnot for my disobedience, nor for my sin, Yahweh.\n'),
	(9991, 16, 59, 4, 'I have done no wrong, yet they are ready to attack me.\nRise up, behold, and help me!\n'),
	(9992, 16, 59, 5, 'You, Yahweh God of Armies, the God of Israel,\nrouse yourself to punish the nations.\nShow no mercy to the wicked traitors.\nSelah.\n'),
	(9993, 16, 59, 6, 'They return at evening, howling like dogs,\nand prowl around the city.\n'),
	(9994, 16, 59, 7, 'Behold, they spew with their mouth.\nSwords are in their lips,\n“For”, they say, “who hears us?”\n'),
	(9995, 16, 59, 8, 'But you, Yahweh, laugh at them.\nYou scoff at all the nations.\n'),
	(9996, 16, 59, 9, 'Oh, my Strength, I watch for you,\nfor God is my high tower.\n'),
	(9997, 16, 59, 10, 'My God will go before me with his loving kindness.\nGod will let me look at my enemies in triumph.\n'),
	(9998, 16, 59, 11, 'Don’t kill them, or my people may forget.\nScatter them by your power, and bring them down, Lord our shield.\n'),
	(9999, 16, 59, 12, 'For the sin of their mouth, and the words of their lips,\nlet them be caught in their pride,\nfor the curses and lies which they utter.\n'),
	(10000, 16, 59, 13, 'Consume them in wrath.\nConsume them, and they will be no more.\nLet them know that God rules in Jacob,\nto the ends of the earth.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10001, 16, 59, 14, 'At evening let them return.\nLet them howl like a dog, and go around the city.\n'),
	(10002, 16, 59, 15, 'They shall wander up and down for food,\nand wait all night if they aren’t satisfied.\n'),
	(10003, 16, 59, 16, 'But I will sing of your strength.\nYes, I will sing aloud of your loving kindness in the morning.\nFor you have been my high tower,\na refuge in the day of my distress.\n'),
	(10004, 16, 59, 17, 'To you, my strength, I will sing praises.\nFor God is my high tower, the God of my mercy.\n'),
	(10005, 16, 60, 1, 'God, you have rejected us.\nYou have broken us down.\nYou have been angry.\nRestore us, again.\n'),
	(10006, 16, 60, 2, 'You have made the land tremble.\nYou have torn it.\nMend its fractures,\nfor it quakes.\n'),
	(10007, 16, 60, 3, 'You have shown your people hard things.\nYou have made us drink the wine that makes us stagger.\n'),
	(10008, 16, 60, 4, 'You have given a banner to those who fear you,\nthat it may be displayed because of the truth.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10009, 16, 60, 5, 'So that your beloved may be delivered,\nsave with your right hand, and answer us.\n'),
	(10010, 16, 60, 6, 'God has spoken from his sanctuary:\n“I will triumph.\nI will divide Shechem,\nand measure out the valley of Succoth.\n'),
	(10011, 16, 60, 7, 'Gilead is mine, and Manasseh is mine.\nEphraim also is the defense of my head.\nJudah is my scepter.\n'),
	(10012, 16, 60, 8, 'Moab is my wash basin.\nI will throw my shoe on Edom.\nI shout in triumph over Philistia.”\n'),
	(10013, 16, 60, 9, 'Who will bring me into the strong city?\nWho has led me to Edom?\n'),
	(10014, 16, 60, 10, 'Haven’t you, God, rejected us?\nYou don’t go out with our armies, God.\n'),
	(10015, 16, 60, 11, 'Give us help against the adversary,\nfor the help of man is vain.\n'),
	(10016, 16, 60, 12, 'Through God we shall do valiantly,\nfor it is he who will tread down our adversaries.\n'),
	(10017, 16, 61, 1, 'Hear my cry, God.\nListen to my prayer.\n'),
	(10018, 16, 61, 2, 'From the end of the earth, I will call to you, when my heart is overwhelmed.\nLead me to the rock that is higher than I.\n'),
	(10019, 16, 61, 3, 'For you have been a refuge for me,\na strong tower from the enemy.\n'),
	(10020, 16, 61, 4, 'I will dwell in your tent forever.\nI will take refuge in the shelter of your wings.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10021, 16, 61, 5, 'For you, God, have heard my vows.\nYou have given me the heritage of those who fear your name.\n'),
	(10022, 16, 61, 6, 'You will prolong the king’s life;\nhis years shall be for generations.\n'),
	(10023, 16, 61, 7, 'He shall be enthroned in God’s presence forever.\nAppoint your loving kindness and truth, that they may preserve him.\n'),
	(10024, 16, 61, 8, 'So I will sing praise to your name forever,\nthat I may fulfill my vows daily.\n'),
	(10025, 16, 62, 1, 'My soul rests in God alone.\nMy salvation is from him.\n'),
	(10026, 16, 62, 2, 'He alone is my rock and my salvation, my fortress—\nI will never be greatly shaken.\n'),
	(10027, 16, 62, 3, 'How long will you assault a man,\nwould all of you throw him down,\nLike a leaning wall, like a tottering fence?\n'),
	(10028, 16, 62, 4, 'They fully intend to throw him down from his lofty place.\nThey delight in lies.\nThey bless with their mouth, but they curse inwardly.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10029, 16, 62, 5, 'My soul, wait in silence for God alone,\nfor my expectation is from him.\n'),
	(10030, 16, 62, 6, 'He alone is my rock and my salvation, my fortress.\nI will not be shaken.\n'),
	(10031, 16, 62, 7, 'With God is my salvation and my honor.\nThe rock of my strength, and my refuge, is in God.\n'),
	(10032, 16, 62, 8, 'Trust in him at all times, you people.\nPour out your heart before him.\nGod is a refuge for us.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10033, 16, 62, 9, 'Surely men of low degree are just a breath,\nand men of high degree are a lie.\nIn the balances they will go up.\nThey are together lighter than a breath.\n'),
	(10034, 16, 62, 10, 'Don’t trust in oppression.\nDon’t become vain in robbery.\nIf riches increase,\ndon’t set your heart on them.\n'),
	(10035, 16, 62, 11, 'God has spoken once;\ntwice I have heard this,\nthat power belongs to God.\n'),
	(10036, 16, 62, 12, 'Also to you, Lord, belongs loving kindness,\nfor you reward every man according to his work.\n'),
	(10037, 16, 63, 1, 'God, you are my God.\nI will earnestly seek you.\nMy soul thirsts for you.\nMy flesh longs for you,\nin a dry and weary land, where there is no water.\n'),
	(10038, 16, 63, 2, 'So I have seen you in the sanctuary,\nwatching your power and your glory.\n'),
	(10039, 16, 63, 3, 'Because your loving kindness is better than life,\nmy lips shall praise you.\n'),
	(10040, 16, 63, 4, 'So I will bless you while I live.\nI will lift up my hands in your name.\n'),
	(10041, 16, 63, 5, 'My soul shall be satisfied as with the richest food.\nMy mouth shall praise you with joyful lips,\n'),
	(10042, 16, 63, 6, 'when I remember you on my bed,\nand think about you in the night watches.\n'),
	(10043, 16, 63, 7, 'For you have been my help.\nI will rejoice in the shadow of your wings.\n'),
	(10044, 16, 63, 8, 'My soul stays close to you.\nYour right hand holds me up.\n'),
	(10045, 16, 63, 9, 'But those who seek my soul, to destroy it,\nshall go into the lower parts of the earth.\n'),
	(10046, 16, 63, 10, 'They shall be given over to the power of the sword.\nThey shall be jackal food.\n'),
	(10047, 16, 63, 11, 'But the king shall rejoice in God.\nEveryone who swears by him will praise him,\nfor the mouth of those who speak lies shall be silenced.\n'),
	(10048, 16, 64, 1, 'Hear my voice, God, in my complaint.\nPreserve my life from fear of the enemy.\n'),
	(10049, 16, 64, 2, 'Hide me from the conspiracy of the wicked,\nfrom the noisy crowd of the ones doing evil;\n'),
	(10050, 16, 64, 3, 'who sharpen their tongue like a sword,\nand aim their arrows, deadly words,\n'),
	(10051, 16, 64, 4, 'to shoot innocent men from ambushes.\nThey shoot at him suddenly and fearlessly.\n'),
	(10052, 16, 64, 5, 'They encourage themselves in evil plans.\nThey talk about laying snares secretly.\nThey say, “Who will see them?”\n'),
	(10053, 16, 64, 6, 'They plot injustice, saying, “We have made a perfect plan!”\nSurely man’s mind and heart are cunning.\n'),
	(10054, 16, 64, 7, 'But God will shoot at them.\nThey will be suddenly struck down with an arrow.\n'),
	(10055, 16, 64, 8, 'Their own tongues shall ruin them.\nAll who see them will shake their heads.\n'),
	(10056, 16, 64, 9, 'All mankind shall be afraid.\nThey shall declare the work of God,\nand shall wisely ponder what he has done.\n'),
	(10057, 16, 64, 10, 'The righteous shall be glad in Yahweh,\nand shall take refuge in him.\nAll the upright in heart shall praise him!\n'),
	(10058, 16, 65, 1, 'Praise waits for you, God, in Zion.\nTo you shall vows be performed.\n'),
	(10059, 16, 65, 2, 'You who hear prayer,\nto you all men will come.\n'),
	(10060, 16, 65, 3, 'Sins overwhelmed me,\nbut you atoned for our transgressions.\n'),
	(10061, 16, 65, 4, 'Blessed is one whom you choose, and cause to come near,\nthat he may live in your courts.\nWe will be filled with the goodness of your house,\nyour holy temple.\n'),
	(10062, 16, 65, 5, 'By awesome deeds of righteousness, you answer us,\nGod of our salvation.\nYou who are the hope of all the ends of the earth,\nof those who are far away on the sea;\n'),
	(10063, 16, 65, 6, 'Who by his power forms the mountains,\nhaving armed yourself with strength;\n'),
	(10064, 16, 65, 7, 'who stills the roaring of the seas,\nthe roaring of their waves,\nand the turmoil of the nations.\n'),
	(10065, 16, 65, 8, 'They also who dwell in faraway places are afraid at your wonders.\nYou call the morning’s dawn and the evening with songs of joy.\n'),
	(10066, 16, 65, 9, 'You visit the earth, and water it.\nYou greatly enrich it.\nThe river of God is full of water.\nYou provide them grain, for so you have ordained it.\n'),
	(10067, 16, 65, 10, 'You drench its furrows.\nYou level its ridges.\nYou soften it with showers.\nYou bless it with a crop.\n'),
	(10068, 16, 65, 11, 'You crown the year with your bounty.\nYour carts overflow with abundance.\n'),
	(10069, 16, 65, 12, 'The wilderness grasslands overflow.\nThe hills are clothed with gladness.\n'),
	(10070, 16, 65, 13, 'The pastures are covered with flocks.\nThe valleys also are clothed with grain.\nThey shout for joy!\nThey also sing.\n'),
	(10071, 16, 66, 1, 'Make a joyful shout to God, all the earth!\n'),
	(10072, 16, 66, 2, 'Sing to the glory of his name!\nOffer glory and praise!\n'),
	(10073, 16, 66, 3, 'Tell God, “How awesome are your deeds!\nThrough the greatness of your power, your enemies submit themselves to you.\n'),
	(10074, 16, 66, 4, 'All the earth will worship you,\nand will sing to you;\nthey will sing to your name.”\nSelah.\n'),
	(10075, 16, 66, 5, 'Come, and see God’s deeds—\nawesome work on behalf of the children of men.\n'),
	(10076, 16, 66, 6, 'He turned the sea into dry land.\nThey went through the river on foot.\nThere, we rejoiced in him.\n'),
	(10077, 16, 66, 7, 'He rules by his might forever.\nHis eyes watch the nations.\nDon’t let the rebellious rise up against him.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10078, 16, 66, 8, 'Praise our God, you peoples!\nMake the sound of his praise heard,\n'),
	(10079, 16, 66, 9, 'who preserves our life among the living,\nand doesn’t allow our feet to be moved.\n'),
	(10080, 16, 66, 10, 'For you, God, have tested us.\nYou have refined us, as silver is refined.\n'),
	(10081, 16, 66, 11, 'You brought us into prison.\nYou laid a burden on our backs.\n'),
	(10082, 16, 66, 12, 'You allowed men to ride over our heads.\nWe went through fire and through water,\nbut you brought us to the place of abundance.\n'),
	(10083, 16, 66, 13, 'I will come into your temple with burnt offerings.\nI will pay my vows to you,\n'),
	(10084, 16, 66, 14, 'which my lips promised,\nand my mouth spoke, when I was in distress.\n'),
	(10085, 16, 66, 15, 'I will offer to you burnt offerings of fat animals,\nwith the offering of rams,\nI will offer bulls with goats.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10086, 16, 66, 16, 'Come, and hear, all you who fear God.\nI will declare what he has done for my soul.\n'),
	(10087, 16, 66, 17, 'I cried to him with my mouth.\nHe was extolled with my tongue.\n'),
	(10088, 16, 66, 18, 'If I cherished sin in my heart,\nthe Lord wouldn’t have listened.\n'),
	(10089, 16, 66, 19, 'But most certainly, God has listened.\nHe has heard the voice of my prayer.\n'),
	(10090, 16, 66, 20, 'Blessed be God, who has not turned away my prayer,\nnor his loving kindness from me.\n'),
	(10091, 16, 67, 1, 'May God be merciful to us, bless us,\nand cause his face to shine on us.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10092, 16, 67, 2, 'That your way may be known on earth,\nand your salvation among all nations,\n'),
	(10093, 16, 67, 3, 'let the peoples praise you, God.\nLet all the peoples praise you.\n'),
	(10094, 16, 67, 4, 'Oh let the nations be glad and sing for joy,\nfor you will judge the peoples with equity,\nand govern the nations on earth.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10095, 16, 67, 5, 'Let the peoples praise you, God.\nLet all the peoples praise you.\n'),
	(10096, 16, 67, 6, 'The earth has yielded its increase.\nGod, even our own God, will bless us.\n'),
	(10097, 16, 67, 7, 'God will bless us.\nAll the ends of the earth shall fear him.\n'),
	(10098, 16, 68, 1, 'Let God arise!\nLet his enemies be scattered!\nLet them who hate him also flee before him.\n'),
	(10099, 16, 68, 2, 'As smoke is driven away,\nso drive them away.\nAs wax melts before the fire,\nso let the wicked perish at the presence of God.\n'),
	(10100, 16, 68, 3, 'But let the righteous be glad.\nLet them rejoice before God.\nYes, let them rejoice with gladness.\n'),
	(10101, 16, 68, 4, 'Sing to God! Sing praises to his name!\nExtol him who rides on the clouds:\nto Yah, his name!\nRejoice before him!\n'),
	(10102, 16, 68, 5, 'A father of the fatherless, and a defender of the widows,\nis God in his holy habitation.\n'),
	(10103, 16, 68, 6, 'God sets the lonely in families.\nHe brings out the prisoners with singing,\nbut the rebellious dwell in a sun-scorched land.\n'),
	(10104, 16, 68, 7, 'God, when you went out before your people,\nwhen you marched through the wilderness...\nSelah.\n'),
	(10105, 16, 68, 8, 'The earth trembled.\nThe sky also poured down rain at the presence of the God of Sinai—\nat the presence of God, the God of Israel.\n'),
	(10106, 16, 68, 9, 'You, God, sent a plentiful rain.\nYou confirmed your inheritance, when it was weary.\n'),
	(10107, 16, 68, 10, 'Your congregation lived therein.\nYou, God, prepared your goodness for the poor.\n'),
	(10108, 16, 68, 11, 'The Lord announced the word.\nThe ones who proclaim it are a great company.\n'),
	(10109, 16, 68, 12, '“Kings of armies flee! They flee!”\nShe who waits at home divides the plunder,\n'),
	(10110, 16, 68, 13, 'while you sleep among the camp fires,\nthe wings of a dove sheathed with silver,\nher feathers with shining gold.\n'),
	(10111, 16, 68, 14, 'When the Almighty scattered kings in her,\nit snowed on Zalmon.\n'),
	(10112, 16, 68, 15, 'The mountains of Bashan are majestic mountains.\nThe mountains of Bashan are rugged.\n'),
	(10113, 16, 68, 16, 'Why do you look in envy, you rugged mountains,\nat the mountain where God chooses to reign?\nYes, Yahweh will dwell there forever.\n'),
	(10114, 16, 68, 17, 'The chariots of God are tens of thousands and thousands of thousands.\nThe Lord is among them, from Sinai, into the sanctuary.\n'),
	(10115, 16, 68, 18, 'You have ascended on high.\nYou have led away captives.\nYou have received gifts among men,\nyes, among the rebellious also, that Yah God might dwell there.\n'),
	(10116, 16, 68, 19, 'Blessed be the Lord, who daily bears our burdens,\neven the God who is our salvation.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10117, 16, 68, 20, 'God is to us a God of deliverance.\nTo Yahweh, the Lord, belongs escape from death.\n'),
	(10118, 16, 68, 21, 'But God will strike through the head of his enemies,\nthe hairy scalp of such a one as still continues in his guiltiness.\n'),
	(10119, 16, 68, 22, 'The Lord said, “I will bring you again from Bashan,\nI will bring you again from the depths of the sea;\n'),
	(10120, 16, 68, 23, 'That you may crush them, dipping your foot in blood,\nthat the tongues of your dogs may have their portion from your enemies.”\n'),
	(10121, 16, 68, 24, 'They have seen your processions, God,\neven the processions of my God, my King, into the sanctuary.\n'),
	(10122, 16, 68, 25, 'The singers went before, the minstrels followed after,\namong the ladies playing with tambourines,\n'),
	(10123, 16, 68, 26, '“Bless God in the congregations,\neven the Lord in the assembly of Israel!”\n'),
	(10124, 16, 68, 27, 'There is little Benjamin, their ruler,\nthe princes of Judah, their council,\nthe princes of Zebulun, and the princes of Naphtali.\n'),
	(10125, 16, 68, 28, 'Your God has commanded your strength.\nStrengthen, God, that which you have done for us.\n'),
	(10126, 16, 68, 29, 'Because of your temple at Jerusalem,\nkings shall bring presents to you.\n'),
	(10127, 16, 68, 30, 'Rebuke the wild animal of the reeds,\nthe multitude of the bulls, with the calves of the peoples.\nBeing humbled, may it bring bars of silver.\nScatter the nations that delight in war.\n'),
	(10128, 16, 68, 31, 'Princes shall come out of Egypt.\nEthiopia shall hurry to stretch out her hands to God.\n'),
	(10129, 16, 68, 32, 'Sing to God, you kingdoms of the earth!\nSing praises to the Lord!\nSelah.\n'),
	(10130, 16, 68, 33, 'To him who rides on the heaven of heavens, which are of old;\nbehold, he utters his voice, a mighty voice.\n'),
	(10131, 16, 68, 34, 'Ascribe strength to God!\nHis excellency is over Israel,\nhis strength is in the skies.\n'),
	(10132, 16, 68, 35, 'You are awesome, God, in your sanctuaries.\nThe God of Israel gives strength and power to his people.\nPraise be to God!\n'),
	(10133, 16, 69, 1, 'Save me, God,\nfor the waters have come up to my neck!\n'),
	(10134, 16, 69, 2, 'I sink in deep mire, where there is no foothold.\nI have come into deep waters, where the floods overflow me.\n'),
	(10135, 16, 69, 3, 'I am weary with my crying.\nMy throat is dry.\nMy eyes fail, looking for my God.\n'),
	(10136, 16, 69, 4, 'Those who hate me without a cause are more than the hairs of my head.\nThose who want to cut me off, being my enemies wrongfully, are mighty.\nI have to restore what I didn’t take away.\n'),
	(10137, 16, 69, 5, 'God, you know my foolishness.\nMy sins aren’t hidden from you.\n'),
	(10138, 16, 69, 6, 'Don’t let those who wait for you be shamed through me, Lord Yahweh of Armies.\nDon’t let those who seek you be brought to dishonor through me, God of Israel.\n'),
	(10139, 16, 69, 7, 'Because for your sake, I have borne reproach.\nShame has covered my face.\n'),
	(10140, 16, 69, 8, 'I have become a stranger to my brothers,\nan alien to my mother’s children.\n'),
	(10141, 16, 69, 9, 'For the zeal of your house consumes me.\nThe reproaches of those who reproach you have fallen on me.\n'),
	(10142, 16, 69, 10, 'When I wept and I fasted,\nthat was to my reproach.\n'),
	(10143, 16, 69, 11, 'When I made sackcloth my clothing,\nI became a byword to them.\n'),
	(10144, 16, 69, 12, 'Those who sit in the gate talk about me.\nI am the song of the drunkards.\n'),
	(10145, 16, 69, 13, 'But as for me, my prayer is to you, Yahweh, in an acceptable time.\nGod, in the abundance of your loving kindness, answer me in the truth of your salvation.\n'),
	(10146, 16, 69, 14, 'Deliver me out of the mire, and don’t let me sink.\nLet me be delivered from those who hate me, and out of the deep waters.\n'),
	(10147, 16, 69, 15, 'Don’t let the flood waters overwhelm me,\nneither let the deep swallow me up.\nDon’t let the pit shut its mouth on me.\n'),
	(10148, 16, 69, 16, 'Answer me, Yahweh, for your loving kindness is good.\nAccording to the multitude of your tender mercies, turn to me.\n'),
	(10149, 16, 69, 17, 'Don’t hide your face from your servant,\nfor I am in distress.\nAnswer me speedily!\n'),
	(10150, 16, 69, 18, 'Draw near to my soul, and redeem it.\nRansom me because of my enemies.\n'),
	(10151, 16, 69, 19, 'You know my reproach, my shame, and my dishonor.\nMy adversaries are all before you.\n'),
	(10152, 16, 69, 20, 'Reproach has broken my heart, and I am full of heaviness.\nI looked for some to take pity, but there was none;\nfor comforters, but I found none.\n'),
	(10153, 16, 69, 21, 'They also gave me gall for my food.\nIn my thirst, they gave me vinegar to drink.\n'),
	(10154, 16, 69, 22, 'Let their table before them become a snare.\nMay it become a retribution and a trap.\n'),
	(10155, 16, 69, 23, 'Let their eyes be darkened, so that they can’t see.\nLet their backs be continually bent.\n'),
	(10156, 16, 69, 24, 'Pour out your indignation on them.\nLet the fierceness of your anger overtake them.\n'),
	(10157, 16, 69, 25, 'Let their habitation be desolate.\nLet no one dwell in their tents.\n'),
	(10158, 16, 69, 26, 'For they persecute him whom you have wounded.\nThey tell of the sorrow of those whom you have hurt.\n'),
	(10159, 16, 69, 27, 'Charge them with crime upon crime.\nDon’t let them come into your righteousness.\n'),
	(10160, 16, 69, 28, 'Let them be blotted out of the book of life,\nand not be written with the righteous.\n'),
	(10161, 16, 69, 29, 'But I am in pain and distress.\nLet your salvation, God, protect me.\n'),
	(10162, 16, 69, 30, 'I will praise the name of God with a song,\nand will magnify him with thanksgiving.\n'),
	(10163, 16, 69, 31, 'It will please Yahweh better than an ox,\nor a bull that has horns and hoofs.\n'),
	(10164, 16, 69, 32, 'The humble have seen it, and are glad.\nYou who seek after God, let your heart live.\n'),
	(10165, 16, 69, 33, 'For Yahweh hears the needy,\nand doesn’t despise his captive people.\n'),
	(10166, 16, 69, 34, 'Let heaven and earth praise him;\nthe seas, and everything that moves therein!\n'),
	(10167, 16, 69, 35, 'For God will save Zion, and build the cities of Judah.\nThey shall settle there, and own it.\n'),
	(10168, 16, 69, 36, 'The children also of his servants shall inherit it.\nThose who love his name shall dwell therein.\n'),
	(10169, 16, 70, 1, 'Hurry, God, to deliver me.\nCome quickly to help me, Yahweh.\n'),
	(10170, 16, 70, 2, 'Let them be disappointed and confounded who seek my soul.\nLet those who desire my ruin be turned back in disgrace.\n'),
	(10171, 16, 70, 3, 'Let them be turned because of their shame\nWho say, “Aha! Aha!”\n'),
	(10172, 16, 70, 4, 'Let all those who seek you rejoice and be glad in you.\nLet those who love your salvation continually say,\n“Let God be exalted!”\n'),
	(10173, 16, 70, 5, 'But I am poor and needy.\nCome to me quickly, God.\nYou are my help and my deliverer.\nYahweh, don’t delay.\n'),
	(10174, 16, 71, 1, 'In you, Yahweh, I take refuge.\nNever let me be disappointed.\n'),
	(10175, 16, 71, 2, 'Deliver me in your righteousness, and rescue me.\nTurn your ear to me, and save me.\n'),
	(10176, 16, 71, 3, 'Be to me a rock of refuge to which I may always go.\nGive the command to save me,\nfor you are my rock and my fortress.\n'),
	(10177, 16, 71, 4, 'Rescue me, my God, from the hand of the wicked,\nfrom the hand of the unrighteous and cruel man.\n'),
	(10178, 16, 71, 5, 'For you are my hope, Lord Yahweh;\nmy confidence from my youth.\n'),
	(10179, 16, 71, 6, 'I have relied on you from the womb.\nYou are he who took me out of my mother’s womb.\nI will always praise you.\n'),
	(10180, 16, 71, 7, 'I am a marvel to many,\nbut you are my strong refuge.\n'),
	(10181, 16, 71, 8, 'My mouth shall be filled with your praise,\nwith your honor all day long.\n'),
	(10182, 16, 71, 9, 'Don’t reject me in my old age.\nDon’t forsake me when my strength fails.\n'),
	(10183, 16, 71, 10, 'For my enemies talk about me.\nThose who watch for my soul conspire together,\n'),
	(10184, 16, 71, 11, 'saying, “God has forsaken him.\nPursue and take him, for no one will rescue him.”\n'),
	(10185, 16, 71, 12, 'God, don’t be far from me.\nMy God, hurry to help me.\n'),
	(10186, 16, 71, 13, 'Let my accusers be disappointed and consumed.\nLet them be covered with disgrace and scorn who want to harm me.\n'),
	(10187, 16, 71, 14, 'But I will always hope,\nand will add to all of your praise.\n'),
	(10188, 16, 71, 15, 'My mouth will tell about your righteousness,\nand of your salvation all day,\nthough I don’t know its full measure.\n'),
	(10189, 16, 71, 16, 'I will come with the mighty acts of the Lord Yahweh.\nI will make mention of your righteousness, even of yours alone.\n'),
	(10190, 16, 71, 17, 'God, you have taught me from my youth.\nUntil now, I have declared your wondrous works.\n'),
	(10191, 16, 71, 18, 'Yes, even when I am old and gray-haired, God, don’t forsake me,\nuntil I have declared your strength to the next generation,\nyour might to everyone who is to come.\n'),
	(10192, 16, 71, 19, 'Your righteousness also, God, reaches to the heavens;\nyou have done great things.\nGod, who is like you?\n'),
	(10193, 16, 71, 20, 'You, who have shown us many and bitter troubles,\nyou will let me live.\nYou will bring us up again from the depths of the earth.\n'),
	(10194, 16, 71, 21, 'Increase my honor,\nand comfort me again.\n'),
	(10195, 16, 71, 22, 'I will also praise you with the harp for your faithfulness, my God.\nI sing praises to you with the lyre, Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(10196, 16, 71, 23, 'My lips shall shout for joy!\nMy soul, which you have redeemed, sings praises to you!\n'),
	(10197, 16, 71, 24, 'My tongue will also talk about your righteousness all day long,\nfor they are disappointed, and they are confounded,\nwho want to harm me.\n'),
	(10198, 16, 72, 1, 'God, give the king your justice;\nyour righteousness to the royal son.\n'),
	(10199, 16, 72, 2, 'He will judge your people with righteousness,\nand your poor with justice.\n'),
	(10200, 16, 72, 3, 'The mountains shall bring prosperity to the people.\nThe hills bring the fruit of righteousness.\n'),
	(10201, 16, 72, 4, 'He will judge the poor of the people.\nHe will save the children of the needy,\nand will break the oppressor in pieces.\n'),
	(10202, 16, 72, 5, 'They shall fear you while the sun endures;\nand as long as the moon, throughout all generations.\n'),
	(10203, 16, 72, 6, 'He will come down like rain on the mown grass,\nas showers that water the earth.\n'),
	(10204, 16, 72, 7, 'In his days, the righteous shall flourish,\nand abundance of peace, until the moon is no more.\n'),
	(10205, 16, 72, 8, 'He shall have dominion also from sea to sea,\nfrom the River to the ends of the earth.\n'),
	(10206, 16, 72, 9, 'Those who dwell in the wilderness shall bow before him.\nHis enemies shall lick the dust.\n'),
	(10207, 16, 72, 10, 'The kings of Tarshish and of the islands will bring tribute.\nThe kings of Sheba and Seba shall offer gifts.\n'),
	(10208, 16, 72, 11, 'Yes, all kings shall fall down before him.\nAll nations shall serve him.\n'),
	(10209, 16, 72, 12, 'For he will deliver the needy when he cries;\nthe poor, who has no helper.\n'),
	(10210, 16, 72, 13, 'He will have pity on the poor and needy.\nHe will save the souls of the needy.\n'),
	(10211, 16, 72, 14, 'He will redeem their soul from oppression and violence.\nTheir blood will be precious in his sight.\n'),
	(10212, 16, 72, 15, 'They shall live, and to him shall be given of the gold of Sheba.\nMen shall pray for him continually.\nThey shall bless him all day long.\n'),
	(10213, 16, 72, 16, 'Abundance of grain shall be throughout the land.\nIts fruit sways like Lebanon.\nLet it flourish, thriving like the grass of the field.\n'),
	(10214, 16, 72, 17, 'His name endures forever.\nHis name continues as long as the sun.\nMen shall be blessed by him.\nAll nations will call him blessed.\n'),
	(10215, 16, 72, 18, 'Praise be to Yahweh God, the God of Israel,\nwho alone does marvelous deeds.\n'),
	(10216, 16, 72, 19, 'Blessed be his glorious name forever!\nLet the whole earth be filled with his glory!\nAmen and amen.\n'),
	(10217, 16, 72, 20, 'This ends the prayers by David, the son of Jesse.\n'),
	(10218, 16, 73, 1, 'Surely God is good to Israel,\nto those who are pure in heart.\n'),
	(10219, 16, 73, 2, 'But as for me, my feet were almost gone.\nMy steps had nearly slipped.\n'),
	(10220, 16, 73, 3, 'For I was envious of the arrogant,\nwhen I saw the prosperity of the wicked.\n'),
	(10221, 16, 73, 4, 'For there are no struggles in their death,\nbut their strength is firm.\n'),
	(10222, 16, 73, 5, 'They are free from burdens of men,\nneither are they plagued like other men.\n'),
	(10223, 16, 73, 6, 'Therefore pride is like a chain around their neck.\nViolence covers them like a garment.\n'),
	(10224, 16, 73, 7, 'Their eyes bulge with fat.\nTheir minds pass the limits of conceit.\n'),
	(10225, 16, 73, 8, 'They scoff and speak with malice.\nIn arrogance, they threaten oppression.\n'),
	(10226, 16, 73, 9, 'They have set their mouth in the heavens.\nTheir tongue walks through the earth.\n'),
	(10227, 16, 73, 10, 'Therefore their people return to them,\nand they drink up waters of abundance.\n'),
	(10228, 16, 73, 11, 'They say, “How does God know?\nIs there knowledge in the Most High?”\n'),
	(10229, 16, 73, 12, 'Behold, these are the wicked.\nBeing always at ease, they increase in riches.\n'),
	(10230, 16, 73, 13, 'Surely I have cleansed my heart in vain,\nand washed my hands in innocence,\n'),
	(10231, 16, 73, 14, 'For all day long I have been plagued,\nand punished every morning.\n'),
	(10232, 16, 73, 15, 'If I had said, “I will speak thus”;\nbehold, I would have betrayed the generation of your children.\n'),
	(10233, 16, 73, 16, 'When I tried to understand this,\nit was too painful for me;\n'),
	(10234, 16, 73, 17, 'Until I entered God’s sanctuary,\nand considered their latter end.\n'),
	(10235, 16, 73, 18, 'Surely you set them in slippery places.\nYou throw them down to destruction.\n'),
	(10236, 16, 73, 19, 'How they are suddenly destroyed!\nThey are completely swept away with terrors.\n'),
	(10237, 16, 73, 20, 'As a dream when one wakes up,\nso, Lord, when you awake, you will despise their fantasies.\n'),
	(10238, 16, 73, 21, 'For my soul was grieved.\nI was embittered in my heart.\n'),
	(10239, 16, 73, 22, 'I was so senseless and ignorant.\nI was a brute beast before you.\n'),
	(10240, 16, 73, 23, 'Nevertheless, I am continually with you.\nYou have held my right hand.\n'),
	(10241, 16, 73, 24, 'You will guide me with your counsel,\nand afterward receive me to glory.\n'),
	(10242, 16, 73, 25, 'Whom do I have in heaven?\nThere is no one on earth whom I desire besides you.\n'),
	(10243, 16, 73, 26, 'My flesh and my heart fails,\nbut God is the strength of my heart and my portion forever.\n'),
	(10244, 16, 73, 27, 'For, behold, those who are far from you shall perish.\nYou have destroyed all those who are unfaithful to you.\n'),
	(10245, 16, 73, 28, 'But it is good for me to come close to God.\nI have made the Lord Yahweh my refuge,\nthat I may tell of all your works.\n'),
	(10246, 16, 74, 1, 'God, why have you rejected us forever?\nWhy does your anger smolder against the sheep of your pasture?\n'),
	(10247, 16, 74, 2, 'Remember your congregation, which you purchased of old,\nwhich you have redeemed to be the tribe of your inheritance;\nMount Zion, in which you have lived.\n'),
	(10248, 16, 74, 3, 'Lift up your feet to the perpetual ruins,\nall the evil that the enemy has done in the sanctuary.\n'),
	(10249, 16, 74, 4, 'Your adversaries have roared in the middle of your assembly.\nThey have set up their standards as signs.\n'),
	(10250, 16, 74, 5, 'They behaved like men wielding axes,\ncutting through a thicket of trees.\n'),
	(10251, 16, 74, 6, 'Now they break all its carved work down with hatchet and hammers.\n'),
	(10252, 16, 74, 7, 'They have burned your sanctuary to the ground.\nThey have profaned the dwelling place of your Name.\n'),
	(10253, 16, 74, 8, 'They said in their heart, “We will crush them completely.”\nThey have burned up all the places in the land where God was worshiped.\n'),
	(10254, 16, 74, 9, 'We see no miraculous signs.\nThere is no longer any prophet,\nneither is there among us anyone who knows how long.\n'),
	(10255, 16, 74, 10, 'How long, God, shall the adversary reproach?\nShall the enemy blaspheme your name forever?\n'),
	(10256, 16, 74, 11, 'Why do you draw back your hand, even your right hand?\nTake it from your chest and consume them!\n'),
	(10257, 16, 74, 12, 'Yet God is my King of old,\nworking salvation throughout the earth.\n'),
	(10258, 16, 74, 13, 'You divided the sea by your strength.\nYou broke the heads of the sea monsters in the waters.\n'),
	(10259, 16, 74, 14, 'You broke the heads of Leviathan in pieces.\nYou gave him as food to people and desert creatures.\n'),
	(10260, 16, 74, 15, 'You opened up spring and stream.\nYou dried up mighty rivers.\n'),
	(10261, 16, 74, 16, 'The day is yours, the night is also yours.\nYou have prepared the light and the sun.\n'),
	(10262, 16, 74, 17, 'You have set all the boundaries of the earth.\nYou have made summer and winter.\n'),
	(10263, 16, 74, 18, 'Remember this, that the enemy has mocked you, Yahweh.\nFoolish people have blasphemed your name.\n'),
	(10264, 16, 74, 19, 'Don’t deliver the soul of your dove to wild beasts.\nDon’t forget the life of your poor forever.\n'),
	(10265, 16, 74, 20, 'Honor your covenant,\nfor haunts of violence fill the dark places of the earth.\n'),
	(10266, 16, 74, 21, 'Don’t let the oppressed return ashamed.\nLet the poor and needy praise your name.\n'),
	(10267, 16, 74, 22, 'Arise, God! Plead your own cause.\nRemember how the foolish man mocks you all day.\n'),
	(10268, 16, 74, 23, 'Don’t forget the voice of your adversaries.\nThe tumult of those who rise up against you ascends continually.\n'),
	(10269, 16, 75, 1, 'We give thanks to you, God.\nWe give thanks, for your Name is near.\nMen tell about your wondrous works.\n'),
	(10270, 16, 75, 2, 'When I choose the appointed time,\nI will judge blamelessly.\n'),
	(10271, 16, 75, 3, 'The earth and all its inhabitants quake.\nI firmly hold its pillars.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10272, 16, 75, 4, 'I said to the arrogant, “Don’t boast!”\nI said to the wicked, “Don’t lift up the horn.\n'),
	(10273, 16, 75, 5, 'Don’t lift up your horn on high.\nDon’t speak with a stiff neck.”\n'),
	(10274, 16, 75, 6, 'For neither from the east, nor from the west,\nnor yet from the south, comes exaltation.\n'),
	(10275, 16, 75, 7, 'But God is the judge.\nHe puts down one, and lifts up another.\n'),
	(10276, 16, 75, 8, 'For in Yahweh’s hand there is a cup,\nfull of foaming wine mixed with spices.\nHe pours it out.\nIndeed the wicked of the earth drink and drink it to its very dregs.\n'),
	(10277, 16, 75, 9, 'But I will declare this forever:\nI will sing praises to the God of Jacob.\n'),
	(10278, 16, 75, 10, 'I will cut off all the horns of the wicked,\nbut the horns of the righteous shall be lifted up.\n'),
	(10279, 16, 76, 1, 'In Judah, God is known.\nHis name is great in Israel.\n'),
	(10280, 16, 76, 2, 'His tabernacle is also in Salem;\nHis dwelling place in Zion.\n'),
	(10281, 16, 76, 3, 'There he broke the flaming arrows of the bow,\nthe shield, and the sword, and the weapons of war.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10282, 16, 76, 4, 'Glorious are you, and excellent,\nmore than mountains of game.\n'),
	(10283, 16, 76, 5, 'Valiant men lie plundered,\nthey have slept their last sleep.\nNone of the men of war can lift their hands.\n'),
	(10284, 16, 76, 6, 'At your rebuke, God of Jacob,\nboth chariot and horse are cast into a dead sleep.\n'),
	(10285, 16, 76, 7, 'You, even you, are to be feared.\nWho can stand in your sight when you are angry?\n'),
	(10286, 16, 76, 8, 'You pronounced judgment from heaven.\nThe earth feared, and was silent,\n'),
	(10287, 16, 76, 9, 'when God arose to judgment,\nto save all the afflicted ones of the earth.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10288, 16, 76, 10, 'Surely the wrath of man praises you.\nThe survivors of your wrath are restrained.\n'),
	(10289, 16, 76, 11, 'Make vows to Yahweh your God, and fulfill them!\nLet all of his neighbors bring presents to him who is to be feared.\n'),
	(10290, 16, 76, 12, 'He will cut off the spirit of princes.\nHe is feared by the kings of the earth.\n'),
	(10291, 16, 77, 1, 'My cry goes to God!\nIndeed, I cry to God for help,\nand for him to listen to me.\n'),
	(10292, 16, 77, 2, 'In the day of my trouble I sought the Lord.\nMy hand was stretched out in the night, and didn’t get tired.\nMy soul refused to be comforted.\n'),
	(10293, 16, 77, 3, 'I remember God, and I groan.\nI complain, and my spirit is overwhelmed.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10294, 16, 77, 4, 'You hold my eyelids open.\nI am so troubled that I can’t speak.\n'),
	(10295, 16, 77, 5, 'I have considered the days of old,\nthe years of ancient times.\n'),
	(10296, 16, 77, 6, 'I remember my song in the night.\nI consider in my own heart;\nmy spirit diligently inquires:\n'),
	(10297, 16, 77, 7, '“Will the Lord reject us forever?\nWill he be favorable no more?\n'),
	(10298, 16, 77, 8, 'Has his loving kindness vanished forever?\nDoes his promise fail for generations?\n'),
	(10299, 16, 77, 9, 'Has God forgotten to be gracious?\nHas he, in anger, withheld his compassion?”\nSelah.\n'),
	(10300, 16, 77, 10, 'Then I thought, “I will appeal to this:\nthe years of the right hand of the Most High.”\n'),
	(10301, 16, 77, 11, 'I will remember Yah’s deeds;\nfor I will remember your wonders of old.\n'),
	(10302, 16, 77, 12, 'I will also meditate on all your work,\nand consider your doings.\n'),
	(10303, 16, 77, 13, 'Your way, God, is in the sanctuary.\nWhat god is great like God?\n'),
	(10304, 16, 77, 14, 'You are the God who does wonders.\nYou have made your strength known among the peoples.\n'),
	(10305, 16, 77, 15, 'You have redeemed your people with your arm,\nthe sons of Jacob and Joseph.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10306, 16, 77, 16, 'The waters saw you, God.\nThe waters saw you, and they writhed.\nThe depths also convulsed.\n'),
	(10307, 16, 77, 17, 'The clouds poured out water.\nThe skies resounded with thunder.\nYour arrows also flashed around.\n'),
	(10308, 16, 77, 18, 'The voice of your thunder was in the whirlwind.\nThe lightnings lit up the world.\nThe earth trembled and shook.\n'),
	(10309, 16, 77, 19, 'Your way was through the sea;\nyour paths through the great waters.\nYour footsteps were not known.\n'),
	(10310, 16, 77, 20, 'You led your people like a flock,\nby the hand of Moses and Aaron.\n'),
	(10311, 16, 78, 1, 'Hear my teaching, my people.\nTurn your ears to the words of my mouth.\n'),
	(10312, 16, 78, 2, 'I will open my mouth in a parable.\nI will utter dark sayings of old,\n'),
	(10313, 16, 78, 3, 'Which we have heard and known,\nand our fathers have told us.\n'),
	(10314, 16, 78, 4, 'We will not hide them from their children,\ntelling to the generation to come the praises of Yahweh,\nhis strength, and his wondrous deeds that he has done.\n'),
	(10315, 16, 78, 5, 'For he established a testimony in Jacob,\nand appointed a teaching in Israel,\nwhich he commanded our fathers,\nthat they should make them known to their children;\n'),
	(10316, 16, 78, 6, 'that the generation to come might know, even the children who should be born;\nwho should arise and tell their children,\n'),
	(10317, 16, 78, 7, 'that they might set their hope in God,\nand not forget God’s deeds,\nbut keep his commandments,\n'),
	(10318, 16, 78, 8, 'and might not be as their fathers,\na stubborn and rebellious generation,\na generation that didn’t make their hearts loyal,\nwhose spirit was not steadfast with God.\n'),
	(10319, 16, 78, 9, 'The children of Ephraim, being armed and carrying bows,\nturned back in the day of battle.\n'),
	(10320, 16, 78, 10, 'They didn’t keep God’s covenant,\nand refused to walk in his law.\n'),
	(10321, 16, 78, 11, 'They forgot his doings,\nhis wondrous deeds that he had shown them.\n'),
	(10322, 16, 78, 12, 'He did marvelous things in the sight of their fathers,\nin the land of Egypt, in the field of Zoan.\n'),
	(10323, 16, 78, 13, 'He split the sea, and caused them to pass through.\nHe made the waters stand as a heap.\n'),
	(10324, 16, 78, 14, 'In the daytime he also led them with a cloud,\nand all night with a light of fire.\n'),
	(10325, 16, 78, 15, 'He split rocks in the wilderness,\nand gave them drink abundantly as out of the depths.\n'),
	(10326, 16, 78, 16, 'He brought streams also out of the rock,\nand caused waters to run down like rivers.\n'),
	(10327, 16, 78, 17, 'Yet they still went on to sin against him,\nto rebel against the Most High in the desert.\n'),
	(10328, 16, 78, 18, 'They tempted God in their heart\nby asking food according to their desire.\n'),
	(10329, 16, 78, 19, 'Yes, they spoke against God.\nThey said, “Can God prepare a table in the wilderness?\n'),
	(10330, 16, 78, 20, 'Behold, he struck the rock, so that waters gushed out,\nand streams overflowed.\nCan he give bread also?\nWill he provide meat for his people?”\n'),
	(10331, 16, 78, 21, 'Therefore Yahweh heard, and was angry.\nA fire was kindled against Jacob,\nanger also went up against Israel,\n'),
	(10332, 16, 78, 22, 'because they didn’t believe in God,\nand didn’t trust in his salvation.\n'),
	(10333, 16, 78, 23, 'Yet he commanded the skies above,\nand opened the doors of heaven.\n'),
	(10334, 16, 78, 24, 'He rained down manna on them to eat,\nand gave them food from the sky.\n'),
	(10335, 16, 78, 25, 'Man ate the bread of angels.\nHe sent them food to the full.\n'),
	(10336, 16, 78, 26, 'He caused the east wind to blow in the sky.\nBy his power he guided the south wind.\n'),
	(10337, 16, 78, 27, 'He rained also meat on them as the dust;\nwinged birds as the sand of the seas.\n'),
	(10338, 16, 78, 28, 'He let them fall in the middle of their camp,\naround their habitations.\n'),
	(10339, 16, 78, 29, 'So they ate, and were well filled.\nHe gave them their own desire.\n'),
	(10340, 16, 78, 30, 'They didn’t turn from their cravings.\nTheir food was yet in their mouths,\n'),
	(10341, 16, 78, 31, 'when the anger of God went up against them,\nkilled some of their fattest,\nand struck down the young men of Israel.\n'),
	(10342, 16, 78, 32, 'For all this they still sinned,\nand didn’t believe in his wondrous works.\n'),
	(10343, 16, 78, 33, 'Therefore he consumed their days in vanity,\nand their years in terror.\n'),
	(10344, 16, 78, 34, 'When he killed them, then they inquired after him.\nThey returned and sought God earnestly.\n'),
	(10345, 16, 78, 35, 'They remembered that God was their rock,\nthe Most High God, their redeemer.\n'),
	(10346, 16, 78, 36, 'But they flattered him with their mouth,\nand lied to him with their tongue.\n'),
	(10347, 16, 78, 37, 'For their heart was not right with him,\nneither were they faithful in his covenant.\n'),
	(10348, 16, 78, 38, 'But he, being merciful, forgave iniquity, and didn’t destroy them.\nYes, many times he turned his anger away,\nand didn’t stir up all his wrath.\n'),
	(10349, 16, 78, 39, 'He remembered that they were but flesh,\na wind that passes away, and doesn’t come again.\n'),
	(10350, 16, 78, 40, 'How often they rebelled against him in the wilderness,\nand grieved him in the desert!\n'),
	(10351, 16, 78, 41, 'They turned again and tempted God,\nand provoked the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(10352, 16, 78, 42, 'They didn’t remember his hand,\nnor the day when he redeemed them from the adversary;\n'),
	(10353, 16, 78, 43, 'how he set his signs in Egypt,\nhis wonders in the field of Zoan,\n'),
	(10354, 16, 78, 44, 'he turned their rivers into blood,\nand their streams, so that they could not drink.\n'),
	(10355, 16, 78, 45, 'He sent among them swarms of flies, which devoured them;\nand frogs, which destroyed them.\n'),
	(10356, 16, 78, 46, 'He gave also their increase to the caterpillar,\nand their labor to the locust.\n'),
	(10357, 16, 78, 47, 'He destroyed their vines with hail,\ntheir sycamore fig trees with frost.\n'),
	(10358, 16, 78, 48, 'He gave over their livestock also to the hail,\nand their flocks to hot thunderbolts.\n'),
	(10359, 16, 78, 49, 'He threw on them the fierceness of his anger,\nwrath, indignation, and trouble,\nand a band of angels of evil.\n'),
	(10360, 16, 78, 50, 'He made a path for his anger.\nHe didn’t spare their soul from death,\nbut gave their life over to the pestilence,\n'),
	(10361, 16, 78, 51, 'and struck all the firstborn in Egypt,\nthe chief of their strength in the tents of Ham.\n'),
	(10362, 16, 78, 52, 'But he led out his own people like sheep,\nand guided them in the wilderness like a flock.\n'),
	(10363, 16, 78, 53, 'He led them safely, so that they weren’t afraid,\nbut the sea overwhelmed their enemies.\n'),
	(10364, 16, 78, 54, 'He brought them to the border of his sanctuary,\nto this mountain, which his right hand had taken.\n'),
	(10365, 16, 78, 55, 'He also drove out the nations before them,\nallotted them for an inheritance by line,\nand made the tribes of Israel to dwell in their tents.\n'),
	(10366, 16, 78, 56, 'Yet they tempted and rebelled against the Most High God,\nand didn’t keep his testimonies;\n'),
	(10367, 16, 78, 57, 'but turned back, and dealt treacherously like their fathers.\nThey were twisted like a deceitful bow.\n'),
	(10368, 16, 78, 58, 'For they provoked him to anger with their high places,\nand moved him to jealousy with their engraved images.\n'),
	(10369, 16, 78, 59, 'When God heard this, he was angry,\nand greatly abhorred Israel;\n'),
	(10370, 16, 78, 60, 'So that he abandoned the tent of Shiloh,\nthe tent which he placed among men;\n'),
	(10371, 16, 78, 61, 'and delivered his strength into captivity,\nhis glory into the adversary’s hand.\n'),
	(10372, 16, 78, 62, 'He also gave his people over to the sword,\nand was angry with his inheritance.\n'),
	(10373, 16, 78, 63, 'Fire devoured their young men.\nTheir virgins had no wedding song.\n'),
	(10374, 16, 78, 64, 'Their priests fell by the sword,\nand their widows couldn’t weep.\n'),
	(10375, 16, 78, 65, 'Then the Lord awakened as one out of sleep,\nlike a mighty man who shouts by reason of wine.\n'),
	(10376, 16, 78, 66, 'He struck his adversaries backward.\nHe put them to a perpetual reproach.\n'),
	(10377, 16, 78, 67, 'Moreover he rejected the tent of Joseph,\nand didn’t choose the tribe of Ephraim,\n'),
	(10378, 16, 78, 68, 'But chose the tribe of Judah,\nMount Zion which he loved.\n'),
	(10379, 16, 78, 69, 'He built his sanctuary like the heights,\nlike the earth which he has established forever.\n'),
	(10380, 16, 78, 70, 'He also chose David his servant,\nand took him from the sheepfolds;\n'),
	(10381, 16, 78, 71, 'from following the ewes that have their young,\nhe brought him to be the shepherd of Jacob, his people,\nand Israel, his inheritance.\n'),
	(10382, 16, 78, 72, 'So he was their shepherd according to the integrity of his heart,\nand guided them by the skillfulness of his hands.\n'),
	(10383, 16, 79, 1, 'God, the nations have come into your inheritance.\nThey have defiled your holy temple.\nThey have laid Jerusalem in heaps.\n'),
	(10384, 16, 79, 2, 'They have given the dead bodies of your servants to be food for the birds of the sky,\nthe flesh of your saints to the animals of the earth.\n'),
	(10385, 16, 79, 3, 'Their blood they have shed like water around Jerusalem.\nThere was no one to bury them.\n'),
	(10386, 16, 79, 4, 'We have become a reproach to our neighbors,\na scoffing and derision to those who are around us.\n'),
	(10387, 16, 79, 5, 'How long, Yahweh?\nWill you be angry forever?\nWill your jealousy burn like fire?\n'),
	(10388, 16, 79, 6, 'Pour out your wrath on the nations that don’t know you;\non the kingdoms that don’t call on your name;\n'),
	(10389, 16, 79, 7, 'For they have devoured Jacob,\nand destroyed his homeland.\n'),
	(10390, 16, 79, 8, 'Don’t hold the iniquities of our forefathers against us.\nLet your tender mercies speedily meet us,\nfor we are in desperate need.\n'),
	(10391, 16, 79, 9, 'Help us, God of our salvation, for the glory of your name.\nDeliver us, and forgive our sins, for your name’s sake.\n'),
	(10392, 16, 79, 10, 'Why should the nations say, “Where is their God?”\nLet it be known among the nations, before our eyes,\nthat vengeance for your servants’ blood is being poured out.\n'),
	(10393, 16, 79, 11, 'Let the sighing of the prisoner come before you.\nAccording to the greatness of your power, preserve those who are sentenced to death.\n'),
	(10394, 16, 79, 12, 'Pay back to our neighbors seven times into their bosom\ntheir reproach with which they have reproached you, Lord.\n'),
	(10395, 16, 79, 13, 'So we, your people and sheep of your pasture,\nwill give you thanks forever.\nWe will praise you forever, to all generations.\n'),
	(10396, 16, 80, 1, 'Hear us, Shepherd of Israel,\nyou who lead Joseph like a flock,\nyou who sit above the cherubim, shine out.\n'),
	(10397, 16, 80, 2, 'Before Ephraim and Benjamin and Manasseh, stir up your might!\nCome to save us!\n'),
	(10398, 16, 80, 3, 'Turn us again, God.\nCause your face to shine,\nand we will be saved.\n'),
	(10399, 16, 80, 4, 'Yahweh God of Armies,\nHow long will you be angry against the prayer of your people?\n'),
	(10400, 16, 80, 5, 'You have fed them with the bread of tears,\nand given them tears to drink in large measure.\n'),
	(10401, 16, 80, 6, 'You make us a source of contention to our neighbors.\nOur enemies laugh among themselves.\n'),
	(10402, 16, 80, 7, 'Turn us again, God of Armies.\nCause your face to shine,\nand we will be saved.\n'),
	(10403, 16, 80, 8, 'You brought a vine out of Egypt.\nYou drove out the nations, and planted it.\n'),
	(10404, 16, 80, 9, 'You cleared the ground for it.\nIt took deep root, and filled the land.\n'),
	(10405, 16, 80, 10, 'The mountains were covered with its shadow.\nIts boughs were like God’s cedars.\n'),
	(10406, 16, 80, 11, 'It sent out its branches to the sea,\nIts shoots to the River.\n'),
	(10407, 16, 80, 12, 'Why have you broken down its walls,\nso that all those who pass by the way pluck it?\n'),
	(10408, 16, 80, 13, 'The boar out of the wood ravages it.\nThe wild animals of the field feed on it.\n'),
	(10409, 16, 80, 14, 'Turn again, we beg you, God of Armies.\nLook down from heaven, and see, and visit this vine,\n'),
	(10410, 16, 80, 15, 'the stock which your right hand planted,\nthe branch that you made strong for yourself.\n'),
	(10411, 16, 80, 16, 'It’s burned with fire.\nIt’s cut down.\nThey perish at your rebuke.\n'),
	(10412, 16, 80, 17, 'Let your hand be on the man of your right hand,\non the son of man whom you made strong for yourself.\n'),
	(10413, 16, 80, 18, 'So we will not turn away from you.\nRevive us, and we will call on your name.\n'),
	(10414, 16, 80, 19, 'Turn us again, Yahweh God of Armies.\nCause your face to shine, and we will be saved.\n'),
	(10415, 16, 81, 1, 'Sing aloud to God, our strength!\nMake a joyful shout to the God of Jacob!\n'),
	(10416, 16, 81, 2, 'Raise a song, and bring here the tambourine,\nthe pleasant lyre with the harp.\n'),
	(10417, 16, 81, 3, 'Blow the trumpet at the New Moon,\nat the full moon, on our feast day.\n'),
	(10418, 16, 81, 4, 'For it is a statute for Israel,\nan ordinance of the God of Jacob.\n'),
	(10419, 16, 81, 5, 'He appointed it in Joseph for a testimony,\nwhen he went out over the land of Egypt,\nI heard a language that I didn’t know.\n'),
	(10420, 16, 81, 6, '“I removed his shoulder from the burden.\nHis hands were freed from the basket.\n'),
	(10421, 16, 81, 7, 'You called in trouble, and I delivered you.\nI answered you in the secret place of thunder.\nI tested you at the waters of Meribah.”\nSelah.\n'),
	(10422, 16, 81, 8, '“Hear, my people, and I will testify to you,\nIsrael, if you would listen to me!\n'),
	(10423, 16, 81, 9, 'There shall be no strange god in you,\nneither shall you worship any foreign god.\n'),
	(10424, 16, 81, 10, 'I am Yahweh, your God,\nwho brought you up out of the land of Egypt.\nOpen your mouth wide, and I will fill it.\n'),
	(10425, 16, 81, 11, 'But my people didn’t listen to my voice.\nIsrael desired none of me.\n'),
	(10426, 16, 81, 12, 'So I let them go after the stubbornness of their hearts,\nthat they might walk in their own counsels.\n'),
	(10427, 16, 81, 13, 'Oh that my people would listen to me,\nthat Israel would walk in my ways!\n'),
	(10428, 16, 81, 14, 'I would soon subdue their enemies,\nand turn my hand against their adversaries.\n'),
	(10429, 16, 81, 15, 'The haters of Yahweh would cringe before him,\nand their punishment would last forever.\n'),
	(10430, 16, 81, 16, 'But he would have also fed them with the finest of the wheat.\nI will satisfy you with honey out of the rock.”\n'),
	(10431, 16, 82, 1, 'God presides in the great assembly.\nHe judges among the gods.\n'),
	(10432, 16, 82, 2, '“How long will you judge unjustly,\nand show partiality to the wicked?”\nSelah.\n'),
	(10433, 16, 82, 3, '“Defend the weak, the poor, and the fatherless.\nMaintain the rights of the poor and oppressed.\n'),
	(10434, 16, 82, 4, 'Rescue the weak and needy.\nDeliver them out of the hand of the wicked.”\n'),
	(10435, 16, 82, 5, 'They don’t know, neither do they understand.\nThey walk back and forth in darkness.\nAll the foundations of the earth are shaken.\n'),
	(10436, 16, 82, 6, 'I said, “You are gods,\nall of you are sons of the Most High.\n'),
	(10437, 16, 82, 7, 'Nevertheless you shall die like men,\nand fall like one of the rulers.”\n'),
	(10438, 16, 82, 8, 'Arise, God, judge the earth,\nfor you inherit all of the nations.\n'),
	(10439, 16, 83, 1, 'God, don’t keep silent.\nDon’t keep silent,\nand don’t be still, God.\n'),
	(10440, 16, 83, 2, 'For, behold, your enemies are stirred up.\nThose who hate you have lifted up their heads.\n'),
	(10441, 16, 83, 3, 'They conspire with cunning against your people.\nThey plot against your cherished ones.\n'),
	(10442, 16, 83, 4, '“Come,” they say, “let’s destroy them as a nation,\nthat the name of Israel may be remembered no more.”\n'),
	(10443, 16, 83, 5, 'For they have conspired together with one mind.\nThey form an alliance against you.\n'),
	(10444, 16, 83, 6, 'The tents of Edom and the Ishmaelites;\nMoab, and the Hagrites;\n'),
	(10445, 16, 83, 7, 'Gebal, Ammon, and Amalek;\nPhilistia with the inhabitants of Tyre;\n'),
	(10446, 16, 83, 8, 'Assyria also is joined with them.\nThey have helped the children of Lot.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10447, 16, 83, 9, 'Do to them as you did to Midian,\nas to Sisera, as to Jabin, at the river Kishon;\n'),
	(10448, 16, 83, 10, 'who perished at Endor,\nwho became as dung for the earth.\n'),
	(10449, 16, 83, 11, 'Make their nobles like Oreb and Zeeb;\nyes, all their princes like Zebah and Zalmunna;\n'),
	(10450, 16, 83, 12, 'who said, “Let us take possession of God’s pasture lands.”\n'),
	(10451, 16, 83, 13, 'My God, make them like tumbleweed;\nlike chaff before the wind.\n'),
	(10452, 16, 83, 14, 'As the fire that burns the forest,\nas the flame that sets the mountains on fire,\n'),
	(10453, 16, 83, 15, 'so pursue them with your tempest,\nand terrify them with your storm.\n'),
	(10454, 16, 83, 16, 'Fill their faces with confusion,\nthat they may seek your name, Yahweh.\n'),
	(10455, 16, 83, 17, 'Let them be disappointed and dismayed forever.\nYes, let them be confounded and perish;\n'),
	(10456, 16, 83, 18, 'that they may know that you alone, whose name is Yahweh,\nare the Most High over all the earth.\n'),
	(10457, 16, 84, 1, 'How lovely are your dwellings,\nYahweh of Armies!\n'),
	(10458, 16, 84, 2, 'My soul longs, and even faints for the courts of Yahweh.\nMy heart and my flesh cry out for the living God.\n'),
	(10459, 16, 84, 3, 'Yes, the sparrow has found a home,\nand the swallow a nest for herself, where she may have her young,\nnear your altars, Yahweh of Armies, my King, and my God.\n'),
	(10460, 16, 84, 4, 'Blessed are those who dwell in your house.\nThey are always praising you.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10461, 16, 84, 5, 'Blessed are those whose strength is in you;\nwho have set their hearts on a pilgrimage.\n'),
	(10462, 16, 84, 6, 'Passing through the valley of Weeping, they make it a place of springs.\nYes, the autumn rain covers it with blessings.\n'),
	(10463, 16, 84, 7, 'They go from strength to strength.\nEveryone of them appears before God in Zion.\n'),
	(10464, 16, 84, 8, 'Yahweh, God of Armies, hear my prayer.\nListen, God of Jacob.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10465, 16, 84, 9, 'Behold, God our shield,\nlook at the face of your anointed.\n'),
	(10466, 16, 84, 10, 'For a day in your courts is better than a thousand.\nI would rather be a doorkeeper in the house of my God,\nthan to dwell in the tents of wickedness.\n'),
	(10467, 16, 84, 11, 'For Yahweh God is a sun and a shield.\nYahweh will give grace and glory.\nHe withholds no good thing from those who walk blamelessly.\n'),
	(10468, 16, 84, 12, 'Yahweh of Armies,\nblessed is the man who trusts in you.\n'),
	(10469, 16, 85, 1, 'Yahweh, you have been favorable to your land.\nYou have restored the fortunes of Jacob.\n'),
	(10470, 16, 85, 2, 'You have forgiven the iniquity of your people.\nYou have covered all their sin.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10471, 16, 85, 3, 'You have taken away all your wrath.\nYou have turned from the fierceness of your anger.\n'),
	(10472, 16, 85, 4, 'Turn us, God of our salvation,\nand cause your indignation toward us to cease.\n'),
	(10473, 16, 85, 5, 'Will you be angry with us forever?\nWill you draw out your anger to all generations?\n'),
	(10474, 16, 85, 6, 'Won’t you revive us again,\nthat your people may rejoice in you?\n'),
	(10475, 16, 85, 7, 'Show us your loving kindness, Yahweh.\nGrant us your salvation.\n'),
	(10476, 16, 85, 8, 'I will hear what God, Yahweh, will speak,\nfor he will speak peace to his people, his saints;\nbut let them not turn again to folly.\n'),
	(10477, 16, 85, 9, 'Surely his salvation is near those who fear him,\nthat glory may dwell in our land.\n'),
	(10478, 16, 85, 10, 'Mercy and truth meet together.\nRighteousness and peace have kissed each other.\n'),
	(10479, 16, 85, 11, 'Truth springs out of the earth.\nRighteousness has looked down from heaven.\n'),
	(10480, 16, 85, 12, 'Yes, Yahweh will give that which is good.\nOur land will yield its increase.\n'),
	(10481, 16, 85, 13, 'Righteousness goes before him,\nAnd prepares the way for his steps.\n'),
	(10482, 16, 86, 1, 'Hear, Yahweh, and answer me,\nfor I am poor and needy.\n'),
	(10483, 16, 86, 2, 'Preserve my soul, for I am godly.\nYou, my God, save your servant who trusts in you.\n'),
	(10484, 16, 86, 3, 'Be merciful to me, Lord,\nfor I call to you all day long.\n'),
	(10485, 16, 86, 4, 'Bring joy to the soul of your servant,\nfor to you, Lord, do I lift up my soul.\n'),
	(10486, 16, 86, 5, 'For you, Lord, are good, and ready to forgive;\nabundant in loving kindness to all those who call on you.\n'),
	(10487, 16, 86, 6, 'Hear, Yahweh, my prayer.\nListen to the voice of my petitions.\n'),
	(10488, 16, 86, 7, 'In the day of my trouble I will call on you,\nfor you will answer me.\n'),
	(10489, 16, 86, 8, 'There is no one like you among the gods, Lord,\nnor any deeds like your deeds.\n'),
	(10490, 16, 86, 9, 'All nations you have made will come and worship before you, Lord.\nThey shall glorify your name.\n'),
	(10491, 16, 86, 10, 'For you are great, and do wondrous things.\nYou are God alone.\n'),
	(10492, 16, 86, 11, 'Teach me your way, Yahweh.\nI will walk in your truth.\nMake my heart undivided to fear your name.\n'),
	(10493, 16, 86, 12, 'I will praise you, Lord my God, with my whole heart.\nI will glorify your name forever more.\n'),
	(10494, 16, 86, 13, 'For your loving kindness is great toward me.\nYou have delivered my soul from the lowest Sheol.\n'),
	(10495, 16, 86, 14, 'God, the proud have risen up against me.\nA company of violent men have sought after my soul,\nand they don’t hold regard for you before them.\n'),
	(10496, 16, 86, 15, 'But you, Lord, are a merciful and gracious God,\nslow to anger, and abundant in loving kindness and truth.\n'),
	(10497, 16, 86, 16, 'Turn to me, and have mercy on me!\nGive your strength to your servant.\nSave the son of your servant.\n'),
	(10498, 16, 86, 17, 'Show me a sign of your goodness,\nthat those who hate me may see it, and be shamed,\nbecause you, Yahweh, have helped me, and comforted me.\n'),
	(10499, 16, 87, 1, 'His foundation is in the holy mountains.\n'),
	(10500, 16, 87, 2, 'Yahweh loves the gates of Zion more than all the dwellings of Jacob.\n'),
	(10501, 16, 87, 3, 'Glorious things are spoken about you, city of God.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10502, 16, 87, 4, 'I will record Rahab and Babylon among those who acknowledge me.\nBehold, Philistia, Tyre, and also Ethiopia:\n“This one was born there.”\n'),
	(10503, 16, 87, 5, 'Yes, of Zion it will be said, “This one and that one was born in her”;\nthe Most High himself will establish her.\n'),
	(10504, 16, 87, 6, 'Yahweh will count, when he writes up the peoples,\n“This one was born there.”\nSelah.\n'),
	(10505, 16, 87, 7, 'Those who sing as well as those who dance say,\n“All my springs are in you.”\n'),
	(10506, 16, 88, 1, 'Yahweh, the God of my salvation,\nI have cried day and night before you.\n'),
	(10507, 16, 88, 2, 'Let my prayer enter into your presence.\nTurn your ear to my cry.\n'),
	(10508, 16, 88, 3, 'For my soul is full of troubles.\nMy life draws near to Sheol.\n'),
	(10509, 16, 88, 4, 'I am counted among those who go down into the pit.\nI am like a man who has no help,\n'),
	(10510, 16, 88, 5, 'set apart among the dead,\nlike the slain who lie in the grave,\nwhom you remember no more.\nThey are cut off from your hand.\n'),
	(10511, 16, 88, 6, 'You have laid me in the lowest pit,\nin the darkest depths.\n'),
	(10512, 16, 88, 7, 'Your wrath lies heavily on me.\nYou have afflicted me with all your waves.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10513, 16, 88, 8, 'You have taken my friends from me.\nYou have made me an abomination to them.\nI am confined, and I can’t escape.\n'),
	(10514, 16, 88, 9, 'My eyes are dim from grief.\nI have called on you daily, Yahweh.\nI have spread out my hands to you.\n'),
	(10515, 16, 88, 10, 'Do you show wonders to the dead?\nDo the departed spirits rise up and praise you?\nSelah.\n'),
	(10516, 16, 88, 11, 'Is your loving kindness declared in the grave?\nOr your faithfulness in Destruction?\n'),
	(10517, 16, 88, 12, 'Are your wonders made known in the dark?\nOr your righteousness in the land of forgetfulness?\n'),
	(10518, 16, 88, 13, 'But to you, Yahweh, I have cried.\nIn the morning, my prayer comes before you.\n'),
	(10519, 16, 88, 14, 'Yahweh, why do you reject my soul?\nWhy do you hide your face from me?\n'),
	(10520, 16, 88, 15, 'I am afflicted and ready to die from my youth up.\nWhile I suffer your terrors, I am distracted.\n'),
	(10521, 16, 88, 16, 'Your fierce wrath has gone over me.\nYour terrors have cut me off.\n'),
	(10522, 16, 88, 17, 'They came around me like water all day long.\nThey completely engulfed me.\n'),
	(10523, 16, 88, 18, 'You have put lover and friend far from me,\nand my friends into darkness.\n'),
	(10524, 16, 89, 1, 'I will sing of the loving kindness of Yahweh forever.\nWith my mouth, I will make known your faithfulness to all generations.\n'),
	(10525, 16, 89, 2, 'I indeed declare, “Love stands firm forever.\nYou established the heavens.\nYour faithfulness is in them.”\n'),
	(10526, 16, 89, 3, '“I have made a covenant with my chosen one,\nI have sworn to David, my servant,\n'),
	(10527, 16, 89, 4, '‘I will establish your offspring forever,\nand build up your throne to all generations.’”\nSelah.\n'),
	(10528, 16, 89, 5, 'The heavens will praise your wonders, Yahweh;\nyour faithfulness also in the assembly of the holy ones.\n'),
	(10529, 16, 89, 6, 'For who in the skies can be compared to Yahweh?\nWho among the sons of the heavenly beings is like Yahweh,\n'),
	(10530, 16, 89, 7, 'a very awesome God in the council of the holy ones,\nto be feared above all those who are around him?\n'),
	(10531, 16, 89, 8, 'Yahweh, God of Armies, who is a mighty one, like you?\nYah, your faithfulness is around you.\n'),
	(10532, 16, 89, 9, 'You rule the pride of the sea.\nWhen its waves rise up, you calm them.\n'),
	(10533, 16, 89, 10, 'You have broken Rahab in pieces, like one of the slain.\nYou have scattered your enemies with your mighty arm.\n'),
	(10534, 16, 89, 11, 'The heavens are yours.\nThe earth also is yours;\nthe world and its fullness.\nYou have founded them.\n'),
	(10535, 16, 89, 12, 'The north and the south, you have created them.\nTabor and Hermon rejoice in your name.\n'),
	(10536, 16, 89, 13, 'You have a mighty arm.\nYour hand is strong, and your right hand is exalted.\n'),
	(10537, 16, 89, 14, 'Righteousness and justice are the foundation of your throne.\nLoving kindness and truth go before your face.\n'),
	(10538, 16, 89, 15, 'Blessed are the people who learn to acclaim you.\nThey walk in the light of your presence, Yahweh.\n'),
	(10539, 16, 89, 16, 'In your name they rejoice all day.\nIn your righteousness, they are exalted.\n'),
	(10540, 16, 89, 17, 'For you are the glory of their strength.\nIn your favor, our horn will be exalted.\n'),
	(10541, 16, 89, 18, 'For our shield belongs to Yahweh;\nour king to the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(10542, 16, 89, 19, 'Then you spoke in vision to your saints,\nand said, “I have given strength to the warrior.\nI have exalted a young man from the people.\n'),
	(10543, 16, 89, 20, 'I have found David, my servant.\nI have anointed him with my holy oil,\n'),
	(10544, 16, 89, 21, 'with whom my hand shall be established.\nMy arm will also strengthen him.\n'),
	(10545, 16, 89, 22, 'No enemy will tax him.\nNo wicked man will oppress him.\n'),
	(10546, 16, 89, 23, 'I will beat down his adversaries before him,\nand strike those who hate him.\n'),
	(10547, 16, 89, 24, 'But my faithfulness and my loving kindness will be with him.\nIn my name, his horn will be exalted.\n'),
	(10548, 16, 89, 25, 'I will set his hand also on the sea,\nand his right hand on the rivers.\n'),
	(10549, 16, 89, 26, 'He will call to me, ‘You are my Father,\nmy God, and the rock of my salvation!’\n'),
	(10550, 16, 89, 27, 'I will also appoint him my firstborn,\nthe highest of the kings of the earth.\n'),
	(10551, 16, 89, 28, 'I will keep my loving kindness for him forever more.\nMy covenant will stand firm with him.\n'),
	(10552, 16, 89, 29, 'I will also make his offspring endure forever,\nand his throne as the days of heaven.\n'),
	(10553, 16, 89, 30, 'If his children forsake my law,\nand don’t walk in my ordinances;\n'),
	(10554, 16, 89, 31, 'if they break my statutes,\nand don’t keep my commandments;\n'),
	(10555, 16, 89, 32, 'then I will punish their sin with the rod,\nand their iniquity with stripes.\n'),
	(10556, 16, 89, 33, 'But I will not completely take my loving kindness from him,\nnor allow my faithfulness to fail.\n'),
	(10557, 16, 89, 34, 'I will not break my covenant,\nnor alter what my lips have uttered.\n'),
	(10558, 16, 89, 35, 'Once I have sworn by my holiness,\nI will not lie to David.\n'),
	(10559, 16, 89, 36, 'His offspring will endure forever,\nhis throne like the sun before me.\n'),
	(10560, 16, 89, 37, 'It will be established forever like the moon,\nthe faithful witness in the sky.”\nSelah.\n'),
	(10561, 16, 89, 38, 'But you have rejected and spurned.\nYou have been angry with your anointed.\n'),
	(10562, 16, 89, 39, 'You have renounced the covenant of your servant.\nYou have defiled his crown in the dust.\n'),
	(10563, 16, 89, 40, 'You have broken down all his hedges.\nYou have brought his strongholds to ruin.\n'),
	(10564, 16, 89, 41, 'All who pass by the way rob him.\nHe has become a reproach to his neighbors.\n'),
	(10565, 16, 89, 42, 'You have exalted the right hand of his adversaries.\nYou have made all of his enemies rejoice.\n'),
	(10566, 16, 89, 43, 'Yes, you turn back the edge of his sword,\nand haven’t supported him in battle.\n'),
	(10567, 16, 89, 44, 'You have ended his splendor,\nand thrown his throne down to the ground.\n'),
	(10568, 16, 89, 45, 'You have shortened the days of his youth.\nYou have covered him with shame.\nSelah.\n'),
	(10569, 16, 89, 46, 'How long, Yahweh?\nWill you hide yourself forever?\nWill your wrath burn like fire?\n'),
	(10570, 16, 89, 47, 'Remember how short my time is!\nFor what vanity have you created all the children of men!\n'),
	(10571, 16, 89, 48, 'What man is he who shall live and not see death,\nwho shall deliver his soul from the power of Sheol?\nSelah.\n'),
	(10572, 16, 89, 49, 'Lord, where are your former loving kindnesses,\nwhich you swore to David in your faithfulness?\n'),
	(10573, 16, 89, 50, 'Remember, Lord, the reproach of your servants,\nhow I bear in my heart the taunts of all the mighty peoples,\n'),
	(10574, 16, 89, 51, 'With which your enemies have mocked, Yahweh,\nwith which they have mocked the footsteps of your anointed one.\n'),
	(10575, 16, 89, 52, 'Blessed be Yahweh forever more.\nAmen, and Amen.\n'),
	(10576, 16, 90, 1, 'Lord, you have been our dwelling place for all generations.\n'),
	(10577, 16, 90, 2, 'Before the mountains were born,\nbefore you had formed the earth and the world,\neven from everlasting to everlasting, you are God.\n'),
	(10578, 16, 90, 3, 'You turn man to destruction, saying,\n“Return, you children of men.”\n'),
	(10579, 16, 90, 4, 'For a thousand years in your sight are just like yesterday when it is past,\nlike a watch in the night.\n'),
	(10580, 16, 90, 5, 'You sweep them away as they sleep.\nIn the morning they sprout like new grass.\n'),
	(10581, 16, 90, 6, 'In the morning it sprouts and springs up.\nBy evening, it is withered and dry.\n'),
	(10582, 16, 90, 7, 'For we are consumed in your anger.\nWe are troubled in your wrath.\n'),
	(10583, 16, 90, 8, 'You have set our iniquities before you,\nour secret sins in the light of your presence.\n'),
	(10584, 16, 90, 9, 'For all our days have passed away in your wrath.\nWe bring our years to an end as a sigh.\n'),
	(10585, 16, 90, 10, 'The days of our years are seventy,\nor even by reason of strength eighty years;\nyet their pride is but labor and sorrow,\nfor it passes quickly, and we fly away.\n'),
	(10586, 16, 90, 11, 'Who knows the power of your anger,\nyour wrath according to the fear that is due to you?\n'),
	(10587, 16, 90, 12, 'So teach us to count our days,\nthat we may gain a heart of wisdom.\n'),
	(10588, 16, 90, 13, 'Relent, Yahweh!\nHow long?\nHave compassion on your servants!\n'),
	(10589, 16, 90, 14, 'Satisfy us in the morning with your loving kindness,\nthat we may rejoice and be glad all our days.\n'),
	(10590, 16, 90, 15, 'Make us glad for as many days as you have afflicted us,\nfor as many years as we have seen evil.\n'),
	(10591, 16, 90, 16, 'Let your work appear to your servants;\nyour glory to their children.\n'),
	(10592, 16, 90, 17, 'Let the favor of the Lord our God be on us;\nestablish the work of our hands for us;\nyes, establish the work of our hands.\n'),
	(10593, 16, 91, 1, 'He who dwells in the secret place of the Most High\nwill rest in the shadow of the Almighty.\n'),
	(10594, 16, 91, 2, 'I will say of Yahweh, “He is my refuge and my fortress;\nmy God, in whom I trust.”\n'),
	(10595, 16, 91, 3, 'For he will deliver you from the snare of the fowler,\nand from the deadly pestilence.\n'),
	(10596, 16, 91, 4, 'He will cover you with his feathers.\nUnder his wings you will take refuge.\nHis faithfulness is your shield and rampart.\n'),
	(10597, 16, 91, 5, 'You shall not be afraid of the terror by night,\nnor of the arrow that flies by day;\n'),
	(10598, 16, 91, 6, 'nor of the pestilence that walks in darkness,\nnor of the destruction that wastes at noonday.\n'),
	(10599, 16, 91, 7, 'A thousand may fall at your side,\nand ten thousand at your right hand;\nbut it will not come near you.\n'),
	(10600, 16, 91, 8, 'You will only look with your eyes,\nand see the recompense of the wicked.\n'),
	(10601, 16, 91, 9, 'Because you have made Yahweh your refuge,\nand the Most High your dwelling place,\n'),
	(10602, 16, 91, 10, 'no evil shall happen to you,\nneither shall any plague come near your dwelling.\n'),
	(10603, 16, 91, 11, 'For he will put his angels in charge of you,\nto guard you in all your ways.\n'),
	(10604, 16, 91, 12, 'They will bear you up in their hands,\nso that you won’t dash your foot against a stone.\n'),
	(10605, 16, 91, 13, 'You will tread on the lion and cobra.\nYou will trample the young lion and the serpent underfoot.\n'),
	(10606, 16, 91, 14, '“Because he has set his love on me, therefore I will deliver him.\nI will set him on high, because he has known my name.\n'),
	(10607, 16, 91, 15, 'He will call on me, and I will answer him.\nI will be with him in trouble.\nI will deliver him, and honor him.\n'),
	(10608, 16, 91, 16, 'I will satisfy him with long life,\nand show him my salvation.”\n'),
	(10609, 16, 92, 1, 'It is a good thing to give thanks to Yahweh,\nto sing praises to your name, Most High;\n'),
	(10610, 16, 92, 2, 'to proclaim your loving kindness in the morning,\nand your faithfulness every night,\n'),
	(10611, 16, 92, 3, 'with the ten-stringed lute, with the harp,\nand with the melody of the lyre.\n'),
	(10612, 16, 92, 4, 'For you, Yahweh, have made me glad through your work.\nI will triumph in the works of your hands.\n'),
	(10613, 16, 92, 5, 'How great are your works, Yahweh!\nYour thoughts are very deep.\n'),
	(10614, 16, 92, 6, 'A senseless man doesn’t know,\nneither does a fool understand this:\n'),
	(10615, 16, 92, 7, 'though the wicked spring up as the grass,\nand all the evildoers flourish,\nthey will be destroyed forever.\n'),
	(10616, 16, 92, 8, 'But you, Yahweh, are on high forever more.\n'),
	(10617, 16, 92, 9, 'For, behold, your enemies, Yahweh,\nfor, behold, your enemies shall perish.\nAll the evildoers will be scattered.\n'),
	(10618, 16, 92, 10, 'But you have exalted my horn like that of the wild ox.\nI am anointed with fresh oil.\n'),
	(10619, 16, 92, 11, 'My eye has also seen my enemies.\nMy ears have heard of the wicked enemies who rise up against me.\n'),
	(10620, 16, 92, 12, 'The righteous shall flourish like the palm tree.\nHe will grow like a cedar in Lebanon.\n'),
	(10621, 16, 92, 13, 'They are planted in Yahweh’s house.\nThey will flourish in our God’s courts.\n'),
	(10622, 16, 92, 14, 'They will still produce fruit in old age.\nThey will be full of sap and green,\n'),
	(10623, 16, 92, 15, 'to show that Yahweh is upright.\nHe is my rock,\nand there is no unrighteousness in him.\n'),
	(10624, 16, 93, 1, 'Yahweh reigns!\nHe is clothed with majesty!\nYahweh is armed with strength.\nThe world also is established.\nIt can’t be moved.\n'),
	(10625, 16, 93, 2, 'Your throne is established from long ago.\nYou are from everlasting.\n'),
	(10626, 16, 93, 3, 'The floods have lifted up, Yahweh,\nthe floods have lifted up their voice.\nThe floods lift up their waves.\n'),
	(10627, 16, 93, 4, 'Above the voices of many waters,\nthe mighty breakers of the sea,\nYahweh on high is mighty.\n'),
	(10628, 16, 93, 5, 'Your statutes stand firm.\nHoliness adorns your house,\nYahweh, forever more.\n'),
	(10629, 16, 94, 1, 'Yahweh, you God to whom vengeance belongs,\nyou God to whom vengeance belongs, shine out.\n'),
	(10630, 16, 94, 2, 'Rise up, you judge of the earth.\nPay back the proud what they deserve.\n'),
	(10631, 16, 94, 3, 'Yahweh, how long will the wicked,\nhow long will the wicked triumph?\n'),
	(10632, 16, 94, 4, 'They pour out arrogant words.\nAll the evildoers boast.\n'),
	(10633, 16, 94, 5, 'They break your people in pieces, Yahweh,\nand afflict your heritage.\n'),
	(10634, 16, 94, 6, 'They kill the widow and the alien,\nand murder the fatherless.\n'),
	(10635, 16, 94, 7, 'They say, “Yah will not see,\nneither will Jacob’s God consider.”\n'),
	(10636, 16, 94, 8, 'Consider, you senseless among the people;\nyou fools, when will you be wise?\n'),
	(10637, 16, 94, 9, 'He who implanted the ear, won’t he hear?\nHe who formed the eye, won’t he see?\n'),
	(10638, 16, 94, 10, 'He who disciplines the nations, won’t he punish?\nHe who teaches man knows.\n'),
	(10639, 16, 94, 11, 'Yahweh knows the thoughts of man,\nthat they are futile.\n'),
	(10640, 16, 94, 12, 'Blessed is the man whom you discipline, Yah,\nand teach out of your law;\n'),
	(10641, 16, 94, 13, 'that you may give him rest from the days of adversity,\nuntil the pit is dug for the wicked.\n'),
	(10642, 16, 94, 14, 'For Yahweh won’t reject his people,\nneither will he forsake his inheritance.\n'),
	(10643, 16, 94, 15, 'For judgment will return to righteousness.\nAll the upright in heart shall follow it.\n'),
	(10644, 16, 94, 16, 'Who will rise up for me against the wicked?\nWho will stand up for me against the evildoers?\n'),
	(10645, 16, 94, 17, 'Unless Yahweh had been my help,\nmy soul would have soon lived in silence.\n'),
	(10646, 16, 94, 18, 'When I said, “My foot is slipping!”\nYour loving kindness, Yahweh, held me up.\n'),
	(10647, 16, 94, 19, 'In the multitude of my thoughts within me,\nyour comforts delight my soul.\n'),
	(10648, 16, 94, 20, 'Shall the throne of wickedness have fellowship with you,\nwhich brings about mischief by statute?\n'),
	(10649, 16, 94, 21, 'They gather themselves together against the soul of the righteous,\nand condemn the innocent blood.\n'),
	(10650, 16, 94, 22, 'But Yahweh has been my high tower,\nmy God, the rock of my refuge.\n'),
	(10651, 16, 94, 23, 'He has brought on them their own iniquity,\nand will cut them off in their own wickedness.\nYahweh, our God, will cut them off.\n'),
	(10652, 16, 95, 1, 'Oh come, let’s sing to Yahweh.\nLet’s shout aloud to the rock of our salvation!\n'),
	(10653, 16, 95, 2, 'Let’s come before his presence with thanksgiving.\nLet’s extol him with songs!\n'),
	(10654, 16, 95, 3, 'For Yahweh is a great God,\na great King above all gods.\n'),
	(10655, 16, 95, 4, 'In his hand are the deep places of the earth.\nThe heights of the mountains are also his.\n'),
	(10656, 16, 95, 5, 'The sea is his, and he made it.\nHis hands formed the dry land.\n'),
	(10657, 16, 95, 6, 'Oh come, let’s worship and bow down.\nLet’s kneel before Yahweh, our Maker,\n'),
	(10658, 16, 95, 7, 'for he is our God.\nWe are the people of his pasture,\nand the sheep in his care.\nToday, oh that you would hear his voice!\n'),
	(10659, 16, 95, 8, 'Don’t harden your heart, as at Meribah,\nas in the day of Massah in the wilderness,\n'),
	(10660, 16, 95, 9, 'when your fathers tempted me,\ntested me, and saw my work.\n'),
	(10661, 16, 95, 10, 'Forty long years I was grieved with that generation,\nand said, “It is a people that errs in their heart.\nThey have not known my ways.”\n'),
	(10662, 16, 95, 11, 'Therefore I swore in my wrath,\n“They won’t enter into my rest.”\n'),
	(10663, 16, 96, 1, 'Sing to Yahweh a new song!\nSing to Yahweh, all the earth.\n'),
	(10664, 16, 96, 2, 'Sing to Yahweh!\nBless his name!\nProclaim his salvation from day to day!\n'),
	(10665, 16, 96, 3, 'Declare his glory among the nations,\nhis marvelous works among all the peoples.\n'),
	(10666, 16, 96, 4, 'For great is Yahweh, and greatly to be praised!\nHe is to be feared above all gods.\n'),
	(10667, 16, 96, 5, 'For all the gods of the peoples are idols,\nbut Yahweh made the heavens.\n'),
	(10668, 16, 96, 6, 'Honor and majesty are before him.\nStrength and beauty are in his sanctuary.\n'),
	(10669, 16, 96, 7, 'Ascribe to Yahweh, you families of nations,\nascribe to Yahweh glory and strength.\n'),
	(10670, 16, 96, 8, 'Ascribe to Yahweh the glory due to his name.\nBring an offering, and come into his courts.\n'),
	(10671, 16, 96, 9, 'Worship Yahweh in holy array.\nTremble before him, all the earth.\n'),
	(10672, 16, 96, 10, 'Say among the nations, “Yahweh reigns.”\nThe world is also established.\nIt can’t be moved.\nHe will judge the peoples with equity.\n'),
	(10673, 16, 96, 11, 'Let the heavens be glad, and let the earth rejoice.\nLet the sea roar, and its fullness!\n'),
	(10674, 16, 96, 12, 'Let the field and all that is in it exult!\nThen all the trees of the woods shall sing for joy\n'),
	(10675, 16, 96, 13, 'before Yahweh; for he comes,\nfor he comes to judge the earth.\nHe will judge the world with righteousness,\nthe peoples with his truth.\n'),
	(10676, 16, 97, 1, 'Yahweh reigns!\nLet the earth rejoice!\nLet the multitude of islands be glad!\n'),
	(10677, 16, 97, 2, 'Clouds and darkness are around him.\nRighteousness and justice are the foundation of his throne.\n'),
	(10678, 16, 97, 3, 'A fire goes before him,\nand burns up his adversaries on every side.\n'),
	(10679, 16, 97, 4, 'His lightning lights up the world.\nThe earth sees, and trembles.\n'),
	(10680, 16, 97, 5, 'The mountains melt like wax at the presence of Yahweh,\nat the presence of the Lord of the whole earth.\n'),
	(10681, 16, 97, 6, 'The heavens declare his righteousness.\nAll the peoples have seen his glory.\n'),
	(10682, 16, 97, 7, 'Let all them be shamed who serve engraved images,\nwho boast in their idols.\nWorship him, all you gods!\n'),
	(10683, 16, 97, 8, 'Zion heard and was glad.\nThe daughters of Judah rejoiced,\nbecause of your judgments, Yahweh.\n'),
	(10684, 16, 97, 9, 'For you, Yahweh, are most high above all the earth.\nYou are exalted far above all gods.\n'),
	(10685, 16, 97, 10, 'You who love Yahweh, hate evil.\nHe preserves the souls of his saints.\nHe delivers them out of the hand of the wicked.\n'),
	(10686, 16, 97, 11, 'Light is sown for the righteous,\nand gladness for the upright in heart.\n'),
	(10687, 16, 97, 12, 'Be glad in Yahweh, you righteous people!\nGive thanks to his holy Name.\n'),
	(10688, 16, 98, 1, 'Sing to Yahweh a new song,\nfor he has done marvelous things!\nHis right hand, and his holy arm, have worked salvation for him.\n'),
	(10689, 16, 98, 2, 'Yahweh has made known his salvation.\nHe has openly shown his righteousness in the sight of the nations.\n'),
	(10690, 16, 98, 3, 'He has remembered his loving kindness and his faithfulness toward the house of Israel.\nAll the ends of the earth have seen the salvation of our God.\n'),
	(10691, 16, 98, 4, 'Make a joyful noise to Yahweh, all the earth!\nBurst out and sing for joy, yes, sing praises!\n'),
	(10692, 16, 98, 5, 'Sing praises to Yahweh with the harp,\nwith the harp and the voice of melody.\n'),
	(10693, 16, 98, 6, 'With trumpets and sound of the ram’s horn,\nmake a joyful noise before the King, Yahweh.\n'),
	(10694, 16, 98, 7, 'Let the sea roar with its fullness;\nthe world, and those who dwell therein.\n'),
	(10695, 16, 98, 8, 'Let the rivers clap their hands.\nLet the mountains sing for joy together.\n'),
	(10696, 16, 98, 9, 'Let them sing before Yahweh,\nfor he comes to judge the earth.\nHe will judge the world with righteousness,\nand the peoples with equity.\n'),
	(10697, 16, 99, 1, 'Yahweh reigns! Let the peoples tremble.\nHe sits enthroned among the cherubim.\nLet the earth be moved.\n'),
	(10698, 16, 99, 2, 'Yahweh is great in Zion.\nHe is high above all the peoples.\n'),
	(10699, 16, 99, 3, 'Let them praise your great and awesome name.\nHe is Holy!\n'),
	(10700, 16, 99, 4, 'The King’s strength also loves justice.\nYou do establish equity.\nYou execute justice and righteousness in Jacob.\n'),
	(10701, 16, 99, 5, 'Exalt Yahweh our God.\nWorship at his footstool.\nHe is Holy!\n'),
	(10702, 16, 99, 6, 'Moses and Aaron were among his priests,\nSamuel among those who call on his name;\nthey called on Yahweh, and he answered them.\n'),
	(10703, 16, 99, 7, 'He spoke to them in the pillar of cloud.\nThey kept his testimonies,\nthe statute that he gave them.\n'),
	(10704, 16, 99, 8, 'You answered them, Yahweh our God.\nYou are a God who forgave them,\nalthough you took vengeance for their doings.\n'),
	(10705, 16, 99, 9, 'Exalt Yahweh, our God.\nWorship at his holy hill,\nfor Yahweh, our God, is holy!\n'),
	(10706, 16, 100, 1, 'Shout for joy to Yahweh, all you lands!\n'),
	(10707, 16, 100, 2, 'Serve Yahweh with gladness.\nCome before his presence with singing.\n'),
	(10708, 16, 100, 3, 'Know that Yahweh, he is God.\nIt is he who has made us, and we are his.\nWe are his people, and the sheep of his pasture.\n'),
	(10709, 16, 100, 4, 'Enter into his gates with thanksgiving,\ninto his courts with praise.\nGive thanks to him, and bless his name.\n'),
	(10710, 16, 100, 5, 'For Yahweh is good.\nHis loving kindness endures forever,\nhis faithfulness to all generations.\n'),
	(10711, 16, 101, 1, 'I will sing of loving kindness and justice.\nTo you, Yahweh, I will sing praises.\n'),
	(10712, 16, 101, 2, 'I will be careful to live a blameless life.\nWhen will you come to me?\nI will walk within my house with a blameless heart.\n'),
	(10713, 16, 101, 3, 'I will set no vile thing before my eyes.\nI hate the deeds of faithless men.\nThey will not cling to me.\n'),
	(10714, 16, 101, 4, 'A perverse heart will be far from me.\nI will have nothing to do with evil.\n'),
	(10715, 16, 101, 5, 'I will silence whoever secretly slanders his neighbor.\nI won’t tolerate one who is haughty and conceited.\n'),
	(10716, 16, 101, 6, 'My eyes will be on the faithful of the land,\nthat they may dwell with me.\nHe who walks in a perfect way,\nhe will serve me.\n'),
	(10717, 16, 101, 7, 'He who practices deceit won’t dwell within my house.\nHe who speaks falsehood won’t be established before my eyes.\n'),
	(10718, 16, 101, 8, 'Morning by morning, I will destroy all the wicked of the land;\nto cut off all the workers of iniquity from Yahweh’s city.\n'),
	(10719, 16, 102, 1, 'Hear my prayer, Yahweh!\nLet my cry come to you.\n'),
	(10720, 16, 102, 2, 'Don’t hide your face from me in the day of my distress.\nTurn your ear to me.\nAnswer me quickly in the day when I call.\n'),
	(10721, 16, 102, 3, 'For my days consume away like smoke.\nMy bones are burned as a torch.\n'),
	(10722, 16, 102, 4, 'My heart is blighted like grass, and withered,\nfor I forget to eat my bread.\n'),
	(10723, 16, 102, 5, 'By reason of the voice of my groaning,\nmy bones stick to my skin.\n'),
	(10724, 16, 102, 6, 'I am like a pelican of the wilderness.\nI have become as an owl of the waste places.\n'),
	(10725, 16, 102, 7, 'I watch, and have become like a sparrow that is alone on the housetop.\n'),
	(10726, 16, 102, 8, 'My enemies reproach me all day.\nThose who are mad at me use my name as a curse.\n'),
	(10727, 16, 102, 9, 'For I have eaten ashes like bread,\nand mixed my drink with tears,\n'),
	(10728, 16, 102, 10, 'Because of your indignation and your wrath,\nfor you have taken me up, and thrown me away.\n'),
	(10729, 16, 102, 11, 'My days are like a long shadow.\nI have withered like grass.\n'),
	(10730, 16, 102, 12, 'But you, Yahweh, will remain forever;\nyour renown endures to all generations.\n'),
	(10731, 16, 102, 13, 'You will arise and have mercy on Zion;\nfor it is time to have pity on her.\nYes, the set time has come.\n'),
	(10732, 16, 102, 14, 'For your servants take pleasure in her stones,\nand have pity on her dust.\n'),
	(10733, 16, 102, 15, 'So the nations will fear Yahweh’s name;\nall the kings of the earth your glory.\n'),
	(10734, 16, 102, 16, 'For Yahweh has built up Zion.\nHe has appeared in his glory.\n'),
	(10735, 16, 102, 17, 'He has responded to the prayer of the destitute,\nand has not despised their prayer.\n'),
	(10736, 16, 102, 18, 'This will be written for the generation to come.\nA people which will be created will praise Yah.\n'),
	(10737, 16, 102, 19, 'For he has looked down from the height of his sanctuary.\nFrom heaven, Yahweh saw the earth;\n'),
	(10738, 16, 102, 20, 'to hear the groans of the prisoner;\nto free those who are condemned to death;\n'),
	(10739, 16, 102, 21, 'that men may declare Yahweh’s name in Zion,\nand his praise in Jerusalem;\n'),
	(10740, 16, 102, 22, 'when the peoples are gathered together,\nthe kingdoms, to serve Yahweh.\n'),
	(10741, 16, 102, 23, 'He weakened my strength along the course.\nHe shortened my days.\n'),
	(10742, 16, 102, 24, 'I said, “My God, don’t take me away in the middle of my days.\nYour years are throughout all generations.\n'),
	(10743, 16, 102, 25, 'Of old, you laid the foundation of the earth.\nThe heavens are the work of your hands.\n'),
	(10744, 16, 102, 26, 'They will perish, but you will endure.\nYes, all of them will wear out like a garment.\nYou will change them like a cloak, and they will be changed.\n'),
	(10745, 16, 102, 27, 'But you are the same.\nYour years will have no end.\n'),
	(10746, 16, 102, 28, 'The children of your servants will continue.\nTheir offspring will be established before you.”\n'),
	(10747, 16, 103, 1, 'Praise Yahweh, my soul!\nAll that is within me, praise his holy name!\n'),
	(10748, 16, 103, 2, 'Praise Yahweh, my soul,\nand don’t forget all his benefits;\n'),
	(10749, 16, 103, 3, 'who forgives all your sins;\nwho heals all your diseases;\n'),
	(10750, 16, 103, 4, 'who redeems your life from destruction;\nwho crowns you with loving kindness and tender mercies;\n'),
	(10751, 16, 103, 5, 'who satisfies your desire with good things,\nso that your youth is renewed like the eagle’s.\n'),
	(10752, 16, 103, 6, 'Yahweh executes righteous acts,\nand justice for all who are oppressed.\n'),
	(10753, 16, 103, 7, 'He made known his ways to Moses,\nhis deeds to the children of Israel.\n'),
	(10754, 16, 103, 8, 'Yahweh is merciful and gracious,\nslow to anger, and abundant in loving kindness.\n'),
	(10755, 16, 103, 9, 'He will not always accuse;\nneither will he stay angry forever.\n'),
	(10756, 16, 103, 10, 'He has not dealt with us according to our sins,\nnor repaid us for our iniquities.\n'),
	(10757, 16, 103, 11, 'For as the heavens are high above the earth,\nso great is his loving kindness toward those who fear him.\n'),
	(10758, 16, 103, 12, 'As far as the east is from the west,\nso far has he removed our transgressions from us.\n'),
	(10759, 16, 103, 13, 'Like a father has compassion on his children,\nso Yahweh has compassion on those who fear him.\n'),
	(10760, 16, 103, 14, 'For he knows how we are made.\nHe remembers that we are dust.\n'),
	(10761, 16, 103, 15, 'As for man, his days are like grass.\nAs a flower of the field, so he flourishes.\n'),
	(10762, 16, 103, 16, 'For the wind passes over it, and it is gone.\nIts place remembers it no more.\n'),
	(10763, 16, 103, 17, 'But Yahweh’s loving kindness is from everlasting to everlasting with those who fear him,\nhis righteousness to children’s children;\n'),
	(10764, 16, 103, 18, 'to those who keep his covenant,\nto those who remember to obey his precepts.\n'),
	(10765, 16, 103, 19, 'Yahweh has established his throne in the heavens.\nHis kingdom rules over all.\n'),
	(10766, 16, 103, 20, 'Praise Yahweh, you angels of his,\nwho are mighty in strength, who fulfill his word,\nobeying the voice of his word.\n'),
	(10767, 16, 103, 21, 'Praise Yahweh, all you armies of his,\nyou servants of his, who do his pleasure.\n'),
	(10768, 16, 103, 22, 'Praise Yahweh, all you works of his,\nin all places of his dominion.\nPraise Yahweh, my soul!\n'),
	(10769, 16, 104, 1, 'Bless Yahweh, my soul.\nYahweh, my God, you are very great.\nYou are clothed with honor and majesty.\n'),
	(10770, 16, 104, 2, 'He covers himself with light as with a garment.\nHe stretches out the heavens like a curtain.\n'),
	(10771, 16, 104, 3, 'He lays the beams of his rooms in the waters.\nHe makes the clouds his chariot.\nHe walks on the wings of the wind.\n'),
	(10772, 16, 104, 4, 'He makes his messengers winds;\nhis servants flames of fire.\n'),
	(10773, 16, 104, 5, 'He laid the foundations of the earth,\nthat it should not be moved forever.\n'),
	(10774, 16, 104, 6, 'You covered it with the deep as with a cloak.\nThe waters stood above the mountains.\n'),
	(10775, 16, 104, 7, 'At your rebuke they fled.\nAt the voice of your thunder they hurried away.\n'),
	(10776, 16, 104, 8, 'The mountains rose,\nthe valleys sank down,\nto the place which you had assigned to them.\n'),
	(10777, 16, 104, 9, 'You have set a boundary that they may not pass over;\nthat they don’t turn again to cover the earth.\n'),
	(10778, 16, 104, 10, 'He sends springs into the valleys.\nThey run among the mountains.\n'),
	(10779, 16, 104, 11, 'They give drink to every animal of the field.\nThe wild donkeys quench their thirst.\n'),
	(10780, 16, 104, 12, 'The birds of the sky nest by them.\nThey sing among the branches.\n'),
	(10781, 16, 104, 13, 'He waters the mountains from his rooms.\nThe earth is filled with the fruit of your works.\n'),
	(10782, 16, 104, 14, 'He causes the grass to grow for the livestock,\nand plants for man to cultivate,\nthat he may produce food out of the earth:\n'),
	(10783, 16, 104, 15, 'wine that makes glad the heart of man,\noil to make his face to shine,\nand bread that strengthens man’s heart.\n'),
	(10784, 16, 104, 16, 'Yahweh’s trees are well watered,\nthe cedars of Lebanon, which he has planted;\n'),
	(10785, 16, 104, 17, 'where the birds make their nests.\nThe stork makes its home in the cypress trees.\n'),
	(10786, 16, 104, 18, 'The high mountains are for the wild goats.\nThe rocks are a refuge for the rock badgers.\n'),
	(10787, 16, 104, 19, 'He appointed the moon for seasons.\nThe sun knows when to set.\n'),
	(10788, 16, 104, 20, 'You make darkness, and it is night,\nin which all the animals of the forest prowl.\n'),
	(10789, 16, 104, 21, 'The young lions roar after their prey,\nand seek their food from God.\n'),
	(10790, 16, 104, 22, 'The sun rises, and they steal away,\nand lay down in their dens.\n'),
	(10791, 16, 104, 23, 'Man goes out to his work,\nto his labor until the evening.\n'),
	(10792, 16, 104, 24, 'Yahweh, how many are your works!\nIn wisdom have you made them all.\nThe earth is full of your riches.\n'),
	(10793, 16, 104, 25, 'There is the sea, great and wide,\nin which are innumerable living things,\nboth small and large animals.\n'),
	(10794, 16, 104, 26, 'There the ships go,\nand leviathan, whom you formed to play there.\n'),
	(10795, 16, 104, 27, 'These all wait for you,\nthat you may give them their food in due season.\n'),
	(10796, 16, 104, 28, 'You give to them; they gather.\nYou open your hand; they are satisfied with good.\n'),
	(10797, 16, 104, 29, 'You hide your face: they are troubled;\nyou take away their breath: they die, and return to the dust.\n'),
	(10798, 16, 104, 30, 'You send out your Spirit and they are created.\nYou renew the face of the ground.\n'),
	(10799, 16, 104, 31, 'Let Yahweh’s glory endure forever.\nLet Yahweh rejoice in his works.\n'),
	(10800, 16, 104, 32, 'He looks at the earth, and it trembles.\nHe touches the mountains, and they smoke.\n'),
	(10801, 16, 104, 33, 'I will sing to Yahweh as long as I live.\nI will sing praise to my God while I have any being.\n'),
	(10802, 16, 104, 34, 'Let my meditation be sweet to him.\nI will rejoice in Yahweh.\n'),
	(10803, 16, 104, 35, 'Let sinners be consumed out of the earth.\nLet the wicked be no more.\nBless Yahweh, my soul.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(10804, 16, 105, 1, 'Give thanks to Yahweh! Call on his name!\nMake his doings known among the peoples.\n'),
	(10805, 16, 105, 2, 'Sing to him, sing praises to him!\nTell of all his marvelous works.\n'),
	(10806, 16, 105, 3, 'Glory in his holy name.\nLet the heart of those who seek Yahweh rejoice.\n'),
	(10807, 16, 105, 4, 'Seek Yahweh and his strength.\nSeek his face forever more.\n'),
	(10808, 16, 105, 5, 'Remember his marvelous works that he has done;\nhis wonders, and the judgments of his mouth,\n'),
	(10809, 16, 105, 6, 'you offspring of Abraham, his servant,\nyou children of Jacob, his chosen ones.\n'),
	(10810, 16, 105, 7, 'He is Yahweh, our God.\nHis judgments are in all the earth.\n'),
	(10811, 16, 105, 8, 'He has remembered his covenant forever,\nthe word which he commanded to a thousand generations,\n'),
	(10812, 16, 105, 9, 'the covenant which he made with Abraham,\nhis oath to Isaac,\n'),
	(10813, 16, 105, 10, 'and confirmed the same to Jacob for a statute;\nto Israel for an everlasting covenant,\n'),
	(10814, 16, 105, 11, 'saying, “To you I will give the land of Canaan,\nthe lot of your inheritance”;\n'),
	(10815, 16, 105, 12, 'when they were but a few men in number,\nyes, very few, and foreigners in it.\n'),
	(10816, 16, 105, 13, 'They went about from nation to nation,\nfrom one kingdom to another people.\n'),
	(10817, 16, 105, 14, 'He allowed no one to do them wrong.\nYes, he reproved kings for their sakes,\n'),
	(10818, 16, 105, 15, '“Don’t touch my anointed ones!\nDo my prophets no harm!”\n'),
	(10819, 16, 105, 16, 'He called for a famine on the land.\nHe destroyed the food supplies.\n'),
	(10820, 16, 105, 17, 'He sent a man before them.\nJoseph was sold for a slave.\n'),
	(10821, 16, 105, 18, 'They bruised his feet with shackles.\nHis neck was locked in irons,\n'),
	(10822, 16, 105, 19, 'until the time that his word happened,\nand Yahweh’s word proved him true.\n'),
	(10823, 16, 105, 20, 'The king sent and freed him;\neven the ruler of peoples, and let him go free.\n'),
	(10824, 16, 105, 21, 'He made him lord of his house,\nand ruler of all of his possessions;\n'),
	(10825, 16, 105, 22, 'to discipline his princes at his pleasure,\nand to teach his elders wisdom.\n'),
	(10826, 16, 105, 23, 'Israel also came into Egypt.\nJacob lived in the land of Ham.\n'),
	(10827, 16, 105, 24, 'He increased his people greatly,\nand made them stronger than their adversaries.\n'),
	(10828, 16, 105, 25, 'He turned their heart to hate his people,\nto conspire against his servants.\n'),
	(10829, 16, 105, 26, 'He sent Moses, his servant,\nand Aaron, whom he had chosen.\n'),
	(10830, 16, 105, 27, 'They performed miracles among them,\nand wonders in the land of Ham.\n'),
	(10831, 16, 105, 28, 'He sent darkness, and made it dark.\nThey didn’t rebel against his words.\n'),
	(10832, 16, 105, 29, 'He turned their waters into blood,\nand killed their fish.\n'),
	(10833, 16, 105, 30, 'Their land swarmed with frogs,\neven in the rooms of their kings.\n'),
	(10834, 16, 105, 31, 'He spoke, and swarms of flies came,\nand lice in all their borders.\n'),
	(10835, 16, 105, 32, 'He gave them hail for rain,\nwith lightning in their land.\n'),
	(10836, 16, 105, 33, 'He struck their vines and also their fig trees,\nand shattered the trees of their country.\n'),
	(10837, 16, 105, 34, 'He spoke, and the locusts came,\nand the grasshoppers, without number,\n'),
	(10838, 16, 105, 35, 'ate up every plant in their land;\nand ate up the fruit of their ground.\n'),
	(10839, 16, 105, 36, 'He struck also all the firstborn in their land,\nthe first fruits of all their manhood.\n'),
	(10840, 16, 105, 37, 'He brought them out with silver and gold.\nThere was not one feeble person among his tribes.\n'),
	(10841, 16, 105, 38, 'Egypt was glad when they departed,\nfor the fear of them had fallen on them.\n'),
	(10842, 16, 105, 39, 'He spread a cloud for a covering,\nfire to give light in the night.\n'),
	(10843, 16, 105, 40, 'They asked, and he brought quails,\nand satisfied them with the bread of the sky.\n'),
	(10844, 16, 105, 41, 'He opened the rock, and waters gushed out.\nThey ran as a river in the dry places.\n'),
	(10845, 16, 105, 42, 'For he remembered his holy word,\nand Abraham, his servant.\n'),
	(10846, 16, 105, 43, 'He brought his people out with joy,\nhis chosen with singing.\n'),
	(10847, 16, 105, 44, 'He gave them the lands of the nations.\nThey took the labor of the peoples in possession,\n'),
	(10848, 16, 105, 45, 'that they might keep his statutes,\nand observe his laws.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(10849, 16, 106, 1, 'Praise Yahweh!\nGive thanks to Yahweh, for he is good,\nfor his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(10850, 16, 106, 2, 'Who can utter the mighty acts of Yahweh,\nor fully declare all his praise?\n'),
	(10851, 16, 106, 3, 'Blessed are those who keep justice.\nBlessed is one who does what is right at all times.\n'),
	(10852, 16, 106, 4, 'Remember me, Yahweh, with the favor that you show to your people.\nVisit me with your salvation,\n'),
	(10853, 16, 106, 5, 'that I may see the prosperity of your chosen,\nthat I may rejoice in the gladness of your nation,\nthat I may glory with your inheritance.\n'),
	(10854, 16, 106, 6, 'We have sinned with our fathers.\nWe have committed iniquity.\nWe have done wickedly.\n'),
	(10855, 16, 106, 7, 'Our fathers didn’t understand your wonders in Egypt.\nThey didn’t remember the multitude of your loving kindnesses,\nbut were rebellious at the sea, even at the Red Sea.\n'),
	(10856, 16, 106, 8, 'Nevertheless he saved them for his name’s sake,\nthat he might make his mighty power known.\n'),
	(10857, 16, 106, 9, 'He rebuked the Red Sea also, and it was dried up;\nso he led them through the depths, as through a desert.\n'),
	(10858, 16, 106, 10, 'He saved them from the hand of him who hated them,\nand redeemed them from the hand of the enemy.\n'),
	(10859, 16, 106, 11, 'The waters covered their adversaries.\nThere was not one of them left.\n'),
	(10860, 16, 106, 12, 'Then they believed his words.\nThey sang his praise.\n'),
	(10861, 16, 106, 13, 'They soon forgot his works.\nThey didn’t wait for his counsel,\n'),
	(10862, 16, 106, 14, 'but gave in to craving in the desert,\nand tested God in the wasteland.\n'),
	(10863, 16, 106, 15, 'He gave them their request,\nbut sent leanness into their soul.\n'),
	(10864, 16, 106, 16, 'They envied Moses also in the camp,\nand Aaron, Yahweh’s saint.\n'),
	(10865, 16, 106, 17, 'The earth opened and swallowed up Dathan,\nand covered the company of Abiram.\n'),
	(10866, 16, 106, 18, 'A fire was kindled in their company.\nThe flame burned up the wicked.\n'),
	(10867, 16, 106, 19, 'They made a calf in Horeb,\nand worshiped a molten image.\n'),
	(10868, 16, 106, 20, 'Thus they exchanged their glory\nfor an image of a bull that eats grass.\n'),
	(10869, 16, 106, 21, 'They forgot God, their Savior,\nwho had done great things in Egypt,\n'),
	(10870, 16, 106, 22, 'Wondrous works in the land of Ham,\nand awesome things by the Red Sea.\n'),
	(10871, 16, 106, 23, 'Therefore he said that he would destroy them,\nhad Moses, his chosen, not stood before him in the breach,\nto turn away his wrath, so that he wouldn’t destroy them.\n'),
	(10872, 16, 106, 24, 'Yes, they despised the pleasant land.\nThey didn’t believe his word,\n'),
	(10873, 16, 106, 25, 'but murmured in their tents,\nand didn’t listen to Yahweh’s voice.\n'),
	(10874, 16, 106, 26, 'Therefore he swore to them\nthat he would overthrow them in the wilderness,\n'),
	(10875, 16, 106, 27, 'that he would overthrow their offspring among the nations,\nand scatter them in the lands.\n'),
	(10876, 16, 106, 28, 'They joined themselves also to Baal Peor,\nand ate the sacrifices of the dead.\n'),
	(10877, 16, 106, 29, 'Thus they provoked him to anger with their deeds.\nThe plague broke in on them.\n'),
	(10878, 16, 106, 30, 'Then Phinehas stood up, and executed judgment,\nso the plague was stopped.\n'),
	(10879, 16, 106, 31, 'That was credited to him for righteousness,\nfor all generations to come.\n'),
	(10880, 16, 106, 32, 'They angered him also at the waters of Meribah,\nso that Moses was troubled for their sakes;\n'),
	(10881, 16, 106, 33, 'because they were rebellious against his spirit,\nhe spoke rashly with his lips.\n'),
	(10882, 16, 106, 34, 'They didn’t destroy the peoples,\nas Yahweh commanded them,\n'),
	(10883, 16, 106, 35, 'but mixed themselves with the nations,\nand learned their works.\n'),
	(10884, 16, 106, 36, 'They served their idols,\nwhich became a snare to them.\n'),
	(10885, 16, 106, 37, 'Yes, they sacrificed their sons and their daughters to demons.\n'),
	(10886, 16, 106, 38, 'They shed innocent blood,\neven the blood of their sons and of their daughters,\nwhom they sacrificed to the idols of Canaan.\nThe land was polluted with blood.\n'),
	(10887, 16, 106, 39, 'Thus were they defiled with their works,\nand prostituted themselves in their deeds.\n'),
	(10888, 16, 106, 40, 'Therefore Yahweh burned with anger against his people.\nHe abhorred his inheritance.\n'),
	(10889, 16, 106, 41, 'He gave them into the hand of the nations.\nThose who hated them ruled over them.\n'),
	(10890, 16, 106, 42, 'Their enemies also oppressed them.\nThey were brought into subjection under their hand.\n'),
	(10891, 16, 106, 43, 'He rescued them many times,\nbut they were rebellious in their counsel,\nand were brought low in their iniquity.\n'),
	(10892, 16, 106, 44, 'Nevertheless he regarded their distress,\nwhen he heard their cry.\n'),
	(10893, 16, 106, 45, 'He remembered for them his covenant,\nand repented according to the multitude of his loving kindnesses.\n'),
	(10894, 16, 106, 46, 'He made them also to be pitied\nby all those who carried them captive.\n'),
	(10895, 16, 106, 47, 'Save us, Yahweh, our God,\ngather us from among the nations,\nto give thanks to your holy name,\nto triumph in your praise!\n'),
	(10896, 16, 106, 48, 'Blessed be Yahweh, the God of Israel,\nfrom everlasting even to everlasting!\nLet all the people say, “Amen.”\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(10897, 16, 107, 1, 'Give thanks to Yahweh, for he is good,\nfor his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(10898, 16, 107, 2, 'Let the redeemed by Yahweh say so,\nwhom he has redeemed from the hand of the adversary,\n'),
	(10899, 16, 107, 3, 'And gathered out of the lands,\nfrom the east and from the west,\nfrom the north and from the south.\n'),
	(10900, 16, 107, 4, 'They wandered in the wilderness in a desert way.\nThey found no city to live in.\n'),
	(10901, 16, 107, 5, 'Hungry and thirsty,\ntheir soul fainted in them.\n'),
	(10902, 16, 107, 6, 'Then they cried to Yahweh in their trouble,\nand he delivered them out of their distresses,\n'),
	(10903, 16, 107, 7, 'he led them also by a straight way,\nthat they might go to a city to live in.\n'),
	(10904, 16, 107, 8, 'Let them praise Yahweh for his loving kindness,\nfor his wonderful deeds to the children of men!\n'),
	(10905, 16, 107, 9, 'For he satisfies the longing soul.\nHe fills the hungry soul with good.\n'),
	(10906, 16, 107, 10, 'Some sat in darkness and in the shadow of death,\nbeing bound in affliction and iron,\n'),
	(10907, 16, 107, 11, 'because they rebelled against the words of God,\nand condemned the counsel of the Most High.\n'),
	(10908, 16, 107, 12, 'Therefore he brought down their heart with labor.\nThey fell down, and there was no one to help.\n'),
	(10909, 16, 107, 13, 'Then they cried to Yahweh in their trouble,\nand he saved them out of their distresses.\n'),
	(10910, 16, 107, 14, 'He brought them out of darkness and the shadow of death,\nand broke away their chains.\n'),
	(10911, 16, 107, 15, 'Let them praise Yahweh for his loving kindness,\nfor his wonderful deeds to the children of men!\n'),
	(10912, 16, 107, 16, 'For he has broken the gates of brass,\nand cut through bars of iron.\n'),
	(10913, 16, 107, 17, 'Fools are afflicted because of their disobedience,\nand because of their iniquities.\n'),
	(10914, 16, 107, 18, 'Their soul abhors all kinds of food.\nThey draw near to the gates of death.\n'),
	(10915, 16, 107, 19, 'Then they cry to Yahweh in their trouble,\nhe saves them out of their distresses.\n'),
	(10916, 16, 107, 20, 'He sends his word, and heals them,\nand delivers them from their graves.\n'),
	(10917, 16, 107, 21, 'Let them praise Yahweh for his loving kindness,\nfor his wonderful deeds to the children of men!\n'),
	(10918, 16, 107, 22, 'Let them offer the sacrifices of thanksgiving,\nand declare his deeds with singing.\n'),
	(10919, 16, 107, 23, 'Those who go down to the sea in ships,\nwho do business in great waters;\n'),
	(10920, 16, 107, 24, 'These see Yahweh’s deeds,\nand his wonders in the deep.\n'),
	(10921, 16, 107, 25, 'For he commands, and raises the stormy wind,\nwhich lifts up its waves.\n'),
	(10922, 16, 107, 26, 'They mount up to the sky; they go down again to the depths.\nTheir soul melts away because of trouble.\n'),
	(10923, 16, 107, 27, 'They reel back and forth, and stagger like a drunken man,\nand are at their wits’ end.\n'),
	(10924, 16, 107, 28, 'Then they cry to Yahweh in their trouble,\nand he brings them out of their distress.\n'),
	(10925, 16, 107, 29, 'He makes the storm a calm,\nso that its waves are still.\n'),
	(10926, 16, 107, 30, 'Then they are glad because it is calm,\nso he brings them to their desired haven.\n'),
	(10927, 16, 107, 31, 'Let them praise Yahweh for his loving kindness,\nfor his wonderful deeds for the children of men!\n'),
	(10928, 16, 107, 32, 'Let them exalt him also in the assembly of the people,\nand praise him in the seat of the elders.\n'),
	(10929, 16, 107, 33, 'He turns rivers into a desert,\nwater springs into a thirsty ground,\n'),
	(10930, 16, 107, 34, 'and a fruitful land into a salt waste,\nfor the wickedness of those who dwell in it.\n'),
	(10931, 16, 107, 35, 'He turns a desert into a pool of water,\nand a dry land into water springs.\n'),
	(10932, 16, 107, 36, 'There he makes the hungry live,\nthat they may prepare a city to live in,\n'),
	(10933, 16, 107, 37, 'sow fields, plant vineyards,\nand reap the fruits of increase.\n'),
	(10934, 16, 107, 38, 'He blesses them also, so that they are multiplied greatly.\nHe doesn’t allow their livestock to decrease.\n'),
	(10935, 16, 107, 39, 'Again, they are diminished and bowed down\nthrough oppression, trouble, and sorrow.\n'),
	(10936, 16, 107, 40, 'He pours contempt on princes,\nand causes them to wander in a trackless waste.\n'),
	(10937, 16, 107, 41, 'Yet he lifts the needy out of their affliction,\nand increases their families like a flock.\n'),
	(10938, 16, 107, 42, 'The upright will see it, and be glad.\nAll the wicked will shut their mouths.\n'),
	(10939, 16, 107, 43, 'Whoever is wise will pay attention to these things.\nThey will consider the loving kindnesses of Yahweh.\n'),
	(10940, 16, 108, 1, 'My heart is steadfast, God.\nI will sing and I will make music with my soul.\n'),
	(10941, 16, 108, 2, 'Wake up, harp and lyre!\nI will wake up the dawn.\n'),
	(10942, 16, 108, 3, 'I will give thanks to you, Yahweh, among the nations.\nI will sing praises to you among the peoples.\n'),
	(10943, 16, 108, 4, 'For your loving kindness is great above the heavens.\nYour faithfulness reaches to the skies.\n'),
	(10944, 16, 108, 5, 'Be exalted, God, above the heavens!\nLet your glory be over all the earth.\n'),
	(10945, 16, 108, 6, 'That your beloved may be delivered,\nsave with your right hand, and answer us.\n'),
	(10946, 16, 108, 7, 'God has spoken from his sanctuary: “In triumph,\nI will divide Shechem, and measure out the valley of Succoth.\n'),
	(10947, 16, 108, 8, 'Gilead is mine. Manasseh is mine.\nEphraim also is my helmet.\nJudah is my scepter.\n'),
	(10948, 16, 108, 9, 'Moab is my wash pot.\nI will toss my sandal on Edom.\nI will shout over Philistia.”\n'),
	(10949, 16, 108, 10, 'Who will bring me into the fortified city?\nWho has led me to Edom?\n'),
	(10950, 16, 108, 11, 'Haven’t you rejected us, God?\nYou don’t go out, God, with our armies.\n'),
	(10951, 16, 108, 12, 'Give us help against the enemy,\nfor the help of man is vain.\n'),
	(10952, 16, 108, 13, 'Through God, we will do valiantly.\nFor it is he who will tread down our enemies.\n'),
	(10953, 16, 109, 1, 'God of my praise, don’t remain silent,\n'),
	(10954, 16, 109, 2, 'for they have opened the mouth of the wicked and the mouth of deceit against me.\nThey have spoken to me with a lying tongue.\n'),
	(10955, 16, 109, 3, 'They have also surrounded me with words of hatred,\nand fought against me without a cause.\n'),
	(10956, 16, 109, 4, 'In return for my love, they are my adversaries;\nbut I am in prayer.\n'),
	(10957, 16, 109, 5, 'They have rewarded me evil for good,\nand hatred for my love.\n'),
	(10958, 16, 109, 6, 'Set a wicked man over him.\nLet an adversary stand at his right hand.\n'),
	(10959, 16, 109, 7, 'When he is judged, let him come out guilty.\nLet his prayer be turned into sin.\n'),
	(10960, 16, 109, 8, 'Let his days be few.\nLet another take his office.\n'),
	(10961, 16, 109, 9, 'Let his children be fatherless,\nand his wife a widow.\n'),
	(10962, 16, 109, 10, 'Let his children be wandering beggars.\nLet them be sought from their ruins.\n'),
	(10963, 16, 109, 11, 'Let the creditor seize all that he has.\nLet strangers plunder the fruit of his labor.\n'),
	(10964, 16, 109, 12, 'Let there be no one to extend kindness to him,\nneither let there be anyone to have pity on his fatherless children.\n'),
	(10965, 16, 109, 13, 'Let his posterity be cut off.\nIn the generation following let their name be blotted out.\n'),
	(10966, 16, 109, 14, 'Let the iniquity of his fathers be remembered by Yahweh.\nDon’t let the sin of his mother be blotted out.\n'),
	(10967, 16, 109, 15, 'Let them be before Yahweh continually,\nthat he may cut off their memory from the earth;\n'),
	(10968, 16, 109, 16, 'because he didn’t remember to show kindness,\nbut persecuted the poor and needy man,\nthe broken in heart, to kill them.\n'),
	(10969, 16, 109, 17, 'Yes, he loved cursing, and it came to him.\nHe didn’t delight in blessing, and it was far from him.\n'),
	(10970, 16, 109, 18, 'He clothed himself also with cursing as with his garment.\nIt came into his inward parts like water,\nlike oil into his bones.\n'),
	(10971, 16, 109, 19, 'Let it be to him as the clothing with which he covers himself,\nfor the belt that is always around him.\n'),
	(10972, 16, 109, 20, 'This is the reward of my adversaries from Yahweh,\nof those who speak evil against my soul.\n'),
	(10973, 16, 109, 21, 'But deal with me, Yahweh the Lord, for your name’s sake,\nbecause your loving kindness is good, deliver me;\n'),
	(10974, 16, 109, 22, 'for I am poor and needy.\nMy heart is wounded within me.\n'),
	(10975, 16, 109, 23, 'I fade away like an evening shadow.\nI am shaken off like a locust.\n'),
	(10976, 16, 109, 24, 'My knees are weak through fasting.\nMy body is thin and lacks fat.\n'),
	(10977, 16, 109, 25, 'I have also become a reproach to them.\nWhen they see me, they shake their head.\n'),
	(10978, 16, 109, 26, 'Help me, Yahweh, my God.\nSave me according to your loving kindness;\n'),
	(10979, 16, 109, 27, 'that they may know that this is your hand;\nthat you, Yahweh, have done it.\n'),
	(10980, 16, 109, 28, 'They may curse, but you bless.\nWhen they arise, they will be shamed,\nbut your servant shall rejoice.\n'),
	(10981, 16, 109, 29, 'Let my adversaries be clothed with dishonor.\nLet them cover themselves with their own shame as with a robe.\n'),
	(10982, 16, 109, 30, 'I will give great thanks to Yahweh with my mouth.\nYes, I will praise him among the multitude.\n'),
	(10983, 16, 109, 31, 'For he will stand at the right hand of the needy,\nto save him from those who judge his soul.\n'),
	(10984, 16, 110, 1, 'Yahweh says to my Lord, “Sit at my right hand,\nuntil I make your enemies your footstool for your feet.”\n'),
	(10985, 16, 110, 2, 'Yahweh will send out the rod of your strength out of Zion.\nRule among your enemies.\n'),
	(10986, 16, 110, 3, 'Your people offer themselves willingly in the day of your power, in holy array.\nOut of the womb of the morning, you have the dew of your youth.\n'),
	(10987, 16, 110, 4, 'Yahweh has sworn, and will not change his mind:\n“You are a priest forever in the order of Melchizedek.”\n'),
	(10988, 16, 110, 5, 'The Lord is at your right hand.\nHe will crush kings in the day of his wrath.\n'),
	(10989, 16, 110, 6, 'He will judge among the nations.\nHe will heap up dead bodies.\nHe will crush the ruler of the whole earth.\n'),
	(10990, 16, 110, 7, 'He will drink of the brook on the way;\ntherefore he will lift up his head.\n'),
	(10991, 16, 111, 1, 'Praise Yah!\nI will give thanks to Yahweh with my whole heart,\nin the council of the upright, and in the congregation.\n'),
	(10992, 16, 111, 2, 'Yahweh’s works are great,\npondered by all those who delight in them.\n'),
	(10993, 16, 111, 3, 'His work is honor and majesty.\nHis righteousness endures forever.\n'),
	(10994, 16, 111, 4, 'He has caused his wonderful works to be remembered.\nYahweh is gracious and merciful.\n'),
	(10995, 16, 111, 5, 'He has given food to those who fear him.\nHe always remembers his covenant.\n'),
	(10996, 16, 111, 6, 'He has shown his people the power of his works,\nin giving them the heritage of the nations.\n'),
	(10997, 16, 111, 7, 'The works of his hands are truth and justice.\nAll his precepts are sure.\n'),
	(10998, 16, 111, 8, 'They are established forever and ever.\nThey are done in truth and uprightness.\n'),
	(10999, 16, 111, 9, 'He has sent redemption to his people.\nHe has ordained his covenant forever.\nHis name is holy and awesome!\n'),
	(11000, 16, 111, 10, 'The fear of Yahweh is the beginning of wisdom.\nAll those who do his work have a good understanding.\nHis praise endures forever!\n'),
	(11001, 16, 112, 1, 'Praise Yah!\nBlessed is the man who fears Yahweh,\nwho delights greatly in his commandments.\n'),
	(11002, 16, 112, 2, 'His offspring will be mighty in the land.\nThe generation of the upright will be blessed.\n'),
	(11003, 16, 112, 3, 'Wealth and riches are in his house.\nHis righteousness endures forever.\n'),
	(11004, 16, 112, 4, 'Light dawns in the darkness for the upright,\ngracious, merciful, and righteous.\n'),
	(11005, 16, 112, 5, 'It is well with the man who deals graciously and lends.\nHe will maintain his cause in judgment.\n'),
	(11006, 16, 112, 6, 'For he will never be shaken.\nThe righteous will be remembered forever.\n'),
	(11007, 16, 112, 7, 'He will not be afraid of evil news.\nHis heart is steadfast, trusting in Yahweh.\n'),
	(11008, 16, 112, 8, 'His heart is established.\nHe will not be afraid in the end when he sees his adversaries.\n'),
	(11009, 16, 112, 9, 'He has dispersed, he has given to the poor.\nHis righteousness endures forever.\nHis horn will be exalted with honor.\n'),
	(11010, 16, 112, 10, 'The wicked will see it, and be grieved.\nHe shall gnash with his teeth, and melt away.\nThe desire of the wicked will perish.\n'),
	(11011, 16, 113, 1, 'Praise Yah!\nPraise, you servants of Yahweh,\npraise Yahweh’s name.\n'),
	(11012, 16, 113, 2, 'Blessed be Yahweh’s name,\nfrom this time forward and forever more.\n'),
	(11013, 16, 113, 3, 'From the rising of the sun to the going down of the same,\nYahweh’s name is to be praised.\n'),
	(11014, 16, 113, 4, 'Yahweh is high above all nations,\nhis glory above the heavens.\n'),
	(11015, 16, 113, 5, 'Who is like Yahweh, our God,\nwho has his seat on high,\n'),
	(11016, 16, 113, 6, 'Who stoops down to see in heaven and in the earth?\n'),
	(11017, 16, 113, 7, 'He raises up the poor out of the dust.\nLifts up the needy from the ash heap;\n'),
	(11018, 16, 113, 8, 'that he may set him with princes,\neven with the princes of his people.\n'),
	(11019, 16, 113, 9, 'He settles the barren woman in her home,\nas a joyful mother of children.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11020, 16, 114, 1, 'When Israel went out of Egypt,\nthe house of Jacob from a people of foreign language;\n'),
	(11021, 16, 114, 2, 'Judah became his sanctuary,\nIsrael his dominion.\n'),
	(11022, 16, 114, 3, 'The sea saw it, and fled.\nThe Jordan was driven back.\n'),
	(11023, 16, 114, 4, 'The mountains skipped like rams,\nthe little hills like lambs.\n'),
	(11024, 16, 114, 5, 'What was it, you sea, that you fled?\nYou Jordan, that you turned back?\n'),
	(11025, 16, 114, 6, 'You mountains, that you skipped like rams;\nyou little hills, like lambs?\n'),
	(11026, 16, 114, 7, 'Tremble, you earth, at the presence of the Lord,\nat the presence of the God of Jacob,\n'),
	(11027, 16, 114, 8, 'who turned the rock into a pool of water,\nthe flint into a spring of waters.\n'),
	(11028, 16, 115, 1, 'Not to us, Yahweh, not to us,\nbut to your name give glory,\nfor your loving kindness, and for your truth’s sake.\n'),
	(11029, 16, 115, 2, 'Why should the nations say,\n“Where is their God, now?”\n'),
	(11030, 16, 115, 3, 'But our God is in the heavens.\nHe does whatever he pleases.\n'),
	(11031, 16, 115, 4, 'Their idols are silver and gold,\nthe work of men’s hands.\n'),
	(11032, 16, 115, 5, 'They have mouths, but they don’t speak.\nThey have eyes, but they don’t see.\n'),
	(11033, 16, 115, 6, 'They have ears, but they don’t hear.\nThey have noses, but they don’t smell.\n'),
	(11034, 16, 115, 7, 'They have hands, but they don’t feel.\nThey have feet, but they don’t walk,\nneither do they speak through their throat.\n'),
	(11035, 16, 115, 8, 'Those who make them will be like them;\nyes, everyone who trusts in them.\n'),
	(11036, 16, 115, 9, 'Israel, trust in Yahweh!\nHe is their help and their shield.\n'),
	(11037, 16, 115, 10, 'House of Aaron, trust in Yahweh!\nHe is their help and their shield.\n'),
	(11038, 16, 115, 11, 'You who fear Yahweh, trust in Yahweh!\nHe is their help and their shield.\n'),
	(11039, 16, 115, 12, 'Yahweh remembers us. He will bless us.\nHe will bless the house of Israel.\nHe will bless the house of Aaron.\n'),
	(11040, 16, 115, 13, 'He will bless those who fear Yahweh,\nboth small and great.\n'),
	(11041, 16, 115, 14, 'May Yahweh increase you more and more,\nyou and your children.\n'),
	(11042, 16, 115, 15, 'Blessed are you by Yahweh,\nwho made heaven and earth.\n'),
	(11043, 16, 115, 16, 'The heavens are the heavens of Yahweh;\nbut the earth has he given to the children of men.\n'),
	(11044, 16, 115, 17, 'The dead don’t praise Yah,\nneither any who go down into silence;\n'),
	(11045, 16, 115, 18, 'But we will bless Yah,\nfrom this time forward and forever more.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11046, 16, 116, 1, 'I love Yahweh, because he listens to my voice,\nand my cries for mercy.\n'),
	(11047, 16, 116, 2, 'Because he has turned his ear to me,\ntherefore I will call on him as long as I live.\n'),
	(11048, 16, 116, 3, 'The cords of death surrounded me,\nthe pains of Sheol got a hold of me.\nI found trouble and sorrow.\n'),
	(11049, 16, 116, 4, 'Then I called on Yahweh’s name:\n“Yahweh, I beg you, deliver my soul.”\n'),
	(11050, 16, 116, 5, 'Yahweh is Gracious and righteous.\nYes, our God is merciful.\n'),
	(11051, 16, 116, 6, 'Yahweh preserves the simple.\nI was brought low, and he saved me.\n'),
	(11052, 16, 116, 7, 'Return to your rest, my soul,\nfor Yahweh has dealt bountifully with you.\n'),
	(11053, 16, 116, 8, 'For you have delivered my soul from death,\nmy eyes from tears,\nand my feet from falling.\n'),
	(11054, 16, 116, 9, 'I will walk before Yahweh in the land of the living.\n'),
	(11055, 16, 116, 10, 'I believed, therefore I said,\n“I was greatly afflicted.”\n'),
	(11056, 16, 116, 11, 'I said in my haste,\n“All men are liars.”\n'),
	(11057, 16, 116, 12, 'What will I give to Yahweh for all his benefits toward me?\n'),
	(11058, 16, 116, 13, 'I will take the cup of salvation, and call on Yahweh’s name.\n'),
	(11059, 16, 116, 14, 'I will pay my vows to Yahweh,\nyes, in the presence of all his people.\n'),
	(11060, 16, 116, 15, 'Precious in Yahweh’s sight is the death of his saints.\n'),
	(11061, 16, 116, 16, 'Yahweh, truly I am your servant.\nI am your servant, the son of your servant.\nYou have freed me from my chains.\n'),
	(11062, 16, 116, 17, 'I will offer to you the sacrifice of thanksgiving,\nand will call on Yahweh’s name.\n'),
	(11063, 16, 116, 18, 'I will pay my vows to Yahweh,\nyes, in the presence of all his people,\n'),
	(11064, 16, 116, 19, 'in the courts of Yahweh’s house,\nin the middle of you, Jerusalem.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11065, 16, 117, 1, 'Praise Yahweh, all you nations!\nExtol him, all you peoples!\n'),
	(11066, 16, 117, 2, 'For his loving kindness is great toward us.\nYahweh’s faithfulness endures forever.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11067, 16, 118, 1, 'Give thanks to Yahweh, for he is good,\nfor his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(11068, 16, 118, 2, 'Let Israel now say\nthat his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(11069, 16, 118, 3, 'Let the house of Aaron now say\nthat his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(11070, 16, 118, 4, 'Now let those who fear Yahweh say\nthat his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(11071, 16, 118, 5, 'Out of my distress, I called on Yah.\nYah answered me with freedom.\n'),
	(11072, 16, 118, 6, 'Yahweh is on my side. I will not be afraid.\nWhat can man do to me?\n'),
	(11073, 16, 118, 7, 'Yahweh is on my side among those who help me.\nTherefore I will look in triumph at those who hate me.\n'),
	(11074, 16, 118, 8, 'It is better to take refuge in Yahweh,\nthan to put confidence in man.\n'),
	(11075, 16, 118, 9, 'It is better to take refuge in Yahweh,\nthan to put confidence in princes.\n'),
	(11076, 16, 118, 10, 'All the nations surrounded me,\nbut in Yahweh’s name, I cut them off.\n'),
	(11077, 16, 118, 11, 'They surrounded me, yes, they surrounded me.\nIn Yahweh’s name I indeed cut them off.\n'),
	(11078, 16, 118, 12, 'They surrounded me like bees.\nThey are quenched like the burning thorns.\nIn Yahweh’s name I cut them off.\n'),
	(11079, 16, 118, 13, 'You pushed me back hard, to make me fall,\nbut Yahweh helped me.\n'),
	(11080, 16, 118, 14, 'Yah is my strength and song.\nHe has become my salvation.\n'),
	(11081, 16, 118, 15, 'The voice of rejoicing and salvation is in the tents of the righteous.\n“The right hand of Yahweh does valiantly.\n'),
	(11082, 16, 118, 16, 'The right hand of Yahweh is exalted!\nThe right hand of Yahweh does valiantly!”\n'),
	(11083, 16, 118, 17, 'I will not die, but live,\nand declare Yah’s works.\n'),
	(11084, 16, 118, 18, 'Yah has punished me severely,\nbut he has not given me over to death.\n'),
	(11085, 16, 118, 19, 'Open to me the gates of righteousness.\nI will enter into them.\nI will give thanks to Yah.\n'),
	(11086, 16, 118, 20, 'This is the gate of Yahweh;\nthe righteous will enter into it.\n'),
	(11087, 16, 118, 21, 'I will give thanks to you, for you have answered me,\nand have become my salvation.\n'),
	(11088, 16, 118, 22, 'The stone which the builders rejected\nhas become the cornerstone.\n'),
	(11089, 16, 118, 23, 'This is Yahweh’s doing.\nIt is marvelous in our eyes.\n'),
	(11090, 16, 118, 24, 'This is the day that Yahweh has made.\nWe will rejoice and be glad in it!\n'),
	(11091, 16, 118, 25, 'Save us now, we beg you, Yahweh!\nYahweh, we beg you, send prosperity now.\n'),
	(11092, 16, 118, 26, 'Blessed is he who comes in Yahweh’s name!\nWe have blessed you out of Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(11093, 16, 118, 27, 'Yahweh is God, and he has given us light.\nBind the sacrifice with cords, even to the horns of the altar.\n'),
	(11094, 16, 118, 28, 'You are my God, and I will give thanks to you.\nYou are my God, I will exalt you.\n'),
	(11095, 16, 118, 29, 'Oh give thanks to Yahweh, for he is good,\nfor his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(11096, 16, 119, 1, 'Blessed are those whose ways are blameless,\nwho walk according to Yahweh’s law.\n'),
	(11097, 16, 119, 2, 'Blessed are those who keep his statutes,\nwho seek him with their whole heart.\n'),
	(11098, 16, 119, 3, 'Yes, they do nothing wrong.\nThey walk in his ways.\n'),
	(11099, 16, 119, 4, 'You have commanded your precepts,\nthat we should fully obey them.\n'),
	(11100, 16, 119, 5, 'Oh that my ways were steadfast\nto obey your statutes!\n'),
	(11101, 16, 119, 6, 'Then I wouldn’t be disappointed,\nwhen I consider all of your commandments.\n'),
	(11102, 16, 119, 7, 'I will give thanks to you with uprightness of heart,\nwhen I learn your righteous judgments.\n'),
	(11103, 16, 119, 8, 'I will observe your statutes.\nDon’t utterly forsake me.\n'),
	(11104, 16, 119, 9, 'How can a young man keep his way pure?\nBy living according to your word.\n'),
	(11105, 16, 119, 10, 'With my whole heart, I have sought you.\nDon’t let me wander from your commandments.\n'),
	(11106, 16, 119, 11, 'I have hidden your word in my heart,\nthat I might not sin against you.\n'),
	(11107, 16, 119, 12, 'Blessed are you, Yahweh.\nTeach me your statutes.\n'),
	(11108, 16, 119, 13, 'With my lips,\nI have declared all the ordinances of your mouth.\n'),
	(11109, 16, 119, 14, 'I have rejoiced in the way of your testimonies,\nas much as in all riches.\n'),
	(11110, 16, 119, 15, 'I will meditate on your precepts,\nand consider your ways.\n'),
	(11111, 16, 119, 16, 'I will delight myself in your statutes.\nI will not forget your word.\n'),
	(11112, 16, 119, 17, 'Do good to your servant.\nI will live and I will obey your word.\n'),
	(11113, 16, 119, 18, 'Open my eyes,\nthat I may see wondrous things out of your law.\n'),
	(11114, 16, 119, 19, 'I am a stranger on the earth.\nDon’t hide your commandments from me.\n'),
	(11115, 16, 119, 20, 'My soul is consumed with longing for your ordinances at all times.\n'),
	(11116, 16, 119, 21, 'You have rebuked the proud who are cursed,\nwho wander from your commandments.\n'),
	(11117, 16, 119, 22, 'Take reproach and contempt away from me,\nfor I have kept your statutes.\n'),
	(11118, 16, 119, 23, 'Though princes sit and slander me,\nyour servant will meditate on your statutes.\n'),
	(11119, 16, 119, 24, 'Indeed your statutes are my delight,\nand my counselors.\n'),
	(11120, 16, 119, 25, 'My soul is laid low in the dust.\nRevive me according to your word!\n'),
	(11121, 16, 119, 26, 'I declared my ways, and you answered me.\nTeach me your statutes.\n'),
	(11122, 16, 119, 27, 'Let me understand the teaching of your precepts!\nThen I will meditate on your wondrous works.\n'),
	(11123, 16, 119, 28, 'My soul is weary with sorrow:\nstrengthen me according to your word.\n'),
	(11124, 16, 119, 29, 'Keep me from the way of deceit.\nGrant me your law graciously!\n'),
	(11125, 16, 119, 30, 'I have chosen the way of truth.\nI have set your ordinances before me.\n'),
	(11126, 16, 119, 31, 'I cling to your statutes, Yahweh.\nDon’t let me be disappointed.\n'),
	(11127, 16, 119, 32, 'I run in the path of your commandments,\nfor you have set my heart free.\n'),
	(11128, 16, 119, 33, 'Teach me, Yahweh, the way of your statutes.\nI will keep them to the end.\n'),
	(11129, 16, 119, 34, 'Give me understanding, and I will keep your law.\nYes, I will obey it with my whole heart.\n'),
	(11130, 16, 119, 35, 'Direct me in the path of your commandments,\nfor I delight in them.\n'),
	(11131, 16, 119, 36, 'Turn my heart toward your statutes,\nnot toward selfish gain.\n'),
	(11132, 16, 119, 37, 'Turn my eyes away from looking at worthless things.\nRevive me in your ways.\n'),
	(11133, 16, 119, 38, 'Fulfill your promise to your servant,\nthat you may be feared.\n'),
	(11134, 16, 119, 39, 'Take away my disgrace that I dread,\nfor your ordinances are good.\n'),
	(11135, 16, 119, 40, 'Behold, I long for your precepts!\nRevive me in your righteousness.\n'),
	(11136, 16, 119, 41, 'Let your loving kindness also come to me, Yahweh,\nyour salvation, according to your word.\n'),
	(11137, 16, 119, 42, 'So I will have an answer for him who reproaches me,\nfor I trust in your word.\n'),
	(11138, 16, 119, 43, 'Don’t snatch the word of truth out of my mouth,\nfor I put my hope in your ordinances.\n'),
	(11139, 16, 119, 44, 'So I will obey your law continually,\nforever and ever.\n'),
	(11140, 16, 119, 45, 'I will walk in liberty,\nfor I have sought your precepts.\n'),
	(11141, 16, 119, 46, 'I will also speak of your statutes before kings,\nand will not be disappointed.\n'),
	(11142, 16, 119, 47, 'I will delight myself in your commandments,\nbecause I love them.\n'),
	(11143, 16, 119, 48, 'I reach out my hands for your commandments, which I love.\nI will meditate on your statutes.\n'),
	(11144, 16, 119, 49, 'Remember your word to your servant,\nbecause you gave me hope.\n'),
	(11145, 16, 119, 50, 'This is my comfort in my affliction,\nfor your word has revived me.\n'),
	(11146, 16, 119, 51, 'The arrogant mock me excessively,\nbut I don’t swerve from your law.\n'),
	(11147, 16, 119, 52, 'I remember your ordinances of old, Yahweh,\nand have comforted myself.\n'),
	(11148, 16, 119, 53, 'Indignation has taken hold on me,\nbecause of the wicked who forsake your law.\n'),
	(11149, 16, 119, 54, 'Your statutes have been my songs,\nin the house where I live.\n'),
	(11150, 16, 119, 55, 'I have remembered your name, Yahweh, in the night,\nand I obey your law.\n'),
	(11151, 16, 119, 56, 'This is my way,\nthat I keep your precepts.\n'),
	(11152, 16, 119, 57, 'Yahweh is my portion.\nI promised to obey your words.\n'),
	(11153, 16, 119, 58, 'I sought your favor with my whole heart.\nBe merciful to me according to your word.\n'),
	(11154, 16, 119, 59, 'I considered my ways,\nand turned my steps to your statutes.\n'),
	(11155, 16, 119, 60, 'I will hurry, and not delay,\nto obey your commandments.\n'),
	(11156, 16, 119, 61, 'The ropes of the wicked bind me,\nbut I won’t forget your law.\n'),
	(11157, 16, 119, 62, 'At midnight I will rise to give thanks to you,\nbecause of your righteous ordinances.\n'),
	(11158, 16, 119, 63, 'I am a friend of all those who fear you,\nof those who observe your precepts.\n'),
	(11159, 16, 119, 64, 'The earth is full of your loving kindness, Yahweh.\nTeach me your statutes.\n'),
	(11160, 16, 119, 65, 'Do good to your servant,\naccording to your word, Yahweh.\n'),
	(11161, 16, 119, 66, 'Teach me good judgment and knowledge,\nfor I believe in your commandments.\n'),
	(11162, 16, 119, 67, 'Before I was afflicted, I went astray;\nbut now I observe your word.\n'),
	(11163, 16, 119, 68, 'You are good, and do good.\nTeach me your statutes.\n'),
	(11164, 16, 119, 69, 'The proud have smeared a lie upon me.\nWith my whole heart, I will keep your precepts.\n'),
	(11165, 16, 119, 70, 'Their heart is as callous as the fat,\nbut I delight in your law.\n'),
	(11166, 16, 119, 71, 'It is good for me that I have been afflicted,\nthat I may learn your statutes.\n'),
	(11167, 16, 119, 72, 'The law of your mouth is better to me than thousands of pieces of gold and silver.\n'),
	(11168, 16, 119, 73, 'Your hands have made me and formed me.\nGive me understanding, that I may learn your commandments.\n'),
	(11169, 16, 119, 74, 'Those who fear you will see me and be glad,\nbecause I have put my hope in your word.\n'),
	(11170, 16, 119, 75, 'Yahweh, I know that your judgments are righteous,\nthat in faithfulness you have afflicted me.\n'),
	(11171, 16, 119, 76, 'Please let your loving kindness be for my comfort,\naccording to your word to your servant.\n'),
	(11172, 16, 119, 77, 'Let your tender mercies come to me, that I may live;\nfor your law is my delight.\n'),
	(11173, 16, 119, 78, 'Let the proud be disappointed, for they have overthrown me wrongfully.\nI will meditate on your precepts.\n'),
	(11174, 16, 119, 79, 'Let those who fear you turn to me.\nThey will know your statutes.\n'),
	(11175, 16, 119, 80, 'Let my heart be blameless toward your decrees,\nthat I may not be disappointed.\n'),
	(11176, 16, 119, 81, 'My soul faints for your salvation.\nI hope in your word.\n'),
	(11177, 16, 119, 82, 'My eyes fail for your word.\nI say, “When will you comfort me?”\n'),
	(11178, 16, 119, 83, 'For I have become like a wineskin in the smoke.\nI don’t forget your statutes.\n'),
	(11179, 16, 119, 84, 'How many are the days of your servant?\nWhen will you execute judgment on those who persecute me?\n'),
	(11180, 16, 119, 85, 'The proud have dug pits for me,\ncontrary to your law.\n'),
	(11181, 16, 119, 86, 'All of your commandments are faithful.\nThey persecute me wrongfully.\nHelp me!\n'),
	(11182, 16, 119, 87, 'They had almost wiped me from the earth,\nbut I didn’t forsake your precepts.\n'),
	(11183, 16, 119, 88, 'Preserve my life according to your loving kindness,\nso I will obey the statutes of your mouth.\n'),
	(11184, 16, 119, 89, 'Yahweh, your word is settled in heaven forever.\n'),
	(11185, 16, 119, 90, 'Your faithfulness is to all generations.\nYou have established the earth, and it remains.\n'),
	(11186, 16, 119, 91, 'Your laws remain to this day,\nfor all things serve you.\n'),
	(11187, 16, 119, 92, 'Unless your law had been my delight,\nI would have perished in my affliction.\n'),
	(11188, 16, 119, 93, 'I will never forget your precepts,\nfor with them, you have revived me.\n'),
	(11189, 16, 119, 94, 'I am yours.\nSave me, for I have sought your precepts.\n'),
	(11190, 16, 119, 95, 'The wicked have waited for me, to destroy me.\nI will consider your statutes.\n'),
	(11191, 16, 119, 96, 'I have seen a limit to all perfection,\nbut your commands are boundless.\n'),
	(11192, 16, 119, 97, 'How I love your law!\nIt is my meditation all day.\n'),
	(11193, 16, 119, 98, 'Your commandments make me wiser than my enemies,\nfor your commandments are always with me.\n'),
	(11194, 16, 119, 99, 'I have more understanding than all my teachers,\nfor your testimonies are my meditation.\n'),
	(11195, 16, 119, 100, 'I understand more than the aged,\nbecause I have kept your precepts.\n'),
	(11196, 16, 119, 101, 'I have kept my feet from every evil way,\nthat I might observe your word.\n'),
	(11197, 16, 119, 102, 'I have not turned away from your ordinances,\nfor you have taught me.\n'),
	(11198, 16, 119, 103, 'How sweet are your promises to my taste,\nmore than honey to my mouth!\n'),
	(11199, 16, 119, 104, 'Through your precepts, I get understanding;\ntherefore I hate every false way.\n'),
	(11200, 16, 119, 105, 'Your word is a lamp to my feet,\nand a light for my path.\n'),
	(11201, 16, 119, 106, 'I have sworn, and have confirmed it,\nthat I will obey your righteous ordinances.\n'),
	(11202, 16, 119, 107, 'I am afflicted very much.\nRevive me, Yahweh, according to your word.\n'),
	(11203, 16, 119, 108, 'Accept, I beg you, the willing offerings of my mouth.\nYahweh, teach me your ordinances.\n'),
	(11204, 16, 119, 109, 'My soul is continually in my hand,\nyet I won’t forget your law.\n'),
	(11205, 16, 119, 110, 'The wicked have laid a snare for me,\nyet I haven’t gone astray from your precepts.\n'),
	(11206, 16, 119, 111, 'I have taken your testimonies as a heritage forever,\nfor they are the joy of my heart.\n'),
	(11207, 16, 119, 112, 'I have set my heart to perform your statutes forever,\neven to the end.\n'),
	(11208, 16, 119, 113, 'I hate double-minded men,\nbut I love your law.\n'),
	(11209, 16, 119, 114, 'You are my hiding place and my shield.\nI hope in your word.\n'),
	(11210, 16, 119, 115, 'Depart from me, you evildoers,\nthat I may keep the commandments of my God.\n'),
	(11211, 16, 119, 116, 'Uphold me according to your word, that I may live.\nLet me not be ashamed of my hope.\n'),
	(11212, 16, 119, 117, 'Hold me up, and I will be safe,\nand will have respect for your statutes continually.\n'),
	(11213, 16, 119, 118, 'You reject all those who stray from your statutes,\nfor their deceit is in vain.\n'),
	(11214, 16, 119, 119, 'You put away all the wicked of the earth like dross.\nTherefore I love your testimonies.\n'),
	(11215, 16, 119, 120, 'My flesh trembles for fear of you.\nI am afraid of your judgments.\n'),
	(11216, 16, 119, 121, 'I have done what is just and righteous.\nDon’t leave me to my oppressors.\n'),
	(11217, 16, 119, 122, 'Ensure your servant’s well-being.\nDon’t let the proud oppress me.\n'),
	(11218, 16, 119, 123, 'My eyes fail looking for your salvation,\nfor your righteous word.\n'),
	(11219, 16, 119, 124, 'Deal with your servant according to your loving kindness.\nTeach me your statutes.\n'),
	(11220, 16, 119, 125, 'I am your servant. Give me understanding,\nthat I may know your testimonies.\n'),
	(11221, 16, 119, 126, 'It is time to act, Yahweh,\nfor they break your law.\n'),
	(11222, 16, 119, 127, 'Therefore I love your commandments more than gold,\nyes, more than pure gold.\n'),
	(11223, 16, 119, 128, 'Therefore I consider all of your precepts to be right.\nI hate every false way.\n'),
	(11224, 16, 119, 129, 'Your testimonies are wonderful,\ntherefore my soul keeps them.\n'),
	(11225, 16, 119, 130, 'The entrance of your words gives light.\nIt gives understanding to the simple.\n'),
	(11226, 16, 119, 131, 'I opened my mouth wide and panted,\nfor I longed for your commandments.\n'),
	(11227, 16, 119, 132, 'Turn to me, and have mercy on me,\nas you always do to those who love your name.\n'),
	(11228, 16, 119, 133, 'Establish my footsteps in your word.\nDon’t let any iniquity have dominion over me.\n'),
	(11229, 16, 119, 134, 'Redeem me from the oppression of man,\nso I will observe your precepts.\n'),
	(11230, 16, 119, 135, 'Make your face shine on your servant.\nTeach me your statutes.\n'),
	(11231, 16, 119, 136, 'Streams of tears run down my eyes,\nbecause they don’t observe your law.\n'),
	(11232, 16, 119, 137, 'You are righteous, Yahweh.\nYour judgments are upright.\n'),
	(11233, 16, 119, 138, 'You have commanded your statutes in righteousness.\nThey are fully trustworthy.\n'),
	(11234, 16, 119, 139, 'My zeal wears me out,\nbecause my enemies ignore your words.\n'),
	(11235, 16, 119, 140, 'Your promises have been thoroughly tested,\nand your servant loves them.\n'),
	(11236, 16, 119, 141, 'I am small and despised.\nI don’t forget your precepts.\n'),
	(11237, 16, 119, 142, 'Your righteousness is an everlasting righteousness.\nYour law is truth.\n'),
	(11238, 16, 119, 143, 'Trouble and anguish have taken hold of me.\nYour commandments are my delight.\n'),
	(11239, 16, 119, 144, 'Your testimonies are righteous forever.\nGive me understanding, that I may live.\n'),
	(11240, 16, 119, 145, 'I have called with my whole heart.\nAnswer me, Yahweh!\nI will keep your statutes.\n'),
	(11241, 16, 119, 146, 'I have called to you. Save me!\nI will obey your statutes.\n'),
	(11242, 16, 119, 147, 'I rise before dawn and cry for help.\nI put my hope in your words.\n'),
	(11243, 16, 119, 148, 'My eyes stay open through the night watches,\nthat I might meditate on your word.\n'),
	(11244, 16, 119, 149, 'Hear my voice according to your loving kindness.\nRevive me, Yahweh, according to your ordinances.\n'),
	(11245, 16, 119, 150, 'They draw near who follow after wickedness.\nThey are far from your law.\n'),
	(11246, 16, 119, 151, 'You are near, Yahweh.\nAll your commandments are truth.\n'),
	(11247, 16, 119, 152, 'Of old I have known from your testimonies,\nthat you have founded them forever.\n'),
	(11248, 16, 119, 153, 'Consider my affliction, and deliver me,\nfor I don’t forget your law.\n'),
	(11249, 16, 119, 154, 'Plead my cause, and redeem me!\nRevive me according to your promise.\n'),
	(11250, 16, 119, 155, 'Salvation is far from the wicked,\nfor they don’t seek your statutes.\n'),
	(11251, 16, 119, 156, 'Great are your tender mercies, Yahweh.\nRevive me according to your ordinances.\n'),
	(11252, 16, 119, 157, 'Many are my persecutors and my adversaries.\nI haven’t swerved from your testimonies.\n'),
	(11253, 16, 119, 158, 'I look at the faithless with loathing,\nbecause they don’t observe your word.\n'),
	(11254, 16, 119, 159, 'Consider how I love your precepts.\nRevive me, Yahweh, according to your loving kindness.\n'),
	(11255, 16, 119, 160, 'All of your words are truth.\nEvery one of your righteous ordinances endures forever.\n'),
	(11256, 16, 119, 161, 'Princes have persecuted me without a cause,\nbut my heart stands in awe of your words.\n'),
	(11257, 16, 119, 162, 'I rejoice at your word,\nas one who finds great plunder.\n'),
	(11258, 16, 119, 163, 'I hate and abhor falsehood.\nI love your law.\n'),
	(11259, 16, 119, 164, 'Seven times a day, I praise you,\nbecause of your righteous ordinances.\n'),
	(11260, 16, 119, 165, 'Those who love your law have great peace.\nNothing causes them to stumble.\n'),
	(11261, 16, 119, 166, 'I have hoped for your salvation, Yahweh.\nI have done your commandments.\n'),
	(11262, 16, 119, 167, 'My soul has observed your testimonies.\nI love them exceedingly.\n'),
	(11263, 16, 119, 168, 'I have obeyed your precepts and your testimonies,\nfor all my ways are before you.\n'),
	(11264, 16, 119, 169, 'Let my cry come before you, Yahweh.\nGive me understanding according to your word.\n'),
	(11265, 16, 119, 170, 'Let my supplication come before you.\nDeliver me according to your word.\n'),
	(11266, 16, 119, 171, 'Let my lips utter praise,\nfor you teach me your statutes.\n'),
	(11267, 16, 119, 172, 'Let my tongue sing of your word,\nfor all your commandments are righteousness.\n'),
	(11268, 16, 119, 173, 'Let your hand be ready to help me,\nfor I have chosen your precepts.\n'),
	(11269, 16, 119, 174, 'I have longed for your salvation, Yahweh.\nYour law is my delight.\n'),
	(11270, 16, 119, 175, 'Let my soul live, that I may praise you.\nLet your ordinances help me.\n'),
	(11271, 16, 119, 176, 'I have gone astray like a lost sheep.\nSeek your servant, for I don’t forget your commandments.\n'),
	(11272, 16, 120, 1, 'In my distress, I cried to Yahweh.\nHe answered me.\n'),
	(11273, 16, 120, 2, 'Deliver my soul, Yahweh, from lying lips,\nfrom a deceitful tongue.\n'),
	(11274, 16, 120, 3, 'What will be given to you, and what will be done more to you,\nyou deceitful tongue?\n'),
	(11275, 16, 120, 4, 'Sharp arrows of the mighty,\nwith coals of juniper.\n'),
	(11276, 16, 120, 5, 'Woe is me, that I live in Meshech,\nthat I dwell among the tents of Kedar!\n'),
	(11277, 16, 120, 6, 'My soul has had her dwelling too long\nwith him who hates peace.\n'),
	(11278, 16, 120, 7, 'I am for peace,\nbut when I speak, they are for war.\n'),
	(11279, 16, 121, 1, 'I will lift up my eyes to the hills.\nWhere does my help come from?\n'),
	(11280, 16, 121, 2, 'My help comes from Yahweh,\nwho made heaven and earth.\n'),
	(11281, 16, 121, 3, 'He will not allow your foot to be moved.\nHe who keeps you will not slumber.\n'),
	(11282, 16, 121, 4, 'Behold, he who keeps Israel\nwill neither slumber nor sleep.\n'),
	(11283, 16, 121, 5, 'Yahweh is your keeper.\nYahweh is your shade on your right hand.\n'),
	(11284, 16, 121, 6, 'The sun will not harm you by day,\nnor the moon by night.\n'),
	(11285, 16, 121, 7, 'Yahweh will keep you from all evil.\nHe will keep your soul.\n'),
	(11286, 16, 121, 8, 'Yahweh will keep your going out and your coming in,\nfrom this time forward, and forever more.\n'),
	(11287, 16, 122, 1, 'I was glad when they said to me,\n“Let’s go to Yahweh’s house!”\n'),
	(11288, 16, 122, 2, 'Our feet are standing within your gates, Jerusalem;\n'),
	(11289, 16, 122, 3, 'Jerusalem, that is built as a city that is compact together;\n'),
	(11290, 16, 122, 4, 'where the tribes go up, even Yah’s tribes,\naccording to an ordinance for Israel,\nto give thanks to Yahweh’s name.\n'),
	(11291, 16, 122, 5, 'For there are set thrones for judgment,\nthe thrones of David’s house.\n'),
	(11292, 16, 122, 6, 'Pray for the peace of Jerusalem.\nThose who love you will prosper.\n'),
	(11293, 16, 122, 7, 'Peace be within your walls,\nand prosperity within your palaces.\n'),
	(11294, 16, 122, 8, 'For my brothers’ and companions’ sakes,\nI will now say, “Peace be within you.”\n'),
	(11295, 16, 122, 9, 'For the sake of the house of Yahweh our God,\nI will seek your good.\n'),
	(11296, 16, 123, 1, 'To you I do lift up my eyes,\nyou who sit in the heavens.\n'),
	(11297, 16, 123, 2, 'Behold, as the eyes of servants look to the hand of their master,\nas the eyes of a maid to the hand of her mistress;\nso our eyes look to Yahweh, our God,\nuntil he has mercy on us.\n'),
	(11298, 16, 123, 3, 'Have mercy on us, Yahweh, have mercy on us,\nfor we have endured much contempt.\n'),
	(11299, 16, 123, 4, 'Our soul is exceedingly filled with the scoffing of those who are at ease,\nwith the contempt of the proud.\n'),
	(11300, 16, 124, 1, 'If it had not been Yahweh who was on our side,\nlet Israel now say,\n'),
	(11301, 16, 124, 2, 'if it had not been Yahweh who was on our side,\nwhen men rose up against us;\n'),
	(11302, 16, 124, 3, 'then they would have swallowed us up alive,\nwhen their wrath was kindled against us;\n'),
	(11303, 16, 124, 4, 'then the waters would have overwhelmed us,\nthe stream would have gone over our soul;\n'),
	(11304, 16, 124, 5, 'then the proud waters would have gone over our soul.\n'),
	(11305, 16, 124, 6, 'Blessed be Yahweh,\nwho has not given us as a prey to their teeth.\n'),
	(11306, 16, 124, 7, 'Our soul has escaped like a bird out of the fowler’s snare.\nThe snare is broken, and we have escaped.\n'),
	(11307, 16, 124, 8, 'Our help is in Yahweh’s name,\nwho made heaven and earth.\n'),
	(11308, 16, 125, 1, 'Those who trust in Yahweh are as Mount Zion,\nwhich can’t be moved, but remains forever.\n'),
	(11309, 16, 125, 2, 'As the mountains surround Jerusalem,\nso Yahweh surrounds his people from this time forward and forever more.\n'),
	(11310, 16, 125, 3, 'For the scepter of wickedness won’t remain over the allotment of the righteous;\nso that the righteous won’t use their hands to do evil.\n'),
	(11311, 16, 125, 4, 'Do good, Yahweh, to those who are good,\nto those who are upright in their hearts.\n'),
	(11312, 16, 125, 5, 'But as for those who turn away to their crooked ways,\nYahweh will lead them away with the workers of iniquity.\nPeace be on Israel.\n'),
	(11313, 16, 126, 1, 'When Yahweh brought back those who returned to Zion,\nwe were like those who dream.\n'),
	(11314, 16, 126, 2, 'Then our mouth was filled with laughter,\nand our tongue with singing.\nThen they said among the nations,\n“Yahweh has done great things for them.”\n'),
	(11315, 16, 126, 3, 'Yahweh has done great things for us,\nand we are glad.\n'),
	(11316, 16, 126, 4, 'Restore our fortunes again, Yahweh,\nlike the streams in the Negev.\n'),
	(11317, 16, 126, 5, 'Those who sow in tears will reap in joy.\n'),
	(11318, 16, 126, 6, 'He who goes out weeping, carrying seed for sowing,\nwill certainly come again with joy, carrying his sheaves.\n'),
	(11319, 16, 127, 1, 'Unless Yahweh builds the house,\nthey labor in vain who build it.\nUnless Yahweh watches over the city,\nthe watchman guards it in vain.\n'),
	(11320, 16, 127, 2, 'It is vain for you to rise up early,\nto stay up late,\neating the bread of toil;\nfor he gives sleep to his loved ones.\n'),
	(11321, 16, 127, 3, 'Behold, children are a heritage of Yahweh.\nThe fruit of the womb is his reward.\n'),
	(11322, 16, 127, 4, 'As arrows in the hand of a mighty man,\nso are the children of youth.\n'),
	(11323, 16, 127, 5, 'Happy is the man who has his quiver full of them.\nThey won’t be disappointed when they speak with their enemies in the gate.\n'),
	(11324, 16, 128, 1, 'Blessed is everyone who fears Yahweh,\nwho walks in his ways.\n'),
	(11325, 16, 128, 2, 'For you will eat the labor of your hands.\nYou will be happy, and it will be well with you.\n'),
	(11326, 16, 128, 3, 'Your wife will be as a fruitful vine,\nin the innermost parts of your house;\nyour children like olive plants,\naround your table.\n'),
	(11327, 16, 128, 4, 'Behold, thus is the man blessed who fears Yahweh.\n'),
	(11328, 16, 128, 5, 'May Yahweh bless you out of Zion,\nand may you see the good of Jerusalem all the days of your life.\n'),
	(11329, 16, 128, 6, 'Yes, may you see your children’s children.\nPeace be upon Israel.\n'),
	(11330, 16, 129, 1, 'Many times they have afflicted me from my youth up.\nLet Israel now say,\n'),
	(11331, 16, 129, 2, 'many times they have afflicted me from my youth up,\nyet they have not prevailed against me.\n'),
	(11332, 16, 129, 3, 'The plowers plowed on my back.\nThey made their furrows long.\n'),
	(11333, 16, 129, 4, 'Yahweh is righteous.\nHe has cut apart the cords of the wicked.\n'),
	(11334, 16, 129, 5, 'Let them be disappointed and turned backward,\nall those who hate Zion.\n'),
	(11335, 16, 129, 6, 'Let them be as the grass on the housetops,\nwhich withers before it grows up;\n'),
	(11336, 16, 129, 7, 'with which the reaper doesn’t fill his hand,\nnor he who binds sheaves, his bosom.\n'),
	(11337, 16, 129, 8, 'Neither do those who go by say,\n“The blessing of Yahweh be on you.\nWe bless you in Yahweh’s name.”\n'),
	(11338, 16, 130, 1, 'Out of the depths I have cried to you, Yahweh.\n'),
	(11339, 16, 130, 2, 'Lord, hear my voice.\nLet your ears be attentive to the voice of my petitions.\n'),
	(11340, 16, 130, 3, 'If you, Yah, kept a record of sins,\nLord, who could stand?\n'),
	(11341, 16, 130, 4, 'But there is forgiveness with you,\ntherefore you are feared.\n'),
	(11342, 16, 130, 5, 'I wait for Yahweh.\nMy soul waits.\nI hope in his word.\n'),
	(11343, 16, 130, 6, 'My soul longs for the Lord more than watchmen long for the morning;\nmore than watchmen for the morning.\n'),
	(11344, 16, 130, 7, 'Israel, hope in Yahweh,\nfor with Yahweh there is loving kindness.\nWith him is abundant redemption.\n'),
	(11345, 16, 130, 8, 'He will redeem Israel from all their sins.\n'),
	(11346, 16, 131, 1, 'Yahweh, my heart isn’t haughty, nor my eyes lofty;\nnor do I concern myself with great matters,\nor things too wonderful for me.\n'),
	(11347, 16, 131, 2, 'Surely I have stilled and quieted my soul,\nlike a weaned child with his mother,\nlike a weaned child is my soul within me.\n'),
	(11348, 16, 131, 3, 'Israel, hope in Yahweh,\nfrom this time forward and forever more.\n'),
	(11349, 16, 132, 1, 'Yahweh, remember David and all his affliction,\n'),
	(11350, 16, 132, 2, 'how he swore to Yahweh,\nand vowed to the Mighty One of Jacob:\n'),
	(11351, 16, 132, 3, '“Surely I will not come into the structure of my house,\nnor go up into my bed;\n'),
	(11352, 16, 132, 4, 'I will not give sleep to my eyes,\nor slumber to my eyelids;\n'),
	(11353, 16, 132, 5, 'until I find out a place for Yahweh,\na dwelling for the Mighty One of Jacob.”\n'),
	(11354, 16, 132, 6, 'Behold, we heard of it in Ephrathah.\nWe found it in the field of Jaar:\n'),
	(11355, 16, 132, 7, '“We will go into his dwelling place.\nWe will worship at his footstool.\n'),
	(11356, 16, 132, 8, 'Arise, Yahweh, into your resting place;\nyou, and the ark of your strength.\n'),
	(11357, 16, 132, 9, 'Let your priests be clothed with righteousness.\nLet your saints shout for joy!”\n'),
	(11358, 16, 132, 10, 'For your servant David’s sake,\ndon’t turn away the face of your anointed one.\n'),
	(11359, 16, 132, 11, 'Yahweh has sworn to David in truth.\nHe will not turn from it:\n“I will set the fruit of your body on your throne.\n'),
	(11360, 16, 132, 12, 'If your children will keep my covenant,\nmy testimony that I will teach them,\ntheir children also will sit on your throne forever more.”\n'),
	(11361, 16, 132, 13, 'For Yahweh has chosen Zion.\nHe has desired it for his habitation.\n'),
	(11362, 16, 132, 14, '“This is my resting place forever.\nHere I will live, for I have desired it.\n'),
	(11363, 16, 132, 15, 'I will abundantly bless her provision.\nI will satisfy her poor with bread.\n'),
	(11364, 16, 132, 16, 'Her priests I will also clothe with salvation.\nHer saints will shout aloud for joy.\n'),
	(11365, 16, 132, 17, 'There I will make the horn of David to bud.\nI have ordained a lamp for my anointed.\n'),
	(11366, 16, 132, 18, 'I will clothe his enemies with shame,\nbut on himself, his crown will be resplendent.”\n'),
	(11367, 16, 133, 1, 'See how good and how pleasant it is\nfor brothers to live together in unity!\n'),
	(11368, 16, 133, 2, 'It is like the precious oil on the head,\nthat ran down on the beard,\neven Aaron’s beard;\nthat came down on the edge of his robes;\n'),
	(11369, 16, 133, 3, 'like the dew of Hermon,\nthat comes down on the hills of Zion:\nfor there Yahweh gives the blessing,\neven life forever more.\n'),
	(11370, 16, 134, 1, 'Look! Praise Yahweh, all you servants of Yahweh,\nwho stand by night in Yahweh’s house!\n'),
	(11371, 16, 134, 2, 'Lift up your hands in the sanctuary.\nPraise Yahweh!\n'),
	(11372, 16, 134, 3, 'May Yahweh bless you from Zion;\neven he who made heaven and earth.\n'),
	(11373, 16, 135, 1, 'Praise Yah!\nPraise Yahweh’s name!\nPraise him, you servants of Yahweh,\n'),
	(11374, 16, 135, 2, 'you who stand in Yahweh’s house,\nin the courts of our God’s house.\n'),
	(11375, 16, 135, 3, 'Praise Yah, for Yahweh is good.\nSing praises to his name, for that is pleasant.\n'),
	(11376, 16, 135, 4, 'For Yah has chosen Jacob for himself;\nIsrael for his own possession.\n'),
	(11377, 16, 135, 5, 'For I know that Yahweh is great,\nthat our Lord is above all gods.\n'),
	(11378, 16, 135, 6, 'Whatever Yahweh pleased, that he has done,\nin heaven and in earth, in the seas and in all deeps;\n'),
	(11379, 16, 135, 7, 'who causes the clouds to rise from the ends of the earth;\nwho makes lightnings with the rain;\nwho brings the wind out of his treasuries;\n'),
	(11380, 16, 135, 8, 'Who struck the firstborn of Egypt,\nboth of man and animal;\n'),
	(11381, 16, 135, 9, 'Who sent signs and wonders into the middle of you, Egypt,\non Pharaoh, and on all his servants;\n'),
	(11382, 16, 135, 10, 'who struck many nations,\nand killed mighty kings,\n'),
	(11383, 16, 135, 11, 'Sihon king of the Amorites,\nOg king of Bashan,\nand all the kingdoms of Canaan,\n'),
	(11384, 16, 135, 12, 'and gave their land for a heritage,\na heritage to Israel, his people.\n'),
	(11385, 16, 135, 13, 'Your name, Yahweh, endures forever;\nyour renown, Yahweh, throughout all generations.\n'),
	(11386, 16, 135, 14, 'For Yahweh will judge his people,\nand have compassion on his servants.\n'),
	(11387, 16, 135, 15, 'The idols of the nations are silver and gold,\nthe work of men’s hands.\n'),
	(11388, 16, 135, 16, 'They have mouths, but they can’t speak.\nThey have eyes, but they can’t see.\n'),
	(11389, 16, 135, 17, 'They have ears, but they can’t hear;\nneither is there any breath in their mouths.\n'),
	(11390, 16, 135, 18, 'Those who make them will be like them;\nyes, everyone who trusts in them.\n'),
	(11391, 16, 135, 19, 'House of Israel, praise Yahweh!\nHouse of Aaron, praise Yahweh!\n'),
	(11392, 16, 135, 20, 'House of Levi, praise Yahweh!\nYou who fear Yahweh, praise Yahweh!\n'),
	(11393, 16, 135, 21, 'Blessed be Yahweh from Zion,\nWho dwells at Jerusalem.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11394, 16, 136, 1, 'Give thanks to Yahweh, for he is good;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(11395, 16, 136, 2, 'Give thanks to the God of gods;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(11396, 16, 136, 3, 'Give thanks to the Lord of lords;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11397, 16, 136, 4, 'To him who alone does great wonders;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11398, 16, 136, 5, 'To him who by understanding made the heavens;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11399, 16, 136, 6, 'To him who spread out the earth above the waters;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11400, 16, 136, 7, 'To him who made the great lights;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11401, 16, 136, 8, 'The sun to rule by day;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11402, 16, 136, 9, 'The moon and stars to rule by night;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11403, 16, 136, 10, 'To him who struck down the Egyptian firstborn;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11404, 16, 136, 11, 'And brought out Israel from among them;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11405, 16, 136, 12, 'With a strong hand, and with an outstretched arm;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11406, 16, 136, 13, 'To him who divided the Red Sea apart;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11407, 16, 136, 14, 'And made Israel to pass through the middle of it;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11408, 16, 136, 15, 'But overthrew Pharaoh and his army in the Red Sea;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11409, 16, 136, 16, 'To him who led his people through the wilderness;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11410, 16, 136, 17, 'To him who struck great kings;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11411, 16, 136, 18, 'And killed mighty kings;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11412, 16, 136, 19, 'Sihon king of the Amorites;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11413, 16, 136, 20, 'Og king of Bashan;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11414, 16, 136, 21, 'And gave their land as an inheritance;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11415, 16, 136, 22, 'Even a heritage to Israel his servant;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11416, 16, 136, 23, 'Who remembered us in our low estate;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever;\n'),
	(11417, 16, 136, 24, 'And has delivered us from our adversaries;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever:\n'),
	(11418, 16, 136, 25, 'Who gives food to every creature;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(11419, 16, 136, 26, 'Oh give thanks to the God of heaven;\nfor his loving kindness endures forever.\n'),
	(11420, 16, 137, 1, 'By the rivers of Babylon, there we sat down.\nYes, we wept, when we remembered Zion.\n'),
	(11421, 16, 137, 2, 'On the willows in that land,\nwe hung up our harps.\n'),
	(11422, 16, 137, 3, 'For there, those who led us captive asked us for songs.\nThose who tormented us demanded songs of joy:\n“Sing us one of the songs of Zion!”\n'),
	(11423, 16, 137, 4, 'How can we sing Yahweh’s song in a foreign land?\n'),
	(11424, 16, 137, 5, 'If I forget you, Jerusalem,\nlet my right hand forget its skill.\n'),
	(11425, 16, 137, 6, 'Let my tongue stick to the roof of my mouth if I don’t remember you;\nif I don’t prefer Jerusalem above my chief joy.\n'),
	(11426, 16, 137, 7, 'Remember, Yahweh, against the children of Edom,\nthe day of Jerusalem;\nwho said, “Raze it!\nRaze it even to its foundation!”\n'),
	(11427, 16, 137, 8, 'Daughter of Babylon, doomed to destruction,\nhe will be happy who rewards you,\nas you have served us.\n'),
	(11428, 16, 137, 9, 'Happy shall he be,\nwho takes and dashes your little ones against the rock.\n'),
	(11429, 16, 138, 1, 'I will give you thanks with my whole heart.\nBefore the gods, I will sing praises to you.\n'),
	(11430, 16, 138, 2, 'I will bow down toward your holy temple,\nand give thanks to your Name for your loving kindness and for your truth;\nfor you have exalted your Name and your Word above all.\n'),
	(11431, 16, 138, 3, 'In the day that I called, you answered me.\nYou encouraged me with strength in my soul.\n'),
	(11432, 16, 138, 4, 'All the kings of the earth will give you thanks, Yahweh,\nfor they have heard the words of your mouth.\n'),
	(11433, 16, 138, 5, 'Yes, they will sing of the ways of Yahweh;\nfor great is Yahweh’s glory.\n'),
	(11434, 16, 138, 6, 'For though Yahweh is high, yet he looks after the lowly;\nbut the proud, he knows from afar.\n'),
	(11435, 16, 138, 7, 'Though I walk in the middle of trouble, you will revive me.\nYou will stretch out your hand against the wrath of my enemies.\nYour right hand will save me.\n'),
	(11436, 16, 138, 8, 'Yahweh will fulfill that which concerns me;\nyour loving kindness, Yahweh, endures forever.\nDon’t forsake the works of your own hands.\n'),
	(11437, 16, 139, 1, 'Yahweh, you have searched me,\nand you know me.\n'),
	(11438, 16, 139, 2, 'You know my sitting down and my rising up.\nYou perceive my thoughts from afar.\n'),
	(11439, 16, 139, 3, 'You search out my path and my lying down,\nand are acquainted with all my ways.\n'),
	(11440, 16, 139, 4, 'For there is not a word on my tongue,\nbut, behold, Yahweh, you know it altogether.\n'),
	(11441, 16, 139, 5, 'You hem me in behind and before.\nYou laid your hand on me.\n'),
	(11442, 16, 139, 6, 'This knowledge is beyond me.\nIt’s lofty.\nI can’t attain it.\n'),
	(11443, 16, 139, 7, 'Where could I go from your Spirit?\nOr where could I flee from your presence?\n'),
	(11444, 16, 139, 8, 'If I ascend up into heaven, you are there.\nIf I make my bed in Sheol, behold, you are there!\n'),
	(11445, 16, 139, 9, 'If I take the wings of the dawn,\nand settle in the uttermost parts of the sea;\n'),
	(11446, 16, 139, 10, 'Even there your hand will lead me,\nand your right hand will hold me.\n'),
	(11447, 16, 139, 11, 'If I say, “Surely the darkness will overwhelm me;\nthe light around me will be night”;\n'),
	(11448, 16, 139, 12, 'even the darkness doesn’t hide from you,\nbut the night shines as the day.\nThe darkness is like light to you.\n'),
	(11449, 16, 139, 13, 'For you formed my inmost being.\nYou knit me together in my mother’s womb.\n'),
	(11450, 16, 139, 14, 'I will give thanks to you,\nfor I am fearfully and wonderfully made.\nYour works are wonderful.\nMy soul knows that very well.\n'),
	(11451, 16, 139, 15, 'My frame wasn’t hidden from you,\nwhen I was made in secret,\nwoven together in the depths of the earth.\n'),
	(11452, 16, 139, 16, 'Your eyes saw my body.\nIn your book they were all written,\nthe days that were ordained for me,\nwhen as yet there were none of them.\n'),
	(11453, 16, 139, 17, 'How precious to me are your thoughts, God!\nHow vast is their sum!\n'),
	(11454, 16, 139, 18, 'If I would count them, they are more in number than the sand.\nWhen I wake up, I am still with you.\n'),
	(11455, 16, 139, 19, 'If only you, God, would kill the wicked.\nGet away from me, you bloodthirsty men!\n'),
	(11456, 16, 139, 20, 'For they speak against you wickedly.\nYour enemies take your name in vain.\n'),
	(11457, 16, 139, 21, 'Yahweh, don’t I hate those who hate you?\nAm I not grieved with those who rise up against you?\n'),
	(11458, 16, 139, 22, 'I hate them with perfect hatred.\nThey have become my enemies.\n'),
	(11459, 16, 139, 23, 'Search me, God, and know my heart.\nTry me, and know my thoughts.\n'),
	(11460, 16, 139, 24, 'See if there is any wicked way in me,\nand lead me in the everlasting way.\n'),
	(11461, 16, 140, 1, 'Deliver me, Yahweh, from the evil man.\nPreserve me from the violent man;\n'),
	(11462, 16, 140, 2, 'those who devise mischief in their hearts.\nThey continually gather themselves together for war.\n'),
	(11463, 16, 140, 3, 'They have sharpened their tongues like a serpent.\nViper’s poison is under their lips.\nSelah.\n'),
	(11464, 16, 140, 4, 'Yahweh, keep me from the hands of the wicked.\nPreserve me from the violent men who have determined to trip my feet.\n'),
	(11465, 16, 140, 5, 'The proud have hidden a snare for me,\nthey have spread the cords of a net by the path.\nThey have set traps for me.\nSelah.\n'),
	(11466, 16, 140, 6, 'I said to Yahweh, “You are my God.”\nListen to the cry of my petitions, Yahweh.\n'),
	(11467, 16, 140, 7, 'Yahweh, the Lord, the strength of my salvation,\nyou have covered my head in the day of battle.\n'),
	(11468, 16, 140, 8, 'Yahweh, don’t grant the desires of the wicked.\nDon’t let their evil plans succeed, or they will become proud.\nSelah.\n'),
	(11469, 16, 140, 9, 'As for the head of those who surround me,\nlet the mischief of their own lips cover them.\n'),
	(11470, 16, 140, 10, 'Let burning coals fall on them.\nLet them be thrown into the fire,\ninto miry pits, from where they never rise.\n'),
	(11471, 16, 140, 11, 'An evil speaker won’t be established in the earth.\nEvil will hunt the violent man to overthrow him.\n'),
	(11472, 16, 140, 12, 'I know that Yahweh will maintain the cause of the afflicted,\nand justice for the needy.\n'),
	(11473, 16, 140, 13, 'Surely the righteous will give thanks to your name.\nThe upright will dwell in your presence.\n'),
	(11474, 16, 141, 1, 'Yahweh, I have called on you.\nCome to me quickly!\nListen to my voice when I call to you.\n'),
	(11475, 16, 141, 2, 'Let my prayer be set before you like incense;\nthe lifting up of my hands like the evening sacrifice.\n'),
	(11476, 16, 141, 3, 'Set a watch, Yahweh, before my mouth.\nKeep the door of my lips.\n'),
	(11477, 16, 141, 4, 'Don’t incline my heart to any evil thing,\nto practice deeds of wickedness with men who work iniquity.\nDon’t let me eat of their delicacies.\n'),
	(11478, 16, 141, 5, 'Let the righteous strike me, it is kindness;\nlet him reprove me, it is like oil on the head;\ndon’t let my head refuse it;\nYet my prayer is always against evil deeds.\n'),
	(11479, 16, 141, 6, 'Their judges are thrown down by the sides of the rock.\nThey will hear my words, for they are well spoken.\n'),
	(11480, 16, 141, 7, '“As when one plows and breaks up the earth,\nour bones are scattered at the mouth of Sheol.”\n'),
	(11481, 16, 141, 8, 'For my eyes are on you, Yahweh, the Lord.\nIn you, I take refuge.\nDon’t leave my soul destitute.\n'),
	(11482, 16, 141, 9, 'Keep me from the snare which they have laid for me,\nfrom the traps of the workers of iniquity.\n'),
	(11483, 16, 141, 10, 'Let the wicked fall together into their own nets,\nwhile I pass by.\n'),
	(11484, 16, 142, 1, 'I cry with my voice to Yahweh.\nWith my voice, I ask Yahweh for mercy.\n'),
	(11485, 16, 142, 2, 'I pour out my complaint before him.\nI tell him my troubles.\n'),
	(11486, 16, 142, 3, 'When my spirit was overwhelmed within me,\nyou knew my route.\nOn the path in which I walk,\nthey have hidden a snare for me.\n'),
	(11487, 16, 142, 4, 'Look on my right, and see;\nfor there is no one who is concerned for me.\nRefuge has fled from me.\nNo one cares for my soul.\n'),
	(11488, 16, 142, 5, 'I cried to you, Yahweh.\nI said, “You are my refuge,\nmy portion in the land of the living.”\n'),
	(11489, 16, 142, 6, 'Listen to my cry,\nfor I am in desperate need.\ndeliver me from my persecutors,\nFor they are stronger than me.\n'),
	(11490, 16, 142, 7, 'Bring my soul out of prison,\nthat I may give thanks to your name.\nThe righteous will surround me,\nfor you will be good to me.\n'),
	(11491, 16, 143, 1, 'Hear my prayer, Yahweh.\nListen to my petitions.\nIn your faithfulness and righteousness, relieve me.\n'),
	(11492, 16, 143, 2, 'Don’t enter into judgment with your servant,\nfor in your sight no man living is righteous.\n'),
	(11493, 16, 143, 3, 'For the enemy pursues my soul.\nHe has struck my life down to the ground.\nHe has made me live in dark places, as those who have been long dead.\n'),
	(11494, 16, 143, 4, 'Therefore my spirit is overwhelmed within me.\nMy heart within me is desolate.\n'),
	(11495, 16, 143, 5, 'I remember the days of old.\nI meditate on all your doings.\nI contemplate the work of your hands.\n'),
	(11496, 16, 143, 6, 'I spread out my hands to you.\nMy soul thirsts for you, like a parched land.\nSelah.\n'),
	(11497, 16, 143, 7, 'Hurry to answer me, Yahweh.\nMy spirit fails.\nDon’t hide your face from me,\nso that I don’t become like those who go down into the pit.\n'),
	(11498, 16, 143, 8, 'Cause me to hear your loving kindness in the morning,\nfor I trust in you.\nCause me to know the way in which I should walk,\nfor I lift up my soul to you.\n'),
	(11499, 16, 143, 9, 'Deliver me, Yahweh, from my enemies.\nI flee to you to hide me.\n'),
	(11500, 16, 143, 10, 'Teach me to do your will,\nfor you are my God.\nYour Spirit is good.\nLead me in the land of uprightness.\n'),
	(11501, 16, 143, 11, 'Revive me, Yahweh, for your name’s sake.\nIn your righteousness, bring my soul out of trouble.\n'),
	(11502, 16, 143, 12, 'In your loving kindness, cut off my enemies,\nand destroy all those who afflict my soul,\nFor I am your servant.\n'),
	(11503, 16, 144, 1, 'Blessed be Yahweh, my rock,\nwho teaches my hands to war,\nand my fingers to battle:\n'),
	(11504, 16, 144, 2, 'my loving kindness, my fortress,\nmy high tower, my deliverer,\nmy shield, and he in whom I take refuge;\nwho subdues my people under me.\n'),
	(11505, 16, 144, 3, 'Yahweh, what is man, that you care for him?\nOr the son of man, that you think of him?\n'),
	(11506, 16, 144, 4, 'Man is like a breath.\nHis days are like a shadow that passes away.\n'),
	(11507, 16, 144, 5, 'Part your heavens, Yahweh, and come down.\nTouch the mountains, and they will smoke.\n'),
	(11508, 16, 144, 6, 'Throw out lightning, and scatter them.\nSend out your arrows, and rout them.\n'),
	(11509, 16, 144, 7, 'Stretch out your hand from above,\nrescue me, and deliver me out of great waters,\nout of the hands of foreigners;\n'),
	(11510, 16, 144, 8, 'whose mouths speak deceit,\nWhose right hand is a right hand of falsehood.\n'),
	(11511, 16, 144, 9, 'I will sing a new song to you, God.\nOn a ten-stringed lyre, I will sing praises to you.\n'),
	(11512, 16, 144, 10, 'You are he who gives salvation to kings,\nwho rescues David, his servant, from the deadly sword.\n'),
	(11513, 16, 144, 11, 'Rescue me, and deliver me out of the hands of foreigners,\nwhose mouths speak deceit,\nwhose right hand is a right hand of falsehood.\n'),
	(11514, 16, 144, 12, 'Then our sons will be like well-nurtured plants,\nour daughters like pillars carved to adorn a palace.\n'),
	(11515, 16, 144, 13, 'Our barns are full, filled with all kinds of provision.\nOur sheep produce thousands and ten thousands in our fields.\n'),
	(11516, 16, 144, 14, 'Our oxen will pull heavy loads.\nThere is no breaking in, and no going away,\nand no outcry in our streets.\n'),
	(11517, 16, 144, 15, 'Happy are the people who are in such a situation.\nHappy are the people whose God is Yahweh.\n'),
	(11518, 16, 145, 1, 'I will exalt you, my God, the King.\nI will praise your name forever and ever.\n'),
	(11519, 16, 145, 2, 'Every day I will praise you.\nI will extol your name forever and ever.\n'),
	(11520, 16, 145, 3, 'Great is Yahweh, and greatly to be praised!\nHis greatness is unsearchable.\n'),
	(11521, 16, 145, 4, 'One generation will commend your works to another,\nand will declare your mighty acts.\n'),
	(11522, 16, 145, 5, 'Of the glorious majesty of your honor,\nof your wondrous works, I will meditate.\n'),
	(11523, 16, 145, 6, 'Men will speak of the might of your awesome acts.\nI will declare your greatness.\n'),
	(11524, 16, 145, 7, 'They will utter the memory of your great goodness,\nand will sing of your righteousness.\n'),
	(11525, 16, 145, 8, 'Yahweh is gracious, merciful,\nslow to anger, and of great loving kindness.\n'),
	(11526, 16, 145, 9, 'Yahweh is good to all.\nHis tender mercies are over all his works.\n'),
	(11527, 16, 145, 10, 'All your works will give thanks to you, Yahweh.\nYour saints will extol you.\n'),
	(11528, 16, 145, 11, 'They will speak of the glory of your kingdom,\nand talk about your power;\n'),
	(11529, 16, 145, 12, 'to make known to the sons of men his mighty acts,\nthe glory of the majesty of his kingdom.\n'),
	(11530, 16, 145, 13, 'Your kingdom is an everlasting kingdom.\nYour dominion endures throughout all generations.\nYahweh is faithful in all his words,\nand loving in all his deeds.\n'),
	(11531, 16, 145, 14, 'Yahweh upholds all who fall,\nand raises up all those who are bowed down.\n'),
	(11532, 16, 145, 15, 'The eyes of all wait for you.\nYou give them their food in due season.\n'),
	(11533, 16, 145, 16, 'You open your hand,\nand satisfy the desire of every living thing.\n'),
	(11534, 16, 145, 17, 'Yahweh is righteous in all his ways,\nand gracious in all his works.\n'),
	(11535, 16, 145, 18, 'Yahweh is near to all those who call on him,\nto all who call on him in truth.\n'),
	(11536, 16, 145, 19, 'He will fulfill the desire of those who fear him.\nHe also will hear their cry, and will save them.\n'),
	(11537, 16, 145, 20, 'Yahweh preserves all those who love him,\nbut all the wicked he will destroy.\n'),
	(11538, 16, 145, 21, 'My mouth will speak the praise of Yahweh.\nLet all flesh bless his holy name forever and ever.\n'),
	(11539, 16, 146, 1, 'Praise Yah!\nPraise Yahweh, my soul.\n'),
	(11540, 16, 146, 2, 'While I live, I will praise Yahweh.\nI will sing praises to my God as long as I exist.\n'),
	(11541, 16, 146, 3, 'Don’t put your trust in princes,\neach a son of man in whom there is no help.\n'),
	(11542, 16, 146, 4, 'His spirit departs, and he returns to the earth.\nIn that very day, his thoughts perish.\n'),
	(11543, 16, 146, 5, 'Happy is he who has the God of Jacob for his help,\nwhose hope is in Yahweh, his God:\n'),
	(11544, 16, 146, 6, 'who made heaven and earth,\nthe sea, and all that is in them;\nwho keeps truth forever;\n'),
	(11545, 16, 146, 7, 'who executes justice for the oppressed;\nwho gives food to the hungry.\nYahweh frees the prisoners.\n'),
	(11546, 16, 146, 8, 'Yahweh opens the eyes of the blind.\nYahweh raises up those who are bowed down.\nYahweh loves the righteous.\n'),
	(11547, 16, 146, 9, 'Yahweh preserves the foreigners.\nHe upholds the fatherless and widow,\nbut the way of the wicked he turns upside down.\n'),
	(11548, 16, 146, 10, 'Yahweh will reign forever;\nyour God, O Zion, to all generations.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11549, 16, 147, 1, 'Praise Yah,\nfor it is good to sing praises to our God;\nfor it is pleasant and fitting to praise him.\n'),
	(11550, 16, 147, 2, 'Yahweh builds up Jerusalem.\nHe gathers together the outcasts of Israel.\n'),
	(11551, 16, 147, 3, 'He heals the broken in heart,\nand binds up their wounds.\n'),
	(11552, 16, 147, 4, 'He counts the number of the stars.\nHe calls them all by their names.\n'),
	(11553, 16, 147, 5, 'Great is our Lord, and mighty in power.\nHis understanding is infinite.\n'),
	(11554, 16, 147, 6, 'Yahweh upholds the humble.\nHe brings the wicked down to the ground.\n'),
	(11555, 16, 147, 7, 'Sing to Yahweh with thanksgiving.\nSing praises on the harp to our God,\n'),
	(11556, 16, 147, 8, 'who covers the sky with clouds,\nwho prepares rain for the earth,\nwho makes grass grow on the mountains.\n'),
	(11557, 16, 147, 9, 'He provides food for the livestock,\nand for the young ravens when they call.\n'),
	(11558, 16, 147, 10, 'He doesn’t delight in the strength of the horse.\nHe takes no pleasure in the legs of a man.\n'),
	(11559, 16, 147, 11, 'Yahweh takes pleasure in those who fear him,\nin those who hope in his loving kindness.\n'),
	(11560, 16, 147, 12, 'Praise Yahweh, Jerusalem!\nPraise your God, Zion!\n'),
	(11561, 16, 147, 13, 'For he has strengthened the bars of your gates.\nHe has blessed your children within you.\n'),
	(11562, 16, 147, 14, 'He makes peace in your borders.\nHe fills you with the finest of the wheat.\n'),
	(11563, 16, 147, 15, 'He sends out his commandment to the earth.\nHis word runs very swiftly.\n'),
	(11564, 16, 147, 16, 'He gives snow like wool,\nand scatters frost like ashes.\n'),
	(11565, 16, 147, 17, 'He hurls down his hail like pebbles.\nWho can stand before his cold?\n'),
	(11566, 16, 147, 18, 'He sends out his word, and melts them.\nHe causes his wind to blow, and the waters flow.\n'),
	(11567, 16, 147, 19, 'He shows his word to Jacob;\nhis statutes and his ordinances to Israel.\n'),
	(11568, 16, 147, 20, 'He has not done this for just any nation.\nThey don’t know his ordinances.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11569, 16, 148, 1, 'Praise Yah!\nPraise Yahweh from the heavens!\nPraise him in the heights!\n'),
	(11570, 16, 148, 2, 'Praise him, all his angels!\nPraise him, all his army!\n'),
	(11571, 16, 148, 3, 'Praise him, sun and moon!\nPraise him, all you shining stars!\n'),
	(11572, 16, 148, 4, 'Praise him, you heavens of heavens,\nYou waters that are above the heavens.\n'),
	(11573, 16, 148, 5, 'Let them praise Yahweh’s name,\nFor he commanded, and they were created.\n'),
	(11574, 16, 148, 6, 'He has also established them forever and ever.\nHe has made a decree which will not pass away.\n'),
	(11575, 16, 148, 7, 'Praise Yahweh from the earth,\nyou great sea creatures, and all depths;\n'),
	(11576, 16, 148, 8, 'lightning and hail, snow and clouds;\nstormy wind, fulfilling his word;\n'),
	(11577, 16, 148, 9, 'mountains and all hills;\nfruit trees and all cedars;\n'),
	(11578, 16, 148, 10, 'wild animals and all livestock;\nsmall creatures and flying birds;\n'),
	(11579, 16, 148, 11, 'kings of the earth and all peoples;\nprinces and all judges of the earth;\n'),
	(11580, 16, 148, 12, 'both young men and maidens;\nold men and children:\n'),
	(11581, 16, 148, 13, 'let them praise Yahweh’s name,\nfor his name alone is exalted.\nHis glory is above the earth and the heavens.\n'),
	(11582, 16, 148, 14, 'He has lifted up the horn of his people,\nthe praise of all his saints;\neven of the children of Israel, a people near to him.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11583, 16, 149, 1, 'Praise Yahweh!\nSing to Yahweh a new song,\nhis praise in the assembly of the saints.\n'),
	(11584, 16, 149, 2, 'Let Israel rejoice in him who made them.\nLet the children of Zion be joyful in their King.\n'),
	(11585, 16, 149, 3, 'Let them praise his name in the dance!\nLet them sing praises to him with tambourine and harp!\n'),
	(11586, 16, 149, 4, 'For Yahweh takes pleasure in his people.\nHe crowns the humble with salvation.\n'),
	(11587, 16, 149, 5, 'Let the saints rejoice in honor.\nLet them sing for joy on their beds.\n'),
	(11588, 16, 149, 6, 'May the high praises of God be in their mouths,\nand a two-edged sword in their hand;\n'),
	(11589, 16, 149, 7, 'To execute vengeance on the nations,\nand punishments on the peoples;\n'),
	(11590, 16, 149, 8, 'To bind their kings with chains,\nand their nobles with fetters of iron;\n'),
	(11591, 16, 149, 9, 'to execute on them the written judgment.\nAll his saints have this honor.\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11592, 16, 150, 1, 'Praise Yah!\nPraise God in his sanctuary!\nPraise him in his heavens for his acts of power!\n'),
	(11593, 16, 150, 2, 'Praise him for his mighty acts!\nPraise him according to his excellent greatness!\n'),
	(11594, 16, 150, 3, 'Praise him with the sounding of the trumpet!\nPraise him with harp and lyre!\n'),
	(11595, 16, 150, 4, 'Praise him with tambourine and dancing!\nPraise him with stringed instruments and flute!\n'),
	(11596, 16, 150, 5, 'Praise him with loud cymbals!\nPraise him with resounding cymbals!\n'),
	(11597, 16, 150, 6, 'Let everything that has breath praise Yah!\nPraise Yah!\n'),
	(11598, 17, 1, 1, 'The proverbs of Solomon, the son of David, king of Israel:\n'),
	(11599, 17, 1, 2, 'to know wisdom and instruction;\nto discern the words of understanding;\n'),
	(11600, 17, 1, 3, 'to receive instruction in wise dealing,\nin righteousness, justice, and equity;\n'),
	(11601, 17, 1, 4, 'to give prudence to the simple,\nknowledge and discretion to the young man:\n'),
	(11602, 17, 1, 5, 'that the wise man may hear, and increase in learning;\nthat the man of understanding may attain to sound counsel:\n'),
	(11603, 17, 1, 6, 'to understand a proverb, and parables,\nthe words and riddles of the wise.\n'),
	(11604, 17, 1, 7, 'The fear of Yahweh is the beginning of knowledge;\nbut the foolish despise wisdom and instruction.\n'),
	(11605, 17, 1, 8, 'My son, listen to your father’s instruction,\nand don’t forsake your mother’s teaching:\n'),
	(11606, 17, 1, 9, 'for they will be a garland to grace your head,\nand chains around your neck.\n'),
	(11607, 17, 1, 10, 'My son, if sinners entice you,\ndon’t consent.\n'),
	(11608, 17, 1, 11, 'If they say, “Come with us.\nLet’s lay in wait for blood.\nLet’s lurk secretly for the innocent without cause.\n'),
	(11609, 17, 1, 12, 'Let’s swallow them up alive like Sheol,\nand whole, like those who go down into the pit.\n'),
	(11610, 17, 1, 13, 'We’ll find all valuable wealth.\nWe’ll fill our houses with plunder.\n'),
	(11611, 17, 1, 14, 'You shall cast your lot among us.\nWe’ll all have one purse.”\n'),
	(11612, 17, 1, 15, 'My son, don’t walk on the path with them.\nKeep your foot from their path,\n'),
	(11613, 17, 1, 16, 'for their feet run to evil.\nThey hurry to shed blood.\n'),
	(11614, 17, 1, 17, 'For in vain is the net spread in the sight of any bird:\n'),
	(11615, 17, 1, 18, 'but these lay wait for their own blood.\nThey lurk secretly for their own lives.\n'),
	(11616, 17, 1, 19, 'So are the ways of everyone who is greedy for gain.\nIt takes away the life of its owners.\n'),
	(11617, 17, 1, 20, 'Wisdom calls aloud in the street.\nShe utters her voice in the public squares.\n'),
	(11618, 17, 1, 21, 'She calls at the head of noisy places.\nAt the entrance of the city gates, she utters her words:\n'),
	(11619, 17, 1, 22, '“How long, you simple ones, will you love simplicity?\nHow long will mockers delight themselves in mockery,\nand fools hate knowledge?\n'),
	(11620, 17, 1, 23, 'Turn at my reproof.\nBehold, I will pour out my spirit on you.\nI will make known my words to you.\n'),
	(11621, 17, 1, 24, 'Because I have called, and you have refused;\nI have stretched out my hand, and no one has paid attention;\n'),
	(11622, 17, 1, 25, 'but you have ignored all my counsel,\nand wanted none of my reproof;\n'),
	(11623, 17, 1, 26, 'I also will laugh at your disaster.\nI will mock when calamity overtakes you;\n'),
	(11624, 17, 1, 27, 'when calamity overtakes you like a storm,\nwhen your disaster comes on like a whirlwind;\nwhen distress and anguish come on you.\n'),
	(11625, 17, 1, 28, 'Then will they call on me, but I will not answer.\nThey will seek me diligently, but they will not find me;\n'),
	(11626, 17, 1, 29, 'because they hated knowledge,\nand didn’t choose the fear of Yahweh.\n'),
	(11627, 17, 1, 30, 'They wanted none of my counsel.\nThey despised all my reproof.\n'),
	(11628, 17, 1, 31, 'Therefore they will eat of the fruit of their own way,\nand be filled with their own schemes.\n'),
	(11629, 17, 1, 32, 'For the backsliding of the simple will kill them.\nThe careless ease of fools will destroy them.\n'),
	(11630, 17, 1, 33, 'But whoever listens to me will dwell securely,\nand will be at ease, without fear of harm.”\n'),
	(11631, 17, 2, 1, 'My son, if you will receive my words,\nand store up my commandments within you;\n'),
	(11632, 17, 2, 2, 'So as to turn your ear to wisdom,\nand apply your heart to understanding;\n'),
	(11633, 17, 2, 3, 'Yes, if you call out for discernment,\nand lift up your voice for understanding;\n'),
	(11634, 17, 2, 4, 'If you seek her as silver,\nand search for her as for hidden treasures:\n'),
	(11635, 17, 2, 5, 'then you will understand the fear of Yahweh,\nand find the knowledge of God.\n'),
	(11636, 17, 2, 6, 'For Yahweh gives wisdom.\nOut of his mouth comes knowledge and understanding.\n'),
	(11637, 17, 2, 7, 'He lays up sound wisdom for the upright.\nHe is a shield to those who walk in integrity;\n'),
	(11638, 17, 2, 8, 'that he may guard the paths of justice,\nand preserve the way of his saints.\n'),
	(11639, 17, 2, 9, 'Then you will understand righteousness and justice,\nequity and every good path.\n'),
	(11640, 17, 2, 10, 'For wisdom will enter into your heart.\nKnowledge will be pleasant to your soul.\n'),
	(11641, 17, 2, 11, 'Discretion will watch over you.\nUnderstanding will keep you,\n'),
	(11642, 17, 2, 12, 'to deliver you from the way of evil,\nfrom the men who speak perverse things;\n'),
	(11643, 17, 2, 13, 'who forsake the paths of uprightness,\nto walk in the ways of darkness;\n'),
	(11644, 17, 2, 14, 'who rejoice to do evil,\nand delight in the perverseness of evil;\n'),
	(11645, 17, 2, 15, 'who are crooked in their ways,\nand wayward in their paths:\n'),
	(11646, 17, 2, 16, 'To deliver you from the strange woman,\neven from the foreigner who flatters with her words;\n'),
	(11647, 17, 2, 17, 'who forsakes the friend of her youth,\nand forgets the covenant of her God:\n'),
	(11648, 17, 2, 18, 'for her house leads down to death,\nher paths to the departed spirits.\n'),
	(11649, 17, 2, 19, 'None who go to her return again,\nneither do they attain to the paths of life:\n'),
	(11650, 17, 2, 20, 'that you may walk in the way of good men,\nand keep the paths of the righteous.\n'),
	(11651, 17, 2, 21, 'For the upright will dwell in the land.\nThe perfect will remain in it.\n'),
	(11652, 17, 2, 22, 'But the wicked will be cut off from the land.\nThe treacherous will be rooted out of it.\n'),
	(11653, 17, 3, 1, 'My son, don’t forget my teaching;\nbut let your heart keep my commandments:\n'),
	(11654, 17, 3, 2, 'for length of days, and years of life,\nand peace, will they add to you.\n'),
	(11655, 17, 3, 3, 'Don’t let kindness and truth forsake you.\nBind them around your neck.\nWrite them on the tablet of your heart.\n'),
	(11656, 17, 3, 4, 'So you will find favor,\nand good understanding in the sight of God and man.\n'),
	(11657, 17, 3, 5, 'Trust in Yahweh with all your heart,\nand don’t lean on your own understanding.\n'),
	(11658, 17, 3, 6, 'In all your ways acknowledge him,\nand he will make your paths straight.\n'),
	(11659, 17, 3, 7, 'Don’t be wise in your own eyes.\nFear Yahweh, and depart from evil.\n'),
	(11660, 17, 3, 8, 'It will be health to your body,\nand nourishment to your bones.\n'),
	(11661, 17, 3, 9, 'Honor Yahweh with your substance,\nwith the first fruits of all your increase:\n'),
	(11662, 17, 3, 10, 'so your barns will be filled with plenty,\nand your vats will overflow with new wine.\n'),
	(11663, 17, 3, 11, 'My son, don’t despise Yahweh’s discipline,\nneither be weary of his reproof:\n'),
	(11664, 17, 3, 12, 'for whom Yahweh loves, he reproves;\neven as a father reproves the son in whom he delights.\n'),
	(11665, 17, 3, 13, 'Happy is the man who finds wisdom,\nthe man who gets understanding.\n'),
	(11666, 17, 3, 14, 'For her good profit is better than getting silver,\nand her return is better than fine gold.\n'),
	(11667, 17, 3, 15, 'She is more precious than rubies.\nNone of the things you can desire are to be compared to her.\n'),
	(11668, 17, 3, 16, 'Length of days is in her right hand.\nIn her left hand are riches and honor.\n'),
	(11669, 17, 3, 17, 'Her ways are ways of pleasantness.\nAll her paths are peace.\n'),
	(11670, 17, 3, 18, 'She is a tree of life to those who lay hold of her.\nHappy is everyone who retains her.\n'),
	(11671, 17, 3, 19, 'By wisdom Yahweh founded the earth.\nBy understanding, he established the heavens.\n'),
	(11672, 17, 3, 20, 'By his knowledge, the depths were broken up,\nand the skies drop down the dew.\n'),
	(11673, 17, 3, 21, 'My son, let them not depart from your eyes.\nKeep sound wisdom and discretion:\n'),
	(11674, 17, 3, 22, 'so they will be life to your soul,\nand grace for your neck.\n'),
	(11675, 17, 3, 23, 'Then you shall walk in your way securely.\nYour foot won’t stumble.\n'),
	(11676, 17, 3, 24, 'When you lie down, you will not be afraid.\nYes, you will lie down, and your sleep will be sweet.\n'),
	(11677, 17, 3, 25, 'Don’t be afraid of sudden fear,\nneither of the desolation of the wicked, when it comes:\n'),
	(11678, 17, 3, 26, 'for Yahweh will be your confidence,\nand will keep your foot from being taken.\n'),
	(11679, 17, 3, 27, 'Don’t withhold good from those to whom it is due,\nwhen it is in the power of your hand to do it.\n'),
	(11680, 17, 3, 28, 'Don’t say to your neighbor, “Go, and come again;\ntomorrow I will give it to you,”\nwhen you have it by you.\n'),
	(11681, 17, 3, 29, 'Don’t devise evil against your neighbor,\nsince he dwells securely by you.\n'),
	(11682, 17, 3, 30, 'Don’t strive with a man without cause,\nif he has done you no harm.\n'),
	(11683, 17, 3, 31, 'Don’t envy the man of violence.\nChoose none of his ways.\n'),
	(11684, 17, 3, 32, 'For the perverse is an abomination to Yahweh,\nbut his friendship is with the upright.\n'),
	(11685, 17, 3, 33, 'Yahweh’s curse is in the house of the wicked,\nbut he blesses the habitation of the righteous.\n'),
	(11686, 17, 3, 34, 'Surely he mocks the mockers,\nbut he gives grace to the humble.\n'),
	(11687, 17, 3, 35, 'The wise will inherit glory,\nbut shame will be the promotion of fools.\n'),
	(11688, 17, 4, 1, 'Listen, sons, to a father’s instruction.\nPay attention and know understanding;\n'),
	(11689, 17, 4, 2, 'for I give you sound learning.\nDon’t forsake my law.\n'),
	(11690, 17, 4, 3, 'For I was a son to my father,\ntender and an only child in the sight of my mother.\n'),
	(11691, 17, 4, 4, 'He taught me, and said to me:\n“Let your heart retain my words.\nKeep my commandments, and live.\n'),
	(11692, 17, 4, 5, 'Get wisdom.\nGet understanding.\nDon’t forget, and don’t deviate from the words of my mouth.\n'),
	(11693, 17, 4, 6, 'Don’t forsake her, and she will preserve you.\nLove her, and she will keep you.\n'),
	(11694, 17, 4, 7, 'Wisdom is supreme.\nGet wisdom.\nYes, though it costs all your possessions, get understanding.\n'),
	(11695, 17, 4, 8, 'Esteem her, and she will exalt you.\nShe will bring you to honor, when you embrace her.\n'),
	(11696, 17, 4, 9, 'She will give to your head a garland of grace.\nShe will deliver a crown of splendor to you.”\n'),
	(11697, 17, 4, 10, 'Listen, my son, and receive my sayings.\nThe years of your life will be many.\n'),
	(11698, 17, 4, 11, 'I have taught you in the way of wisdom.\nI have led you in straight paths.\n'),
	(11699, 17, 4, 12, 'When you go, your steps will not be hampered.\nWhen you run, you will not stumble.\n'),
	(11700, 17, 4, 13, 'Take firm hold of instruction.\nDon’t let her go.\nKeep her, for she is your life.\n'),
	(11701, 17, 4, 14, 'Don’t enter into the path of the wicked.\nDon’t walk in the way of evil men.\n'),
	(11702, 17, 4, 15, 'Avoid it, and don’t pass by it.\nTurn from it, and pass on.\n'),
	(11703, 17, 4, 16, 'For they don’t sleep, unless they do evil.\nTheir sleep is taken away, unless they make someone fall.\n'),
	(11704, 17, 4, 17, 'For they eat the bread of wickedness,\nand drink the wine of violence.\n'),
	(11705, 17, 4, 18, 'But the path of the righteous is like the dawning light,\nthat shines more and more until the perfect day.\n'),
	(11706, 17, 4, 19, 'The way of the wicked is like darkness.\nThey don’t know what they stumble over.\n'),
	(11707, 17, 4, 20, 'My son, attend to my words.\nTurn your ear to my sayings.\n'),
	(11708, 17, 4, 21, 'Let them not depart from your eyes.\nKeep them in the center of your heart.\n'),
	(11709, 17, 4, 22, 'For they are life to those who find them,\nand health to their whole body.\n'),
	(11710, 17, 4, 23, 'Keep your heart with all diligence,\nfor out of it is the wellspring of life.\n'),
	(11711, 17, 4, 24, 'Put away from yourself a perverse mouth.\nPut corrupt lips far from you.\n'),
	(11712, 17, 4, 25, 'Let your eyes look straight ahead.\nFix your gaze directly before you.\n'),
	(11713, 17, 4, 26, 'Make the path of your feet level.\nLet all of your ways be established.\n'),
	(11714, 17, 4, 27, 'Don’t turn to the right hand nor to the left.\nRemove your foot from evil.\n'),
	(11715, 17, 5, 1, 'My son, pay attention to my wisdom.\nTurn your ear to my understanding:\n'),
	(11716, 17, 5, 2, 'that you may maintain discretion,\nthat your lips may preserve knowledge.\n'),
	(11717, 17, 5, 3, 'For the lips of an adulteress drip honey.\nHer mouth is smoother than oil,\n'),
	(11718, 17, 5, 4, 'but in the end she is as bitter as wormwood,\nand as sharp as a two-edged sword.\n'),
	(11719, 17, 5, 5, 'Her feet go down to death.\nHer steps lead straight to Sheol.\n'),
	(11720, 17, 5, 6, 'She gives no thought to the way of life.\nHer ways are crooked, and she doesn’t know it.\n'),
	(11721, 17, 5, 7, 'Now therefore, my sons, listen to me.\nDon’t depart from the words of my mouth.\n'),
	(11722, 17, 5, 8, 'Remove your way far from her.\nDon’t come near the door of her house,\n'),
	(11723, 17, 5, 9, 'lest you give your honor to others,\nand your years to the cruel one;\n'),
	(11724, 17, 5, 10, 'lest strangers feast on your wealth,\nand your labors enrich another man’s house.\n'),
	(11725, 17, 5, 11, 'You will groan at your latter end,\nwhen your flesh and your body are consumed,\n'),
	(11726, 17, 5, 12, 'and say, “How I have hated instruction,\nand my heart despised reproof;\n'),
	(11727, 17, 5, 13, 'neither have I obeyed the voice of my teachers,\nnor turned my ear to those who instructed me!\n'),
	(11728, 17, 5, 14, 'I have come to the brink of utter ruin,\namong the gathered assembly.”\n'),
	(11729, 17, 5, 15, 'Drink water out of your own cistern,\nrunning water out of your own well.\n'),
	(11730, 17, 5, 16, 'Should your springs overflow in the streets,\nstreams of water in the public squares?\n'),
	(11731, 17, 5, 17, 'Let them be for yourself alone,\nnot for strangers with you.\n'),
	(11732, 17, 5, 18, 'Let your spring be blessed.\nRejoice in the wife of your youth.\n'),
	(11733, 17, 5, 19, 'A loving doe and a graceful deer—\nlet her breasts satisfy you at all times.\nBe captivated always with her love.\n'),
	(11734, 17, 5, 20, 'For why should you, my son, be captivated with an adulteress?\nWhy embrace the bosom of another?\n'),
	(11735, 17, 5, 21, 'For the ways of man are before Yahweh’s eyes.\nHe examines all his paths.\n'),
	(11736, 17, 5, 22, 'The evil deeds of the wicked ensnare him.\nThe cords of his sin hold him firmly.\n'),
	(11737, 17, 5, 23, 'He will die for lack of instruction.\nIn the greatness of his folly, he will go astray.\n'),
	(11738, 17, 6, 1, 'My son, if you have become collateral for your neighbor,\nif you have struck your hands in pledge for a stranger;\n'),
	(11739, 17, 6, 2, 'You are trapped by the words of your mouth.\nYou are ensnared with the words of your mouth.\n'),
	(11740, 17, 6, 3, 'Do this now, my son, and deliver yourself,\nsince you have come into the hand of your neighbor.\nGo, humble yourself.\nPress your plea with your neighbor.\n'),
	(11741, 17, 6, 4, 'Give no sleep to your eyes,\nnor slumber to your eyelids.\n'),
	(11742, 17, 6, 5, 'Free yourself, like a gazelle from the hand of the hunter,\nlike a bird from the snare of the fowler.\n'),
	(11743, 17, 6, 6, 'Go to the ant, you sluggard.\nConsider her ways, and be wise;\n'),
	(11744, 17, 6, 7, 'which having no chief, overseer, or ruler,\n'),
	(11745, 17, 6, 8, 'provides her bread in the summer,\nand gathers her food in the harvest.\n'),
	(11746, 17, 6, 9, 'How long will you sleep, sluggard?\nWhen will you arise out of your sleep?\n'),
	(11747, 17, 6, 10, 'A little sleep, a little slumber,\na little folding of the hands to sleep:\n'),
	(11748, 17, 6, 11, 'so your poverty will come as a robber,\nand your scarcity as an armed man.\n'),
	(11749, 17, 6, 12, 'A worthless person, a man of iniquity,\nis he who walks with a perverse mouth;\n'),
	(11750, 17, 6, 13, 'who winks with his eyes, who signals with his feet,\nwho motions with his fingers;\n'),
	(11751, 17, 6, 14, 'in whose heart is perverseness,\nwho devises evil continually,\nwho always sows discord.\n'),
	(11752, 17, 6, 15, 'Therefore his calamity will come suddenly.\nHe will be broken suddenly, and that without remedy.\n'),
	(11753, 17, 6, 16, 'There are six things which Yahweh hates;\nyes, seven which are an abomination to him:\n'),
	(11754, 17, 6, 17, 'haughty eyes, a lying tongue,\nhands that shed innocent blood;\n'),
	(11755, 17, 6, 18, 'a heart that devises wicked schemes,\nfeet that are swift in running to mischief,\n'),
	(11756, 17, 6, 19, 'a false witness who utters lies,\nand he who sows discord among brothers.\n'),
	(11757, 17, 6, 20, 'My son, keep your father’s commandment,\nand don’t forsake your mother’s teaching.\n'),
	(11758, 17, 6, 21, 'Bind them continually on your heart.\nTie them around your neck.\n'),
	(11759, 17, 6, 22, 'When you walk, it will lead you.\nWhen you sleep, it will watch over you.\nWhen you awake, it will talk with you.\n'),
	(11760, 17, 6, 23, 'For the commandment is a lamp,\nand the law is light.\nReproofs of instruction are the way of life,\n'),
	(11761, 17, 6, 24, 'to keep you from the immoral woman,\nfrom the flattery of the wayward wife’s tongue.\n'),
	(11762, 17, 6, 25, 'Don’t lust after her beauty in your heart,\nneither let her captivate you with her eyelids.\n'),
	(11763, 17, 6, 26, 'For a prostitute reduces you to a piece of bread.\nThe adulteress hunts for your precious life.\n'),
	(11764, 17, 6, 27, 'Can a man scoop fire into his lap,\nand his clothes not be burned?\n'),
	(11765, 17, 6, 28, 'Or can one walk on hot coals,\nand his feet not be scorched?\n'),
	(11766, 17, 6, 29, 'So is he who goes in to his neighbor’s wife.\nWhoever touches her will not be unpunished.\n'),
	(11767, 17, 6, 30, 'Men don’t despise a thief,\nif he steals to satisfy himself when he is hungry:\n'),
	(11768, 17, 6, 31, 'but if he is found, he shall restore seven times.\nHe shall give all the wealth of his house.\n'),
	(11769, 17, 6, 32, 'He who commits adultery with a woman is void of understanding.\nHe who does it destroys his own soul.\n'),
	(11770, 17, 6, 33, 'He will get wounds and dishonor.\nHis reproach will not be wiped away.\n'),
	(11771, 17, 6, 34, 'For jealousy arouses the fury of the husband.\nHe won’t spare in the day of vengeance.\n'),
	(11772, 17, 6, 35, 'He won’t regard any ransom,\nneither will he rest content, though you give many gifts.\n'),
	(11773, 17, 7, 1, 'My son, keep my words.\nLay up my commandments within you.\n'),
	(11774, 17, 7, 2, 'Keep my commandments and live!\nGuard my teaching as the apple of your eye.\n'),
	(11775, 17, 7, 3, 'Bind them on your fingers.\nWrite them on the tablet of your heart.\n'),
	(11776, 17, 7, 4, 'Tell wisdom, “You are my sister.”\nCall understanding your relative,\n'),
	(11777, 17, 7, 5, 'that they may keep you from the strange woman,\nfrom the foreigner who flatters with her words.\n'),
	(11778, 17, 7, 6, 'For at the window of my house,\nI looked out through my lattice.\n'),
	(11779, 17, 7, 7, 'I saw among the simple ones.\nI discerned among the youths a young man void of understanding,\n'),
	(11780, 17, 7, 8, 'passing through the street near her corner,\nhe went the way to her house,\n'),
	(11781, 17, 7, 9, 'in the twilight, in the evening of the day,\nin the middle of the night and in the darkness.\n'),
	(11782, 17, 7, 10, 'Behold, there a woman met him with the attire of a prostitute,\nand with crafty intent.\n'),
	(11783, 17, 7, 11, 'She is loud and defiant.\nHer feet don’t stay in her house.\n'),
	(11784, 17, 7, 12, 'Now she is in the streets, now in the squares,\nand lurking at every corner.\n'),
	(11785, 17, 7, 13, 'So she caught him, and kissed him.\nWith an impudent face she said to him:\n'),
	(11786, 17, 7, 14, '“Sacrifices of peace offerings are with me.\nToday I have paid my vows.\n'),
	(11787, 17, 7, 15, 'Therefore I came out to meet you,\nto diligently seek your face,\nand I have found you.\n'),
	(11788, 17, 7, 16, 'I have spread my couch with carpets of tapestry,\nwith striped cloths of the yarn of Egypt.\n'),
	(11789, 17, 7, 17, 'I have perfumed my bed with myrrh, aloes, and cinnamon.\n'),
	(11790, 17, 7, 18, 'Come, let’s take our fill of loving until the morning.\nLet’s solace ourselves with loving.\n'),
	(11791, 17, 7, 19, 'For my husband isn’t at home.\nHe has gone on a long journey.\n'),
	(11792, 17, 7, 20, 'He has taken a bag of money with him.\nHe will come home at the full moon.”\n'),
	(11793, 17, 7, 21, 'With persuasive words, she led him astray.\nWith the flattering of her lips, she seduced him.\n'),
	(11794, 17, 7, 22, 'He followed her immediately,\nas an ox goes to the slaughter,\nas a fool stepping into a noose.\n'),
	(11795, 17, 7, 23, 'Until an arrow strikes through his liver,\nas a bird hurries to the snare,\nand doesn’t know that it will cost his life.\n'),
	(11796, 17, 7, 24, 'Now therefore, sons, listen to me.\nPay attention to the words of my mouth.\n'),
	(11797, 17, 7, 25, 'Don’t let your heart turn to her ways.\nDon’t go astray in her paths,\n'),
	(11798, 17, 7, 26, 'for she has thrown down many wounded.\nYes, all her slain are a mighty army.\n'),
	(11799, 17, 7, 27, 'Her house is the way to Sheol,\ngoing down to the rooms of death.\n'),
	(11800, 17, 8, 1, 'Doesn’t wisdom cry out?\nDoesn’t understanding raise her voice?\n'),
	(11801, 17, 8, 2, 'On the top of high places by the way,\nwhere the paths meet, she stands.\n'),
	(11802, 17, 8, 3, 'Beside the gates, at the entry of the city,\nat the entry doors, she cries aloud:\n'),
	(11803, 17, 8, 4, '“To you men, I call!\nI send my voice to the sons of mankind.\n'),
	(11804, 17, 8, 5, 'You simple, understand prudence.\nYou fools, be of an understanding heart.\n'),
	(11805, 17, 8, 6, 'Hear, for I will speak excellent things.\nThe opening of my lips is for right things.\n'),
	(11806, 17, 8, 7, 'For my mouth speaks truth.\nWickedness is an abomination to my lips.\n'),
	(11807, 17, 8, 8, 'All the words of my mouth are in righteousness.\nThere is nothing crooked or perverse in them.\n'),
	(11808, 17, 8, 9, 'They are all plain to him who understands,\nright to those who find knowledge.\n'),
	(11809, 17, 8, 10, 'Receive my instruction rather than silver;\nknowledge rather than choice gold.\n'),
	(11810, 17, 8, 11, 'For wisdom is better than rubies.\nAll the things that may be desired can’t be compared to it.\n'),
	(11811, 17, 8, 12, '“I, wisdom, have made prudence my dwelling.\nFind out knowledge and discretion.\n'),
	(11812, 17, 8, 13, 'The fear of Yahweh is to hate evil.\nI hate pride, arrogance, the evil way, and the perverse mouth.\n'),
	(11813, 17, 8, 14, 'Counsel and sound knowledge are mine.\nI have understanding and power.\n'),
	(11814, 17, 8, 15, 'By me kings reign,\nand princes decree justice.\n'),
	(11815, 17, 8, 16, 'By me princes rule;\nnobles, and all the righteous rulers of the earth.\n'),
	(11816, 17, 8, 17, 'I love those who love me.\nThose who seek me diligently will find me.\n'),
	(11817, 17, 8, 18, 'With me are riches, honor,\nenduring wealth, and prosperity.\n'),
	(11818, 17, 8, 19, 'My fruit is better than gold, yes, than fine gold;\nmy yield than choice silver.\n'),
	(11819, 17, 8, 20, 'I walk in the way of righteousness,\nin the middle of the paths of justice;\n'),
	(11820, 17, 8, 21, 'that I may give wealth to those who love me.\nI fill their treasuries.\n'),
	(11821, 17, 8, 22, '“Yahweh possessed me in the beginning of his work,\nbefore his deeds of old.\n'),
	(11822, 17, 8, 23, 'I was set up from everlasting, from the beginning,\nbefore the earth existed.\n'),
	(11823, 17, 8, 24, 'When there were no depths, I was born,\nwhen there were no springs abounding with water.\n'),
	(11824, 17, 8, 25, 'Before the mountains were settled in place,\nbefore the hills, I was born;\n'),
	(11825, 17, 8, 26, 'while as yet he had not made the earth, nor the fields,\nnor the beginning of the dust of the world.\n'),
	(11826, 17, 8, 27, 'When he established the heavens, I was there;\nwhen he set a circle on the surface of the deep,\n'),
	(11827, 17, 8, 28, 'when he established the clouds above,\nwhen the springs of the deep became strong,\n'),
	(11828, 17, 8, 29, 'when he gave to the sea its boundary,\nthat the waters should not violate his commandment,\nwhen he marked out the foundations of the earth;\n'),
	(11829, 17, 8, 30, 'then I was the craftsman by his side.\nI was a delight day by day,\nalways rejoicing before him,\n'),
	(11830, 17, 8, 31, 'rejoicing in his whole world.\nMy delight was with the sons of men.\n'),
	(11831, 17, 8, 32, '“Now therefore, my sons, listen to me,\nfor blessed are those who keep my ways.\n'),
	(11832, 17, 8, 33, 'Hear instruction, and be wise.\nDon’t refuse it.\n'),
	(11833, 17, 8, 34, 'Blessed is the man who hears me,\nwatching daily at my gates,\nwaiting at my door posts.\n'),
	(11834, 17, 8, 35, 'For whoever finds me, finds life,\nand will obtain favor from Yahweh.\n'),
	(11835, 17, 8, 36, 'But he who sins against me wrongs his own soul.\nAll those who hate me love death.”\n'),
	(11836, 17, 9, 1, 'Wisdom has built her house.\nShe has carved out her seven pillars.\n'),
	(11837, 17, 9, 2, 'She has prepared her meat.\nShe has mixed her wine.\nShe has also set her table.\n'),
	(11838, 17, 9, 3, 'She has sent out her maidens.\nShe cries from the highest places of the city:\n'),
	(11839, 17, 9, 4, '“Whoever is simple, let him turn in here!”\nAs for him who is void of understanding, she says to him,\n'),
	(11840, 17, 9, 5, '“Come, eat some of my bread,\nDrink some of the wine which I have mixed!\n'),
	(11841, 17, 9, 6, 'Leave your simple ways, and live.\nWalk in the way of understanding.”\n'),
	(11842, 17, 9, 7, 'He who corrects a mocker invites insult.\nHe who reproves a wicked man invites abuse.\n'),
	(11843, 17, 9, 8, 'Don’t reprove a scoffer, lest he hate you.\nReprove a wise man, and he will love you.\n'),
	(11844, 17, 9, 9, 'Instruct a wise man, and he will be still wiser.\nTeach a righteous man, and he will increase in learning.\n'),
	(11845, 17, 9, 10, 'The fear of Yahweh is the beginning of wisdom.\nThe knowledge of the Holy One is understanding.\n'),
	(11846, 17, 9, 11, 'For by me your days will be multiplied.\nThe years of your life will be increased.\n'),
	(11847, 17, 9, 12, 'If you are wise, you are wise for yourself.\nIf you mock, you alone will bear it.\n'),
	(11848, 17, 9, 13, 'The foolish woman is loud,\nundisciplined, and knows nothing.\n'),
	(11849, 17, 9, 14, 'She sits at the door of her house,\non a seat in the high places of the city,\n'),
	(11850, 17, 9, 15, 'To call to those who pass by,\nwho go straight on their ways,\n'),
	(11851, 17, 9, 16, '“Whoever is simple, let him turn in here.”\nas for him who is void of understanding, she says to him,\n'),
	(11852, 17, 9, 17, '“Stolen water is sweet.\nFood eaten in secret is pleasant.”\n'),
	(11853, 17, 9, 18, 'But he doesn’t know that the departed spirits are there,\nthat her guests are in the depths of Sheol.\n'),
	(11854, 17, 10, 1, 'The proverbs of Solomon.\nA wise son makes a glad father;\nbut a foolish son brings grief to his mother.\n'),
	(11855, 17, 10, 2, 'Treasures of wickedness profit nothing,\nbut righteousness delivers from death.\n'),
	(11856, 17, 10, 3, 'Yahweh will not allow the soul of the righteous to go hungry,\nbut he thrusts away the desire of the wicked.\n'),
	(11857, 17, 10, 4, 'He becomes poor who works with a lazy hand,\nbut the hand of the diligent brings wealth.\n'),
	(11858, 17, 10, 5, 'He who gathers in summer is a wise son,\nbut he who sleeps during the harvest is a son who causes shame.\n'),
	(11859, 17, 10, 6, 'Blessings are on the head of the righteous,\nbut violence covers the mouth of the wicked.\n'),
	(11860, 17, 10, 7, 'The memory of the righteous is blessed,\nbut the name of the wicked will rot.\n'),
	(11861, 17, 10, 8, 'The wise in heart accept commandments,\nbut a chattering fool will fall.\n'),
	(11862, 17, 10, 9, 'He who walks blamelessly walks surely,\nbut he who perverts his ways will be found out.\n'),
	(11863, 17, 10, 10, 'One winking with the eye causes sorrow,\nbut a chattering fool will fall.\n'),
	(11864, 17, 10, 11, 'The mouth of the righteous is a spring of life,\nbut violence covers the mouth of the wicked.\n'),
	(11865, 17, 10, 12, 'Hatred stirs up strife,\nbut love covers all wrongs.\n'),
	(11866, 17, 10, 13, 'Wisdom is found on the lips of him who has discernment,\nbut a rod is for the back of him who is void of understanding.\n'),
	(11867, 17, 10, 14, 'Wise men lay up knowledge,\nbut the mouth of the foolish is near ruin.\n'),
	(11868, 17, 10, 15, 'The rich man’s wealth is his strong city.\nThe destruction of the poor is their poverty.\n'),
	(11869, 17, 10, 16, 'The labor of the righteous leads to life.\nThe increase of the wicked leads to sin.\n'),
	(11870, 17, 10, 17, 'He is in the way of life who heeds correction,\nbut he who forsakes reproof leads others astray.\n'),
	(11871, 17, 10, 18, 'He who hides hatred has lying lips.\nHe who utters a slander is a fool.\n'),
	(11872, 17, 10, 19, 'In the multitude of words there is no lack of disobedience,\nbut he who restrains his lips does wisely.\n'),
	(11873, 17, 10, 20, 'The tongue of the righteous is like choice silver.\nThe heart of the wicked is of little worth.\n'),
	(11874, 17, 10, 21, 'The lips of the righteous feed many,\nbut the foolish die for lack of understanding.\n'),
	(11875, 17, 10, 22, 'Yahweh’s blessing brings wealth,\nand he adds no trouble to it.\n'),
	(11876, 17, 10, 23, 'It is a fool’s pleasure to do wickedness,\nbut wisdom is a man of understanding’s pleasure.\n'),
	(11877, 17, 10, 24, 'What the wicked fear, will overtake them,\nbut the desire of the righteous will be granted.\n'),
	(11878, 17, 10, 25, 'When the whirlwind passes, the wicked is no more;\nbut the righteous stand firm forever.\n'),
	(11879, 17, 10, 26, 'As vinegar to the teeth, and as smoke to the eyes,\nso is the sluggard to those who send him.\n'),
	(11880, 17, 10, 27, 'The fear of Yahweh prolongs days,\nbut the years of the wicked shall be shortened.\n'),
	(11881, 17, 10, 28, 'The prospect of the righteous is joy,\nbut the hope of the wicked will perish.\n'),
	(11882, 17, 10, 29, 'The way of Yahweh is a stronghold to the upright,\nbut it is a destruction to the workers of iniquity.\n'),
	(11883, 17, 10, 30, 'The righteous will never be removed,\nbut the wicked will not dwell in the land.\n'),
	(11884, 17, 10, 31, 'The mouth of the righteous produces wisdom,\nbut the perverse tongue will be cut off.\n'),
	(11885, 17, 10, 32, 'The lips of the righteous know what is acceptable,\nbut the mouth of the wicked is perverse.\n'),
	(11886, 17, 11, 1, 'A false balance is an abomination to Yahweh,\nbut accurate weights are his delight.\n'),
	(11887, 17, 11, 2, 'When pride comes, then comes shame,\nbut with humility comes wisdom.\n'),
	(11888, 17, 11, 3, 'The integrity of the upright shall guide them,\nbut the perverseness of the treacherous shall destroy them.\n'),
	(11889, 17, 11, 4, 'Riches don’t profit in the day of wrath,\nbut righteousness delivers from death.\n'),
	(11890, 17, 11, 5, 'The righteousness of the blameless will direct his way,\nbut the wicked shall fall by his own wickedness.\n'),
	(11891, 17, 11, 6, 'The righteousness of the upright shall deliver them,\nbut the unfaithful will be trapped by evil desires.\n'),
	(11892, 17, 11, 7, 'When a wicked man dies, hope perishes,\nand expectation of power comes to nothing.\n'),
	(11893, 17, 11, 8, 'A righteous person is delivered out of trouble,\nand the wicked takes his place.\n'),
	(11894, 17, 11, 9, 'With his mouth the godless man destroys his neighbor,\nbut the righteous will be delivered through knowledge.\n'),
	(11895, 17, 11, 10, 'When it goes well with the righteous, the city rejoices.\nWhen the wicked perish, there is shouting.\n'),
	(11896, 17, 11, 11, 'By the blessing of the upright, the city is exalted,\nbut it is overthrown by the mouth of the wicked.\n'),
	(11897, 17, 11, 12, 'One who despises his neighbor is void of wisdom,\nbut a man of understanding holds his peace.\n'),
	(11898, 17, 11, 13, 'One who brings gossip betrays a confidence,\nbut one who is of a trustworthy spirit is one who keeps a secret.\n'),
	(11899, 17, 11, 14, 'Where there is no wise guidance, the nation falls,\nbut in the multitude of counselors there is victory.\n'),
	(11900, 17, 11, 15, 'He who is collateral for a stranger will suffer for it,\nbut he who refuses pledges of collateral is secure.\n'),
	(11901, 17, 11, 16, 'A gracious woman obtains honor,\nbut violent men obtain riches.\n'),
	(11902, 17, 11, 17, 'The merciful man does good to his own soul,\nbut he who is cruel troubles his own flesh.\n'),
	(11903, 17, 11, 18, 'Wicked people earn deceitful wages,\nbut one who sows righteousness reaps a sure reward.\n'),
	(11904, 17, 11, 19, 'He who is truly righteous gets life.\nHe who pursues evil gets death.\n'),
	(11905, 17, 11, 20, 'Those who are perverse in heart are an abomination to Yahweh,\nbut those whose ways are blameless are his delight.\n'),
	(11906, 17, 11, 21, 'Most certainly, the evil man will not be unpunished,\nbut the offspring of the righteous will be delivered.\n'),
	(11907, 17, 11, 22, 'Like a gold ring in a pig’s snout,\nis a beautiful woman who lacks discretion.\n'),
	(11908, 17, 11, 23, 'The desire of the righteous is only good.\nThe expectation of the wicked is wrath.\n'),
	(11909, 17, 11, 24, 'There is one who scatters, and increases yet more.\nThere is one who withholds more than is appropriate, but gains poverty.\n'),
	(11910, 17, 11, 25, 'The liberal soul shall be made fat.\nHe who waters shall be watered also himself.\n'),
	(11911, 17, 11, 26, 'People curse someone who withholds grain,\nbut blessing will be on the head of him who sells it.\n'),
	(11912, 17, 11, 27, 'He who diligently seeks good seeks favor,\nbut he who searches after evil, it shall come to him.\n'),
	(11913, 17, 11, 28, 'He who trusts in his riches will fall,\nbut the righteous shall flourish as the green leaf.\n'),
	(11914, 17, 11, 29, 'He who troubles his own house shall inherit the wind.\nThe foolish shall be servant to the wise of heart.\n'),
	(11915, 17, 11, 30, 'The fruit of the righteous is a tree of life.\nHe who is wise wins souls.\n'),
	(11916, 17, 11, 31, 'Behold, the righteous shall be repaid in the earth;\nhow much more the wicked and the sinner!\n'),
	(11917, 17, 12, 1, 'Whoever loves correction loves knowledge,\nbut he who hates reproof is stupid.\n'),
	(11918, 17, 12, 2, 'A good man shall obtain favor from Yahweh,\nbut he will condemn a man of wicked plans.\n'),
	(11919, 17, 12, 3, 'A man shall not be established by wickedness,\nbut the root of the righteous shall not be moved.\n'),
	(11920, 17, 12, 4, 'A worthy woman is the crown of her husband,\nbut a disgraceful wife is as rottenness in his bones.\n'),
	(11921, 17, 12, 5, 'The thoughts of the righteous are just,\nbut the advice of the wicked is deceitful.\n'),
	(11922, 17, 12, 6, 'The words of the wicked are about lying in wait for blood,\nbut the speech of the upright rescues them.\n'),
	(11923, 17, 12, 7, 'The wicked are overthrown, and are no more,\nbut the house of the righteous shall stand.\n'),
	(11924, 17, 12, 8, 'A man shall be commended according to his wisdom,\nbut he who has a warped mind shall be despised.\n'),
	(11925, 17, 12, 9, 'Better is he who is little know, and has a servant,\nthan he who honors himself, and lacks bread.\n'),
	(11926, 17, 12, 10, 'A righteous man respects the life of his animal,\nbut the tender mercies of the wicked are cruel.\n'),
	(11927, 17, 12, 11, 'He who tills his land shall have plenty of bread,\nbut he who chases fantasies is void of understanding.\n'),
	(11928, 17, 12, 12, 'The wicked desires the plunder of evil men,\nbut the root of the righteous flourishes.\n'),
	(11929, 17, 12, 13, 'An evil man is trapped by sinfulness of lips,\nbut the righteous shall come out of trouble.\n'),
	(11930, 17, 12, 14, 'A man shall be satisfied with good by the fruit of his mouth.\nThe work of a man’s hands shall be rewarded to him.\n'),
	(11931, 17, 12, 15, 'The way of a fool is right in his own eyes,\nbut he who is wise listens to counsel.\n'),
	(11932, 17, 12, 16, 'A fool shows his annoyance the same day,\nbut one who overlooks an insult is prudent.\n'),
	(11933, 17, 12, 17, 'He who is truthful testifies honestly,\nbut a false witness lies.\n'),
	(11934, 17, 12, 18, 'There is one who speaks rashly like the piercing of a sword,\nbut the tongue of the wise heals.\n'),
	(11935, 17, 12, 19, 'Truth’s lips will be established forever,\nbut a lying tongue is only momentary.\n'),
	(11936, 17, 12, 20, 'Deceit is in the heart of those who plot evil,\nbut joy comes to the promoters of peace.\n'),
	(11937, 17, 12, 21, 'No mischief shall happen to the righteous,\nbut the wicked shall be filled with evil.\n'),
	(11938, 17, 12, 22, 'Lying lips are an abomination to Yahweh,\nbut those who do the truth are his delight.\n'),
	(11939, 17, 12, 23, 'A prudent man keeps his knowledge,\nbut the hearts of fools proclaim foolishness.\n'),
	(11940, 17, 12, 24, 'The hands of the diligent ones shall rule,\nbut laziness ends in slave labor.\n'),
	(11941, 17, 12, 25, 'Anxiety in a man’s heart weighs it down,\nbut a kind word makes it glad.\n'),
	(11942, 17, 12, 26, 'A righteous person is cautious in friendship,\nbut the way of the wicked leads them astray.\n'),
	(11943, 17, 12, 27, 'The slothful man doesn’t roast his game,\nbut the possessions of diligent men are prized.\n'),
	(11944, 17, 12, 28, 'In the way of righteousness is life;\nin its path there is no death.\n'),
	(11945, 17, 13, 1, 'A wise son listens to his father’s instruction,\nbut a scoffer doesn’t listen to rebuke.\n'),
	(11946, 17, 13, 2, 'By the fruit of his lips, a man enjoys good things;\nbut the unfaithful crave violence.\n'),
	(11947, 17, 13, 3, 'He who guards his mouth guards his soul.\nOne who opens wide his lips comes to ruin.\n'),
	(11948, 17, 13, 4, 'The soul of the sluggard desires, and has nothing,\nbut the desire of the diligent shall be fully satisfied.\n'),
	(11949, 17, 13, 5, 'A righteous man hates lies,\nbut a wicked man brings shame and disgrace.\n'),
	(11950, 17, 13, 6, 'Righteousness guards the way of integrity,\nbut wickedness overthrows the sinner.\n'),
	(11951, 17, 13, 7, 'There are some who pretend to be rich, yet have nothing.\nThere are some who pretend to be poor, yet have great wealth.\n'),
	(11952, 17, 13, 8, 'The ransom of a man’s life is his riches,\nbut the poor hear no threats.\n'),
	(11953, 17, 13, 9, 'The light of the righteous shines brightly,\nbut the lamp of the wicked is snuffed out.\n'),
	(11954, 17, 13, 10, 'Pride only breeds quarrels,\nbut with ones who take advice is wisdom.\n'),
	(11955, 17, 13, 11, 'Wealth gained dishonestly dwindles away,\nbut he who gathers by hand makes it grow.\n'),
	(11956, 17, 13, 12, 'Hope deferred makes the heart sick,\nbut when longing is fulfilled, it is a tree of life.\n'),
	(11957, 17, 13, 13, 'Whoever despises instruction will pay for it,\nbut he who respects a command will be rewarded.\n'),
	(11958, 17, 13, 14, 'The teaching of the wise is a spring of life,\nto turn from the snares of death.\n'),
	(11959, 17, 13, 15, 'Good understanding wins favor;\nbut the way of the unfaithful is hard.\n'),
	(11960, 17, 13, 16, 'Every prudent man acts from knowledge,\nbut a fool exposes folly.\n'),
	(11961, 17, 13, 17, 'A wicked messenger falls into trouble,\nbut a trustworthy envoy gains healing.\n'),
	(11962, 17, 13, 18, 'Poverty and shame come to him who refuses discipline,\nbut he who heeds correction shall be honored.\n'),
	(11963, 17, 13, 19, 'Longing fulfilled is sweet to the soul,\nbut fools detest turning from evil.\n'),
	(11964, 17, 13, 20, 'One who walks with wise men grows wise,\nbut a companion of fools suffers harm.\n'),
	(11965, 17, 13, 21, 'Misfortune pursues sinners,\nbut prosperity rewards the righteous.\n'),
	(11966, 17, 13, 22, 'A good man leaves an inheritance to his children’s children,\nbut the wealth of the sinner is stored for the righteous.\n'),
	(11967, 17, 13, 23, 'An abundance of food is in poor people’s fields,\nbut injustice sweeps it away.\n'),
	(11968, 17, 13, 24, 'One who spares the rod hates his son,\nbut one who loves him is careful to discipline him.\n'),
	(11969, 17, 13, 25, 'The righteous one eats to the satisfying of his soul,\nbut the belly of the wicked goes hungry.\n'),
	(11970, 17, 14, 1, 'Every wise woman builds her house,\nbut the foolish one tears it down with her own hands.\n'),
	(11971, 17, 14, 2, 'He who walks in his uprightness fears Yahweh,\nbut he who is perverse in his ways despises him.\n'),
	(11972, 17, 14, 3, 'The fool’s talk brings a rod to his back,\nbut the lips of the wise protect them.\n'),
	(11973, 17, 14, 4, 'Where no oxen are, the crib is clean,\nbut much increase is by the strength of the ox.\n'),
	(11974, 17, 14, 5, 'A truthful witness will not lie,\nbut a false witness pours out lies.\n'),
	(11975, 17, 14, 6, 'A scoffer seeks wisdom, and doesn’t find it,\nbut knowledge comes easily to a discerning person.\n'),
	(11976, 17, 14, 7, 'Stay away from a foolish man,\nfor you won’t find knowledge on his lips.\n'),
	(11977, 17, 14, 8, 'The wisdom of the prudent is to think about his way,\nbut the folly of fools is deceit.\n'),
	(11978, 17, 14, 9, 'Fools mock at making atonement for sins,\nbut among the upright there is good will.\n'),
	(11979, 17, 14, 10, 'The heart knows its own bitterness and joy;\nhe will not share these with a stranger.\n'),
	(11980, 17, 14, 11, 'The house of the wicked will be overthrown,\nbut the tent of the upright will flourish.\n'),
	(11981, 17, 14, 12, 'There is a way which seems right to a man,\nbut in the end it leads to death.\n'),
	(11982, 17, 14, 13, 'Even in laughter the heart may be sorrowful,\nand mirth may end in heaviness.\n'),
	(11983, 17, 14, 14, 'The unfaithful will be repaid for his own ways;\nlikewise a good man will be rewarded for his ways.\n'),
	(11984, 17, 14, 15, 'A simple man believes everything,\nbut the prudent man carefully considers his ways.\n'),
	(11985, 17, 14, 16, 'A wise man fears and shuns evil,\nbut the fool is hot headed and reckless.\n'),
	(11986, 17, 14, 17, 'He who is quick to become angry will commit folly,\nand a crafty man is hated.\n'),
	(11987, 17, 14, 18, 'The simple inherit folly,\nbut the prudent are crowned with knowledge.\n'),
	(11988, 17, 14, 19, 'The evil bow down before the good,\nand the wicked at the gates of the righteous.\n'),
	(11989, 17, 14, 20, 'The poor person is shunned even by his own neighbor,\nbut the rich person has many friends.\n'),
	(11990, 17, 14, 21, 'He who despises his neighbor sins,\nbut blessed is he who has pity on the poor.\n'),
	(11991, 17, 14, 22, 'Don’t they go astray who plot evil?\nBut love and faithfulness belong to those who plan good.\n'),
	(11992, 17, 14, 23, 'In all hard work there is profit,\nbut the talk of the lips leads only to poverty.\n'),
	(11993, 17, 14, 24, 'The crown of the wise is their riches,\nbut the folly of fools crowns them with folly.\n'),
	(11994, 17, 14, 25, 'A truthful witness saves souls,\nbut a false witness is deceitful.\n'),
	(11995, 17, 14, 26, 'In the fear of Yahweh is a secure fortress,\nand he will be a refuge for his children.\n'),
	(11996, 17, 14, 27, 'The fear of Yahweh is a fountain of life,\nturning people from the snares of death.\n'),
	(11997, 17, 14, 28, 'In the multitude of people is the king’s glory,\nbut in the lack of people is the destruction of the prince.\n'),
	(11998, 17, 14, 29, 'He who is slow to anger has great understanding,\nbut he who has a quick temper displays folly.\n'),
	(11999, 17, 14, 30, 'The life of the body is a heart at peace,\nbut envy rots the bones.\n'),
	(12000, 17, 14, 31, 'He who oppresses the poor shows contempt for his Maker,\nbut he who is kind to the needy honors him.\n'),
	(12001, 17, 14, 32, 'The wicked is brought down in his calamity,\nbut in death, the righteous has a refuge.\n'),
	(12002, 17, 14, 33, 'Wisdom rests in the heart of one who has understanding,\nand is even made known in the inward part of fools.\n'),
	(12003, 17, 14, 34, 'Righteousness exalts a nation,\nbut sin is a disgrace to any people.\n'),
	(12004, 17, 14, 35, 'The king’s favor is toward a servant who deals wisely,\nbut his wrath is toward one who causes shame.\n'),
	(12005, 17, 15, 1, 'A gentle answer turns away wrath,\nbut a harsh word stirs up anger.\n'),
	(12006, 17, 15, 2, 'The tongue of the wise commends knowledge,\nbut the mouth of fools gush out folly.\n'),
	(12007, 17, 15, 3, 'Yahweh’s eyes are everywhere,\nkeeping watch on the evil and the good.\n'),
	(12008, 17, 15, 4, 'A gentle tongue is a tree of life,\nbut deceit in it crushes the spirit.\n'),
	(12009, 17, 15, 5, 'A fool despises his father’s correction,\nbut he who heeds reproof shows prudence.\n'),
	(12010, 17, 15, 6, 'In the house of the righteous is much treasure,\nbut the income of the wicked brings trouble.\n'),
	(12011, 17, 15, 7, 'The lips of the wise spread knowledge;\nnot so with the heart of fools.\n'),
	(12012, 17, 15, 8, 'The sacrifice made by the wicked is an abomination to Yahweh,\nbut the prayer of the upright is his delight.\n'),
	(12013, 17, 15, 9, 'The way of the wicked is an abomination to Yahweh,\nbut he loves him who follows after righteousness.\n'),
	(12014, 17, 15, 10, 'There is stern discipline for one who forsakes the way:\nwhoever hates reproof shall die.\n'),
	(12015, 17, 15, 11, 'Sheol and Abaddon are before Yahweh—\nhow much more then the hearts of the children of men!\n'),
	(12016, 17, 15, 12, 'A scoffer doesn’t love to be reproved;\nhe will not go to the wise.\n'),
	(12017, 17, 15, 13, 'A glad heart makes a cheerful face;\nbut an aching heart breaks the spirit.\n'),
	(12018, 17, 15, 14, 'The heart of one who has understanding seeks knowledge,\nbut the mouths of fools feed on folly.\n'),
	(12019, 17, 15, 15, 'All the days of the afflicted are wretched,\nbut one who has a cheerful heart enjoys a continual feast.\n'),
	(12020, 17, 15, 16, 'Better is little, with the fear of Yahweh,\nthan great treasure with trouble.\n'),
	(12021, 17, 15, 17, 'Better is a dinner of herbs, where love is,\nthan a fattened calf with hatred.\n'),
	(12022, 17, 15, 18, 'A wrathful man stirs up contention,\nbut one who is slow to anger appeases strife.\n'),
	(12023, 17, 15, 19, 'The way of the sluggard is like a thorn patch,\nbut the path of the upright is a highway.\n'),
	(12024, 17, 15, 20, 'A wise son makes a father glad,\nbut a foolish man despises his mother.\n'),
	(12025, 17, 15, 21, 'Folly is joy to one who is void of wisdom,\nbut a man of understanding keeps his way straight.\n'),
	(12026, 17, 15, 22, 'Where there is no counsel, plans fail;\nbut in a multitude of counselors they are established.\n'),
	(12027, 17, 15, 23, 'Joy comes to a man with the reply of his mouth.\nHow good is a word at the right time!\n'),
	(12028, 17, 15, 24, 'The path of life leads upward for the wise,\nto keep him from going downward to Sheol.\n'),
	(12029, 17, 15, 25, 'Yahweh will uproot the house of the proud,\nbut he will keep the widow’s borders intact.\n'),
	(12030, 17, 15, 26, 'Yahweh detests the thoughts of the wicked,\nbut the thoughts of the pure are pleasing.\n'),
	(12031, 17, 15, 27, 'He who is greedy for gain troubles his own house,\nbut he who hates bribes will live.\n'),
	(12032, 17, 15, 28, 'The heart of the righteous weighs answers,\nbut the mouth of the wicked gushes out evil.\n'),
	(12033, 17, 15, 29, 'Yahweh is far from the wicked,\nbut he hears the prayer of the righteous.\n'),
	(12034, 17, 15, 30, 'The light of the eyes rejoices the heart.\nGood news gives health to the bones.\n'),
	(12035, 17, 15, 31, 'The ear that listens to reproof lives,\nand will be at home among the wise.\n'),
	(12036, 17, 15, 32, 'He who refuses correction despises his own soul,\nbut he who listens to reproof gets understanding.\n'),
	(12037, 17, 15, 33, 'The fear of Yahweh teaches wisdom.\nBefore honor is humility.\n'),
	(12038, 17, 16, 1, 'The plans of the heart belong to man,\nbut the answer of the tongue is from Yahweh.\n'),
	(12039, 17, 16, 2, 'All the ways of a man are clean in his own eyes;\nbut Yahweh weighs the motives.\n'),
	(12040, 17, 16, 3, 'Commit your deeds to Yahweh,\nand your plans shall succeed.\n'),
	(12041, 17, 16, 4, 'Yahweh has made everything for its own end—\nyes, even the wicked for the day of evil.\n'),
	(12042, 17, 16, 5, 'Everyone who is proud in heart is an abomination to Yahweh:\nthey shall certainly not be unpunished.\n'),
	(12043, 17, 16, 6, 'By mercy and truth iniquity is atoned for.\nBy the fear of Yahweh men depart from evil.\n'),
	(12044, 17, 16, 7, 'When a man’s ways please Yahweh,\nhe makes even his enemies to be at peace with him.\n'),
	(12045, 17, 16, 8, 'Better is a little with righteousness,\nthan great revenues with injustice.\n'),
	(12046, 17, 16, 9, 'A man’s heart plans his course,\nbut Yahweh directs his steps.\n'),
	(12047, 17, 16, 10, 'Inspired judgments are on the lips of the king.\nHe shall not betray his mouth.\n'),
	(12048, 17, 16, 11, 'Honest balances and scales are Yahweh’s;\nall the weights in the bag are his work.\n'),
	(12049, 17, 16, 12, 'It is an abomination for kings to do wrong,\nfor the throne is established by righteousness.\n'),
	(12050, 17, 16, 13, 'Righteous lips are the delight of kings.\nThey value one who speaks the truth.\n'),
	(12051, 17, 16, 14, 'The king’s wrath is a messenger of death,\nbut a wise man will pacify it.\n'),
	(12052, 17, 16, 15, 'In the light of the king’s face is life.\nHis favor is like a cloud of the spring rain.\n'),
	(12053, 17, 16, 16, 'How much better it is to get wisdom than gold!\nYes, to get understanding is to be chosen rather than silver.\n'),
	(12054, 17, 16, 17, 'The highway of the upright is to depart from evil.\nHe who keeps his way preserves his soul.\n'),
	(12055, 17, 16, 18, 'Pride goes before destruction,\nand a haughty spirit before a fall.\n'),
	(12056, 17, 16, 19, 'It is better to be of a lowly spirit with the poor,\nthan to divide the plunder with the proud.\n'),
	(12057, 17, 16, 20, 'He who heeds the Word finds prosperity.\nWhoever trusts in Yahweh is blessed.\n'),
	(12058, 17, 16, 21, 'The wise in heart shall be called prudent.\nPleasantness of the lips promotes instruction.\n'),
	(12059, 17, 16, 22, 'Understanding is a fountain of life to one who has it,\nbut the punishment of fools is their folly.\n'),
	(12060, 17, 16, 23, 'The heart of the wise instructs his mouth,\nand adds learning to his lips.\n'),
	(12061, 17, 16, 24, 'Pleasant words are a honeycomb,\nsweet to the soul, and health to the bones.\n'),
	(12062, 17, 16, 25, 'There is a way which seems right to a man,\nbut in the end it leads to death.\n'),
	(12063, 17, 16, 26, 'The appetite of the laboring man labors for him;\nfor his mouth urges him on.\n'),
	(12064, 17, 16, 27, 'A worthless man devises mischief.\nHis speech is like a scorching fire.\n'),
	(12065, 17, 16, 28, 'A perverse man stirs up strife.\nA whisperer separates close friends.\n'),
	(12066, 17, 16, 29, 'A man of violence entices his neighbor,\nand leads him in a way that is not good.\n'),
	(12067, 17, 16, 30, 'One who winks his eyes to plot perversities,\none who compresses his lips, is bent on evil.\n'),
	(12068, 17, 16, 31, 'Gray hair is a crown of glory.\nIt is attained by a life of righteousness.\n'),
	(12069, 17, 16, 32, 'One who is slow to anger is better than the mighty;\none who rules his spirit, than he who takes a city.\n'),
	(12070, 17, 16, 33, 'The lot is cast into the lap,\nbut its every decision is from Yahweh.\n'),
	(12071, 17, 17, 1, 'Better is a dry morsel with quietness,\nthan a house full of feasting with strife.\n'),
	(12072, 17, 17, 2, 'A servant who deals wisely will rule over a son who causes shame,\nand shall have a part in the inheritance among the brothers.\n'),
	(12073, 17, 17, 3, 'The refining pot is for silver, and the furnace for gold,\nbut Yahweh tests the hearts.\n'),
	(12074, 17, 17, 4, 'An evildoer heeds wicked lips.\nA liar gives ear to a mischievous tongue.\n'),
	(12075, 17, 17, 5, 'Whoever mocks the poor reproaches his Maker.\nHe who is glad at calamity shall not be unpunished.\n'),
	(12076, 17, 17, 6, 'Children’s children are the crown of old men;\nthe glory of children are their parents.\n'),
	(12077, 17, 17, 7, 'Arrogant speech isn’t fitting for a fool,\nmuch less do lying lips fit a prince.\n'),
	(12078, 17, 17, 8, 'A bribe is a precious stone in the eyes of him who gives it;\nwherever he turns, he prospers.\n'),
	(12079, 17, 17, 9, 'He who covers an offense promotes love;\nbut he who repeats a matter separates best friends.\n'),
	(12080, 17, 17, 10, 'A rebuke enters deeper into one who has understanding\nthan a hundred lashes into a fool.\n'),
	(12081, 17, 17, 11, 'An evil man seeks only rebellion;\ntherefore a cruel messenger shall be sent against him.\n'),
	(12082, 17, 17, 12, 'Let a bear robbed of her cubs meet a man,\nrather than a fool in his folly.\n'),
	(12083, 17, 17, 13, 'Whoever rewards evil for good,\nevil shall not depart from his house.\n'),
	(12084, 17, 17, 14, 'The beginning of strife is like breaching a dam,\ntherefore stop contention before quarreling breaks out.\n'),
	(12085, 17, 17, 15, 'He who justifies the wicked, and he who condemns the righteous,\nboth of them alike are an abomination to Yahweh.\n'),
	(12086, 17, 17, 16, 'Why is there money in the hand of a fool to buy wisdom,\nsince he has no understanding?\n'),
	(12087, 17, 17, 17, 'A friend loves at all times;\nand a brother is born for adversity.\n'),
	(12088, 17, 17, 18, 'A man void of understanding strikes hands,\nand becomes collateral in the presence of his neighbor.\n'),
	(12089, 17, 17, 19, 'He who loves disobedience loves strife.\nOne who builds a high gate seeks destruction.\n'),
	(12090, 17, 17, 20, 'One who has a perverse heart doesn’t find prosperity,\nand one who has a deceitful tongue falls into trouble.\n'),
	(12091, 17, 17, 21, 'He who becomes the father of a fool grieves.\nThe father of a fool has no joy.\n'),
	(12092, 17, 17, 22, 'A cheerful heart makes good medicine,\nbut a crushed spirit dries up the bones.\n'),
	(12093, 17, 17, 23, 'A wicked man receives a bribe in secret,\nto pervert the ways of justice.\n'),
	(12094, 17, 17, 24, 'Wisdom is before the face of one who has understanding,\nbut the eyes of a fool wander to the ends of the earth.\n'),
	(12095, 17, 17, 25, 'A foolish son brings grief to his father,\nand bitterness to her who bore him.\n'),
	(12096, 17, 17, 26, 'Also to punish the righteous is not good,\nnor to flog officials for their integrity.\n'),
	(12097, 17, 17, 27, 'He who spares his words has knowledge.\nHe who is even tempered is a man of understanding.\n'),
	(12098, 17, 17, 28, 'Even a fool, when he keeps silent, is counted wise.\nWhen he shuts his lips, he is thought to be discerning.\n'),
	(12099, 17, 18, 1, 'An unfriendly man pursues selfishness,\nand defies all sound judgment.\n'),
	(12100, 17, 18, 2, 'A fool has no delight in understanding,\nbut only in revealing his own opinion.\n'),
	(12101, 17, 18, 3, 'When wickedness comes, contempt also comes,\nand with shame comes disgrace.\n'),
	(12102, 17, 18, 4, 'The words of a man’s mouth are like deep waters.\nThe fountain of wisdom is like a flowing brook.\n'),
	(12103, 17, 18, 5, 'To be partial to the faces of the wicked is not good,\nnor to deprive the innocent of justice.\n'),
	(12104, 17, 18, 6, 'A fool’s lips come into strife,\nand his mouth invites beatings.\n'),
	(12105, 17, 18, 7, 'A fool’s mouth is his destruction,\nand his lips are a snare to his soul.\n'),
	(12106, 17, 18, 8, 'The words of a gossip are like dainty morsels:\nthey go down into a person’s innermost parts.\n'),
	(12107, 17, 18, 9, 'One who is slack in his work\nis brother to him who is a master of destruction.\n'),
	(12108, 17, 18, 10, 'Yahweh’s name is a strong tower:\nthe righteous run to him, and are safe.\n'),
	(12109, 17, 18, 11, 'The rich man’s wealth is his strong city,\nlike an unscalable wall in his own imagination.\n'),
	(12110, 17, 18, 12, 'Before destruction the heart of man is proud,\nbut before honor is humility.\n'),
	(12111, 17, 18, 13, 'He who gives answer before he hears,\nthat is folly and shame to him.\n'),
	(12112, 17, 18, 14, 'A man’s spirit will sustain him in sickness,\nbut a crushed spirit, who can bear?\n'),
	(12113, 17, 18, 15, 'The heart of the discerning gets knowledge.\nThe ear of the wise seeks knowledge.\n'),
	(12114, 17, 18, 16, 'A man’s gift makes room for him,\nand brings him before great men.\n'),
	(12115, 17, 18, 17, 'He who pleads his cause first seems right;\nuntil another comes and questions him.\n'),
	(12116, 17, 18, 18, 'The lot settles disputes,\nand keeps strong ones apart.\n'),
	(12117, 17, 18, 19, 'A brother offended is more difficult than a fortified city;\nand disputes are like the bars of a fortress.\n'),
	(12118, 17, 18, 20, 'A man’s stomach is filled with the fruit of his mouth.\nWith the harvest of his lips he is satisfied.\n'),
	(12119, 17, 18, 21, 'Death and life are in the power of the tongue;\nthose who love it will eat its fruit.\n'),
	(12120, 17, 18, 22, 'Whoever finds a wife finds a good thing,\nand obtains favor of Yahweh.\n'),
	(12121, 17, 18, 23, 'The poor plead for mercy,\nbut the rich answer harshly.\n'),
	(12122, 17, 18, 24, 'A man of many companions may be ruined,\nbut there is a friend who sticks closer than a brother.\n'),
	(12123, 17, 19, 1, 'Better is the poor who walks in his integrity\nthan he who is perverse in his lips and is a fool.\n'),
	(12124, 17, 19, 2, 'It isn’t good to have zeal without knowledge;\nnor being hasty with one’s feet and missing the way.\n'),
	(12125, 17, 19, 3, 'The foolishness of man subverts his way;\nhis heart rages against Yahweh.\n'),
	(12126, 17, 19, 4, 'Wealth adds many friends,\nbut the poor is separated from his friend.\n'),
	(12127, 17, 19, 5, 'A false witness shall not be unpunished.\nHe who pours out lies shall not go free.\n'),
	(12128, 17, 19, 6, 'Many will entreat the favor of a ruler,\nand everyone is a friend to a man who gives gifts.\n'),
	(12129, 17, 19, 7, 'All the relatives of the poor shun him:\nhow much more do his friends avoid him!\nHe pursues them with pleas, but they are gone.\n'),
	(12130, 17, 19, 8, 'He who gets wisdom loves his own soul.\nHe who keeps understanding shall find good.\n'),
	(12131, 17, 19, 9, 'A false witness shall not be unpunished.\nHe who utters lies shall perish.\n'),
	(12132, 17, 19, 10, 'Delicate living is not appropriate for a fool,\nmuch less for a servant to have rule over princes.\n'),
	(12133, 17, 19, 11, 'The discretion of a man makes him slow to anger.\nIt is his glory to overlook an offense.\n'),
	(12134, 17, 19, 12, 'The king’s wrath is like the roaring of a lion,\nbut his favor is like dew on the grass.\n'),
	(12135, 17, 19, 13, 'A foolish son is the calamity of his father.\nA wife’s quarrels are a continual dripping.\n'),
	(12136, 17, 19, 14, 'House and riches are an inheritance from fathers,\nbut a prudent wife is from Yahweh.\n'),
	(12137, 17, 19, 15, 'Slothfulness casts into a deep sleep.\nThe idle soul shall suffer hunger.\n'),
	(12138, 17, 19, 16, 'He who keeps the commandment keeps his soul,\nbut he who is contemptuous in his ways shall die.\n'),
	(12139, 17, 19, 17, 'He who has pity on the poor lends to Yahweh;\nhe will reward him.\n'),
	(12140, 17, 19, 18, 'Discipline your son, for there is hope;\ndon’t be a willing party to his death.\n'),
	(12141, 17, 19, 19, 'A hot-tempered man must pay the penalty,\nfor if you rescue him, you must do it again.\n'),
	(12142, 17, 19, 20, 'Listen to counsel and receive instruction,\nthat you may be wise in your latter end.\n'),
	(12143, 17, 19, 21, 'There are many plans in a man’s heart,\nbut Yahweh’s counsel will prevail.\n'),
	(12144, 17, 19, 22, 'That which makes a man to be desired is his kindness.\nA poor man is better than a liar.\n'),
	(12145, 17, 19, 23, 'The fear of Yahweh leads to life, then contentment;\nhe rests and will not be touched by trouble.\n'),
	(12146, 17, 19, 24, 'The sluggard buries his hand in the dish;\nhe will not so much as bring it to his mouth again.\n'),
	(12147, 17, 19, 25, 'Flog a scoffer, and the simple will learn prudence;\nrebuke one who has understanding, and he will gain knowledge.\n'),
	(12148, 17, 19, 26, 'He who robs his father and drives away his mother,\nis a son who causes shame and brings reproach.\n'),
	(12149, 17, 19, 27, 'If you stop listening to instruction, my son,\nyou will stray from the words of knowledge.\n'),
	(12150, 17, 19, 28, 'A corrupt witness mocks justice,\nand the mouth of the wicked gulps down iniquity.\n'),
	(12151, 17, 19, 29, 'Penalties are prepared for scoffers,\nand beatings for the backs of fools.\n'),
	(12152, 17, 20, 1, 'Wine is a mocker, and beer is a brawler.\nWhoever is led astray by them is not wise.\n'),
	(12153, 17, 20, 2, 'The terror of a king is like the roaring of a lion.\nHe who provokes him to anger forfeits his own life.\n'),
	(12154, 17, 20, 3, 'It is an honor for a man to keep aloof from strife;\nbut every fool will be quarreling.\n'),
	(12155, 17, 20, 4, 'The sluggard will not plow by reason of the winter;\ntherefore he shall beg in harvest, and have nothing.\n'),
	(12156, 17, 20, 5, 'Counsel in the heart of man is like deep water;\nbut a man of understanding will draw it out.\n'),
	(12157, 17, 20, 6, 'Many men claim to be men of unfailing love,\nbut who can find a faithful man?\n'),
	(12158, 17, 20, 7, 'A righteous man walks in integrity.\nBlessed are his children after him.\n'),
	(12159, 17, 20, 8, 'A king who sits on the throne of judgment\nscatters away all evil with his eyes.\n'),
	(12160, 17, 20, 9, 'Who can say, “I have made my heart pure.\nI am clean and without sin?”\n'),
	(12161, 17, 20, 10, 'Differing weights and differing measures,\nboth of them alike are an abomination to Yahweh.\n'),
	(12162, 17, 20, 11, 'Even a child makes himself known by his doings,\nwhether his work is pure, and whether it is right.\n'),
	(12163, 17, 20, 12, 'The hearing ear, and the seeing eye,\nYahweh has made even both of them.\n'),
	(12164, 17, 20, 13, 'Don’t love sleep, lest you come to poverty.\nOpen your eyes, and you shall be satisfied with bread.\n'),
	(12165, 17, 20, 14, '“It’s no good, it’s no good,” says the buyer;\nbut when he is gone his way, then he boasts.\n'),
	(12166, 17, 20, 15, 'There is gold and abundance of rubies;\nbut the lips of knowledge are a rare jewel.\n'),
	(12167, 17, 20, 16, 'Take the garment of one who puts up collateral for a stranger;\nand hold him in pledge for a wayward woman.\n'),
	(12168, 17, 20, 17, 'Fraudulent food is sweet to a man,\nbut afterwards his mouth is filled with gravel.\n'),
	(12169, 17, 20, 18, 'Plans are established by advice;\nby wise guidance you wage war!\n'),
	(12170, 17, 20, 19, 'He who goes about as a tale-bearer reveals secrets;\ntherefore don’t keep company with him who opens wide his lips.\n'),
	(12171, 17, 20, 20, 'Whoever curses his father or his mother,\nhis lamp shall be put out in blackness of darkness.\n'),
	(12172, 17, 20, 21, 'An inheritance quickly gained at the beginning,\nwon’t be blessed in the end.\n'),
	(12173, 17, 20, 22, 'Don’t say, “I will pay back evil.”\nWait for Yahweh, and he will save you.\n'),
	(12174, 17, 20, 23, 'Yahweh detests differing weights,\nand dishonest scales are not pleasing.\n'),
	(12175, 17, 20, 24, 'A man’s steps are from Yahweh;\nhow then can man understand his way?\n'),
	(12176, 17, 20, 25, 'It is a snare to a man to make a rash dedication,\nthen later to consider his vows.\n'),
	(12177, 17, 20, 26, 'A wise king winnows out the wicked,\nand drives the threshing wheel over them.\n'),
	(12178, 17, 20, 27, 'The spirit of man is Yahweh’s lamp,\nsearching all his innermost parts.\n'),
	(12179, 17, 20, 28, 'Love and faithfulness keep the king safe.\nHis throne is sustained by love.\n'),
	(12180, 17, 20, 29, 'The glory of young men is their strength.\nThe splendor of old men is their gray hair.\n'),
	(12181, 17, 20, 30, 'Wounding blows cleanse away evil,\nand beatings purge the innermost parts.\n'),
	(12182, 17, 21, 1, 'The king’s heart is in Yahweh’s hand like the watercourses.\nHe turns it wherever he desires.\n'),
	(12183, 17, 21, 2, 'Every way of a man is right in his own eyes,\nbut Yahweh weighs the hearts.\n'),
	(12184, 17, 21, 3, 'To do righteousness and justice\nis more acceptable to Yahweh than sacrifice.\n'),
	(12185, 17, 21, 4, 'A high look, and a proud heart,\nthe lamp of the wicked, is sin.\n'),
	(12186, 17, 21, 5, 'The plans of the diligent surely lead to profit;\nand everyone who is hasty surely rushes to poverty.\n'),
	(12187, 17, 21, 6, 'Getting treasures by a lying tongue\nis a fleeting vapor for those who seek death.\n'),
	(12188, 17, 21, 7, 'The violence of the wicked will drive them away,\nbecause they refuse to do what is right.\n'),
	(12189, 17, 21, 8, 'The way of the guilty is devious,\nbut the conduct of the innocent is upright.\n'),
	(12190, 17, 21, 9, 'It is better to dwell in the corner of the housetop,\nthan to share a house with a contentious woman.\n'),
	(12191, 17, 21, 10, 'The soul of the wicked desires evil;\nhis neighbor finds no mercy in his eyes.\n'),
	(12192, 17, 21, 11, 'When the mocker is punished, the simple gains wisdom.\nWhen the wise is instructed, he receives knowledge.\n'),
	(12193, 17, 21, 12, 'The Righteous One considers the house of the wicked,\nand brings the wicked to ruin.\n'),
	(12194, 17, 21, 13, 'Whoever stops his ears at the cry of the poor,\nhe will also cry out, but shall not be heard.\n'),
	(12195, 17, 21, 14, 'A gift in secret pacifies anger;\nand a bribe in the cloak, strong wrath.\n'),
	(12196, 17, 21, 15, 'It is joy to the righteous to do justice;\nbut it is a destruction to the workers of iniquity.\n'),
	(12197, 17, 21, 16, 'The man who wanders out of the way of understanding\nshall rest in the assembly of the departed spirits.\n'),
	(12198, 17, 21, 17, 'He who loves pleasure shall be a poor man.\nHe who loves wine and oil shall not be rich.\n'),
	(12199, 17, 21, 18, 'The wicked is a ransom for the righteous;\nthe treacherous for the upright.\n'),
	(12200, 17, 21, 19, 'It is better to dwell in a desert land,\nthan with a contentious and fretful woman.\n'),
	(12201, 17, 21, 20, 'There is precious treasure and oil in the dwelling of the wise;\nbut a foolish man swallows it up.\n'),
	(12202, 17, 21, 21, 'He who follows after righteousness and kindness\nfinds life, righteousness, and honor.\n'),
	(12203, 17, 21, 22, 'A wise man scales the city of the mighty,\nand brings down the strength of its confidence.\n'),
	(12204, 17, 21, 23, 'Whoever guards his mouth and his tongue\nkeeps his soul from troubles.\n'),
	(12205, 17, 21, 24, 'The proud and haughty man, “scoffer” is his name;\nhe works in the arrogance of pride.\n'),
	(12206, 17, 21, 25, 'The desire of the sluggard kills him,\nfor his hands refuse to labor.\n'),
	(12207, 17, 21, 26, 'There are those who covet greedily all day long;\nbut the righteous give and don’t withhold.\n'),
	(12208, 17, 21, 27, 'The sacrifice of the wicked is an abomination;\nhow much more, when he brings it with a wicked mind!\n'),
	(12209, 17, 21, 28, 'A false witness will perish,\nand a man who listens speaks to eternity.\n'),
	(12210, 17, 21, 29, 'A wicked man hardens his face;\nbut as for the upright, he establishes his ways.\n'),
	(12211, 17, 21, 30, 'There is no wisdom nor understanding\nnor counsel against Yahweh.\n'),
	(12212, 17, 21, 31, 'The horse is prepared for the day of battle;\nbut victory is with Yahweh.\n'),
	(12213, 17, 22, 1, 'A good name is more desirable than great riches,\nand loving favor is better than silver and gold.\n'),
	(12214, 17, 22, 2, 'The rich and the poor have this in common:\nYahweh is the maker of them all.\n'),
	(12215, 17, 22, 3, 'A prudent man sees danger, and hides himself;\nbut the simple pass on, and suffer for it.\n'),
	(12216, 17, 22, 4, 'The result of humility and the fear of Yahweh\nis wealth, honor, and life.\n'),
	(12217, 17, 22, 5, 'Thorns and snares are in the path of the wicked:\nwhoever guards his soul stays from them.\n'),
	(12218, 17, 22, 6, 'Train up a child in the way he should go,\nand when he is old he will not depart from it.\n'),
	(12219, 17, 22, 7, 'The rich rule over the poor.\nThe borrower is servant to the lender.\n'),
	(12220, 17, 22, 8, 'He who sows wickedness reaps trouble,\nand the rod of his fury will be destroyed.\n'),
	(12221, 17, 22, 9, 'He who has a generous eye will be blessed;\nfor he shares his food with the poor.\n'),
	(12222, 17, 22, 10, 'Drive out the mocker, and strife will go out;\nyes, quarrels and insults will stop.\n'),
	(12223, 17, 22, 11, 'He who loves purity of heart and speaks gracefully\nis the king’s friend.\n'),
	(12224, 17, 22, 12, 'Yahweh’s eyes watch over knowledge;\nbut he frustrates the words of the unfaithful.\n'),
	(12225, 17, 22, 13, 'The sluggard says, “There is a lion outside!\nI will be killed in the streets!”\n'),
	(12226, 17, 22, 14, 'The mouth of an adulteress is a deep pit.\nHe who is under Yahweh’s wrath will fall into it.\n'),
	(12227, 17, 22, 15, 'Folly is bound up in the heart of a child:\nthe rod of discipline drives it far from him.\n'),
	(12228, 17, 22, 16, 'Whoever oppresses the poor for his own increase and whoever gives to the rich,\nboth come to poverty.\n'),
	(12229, 17, 22, 17, 'Turn your ear, and listen to the words of the wise.\nApply your heart to my teaching.\n'),
	(12230, 17, 22, 18, 'For it is a pleasant thing if you keep them within you,\nif all of them are ready on your lips.\n'),
	(12231, 17, 22, 19, ' I teach you today, even you,\nSo that your trust may be in Yahweh.\n'),
	(12232, 17, 22, 20, 'Haven’t I written to you thirty excellent things\nof counsel and knowledge,\n'),
	(12233, 17, 22, 21, 'To teach you truth, reliable words,\nto give sound answers to the ones who sent you?\n'),
	(12234, 17, 22, 22, 'Don’t exploit the poor, because he is poor;\nand don’t crush the needy in court;\n'),
	(12235, 17, 22, 23, 'for Yahweh will plead their case,\nand plunder the life of those who plunder them.\n'),
	(12236, 17, 22, 24, 'Don’t befriend a hot-tempered man,\nand don’t associate with one who harbors anger:\n'),
	(12237, 17, 22, 25, 'lest you learn his ways,\nand ensnare your soul.\n'),
	(12238, 17, 22, 26, 'Don’t you be one of those who strike hands,\nof those who are collateral for debts.\n'),
	(12239, 17, 22, 27, 'If you don’t have means to pay,\nwhy should he take away your bed from under you?\n'),
	(12240, 17, 22, 28, 'Don’t move the ancient boundary stone,\nwhich your fathers have set up.\n'),
	(12241, 17, 22, 29, 'Do you see a man skilled in his work?\nHe will serve kings.\nHe won’t serve obscure men.\n'),
	(12242, 17, 23, 1, 'When you sit to eat with a ruler,\nconsider diligently what is before you;\n'),
	(12243, 17, 23, 2, 'put a knife to your throat,\nif you are a man given to appetite.\n'),
	(12244, 17, 23, 3, 'Don’t be desirous of his dainties,\nsince they are deceitful food.\n'),
	(12245, 17, 23, 4, 'Don’t weary yourself to be rich.\nIn your wisdom, show restraint.\n'),
	(12246, 17, 23, 5, 'Why do you set your eyes on that which is not?\nFor it certainly sprouts wings like an eagle and flies in the sky.\n'),
	(12247, 17, 23, 6, 'Don’t eat the food of him who has a stingy eye,\nand don’t crave his delicacies:\n'),
	(12248, 17, 23, 7, 'for as he thinks about the cost, so he is.\n“Eat and drink!” he says to you,\nbut his heart is not with you.\n'),
	(12249, 17, 23, 8, 'The morsel which you have eaten you shall vomit up,\nand lose your good words.\n'),
	(12250, 17, 23, 9, 'Don’t speak in the ears of a fool,\nfor he will despise the wisdom of your words.\n'),
	(12251, 17, 23, 10, 'Don’t move the ancient boundary stone.\nDon’t encroach on the fields of the fatherless:\n'),
	(12252, 17, 23, 11, 'for their Defender is strong.\nHe will plead their case against you.\n'),
	(12253, 17, 23, 12, 'Apply your heart to instruction,\nand your ears to the words of knowledge.\n'),
	(12254, 17, 23, 13, 'Don’t withhold correction from a child.\nIf you punish him with the rod, he will not die.\n'),
	(12255, 17, 23, 14, 'Punish him with the rod,\nand save his soul from Sheol.\n'),
	(12256, 17, 23, 15, 'My son, if your heart is wise,\nthen my heart will be glad, even mine:\n'),
	(12257, 17, 23, 16, 'yes, my heart will rejoice,\nwhen your lips speak what is right.\n'),
	(12258, 17, 23, 17, 'Don’t let your heart envy sinners;\nbut rather fear Yahweh all day long.\n'),
	(12259, 17, 23, 18, 'Indeed surely there is a future hope,\nand your hope will not be cut off.\n'),
	(12260, 17, 23, 19, 'Listen, my son, and be wise,\nand keep your heart on the right path!\n'),
	(12261, 17, 23, 20, 'Don’t be among ones drinking too much wine,\nor those who gorge themselves on meat:\n'),
	(12262, 17, 23, 21, 'for the drunkard and the glutton shall become poor;\nand drowsiness clothes them in rags.\n'),
	(12263, 17, 23, 22, 'Listen to your father who gave you life,\nand don’t despise your mother when she is old.\n'),
	(12264, 17, 23, 23, 'Buy the truth, and don’t sell it.\nGet wisdom, discipline, and understanding.\n'),
	(12265, 17, 23, 24, 'The father of the righteous has great joy.\nWhoever fathers a wise child delights in him.\n'),
	(12266, 17, 23, 25, 'Let your father and your mother be glad!\nLet her who bore you rejoice!\n'),
	(12267, 17, 23, 26, 'My son, give me your heart;\nand let your eyes keep in my ways.\n'),
	(12268, 17, 23, 27, 'For a prostitute is a deep pit;\nand a wayward wife is a narrow well.\n'),
	(12269, 17, 23, 28, 'Yes, she lies in wait like a robber,\nand increases the unfaithful among men.\n'),
	(12270, 17, 23, 29, 'Who has woe?\nWho has sorrow?\nWho has strife?\nWho has complaints?\nWho has needless bruises?\nWho has bloodshot eyes?\n'),
	(12271, 17, 23, 30, 'Those who stay long at the wine;\nthose who go to seek out mixed wine.\n'),
	(12272, 17, 23, 31, 'Don’t look at the wine when it is red,\nwhen it sparkles in the cup,\nwhen it goes down smoothly.\n'),
	(12273, 17, 23, 32, 'In the end, it bites like a snake,\nand poisons like a viper.\n'),
	(12274, 17, 23, 33, 'Your eyes will see strange things,\nand your mind will imagine confusing things.\n'),
	(12275, 17, 23, 34, 'Yes, you will be as he who lies down in the middle of the sea,\nor as he who lies on top of the rigging:\n'),
	(12276, 17, 23, 35, '“They hit me, and I was not hurt!\nThey beat me, and I don’t feel it!\nWhen will I wake up? I can do it again.\nI can find another.”\n'),
	(12277, 17, 24, 1, 'Don’t be envious of evil men;\nneither desire to be with them:\n'),
	(12278, 17, 24, 2, 'for their hearts plot violence,\nand their lips talk about mischief.\n'),
	(12279, 17, 24, 3, 'Through wisdom a house is built;\nby understanding it is established;\n'),
	(12280, 17, 24, 4, 'by knowledge the rooms are filled\nwith all rare and beautiful treasure.\n'),
	(12281, 17, 24, 5, 'A wise man has great power;\nand a knowledgeable man increases strength;\n'),
	(12282, 17, 24, 6, 'for by wise guidance you wage your war;\nand victory is in many advisors.\n'),
	(12283, 17, 24, 7, 'Wisdom is too high for a fool:\nhe doesn’t open his mouth in the gate.\n'),
	(12284, 17, 24, 8, 'One who plots to do evil\nwill be called a schemer.\n'),
	(12285, 17, 24, 9, 'The schemes of folly are sin.\nThe mocker is detested by men.\n'),
	(12286, 17, 24, 10, 'If you falter in the time of trouble,\nyour strength is small.\n'),
	(12287, 17, 24, 11, 'Rescue those who are being led away to death!\nIndeed, hold back those who are staggering to the slaughter!\n'),
	(12288, 17, 24, 12, 'If you say, “Behold, we didn’t know this”;\ndoesn’t he who weighs the hearts consider it?\nHe who keeps your soul, doesn’t he know it?\nShall he not render to every man according to his work?\n'),
	(12289, 17, 24, 13, 'My son, eat honey, for it is good;\nthe droppings of the honeycomb, which are sweet to your taste:\n'),
	(12290, 17, 24, 14, 'so you shall know wisdom to be to your soul;\nif you have found it, then there will be a reward,\nyour hope will not be cut off.\n'),
	(12291, 17, 24, 15, 'Don’t lay in wait, wicked man, against the habitation of the righteous.\nDon’t destroy his resting place:\n'),
	(12292, 17, 24, 16, 'for a righteous man falls seven times, and rises up again;\nbut the wicked are overthrown by calamity.\n'),
	(12293, 17, 24, 17, 'Don’t rejoice when your enemy falls.\nDon’t let your heart be glad when he is overthrown;\n'),
	(12294, 17, 24, 18, 'lest Yahweh see it, and it displease him,\nand he turn away his wrath from him.\n'),
	(12295, 17, 24, 19, 'Don’t fret yourself because of evildoers;\nneither be envious of the wicked:\n'),
	(12296, 17, 24, 20, 'for there will be no reward to the evil man;\nand the lamp of the wicked shall be snuffed out.\n'),
	(12297, 17, 24, 21, 'My son, fear Yahweh and the king.\nDon’t join those who are rebellious:\n'),
	(12298, 17, 24, 22, 'for their calamity will rise suddenly;\nthe destruction from them both—who knows?\n'),
	(12299, 17, 24, 23, 'These also are sayings of the wise.\nTo show partiality in judgment is not good.\n'),
	(12300, 17, 24, 24, 'He who says to the wicked, “You are righteous”;\npeoples will curse him, and nations will abhor him—\n'),
	(12301, 17, 24, 25, 'but it will go well with those who convict the guilty,\nand a rich blessing will come on them.\n'),
	(12302, 17, 24, 26, 'An honest answer\nis like a kiss on the lips.\n'),
	(12303, 17, 24, 27, 'Prepare your work outside,\nand get your fields ready.\nAfterwards, build your house.\n'),
	(12304, 17, 24, 28, 'Don’t be a witness against your neighbor without cause.\nDon’t deceive with your lips.\n'),
	(12305, 17, 24, 29, 'Don’t say, “I will do to him as he has done to me;\nI will render to the man according to his work.”\n'),
	(12306, 17, 24, 30, 'I went by the field of the sluggard,\nby the vineyard of the man void of understanding;\n'),
	(12307, 17, 24, 31, 'Behold, it was all grown over with thorns.\nIts surface was covered with nettles,\nand its stone wall was broken down.\n'),
	(12308, 17, 24, 32, 'Then I saw, and considered well.\nI saw, and received instruction:\n'),
	(12309, 17, 24, 33, 'a little sleep, a little slumber,\na little folding of the hands to sleep;\n'),
	(12310, 17, 24, 34, 'so your poverty will come as a robber,\nand your want as an armed man.\n'),
	(12311, 17, 25, 1, 'These also are proverbs of Solomon, which the men of Hezekiah king of Judah copied out.\n'),
	(12312, 17, 25, 2, 'It is the glory of God to conceal a thing,\nbut the glory of kings is to search out a matter.\n'),
	(12313, 17, 25, 3, 'As the heavens for height, and the earth for depth,\nso the hearts of kings are unsearchable.\n'),
	(12314, 17, 25, 4, 'Take away the dross from the silver,\nand material comes out for the refiner;\n'),
	(12315, 17, 25, 5, 'Take away the wicked from the king’s presence,\nand his throne will be established in righteousness.\n'),
	(12316, 17, 25, 6, 'Don’t exalt yourself in the presence of the king,\nor claim a place among great men;\n'),
	(12317, 17, 25, 7, 'for it is better that it be said to you, “Come up here,”\nthan that you should be put lower in the presence of the prince,\nwhom your eyes have seen.\n'),
	(12318, 17, 25, 8, 'Don’t be hasty in bringing charges to court.\nWhat will you do in the end when your neighbor shames you?\n'),
	(12319, 17, 25, 9, 'Debate your case with your neighbor,\nand don’t betray the confidence of another;\n'),
	(12320, 17, 25, 10, 'lest one who hears it put you to shame,\nand your bad reputation never depart.\n'),
	(12321, 17, 25, 11, 'A word fitly spoken\nis like apples of gold in settings of silver.\n'),
	(12322, 17, 25, 12, 'As an earring of gold, and an ornament of fine gold,\nso is a wise reprover to an obedient ear.\n'),
	(12323, 17, 25, 13, 'As the cold of snow in the time of harvest,\nso is a faithful messenger to those who send him;\nfor he refreshes the soul of his masters.\n'),
	(12324, 17, 25, 14, 'As clouds and wind without rain,\nso is he who boasts of gifts deceptively.\n'),
	(12325, 17, 25, 15, 'By patience a ruler is persuaded.\nA soft tongue breaks the bone.\n'),
	(12326, 17, 25, 16, 'Have you found honey?\nEat as much as is sufficient for you,\nlest you eat too much, and vomit it.\n'),
	(12327, 17, 25, 17, 'Let your foot be seldom in your neighbor’s house,\nlest he be weary of you, and hate you.\n'),
	(12328, 17, 25, 18, 'A man who gives false testimony against his neighbor\nis like a club, a sword, or a sharp arrow.\n'),
	(12329, 17, 25, 19, 'Confidence in someone unfaithful in time of trouble\nis like a bad tooth, or a lame foot.\n'),
	(12330, 17, 25, 20, 'As one who takes away a garment in cold weather,\nor vinegar on soda,\nso is one who sings songs to a heavy heart.\n'),
	(12331, 17, 25, 21, 'If your enemy is hungry, give him food to eat.\nIf he is thirsty, give him water to drink:\n'),
	(12332, 17, 25, 22, 'for you will heap coals of fire on his head,\nand Yahweh will reward you.\n'),
	(12333, 17, 25, 23, 'The north wind produces rain;\nso a backbiting tongue brings an angry face.\n'),
	(12334, 17, 25, 24, 'It is better to dwell in the corner of the housetop,\nthan to share a house with a contentious woman.\n'),
	(12335, 17, 25, 25, 'Like cold water to a thirsty soul,\nso is good news from a far country.\n'),
	(12336, 17, 25, 26, 'Like a muddied spring, and a polluted well,\nso is a righteous man who gives way before the wicked.\n'),
	(12337, 17, 25, 27, 'It is not good to eat much honey;\nnor is it honorable to seek one’s own honor.\n'),
	(12338, 17, 25, 28, 'Like a city that is broken down and without walls\nis a man whose spirit is without restraint.\n'),
	(12339, 17, 26, 1, 'Like snow in summer, and as rain in harvest,\nso honor is not fitting for a fool.\n'),
	(12340, 17, 26, 2, 'Like a fluttering sparrow,\nlike a darting swallow,\nso the undeserved curse doesn’t come to rest.\n'),
	(12341, 17, 26, 3, 'A whip is for the horse,\na bridle for the donkey,\nand a rod for the back of fools!\n'),
	(12342, 17, 26, 4, 'Don’t answer a fool according to his folly,\nlest you also be like him.\n'),
	(12343, 17, 26, 5, 'Answer a fool according to his folly,\nlest he be wise in his own eyes.\n'),
	(12344, 17, 26, 6, 'One who sends a message by the hand of a fool\nis cutting off feet and drinking violence.\n'),
	(12345, 17, 26, 7, 'Like the legs of the lame that hang loose,\nso is a parable in the mouth of fools.\n'),
	(12346, 17, 26, 8, 'As one who binds a stone in a sling,\nso is he who gives honor to a fool.\n'),
	(12347, 17, 26, 9, 'Like a thorn bush that goes into the hand of a drunkard,\nso is a parable in the mouth of fools.\n'),
	(12348, 17, 26, 10, 'As an archer who wounds all,\nso is he who hires a fool\nor he who hires those who pass by.\n'),
	(12349, 17, 26, 11, 'As a dog that returns to his vomit,\nso is a fool who repeats his folly.\n'),
	(12350, 17, 26, 12, 'Do you see a man wise in his own eyes?\nThere is more hope for a fool than for him.\n'),
	(12351, 17, 26, 13, 'The sluggard says, “There is a lion in the road!\nA fierce lion roams the streets!”\n'),
	(12352, 17, 26, 14, 'As the door turns on its hinges,\nso does the sluggard on his bed.\n'),
	(12353, 17, 26, 15, 'The sluggard buries his hand in the dish.\nHe is too lazy to bring it back to his mouth.\n'),
	(12354, 17, 26, 16, 'The sluggard is wiser in his own eyes\nthan seven men who answer with discretion.\n'),
	(12355, 17, 26, 17, 'Like one who grabs a dog’s ears\nis one who passes by and meddles in a quarrel not his own.\n'),
	(12356, 17, 26, 18, 'Like a madman who shoots torches, arrows, and death,\n'),
	(12357, 17, 26, 19, 'is the man who deceives his neighbor and says, “Am I not joking?”\n'),
	(12358, 17, 26, 20, 'For lack of wood a fire goes out.\nWithout gossip, a quarrel dies down.\n'),
	(12359, 17, 26, 21, 'As coals are to hot embers,\nand wood to fire,\nso is a contentious man to kindling strife.\n'),
	(12360, 17, 26, 22, 'The words of a whisperer are as dainty morsels,\nthey go down into the innermost parts.\n'),
	(12361, 17, 26, 23, 'Like silver dross on an earthen vessel\nare the lips of a fervent one with an evil heart.\n'),
	(12362, 17, 26, 24, 'A malicious man disguises himself with his lips,\nbut he harbors evil in his heart.\n'),
	(12363, 17, 26, 25, 'When his speech is charming, don’t believe him;\nfor there are seven abominations in his heart.\n'),
	(12364, 17, 26, 26, 'His malice may be concealed by deception,\nbut his wickedness will be exposed in the assembly.\n'),
	(12365, 17, 26, 27, 'Whoever digs a pit shall fall into it.\nWhoever rolls a stone, it will come back on him.\n'),
	(12366, 17, 26, 28, 'A lying tongue hates those it hurts;\nand a flattering mouth works ruin.\n'),
	(12367, 17, 27, 1, 'Don’t boast about tomorrow;\nfor you don’t know what a day may bring.\n'),
	(12368, 17, 27, 2, 'Let another man praise you,\nand not your own mouth;\na stranger, and not your own lips.\n'),
	(12369, 17, 27, 3, 'A stone is heavy,\nand sand is a burden;\nbut a fool’s provocation is heavier than both.\n'),
	(12370, 17, 27, 4, 'Wrath is cruel,\nand anger is overwhelming;\nbut who is able to stand before jealousy?\n'),
	(12371, 17, 27, 5, 'Better is open rebuke\nthan hidden love.\n'),
	(12372, 17, 27, 6, 'Faithful are the wounds of a friend;\nalthough the kisses of an enemy are profuse.\n'),
	(12373, 17, 27, 7, 'A full soul loathes a honeycomb;\nbut to a hungry soul, every bitter thing is sweet.\n'),
	(12374, 17, 27, 8, 'As a bird that wanders from her nest,\nso is a man who wanders from his home.\n'),
	(12375, 17, 27, 9, 'Perfume and incense bring joy to the heart;\nso does earnest counsel from a man’s friend.\n'),
	(12376, 17, 27, 10, 'Don’t forsake your friend and your father’s friend.\nDon’t go to your brother’s house in the day of your disaster:\nbetter is a neighbor who is near than a distant brother.\n'),
	(12377, 17, 27, 11, 'Be wise, my son,\nand bring joy to my heart,\nthen I can answer my tormentor.\n'),
	(12378, 17, 27, 12, 'A prudent man sees danger and takes refuge;\nbut the simple pass on, and suffer for it.\n'),
	(12379, 17, 27, 13, 'Take his garment when he puts up collateral for a stranger.\nHold it for a wayward woman!\n'),
	(12380, 17, 27, 14, 'He who blesses his neighbor with a loud voice early in the morning,\nit will be taken as a curse by him.\n'),
	(12381, 17, 27, 15, 'A continual dropping on a rainy day\nand a contentious wife are alike:\n'),
	(12382, 17, 27, 16, 'restraining her is like restraining the wind,\nor like grasping oil in his right hand.\n'),
	(12383, 17, 27, 17, 'Iron sharpens iron;\nso a man sharpens his friend’s countenance.\n'),
	(12384, 17, 27, 18, 'Whoever tends the fig tree shall eat its fruit.\nHe who looks after his master shall be honored.\n'),
	(12385, 17, 27, 19, 'Like water reflects a face,\nso a man’s heart reflects the man.\n'),
	(12386, 17, 27, 20, 'Sheol and Abaddon are never satisfied;\nand a man’s eyes are never satisfied.\n'),
	(12387, 17, 27, 21, 'The crucible is for silver,\nand the furnace for gold;\nbut man is refined by his praise.\n'),
	(12388, 17, 27, 22, 'Though you grind a fool in a mortar with a pestle along with grain,\nyet his foolishness will not be removed from him.\n'),
	(12389, 17, 27, 23, 'Know well the state of your flocks,\nand pay attention to your herds:\n'),
	(12390, 17, 27, 24, 'for riches are not forever,\nnor does the crown endure to all generations.\n'),
	(12391, 17, 27, 25, 'The hay is removed, and the new growth appears,\nthe grasses of the hills are gathered in.\n'),
	(12392, 17, 27, 26, 'The lambs are for your clothing,\nand the goats are the price of a field.\n'),
	(12393, 17, 27, 27, 'There will be plenty of goats’ milk for your food,\nfor your family’s food,\nand for the nourishment of your servant girls.\n'),
	(12394, 17, 28, 1, 'The wicked flee when no one pursues;\nbut the righteous are as bold as a lion.\n'),
	(12395, 17, 28, 2, 'In rebellion, a land has many rulers,\nbut order is maintained by a man of understanding and knowledge.\n'),
	(12396, 17, 28, 3, 'A needy man who oppresses the poor\nis like a driving rain which leaves no crops.\n'),
	(12397, 17, 28, 4, 'Those who forsake the law praise the wicked;\nbut those who keep the law contend with them.\n'),
	(12398, 17, 28, 5, 'Evil men don’t understand justice;\nbut those who seek Yahweh understand it fully.\n'),
	(12399, 17, 28, 6, 'Better is the poor who walks in his integrity,\nthan he who is perverse in his ways, and he is rich.\n'),
	(12400, 17, 28, 7, 'Whoever keeps the law is a wise son;\nbut he who is a companion of gluttons shames his father.\n'),
	(12401, 17, 28, 8, 'He who increases his wealth by excessive interest\ngathers it for one who has pity on the poor.\n'),
	(12402, 17, 28, 9, 'He who turns away his ear from hearing the law,\neven his prayer is an abomination.\n'),
	(12403, 17, 28, 10, 'Whoever causes the upright to go astray in an evil way,\nhe will fall into his own trap;\nbut the blameless will inherit good.\n'),
	(12404, 17, 28, 11, 'The rich man is wise in his own eyes;\nbut the poor who has understanding sees through him.\n'),
	(12405, 17, 28, 12, 'When the righteous triumph, there is great glory;\nbut when the wicked rise, men hide themselves.\n'),
	(12406, 17, 28, 13, 'He who conceals his sins doesn’t prosper,\nbut whoever confesses and renounces them finds mercy.\n'),
	(12407, 17, 28, 14, 'Blessed is the man who always fears;\nbut one who hardens his heart falls into trouble.\n'),
	(12408, 17, 28, 15, 'As a roaring lion or a charging bear,\nso is a wicked ruler over helpless people.\n'),
	(12409, 17, 28, 16, 'A tyrannical ruler lacks judgment.\nOne who hates ill-gotten gain will have long days.\n'),
	(12410, 17, 28, 17, 'A man who is tormented by life blood will be a fugitive until death;\nno one will support him.\n'),
	(12411, 17, 28, 18, 'Whoever walks blamelessly is kept safe;\nbut one with perverse ways will fall suddenly.\n'),
	(12412, 17, 28, 19, 'One who works his land will have an abundance of food;\nbut one who chases fantasies will have his fill of poverty.\n'),
	(12413, 17, 28, 20, 'A faithful man is rich with blessings;\nbut one who is eager to be rich will not go unpunished.\n'),
	(12414, 17, 28, 21, 'To show partiality is not good;\nyet a man will do wrong for a piece of bread.\n'),
	(12415, 17, 28, 22, 'A stingy man hurries after riches,\nand doesn’t know that poverty waits for him.\n'),
	(12416, 17, 28, 23, 'One who rebukes a man will afterward find more favor\nthan one who flatters with the tongue.\n'),
	(12417, 17, 28, 24, 'Whoever robs his father or his mother, and says, “It’s not wrong.”\nHe is a partner with a destroyer.\n'),
	(12418, 17, 28, 25, 'One who is greedy stirs up strife;\nbut one who trusts in Yahweh will prosper.\n'),
	(12419, 17, 28, 26, 'One who trusts in himself is a fool;\nbut one who walks in wisdom is kept safe.\n'),
	(12420, 17, 28, 27, 'One who gives to the poor has no lack;\nbut one who closes his eyes will have many curses.\n'),
	(12421, 17, 28, 28, 'When the wicked rise, men hide themselves;\nbut when they perish, the righteous thrive.\n'),
	(12422, 17, 29, 1, 'He who is often rebuked and stiffens his neck\nwill be destroyed suddenly, with no remedy.\n'),
	(12423, 17, 29, 2, 'When the righteous thrive, the people rejoice;\nbut when the wicked rule, the people groan.\n'),
	(12424, 17, 29, 3, 'Whoever loves wisdom brings joy to his father;\nbut a companion of prostitutes squanders his wealth.\n'),
	(12425, 17, 29, 4, 'The king by justice makes the land stable,\nbut he who takes bribes tears it down.\n'),
	(12426, 17, 29, 5, 'A man who flatters his neighbor\nspreads a net for his feet.\n'),
	(12427, 17, 29, 6, 'An evil man is snared by his sin,\nbut the righteous can sing and be glad.\n'),
	(12428, 17, 29, 7, 'The righteous care about justice for the poor.\nThe wicked aren’t concerned about knowledge.\n'),
	(12429, 17, 29, 8, 'Mockers stir up a city,\nbut wise men turn away anger.\n'),
	(12430, 17, 29, 9, 'If a wise man goes to court with a foolish man,\nthe fool rages or scoffs, and there is no peace.\n'),
	(12431, 17, 29, 10, 'The bloodthirsty hate a man of integrity;\nand they seek the life of the upright.\n'),
	(12432, 17, 29, 11, 'A fool vents all of his anger,\nbut a wise man brings himself under control.\n'),
	(12433, 17, 29, 12, 'If a ruler listens to lies,\nall of his officials are wicked.\n'),
	(12434, 17, 29, 13, 'The poor man and the oppressor have this in common:\nYahweh gives sight to the eyes of both.\n'),
	(12435, 17, 29, 14, 'The king who fairly judges the poor,\nhis throne shall be established forever.\n'),
	(12436, 17, 29, 15, 'The rod of correction gives wisdom,\nbut a child left to himself causes shame to his mother.\n'),
	(12437, 17, 29, 16, 'When the wicked increase, sin increases;\nbut the righteous will see their downfall.\n'),
	(12438, 17, 29, 17, 'Correct your son, and he will give you peace;\nyes, he will bring delight to your soul.\n'),
	(12439, 17, 29, 18, 'Where there is no revelation, the people cast off restraint;\nbut one who keeps the law is blessed.\n'),
	(12440, 17, 29, 19, 'A servant can’t be corrected by words.\nThough he understands, yet he will not respond.\n'),
	(12441, 17, 29, 20, 'Do you see a man who is hasty in his words?\nThere is more hope for a fool than for him.\n'),
	(12442, 17, 29, 21, 'He who pampers his servant from youth\nwill have him become a son in the end.\n'),
	(12443, 17, 29, 22, 'An angry man stirs up strife,\nand a wrathful man abounds in sin.\n'),
	(12444, 17, 29, 23, 'A man’s pride brings him low,\nbut one of lowly spirit gains honor.\n'),
	(12445, 17, 29, 24, 'Whoever is an accomplice of a thief is an enemy of his own soul.\nHe takes an oath, but dares not testify.\n'),
	(12446, 17, 29, 25, 'The fear of man proves to be a snare,\nbut whoever puts his trust in Yahweh is kept safe.\n'),
	(12447, 17, 29, 26, 'Many seek the ruler’s favor,\nbut a man’s justice comes from Yahweh.\n'),
	(12448, 17, 29, 27, 'A dishonest man detests the righteous,\nand the upright in their ways detest the wicked.\n'),
	(12449, 17, 30, 1, 'The words of Agur the son of Jakeh; the revelation:\nthe man says to Ithiel,\nto Ithiel and Ucal:\n'),
	(12450, 17, 30, 2, '“Surely I am the most ignorant man,\nand don’t have a man’s understanding.\n'),
	(12451, 17, 30, 3, 'I have not learned wisdom,\nneither do I have the knowledge of the Holy One.\n'),
	(12452, 17, 30, 4, 'Who has ascended up into heaven, and descended?\nWho has gathered the wind in his fists?\nWho has bound the waters in his garment?\nWho has established all the ends of the earth?\nWhat is his name, and what is his son’s name, if you know?\n'),
	(12453, 17, 30, 5, '“Every word of God is flawless.\nHe is a shield to those who take refuge in him.\n'),
	(12454, 17, 30, 6, 'Don’t you add to his words,\nlest he reprove you, and you be found a liar.\n'),
	(12455, 17, 30, 7, '“Two things I have asked of you;\ndon’t deny me before I die:\n'),
	(12456, 17, 30, 8, 'Remove far from me falsehood and lies.\nGive me neither poverty nor riches.\nFeed me with the food that is needful for me;\n'),
	(12457, 17, 30, 9, 'lest I be full, deny you, and say, ‘Who is Yahweh?’\nor lest I be poor, and steal,\nand so dishonor the name of my God.\n'),
	(12458, 17, 30, 10, '“Don’t slander a servant to his master,\nlest he curse you, and you be held guilty.\n'),
	(12459, 17, 30, 11, 'There is a generation that curses their father,\nand doesn’t bless their mother.\n'),
	(12460, 17, 30, 12, 'There is a generation that is pure in their own eyes,\nyet are not washed from their filthiness.\n'),
	(12461, 17, 30, 13, 'There is a generation, oh how lofty are their eyes!\nTheir eyelids are lifted up.\n'),
	(12462, 17, 30, 14, 'There is a generation whose teeth are like swords,\nand their jaws like knives,\nto devour the poor from the earth, and the needy from among men.\n'),
	(12463, 17, 30, 15, '“The leach has two daughters:\n‘Give, give.’\n“There are three things that are never satisfied;\nfour that don’t say, ‘Enough:’\n'),
	(12464, 17, 30, 16, 'Sheol,\nthe barren womb;\nthe earth that is not satisfied with water;\nand the fire that doesn’t say, ‘Enough.’\n'),
	(12465, 17, 30, 17, '“The eye that mocks at his father,\nand scorns obedience to his mother:\nthe ravens of the valley shall pick it out,\nthe young eagles shall eat it.\n'),
	(12466, 17, 30, 18, '“There are three things which are too amazing for me,\nfour which I don’t understand:\n'),
	(12467, 17, 30, 19, 'The way of an eagle in the air;\nthe way of a serpent on a rock;\nthe way of a ship in the middle of the sea;\nand the way of a man with a maiden.\n'),
	(12468, 17, 30, 20, '“So is the way of an adulterous woman:\nshe eats and wipes her mouth,\nand says, ‘I have done nothing wrong.’\n'),
	(12469, 17, 30, 21, '“For three things the earth trembles,\nand under four, it can’t bear up:\n'),
	(12470, 17, 30, 22, 'For a servant when he is king;\na fool when he is filled with food;\n'),
	(12471, 17, 30, 23, 'for an unloved woman when she is married;\nand a servant who is heir to her mistress.\n'),
	(12472, 17, 30, 24, '“There are four things which are little on the earth,\nbut they are exceedingly wise:\n'),
	(12473, 17, 30, 25, 'the ants are not a strong people,\nyet they provide their food in the summer.\n'),
	(12474, 17, 30, 26, 'The conies are but a feeble folk,\nyet make they their houses in the rocks.\n'),
	(12475, 17, 30, 27, 'The locusts have no king,\nyet they advance in ranks.\n'),
	(12476, 17, 30, 28, 'You can catch a lizard with your hands,\nyet it is in kings’ palaces.\n'),
	(12477, 17, 30, 29, '“There are three things which are stately in their march,\nfour which are stately in going:\n'),
	(12478, 17, 30, 30, 'The lion, which is mightiest among animals,\nand doesn’t turn away for any;\n'),
	(12479, 17, 30, 31, 'the greyhound,\nthe male goat also;\nand the king against whom there is no rising up.\n'),
	(12480, 17, 30, 32, '“If you have done foolishly in lifting up yourself,\nor if you have thought evil,\nput your hand over your mouth.\n'),
	(12481, 17, 30, 33, 'For as the churning of milk produces butter,\nand the wringing of the nose produces blood;\nso the forcing of wrath produces strife.”\n'),
	(12482, 17, 31, 1, 'The words of king Lemuel; the revelation which his mother taught him.\n'),
	(12483, 17, 31, 2, '“Oh, my son!\nOh, son of my womb!\nOh, son of my vows!\n'),
	(12484, 17, 31, 3, 'Don’t give your strength to women,\nnor your ways to that which destroys kings.\n'),
	(12485, 17, 31, 4, 'It is not for kings, Lemuel;\nit is not for kings to drink wine;\nnor for princes to say, ‘Where is strong drink?’\n'),
	(12486, 17, 31, 5, 'lest they drink, and forget the law,\nand pervert the justice due to anyone who is afflicted.\n'),
	(12487, 17, 31, 6, 'Give strong drink to him who is ready to perish;\nand wine to the bitter in soul:\n'),
	(12488, 17, 31, 7, 'Let him drink, and forget his poverty,\nand remember his misery no more.\n'),
	(12489, 17, 31, 8, 'Open your mouth for the mute,\nin the cause of all who are left desolate.\n'),
	(12490, 17, 31, 9, 'Open your mouth, judge righteously,\nand serve justice to the poor and needy.”\n'),
	(12491, 17, 31, 10, '\nWho can find a worthy woman?\nFor her price is far above rubies.\n'),
	(12492, 17, 31, 11, 'The heart of her husband trusts in her.\nHe shall have no lack of gain.\n'),
	(12493, 17, 31, 12, 'She does him good, and not harm,\nall the days of her life.\n'),
	(12494, 17, 31, 13, 'She seeks wool and flax,\nand works eagerly with her hands.\n'),
	(12495, 17, 31, 14, 'She is like the merchant ships.\nShe brings her bread from afar.\n'),
	(12496, 17, 31, 15, 'She rises also while it is yet night,\ngives food to her household,\nand portions for her servant girls.\n'),
	(12497, 17, 31, 16, 'She considers a field, and buys it.\nWith the fruit of her hands, she plants a vineyard.\n'),
	(12498, 17, 31, 17, 'She arms her waist with strength,\nand makes her arms strong.\n'),
	(12499, 17, 31, 18, 'She perceives that her merchandise is profitable.\nHer lamp doesn’t go out by night.\n'),
	(12500, 17, 31, 19, 'She lays her hands to the distaff,\nand her hands hold the spindle.\n'),
	(12501, 17, 31, 20, 'She opens her arms to the poor;\nyes, she extends her hands to the needy.\n'),
	(12502, 17, 31, 21, 'She is not afraid of the snow for her household;\nfor all her household are clothed with scarlet.\n'),
	(12503, 17, 31, 22, 'She makes for herself carpets of tapestry.\nHer clothing is fine linen and purple.\n'),
	(12504, 17, 31, 23, 'Her husband is respected in the gates,\nwhen he sits among the elders of the land.\n'),
	(12505, 17, 31, 24, 'She makes linen garments and sells them,\nand delivers sashes to the merchant.\n'),
	(12506, 17, 31, 25, 'Strength and dignity are her clothing.\nShe laughs at the time to come.\n'),
	(12507, 17, 31, 26, 'She opens her mouth with wisdom.\nFaithful instruction is on her tongue.\n'),
	(12508, 17, 31, 27, 'She looks well to the ways of her household,\nand doesn’t eat the bread of idleness.\n'),
	(12509, 17, 31, 28, 'Her children rise up and call her blessed.\nHer husband also praises her:\n'),
	(12510, 17, 31, 29, '“Many women do noble things,\nbut you excel them all.”\n'),
	(12511, 17, 31, 30, 'Charm is deceitful, and beauty is vain;\nbut a woman who fears Yahweh, she shall be praised.\n'),
	(12512, 17, 31, 31, 'Give her of the fruit of her hands!\nLet her works praise her in the gates!\n'),
	(12513, 18, 1, 1, 'The words of the Preacher, the son of David, king in Jerusalem:\n'),
	(12514, 18, 1, 2, '“Vanity of vanities,” says the Preacher; “Vanity of vanities, all is vanity.”\n'),
	(12515, 18, 1, 3, 'What does man gain from all his labor in which he labors under the sun?\n'),
	(12516, 18, 1, 4, 'One generation goes, and another generation comes; but the earth remains forever.\n'),
	(12517, 18, 1, 5, 'The sun also rises, and the sun goes down, and hurries to its place where it rises.\n'),
	(12518, 18, 1, 6, 'The wind goes toward the south, and turns around to the north. It turns around continually as it goes, and the wind returns again to its courses.\n'),
	(12519, 18, 1, 7, 'All the rivers run into the sea, yet the sea is not full. To the place where the rivers flow, there they flow again.\n'),
	(12520, 18, 1, 8, 'All things are full of weariness beyond uttering. The eye is not satisfied with seeing, nor the ear filled with hearing.\n'),
	(12521, 18, 1, 9, 'That which has been is that which shall be; and that which has been done is that which shall be done: and there is no new thing under the sun.\n'),
	(12522, 18, 1, 10, 'Is there a thing of which it may be said, “Behold, this is new?” It has been long ago, in the ages which were before us.\n'),
	(12523, 18, 1, 11, 'There is no memory of the former; neither shall there be any memory of the latter that are to come, among those that shall come after.\n'),
	(12524, 18, 1, 12, 'I, the Preacher, was king over Israel in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(12525, 18, 1, 13, 'I applied my heart to seek and to search out by wisdom concerning all that is done under the sky. It is a heavy burden that God has given to the sons of men to be afflicted with.\n'),
	(12526, 18, 1, 14, 'I have seen all the works that are done under the sun; and behold, all is vanity and a chasing after wind.\n'),
	(12527, 18, 1, 15, 'That which is crooked can’t be made straight; and that which is lacking can’t be counted.\n'),
	(12528, 18, 1, 16, 'I said to myself, “Behold, I have obtained for myself great wisdom above all who were before me in Jerusalem. Yes, my heart has had great experience of wisdom and knowledge.”\n'),
	(12529, 18, 1, 17, 'I applied my heart to know wisdom, and to know madness and folly. I perceived that this also was a chasing after wind.\n'),
	(12530, 18, 1, 18, 'For in much wisdom is much grief; and he who increases knowledge increases sorrow.\n'),
	(12531, 18, 2, 1, 'I said in my heart, “Come now, I will test you with mirth: therefore enjoy pleasure”; and behold, this also was vanity.\n'),
	(12532, 18, 2, 2, 'I said of laughter, “It is foolishness”; and of mirth, “What does it accomplish?”\n'),
	(12533, 18, 2, 3, 'I searched in my heart how to cheer my flesh with wine, my heart yet guiding me with wisdom, and how to lay hold of folly, until I might see what it was good for the sons of men that they should do under heaven all the days of their lives.\n'),
	(12534, 18, 2, 4, 'I made myself great works. I built myself houses. I planted myself vineyards.\n'),
	(12535, 18, 2, 5, 'I made myself gardens and parks, and I planted trees in them of all kinds of fruit.\n'),
	(12536, 18, 2, 6, 'I made myself pools of water, to water from it the forest where trees were reared.\n'),
	(12537, 18, 2, 7, 'I bought male servants and female servants, and had servants born in my house. I also had great possessions of herds and flocks, above all who were before me in Jerusalem;\n'),
	(12538, 18, 2, 8, 'I also gathered silver and gold for myself, and the treasure of kings and of the provinces. I got myself male and female singers, and the delights of the sons of men—musical instruments, and that of all sorts.\n'),
	(12539, 18, 2, 9, 'So I was great, and increased more than all who were before me in Jerusalem. My wisdom also remained with me.\n'),
	(12540, 18, 2, 10, 'Whatever my eyes desired, I didn’t keep from them. I didn’t withhold my heart from any joy, for my heart rejoiced because of all my labor, and this was my portion from all my labor.\n'),
	(12541, 18, 2, 11, 'Then I looked at all the works that my hands had worked, and at the labor that I had labored to do; and behold, all was vanity and a chasing after wind, and there was no profit under the sun.\n'),
	(12542, 18, 2, 12, 'I turned myself to consider wisdom, madness, and folly: for what can the king’s successor do? Just that which has been done long ago.\n'),
	(12543, 18, 2, 13, 'Then I saw that wisdom excels folly, as far as light excels darkness.\n'),
	(12544, 18, 2, 14, 'The wise man’s eyes are in his head, and the fool walks in darkness—and yet I perceived that one event happens to them all.\n'),
	(12545, 18, 2, 15, 'Then I said in my heart, “As it happens to the fool, so will it happen even to me; and why was I then more wise?” Then I said in my heart that this also is vanity.\n'),
	(12546, 18, 2, 16, 'For of the wise man, even as of the fool, there is no memory for ever, since in the days to come all will have been long forgotten. Indeed, the wise man must die just like the fool!\n'),
	(12547, 18, 2, 17, 'So I hated life, because the work that is worked under the sun was grievous to me; for all is vanity and a chasing after wind.\n'),
	(12548, 18, 2, 18, 'I hated all my labor in which I labored under the sun, because I must leave it to the man who comes after me.\n'),
	(12549, 18, 2, 19, 'Who knows whether he will be a wise man or a fool? Yet he will have rule over all of my labor in which I have labored, and in which I have shown myself wise under the sun. This also is vanity.\n'),
	(12550, 18, 2, 20, 'Therefore I began to cause my heart to despair concerning all the labor in which I had labored under the sun.\n'),
	(12551, 18, 2, 21, 'For there is a man whose labor is with wisdom, with knowledge, and with skillfulness; yet he shall leave it for his portion to a man who has not labored for it. This also is vanity and a great evil.\n'),
	(12552, 18, 2, 22, 'For what has a man of all his labor, and of the striving of his heart, in which he labors under the sun?\n'),
	(12553, 18, 2, 23, 'For all his days are sorrows, and his travail is grief; yes, even in the night his heart takes no rest. This also is vanity.\n'),
	(12554, 18, 2, 24, 'There is nothing better for a man than that he should eat and drink, and make his soul enjoy good in his labor. This also I saw, that it is from the hand of God.\n'),
	(12555, 18, 2, 25, 'For who can eat, or who can have enjoyment, more than I?\n'),
	(12556, 18, 2, 26, 'For to the man who pleases him, God gives wisdom, knowledge, and joy; but to the sinner he gives travail, to gather and to heap up, that he may give to him who pleases God. This also is vanity and a chasing after wind.\n'),
	(12557, 18, 3, 1, 'For everything there is a season, and a time for every purpose under heaven:\n'),
	(12558, 18, 3, 2, 'a time to be born,\nand a time to die;\na time to plant,\nand a time to pluck up that which is planted;\n'),
	(12559, 18, 3, 3, 'a time to kill,\nand a time to heal;\na time to break down,\nand a time to build up;\n'),
	(12560, 18, 3, 4, 'a time to weep,\nand a time to laugh;\na time to mourn,\nand a time to dance;\n'),
	(12561, 18, 3, 5, 'a time to cast away stones,\nand a time to gather stones together;\na time to embrace,\nand a time to refrain from embracing;\n'),
	(12562, 18, 3, 6, 'a time to seek,\nand a time to lose;\na time to keep,\nand a time to cast away;\n'),
	(12563, 18, 3, 7, 'a time to tear,\nand a time to sew;\na time to keep silence,\nand a time to speak;\n'),
	(12564, 18, 3, 8, 'a time to love,\nand a time to hate;\na time for war,\nand a time for peace.\n'),
	(12565, 18, 3, 9, 'What profit has he who works in that in which he labors?\n'),
	(12566, 18, 3, 10, 'I have seen the burden which God has given to the sons of men to be afflicted with.\n'),
	(12567, 18, 3, 11, 'He has made everything beautiful in its time. He has also set eternity in their hearts, yet so that man can’t find out the work that God has done from the beginning even to the end.\n'),
	(12568, 18, 3, 12, 'I know that there is nothing better for them than to rejoice, and to do good as long as they live.\n'),
	(12569, 18, 3, 13, 'Also that every man should eat and drink, and enjoy good in all his labor, is the gift of God.\n'),
	(12570, 18, 3, 14, 'I know that whatever God does, it shall be forever. Nothing can be added to it, nor anything taken from it; and God has done it, that men should fear before him.\n'),
	(12571, 18, 3, 15, 'That which is has been long ago, and that which is to be has been long ago: and God seeks again that which is passed away.\n'),
	(12572, 18, 3, 16, 'Moreover I saw under the sun, in the place of justice, that wickedness was there; and in the place of righteousness, that wickedness was there.\n'),
	(12573, 18, 3, 17, 'I said in my heart, “God will judge the righteous and the wicked; for there is a time there for every purpose and for every work.”\n'),
	(12574, 18, 3, 18, 'I said in my heart, “As for the sons of men, God tests them, so that they may see that they themselves are like animals.\n'),
	(12575, 18, 3, 19, 'For that which happens to the sons of men happens to animals. Even one thing happens to them. As the one dies, so the other dies. Yes, they have all one breath; and man has no advantage over the animals: for all is vanity.\n'),
	(12576, 18, 3, 20, 'All go to one place. All are from the dust, and all turn to dust again.\n'),
	(12577, 18, 3, 21, 'Who knows the spirit of man, whether it goes upward, and the spirit of the animal, whether it goes downward to the earth?”\n'),
	(12578, 18, 3, 22, 'Therefore I saw that there is nothing better, than that a man should rejoice in his works; for that is his portion: for who can bring him to see what will be after him?\n'),
	(12579, 18, 4, 1, 'Then I returned and saw all the oppressions that are done under the sun: and behold, the tears of those who were oppressed, and they had no comforter; and on the side of their oppressors there was power; but they had no comforter.\n'),
	(12580, 18, 4, 2, 'Therefore I praised the dead who have been long dead more than the living who are yet alive.\n'),
	(12581, 18, 4, 3, 'Yes, better than them both is him who has not yet been, who has not seen the evil work that is done under the sun.\n'),
	(12582, 18, 4, 4, 'Then I saw all the labor and achievement that is the envy of a man’s neighbor. This also is vanity and a striving after wind.\n'),
	(12583, 18, 4, 5, 'The fool folds his hands together and ruins himself.\n'),
	(12584, 18, 4, 6, 'Better is a handful, with quietness, than two handfuls with labor and chasing after wind.\n'),
	(12585, 18, 4, 7, 'Then I returned and saw vanity under the sun.\n'),
	(12586, 18, 4, 8, 'There is one who is alone, and he has neither son nor brother. There is no end to all of his labor, neither are his eyes satisfied with wealth. “For whom then, do I labor, and deprive my soul of enjoyment?” This also is vanity. Yes, it is a miserable business.\n'),
	(12587, 18, 4, 9, 'Two are better than one, because they have a good reward for their labor.\n'),
	(12588, 18, 4, 10, 'For if they fall, the one will lift up his fellow; but woe to him who is alone when he falls, and doesn’t have another to lift him up.\n'),
	(12589, 18, 4, 11, 'Again, if two lie together, then they have warmth; but how can one keep warm alone?\n'),
	(12590, 18, 4, 12, 'If a man prevails against one who is alone, two shall withstand him; and a threefold cord is not quickly broken.\n'),
	(12591, 18, 4, 13, 'Better is a poor and wise youth than an old and foolish king who doesn’t know how to receive admonition any more.\n'),
	(12592, 18, 4, 14, 'For out of prison he came out to be king; yes, even in his kingdom he was born poor.\n'),
	(12593, 18, 4, 15, 'I saw all the living who walk under the sun, that they were with the youth, the other, who succeeded him.\n'),
	(12594, 18, 4, 16, 'There was no end of all the people, even of all them over whom he was—yet those who come after shall not rejoice in him. Surely this also is vanity and a chasing after wind.\n'),
	(12595, 18, 5, 1, 'Guard your steps when you go to God’s house; for to draw near to listen is better than to give the sacrifice of fools, for they don’t know that they do evil.\n'),
	(12596, 18, 5, 2, 'Don’t be rash with your mouth, and don’t let your heart be hasty to utter anything before God; for God is in heaven, and you on earth. Therefore let your words be few.\n'),
	(12597, 18, 5, 3, 'For as a dream comes with a multitude of cares, so a fool’s speech with a multitude of words.\n'),
	(12598, 18, 5, 4, 'When you vow a vow to God, don’t defer to pay it; for he has no pleasure in fools. Pay that which you vow.\n'),
	(12599, 18, 5, 5, 'It is better that you should not vow, than that you should vow and not pay.\n'),
	(12600, 18, 5, 6, 'Don’t allow your mouth to lead you into sin. Don’t protest before the messenger that this was a mistake. Why should God be angry at your voice, and destroy the work of your hands?\n'),
	(12601, 18, 5, 7, 'For in the multitude of dreams there are vanities, as well as in many words: but you must fear God.\n'),
	(12602, 18, 5, 8, 'If you see the oppression of the poor, and the violent taking away of justice and righteousness in a district, don’t marvel at the matter: for one official is eyed by a higher one; and there are officials over them.\n'),
	(12603, 18, 5, 9, 'Moreover the profit of the earth is for all. The king profits from the field.\n'),
	(12604, 18, 5, 10, 'He who loves silver shall not be satisfied with silver; nor he who loves abundance, with increase: this also is vanity.\n'),
	(12605, 18, 5, 11, 'When goods increase, those who eat them are increased; and what advantage is there to its owner, except to feast on them with his eyes?\n'),
	(12606, 18, 5, 12, 'The sleep of a laboring man is sweet, whether he eats little or much; but the abundance of the rich will not allow him to sleep.\n'),
	(12607, 18, 5, 13, 'There is a grievous evil which I have seen under the sun: wealth kept by its owner to his harm.\n'),
	(12608, 18, 5, 14, 'Those riches perish by misfortune, and if he has fathered a son, there is nothing in his hand.\n'),
	(12609, 18, 5, 15, 'As he came out of his mother’s womb, naked shall he go again as he came, and shall take nothing for his labor, which he may carry away in his hand.\n'),
	(12610, 18, 5, 16, 'This also is a grievous evil, that in all points as he came, so shall he go. And what profit does he have who labors for the wind?\n'),
	(12611, 18, 5, 17, 'All his days he also eats in darkness, he is frustrated, and has sickness and wrath.\n'),
	(12612, 18, 5, 18, 'Behold, that which I have seen to be good and proper is for one to eat and to drink, and to enjoy good in all his labor, in which he labors under the sun, all the days of his life which God has given him; for this is his portion.\n'),
	(12613, 18, 5, 19, 'Every man also to whom God has given riches and wealth, and has given him power to eat of it, and to take his portion, and to rejoice in his labor—this is the gift of God.\n'),
	(12614, 18, 5, 20, 'For he shall not often reflect on the days of his life; because God occupies him with the joy of his heart.\n'),
	(12615, 18, 6, 1, 'There is an evil which I have seen under the sun, and it is heavy on men:\n'),
	(12616, 18, 6, 2, 'a man to whom God gives riches, wealth, and honor, so that he lacks nothing for his soul of all that he desires, yet God gives him no power to eat of it, but an alien eats it. This is vanity, and it is an evil disease.\n'),
	(12617, 18, 6, 3, 'If a man fathers a hundred children, and lives many years, so that the days of his years are many, but his soul is not filled with good, and moreover he has no burial; I say, that a stillborn child is better than he:\n'),
	(12618, 18, 6, 4, 'for it comes in vanity, and departs in darkness, and its name is covered with darkness.\n'),
	(12619, 18, 6, 5, 'Moreover it has not seen the sun nor known it. This has rest rather than the other.\n'),
	(12620, 18, 6, 6, 'Yes, though he live a thousand years twice told, and yet fails to enjoy good, don’t all go to one place?\n'),
	(12621, 18, 6, 7, 'All the labor of man is for his mouth, and yet the appetite is not filled.\n'),
	(12622, 18, 6, 8, 'For what advantage has the wise more than the fool? What has the poor man, that knows how to walk before the living?\n'),
	(12623, 18, 6, 9, 'Better is the sight of the eyes than the wandering of the desire. This also is vanity and a chasing after wind.\n'),
	(12624, 18, 6, 10, 'Whatever has been, its name was given long ago; and it is known what man is; neither can he contend with him who is mightier than he.\n'),
	(12625, 18, 6, 11, 'For there are many words that create vanity. What does that profit man?\n'),
	(12626, 18, 6, 12, 'For who knows what is good for man in life, all the days of his vain life which he spends like a shadow? For who can tell a man what will be after him under the sun?\n'),
	(12627, 18, 7, 1, 'A good name is better than fine perfume; and the day of death better than the day of one’s birth.\n'),
	(12628, 18, 7, 2, 'It is better to go to the house of mourning than to go to the house of feasting: for that is the end of all men, and the living should take this to heart.\n'),
	(12629, 18, 7, 3, 'Sorrow is better than laughter; for by the sadness of the face the heart is made good.\n'),
	(12630, 18, 7, 4, 'The heart of the wise is in the house of mourning; but the heart of fools is in the house of mirth.\n'),
	(12631, 18, 7, 5, 'It is better to hear the rebuke of the wise, than for a man to hear the song of fools.\n'),
	(12632, 18, 7, 6, 'For as the crackling of thorns under a pot, so is the laughter of the fool. This also is vanity.\n'),
	(12633, 18, 7, 7, 'Surely extortion makes the wise man foolish; and a bribe destroys the understanding.\n'),
	(12634, 18, 7, 8, 'Better is the end of a thing than its beginning.\nThe patient in spirit is better than the proud in spirit.\n'),
	(12635, 18, 7, 9, 'Don’t be hasty in your spirit to be angry, for anger rests in the bosom of fools.\n'),
	(12636, 18, 7, 10, 'Don’t say, “Why were the former days better than these?” For you do not ask wisely about this.\n'),
	(12637, 18, 7, 11, 'Wisdom is as good as an inheritance. Yes, it is more excellent for those who see the sun.\n'),
	(12638, 18, 7, 12, 'For wisdom is a defense, even as money is a defense; but the excellency of knowledge is that wisdom preserves the life of him who has it.\n'),
	(12639, 18, 7, 13, 'Consider the work of God, for who can make that straight, which he has made crooked?\n'),
	(12640, 18, 7, 14, 'In the day of prosperity be joyful, and in the day of adversity consider; yes, God has made the one side by side with the other, to the end that man should not find out anything after him.\n'),
	(12641, 18, 7, 15, 'All this I have seen in my days of vanity: there is a righteous man who perishes in his righteousness, and there is a wicked man who lives long in his evildoing.\n'),
	(12642, 18, 7, 16, 'Don’t be overly righteous, neither make yourself overly wise. Why should you destroy yourself?\n'),
	(12643, 18, 7, 17, 'Don’t be too wicked, neither be foolish. Why should you die before your time?\n'),
	(12644, 18, 7, 18, 'It is good that you should take hold of this. Yes, also from that don’t withdraw your hand; for he who fears God will come out of them all.\n'),
	(12645, 18, 7, 19, 'Wisdom is a strength to the wise man more than ten rulers who are in a city.\n'),
	(12646, 18, 7, 20, 'Surely there is not a righteous man on earth, who does good and doesn’t sin.\n'),
	(12647, 18, 7, 21, 'Also don’t take heed to all words that are spoken, lest you hear your servant curse you;\n'),
	(12648, 18, 7, 22, 'for often your own heart knows that you yourself have likewise cursed others.\n'),
	(12649, 18, 7, 23, 'All this I have proved in wisdom. I said, “I will be wise”; but it was far from me.\n'),
	(12650, 18, 7, 24, 'That which is, is far off and exceedingly deep. Who can find it out?\n'),
	(12651, 18, 7, 25, 'I turned around, and my heart sought to know and to search out, and to seek wisdom and the scheme of things, and to know that wickedness is stupidity, and that foolishness is madness.\n'),
	(12652, 18, 7, 26, 'I find more bitter than death the woman whose heart is snares and traps, whose hands are chains. Whoever pleases God shall escape from her; but the sinner will be ensnared by her.\n'),
	(12653, 18, 7, 27, '“Behold, I have found this,” says the Preacher, “to one another, to find out the scheme;\n'),
	(12654, 18, 7, 28, 'which my soul still seeks; but I have not found. I have found one man among a thousand; but I have not found a woman among all those.\n'),
	(12655, 18, 7, 29, 'Behold, I have only found this: that God made man upright; but they search for many schemes.”\n'),
	(12656, 18, 8, 1, 'Who is like the wise man? And who knows the interpretation of a thing? A man’s wisdom makes his face shine, and the hardness of his face is changed.\n'),
	(12657, 18, 8, 2, 'I say, “Keep the king’s command!” because of the oath to God.\n'),
	(12658, 18, 8, 3, 'Don’t be hasty to go out of his presence. Don’t persist in an evil thing, for he does whatever pleases him,\n'),
	(12659, 18, 8, 4, 'for the king’s word is supreme. Who can say to him, “What are you doing?”\n'),
	(12660, 18, 8, 5, 'Whoever keeps the commandment shall not come to harm, and his wise heart will know the time and procedure.\n'),
	(12661, 18, 8, 6, 'For there is a time and procedure for every purpose, although the misery of man is heavy on him.\n'),
	(12662, 18, 8, 7, 'For he doesn’t know that which will be; for who can tell him how it will be?\n'),
	(12663, 18, 8, 8, 'There is no man who has power over the spirit to contain the spirit; neither does he have power over the day of death. There is no discharge in war; neither shall wickedness deliver those who practice it.\n'),
	(12664, 18, 8, 9, 'All this I have seen, and applied my mind to every work that is done under the sun. There is a time in which one man has power over another to his hurt.\n'),
	(12665, 18, 8, 10, 'So I saw the wicked buried. Indeed they came also from holiness. They went and were forgotten in the city where they did this. This also is vanity.\n'),
	(12666, 18, 8, 11, 'Because sentence against an evil work is not executed speedily, therefore the heart of the sons of men is fully set in them to do evil.\n'),
	(12667, 18, 8, 12, 'Though a sinner commits crimes a hundred times, and lives long, yet surely I know that it will be better with those who fear God, who are reverent before him.\n'),
	(12668, 18, 8, 13, 'But it shall not be well with the wicked, neither shall he lengthen days like a shadow; because he doesn’t fear God.\n'),
	(12669, 18, 8, 14, 'There is a vanity which is done on the earth, that there are righteous men to whom it happens according to the work of the wicked. Again, there are wicked men to whom it happens according to the work of the righteous. I said that this also is vanity.\n'),
	(12670, 18, 8, 15, 'Then I commended mirth, because a man has no better thing under the sun, than to eat, and to drink, and to be joyful: for that will accompany him in his labor all the days of his life which God has given him under the sun.\n'),
	(12671, 18, 8, 16, 'When I applied my heart to know wisdom, and to see the business that is done on the earth (for also there is that neither day nor night sees sleep with his eyes),\n'),
	(12672, 18, 8, 17, 'then I saw all the work of God, that man can’t find out the work that is done under the sun, because however much a man labors to seek it out, yet he won’t find it. Yes even though a wise man thinks he can comprehend it, he won’t be able to find it.\n'),
	(12673, 18, 9, 1, 'For all this I laid to my heart, even to explore all this: that the righteous, and the wise, and their works, are in the hand of God; whether it is love or hatred, man doesn’t know it; all is before them.\n'),
	(12674, 18, 9, 2, 'All things come alike to all. There is one event to the righteous and to the wicked; to the good, to the clean, to the unclean, to him who sacrifices, and to him who doesn’t sacrifice. As is the good, so is the sinner; he who takes an oath, as he who fears an oath.\n'),
	(12675, 18, 9, 3, 'This is an evil in all that is done under the sun, that there is one event to all: yes also, the heart of the sons of men is full of evil, and madness is in their heart while they live, and after that they go to the dead.\n'),
	(12676, 18, 9, 4, 'For to him who is joined with all the living there is hope; for a living dog is better than a dead lion.\n'),
	(12677, 18, 9, 5, 'For the living know that they will die, but the dead don’t know anything, neither do they have any more a reward; for their memory is forgotten.\n'),
	(12678, 18, 9, 6, 'Also their love, their hatred, and their envy has perished long ago; neither have they any more a portion forever in anything that is done under the sun.\n'),
	(12679, 18, 9, 7, 'Go your way—eat your bread with joy, and drink your wine with a merry heart; for God has already accepted your works.\n'),
	(12680, 18, 9, 8, 'Let your garments be always white, and don’t let your head lack oil.\n'),
	(12681, 18, 9, 9, 'Live joyfully with the wife whom you love all the days of your life of vanity, which he has given you under the sun, all your days of vanity: for that is your portion in life, and in your labor in which you labor under the sun.\n'),
	(12682, 18, 9, 10, 'Whatever your hand finds to do, do it with your might; for there is no work, nor plan, nor knowledge, nor wisdom, in Sheol, where you are going.\n'),
	(12683, 18, 9, 11, 'I returned, and saw under the sun, that the race is not to the swift, nor the battle to the strong, neither yet bread to the wise, nor yet riches to men of understanding, nor yet favor to men of skill; but time and chance happen to them all.\n'),
	(12684, 18, 9, 12, 'For man also doesn’t know his time. As the fish that are taken in an evil net, and as the birds that are caught in the snare, even so are the sons of men snared in an evil time, when it falls suddenly on them.\n'),
	(12685, 18, 9, 13, 'I have also seen wisdom under the sun in this way, and it seemed great to me.\n'),
	(12686, 18, 9, 14, 'There was a little city, and few men within it; and a great king came against it, besieged it, and built great bulwarks against it.\n'),
	(12687, 18, 9, 15, 'Now a poor wise man was found in it, and he by his wisdom delivered the city; yet no man remembered that same poor man.\n'),
	(12688, 18, 9, 16, 'Then I said, “Wisdom is better than strength.” Nevertheless the poor man’s wisdom is despised, and his words are not heard.\n'),
	(12689, 18, 9, 17, 'The words of the wise heard in quiet are better than the cry of him who rules among fools.\n'),
	(12690, 18, 9, 18, 'Wisdom is better than weapons of war; but one sinner destroys much good.\n'),
	(12691, 18, 10, 1, 'Dead flies cause the oil of the perfumer to produce an evil odor;\nso does a little folly outweigh wisdom and honor.\n'),
	(12692, 18, 10, 2, 'A wise man’s heart is at his right hand,\nbut a fool’s heart at his left.\n'),
	(12693, 18, 10, 3, 'Yes also, when the fool walks by the way, his understanding fails him, and he says to everyone that he is a fool.\n'),
	(12694, 18, 10, 4, 'If the spirit of the ruler rises up against you, don’t leave your place; for gentleness lays great offenses to rest.\n'),
	(12695, 18, 10, 5, 'There is an evil which I have seen under the sun, the sort of error which proceeds from the ruler.\n'),
	(12696, 18, 10, 6, 'Folly is set in great dignity, and the rich sit in a low place.\n'),
	(12697, 18, 10, 7, 'I have seen servants on horses, and princes walking like servants on the earth.\n'),
	(12698, 18, 10, 8, 'He who digs a pit may fall into it; and whoever breaks through a wall may be bitten by a snake.\n'),
	(12699, 18, 10, 9, 'Whoever carves out stones may be injured by them. Whoever splits wood may be endangered thereby.\n'),
	(12700, 18, 10, 10, 'If the ax is blunt, and one doesn’t sharpen the edge, then he must use more strength; but skill brings success.\n'),
	(12701, 18, 10, 11, 'If the snake bites before it is charmed, then is there no profit for the charmer’s tongue.\n'),
	(12702, 18, 10, 12, 'The words of a wise man’s mouth are gracious; but a fool is swallowed by his own lips.\n'),
	(12703, 18, 10, 13, 'The beginning of the words of his mouth is foolishness; and the end of his talk is mischievous madness.\n'),
	(12704, 18, 10, 14, 'A fool also multiplies words.\nMan doesn’t know what will be; and that which will be after him, who can tell him?\n'),
	(12705, 18, 10, 15, 'The labor of fools wearies every one of them; for he doesn’t know how to go to the city.\n'),
	(12706, 18, 10, 16, 'Woe to you, land, when your king is a child,\nand your princes eat in the morning!\n'),
	(12707, 18, 10, 17, 'Happy are you, land, when your king is the son of nobles,\nand your princes eat in due season,\nfor strength, and not for drunkenness!\n'),
	(12708, 18, 10, 18, 'By slothfulness the roof sinks in;\nand through idleness of the hands the house leaks.\n'),
	(12709, 18, 10, 19, 'A feast is made for laughter,\nand wine makes the life glad;\nand money is the answer for all things.\n'),
	(12710, 18, 10, 20, 'Don’t curse the king, no, not in your thoughts;\nand don’t curse the rich in your bedroom:\nfor a bird of the sky may carry your voice,\nand that which has wings may tell the matter.\n'),
	(12711, 18, 11, 1, 'Cast your bread on the waters;\nfor you shall find it after many days.\n'),
	(12712, 18, 11, 2, 'Give a portion to seven, yes, even to eight;\nfor you don’t know what evil will be on the earth.\n'),
	(12713, 18, 11, 3, 'If the clouds are full of rain, they empty themselves on the earth;\nand if a tree falls toward the south, or toward the north,\nin the place where the tree falls, there shall it be.\n'),
	(12714, 18, 11, 4, 'He who observes the wind won’t sow;\nand he who regards the clouds won’t reap.\n'),
	(12715, 18, 11, 5, 'As you don’t know what is the way of the wind,\nnor how the bones grow in the womb of her who is with child;\neven so you don’t know the work of God who does all.\n'),
	(12716, 18, 11, 6, 'In the morning sow your seed,\nand in the evening don’t withhold your hand;\nfor you don’t know which will prosper, whether this or that,\nor whether they both will be equally good.\n'),
	(12717, 18, 11, 7, 'Truly the light is sweet,\nand a pleasant thing it is for the eyes to see the sun.\n'),
	(12718, 18, 11, 8, 'Yes, if a man lives many years, let him rejoice in them all;\nbut let him remember the days of darkness, for they shall be many.\nAll that comes is vanity.\n'),
	(12719, 18, 11, 9, 'Rejoice, young man, in your youth,\nand let your heart cheer you in the days of your youth,\nand walk in the ways of your heart,\nand in the sight of your eyes;\nbut know that for all these things God will bring you into judgment.\n'),
	(12720, 18, 11, 10, 'Therefore remove sorrow from your heart,\nand put away evil from your flesh;\nfor youth and the dawn of life are vanity.\n'),
	(12721, 18, 12, 1, 'Remember also your Creator in the days of your youth,\nbefore the evil days come, and the years draw near,\nwhen you will say, “I have no pleasure in them”;\n'),
	(12722, 18, 12, 2, 'Before the sun, the light, the moon, and the stars are darkened,\nand the clouds return after the rain;\n'),
	(12723, 18, 12, 3, 'in the day when the keepers of the house shall tremble,\nand the strong men shall bow themselves,\nand the grinders cease because they are few,\nand those who look out of the windows are darkened,\n'),
	(12724, 18, 12, 4, 'and the doors shall be shut in the street;\nwhen the sound of the grinding is low,\nand one shall rise up at the voice of a bird,\nand all the daughters of music shall be brought low;\n'),
	(12725, 18, 12, 5, 'yes, they shall be afraid of heights,\nand terrors will be on the way;\nand the almond tree shall blossom,\nand the grasshopper shall be a burden,\nand desire shall fail;\nbecause man goes to his everlasting home,\nand the mourners go about the streets:\n'),
	(12726, 18, 12, 6, 'before the silver cord is severed,\nor the golden bowl is broken,\nor the pitcher is broken at the spring,\nor the wheel broken at the cistern,\n'),
	(12727, 18, 12, 7, 'and the dust returns to the earth as it was,\nand the spirit returns to God who gave it.\n'),
	(12728, 18, 12, 8, '“Vanity of vanities,” says the Preacher.\n“All is vanity!”\n'),
	(12729, 18, 12, 9, 'Further, because the Preacher was wise, he still taught the people knowledge. Yes, he pondered, sought out, and set in order many proverbs.\n'),
	(12730, 18, 12, 10, 'The Preacher sought to find out acceptable words, and that which was written blamelessly, words of truth.\n'),
	(12731, 18, 12, 11, 'The words of the wise are like goads; and like nails well fastened are words from the masters of assemblies, which are given from one shepherd.\n'),
	(12732, 18, 12, 12, 'Furthermore, my son, be admonished: of making many books there is no end; and much study is a weariness of the flesh.\n'),
	(12733, 18, 12, 13, 'This is the end of the matter. All has been heard. Fear God, and keep his commandments; for this is the whole duty of man.\n'),
	(12734, 18, 12, 14, 'For God will bring every work into judgment, with every hidden thing, whether it is good, or whether it is evil.\n'),
	(12735, 19, 1, 1, 'The Song of songs, which is Solomon’s.\n'),
	(12736, 19, 1, 2, 'Let him kiss me with the kisses of his mouth;\nfor your love is better than wine.\n'),
	(12737, 19, 1, 3, 'Your oils have a pleasing fragrance.\nYour name is oil poured out,\ntherefore the virgins love you.\n'),
	(12738, 19, 1, 4, 'Take me away with you.\nLet us hurry.\nThe king has brought me into his rooms.\nFriends\nWe will be glad and rejoice in you.\nWe will praise your love more than wine!\nBeloved\nThey are right to love you.\n'),
	(12739, 19, 1, 5, 'I am dark, but lovely,\nyou daughters of Jerusalem,\nlike Kedar’s tents,\nlike Solomon’s curtains.\n'),
	(12740, 19, 1, 6, 'Don’t stare at me because I am dark,\nbecause the sun has scorched me.\nMy mother’s sons were angry with me.\nThey made me keeper of the vineyards.\nI haven’t kept my own vineyard.\n'),
	(12741, 19, 1, 7, 'Tell me, you whom my soul loves,\nwhere you graze your flock,\nwhere you rest them at noon;\nFor why should I be as one who is veiled\nbeside the flocks of your companions?\n'),
	(12742, 19, 1, 8, 'If you don’t know, most beautiful among women,\nfollow the tracks of the sheep.\nGraze your young goats beside the shepherds’ tents.\n'),
	(12743, 19, 1, 9, 'I have compared you, my love,\nto a steed in Pharaoh’s chariots.\n'),
	(12744, 19, 1, 10, 'Your cheeks are beautiful with earrings,\nyour neck with strings of jewels.\n'),
	(12745, 19, 1, 11, 'We will make you earrings of gold,\nwith studs of silver.\n'),
	(12746, 19, 1, 12, 'While the king sat at his table,\nmy perfume spread its fragrance.\n'),
	(12747, 19, 1, 13, 'My beloved is to me a sachet of myrrh,\nthat lies between my breasts.\n'),
	(12748, 19, 1, 14, 'My beloved is to me a cluster of henna blossoms\nfrom the vineyards of En Gedi.\n'),
	(12749, 19, 1, 15, 'Behold, you are beautiful, my love.\nBehold, you are beautiful.\nYour eyes are doves.\n'),
	(12750, 19, 1, 16, 'Behold, you are beautiful, my beloved, yes, pleasant;\nand our couch is verdant.\n'),
	(12751, 19, 1, 17, 'The beams of our house are cedars.\nOur rafters are firs.\n'),
	(12752, 19, 2, 1, 'I am a rose of Sharon,\na lily of the valleys.\n'),
	(12753, 19, 2, 2, 'As a lily among thorns,\nso is my love among the daughters.\n'),
	(12754, 19, 2, 3, 'As the apple tree among the trees of the wood,\nso is my beloved among the sons.\nI sat down under his shadow with great delight,\nhis fruit was sweet to my taste.\n'),
	(12755, 19, 2, 4, 'He brought me to the banquet hall.\nHis banner over me is love.\n'),
	(12756, 19, 2, 5, 'Strengthen me with raisins,\nrefresh me with apples;\nFor I am faint with love.\n'),
	(12757, 19, 2, 6, 'His left hand is under my head.\nHis right hand embraces me.\n'),
	(12758, 19, 2, 7, 'I adjure you, daughters of Jerusalem,\nby the roes, or by the hinds of the field,\nthat you not stir up, nor awaken love,\nuntil it so desires.\n'),
	(12759, 19, 2, 8, 'The voice of my beloved!\nBehold, he comes,\nleaping on the mountains,\nskipping on the hills.\n'),
	(12760, 19, 2, 9, 'My beloved is like a roe or a young deer.\nBehold, he stands behind our wall!\nHe looks in at the windows.\nHe glances through the lattice.\n'),
	(12761, 19, 2, 10, 'My beloved spoke, and said to me,\n“Rise up, my love, my beautiful one, and come away.\n'),
	(12762, 19, 2, 11, 'For, behold, the winter is past.\nThe rain is over and gone.\n'),
	(12763, 19, 2, 12, 'The flowers appear on the earth.\nThe time of the singing has come,\nand the voice of the turtledove is heard in our land.\n'),
	(12764, 19, 2, 13, 'The fig tree ripens her green figs.\nThe vines are in blossom.\nThey give out their fragrance.\nArise, my love, my beautiful one,\nand come away.”\n'),
	(12765, 19, 2, 14, 'My dove in the clefts of the rock,\nIn the hiding places of the mountainside,\nLet me see your face.\nLet me hear your voice;\nfor your voice is sweet, and your face is lovely.\n'),
	(12766, 19, 2, 15, 'Catch for us the foxes,\nthe little foxes that plunder the vineyards;\nfor our vineyards are in blossom.\n'),
	(12767, 19, 2, 16, 'My beloved is mine, and I am his.\nHe browses among the lilies.\n'),
	(12768, 19, 2, 17, 'Until the day is cool, and the shadows flee away,\nturn, my beloved,\nand be like a roe or a young deer on the mountains of Bether.\n'),
	(12769, 19, 3, 1, 'By night on my bed,\nI sought him whom my soul loves.\nI sought him, but I didn’t find him.\n'),
	(12770, 19, 3, 2, 'I will get up now, and go about the city;\nin the streets and in the squares I will seek him whom my soul loves.\nI sought him, but I didn’t find him.\n'),
	(12771, 19, 3, 3, 'The watchmen who go about the city found me;\n“Have you seen him whom my soul loves?”\n'),
	(12772, 19, 3, 4, 'I had scarcely passed from them,\nwhen I found him whom my soul loves.\nI held him, and would not let him go,\nuntil I had brought him into my mother’s house,\ninto the room of her who conceived me.\n'),
	(12773, 19, 3, 5, 'I adjure you, daughters of Jerusalem,\nby the roes, or by the hinds of the field,\nthat you not stir up, nor awaken love,\nuntil it so desires.\n'),
	(12774, 19, 3, 6, 'Who is this who comes up from the wilderness like pillars of smoke,\nperfumed with myrrh and frankincense,\nwith all spices of the merchant?\n'),
	(12775, 19, 3, 7, 'Behold, it is Solomon’s carriage!\nSixty mighty men are around it,\nof the mighty men of Israel.\n'),
	(12776, 19, 3, 8, 'They all handle the sword, and are expert in war.\nEvery man has his sword on his thigh,\nbecause of fear in the night.\n'),
	(12777, 19, 3, 9, 'King Solomon made himself a carriage\nof the wood of Lebanon.\n'),
	(12778, 19, 3, 10, 'He made its pillars of silver,\nits bottom of gold, its seat of purple,\nthe middle of it being paved with love,\nfrom the daughters of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(12779, 19, 3, 11, 'Go out, you daughters of Zion, and see king Solomon,\nwith the crown with which his mother has crowned him,\nin the day of his weddings,\nin the day of the gladness of his heart.\n'),
	(12780, 19, 4, 1, 'Behold, you are beautiful, my love.\nBehold, you are beautiful.\nYour eyes are doves behind your veil.\nYour hair is as a flock of goats,\nthat descend from Mount Gilead.\n'),
	(12781, 19, 4, 2, 'Your teeth are like a newly shorn flock,\nwhich have come up from the washing,\nwhere every one of them has twins.\nNone is bereaved among them.\n'),
	(12782, 19, 4, 3, 'Your lips are like scarlet thread.\nYour mouth is lovely.\nYour temples are like a piece of a pomegranate behind your veil.\n'),
	(12783, 19, 4, 4, 'Your neck is like David’s tower built for an armory,\nwhereon a thousand shields hang,\nall the shields of the mighty men.\n'),
	(12784, 19, 4, 5, 'Your two breasts are like two fawns\nthat are twins of a roe,\nwhich feed among the lilies.\n'),
	(12785, 19, 4, 6, 'Until the day is cool, and the shadows flee away,\nI will go to the mountain of myrrh,\nto the hill of frankincense.\n'),
	(12786, 19, 4, 7, 'You are all beautiful, my love.\nThere is no spot in you.\n'),
	(12787, 19, 4, 8, 'Come with me from Lebanon, my bride,\nwith me from Lebanon.\nLook from the top of Amana,\nfrom the top of Senir and Hermon,\nfrom the lions’ dens,\nfrom the mountains of the leopards.\n'),
	(12788, 19, 4, 9, 'You have ravished my heart, my sister, my bride.\nYou have ravished my heart with one of your eyes,\nwith one chain of your neck.\n'),
	(12789, 19, 4, 10, 'How beautiful is your love, my sister, my bride!\nHow much better is your love than wine!\nThe fragrance of your perfumes than all kinds of spices!\n'),
	(12790, 19, 4, 11, 'Your lips, my bride, drip like the honeycomb.\nHoney and milk are under your tongue.\nThe smell of your garments is like the smell of Lebanon.\n'),
	(12791, 19, 4, 12, 'A locked up garden is my sister, my bride;\na locked up spring,\na sealed fountain.\n'),
	(12792, 19, 4, 13, 'Your shoots are an orchard of pomegranates, with precious fruits:\nhenna with spikenard plants,\n'),
	(12793, 19, 4, 14, 'spikenard and saffron,\ncalamus and cinnamon, with every kind of incense tree;\nmyrrh and aloes, with all the best spices,\n'),
	(12794, 19, 4, 15, 'a fountain of gardens,\na well of living waters,\nflowing streams from Lebanon.\n'),
	(12795, 19, 4, 16, 'Awake, north wind; and come, you south!\nBlow on my garden, that its spices may flow out.\nLet my beloved come into his garden,\nand taste his precious fruits.\n'),
	(12796, 19, 5, 1, 'I have come into my garden, my sister, my bride.\nI have gathered my myrrh with my spice;\nI have eaten my honeycomb with my honey;\nI have drunk my wine with my milk.\nFriends\nEat, friends!\nDrink, yes, drink abundantly, beloved.\n'),
	(12797, 19, 5, 2, 'I was asleep, but my heart was awake.\nIt is the voice of my beloved who knocks:\n“Open to me, my sister, my love, my dove, my undefiled;\nfor my head is filled with dew,\nand my hair with the dampness of the night.”\n'),
	(12798, 19, 5, 3, 'I have taken off my robe. Indeed, must I put it on?\nI have washed my feet. Indeed, must I soil them?\n'),
	(12799, 19, 5, 4, 'My beloved thrust his hand in through the latch opening.\nMy heart pounded for him.\n'),
	(12800, 19, 5, 5, 'I rose up to open for my beloved.\nMy hands dripped with myrrh,\nmy fingers with liquid myrrh,\non the handles of the lock.\n'),
	(12801, 19, 5, 6, 'I opened to my beloved;\nbut my beloved left; and had gone away.\nMy heart went out when he spoke.\nI looked for him, but I didn’t find him.\nI called him, but he didn’t answer.\n'),
	(12802, 19, 5, 7, 'The watchmen who go about the city found me.\nThey beat me.\nThey bruised me.\nThe keepers of the walls took my cloak away from me.\n'),
	(12803, 19, 5, 8, 'I adjure you, daughters of Jerusalem,\nIf you find my beloved,\nthat you tell him that I am faint with love.\n'),
	(12804, 19, 5, 9, 'How is your beloved better than another beloved,\nyou fairest among women?\nHow is your beloved better than another beloved,\nthat you do so adjure us?\n'),
	(12805, 19, 5, 10, 'My beloved is white and ruddy.\nThe best among ten thousand.\n'),
	(12806, 19, 5, 11, 'His head is like the purest gold.\nHis hair is bushy, black as a raven.\n'),
	(12807, 19, 5, 12, 'His eyes are like doves beside the water brooks,\nwashed with milk, mounted like jewels.\n'),
	(12808, 19, 5, 13, 'His cheeks are like a bed of spices with towers of perfumes.\nHis lips are like lilies, dropping liquid myrrh.\n'),
	(12809, 19, 5, 14, 'His hands are like rings of gold set with beryl.\nHis body is like ivory work overlaid with sapphires.\n'),
	(12810, 19, 5, 15, 'His legs are like pillars of marble set on sockets of fine gold.\nHis appearance is like Lebanon, excellent as the cedars.\n'),
	(12811, 19, 5, 16, 'His mouth is sweetness;\nyes, he is altogether lovely.\nThis is my beloved, and this is my friend,\ndaughters of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(12812, 19, 6, 1, 'Where has your beloved gone, you fairest among women?\nWhere has your beloved turned, that we may seek him with you?\n'),
	(12813, 19, 6, 2, 'My beloved has gone down to his garden,\nto the beds of spices,\nto feed in the gardens, and to gather lilies.\n'),
	(12814, 19, 6, 3, 'I am my beloved’s, and my beloved is mine.\nHe browses among the lilies,\n'),
	(12815, 19, 6, 4, 'You are beautiful, my love, as Tirzah,\nlovely as Jerusalem,\nawesome as an army with banners.\n'),
	(12816, 19, 6, 5, 'Turn away your eyes from me,\nfor they have overcome me.\nYour hair is like a flock of goats,\nthat lie along the side of Gilead.\n'),
	(12817, 19, 6, 6, 'Your teeth are like a flock of ewes,\nwhich have come up from the washing;\nof which every one has twins;\nno one is bereaved among them.\n'),
	(12818, 19, 6, 7, 'Your temples are like a piece of a pomegranate behind your veil.\n'),
	(12819, 19, 6, 8, 'There are sixty queens, eighty concubines,\nand virgins without number.\n'),
	(12820, 19, 6, 9, 'My dove, my perfect one, is unique.\nShe is her mother’s only daughter.\nShe is the favorite one of her who bore her.\nThe daughters saw her, and called her blessed;\nthe queens and the concubines, and they praised her.\n'),
	(12821, 19, 6, 10, 'Who is she who looks out as the morning,\nbeautiful as the moon,\nclear as the sun,\nand awesome as an army with banners?\n'),
	(12822, 19, 6, 11, 'I went down into the nut tree grove,\nto see the green plants of the valley,\nto see whether the vine budded,\nand the pomegranates were in flower.\n'),
	(12823, 19, 6, 12, 'Without realizing it,\nmy desire set me with my royal people’s chariots.\n'),
	(12824, 19, 6, 13, 'Return, return, Shulammite!\nReturn, return, that we may gaze at you.\nLover\nWhy do you desire to gaze at the Shulammite,\nas at the dance of Mahanaim?\n'),
	(12825, 19, 7, 1, 'How beautiful are your feet in sandals, prince’s daughter!\nYour rounded thighs are like jewels,\nthe work of the hands of a skillful workman.\n'),
	(12826, 19, 7, 2, 'Your body is like a round goblet,\nno mixed wine is wanting.\nYour waist is like a heap of wheat,\nset about with lilies.\n'),
	(12827, 19, 7, 3, 'Your two breasts are like two fawns,\nthat are twins of a roe.\n'),
	(12828, 19, 7, 4, 'Your neck is like an ivory tower.\nYour eyes are like the pools in Heshbon by the gate of Bathrabbim.\nYour nose is like the tower of Lebanon which looks toward Damascus.\n'),
	(12829, 19, 7, 5, 'Your head on you is like Carmel.\nThe hair of your head like purple.\nThe king is held captive in its tresses.\n'),
	(12830, 19, 7, 6, 'How beautiful and how pleasant you are,\nlove, for delights!\n'),
	(12831, 19, 7, 7, 'This, your stature, is like a palm tree,\nyour breasts like its fruit.\n'),
	(12832, 19, 7, 8, 'I said, “I will climb up into the palm tree.\nI will take hold of its fruit.”\nLet your breasts be like clusters of the vine,\nthe smell of your breath like apples,\n'),
	(12833, 19, 7, 9, 'Your mouth like the best wine,\nthat goes down smoothly for my beloved,\ngliding through the lips of those who are asleep.\n'),
	(12834, 19, 7, 10, 'I am my beloved’s.\nHis desire is toward me.\n'),
	(12835, 19, 7, 11, 'Come, my beloved, let us go out into the field.\nLet us lodge in the villages.\n'),
	(12836, 19, 7, 12, 'Let’s go early up to the vineyards.\nLet’s see whether the vine has budded,\nits blossom is open,\nand the pomegranates are in flower.\nThere I will give you my love.\n'),
	(12837, 19, 7, 13, 'The mandrakes produce fragrance.\nAt our doors are all kinds of precious fruits, new and old,\nwhich I have stored up for you, my beloved.\n'),
	(12838, 19, 8, 1, 'Oh that you were like my brother,\nwho nursed from the breasts of my mother!\nIf I found you outside, I would kiss you;\nyes, and no one would despise me.\n'),
	(12839, 19, 8, 2, 'I would lead you, bringing you into my mother’s house,\nwho would instruct me.\nI would have you drink spiced wine,\nof the juice of my pomegranate.\n'),
	(12840, 19, 8, 3, 'His left hand would be under my head.\nHis right hand would embrace me.\n'),
	(12841, 19, 8, 4, 'I adjure you, daughters of Jerusalem,\nthat you not stir up, nor awaken love,\nuntil it so desires.\n'),
	(12842, 19, 8, 5, 'Who is this who comes up from the wilderness,\nleaning on her beloved?\nUnder the apple tree I aroused you.\nThere your mother conceived you.\nThere she was in labor and bore you.\n'),
	(12843, 19, 8, 6, 'Set me as a seal on your heart,\nas a seal on your arm;\nfor love is strong as death.\nJealousy is as cruel as Sheol.\nIts flashes are flashes of fire,\na very flame of Yahweh.\n'),
	(12844, 19, 8, 7, 'Many waters can’t quench love,\nneither can floods drown it.\nIf a man would give all the wealth of his house for love,\nhe would be utterly scorned.\n'),
	(12845, 19, 8, 8, 'We have a little sister.\nShe has no breasts.\nWhat shall we do for our sister\nin the day when she is to be spoken for?\n'),
	(12846, 19, 8, 9, 'If she is a wall,\nwe will build on her a turret of silver.\nif she is a door,\nwe will enclose her with boards of cedar.\n'),
	(12847, 19, 8, 10, 'I am a wall, and my breasts like towers,\nthen I was in his eyes like one who found peace.\n'),
	(12848, 19, 8, 11, 'Solomon had a vineyard at Baal Hamon.\nHe leased out the vineyard to keepers.\nEach was to bring a thousand shekels of silver for its fruit.\n'),
	(12849, 19, 8, 12, 'My own vineyard is before me.\nThe thousand are for you, Solomon;\ntwo hundred for those who tend its fruit.\n'),
	(12850, 19, 8, 13, 'You who dwell in the gardens, with friends in attendance,\nlet me hear your voice!\n'),
	(12851, 19, 8, 14, 'Come away, my beloved!\nBe like a gazelle or a young stag on the mountains of spices!\n'),
	(12852, 20, 1, 1, 'The vision of Isaiah the son of Amoz, which he saw concerning Judah and Jerusalem, in the days of Uzziah, Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah, kings of Judah.\n'),
	(12853, 20, 1, 2, 'Hear, heavens,\nand listen, earth; for Yahweh has spoken:\n“I have nourished and brought up children,\nand they have rebelled against me.\n'),
	(12854, 20, 1, 3, 'The ox knows his owner,\nand the donkey his master’s crib;\nbut Israel doesn’t know,\nmy people don’t consider.”\n'),
	(12855, 20, 1, 4, 'Ah sinful nation,\na people loaded with iniquity,\noffspring of evildoers,\nchildren who deal corruptly!\nThey have forsaken Yahweh.\nThey have despised the Holy One of Israel.\nThey are estranged and backward.\n'),
	(12856, 20, 1, 5, 'Why should you be beaten more,\nthat you revolt more and more?\nThe whole head is sick,\nand the whole heart faint.\n'),
	(12857, 20, 1, 6, 'From the sole of the foot even to the head there is no soundness in it:\nwounds, welts, and open sores.\nThey haven’t been closed, neither bandaged, neither soothed with oil.\n'),
	(12858, 20, 1, 7, 'Your country is desolate.\nYour cities are burned with fire.\nStrangers devour your land in your presence,\nand it is desolate,\nas overthrown by strangers.\n'),
	(12859, 20, 1, 8, 'The daughter of Zion is left like a shelter in a vineyard,\nlike a hut in a field of melons,\nlike a besieged city.\n'),
	(12860, 20, 1, 9, 'Unless Yahweh of Armies had left to us a very small remnant,\nwe would have been as Sodom;\nwe would have been like Gomorrah.\n'),
	(12861, 20, 1, 10, 'Hear Yahweh’s word, you rulers of Sodom!\nListen to the law of our God, you people of Gomorrah!\n'),
	(12862, 20, 1, 11, '“What are the multitude of your sacrifices to me?”, says Yahweh.\n“I have had enough of the burnt offerings of rams,\nand the fat of fed animals.\nI don’t delight in the blood of bulls,\nor of lambs,\nor of male goats.\n'),
	(12863, 20, 1, 12, 'When you come to appear before me,\nwho has required this at your hand, to trample my courts?\n'),
	(12864, 20, 1, 13, 'Bring no more vain offerings.\nIncense is an abomination to me;\nnew moons, Sabbaths, and convocations:\nI can’t stand evil assemblies.\n'),
	(12865, 20, 1, 14, 'My soul hates your New Moons and your appointed feasts.\nThey are a burden to me.\nI am weary of bearing them.\n'),
	(12866, 20, 1, 15, 'When you spread out your hands, I will hide my eyes from you.\nYes, when you make many prayers, I will not hear.\nYour hands are full of blood.\n'),
	(12867, 20, 1, 16, 'Wash yourselves, make yourself clean.\nPut away the evil of your doings from before my eyes.\nCease to do evil.\n'),
	(12868, 20, 1, 17, 'Learn to do well.\nSeek justice.\nRelieve the oppressed.\nJudge the fatherless.\nPlead for the widow.”\n'),
	(12869, 20, 1, 18, '“Come now, and let us reason together,” says Yahweh:\n“Though your sins be as scarlet, they shall be as white as snow.\nThough they be red like crimson, they shall be as wool.\n'),
	(12870, 20, 1, 19, 'If you are willing and obedient,\nyou shall eat the good of the land;\n'),
	(12871, 20, 1, 20, 'but if you refuse and rebel, you shall be devoured with the sword;\nfor the mouth of Yahweh has spoken it.”\n'),
	(12872, 20, 1, 21, 'How the faithful city has become a prostitute!\nShe was full of justice; righteousness lodged in her,\nbut now murderers.\n'),
	(12873, 20, 1, 22, 'Your silver has become dross,\nyour wine mixed with water.\n'),
	(12874, 20, 1, 23, 'Your princes are rebellious, and companions of thieves.\nEveryone loves bribes, and follows after rewards.\nThey don’t judge the fatherless,\nneither does the cause of the widow come to them.\n'),
	(12875, 20, 1, 24, 'Therefore the Lord, Yahweh of Armies,\nthe Mighty One of Israel, says:\n“Ah, I will get relief from my adversaries,\nand avenge myself on my enemies;\n'),
	(12876, 20, 1, 25, 'and I will turn my hand on you,\nthoroughly purge away your dross,\nand will take away all your tin.\n'),
	(12877, 20, 1, 26, 'I will restore your judges as at the first,\nand your counselors as at the beginning.\nAfterward you shall be called ‘The city of righteousness,\na faithful town.’\n'),
	(12878, 20, 1, 27, 'Zion shall be redeemed with justice,\nand her converts with righteousness.\n'),
	(12879, 20, 1, 28, 'But the destruction of transgressors and sinners shall be together,\nand those who forsake Yahweh shall be consumed.\n'),
	(12880, 20, 1, 29, 'For they shall be ashamed of the oaks which you have desired,\nand you shall be confounded for the gardens that you have chosen.\n'),
	(12881, 20, 1, 30, 'For you shall be as an oak whose leaf fades,\nand as a garden that has no water.\n'),
	(12882, 20, 1, 31, 'The strong will be like tinder,\nand his work like a spark.\nThey will both burn together,\nand no one will quench them.”\n'),
	(12883, 20, 2, 1, 'This is what Isaiah the son of Amoz saw concerning Judah and Jerusalem.\n'),
	(12884, 20, 2, 2, 'It shall happen in the latter days, that the mountain of Yahweh’s house shall be established on the top of the mountains,\nand shall be raised above the hills;\nand all nations shall flow to it.\n'),
	(12885, 20, 2, 3, 'Many peoples shall go and say,\n“Come, let’s go up to the mountain of Yahweh,\nto the house of the God of Jacob;\nand he will teach us of his ways,\nand we will walk in his paths.”\nFor out of Zion the law shall go out,\nand Yahweh’s word from Jerusalem.\n'),
	(12886, 20, 2, 4, 'He will judge between the nations,\nand will decide concerning many peoples;\nand they shall beat their swords into plowshares,\nand their spears into pruning hooks.\nNation shall not lift up sword against nation,\nneither shall they learn war any more.\n'),
	(12887, 20, 2, 5, 'House of Jacob, come, and let us walk in the light of Yahweh.\n'),
	(12888, 20, 2, 6, 'For you have forsaken your people, the house of Jacob,\nbecause they are filled from the east,\nwith those who practice divination like the Philistines,\nand they clasp hands with the children of foreigners.\n'),
	(12889, 20, 2, 7, 'Their land is full of silver and gold,\nneither is there any end of their treasures.\nTheir land also is full of horses,\nneither is there any end of their chariots.\n'),
	(12890, 20, 2, 8, 'Their land also is full of idols.\nThey worship the work of their own hands,\nthat which their own fingers have made.\n'),
	(12891, 20, 2, 9, 'Man is brought low,\nand mankind is humbled;\ntherefore don’t forgive them.\n'),
	(12892, 20, 2, 10, 'Enter into the rock,\nand hide in the dust,\nfrom before the terror of Yahweh,\nand from the glory of his majesty.\n'),
	(12893, 20, 2, 11, 'The lofty looks of man will be brought low,\nthe haughtiness of men will be bowed down,\nand Yahweh alone will be exalted in that day.\n'),
	(12894, 20, 2, 12, 'For there will be a day of Yahweh of Armies for all that is proud and haughty,\nand for all that is lifted up;\nand it shall be brought low:\n'),
	(12895, 20, 2, 13, 'For all the cedars of Lebanon, that are high and lifted up,\nfor all the oaks of Bashan,\n'),
	(12896, 20, 2, 14, 'For all the high mountains,\nfor all the hills that are lifted up,\n'),
	(12897, 20, 2, 15, 'For every lofty tower,\nfor every fortified wall,\n'),
	(12898, 20, 2, 16, 'For all the ships of Tarshish,\nand for all pleasant imagery.\n'),
	(12899, 20, 2, 17, 'The loftiness of man shall be bowed down,\nand the haughtiness of men shall be brought low;\nand Yahweh alone shall be exalted in that day.\n'),
	(12900, 20, 2, 18, 'The idols shall utterly pass away.\n'),
	(12901, 20, 2, 19, 'Men shall go into the caves of the rocks,\nand into the holes of the earth,\nfrom before the terror of Yahweh,\nand from the glory of his majesty,\nwhen he arises to shake the earth mightily.\n'),
	(12902, 20, 2, 20, 'In that day, men shall cast away their idols of silver,\nand their idols of gold,\nwhich have been made for themselves to worship,\nto the moles and to the bats;\n'),
	(12903, 20, 2, 21, 'To go into the caverns of the rocks,\nand into the clefts of the ragged rocks,\nfrom before the terror of Yahweh,\nand from the glory of his majesty,\nwhen he arises to shake the earth mightily.\n');
REPLACE INTO `verses` (`id`, `book_id`, `chapter_number`, `verse_number`, `text`) VALUES
	(12904, 20, 2, 22, 'Stop trusting in man, whose breath is in his nostrils;\nfor of what account is he?\n'),
	(12905, 20, 3, 1, 'For, behold, the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, takes away from Jerusalem and from Judah supply and support,\nthe whole supply of bread,\nand the whole supply of water;\n'),
	(12906, 20, 3, 2, 'the mighty man,\nthe man of war,\nthe judge,\nthe prophet,\nthe diviner,\nthe elder,\n'),
	(12907, 20, 3, 3, 'the captain of fifty,\nthe honorable man,\nthe counselor,\nthe skilled craftsman,\nand the clever enchanter.\n'),
	(12908, 20, 3, 4, 'I will give boys to be their princes,\nand children shall rule over them.\n'),
	(12909, 20, 3, 5, 'The people will be oppressed,\neveryone by another,\nand everyone by his neighbor.\nThe child will behave himself proudly against the old man,\nand the wicked against the honorable.\n'),
	(12910, 20, 3, 6, 'Indeed a man shall take hold of his brother in the house of his father, saying,\n“You have clothing, you be our ruler,\nand let this ruin be under your hand.”\n'),
	(12911, 20, 3, 7, 'In that day he will cry out, saying, “I will not be a healer;\nfor in my house is neither bread nor clothing.\nYou shall not make me ruler of the people.”\n'),
	(12912, 20, 3, 8, 'For Jerusalem is ruined, and Judah is fallen;\nbecause their tongue and their doings are against Yahweh,\nto provoke the eyes of his glory.\n'),
	(12913, 20, 3, 9, 'The look of their faces testify against them.\nThey parade their sin like Sodom.\nThey don’t hide it.\nWoe to their soul!\nFor they have brought disaster upon themselves.\n'),
	(12914, 20, 3, 10, 'Tell the righteous “Good!”\nFor they shall eat the fruit of their deeds.\n'),
	(12915, 20, 3, 11, 'Woe to the wicked!\nDisaster is upon them;\nfor the deeds of his hands will be paid back to him.\n'),
	(12916, 20, 3, 12, 'As for my people, children are their oppressors,\nand women rule over them.\nMy people, those who lead you cause you to err,\nand destroy the way of your paths.\n'),
	(12917, 20, 3, 13, 'Yahweh stands up to contend,\nand stands to judge the peoples.\n'),
	(12918, 20, 3, 14, 'Yahweh will enter into judgment with the elders of his people,\nand their leaders:\n“It is you who have eaten up the vineyard.\nThe plunder of the poor is in your houses.\n'),
	(12919, 20, 3, 15, 'What do you mean that you crush my people,\nand grind the face of the poor?” says the Lord, Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(12920, 20, 3, 16, 'Moreover Yahweh said, “Because the daughters of Zion are haughty,\nand walk with outstretched necks and flirting eyes,\nwalking to trip as they go,\njingling ornaments on their feet;\n'),
	(12921, 20, 3, 17, 'therefore the Lord brings sores on the crown of the head of the women of Zion,\nand Yahweh will make their scalps bald.”\n'),
	(12922, 20, 3, 18, 'In that day the Lord will take away the beauty of their anklets, the headbands, the crescent necklaces,\n'),
	(12923, 20, 3, 19, 'the earrings, the bracelets, the veils,\n'),
	(12924, 20, 3, 20, 'the headdresses, the ankle chains, the sashes, the perfume bottles, the charms,\n'),
	(12925, 20, 3, 21, 'the signet rings, the nose rings,\n'),
	(12926, 20, 3, 22, 'the fine robes, the capes, the cloaks, the purses,\n'),
	(12927, 20, 3, 23, 'the hand mirrors, the fine linen garments, the tiaras, and the shawls.\n'),
	(12928, 20, 3, 24, 'It shall happen that instead of sweet spices, there shall be rottenness;\ninstead of a belt, a rope;\ninstead of well set hair, baldness;\ninstead of a robe, a wearing of sackcloth;\nand branding instead of beauty.\n'),
	(12929, 20, 3, 25, 'Your men shall fall by the sword,\nand your mighty in the war.\n'),
	(12930, 20, 3, 26, 'Her gates shall lament and mourn;\nand she shall be desolate and sit on the ground.\n'),
	(12931, 20, 4, 1, 'Seven women shall take hold of one man in that day, saying, “We will eat our own bread, and wear our own clothing: only let us be called by your name. Take away our reproach.”\n'),
	(12932, 20, 4, 2, 'In that day, Yahweh’s branch will be beautiful and glorious, and the fruit of the land will be the beauty and glory of the survivors of Israel.\n'),
	(12933, 20, 4, 3, 'It will happen, that he who is left in Zion, and he who remains in Jerusalem, shall be called holy, even everyone who is written among the living in Jerusalem;\n'),
	(12934, 20, 4, 4, 'when the Lord shall have washed away the filth of the daughters of Zion, and shall have purged the blood of Jerusalem from within it, by the spirit of justice, and by the spirit of burning.\n'),
	(12935, 20, 4, 5, 'Yahweh will create over the whole habitation of Mount Zion, and over her assemblies, a cloud and smoke by day, and the shining of a flaming fire by night; for over all the glory will be a canopy.\n'),
	(12936, 20, 4, 6, 'There will be a pavilion for a shade in the daytime from the heat, and for a refuge and for a shelter from storm and from rain.\n'),
	(12937, 20, 5, 1, 'Let me sing for my well beloved a song of my beloved about his vineyard.\nMy beloved had a vineyard on a very fruitful hill.\n'),
	(12938, 20, 5, 2, 'He dug it up,\ngathered out its stones,\nplanted it with the choicest vine,\nbuilt a tower in the middle of it,\nand also cut out a wine press therein.\nHe looked for it to yield grapes,\nbut it yielded wild grapes.\n'),
	(12939, 20, 5, 3, '“Now, inhabitants of Jerusalem and men of Judah,\nplease judge between me and my vineyard.\n'),
	(12940, 20, 5, 4, 'What could have been done more to my vineyard, that I have not done in it?\nWhy, when I looked for it to yield grapes, did it yield wild grapes?\n'),
	(12941, 20, 5, 5, 'Now I will tell you what I will do to my vineyard.\nI will take away its hedge, and it will be eaten up.\nI will break down its wall, and it will be trampled down.\n'),
	(12942, 20, 5, 6, 'I will lay it a wasteland.\nIt won’t be pruned nor hoed,\nbut it will grow briers and thorns.\nI will also command the clouds that they rain no rain on it.”\n'),
	(12943, 20, 5, 7, 'For the vineyard of Yahweh of Armies is the house of Israel,\nand the men of Judah his pleasant plant:\nand he looked for justice, but, behold, oppression;\nfor righteousness, but, behold, a cry of distress.\n'),
	(12944, 20, 5, 8, 'Woe to those who join house to house,\nwho lay field to field, until there is no room,\nand you are made to dwell alone in the middle of the land!\n'),
	(12945, 20, 5, 9, 'In my ears, Yahweh of Armies says: “Surely many houses will be desolate,\neven great and beautiful, unoccupied.\n'),
	(12946, 20, 5, 10, 'For ten acres of vineyard shall yield one bath,\nand a homer of seed shall yield an ephah.”\n'),
	(12947, 20, 5, 11, 'Woe to those who rise up early in the morning, that they may follow strong drink;\nwho stay late into the night, until wine inflames them!\n'),
	(12948, 20, 5, 12, 'The harp, lyre, tambourine, and flute, with wine, are at their feasts;\nbut they don’t respect the work of Yahweh,\nneither have they considered the operation of his hands.\n'),
	(12949, 20, 5, 13, 'Therefore my people go into captivity for lack of knowledge.\nTheir honorable men are famished,\nand their multitudes are parched with thirst.\n'),
	(12950, 20, 5, 14, 'Therefore Sheol has enlarged its desire,\nand opened its mouth without measure;\nand their glory, their multitude, their pomp, and he who rejoices among them, descend into it.\n'),
	(12951, 20, 5, 15, 'So man is brought low,\nmankind is humbled,\nand the eyes of the arrogant ones are humbled;\n'),
	(12952, 20, 5, 16, 'but Yahweh of Armies is exalted in justice,\nand God the Holy One is sanctified in righteousness.\n'),
	(12953, 20, 5, 17, 'Then the lambs will graze as in their pasture,\nand strangers will eat the ruins of the rich.\n'),
	(12954, 20, 5, 18, 'Woe to those who draw iniquity with cords of falsehood,\nand wickedness as with cart rope;\n'),
	(12955, 20, 5, 19, 'Who say, “Let him make speed, let him hasten his work, that we may see it;\nand let the counsel of the Holy One of Israel draw near and come,\nthat we may know it!”\n'),
	(12956, 20, 5, 20, 'Woe to those who call evil good, and good evil;\nwho put darkness for light,\nand light for darkness;\nwho put bitter for sweet,\nand sweet for bitter!\n'),
	(12957, 20, 5, 21, 'Woe to those who are wise in their own eyes,\nand prudent in their own sight!\n'),
	(12958, 20, 5, 22, 'Woe to those who are mighty to drink wine,\nand champions at mixing strong drink;\n'),
	(12959, 20, 5, 23, 'who acquit the guilty for a bribe,\nbut deny justice for the innocent!\n'),
	(12960, 20, 5, 24, 'Therefore as the tongue of fire devours the stubble,\nand as the dry grass sinks down in the flame,\nso their root shall be as rottenness,\nand their blossom shall go up as dust;\nbecause they have rejected the law of Yahweh of Armies,\nand despised the word of the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(12961, 20, 5, 25, 'Therefore Yahweh’s anger burns against his people,\nand he has stretched out his hand against them, and has struck them.\nThe mountains tremble,\nand their dead bodies are as refuse in the middle of the streets.\nFor all this, his anger is not turned away,\nbut his hand is still stretched out.\n'),
	(12962, 20, 5, 26, 'He will lift up a banner to the nations from far,\nand he will whistle for them from the end of the earth.\nBehold, they will come speedily and swiftly.\n'),
	(12963, 20, 5, 27, 'No one shall be weary nor stumble among them;\nno one shall slumber nor sleep;\nneither shall the belt of their waist be untied,\nnor the strap of their sandals be broken:\n'),
	(12964, 20, 5, 28, 'whose arrows are sharp,\nand all their bows bent.\nTheir horses’ hoofs will be like flint,\nand their wheels like a whirlwind.\n'),
	(12965, 20, 5, 29, 'Their roaring will be like a lioness.\nThey will roar like young lions.\nYes, they shall roar,\nand seize their prey and carry it off,\nand there will be no one to deliver.\n'),
	(12966, 20, 5, 30, 'They will roar against them in that day like the roaring of the sea.\nIf one looks to the land behold, darkness and distress.\nThe light is darkened in its clouds.\n'),
	(12967, 20, 6, 1, 'In the year that king Uzziah died, I saw the Lord sitting on a throne, high and lifted up; and his train filled the temple.\n'),
	(12968, 20, 6, 2, 'Above him stood the seraphim. Each one had six wings. With two he covered his face. With two he covered his feet. With two he flew.\n'),
	(12969, 20, 6, 3, 'One called to another, and said,\n“Holy, holy, holy, is Yahweh of Armies!\nThe whole earth is full of his glory!”\n'),
	(12970, 20, 6, 4, 'The foundations of the thresholds shook at the voice of him who called, and the house was filled with smoke.\n'),
	(12971, 20, 6, 5, 'Then I said, “Woe is me! For I am undone, because I am a man of unclean lips, and I dwell among a people of unclean lips: for my eyes have seen the King, Yahweh of Armies!”\n'),
	(12972, 20, 6, 6, 'Then one of the seraphim flew to me, having a live coal in his hand, which he had taken with the tongs from off the altar.\n'),
	(12973, 20, 6, 7, 'He touched my mouth with it, and said, “Behold, this has touched your lips; and your iniquity is taken away, and your sin forgiven.”\n'),
	(12974, 20, 6, 8, 'I heard the Lord’s voice, saying, “Whom shall I send, and who will go for us?”\nThen I said, “Here I am. Send me!”\n'),
	(12975, 20, 6, 9, 'He said, “Go, and tell this people,\n‘You hear indeed,\nbut don’t understand;\nand you see indeed,\nbut don’t perceive.’\n'),
	(12976, 20, 6, 10, 'Make the heart of this people fat.\nMake their ears heavy, and shut their eyes;\nlest they see with their eyes,\nand hear with their ears,\nand understand with their heart,\nand turn again, and be healed.”\n'),
	(12977, 20, 6, 11, 'Then I said, “Lord, how long?”\nHe answered,\n“Until cities are waste without inhabitant,\nand houses without man,\nand the land becomes utterly waste,\n'),
	(12978, 20, 6, 12, 'And Yahweh has removed men far away,\nand the forsaken places are many within the land.\n'),
	(12979, 20, 6, 13, 'If there is a tenth left in it,\nthat also will in turn be consumed:\nas a terebinth, and as an oak, whose stock remains when they are felled;\nso the holy seed is its stock.”\n'),
	(12980, 20, 7, 1, 'In the days of Ahaz the son of Jotham, the son of Uzziah, king of Judah, Rezin the king of Syria, and Pekah the son of Remaliah, king of Israel, went up to Jerusalem to war against it, but could not prevail against it.\n'),
	(12981, 20, 7, 2, 'David’s house was told, “Syria is allied with Ephraim.” His heart trembled, and the heart of his people, as the trees of the forest tremble with the wind.\n'),
	(12982, 20, 7, 3, 'Then Yahweh said to Isaiah, “Go out now to meet Ahaz, you, and Shearjashub your son, at the end of the conduit of the upper pool, on the highway of the fuller’s field.\n'),
	(12983, 20, 7, 4, 'Tell him, ‘Be careful, and keep calm. Don’t be afraid, neither let your heart be faint because of these two tails of smoking torches, for the fierce anger of Rezin and Syria, and of the son of Remaliah.\n'),
	(12984, 20, 7, 5, 'Because Syria, Ephraim, and the son of Remaliah, have plotted evil against you, saying,\n'),
	(12985, 20, 7, 6, '“Let’s go up against Judah, and tear it apart, and let’s divide it among ourselves, and set up a king within it, even the son of Tabeel.”\n'),
	(12986, 20, 7, 7, 'This is what the Lord Yahweh says: “It shall not stand, neither shall it happen.”\n'),
	(12987, 20, 7, 8, 'For the head of Syria is Damascus, and the head of Damascus is Rezin; and within sixty-five years Ephraim shall be broken in pieces, so that it shall not be a people;\n'),
	(12988, 20, 7, 9, 'and the head of Ephraim is Samaria, and the head of Samaria is Remaliah’s son. If you will not believe, surely you shall not be established.’”\n'),
	(12989, 20, 7, 10, 'Yahweh spoke again to Ahaz, saying,\n'),
	(12990, 20, 7, 11, '“Ask a sign of Yahweh your God; ask it either in the depth, or in the height above.”\n'),
	(12991, 20, 7, 12, 'But Ahaz said, “I will not ask, neither will I tempt Yahweh.”\n'),
	(12992, 20, 7, 13, 'He said, “Listen now, house of David. Is it not enough for you to try the patience of men, that you will try the patience of my God also?\n'),
	(12993, 20, 7, 14, 'Therefore the Lord himself will give you a sign. Behold, the virgin will conceive, and bear a son, and shall call his name Immanuel.\n'),
	(12994, 20, 7, 15, 'He shall eat butter and honey when he knows to refuse the evil, and choose the good.\n'),
	(12995, 20, 7, 16, 'For before the child knows to refuse the evil, and choose the good, the land whose two kings you abhor shall be forsaken.\n'),
	(12996, 20, 7, 17, 'Yahweh will bring on you, on your people, and on your father’s house, days that have not come, from the day that Ephraim departed from Judah; even the king of Assyria.\n'),
	(12997, 20, 7, 18, 'It will happen in that day that Yahweh will whistle for the fly that is in the uttermost part of the rivers of Egypt, and for the bee that is in the land of Assyria.\n'),
	(12998, 20, 7, 19, 'They shall come, and shall all rest in the desolate valleys, in the clefts of the rocks, on all thorn hedges, and on all pastures.\n'),
	(12999, 20, 7, 20, 'In that day the Lord will shave with a razor that is hired in the parts beyond the River, even with the king of Assyria, the head and the hair of the feet; and it shall also consume the beard.\n'),
	(13000, 20, 7, 21, 'It shall happen in that day that a man shall keep alive a young cow, and two sheep;\n'),
	(13001, 20, 7, 22, 'and it shall happen, that because of the abundance of milk which they shall give he shall eat butter: for everyone will eat butter and honey that is left within the land.\n'),
	(13002, 20, 7, 23, 'It will happen in that day that every place where there were a thousand vines at a thousand silver shekels, shall be for briers and thorns.\n'),
	(13003, 20, 7, 24, 'People will go there with arrows and with bow, because all the land will be briers and thorns.\n'),
	(13004, 20, 7, 25, 'All the hills that were cultivated with the hoe, you shall not come there for fear of briers and thorns; but it shall be for the sending out of oxen, and for the treading of sheep.”\n'),
	(13005, 20, 8, 1, 'Yahweh said to me, “Take a large tablet, and write on it with a man’s pen, ‘For Maher Shalal Hash Baz’;\n'),
	(13006, 20, 8, 2, 'and I will take for myself faithful witnesses to testify: Uriah the priest, and Zechariah the son of Jeberechiah.”\n'),
	(13007, 20, 8, 3, 'I went to the prophetess, and she conceived, and bore a son. Then Yahweh said to me, “Call his name ‘Maher Shalal Hash Baz.’\n'),
	(13008, 20, 8, 4, 'For before the child knows how to say, ‘My father,’ and, ‘My mother,’ the riches of Damascus and the plunder of Samaria will be carried away by the king of Assyria.”\n'),
	(13009, 20, 8, 5, 'Yahweh spoke to me yet again, saying,\n'),
	(13010, 20, 8, 6, '“Because this people have refused the waters of Shiloah that go softly, and rejoice in Rezin and Remaliah’s son;\n'),
	(13011, 20, 8, 7, 'now therefore, behold, the Lord brings upon them the mighty flood waters of the River: the king of Assyria and all his glory. It will come up over all its channels, and go over all its banks.\n'),
	(13012, 20, 8, 8, 'It will sweep onward into Judah. It will overflow and pass through; it will reach even to the neck; and the stretching out of its wings will fill the width of your land, Immanuel.\n'),
	(13013, 20, 8, 9, 'Make an uproar, you peoples, and be broken in pieces! Listen, all you from far countries: dress for battle, and be shattered! Dress for battle, and be shattered!\n'),
	(13014, 20, 8, 10, 'Take counsel together, and it will be brought to nothing; speak the word, and it will not stand: for God is with us.”\n'),
	(13015, 20, 8, 11, 'For Yahweh spoke thus to me with a strong hand, and instructed me not to walk in the way of this people, saying,\n'),
	(13016, 20, 8, 12, '“Don’t say, ‘A conspiracy!’ concerning all about which this people say, ‘A conspiracy!’ neither fear their threats, nor be terrorized.\n'),
	(13017, 20, 8, 13, 'Yahweh of Armies is who you must respect as holy. He is the one you must fear. He is the one you must dread.\n'),
	(13018, 20, 8, 14, 'He will be a sanctuary, but for both houses of Israel, he will be a trap and a snare for the inhabitants of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(13019, 20, 8, 15, 'Many will stumble over it, fall, be broken, be snared, and be captured.”\n'),
	(13020, 20, 8, 16, 'Wrap up the testimony. Seal the law among my disciples.\n'),
	(13021, 20, 8, 17, 'I will wait for Yahweh, who hides his face from the house of Jacob, and I will look for him.\n'),
	(13022, 20, 8, 18, 'Behold, I and the children whom Yahweh has given me are for signs and for wonders in Israel from Yahweh of Armies, who dwells in Mount Zion.\n'),
	(13023, 20, 8, 19, 'When they tell you, “Consult with those who have familiar spirits and with the wizards, who chirp and who mutter:” shouldn’t a people consult with their God? Should they consult the dead on behalf of the living?\n'),
	(13024, 20, 8, 20, 'Turn to the law and to the testimony! If they don’t speak according to this word, surely there is no morning for them.\n'),
	(13025, 20, 8, 21, 'They will pass through it, very distressed and hungry; and it will happen that when they are hungry, they will worry, and curse by their king and by their God. They will turn their faces upward,\n'),
	(13026, 20, 8, 22, 'and look to the earth, and see distress, darkness, and the gloom of anguish. They will be driven into thick darkness.\n'),
	(13027, 20, 9, 1, 'But there shall be no more gloom for her who was in anguish. In the former time, he brought into contempt the land of Zebulun and the land of Naphtali; but in the latter time he has made it glorious, by the way of the sea, beyond the Jordan, Galilee of the nations.\n'),
	(13028, 20, 9, 2, 'The people who walked in darkness have seen a great light.\nThose who lived in the land of the shadow of death, on them the light has shined.\n'),
	(13029, 20, 9, 3, 'You have multiplied the nation.\nYou have increased their joy.\nThey rejoice before you according to the joy in harvest, as men rejoice when they divide the plunder.\n'),
	(13030, 20, 9, 4, 'For the yoke of his burden, and the staff of his shoulder, the rod of his oppressor, you have broken as in the day of Midian.\n'),
	(13031, 20, 9, 5, 'For all the armor of the armed man in the noisy battle, and the garments rolled in blood, will be for burning, fuel for the fire.\n'),
	(13032, 20, 9, 6, 'For to us a child is born. To us a son is given; and the government will be on his shoulders. His name will be called Wonderful, Counselor, Mighty God, Everlasting Father, Prince of Peace.\n'),
	(13033, 20, 9, 7, 'Of the increase of his government and of peace there shall be no end, on David’s throne, and on his kingdom, to establish it, and to uphold it with justice and with righteousness from that time on, even forever. The zeal of Yahweh of Armies will perform this.\n'),
	(13034, 20, 9, 8, 'The Lord sent a word into Jacob,\nand it falls on Israel.\n'),
	(13035, 20, 9, 9, 'All the people will know,\nincluding Ephraim and the inhabitants of Samaria, who say in pride and in arrogance of heart,\n'),
	(13036, 20, 9, 10, '“The bricks have fallen,\nbut we will build with cut stone.\nThe sycamore fig trees have been cut down,\nbut we will put cedars in their place.”\n'),
	(13037, 20, 9, 11, 'Therefore Yahweh will set up on high against him the adversaries of Rezin,\nand will stir up his enemies,\n'),
	(13038, 20, 9, 12, 'The Syrians in front,\nand the Philistines behind;\nand they will devour Israel with open mouth.\nFor all this, his anger is not turned away,\nbut his hand is stretched out still.\n'),
	(13039, 20, 9, 13, 'Yet the people have not turned to him who struck them,\nneither have they sought Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(13040, 20, 9, 14, 'Therefore Yahweh will cut off from Israel head and tail,\npalm branch and reed, in one day.\n'),
	(13041, 20, 9, 15, 'The elder and the honorable man is the head,\nand the prophet who teaches lies is the tail.\n'),
	(13042, 20, 9, 16, 'For those who lead this people lead them astray;\nand those who are led by them are destroyed.\n'),
	(13043, 20, 9, 17, 'Therefore the Lord will not rejoice over their young men,\nneither will he have compassion on their fatherless and widows;\nfor everyone is profane and an evildoer,\nand every mouth speaks folly.\nFor all this his anger is not turned away,\nbut his hand is stretched out still.\n'),
	(13044, 20, 9, 18, 'For wickedness burns like a fire.\nIt devours the briers and thorns;\nyes, it kindles in the thickets of the forest,\nand they roll upward in a column of smoke.\n'),
	(13045, 20, 9, 19, 'Through Yahweh of Armies’ wrath, the land is burned up;\nand the people are the fuel for the fire.\nNo one spares his brother.\n'),
	(13046, 20, 9, 20, 'One will devour on the right hand, and be hungry;\nand he will eat on the left hand, and they will not be satisfied.\nEveryone will eat the flesh of his own arm:\n'),
	(13047, 20, 9, 21, 'Manasseh, Ephraim; and Ephraim, Manasseh; and they together shall be against Judah.\nFor all this his anger is not turned away,\nbut his hand is stretched out still.\n'),
	(13048, 20, 10, 1, 'Woe to those who decree unrighteous decrees, and to the writers who write oppressive decrees;\n'),
	(13049, 20, 10, 2, 'to deprive the needy from justice, and to rob the poor among my people of their rights, that widows may be their plunder, and that they may make the fatherless their prey!\n'),
	(13050, 20, 10, 3, 'What will you do in the day of visitation, and in the desolation which will come from afar? To whom will you flee for help? Where will you leave your wealth?\n'),
	(13051, 20, 10, 4, 'They will only bow down under the prisoners,\nand will fall under the slain.\nFor all this his anger is not turned away,\nbut his hand is stretched out still.\n'),
	(13052, 20, 10, 5, 'Alas Assyrian, the rod of my anger, the staff in whose hand is my indignation!\n'),
	(13053, 20, 10, 6, 'I will send him against a profane nation, and against the people who anger me will I give him a command to take the plunder and to take the prey, and to tread them down like the mire of the streets.\n'),
	(13054, 20, 10, 7, 'However he doesn’t mean so, neither does his heart think so; but it is in his heart to destroy, and to cut off not a few nations.\n'),
	(13055, 20, 10, 8, 'For he says, “Aren’t all of my princes kings?\n'),
	(13056, 20, 10, 9, 'Isn’t Calno like Carchemish? Isn’t Hamath like Arpad? Isn’t Samaria like Damascus?”\n'),
	(13057, 20, 10, 10, 'As my hand has found the kingdoms of the idols, whose engraved images exceeded those of Jerusalem and of Samaria;\n'),
	(13058, 20, 10, 11, 'shall I not, as I have done to Samaria and her idols, so do to Jerusalem and her idols?\n'),
	(13059, 20, 10, 12, 'Therefore it will happen that, when the Lord has performed his whole work on Mount Zion and on Jerusalem, I will punish the fruit of the willful proud heart of the king of Assyria, and the insolence of his haughty looks.\n'),
	(13060, 20, 10, 13, 'For he has said, “By the strength of my hand I have done it, and by my wisdom; for I have understanding: and I have removed the boundaries of the peoples, and have robbed their treasures. Like a valiant man I have brought down their rulers.\n'),
	(13061, 20, 10, 14, 'My hand has found the riches of the peoples like a nest, and like one gathers eggs that are abandoned, I have gathered all the earth. There was no one who moved their wing, or that opened their mouth, or chirped.”\n'),
	(13062, 20, 10, 15, 'Should an ax brag against him who chops with it? Should a saw exalt itself above him who saws with it? As if a rod should lift those who lift it up, or as if a staff should lift up someone who is not wood.\n'),
	(13063, 20, 10, 16, 'Therefore the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, will send among his fat ones leanness; and under his glory a burning will be kindled like the burning of fire.\n'),
	(13064, 20, 10, 17, 'The light of Israel will be for a fire, and his Holy One for a flame; and it will burn and devour his thorns and his briers in one day.\n'),
	(13065, 20, 10, 18, 'He will consume the glory of his forest, and of his fruitful field, both soul and body. It will be as when a standard bearer faints.\n'),
	(13066, 20, 10, 19, 'The remnant of the trees of his forest shall be few, so that a child could write their number.\n'),
	(13067, 20, 10, 20, 'It will come to pass in that day that the remnant of Israel, and those who have escaped from the house of Jacob will no more again lean on him who struck them, but shall lean on Yahweh, the Holy One of Israel, in truth.\n'),
	(13068, 20, 10, 21, 'A remnant will return, even the remnant of Jacob, to the mighty God.\n'),
	(13069, 20, 10, 22, 'For though your people, Israel, are like the sand of the sea, only a remnant of them will return. A destruction is determined, overflowing with righteousness.\n'),
	(13070, 20, 10, 23, 'For the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, will make a full end, and that determined, throughout all the earth.\n'),
	(13071, 20, 10, 24, 'Therefore the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, says “My people who dwell in Zion, don’t be afraid of the Assyrian, though he strike you with the rod, and lift up his staff against you, as Egypt did.\n'),
	(13072, 20, 10, 25, 'For yet a very little while, and the indignation against you will be accomplished, and my anger will be directed to his destruction.”\n'),
	(13073, 20, 10, 26, 'Yahweh of Armies will stir up a scourge against him, as in the slaughter of Midian at the rock of Oreb. His rod will be over the sea, and he will lift it up like he did against Egypt.\n'),
	(13074, 20, 10, 27, 'It will happen in that day, that his burden will depart from off your shoulder, and his yoke from off your neck, and the yoke shall be destroyed because of the anointing oil.\n'),
	(13075, 20, 10, 28, 'He has come to Aiath. He has passed through Migron. At Michmash he stores his baggage.\n'),
	(13076, 20, 10, 29, 'They have gone over the pass. They have taken up their lodging at Geba. Ramah trembles. Gibeah of Saul has fled.\n'),
	(13077, 20, 10, 30, 'Cry aloud with your voice, daughter of Gallim! Listen, Laishah! You poor Anathoth!\n'),
	(13078, 20, 10, 31, 'Madmenah is a fugitive. The inhabitants of Gebim flee for safety.\n'),
	(13079, 20, 10, 32, 'This very day he will halt at Nob. He shakes his hand at the mountain of the daughter of Zion, the hill of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(13080, 20, 10, 33, 'Behold, the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, will lop the boughs with terror. The tall will be cut down, and the lofty will be brought low.\n'),
	(13081, 20, 10, 34, 'He will cut down the thickets of the forest with iron, and Lebanon will fall by the Mighty One.\n'),
	(13082, 20, 11, 1, 'A shoot will come out of the stock of Jesse,\nand a branch out of his roots will bear fruit.\n'),
	(13083, 20, 11, 2, 'Yahweh’s Spirit will rest on him:\nthe spirit of wisdom and understanding,\nthe spirit of counsel and might,\nthe spirit of knowledge and of the fear of Yahweh.\n'),
	(13084, 20, 11, 3, 'His delight will be in the fear of Yahweh.\nHe will not judge by the sight of his eyes,\nneither decide by the hearing of his ears;\n'),
	(13085, 20, 11, 4, 'but with righteousness he will judge the poor,\nand decide with equity for the humble of the earth.\nHe will strike the earth with the rod of his mouth;\nand with the breath of his lips he will kill the wicked.\n'),
	(13086, 20, 11, 5, 'Righteousness will be the belt of his waist,\nand faithfulness the belt of his waist.\n'),
	(13087, 20, 11, 6, 'The wolf will live with the lamb,\nand the leopard will lie down with the young goat;\nThe calf, the young lion, and the fattened calf together;\nand a little child will lead them.\n'),
	(13088, 20, 11, 7, 'The cow and the bear will graze.\nTheir young ones will lie down together.\nThe lion will eat straw like the ox.\n'),
	(13089, 20, 11, 8, 'The nursing child will play near a cobra’s hole,\nand the weaned child will put his hand on the viper’s den.\n'),
	(13090, 20, 11, 9, 'They will not hurt nor destroy in all my holy mountain;\nfor the earth will be full of the knowledge of Yahweh,\nas the waters cover the sea.\n'),
	(13091, 20, 11, 10, 'It will happen in that day that the nations will seek the root of Jesse, who stands as a banner of the peoples; and his resting place will be glorious.\n'),
	(13092, 20, 11, 11, 'It will happen in that day that the Lord will set his hand again the second time to recover the remnant that is left of his people from Assyria, from Egypt, from Pathros, from Cush, from Elam, from Shinar, from Hamath, and from the islands of the sea.\n'),
	(13093, 20, 11, 12, 'He will set up a banner for the nations, and will assemble the outcasts of Israel, and gather together the dispersed of Judah from the four corners of the earth.\n'),
	(13094, 20, 11, 13, 'The envy also of Ephraim will depart, and those who persecute Judah will be cut off. Ephraim won’t envy Judah, and Judah won’t persecute Ephraim.\n'),
	(13095, 20, 11, 14, 'They will fly down on the shoulders of the Philistines on the west. Together they will plunder the children of the east. They will extend their power over Edom and Moab, and the children of Ammon will obey them.\n'),
	(13096, 20, 11, 15, 'Yahweh will utterly destroy the tongue of the Egyptian sea; and with his scorching wind he will wave his hand over the River, and will split it into seven streams, and cause men to march over in sandals.\n'),
	(13097, 20, 11, 16, 'There will be a highway for the remnant that is left of his people from Assyria, like there was for Israel in the day that he came up out of the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(13098, 20, 12, 1, 'In that day you will say, “I will give thanks to you, Yahweh; for though you were angry with me, your anger has turned away and you comfort me.\n'),
	(13099, 20, 12, 2, 'Behold, God is my salvation. I will trust, and will not be afraid; for Yah, Yahweh, is my strength and song; and he has become my salvation.”\n'),
	(13100, 20, 12, 3, 'Therefore with joy you will draw water out of the wells of salvation.\n'),
	(13101, 20, 12, 4, 'In that day you will say, “Give thanks to Yahweh! Call on his name. Declare his doings among the peoples. Proclaim that his name is exalted!\n'),
	(13102, 20, 12, 5, 'Sing to Yahweh, for he has done excellent things! Let this be known in all the earth!\n'),
	(13103, 20, 12, 6, 'Cry aloud and shout, you inhabitant of Zion; for the Holy One of Israel is great among you!”\n'),
	(13104, 20, 13, 1, 'The burden of Babylon, which Isaiah the son of Amoz saw.\n'),
	(13105, 20, 13, 2, 'Set up a banner on the bare mountain! Lift up your voice to them! Wave your hand, that they may go into the gates of the nobles.\n'),
	(13106, 20, 13, 3, 'I have commanded my consecrated ones; yes, I have called my mighty men for my anger, even my proudly exulting ones.\n'),
	(13107, 20, 13, 4, 'The noise of a multitude is in the mountains, as of a great people; the noise of an uproar of the kingdoms of the nations gathered together! Yahweh of Armies is mustering the army for the battle.\n'),
	(13108, 20, 13, 5, 'They come from a far country, from the uttermost part of heaven, even Yahweh, and the weapons of his indignation, to destroy the whole land.\n'),
	(13109, 20, 13, 6, 'Wail; for the day of Yahweh is at hand! It will come as destruction from the Almighty.\n'),
	(13110, 20, 13, 7, 'Therefore all hands will be feeble, and everyone’s heart will melt.\n'),
	(13111, 20, 13, 8, 'They will be dismayed. Pangs and sorrows will seize them. They will be in pain like a woman in labor. They will look in amazement one at another. Their faces will be faces of flame.\n'),
	(13112, 20, 13, 9, 'Behold, the day of Yahweh comes, cruel, with wrath and fierce anger; to make the land a desolation, and to destroy its sinners out of it.\n'),
	(13113, 20, 13, 10, 'For the stars of the sky and its constellations will not give their light. The sun will be darkened in its going out, and the moon will not cause its light to shine.\n'),
	(13114, 20, 13, 11, 'I will punish the world for their evil, and the wicked for their iniquity. I will cause the arrogance of the proud to cease, and will humble the haughtiness of the terrible.\n'),
	(13115, 20, 13, 12, 'I will make people more rare than fine gold, even a person than the pure gold of Ophir.\n'),
	(13116, 20, 13, 13, 'Therefore I will make the heavens tremble, and the earth will be shaken out of its place in Yahweh of Armies’ wrath, and in the day of his fierce anger.\n'),
	(13117, 20, 13, 14, 'It will happen that like a hunted gazelle, and like sheep that no one gathers, they will each turn to their own people, and will each flee to their own land.\n'),
	(13118, 20, 13, 15, 'Everyone who is found will be thrust through. Everyone who is captured will fall by the sword.\n'),
	(13119, 20, 13, 16, 'Their infants also will be dashed in pieces before their eyes. Their houses will be ransacked, and their wives raped.\n'),
	(13120, 20, 13, 17, 'Behold, I will stir up the Medes against them, who will not value silver, and as for gold, they will not delight in it.\n'),
	(13121, 20, 13, 18, 'Their bows will dash the young men in pieces; and they shall have no pity on the fruit of the womb. Their eyes will not spare children.\n'),
	(13122, 20, 13, 19, 'Babylon, the glory of kingdoms, the beauty of the Chaldeans’ pride, will be like when God overthrew Sodom and Gomorrah.\n'),
	(13123, 20, 13, 20, 'It will never be inhabited, neither will it be lived in from generation to generation. The Arabian will not pitch a tent there, neither will shepherds make their flocks lie down there.\n'),
	(13124, 20, 13, 21, 'But wild animals of the desert will lie there, and their houses will be full of jackals. Ostriches will dwell there, and wild goats will frolic there.\n'),
	(13125, 20, 13, 22, 'Wolves will cry in their fortresses, and jackals in the pleasant palaces. Her time is near to come, and her days will not be prolonged.\n'),
	(13126, 20, 14, 1, 'For Yahweh will have compassion on Jacob, and will yet choose Israel, and set them in their own land. The foreigner will join himself with them, and they will unite with the house of Jacob.\n'),
	(13127, 20, 14, 2, 'The peoples will take them, and bring them to their place. The house of Israel will possess them in Yahweh’s land for servants and for handmaids. They will take as captives those whose captives they were; and they shall rule over their oppressors.\n'),
	(13128, 20, 14, 3, 'It will happen in the day that Yahweh will give you rest from your sorrow, from your trouble, and from the hard service in which you were made to serve,\n'),
	(13129, 20, 14, 4, 'that you will take up this parable against the king of Babylon, and say, “How the oppressor has ceased! The golden city has ceased!”\n'),
	(13130, 20, 14, 5, 'Yahweh has broken the staff of the wicked, the scepter of the rulers,\n'),
	(13131, 20, 14, 6, 'who struck the peoples in wrath with a continual stroke, who ruled the nations in anger, with a persecution that no one restrained.\n'),
	(13132, 20, 14, 7, 'The whole earth is at rest, and is quiet. They break out in song.\n'),
	(13133, 20, 14, 8, 'Yes, the cypress trees rejoice with you, with the cedars of Lebanon, saying, “Since you are humbled, no lumberjack has come up against us.”\n'),
	(13134, 20, 14, 9, 'Sheol from beneath has moved for you to meet you at your coming. It stirs up the departed spirits for you, even all the rulers of the earth. It has raised up from their thrones all the kings of the nations.\n'),
	(13135, 20, 14, 10, 'They all will answer and ask you, “Have you also become as weak as we are? Have you become like us?”\n'),
	(13136, 20, 14, 11, 'Your pomp is brought down to Sheol, with the sound of your stringed instruments. Maggots are spread out under you, and worms cover you.\n'),
	(13137, 20, 14, 12, 'How you have fallen from heaven, morning star, son of the dawn! How you are cut down to the ground, who laid the nations low!\n'),
	(13138, 20, 14, 13, 'You said in your heart, “I will ascend into heaven! I will exalt my throne above the stars of God! I will sit on the mountain of assembly, in the far north!\n'),
	(13139, 20, 14, 14, 'I will ascend above the heights of the clouds! I will make myself like the Most High!”\n'),
	(13140, 20, 14, 15, 'Yet you shall be brought down to Sheol, to the depths of the pit.\n'),
	(13141, 20, 14, 16, 'Those who see you will stare at you. They will ponder you, saying, “Is this the man who made the earth to tremble, who shook kingdoms;\n'),
	(13142, 20, 14, 17, 'who made the world like a wilderness, and overthrew its cities; who didn’t release his prisoners to their home?”\n'),
	(13143, 20, 14, 18, 'All the kings of the nations, sleep in glory, everyone in his own house.\n'),
	(13144, 20, 14, 19, 'But you are cast away from your tomb like an abominable branch, clothed with the slain, who are thrust through with the sword, who go down to the stones of the pit; like a dead body trodden under foot.\n'),
	(13145, 20, 14, 20, 'You will not join them in burial, because you have destroyed your land. You have killed your people. The offspring of evildoers will not be named forever.\n'),
	(13146, 20, 14, 21, 'Prepare for slaughter of his children because of the iniquity of their fathers, that they not rise up and possess the earth, and fill the surface of the world with cities.\n'),
	(13147, 20, 14, 22, '“I will rise up against them,” says Yahweh of Armies, “and cut off from Babylon name and remnant, and son and son’s son,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(13148, 20, 14, 23, '“I will also make it a possession for the porcupine, and pools of water. I will sweep it with the broom of destruction,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(13149, 20, 14, 24, 'Yahweh of Armies has sworn, saying, “Surely, as I have thought, so shall it happen; and as I have purposed, so shall it stand:\n'),
	(13150, 20, 14, 25, 'that I will break the Assyrian in my land, and tread him under foot on my mountains. Then his yoke will leave them, and his burden leave their shoulders.\n'),
	(13151, 20, 14, 26, 'This is the plan that is determined for the whole earth. This is the hand that is stretched out over all the nations.\n'),
	(13152, 20, 14, 27, 'For Yahweh of Armies has planned, and who can stop it? His hand is stretched out, and who can turn it back?”\n'),
	(13153, 20, 14, 28, 'This burden was in the year that king Ahaz died.\n'),
	(13154, 20, 14, 29, 'Don’t rejoice, O Philistia, all of you, because the rod that struck you is broken; for out of the serpent’s root an adder will emerge, and his fruit will be a fiery flying serpent.\n'),
	(13155, 20, 14, 30, 'The firstborn of the poor will eat, and the needy will lie down in safety; and I will kill your root with famine, and your remnant will be killed.\n'),
	(13156, 20, 14, 31, 'Howl, gate! Cry, city! You are melted away, Philistia, all of you; for smoke comes out of the north, and there is no straggler in his ranks.\n'),
	(13157, 20, 14, 32, 'What will they answer the messengers of the nation? That Yahweh has founded Zion, and in her the afflicted of his people will take refuge.\n'),
	(13158, 20, 15, 1, 'The burden of Moab.\nFor in a night, Ar of Moab is laid waste, and brought to nothing. For in a night Kir of Moab is laid waste, and brought to nothing.\n'),
	(13159, 20, 15, 2, 'They have gone up to Bayith, and to Dibon, to the high places, to weep. Moab wails over Nebo and over Medeba. Baldness is on all of their heads. Every beard is cut off.\n'),
	(13160, 20, 15, 3, 'In their streets, they clothe themselves in sackcloth. In their streets and on their housetops, everyone wails, weeping abundantly.\n'),
	(13161, 20, 15, 4, 'Heshbon cries out with Elealeh. Their voice is heard even to Jahaz. Therefore the armed men of Moab cry aloud. Their souls tremble within them.\n'),
	(13162, 20, 15, 5, 'My heart cries out for Moab! Her nobles flee to Zoar, to Eglath Shelishiyah; for they go up by the ascent of Luhith with weeping; for on the way to Horonaim, they raise up a cry of destruction.\n'),
	(13163, 20, 15, 6, 'For the waters of Nimrim will be desolate; for the grass has withered away, the tender grass fails, there is no green thing.\n'),
	(13164, 20, 15, 7, 'Therefore they will carry away the abundance they have gotten, and that which they have stored up, over the brook of the willows.\n'),
	(13165, 20, 15, 8, 'For the cry has gone around the borders of Moab; its wailing to Eglaim, and its wailing to Beer Elim.\n'),
	(13166, 20, 15, 9, 'For the waters of Dimon are full of blood; for I will bring yet more on Dimon, a lion on those of Moab who escape, and on the remnant of the land.\n'),
	(13167, 20, 16, 1, 'Send the lambs for the ruler of the land from Selah to the wilderness, to the mountain of the daughter of Zion.\n'),
	(13168, 20, 16, 2, 'For it will be that as wandering birds, as a scattered nest, so will the daughters of Moab be at the fords of the Arnon.\n'),
	(13169, 20, 16, 3, 'Give counsel! Execute justice! Make your shade like the night in the middle of the noonday! Hide the outcasts! Don’t betray the fugitive!\n'),
	(13170, 20, 16, 4, 'Let my outcasts dwell with you! As for Moab, be a hiding place for him from the face of the destroyer. For the extortionist is brought to nothing. Destruction ceases. The oppressors are consumed out of the land.\n'),
	(13171, 20, 16, 5, 'A throne will be established in loving kindness. One will sit on it in truth, in the tent of David, judging, seeking justice, and swift to do righteousness.\n'),
	(13172, 20, 16, 6, 'We have heard of the pride of Moab, that he is very proud; even of his arrogance, his pride, and his wrath. His boastings are nothing.\n'),
	(13173, 20, 16, 7, 'Therefore Moab will wail for Moab. Everyone will wail. You will mourn for the raisin cakes of Kir Hareseth, utterly stricken.\n'),
	(13174, 20, 16, 8, 'For the fields of Heshbon languish with the vine of Sibmah. The lords of the nations have broken down its choice branches, which reached even to Jazer, which wandered into the wilderness. Its shoots were spread abroad. They passed over the sea.\n'),
	(13175, 20, 16, 9, 'Therefore I will weep with the weeping of Jazer for the vine of Sibmah. I will water you with my tears, Heshbon, and Elealeh: for on your summer fruits and on your harvest the battle shout has fallen.\n'),
	(13176, 20, 16, 10, 'Gladness is taken away, and joy out of the fruitful field; and in the vineyards there will be no singing, neither joyful noise. Nobody will tread out wine in the presses. I have made the shouting stop.\n'),
	(13177, 20, 16, 11, 'Therefore my heart sounds like a harp for Moab, and my inward parts for Kir Heres.\n'),
	(13178, 20, 16, 12, 'It will happen that when Moab presents himself, when he wearies himself on the high place, and comes to his sanctuary to pray, that he will not prevail.\n'),
	(13179, 20, 16, 13, 'This is the word that Yahweh spoke concerning Moab in time past.\n'),
	(13180, 20, 16, 14, 'But now Yahweh has spoken, saying, “Within three years, as a worker bound by contract would count them, the glory of Moab shall be brought into contempt, with all his great multitude; and the remnant will be very small and feeble.”\n'),
	(13181, 20, 17, 1, 'The burden of Damascus.\n“Behold, Damascus is taken away from being a city, and it will be a ruinous heap.\n'),
	(13182, 20, 17, 2, 'The cities of Aroer are forsaken. They will be for flocks, which shall lie down, and no one shall make them afraid.\n'),
	(13183, 20, 17, 3, 'The fortress shall cease from Ephraim, and the kingdom from Damascus, and the remnant of Syria. They will be as the glory of the children of Israel,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(13184, 20, 17, 4, '“It will happen in that day that the glory of Jacob will be made thin, and the fatness of his flesh will become lean.\n'),
	(13185, 20, 17, 5, 'It will be like when the harvester gathers the wheat, and his arm reaps the grain. Yes, it will be like when one gleans grain in the valley of Rephaim.\n'),
	(13186, 20, 17, 6, 'Yet gleanings will be left there, like the shaking of an olive tree, two or three olives in the top of the uppermost bough, four or five in the outermost branches of a fruitful tree,” says Yahweh, the God of Israel.\n'),
	(13187, 20, 17, 7, 'In that day, people will look to their Maker, and their eyes will have respect for the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(13188, 20, 17, 8, 'They will not look to the altars, the work of their hands; neither shall they respect that which their fingers have made, either the Asherah poles, or the incense altars.\n'),
	(13189, 20, 17, 9, 'In that day, their strong cities will be like the forsaken places in the woods and on the mountain top, which were forsaken from before the children of Israel; and it will be a desolation.\n'),
	(13190, 20, 17, 10, 'For you have forgotten the God of your salvation, and have not remembered the rock of your strength. Therefore you plant pleasant plants, and set out foreign seedlings.\n'),
	(13191, 20, 17, 11, 'In the day of your planting, you hedge it in. In the morning, you make your seed blossom, but the harvest flees away in the day of grief and of desperate sorrow.\n'),
	(13192, 20, 17, 12, 'Ah, the uproar of many peoples, who roar like the roaring of the seas; and the rushing of nations, that rush like the rushing of mighty waters!\n'),
	(13193, 20, 17, 13, 'The nations will rush like the rushing of many waters: but he will rebuke them, and they will flee far off, and will be chased like the chaff of the mountains before the wind, and like the whirling dust before the storm.\n'),
	(13194, 20, 17, 14, 'At evening, behold, terror! Before the morning, they are no more. This is the portion of those who plunder us, and the lot of those who rob us.\n'),
	(13195, 20, 18, 1, 'Ah, the land of the rustling of wings, which is beyond the rivers of Ethiopia;\n'),
	(13196, 20, 18, 2, 'that sends ambassadors by the sea, even in vessels of papyrus on the waters, saying, “Go, you swift messengers, to a nation tall and smooth, to a people awesome from their beginning onward, a nation that measures out and treads down, whose land the rivers divide!”\n'),
	(13197, 20, 18, 3, 'All you inhabitants of the world, and you dwellers on the earth, when a banner is lifted up on the mountains, look! When the trumpet is blown, listen!\n'),
	(13198, 20, 18, 4, 'For Yahweh said to me, “I will be still, and I will see in my dwelling place, like clear heat in sunshine, like a cloud of dew in the heat of harvest.”\n'),
	(13199, 20, 18, 5, 'For before the harvest, when the blossom is over, and the flower becomes a ripening grape, he will cut off the sprigs with pruning hooks, and he will cut down and take away the spreading branches.\n'),
	(13200, 20, 18, 6, 'They will be left together for the ravenous birds of the mountains, and for the animals of the earth. The ravenous birds will summer on them, and all the animals of the earth will winter on them.\n'),
	(13201, 20, 18, 7, 'In that time, a present will be brought to Yahweh of Armies from a people tall and smooth, even from a people awesome from their beginning onward, a nation that measures out and treads down, whose land the rivers divide, to the place of the name of Yahweh of Armies, Mount Zion.\n'),
	(13202, 20, 19, 1, 'The burden of Egypt.\n“Behold, Yahweh rides on a swift cloud, and comes to Egypt. The idols of Egypt will tremble at his presence; and the heart of Egypt will melt within it.\n'),
	(13203, 20, 19, 2, 'I will stir up the Egyptians against the Egyptians, and they will fight everyone against his brother, and everyone against his neighbor; city against city, and kingdom against kingdom.\n'),
	(13204, 20, 19, 3, 'The spirit of Egypt will fail within it. I will destroy its counsel. They will seek the idols, the charmers, those who have familiar spirits, and the wizards.\n'),
	(13205, 20, 19, 4, 'I will give over the Egyptians into the hand of a cruel lord. A fierce king will rule over them,” says the Lord, Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(13206, 20, 19, 5, 'The waters will fail from the sea, and the river will be wasted and become dry.\n'),
	(13207, 20, 19, 6, 'The rivers will become foul. The streams of Egypt will be diminished and dried up. The reeds and flags will wither away.\n'),
	(13208, 20, 19, 7, 'The meadows by the Nile, by the brink of the Nile, and all the sown fields of the Nile, will become dry, be driven away, and be no more.\n'),
	(13209, 20, 19, 8, 'The fishermen will lament, and all those who fish in the Nile will mourn, and those who spread nets on the waters will languish.\n'),
	(13210, 20, 19, 9, 'Moreover those who work in combed flax, and those who weave white cloth, will be confounded.\n'),
	(13211, 20, 19, 10, 'The pillars will be broken in pieces. All those who work for hire will be grieved in soul.\n'),
	(13212, 20, 19, 11, 'The princes of Zoan are utterly foolish. The counsel of the wisest counselors of Pharaoh has become stupid. How do you say to Pharaoh, “I am the son of the wise, the son of ancient kings?”\n'),
	(13213, 20, 19, 12, 'Where then are your wise men? Let them tell you now; and let them know what Yahweh of Armies has purposed concerning Egypt.\n'),
	(13214, 20, 19, 13, 'The princes of Zoan have become fools. The princes of Memphis are deceived. They have caused Egypt to go astray, who are the cornerstone of her tribes.\n'),
	(13215, 20, 19, 14, 'Yahweh has mixed a spirit of perverseness in the middle of her; and they have caused Egypt to go astray in all of its works, like a drunken man staggers in his vomit.\n'),
	(13216, 20, 19, 15, 'Neither shall there be any work for Egypt, which head or tail, palm branch or rush, may do.\n'),
	(13217, 20, 19, 16, 'In that day the Egyptians will be like women. They will tremble and fear because of the shaking of Yahweh of Armies’s hand, which he shakes over them.\n'),
	(13218, 20, 19, 17, 'The land of Judah will become a terror to Egypt. Everyone to whom mention is made of it will be afraid, because of the plans of Yahweh of Armies, which he determines against it.\n'),
	(13219, 20, 19, 18, 'In that day, there will be five cities in the land of Egypt that speak the language of Canaan, and swear to Yahweh of Armies. One will be called “The city of destruction.”\n'),
	(13220, 20, 19, 19, 'In that day, there will be an altar to Yahweh in the middle of the land of Egypt, and a pillar to Yahweh at its border.\n'),
	(13221, 20, 19, 20, 'It will be for a sign and for a witness to Yahweh of Armies in the land of Egypt; for they will cry to Yahweh because of oppressors, and he will send them a savior and a defender, and he will deliver them.\n'),
	(13222, 20, 19, 21, 'Yahweh will be known to Egypt, and the Egyptians will know Yahweh in that day. Yes, they will worship with sacrifice and offering, and will vow a vow to Yahweh, and will perform it.\n'),
	(13223, 20, 19, 22, 'Yahweh will strike Egypt, striking and healing. They will return to Yahweh, and he will be entreated by them, and will heal them.\n'),
	(13224, 20, 19, 23, 'In that day there will be a highway out of Egypt to Assyria, and the Assyrian shall come into Egypt, and the Egyptian into Assyria; and the Egyptians will worship with the Assyrians.\n'),
	(13225, 20, 19, 24, 'In that day, Israel will be the third with Egypt and with Assyria, a blessing within the earth;\n'),
	(13226, 20, 19, 25, 'because Yahweh of Armies has blessed them, saying, “Blessed be Egypt my people, Assyria the work of my hands, and Israel my inheritance.”\n'),
	(13227, 20, 20, 1, 'In the year that Tartan came to Ashdod, when Sargon the king of Assyria sent him, and he fought against Ashdod and took it;\n'),
	(13228, 20, 20, 2, 'at that time Yahweh spoke by Isaiah the son of Amoz, saying, “Go, and loosen the sackcloth from off your waist, and take your shoes from off your feet.” He did so, walking naked and barefoot.\n'),
	(13229, 20, 20, 3, 'Yahweh said, “As my servant Isaiah has walked naked and barefoot three years for a sign and a wonder concerning Egypt and concerning Ethiopia,\n'),
	(13230, 20, 20, 4, 'so the king of Assyria will lead away the captives of Egypt and the exiles of Ethiopia, young and old, naked and barefoot, and with buttocks uncovered, to the shame of Egypt.\n'),
	(13231, 20, 20, 5, 'They will be dismayed and confounded, because of Ethiopia their expectation, and of Egypt their glory.\n'),
	(13232, 20, 20, 6, 'The inhabitants of this coast land will say in that day, ‘Behold, this is our expectation, where we fled for help to be delivered from the king of Assyria. And we, how will we escape?’”\n'),
	(13233, 20, 21, 1, 'The burden of the wilderness of the sea.\nAs whirlwinds in the South sweep through, it comes from the wilderness, from an awesome land.\n'),
	(13234, 20, 21, 2, 'A grievous vision is declared to me. The treacherous man deals treacherously, and the destroyer destroys. Go up, Elam; attack! I have stopped all of Media’s sighing.\n'),
	(13235, 20, 21, 3, 'Therefore my thighs are filled with anguish. Pains have taken hold on me, like the pains of a woman in labor. I am in so much pain that I can’t hear. I so am dismayed that I can’t see.\n'),
	(13236, 20, 21, 4, 'My heart flutters. Horror has frightened me. The twilight that I desired has been turned into trembling for me.\n'),
	(13237, 20, 21, 5, 'They prepare the table. They set the watch. They eat. They drink. Rise up, you princes, oil the shield!\n'),
	(13238, 20, 21, 6, 'For the Lord said to me, “Go, set a watchman. Let him declare what he sees.\n'),
	(13239, 20, 21, 7, 'When he sees a troop, horsemen in pairs, a troop of donkeys, a troop of camels, he shall listen diligently with great attentiveness.”\n'),
	(13240, 20, 21, 8, 'He cried like a lion: “Lord, I stand continually on the watchtower in the daytime, and every night I stay at my post.\n'),
	(13241, 20, 21, 9, 'Behold, here comes a troop of men, horsemen in pairs.” He answered, “Fallen, fallen is Babylon; and all the engraved images of her gods are broken to the ground.\n'),
	(13242, 20, 21, 10, 'You are my threshing, and the grain of my floor!” That which I have heard from Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, I have declared to you.\n'),
	(13243, 20, 21, 11, 'The burden of Dumah.\nOne calls to me out of Seir, “Watchman, what of the night? Watchman, what of the night?”\n'),
	(13244, 20, 21, 12, 'The watchman said, “The morning comes, and also the night. If you will inquire, inquire. Come back again.”\n'),
	(13245, 20, 21, 13, 'The burden on Arabia.\nIn the forest in Arabia you will lodge, you caravans of Dedanites.\n'),
	(13246, 20, 21, 14, 'They brought water to him who was thirsty. The inhabitants of the land of Tema met the fugitives with their bread.\n'),
	(13247, 20, 21, 15, 'For they fled away from the swords, from the drawn sword, from the bent bow, and from the heat of battle.\n'),
	(13248, 20, 21, 16, 'For the Lord said to me, “Within a year, as a worker bound by contract would count it, all the glory of Kedar will fail,\n'),
	(13249, 20, 21, 17, 'and the residue of the number of the archers, the mighty men of the children of Kedar, will be few; for Yahweh, the God of Israel, has spoken it.”\n'),
	(13250, 20, 22, 1, 'The burden of the valley of vision.\nWhat ails you now, that you have all gone up to the housetops?\n'),
	(13251, 20, 22, 2, 'You that are full of shouting, a tumultuous city, a joyous town; your slain are not slain with the sword, neither are they dead in battle.\n'),
	(13252, 20, 22, 3, 'All your rulers fled away together. They were bound by the archers. All who were found by you were bound together. They fled far away.\n'),
	(13253, 20, 22, 4, 'Therefore I said, “Look away from me. I will weep bitterly. Don’t labor to comfort me for the destruction of the daughter of my people.\n'),
	(13254, 20, 22, 5, 'For it is a day of confusion, and of treading down, and of perplexity, from the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, in the valley of vision; a breaking down of the walls, and a crying to the mountains.”\n'),
	(13255, 20, 22, 6, 'Elam carried his quiver, with chariots of men and horsemen; and Kir uncovered the shield.\n'),
	(13256, 20, 22, 7, 'Your choicest valleys were full of chariots, and the horsemen set themselves in array at the gate.\n'),
	(13257, 20, 22, 8, 'He took away the covering of Judah; and you looked in that day to the armor in the house of the forest.\n'),
	(13258, 20, 22, 9, 'You saw the breaches of David’s city, that they were many; and you gathered together the waters of the lower pool.\n'),
	(13259, 20, 22, 10, 'You counted the houses of Jerusalem, and you broke down the houses to fortify the wall.\n'),
	(13260, 20, 22, 11, 'You also made a reservoir between the two walls for the water of the old pool. But you didn’t look to him who had done this, neither did you have respect for him who purposed it long ago.\n'),
	(13261, 20, 22, 12, 'In that day, the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, called to weeping, and to mourning, and to baldness, and to dressing in sackcloth:\n'),
	(13262, 20, 22, 13, 'and behold, joy and gladness, killing cattle and killing sheep, eating meat and drinking wine: “Let us eat and drink, for tomorrow we will die.”\n'),
	(13263, 20, 22, 14, 'Yahweh of Armies revealed himself in my ears, “Surely this iniquity will not be forgiven you until you die,” says the Lord, Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(13264, 20, 22, 15, 'Thus says the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, “Go, get yourself to this treasurer, even to Shebna, who is over the house, and say,\n'),
	(13265, 20, 22, 16, '‘What are you doing here? Who has you here, that you have dug out a tomb here?’ Cutting himself out a tomb on high, chiseling a habitation for himself in the rock!”\n'),
	(13266, 20, 22, 17, 'Behold, Yahweh will overcome you and hurl you away violently. Yes, he will grasp you firmly.\n'),
	(13267, 20, 22, 18, 'He will surely wind you around and around, and throw you like a ball into a large country. There you will die, and there the chariots of your glory will be, you shame of your lord’s house.\n'),
	(13268, 20, 22, 19, 'I will thrust you from your office. You will be pulled down from your station.\n'),
	(13269, 20, 22, 20, 'It will happen in that day that I will call my servant Eliakim the son of Hilkiah,\n'),
	(13270, 20, 22, 21, 'and I will clothe him with your robe, and strengthen him with your belt. I will commit your government into his hand; and he will be a father to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, and to the house of Judah.\n'),
	(13271, 20, 22, 22, 'I will lay the key of David’s house on his shoulder. He will open, and no one will shut. He will shut, and no one will open.\n'),
	(13272, 20, 22, 23, 'I will fasten him like a nail in a sure place. He will be for a throne of glory to his father’s house.\n'),
	(13273, 20, 22, 24, 'They will hang on him all the glory of his father’s house, the offspring and the issue, every small vessel, from the cups even to all the pitchers.\n'),
	(13274, 20, 22, 25, '“In that day,” says Yahweh of Armies, “the nail that was fastened in a sure place will give way. It will be cut down, and fall. The burden that was on it will be cut off, for Yahweh has spoken it.”\n'),
	(13275, 20, 23, 1, 'The burden of Tyre.\nHowl, you ships of Tarshish! For it is laid waste, so that there is no house, no entering in. From the land of Kittim it is revealed to them.\n'),
	(13276, 20, 23, 2, 'Be still, you inhabitants of the coast, you whom the merchants of Sidon, that pass over the sea, have replenished.\n'),
	(13277, 20, 23, 3, 'On great waters, the seed of the Shihor, the harvest of the Nile, was her revenue. She was the market of nations.\n'),
	(13278, 20, 23, 4, 'Be ashamed, Sidon; for the sea has spoken, the stronghold of the sea, saying, “I have not travailed, nor given birth, neither have I nourished young men, nor brought up virgins.”\n'),
	(13279, 20, 23, 5, 'When the report comes to Egypt, they will be in anguish at the report of Tyre.\n'),
	(13280, 20, 23, 6, 'Pass over to Tarshish! Wail, you inhabitants of the coast!\n'),
	(13281, 20, 23, 7, 'Is this your joyous city, whose antiquity is of ancient days, whose feet carried her far away to travel?\n'),
	(13282, 20, 23, 8, 'Who has planned this against Tyre, the giver of crowns, whose merchants are princes, whose traders are the honorable of the earth?\n'),
	(13283, 20, 23, 9, 'Yahweh of Armies has planned it, to stain the pride of all glory, to bring into contempt all the honorable of the earth.\n'),
	(13284, 20, 23, 10, 'Pass through your land like the Nile, daughter of Tarshish. There is no restraint any more.\n'),
	(13285, 20, 23, 11, 'He has stretched out his hand over the sea. He has shaken the kingdoms. Yahweh has ordered the destruction of Canaan’s strongholds.\n'),
	(13286, 20, 23, 12, 'He said, “You shall rejoice no more, you oppressed virgin daughter of Sidon. Arise, pass over to Kittim. Even there you will have no rest.”\n'),
	(13287, 20, 23, 13, 'Behold, the land of the Chaldeans. This people was not. The Assyrians founded it for those who dwell in the wilderness. They set up their towers. They overthrew its palaces. They made it a ruin.\n'),
	(13288, 20, 23, 14, 'Howl, you ships of Tarshish, for your stronghold is laid waste!\n'),
	(13289, 20, 23, 15, 'It will come to pass in that day that Tyre will be forgotten seventy years, according to the days of one king. After the end of seventy years it will be to Tyre like in the song of the prostitute.\n'),
	(13290, 20, 23, 16, 'Take a harp; go about the city, you prostitute that has been forgotten. Make sweet melody. Sing many songs, that you may be remembered.\n'),
	(13291, 20, 23, 17, 'It will happen after the end of seventy years that Yahweh will visit Tyre, and she shall return to her wages, and will play the prostitute with all the kingdoms of the world on the surface of the earth.\n'),
	(13292, 20, 23, 18, 'Her merchandise and her wages will be holiness to Yahweh. It will not be treasured nor laid up; for her merchandise will be for those who dwell before Yahweh, to eat sufficiently, and for durable clothing.\n'),
	(13293, 20, 24, 1, 'Behold, Yahweh makes the earth empty, makes it waste, turns it upside down, and scatters its inhabitants.\n'),
	(13294, 20, 24, 2, 'It will be as with the people, so with the priest; as with the servant, so with his master; as with the maid, so with her mistress; as with the buyer, so with the seller; as with the creditor, so with the debtor; as with the taker of interest, so with the giver of interest.\n'),
	(13295, 20, 24, 3, 'The earth will be utterly emptied and utterly laid waste; for Yahweh has spoken this word.\n'),
	(13296, 20, 24, 4, 'The earth mourns and fades away. The world languishes and fades away. The lofty people of the earth languish.\n'),
	(13297, 20, 24, 5, 'The earth also is polluted under its inhabitants, because they have transgressed the laws, violated the statutes, and broken the everlasting covenant.\n'),
	(13298, 20, 24, 6, 'Therefore the curse has devoured the earth, and those who dwell therein are found guilty. Therefore the inhabitants of the earth are burned, and few men left.\n'),
	(13299, 20, 24, 7, 'The new wine mourns. The vine languishes. All the merry-hearted sigh.\n'),
	(13300, 20, 24, 8, 'The mirth of tambourines ceases. The sound of those who rejoice ends. The joy of the harp ceases.\n'),
	(13301, 20, 24, 9, 'They will not drink wine with a song. Strong drink will be bitter to those who drink it.\n'),
	(13302, 20, 24, 10, 'The confused city is broken down. Every house is shut up, that no man may come in.\n'),
	(13303, 20, 24, 11, 'There is a crying in the streets because of the wine. All joy is darkened. The mirth of the land is gone.\n'),
	(13304, 20, 24, 12, 'The city is left in desolation, and the gate is struck with destruction.\n'),
	(13305, 20, 24, 13, 'For it will be so within the earth among the peoples, as the shaking of an olive tree, as the gleanings when the vintage is done.\n'),
	(13306, 20, 24, 14, 'These shall lift up their voice. They will shout for the majesty of Yahweh. They cry aloud from the sea.\n'),
	(13307, 20, 24, 15, 'Therefore glorify Yahweh in the east, even the name of Yahweh, the God of Israel, in the islands of the sea!\n'),
	(13308, 20, 24, 16, 'From the uttermost part of the earth have we heard songs. Glory to the righteous!\nBut I said, “I pine away! I pine away! woe is me!” The treacherous have dealt treacherously. Yes, the treacherous have dealt very treacherously.\n'),
	(13309, 20, 24, 17, 'Fear, the pit, and the snare, are on you who inhabitant the earth.\n'),
	(13310, 20, 24, 18, 'It will happen that he who flees from the noise of the fear will fall into the pit; and he who comes up out of the middle of the pit will be taken in the snare; for the windows on high are opened, and the foundations of the earth tremble.\n'),
	(13311, 20, 24, 19, 'The earth is utterly broken. The earth is torn apart. The earth is shaken violently.\n'),
	(13312, 20, 24, 20, 'The earth will stagger like a drunken man, and will sway back and forth like a hammock. Its disobedience will be heavy on it, and it will fall and not rise again.\n'),
	(13313, 20, 24, 21, 'It shall happen in that day that Yahweh will punish the army of the high ones on high, and the kings of the earth on the earth.\n'),
	(13314, 20, 24, 22, 'They shall be gathered together, as prisoners are gathered in the pit, and shall be shut up in the prison; and after many days shall they be visited.\n'),
	(13315, 20, 24, 23, 'Then the moon shall be confounded, and the sun ashamed; for Yahweh of Armies will reign on Mount Zion, and in Jerusalem; and before his elders will be glory.\n'),
	(13316, 20, 25, 1, 'Yahweh, you are my God. I will exalt you! I will praise your name, for you have done wonderful things, things planned long ago, in complete faithfulness and truth.\n'),
	(13317, 20, 25, 2, 'For you have made a city into a heap, a fortified city into a ruin, a palace of strangers to be no city. It will never be built.\n'),
	(13318, 20, 25, 3, 'Therefore a strong people will glorify you. A city of awesome nations will fear you.\n'),
	(13319, 20, 25, 4, 'For you have been a stronghold to the poor, a stronghold to the needy in his distress, a refuge from the storm, a shade from the heat, when the blast of the dreaded ones is like a storm against the wall.\n'),
	(13320, 20, 25, 5, 'As the heat in a dry place will you bring down the noise of strangers; as the heat by the shade of a cloud, the song of the dreaded ones will be brought low.\n'),
	(13321, 20, 25, 6, 'In this mountain, Yahweh of Armies will make all peoples a feast of choice meat, a feast of choice wines, of choice meat full of marrow, of well refined choice wines.\n'),
	(13322, 20, 25, 7, 'He will destroy in this mountain the surface of the covering that covers all peoples, and the veil that is spread over all nations.\n'),
	(13323, 20, 25, 8, 'He has swallowed up death forever! The Lord Yahweh will wipe away tears from off all faces. He will take the reproach of his people away from off all the earth, for Yahweh has spoken it.\n'),
	(13324, 20, 25, 9, 'It shall be said in that day, “Behold, this is our God! We have waited for him, and he will save us! This is Yahweh! We have waited for him. We will be glad and rejoice in his salvation!”\n'),
	(13325, 20, 25, 10, 'For in this mountain Yahweh’s hand will rest.\nMoab will be trodden down in his place, even like straw is trodden down in the water of the dunghill.\n'),
	(13326, 20, 25, 11, 'He will spread out his hands in the middle of it, like one who swims spreads out hands to swim, but his pride will be humbled together with the craft of his hands.\n'),
	(13327, 20, 25, 12, 'He has brought the high fortress of your walls down, laid low, and brought to the ground, even to the dust.\n'),
	(13328, 20, 26, 1, 'In that day, this song will be sung in the land of Judah:\n“We have a strong city.\nGod appoints salvation for walls and bulwarks.\n'),
	(13329, 20, 26, 2, 'Open the gates, that the righteous nation may enter:\nthe one which keeps faith.\n'),
	(13330, 20, 26, 3, 'You will keep whoever’s mind is steadfast in perfect peace,\nbecause he trusts in you.\n'),
	(13331, 20, 26, 4, 'Trust in Yahweh forever;\nfor in Yah, Yahweh, is an everlasting Rock.\n'),
	(13332, 20, 26, 5, 'For he has brought down those who dwell on high, the lofty city.\nHe lays it low.\nHe lays it low even to the ground.\nHe brings it even to the dust.\n'),
	(13333, 20, 26, 6, 'The foot shall tread it down;\nEven the feet of the poor,\nand the steps of the needy.”\n'),
	(13334, 20, 26, 7, 'The way of the just is uprightness.\nYou who are upright make the path of the righteous level.\n'),
	(13335, 20, 26, 8, 'Yes, in the way of your judgments, Yahweh, have we waited for you.\nYour name and your renown are the desire of our soul.\n'),
	(13336, 20, 26, 9, 'With my soul I have desired you in the night.\nYes, with my spirit within me will I seek you earnestly;\nfor when your judgments are in the earth, the inhabitants of the world learn righteousness.\n'),
	(13337, 20, 26, 10, 'Let favor be shown to the wicked,\nyet he will not learn righteousness.\nIn the land of uprightness he will deal wrongfully,\nand will not see Yahweh’s majesty.\n'),
	(13338, 20, 26, 11, 'Yahweh, your hand is lifted up, yet they don’t see;\nbut they will see your zeal for the people, and be disappointed.\nYes, fire will consume your adversaries.\n'),
	(13339, 20, 26, 12, 'Yahweh, you will ordain peace for us,\nfor you have also done all our work for us.\n'),
	(13340, 20, 26, 13, 'Yahweh our God, other lords besides you have had dominion over us,\nbut by you only will we make mention of your name.\n'),
	(13341, 20, 26, 14, 'The dead shall not live.\nThe departed spirits shall not rise.\nTherefore you have visited and destroyed them,\nand caused all memory of them to perish.\n'),
	(13342, 20, 26, 15, 'You have increased the nation, O Yahweh.\nYou have increased the nation!\nYou are glorified!\nYou have enlarged all the borders of the land.\n'),
	(13343, 20, 26, 16, 'Yahweh, in trouble they have visited you.\nThey poured out a prayer when your chastening was on them.\n'),
	(13344, 20, 26, 17, 'Just as a woman with child, who draws near the time of her delivery,\nis in pain and cries out in her pangs;\nso we have been before you, Yahweh.\n'),
	(13345, 20, 26, 18, 'We have been with child.\nWe have been in pain.\nWe gave birth, it seems, only to wind.\nWe have not worked any deliverance in the earth;\nneither have the inhabitants of the world fallen.\n'),
	(13346, 20, 26, 19, 'Your dead shall live.\nMy dead bodies shall arise.\nAwake and sing, you who dwell in the dust;\nfor your dew is like the dew of herbs,\nand the earth will cast out the departed spirits.\n'),
	(13347, 20, 26, 20, 'Come, my people, enter into your rooms,\nand shut your doors behind you.\nHide yourself for a little moment,\nuntil the indignation is past.\n'),
	(13348, 20, 26, 21, 'For, behold, Yahweh comes out of his place to punish the inhabitants of the earth for their iniquity.\nThe earth also will disclose her blood, and will no longer cover her slain.\n'),
	(13349, 20, 27, 1, 'In that day, Yahweh with his hard and great and strong sword will punish leviathan, the fleeing serpent, and leviathan the twisted serpent; and he will kill the dragon that is in the sea.\n'),
	(13350, 20, 27, 2, 'In that day, sing to her, “A pleasant vineyard!\n'),
	(13351, 20, 27, 3, 'I, Yahweh, am its keeper. I will water it every moment. Lest anyone damage it, I will keep it night and day.\n'),
	(13352, 20, 27, 4, 'Wrath is not in me, but if I should find briers and thorns, I would do battle! I would march on them and I would burn them together.\n'),
	(13353, 20, 27, 5, 'Or else let him take hold of my strength, that he may make peace with me. Let him make peace with me.”\n'),
	(13354, 20, 27, 6, 'In days to come, Jacob will take root. Israel will blossom and bud. They will fill the surface of the world with fruit.\n'),
	(13355, 20, 27, 7, 'Has he struck them as he struck those who struck them? Or are they killed like those who killed them were killed?\n'),
	(13356, 20, 27, 8, 'In measure, when you send them away, you contend with them. He has removed them with his rough blast in the day of the east wind.\n'),
	(13357, 20, 27, 9, 'Therefore by this the iniquity of Jacob will be forgiven, and this is all the fruit of taking away his sin: that he makes all the stones of the altar as chalk stones that are beaten in pieces, so that the Asherah poles and the incense altars shall rise no more.\n'),
	(13358, 20, 27, 10, 'For the fortified city is solitary, a habitation deserted and forsaken, like the wilderness. The calf will feed there, and there he will lie down, and consume its branches.\n'),
	(13359, 20, 27, 11, 'When its boughs are withered, they will be broken off. The women will come and set them on fire, for they are a people of no understanding. Therefore he who made them will not have compassion on them, and he who formed them will show them no favor.\n'),
	(13360, 20, 27, 12, 'It will happen in that day, that Yahweh will thresh from the flowing stream of the Euphrates to the brook of Egypt; and you will be gathered one by one, children of Israel.\n'),
	(13361, 20, 27, 13, 'It will happen in that day that a great trumpet will be blown; and those who were ready to perish in the land of Assyria, and those who were outcasts in the land of Egypt, shall come; and they will worship Yahweh in the holy mountain at Jerusalem.\n'),
	(13362, 20, 28, 1, 'Woe to the crown of pride of the drunkards of Ephraim, and to the fading flower of his glorious beauty, which is on the head of the fertile valley of those who are overcome with wine!\n'),
	(13363, 20, 28, 2, 'Behold, the Lord has a mighty and strong one. Like a storm of hail, a destroying storm, and like a storm of mighty waters overflowing, he will cast them down to the earth with his hand.\n'),
	(13364, 20, 28, 3, 'The crown of pride of the drunkards of Ephraim will be trodden under foot.\n'),
	(13365, 20, 28, 4, 'The fading flower of his glorious beauty, which is on the head of the fertile valley, shall be like the first-ripe fig before the summer; which someone picks and eats as soon as he sees it.\n'),
	(13366, 20, 28, 5, 'In that day, Yahweh of Armies will become a crown of glory, and a diadem of beauty, to the residue of his people;\n'),
	(13367, 20, 28, 6, 'and a spirit of justice to him who sits in judgment, and strength to those who turn back the battle at the gate.\n'),
	(13368, 20, 28, 7, 'They also reel with wine, and stagger with strong drink. The priest and the prophet reel with strong drink. They are swallowed up by wine. They stagger with strong drink. They err in vision. They stumble in judgment.\n'),
	(13369, 20, 28, 8, 'For all tables are completely full of filthy vomit and filthiness.\n'),
	(13370, 20, 28, 9, 'Whom will he teach knowledge? To whom will he explain the message? Those who are weaned from the milk, and drawn from the breasts?\n'),
	(13371, 20, 28, 10, 'For it is precept on precept, precept on precept; line on line, line on line; here a little, there a little.\n'),
	(13372, 20, 28, 11, 'But he will speak to this nation with stammering lips and in another language;\n'),
	(13373, 20, 28, 12, 'to whom he said, “This is the resting place. Give rest to weary”; and “This is the refreshing”; yet they would not hear.\n'),
	(13374, 20, 28, 13, 'Therefore Yahweh’s word will be to them precept on precept, precept on precept; line on line, line on line; here a little, there a little; that they may go, fall backward, be broken, be snared, and be taken.\n'),
	(13375, 20, 28, 14, 'Therefore hear Yahweh’s word, you scoffers, that rule this people in Jerusalem:\n'),
	(13376, 20, 28, 15, '“Because you have said, ‘We have made a covenant with death, and with Sheol\n are we in agreement. When the overflowing scourge passes through, it won’t come to us; for we have made lies our refuge, and we have hidden ourselves under falsehood.’”\n'),
	(13377, 20, 28, 16, 'Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh, “Behold, I lay in Zion for a foundation a stone, a tried stone, a precious cornerstone of a sure foundation. He who believes shall not act hastily.\n'),
	(13378, 20, 28, 17, 'I will make justice the measuring line, and righteousness the plumb line. The hail will sweep away the refuge of lies, and the waters will overflow the hiding place.\n'),
	(13379, 20, 28, 18, 'Your covenant with death shall be annulled, and your agreement with Sheol\n shall not stand. When the overflowing scourge passes through, then you will be trampled down by it.\n'),
	(13380, 20, 28, 19, 'As often as it passes through, it will seize you; for morning by morning it will pass through, by day and by night; and it will be nothing but terror to understand the message.”\n'),
	(13381, 20, 28, 20, 'For the bed is too short to stretch out on, and the blanket is too narrow to wrap oneself in.\n'),
	(13382, 20, 28, 21, 'For Yahweh will rise up as on Mount Perazim. He will be angry as in the valley of Gibeon; that he may do his work, his unusual work, and bring to pass his act, his extraordinary act.\n'),
	(13383, 20, 28, 22, 'Now therefore don’t be scoffers, lest your bonds be made strong; for I have heard a decree of destruction from the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, on the whole earth.\n'),
	(13384, 20, 28, 23, 'Give ear, and hear my voice! Listen, and hear my speech!\n'),
	(13385, 20, 28, 24, 'Does he who plows to sow plow continually? Does he keep turning the soil and breaking the clods?\n'),
	(13386, 20, 28, 25, 'When he has leveled its surface, doesn’t he plant the dill, and scatter the cumin seed, and put in the wheat in rows, the barley in the appointed place, and the spelt in its place?\n'),
	(13387, 20, 28, 26, 'For his God instructs him in right judgment, and teaches him.\n'),
	(13388, 20, 28, 27, 'For the dill are not threshed with a sharp instrument, neither is a cart wheel turned over the cumin; but the dill is beaten out with a stick, and the cumin with a rod.\n'),
	(13389, 20, 28, 28, 'Bread flour must be ground; so he will not always be threshing it. Although he drives the wheel of his threshing cart over it, his horses don’t grind it.\n'),
	(13390, 20, 28, 29, 'This also comes out from Yahweh of Armies, who is wonderful in counsel, and excellent in wisdom.\n'),
	(13391, 20, 29, 1, 'Woe to Ariel! Ariel, the city where David encamped! Add year to year; let the feasts come around;\n'),
	(13392, 20, 29, 2, 'then I will distress Ariel, and there will be mourning and lamentation. She shall be to me as an altar hearth.\n'),
	(13393, 20, 29, 3, 'I will encamp against you all around you, and will lay siege against you with posted troops. I will raise siege works against you.\n'),
	(13394, 20, 29, 4, 'You will be brought down, and will speak out of the ground. Your speech will mumble out of the dust. Your voice will be as of one who has a familiar spirit, out of the ground, and your speech will whisper out of the dust.\n'),
	(13395, 20, 29, 5, 'But the multitude of your foes will be like fine dust, and the multitude of the ruthless ones like chaff that blows away. Yes, it will be in an instant, suddenly.\n'),
	(13396, 20, 29, 6, 'She will be visited by Yahweh of Armies with thunder, with earthquake, with great noise, with whirlwind and storm, and with the flame of a devouring fire.\n'),
	(13397, 20, 29, 7, 'The multitude of all the nations that fight against Ariel, even all who fight against her and her stronghold, and who distress her, will be like a dream, a vision of the night.\n'),
	(13398, 20, 29, 8, 'It will be like when a hungry man dreams, and behold, he eats; but he awakes, and his hunger isn’t satisfied; or like when a thirsty man dreams, and behold, he drinks; but he awakes, and behold, he is faint, and he is still thirsty. The multitude of all the nations that fight against Mount Zion will be like that.\n'),
	(13399, 20, 29, 9, 'Pause and wonder! Blind yourselves and be blind! They are drunken, but not with wine; they stagger, but not with strong drink.\n'),
	(13400, 20, 29, 10, 'For Yahweh has poured out on you a spirit of deep sleep, and has closed your eyes, the prophets; and he has covered your heads, the seers.\n'),
	(13401, 20, 29, 11, 'All vision has become to you like the words of a book that is sealed, which men deliver to one who is educated, saying, “Read this, please”; and he says, “I can’t, for it is sealed:”\n'),
	(13402, 20, 29, 12, 'and the book is delivered to one who is not educated, saying, “Read this, please”; and he says, “I can’t read.”\n'),
	(13403, 20, 29, 13, 'The Lord said, “Because this people draws near with their mouth and honors me with their lips, but they have removed their heart far from me, and their fear of me is a commandment of men which has been taught;\n'),
	(13404, 20, 29, 14, 'therefore, behold, I will proceed to do a marvelous work among this people, even a marvelous work and a wonder; and the wisdom of their wise men will perish, and the understanding of their prudent men will be hidden.”\n'),
	(13405, 20, 29, 15, 'Woe to those who deeply hide their counsel from Yahweh, and whose deeds are in the dark, and who say, “Who sees us?” and “Who knows us?”\n'),
	(13406, 20, 29, 16, 'You turn things upside down! Should the potter be thought to be like clay; that the thing made should say about him who made it, “He didn’t make me”; or the thing formed say of him who formed it, “He has no understanding?”\n'),
	(13407, 20, 29, 17, 'Isn’t it yet a very little while, and Lebanon will be turned into a fruitful field, and the fruitful field will be regarded as a forest?\n'),
	(13408, 20, 29, 18, 'In that day, the deaf will hear the words of the book, and the eyes of the blind will see out of obscurity and out of darkness.\n'),
	(13409, 20, 29, 19, 'The humble also will increase their joy in Yahweh, and the poor among men will rejoice in the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(13410, 20, 29, 20, 'For the ruthless is brought to nothing, and the scoffer ceases, and all those who are alert to do evil are cut off—\n'),
	(13411, 20, 29, 21, 'who cause a person to be indicted by a word, and lay a snare for the arbiter in the gate, and who deprive the innocent of justice with false testimony.\n'),
	(13412, 20, 29, 22, 'Therefore Yahweh, who redeemed Abraham, says concerning the house of Jacob: “Jacob shall no longer be ashamed, neither shall his face grow pale.\n'),
	(13413, 20, 29, 23, 'But when he sees his children, the work of my hands, in the middle of him, they will sanctify my name. Yes, they will sanctify the Holy One of Jacob, and will stand in awe of the God of Israel.\n'),
	(13414, 20, 29, 24, 'They also who err in spirit will come to understanding, and those who grumble will receive instruction.”\n'),
	(13415, 20, 30, 1, '“Woe to the rebellious children”, says Yahweh, “who take counsel, but not from me; and who make an alliance, but not with my Spirit, that they may add sin to sin,\n'),
	(13416, 20, 30, 2, 'who set out to go down into Egypt, and have not asked my advice; to strengthen themselves in the strength of Pharaoh, and to take refuge in the shadow of Egypt!\n'),
	(13417, 20, 30, 3, 'Therefore the strength of Pharaoh will be your shame, and the refuge in the shadow of Egypt your confusion.\n'),
	(13418, 20, 30, 4, 'For their princes are at Zoan, and their ambassadors have come to Hanes.\n'),
	(13419, 20, 30, 5, 'They shall all be ashamed because of a people that can’t profit them, that are not a help nor profit, but a shame, and also a reproach.”\n'),
	(13420, 20, 30, 6, 'The burden of the animals of the South.\nThrough the land of trouble and anguish, of the lioness and the lion, the viper and fiery flying serpent, they carry their riches on the shoulders of young donkeys, and their treasures on the humps of camels, to an unprofitable people.\n'),
	(13421, 20, 30, 7, 'For Egypt helps in vain, and to no purpose; therefore I have called her Rahab who sits still.\n'),
	(13422, 20, 30, 8, 'Now go, write it before them on a tablet, and inscribe it in a book, that it may be for the time to come forever and ever.\n'),
	(13423, 20, 30, 9, 'For it is a rebellious people, lying children, children who will not hear Yahweh’s law;\n'),
	(13424, 20, 30, 10, 'who tell the seers, “Don’t see!” and to the prophets, “Don’t prophesy to us right things. Tell us pleasant things. Prophesy deceits.\n'),
	(13425, 20, 30, 11, 'Get out of the way. Turn away from the path. Cause the Holy One of Israel to cease from before us.”\n'),
	(13426, 20, 30, 12, 'Therefore thus says the Holy One of Israel, “Because you despise this word, and trust in oppression and perverseness, and rely on it;\n'),
	(13427, 20, 30, 13, 'therefore this iniquity shall be to you like a breach ready to fall, swelling out in a high wall, whose breaking comes suddenly in an instant.\n'),
	(13428, 20, 30, 14, 'He will break it as a potter’s vessel is broken, breaking it in pieces without sparing, so that there won’t be found among the broken pieces a piece good enough to take fire from the hearth, or to dip up water out of the cistern.”\n'),
	(13429, 20, 30, 15, 'For thus said the Lord Yahweh, the Holy One of Israel, “You will be saved in returning and rest. Your strength will be in quietness and in confidence.” You refused,\n'),
	(13430, 20, 30, 16, 'but you said, “No, for we will flee on horses”; therefore you will flee; and, “We will ride on the swift”; therefore those who pursue you will be swift.\n'),
	(13431, 20, 30, 17, 'One thousand will flee at the threat of one. At the threat of five, you will flee until you are left like a beacon on the top of a mountain, and like a banner on a hill.\n'),
	(13432, 20, 30, 18, 'Therefore Yahweh will wait, that he may be gracious to you; and therefore he will be exalted, that he may have mercy on you, for Yahweh is a God of justice. Blessed are all those who wait for him.\n'),
	(13433, 20, 30, 19, 'For the people will dwell in Zion at Jerusalem. You will weep no more. He will surely be gracious to you at the voice of your cry. When he hears you, he will answer you.\n'),
	(13434, 20, 30, 20, 'Though the Lord may give you the bread of adversity and the water of affliction, yet your teachers won’t be hidden any more, but your eyes will see your teachers;\n'),
	(13435, 20, 30, 21, 'and when you turn to the right hand, and when you turn to the left, your ears will hear a voice behind you, saying, “This is the way. Walk in it.”\n'),
	(13436, 20, 30, 22, 'You shall defile the overlaying of your engraved images of silver, and the plating of your molten images of gold. You shall cast them away as an unclean thing. You shall tell it, “Go away!”\n'),
	(13437, 20, 30, 23, 'He will give the rain for your seed, with which you will sow the ground; and bread of the increase of the ground will be rich and plentiful. In that day, your livestock will feed in large pastures.\n'),
	(13438, 20, 30, 24, 'The oxen likewise and the young donkeys that till the ground will eat savory feed, which has been winnowed with the shovel and with the fork.\n'),
	(13439, 20, 30, 25, 'There shall be brooks and streams of water on every lofty mountain and on every high hill in the day of the great slaughter, when the towers fall.\n'),
	(13440, 20, 30, 26, 'Moreover the light of the moon will be like the light of the sun, and the light of the sun will be seven times brighter, like the light of seven days, in the day that Yahweh binds up the fracture of his people, and heals the wound they were struck with.\n'),
	(13441, 20, 30, 27, 'Behold, Yahweh’s name comes from far away, burning with his anger, and in thick rising smoke. His lips are full of indignation, and his tongue is as a devouring fire.\n'),
	(13442, 20, 30, 28, 'His breath is as an overflowing stream that reaches even to the neck, to sift the nations with the sieve of destruction; and a bridle that leads to ruin will be in the jaws of the peoples.\n'),
	(13443, 20, 30, 29, 'You will have a song, as in the night when a holy feast is kept; and gladness of heart, as when one goes with a flute to come to Yahweh’s mountain, to Israel’s Rock.\n'),
	(13444, 20, 30, 30, 'Yahweh will cause his glorious voice to be heard, and will show the descent of his arm, with the indignation of his anger, and the flame of a devouring fire, with a blast, storm, and hailstones.\n'),
	(13445, 20, 30, 31, 'For through Yahweh’s voice the Assyrian will be dismayed. He will strike him with his rod.\n'),
	(13446, 20, 30, 32, 'Every stroke of the rod of punishment, which Yahweh will lay on him, will be with the sound of tambourines and harps. He will fight with them in battles, brandishing weapons.\n'),
	(13447, 20, 30, 33, 'For his burning place has long been ready. Yes, for the king it is prepared. He has made its pyre deep and large with fire and much wood. Yahweh’s breath, like a stream of sulfur, kindles it.\n'),
	(13448, 20, 31, 1, 'Woe to those who go down to Egypt for help,\nand rely on horses,\nand trust in chariots because they are many,\nand in horsemen because they are very strong,\nbut they don’t look to the Holy One of Israel,\nand they don’t seek Yahweh!\n'),
	(13449, 20, 31, 2, 'Yet he also is wise, and will bring disaster,\nand will not call back his words, but will arise against the house of the evildoers,\nand against the help of those who work iniquity.\n'),
	(13450, 20, 31, 3, 'Now the Egyptians are men, and not God;\nand their horses flesh, and not spirit.\nWhen Yahweh stretches out his hand, both he who helps shall stumble,\nand he who is helped shall fall,\nand they all shall be consumed together.\n'),
	(13451, 20, 31, 4, 'For Yahweh says to me,\n“As the lion and the young lion growling over his prey,\nif a multitude of shepherds is called together against him,\nwill not be dismayed at their voice,\nnor abase himself for their noise,\nso Yahweh of Armies will come down to fight on Mount Zion and on its heights.\n'),
	(13452, 20, 31, 5, 'As birds hovering, so Yahweh of Armies will protect Jerusalem.\nHe will protect and deliver it.\nHe will pass over and preserve it.”\n'),
	(13453, 20, 31, 6, 'Return to him from whom you have deeply revolted, children of Israel.\n'),
	(13454, 20, 31, 7, 'For in that day everyone shall cast away his idols of silver and his idols of gold—sin which your own hands have made for you.\n'),
	(13455, 20, 31, 8, '“The Assyrian will fall by the sword, not of man;\nand the sword, not of mankind, shall devour him.\nHe will flee from the sword,\nand his young men will become subject to forced labor.\n'),
	(13456, 20, 31, 9, 'His rock will pass away by reason of terror,\nand his princes will be afraid of the banner,”\nsays Yahweh, whose fire is in Zion,\nand his furnace in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(13457, 20, 32, 1, 'Behold, a king shall reign in righteousness,\nand princes shall rule in justice.\n'),
	(13458, 20, 32, 2, 'A man shall be as a hiding place from the wind,\nand a covert from the storm,\nas streams of water in a dry place,\nas the shade of a large rock in a weary land.\n'),
	(13459, 20, 32, 3, 'The eyes of those who see will not be dim,\nand the ears of those who hear will listen.\n'),
	(13460, 20, 32, 4, 'The heart of the rash will understand knowledge,\nand the tongue of the stammerers will be ready to speak plainly.\n'),
	(13461, 20, 32, 5, 'The fool will no longer be called noble,\nnor the scoundrel be highly respected.\n'),
	(13462, 20, 32, 6, 'For the fool will speak folly,\nand his heart will work iniquity,\nto practice profanity,\nand to utter error against Yahweh,\nTo make empty the soul of the hungry,\nand to cause the drink of the thirsty to fail.\n'),
	(13463, 20, 32, 7, 'The ways of the scoundrel are evil.\nHe devises wicked plans to destroy the humble with lying words,\neven when the needy speaks right.\n'),
	(13464, 20, 32, 8, 'But the noble devises noble things;\nand he will continue in noble things.\n'),
	(13465, 20, 32, 9, 'Rise up, you women who are at ease! Hear my voice!\nYou careless daughters, give ear to my speech!\n'),
	(13466, 20, 32, 10, 'For days beyond a year you will be troubled, you careless women;\nfor the vintage shall fail.\nThe harvest won’t come.\n'),
	(13467, 20, 32, 11, 'Tremble, you women who are at ease!\nBe troubled, you careless ones!\nStrip yourselves, make yourselves naked,\nand put sackcloth on your waist.\n'),
	(13468, 20, 32, 12, 'Beat your breasts for the pleasant fields,\nfor the fruitful vine.\n'),
	(13469, 20, 32, 13, 'Thorns and briers will come up on my people’s land;\nyes, on all the houses of joy in the joyous city.\n'),
	(13470, 20, 32, 14, 'For the palace will be forsaken.\nThe populous city will be deserted.\nThe hill and the watchtower will be for dens forever,\na delight for wild donkeys,\na pasture of flocks;\n'),
	(13471, 20, 32, 15, 'Until the Spirit is poured on us from on high,\nand the wilderness becomes a fruitful field,\nand the fruitful field is considered a forest.\n'),
	(13472, 20, 32, 16, 'Then justice will dwell in the wilderness;\nand righteousness will remain in the fruitful field.\n'),
	(13473, 20, 32, 17, 'The work of righteousness will be peace;\nand the effect of righteousness, quietness and confidence forever.\n'),
	(13474, 20, 32, 18, 'My people will live in a peaceful habitation,\nin safe dwellings,\nand in quiet resting places.\n'),
	(13475, 20, 32, 19, 'Though hail flattens the forest,\nand the city is leveled completely.\n'),
	(13476, 20, 32, 20, 'Blessed are you who sow beside all waters,\nwho send out the feet of the ox and the donkey.\n'),
	(13477, 20, 33, 1, 'Woe to you who destroy, but you weren’t destroyed;\nand who betray, but nobody betrayed you!\nWhen you have finished destroying, you will be destroyed;\nand when you have finished betrayal, you will be betrayed.\n'),
	(13478, 20, 33, 2, 'Yahweh, be gracious to us. We have waited for you.\nBe our strength every morning,\nour salvation also in the time of trouble.\n'),
	(13479, 20, 33, 3, 'At the noise of the thunder, the peoples have fled.\nWhen you lift yourself up, the nations are scattered.\n'),
	(13480, 20, 33, 4, 'Your plunder will be gathered as the caterpillar gathers.\nMen will leap on it as locusts leap.\n'),
	(13481, 20, 33, 5, 'Yahweh is exalted, for he dwells on high.\nHe has filled Zion with justice and righteousness.\n'),
	(13482, 20, 33, 6, 'There will be stability in your times, abundance of salvation, wisdom, and knowledge.\nThe fear of Yahweh is your treasure.\n'),
	(13483, 20, 33, 7, 'Behold, their valiant ones cry outside;\nthe ambassadors of peace weep bitterly.\n'),
	(13484, 20, 33, 8, 'The highways are desolate.\nThe traveling man ceases.\nThe covenant is broken.\nHe has despised the cities.\nHe doesn’t respect man.\n'),
	(13485, 20, 33, 9, 'The land mourns and languishes.\nLebanon is confounded and withers away.\nSharon is like a desert, and Bashan and Carmel are stripped bare.\n'),
	(13486, 20, 33, 10, '“Now I will arise,” says Yahweh;\n“Now I will lift myself up.\nNow I will be exalted.\n'),
	(13487, 20, 33, 11, 'You will conceive chaff.\nYou will give birth to stubble.\nYour breath is a fire that will devour you.\n'),
	(13488, 20, 33, 12, 'The peoples will be like the burning of lime,\nlike thorns that are cut down and burned in the fire.\n'),
	(13489, 20, 33, 13, 'Hear, you who are far off, what I have done;\nand, you who are near, acknowledge my might.”\n'),
	(13490, 20, 33, 14, 'The sinners in Zion are afraid.\nTrembling has seized the godless ones.\nWho among us can live with the devouring fire?\nWho among us can live with everlasting burning?\n'),
	(13491, 20, 33, 15, 'He who walks righteously,\nand speaks blamelessly;\nHe who despises the gain of oppressions,\nwho gestures with his hands, refusing to take a bribe,\nwho stops his ears from hearing of blood,\nand shuts his eyes from looking at evil—\n'),
	(13492, 20, 33, 16, 'he will dwell on high.\nHis place of defense will be the fortress of rocks.\nHis bread will be supplied.\nHis waters will be sure.\n'),
	(13493, 20, 33, 17, 'Your eyes will see the king in his beauty.\nThey will see a distant land.\n'),
	(13494, 20, 33, 18, 'Your heart will meditate on the terror.\nWhere is he who counted?\nWhere is he who weighed?\nWhere is he who counted the towers?\n'),
	(13495, 20, 33, 19, 'You will no longer see the fierce people,\na people of a deep speech that you can’t comprehend,\nwith a strange language that you can’t understand.\n'),
	(13496, 20, 33, 20, 'Look at Zion, the city of our appointed festivals.\nYour eyes will see Jerusalem, a quiet habitation,\na tent that won’t be removed.\nIts stakes will never be plucked up,\nnor will any of its cords be broken.\n'),
	(13497, 20, 33, 21, 'But there Yahweh will be with us in majesty,\na place of wide rivers and streams,\nin which no galley with oars will go,\nneither will any gallant ship pass by there.\n'),
	(13498, 20, 33, 22, 'For Yahweh is our judge.\nYahweh is our lawgiver.\nYahweh is our king.\nHe will save us.\n'),
	(13499, 20, 33, 23, 'Your rigging is untied.\nThey couldn’t strengthen the foot of their mast.\nThey couldn’t spread the sail.\nThen the prey of a great plunder was divided.\nThe lame took the prey.\n'),
	(13500, 20, 33, 24, 'The inhabitant won’t say, “I am sick.”\nThe people who dwell therein will be forgiven their iniquity.\n'),
	(13501, 20, 34, 1, 'Come near, you nations, to hear!\nListen, you peoples.\nLet the earth and all it contains hear;\nthe world, and everything that comes from it.\n'),
	(13502, 20, 34, 2, 'For Yahweh is enraged against all the nations,\nand angry with all their armies.\nHe has utterly destroyed them.\nHe has given them over for slaughter.\n'),
	(13503, 20, 34, 3, 'Their slain will also be cast out,\nand the stench of their dead bodies will come up;\nand the mountains will melt in their blood.\n'),
	(13504, 20, 34, 4, 'All of the army of the sky will be dissolved.\nThe sky will be rolled up like a scroll,\nand all its armies will fade away,\nas a leaf fades from off a vine or a fig tree.\n'),
	(13505, 20, 34, 5, 'For my sword has drunk its fill in the sky.\nBehold, it will come down on Edom,\nand on the people of my curse, for judgment.\n'),
	(13506, 20, 34, 6, 'Yahweh’s sword is filled with blood.\nIt is covered with fat, with the blood of lambs and goats,\nwith the fat of the kidneys of rams;\nfor Yahweh has a sacrifice in Bozrah,\nAnd a great slaughter in the land of Edom.\n'),
	(13507, 20, 34, 7, 'The wild oxen will come down with them,\nand the young bulls with the mighty bulls;\nand their land will be drunken with blood,\nand their dust made greasy with fat.\n'),
	(13508, 20, 34, 8, 'For Yahweh has a day of vengeance,\na year of recompense for the cause of Zion.\n'),
	(13509, 20, 34, 9, 'Its streams will be turned into pitch,\nits dust into sulfur,\nAnd its land will become burning pitch.\n'),
	(13510, 20, 34, 10, 'It won’t be quenched night nor day.\nIts smoke will go up forever.\nFrom generation to generation, it will lie waste.\nNo one will pass through it forever and ever.\n'),
	(13511, 20, 34, 11, 'But the pelican and the porcupine will possess it.\nThe owl and the raven will dwell in it.\nHe will stretch the line of confusion over it,\nand the plumb line of emptiness.\n'),
	(13512, 20, 34, 12, 'They shall call its nobles to the kingdom, but none shall be there;\nand all its princes shall be nothing.\n'),
	(13513, 20, 34, 13, 'Thorns will come up in its palaces,\nnettles and thistles in its fortresses;\nand it will be a habitation of jackals,\na court for ostriches.\n'),
	(13514, 20, 34, 14, 'The wild animals of the desert will meet with the wolves,\nand the wild goat will cry to his fellow.\nYes, the night creature shall settle there,\nand shall find herself a place of rest.\n'),
	(13515, 20, 34, 15, 'The arrow snake will make her nest there,\nand lay, hatch, and gather under her shade.\nYes, the kites will be gathered there, every one with her mate.\n'),
	(13516, 20, 34, 16, 'Search in the book of Yahweh, and read:\nnot one of these will be missing.\nNone will lack her mate.\nFor my mouth has commanded,\nand his Spirit has gathered them.\n'),
	(13517, 20, 34, 17, 'He has cast the lot for them,\nand his hand has divided it to them with a measuring line.\nThey shall possess it forever.\nFrom generation to generation they will dwell in it.\n'),
	(13518, 20, 35, 1, 'The wilderness and the dry land will be glad.\nThe desert will rejoice and blossom like a rose.\n'),
	(13519, 20, 35, 2, 'It will blossom abundantly,\nand rejoice even with joy and singing.\nLebanon’s glory will be given to it,\nthe excellence of Carmel and Sharon.\nThey will see Yahweh’s glory,\nthe excellence of our God.\n'),
	(13520, 20, 35, 3, 'Strengthen the weak hands,\nand make firm the feeble knees.\n'),
	(13521, 20, 35, 4, 'Tell those who have a fearful heart, “Be strong.\nDon’t be afraid.\nBehold, your God will come with vengeance, God’s retribution.\nHe will come and save you.\n'),
	(13522, 20, 35, 5, 'Then the eyes of the blind will be opened,\nand the ears of the deaf will be unstopped.\n'),
	(13523, 20, 35, 6, 'Then the lame man will leap like a deer,\nand the tongue of the mute will sing;\nfor waters will break out in the wilderness,\nand streams in the desert.\n'),
	(13524, 20, 35, 7, 'The burning sand will become a pool,\nand the thirsty ground springs of water.\nGrass with reeds and rushes will be in the habitation of jackals, where they lay.\n'),
	(13525, 20, 35, 8, 'A highway will be there, a road,\nand it will be called The Holy Way.\nThe unclean shall not pass over it,\nbut it will be for those who walk in the Way.\nWicked fools will not go there.\n'),
	(13526, 20, 35, 9, 'No lion will be there,\nnor will any ravenous animal go up on it.\nThey will not be found there;\nbut the redeemed will walk there.\n'),
	(13527, 20, 35, 10, 'The Yahweh’s ransomed ones will return,\nand come with singing to Zion;\nand everlasting joy will be on their heads.\nThey will obtain gladness and joy,\nand sorrow and sighing will flee away.”\n'),
	(13528, 20, 36, 1, 'Now in the fourteenth year of king Hezekiah, Sennacherib king of Assyria attacked all of the fortified cities of Judah, and captured them.\n'),
	(13529, 20, 36, 2, 'The king of Assyria sent Rabshakeh from Lachish to Jerusalem to king Hezekiah with a large army. He stood by the aqueduct from the upper pool in the fuller’s field highway.\n'),
	(13530, 20, 36, 3, 'Then Eliakim the son of Hilkiah, who was over the household, and Shebna the scribe, and Joah, the son of Asaph, the recorder came out to him.\n'),
	(13531, 20, 36, 4, 'Rabshakeh said to them, “Now tell Hezekiah, ‘Thus says the great king, the king of Assyria, “What confidence is this in which you trust?\n'),
	(13532, 20, 36, 5, 'I say that your counsel and strength for the war are only vain words. Now in whom do you trust, that you have rebelled against me?\n'),
	(13533, 20, 36, 6, 'Behold, you trust in the staff of this bruised reed, even in Egypt, which if a man leans on it, it will go into his hand and pierce it. So is Pharaoh king of Egypt to all who trust in him.\n'),
	(13534, 20, 36, 7, 'But if you tell me, ‘We trust in Yahweh our God,’ isn’t that he whose high places and whose altars Hezekiah has taken away, and has said to Judah and to Jerusalem, ‘You shall worship before this altar?’”\n'),
	(13535, 20, 36, 8, 'Now therefore, please make a pledge to my master the king of Assyria, and I will give you two thousand horses, if you are able on your part to set riders on them.\n'),
	(13536, 20, 36, 9, 'How then can you turn away the face of one captain of the least of my master’s servants, and put your trust on Egypt for chariots and for horsemen?\n'),
	(13537, 20, 36, 10, 'Have I come up now without Yahweh against this land to destroy it? Yahweh said to me, “Go up against this land, and destroy it.”’”\n'),
	(13538, 20, 36, 11, 'Then Eliakim, Shebna and Joah said to Rabshakeh, “Please speak to your servants in Aramaic, for we understand it; and don’t speak to us in the Jews’ language in the hearing of the people who are on the wall.”\n'),
	(13539, 20, 36, 12, 'But Rabshakeh said, “Has my master sent me only to your master and to you, to speak these words, and not to the men who sit on the wall, who will eat their own dung and drink their own urine with you?”\n'),
	(13540, 20, 36, 13, 'Then Rabshakeh stood, and called out with a loud voice in the Jews’ language, and said, “Hear the words of the great king, the king of Assyria!\n'),
	(13541, 20, 36, 14, 'Thus says the king, ‘Don’t let Hezekiah deceive you; for he will not be able to deliver you.\n'),
	(13542, 20, 36, 15, 'Don’t let Hezekiah make you trust in Yahweh, saying, “Yahweh will surely deliver us. This city won’t be given into the hand of the king of Assyria.”’\n'),
	(13543, 20, 36, 16, 'Don’t listen to Hezekiah, for thus says the king of Assyria, ‘Make your peace with me, and come out to me; and each of you eat from his vine, and each one from his fig tree, and each one of you drink the waters of his own cistern;\n'),
	(13544, 20, 36, 17, 'until I come and take you away to a land like your own land, a land of grain and new wine, a land of bread and vineyards.\n'),
	(13545, 20, 36, 18, 'Beware lest Hezekiah persuade you, saying, “Yahweh will deliver us.” Have any of the gods of the nations delivered their lands from the hand of the king of Assyria?\n'),
	(13546, 20, 36, 19, 'Where are the gods of Hamath and Arpad? Where are the gods of Sepharvaim? Have they delivered Samaria from my hand?\n'),
	(13547, 20, 36, 20, 'Who are they among all the gods of these countries that have delivered their country out of my hand, that Yahweh should deliver Jerusalem out of my hand?’”\n'),
	(13548, 20, 36, 21, 'But they remained silent, and said nothing in reply, for the king’s commandment was, “Don’t answer him.”\n'),
	(13549, 20, 36, 22, 'Then Eliakim the son of Hilkiah, who was over the household, and Shebna the scribe, and Joah, the son of Asaph, the recorder, came to Hezekiah with their clothes torn, and told him the words of Rabshakeh.\n'),
	(13550, 20, 37, 1, 'When king Hezekiah heard it, he tore his clothes, covered himself with sackcloth, and went into Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(13551, 20, 37, 2, 'He sent Eliakim, who was over the household, and Shebna the scribe, and the elders of the priests, covered with sackcloth, to Isaiah the prophet, the son of Amoz.\n'),
	(13552, 20, 37, 3, 'They said to him, “Thus says Hezekiah, ‘Today is a day of trouble, and of rebuke, and of rejection; for the children have come to the birth, and there is no strength to give birth.\n'),
	(13553, 20, 37, 4, 'It may be Yahweh your God will hear the words of Rabshakeh, whom the king of Assyria his master has sent to defy the living God, and will rebuke the words which Yahweh your God has heard. Therefore lift up your prayer for the remnant that is left.’”\n'),
	(13554, 20, 37, 5, 'So the servants of king Hezekiah came to Isaiah.\n'),
	(13555, 20, 37, 6, 'Isaiah said to them, “Tell your master, ‘Yahweh says, “Don’t be afraid of the words that you have heard, with which the servants of the king of Assyria have blasphemed me.\n'),
	(13556, 20, 37, 7, 'Behold, I will put a spirit in him and he will hear news, and will return to his own land. I will cause him to fall by the sword in his own land.”’”\n'),
	(13557, 20, 37, 8, 'So Rabshakeh returned, and found the king of Assyria warring against Libnah, for he had heard that he was departed from Lachish.\n'),
	(13558, 20, 37, 9, 'He heard news concerning Tirhakah king of Ethiopia, “He has come out to fight against you.” When he heard it, he sent messengers to Hezekiah, saying,\n'),
	(13559, 20, 37, 10, '“Thus you shall speak to Hezekiah king of Judah, saying, ‘Don’t let your God in whom you trust deceive you, saying, “Jerusalem won’t be given into the hand of the king of Assyria.”\n'),
	(13560, 20, 37, 11, 'Behold, you have heard what the kings of Assyria have done to all lands, by destroying them utterly. Shall you be delivered?\n'),
	(13561, 20, 37, 12, 'Have the gods of the nations delivered them, which my fathers have destroyed, Gozan, Haran, Rezeph, and the children of Eden who were in Telassar?\n'),
	(13562, 20, 37, 13, 'Where is the king of Hamath, and the king of Arpad, and the king of the city of Sepharvaim, of Hena, and Ivvah?’”\n'),
	(13563, 20, 37, 14, 'Hezekiah received the letter from the hand of the messengers and read it. Then Hezekiah went up to Yahweh’s house, and spread it before Yahweh.\n'),
	(13564, 20, 37, 15, 'Hezekiah prayed to Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(13565, 20, 37, 16, '“Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, who is enthroned among the cherubim, you are the God, even you alone, of all the kingdoms of the earth. You have made heaven and earth.\n'),
	(13566, 20, 37, 17, 'Turn your ear, Yahweh, and hear. Open your eyes, Yahweh, and behold. Hear all of the words of Sennacherib, who has sent to defy the living God.\n'),
	(13567, 20, 37, 18, 'Truly, Yahweh, the kings of Assyria have destroyed all the countries and their land,\n'),
	(13568, 20, 37, 19, 'and have cast their gods into the fire; for they were no gods, but the work of men’s hands, wood and stone; therefore they have destroyed them.\n'),
	(13569, 20, 37, 20, 'Now therefore, Yahweh our God, save us from his hand, that all the kingdoms of the earth may know that you are Yahweh, even you only.”\n'),
	(13570, 20, 37, 21, 'Then Isaiah the son of Amoz sent to Hezekiah, saying, “Yahweh, the God of Israel says, ‘Because you have prayed to me against Sennacherib king of Assyria,\n'),
	(13571, 20, 37, 22, 'this is the word which Yahweh has spoken concerning him. The virgin daughter of Zion has despised you and ridiculed you. The daughter of Jerusalem has shaken her head at you.\n'),
	(13572, 20, 37, 23, 'Whom have you defied and blasphemed? Against whom have you exalted your voice and lifted up your eyes on high? Against the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(13573, 20, 37, 24, 'By your servants, have you defied the Lord, and have said, “With the multitude of my chariots I have come up to the height of the mountains, to the innermost parts of Lebanon. I will cut down its tall cedars and its choice cypress trees. I will enter into its farthest height, the forest of its fruitful field.\n'),
	(13574, 20, 37, 25, 'I have dug and drunk water, and with the sole of my feet I will dry up all the rivers of Egypt.”\n'),
	(13575, 20, 37, 26, '“‘Have you not heard how I have done it long ago, and formed it in ancient times? Now I have brought it to pass, that it should be yours to destroy fortified cities, turning them into ruinous heaps.\n'),
	(13576, 20, 37, 27, 'Therefore their inhabitants had little power. They were dismayed and confounded. They were like the grass of the field, and like the green herb, like the grass on the housetops, and like a field before its crop has grown.\n'),
	(13577, 20, 37, 28, 'But I know your sitting down, your going out, your coming in, and your raging against me.\n'),
	(13578, 20, 37, 29, 'Because of your raging against me, and because your arrogance has come up into my ears, therefore will I put my hook in your nose and my bridle in your lips, and I will turn you back by the way by which you came.\n'),
	(13579, 20, 37, 30, '“‘This shall be the sign to you. You will eat this year that which grows of itself, and in the second year that which springs from the same; and in the third year sow and reap and plant vineyards, and eat their fruit.\n'),
	(13580, 20, 37, 31, 'The remnant that is escaped of the house of Judah will again take root downward, and bear fruit upward.\n'),
	(13581, 20, 37, 32, 'For out of Jerusalem a remnant will go out, and survivors will escape from Mount Zion. The zeal of Yahweh of Armies will perform this.’\n'),
	(13582, 20, 37, 33, '“Therefore Yahweh says concerning the king of Assyria, ‘He will not come to this city, nor shoot an arrow there, neither will he come before it with shield, nor cast up a mound against it.\n'),
	(13583, 20, 37, 34, 'By the way that he came, by the same he shall return, and he shall not come to this city,’ says Yahweh.\n'),
	(13584, 20, 37, 35, '‘For I will defend this city to save it, for my own sake, and for my servant David’s sake.’”\n'),
	(13585, 20, 37, 36, 'Then Yahweh’s angel went out and struck one hundred and eighty-five thousand men in the camp of the Assyrians. When men arose early in the morning, behold, these were all dead bodies.\n'),
	(13586, 20, 37, 37, 'So Sennacherib king of Assyria departed, went away, returned to Nineveh, and stayed there.\n'),
	(13587, 20, 37, 38, 'As he was worshiping in the house of Nisroch his god, Adrammelech and Sharezer his sons struck him with the sword; and they escaped into the land of Ararat. Esar Haddon his son reigned in his place.\n'),
	(13588, 20, 38, 1, 'In those days was Hezekiah sick and near death. Isaiah the prophet, the son of Amoz, came to him, and said to him, “Yahweh says, ‘Set your house in order, for you will die, and not live.’”\n'),
	(13589, 20, 38, 2, 'Then Hezekiah turned his face to the wall and prayed to Yahweh,\n'),
	(13590, 20, 38, 3, 'and said, “Remember now, Yahweh, I beg you, how I have walked before you in truth and with a perfect heart, and have done that which is good in your sight.” Hezekiah wept bitterly.\n'),
	(13591, 20, 38, 4, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to Isaiah, saying,\n'),
	(13592, 20, 38, 5, '“Go, and tell Hezekiah, ‘Yahweh, the God of David your father, says, “I have heard your prayer. I have seen your tears. Behold, I will add fifteen years to your life.\n'),
	(13593, 20, 38, 6, 'I will deliver you and this city out of the hand of the king of Assyria, and I will defend this city.\n'),
	(13594, 20, 38, 7, 'This shall be the sign to you from Yahweh, that Yahweh will do this thing that he has spoken.\n'),
	(13595, 20, 38, 8, 'Behold, I will cause the shadow on the sundial, which has gone down on the sundial of Ahaz with the sun, to return backward ten steps. So the sun returned ten steps on the sundial on which it had gone down.”’”\n'),
	(13596, 20, 38, 9, 'The writing of Hezekiah king of Judah, when he had been sick, and had recovered of his sickness.\n'),
	(13597, 20, 38, 10, 'I said, “In the middle of my life I go into the gates of Sheol.\nI am deprived of the residue of my years.”\n'),
	(13598, 20, 38, 11, 'I said, “I won’t see Yah,\nYah in the land of the living.\nI will see man no more with the inhabitants of the world.\n'),
	(13599, 20, 38, 12, 'My dwelling is removed,\nand is carried away from me like a shepherd’s tent.\nI have rolled up, like a weaver, my life.\nHe will cut me off from the loom.\nFrom day even to night you will make an end of me.\n'),
	(13600, 20, 38, 13, 'I waited patiently until morning.\nHe breaks all my bones like a lion.\nFrom day even to night you will make an end of me.\n'),
	(13601, 20, 38, 14, 'I chattered like a swallow or a crane.\nI moaned like a dove.\nMy eyes weaken looking upward.\nLord, I am oppressed.\nBe my security.”\n'),
	(13602, 20, 38, 15, 'What will I say?\nHe has both spoken to me, and himself has done it.\nI will walk carefully all my years because of the anguish of my soul.\n'),
	(13603, 20, 38, 16, 'Lord, men live by these things;\nand my spirit finds life in all of them:\nyou restore me, and cause me to live.\n'),
	(13604, 20, 38, 17, 'Behold, for peace I had great anguish,\nbut you have in love for my soul delivered it from the pit of corruption;\nfor you have cast all my sins behind your back.\n'),
	(13605, 20, 38, 18, 'For Sheol can’t praise you.\nDeath can’t celebrate you.\nThose who go down into the pit can’t hope for your truth.\n'),
	(13606, 20, 38, 19, 'The living, the living, he shall praise you, as I do today.\nThe father shall make known your truth to the children.\n'),
	(13607, 20, 38, 20, 'Yahweh will save me.\nTherefore we will sing my songs with stringed instruments all the days of our life in Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(13608, 20, 38, 21, 'Now Isaiah had said, “Let them take a cake of figs, and lay it for a poultice on the boil, and he shall recover.”\n'),
	(13609, 20, 38, 22, 'Hezekiah also had said, “What is the sign that I will go up to Yahweh’s house?”\n'),
	(13610, 20, 39, 1, 'At that time, Merodach Baladan the son of Baladan, king of Babylon, sent letters and a present to Hezekiah; for he heard that he had been sick, and had recovered.\n'),
	(13611, 20, 39, 2, 'Hezekiah was pleased with them, and showed them the house of his precious things, the silver, and the gold, the spices, and the precious oil, and all the house of his armor, and all that was found in his treasures. There was nothing in his house, nor in all his dominion, that Hezekiah didn’t show them.\n'),
	(13612, 20, 39, 3, 'Then Isaiah the prophet came to king Hezekiah, and asked him, “What did these men say? Where did they come from to you?”\nHezekiah said, “They have come from a country far from me, even from Babylon.”\n'),
	(13613, 20, 39, 4, 'Then he asked, “What have they seen in your house?”\nHezekiah answered, “They have seen all that is in my house. There is nothing among my treasures that I have not shown them.”\n'),
	(13614, 20, 39, 5, 'Then Isaiah said to Hezekiah, “Hear the word of Yahweh of Armies:\n'),
	(13615, 20, 39, 6, '‘Behold, the days are coming when all that is in your house, and that which your fathers have stored up until today, will be carried to Babylon. Nothing will be left,’ says Yahweh.\n'),
	(13616, 20, 39, 7, '‘They will take away your sons who will issue from you, whom you shall father, and they will be eunuchs in the king of Babylon’s palace.’”\n'),
	(13617, 20, 39, 8, 'Then Hezekiah said to Isaiah, “Yahweh’s word which you have spoken is good.” He said moreover, “For there will be peace and truth in my days.”\n'),
	(13618, 20, 40, 1, '“Comfort, comfort my people,” says your God.\n'),
	(13619, 20, 40, 2, '“Speak comfortably to Jerusalem; and call out to her that her warfare is accomplished, that her iniquity is pardoned, that she has received of Yahweh’s hand double for all her sins.”\n'),
	(13620, 20, 40, 3, 'The voice of one who calls out,\n“Prepare the way of Yahweh in the wilderness!\nMake a level highway in the desert for our God.\n'),
	(13621, 20, 40, 4, 'Every valley shall be exalted,\nand every mountain and hill shall be made low.\nThe uneven shall be made level,\nand the rough places a plain.\n'),
	(13622, 20, 40, 5, 'Yahweh’s glory shall be revealed,\nand all flesh shall see it together;\nfor the mouth of Yahweh has spoken it.”\n'),
	(13623, 20, 40, 6, 'The voice of one saying, “Cry!”\nOne said, “What shall I cry?”\n“All flesh is like grass,\nand all its glory is like the flower of the field.\n'),
	(13624, 20, 40, 7, 'The grass withers,\nthe flower fades,\nbecause Yahweh’s breath blows on it.\nSurely the people are like grass.\n'),
	(13625, 20, 40, 8, 'The grass withers,\nthe flower fades;\nbut the word of our God stands forever.”\n'),
	(13626, 20, 40, 9, 'You who tell good news to Zion, go up on a high mountain.\nYou who tell good news to Jerusalem, lift up your voice with strength.\nLift it up. Don’t be afraid.\nSay to the cities of Judah, “Behold, your God!”\n'),
	(13627, 20, 40, 10, 'Behold, the Lord Yahweh will come as a mighty one,\nand his arm will rule for him.\nBehold, his reward is with him,\nand his recompense before him.\n'),
	(13628, 20, 40, 11, 'He will feed his flock like a shepherd.\nHe will gather the lambs in his arm,\nand carry them in his bosom.\nHe will gently lead those who have their young.\n'),
	(13629, 20, 40, 12, 'Who has measured the waters in the hollow of his hand,\nand marked off the sky with his span,\nand calculated the dust of the earth in a measuring basket,\nand weighed the mountains in scales,\nand the hills in a balance?\n'),
	(13630, 20, 40, 13, 'Who has directed Yahweh’s Spirit,\nor has taught him as his counselor?\n'),
	(13631, 20, 40, 14, 'Who did he take counsel with,\nand who instructed him,\nand taught him in the path of justice,\nand taught him knowledge,\nand showed him the way of understanding?\n'),
	(13632, 20, 40, 15, 'Behold, the nations are like a drop in a bucket,\nand are regarded as a speck of dust on a balance.\nBehold, he lifts up the islands like a very little thing.\n'),
	(13633, 20, 40, 16, 'Lebanon is not sufficient to burn,\nnor its animals sufficient for a burnt offering.\n'),
	(13634, 20, 40, 17, 'All the nations are like nothing before him.\nThey are regarded by him as less than nothing, and vanity.\n'),
	(13635, 20, 40, 18, 'To whom then will you liken God?\nOr what likeness will you compare to him?\n'),
	(13636, 20, 40, 19, 'A workman has cast an image,\nand the goldsmith overlays it with gold,\nand casts silver chains for it.\n'),
	(13637, 20, 40, 20, 'He who is too impoverished for such an offering chooses a tree that will not rot.\nHe seeks a skillful workman to set up a carved image for him that will not be moved.\n'),
	(13638, 20, 40, 21, 'Haven’t you known?\nHaven’t you heard?\nHaven’t you been told from the beginning?\nHaven’t you understood from the foundations of the earth?\n'),
	(13639, 20, 40, 22, 'It is he who sits above the circle of the earth,\nand its inhabitants are like grasshoppers;\nwho stretches out the heavens like a curtain,\nand spreads them out like a tent to dwell in;\n'),
	(13640, 20, 40, 23, 'who brings princes to nothing;\nwho makes the judges of the earth like meaningless.\n'),
	(13641, 20, 40, 24, 'They are planted scarcely.\nThey are sown scarcely.\nTheir stock has scarcely taken root in the ground.\nHe merely blows on them, and they wither,\nand the whirlwind takes them away as stubble.\n'),
	(13642, 20, 40, 25, '“To whom then will you liken me?\nWho is my equal?” says the Holy One.\n'),
	(13643, 20, 40, 26, 'Lift up your eyes on high,\nand see who has created these,\nwho brings out their army by number.\nHe calls them all by name.\nby the greatness of his might,\nand because he is strong in power,\nNot one is lacking.\n'),
	(13644, 20, 40, 27, 'Why do you say, Jacob,\nand speak, Israel,\n“My way is hidden from Yahweh,\nand the justice due me is disregarded by my God?”\n'),
	(13645, 20, 40, 28, 'Haven’t you known?\nHaven’t you heard?\nThe everlasting God, Yahweh,\nThe Creator of the ends of the earth, doesn’t faint.\nHe isn’t weary.\nHis understanding is unsearchable.\n'),
	(13646, 20, 40, 29, 'He gives power to the weak.\nHe increases the strength of him who has no might.\n'),
	(13647, 20, 40, 30, 'Even the youths faint and get weary,\nand the young men utterly fall;\n'),
	(13648, 20, 40, 31, 'But those who wait for Yahweh will renew their strength.\nThey will mount up with wings like eagles.\nThey will run, and not be weary.\nThey will walk, and not faint.\n'),
	(13649, 20, 41, 1, '“Keep silent before me, islands,\nand let the peoples renew their strength.\nLet them come near,\nthen let them speak.\nLet’s meet together for judgment.\n'),
	(13650, 20, 41, 2, 'Who has raised up one from the east?\nWho called him to his foot in righteousness?\nHe hands over nations to him,\nand makes him rule over kings.\nHe gives them like the dust to his sword,\nlike the driven stubble to his bow.\n'),
	(13651, 20, 41, 3, 'He pursues them,\nand passes by safely,\nEven by a way that he had not gone with his feet.\n'),
	(13652, 20, 41, 4, 'Who has worked and done it,\ncalling the generations from the beginning?\nI, Yahweh, the first, and with the last, I am he.”\n'),
	(13653, 20, 41, 5, 'The islands have seen, and fear.\nThe ends of the earth tremble.\nThey approach, and come.\n'),
	(13654, 20, 41, 6, 'Everyone helps his neighbor.\nThey say to their brothers, “Be strong!”\n'),
	(13655, 20, 41, 7, 'So the carpenter encourages the goldsmith.\nHe who smoothes with the hammer encourages him who strikes the anvil,\nsaying of the soldering, “It is good”;\nand he fastens it with nails, that it might not totter.\n'),
	(13656, 20, 41, 8, '“But you, Israel, my servant,\nJacob whom I have chosen,\nthe offspring of Abraham my friend,\n'),
	(13657, 20, 41, 9, 'You whom I have taken hold of from the ends of the earth,\nand called from its corners,\nand said to you, ‘You are my servant, I have chosen you and have not cast you away.’\n'),
	(13658, 20, 41, 10, 'Don’t you be afraid, for I am with you.\nDon’t be dismayed, for I am your God.\nI will strengthen you.\nYes, I will help you.\nYes, I will uphold you with the right hand of my righteousness.\n'),
	(13659, 20, 41, 11, 'Behold, all those who are incensed against you will be disappointed and confounded.\nThose who strive with you will be like nothing, and shall perish.\n'),
	(13660, 20, 41, 12, 'You will seek them, and won’t find them,\neven those who contend with you.\nThose who war against you will be as nothing,\nas a non-existent thing.\n'),
	(13661, 20, 41, 13, 'For I, Yahweh your God, will hold your right hand,\nsaying to you, ‘Don’t be afraid.\nI will help you.’\n'),
	(13662, 20, 41, 14, 'Don’t be afraid, you worm Jacob,\nand you men of Israel.\nI will help you,” says Yahweh,\n“and your Redeemer is the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(13663, 20, 41, 15, 'Behold, I have made you into a new sharp threshing instrument with teeth.\nYou will thresh the mountains,\nand beat them small,\nand will make the hills like chaff.\n'),
	(13664, 20, 41, 16, 'You will winnow them,\nand the wind will carry them away,\nand the whirlwind will scatter them.\nYou will rejoice in Yahweh.\nYou will glory in the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(13665, 20, 41, 17, 'The poor and needy seek water, and there is none.\nTheir tongue fails for thirst.\nI, Yahweh, will answer them.\nI, the God of Israel, will not forsake them.\n'),
	(13666, 20, 41, 18, 'I will open rivers on the bare heights,\nand springs in the middle of the valleys.\nI will make the wilderness a pool of water,\nand the dry land springs of water.\n'),
	(13667, 20, 41, 19, 'I will put cedar, acacia, myrtle, and oil trees in the wilderness.\nI will set cypress trees, pine, and box trees together in the desert;\n'),
	(13668, 20, 41, 20, 'that they may see, know, consider, and understand together,\nthat Yahweh’s hand has done this,\nand the Holy One of Israel has created it.\n'),
	(13669, 20, 41, 21, 'Produce your cause,” says Yahweh.\n“Bring out your strong reasons,” says the King of Jacob.\n'),
	(13670, 20, 41, 22, '“Let them announce, and declare to us what shall happen.\nDeclare the former things, what they are,\nthat we may consider them, and know the latter end of them;\nor show us things to come.\n'),
	(13671, 20, 41, 23, 'Declare the things that are to come hereafter,\nthat we may know that you are gods.\nYes, do good, or do evil,\nthat we may be dismayed,\nand see it together.\n'),
	(13672, 20, 41, 24, 'Behold, you are of nothing,\nand your work is of nothing.\nHe who chooses you is an abomination.\n'),
	(13673, 20, 41, 25, '“I have raised up one from the north, and he has come;\nfrom the rising of the sun, one who calls on my name;\nand he shall come on rulers as on mortar,\nand as the potter treads clay.\n'),
	(13674, 20, 41, 26, 'Who has declared it from the beginning, that we may know?\nAnd before, that we may say, ‘He is right?’\nSurely, there is no one who declares.\nSurely, there is no one who shows.\nSurely, there is no one who hears your words.\n'),
	(13675, 20, 41, 27, 'I am the first to say to Zion, ‘Behold, look at them;’\nand I will give one who brings good news to Jerusalem.\n'),
	(13676, 20, 41, 28, 'When I look, there is no man;\neven among them there is no counselor who, when I ask of them, can answer a word.\n'),
	(13677, 20, 41, 29, 'Behold, all of them, their deeds are vanity and nothing.\nTheir molten images are wind and confusion.\n'),
	(13678, 20, 42, 1, '“Behold, my servant, whom I uphold;\nmy chosen, in whom my soul delights—\nI have put my Spirit on him.\nHe will bring justice to the nations.\n'),
	(13679, 20, 42, 2, 'He will not shout,\nnor raise his voice,\nnor cause it to be heard in the street.\n'),
	(13680, 20, 42, 3, 'He won’t break a bruised reed.\nHe won’t quench a dimly burning wick.\nHe will faithfully bring justice.\n'),
	(13681, 20, 42, 4, 'He will not fail nor be discouraged,\nuntil he has set justice in the earth,\nand the islands will wait for his law.”\n'),
	(13682, 20, 42, 5, 'Thus says God Yahweh,\nhe who created the heavens and stretched them out,\nhe who spread out the earth and that which comes out of it,\nhe who gives breath to its people and spirit to those who walk in it.\n'),
	(13683, 20, 42, 6, '“I, Yahweh, have called you in righteousness,\nand will hold your hand,\nand will keep you,\nand make you a covenant for the people,\nas a light for the nations;\n'),
	(13684, 20, 42, 7, 'to open the blind eyes,\nto bring the prisoners out of the dungeon,\nand those who sit in darkness out of the prison.\n'),
	(13685, 20, 42, 8, '“I am Yahweh.\nThat is my name.\nI will not give my glory to another,\nnor my praise to engraved images.\n'),
	(13686, 20, 42, 9, 'Behold, the former things have happened,\nand I declare new things.\nI tell you about them before they come up.”\n'),
	(13687, 20, 42, 10, 'Sing to Yahweh a new song,\nand his praise from the end of the earth,\nyou who go down to the sea,\nand all that is therein,\nthe islands and their inhabitants.\n'),
	(13688, 20, 42, 11, 'Let the wilderness and its cities raise their voices,\nwith the villages that Kedar inhabits.\nLet the inhabitants of Sela sing.\nLet them shout from the top of the mountains!\n'),
	(13689, 20, 42, 12, 'Let them give glory to Yahweh,\nand declare his praise in the islands.\n'),
	(13690, 20, 42, 13, 'Yahweh will go out like a mighty man.\nHe will stir up zeal like a man of war.\nHe will raise a war cry.\nYes, he will shout aloud.\nHe will triumph over his enemies.\n'),
	(13691, 20, 42, 14, '“I have been silent a long time.\nI have been quiet and restrained myself.\nNow I will cry out like a travailing woman. I will both gasp and pant.\n'),
	(13692, 20, 42, 15, 'I will destroy mountains and hills,\nand dry up all their herbs.\nI will make the rivers islands,\nand will dry up the pools.\n'),
	(13693, 20, 42, 16, 'I will bring the blind by a way that they don’t know.\nI will lead them in paths that they don’t know.\nI will make darkness light before them,\nand crooked places straight.\nI will do these things,\nand I will not forsake them.\n'),
	(13694, 20, 42, 17, '“Those who trust in engraved images,\nwho tell molten images,\n‘You are our gods’\nwill be turned back.\nThey will be utterly disappointed.\n'),
	(13695, 20, 42, 18, '“Hear, you deaf,\nand look, you blind,\nthat you may see.\n'),
	(13696, 20, 42, 19, 'Who is blind, but my servant?\nOr who is as deaf as my messenger whom I send?\nWho is as blind as he who is at peace,\nand as blind as Yahweh’s servant?\n'),
	(13697, 20, 42, 20, 'You see many things, but don’t observe.\nHis ears are open, but he doesn’t listen.\n'),
	(13698, 20, 42, 21, 'It pleased Yahweh, for his righteousness’ sake, to magnify the law,\nand make it honorable.\n'),
	(13699, 20, 42, 22, 'But this is a robbed and plundered people.\nAll of them are snared in holes,\nand they are hidden in prisons.\nThey have become captives, and no one delivers;\nand a plunder, and no one says, ‘Restore them!’\n'),
	(13700, 20, 42, 23, 'Who is there among you who will give ear to this?\nWho will listen and hear for the time to come?\n'),
	(13701, 20, 42, 24, 'Who gave Jacob as plunder,\nand Israel to the robbers?\nDidn’t Yahweh, he against whom we have sinned?\nFor they would not walk in his ways,\nand they disobeyed his law.\n'),
	(13702, 20, 42, 25, 'Therefore he poured the fierceness of his anger on him,\nand the strength of battle;\nand it set him on fire all around, but he didn’t know;\nand it burned him, but he didn’t take it to heart.”\n'),
	(13703, 20, 43, 1, 'But now Yahweh who created you, Jacob,\nand he who formed you, Israel says:\n“Don’t be afraid, for I have redeemed you.\nI have called you by your name.\nYou are mine.\n'),
	(13704, 20, 43, 2, 'When you pass through the waters, I will be with you;\nand through the rivers, they will not overflow you.\nWhen you walk through the fire, you will not be burned,\nand flame will not scorch you.\n'),
	(13705, 20, 43, 3, 'For I am Yahweh your God,\nthe Holy One of Israel,\nyour Savior.\nI have given Egypt as your ransom,\nEthiopia and Seba in your place.\n'),
	(13706, 20, 43, 4, 'Since you have been precious and honored in my sight,\nand I have loved you;\ntherefore I will give people in your place,\nand nations instead of your life.\n'),
	(13707, 20, 43, 5, 'Don’t be afraid; for I am with you.\nI will bring your offspring from the east,\nand gather you from the west.\n'),
	(13708, 20, 43, 6, 'I will tell the north, ‘Give them up!’\nand tell the south, ‘Don’t hold them back!\nBring my sons from far,\nand my daughters from the ends of the earth—\n'),
	(13709, 20, 43, 7, 'everyone who is called by my name,\nand whom I have created for my glory,\nwhom I have formed,\nyes, whom I have made.’”\n'),
	(13710, 20, 43, 8, 'Bring out the blind people who have eyes,\nand the deaf who have ears.\n'),
	(13711, 20, 43, 9, 'Let all the nations be gathered together,\nand let the peoples be assembled.\nWho among them can declare this,\nand show us former things?\nLet them bring their witnesses, that they may be justified;\nor let them hear, and say, “That is true.”\n'),
	(13712, 20, 43, 10, '“You are my witnesses,” says Yahweh,\n“With my servant whom I have chosen;\nthat you may know and believe me,\nand understand that I am he.\nBefore me there was no God formed,\nneither will there be after me.\n'),
	(13713, 20, 43, 11, 'I myself am Yahweh;\nand besides me there is no savior.\n'),
	(13714, 20, 43, 12, 'I have declared, I have saved, and I have shown;\nand there was no strange god among you.\nTherefore you are my witnesses”,\nsays Yahweh, “and I am God.\n'),
	(13715, 20, 43, 13, 'Yes, since the day was, I am he;\nand there is no one who can deliver out of my hand.\nI will work, and who can hinder it?”\n'),
	(13716, 20, 43, 14, 'Yahweh, your Redeemer, the Holy One of Israel says: “For your sake, I have sent to Babylon, and I will bring all of them down as fugitives, even the Chaldeans, in the ships of their rejoicing.\n'),
	(13717, 20, 43, 15, 'I am Yahweh, your Holy One, the Creator of Israel, your King.”\n'),
	(13718, 20, 43, 16, 'Yahweh, who makes a way in the sea,\nand a path in the mighty waters says:\n'),
	(13719, 20, 43, 17, 'who brings out the chariot and horse,\nthe army and the mighty man\n(they lie down together, they shall not rise;\nthey are extinct, they are quenched like a wick):\n'),
	(13720, 20, 43, 18, '“Don’t remember the former things,\nand don’t consider the things of old.\n'),
	(13721, 20, 43, 19, 'Behold, I will do a new thing.\nIt springs out now.\nDon’t you know it?\nI will even make a way in the wilderness,\nand rivers in the desert.\n'),
	(13722, 20, 43, 20, 'The animals of the field shall honor me,\nthe jackals and the ostriches;\nbecause I give water in the wilderness and rivers in the desert,\nto give drink to my people, my chosen,\n'),
	(13723, 20, 43, 21, 'the people which I formed for myself,\nthat they might declare my praise.\n'),
	(13724, 20, 43, 22, 'Yet you have not called on me, Jacob;\nbut you have been weary of me, Israel.\n'),
	(13725, 20, 43, 23, 'You have not brought me of your sheep for burnt offerings;\nneither have you honored me with your sacrifices.\nI have not burdened you with offerings,\nnor wearied you with frankincense.\n'),
	(13726, 20, 43, 24, 'You have bought me no sweet cane with money,\nnor have you filled me with the fat of your sacrifices;\nbut you have burdened me with your sins.\nYou have wearied me with your iniquities.\n'),
	(13727, 20, 43, 25, 'I, even I, am he who blots out your transgressions for my own sake;\nand I will not remember your sins.\n'),
	(13728, 20, 43, 26, 'Put me in remembrance.\nLet us plead together.\nDeclare your case,\nthat you may be justified.\n'),
	(13729, 20, 43, 27, 'Your first father sinned,\nand your teachers have transgressed against me.\n'),
	(13730, 20, 43, 28, 'Therefore I will profane the princes of the sanctuary;\nand I will make Jacob a curse,\nand Israel an insult.”\n'),
	(13731, 20, 44, 1, 'Yet listen now, Jacob my servant,\nand Israel, whom I have chosen.\n'),
	(13732, 20, 44, 2, 'This is what Yahweh who made you,\nand formed you from the womb,\nwho will help you says:\n“Don’t be afraid, Jacob my servant;\nand you, Jeshurun, whom I have chosen.\n'),
	(13733, 20, 44, 3, 'For I will pour water on him who is thirsty,\nand streams on the dry ground.\nI will pour my Spirit on your descendants,\nand my blessing on your offspring:\n'),
	(13734, 20, 44, 4, 'and they will spring up among the grass,\nas willows by the watercourses.\n'),
	(13735, 20, 44, 5, 'One will say, ‘I am Yahweh’s;’\nand another will be called by the name of Jacob;\nand another will write with his hand ‘to Yahweh,’\nand honor the name of Israel.”\n'),
	(13736, 20, 44, 6, 'This is what Yahweh, the King of Israel,\nand his Redeemer, Yahweh of Armies, says:\n“I am the first, and I am the last;\nand besides me there is no God.\n'),
	(13737, 20, 44, 7, 'Who is like me?\nWho will call,\nand will declare it,\nand set it in order for me,\nsince I established the ancient people?\nLet them declare the things that are coming,\nand that will happen.\n'),
	(13738, 20, 44, 8, 'Don’t fear,\nneither be afraid.\nHaven’t I declared it to you long ago,\nand shown it?\nYou are my witnesses.\nIs there a God besides me?\nIndeed, there is not.\nI don’t know any other Rock.”\n'),
	(13739, 20, 44, 9, 'Everyone who makes a carved image is vain.\nThe things that they delight in will not profit.\nTheir own witnesses don’t see, nor know, that they may be disappointed.\n'),
	(13740, 20, 44, 10, 'Who has fashioned a god,\nor molds an image that is profitable for nothing?\n'),
	(13741, 20, 44, 11, 'Behold, all his fellows will be disappointed;\nand the workmen are mere men.\nLet them all be gathered together.\nLet them stand up.\nThey will fear.\nThey will be put to shame together.\n'),
	(13742, 20, 44, 12, 'The blacksmith takes an ax,\nworks in the coals,\nfashions it with hammers,\nand works it with his strong arm.\nHe is hungry,\nand his strength fails;\nhe drinks no water,\nand is faint.\n'),
	(13743, 20, 44, 13, 'The carpenter stretches out a line.\nHe marks it out with a pencil.\nHe shapes it with planes.\nHe marks it out with compasses,\nand shapes it like the figure of a man,\nwith the beauty of a man,\nto reside in a house.\n'),
	(13744, 20, 44, 14, 'He cuts down cedars for himself,\nand takes the cypress and the oak,\nand strengthens for himself one among the trees of the forest.\nHe plants a cypress tree,\nand the rain nourishes it.\n'),
	(13745, 20, 44, 15, 'Then it will be for a man to burn;\nand he takes some of it, and warms himself.\nYes, he burns it, and bakes bread.\nYes, he makes a god, and worships it;\nhe makes it a carved image, and falls down to it.\n'),
	(13746, 20, 44, 16, 'He burns part of it in the fire.\nWith part of it, he eats meat.\nHe roasts a roast, and is satisfied.\nYes, he warms himself,\nand says, “Aha! I am warm. I have seen the fire.”\n'),
	(13747, 20, 44, 17, 'The rest of it he makes into a god,\neven his engraved image.\nHe bows down to it and worships,\nand prays to it, and says, “Deliver me; for you are my god!”\n'),
	(13748, 20, 44, 18, 'They don’t know, neither do they consider:\nfor he has shut their eyes, that they can’t see;\nand their hearts, that they can’t understand.\n'),
	(13749, 20, 44, 19, 'No one thinks,\nneither is there knowledge nor understanding to say,\n“I have burned part of it in the fire.\nYes, I have also baked bread on its coals.\nI have roasted meat and eaten it.\nShall I make the rest of it into an abomination?\nShall I bow down to a tree trunk?”\n'),
	(13750, 20, 44, 20, 'He feeds on ashes.\nA deceived heart has turned him aside;\nand he can’t deliver his soul,\nnor say, “Isn’t there a lie in my right hand?”\n'),
	(13751, 20, 44, 21, 'Remember these things, Jacob and Israel;\nfor you are my servant.\nI have formed you.\nYou are my servant.\nIsrael, you will not be forgotten by me.\n'),
	(13752, 20, 44, 22, 'I have blotted out, as a thick cloud, your transgressions,\nand, as a cloud, your sins.\nReturn to me, for I have redeemed you.\n'),
	(13753, 20, 44, 23, 'Sing, you heavens, for Yahweh has done it!\nShout, you lower parts of the earth!\nBreak out into singing, you mountains, O forest, all of your trees,\nfor Yahweh has redeemed Jacob,\nand will glorify himself in Israel.\n'),
	(13754, 20, 44, 24, 'Yahweh, your Redeemer,\nand he who formed you from the womb says:\n“I am Yahweh, who makes all things;\nwho alone stretches out the heavens;\nwho spreads out the earth by myself;\n'),
	(13755, 20, 44, 25, 'who frustrates the signs of the liars,\nand makes diviners mad;\nwho turns wise men backward,\nand makes their knowledge foolish;\n'),
	(13756, 20, 44, 26, 'who confirms the word of his servant,\nand performs the counsel of his messengers;\nwho says of Jerusalem, ‘She will be inhabited;’\nand of the cities of Judah, ‘They will be built,’\nand ‘I will raise up its waste places;’\n'),
	(13757, 20, 44, 27, 'who says to the deep, ‘Be dry,’\nand ‘I will dry up your rivers;’\n'),
	(13758, 20, 44, 28, 'Who says of Cyrus, ‘He is my shepherd, and shall perform all my pleasure,’\neven saying of Jerusalem, ‘She will be built;’\nand of the temple, ‘Your foundation will be laid.’”\n'),
	(13759, 20, 45, 1, 'Yahweh says to his anointed, to Cyrus, whose right hand I have held, to subdue nations before him, and strip kings of their armor; to open the doors before him, and the gates shall not be shut:\n'),
	(13760, 20, 45, 2, '“I will go before you,\nand make the rough places smooth.\nI will break the doors of brass in pieces,\nand cut apart the bars of iron.\n'),
	(13761, 20, 45, 3, 'I will give you the treasures of darkness,\nand hidden riches of secret places,\nthat you may know that it is I, Yahweh, who call you by your name,\neven the God of Israel.\n'),
	(13762, 20, 45, 4, 'For Jacob my servant’s sake,\nand Israel my chosen,\nI have called you by your name.\nI have given you a title,\nthough you have not known me.\n'),
	(13763, 20, 45, 5, 'I am Yahweh, and there is no one else.\nBesides me, there is no God.\nI will strengthen you,\nthough you have not known me;\n'),
	(13764, 20, 45, 6, 'that they may know from the rising of the sun,\nand from the west,\nthat there is no one besides me.\nI am Yahweh, and there is no one else.\n'),
	(13765, 20, 45, 7, 'I form the light,\nand create darkness.\nI make peace,\nand create calamity.\nI am Yahweh,\nwho does all these things.\n'),
	(13766, 20, 45, 8, 'Rain, you heavens, from above,\nand let the skies pour down righteousness.\nLet the earth open, that it may produce salvation,\nand let it cause righteousness to spring up with it.\nI, Yahweh, have created it.\n'),
	(13767, 20, 45, 9, 'Woe to him who strives with his Maker—\na clay pot among the clay pots of the earth!\nShall the clay ask him who fashions it, ‘What are you making?’\nor your work, ‘He has no hands?’\n'),
	(13768, 20, 45, 10, 'Woe to him who says to a father, ‘What have you become the father of?’\nor to a mother, ‘To what have you given birth?’”\n'),
	(13769, 20, 45, 11, 'Yahweh, the Holy One of Israel,\nand his Maker says:\n“You ask me about the things that are to come, concerning my sons,\nand you command me concerning the work of my hands!\n'),
	(13770, 20, 45, 12, 'I have made the earth, and created man on it.\nI, even my hands, have stretched out the heavens;\nand I have commanded all their army.\n'),
	(13771, 20, 45, 13, 'I have raised him up in righteousness,\nand I will make straight all his ways.\nHe shall build my city,\nand he shall let my exiles go free,\nnot for price nor reward,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(13772, 20, 45, 14, 'Yahweh says: “The labor of Egypt,\nand the merchandise of Ethiopia,\nand the Sabeans, men of stature, shall come over to you,\nand they shall be yours.\nThey will go after you.\nThey shall come over in chains;\nand they will bow down to you.\nThey will make supplication to you:\n‘Surely God is in you; and there is no one else.\nThere is no other god.\n'),
	(13773, 20, 45, 15, 'Most certainly you are a God who has hidden yourself,\nGod of Israel, the Savior.’”\n'),
	(13774, 20, 45, 16, 'They will be disappointed,\nyes, confounded, all of them.\nThose who are makers of idols will go into confusion together.\n'),
	(13775, 20, 45, 17, 'Israel will be saved by Yahweh with an everlasting salvation.\nYou will not be disappointed nor confounded to ages everlasting.\n'),
	(13776, 20, 45, 18, 'For Yahweh who created the heavens,\nthe God who formed the earth and made it,\nwho established it and didn’t create it a waste,\nwho formed it to be inhabited says:\n“I am Yahweh;\nand there is no other.\n'),
	(13777, 20, 45, 19, 'I have not spoken in secret,\nin a place of the land of darkness.\nI didn’t say to the offspring of Jacob, ‘Seek me in vain.’\nI, Yahweh, speak righteousness.\nI declare things that are right.\n'),
	(13778, 20, 45, 20, '“Assemble yourselves and come.\nDraw near together, you who have escaped from the nations.\nThose have no knowledge who carry the wood of their engraved image,\nand pray to a god that can’t save.\n'),
	(13779, 20, 45, 21, 'Declare and present it.\nYes, let them take counsel together.\nWho has shown this from ancient time?\nWho has declared it of old?\nHaven’t I, Yahweh?\nThere is no other God besides me, a just God and a Savior;\nThere is no one besides me.\n'),
	(13780, 20, 45, 22, '“Look to me, and be saved, all the ends of the earth;\nfor I am God, and there is no other.\n'),
	(13781, 20, 45, 23, 'I have sworn by myself.\nThe word has gone out of my mouth in righteousness, and will not be revoked,\nthat to me every knee shall bow,\nevery tongue shall take an oath.\n'),
	(13782, 20, 45, 24, 'They will say of me,\n‘There is righteousness and strength only in Yahweh.’”\nEven to him shall men come;\nand all those who raged against him shall be disappointed.\n'),
	(13783, 20, 45, 25, 'All the offspring of Israel will be justified in Yahweh,\nand will rejoice!\n'),
	(13784, 20, 46, 1, 'Bel bows down.\nNebo stoops.\nTheir idols are carried by animals,\nand on the livestock.\nThe things that you carried around are heavy loads,\na burden for the weary.\n'),
	(13785, 20, 46, 2, 'They stoop and they bow down together.\nThey could not deliver the burden,\nbut they have gone into captivity.\n'),
	(13786, 20, 46, 3, '“Listen to me, house of Jacob,\nand all the remnant of the house of Israel,\nthat have been carried from their birth,\nthat have been carried from the womb.\n'),
	(13787, 20, 46, 4, 'Even to old age I am he,\nand even to gray hairs I will carry you.\nI have made, and I will bear.\nYes, I will carry, and will deliver.\n'),
	(13788, 20, 46, 5, '“To whom will you compare me, and consider my equal,\nand compare me, as if we were the same?\n'),
	(13789, 20, 46, 6, 'Some pour out gold from the bag,\nand weigh silver in the balance.\nThey hire a goldsmith,\nand he makes it a god.\nThey fall down—\nyes, they worship.\n'),
	(13790, 20, 46, 7, 'They bear it on their shoulder.\nThey carry it, and set it in its place, and it stands there.\nIt cannot move from its place.\nYes, one may cry to it, yet it can not answer.\nIt cannot save him out of his trouble.\n'),
	(13791, 20, 46, 8, '“Remember this, and show yourselves men.\nBring it to mind again, you transgressors.\n'),
	(13792, 20, 46, 9, 'Remember the former things of old:\nfor I am God, and there is no other.\nI am God, and there is none like me.\n'),
	(13793, 20, 46, 10, 'I declare the end from the beginning,\nand from ancient times things that are not yet done.\nI say: My counsel will stand,\nand I will do all that I please.\n'),
	(13794, 20, 46, 11, 'I call a ravenous bird from the east,\nthe man of my counsel from a far country.\nYes, I have spoken.\nI will also bring it to pass.\nI have planned.\nI will also do it.\n'),
	(13795, 20, 46, 12, 'Listen to me, you stubborn-hearted,\nwho are far from righteousness!\n'),
	(13796, 20, 46, 13, 'I bring my righteousness near.\nIt is not far off,\nand my salvation will not wait.\nI will grant salvation to Zion,\nmy glory to Israel.\n'),
	(13797, 20, 47, 1, '“Come down, and sit in the dust, virgin daughter of Babylon.\nSit on the ground without a throne, daughter of the Chaldeans.\nFor you will no longer be called tender and delicate.\n'),
	(13798, 20, 47, 2, 'Take the millstones, and grind flour.\nRemove your veil, lift up your skirt, uncover your legs,\nand wade through the rivers.\n'),
	(13799, 20, 47, 3, 'Your nakedness will be uncovered.\nYes, your shame will be seen.\nI will take vengeance,\nand will spare no one.”\n'),
	(13800, 20, 47, 4, 'Our Redeemer, Yahweh of Armies is his name,\nis the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(13801, 20, 47, 5, '“Sit in silence, and go into darkness,\ndaughter of the Chaldeans.\nFor you shall no longer be called\nthe mistress of kingdoms.\n'),
	(13802, 20, 47, 6, 'I was angry with my people.\nI profaned my inheritance,\nand gave them into your hand.\nYou showed them no mercy.\nYou laid a very heavy yoke on the aged.\n'),
	(13803, 20, 47, 7, 'You said, ‘I will be a princess forever;’\nso that you did not lay these things to your heart,\nnor did you remember the results.\n'),
	(13804, 20, 47, 8, '“Now therefore hear this, you who are given to pleasures,\nwho sit securely,\nwho say in your heart,\n‘I am, and there is no one else besides me.\nI shall not sit as a widow,\nneither shall I know the loss of children.’\n'),
	(13805, 20, 47, 9, 'But these two things shall come to you in a moment in one day,\nthe loss of children and widowhood.\nThey will come on you in their full measure,\nin the multitude of your sorceries,\nand the great abundance of your enchantments.\n'),
	(13806, 20, 47, 10, 'For you have trusted in your wickedness.\nYou have said, ‘No one sees me.’\nYour wisdom and your knowledge has perverted you.\nYou have said in your heart, ‘I am, and there is no one else besides me.’\n'),
	(13807, 20, 47, 11, 'Therefore disaster will come on you.\nYou won’t know when it dawns.\nMischief will fall on you.\nYou won’t be able to put it away.\nDesolation will come on you suddenly,\nwhich you don’t understand.\n'),
	(13808, 20, 47, 12, '“Stand now with your enchantments,\nand with the multitude of your sorceries,\nin which you have labored from your youth;\nas if you might profit;\nas if you might prevail.\n'),
	(13809, 20, 47, 13, 'You are wearied in the multitude of your counsels.\nNow let the astrologers, the stargazers, and the monthly prognosticators, stand up and save you from the things that will come on you.\n'),
	(13810, 20, 47, 14, 'Behold, they are like stubble.\nThe fire will burn them.\nThey won’t deliver themselves from the power of the flame.\nIt won’t be a coal to warm at\nor a fire to sit by.\n'),
	(13811, 20, 47, 15, 'The things that you labored in will be like this:\nthose who have trafficked with you from your youth will each wander in his own way.\nThere will be no one to save you.\n'),
	(13812, 20, 48, 1, '“Hear this, house of Jacob,\nyou who are called by the name of Israel,\nand have come out of the waters of Judah.\nYou swear by Yahweh’s name,\nand make mention of the God of Israel,\nbut not in truth, nor in righteousness\n'),
	(13813, 20, 48, 2, '(for they call themselves citizens of the holy city,\nand rely on the God of Israel;\nYahweh of Armies is his name):\n'),
	(13814, 20, 48, 3, 'I have declared the former things from of old;\nyes, they went out of my mouth, and I revealed them.\nI did them suddenly, and they happened.\n'),
	(13815, 20, 48, 4, 'Because I knew that you are obstinate,\nand your neck is an iron sinew,\nand your brow brass;\n'),
	(13816, 20, 48, 5, 'therefore I have declared it to you from of old;\nbefore it came to pass I showed it to you;\nlest you should say, ‘My idol has done them, and my engraved image, and my molten image, has commanded them.’\n'),
	(13817, 20, 48, 6, 'You have heard it;\nsee all this.\nAnd you, won’t you declare it?\n“I have shown you new things from this time,\neven hidden things, which you have not known.\n'),
	(13818, 20, 48, 7, 'They are created now, and not from of old;\nand before today you didn’t hear them;\nlest you should say, ‘Behold, I knew them.’\n'),
	(13819, 20, 48, 8, 'Yes, you didn’t hear;\nyes, you didn’t know;\nyes, from of old your ear was not opened:\nfor I knew that you dealt very treacherously,\nand were called a transgressor from the womb.\n'),
	(13820, 20, 48, 9, 'For my name’s sake, I will defer my anger,\nand for my praise I hold it back for you,\nso that I don’t cut you off.\n'),
	(13821, 20, 48, 10, 'Behold, I have refined you,\nbut not as silver.\nI have chosen you in the furnace of affliction.\n'),
	(13822, 20, 48, 11, 'For my own sake,\nfor my own sake, I will do it;\nfor how would my name be profaned?\nI will not give my glory to another.\n'),
	(13823, 20, 48, 12, '“Listen to me, O Jacob,\nand Israel my called:\nI am he;\nI am the first,\nI am also the last.\n'),
	(13824, 20, 48, 13, 'Yes, my hand has laid the foundation of the earth,\nand my right hand has spread out the heavens.\nwhen I call to them, they stand up together.\n'),
	(13825, 20, 48, 14, '“Assemble yourselves, all of you, and hear;\nwho among them has declared these things?\nHe whom Yahweh loves will do what he likes to Babylon,\nand his arm will be against the Chaldeans.\n'),
	(13826, 20, 48, 15, 'I, even I, have spoken;\nyes, I have called him.\nI have brought him,\nand he shall make his way prosperous.\n'),
	(13827, 20, 48, 16, '“Come near to me and hear this:\n“From the beginning I have not spoken in secret;\nfrom the time that it happened, I was there.”\nNow the Lord Yahweh has sent me,\nwith his Spirit.\n'),
	(13828, 20, 48, 17, 'Yahweh,\nyour Redeemer,\nthe Holy One of Israel says:\n“I am Yahweh your God,\nwho teaches you to profit,\nwho leads you by the way that you should go.\n'),
	(13829, 20, 48, 18, 'Oh that you had listened to my commandments!\nThen your peace would have been like a river,\nand your righteousness like the waves of the sea.\n'),
	(13830, 20, 48, 19, 'Your offspring also would have been as the sand,\nand the descendants of your body like its grains.\nHis name would not be cut off nor destroyed from before me.”\n'),
	(13831, 20, 48, 20, 'Leave Babylon!\nFlee from the Chaldeans!\nWith a voice of singing announce this,\ntell it even to the end of the earth:\nsay, “Yahweh has redeemed his servant Jacob!”\n'),
	(13832, 20, 48, 21, 'They didn’t thirst when he led them through the deserts.\nHe caused the waters to flow out of the rock for them.\nHe split the rock also, and the waters gushed out.\n'),
	(13833, 20, 48, 22, '“There is no peace”, says Yahweh, “for the wicked.”\n'),
	(13834, 20, 49, 1, 'Listen, islands, to me.\nListen, you peoples, from afar:\nYahweh has called me from the womb;\nfrom the inside of my mother he has mentioned my name.\n'),
	(13835, 20, 49, 2, 'He has made my mouth like a sharp sword.\nHe has hidden me in the shadow of his hand.\nHe has made me a polished shaft.\nHe has kept me close in his quiver.\n'),
	(13836, 20, 49, 3, 'He said to me, “You are my servant;\nIsrael, in whom I will be glorified.”\n'),
	(13837, 20, 49, 4, 'But I said, “I have labored in vain.\nI have spent my strength in vain for nothing;\nyet surely the justice due to me is with Yahweh,\nand my reward with my God.”\n'),
	(13838, 20, 49, 5, 'Now Yahweh says, he who formed me from the womb to be his servant,\nto bring Jacob again to him,\nand to gather Israel to him,\nfor I am honorable in Yahweh’s eyes,\nand my God has become my strength.\n'),
	(13839, 20, 49, 6, 'Indeed, he says, “It is too light a thing that you should be my servant to raise up the tribes of Jacob,\nand to restore the preserved of Israel?\nI will also give you as a light to the nations,\nthat you may be my salvation to the end of the earth.”\n'),
	(13840, 20, 49, 7, 'Yahweh, the Redeemer of Israel, and his Holy One,\nsays to him whom man despises, to him whom the nation abhors, to a servant of rulers:\n“Kings shall see and rise up;\nprinces, and they shall worship;\nbecause of Yahweh who is faithful, even the Holy One of Israel, who has chosen you.”\n'),
	(13841, 20, 49, 8, 'Yahweh says, “In an acceptable time I have answered you,\nand in a day of salvation I have helped you.\nI will preserve you, and give you for a covenant of the people,\nto raise up the land, to make them inherit the desolate heritage,\n'),
	(13842, 20, 49, 9, 'saying to those who are bound, ‘Come out!’;\nto those who are in darkness, ‘Show yourselves!’\n“They shall feed along the paths,\nand their pasture shall be on all treeless heights.\n'),
	(13843, 20, 49, 10, 'They shall not hunger nor thirst;\nneither shall the heat nor sun strike them:\nfor he who has mercy on them will lead them.\nHe will guide them by springs of water.\n'),
	(13844, 20, 49, 11, 'I will make all my mountains a road,\nand my highways shall be exalted.\n'),
	(13845, 20, 49, 12, 'Behold, these shall come from afar;\nand behold, these from the north and from the west;\nand these from the land of Sinim.”\n'),
	(13846, 20, 49, 13, 'Sing, heavens; and be joyful, earth;\nand break out into singing, mountains:\nfor Yahweh has comforted his people,\nand will have compassion on his afflicted.\n'),
	(13847, 20, 49, 14, 'But Zion said, “Yahweh has forsaken me,\nand the Lord has forgotten me.”\n'),
	(13848, 20, 49, 15, '“Can a woman forget her nursing child,\nthat she should not have compassion on the son of her womb?\nYes, these may forget,\nyet I will not forget you!\n'),
	(13849, 20, 49, 16, 'Behold, I have engraved you on the palms of my hands.\nyour walls are continually before me.\n'),
	(13850, 20, 49, 17, 'Your children hurry.\nYour destroyers and those who devastated you will leave you.\n'),
	(13851, 20, 49, 18, 'Lift up your eyes all around, and see:\nall these gather themselves together, and come to you.\nAs I live,” says Yahweh, “you shall surely clothe yourself with them all as with an ornament,\nand dress yourself with them, like a bride.\n'),
	(13852, 20, 49, 19, '“For, as for your waste and your desolate places,\nand your land that has been destroyed,\nsurely now that land will be too small for the inhabitants,\nand those who swallowed you up will be far away.\n'),
	(13853, 20, 49, 20, 'The children of your bereavement will say in your ears,\n‘This place is too small for me.\nGive me a place to live in.’\n'),
	(13854, 20, 49, 21, 'Then you will say in your heart, ‘Who has conceived these for me, since I have been bereaved of my children,\nand am solitary, an exile, and wandering back and forth?\nWho has brought these up?\nBehold, I was left alone. Where were these?’”\n'),
	(13855, 20, 49, 22, 'Thus says the Lord Yahweh, “Behold, I will lift up my hand to the nations,\nand lift up my banner to the peoples;\nand they shall bring your sons in their bosom,\nand your daughters shall be carried on their shoulders.\n'),
	(13856, 20, 49, 23, 'Kings shall be your foster fathers,\nand their queens your nursing mothers.\nThey will bow down to you with their faces to the earth,\nand lick the dust of your feet;\nThen you will know that I am Yahweh;\nand those who wait for me shall not be disappointed.”\n'),
	(13857, 20, 49, 24, 'Shall the plunder be taken from the mighty,\nor the lawful captives be delivered?\n'),
	(13858, 20, 49, 25, 'But Yahweh says, “Even the captives of the mighty shall be taken away,\nand the plunder retrieved from the fierce;\nfor I will contend with him who contends with you,\nand I will save your children.\n'),
	(13859, 20, 49, 26, 'I will feed those who oppress you with their own flesh;\nand they will be drunk on their own blood, as with sweet wine.\nThen all flesh shall know that I, Yahweh, am your Savior,\nand your Redeemer, the Mighty One of Jacob.”\n'),
	(13860, 20, 50, 1, 'Yahweh says, “Where is the bill of your mother’s divorce, with which I have put her away?\nor to which of my creditors have I sold you?\nBehold, you were sold for your iniquities,\nand your mother was put away for your transgressions.\n'),
	(13861, 20, 50, 2, 'Why, when I came, was there no one?\nwhen I called, why was there no one to answer?\nIs my hand shortened at all, that it can’t redeem?\nor have I no power to deliver?\nBehold, at my rebuke I dry up the sea.\nI make the rivers a wilderness:\ntheir fish stink, because there is no water, and die for thirst.\n'),
	(13862, 20, 50, 3, 'I clothe the heavens with blackness,\nand I make sackcloth their covering.”\n'),
	(13863, 20, 50, 4, 'The Lord Yahweh has given me the tongue of those who are taught,\nthat I may know how to sustain with words him who is weary.\nHe wakens morning by morning,\nhe wakens my ear to hear as those who are taught.\n'),
	(13864, 20, 50, 5, 'The Lord Yahweh has opened my ear,\nand I was not rebellious.\nI have not turned back.\n'),
	(13865, 20, 50, 6, 'I gave my back to those who beat me,\nand my cheeks to those who plucked off the hair.\nI didn’t hide my face from shame and spitting.\n'),
	(13866, 20, 50, 7, 'For the Lord Yahweh will help me.\nTherefore I have not been confounded.\nTherefore I have set my face like a flint,\nand I know that I shall not be disappointed.\n'),
	(13867, 20, 50, 8, 'He who justifies me is near.\nWho will bring charges against me?\nLet us stand up together.\nWho is my adversary?\nLet him come near to me.\n'),
	(13868, 20, 50, 9, 'Behold, the Lord Yahweh will help me!\nWho is he who will condemn me?\nBehold, they will all grow old like a garment.\nThe moths will eat them up.\n'),
	(13869, 20, 50, 10, 'Who among you fears Yahweh,\nand obeys the voice of his servant?\nHe who walks in darkness,\nand has no light,\nlet him trust in Yahweh’s name,\nand rely on his God.\n'),
	(13870, 20, 50, 11, 'Behold, all you who kindle a fire,\nwho adorn yourselves with torches around yourselves;\nwalk in the flame of your fire,\nand among the torches that you have kindled.\nYou will have this from my hand:\nYou will lie down in sorrow.\n'),
	(13871, 20, 51, 1, '“Listen to me, you who follow after righteousness,\nyou who seek Yahweh:\nlook to the rock you were cut from,\nand to the quarry you were dug from.\n'),
	(13872, 20, 51, 2, 'Look to Abraham your father,\nand to Sarah who bore you;\nfor when he was but one I called him,\nand I blessed him,\nand made him many.\n'),
	(13873, 20, 51, 3, 'For Yahweh has comforted Zion.\nHe has comforted all her waste places,\nand has made her wilderness like Eden,\nand her desert like the garden of Yahweh.\nJoy and gladness will be found therein,\nthanksgiving, and the voice of melody.\n'),
	(13874, 20, 51, 4, '“Listen to me, my people;\nand hear me, my nation:\nfor a law will go out from me,\nand I will establish my justice for a light to the peoples.\n'),
	(13875, 20, 51, 5, 'My righteousness is near.\nMy salvation has gone out,\nand my arms will judge the peoples.\nThe islands will wait for me,\nand they will trust my arm.\n'),
	(13876, 20, 51, 6, 'Lift up your eyes to the heavens,\nand look on the earth beneath;\nfor the heavens will vanish away like smoke,\nand the earth will wear out like a garment;\nand its inhabitants will die in the same way:\nbut my salvation will be forever,\nand my righteousness will not be abolished.\n'),
	(13877, 20, 51, 7, '“Listen to me, you who know righteousness,\nthe people in whose heart is my law:\nDon’t fear the reproach of men,\nand don’t be dismayed at their insults.\n'),
	(13878, 20, 51, 8, 'For the moth will eat them up like a garment,\nand the worm will eat them like wool;\nbut my righteousness will be forever,\nand my salvation to all generations.”\n'),
	(13879, 20, 51, 9, 'Awake, awake, put on strength, arm of Yahweh!\nAwake, as in the days of old,\nthe generations of ancient times.\nIsn’t it you who cut Rahab in pieces,\nwho pierced the monster?\n'),
	(13880, 20, 51, 10, 'Isn’t it you who dried up the sea,\nthe waters of the great deep;\nwho made the depths of the sea a way for the redeemed to pass over?\n'),
	(13881, 20, 51, 11, 'Those ransomed by Yahweh will return,\nand come with singing to Zion;\nand everlasting joy shall be on their heads.\nThey will obtain gladness and joy.\nSorrow and sighing shall flee away.\n'),
	(13882, 20, 51, 12, '“I, even I, am he who comforts you.\nWho are you, that you are afraid of man who shall die,\nand of the son of man who will be made as grass?\n'),
	(13883, 20, 51, 13, 'Have you forgotten Yahweh your Maker,\nwho stretched out the heavens,\nand laid the foundations of the earth?\nDo you live in fear continually all day because of the fury of the oppressor,\nwhen he prepares to destroy?\nWhere is the fury of the oppressor?\n'),
	(13884, 20, 51, 14, 'The captive exile will speedily be freed;\nand he will not die and go down into the pit,\nand his bread will not fail.\n'),
	(13885, 20, 51, 15, 'For I am Yahweh your God, who stirs up the sea,\nso that its waves roar:\nYahweh of Armies is his name.\n'),
	(13886, 20, 51, 16, 'I have put my words in your mouth,\nand have covered you in the shadow of my hand,\nthat I may plant the heavens,\nand lay the foundations of the earth,\nand tell Zion, ‘You are my people.’”\n'),
	(13887, 20, 51, 17, 'Awake, awake!\nStand up, Jerusalem,\nyou who have drunk from Yahweh’s hand the cup of his wrath.\nYou have drunken the bowl of the cup of staggering,\nand drained it.\n'),
	(13888, 20, 51, 18, 'There is no one to guide her among all the sons to whom she has given birth;\nand there is no one who takes her by the hand among all the sons who she has brought up.\n'),
	(13889, 20, 51, 19, 'These two things have happened to you—\nwho will grieve with you?—\ndesolation and destruction,\nand famine and the sword.\nHow can I comfort you?\n'),
	(13890, 20, 51, 20, 'Your sons have fainted.\nThey lie at the head of all the streets,\nlike an antelope in a net.\nThey are full of the Yahweh’s wrath,\nthe rebuke of your God.\n'),
	(13891, 20, 51, 21, 'Therefore now hear this, you afflicted,\nand drunken, but not with wine:\n'),
	(13892, 20, 51, 22, 'Thus says your Lord Yahweh,\nyour God who pleads the cause of his people,\n“Behold, I have taken out of your hand the cup of staggering,\neven the bowl of the cup of my wrath.\nYou will not drink it any more:\n'),
	(13893, 20, 51, 23, 'and I will put it into the hand of those who afflict you,\nwho have said to your soul, ‘Bow down, that we may walk over you;’\nand you have laid your back as the ground,\nlike a street to those who walk over.”\n'),
	(13894, 20, 52, 1, 'Awake, awake! Put on your strength, Zion.\nPut on your beautiful garments, Jerusalem, the holy city:\nfor from now on the uncircumcised and the unclean will no more come into you.\n'),
	(13895, 20, 52, 2, 'Shake yourself from the dust!\nArise, sit up, Jerusalem!\nRelease yourself from the bonds of your neck, captive daughter of Zion!\n'),
	(13896, 20, 52, 3, 'For Yahweh says, “You were sold for nothing;\nand you will be redeemed without money.”\n'),
	(13897, 20, 52, 4, 'For thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“My people went down at the first into Egypt to live there:\nand the Assyrian has oppressed them without cause.\n'),
	(13898, 20, 52, 5, '“Now therefore, what do I do here,” says Yahweh,\n“seeing that my people are taken away for nothing?\nThose who rule over them mock,” says Yahweh,\n“and my name is blasphemed continually all day long.\n'),
	(13899, 20, 52, 6, 'Therefore my people shall know my name.\nTherefore they shall know in that day that I am he who speaks.\nBehold, it is I.”\n'),
	(13900, 20, 52, 7, 'How beautiful on the mountains are the feet of him who brings good news,\nwho publishes peace,\nwho brings good news,\nwho proclaims salvation,\nwho says to Zion, “Your God reigns!”\n'),
	(13901, 20, 52, 8, 'Your watchmen lift up their voice,\ntogether they sing;\nfor they shall see eye to eye, when Yahweh returns to Zion.\n'),
	(13902, 20, 52, 9, 'Break out into joy,\nsing together, you waste places of Jerusalem;\nfor Yahweh has comforted his people.\nHe has redeemed Jerusalem.\n'),
	(13903, 20, 52, 10, 'Yahweh has made bare his holy arm in the eyes of all the nations;\nand all the ends of the earth have seen the salvation of our God.\n'),
	(13904, 20, 52, 11, 'Depart, depart, go out from there; touch no unclean thing!\nGo out from among her!\nCleanse yourselves, you who carry Yahweh’s vessels.\n'),
	(13905, 20, 52, 12, 'For you shall not go out in haste,\nneither shall you go by flight:\nfor Yahweh will go before you;\nand the God of Israel will be your rear guard.\n'),
	(13906, 20, 52, 13, 'Behold, my servant will deal wisely.\nHe will be exalted and lifted up,\nand will be very high.\n'),
	(13907, 20, 52, 14, 'Just as many were astonished at you\n(his appearance was marred more than any man, and his form more than the sons of men),\n'),
	(13908, 20, 52, 15, 'so he will cleanse many nations.\nKings will shut their mouths at him:\nfor they will see that which had not been told them;\nand they will understand that which they had not heard.\n'),
	(13909, 20, 53, 1, 'Who has believed our message?\nTo whom has the arm of Yahweh been revealed?\n'),
	(13910, 20, 53, 2, 'For he grew up before him as a tender plant,\nand as a root out of dry ground.\nHe has no good looks or majesty.\nWhen we see him, there is no beauty that we should desire him.\n'),
	(13911, 20, 53, 3, 'He was despised,\nand rejected by men;\na man of suffering,\nand acquainted with disease.\nHe was despised as one from whom men hide their face;\nand we didn’t respect him.\n'),
	(13912, 20, 53, 4, 'Surely he has borne our sickness,\nand carried our suffering;\nyet we considered him plagued,\nstruck by God, and afflicted.\n'),
	(13913, 20, 53, 5, 'But he was pierced for our transgressions.\nHe was crushed for our iniquities.\nThe punishment that brought our peace was on him;\nand by his wounds we are healed.\n'),
	(13914, 20, 53, 6, 'All we like sheep have gone astray.\nEveryone has turned to his own way;\nand Yahweh has laid on him the iniquity of us all.\n'),
	(13915, 20, 53, 7, 'He was oppressed,\nyet when he was afflicted he didn’t open his mouth.\nAs a lamb that is led to the slaughter,\nand as a sheep that before its shearers is silent,\nso he didn’t open his mouth.\n'),
	(13916, 20, 53, 8, 'He was taken away by oppression and judgment;\nand as for his generation,\nwho considered that he was cut off out of the land of the living\nand stricken for the disobedience of my people?\n'),
	(13917, 20, 53, 9, 'They made his grave with the wicked,\nand with a rich man in his death;\nalthough he had done no violence,\nnor was any deceit in his mouth.\n'),
	(13918, 20, 53, 10, 'Yet it pleased Yahweh to bruise him.\nHe has caused him to suffer.\nWhen you make his soul an offering for sin,\nhe will see his offspring.\nHe will prolong his days,\nand Yahweh’s pleasure will prosper in his hand.\n'),
	(13919, 20, 53, 11, 'After the suffering of his soul,\nhe will see the light and be satisfied.\nMy righteous servant will justify many by the knowledge of himself;\nand he will bear their iniquities.\n'),
	(13920, 20, 53, 12, 'Therefore will I give him a portion with the great,\nand he will divide the plunder with the strong;\nbecause he poured out his soul to death,\nand was counted with the transgressors;\nyet he bore the sin of many,\nand made intercession for the transgressors.\n'),
	(13921, 20, 54, 1, '“Sing, barren, you who didn’t give birth;\nbreak out into singing, and cry aloud, you who did not travail with child:\nfor more are the children of the desolate than the children of the married wife,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(13922, 20, 54, 2, '“Enlarge the place of your tent,\nand let them stretch out the curtains of your habitations;\ndon’t spare: lengthen your cords, and strengthen your stakes.\n'),
	(13923, 20, 54, 3, 'For you will spread out on the right hand and on the left;\nand your offspring will possess the nations,\nand settle in desolate cities.\n'),
	(13924, 20, 54, 4, '“Don’t be afraid; for you will not be ashamed.\nDon’t be confounded; for you will not be disappointed.\nFor you will forget the shame of your youth;\nand the reproach of your widowhood you shall remember no more.\n'),
	(13925, 20, 54, 5, 'For your Maker is your husband; Yahweh of Armies is his name.\nThe Holy One of Israel is your Redeemer.\nHe will be called the God of the whole earth.\n'),
	(13926, 20, 54, 6, 'For Yahweh has called you as a wife forsaken and grieved in spirit,\neven a wife of youth, when she is cast off,” says your God.\n'),
	(13927, 20, 54, 7, '“For a small moment I have forsaken you;\nbut with great mercies will I gather you.\n'),
	(13928, 20, 54, 8, 'In overflowing wrath I hid my face from you for a moment;\nbut with everlasting loving kindness I will have mercy on you,” says Yahweh your Redeemer.\n'),
	(13929, 20, 54, 9, '“For this is like the waters of Noah to me;\nfor as I have sworn that the waters of Noah will no more go over the earth,\nso I have sworn that I will not be angry with you, nor rebuke you.\n'),
	(13930, 20, 54, 10, 'For the mountains may depart,\nand the hills be removed;\nbut my loving kindness will not depart from you,\nand my covenant of peace will not be removed,”\nsays Yahweh who has mercy on you.\n'),
	(13931, 20, 54, 11, '“You afflicted, tossed with storms, and not comforted,\nbehold, I will set your stones in beautiful colors,\nand lay your foundations with sapphires.\n'),
	(13932, 20, 54, 12, 'I will make your pinnacles of rubies,\nyour gates of sparkling jewels,\nand all your walls of precious stones.\n'),
	(13933, 20, 54, 13, 'All your children will be taught by Yahweh;\nand your children’s peace will be great.\n'),
	(13934, 20, 54, 14, 'In righteousness you will be established.\nYou will be far from oppression,\nfor you will not be afraid;\nand far from terror,\nfor it shall not come near you.\n'),
	(13935, 20, 54, 15, 'Behold, they may gather together, but not by me.\nWhoever gathers together against you will fall because of you.\n'),
	(13936, 20, 54, 16, '“Behold, I have created the blacksmith who fans the coals into flame,\nand forges a weapon for his work;\nand I have created the destroyer to destroy.\n'),
	(13937, 20, 54, 17, 'No weapon that is formed against you will prevail;\nand you will condemn every tongue that rises against you in judgment.\nThis is the heritage of Yahweh’s servants,\nand their righteousness is of me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(13938, 20, 55, 1, '“Hey! Come, everyone who thirsts, to the waters!\nCome, he who has no money, buy, and eat!\nYes, come, buy wine and milk without money and without price.\n'),
	(13939, 20, 55, 2, 'Why do you spend money for that which is not bread,\nand your labor for that which doesn’t satisfy?\nListen diligently to me, and eat that which is good,\nand let your soul delight itself in richness.\n'),
	(13940, 20, 55, 3, 'Turn your ear, and come to me.\nHear, and your soul will live:\nand I will make an everlasting covenant with you, even the sure mercies of David.\n'),
	(13941, 20, 55, 4, 'Behold, I have given him for a witness to the peoples,\na leader and commander to the peoples.\n'),
	(13942, 20, 55, 5, 'Behold, you shall call a nation that you don’t know;\nand a nation that didn’t know you shall run to you,\nbecause of Yahweh your God,\nand for the Holy One of Israel;\nfor he has glorified you.”\n'),
	(13943, 20, 55, 6, 'Seek Yahweh while he may be found.\nCall on him while he is near.\n'),
	(13944, 20, 55, 7, 'Let the wicked forsake his way,\nand the unrighteous man his thoughts.\nLet him return to Yahweh, and he will have mercy on him;\nand to our God, for he will freely pardon.\n'),
	(13945, 20, 55, 8, '“For my thoughts are not your thoughts,\nand your ways are not my ways,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(13946, 20, 55, 9, '“For as the heavens are higher than the earth,\nso are my ways higher than your ways,\nand my thoughts than your thoughts.\n'),
	(13947, 20, 55, 10, 'For as the rain comes down and the snow from the sky,\nand doesn’t return there, but waters the earth,\nand makes it grow and bud,\nand gives seed to the sower and bread to the eater;\n'),
	(13948, 20, 55, 11, 'so is my word that goes out of my mouth:\nit will not return to me void,\nbut it will accomplish that which I please,\nand it will prosper in the thing I sent it to do.\n'),
	(13949, 20, 55, 12, 'For you shall go out with joy,\nand be led out with peace.\nThe mountains and the hills will break out before you into singing;\nand all the trees of the fields will clap their hands.\n'),
	(13950, 20, 55, 13, 'Instead of the thorn the cypress tree will come up;\nand instead of the brier the myrtle tree will come up:\nand it will make a name for Yahweh,\nfor an everlasting sign that will not be cut off.”\n'),
	(13951, 20, 56, 1, 'Yahweh says,\n“Maintain justice,\nand do what is right;\nfor my salvation is near,\nand my righteousness will soon be revealed.\n'),
	(13952, 20, 56, 2, 'Blessed is the man who does this,\nand the son of man who holds it fast;\nwho keeps the Sabbath without profaning it,\nand keeps his hand from doing any evil.”\n'),
	(13953, 20, 56, 3, 'Let no foreigner, who has joined himself to Yahweh, speak, saying,\n“Yahweh will surely separate me from his people.”\nDo not let the eunuch say, “Behold, I am a dry tree.”\n'),
	(13954, 20, 56, 4, 'For Yahweh says, “To the eunuchs who keep my Sabbaths,\nand choose the things that please me,\nand hold fast to my covenant:\n'),
	(13955, 20, 56, 5, 'I will give them in my house and within my walls a memorial and a name better than of sons and of daughters.\nI will give them an everlasting name, that will not be cut off.\n'),
	(13956, 20, 56, 6, 'Also the foreigners who join themselves to Yahweh,\nto serve him,\nand to love Yahweh’s name,\nto be his servants,\neveryone who keeps the Sabbath from profaning it,\nand holds fast my covenant;\n'),
	(13957, 20, 56, 7, 'I will bring these to my holy mountain,\nand make them joyful in my house of prayer.\nTheir burnt offerings and their sacrifices will be accepted on my altar;\nfor my house will be called a house of prayer for all peoples.”\n'),
	(13958, 20, 56, 8, 'The Lord Yahweh, who gathers the outcasts of Israel, says,\n“I will yet gather others to him,\nbesides his own who are gathered.”\n'),
	(13959, 20, 56, 9, 'All you animals of the field,\ncome to devour,\nall you animals in the forest.\n'),
	(13960, 20, 56, 10, 'His watchmen are blind.\nThey are all without knowledge.\nThey are all mute dogs.\nThey can’t bark;\ndreaming, lying down, loving to slumber.\n'),
	(13961, 20, 56, 11, 'Yes, the dogs are greedy.\nThey can never have enough.\nThey are shepherds who can’t understand.\nThey have all turned to their own way,\neach one to his gain, from every quarter.\n'),
	(13962, 20, 56, 12, '“Come,” say they, “I will get wine,\nand we will fill ourselves with strong drink;\nand tomorrow will be as today,\ngreat beyond measure.”\n'),
	(13963, 20, 57, 1, 'The righteous perish,\nand no one lays it to heart.\nMerciful men are taken away,\nand no one considers that the righteous is taken away from the evil.\n'),
	(13964, 20, 57, 2, 'He enters into peace.\nThey rest in their beds,\neach one who walks in his uprightness.\n'),
	(13965, 20, 57, 3, '“But draw near here, you sons of a sorceress,\nyou offspring of adulterers and prostitutes.\n'),
	(13966, 20, 57, 4, 'Whom do you mock?\nAgainst whom do you make a wide mouth,\nand stick out your tongue?\nAren’t you children of disobedience,\nand offspring of falsehood,\n'),
	(13967, 20, 57, 5, 'you who inflame yourselves among the oaks,\nunder every green tree;\nwho kill the children in the valleys,\nunder the clefts of the rocks?\n'),
	(13968, 20, 57, 6, 'Among the smooth stones of the valley is your portion;\nthey, they are your lot.\nYou have even poured a drink offering to them.\nYou have offered an offering.\nShall I be appeased for these things?\n'),
	(13969, 20, 57, 7, 'On a high and lofty mountain you have set your bed.\nYou also went up there to offer sacrifice.\n'),
	(13970, 20, 57, 8, 'You have set up your memorial behind the doors and the posts;\nfor you have exposed yourself to someone besides me,\nand have gone up;\nyou have enlarged your bed,\nand made you a covenant with them.\nYou loved what you saw on their bed.\n'),
	(13971, 20, 57, 9, 'You went to the king with oil,\nand increased your perfumes,\nand sent your ambassadors far off,\nand degraded yourself even to Sheol.\n'),
	(13972, 20, 57, 10, 'You were wearied with the length of your ways;\nyet you didn’t say, ‘It is in vain.’\nYou found a reviving of your strength;\ntherefore you weren’t faint.\n'),
	(13973, 20, 57, 11, '“Whom have you dreaded and feared,\nso that you lie,\nand have not remembered me, nor laid it to your heart?\nHaven’t I held my peace for a long time,\nand you don’t fear me?\n'),
	(13974, 20, 57, 12, 'I will declare your righteousness;\nand as for your works, they will not benefit you.\n'),
	(13975, 20, 57, 13, 'When you cry,\nlet those whom you have gathered deliver you;\nbut the wind will take them.\na breath will carry them all away:\nbut he who takes refuge in me will possess the land,\nand will inherit my holy mountain.”\n'),
	(13976, 20, 57, 14, 'He will say, “Build up, build up, prepare the way!\nRemove the stumbling-block out of the way of my people.”\n'),
	(13977, 20, 57, 15, 'For thus says the high and lofty One who inhabits eternity,\nwhose name is Holy:\n“I dwell in the high and holy place, with him also who is of a contrite and humble spirit,\nto revive the spirit of the humble,\nand to revive the heart of the contrite.\n'),
	(13978, 20, 57, 16, 'For I will not contend forever, neither will I be always angry;\nfor the spirit would faint before me,\nand the souls whom I have made.\n'),
	(13979, 20, 57, 17, 'I was angry because of the iniquity of his covetousness, and struck him;\nI hid myself and was angry;\nand he went on backsliding in the way of his heart.\n'),
	(13980, 20, 57, 18, 'I have seen his ways, and will heal him:\nI will lead him also,\nand restore comforts to him and to his mourners.\n'),
	(13981, 20, 57, 19, 'I create the fruit of the lips:\nPeace, peace, to him who is far off and to him who is near,”\nsays Yahweh; “and I will heal them.”\n'),
	(13982, 20, 57, 20, 'But the wicked are like the troubled sea;\nfor it can’t rest, and its waters cast up mire and mud.\n'),
	(13983, 20, 57, 21, '“There is no peace”, says my God,\n“for the wicked.”\n'),
	(13984, 20, 58, 1, '“Cry aloud, don’t spare.\nLift up your voice like a trumpet.\nDeclare to my people their disobedience,\nand to the house of Jacob their sins.\n'),
	(13985, 20, 58, 2, 'Yet they seek me daily,\nand delight to know my ways.\nAs a nation that did righteousness,\nand didn’t forsake the ordinance of their God,\nthey ask of me righteous judgments.\nThey delight to draw near to God.\n'),
	(13986, 20, 58, 3, '‘Why have we fasted,’ say they, ‘and you don’t see?\nWhy have we afflicted our soul, and you don’t notice?’\n“Behold, in the day of your fast you find pleasure,\nand oppress all your laborers.\n'),
	(13987, 20, 58, 4, 'Behold, you fast for strife and contention,\nand to strike with the fist of wickedness.\nYou don’t fast today so as to make your voice to be heard on high.\n'),
	(13988, 20, 58, 5, 'Is this the fast that I have chosen?\nA day for a man to humble his soul?\nIs it to bow down his head like a reed,\nand to spread sackcloth and ashes under himself?\nWill you call this a fast,\nand an acceptable day to Yahweh?\n'),
	(13989, 20, 58, 6, '“Isn’t this the fast that I have chosen:\nto release the bonds of wickedness,\nto undo the straps of the yoke,\nto let the oppressed go free,\nand that you break every yoke?\n'),
	(13990, 20, 58, 7, 'Isn’t it to distribute your bread to the hungry,\nand that you bring the poor who are cast out to your house?\nWhen you see the naked,\nthat you cover him;\nand that you not hide yourself from your own flesh?\n'),
	(13991, 20, 58, 8, 'Then your light will break out as the morning,\nand your healing will appear quickly;\nthen your righteousness shall go before you;\nand Yahweh’s glory will be your rear guard.\n'),
	(13992, 20, 58, 9, 'Then you will call, and Yahweh will answer;\nyou will cry for help, and he will say, ‘Here I am.’\n“If you take away from among you the yoke,\nfinger pointing,\nand speaking wickedly;\n'),
	(13993, 20, 58, 10, 'and if you pour out your soul to the hungry,\nand satisfy the afflicted soul:\nthen your light will rise in darkness,\nand your obscurity will be as the noonday;\n'),
	(13994, 20, 58, 11, 'and Yahweh will guide you continually,\nand satisfy your soul in dry places,\nand make your bones strong;\nand you shall be like a watered garden,\nand like a spring of water,\nwhose waters don’t fail.\n'),
	(13995, 20, 58, 12, 'Those who shall be of you shall build the old waste places;\nyou shall raise up the foundations of many generations;\nand you shall be called Repairer of the Breach,\nRestorer of Paths with Dwellings.\n'),
	(13996, 20, 58, 13, '“If you turn away your foot from the Sabbath,\nfrom doing your pleasure on my holy day;\nand call the Sabbath a delight,\nand the holy of Yahweh honorable;\nand shall honor it,\nnot doing your own ways,\nnor finding your own pleasure,\nnor speaking your own words:\n'),
	(13997, 20, 58, 14, 'then you shall delight yourself in Yahweh;\nand I will make you to ride on the high places of the earth;\nand I will feed you with the heritage of Jacob your father:”\nfor Yahweh’s mouth has spoken it.\n'),
	(13998, 20, 59, 1, 'Behold, Yahweh’s hand is not shortened, that it can’t save;\nnor his ear dull, that it can’t hear.\n'),
	(13999, 20, 59, 2, 'But your iniquities have separated you and your God,\nand your sins have hidden his face from you,\nso that he will not hear.\n'),
	(14000, 20, 59, 3, 'For your hands are defiled with blood,\nand your fingers with iniquity.\nYour lips have spoken lies.\nYour tongue mutters wickedness.\n'),
	(14001, 20, 59, 4, 'No one sues in righteousness,\nand no one pleads in truth.\nThey trust in vanity,\nand speak lies.\nThey conceive mischief,\nand give birth to iniquity.\n'),
	(14002, 20, 59, 5, 'They hatch adders’ eggs,\nand weave the spider’s web.\nHe who eats of their eggs dies;\nand that which is crushed breaks out into a viper.\n'),
	(14003, 20, 59, 6, 'Their webs won’t become garments.\nThey won’t cover themselves with their works.\nTheir works are works of iniquity,\nand acts of violence are in their hands.\n'),
	(14004, 20, 59, 7, 'Their feet run to evil,\nand they hurry to shed innocent blood.\nTheir thoughts are thoughts of iniquity.\ndesolation and destruction are in their paths.\n'),
	(14005, 20, 59, 8, 'They don’t know the way of peace;\nand there is no justice in their ways.\nThey have made crooked paths for themselves;\nwhoever goes in them doesn’t know peace.\n'),
	(14006, 20, 59, 9, 'Therefore is justice far from us,\nand righteousness doesn’t overtake us.\nWe look for light, but see darkness;\nfor brightness, but we walk in obscurity.\n'),
	(14007, 20, 59, 10, 'We grope for the wall like the blind.\nYes, we grope as those who have no eyes.\nWe stumble at noon as if it were twilight.\nAmong those who are strong, we are like dead men.\n'),
	(14008, 20, 59, 11, 'We all roar like bears,\nand moan bitterly like doves.\nWe look for justice, but there is none;\nfor salvation, but it is far off from us.\n'),
	(14009, 20, 59, 12, 'For our transgressions are multiplied before you,\nand our sins testify against us;\nfor our transgressions are with us,\nand as for our iniquities, we know them:\n'),
	(14010, 20, 59, 13, 'transgressing and denying Yahweh,\nand turning away from following our God,\nspeaking oppression and revolt,\nconceiving and uttering from the heart words of falsehood.\n'),
	(14011, 20, 59, 14, 'Justice is turned away backward,\nand righteousness stands far away;\nfor truth has fallen in the street,\nand uprightness can’t enter.\n'),
	(14012, 20, 59, 15, 'Yes, truth is lacking;\nand he who departs from evil makes himself a prey.\nYahweh saw it,\nand it displeased him that there was no justice.\n'),
	(14013, 20, 59, 16, 'He saw that there was no man,\nand wondered that there was no intercessor.\nTherefore his own arm brought salvation to him;\nand his righteousness sustained him.\n'),
	(14014, 20, 59, 17, 'He put on righteousness as a breastplate,\nand a helmet of salvation on his head.\nHe put on garments of vengeance for clothing,\nand was clad with zeal as a mantle.\n'),
	(14015, 20, 59, 18, 'According to their deeds,\nhe will repay as appropriate,\nwrath to his adversaries,\nrecompense to his enemies;\nhe will repay the islands their due.\n'),
	(14016, 20, 59, 19, 'So shall they fear Yahweh’s name from the west,\nand his glory from the rising of the sun;\nfor he will come as a rushing stream,\nwhich Yahweh’s breath drives.\n'),
	(14017, 20, 59, 20, '“A Redeemer will come to Zion,\nand to those who turn from disobedience in Jacob,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14018, 20, 59, 21, '“As for me, this is my covenant with them,” says Yahweh. “My Spirit who is on you, and my words which I have put in your mouth, shall not depart out of your mouth, nor out of the mouth of your offspring, nor out of the mouth of your offspring’s offspring,” says Yahweh, “from henceforth and forever.”\n'),
	(14019, 20, 60, 1, '“Arise, shine; for your light has come,\nand Yahweh’s glory has risen on you.\n'),
	(14020, 20, 60, 2, 'For, behold, darkness will cover the earth,\nand thick darkness the peoples;\nbut Yahweh will arise on you,\nand his glory shall be seen on you.\n'),
	(14021, 20, 60, 3, 'Nations will come to your light,\nand kings to the brightness of your rising.\n'),
	(14022, 20, 60, 4, '“Lift up your eyes all around, and see:\nthey all gather themselves together.\nThey come to you.\nYour sons will come from far away,\nand your daughters will be carried in arms.\n'),
	(14023, 20, 60, 5, 'Then you shall see and be radiant,\nand your heart will thrill and be enlarged;\nbecause the abundance of the sea will be turned to you.\nThe wealth of the nations will come to you.\n'),
	(14024, 20, 60, 6, 'A multitude of camels will cover you,\nthe dromedaries of Midian and Ephah.\nAll from Sheba will come.\nThey will bring gold and frankincense,\nand will proclaim the praises of Yahweh.\n'),
	(14025, 20, 60, 7, 'All the flocks of Kedar will be gathered together to you.\nThe rams of Nebaioth will serve you.\nThey will be accepted as offerings on my altar;\nand I will beautify my glorious house.\n'),
	(14026, 20, 60, 8, '“Who are these who fly as a cloud,\nand as the doves to their windows?\n'),
	(14027, 20, 60, 9, 'Surely the islands will wait for me,\nand the ships of Tarshish first,\nto bring your sons from far,\ntheir silver and their gold with them,\nfor the name of Yahweh your God,\nand for the Holy One of Israel,\nbecause he has glorified you.\n'),
	(14028, 20, 60, 10, '“Foreigners will build up your walls,\nand their kings will serve you:\nfor in my wrath I struck you,\nbut in my favor I have had mercy on you.\n'),
	(14029, 20, 60, 11, 'Your gates also shall be open continually; they shall not be shut day nor night; that men may bring to you the wealth of the nations, and their kings led captive.\n'),
	(14030, 20, 60, 12, 'For that nation and kingdom that will not serve you shall perish; yes, those nations shall be utterly wasted.\n'),
	(14031, 20, 60, 13, '“The glory of Lebanon shall come to you, the cypress tree, the pine, and the box tree together, to beautify the place of my sanctuary; and I will make the place of my feet glorious.\n'),
	(14032, 20, 60, 14, 'The sons of those who afflicted you will come bowing to you;\nand all those who despised you will bow themselves down at the soles of your feet.\nThey will call you Yahweh’s City,\nThe Zion of the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(14033, 20, 60, 15, '“Whereas you have been forsaken and hated,\nso that no one passed through you,\nI will make you an eternal excellency,\na joy of many generations.\n'),
	(14034, 20, 60, 16, 'You will also drink the milk of the nations,\nand will nurse from royal breasts.\nThen you will know that I, Yahweh, am your Savior,\nyour Redeemer,\nthe Mighty One of Jacob.\n'),
	(14035, 20, 60, 17, 'For brass I will bring gold;\nfor iron I will bring silver;\nfor wood, brass,\nand for stones, iron.\nI will also make peace your governor,\nand righteousness your ruler.\n'),
	(14036, 20, 60, 18, 'Violence shall no more be heard in your land,\nnor desolation or destruction within your borders;\nbut you will call your walls Salvation,\nand your gates Praise.\n'),
	(14037, 20, 60, 19, 'The sun will be no more your light by day;\nnor will the brightness of the moon give light to you,\nbut Yahweh will be your everlasting light,\nand your God will be your glory.\n'),
	(14038, 20, 60, 20, 'Your sun will not go down any more,\nnor will your moon withdraw itself;\nfor Yahweh will be your everlasting light,\nand the days of your mourning will end.\n'),
	(14039, 20, 60, 21, 'Then your people will all be righteous.\nThey will inherit the land forever,\nthe branch of my planting,\nthe work of my hands,\nthat I may be glorified.\n'),
	(14040, 20, 60, 22, 'The little one will become a thousand,\nand the small one a strong nation.\nI, Yahweh, will do this quickly in its time.”\n'),
	(14041, 20, 61, 1, 'The Lord Yahweh’s Spirit is on me;\nbecause Yahweh has anointed me to preach good news to the humble.\nHe has sent me to bind up the broken hearted,\nto proclaim liberty to the captives,\nand release to those who are bound;\n'),
	(14042, 20, 61, 2, 'to proclaim the year of Yahweh’s favor,\nand the day of vengeance of our God;\nto comfort all who mourn;\n'),
	(14043, 20, 61, 3, 'to provide for those who mourn in Zion,\nto give to them a garland for ashes,\nthe oil of joy for mourning,\nthe garment of praise for the spirit of heaviness;\nthat they may be called trees of righteousness,\nthe planting of Yahweh,\nthat he may be glorified.\n'),
	(14044, 20, 61, 4, 'They will rebuild the old ruins.\nThey will raise up the places long devastated.\nThey will repair the ruined cities,\nthat have been devastated for many generations.\n'),
	(14045, 20, 61, 5, 'Strangers will stand and feed your flocks,\nand foreigners will work your fields and your vineyards.\n'),
	(14046, 20, 61, 6, 'But you will be called Yahweh’s priests.\nMen will call you the servants of our God.\nYou will eat the wealth of the nations,\nand you will boast in their glory.\n'),
	(14047, 20, 61, 7, 'Instead of your shame you will have double.\nInstead of dishonor, they will rejoice in their portion.\nTherefore in their land, they will possess double.\nEverlasting joy will be to them.\n'),
	(14048, 20, 61, 8, '“For I, Yahweh, love justice.\nI hate robbery and iniquity.\nI will give them their reward in truth,\nand I will make an everlasting covenant with them.\n'),
	(14049, 20, 61, 9, 'Their offspring will be known among the nations,\nand their offspring among the peoples.\nAll who see them will acknowledge them,\nthat they are the offspring which Yahweh has blessed.”\n'),
	(14050, 20, 61, 10, 'I will greatly rejoice in Yahweh!\nMy soul will be joyful in my God;\nfor he has clothed me with the garments of salvation.\nHe has covered me with the robe of righteousness,\nas a bridegroom decks himself with a garland,\nand as a bride adorns herself with her jewels.\n'),
	(14051, 20, 61, 11, 'For as the earth produces its bud,\nand as the garden causes the things that are sown in it to spring up;\nso the Lord Yahweh will cause righteousness and praise to spring up before all the nations.\n'),
	(14052, 20, 62, 1, 'For Zion’s sake will I not hold my peace,\nand for Jerusalem’s sake I will not rest,\nuntil her righteousness shines out like the dawn,\nand her salvation like a burning lamp.\n'),
	(14053, 20, 62, 2, 'The nations will see your righteousness,\nand all kings your glory,\nand you will be called by a new name,\nwhich Yahweh‘s mouth will name.\n'),
	(14054, 20, 62, 3, 'You will also be a crown of beauty in Yahweh‘s hand,\nand a royal diadem in your God‘s hand.\n'),
	(14055, 20, 62, 4, 'You will not be called Forsaken any more;\nnor will your land be called Desolate any more:\nbut you will be called Hephzibah,\nand your land Beulah;\nfor Yahweh delights in you,\nand your land will be married.\n'),
	(14056, 20, 62, 5, 'For as a young man marries a virgin,\nso your sons will marry you.\nAs a bridegroom rejoices over his bride,\nso your God will rejoice over you.\n'),
	(14057, 20, 62, 6, 'I have set watchmen on your walls, Jerusalem.\nThey will never be silent day nor night.\nYou who call on Yahweh, take no rest,\n'),
	(14058, 20, 62, 7, 'and give him no rest, until he establishes,\nand until he makes Jerusalem a praise in the earth.\n'),
	(14059, 20, 62, 8, 'Yahweh has sworn by his right hand,\nand by the arm of his strength,\n“Surely I will no more give your grain to be food for your enemies;\nand foreigners will not drink your new wine, for which you have labored;\n'),
	(14060, 20, 62, 9, 'but those who have harvested it will eat it, and praise Yahweh;\nand those who have gathered it will drink it in the courts of my sanctuary.”\n'),
	(14061, 20, 62, 10, 'Go through, go through the gates!\nPrepare the way of the people!\nBuild up, build up the highway!\nGather out the stones!\nLift up a banner for the peoples.\n'),
	(14062, 20, 62, 11, 'Behold, Yahweh has proclaimed to the end of the earth,\n“Say to the daughter of Zion,\n‘Behold, your salvation comes.\nBehold, his reward is with him,\nand his recompense before him.’”\n'),
	(14063, 20, 62, 12, 'They will call them The holy people,\nYahweh’s redeemed.\nYou will be called Sought out,\nA city not forsaken.\n'),
	(14064, 20, 63, 1, 'Who is this who comes from Edom,\nwith dyed garments from Bozrah?\nWho this who is glorious in his clothing,\nmarching in the greatness of his strength?\n“It is I who speak in righteousness,\nmighty to save.”\n'),
	(14065, 20, 63, 2, 'Why is your clothing red,\nand your garments like him who treads in the wine vat?\n'),
	(14066, 20, 63, 3, '“I have trodden the wine press alone;\nand of the peoples, no one was with me:\nYes, I trod them in my anger,\nand trampled them in my wrath.\nTheir lifeblood is sprinkled on my garments,\nand I have stained all my clothing.\n'),
	(14067, 20, 63, 4, 'For the day of vengeance was in my heart,\nand the year of my redeemed has come.\n'),
	(14068, 20, 63, 5, 'I looked, and there was no one to help;\nand I wondered that there was no one to uphold:\ntherefore my own arm brought salvation to me;\nand my own wrath upheld me.\n'),
	(14069, 20, 63, 6, 'I trod down the peoples in my anger,\nand made them drunk in my wrath,\nand I poured out their lifeblood on the earth.”\n'),
	(14070, 20, 63, 7, 'I will tell of the loving kindnesses of Yahweh\nand the praises of Yahweh,\naccording to all that Yahweh has given to us,\nand the great goodness toward the house of Israel,\nwhich he has given to them according to his mercies,\nand according to the multitude of his loving kindnesses.\n'),
	(14071, 20, 63, 8, 'For he said, “Surely, they are my people,\nchildren who will not deal falsely;”\nso he became their Savior.\n'),
	(14072, 20, 63, 9, 'In all their affliction he was afflicted,\nand the angel of his presence saved them.\nIn his love and in his pity he redeemed them.\nHe bore them,\nand carried them all the days of old.\n'),
	(14073, 20, 63, 10, 'But they rebelled,\nand grieved his holy Spirit.\nTherefore he turned and became their enemy,\nand he himself fought against them.\n'),
	(14074, 20, 63, 11, 'Then he remembered the days of old,\nMoses and his people, saying,\n“Where is he who brought them up out of the sea with the shepherds of his flock?\nWhere is he who put his Holy Spirit among them?”\n'),
	(14075, 20, 63, 12, 'Who caused his glorious arm to be at Moses’ right hand?\nWho divided the waters before them, to make himself an everlasting name?\n'),
	(14076, 20, 63, 13, 'Who led them through the depths,\nlike a horse in the wilderness,\nso that they didn’t stumble?\n'),
	(14077, 20, 63, 14, 'As the livestock that go down into the valley,\nYahweh’s Spirit caused them to rest.\nSo you led your people, to make yourself a glorious name.\n'),
	(14078, 20, 63, 15, 'Look down from heaven,\nand see from the habitation of your holiness and of your glory.\nWhere are your zeal and your mighty acts?\nThe yearning of your heart and your compassion is restrained toward me.\n'),
	(14079, 20, 63, 16, 'For you are our Father,\nthough Abraham doesn’t know us,\nand Israel does not acknowledge us.\nYou, Yahweh, are our Father.\nOur Redeemer from everlasting is your name.\n'),
	(14080, 20, 63, 17, 'O Yahweh, why do you make us wander from your ways,\nand harden our heart from your fear?\nReturn for your servants’ sake,\nthe tribes of your inheritance.\n'),
	(14081, 20, 63, 18, 'Your holy people possessed it but a little while.\nOur adversaries have trodden down your sanctuary.\n'),
	(14082, 20, 63, 19, 'We have become like those over whom you never ruled,\nlike those who were not called by your name.\n'),
	(14083, 20, 64, 1, 'Oh that you would tear the heavens,\nthat you would come down,\nthat the mountains might quake at your presence.\n'),
	(14084, 20, 64, 2, 'As when fire kindles the brushwood,\nand the fire causes the water to boil;\nMake your name known to your adversaries,\nthat the nations may tremble at your presence!\n'),
	(14085, 20, 64, 3, 'When you did awesome things which we didn’t look for,\nyou came down, and the mountains quaked at your presence.\n'),
	(14086, 20, 64, 4, 'For from of old men have not heard,\nnor perceived by the ear,\nnor has the eye seen a God besides you,\nwho works for him who waits for him.\n'),
	(14087, 20, 64, 5, 'You meet him who rejoices and does righteousness,\nthose who remember you in your ways.\nBehold, you were angry, and we sinned.\nWe have been in sin for a long time.\nShall we be saved?\n'),
	(14088, 20, 64, 6, 'For we have all become like one who is unclean,\nand all our righteousness is like a polluted garment.\nWe all fade like a leaf;\nand our iniquities, like the wind, take us away.\n'),
	(14089, 20, 64, 7, 'There is no one who calls on your name,\nwho stirs himself up to take hold of you;\nfor you have hidden your face from us,\nand have consumed us by means of our iniquities.\n'),
	(14090, 20, 64, 8, 'But now, Yahweh, you are our Father.\nWe are the clay, and you our potter.\nWe all are the work of your hand.\n'),
	(14091, 20, 64, 9, 'Don’t be furious, Yahweh,\nand don’t remember iniquity forever.\nLook and see, we beg you,\nwe are all your people.\n'),
	(14092, 20, 64, 10, 'Your holy cities have become a wilderness.\nZion has become a wilderness,\nJerusalem a desolation.\n'),
	(14093, 20, 64, 11, 'Our holy and our beautiful house, where our fathers praised you,\nis burned with fire;\nand all our pleasant places are laid waste.\n'),
	(14094, 20, 64, 12, 'Will you hold yourself back for these things, Yahweh?\nWill you keep silent, and punish us very severely?\n'),
	(14095, 20, 65, 1, '“I am inquired of by those who didn’t ask.\nI am found by those who didn’t seek me.\nI said, ‘See me, see me,’ to a nation that was not called by my name.\n'),
	(14096, 20, 65, 2, 'I have spread out my hands all day to a rebellious people,\nwho walk in a way that is not good,\nafter their own thoughts;\n'),
	(14097, 20, 65, 3, 'a people who provoke me to my face continually,\nsacrificing in gardens,\nand burning incense on bricks;\n'),
	(14098, 20, 65, 4, 'who sit among the graves,\nand spend nights in secret places;\nwho eat pig’s meat,\nand broth of abominable things is in their vessels;\n'),
	(14099, 20, 65, 5, 'who say, ‘Stay by yourself,\ndon’t come near to me,\nfor I am holier than you.’\nThese are smoke in my nose,\na fire that burns all day.\n'),
	(14100, 20, 65, 6, '“Behold, it is written before me:\nI will not keep silence,\nbut will repay,\nyes, I will repay into their bosom,\n'),
	(14101, 20, 65, 7, 'your own iniquities, and the iniquities of your fathers together”, says Yahweh,\n“who have burned incense on the mountains,\nand blasphemed me on the hills.\nTherefore I will first measure their work into their bosom.”\n'),
	(14102, 20, 65, 8, 'Yahweh says,\n“As the new wine is found in the cluster,\nand one says, ‘Don’t destroy it, for a blessing is in it:’\nso will I do for my servants’ sake,\nthat I may not destroy them all.\n'),
	(14103, 20, 65, 9, 'I will bring offspring out of Jacob,\nand out of Judah an inheritor of my mountains.\nMy chosen will inherit it,\nand my servants will dwell there.\n'),
	(14104, 20, 65, 10, 'Sharon will be a fold of flocks,\nand the valley of Achor a place for herds to lie down in,\nfor my people who have sought me.\n'),
	(14105, 20, 65, 11, '“But you who forsake Yahweh,\nwho forget my holy mountain,\nwho prepare a table for Fortune,\nand who fill up mixed wine to Destiny;\n'),
	(14106, 20, 65, 12, 'I will destine you to the sword,\nand you will all bow down to the slaughter;\nbecause when I called, you didn’t answer.\nWhen I spoke, you didn’t listen;\nbut you did that which was evil in my eyes,\nand chose that in which I didn’t delight.”\n'),
	(14107, 20, 65, 13, 'Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh,\n“Behold, my servants will eat,\nbut you will be hungry;\nbehold, my servants will drink,\nbut you will be thirsty.\nBehold, my servants will rejoice,\nbut you will be disappointed;\n'),
	(14108, 20, 65, 14, 'Behold, my servants will sing for joy of heart,\nbut you will cry for sorrow of heart,\nand will wail for anguish of spirit.\n'),
	(14109, 20, 65, 15, 'You will leave your name for a curse to my chosen;\nand the Lord Yahweh will kill you.\nHe will call his servants by another name,\n'),
	(14110, 20, 65, 16, 'so that he who blesses himself in the earth will bless himself in the God of truth;\nand he who swears in the earth will swear by the God of truth;\nbecause the former troubles are forgotten,\nand because they are hidden from my eyes.\n'),
	(14111, 20, 65, 17, '“For, behold, I create new heavens and a new earth;\nand the former things will not be remembered,\nnor come into mind.\n'),
	(14112, 20, 65, 18, 'But be glad and rejoice forever in that which I create;\nfor, behold, I create Jerusalem to be a delight,\nand her people a joy.\n'),
	(14113, 20, 65, 19, 'I will rejoice in Jerusalem,\nand delight in my people;\nand the voice of weeping and the voice of crying\nwill be heard in her no more.\n'),
	(14114, 20, 65, 20, '“No more will there be an infant who only lives a few days,\nnor an old man who has not filled his days;\nfor the child will die one hundred years old,\nand the sinner being one hundred years old will be accursed.\n'),
	(14115, 20, 65, 21, 'They will build houses, and inhabit them.\nThey will plant vineyards, and eat their fruit.\n'),
	(14116, 20, 65, 22, 'They will not build, and another inhabit.\nThey will not plant, and another eat:\nfor the days of my people will be like the days of a tree,\nand my chosen will long enjoy the work of their hands.\n'),
	(14117, 20, 65, 23, 'They will not labor in vain,\nnor give birth for calamity;\nfor they are the offspring of Yahweh’s blessed,\nand their descendants with them.\n'),
	(14118, 20, 65, 24, 'It will happen that, before they call, I will answer;\nand while they are yet speaking, I will hear.\n'),
	(14119, 20, 65, 25, 'The wolf and the lamb will feed together,\nand the lion will eat straw like the ox.\nDust will be the serpent’s food.\nThey will not hurt nor destroy in all my holy mountain,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(14120, 20, 66, 1, 'Yahweh says,\n“Heaven is my throne, and the earth is my footstool.\nWhat kind of house will you build to me?\nWhere will I rest?\n'),
	(14121, 20, 66, 2, 'For my hand has made all these things,\nand so all these things came to be,” says Yahweh:\n“but to this man will I look,\neven to he who is poor and of a contrite spirit,\nand who trembles at my word.\n'),
	(14122, 20, 66, 3, 'He who kills an ox is as he who kills a man;\nhe who sacrifices a lamb, as he who breaks a dog’s neck;\nhe who offers an offering, as he who offers pig’s blood;\nhe who burns frankincense, as he who blesses an idol.\nYes, they have chosen their own ways,\nand their soul delights in their abominations:\n'),
	(14123, 20, 66, 4, 'I also will choose their delusions,\nand will bring their fears on them;\nbecause when I called, no one answered;\nwhen I spoke, they didn’t listen;\nbut they did that which was evil in my eyes,\nand chose that in which I didn’t delight.”\n'),
	(14124, 20, 66, 5, 'Hear Yahweh’s word,\nyou who tremble at his word:\n“Your brothers who hate you,\nwho cast you out for my name’s sake, have said,\n‘Let Yahweh be glorified,\nthat we may see your joy;’\nbut it is those who shall be disappointed.\n'),
	(14125, 20, 66, 6, 'A voice of tumult from the city,\na voice from the temple,\na voice of Yahweh that repays his enemies what they deserve.\n'),
	(14126, 20, 66, 7, '“Before she travailed, she gave birth.\nBefore her pain came, she delivered a son.\n'),
	(14127, 20, 66, 8, 'Who has heard of such a thing?\nWho has seen such things?\nShall a land be born in one day?\nShall a nation be born at once?\nFor as soon as Zion travailed,\nshe gave birth to her children.\n'),
	(14128, 20, 66, 9, 'Shall I bring to the birth, and not cause to be delivered?” says Yahweh.\n“Shall I who cause to give birth shut the womb?” says your God.\n'),
	(14129, 20, 66, 10, '“Rejoice with Jerusalem, and be glad for her, all you who love her.\nRejoice for joy with her, all you who mourn over her;\n'),
	(14130, 20, 66, 11, 'that you may nurse and be satisfied at the comforting breasts;\nthat you may drink deeply,\nand be delighted with the abundance of her glory.”\n'),
	(14131, 20, 66, 12, 'For Yahweh says, “Behold, I will extend peace to her like a river,\nand the glory of the nations like an overflowing stream;\nand you will nurse.\nYou will be carried on her side,\nand will be dandled on her knees.\n'),
	(14132, 20, 66, 13, 'As one whom his mother comforts,\nso will I comfort you.\nYou will be comforted in Jerusalem.”\n'),
	(14133, 20, 66, 14, 'You will see it, and your heart shall rejoice,\nand your bones will flourish like the tender grass.\nYahweh’s hand will be known among his servants;\nand he will have indignation against his enemies.\n'),
	(14134, 20, 66, 15, 'For, behold, Yahweh will come with fire,\nand his chariots will be like the whirlwind;\nto render his anger with fierceness,\nand his rebuke with flames of fire.\n'),
	(14135, 20, 66, 16, 'For Yahweh will execute judgment by fire and by his sword on all flesh;\nand those slain by Yahweh will be many.\n'),
	(14136, 20, 66, 17, '“Those who sanctify themselves and purify themselves to go to the gardens, behind one in the middle, eating pig’s meat, abominable things, and the mouse, they shall come to an end together,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14137, 20, 66, 18, '“For I know their works and their thoughts. The time comes that I will gather all nations and languages, and they will come, and will see my glory.\n'),
	(14138, 20, 66, 19, '“I will set a sign among them, and I will send those who escape of them to the nations, to Tarshish, Pul, and Lud, who draw the bow, to Tubal and Javan, to far-away islands, who have not heard my fame, nor have seen my glory; and they shall declare my glory among the nations.\n'),
	(14139, 20, 66, 20, 'They shall bring all your brothers out of all the nations for an offering to Yahweh, on horses, in chariots, in litters, on mules, and on camels, to my holy mountain Jerusalem, says Yahweh, as the children of Israel bring their offering in a clean vessel into Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(14140, 20, 66, 21, 'Of them I will also select priests and Levites,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14141, 20, 66, 22, '“For as the new heavens and the new earth, which I will make, shall remain before me,” says Yahweh, “so your offspring and your name shall remain.\n'),
	(14142, 20, 66, 23, 'It shall happen that from one new moon to another, and from one Sabbath to another, all flesh will come to worship before me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14143, 20, 66, 24, '“They will go out, and look at the dead bodies of the men who have transgressed against me; for their worm will not die, nor will their fire be quenched, and they will be loathsome to all mankind.”\n'),
	(14144, 21, 1, 1, 'The words of Jeremiah the son of Hilkiah, one of the priests who were in Anathoth in the land of Benjamin.\n'),
	(14145, 21, 1, 2, 'Yahweh’s word came to him in the days of Josiah the son of Amon, king of Judah, in the thirteenth year of his reign.\n'),
	(14146, 21, 1, 3, 'It came also in the days of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah, to the end of the eleventh year of Zedekiah, the son of Josiah, king of Judah, to the carrying away of Jerusalem captive in the fifth month.\n'),
	(14147, 21, 1, 4, 'Now Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(14148, 21, 1, 5, '“Before I formed you in the womb, I knew you.\nBefore you were born, I sanctified you.\nI have appointed you a prophet to the nations.”\n'),
	(14149, 21, 1, 6, 'Then I said, “Ah, Lord Yahweh! Behold, I don’t know how to speak; for I am a child.”\n'),
	(14150, 21, 1, 7, 'But Yahweh said to me, “Don’t say, ‘I am a child;’ for you must go to whomever I send you, and you must say whatever I command you.\n'),
	(14151, 21, 1, 8, 'Don’t be afraid because of them, for I am with you to rescue you,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14152, 21, 1, 9, 'Then Yahweh stretched out his hand, and touched my mouth. Then Yahweh said to me, “Behold, I have put my words in your mouth.\n'),
	(14153, 21, 1, 10, 'Behold, I have today set you over the nations and over the kingdoms, to uproot and to tear down, to destroy and to overthrow, to build and to plant.”\n'),
	(14154, 21, 1, 11, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to me, saying, “Jeremiah, what do you see?”\nI said, “I see a branch of an almond tree.”\n'),
	(14155, 21, 1, 12, 'Then Yahweh said to me, “You have seen well; for I watch over my word to perform it.”\n'),
	(14156, 21, 1, 13, 'Yahweh’s word came to me the second time, saying, “What do you see?”\nI said, “I see a boiling cauldron; and it is tipping away from the north.”\n'),
	(14157, 21, 1, 14, 'Then Yahweh said to me, “Out of the north, evil will break out on all the inhabitants of the land.\n'),
	(14158, 21, 1, 15, 'For, behold, I will call all the families of the kingdoms of the north,” says Yahweh.\n“They will come, and they will each set his throne at the entrance of the gates of Jerusalem,\nand against all its walls all around, and against all the cities of Judah.\n'),
	(14159, 21, 1, 16, 'I will utter my judgments against them concerning all their wickedness,\nin that they have forsaken me,\nand have burned incense to other gods,\nand worshiped the works of their own hands.\n'),
	(14160, 21, 1, 17, '“You therefore put your belt on your waist, arise, and say to them all that I command you. Don’t be dismayed at them, lest I dismay you before them.\n'),
	(14161, 21, 1, 18, 'For, behold, I have made you today a fortified city, an iron pillar, and bronze walls, against the whole land, against the kings of Judah, against its princes, against its priests, and against the people of the land.\n'),
	(14162, 21, 1, 19, 'They will fight against you, but they will not prevail against you; for I am with you”, says Yahweh, “to rescue you.”\n'),
	(14163, 21, 2, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(14164, 21, 2, 2, '“Go, and proclaim in the ears of Jerusalem, saying, ‘Yahweh says,\n“I remember for you the kindness of your youth,\nthe love of your weddings;\nhow you went after me in the wilderness,\nin a land that was not sown.\n'),
	(14165, 21, 2, 3, 'Israel was holiness to Yahweh,\nthe first fruits of his increase.\nAll who devour him will be held guilty.\nEvil will come on them,”’ says Yahweh.”\n'),
	(14166, 21, 2, 4, 'Hear Yahweh’s word, O house of Jacob, and all the families of the house of Israel!\n'),
	(14167, 21, 2, 5, 'Yahweh says,\n“What unrighteousness have your fathers found in me,\nthat they have gone far from me,\nand have walked after worthless vanity,\nand have become worthless?\n'),
	(14168, 21, 2, 6, 'They didn’t say, ‘Where is Yahweh who brought us up out of the land of Egypt,\nwho led us through the wilderness,\nthrough a land of deserts and of pits,\nthrough a land of drought and of the shadow of death,\nthrough a land that no one passed through,\nand where no man lived?’\n'),
	(14169, 21, 2, 7, 'I brought you into a plentiful land,\nto eat its fruit and its goodness;\nbut when you entered, you defiled my land,\nand made my heritage an abomination.\n'),
	(14170, 21, 2, 8, 'The priests didn’t say, ‘Where is Yahweh?’\nand those who handle the law didn’t know me.\nThe rulers also transgressed against me,\nand the prophets prophesied by Baal,\nand followed things that do not profit.\n'),
	(14171, 21, 2, 9, '“Therefore I will yet contend with you,” says Yahweh,\n“and I will contend with your children’s children.\n'),
	(14172, 21, 2, 10, 'For pass over to the islands of Kittim, and see;\nand send to Kedar, and consider diligently;\nand see if there has been such a thing.\n'),
	(14173, 21, 2, 11, 'Has a nation changed its gods,\nwhich really are no gods?\nBut my people have changed their glory for that which does not profit.\n'),
	(14174, 21, 2, 12, '“Be astonished, you heavens, at this,\nand be horribly afraid.\nBe very desolate,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14175, 21, 2, 13, '“For my people have committed two evils:\nthey have forsaken me, the spring of living waters,\nand cut them out cisterns, broken cisterns, that can hold no water.\n'),
	(14176, 21, 2, 14, 'Is Israel a slave?\nIs he born into slavery?\nWhy has he become a captive?\n'),
	(14177, 21, 2, 15, 'The young lions have roared at him, and yelled.\nThey have made his land waste.\nHis cities are burned up, without inhabitant.\n'),
	(14178, 21, 2, 16, 'The children also of Memphis and Tahpanhes have broken the crown of your head.\n'),
	(14179, 21, 2, 17, '“Haven’t you brought this on yourself,\nin that you have forsaken Yahweh your God, when he led you by the way?\n'),
	(14180, 21, 2, 18, 'Now what do you gain by going to Egypt, to drink the waters of the Shihor?\nOr why do you to go on the way to Assyria, to drink the waters of the River?\n'),
	(14181, 21, 2, 19, '“Your own wickedness will correct you,\nand your backsliding will rebuke you.\nKnow therefore and see that it is an evil and bitter thing,\nthat you have forsaken Yahweh your God,\nand that my fear is not in you,” says the Lord, Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(14182, 21, 2, 20, '“For long ago I broke off your yoke,\nand burst your bonds.\nYou said, ‘I will not serve;’\nfor on every high hill and under every green tree you bowed yourself,\nplaying the prostitute.\n'),
	(14183, 21, 2, 21, 'Yet I had planted you a noble vine,\na pure and faithful seed.\nHow then have you turned into the degenerate branches of a foreign vine to me?\n'),
	(14184, 21, 2, 22, 'For though you wash yourself with lye,\nand use much soap,\nyet your iniquity is marked before me,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(14185, 21, 2, 23, '“How can you say, ‘I am not defiled.\nI have not gone after the Baals’?\nSee your way in the valley.\nKnow what you have done.\nYou are a swift dromedary traversing her ways;\n'),
	(14186, 21, 2, 24, 'a wild donkey used to the wilderness, that sniffs the wind in her craving.\nWhen she is in heat, who can turn her away?\nAll those who seek her will not weary themselves. In her month, they will find her.\n'),
	(14187, 21, 2, 25, '“Keep your feet from being bare,\nand your throat from thirst.\nBut you said, ‘It is in vain.\nNo, for I have loved strangers,\nand I will go after them.’\n'),
	(14188, 21, 2, 26, 'As the thief is ashamed when he is found,\nso is the house of Israel ashamed;\nthey, their kings, their princes, and their priests, and their prophets;\n'),
	(14189, 21, 2, 27, 'who tell wood, ‘You are my father;’\nand a stone, ‘You have given birth to me:’\nfor they have turned their back to me,\nand not their face;\nbut in the time of their trouble they will say, ‘Arise, and save us.’\n'),
	(14190, 21, 2, 28, '“But where are your gods that you have made for yourselves?\nLet them arise, if they can save you in the time of your trouble:\nfor you have as many gods as you have towns, O Judah.\n'),
	(14191, 21, 2, 29, '“Why will you contend with me?\nYou all have transgressed against me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14192, 21, 2, 30, '“I have struck your children in vain.\nThey received no correction.\nYour own sword has devoured your prophets,\nlike a destroying lion.\n'),
	(14193, 21, 2, 31, 'Generation, consider Yahweh’s word.\nHave I been a wilderness to Israel?\nOr a land of thick darkness?\nWhy do my people say, ‘We have broken loose.\nWe will come to you no more?’\n'),
	(14194, 21, 2, 32, '“Can a virgin forget her ornaments,\nor a bride her attire?\nYet my people have forgotten me for days without number.\n'),
	(14195, 21, 2, 33, 'How well you prepare your way to seek love!\nTherefore you have even taught the wicked women your ways.\n'),
	(14196, 21, 2, 34, 'Also the blood of the souls of the innocent poor is found in your skirts.\nYou did not find them breaking in;\nbut it is because of all these things.\n'),
	(14197, 21, 2, 35, '“Yet you said, ‘I am innocent.\nSurely his anger has turned away from me.’\n“Behold, I will judge you,\nbecause you say, ‘I have not sinned.’\n'),
	(14198, 21, 2, 36, 'Why do you go about so much to change your ways?\nYou will be ashamed of Egypt also,\nas you were ashamed of Assyria.\n'),
	(14199, 21, 2, 37, 'You will also leave that place with your hands on your head;\nfor Yahweh has rejected those in whom you trust,\nand you won’t prosper with them.\n'),
	(14200, 21, 3, 1, '“They say, ‘If a man puts away his wife, and she goes from him, and becomes another man’s, should he return to her again?’ Wouldn’t that land be greatly polluted? But you have played the prostitute with many lovers; yet return again to me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14201, 21, 3, 2, '“Lift up your eyes to the bare heights, and see! Where have you not been lain with? You have sat waiting for them by the road, as an Arabian in the wilderness. You have polluted the land with your prostitution and with your wickedness.\n'),
	(14202, 21, 3, 3, 'Therefore the showers have been withheld and there has been no latter rain; yet you have had a prostitute’s forehead and you refused to be ashamed.\n'),
	(14203, 21, 3, 4, 'Will you not from this time cry to me, ‘My Father, you are the guide of my youth?’\n'),
	(14204, 21, 3, 5, '“‘Will he retain his anger forever? Will he keep it to the end?’ Behold, you have spoken and have done evil things, and have had your way.”\n'),
	(14205, 21, 3, 6, 'Moreover, Yahweh said to me in the days of Josiah the king, “Have you seen that which backsliding Israel has done? She has gone up on every high mountain and under every green tree, and has played the prostitute there.\n'),
	(14206, 21, 3, 7, 'I said after she had done all these things, ‘She will return to me;’ but she didn’t return; and her treacherous sister Judah saw it.\n'),
	(14207, 21, 3, 8, 'I saw when, for this very cause, that backsliding Israel had committed adultery, I had put her away and given her a bill of divorce, yet treacherous Judah, her sister, had no fear; but she also went and played the prostitute.\n'),
	(14208, 21, 3, 9, 'Because she took her prostitution lightly, the land was polluted, and she committed adultery with stones and with wood.\n'),
	(14209, 21, 3, 10, 'Yet for all this her treacherous sister, Judah, has not returned to me with her whole heart, but only in pretense,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14210, 21, 3, 11, 'Yahweh said to me, “Backsliding Israel has shown herself more righteous than treacherous Judah.\n'),
	(14211, 21, 3, 12, 'Go, and proclaim these words toward the north, and say, ‘Return, you backsliding Israel,’ says Yahweh; ‘I will not look in anger on you; for I am merciful,’ says Yahweh. ‘I will not keep anger forever.\n'),
	(14212, 21, 3, 13, 'Only acknowledge your iniquity, that you have transgressed against Yahweh your God, and have scattered your ways to the strangers under every green tree, and you have not obeyed my voice,’ says Yahweh.”\n'),
	(14213, 21, 3, 14, '“Return, backsliding children,” says Yahweh; “for I am a husband to you. I will take one of you from a city, and two from a family, and I will bring you to Zion.\n'),
	(14214, 21, 3, 15, 'I will give you shepherds according to my heart, who will feed you with knowledge and understanding.\n'),
	(14215, 21, 3, 16, 'It will come to pass, when you are multiplied and increased in the land, in those days,” says Yahweh, “they will no longer say, ‘the ark of Yahweh’s covenant!’ It will not come to mind. They won’t remember it. They won’t miss it, nor will another be made.\n'),
	(14216, 21, 3, 17, 'At that time they will call Jerusalem ‘Yahweh’s Throne;’ and all the nations will be gathered to it, to Yahweh’s name, to Jerusalem. They will no longer walk after the stubbornness of their evil heart.\n'),
	(14217, 21, 3, 18, 'In those days the house of Judah will walk with the house of Israel, and they will come together out of the land of the north to the land that I gave for an inheritance to your fathers.\n'),
	(14218, 21, 3, 19, '“But I said, ‘How I desire to put you among the children, and give you a pleasant land, a goodly heritage of the armies of the nations!’ and I said, ‘You shall call me “My Father”, and shall not turn away from following me.’\n'),
	(14219, 21, 3, 20, '“Surely as a wife treacherously departs from her husband, so you have dealt treacherously with me, house of Israel,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14220, 21, 3, 21, 'A voice is heard on the bare heights, the weeping and the petitions of the children of Israel; because they have perverted their way, they have forgotten Yahweh their God.\n'),
	(14221, 21, 3, 22, 'Return, you backsliding children, and I will heal your backsliding.\n“Behold, we have come to you; for you are Yahweh our God.\n'),
	(14222, 21, 3, 23, 'Truly in vain is help from the hills, the tumult on the mountains. Truly the salvation of Israel is in Yahweh our God.\n'),
	(14223, 21, 3, 24, 'But the shameful thing has devoured the labor of our fathers from our youth, their flocks and their herds, their sons and their daughters.\n'),
	(14224, 21, 3, 25, 'Let us lie down in our shame, and let our confusion cover us; for we have sinned against Yahweh our God, we and our fathers, from our youth even to this day. We have not obeyed Yahweh our God’s voice.”\n'),
	(14225, 21, 4, 1, '“If you will return, Israel,” says Yahweh, “if you will return to me, and if you will put away your abominations out of my sight; then you will not be removed;\n'),
	(14226, 21, 4, 2, 'and you will swear, ‘As Yahweh lives,’ in truth, in justice, and in righteousness. The nations will bless themselves in him, and they will glory in him.”\n'),
	(14227, 21, 4, 3, 'For Yahweh says to the men of Judah and to Jerusalem, “Break up your fallow ground, and don’t sow among thorns.\n'),
	(14228, 21, 4, 4, 'Circumcise yourselves to Yahweh, and take away the foreskins of your heart, you men of Judah and inhabitants of Jerusalem; lest my wrath go out like fire, and burn so that no one can quench it, because of the evil of your doings.\n'),
	(14229, 21, 4, 5, 'Declare in Judah, and publish in Jerusalem; and say, ‘Blow the trumpet in the land!’ Cry aloud and say, ‘Assemble yourselves! Let us go into the fortified cities!’\n'),
	(14230, 21, 4, 6, 'Set up a standard toward Zion. Flee for safety! Don’t wait; for I will bring evil from the north, and a great destruction.”\n'),
	(14231, 21, 4, 7, 'A lion has gone up from his thicket, and a destroyer of nations. He is on his way. He has gone out from his place, to make your land desolate, that your cities be laid waste, without inhabitant.\n'),
	(14232, 21, 4, 8, 'For this, clothe yourself with sackcloth, lament and wail; for the fierce anger of Yahweh hasn’t turned back from us.\n'),
	(14233, 21, 4, 9, '“It will happen at that day,” says Yahweh, “that the heart of the king will perish, along with the heart of the princes. The priests will be astonished, and the prophets will wonder.”\n'),
	(14234, 21, 4, 10, 'Then I said, “Ah, Lord Yahweh! Surely you have greatly deceived this people and Jerusalem, saying, ‘You will have peace;’ whereas the sword reaches to the heart.”\n'),
	(14235, 21, 4, 11, 'At that time it will be said to this people and to Jerusalem, “A hot wind from the bare heights in the wilderness toward the daughter of my people, not to winnow, nor to cleanse;\n'),
	(14236, 21, 4, 12, 'a full wind from these will come for me. Now I will also utter judgments against them.”\n'),
	(14237, 21, 4, 13, 'Behold, he will come up as clouds, and his chariots will be as the whirlwind. His horses are swifter than eagles. Woe to us! For we are ruined.\n'),
	(14238, 21, 4, 14, 'Jerusalem, wash your heart from wickedness, that you may be saved. How long will your evil thoughts lodge within you?\n'),
	(14239, 21, 4, 15, 'For a voice declares from Dan, and publishes evil from the hills of Ephraim:\n'),
	(14240, 21, 4, 16, '“Tell the nations; behold, publish against Jerusalem, ‘Watchers come from a far country, and raise their voice against the cities of Judah.\n'),
	(14241, 21, 4, 17, 'As keepers of a field, they are against her all around, because she has been rebellious against me,’” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14242, 21, 4, 18, '“Your way and your doings have brought these things to you. This is your wickedness; for it is bitter, for it reaches to your heart.”\n'),
	(14243, 21, 4, 19, 'My anguish, my anguish! I am pained at my very heart! My heart trembles within me. I can’t hold my peace, because you have heard, O my soul, the sound of the trumpet, the alarm of war.\n'),
	(14244, 21, 4, 20, 'Destruction on destruction is decreed, for the whole land is laid waste. Suddenly my tents are destroyed, and my curtains gone in a moment.\n'),
	(14245, 21, 4, 21, 'How long will I see the standard and hear the sound of the trumpet?\n'),
	(14246, 21, 4, 22, '“For my people are foolish. They don’t know me. They are foolish children, and they have no understanding. They are skillful in doing evil, but they don’t know how to do good.”\n'),
	(14247, 21, 4, 23, 'I saw the earth, and, behold, it was waste and void; and the heavens, and they had no light.\n'),
	(14248, 21, 4, 24, 'I saw the mountains, and behold, they trembled, and all the hills moved back and forth.\n'),
	(14249, 21, 4, 25, 'I saw, and behold, there was no man, and all the birds of the sky had fled.\n'),
	(14250, 21, 4, 26, 'I saw, and behold, the fruitful field was a wilderness, and all its cities were broken down at the presence of Yahweh, before his fierce anger.\n'),
	(14251, 21, 4, 27, 'For Yahweh says, “The whole land will be a desolation; yet will I not make a full end.\n'),
	(14252, 21, 4, 28, 'For this the earth will mourn, and the heavens above be black; because I have spoken it. I have planned it, and I have not repented, neither will I turn back from it.”\n'),
	(14253, 21, 4, 29, 'Every city flees for the noise of the horsemen and archers. They go into the thickets, and climb up on the rocks. Every city is forsaken, and not a man dwells therein.\n'),
	(14254, 21, 4, 30, 'You, when you are made desolate, what will you do? Though you clothe yourself with scarlet, though you deck yourself with ornaments of gold, though you enlarge your eyes with makeup, you make yourself beautiful in vain. Your lovers despise you. They seek your life.\n'),
	(14255, 21, 4, 31, 'For I have heard a voice as of a woman in travail, the anguish as of her who gives birth to her first child, the voice of the daughter of Zion, who gasps for breath, who spreads her hands, saying, “Woe is me now! For my soul faints before the murderers.”\n'),
	(14256, 21, 5, 1, '“Run back and forth through the streets of Jerusalem, and see now, and know, and seek in its wide places, if you can find a man, if there is anyone who does justly, who seeks truth, then I will pardon her.\n'),
	(14257, 21, 5, 2, 'Though they say, ‘As Yahweh lives,’ surely they swear falsely.”\n'),
	(14258, 21, 5, 3, 'O Yahweh, don’t your eyes look on truth? You have stricken them, but they were not grieved. You have consumed them, but they have refused to receive correction. They have made their faces harder than a rock. They have refused to return.\n'),
	(14259, 21, 5, 4, 'Then I said, “Surely these are poor. They are foolish; for they don’t know the way of Yahweh, nor the law of their God.\n'),
	(14260, 21, 5, 5, 'I will go to the great men, and will speak to them; for they know the way of Yahweh, and the law of their God.” But these with one accord have broken the yoke, and burst the bonds.\n'),
	(14261, 21, 5, 6, 'Therefore a lion out of the forest will kill them, a wolf of the evenings will destroy them, a leopard will watch against their cities. Everyone who goes out there will be torn in pieces, because their transgressions are many, and their backsliding has increased.\n'),
	(14262, 21, 5, 7, '“How can I pardon you? Your children have forsaken me, and sworn by what are no gods. When I had fed them to the full, they committed adultery, and assembled themselves in troops at the prostitutes’ houses.\n'),
	(14263, 21, 5, 8, 'They were as fed horses roaming at large. Everyone neighed after his neighbor’s wife.\n'),
	(14264, 21, 5, 9, 'Shouldn’t I punish them for these things?” says Yahweh. “Shouldn’t my soul be avenged on such a nation as this?\n'),
	(14265, 21, 5, 10, '“Go up on her walls, and destroy; but don’t make a full end. Take away her branches, for they are not Yahweh’s.\n'),
	(14266, 21, 5, 11, 'For the house of Israel and the house of Judah have dealt very treacherously against me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14267, 21, 5, 12, 'They have denied Yahweh, and said, “It is not he. Evil will won’t come on us. We won’t see sword or famine.\n'),
	(14268, 21, 5, 13, 'The prophets will become wind, and the word is not in them. Thus it will be done to them.”\n'),
	(14269, 21, 5, 14, 'Therefore Yahweh, the God of Armies says, “Because you speak this word, behold, I will make my words in your mouth fire, and this people wood, and it will devour them.\n'),
	(14270, 21, 5, 15, 'Behold, I will bring a nation on you from far away, house of Israel,” says Yahweh. “It is a mighty nation. It is an ancient nation, a nation whose language you don’t know and don’t understand what they say.\n'),
	(14271, 21, 5, 16, 'Their quiver is an open tomb. They are all mighty men.\n'),
	(14272, 21, 5, 17, 'They will eat up your harvest and your bread, which your sons and your daughters should eat. They will eat up your flocks and your herds. They will eat up your vines and your fig trees. They will beat down your fortified cities in which you trust with the sword.\n'),
	(14273, 21, 5, 18, '“But even in those days,” says Yahweh, “I will not make a full end of you.\n'),
	(14274, 21, 5, 19, 'It will happen, when you say, ‘Why has Yahweh our God done all these things to us?’ Then you shall say to them, ‘Just as you have forsaken me, and served foreign gods in your land, so you will serve strangers in a land that is not yours.’\n'),
	(14275, 21, 5, 20, '“Declare this in the house of Jacob, and publish it in Judah, saying,\n'),
	(14276, 21, 5, 21, '‘Hear this now, foolish people without understanding; who have eyes, and don’t see; who have ears, and don’t hear:\n'),
	(14277, 21, 5, 22, 'Don’t you fear me?’ says Yahweh ‘Won’t you tremble at my presence, who have placed the sand for the bound of the sea, by a perpetual decree, that it can’t pass it? Though its waves toss themselves, yet they can’t prevail. Though they roar, they still can’t pass over it.’\n'),
	(14278, 21, 5, 23, '“But this people has a revolting and a rebellious heart. They have revolted and gone.\n'),
	(14279, 21, 5, 24, 'They don’t say in their heart, ‘Let us now fear Yahweh our God, who gives rain, both the former and the latter, in its season; who preserves to us the appointed weeks of the harvest.’\n'),
	(14280, 21, 5, 25, '“Your iniquities have turned away these things, and your sins have withheld good from you.\n'),
	(14281, 21, 5, 26, 'For among my people are found wicked men. They watch, as fowlers lie in wait. They set a trap. They catch men.\n'),
	(14282, 21, 5, 27, 'As a cage is full of birds, so are their houses full of deceit. Therefore they have become great, and grew rich.\n'),
	(14283, 21, 5, 28, 'They have grown fat. They shine; yes, they excel in deeds of wickedness. They don’t plead the cause, the cause of the fatherless, that they may prosper; and they don’t judge the right of the needy.\n'),
	(14284, 21, 5, 29, '“Shouldn’t I punish for these things?” says Yahweh. “Shouldn’t my soul be avenged on such a nation as this?\n'),
	(14285, 21, 5, 30, '“An astonishing and horrible thing has happened in the land.\n'),
	(14286, 21, 5, 31, 'The prophets prophesy falsely, and the priests rule by their own authority; and my people love to have it so. What will you do in the end of it?\n'),
	(14287, 21, 6, 1, '“Flee for safety, you children of Benjamin, out of the middle of Jerusalem! Blow the trumpet in Tekoa and raise up a signal on Beth Haccherem, for evil looks out from the north with a great destruction.\n'),
	(14288, 21, 6, 2, 'I will cut off the beautiful and delicate one, the daughter of Zion.\n'),
	(14289, 21, 6, 3, 'Shepherds with their flocks will come to her. They will pitch their tents against her all around. They will feed everyone in his place.”\n'),
	(14290, 21, 6, 4, '“Prepare war against her! Arise, and let us go up at noon. Woe to us! For the day declines, for the shadows of the evening are stretched out.\n'),
	(14291, 21, 6, 5, 'Arise, and let us go up by night, and let us destroy her palaces.”\n'),
	(14292, 21, 6, 6, 'For Yahweh of Armies said, “Cut down trees, and cast up a mound against Jerusalem. This is the city to be visited. She is wholly oppression within herself.\n'),
	(14293, 21, 6, 7, 'As a well produces its waters, so she produces her wickedness. Violence and destruction is heard in her. Sickness and wounds are continually before me.\n'),
	(14294, 21, 6, 8, 'Be instructed, Jerusalem, lest my soul be alienated from you; lest I make you a desolation, an uninhabited land.”\n'),
	(14295, 21, 6, 9, 'Yahweh of Armies says, “They will thoroughly glean the remnant of Israel like a vine. Turn again your hand as a grape gatherer into the baskets.”\n'),
	(14296, 21, 6, 10, 'To whom should I speak and testify, that they may hear? Behold, their ear is uncircumcised, and they can’t listen. Behold, Yahweh’s word has become a reproach to them. They have no delight in it.\n'),
	(14297, 21, 6, 11, 'Therefore I am full of Yahweh’s wrath. I am weary with holding it in.\n“Pour it out on the children in the street,\nand on the assembly of young men together;\nfor even the husband with the wife will be taken,\nthe aged with him who is full of days.\n'),
	(14298, 21, 6, 12, 'Their houses will be turned to others,\ntheir fields and their wives together;\nfor I will stretch out my hand on the inhabitants of the land, says Yahweh.”\n'),
	(14299, 21, 6, 13, '“For from their least even to their greatest, everyone is given to covetousness.\nFrom the prophet even to the priest, everyone deals falsely.\n'),
	(14300, 21, 6, 14, 'They have healed also the hurt of my people superficially,\nsaying, ‘Peace, peace!’ when there is no peace.\n'),
	(14301, 21, 6, 15, 'Were they ashamed when they had committed abomination?\nNo, they were not at all ashamed, neither could they blush.\nTherefore they will fall among those who fall.\nWhen I visit them, they will be cast down,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14302, 21, 6, 16, 'Yahweh says, “Stand in the ways and see, and ask for the old paths, ‘Where is the good way?’ and walk in it, and you will find rest for your souls. But they said, ‘We will not walk in it.’\n'),
	(14303, 21, 6, 17, 'I set watchmen over you, saying, ‘Listen to the sound of the trumpet!’ But they said, ‘We will not listen!’\n'),
	(14304, 21, 6, 18, 'Therefore hear, you nations, and know, congregation, what is among them.\n'),
	(14305, 21, 6, 19, 'Hear, earth! Behold, I will bring evil on this people, even the fruit of their thoughts, because they have not listened to my words; and as for my law, they have rejected it.\n'),
	(14306, 21, 6, 20, 'To what purpose does frankincense from Sheba come to me, and the sweet cane from a far country? Your burnt offerings are not acceptable, and your sacrifices are not pleasing to me.”\n'),
	(14307, 21, 6, 21, 'Therefore Yahweh says, “Behold, I will lay stumbling blocks before this people. The fathers and the sons together will stumble against them. The neighbor and his friend will perish.”\n'),
	(14308, 21, 6, 22, 'Yahweh says, “Behold, a people comes from the north country. A great nation will be stirred up from the uttermost parts of the earth.\n'),
	(14309, 21, 6, 23, 'They take hold of bow and spear. They are cruel, and have no mercy. Their voice roars like the sea, and they ride on horses, everyone set in array, as a man to the battle, against you, daughter of Zion.”\n'),
	(14310, 21, 6, 24, 'We have heard its report. Our hands become feeble. Anguish has taken hold of us, and pains as of a woman in labor.\n'),
	(14311, 21, 6, 25, 'Don’t go out into the field, nor walk by the way; for the sword of the enemy and terror are on every side.\n'),
	(14312, 21, 6, 26, 'Daughter of my people, clothe yourself with sackcloth, and wallow in ashes! Mourn, as for an only son, most bitter lamentation, for the destroyer will suddenly come on us.\n'),
	(14313, 21, 6, 27, '“I have made you a tester of metals and a fortress among my people, that you may know and try their way.\n'),
	(14314, 21, 6, 28, 'They are all grievous rebels, going around to slander. They are brass and iron. All of them deal corruptly.\n'),
	(14315, 21, 6, 29, 'The bellows blow fiercely. The lead is consumed in the fire. In vain they go on refining, for the wicked are not plucked away.\n'),
	(14316, 21, 6, 30, 'Men will call them rejected silver, because Yahweh has rejected them.”\n'),
	(14317, 21, 7, 1, 'The word that came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(14318, 21, 7, 2, '“Stand in the gate of Yahweh’s house, and proclaim this word there, and say, ‘Hear Yahweh’s word, all you of Judah, who enter in at these gates to worship Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(14319, 21, 7, 3, 'Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says, “Amend your ways and your doings, and I will cause you to dwell in this place.\n'),
	(14320, 21, 7, 4, 'Don’t trust in lying words, saying, ‘Yahweh’s temple, Yahweh’s temple, Yahweh’s temple, are these.’\n'),
	(14321, 21, 7, 5, 'For if you thoroughly amend your ways and your doings, if you thoroughly execute justice between a man and his neighbor;\n'),
	(14322, 21, 7, 6, 'if you don’t oppress the foreigner, the fatherless, and the widow, and don’t shed innocent blood in this place, and don’t walk after other gods to your own hurt;\n'),
	(14323, 21, 7, 7, 'then I will cause you to dwell in this place, in the land that I gave to your fathers, from of old even forever more.\n'),
	(14324, 21, 7, 8, 'Behold, you trust in lying words that can’t profit.\n'),
	(14325, 21, 7, 9, 'Will you steal, murder, commit adultery, swear falsely, burn incense to Baal, and walk after other gods that you have not known,\n'),
	(14326, 21, 7, 10, 'then come and stand before me in this house, which is called by my name, and say, ‘We are delivered;’ that you may do all these abominations?\n'),
	(14327, 21, 7, 11, 'Has this house, which is called by my name, become a den of robbers in your eyes? Behold, I myself have seen it,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14328, 21, 7, 12, '“But go now to my place which was in Shiloh, where I caused my name to dwell at the first, and see what I did to it for the wickedness of my people Israel.\n'),
	(14329, 21, 7, 13, 'Now, because you have done all these works,” says Yahweh, “and I spoke to you, rising up early and speaking, but you didn’t hear; and I called you, but you didn’t answer;\n'),
	(14330, 21, 7, 14, 'therefore I will do to the house which is called by my name, in which you trust, and to the place which I gave to you and to your fathers, as I did to Shiloh.\n'),
	(14331, 21, 7, 15, 'I will cast you out of my sight, as I have cast out all your brothers, even the whole offspring of Ephraim.\n'),
	(14332, 21, 7, 16, '“Therefore don’t pray for this people. Don’t lift up a cry or prayer for them or make intercession to me; for I will not hear you.\n'),
	(14333, 21, 7, 17, 'Don’t you see what they do in the cities of Judah and in the streets of Jerusalem?\n'),
	(14334, 21, 7, 18, 'The children gather wood, and the fathers kindle the fire, and the women knead the dough, to make cakes to the queen of the sky, and to pour out drink offerings to other gods, that they may provoke me to anger.\n'),
	(14335, 21, 7, 19, 'Do they provoke me to anger?” says Yahweh. “Don’t they provoke themselves, to the confusion of their own faces?”\n'),
	(14336, 21, 7, 20, 'Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, my anger and my wrath will be poured out on this place, on man, on animal, on the trees of the field, and on the fruit of the ground; and it will burn and will not be quenched.”\n'),
	(14337, 21, 7, 21, 'Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says: “Add your burnt offerings to your sacrifices and eat meat.\n'),
	(14338, 21, 7, 22, 'For I didn’t speak to your fathers or command them in the day that I brought them out of the land of Egypt concerning burnt offerings or sacrifices;\n'),
	(14339, 21, 7, 23, 'but this thing I commanded them, saying, ‘Listen to my voice, and I will be your God, and you shall be my people; and walk in all the way that I command you, that it may be well with you.’\n'),
	(14340, 21, 7, 24, 'But they didn’t listen or turn their ear, but walked in their own counsels and in the stubbornness of their evil heart, and went backward, and not forward.\n'),
	(14341, 21, 7, 25, 'Since the day that your fathers came out of the land of Egypt to this day, I have sent to you all my servants the prophets, daily rising up early and sending them.\n'),
	(14342, 21, 7, 26, 'Yet they didn’t listen to me or incline their ear, but made their neck stiff. They did worse than their fathers.\n'),
	(14343, 21, 7, 27, '“You shall speak all these words to them, but they will not listen to you. You shall also call to them, but they will not answer you.\n'),
	(14344, 21, 7, 28, 'You shall tell them, ‘This is the nation that has not listened to Yahweh their God’s voice, nor received instruction. Truth has perished, and is cut off from their mouth.’\n'),
	(14345, 21, 7, 29, 'Cut off your hair, and throw it away, and take up a lamentation on the bare heights; for Yahweh has rejected and forsaken the generation of his wrath.\n'),
	(14346, 21, 7, 30, '“For the children of Judah have done that which is evil in my sight,” says Yahweh. “They have set their abominations in the house which is called by my name, to defile it.\n'),
	(14347, 21, 7, 31, 'They have built the high places of Topheth, which is in the valley of the son of Hinnom, to burn their sons and their daughters in the fire; which I didn’t command, nor did it come into my mind.\n'),
	(14348, 21, 7, 32, 'Therefore behold, the days come”, says Yahweh, “that it will no more be called ‘Topheth’ or ‘The valley of the son of Hinnom’, but ‘The valley of Slaughter’; for they will bury in Topheth until there is no place to bury.\n'),
	(14349, 21, 7, 33, 'The dead bodies of this people will be food for the birds of the sky, and for the animals of the earth. No one will frighten them away.\n'),
	(14350, 21, 7, 34, 'Then I will cause to cease from the cities of Judah, and from the streets of Jerusalem, the voice of mirth and the voice of gladness, the voice of the bridegroom and the voice of the bride; for the land will become a waste.”\n'),
	(14351, 21, 8, 1, '“At that time,” says Yahweh, “they will bring out the bones of the kings of Judah, the bones of his princes, the bones of the priests, the bones of the prophets, and the bones of the inhabitants of Jerusalem, out of their graves.\n'),
	(14352, 21, 8, 2, 'They will spread them before the sun, the moon, and all the army of the sky, which they have loved, which they have served, after which they have walked, which they have sought, and which they have worshiped. They will not be gathered or be buried. They will be for dung on the surface of the earth.\n'),
	(14353, 21, 8, 3, 'Death will be chosen rather than life by all the residue that remain of this evil family, that remain in all the places where I have driven them,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(14354, 21, 8, 4, '“Moreover you shall tell them, ‘Yahweh says:\n“‘Do men fall, and not rise up again?\nDoes one turn away, and not return?\n'),
	(14355, 21, 8, 5, 'Why then have the people of Jerusalem fallen back by a perpetual backsliding?\nThey cling to deceit.\nThey refuse to return.\n'),
	(14356, 21, 8, 6, 'I listened and heard, but they didn’t say what is right.\nNo one repents of his wickedness, saying, “What have I done?”\nEveryone turns to his course,\nas a horse that rushes headlong in the battle.\n'),
	(14357, 21, 8, 7, 'Yes, the stork in the sky knows her appointed times.\nThe turtledove, the swallow, and the crane observe the time of their coming;\nbut my people don’t know Yahweh’s law.\n'),
	(14358, 21, 8, 8, '“‘How do you say, “We are wise, and Yahweh’s law is with us?”\nBut, behold, the false pen of the scribes has worked falsely.\n'),
	(14359, 21, 8, 9, 'The wise men are disappointed.\nThey are dismayed and trapped.\nBehold, they have rejected Yahweh’s word.\nWhat kind of wisdom is in them?\n'),
	(14360, 21, 8, 10, 'Therefore will I give their wives to others,\nand their fields to those who will possess them.\nFor everyone from the least even to the greatest is given to covetousness;\nfrom the prophet even to the priest everyone deals falsely.\n'),
	(14361, 21, 8, 11, 'They have healed the hurt of the daughter of my people slightly, saying,\n“Peace, peace,” when there is no peace.\n'),
	(14362, 21, 8, 12, 'Were they ashamed when they had committed abomination?\nNo, they were not at all ashamed.\nThey couldn’t blush.\nTherefore they will fall among those who fall.\nIn the time of their visitation they will be cast down, says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14363, 21, 8, 13, '“‘I will utterly consume them, says Yahweh.\nNo grapes will be on the vine,\nno figs on the fig tree,\nand the leaf will fade.\nThe things that I have given them\nwill pass away from them.’”\n'),
	(14364, 21, 8, 14, '“Why do we sit still?\nAssemble yourselves,\nand let us enter into the fortified cities,\nand let us be silent there;\nfor Yahweh our God has put us to silence,\nand given us water of gall to drink,\nbecause we have sinned against Yahweh.\n'),
	(14365, 21, 8, 15, 'We looked for peace, but no good came;\nand for a time of healing, and behold, dismay!\n'),
	(14366, 21, 8, 16, 'The snorting of his horses is heard from Dan.\nThe whole land trembles at the sound of the neighing of his strong ones;\nfor they have come, and have devoured the land and all that is in it;\nthe city and those who dwell therein.”\n'),
	(14367, 21, 8, 17, '“For, behold, I will send serpents,\nadders among you,\nwhich will not be charmed;\nand they will bite you,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14368, 21, 8, 18, 'Oh that I could comfort myself against sorrow!\nMy heart is faint within me.\n'),
	(14369, 21, 8, 19, 'Behold, the voice of the cry of the daughter of my people from a land that is very far off:\n“Isn’t Yahweh in Zion?\nIsn’t her King in her?”\n“Why have they provoked me to anger with their engraved images,\nand with foreign idols?”\n'),
	(14370, 21, 8, 20, '“The harvest is past.\nThe summer has ended,\nand we are not saved.”\n'),
	(14371, 21, 8, 21, 'For the hurt of the daughter of my people, I am hurt.\nI mourn.\nDismay has taken hold of me.\n'),
	(14372, 21, 8, 22, 'Is there no balm in Gilead?\nIs there no physician there?\nWhy then isn’t the health of the daughter of my people recovered?\n'),
	(14373, 21, 9, 1, 'Oh that my head were waters,\nand my eyes a spring of tears,\nthat I might weep day and night\nfor the slain of the daughter of my people!\n'),
	(14374, 21, 9, 2, 'Oh that I had in the wilderness\na lodging place of wayfaring men;\nthat I might leave my people,\nand go from them!\nFor they are all adulterers,\nan assembly of treacherous men.\n'),
	(14375, 21, 9, 3, '“They bend their tongue,\nas their bow, for falsehood.\nThey have grown strong in the land,\nbut not for truth;\nfor they proceed from evil to evil,\nand they don’t know me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14376, 21, 9, 4, '“Everyone beware of his neighbor,\nand don’t trust in any brother;\nfor every brother will utterly supplant,\nand every neighbor will go around with slanders.\n'),
	(14377, 21, 9, 5, 'Everyone will deceive their neighbors,\nand will not speak the truth.\nThey have taught their tongue to speak lies.\nThey weary themselves commiting iniquity.\n'),
	(14378, 21, 9, 6, 'Your habitation is in the middle of deceit.\nThrough deceit, they refuse to know me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14379, 21, 9, 7, 'Therefore Yahweh of Armies says,\n“Behold, I will melt them and test them;\nfor how should I deal with the daughter of my people?\n'),
	(14380, 21, 9, 8, 'Their tongue is a deadly arrow.\nIt speaks deceit.\nOne speaks peaceably to his neighbor with his mouth,\nbut in his heart, he waits to ambush him.\n'),
	(14381, 21, 9, 9, 'Shouldn’t I punish them for these things?” says Yahweh.\n“Shouldn’t my soul be avenged on a nation such as this?\n'),
	(14382, 21, 9, 10, 'I will weep and wail for the mountains,\nand lament for the pastures of the wilderness,\nbecause they are burned up, so that no one passes through;\nMen can’t hear the voice of the livestock.\nBoth the birds of the sky and the animals have fled.\nThey are gone.\n'),
	(14383, 21, 9, 11, '“I will make Jerusalem heaps,\na dwelling place of jackals.\nI will make the cities of Judah a desolation,\nwithout inhabitant.”\n'),
	(14384, 21, 9, 12, 'Who is wise enough to understand this? Who is he to whom the mouth of Yahweh has spoken, that he may declare it? Why has the land perished and burned up like a wilderness, so that no one passes through?\n'),
	(14385, 21, 9, 13, 'Yahweh says, “Because they have forsaken my law which I set before them, and have not obeyed my voice, neither walked therein,\n'),
	(14386, 21, 9, 14, 'but have walked after the stubbornness of their own heart, and after the Baals, which their fathers taught them.”\n'),
	(14387, 21, 9, 15, 'Therefore Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says, “Behold, I will feed them, even this people, with wormwood, and give them water of gall to drink.\n'),
	(14388, 21, 9, 16, 'I will scatter them also among the nations, whom neither they nor their fathers have known; and I will send the sword after them, until I have consumed them.”\n'),
	(14389, 21, 9, 17, 'Yahweh of Armies says,\n“Consider, and call for the mourning women, that they may come;\nand send for the skillful women, that they may come.\n'),
	(14390, 21, 9, 18, 'Let them make haste,\nand take up a wailing for us,\nthat our eyes may run down with tears,\nand our eyelids gush out with waters.\n'),
	(14391, 21, 9, 19, 'For a voice of wailing is heard out of Zion,\n‘How we are ruined!\nWe are greatly confounded,\nbecause we have forsaken the land,\nbecause they have cast down our dwellings.’”\n'),
	(14392, 21, 9, 20, 'Yet hear Yahweh’s word, you women.\nLet your ear receive the word of his mouth.\nTeach your daughters wailing,\nand everyone her neighbor lamentation.\n'),
	(14393, 21, 9, 21, 'For death has come up into our windows.\nIt has entered into our palaces\nto cut off the children from outside,\nand the young men from the streets.\n'),
	(14394, 21, 9, 22, 'Speak, “Yahweh says,\n“‘The dead bodies of men will fall as dung on the open field,\nand as the handful after the harvester;\nand no one will gather them.’”\n'),
	(14395, 21, 9, 23, 'Yahweh says,\n“Don’t let the wise man glory in his wisdom.\nDon’t let the mighty man glory in his might.\nDon’t let the rich man glory in his riches.\n'),
	(14396, 21, 9, 24, 'But let him who glories glory in this,\nthat he has understanding, and knows me,\nthat I am Yahweh who exercises loving kindness, justice, and righteousness, in the earth;\nfor I delight in these things,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14397, 21, 9, 25, '“Behold, the days come,” says Yahweh, “that I will punish all those who are circumcised only in their flesh:\n'),
	(14398, 21, 9, 26, 'Egypt, Judah, Edom, the children of Ammon, Moab, and all who have the corners of their hair cut off, who dwell in the wilderness; for all the nations are uncircumcised, and all the house of Israel are uncircumcised in heart.”\n'),
	(14399, 21, 10, 1, 'Hear the word which Yahweh speaks to you, house of Israel!\n'),
	(14400, 21, 10, 2, 'Yahweh says,\n“Don’t learn the way of the nations,\nand don’t be dismayed at the signs of the sky;\nfor the nations are dismayed at them.\n'),
	(14401, 21, 10, 3, 'For the customs of the peoples are vanity;\nfor one cuts a tree out of the forest,\nthe work of the hands of the workman with the ax.\n'),
	(14402, 21, 10, 4, 'They deck it with silver and with gold.\nThey fasten it with nails and with hammers,\nso that it can’t move.\n'),
	(14403, 21, 10, 5, 'They are like a palm tree, of turned work,\nand don’t speak.\nThey must be carried,\nbecause they can’t move.\nDon’t be afraid of them;\nfor they can’t do evil,\nneither is it in them to do good.”\n'),
	(14404, 21, 10, 6, 'There is no one like you, Yahweh.\nYou are great,\nand your name is great in might.\n'),
	(14405, 21, 10, 7, 'Who shouldn’t fear you,\nKing of the nations?\nFor it belongs to you.\nBecause among all the wise men of the nations,\nand in all their royal estate,\nthere is no one like you.\n'),
	(14406, 21, 10, 8, 'But they are together brutish and foolish,\ninstructed by idols!\nIt is just wood.\n'),
	(14407, 21, 10, 9, 'There is silver beaten into plates, which is brought from Tarshish,\nand gold from Uphaz,\nthe work of the engraver and of the hands of the goldsmith.\nTheir clothing is blue and purple.\nThey are all the work of skillful men.\n'),
	(14408, 21, 10, 10, 'But Yahweh is the true God.\nHe is the living God,\nand an everlasting King.\nAt his wrath, the earth trembles.\nThe nations aren’t able to withstand his indignation.\n'),
	(14409, 21, 10, 11, '“You shall say this to them: ‘The gods that have not made the heavens and the earth will perish from the earth, and from under the heavens.’”\n'),
	(14410, 21, 10, 12, 'God has made the earth by his power.\nHe has established the world by his wisdom,\nand by his understanding has he stretched out the heavens.\n'),
	(14411, 21, 10, 13, 'When he utters his voice,\nthe waters in the heavens roar,\nand he causes the vapors to ascend from the ends of the earth.\nHe makes lightnings for the rain,\nand brings the wind out of his treasuries.\n'),
	(14412, 21, 10, 14, 'Every man has become brutish and without knowledge.\nEvery goldsmith is disappointed by his engraved image;\nfor his molten image is falsehood,\nand there is no breath in them.\n'),
	(14413, 21, 10, 15, 'They are vanity, a work of delusion.\nIn the time of their visitation they will perish.\n'),
	(14414, 21, 10, 16, 'The portion of Jacob is not like these;\nfor he is the maker of all things;\nand Israel is the tribe of his inheritance:\nYahweh of Armies is his name.\n'),
	(14415, 21, 10, 17, 'Gather up your wares out of the land,\nyou who live under siege.\n'),
	(14416, 21, 10, 18, 'For Yahweh says,\n“Behold, I will sling out the inhabitants of the land at this time,\nand will distress them, that they may feel it.”\n'),
	(14417, 21, 10, 19, 'Woe is me because of my injury!\nMy wound is serious;\nbut I said,\n“Truly this is my grief, and I must bear it.”\n'),
	(14418, 21, 10, 20, 'My tent has been destroyed,\nand all my cords are broken.\nMy children have gone away from me, and they are no more.\nThere is no one to spread my tent any more,\nto set up my curtains.\n'),
	(14419, 21, 10, 21, 'For the shepherds have become brutish,\nand have not inquired of Yahweh.\nTherefore they have not prospered,\nand all their flocks have scattered.\n'),
	(14420, 21, 10, 22, 'The voice of news, behold, it comes,\nand a great commotion out of the north country,\nto make the cities of Judah a desolation,\na dwelling place of jackals.\n'),
	(14421, 21, 10, 23, 'Yahweh, I know that the way of man is not in himself.\nIt is not in man who walks to direct his steps.\n'),
	(14422, 21, 10, 24, 'Yahweh, correct me, but gently;\nnot in your anger,\nlest you reduce me to nothing.\n'),
	(14423, 21, 10, 25, 'Pour out your wrath on the nations that don’t know you,\nand on the families that don’t call on your name;\nfor they have devoured Jacob.\nYes, they have devoured him, consumed him,\nand have laid waste his habitation.\n'),
	(14424, 21, 11, 1, 'The word that came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(14425, 21, 11, 2, '“Hear the words of this covenant, and speak to the men of Judah, and to the inhabitants of Jerusalem;\n'),
	(14426, 21, 11, 3, 'and say to them, Yahweh, the God of Israel says: ‘Cursed is the man who doesn’t hear the words of this covenant,\n'),
	(14427, 21, 11, 4, 'which I commanded your fathers in the day that I brought them out of the land of Egypt, out of the iron furnace,’ saying, ‘Obey my voice, and do them, according to all which I command you; so you shall be my people, and I will be your God;\n'),
	(14428, 21, 11, 5, 'that I may establish the oath which I swore to your fathers, to give them a land flowing with milk and honey,’ as it is today.”\nThen answered I, and said, “Amen, Yahweh.”\n'),
	(14429, 21, 11, 6, 'Yahweh said to me, “Proclaim all these words in the cities of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem, saying, ‘Hear the words of this covenant, and do them.\n'),
	(14430, 21, 11, 7, 'For I earnestly protested to your fathers in the day that I brought them up out of the land of Egypt, even to this day, rising early and protesting, saying, “Obey my voice.”\n'),
	(14431, 21, 11, 8, 'Yet they didn’t obey, nor turn their ear, but everyone walked in the stubbornness of their evil heart. Therefore I brought on them all the words of this covenant, which I commanded them to do, but they didn’t do them.’”\n'),
	(14432, 21, 11, 9, 'Yahweh said to me, “A conspiracy is found among the men of Judah, and among the inhabitants of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(14433, 21, 11, 10, 'They have turned back to the iniquities of their forefathers, who refused to hear my words. They have gone after other gods to serve them. The house of Israel and the house of Judah have broken my covenant which I made with their fathers.\n'),
	(14434, 21, 11, 11, 'Therefore Yahweh says, ‘Behold, I will bring evil on them, which they will not be able to escape; and they will cry to me, but I will not listen to them.\n'),
	(14435, 21, 11, 12, 'Then the cities of Judah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem will go and cry to the gods to which they offer incense, but they will not save them at all in the time of their trouble.\n'),
	(14436, 21, 11, 13, 'For according to the number of your cities are your gods, Judah; and according to the number of the streets of Jerusalem have you set up altars to the shameful thing, even altars to burn incense to Baal.’\n'),
	(14437, 21, 11, 14, '“Therefore don’t pray for this people. Don’t lift up cry or prayer for them; for I will not hear them in the time that they cry to me because of their trouble.\n'),
	(14438, 21, 11, 15, 'What has my beloved to do in my house,\nsince she has behaved lewdly with many,\nand the holy flesh has passed from you?\nWhen you do evil,\nthen you rejoice.”\n'),
	(14439, 21, 11, 16, 'Yahweh called your name, “A green olive tree,\nbeautiful with goodly fruit.”\nWith the noise of a great roar he has kindled fire on it,\nand its branches are broken.\n'),
	(14440, 21, 11, 17, 'For Yahweh of Armies, who planted you, has pronounced evil against you, because of the evil of the house of Israel and of the house of Judah, which they have done to themselves in provoking me to anger by offering incense to Baal.\n'),
	(14441, 21, 11, 18, 'Yahweh gave me knowledge of it, and I knew it. Then you showed me their doings.\n'),
	(14442, 21, 11, 19, 'But I was like a gentle lamb that is led to the slaughter. I didn’t know that they had devised plans against me, saying,\n“Let us destroy the tree with its fruit,\nand let us cut him off from the land of the living,\nthat his name may be no more remembered.”\n'),
	(14443, 21, 11, 20, 'But, Yahweh of Armies, who judges righteously,\nwho tests the heart and the mind,\nI will see your vengeance on them;\nfor to you I have revealed my cause.\n'),
	(14444, 21, 11, 21, '“Therefore Yahweh says concerning the men of Anathoth, who seek your life, saying, ‘You shall not prophesy in Yahweh’s name, that you not die by our hand;’\n'),
	(14445, 21, 11, 22, 'therefore Yahweh of Armies says, ‘Behold, I will punish them. The young men will die by the sword. Their sons and their daughters will die by famine.\n'),
	(14446, 21, 11, 23, 'There will be no remnant to them, for I will bring evil on the men of Anathoth, even the year of their visitation.’”\n'),
	(14447, 21, 12, 1, 'You are righteous, Yahweh,\nwhen I contend with you;\nyet I would like to reason the cause with you.\nWhy does the way of the wicked prosper?\nWhy are they all at ease who deal very treacherously?\n'),
	(14448, 21, 12, 2, 'You have planted them. Yes, they have taken root.\nThey grow. Yes, they produce fruit.\nYou are near in their mouth,\nand far from their heart.\n'),
	(14449, 21, 12, 3, 'But you, Yahweh, know me.\nYou see me, and test my heart toward you.\nPull them out like sheep for the slaughter,\nand prepare them for the day of slaughter.\n'),
	(14450, 21, 12, 4, 'How long will the land mourn,\nand the herbs of the whole country wither?\nBecause of the wickedness of those who dwell therein,\nthe animals and birds are consumed;\nbecause they said,\n“He won’t see our latter end.”\n'),
	(14451, 21, 12, 5, '“If you have run with the footmen,\nand they have wearied you,\nthen how can you contend with horses?\nThough in a land of peace you are secure,\nyet how will you do in the pride of the Jordan?\n'),
	(14452, 21, 12, 6, 'For even your brothers, and the house of your father,\neven they have dealt treacherously with you!\nEven they have cried aloud after you!\nDon’t believe them,\nthough they speak beautiful words to you.\n'),
	(14453, 21, 12, 7, '“I have forsaken my house.\nI have cast off my heritage.\nI have given the dearly beloved of my soul into the hand of her enemies.\n'),
	(14454, 21, 12, 8, 'My heritage has become to me as a lion in the forest.\nShe has uttered her voice against me.\nTherefore I have hated her.\n'),
	(14455, 21, 12, 9, 'Is my heritage to me as a speckled bird of prey?\nAre the birds of prey against her all around?\nGo, assemble all the animals of the field.\nBring them to devour.\n'),
	(14456, 21, 12, 10, 'Many shepherds have destroyed my vineyard.\nThey have trodden my portion under foot.\nThey have made my pleasant portion a desolate wilderness.\n'),
	(14457, 21, 12, 11, 'They have made it a desolation.\nIt mourns to me, being desolate.\nThe whole land is made desolate,\nbecause no one cares.\n'),
	(14458, 21, 12, 12, 'Destroyers have come on all the bare heights in the wilderness;\nfor the sword of Yahweh devours from the one end of the land even to the other end of the land.\nNo flesh has peace.\n'),
	(14459, 21, 12, 13, 'They have sown wheat,\nand have reaped thorns.\nThey have exhausted themselves,\nand profit nothing.\nYou will be ashamed of your fruits,\nbecause of Yahweh’s fierce anger.”\n'),
	(14460, 21, 12, 14, 'Yahweh says, “Concerning all my evil neighbors, who touch the inheritance which I have caused my people Israel to inherit: Behold, I will pluck them up from off their land, and will pluck up the house of Judah from among them.\n'),
	(14461, 21, 12, 15, 'It will happen, that after I have plucked them up, I will return and have compassion on them. I will bring them again, every man to his heritage, and every man to his land.\n'),
	(14462, 21, 12, 16, 'It will happen, if they will diligently learn the ways of my people, to swear by my name, ‘As Yahweh lives;’ even as they taught my people to swear by Baal; then will they be built up in the middle of my people.\n'),
	(14463, 21, 12, 17, 'But if they will not hear, then I will pluck up that nation, plucking up and destroying it,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14464, 21, 13, 1, 'Yahweh said to me, “Go, and buy yourself a linen belt, and put it on your waist, and don’t put it in water.”\n'),
	(14465, 21, 13, 2, 'So I bought a belt according to Yahweh’s word, and put it on my waist.\n'),
	(14466, 21, 13, 3, 'Yahweh’s word came to me the second time, saying,\n'),
	(14467, 21, 13, 4, '“Take the belt that you have bought, which is on your waist, and arise, go to the Euphrates, and hide it there in a cleft of the rock.”\n'),
	(14468, 21, 13, 5, 'So I went, and hid it by the Euphrates, as Yahweh commanded me.\n'),
	(14469, 21, 13, 6, 'After many days, Yahweh said to me, “Arise, go to the Euphrates, and take the belt from there, which I commanded you to hide there.”\n'),
	(14470, 21, 13, 7, 'Then I went to the Euphrates, and dug, and took the belt from the place where I had hidden it; and behold, the belt was ruined. It was profitable for nothing.\n'),
	(14471, 21, 13, 8, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(14472, 21, 13, 9, '“Yahweh says, ‘In this way I, will ruin the pride of Judah, and the great pride of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(14473, 21, 13, 10, 'This evil people, who refuse to hear my words, who walk in the stubbornness of their heart, and have gone after other gods to serve them, and to worship them, will even be as this belt, which is profitable for nothing.\n'),
	(14474, 21, 13, 11, 'For as the belt clings to the waist of a man, so I have caused the whole house of Israel and the whole house of Judah to cling to me,’ says Yahweh; ‘that they may be to me for a people, for a name, for praise, and for glory; but they would not hear.’\n'),
	(14475, 21, 13, 12, '“Therefore you shall speak to them this word: ‘Yahweh, the God of Israel says, “Every bottle should be filled with wine.”’ They will tell you, ‘Do we not certainly know that every bottle should be filled with wine?’\n'),
	(14476, 21, 13, 13, 'Then tell them, ‘Yahweh says, “Behold, I will fill all the inhabitants of this land, even the kings who sit on David’s throne, the priests, the prophets, and all the inhabitants of Jerusalem, with drunkenness.\n'),
	(14477, 21, 13, 14, 'I will dash them one against another, even the fathers and the sons together,” says Yahweh: “I will not pity, spare, or have compassion, that I should not destroy them.”’”\n'),
	(14478, 21, 13, 15, 'Hear, and give ear.\nDon’t be proud,\nfor Yahweh has spoken.\n'),
	(14479, 21, 13, 16, 'Give glory to Yahweh your God,\nbefore he causes darkness,\nand before your feet stumble on the dark mountains,\nand, while you look for light,\nhe turns it into the shadow of death,\nand makes it deep darkness.\n'),
	(14480, 21, 13, 17, 'But if you will not hear it,\nmy soul will weep in secret for your pride.\nMy eye will weep bitterly,\nand run down with tears,\nbecause Yahweh’s flock has been taken captive.\n'),
	(14481, 21, 13, 18, 'Say to the king and to the queen mother,\n“Humble yourselves.\nSit down, for your crowns have come down,\neven the crown of your glory.\n'),
	(14482, 21, 13, 19, 'The cities of the South is shut up,\nand there is no one to open them.\nJudah is carried away captive: all of it.\nIt is wholly carried away captive.\n'),
	(14483, 21, 13, 20, 'Lift up your eyes,\nand see those who come from the north.\nWhere is the flock that was given to you,\nyour beautiful flock?\n'),
	(14484, 21, 13, 21, 'What will you say, when he sets over you as head those whom you have yourself taught to be friends to you?\nWon’t sorrows take hold of you, as of a woman in travail?\n'),
	(14485, 21, 13, 22, 'If you say in your heart,\n“Why have these things come on me?”\nYour skirts are uncovered because of the greatness of your iniquity,\nand your heels suffer violence.\n'),
	(14486, 21, 13, 23, 'Can the Ethiopian change his skin,\nor the leopard his spots?\nThen may you also do good,\nwho are accustomed to do evil.\n'),
	(14487, 21, 13, 24, '“Therefore I will scatter them,\nas the stubble that passes away,\nby the wind of the wilderness.\n'),
	(14488, 21, 13, 25, 'This is your lot,\nthe portion measured to you from me,” says Yahweh,\n“because you have forgotten me,\nand trusted in falsehood.”\n'),
	(14489, 21, 13, 26, 'Therefore will I also uncover your skirts on your face,\nand your shame will appear.\n'),
	(14490, 21, 13, 27, 'I have seen your abominations, even your adulteries,\nand your neighing, the lewdness of your prostitution,\non the hills in the field.\nWoe to you, Jerusalem!\nYou will not be made clean.\nHow long will it yet be?”\n'),
	(14491, 21, 14, 1, 'This is Yahweh’s word that came to Jeremiah concerning the drought.\n'),
	(14492, 21, 14, 2, '“Judah mourns,\nand its gates languish.\nThey sit in black on the ground.\nThe cry of Jerusalem goes up.\n'),
	(14493, 21, 14, 3, 'Their nobles send their little ones to the waters.\nThey come to the cisterns,\nand find no water.\nThey return with their vessels empty.\nThey are disappointed and confounded,\nand cover their heads.\n'),
	(14494, 21, 14, 4, 'Because of the ground which is cracked,\nbecause no rain has been in the land,\nthe plowmen are disappointed.\nThey cover their heads.\n'),
	(14495, 21, 14, 5, 'Yes, the doe in the field also calves and forsakes her young,\nbecause there is no grass.\n'),
	(14496, 21, 14, 6, 'The wild donkeys stand on the bare heights.\nThey pant for air like jackals.\nTheir eyes fail,\nbecause there is no vegetation.\n'),
	(14497, 21, 14, 7, 'Though our iniquities testify against us,\nwork for your name’s sake, Yahweh;\nfor our rebellions are many.\nWe have sinned against you.\n'),
	(14498, 21, 14, 8, 'You hope of Israel,\nits Savior in the time of trouble,\nwhy should you be as a foreigner in the land,\nand as a wayfaring man who turns aside to stay for a night?\n'),
	(14499, 21, 14, 9, 'Why should you be like a scared man,\nas a mighty man who can’t save?\nYet you, Yahweh, are in the middle of us,\nand we are called by your name.\nDon’t leave us.\n'),
	(14500, 21, 14, 10, 'Yahweh says to this people,\n“Even so they have loved to wander.\nThey have not restrained their feet.\nTherefore Yahweh does not accept them.\nNow he will remember their iniquity,\nand punish them for their sins.”\n'),
	(14501, 21, 14, 11, 'Yahweh said to me, “Don’t pray for this people for their good.\n'),
	(14502, 21, 14, 12, 'When they fast, I will not hear their cry; and when they offer burnt offering and meal offering, I will not accept them; but I will consume them by the sword, by famine, and by pestilence.”\n'),
	(14503, 21, 14, 13, 'Then I said, “Ah, Lord Yahweh! Behold, the prophets tell them, ‘You will not see the sword, neither will you have famine; but I will give you assured peace in this place.’”\n'),
	(14504, 21, 14, 14, 'Then Yahweh said to me, “The prophets prophesy lies in my name. I didn’t send them. I didn’t command them. I didn’t speak to them. They prophesy to you a lying vision, divination, and a thing of nothing, and the deceit of their own heart.\n'),
	(14505, 21, 14, 15, 'Therefore Yahweh says concerning the prophets who prophesy in my name, but I didn’t send them, yet they say, ‘Sword and famine will not be in this land.’ Those prophets will be consumed by sword and famine.\n'),
	(14506, 21, 14, 16, 'The people to whom they prophesy will be cast out in the streets of Jerusalem because of the famine and the sword. They will have no one to bury them—them, their wives, their sons, or their daughters, for I will pour their wickedness on them.\n'),
	(14507, 21, 14, 17, '“You shall say this word to them:\n“‘Let my eyes run down with tears night and day,\nand let them not cease;\nfor the virgin daughter of my people is broken with a great breach,\nwith a very grievous wound.\n'),
	(14508, 21, 14, 18, 'If I go out into the field,\nthen, behold, the slain with the sword!\nIf I enter into the city,\nthen, behold, those who are sick with famine!\nFor both the prophet and the priest go about in the land,\nand have no knowledge.’”\n'),
	(14509, 21, 14, 19, 'Have you utterly rejected Judah?\nHas your soul loathed Zion?\nWhy have you struck us, and there is no healing for us?\nWe looked for peace, but no good came;\nand for a time of healing, and behold, dismay!\n'),
	(14510, 21, 14, 20, 'We acknowledge, Yahweh, our wickedness,\nand the iniquity of our fathers;\nfor we have sinned against you.\n'),
	(14511, 21, 14, 21, 'Do not abhor us, for your name’s sake.\nDo not disgrace the throne of your glory.\nRemember, and don’t break your covenant with us.\n'),
	(14512, 21, 14, 22, 'Are there any among the vanities of the nations that can cause rain?\nOr can the sky give showers?\nAren’t you he, Yahweh our God?\nTherefore we will wait for you;\nfor you have made all these things.\n'),
	(14513, 21, 15, 1, 'Then Yahweh said to me, “Though Moses and Samuel stood before me, yet my mind would not be toward this people. Cast them out of my sight, and let them go out!\n'),
	(14514, 21, 15, 2, 'It will happen, when they tell you, ‘Where shall we go out?’ Then you shall tell them, ‘Yahweh says:\n“Such as are for death, to death;\nsuch as are for the sword, to the sword;\nsuch as are for the famine, to the famine;\nand such as are for captivity, to captivity.”’\n'),
	(14515, 21, 15, 3, '“I will appoint over them four kinds,” says Yahweh: “the sword to kill, the dogs to tear, the birds of the sky, and the animals of the earth, to devour and to destroy.\n'),
	(14516, 21, 15, 4, 'I will cause them to be tossed back and forth among all the kingdoms of the earth, because of Manasseh, the son of Hezekiah, king of Judah, for that which he did in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(14517, 21, 15, 5, 'For who will have pity on you, Jerusalem?\nWho will mourn you?\nWho will come to ask of your welfare?\n'),
	(14518, 21, 15, 6, 'You have rejected me,” says Yahweh.\n“You have gone backward.\nTherefore I have stretched out my hand against you,\nand destroyed you.\nI am weary of showing compassion.\n'),
	(14519, 21, 15, 7, 'I have winnowed them with a fan in the gates of the land.\nI have bereaved them of children.\nI have destroyed my people.\nThey didn’t return from their ways.\n'),
	(14520, 21, 15, 8, 'Their widows are increased more than the sand of the seas;\nI have brought on them against the mother of the young men a destroyer at noonday.\nI have caused anguish and terrors to fall on her suddenly.\n'),
	(14521, 21, 15, 9, 'She who has borne seven languishes.\nShe has given up the spirit.\nHer sun has gone down while it was yet day.\nShe has been disappointed and confounded.\nI will deliver their residue to the sword before their enemies,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14522, 21, 15, 10, 'Woe is me, my mother, that you have borne me, a man of strife,\nand a man of contention to the whole earth!\nI have not lent, neither have men lent to me;\nyet every one of them curses me.\n'),
	(14523, 21, 15, 11, 'Yahweh said,\n“Most certainly I will strengthen you for good.\nMost certainly I will cause the enemy to make supplication to you in the time of evil\nand in the time of affliction.\n'),
	(14524, 21, 15, 12, 'Can one break iron,\neven iron from the north, and brass?\n'),
	(14525, 21, 15, 13, 'I will give your substance and your treasures for a plunder without price,\nand that for all your sins,\neven in all your borders.\n'),
	(14526, 21, 15, 14, 'I will make them to pass with your enemies into a land which you don’t know;\nfor a fire is kindled in my anger,\nwhich will burn on you.”\n'),
	(14527, 21, 15, 15, 'Yahweh, you know.\nRemember me, visit me,\nand avenge me of my persecutors.\nYou are patient, so don’t take me away.\nKnow that for your sake I have suffered reproach.\n'),
	(14528, 21, 15, 16, 'Your words were found,\nand I ate them.\nYour words were to me a joy and the rejoicing of my heart,\nfor I am called by your name, Yahweh, God of Armies.\n'),
	(14529, 21, 15, 17, 'I didn’t sit in the assembly of those who make merry and rejoice.\nI sat alone because of your hand,\nfor you have filled me with indignation.\n'),
	(14530, 21, 15, 18, 'Why is my pain perpetual,\nand my wound incurable,\nwhich refuses to be healed?\nWill you indeed be to me as a deceitful brook,\nlike waters that fail?\n'),
	(14531, 21, 15, 19, 'Therefore Yahweh says,\n“If you return, then I will bring you again,\nthat you may stand before me;\nand if you take out the precious from the vile,\nyou will be as my mouth.\nThey will return to you,\nbut you will not return to them.\n'),
	(14532, 21, 15, 20, 'I will make you to this people a fortified bronze wall.\nThey will fight against you,\nbut they will not prevail against you;\nfor I am with you to save you\nand to deliver you,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14533, 21, 15, 21, '“I will deliver you out of the hand of the wicked,\nand I will redeem you out of the hand of the terrible.”\n'),
	(14534, 21, 16, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came also to me, saying,\n'),
	(14535, 21, 16, 2, '“You shall not take a wife, neither shall you have sons or daughters, in this place.”\n'),
	(14536, 21, 16, 3, 'For Yahweh says concerning the sons and concerning the daughters who are born in this place, and concerning their mothers who bore them, and concerning their fathers who became their father in this land:\n'),
	(14537, 21, 16, 4, '“They will die grievous deaths: they will not be lamented, neither will they be buried. They will be as dung on the surface of the ground. They will be consumed by the sword and by famine. Their dead bodies will be food for the birds of the sky and for the animals of the earth.”\n'),
	(14538, 21, 16, 5, 'For Yahweh says, “Don’t enter into the house of mourning. Don’t go to lament. Don’t bemoan them, for I have taken away my peace from this people,” says Yahweh, “even loving kindness and tender mercies.\n'),
	(14539, 21, 16, 6, 'Both great and small will die in this land. They will not be buried. Men won’t lament for them, cut themselves, or make themselves bald for them.\n'),
	(14540, 21, 16, 7, 'Men won’t break bread for them in mourning, to comfort them for the dead. Men won’t give them the cup of consolation to drink for their father or for their mother.\n'),
	(14541, 21, 16, 8, '“You shall not go into the house of feasting to sit with them, to eat and to drink.”\n'),
	(14542, 21, 16, 9, 'For Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says: “Behold, I will cause to cease out of this place, before your eyes and in your days, the voice of mirth and the voice of gladness, the voice of the bridegroom and the voice of the bride.\n'),
	(14543, 21, 16, 10, 'It will happen, when you tell this people all these words, and they ask you, ‘Why has Yahweh pronounced all this great evil against us?’ or ‘What is our iniquity? or ‘What is our sin that we have committed against Yahweh our God?’\n'),
	(14544, 21, 16, 11, 'then you shall tell them, ‘Because your fathers have forsaken me,’ says Yahweh, ‘and have walked after other gods, have served them, have worshiped them, have forsaken me, and have not kept my law.\n'),
	(14545, 21, 16, 12, 'You have done evil more than your fathers, for behold, you each walk after the stubbornness of his evil heart, so that you don’t listen to me.\n'),
	(14546, 21, 16, 13, 'Therefore will I cast you out of this land into the land that you have not known, neither you nor your fathers. There you will serve other gods day and night, for I will show you no favor.’\n'),
	(14547, 21, 16, 14, '“Therefore behold, the days come,” says Yahweh, “that it will no more be said, ‘As Yahweh lives, who brought up the children of Israel out of the land of Egypt;’\n'),
	(14548, 21, 16, 15, 'but, ‘As Yahweh lives, who brought up the children of Israel from the land of the north, and from all the countries where he had driven them.’ I will bring them again into their land that I gave to their fathers.\n'),
	(14549, 21, 16, 16, '“Behold, I will send for many fishermen,” says Yahweh, “and they will fish them up. Afterward I will send for many hunters, and they will hunt them from every mountain, from every hill, and out of the clefts of the rocks.\n'),
	(14550, 21, 16, 17, 'For my eyes are on all their ways. They are not hidden from my face. Their iniquity isn’t concealed from my eyes.\n'),
	(14551, 21, 16, 18, 'First I will recompense their iniquity and their sin double, because they have polluted my land with the carcasses of their detestable things, and have filled my inheritance with their abominations.”\n'),
	(14552, 21, 16, 19, 'Yahweh, my strength, and my stronghold,\nand my refuge in the day of affliction,\nthe nations will come to you from the ends of the earth,\nand will say,\n“Our fathers have inherited nothing but lies,\nvanity and things in which there is no profit.\n'),
	(14553, 21, 16, 20, 'Should a man make to himself gods,\nwhich yet are no gods?”\n'),
	(14554, 21, 16, 21, '“Therefore behold, I will cause them to know,\nthis once I will cause them to know my hand and my might.\nThen they will know that my name is Yahweh.”\n'),
	(14555, 21, 17, 1, '“The sin of Judah is written with a pen of iron,\nand with the point of a diamond.\nIt is engraved on the tablet of their heart,\nand on the horns of your altars.\n'),
	(14556, 21, 17, 2, 'Even their children remember their altars\nand their Asherah poles by the green trees on the high hills.\n'),
	(14557, 21, 17, 3, 'My mountain in the field,\nI will give your substance and all your treasures for a plunder,\nand your high places, because of sin, throughout all your borders.\n'),
	(14558, 21, 17, 4, 'You, even of yourself, will discontinue from your heritage that I gave you.\nI will cause you to serve your enemies in the land which you don’t know,\nfor you have kindled a fire in my anger which will burn forever.”\n'),
	(14559, 21, 17, 5, 'Yahweh says:\n“Cursed is the man who trusts in man,\nrelies on strength of flesh,\nand whose heart departs from Yahweh.\n'),
	(14560, 21, 17, 6, 'For he will be like a bush in the desert,\nand will not see when good comes,\nbut will inhabit the parched places in the wilderness,\nan uninhabited salt land.\n'),
	(14561, 21, 17, 7, '“Blessed is the man who trusts in Yahweh,\nand whose confidence is in Yahweh.\n'),
	(14562, 21, 17, 8, 'For he will be as a tree planted by the waters,\nwho spreads out its roots by the river,\nand will not fear when heat comes,\nbut its leaf will be green;\nand will not be concerned in the year of drought.\nIt won’t cease from yielding fruit.\n'),
	(14563, 21, 17, 9, 'The heart is deceitful above all things\nand it is exceedingly corrupt.\nWho can know it?\n'),
	(14564, 21, 17, 10, '“I, Yahweh, search the mind.\nI try the heart,\neven to give every man according to his ways,\naccording to the fruit of his doings.”\n'),
	(14565, 21, 17, 11, 'As the partridge that sits on eggs which she has not laid,\nso is he who gets riches, and not by right.\nIn the middle of his days, they will leave him.\nAt his end, he will be a fool.\n'),
	(14566, 21, 17, 12, 'A glorious throne, set on high from the beginning,\nis the place of our sanctuary.\n'),
	(14567, 21, 17, 13, 'Yahweh, the hope of Israel,\nall who forsake you will be disappointed.\nThose who depart from me will be written in the earth,\nbecause they have forsaken Yahweh,\nthe spring of living waters.\n'),
	(14568, 21, 17, 14, 'Heal me, O Yahweh, and I will be healed.\nSave me, and I will be saved;\nfor you are my praise.\n'),
	(14569, 21, 17, 15, 'Behold, they tell me,\n“Where is Yahweh’s word?\nLet it be fulfilled now.”\n'),
	(14570, 21, 17, 16, 'As for me, I have not hurried from being a shepherd after you.\nI haven’t desired the woeful day. You know.\nThat which came out of my lips was before your face.\n'),
	(14571, 21, 17, 17, 'Don’t be a terror to me.\nYou are my refuge in the day of evil.\n'),
	(14572, 21, 17, 18, 'Let them be disappointed who persecute me,\nbut let not me be disappointed.\nLet them be dismayed,\nbut don’t let me be dismayed.\nBring on them the day of evil,\nand destroy them with double destruction.\n'),
	(14573, 21, 17, 19, 'Yahweh said this to me: “Go, and stand in the gate of the children of the people, through which the kings of Judah come in and by which they go out, and in all the gates of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(14574, 21, 17, 20, 'Tell them, ‘Hear Yahweh’s word, you kings of Judah, and all Judah, and all the inhabitants of Jerusalem, that enter in by these gates:\n'),
	(14575, 21, 17, 21, 'Yahweh says, “Be careful, and bear no burden on the Sabbath day, nor bring it in by the gates of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(14576, 21, 17, 22, 'Don’t carry a burden out of your houses on the Sabbath day. Don’t do any work, but make the Sabbath day holy, as I commanded your fathers.\n'),
	(14577, 21, 17, 23, 'But they didn’t listen. They didn’t turn their ear, but made their neck stiff, that they might not hear, and might not receive instruction.\n'),
	(14578, 21, 17, 24, 'It will happen, if you diligently listen to me,” says Yahweh, “to bring in no burden through the gates of this city on the Sabbath day, but to make the Sabbath day holy, to do no work therein;\n'),
	(14579, 21, 17, 25, 'then there will enter in by the gates of this city kings and princes sitting on David’s throne, riding in chariots and on horses, they, and their princes, the men of Judah, and the inhabitants of Jerusalem; and this city will remain forever.\n'),
	(14580, 21, 17, 26, 'They will come from the cities of Judah, and from the places around Jerusalem, from the land of Benjamin, from the lowland, from the hill country, and from the South, bringing burnt offerings, sacrifices, meal offerings, and frankincense, and bringing sacrifices of thanksgiving, to Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(14581, 21, 17, 27, 'But if you will not listen to me to make the Sabbath day holy, and not to bear a burden and enter in at the gates of Jerusalem on the Sabbath day, then I will kindle a fire in its gates, and it will devour the palaces of Jerusalem. It will not be quenched.”’”\n'),
	(14582, 21, 18, 1, 'The word which came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(14583, 21, 18, 2, '“Arise, and go down to the potter’s house, and there I will cause you to hear my words.”\n'),
	(14584, 21, 18, 3, 'Then I went down to the potter’s house, and behold, he was making something on the wheels.\n'),
	(14585, 21, 18, 4, 'When the vessel that he made of the clay was marred in the hand of the potter, he made it again another vessel, as seemed good to the potter to make it.\n'),
	(14586, 21, 18, 5, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(14587, 21, 18, 6, '“House of Israel, can’t I do with you as this potter?” says Yahweh. “Behold, as the clay in the potter’s hand, so are you in my hand, house of Israel.\n'),
	(14588, 21, 18, 7, 'At the instant I speak concerning a nation, and concerning a kingdom, to pluck up and to break down and to destroy it;\n'),
	(14589, 21, 18, 8, 'if that nation, concerning which I have spoken, turns from their evil, I will repent of the evil that I thought to do to them.\n'),
	(14590, 21, 18, 9, 'At the instant I speak concerning a nation, and concerning a kingdom, to build and to plant it;\n'),
	(14591, 21, 18, 10, 'if they do that which is evil in my sight, that they not obey my voice, then I will repent of the good with which I said I would benefit them.\n'),
	(14592, 21, 18, 11, '“Now therefore, speak to the men of Judah, and to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, saying, ‘Yahweh says: “Behold, I frame evil against you, and devise a plan against you. Everyone return from his evil way now, and amend your ways and your doings.”’\n'),
	(14593, 21, 18, 12, 'But they say, ‘It is in vain; for we will walk after our own plans, and we will each follow the stubbornness of his evil heart.’”\n'),
	(14594, 21, 18, 13, 'Therefore Yahweh says:\n“Ask now among the nations,\n‘Who has heard such things?’\nThe virgin of Israel has done a very horrible thing.\n'),
	(14595, 21, 18, 14, 'Will the snow of Lebanon fail from the rock of the field?\nWill the cold waters that flow down from afar be dried up?\n'),
	(14596, 21, 18, 15, 'For my people have forgotten me.\nThey have burned incense to false gods.\nThey have been made to stumble in their ways,\nin the ancient paths,\nto walk in byways, in a way not built up;\n'),
	(14597, 21, 18, 16, 'to make their land an astonishment,\nand a perpetual hissing.\nEveryone who passes thereby will be astonished,\nand shake his head.\n'),
	(14598, 21, 18, 17, 'I will scatter them as with an east wind before the enemy.\nI will show them the back, and not the face,\nin the day of their calamity.\n'),
	(14599, 21, 18, 18, 'Then they said, “Come, and let us devise plans against Jeremiah; for the law won’t perish from the priest, nor counsel from the wise, nor the word from the prophet. Come, and let us strike him with the tongue, and let us not give heed to any of his words.”\n'),
	(14600, 21, 18, 19, 'Give heed to me, Yahweh,\nand listen to the voice of those who contend with me.\n'),
	(14601, 21, 18, 20, 'Should evil be recompensed for good?\nFor they have dug a pit for my soul.\nRemember how I stood before you to speak good for them,\nto turn away your wrath from them.\n'),
	(14602, 21, 18, 21, 'Therefore deliver up their children to the famine,\nand give them over to the power of the sword.\nLet their wives become childless, and widows.\nLet their men be killed,\nand their young men struck by the sword in battle.\n'),
	(14603, 21, 18, 22, 'Let a cry be heard from their houses,\nwhen you bring a troop suddenly on them;\nfor they have dug a pit to take me,\nand hidden snares for my feet.\n'),
	(14604, 21, 18, 23, 'Yet, Yahweh, you know all their counsel against me to kill me.\nDon’t forgive their iniquity.\nDon’t blot out their sin from your sight,\nLet them be overthrown before you.\nDeal with them in the time of your anger.\n'),
	(14605, 21, 19, 1, 'Thus said Yahweh, “Go, and buy a potter’s earthen bottle, and take some of the elders of the people, and of the elders of the priests;\n'),
	(14606, 21, 19, 2, 'and go out to the valley of the son of Hinnom, which is by the entry of the gate Harsith, and proclaim there the words that I will tell you.\n'),
	(14607, 21, 19, 3, 'Say, ‘Hear Yahweh’s word, kings of Judah, and inhabitants of Jerusalem: Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says, “Behold, I will bring evil on this place, which whoever hears, his ears will tingle.\n'),
	(14608, 21, 19, 4, 'Because they have forsaken me, and have defiled this place, and have burned incense in it to other gods, that they didn’t know, they and their fathers and the kings of Judah, and have filled this place with the blood of innocents,\n'),
	(14609, 21, 19, 5, 'and have built the high places of Baal, to burn their sons in the fire for burnt offerings to Baal; which I didn’t command, nor speak, which didn’t even enter into my mind:\n'),
	(14610, 21, 19, 6, 'therefore, behold, the days come,” says Yahweh, “that this place will no more be called ‘Topheth’, nor ‘The Valley of the son of Hinnom’, but ‘The valley of Slaughter’.\n'),
	(14611, 21, 19, 7, '“‘“I will make the counsel of Judah and Jerusalem void in this place. I will cause them to fall by the sword before their enemies, and by the hand of those who seek their life. I will give their dead bodies to be food for the birds of the sky and for the animals of the earth.\n'),
	(14612, 21, 19, 8, 'I will make this city an astonishment and a hissing. Everyone who passes by it will be astonished and hiss because of all its plagues.\n'),
	(14613, 21, 19, 9, 'I will cause them to eat the flesh of their sons and the flesh of their daughters. They will each eat the flesh of his friend in the siege and in the distress, with which their enemies, and those who seek their life, will distress them.”’\n'),
	(14614, 21, 19, 10, '“Then you shall break the bottle in the sight of the men who go with you,\n'),
	(14615, 21, 19, 11, 'and shall tell them, ‘Yahweh of Armies says: “Even so I will break this people and this city, as one breaks a potter’s vessel, that can’t be made whole again. They will bury in Topheth, until there is no place to bury.\n'),
	(14616, 21, 19, 12, 'Thus will I do to this place,” says Yahweh, “and to its inhabitants, even making this city as Topheth.\n'),
	(14617, 21, 19, 13, 'The houses of Jerusalem, and the houses of the kings of Judah, which are defiled, will be as the place of Topheth, even all the houses on whose roofs they have burned incense to all the army of the sky, and have poured out drink offerings to other gods.”’”\n'),
	(14618, 21, 19, 14, 'Then Jeremiah came from Topheth, where Yahweh had sent him to prophesy; and he stood in the court of Yahweh’s house, and said to all the people:\n'),
	(14619, 21, 19, 15, '“Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says, ‘Behold, I will bring on this city and on all its towns all the evil that I have pronounced against it, because they have made their neck stiff, that they may not hear my words.’”\n'),
	(14620, 21, 20, 1, 'Now Pashhur, the son of Immer the priest, who was chief officer in Yahweh’s house, heard Jeremiah prophesying these things.\n'),
	(14621, 21, 20, 2, 'Then Pashhur struck Jeremiah the prophet, and put him in the stocks that were in the upper gate of Benjamin, which was in Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(14622, 21, 20, 3, 'On the next day, Pashhur released Jeremiah out of the stocks. Then Jeremiah said to him, “Yahweh has not called your name Pashhur, but Magormissabib.\n'),
	(14623, 21, 20, 4, 'For Yahweh says, ‘Behold, I will make you a terror to yourself and to all your friends. They will fall by the sword of their enemies, and your eyes will see it. I will give all Judah into the hand of the king of Babylon, and he will carry them captive to Babylon, and will kill them with the sword.\n'),
	(14624, 21, 20, 5, 'Moreover I will give all the riches of this city, and all its gains, and all its precious things, yes, I will give all the treasures of the kings of Judah into the hand of their enemies. They will make them captives, take them, and carry them to Babylon.\n'),
	(14625, 21, 20, 6, 'You, Pashhur, and all who dwell in your house will go into captivity. You will come to Babylon, and there you will die, and there you will be buried, you, and all your friends, to whom you have prophesied falsely.’”\n'),
	(14626, 21, 20, 7, 'Yahweh, you have persuaded me, and I was persuaded.\nYou are stronger than I, and have prevailed.\nI have become a laughing-stock all day.\nEveryone mocks me.\n'),
	(14627, 21, 20, 8, 'For as often as I speak, I cry out;\nI cry, “Violence and destruction!”\nbecause Yahweh’s word has been made a reproach to me,\nand a derision, all day.\n'),
	(14628, 21, 20, 9, 'If I say, I will not make mention of him,\nor speak any more in his name,\nthen there is in my heart as it were a burning fire shut up in my bones,\nand I am weary with holding it in,\nand I can’t.\n'),
	(14629, 21, 20, 10, 'For I have heard the defaming of many,\n“Terror on every side!\nDenounce, and we will denounce him!”\nsay all my familiar friends,\nthose who watch for my fall.\n“Perhaps he will be persuaded,\nand we will prevail against him,\nand we will take our revenge on him.”\n'),
	(14630, 21, 20, 11, 'But Yahweh is with me as an awesome mighty one.\nTherefore my persecutors will stumble,\nand they won’t prevail.\nThey will be utterly disappointed,\nbecause they have not dealt wisely,\neven with an everlasting dishonor which will never be forgotten.\n'),
	(14631, 21, 20, 12, 'But, Yahweh of Armies, who tests the righteous,\nwho sees the heart and the mind,\nlet me see your vengeance on them;\nfor to you I have revealed my cause.\n'),
	(14632, 21, 20, 13, 'Sing to Yahweh!\nPraise Yahweh,\nfor he has delivered the soul of the needy from the hand of evildoers.\n'),
	(14633, 21, 20, 14, 'Cursed is the day in which I was born.\nDon’t let the day in which my mother bore me be blessed.\n'),
	(14634, 21, 20, 15, 'Cursed is the man who brought news to my father, saying,\n“A boy is born to you,” making him very glad.\n'),
	(14635, 21, 20, 16, 'Let that man be as the cities which Yahweh overthrew,\nand didn’t repent.\nLet him hear a cry in the morning,\nand shouting at noontime;\n'),
	(14636, 21, 20, 17, 'because he didn’t kill me from the womb.\nSo my mother would have been my grave,\nand her womb always great.\n'),
	(14637, 21, 20, 18, 'Why did I come out of the womb to see labor and sorrow,\nthat my days should be consumed with shame?\n'),
	(14638, 21, 21, 1, 'The word which came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, when king Zedekiah sent to him Pashhur the son of Malchijah, and Zephaniah the son of Maaseiah, the priest, saying,\n'),
	(14639, 21, 21, 2, '“Please inquire of Yahweh for us; for Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon makes war against us. Perhaps Yahweh will deal with us according to all his wondrous works, that he may withdraw from us.”\n'),
	(14640, 21, 21, 3, 'Then Jeremiah said to them, “Tell Zedekiah:\n'),
	(14641, 21, 21, 4, '‘Yahweh, the God of Israel says, “Behold, I will turn back the weapons of war that are in your hands, with which you fight against the king of Babylon, and against the Chaldeans who besiege you outside the walls; and I will gather them into the middle of this city.\n'),
	(14642, 21, 21, 5, 'I myself will fight against you with an outstretched hand and with a strong arm, even in anger, in wrath, and in great indignation.\n'),
	(14643, 21, 21, 6, 'I will strike the inhabitants of this city, both man and animal. They will die of a great pestilence.\n'),
	(14644, 21, 21, 7, 'Afterward,” says Yahweh, “I will deliver Zedekiah king of Judah, his servants, and the people, even those who are left in this city from the pestilence, from the sword, and from the famine, into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, and into the hand of their enemies, and into the hand of those who seek their life. He will strike them with the edge of the sword. He will not spare them, have pity, or have mercy.”’\n'),
	(14645, 21, 21, 8, '“You shall say to this people, ‘Yahweh says: “Behold, I set before you the way of life and the way of death.\n'),
	(14646, 21, 21, 9, 'He who remains in this city will die by the sword, by the famine, and by the pestilence; but he who goes out, and passes over to the Chaldeans who besiege you, he will live, and he will escape with his life.\n'),
	(14647, 21, 21, 10, 'For I have set my face on this city for evil, and not for good,” says Yahweh. “It will be given into the hand of the king of Babylon, and he will burn it with fire.”’\n'),
	(14648, 21, 21, 11, '“Concerning the house of the king of Judah, hear Yahweh’s word:\n'),
	(14649, 21, 21, 12, 'House of David, Yahweh says,\n‘Execute justice in the morning,\nand deliver him who is robbed out of the hand of the oppressor,\nlest my wrath go out like fire,\nand burn so that no one can quench it,\nbecause of the evil of your doings.\n'),
	(14650, 21, 21, 13, 'Behold, I am against you, O inhabitant of the valley,\nand of the rock of the plain,’ says Yahweh.\n‘You that say, “Who would come down against us?”\nor “Who would enter into our homes?”\n'),
	(14651, 21, 21, 14, 'I will punish you according to the fruit of your doings, says Yahweh;\nand I will kindle a fire in her forest,\nand it will devour all that is around her.’”\n'),
	(14652, 21, 22, 1, 'Yahweh said, “Go down to the house of the king of Judah, and speak this word, there:\n'),
	(14653, 21, 22, 2, '‘Hear Yahweh’s word, king of Judah, who sits on David’s throne, you, your servants, and your people who enter in by these gates.\n'),
	(14654, 21, 22, 3, 'Yahweh says: “Execute justice and righteousness, and deliver him who is robbed out of the hand of the oppressor. Do no wrong. Do no violence to the foreigner, the fatherless, or the widow. Don’t shed innocent blood in this place.\n'),
	(14655, 21, 22, 4, 'For if you do this thing indeed, then kings sitting on David’s throne will enter in by the gates of this house, riding in chariots and on horses, he, his servants, and his people.\n'),
	(14656, 21, 22, 5, 'But if you will not hear these words, I swear by myself,” says Yahweh, “that this house will become a desolation.”’”\n'),
	(14657, 21, 22, 6, 'For Yahweh says concerning the house of the king of Judah:\n“You are Gilead to me,\nthe head of Lebanon.\nYet surely I will make you a wilderness,\ncities which are not inhabited.\n'),
	(14658, 21, 22, 7, 'I will prepare destroyers against you,\neveryone with his weapons,\nand they will cut down your choice cedars,\nand cast them into the fire.\n'),
	(14659, 21, 22, 8, '“Many nations will pass by this city, and they will each ask his neighbor, ‘Why has Yahweh done this to this great city?’\n'),
	(14660, 21, 22, 9, 'Then they will answer, ‘Because they abandoned the covenant of Yahweh their God, worshiped other gods, and served them.’”\n'),
	(14661, 21, 22, 10, 'Don’t weep for the dead.\nDon’t bemoan him;\nbut weep bitterly for him who goes away,\nfor he will return no more,\nand not see his native country.\n'),
	(14662, 21, 22, 11, 'For Yahweh says touching Shallum the son of Josiah, king of Judah, who reigned instead of Josiah his father, and who went out of this place: “He won’t return there any more.\n'),
	(14663, 21, 22, 12, 'But in the place where they have led him captive, there will he die. He will see this land no more.”\n'),
	(14664, 21, 22, 13, '“Woe to him who builds his house by unrighteousness,\nand his rooms by injustice;\nwho uses his neighbor’s service without wages,\nand doesn’t give him his hire;\n'),
	(14665, 21, 22, 14, 'who says, ‘I will build myself a wide house and spacious rooms,’\nand cuts out windows for himself;\nwith a cedar ceiling,\nand painted with red.\n'),
	(14666, 21, 22, 15, '“Should you reign, because you strive to excel in cedar?\nDidn’t your father eat and drink,\nand do justice and righteousness?\nThen it was well with him.\n'),
	(14667, 21, 22, 16, 'He judged the cause of the poor and needy;\nso it was well, then.\nWasn’t this to know me?”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(14668, 21, 22, 17, 'But your eyes and your heart are only for your covetousness,\nfor shedding innocent blood,\nfor oppression, and for doing violence.”\n'),
	(14669, 21, 22, 18, 'Therefore Yahweh says concerning Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah:\n“They won’t lament for him,\nsaying, ‘Ah my brother!’ or, ‘Ah sister!’\nThey won’t lament for him,\nsaying ‘Ah lord!’ or, ‘Ah his glory!’\n'),
	(14670, 21, 22, 19, 'He will be buried with the burial of a donkey,\ndrawn and cast out beyond the gates of Jerusalem.”\n'),
	(14671, 21, 22, 20, '“Go up to Lebanon, and cry.\nLift up your voice in Bashan,\nand cry from Abarim;\nfor all your lovers have been destroyed.\n'),
	(14672, 21, 22, 21, 'I spoke to you in your prosperity;\nbut you said, ‘I will not listen.’\nThis has been your way from your youth,\nthat you didn’t obey my voice.\n'),
	(14673, 21, 22, 22, 'The wind will feed all your shepherds,\nand your lovers will go into captivity.\nSurely then you will be ashamed\nand confounded for all your wickedness.\n'),
	(14674, 21, 22, 23, 'Inhabitant of Lebanon,\nwho makes your nest in the cedars,\nhow greatly to be pitied you will be when pangs come on you,\nthe pain as of a woman in travail!\n'),
	(14675, 21, 22, 24, '“As I live,” says Yahweh, “though Coniah the son of Jehoiakim king of Judah were the signet on my right hand, yet would I pluck you from there.\n'),
	(14676, 21, 22, 25, 'I would give you into the hand of those who seek your life, and into the hand of them of whom you are afraid, even into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, and into the hand of the Chaldeans.\n'),
	(14677, 21, 22, 26, 'I will cast you out with your mother who bore you into another country, where you were not born; and there you will die.\n'),
	(14678, 21, 22, 27, 'But to the land to which their soul longs to return, there they will not return.”\n'),
	(14679, 21, 22, 28, 'Is this man Coniah a despised broken vessel?\nIs he a vessel in which no one delights?\nWhy are they cast out, he and his offspring,\nand cast into a land which they don’t know?\n'),
	(14680, 21, 22, 29, 'O earth, earth, earth,\nhear Yahweh’s word!\n'),
	(14681, 21, 22, 30, 'Yahweh says,\n“Record this man as childless,\na man who will not prosper in his days;\nfor no more will a man of his offspring prosper,\nsitting on David’s throne,\nand ruling in Judah.”\n'),
	(14682, 21, 23, 1, '“Woe to the shepherds who destroy and scatter the sheep of my pasture!” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14683, 21, 23, 2, 'Therefore Yahweh, the God of Israel, says against the shepherds who feed my people: “You have scattered my flock, driven them away, and have not visited them. Behold, I will visit on you the evil of your doings,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14684, 21, 23, 3, '“I will gather the remnant of my flock out of all the countries where I have driven them, and will bring them again to their folds; and they will be fruitful and multiply.\n'),
	(14685, 21, 23, 4, 'I will set up shepherds over them, who will feed them. They will no longer be afraid or dismayed, neither will any be lacking,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14686, 21, 23, 5, '“Behold, the days come,” says Yahweh,\n“that I will raise to David a righteous Branch,\nand he will reign as king and deal wisely,\nand will execute justice and righteousness in the land.\n'),
	(14687, 21, 23, 6, 'In his days Judah will be saved,\nand Israel will dwell safely.\nThis is his name by which he will be called:\nYahweh our righteousness.\n'),
	(14688, 21, 23, 7, '“Therefore behold, the days come,” says Yahweh, “that they will no more say, ‘As Yahweh lives, who brought up the children of Israel out of the land of Egypt;’\n'),
	(14689, 21, 23, 8, 'but, ‘As Yahweh lives, who brought up and who led the offspring of the house of Israel out of the north country, and from all the countries where I had driven them.’ Then they will dwell in their own land.”\n'),
	(14690, 21, 23, 9, 'Concerning the prophets:\nMy heart within me is broken.\nAll my bones shake.\nI am like a drunken man,\nand like a man whom wine has overcome,\nbecause of Yahweh,\nand because of his holy words.\n'),
	(14691, 21, 23, 10, 'For the land is full of adulterers;\nfor because of the curse the land mourns.\nThe pastures of the wilderness have dried up.\nTheir course is evil,\nand their might is not right;\n'),
	(14692, 21, 23, 11, 'for both prophet and priest are profane.\nYes, in my house I have found their wickedness,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14693, 21, 23, 12, 'Therefore their way will be to them as slippery places in the darkness.\nThey will be driven on,\nand fall therein;\nfor I will bring evil on them,\neven the year of their visitation,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14694, 21, 23, 13, '“I have seen folly in the prophets of Samaria.\nThey prophesied by Baal,\nand caused my people Israel to err.\n'),
	(14695, 21, 23, 14, 'In the prophets of Jerusalem I have also seen a horrible thing:\nthey commit adultery and walk in lies.\nThey strengthen the hands of evildoers,\nso that no one returns from his wickedness.\nThey have all become to me as Sodom,\nand its inhabitants as Gomorrah.”\n'),
	(14696, 21, 23, 15, 'Therefore Yahweh of Armies says concerning the prophets:\n“Behold, I will feed them with wormwood,\nand make them drink the water of gall;\nfor from the prophets of Jerusalem ungodliness has gone out into all the land.”\n'),
	(14697, 21, 23, 16, 'Yahweh of Armies says,\n“Don’t listen to the words of the prophets who prophesy to you.\nThey teach you vanity.\nThey speak a vision of their own heart,\nand not out of the mouth of Yahweh.\n'),
	(14698, 21, 23, 17, 'They say continually to those who despise me,\n‘Yahweh has said, “You will have peace;”’\nand to everyone who walks in the stubbornness of his own heart they say,\n‘No evil will come on you.’\n'),
	(14699, 21, 23, 18, 'For who has stood in the council of Yahweh,\nthat he should perceive and hear his word?\nWho has listened to my word, and heard it?\n'),
	(14700, 21, 23, 19, 'Behold, Yahweh’s storm, his wrath, has gone out.\nYes, a whirling storm:\nIt will burst on the head of the wicked.\n'),
	(14701, 21, 23, 20, 'Yahweh’s anger will not return until he has executed,\nand until he has performed the intents of his heart.\nIn the latter days, you will understand it perfectly.\n'),
	(14702, 21, 23, 21, 'I didn’t send these prophets, yet they ran.\nI didn’t speak to them, yet they prophesied.\n'),
	(14703, 21, 23, 22, 'But if they had stood in my council,\nthen they would have caused my people to hear my words,\nand would have turned them from their evil way,\nand from the evil of their doings.\n'),
	(14704, 21, 23, 23, '“Am I a God at hand,” says Yahweh,\n“and not a God afar off?\n'),
	(14705, 21, 23, 24, 'Can anyone hide himself in secret places\nso that I can’t see him?” says Yahweh.\n“Don’t I fill heaven and earth?” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14706, 21, 23, 25, '“I have heard what the prophets have said, who prophesy lies in my name, saying, ‘I had a dream! I had a dream!’\n'),
	(14707, 21, 23, 26, 'How long will this be in the heart of the prophets who prophesy lies, even the prophets of the deceit of their own heart?\n'),
	(14708, 21, 23, 27, 'They intend to cause my people to forget my name by their dreams which they each tell his neighbor, as their fathers forgot my name because of Baal.\n'),
	(14709, 21, 23, 28, 'The prophet who has a dream, let him tell a dream; and he who has my word, let him speak my word faithfully. What is the straw to the wheat?” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14710, 21, 23, 29, '“Isn’t my word like fire?” says Yahweh; “and like a hammer that breaks the rock in pieces?\n'),
	(14711, 21, 23, 30, '“Therefore behold, I am against the prophets,” says Yahweh, “who each steal my words from his neighbor.\n'),
	(14712, 21, 23, 31, 'Behold, I am against the prophets,” says Yahweh, “who use their tongues, and say, ‘He says.’\n'),
	(14713, 21, 23, 32, 'Behold, I am against those who prophesy lying dreams,” says Yahweh, “who tell them, and cause my people to err by their lies, and by their vain boasting; yet I didn’t send them or command them. They don’t profit this people at all,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14714, 21, 23, 33, '“When this people, or the prophet, or a priest, asks you, saying, ‘What is the message from Yahweh?’ Then you shall tell them, ‘“What message? I will cast you off,” says Yahweh.’\n'),
	(14715, 21, 23, 34, 'As for the prophet, the priest, and the people, who say, ‘The message from Yahweh,’ I will even punish that man and his household.\n'),
	(14716, 21, 23, 35, 'You will say everyone to his neighbor, and everyone to his brother, ‘What has Yahweh answered?’ and, ‘What has Yahweh said?’\n'),
	(14717, 21, 23, 36, 'You will mention the message from Yahweh no more: for every man’s own word has become his message; for you have perverted the words of the living God, of Yahweh of Armies, our God.\n'),
	(14718, 21, 23, 37, 'You will say to the prophet, ‘What has Yahweh answered you?’ and, ‘What has Yahweh spoken?’\n'),
	(14719, 21, 23, 38, 'Although you say, ‘The message from Yahweh;’ therefore Yahweh says: ‘Because you say this word, “The message from Yahweh,” and I have sent to you, telling you not to say, “The message from Yahweh;”\n'),
	(14720, 21, 23, 39, 'therefore, behold, I will utterly forget you, and I will cast you off, and the city that I gave to you and to your fathers, away from my presence.\n'),
	(14721, 21, 23, 40, 'I will bring an everlasting reproach on you, and a perpetual shame, which will not be forgotten.’”\n'),
	(14722, 21, 24, 1, 'Yahweh showed me, and behold, two baskets of figs were set before Yahweh’s temple, after Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon had carried away captive Jeconiah the son of Jehoiakim, king of Judah, and the princes of Judah, with the craftsmen and smiths, from Jerusalem, and had brought them to Babylon.\n'),
	(14723, 21, 24, 2, 'One basket had very good figs, like the figs that are first-ripe; and the other basket had very bad figs, which could not be eaten, they were so bad.\n'),
	(14724, 21, 24, 3, 'Then Yahweh asked me, “What do you see, Jeremiah?”\nI said, “Figs. The good figs are very good, and the bad are very bad, so bad that can’t be eaten.”\n'),
	(14725, 21, 24, 4, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(14726, 21, 24, 5, '“Yahweh, the God of Israel says: ‘Like these good figs, so I will regard the captives of Judah, whom I have sent out of this place into the land of the Chaldeans, for good.\n'),
	(14727, 21, 24, 6, 'For I will set my eyes on them for good, and I will bring them again to this land. I will build them, and not pull them down. I will plant them, and not pluck them up.\n'),
	(14728, 21, 24, 7, 'I will give them a heart to know me, that I am Yahweh. They will be my people, and I will be their God; for they will return to me with their whole heart.\n'),
	(14729, 21, 24, 8, '“‘As the bad figs, which can’t be eaten, they are so bad,’ surely Yahweh says, ‘So I will give up Zedekiah the king of Judah, and his princes, and the remnant of Jerusalem, who remain in this land, and those who dwell in the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(14730, 21, 24, 9, 'I will even give them up to be tossed back and forth among all the kingdoms of the earth for evil; to be a reproach and a proverb, a taunt and a curse, in all places where I will drive them.\n'),
	(14731, 21, 24, 10, 'I will send the sword, the famine, and the pestilence, among them, until they are consumed from off the land that I gave to them and to their fathers.’”\n'),
	(14732, 21, 25, 1, 'The word that came to Jeremiah concerning all the people of Judah, in the fourth year of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah (the same was the first year of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon),\n'),
	(14733, 21, 25, 2, 'which Jeremiah the prophet spoke to all the people of Judah, and to all the inhabitants of Jerusalem:\n'),
	(14734, 21, 25, 3, 'From the thirteenth year of Josiah the son of Amon, king of Judah, even to this day, these twenty-three years, Yahweh’s word has come to me, and I have spoken to you, rising up early and speaking; but you have not listened.\n'),
	(14735, 21, 25, 4, 'Yahweh has sent to you all his servants the prophets, rising up early and sending them (but you have not listened or inclined your ear to hear),\n'),
	(14736, 21, 25, 5, 'saying, “Return now everyone from his evil way, and from the evil of your doings, and dwell in the land that Yahweh has given to you and to your fathers, from of old and even forever more.\n'),
	(14737, 21, 25, 6, 'Don’t go after other gods to serve them or worship them, and don’t provoke me to anger with the work of your hands; then I will do you no harm.”\n'),
	(14738, 21, 25, 7, '“Yet you have not listened to me,” says Yahweh; “that you may provoke me to anger with the work of your hands to your own hurt.”\n'),
	(14739, 21, 25, 8, 'Therefore Yahweh of Armies says: “Because you have not heard my words,\n'),
	(14740, 21, 25, 9, 'behold, I will send and take all the families of the north,” says Yahweh, “and I will send to Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon, my servant, and will bring them against this land, and against its inhabitants, and against all these nations around. I will utterly destroy them, and make them an astonishment, and a hissing, and perpetual desolations.\n'),
	(14741, 21, 25, 10, 'Moreover I will take from them the voice of mirth and the voice of gladness, the voice of the bridegroom and the voice of the bride, the sound of the millstones, and the light of the lamp.\n'),
	(14742, 21, 25, 11, 'This whole land will be a desolation, and an astonishment; and these nations will serve the king of Babylon seventy years.\n'),
	(14743, 21, 25, 12, '“It will happen, when seventy years are accomplished, that I will punish the king of Babylon and that nation,” says Yahweh, “for their iniquity. I will make the land of the Chaldeans desolate forever.\n'),
	(14744, 21, 25, 13, 'I will bring on that land all my words which I have pronounced against it, even all that is written in this book, which Jeremiah has prophesied against all the nations.\n'),
	(14745, 21, 25, 14, 'For many nations and great kings will make bondservants of them, even of them. I will recompense them according to their deeds, and according to the work of their hands.”\n'),
	(14746, 21, 25, 15, 'For Yahweh, the God of Israel, says to me: “Take this cup of the wine of wrath from my hand, and cause all the nations to whom I send you to drink it.\n'),
	(14747, 21, 25, 16, 'They will drink, and reel back and forth, and be insane, because of the sword that I will send among them.”\n'),
	(14748, 21, 25, 17, 'Then took I the cup at Yahweh’s hand, and made all the nations to drink, to whom Yahweh had sent me:\n'),
	(14749, 21, 25, 18, 'Jerusalem, and the cities of Judah, with its kings and its princes, to make them a desolation, an astonishment, a hissing, and a curse, as it is today;\n'),
	(14750, 21, 25, 19, 'Pharaoh king of Egypt, with his servants, his princes, and all his people;\n'),
	(14751, 21, 25, 20, 'and all the mixed people, and all the kings of the land of Uz, all the kings of the Philistines, Ashkelon, Gaza, Ekron, and the remnant of Ashdod;\n'),
	(14752, 21, 25, 21, 'Edom, Moab, and the children of Ammon;\n'),
	(14753, 21, 25, 22, 'and all the kings of Tyre, all the kings of Sidon, and the kings of the isle which is beyond the sea;\n'),
	(14754, 21, 25, 23, 'Dedan, Tema, Buz, and all who have the corners of their beard cut off;\n'),
	(14755, 21, 25, 24, 'and all the kings of Arabia, all the kings of the mixed people who dwell in the wilderness;\n'),
	(14756, 21, 25, 25, 'and all the kings of Zimri, all the kings of Elam, and all the kings of the Medes;\n'),
	(14757, 21, 25, 26, 'and all the kings of the north, far and near, one with another; and all the kingdoms of the world, which are on the surface of the earth. The king of Sheshach will drink after them.\n'),
	(14758, 21, 25, 27, '“You shall tell them, ‘Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says: “Drink, and be drunk, vomit, fall, and rise no more, because of the sword which I will send among you.”’\n'),
	(14759, 21, 25, 28, 'It shall be, if they refuse to take the cup at your hand to drink, then you shall tell them, ‘Yahweh of Armies says: “You shall surely drink.\n'),
	(14760, 21, 25, 29, 'For, behold, I begin to work evil at the city which is called by my name; and should you be utterly unpunished? You will not be unpunished; for I will call for a sword on all the inhabitants of the earth, says Yahweh of Armies.”’\n'),
	(14761, 21, 25, 30, '“Therefore prophesy against them all these words, and tell them,\n“‘Yahweh will roar from on high,\nand utter his voice from his holy habitation.\nHe will mightily roar against his fold.\nHe will give a shout, as those who tread grapes,\nagainst all the inhabitants of the earth.\n'),
	(14762, 21, 25, 31, 'A noise will come even to the end of the earth;\nfor Yahweh has a controversy with the nations.\nHe will enter into judgment with all flesh.\nAs for the wicked, he will give them to the sword,”’ says Yahweh.”\n'),
	(14763, 21, 25, 32, 'Yahweh of Armies says,\n“Behold, evil will go out from nation to nation,\nand a great storm will be raised up from the uttermost parts of the earth.”\n'),
	(14764, 21, 25, 33, 'The slain of Yahweh will be at that day from one end of the earth even to the other end of the earth. They won’t be lamented. They won’t be gathered or buried. They will be dung on the surface of the ground.\n'),
	(14765, 21, 25, 34, 'Wail, you shepherds, and cry.\nWallow in dust, you leader of the flock;\nfor the days of your slaughter and of your dispersions have fully come,\nand you will fall like fine pottery.\n'),
	(14766, 21, 25, 35, 'The shepherds will have no way to flee.\nThe leader of the flock will have no escape.\n'),
	(14767, 21, 25, 36, 'A voice of the cry of the shepherds,\nand the wailing of the leader of the flock,\nfor Yahweh destroys their pasture.\n'),
	(14768, 21, 25, 37, 'The peaceful folds are brought to silence\nbecause of the fierce anger of Yahweh.\n'),
	(14769, 21, 25, 38, 'He has left his covert, as the lion;\nfor their land has become an astonishment because of the fierceness of the oppression,\nand because of his fierce anger.\n'),
	(14770, 21, 26, 1, 'In the beginning of the reign of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah, this word came from Yahweh:\n'),
	(14771, 21, 26, 2, '“Yahweh says: ‘Stand in the court of Yahweh’s house, and speak to all the cities of Judah, which come to worship in Yahweh’s house, all the words that I command you to speak to them. Don’t omit a word.\n'),
	(14772, 21, 26, 3, 'It may be they will listen, and every man turn from his evil way; that I may relent from the evil which I intend to do to them because of the evil of their doings.’\n'),
	(14773, 21, 26, 4, 'You shall tell them, “Yahweh says: ‘If you will not listen to me, to walk in my law, which I have set before you,\n'),
	(14774, 21, 26, 5, 'to listen to the words of my servants the prophets, whom I send to you, even rising up early and sending them, but you have not listened;\n'),
	(14775, 21, 26, 6, 'then I will make this house like Shiloh, and will make this city a curse to all the nations of the earth.”’”\n'),
	(14776, 21, 26, 7, 'The priests and the prophets and all the people heard Jeremiah speaking these words in Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(14777, 21, 26, 8, 'When Jeremiah had finished speaking all that Yahweh had commanded him to speak to all the people, the priests and the prophets and all the people seized him, saying, “You shall surely die!\n'),
	(14778, 21, 26, 9, 'Why have you prophesied in Yahweh’s name, saying, ‘This house will be like Shiloh, and this city will be desolate, without inhabitant?’” All the people were crowded around Jeremiah in Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(14779, 21, 26, 10, 'When the princes of Judah heard these things, they came up from the king’s house to Yahweh’s house; and they sat in the entry of the new gate of Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(14780, 21, 26, 11, 'Then the priests and the prophets spoke to the princes and to all the people, saying, “This man is worthy of death; for he has prophesied against this city, as you have heard with your ears.”\n'),
	(14781, 21, 26, 12, 'Then Jeremiah spoke to all the princes and to all the people, saying, “Yahweh sent me to prophesy against this house and against this city all the words that you have heard.\n'),
	(14782, 21, 26, 13, 'Now therefore amend your ways and your doings, and obey Yahweh your God’s voice; then Yahweh will relent from the evil that he has pronounced against you.\n'),
	(14783, 21, 26, 14, 'But as for me, behold, I am in your hand. Do with me what is good and right in your eyes.\n'),
	(14784, 21, 26, 15, 'Only know for certain that, if you put me to death, you will bring innocent blood on yourselves, on this city, and on its inhabitants; for in truth Yahweh has sent me to you to speak all these words in your ears.”\n'),
	(14785, 21, 26, 16, 'Then the princes and all the people said to the priests and to the prophets: “This man is not worthy of death; for he has spoken to us in the name of Yahweh our God.”\n'),
	(14786, 21, 26, 17, 'Then certain of the elders of the land rose up, and spoke to all the assembly of the people, saying,\n'),
	(14787, 21, 26, 18, '“Micah the Morashtite prophesied in the days of Hezekiah king of Judah; and he spoke to all the people of Judah, saying, ‘Yahweh of Armies says:\n“‘Zion will be plowed as a field,\nand Jerusalem will become heaps,\nand the mountain of the house as the high places of a forest.’\n'),
	(14788, 21, 26, 19, 'Did Hezekiah king of Judah and all Judah put him to death? Didn’t he fear Yahweh, and entreat the favor of Yahweh, and Yahweh relented of the disaster which he had pronounced against them? We would commit great evil against our own souls that way!”\n'),
	(14789, 21, 26, 20, 'There was also a man who prophesied in Yahweh’s name, Uriah the son of Shemaiah of Kiriath Jearim; and he prophesied against this city and against this land according to all the words of Jeremiah.\n'),
	(14790, 21, 26, 21, 'When Jehoiakim the king, with all his mighty men and all the princes heard his words, the king sought to put him to death; but when Uriah heard it, he was afraid, and fled, and went into Egypt.\n'),
	(14791, 21, 26, 22, 'Then Jehoiakim the king sent men into Egypt, Elnathan the son of Achbor, and certain men with him, into Egypt;\n'),
	(14792, 21, 26, 23, 'and they fetched Uriah out of Egypt, and brought him to Jehoiakim the king, who killed him with the sword, and cast his dead body into the graves of the common people.\n'),
	(14793, 21, 26, 24, 'But the hand of Ahikam the son of Shaphan was with Jeremiah, so that they didn’t give him into the hand of the people to put him to death.\n'),
	(14794, 21, 27, 1, 'In the beginning of the reign of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah, this word came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(14795, 21, 27, 2, 'Yahweh says to me: “Make bonds and bars, and put them on your neck.\n'),
	(14796, 21, 27, 3, 'Then send them to the king of Edom, to the king of Moab, to the king of the children of Ammon, to the king of Tyre, and to the king of Sidon, by the hand of the messengers who come to Jerusalem to Zedekiah king of Judah.\n'),
	(14797, 21, 27, 4, 'Give them a command to their masters, saying, ‘Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says, “You shall tell your masters:\n'),
	(14798, 21, 27, 5, '‘I have made the earth, the men, and the animals that are on the surface of the earth by my great power and by my outstretched arm. I give it to whom it seems right to me.\n'),
	(14799, 21, 27, 6, 'Now I have given all these lands into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon, my servant. I have also given the animals of the field to him to serve him.\n'),
	(14800, 21, 27, 7, 'All the nations will serve him, his son, and his son’s son, until the time of his own land comes. Then many nations and great kings will make him their bondservant.\n'),
	(14801, 21, 27, 8, '“‘“‘It will happen that I will punish the nation and the kingdom which will not serve the same Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, and that will not put their neck under the yoke of the king of Babylon,’ says Yahweh, ‘with the sword, with famine, and with pestilence, until I have consumed them by his hand.\n'),
	(14802, 21, 27, 9, 'But as for you, don’t listen to your prophets, to your diviners, to your dreams, to your soothsayers, or to your sorcerers, who speak to you, saying, “You shall not serve the king of Babylon;”\n'),
	(14803, 21, 27, 10, 'for they prophesy a lie to you, to remove you far from your land, so that I would drive you out, and you would perish.\n'),
	(14804, 21, 27, 11, 'But the nation that brings their neck under the yoke of the king of Babylon and serves him, that nation I will let remain in their own land,’ says Yahweh; ‘and they will till it and dwell in it.’”’”\n'),
	(14805, 21, 27, 12, 'I spoke to Zedekiah king of Judah according to all these words, saying, “Bring your necks under the yoke of the king of Babylon, and serve him and his people, and live.\n'),
	(14806, 21, 27, 13, 'Why will you die, you and your people, by the sword, by the famine, and by the pestilence, as Yahweh has spoken concerning the nation that will not serve the king of Babylon?\n'),
	(14807, 21, 27, 14, 'Don’t listen to the words of the prophets who speak to you, saying, ‘You shall not serve the king of Babylon;’ for they prophesy a lie to you.\n'),
	(14808, 21, 27, 15, 'For I have not sent them,” says Yahweh, “but they prophesy falsely in my name; that I may drive you out, and that you may perish, you, and the prophets who prophesy to you.”\n'),
	(14809, 21, 27, 16, 'Also I spoke to the priests and to all this people, saying, Yahweh says, “Don’t listen to the words of your prophets who prophesy to you, saying, ‘Behold, the vessels of Yahweh’s house will now shortly be brought again from Babylon;’ for they prophesy a lie to you.\n'),
	(14810, 21, 27, 17, 'Don’t listen to them. Serve the king of Babylon, and live. Why should this city become a desolation?\n'),
	(14811, 21, 27, 18, 'But if they are prophets, and if Yahweh’s word is with them, let them now make intercession to Yahweh of Armies, that the vessels which are left in Yahweh’s house, in the house of the king of Judah, and at Jerusalem, don’t go to Babylon.\n'),
	(14812, 21, 27, 19, 'For Yahweh of Armies says concerning the pillars, concerning the sea, concerning the bases, and concerning the rest of the vessels that are left in this city,\n'),
	(14813, 21, 27, 20, 'which Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon didn’t take when he carried away captive Jeconiah the son of Jehoiakim, king of Judah, from Jerusalem to Babylon, and all the nobles of Judah and Jerusalem;\n'),
	(14814, 21, 27, 21, 'yes, Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says concerning the vessels that are left in Yahweh’s house, and in the house of the king of Judah, and at Jerusalem:\n'),
	(14815, 21, 27, 22, '‘They will be carried to Babylon, and there they will be, until the day that I visit them,’ says Yahweh; ‘then I will bring them up, and restore them to this place.’”\n'),
	(14816, 21, 28, 1, 'That same year, in the beginning of the reign of Zedekiah king of Judah, in the fourth year, in the fifth month, Hananiah the son of Azzur, the prophet, who was of Gibeon, spoke to me in Yahweh’s house, in the presence of the priests and of all the people, saying,\n'),
	(14817, 21, 28, 2, '“Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says, ‘I have broken the yoke of the king of Babylon.\n'),
	(14818, 21, 28, 3, 'Within two full years will I bring again into this place all the vessels of Yahweh’s house, that Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon took away from this place, and carried to Babylon.\n'),
	(14819, 21, 28, 4, 'I will bring again to this place Jeconiah the son of Jehoiakim, king of Judah, with all the captives of Judah, who went to Babylon,’ says Yahweh; ‘for I will break the yoke of the king of Babylon.’”\n'),
	(14820, 21, 28, 5, 'Then the prophet Jeremiah said to the prophet Hananiah in the presence of the priests, and in the presence of all the people who stood in Yahweh’s house,\n'),
	(14821, 21, 28, 6, 'even the prophet Jeremiah said, “Amen! May Yahweh do so. May Yahweh perform your words which you have prophesied, to bring again the vessels of Yahweh’s house, and all those who are captives, from Babylon to this place.\n'),
	(14822, 21, 28, 7, 'Nevertheless listen now to this word that I speak in your ears, and in the ears of all the people:\n'),
	(14823, 21, 28, 8, 'The prophets who have been before me and before you of old prophesied against many countries, and against great kingdoms, of war, of evil, and of pestilence.\n'),
	(14824, 21, 28, 9, 'The prophet who prophesies of peace, when the word of the prophet happens, then the prophet will be known, that Yahweh has truly sent him.”\n'),
	(14825, 21, 28, 10, 'Then Hananiah the prophet took the bar from off the prophet Jeremiah’s neck, and broke it.\n'),
	(14826, 21, 28, 11, 'Hananiah spoke in the presence of all the people, saying, “Yahweh says: ‘Even so I will break the yoke of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon from off the neck of all the nations within two full years.’” Then the prophet Jeremiah went his way.\n'),
	(14827, 21, 28, 12, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah, after Hananiah the prophet had broken the bar from off the neck of the prophet Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(14828, 21, 28, 13, '“Go, and tell Hananiah, saying, ‘Yahweh says, “You have broken the bars of wood, but you have made in their place bars of iron.”\n'),
	(14829, 21, 28, 14, 'For Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says, “I have put a yoke of iron on the neck of all these nations, that they may serve Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon; and they will serve him. I have also given him the animals of the field.”’”\n'),
	(14830, 21, 28, 15, 'Then the prophet Jeremiah said to Hananiah the prophet, “Listen, Hananiah! Yahweh has not sent you, but you make this people trust in a lie.\n'),
	(14831, 21, 28, 16, 'Therefore Yahweh says, ‘Behold, I will send you away from off the surface of the earth. This year you will die, because you have spoken rebellion against Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(14832, 21, 28, 17, 'So Hananiah the prophet died the same year in the seventh month.\n'),
	(14833, 21, 29, 1, 'Now these are the words of the letter that Jeremiah the prophet sent from Jerusalem to the residue of the elders of the captivity, and to the priests, to the prophets, and to all the people whom Nebuchadnezzar had carried away captive from Jerusalem to Babylon,\n'),
	(14834, 21, 29, 2, '(after Jeconiah the king, the queen mother, the eunuchs, the princes of Judah and Jerusalem, the craftsmen, and the smiths, had departed from Jerusalem),\n'),
	(14835, 21, 29, 3, 'by the hand of Elasah the son of Shaphan, and Gemariah the son of Hilkiah, (whom Zedekiah king of Judah sent to Babylon to Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon). It said:\n'),
	(14836, 21, 29, 4, 'Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says to all the captives whom I have caused to be carried away captive from Jerusalem to Babylon:\n'),
	(14837, 21, 29, 5, '“Build houses and dwell in them. Plant gardens and eat their fruit.\n'),
	(14838, 21, 29, 6, 'Take wives and father sons and daughters. Take wives for your sons, and give your daughters to husbands, that they may bear sons and daughters. Multiply there, and don’t be diminished.\n'),
	(14839, 21, 29, 7, 'Seek the peace of the city where I have caused you to be carried away captive, and pray to Yahweh for it; for in its peace you will have peace.”\n'),
	(14840, 21, 29, 8, 'For Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says: “Don’t let your prophets who are among you and your diviners deceive you. Don’t listen to your dreams which you cause to be dreamed.\n'),
	(14841, 21, 29, 9, 'For they prophesy falsely to you in my name. I have not sent them,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14842, 21, 29, 10, 'For Yahweh says, “After seventy years are accomplished for Babylon, I will visit you and perform my good word toward you, in causing you to return to this place.\n'),
	(14843, 21, 29, 11, 'For I know the thoughts that I think toward you,” says Yahweh, “thoughts of peace, and not of evil, to give you hope and a future.\n'),
	(14844, 21, 29, 12, 'You shall call on me, and you shall go and pray to me, and I will listen to you.\n'),
	(14845, 21, 29, 13, 'You shall seek me, and find me, when you search for me with all your heart.\n'),
	(14846, 21, 29, 14, 'I will be found by you,” says Yahweh, “and I will turn again your captivity, and I will gather you from all the nations, and from all the places where I have driven you, says Yahweh. I will bring you again to the place from where I caused you to be carried away captive.”\n'),
	(14847, 21, 29, 15, 'Because you have said, “Yahweh has raised us up prophets in Babylon;”\n'),
	(14848, 21, 29, 16, 'Yahweh says concerning the king who sits on David’s throne, and concerning all the people who dwell in this city, your brothers who haven’t gone with you into captivity;\n'),
	(14849, 21, 29, 17, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “Behold, I will send on them the sword, the famine, and the pestilence, and will make them like rotten figs that can’t be eaten, they are so bad.\n'),
	(14850, 21, 29, 18, 'I will pursue after them with the sword, with the famine, and with the pestilence, and will deliver them to be tossed back and forth among all the kingdoms of the earth, to be an object of horror, an astonishment, a hissing, and a reproach among all the nations where I have driven them,\n'),
	(14851, 21, 29, 19, 'because they have not listened to my words,” says Yahweh, “with which I sent to them my servants the prophets, rising up early and sending them; but you would not hear,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14852, 21, 29, 20, 'Hear therefore Yahweh’s word, all you captives, whom I have sent away from Jerusalem to Babylon.\n'),
	(14853, 21, 29, 21, 'Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says concerning Ahab the son of Kolaiah, and concerning Zedekiah the son of Maaseiah, who prophesy a lie to you in my name: “Behold, I will deliver them into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon; and he will kill them before your eyes.\n'),
	(14854, 21, 29, 22, 'A curse will be taken up about them by all the captives of Judah who are in Babylon, saying, ‘Yahweh make you like Zedekiah and like Ahab, whom the king of Babylon roasted in the fire;’\n'),
	(14855, 21, 29, 23, 'because they have done foolish things in Israel, and have committed adultery with their neighbors’ wives, and have spoken words in my name falsely, which I didn’t command them. I am he who knows, and am witness,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14856, 21, 29, 24, 'Concerning Shemaiah the Nehelamite you shall speak, saying,\n'),
	(14857, 21, 29, 25, '“Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says, ‘Because you have sent letters in your own name to all the people who are at Jerusalem, and to Zephaniah the son of Maaseiah, the priest, and to all the priests, saying,\n'),
	(14858, 21, 29, 26, '“Yahweh has made you priest in the place of Jehoiada the priest, that there may be officers in Yahweh’s house, for every man who is crazy, and makes himself a prophet, that you should put him in the stocks and in shackles.\n'),
	(14859, 21, 29, 27, 'Now therefore, why have you not rebuked Jeremiah of Anathoth, who makes himself a prophet to you,\n'),
	(14860, 21, 29, 28, 'because he has sent to us in Babylon, saying, The captivity is long. Build houses, and dwell in them. Plant gardens, and eat their fruit?”’”\n'),
	(14861, 21, 29, 29, 'Zephaniah the priest read this letter in the hearing of Jeremiah the prophet.\n'),
	(14862, 21, 29, 30, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(14863, 21, 29, 31, '“Send to all of the captives, saying, ‘Yahweh says concerning Shemaiah the Nehelamite: “Because Shemaiah has prophesied to you, and I didn’t send him, and he has caused you to trust in a lie;”\n'),
	(14864, 21, 29, 32, 'therefore Yahweh says, “Behold, I will punish Shemaiah the Nehelamite and his offspring. He will not have a man to dwell among this people. He won’t see the good that I will do to my people,” says Yahweh, “because he has spoken rebellion against Yahweh.”’”\n'),
	(14865, 21, 30, 1, 'The word that came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(14866, 21, 30, 2, '“Yahweh, the God of Israel, says, ‘Write all the words that I have spoken to you in a book.\n'),
	(14867, 21, 30, 3, 'For, behold, the days come,’ says Yahweh, ‘that I will reverse the captivity of my people Israel and Judah,’ says Yahweh. ‘I will cause them to return to the land that I gave to their fathers, and they will possess it.’”\n'),
	(14868, 21, 30, 4, 'These are the words that Yahweh spoke concerning Israel and concerning Judah.\n'),
	(14869, 21, 30, 5, 'For Yahweh says:\n“We have heard a voice of trembling;\na voice of fear, and not of peace.\n'),
	(14870, 21, 30, 6, 'Ask now, and see whether a man travails with child.\nWhy do I see every man with his hands on his waist, as a woman in travail,\nand all faces are turned pale?\n'),
	(14871, 21, 30, 7, 'Alas! for that day is great, so that none is like it.\nIt is even the time of Jacob’s trouble;\nbut he will be saved out of it.\n'),
	(14872, 21, 30, 8, 'It will come to pass in that day, says Yahweh of Armies, that I will break his yoke from off your neck,\nand will burst your bonds.\nStrangers will no more make them their bondservants;\n'),
	(14873, 21, 30, 9, 'but they will serve Yahweh their God,\nand David their king,\nwhom I will raise up to them.\n'),
	(14874, 21, 30, 10, 'Therefore don’t be afraid, O Jacob my servant, says Yahweh.\nDon’t be dismayed, Israel.\nFor, behold, I will save you from afar,\nand save your offspring from the land of their captivity.\nJacob will return,\nand will be quiet and at ease.\nNo one will make him afraid.\n'),
	(14875, 21, 30, 11, 'For I am with you, says Yahweh, to save you;\nfor I will make a full end of all the nations where I have scattered you,\nbut I will not make a full end of you;\nbut I will correct you in measure,\nand will in no way leave you unpunished.”\n'),
	(14876, 21, 30, 12, 'For Yahweh says,\n“Your hurt is incurable.\nYour wound is grievous.\n'),
	(14877, 21, 30, 13, 'There is no one to plead your cause,\nthat you may be bound up.\nYou have no healing medicines.\n'),
	(14878, 21, 30, 14, 'All your lovers have forgotten you.\nThey don’t seek you.\nFor I have wounded you with the wound of an enemy,\nwith the chastisement of a cruel one,\nfor the greatness of your iniquity,\nbecause your sins were increased.\n'),
	(14879, 21, 30, 15, 'Why do you cry over your injury?\nYour pain is incurable.\nFor the greatness of your iniquity,\nbecause your sins have increased,\nI have done these things to you.\n'),
	(14880, 21, 30, 16, 'Therefore all those who devour you will be devoured.\nAll your adversaries, everyone of them, will go into captivity.\nThose who plunder you will be plunder.\nI will make all who prey on you become prey.\n'),
	(14881, 21, 30, 17, 'For I will restore health to you,\nand I will heal you of your wounds,” says Yahweh;\n“because they have called you an outcast,\nsaying, ‘It is Zion, whom no man seeks after.’”\n'),
	(14882, 21, 30, 18, 'Yahweh says:\n“Behold, I will reverse the captivity of Jacob’s tents,\nand have compassion on his dwelling places.\nThe city will be built on its own hill,\nand the palace will be inhabited in its own place.\n'),
	(14883, 21, 30, 19, 'Thanksgiving will proceed out of them\nwith the voice of those who make merry.\nI will multiply them,\nand they will not be few;\nI will also glorify them,\nand they will not be small.\n'),
	(14884, 21, 30, 20, 'Their children also will be as before,\nand their congregation will be established before me.\nI will punish all who oppress them.\n'),
	(14885, 21, 30, 21, 'Their prince will be one of them,\nand their ruler will proceed from among them.\nI will cause him to draw near,\nand he will approach to me;\nfor who is he who has had boldness to approach to me?” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14886, 21, 30, 22, '“You shall be my people,\nand I will be your God.\n'),
	(14887, 21, 30, 23, 'Behold, Yahweh’s storm, his wrath, has gone out,\na sweeping storm:\nit will burst on the head of the wicked.\n'),
	(14888, 21, 30, 24, 'The fierce anger of Yahweh will not return until he has accomplished,\nand until he has performed the intentions of his heart.\nIn the latter days you will understand it.”\n'),
	(14889, 21, 31, 1, '“At that time,” says Yahweh, “I will be the God of all the families of Israel, and they will be my people.”\n'),
	(14890, 21, 31, 2, 'Yahweh says, “The people who survive the sword found favor in the wilderness; even Israel, when I went to cause him to rest.”\n'),
	(14891, 21, 31, 3, 'Yahweh appeared of old to me, saying,\n“Yes, I have loved you with an everlasting love.\nTherefore I have drawn you with loving kindness.\n'),
	(14892, 21, 31, 4, 'I will build you again,\nand you will be built, O virgin of Israel.\nYou will again be adorned with your tambourines,\nand will go out in the dances of those who make merry.\n'),
	(14893, 21, 31, 5, 'Again you will plant vineyards on the mountains of Samaria.\nThe planters will plant,\nand will enjoy its fruit.\n'),
	(14894, 21, 31, 6, 'For there will be a day that the watchmen on the hills of Ephraim cry,\n‘Arise, and let us go up to Zion to Yahweh our God.’”\n'),
	(14895, 21, 31, 7, 'For Yahweh says,\n“Sing with gladness for Jacob,\nand shout for the chief of the nations.\nPublish, praise, and say,\n‘Yahweh, save your people,\nthe remnant of Israel!’\n'),
	(14896, 21, 31, 8, 'Behold, I will bring them from the north country,\nand gather them from the uttermost parts of the earth,\nalong with the blind and the lame,\nthe woman with child and her who travails with child together.\nThey will return as a great company.\n'),
	(14897, 21, 31, 9, 'They will come with weeping.\nI will lead them with petitions.\nI will cause them to walk by rivers of waters,\nin a straight way in which they won’t stumble;\nfor I am a father to Israel.\nEphraim is my firstborn.\n'),
	(14898, 21, 31, 10, '“Hear Yahweh’s word, you nations,\nand declare it in the distant islands. Say,\n‘He who scattered Israel will gather him,\nand keep him, as a shepherd does his flock.’\n'),
	(14899, 21, 31, 11, 'For Yahweh has ransomed Jacob,\nand redeemed him from the hand of him who was stronger than he.\n'),
	(14900, 21, 31, 12, 'They will come and sing in the height of Zion,\nand will flow to the goodness of Yahweh,\nto the grain, to the new wine, to the oil,\nand to the young of the flock and of the herd.\nTheir soul will be as a watered garden.\nThey will not sorrow any more at all.\n'),
	(14901, 21, 31, 13, 'Then the virgin will rejoice in the dance;\nthe young men and the old together;\nfor I will turn their mourning into joy,\nand will comfort them, and make them rejoice from their sorrow.\n'),
	(14902, 21, 31, 14, 'I will satiate the soul of the priests with fatness,\nand my people will be satisfied with my goodness,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14903, 21, 31, 15, 'Yahweh says:\n“A voice is heard in Ramah,\nlamentation and bitter weeping,\nRachel weeping for her children.\nShe refuses to be comforted for her children,\nbecause they are no more.”\n'),
	(14904, 21, 31, 16, 'Yahweh says:\n“Refrain your voice from weeping,\nand your eyes from tears;\nfor your work will be rewarded,” says Yahweh.\n“They will come again from the land of the enemy.\n'),
	(14905, 21, 31, 17, 'There is hope for your latter end,” says Yahweh.\n“Your children will come again to their own territory.\n'),
	(14906, 21, 31, 18, '“I have surely heard Ephraim grieving thus,\n‘You have chastised me,\nand I was chastised, as an untrained calf.\nTurn me, and I will be turned;\nfor you are Yahweh my God.\n'),
	(14907, 21, 31, 19, 'Surely after that I was turned.\nI repented.\nAfter that I was instructed.\nI struck my thigh.\nI was ashamed, yes, even confounded,\nbecause I bore the reproach of my youth.’\n'),
	(14908, 21, 31, 20, 'Is Ephraim my dear son?\nIs he a darling child?\nFor as often as I speak against him,\nI still earnestly remember him.\ntherefore my heart yearns for him.\nI will surely have mercy on him,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14909, 21, 31, 21, '“Set up road signs.\nMake guideposts.\nSet your heart toward the highway,\neven the way by which you went.\nTurn again, virgin of Israel.\nTurn again to these your cities.\n'),
	(14910, 21, 31, 22, 'How long will you go here and there,\nyou backsliding daughter?\nFor Yahweh has created a new thing in the earth:\na woman will encompass a man.”\n'),
	(14911, 21, 31, 23, 'Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: “Yet again they will use this speech in the land of Judah and in its cities, when I reverse their captivity: ‘Yahweh bless you, habitation of righteousness, mountain of holiness.’\n'),
	(14912, 21, 31, 24, 'Judah and all its cities will dwell therein together, the farmers, and those who go about with flocks.\n'),
	(14913, 21, 31, 25, 'For I have satiated the weary soul, and I have replenished every sorrowful soul.”\n'),
	(14914, 21, 31, 26, 'On this I awakened, and saw; and my sleep was sweet to me.\n'),
	(14915, 21, 31, 27, '“Behold, the days come,” says Yahweh, “that I will sow the house of Israel and the house of Judah with the seed of man and with the seed of animal.\n'),
	(14916, 21, 31, 28, 'It will happen that, like as I have watched over them to pluck up and to break down and to overthrow and to destroy and to afflict, so will I watch over them to build and to plant,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14917, 21, 31, 29, '“In those days they will say no more,\n“‘The fathers have eaten sour grapes,\nand the children’s teeth are set on edge.’\n'),
	(14918, 21, 31, 30, 'But everyone will die for his own iniquity. Every man who eats the sour grapes, his teeth will be set on edge.\n'),
	(14919, 21, 31, 31, '“Behold, the days come,” says Yahweh,\n“that I will make a new covenant with the house of Israel,\nand with the house of Judah:\n'),
	(14920, 21, 31, 32, 'not according to the covenant that I made with their fathers in the day that I took them by the hand to bring them out of the land of Egypt;\nwhich covenant of mine they broke,\nalthough I was a husband to them,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14921, 21, 31, 33, '“But this is the covenant that I will make with the house of Israel after those days,”\nsays Yahweh:\nI will put my law in their inward parts,\nand I will write it in their heart.\nI will be their God,\nand they shall be my people.\n'),
	(14922, 21, 31, 34, 'They will no longer each teach his neighbor,\nand every man teach his brother, saying, ‘Know Yahweh;’\nfor they will all know me,\nfrom their least to their greatest,” says Yahweh:\n“for I will forgive their iniquity,\nand I will remember their sin no more.”\n'),
	(14923, 21, 31, 35, 'Yahweh, who gives the sun for a light by day,\nand the ordinances of the moon and of the stars for a light by night,\nwho stirs up the sea, so that its waves roar;\nYahweh of Armies is his name, says:\n'),
	(14924, 21, 31, 36, '“If these ordinances depart from before me,” says Yahweh,\n“then the offspring of Israel also will cease from being a nation before me forever.”\n'),
	(14925, 21, 31, 37, 'Yahweh says: “If heaven above can be measured,\nand the foundations of the earth searched out beneath,\nthen I will also cast off all the offspring of Israel for all that they have done,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14926, 21, 31, 38, '“Behold, the days come,” says Yahweh, “that the city will be built to Yahweh from the tower of Hananel to the gate of the corner.\n'),
	(14927, 21, 31, 39, 'The measuring line will go out further straight onward to the hill Gareb, and will turn toward Goah.\n'),
	(14928, 21, 31, 40, 'The whole valley of the dead bodies and of the ashes, and all the fields to the brook Kidron, to the corner of the horse gate toward the east, will be holy to Yahweh. It will not be plucked up or thrown down any more forever.”\n'),
	(14929, 21, 32, 1, 'The word that came to Jeremiah from Yahweh in the tenth year of Zedekiah king of Judah, which was the eighteenth year of Nebuchadnezzar.\n'),
	(14930, 21, 32, 2, 'Now at that time the king of Babylon’s army was besieging Jerusalem. Jeremiah the prophet was shut up in the court of the guard, which was in the king of Judah’s house.\n'),
	(14931, 21, 32, 3, 'For Zedekiah king of Judah had shut him up, saying, “Why do you prophesy, and say, ‘Yahweh says, “Behold, I will give this city into the hand of the king of Babylon, and he will take it;\n'),
	(14932, 21, 32, 4, 'and Zedekiah king of Judah won’t escape out of the hand of the Chaldeans, but will surely be delivered into the hand of the king of Babylon, and will speak with him mouth to mouth, and his eyes will see his eyes;\n'),
	(14933, 21, 32, 5, 'and he will bring Zedekiah to Babylon, and he will be there until I visit him,” says Yahweh: “though you fight with the Chaldeans, you will not prosper?”’”\n'),
	(14934, 21, 32, 6, 'Jeremiah said, “Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(14935, 21, 32, 7, '‘Behold, Hanamel the son of Shallum your uncle will come to you, saying, “Buy my field that is in Anathoth; for the right of redemption is yours to buy it.”’”\n'),
	(14936, 21, 32, 8, '“So Hanamel my uncle’s son came to me in the court of the guard according to Yahweh’s word, and said to me, ‘Please buy my field that is in Anathoth, which is in the land of Benjamin; for the right of inheritance is yours, and the redemption is yours. Buy it for yourself.’\n“Then I knew that this was Yahweh’s word.\n'),
	(14937, 21, 32, 9, 'I bought the field that was in Anathoth of Hanamel my uncle’s son, and weighed him the money, even seventeen shekels of silver.\n'),
	(14938, 21, 32, 10, 'I signed the deed, sealed it, called witnesses, and weighed the money in the balances to him.\n'),
	(14939, 21, 32, 11, 'So I took the deed of the purchase, both that which was sealed, containing the terms and conditions, and that which was open;\n'),
	(14940, 21, 32, 12, 'and I delivered the deed of the purchase to Baruch the son of Neriah, the son of Mahseiah, in the presence of Hanamel my uncle’s son, and in the presence of the witnesses who subscribed the deed of the purchase, before all the Jews who sat in the court of the guard.\n'),
	(14941, 21, 32, 13, '“I commanded Baruch before them, saying,\n'),
	(14942, 21, 32, 14, 'Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says: ‘Take these deeds, this deed of the purchase which is sealed, and this deed which is open, and put them in an earthen vessel, that they may last many days.’\n'),
	(14943, 21, 32, 15, 'For Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says: ‘Houses and fields and vineyards will yet again be bought in this land.’\n'),
	(14944, 21, 32, 16, 'Now after I had delivered the deed of the purchase to Baruch the son of Neriah, I prayed to Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(14945, 21, 32, 17, '“Ah Lord Yahweh! Behold, you have made the heavens and the earth by your great power and by your outstretched arm. There is nothing too hard for you,\n'),
	(14946, 21, 32, 18, 'who show loving kindness to thousands, and repay the iniquity of the fathers into the bosom of their children after them; the great, the mighty God, Yahweh of Armies is his name;\n'),
	(14947, 21, 32, 19, 'great in counsel, and mighty in work; whose eyes are open to all the ways of the sons of men, to give everyone according to his ways, and according to the fruit of his doings;\n'),
	(14948, 21, 32, 20, 'who performed signs and wonders in the land of Egypt, even to this day, both in Israel and among other men; and made yourself a name, as it is today;\n'),
	(14949, 21, 32, 21, 'and brought your people Israel out of the land of Egypt with signs, with wonders, with a strong hand, with an outstretched arm, and with great terror;\n'),
	(14950, 21, 32, 22, 'and gave them this land, which you swore to their fathers to give them, a land flowing with milk and honey.\n'),
	(14951, 21, 32, 23, 'They came in and possessed it, but they didn’t obey your voice and didn’t walk in your law. They have done nothing of all that you commanded them to do. Therefore you have caused all this evil to come upon them.\n'),
	(14952, 21, 32, 24, '“Behold, siege ramps have come to the city to take it. The city is given into the hand of the Chaldeans who fight against it, because of the sword, of the famine, and of the pestilence. What you have spoken has happened. Behold, you see it.\n'),
	(14953, 21, 32, 25, 'You have said to me, Lord Yahweh, ‘Buy the field for money, and call witnesses;’ whereas the city is given into the hand of the Chaldeans.”\n'),
	(14954, 21, 32, 26, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(14955, 21, 32, 27, '“Behold, I am Yahweh, the God of all flesh. Is there anything too hard for me?\n'),
	(14956, 21, 32, 28, 'Therefore Yahweh says: Behold, I will give this city into the hand of the Chaldeans, and into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, and he will take it.\n'),
	(14957, 21, 32, 29, 'The Chaldeans, who fight against this city, will come and set this city on fire, and burn it with the houses on whose roofs they have offered incense to Baal, and poured out drink offerings to other gods, to provoke me to anger.\n'),
	(14958, 21, 32, 30, '“For the children of Israel and the children of Judah have done only that which was evil in my sight from their youth; for the children of Israel have only provoked me to anger with the work of their hands, says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14959, 21, 32, 31, 'For this city has been to me a provocation of my anger and of my wrath from the day that they built it even to this day, so that I should remove it from before my face,\n'),
	(14960, 21, 32, 32, 'because of all the evil of the children of Israel and of the children of Judah, which they have done to provoke me to anger: they, their kings, their princes, their priests, their prophets, the men of Judah, and the inhabitants of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(14961, 21, 32, 33, 'They have turned their backs to me, and not their faces. Although I taught them, rising up early and teaching them, yet they have not listened to receive instruction.\n'),
	(14962, 21, 32, 34, 'But they set their abominations in the house which is called by my name, to defile it.\n'),
	(14963, 21, 32, 35, 'They built the high places of Baal, which are in the valley of the son of Hinnom, to cause their sons and their daughters to pass through fire to Molech; which I didn’t command them. It didn’t even come into my mind, that they should do this abomination, to cause Judah to sin.”\n'),
	(14964, 21, 32, 36, 'Now therefore Yahweh, the God of Israel, says concerning this city, about which you say, “It is given into the hand of the king of Babylon by the sword, by the famine, and by the pestilence:”\n'),
	(14965, 21, 32, 37, '“Behold, I will gather them out of all the countries where I have driven them in my anger, and in my wrath, and in great indignation; and I will bring them again to this place. I will cause them to dwell safely.\n'),
	(14966, 21, 32, 38, 'Then they will be my people, and I will be their God.\n'),
	(14967, 21, 32, 39, 'I will give them one heart and one way, that they may fear me forever, for their good, and the good of their children after them.\n'),
	(14968, 21, 32, 40, 'I will make an everlasting covenant with them, that I will not turn away from following them, to do them good. I will put my fear in their hearts, that they may not depart from me.\n'),
	(14969, 21, 32, 41, 'Yes, I will rejoice over them to do them good, and I will plant them in this land assuredly with my whole heart and with my whole soul.”\n'),
	(14970, 21, 32, 42, 'For Yahweh says: “Just as I have brought all this great evil on this people, so will I bring on them all the good that I have promised them.\n'),
	(14971, 21, 32, 43, 'Fields will be bought in this land, about which you say, ‘It is desolate, without man or animal. It is given into the hand of the Chaldeans.’\n'),
	(14972, 21, 32, 44, 'Men will buy fields for money, sign the deeds, seal them, and call witnesses, in the land of Benjamin, and in the places around Jerusalem, in the cities of Judah, in the cities of the hill country, in the cities of the lowland, and in the cities of the South; for I will cause their captivity to be reversed,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14973, 21, 33, 1, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah the second time, while he was still locked up in the court of the guard, saying,\n'),
	(14974, 21, 33, 2, '“Yahweh who does it, Yahweh who forms it to establish it—Yahweh is his name, says:\n'),
	(14975, 21, 33, 3, '‘Call to me, and I will answer you, and will show you great and difficult things, which you don’t know.’\n'),
	(14976, 21, 33, 4, 'For Yahweh, the God of Israel, says concerning the houses of this city and concerning the houses of the kings of Judah, which are broken down to make a defense against the mounds and against the sword;\n'),
	(14977, 21, 33, 5, 'while men come to fight with the Chaldeans, and to fill them with the dead bodies of men, whom I have killed in my anger and in my wrath, and for all whose wickedness I have hidden my face from this city:\n'),
	(14978, 21, 33, 6, '‘Behold, I will bring it health and cure, and I will cure them; and I will reveal to them abundance of peace and truth.\n'),
	(14979, 21, 33, 7, 'I will cause the captivity of Judah and the captivity of Israel to return, and will build them, as at the first.\n'),
	(14980, 21, 33, 8, 'I will cleanse them from all their iniquity by which they have sinned against me. I will pardon all their iniquities by which they have sinned against me and by which they have transgressed against me.\n'),
	(14981, 21, 33, 9, 'This city will be to me for a name of joy, for praise, and for glory, before all the nations of the earth, which will hear all the good that I do to them, and will fear and tremble for all the good and for all the peace that I provide to it.’”\n'),
	(14982, 21, 33, 10, 'Yahweh says: “Yet again there will be heard in this place, about which you say, ‘It is waste, without man and without animal, even in the cities of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem, that are desolate, without man and without inhabitant and without animal,’\n'),
	(14983, 21, 33, 11, 'the voice of joy and the voice of gladness, the voice of the bridegroom and the voice of the bride, the voice of those who say, ‘Give thanks to Yahweh of Armies, for Yahweh is good, for his loving kindness endures forever;’ who bring thanksgiving into Yahweh’s house. For I will cause the captivity of the land to be reversed as at the first,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14984, 21, 33, 12, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “Yet again there will be in this place, which is waste, without man and without animal, and in all its cities, a habitation of shepherds causing their flocks to lie down.\n'),
	(14985, 21, 33, 13, 'In the cities of the hill country, in the cities of the lowland, in the cities of the South, in the land of Benjamin, in the places around Jerusalem, and in the cities of Judah, the flocks will again pass under the hands of him who counts them,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(14986, 21, 33, 14, '“Behold, the days come,” says Yahweh, “that I will perform that good word which I have spoken concerning the house of Israel and concerning the house of Judah.\n'),
	(14987, 21, 33, 15, '“In those days and at that time,\nI will cause a Branch of righteousness to grow up to David.\nHe will execute justice and righteousness in the land.\n'),
	(14988, 21, 33, 16, 'In those days Judah will be saved,\nand Jerusalem will dwell safely.\nThis is the name by which she will be called:\nYahweh our righteousness.”\n'),
	(14989, 21, 33, 17, 'For Yahweh says: “David will never lack a man to sit on the throne of the house of Israel.\n'),
	(14990, 21, 33, 18, 'The priests the Levites won’t lack a man before me to offer burnt offerings, to burn meal offerings, and to do sacrifice continually.”\n'),
	(14991, 21, 33, 19, 'Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(14992, 21, 33, 20, '“Yahweh says: ‘If you can break my covenant of the day and my covenant of the night, so that there will not be day and night in their time;\n'),
	(14993, 21, 33, 21, 'then may my covenant also be broken with David my servant, that he won’t have a son to reign on his throne; and with the Levites the priests, my ministers.\n'),
	(14994, 21, 33, 22, 'As the army of the sky can’t be counted, and the sand of the sea can’t be measured; so I will multiply the offspring of David my servant and the Levites who minister to me.’”\n'),
	(14995, 21, 33, 23, 'Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(14996, 21, 33, 24, '“Don’t consider what this people has spoken, saying, ‘Has Yahweh cast off the two families which he chose?’ Thus they despise my people, that they should be no more a nation before them.”\n'),
	(14997, 21, 33, 25, 'Yahweh says: “If my covenant of day and night fails, if I have not appointed the ordinances of heaven and earth;\n'),
	(14998, 21, 33, 26, 'then I will also cast away the offspring of Jacob, and of David my servant, so that I will not take of his offspring to be rulers over the offspring of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob: for I will cause their captivity to be reversed and will have mercy on them.”\n'),
	(14999, 21, 34, 1, 'The word which came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, when Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, with all his army, all the kingdoms of the earth that were under his dominion, and all the peoples, were fighting against Jerusalem and against all its cities, saying:\n'),
	(15000, 21, 34, 2, '“Yahweh, the God of Israel, says, ‘Go, and speak to Zedekiah king of Judah, and tell him, Yahweh says, “Behold, I will give this city into the hand of the king of Babylon and he will burn it with fire.\n'),
	(15001, 21, 34, 3, 'You won’t escape out of his hand, but will surely be taken and delivered into his hand. Your eyes will see the eyes of the king of Babylon, and he will speak with you mouth to mouth. You will go to Babylon.”’\n'),
	(15002, 21, 34, 4, '“Yet hear Yahweh’s word, O Zedekiah king of Judah: Yahweh says concerning you, ‘You won’t die by the sword.\n'),
	(15003, 21, 34, 5, 'You will die in peace; and with the burnings of your fathers, the former kings who were before you, so they will make a burning for you. They will lament you, saying, “Ah Lord!” for I have spoken the word,’ says Yahweh.”\n'),
	(15004, 21, 34, 6, 'Then Jeremiah the prophet spoke all these words to Zedekiah king of Judah in Jerusalem,\n'),
	(15005, 21, 34, 7, 'when the king of Babylon’s army was fighting against Jerusalem, and against all the cities of Judah that were left, against Lachish and against Azekah; for these alone remained of the cities of Judah as fortified cities.\n'),
	(15006, 21, 34, 8, 'The word came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, after king Zedekiah had made a covenant with all the people who were at Jerusalem, to proclaim liberty to them;\n'),
	(15007, 21, 34, 9, 'that every man should let his male servant, and every man his female servant, who is a Hebrew or a Hebrewess, go free; that no one should make bondservants of them, of a Jew his brother.\n'),
	(15008, 21, 34, 10, 'All the princes and all the people obeyed who had entered into the covenant, that everyone should let his male servant, and everyone his female servant go free, that no one should make bondservants of them any more. They obeyed and let them go;\n'),
	(15009, 21, 34, 11, 'but afterwards they turned, and caused the servants and the handmaids, whom they had let go free, to return, and brought them into subjection for servants and for handmaids.\n'),
	(15010, 21, 34, 12, 'Therefore Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(15011, 21, 34, 13, '“Yahweh, the God of Israel, says: ‘I made a covenant with your fathers in the day that I brought them out of the land of Egypt, out of the house of bondage, saying,\n'),
	(15012, 21, 34, 14, 'At the end of seven years, every man of you shall release his brother who is a Hebrew, who has been sold to you, and has served you six years. You shall let him go free from you; but your fathers didn’t listen to me, and didn’t incline their ear.\n'),
	(15013, 21, 34, 15, 'You had now turned, and had done that which is right in my eyes, in every man proclaiming liberty to his neighbor. You had made a covenant before me in the house which is called by my name;\n'),
	(15014, 21, 34, 16, 'but you turned and profaned my name, and every man caused his servant, and every man his handmaid, whom you had let go free at their pleasure, to return. You brought them into subjection, to be to you for servants and for handmaids.’”\n'),
	(15015, 21, 34, 17, 'Therefore Yahweh says: “You have not listened to me, to proclaim liberty, every man to his brother, and every man to his neighbor. Behold, I proclaim to you a liberty,” says Yahweh, “to the sword, to the pestilence, and to the famine. I will make you be tossed back and forth among all the kingdoms of the earth.\n'),
	(15016, 21, 34, 18, 'I will give the men who have transgressed my covenant, who have not performed the words of the covenant which they made before me, when they cut the calf in two and passed between its parts:\n'),
	(15017, 21, 34, 19, 'the princes of Judah, the princes of Jerusalem, the eunuchs, the priests, and all the people of the land, who passed between the parts of the calf;\n'),
	(15018, 21, 34, 20, 'I will even give them into the hand of their enemies, and into the hand of those who seek their life. Their dead bodies will be food for the birds of the sky and for the animals of the earth.\n'),
	(15019, 21, 34, 21, '“I will give Zedekiah king of Judah and his princes into the hands of their enemies, into the hands of those who seek their life and into the hands of the king of Babylon’s army, who has gone away from you.\n'),
	(15020, 21, 34, 22, 'Behold, I will command,” says Yahweh, “and cause them to return to this city. They will fight against it, take it, and burn it with fire. I will make the cities of Judah a desolation, without inhabitant.”\n'),
	(15021, 21, 35, 1, 'The word which came to Jeremiah from Yahweh in the days of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah, saying,\n'),
	(15022, 21, 35, 2, '“Go to the house of the Rechabites, and speak to them, and bring them into Yahweh’s house, into one of the rooms, and give them wine to drink.”\n'),
	(15023, 21, 35, 3, 'Then I took Jaazaniah the son of Jeremiah, the son of Habazziniah, with his brothers, all his sons, and the whole house of the Rechabites;\n'),
	(15024, 21, 35, 4, 'and I brought them into Yahweh’s house, into the room of the sons of Hanan the son of Igdaliah, the man of God, which was by the room of the princes, which was above the room of Maaseiah the son of Shallum, the keeper of the threshold.\n'),
	(15025, 21, 35, 5, 'I set before the sons of the house of the Rechabites bowls full of wine, and cups; and I said to them, “Drink wine!”\n'),
	(15026, 21, 35, 6, 'But they said, “We will drink no wine; for Jonadab the son of Rechab, our father, commanded us, saying, ‘You shall drink no wine, neither you, nor your sons, forever.\n'),
	(15027, 21, 35, 7, 'You shall not build a house, sow seed, plant a vineyard, or have any; but all your days you shall dwell in tents, that you may live many days in the land in which you live as nomads.’\n'),
	(15028, 21, 35, 8, 'We have obeyed the voice of Jonadab the son of Rechab, our father, in all that he commanded us, to drink no wine all our days, we, our wives, our sons, or our daughters;\n'),
	(15029, 21, 35, 9, 'and not to build houses for ourselves to dwell in. We have no vineyard, field, or seed;\n'),
	(15030, 21, 35, 10, 'but we have lived in tents, and have obeyed, and done according to all that Jonadab our father commanded us.\n'),
	(15031, 21, 35, 11, 'But when Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon came up into the land, we said, ‘Come, and let us go to Jerusalem for fear of the army of the Chaldeans, and for fear of the army of the Syrians; so we will dwell at Jerusalem.’”\n'),
	(15032, 21, 35, 12, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(15033, 21, 35, 13, '“Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘Go and tell the men of Judah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem, “Will you not receive instruction to listen to my words?” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15034, 21, 35, 14, '“The words of Jonadab the son of Rechab that he commanded his sons, not to drink wine, are performed; and to this day they drink none, for they obey their father’s commandment; but I have spoken to you, rising up early and speaking, and you have not listened to me.\n'),
	(15035, 21, 35, 15, 'I have sent also to you all my servants the prophets, rising up early and sending them, saying, ‘Every one of you must return now from his evil way, amend your doings, and don’t go after other gods to serve them, then you will dwell in the land which I have given to you and to your fathers:’ but you have not inclined your ear, nor listened to me.\n'),
	(15036, 21, 35, 16, 'The sons of Jonadab the son of Rechab have performed the commandment of their father which he commanded them, but this people has not listened to me.”’\n'),
	(15037, 21, 35, 17, '“Therefore Yahweh, the God of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘Behold, I will bring on Judah and on all the inhabitants of Jerusalem all the evil that I have pronounced against them; because I have spoken to them, but they have not heard; and I have called to them, but they have not answered.’”\n'),
	(15038, 21, 35, 18, 'Jeremiah said to the house of the Rechabites, “Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘Because you have obeyed the commandment of Jonadab your father, and kept all his precepts, and done according to all that he commanded you;’\n'),
	(15039, 21, 35, 19, 'therefore Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘Jonadab the son of Rechab will not lack a man to stand before me forever.’”\n'),
	(15040, 21, 36, 1, 'In the fourth year of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah, this word came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, saying,\n'),
	(15041, 21, 36, 2, '“Take a scroll of a book, and write in it all the words that I have spoken to you against Israel, and against Judah, and against all the nations, from the day I spoke to you, from the days of Josiah, even to this day.\n'),
	(15042, 21, 36, 3, 'It may be that the house of Judah will hear all the evil which I intend to do to them; that they may each return from his evil way; that I may forgive their iniquity and their sin.”\n'),
	(15043, 21, 36, 4, 'Then Jeremiah called Baruch the son of Neriah; and Baruch wrote from the mouth of Jeremiah all Yahweh’s words, which he had spoken to him, on a scroll of a book.\n'),
	(15044, 21, 36, 5, 'Jeremiah commanded Baruch, saying, “I am restricted. I can’t go into Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(15045, 21, 36, 6, 'Therefore you go, and read from the scroll which you have written from my mouth, Yahweh’s words, in the ears of the people in Yahweh’s house on the fast day. Also you shall read them in the ears of all Judah who come out of their cities.\n'),
	(15046, 21, 36, 7, 'It may be they will present their supplication before Yahweh, and will each return from his evil way; for Yahweh has pronounced great anger and wrath against this people.”\n'),
	(15047, 21, 36, 8, 'Baruch the son of Neriah did according to all that Jeremiah the prophet commanded him, reading in the book Yahweh’s words in Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(15048, 21, 36, 9, 'Now in the fifth year of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah, in the ninth month, all the people in Jerusalem, and all the people who came from the cities of Judah to Jerusalem, proclaimed a fast before Yahweh.\n'),
	(15049, 21, 36, 10, 'Then Baruch read the words of Jeremiah from the book in Yahweh’s house, in the room of Gemariah the son of Shaphan, the scribe, in the upper court, at the entry of the new gate of Yahweh’s house, in the ears of all the people.\n'),
	(15050, 21, 36, 11, 'When Micaiah the son of Gemariah, the son of Shaphan, had heard out of the book all Yahweh’s words,\n'),
	(15051, 21, 36, 12, 'he went down into the king’s house, into the scribe’s room: and behold, all the princes were sitting there, Elishama the scribe, Delaiah the son of Shemaiah, Elnathan the son of Achbor, Gemariah the son of Shaphan, Zedekiah the son of Hananiah, and all the princes.\n'),
	(15052, 21, 36, 13, 'Then Micaiah declared to them all the words that he had heard, when Baruch read the book in the ears of the people.\n'),
	(15053, 21, 36, 14, 'Therefore all the princes sent Jehudi the son of Nethaniah, the son of Shelemiah, the son of Cushi, to Baruch, saying, “Take in your hand the scroll in which you have read in the ears of the people, and come.”\nSo Baruch the son of Neriah took the scroll in his hand, and came to them.\n'),
	(15054, 21, 36, 15, 'They said to him, “Sit down now, and read it in our hearing.”\nSo Baruch read it in their hearing.\n'),
	(15055, 21, 36, 16, 'Now when they had heard all the words, they turned in fear one toward another, and said to Baruch, “We will surely tell the king of all these words.”\n'),
	(15056, 21, 36, 17, 'They asked Baruch, saying, “Tell us now, how did you write all these words at his mouth?”\n'),
	(15057, 21, 36, 18, 'Then Baruch answered them, “He dictated all these words to me with his mouth, and I wrote them with ink in the book.”\n'),
	(15058, 21, 36, 19, 'Then the princes said to Baruch, “You and Jeremiah go hide. Don’t let anyone know where you are.”\n'),
	(15059, 21, 36, 20, 'They went in to the king into the court; but they had laid up the scroll in the room of Elishama the scribe. Then they told all the words in the hearing of the king.\n'),
	(15060, 21, 36, 21, 'So the king sent Jehudi to get the scroll; and he took it out of the room of Elishama the scribe. Jehudi read it in the hearing of the king, and in the hearing of all the princes who stood beside the king.\n'),
	(15061, 21, 36, 22, 'Now the king was sitting in the winter house in the ninth month; and there was a fire in the brazier burning before him.\n'),
	(15062, 21, 36, 23, 'When Jehudi had read three or four leaves, the king cut it with the penknife, and cast it into the fire that was in the brazier, until all the scroll was consumed in the fire that was in the brazier.\n'),
	(15063, 21, 36, 24, 'The king and his servants who heard all these words were not afraid, and didn’t tear their garments.\n'),
	(15064, 21, 36, 25, 'Moreover Elnathan and Delaiah and Gemariah had made intercession to the king that he would not burn the scroll; but he would not listen to them.\n'),
	(15065, 21, 36, 26, 'The king commanded Jerahmeel the king’s son, and Seraiah the son of Azriel, and Shelemiah the son of Abdeel, to arrest Baruch the scribe and Jeremiah the prophet; but Yahweh hid them.\n'),
	(15066, 21, 36, 27, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah, after the king had burned the scroll, and the words which Baruch wrote at the mouth of Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(15067, 21, 36, 28, '“Take again another scroll, and write in it all the former words that were in the first scroll, which Jehoiakim the king of Judah has burned.\n'),
	(15068, 21, 36, 29, 'Concerning Jehoiakim king of Judah you shall say, ‘Yahweh says: “You have burned this scroll, saying, “Why have you written therein, saying, ‘The king of Babylon will certainly come and destroy this land, and will cause to cease from there man and animal?’”’\n'),
	(15069, 21, 36, 30, 'Therefore Yahweh says concerning Jehoiakim king of Judah: “He will have no one to sit on David’s throne. His dead body will be cast out in the day to the heat, and in the night to the frost.\n'),
	(15070, 21, 36, 31, 'I will punish him, his offspring, and his servants for their iniquity. I will bring on them, on the inhabitants of Jerusalem, and on the men of Judah, all the evil that I have pronounced against them, but they didn’t listen.”’”\n'),
	(15071, 21, 36, 32, 'Then took Jeremiah another scroll, and gave it to Baruch the scribe, the son of Neriah, who wrote therein from the mouth of Jeremiah all the words of the book which Jehoiakim king of Judah had burned in the fire; and many similar words were added to them.\n'),
	(15072, 21, 37, 1, 'Zedekiah the son of Josiah reigned as king, instead of Coniah the son of Jehoiakim, whom Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon made king in the land of Judah.\n'),
	(15073, 21, 37, 2, 'But neither he, nor his servants, nor the people of the land, listened to Yahweh’s words, which he spoke by the prophet Jeremiah.\n'),
	(15074, 21, 37, 3, 'Zedekiah the king sent Jehucal the son of Shelemiah, and Zephaniah the son of Maaseiah, the priest, to the prophet Jeremiah, saying, “Pray now to Yahweh our God for us.”\n'),
	(15075, 21, 37, 4, 'Now Jeremiah came in and went out among the people; for they had not put him into prison.\n'),
	(15076, 21, 37, 5, 'Pharaoh’s army had come out of Egypt; and when the Chaldeans who were besieging Jerusalem heard news of them, they broke up from Jerusalem.\n'),
	(15077, 21, 37, 6, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to the prophet Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(15078, 21, 37, 7, '“Yahweh, the God of Israel, says, ‘You shall tell the king of Judah, who sent you to me to inquire of me: “Behold, Pharaoh’s army, which has come out to help you, will return to Egypt into their own land.\n'),
	(15079, 21, 37, 8, 'The Chaldeans will come again, and fight against this city. They will take it and burn it with fire.”’\n'),
	(15080, 21, 37, 9, '“Yahweh says, ‘Don’t deceive yourselves, saying, “The Chaldeans will surely depart from us;” for they will not depart.\n'),
	(15081, 21, 37, 10, 'For though you had struck the whole army of the Chaldeans who fight against you, and there remained but wounded men among them, yes they would each rise up in his tent and burn this city with fire.’”\n'),
	(15082, 21, 37, 11, 'When the army of the Chaldeans had broken up from Jerusalem for fear of Pharaoh’s army,\n'),
	(15083, 21, 37, 12, 'then Jeremiah went out of Jerusalem to go into the land of Benjamin, to receive his portion there, in the middle of the people.\n'),
	(15084, 21, 37, 13, 'When he was in Benjamin’s gate, a captain of the guard was there, whose name was Irijah, the son of Shelemiah, the son of Hananiah; and he seized Jeremiah the prophet, saying, “You are defecting to the Chaldeans!”\n'),
	(15085, 21, 37, 14, 'Then Jeremiah said, “That is false! I am not defecting to the Chaldeans.”\nBut he didn’t listen to him; so Irijah siezed Jeremiah, and brought him to the princes.\n'),
	(15086, 21, 37, 15, 'The princes were angry with Jeremiah, and struck him, and put him in prison in the house of Jonathan the scribe; for they had made that the prison.\n'),
	(15087, 21, 37, 16, 'When Jeremiah had come into the dungeon house, and into the cells, and Jeremiah had remained there many days,\n'),
	(15088, 21, 37, 17, 'then Zedekiah the king sent, and had him brought out. The king asked him secretly in his house, “Is there any word from Yahweh?”\nJeremiah said, “There is.” He also said, “You will be delivered into the hand of the king of Babylon.”\n'),
	(15089, 21, 37, 18, 'Moreover Jeremiah said to king Zedekiah, “How have I sinned against you, against your servants, or against this people, that you have put me in prison?\n'),
	(15090, 21, 37, 19, 'Now where are your prophets who prophesied to you, saying, ‘The king of Babylon will not come against you, nor against this land?’\n'),
	(15091, 21, 37, 20, 'Now please hear, my lord the king: please let my supplication be presented before you, that you not cause me to return to the house of Jonathan the scribe, lest I die there.”\n'),
	(15092, 21, 37, 21, 'Then Zedekiah the king commanded, and they committed Jeremiah into the court of the guard. They gave him daily a loaf of bread out of the bakers’ street, until all the bread in the city was gone. Thus Jeremiah remained in the court of the guard.\n'),
	(15093, 21, 38, 1, 'Shephatiah the son of Mattan, and Gedaliah the son of Pashhur, and Jucal the son of Shelemiah, and Pashhur the son of Malchijah, heard the words that Jeremiah spoke to all the people, saying,\n'),
	(15094, 21, 38, 2, '“Yahweh says, ‘He who remains in this city will die by the sword, by the famine, and by the pestilence; but he who goes out to the Chaldeans will live, and he will escape with his life, and he will live.’\n'),
	(15095, 21, 38, 3, 'Yahweh says, ‘This city will surely be given into the hand of the army of the king of Babylon, and he will take it.’”\n'),
	(15096, 21, 38, 4, 'Then the princes said to the king, “Please let this man be put to death; because he weakens the hands of the men of war who remain in this city, and the hands of all the people, in speaking such words to them: for this man doesn’t seek the welfare of this people, but harm.”\n'),
	(15097, 21, 38, 5, 'Zedekiah the king said, “Behold, he is in your hand; for the king can’t do anything to oppose you.”\n'),
	(15098, 21, 38, 6, 'Then took they Jeremiah and threw him into the dungeon of Malchijah the king’s son, that was in the court of the guard. They let down Jeremiah with cords. In the dungeon there was no water, but mire; and Jeremiah sank in the mire.\n'),
	(15099, 21, 38, 7, 'Now when Ebedmelech the Ethiopian, a eunuch, who was in the king’s house, heard that they had put Jeremiah in the dungeon (the king was then sitting in Benjamin’s gate),\n'),
	(15100, 21, 38, 8, 'Ebedmelech went out of the king’s house, and spoke to the king, saying,\n'),
	(15101, 21, 38, 9, '“My lord the king, these men have done evil in all that they have done to Jeremiah the prophet, whom they have cast into the dungeon. He is likely to die in the place where he is, because of the famine; for there is no more bread in the city.”\n'),
	(15102, 21, 38, 10, 'Then the king commanded Ebedmelech the Ethiopian, saying, “Take from here thirty men with you, and take up Jeremiah the prophet out of the dungeon, before he dies.”\n'),
	(15103, 21, 38, 11, 'So Ebedmelech took the men with him, and went into the house of the king under the treasury, and took from there rags and worn-out garments, and let them down by cords into the dungeon to Jeremiah.\n'),
	(15104, 21, 38, 12, 'Ebedmelech the Ethiopian said to Jeremiah, “Now put these rags and worn-out garments under your armpits under the cords.”\nJeremiah did so.\n'),
	(15105, 21, 38, 13, 'So they drew up Jeremiah with the cords, and took him up out of the dungeon; and Jeremiah remained in the court of the guard.\n'),
	(15106, 21, 38, 14, 'Then Zedekiah the king sent and took Jeremiah the prophet to himself into the third entry that is in Yahweh’s house. Then the king said to Jeremiah, “I will ask you something. Hide nothing from me.”\n'),
	(15107, 21, 38, 15, 'Then Jeremiah said to Zedekiah, “If I declare it to you, will you not surely put me to death? If I give you counsel, you will not listen to me.”\n'),
	(15108, 21, 38, 16, 'So Zedekiah the king swore secretly to Jeremiah, saying, “As Yahweh lives, who made us this soul, I will not put you to death, neither will I give you into the hand of these men who seek your life.”\n'),
	(15109, 21, 38, 17, 'Then Jeremiah said to Zedekiah, “Yahweh, the God of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘If you will go out to the king of Babylon’s princes, then your soul will live, and this city will not be burned with fire. You will live, along with your house.\n'),
	(15110, 21, 38, 18, 'But if you will not go out to the king of Babylon’s princes, then this city will be given into the hand of the Chaldeans, and they will burn it with fire, and you won’t escape out of their hand.’”\n'),
	(15111, 21, 38, 19, 'Zedekiah the king said to Jeremiah, “I am afraid of the Jews who have defected to the Chaldeans, lest they deliver me into their hand, and they mock me.”\n'),
	(15112, 21, 38, 20, 'But Jeremiah said, “They won’t deliver you. Obey, I beg you, Yahweh’s voice, in that which I speak to you; so it will be well with you, and your soul will live.\n'),
	(15113, 21, 38, 21, 'But if you refuse to go out, this is the word that Yahweh has shown me:\n'),
	(15114, 21, 38, 22, '‘Behold, all the women who are left in the king of Judah’s house will be brought out to the king of Babylon’s princes, and those women will say,\n“Your familiar friends have turned on you,\nand have prevailed over you.\nYour feet are sunk in the mire,\nthey have turned away from you.”\n'),
	(15115, 21, 38, 23, 'They will bring out all your wives and your children to the Chaldeans. You won’t escape out of their hand, but will be taken by the hand of the king of Babylon. You will cause this city to be burned with fire.’”\n'),
	(15116, 21, 38, 24, 'Then Zedekiah said to Jeremiah, “Let no man know of these words, and you won’t die.\n'),
	(15117, 21, 38, 25, 'But if the princes hear that I have talked with you, and they come to you, and tell you, ‘Declare to us now what you have said to the king; don’t hide it from us, and we will not put you to death; also tell us what the king said to you;’\n'),
	(15118, 21, 38, 26, 'then you shall tell them, ‘I presented my supplication before the king, that he would not cause me to return to Jonathan’s house, to die there.’”\n'),
	(15119, 21, 38, 27, 'Then all the princes came to Jeremiah, and asked him; and he told them according to all these words that the king had commanded. So they stopped speaking with him; for the matter was not perceived.\n'),
	(15120, 21, 38, 28, 'So Jeremiah stayed in the court of the guard until the day that Jerusalem was taken.\n'),
	(15121, 21, 39, 1, 'In the ninth year of Zedekiah king of Judah, in the tenth month, Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon and all his army came against Jerusalem, and besieged it.\n'),
	(15122, 21, 39, 2, 'In the eleventh year of Zedekiah, in the fourth month, the ninth day of the month, a breach was made in the city.\n'),
	(15123, 21, 39, 3, 'All the princes of the king of Babylon came in, and sat in the middle gate, Nergal Sharezer, Samgarnebo, Sarsechim, Rabsaris, Nergal Sharezer, Rabmag, with all the rest of the princes of the king of Babylon.\n'),
	(15124, 21, 39, 4, 'When Zedekiah the king of Judah and all the men of war saw them, then they fled, and went out of the city by night, by the way of the king’s garden, through the gate between the two walls; and he went out toward the Arabah.\n'),
	(15125, 21, 39, 5, 'But the army of the Chaldeans pursued them, and overtook Zedekiah in the plains of Jericho. When they had taken him, they brought him up to Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon to Riblah in the land of Hamath; and he pronounced judgment on him.\n'),
	(15126, 21, 39, 6, 'Then the king of Babylon killed Zedekiah’s sons in Riblah before his eyes. The king of Babylon also killed all the nobles of Judah.\n'),
	(15127, 21, 39, 7, 'Moreover he put out Zedekiah’s eyes and bound him in fetters, to carry him to Babylon.\n'),
	(15128, 21, 39, 8, 'The Chaldeans burned the king’s house, and the houses of the people, with fire, and broke down the walls of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(15129, 21, 39, 9, 'Then Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard carried away captive into Babylon the residue of the people who remained in the city, the deserters also who fell away to him, and the residue of the people who remained.\n'),
	(15130, 21, 39, 10, 'But Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard left of the poor of the people, who had nothing, in the land of Judah, and gave them vineyards and fields at the same time.\n'),
	(15131, 21, 39, 11, 'Now Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon commanded Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard concerning Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(15132, 21, 39, 12, '“Take him, and take care of him. Do him no harm; but do to him even as he tells you.”\n'),
	(15133, 21, 39, 13, 'So Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard sent, with Nebushazban, Rabsaris, and Nergal Sharezer, Rabmag, and all the chief officers of the king of Babylon;\n'),
	(15134, 21, 39, 14, 'they sent, and took Jeremiah out of the court of the guard, and committed him to Gedaliah the son of Ahikam, the son of Shaphan, that he should carry him home. So he lived among the people.\n'),
	(15135, 21, 39, 15, 'Now Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah, while he was shut up in the court of the guard, saying,\n'),
	(15136, 21, 39, 16, '“Go, and speak to Ebedmelech the Ethiopian, saying, ‘Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: “Behold, I will bring my words on this city for evil, and not for good; and they will be accomplished before you in that day.\n'),
	(15137, 21, 39, 17, 'But I will deliver you in that day,” says Yahweh; “and you will not be given into the hand of the men of whom you are afraid.\n'),
	(15138, 21, 39, 18, 'For I will surely save you, and you won’t fall by the sword, but you will escape with your life; because you have put your trust in me,” says Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(15139, 21, 40, 1, 'The word which came to Jeremiah from Yahweh, after Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard had let him go from Ramah, when he had taken him being bound in chains among all the captives of Jerusalem and Judah, who were carried away captive to Babylon.\n'),
	(15140, 21, 40, 2, 'The captain of the guard took Jeremiah, and said to him, “Yahweh your God pronounced this evil on this place;\n'),
	(15141, 21, 40, 3, 'and Yahweh has brought it, and done according as he spoke. Because you have sinned against Yahweh, and have not obeyed his voice, therefore this thing has come on you.\n'),
	(15142, 21, 40, 4, 'Now, behold, I release you today from the chains which are on your hand. If it seems good to you to come with me into Babylon, come, and I will take care of you; but if it seems bad to you to come with me into Babylon, don’t. Behold, all the land is before you. Where it seems good and right to you to go, there go.”\n'),
	(15143, 21, 40, 5, 'Now while he had not yet gone back, “Go back then,” he said, “to Gedaliah the son of Ahikam, the son of Shaphan, whom the king of Babylon has made governor over the cities of Judah, and dwell with him among the people; or go wherever it seems right to you to go.”\nSo the captain of the guard gave him food and a present, and let him go.\n'),
	(15144, 21, 40, 6, 'Then Jeremiah went to Gedaliah the son of Ahikam to Mizpah, and lived with him among the people who were left in the land.\n'),
	(15145, 21, 40, 7, 'Now when all the captains of the forces who were in the fields, even they and their men, heard that the king of Babylon had made Gedaliah the son of Ahikam governor in the land, and had committed to him men, women, children, and of the poorest of the land, of those who were not carried away captive to Babylon;\n'),
	(15146, 21, 40, 8, 'then Ishmael the son of Nethaniah, and Johanan and Jonathan the sons of Kareah, and Seraiah the son of Tanhumeth, and the sons of Ephai the Netophathite, and Jezaniah the son of the Maacathite, they and their men came to Gedaliah to Mizpah.\n'),
	(15147, 21, 40, 9, 'Gedaliah the son of Ahikam the son of Shaphan swore to them and to their men, saying, “Don’t be afraid to serve the Chaldeans. Dwell in the land, and serve the king of Babylon, and it will be well with you.\n'),
	(15148, 21, 40, 10, 'As for me, behold, I will dwell at Mizpah, to stand before the Chaldeans who will come to us; but you, gather wine and summer fruits and oil, and put them in your vessels, and dwell in your cities that you have taken.”\n'),
	(15149, 21, 40, 11, 'Likewise when all the Jews who were in Moab, and among the children of Ammon, and in Edom, and who were in all the countries, heard that the king of Babylon had left a remnant of Judah, and that he had set over them Gedaliah the son of Ahikam, the son of Shaphan;\n'),
	(15150, 21, 40, 12, 'then all the Jews returned out of all places where they were driven, and came to the land of Judah, to Gedaliah, to Mizpah, and gathered very much wine and summer fruits.\n'),
	(15151, 21, 40, 13, 'Moreover Johanan the son of Kareah, and all the captains of the forces who were in the fields, came to Gedaliah to Mizpah,\n'),
	(15152, 21, 40, 14, 'and said to him, “Do you know that Baalis the king of the children of Ammon has sent Ishmael the son of Nethaniah to take your life?”\nBut Gedaliah the son of Ahikam didn’t believe them.\n'),
	(15153, 21, 40, 15, 'Then Johanan the son of Kareah spoke to Gedaliah in Mizpah secretly, saying, “Please let me go, and I will kill Ishmael the son of Nethaniah, and no man will know it. Why should he take your life, that all the Jews who are gathered to you should be scattered, and the remnant of Judah perish?”\n'),
	(15154, 21, 40, 16, 'But Gedaliah the son of Ahikam said to Johanan the son of Kareah, “You shall not do this thing; for you speak falsely of Ishmael.”\n'),
	(15155, 21, 41, 1, 'Now in the seventh month, Ishmael the son of Nethaniah, the son of Elishama, of the royal offspring and one of the chief officers of the king, and ten men with him, came to Gedaliah the son of Ahikam to Mizpah; and there they ate bread together in Mizpah.\n'),
	(15156, 21, 41, 2, 'Then Ishmael the son of Nethaniah arose, and the ten men who were with him, and struck Gedaliah the son of Ahikam the son of Shaphan with the sword and killed him, whom the king of Babylon had made governor over the land.\n'),
	(15157, 21, 41, 3, 'Ishmael also killed all the Jews who were with him, with Gedaliah, at Mizpah, and the Chaldeans who were found there, the men of war.\n'),
	(15158, 21, 41, 4, 'The second day after he had killed Gedaliah, and no man knew it,\n'),
	(15159, 21, 41, 5, 'men came from Shechem, from Shiloh, and from Samaria, even eighty men, having their beards shaved and their clothes torn, and having cut themselves, with meal offerings and frankincense in their hand, to bring them to Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(15160, 21, 41, 6, 'Ishmael the son of Nethaniah went out from Mizpah to meet them, weeping all along as he went: and as he met them, he said to them, “Come to Gedaliah the son of Ahikam.”\n'),
	(15161, 21, 41, 7, 'It was so, when they came into the middle of the city, that Ishmael the son of Nethaniah killed them, and cast them into the middle of the pit, he, and the men who were with him.\n'),
	(15162, 21, 41, 8, 'But ten men were found among those who said to Ishmael, “Don’t kill us; for we have stores hidden in the field, of wheat, and of barley, and of oil, and of honey.”\nSo he stopped, and didn’t kill them among their brothers.\n'),
	(15163, 21, 41, 9, 'Now the pit in which Ishmael cast all the dead bodies of the men whom he had killed, by the side of Gedaliah (the same was that which Asa the king had made for fear of Baasha king of Israel), Ishmael the son of Nethaniah filled it with those who were killed.\n'),
	(15164, 21, 41, 10, 'Then Ishmael carried away captive all the of the people who were left in Mizpah, even the king’s daughters, and all the people who remained in Mizpah, whom Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard had committed to Gedaliah the son of Ahikam. Ishmael the son of Nethaniah carried them away captive, and departed to go over to the children of Ammon.\n'),
	(15165, 21, 41, 11, 'But when Johanan the son of Kareah, and all the captains of the forces who were with him, heard of all the evil that Ishmael the son of Nethaniah had done,\n'),
	(15166, 21, 41, 12, 'then they took all the men, and went to fight with Ishmael the son of Nethaniah, and found him by the great waters that are in Gibeon.\n'),
	(15167, 21, 41, 13, 'Now when all the people who were with Ishmael saw Johanan the son of Kareah, and all the captains of the forces who were with him, then they were glad.\n'),
	(15168, 21, 41, 14, 'So all the people who Ishmael had carried away captive from Mizpah turned about and came back, and went to Johanan the son of Kareah.\n'),
	(15169, 21, 41, 15, 'But Ishmael the son of Nethaniah escaped from Johanan with eight men, and went to the children of Ammon.\n'),
	(15170, 21, 41, 16, 'Then Johanan the son of Kareah and all the captains of the forces who were with him took all the remnant of the people whom he had recovered from Ishmael the son of Nethaniah, from Mizpah, after he had killed Gedaliah the son of Ahikam, the men of war, with the women, the children, and the eunuchs, whom he had brought back from Gibeon.\n'),
	(15171, 21, 41, 17, 'They departed and lived in Geruth Chimham, which is by Bethlehem, to go to enter into Egypt\n'),
	(15172, 21, 41, 18, 'because of the Chaldeans; for they were afraid of them, because Ishmael the son of Nethaniah had killed Gedaliah the son of Ahikam, whom the king of Babylon made governor over the land.\n'),
	(15173, 21, 42, 1, 'Then all the captains of the forces, and Johanan the son of Kareah, and Jezaniah the son of Hoshaiah, and all the people from the least even to the greatest, came near,\n'),
	(15174, 21, 42, 2, 'and said to Jeremiah the prophet, “Please let our supplication be presented before you, and pray for us to Yahweh your God, even for all this remnant; for we are left but a few of many, as your eyes see us;\n'),
	(15175, 21, 42, 3, 'that Yahweh your God may show us the way in which we should walk, and the things that we should do.”\n'),
	(15176, 21, 42, 4, 'Then Jeremiah the prophet said to them, “I have heard you. Behold, I will pray to Yahweh your God according to your words; and it will happen that whatever thing Yahweh answers you, I will declare it to you. I will keep nothing back from you.”\n'),
	(15177, 21, 42, 5, 'Then they said to Jeremiah, “May Yahweh be a true and faithful witness among us, if we don’t do according to all the word with which Yahweh your God sends you to tell us.\n'),
	(15178, 21, 42, 6, 'Whether it is good, or whether it is bad, we will obey the voice of Yahweh our God, to whom we send you; that it may be well with us, when we obey the voice of Yahweh our God.”\n'),
	(15179, 21, 42, 7, 'After ten days, Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah.\n'),
	(15180, 21, 42, 8, 'Then he called Johanan the son of Kareah, and all the captains of the forces who were with him, and all the people from the least even to the greatest,\n'),
	(15181, 21, 42, 9, 'and said to them, “Yahweh, the God of Israel, to whom you sent me to present your supplication before him, says:\n'),
	(15182, 21, 42, 10, '‘If you will still live in this land, then I will build you, and not pull you down, and I will plant you, and not pluck you up; for I grieve over the distress that I have brought on you.\n'),
	(15183, 21, 42, 11, 'Don’t be afraid of the king of Babylon, of whom you are afraid. Don’t be afraid of him,’ says Yahweh: ‘for I am with you to save you, and to deliver you from his hand.\n'),
	(15184, 21, 42, 12, 'I will grant you mercy, that he may have mercy on you, and cause you to return to your own land.\n'),
	(15185, 21, 42, 13, '“‘But if you say, “We will not dwell in this land;” so that you don’t obey Yahweh your God’s voice,\n'),
	(15186, 21, 42, 14, 'saying, “No; but we will go into the land of Egypt, where we will see no war, nor hear the sound of the trumpet, nor have hunger of bread; and there will we dwell:”’\n'),
	(15187, 21, 42, 15, 'now therefore hear Yahweh’s word, O remnant of Judah: Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says, ‘If you indeed set your faces to enter into Egypt, and go to live there;\n'),
	(15188, 21, 42, 16, 'then it will happen that the sword, which you fear, will overtake you there in the land of Egypt; and the famine, about which you are afraid, will follow close behind you there in Egypt; and you will die there.\n'),
	(15189, 21, 42, 17, 'So will it be with all the men who set their faces to go into Egypt to live there. They will die by the sword, by the famine, and by the pestilence. None of them will remain or escape from the evil that I will bring on them.’\n'),
	(15190, 21, 42, 18, 'For Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘As my anger and my wrath has been poured out on the inhabitants of Jerusalem, so my wrath will be poured out on you, when you enter into Egypt; and you will be an object of horror, an astonishment, a curse, and a reproach; and you will see this place no more.’\n'),
	(15191, 21, 42, 19, '“Yahweh has spoken concerning you, remnant of Judah, ‘Don’t go into Egypt!’ Know certainly that I have testified to you today.\n'),
	(15192, 21, 42, 20, 'For you have dealt deceitfully against your own souls; for you sent me to Yahweh your God, saying, ‘Pray for us to Yahweh our God; and according to all that Yahweh our God says, so declare to us, and we will do it.’\n'),
	(15193, 21, 42, 21, 'I have declared it to you today; but you have not obeyed Yahweh your God’s voice in anything for which he has sent me to you.\n'),
	(15194, 21, 42, 22, 'Now therefore know certainly that you will die by the sword, by the famine, and by the pestilence in the place where you desire to go to live there.”\n'),
	(15195, 21, 43, 1, 'When Jeremiah had finished speaking to all the people all the words of Yahweh their God, with which Yahweh their God had sent him to them, even all these words,\n'),
	(15196, 21, 43, 2, 'then Azariah the son of Hoshaiah, Johanan the son of Kareah, and all the proud men spoke, saying to Jeremiah, “You speak falsely. Yahweh our God has not sent you to say, ‘You shall not go into Egypt to live there;’\n'),
	(15197, 21, 43, 3, 'but Baruch the son of Neriah has turned you against us, to deliver us into the hand of the Chaldeans, that they may put us to death, and carry us away captive to Babylon.”\n'),
	(15198, 21, 43, 4, 'So Johanan the son of Kareah, and all the captains of the forces, and all the people, didn’t obey Yahweh’s voice, to dwell in the land of Judah.\n'),
	(15199, 21, 43, 5, 'But Johanan the son of Kareah, and all the captains of the forces, took all the remnant of Judah, who had returned from all the nations where they had been driven, to live in the land of Judah;\n'),
	(15200, 21, 43, 6, 'the men, and the women, and the children, and the king’s daughters, and every person who Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard had left with Gedaliah the son of Ahikam, the son of Shaphan; and Jeremiah the prophet, and Baruch the son of Neriah;\n'),
	(15201, 21, 43, 7, 'and they came into the land of Egypt; for they didn’t obey Yahweh’s voice: and they came to Tahpanhes.\n'),
	(15202, 21, 43, 8, 'Then Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah in Tahpanhes, saying,\n'),
	(15203, 21, 43, 9, '“Take great stones in your hand, and hide them in mortar in the brick work, which is at the entry of Pharaoh’s house in Tahpanhes, in the sight of the men of Judah;\n'),
	(15204, 21, 43, 10, 'and tell them, Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘Behold, I will send and take Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon, my servant, and will set his throne on these stones that I have hidden; and he will spread his royal pavilion over them.\n'),
	(15205, 21, 43, 11, 'He will come, and will strike the land of Egypt; such as are for death will be put to death, and such as are for captivity to captivity, and such as are for the sword to the sword.\n'),
	(15206, 21, 43, 12, 'I will kindle a fire in the houses of the gods of Egypt. He will burn them, and carry them away captive. He will array himself with the land of Egypt, as a shepherd puts on his garment; and he will go out from there in peace.\n'),
	(15207, 21, 43, 13, 'He will also break the pillars of Beth Shemesh, that is in the land of Egypt; and he will burn the houses of the gods of Egypt with fire.’”\n'),
	(15208, 21, 44, 1, 'The word that came to Jeremiah concerning all the Jews who lived in the land of Egypt, who lived at Migdol, and at Tahpanhes, and at Memphis, and in the country of Pathros, saying,\n'),
	(15209, 21, 44, 2, '“Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘You have seen all the evil that I have brought on Jerusalem, and on all the cities of Judah. Behold, today they are a desolation, and no man dwells in them,\n'),
	(15210, 21, 44, 3, 'because of their wickedness which they have committed to provoke me to anger, in that they went to burn incense, to serve other gods that they didn’t know, neither they, nor you, nor your fathers.\n'),
	(15211, 21, 44, 4, 'However I sent to you all my servants the prophets, rising up early and sending them, saying, “Oh, don’t do this abominable thing that I hate.”\n'),
	(15212, 21, 44, 5, 'But they didn’t listen and didn’t incline their ear. They didn’t turn from their wickedness, to stop burning incense to other gods.\n'),
	(15213, 21, 44, 6, 'Therefore my wrath and my anger was poured out, and was kindled in the cities of Judah and in the streets of Jerusalem; and they are wasted and desolate, as it is today.’\n'),
	(15214, 21, 44, 7, '“Therefore now Yahweh, the God of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘Why do you commit great evil against your own souls, to cut off from yourselves man and woman, infant and nursing child out of the middle of Judah, to leave yourselves no one remaining;\n'),
	(15215, 21, 44, 8, 'in that you provoke me to anger with the works of your hands, burning incense to other gods in the land of Egypt, where you have gone to live; that you may be cut off, and that you may be a curse and a reproach among all the nations of the earth?\n'),
	(15216, 21, 44, 9, 'Have you forgotten the wickedness of your fathers, and the wickedness of the kings of Judah, and the wickedness of their wives, and your own wickedness, and the wickedness of your wives, which they committed in the land of Judah and in the streets of Jerusalem?\n'),
	(15217, 21, 44, 10, 'They are not humbled even to this day, neither have they feared, nor walked in my law, nor in my statutes, that I set before you and before your fathers.’\n'),
	(15218, 21, 44, 11, '“Therefore Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: ‘Behold, I will set my face against you for evil, even to cut off all Judah.\n'),
	(15219, 21, 44, 12, 'I will take the remnant of Judah, that have set their faces to go into the land of Egypt to live there, and they will all be consumed. They will fall in the land of Egypt. They will be consumed by the sword and by the famine. They will die, from the least even to the greatest, by the sword and by the famine. They will be an object of horror, an astonishment, and a curse, and a reproach.\n'),
	(15220, 21, 44, 13, 'For I will punish those who dwell in the land of Egypt, as I have punished Jerusalem, by the sword, by the famine, and by the pestilence;\n'),
	(15221, 21, 44, 14, 'so that none of the remnant of Judah, who have gone into the land of Egypt to live there, will escape or be left to return into the land of Judah, to which they have a desire to return to dwell there; for no one will return except those who will escape.’”\n'),
	(15222, 21, 44, 15, 'Then all the men who knew that their wives burned incense to other gods, and all the women who stood by, a great assembly, even all the people who lived in the land of Egypt, in Pathros, answered Jeremiah, saying,\n'),
	(15223, 21, 44, 16, '“As for the word that you have spoken to us in Yahweh’s name, we will not listen to you.\n'),
	(15224, 21, 44, 17, 'But we will certainly perform every word that has gone out of our mouth, to burn incense to the queen of the sky, and to pour out drink offerings to her, as we have done, we and our fathers, our kings and our princes, in the cities of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem; for then had we plenty of food, and were well, and saw no evil.\n'),
	(15225, 21, 44, 18, 'But since we stopped burning incense to the queen of the sky, and pouring out drink offerings to her, we have lacked all things, and have been consumed by the sword and by the famine.\n'),
	(15226, 21, 44, 19, '“When we burned incense to the queen of the sky, and poured out drink offerings to her, did we make her cakes to worship her, and pour out drink offerings to her, without our husbands?”\n'),
	(15227, 21, 44, 20, 'Then Jeremiah said to all the people, to the men, and to the women, even to all the people who had given him an answer, saying,\n'),
	(15228, 21, 44, 21, '“The incense that you burned in the cities of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem, you and your fathers, your kings and your princes, and the people of the land, didn’t Yahweh remember them, and didn’t it come into his mind?\n'),
	(15229, 21, 44, 22, 'Thus Yahweh could no longer bear it, because of the evil of your doings, and because of the abominations which you have committed. Therefore your land has become a desolation, and an astonishment, and a curse, without inhabitant, as it is today.\n'),
	(15230, 21, 44, 23, 'Because you have burned incense, and because you have sinned against Yahweh, and have not obeyed Yahweh’s voice, nor walked in his law, nor in his statutes, nor in his testimonies; therefore this evil has happened to you, as it is today.”\n'),
	(15231, 21, 44, 24, 'Moreover Jeremiah said to all the people, including all the women, “Hear Yahweh’s word, all Judah who are in the land of Egypt!\n'),
	(15232, 21, 44, 25, 'Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says, ‘You and your wives have both spoken with your mouths, and with your hands have fulfilled it, saying, “We will surely perform our vows that we have vowed, to burn incense to the queen of the sky, and to pour out drink offerings to her.”\n“‘Establish then your vows, and perform your vows.’\n'),
	(15233, 21, 44, 26, '“Therefore hear Yahweh’s word, all Judah who dwell in the land of Egypt: ‘Behold, I have sworn by my great name,’ says Yahweh, ‘that my name will no more be named in the mouth of any man of Judah in all the land of Egypt, saying, “As the Lord Yahweh lives.”\n'),
	(15234, 21, 44, 27, 'Behold, I watch over them for evil, and not for good; and all the men of Judah who are in the land of Egypt will be consumed by the sword and by the famine, until they are all gone.\n'),
	(15235, 21, 44, 28, 'Those who escape the sword will return out of the land of Egypt into the land of Judah few in number. All the remnant of Judah, who have gone into the land of Egypt to live there, will know whose word will stand, mine or theirs.\n'),
	(15236, 21, 44, 29, '“‘This will be the sign to you,’ says Yahweh, ‘that I will punish you in this place, that you may know that my words will surely stand against you for evil.’\n'),
	(15237, 21, 44, 30, 'Yahweh says, ‘Behold, I will give Pharaoh Hophra king of Egypt into the hand of his enemies, and into the hand of those who seek his life; as I gave Zedekiah king of Judah into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, who was his enemy, and sought his life.’”\n'),
	(15238, 21, 45, 1, 'The message that Jeremiah the prophet spoke to Baruch the son of Neriah, when he wrote these words in a book at the mouth of Jeremiah, in the fourth year of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah, saying,\n'),
	(15239, 21, 45, 2, '“Yahweh, the God of Israel, says to you, Baruch:\n'),
	(15240, 21, 45, 3, '‘You said, “Woe is me now! For Yahweh has added sorrow to my pain! I am weary with my groaning, and I find no rest.”’\n'),
	(15241, 21, 45, 4, '“You shall tell him, Yahweh says: ‘Behold, that which I have built, I will break down, and that which I have planted I will pluck up; and this in the whole land.\n'),
	(15242, 21, 45, 5, 'Do you seek great things for yourself? Don’t seek them; for, behold, I will bring evil on all flesh,’ says Yahweh; ‘but I will let you escape with your life wherever you go.’”\n'),
	(15243, 21, 46, 1, 'Yahweh’s word which came to Jeremiah the prophet concerning the nations.\n'),
	(15244, 21, 46, 2, 'Of Egypt: concerning the army of Pharaoh Necoh king of Egypt, which was by the river Euphrates in Carchemish, which Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon struck in the fourth year of Jehoiakim the son of Josiah, king of Judah.\n'),
	(15245, 21, 46, 3, '“Prepare the buckler and shield,\nand draw near to battle!\n'),
	(15246, 21, 46, 4, 'Harness the horses, and get up, you horsemen,\nand stand up with your helmets.\nPolish the spears,\nput on the coats of mail.\n'),
	(15247, 21, 46, 5, 'Why have I seen it?\nThey are dismayed and are turned backward.\nTheir mighty ones are beaten down,\nhave fled in haste,\nand don’t look back.\nTerror is on every side,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(15248, 21, 46, 6, '“Don’t let the swift flee away,\nnor the mighty man escape.\nIn the north by the river Euphrates\nthey have stumbled and fallen.\n'),
	(15249, 21, 46, 7, '“Who is this who rises up like the Nile,\nwhose waters toss themselves like the rivers?\n'),
	(15250, 21, 46, 8, 'Egypt rises up like the Nile,\nand his waters toss themselves like the rivers.\nHe says, ‘I will rise up. I will cover the earth.\nI will destroy cities and its inhabitants.’\n'),
	(15251, 21, 46, 9, 'Go up, you horses!\nRage, you chariots!\nLet the mighty men go out:\nCush and Put, who handle the shield;\nand the Ludim, who handle and bend the bow.\n'),
	(15252, 21, 46, 10, 'For that day is of the Lord, Yahweh of Armies,\na day of vengeance,\nthat he may avenge himself of his adversaries.\nThe sword will devour and be satiated,\nand will drink its fill of their blood;\nfor the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, has a sacrifice in the north country by the river Euphrates.\n'),
	(15253, 21, 46, 11, 'Go up into Gilead, and take balm, virgin daughter of Egypt.\nYou use many medicines in vain.\nThere is no healing for you.\n'),
	(15254, 21, 46, 12, 'The nations have heard of your shame,\nand the earth is full of your cry;\nfor the mighty man has stumbled against the mighty,\nthey both fall together.”\n'),
	(15255, 21, 46, 13, 'The word that Yahweh spoke to Jeremiah the prophet, how that Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon should come and strike the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(15256, 21, 46, 14, '“Declare in Egypt,\npublish in Migdol,\nand publish in Memphis and in Tahpanhes:\nsay, ‘Stand up, and prepare;\nfor the sword has devoured around you.’\n'),
	(15257, 21, 46, 15, 'Why are your strong ones swept away?\nThey didn’t stand, because Yahweh pushed them.\n'),
	(15258, 21, 46, 16, 'He made many to stumble.\nYes, they fell on one another.\nThey said, ‘Arise, and let us go again to our own people,\nand to the land of our birth,\nfrom the oppressing sword.’\n'),
	(15259, 21, 46, 17, 'They cried there, ‘Pharaoh king of Egypt is but a noise;\nhe has let the appointed time pass by.’\n'),
	(15260, 21, 46, 18, '“As I live,” says the King,\nwhose name is Yahweh of Armies,\n“surely like Tabor among the mountains,\nand like Carmel by the sea,\nso he will come.\n'),
	(15261, 21, 46, 19, 'You daughter who dwells in Egypt,\nfurnish yourself to go into captivity;\nfor Memphis will become a desolation,\nand will be burned up,\nwithout inhabitant.\n'),
	(15262, 21, 46, 20, '“Egypt is a very beautiful heifer;\nbut destruction out of the north has come.\nIt has come.\n'),
	(15263, 21, 46, 21, 'Also her hired men in the middle of her are like calves of the stall;\nfor they also are turned back.\nThey have fled away together.\nThey didn’t stand,\nfor the day of their calamity has come on them,\nthe time of their visitation.\n'),
	(15264, 21, 46, 22, 'It’s sound will go like the serpent;\nfor they will march with an army,\nand come against her with axes, as wood cutters.\n'),
	(15265, 21, 46, 23, 'They will cut down her forest,” says Yahweh,\n“though it can’t be searched;\nbecause they are more than the locusts,\nand are innumerable.\n'),
	(15266, 21, 46, 24, 'The daughter of Egypt will be disappointed;\nshe will be delivered into the hand of the people of the north.”\n'),
	(15267, 21, 46, 25, 'Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says: “Behold, I will punish Amon of No, and Pharaoh, and Egypt, with her gods, and her kings; even Pharaoh, and those who trust in him.\n'),
	(15268, 21, 46, 26, 'I will deliver them into the hand of those who seek their lives, and into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, and into the hand of his servants. Afterwards it will be inhabited, as in the days of old,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15269, 21, 46, 27, '“But don’t you be afraid, Jacob my servant.\nDon’t be dismayed, Israel;\nfor, behold, I will save you from afar,\nand your offspring from the land of their captivity.\nJacob will return,\nand will be quiet and at ease.\nNo one will make him afraid.\n'),
	(15270, 21, 46, 28, 'Don’t be afraid, O Jacob my servant,” says Yahweh;\n“for I am with you;\nfor I will make a full end of all the nations where I have driven you;\nbut I will not make a full end of you,\nbut I will correct you in measure,\nand will in no way leave you unpunished.”\n'),
	(15271, 21, 47, 1, 'Yahweh’s word that came to Jeremiah the prophet concerning the Philistines, before Pharaoh struck Gaza.\n'),
	(15272, 21, 47, 2, 'Yahweh says:\n“Behold, waters rise up out of the north,\nand will become an overflowing stream,\nand will overflow the land and all that is therein,\nthe city and those who dwell therein.\nThe men will cry,\nand all the inhabitants of the land will wail.\n'),
	(15273, 21, 47, 3, 'At the noise of the stamping of the hoofs of his strong ones,\nat the rushing of his chariots,\nat the rumbling of his wheels,\nthe fathers don’t look back to their children\nfor feebleness of hands;\n'),
	(15274, 21, 47, 4, 'because of the day that comes to destroy all the Philistines,\nto cut off from Tyre and Sidon every helper who remains;\nfor Yahweh will destroy the Philistines,\nthe remnant of the isle of Caphtor.\n'),
	(15275, 21, 47, 5, 'Baldness has come on Gaza;\nAshkelon is brought to nothing,\nthe remnant of their valley:\nhow long will you cut yourself?\n'),
	(15276, 21, 47, 6, '“‘You sword of Yahweh, how long will it be before you are quiet?\nPut yourself back into your scabbard;\nrest, and be still.’\n'),
	(15277, 21, 47, 7, '“How can you be quiet,\nsince Yahweh has given you a command?\nAgainst Ashkelon, and against the seashore,\nthere has he appointed it.”\n'),
	(15278, 21, 48, 1, 'Of Moab. Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says:\n“Woe to Nebo!\nFor it is laid waste.\nKiriathaim is disappointed.\nIt is taken.\nMisgab is put to shame\nand broken down.\n'),
	(15279, 21, 48, 2, 'The praise of Moab is no more.\nIn Heshbon they have devised evil against her:\n‘Come, and let us cut her off from being a nation.’\nYou also, Madmen, will be brought to silence.\nThe sword will pursue you.\n'),
	(15280, 21, 48, 3, 'The sound of a cry from Horonaim,\ndesolation and great destruction!\n'),
	(15281, 21, 48, 4, 'Moab is destroyed.\nHer little ones have caused a cry to be heard.\n'),
	(15282, 21, 48, 5, 'For they will go up by the ascent of Luhith with continual weeping.\nFor at the descent of Horonaim they have heard the distress of the cry of destruction.\n'),
	(15283, 21, 48, 6, 'Flee! Save your lives!\nBe like the juniper bush in the wilderness.\n'),
	(15284, 21, 48, 7, 'For, because you have trusted in your works and in your treasures,\nyou also will be taken.\nChemosh will go out into captivity,\nhis priests and his princes together.\n'),
	(15285, 21, 48, 8, 'The destroyer will come on every city,\nand no city will escape;\nthe valley also will perish,\nand the plain will be destroyed; as Yahweh has spoken.\n'),
	(15286, 21, 48, 9, 'Give wings to Moab,\nthat she may fly and get herself away:\nand her cities will become a desolation,\nwithout anyone to dwell in them.\n'),
	(15287, 21, 48, 10, '“Cursed is he who does the work of Yahweh negligently;\nand cursed is he who keeps back his sword from blood.\n'),
	(15288, 21, 48, 11, '“Moab has been at ease from his youth,\nand he has settled on his lees,\nand has not been emptied from vessel to vessel,\nneither has he gone into captivity:\ntherefore his taste remains in him,\nand his scent is not changed.\n'),
	(15289, 21, 48, 12, 'Therefore behold, the days come,” says Yahweh,\n“that I will send to him those who pour off,\nand they will pour him off;\nand they will empty his vessels,\nand break their bottles in pieces.\n'),
	(15290, 21, 48, 13, 'Moab will be ashamed of Chemosh,\nas the house of Israel was ashamed of Bethel, their confidence.\n'),
	(15291, 21, 48, 14, '“How do you say, ‘We are mighty men,\nand valiant men for the war?’\n'),
	(15292, 21, 48, 15, 'Moab is laid waste,\nand they have gone up into his cities,\nand his chosen young men have gone down to the slaughter,”\nsays the King, whose name is Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(15293, 21, 48, 16, '“The calamity of Moab is near to come,\nand his affliction hurries fast.\n'),
	(15294, 21, 48, 17, 'All you who are around him, bemoan him,\nand all you who know his name; say,\n‘How the strong staff is broken,\nthe beautiful rod!’\n'),
	(15295, 21, 48, 18, '“You daughter who dwells in Dibon,\ncome down from your glory,\nand sit in thirst;\nfor the destroyer of Moab has come up against you.\nHe has destroyed your strongholds.\n'),
	(15296, 21, 48, 19, 'Inhabitant of Aroer, stand by the way and watch.\nAsk him who flees, and her who escapes;\nsay, ‘What has been done?’\n'),
	(15297, 21, 48, 20, 'Moab is disappointed;\nfor it is broken down.\nWail and cry!\nTell it by the Arnon, that Moab is laid waste.\n'),
	(15298, 21, 48, 21, 'Judgment has come on the plain country,\non Holon, on Jahzah, on Mephaath,\n'),
	(15299, 21, 48, 22, 'on Dibon, on Nebo, on Beth Diblathaim,\n'),
	(15300, 21, 48, 23, 'on Kiriathaim, on Beth Gamul, on Beth Meon,\n'),
	(15301, 21, 48, 24, 'on Kerioth, on Bozrah,\nand on all the cities of the land of Moab, far or near.\n'),
	(15302, 21, 48, 25, 'The horn of Moab is cut off,\nand his arm is broken,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15303, 21, 48, 26, '“Make him drunken;\nfor he magnified himself against Yahweh.\nMoab will wallow in his vomit,\nand he also will be in derision.\n'),
	(15304, 21, 48, 27, 'For wasn’t Israel a derision to you?\nWas he found among thieves?\nFor as often as you speak of him,\nyou shake your head.\n'),
	(15305, 21, 48, 28, 'You inhabitants of Moab, leave the cities, and dwell in the rock.\nBe like the dove that makes her nest over the mouth of the abyss.\n'),
	(15306, 21, 48, 29, '“We have heard of the pride of Moab.\nHe is very proud in his loftiness, his pride,\nhis arrogance, and the haughtiness of his heart.\n'),
	(15307, 21, 48, 30, 'I know his wrath,” says Yahweh, “that it is nothing;\nhis boastings have done nothing.\n'),
	(15308, 21, 48, 31, 'Therefore I will wail for Moab.\nYes, I will cry out for all Moab.\nThey will mourn for the men of Kir Heres.\n'),
	(15309, 21, 48, 32, 'With more than the weeping of Jazer\nwill I weep for you, vine of Sibmah.\nYour branches passed over the sea.\nThey reached even to the sea of Jazer.\nThe destroyer has fallen on your summer fruits\nand on your vintage.\n'),
	(15310, 21, 48, 33, 'Gladness and joy is taken away from the fruitful field\nand from the land of Moab.\nI have caused wine to cease from the wine presses.\nNo one will tread with shouting.\nThe shouting will be no shouting.\n'),
	(15311, 21, 48, 34, 'From the cry of Heshbon even to Elealeh,\neven to Jahaz have they uttered their voice,\nfrom Zoar even to Horonaim, to Eglath Shelishiyah;\nfor the waters of Nimrim will also become desolate.\n'),
	(15312, 21, 48, 35, 'Moreover I will cause to cease in Moab,” says Yahweh,\n“him who offers in the high place,\nand him who burns incense to his gods.\n'),
	(15313, 21, 48, 36, 'Therefore my heart sounds for Moab like pipes,\nand my heart sounds like pipes for the men of Kir Heres.\nTherefore the abundance that he has gotten has perished.\n'),
	(15314, 21, 48, 37, 'For every head is bald,\nand every beard clipped.\nThere are cuttings on all the hands,\nand sackcloth on the waist.\n'),
	(15315, 21, 48, 38, 'On all the housetops of Moab,\nand in its streets, there is lamentation everywhere;\nfor I have broken Moab like a vessel in which no one delights,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15316, 21, 48, 39, '“How it is broken down!\nHow they wail!\nHow Moab has turned the back with shame!\nSo will Moab become a derision\nand a terror to all who are around him.”\n'),
	(15317, 21, 48, 40, 'For Yahweh says: “Behold, he will fly as an eagle,\nand will spread out his wings against Moab.\n'),
	(15318, 21, 48, 41, 'Kerioth is taken,\nand the strongholds are seized.\nThe heart of the mighty men of Moab at that day\nwill be as the heart of a woman in her pangs.\n'),
	(15319, 21, 48, 42, 'Moab will be destroyed from being a people,\nbecause he has magnified himself against Yahweh.\n'),
	(15320, 21, 48, 43, 'Terror, the pit, and the snare are on you,\ninhabitant of Moab,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15321, 21, 48, 44, '“He who flees from the terror will fall into the pit;\nand he who gets up out of the pit will be taken in the snare:\nfor I will bring on him, even on Moab,\nthe year of their visitation,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15322, 21, 48, 45, '“Those who fled stand without strength under the shadow of Heshbon;\nfor a fire has gone out of Heshbon,\nand a flame from the middle of Sihon,\nand has devoured the corner of Moab,\nand the crown of the head of the tumultuous ones.\n'),
	(15323, 21, 48, 46, 'Woe to you, O Moab!\nThe people of Chemosh are undone;\nfor your sons are taken away captive,\nand your daughters into captivity.\n'),
	(15324, 21, 48, 47, '“Yet I will reverse the captivity of Moab in the latter days,”\nsays Yahweh.\nThus far is the judgment of Moab.\n'),
	(15325, 21, 49, 1, 'Of the children of Ammon. Yahweh says:\n“Has Israel no sons?\nHas he no heir?\nWhy then does Malcam possess Gad,\nand his people dwell in its cities?\n'),
	(15326, 21, 49, 2, 'Therefore behold, the days come,”\nsays Yahweh,\n“that I will cause an alarm of war to be heard against Rabbah of the children of Ammon;\nand it will become a desolate heap,\nand her daughters will be burned with fire:\nthen Israel will possess those who possessed him,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(15327, 21, 49, 3, '“Wail, Heshbon, for Ai is laid waste!\nCry, you daughters of Rabbah!\nClothe yourself in sackcloth.\nLament, and run back and forth among the fences;\nfor Malcam will go into captivity,\nhis priests and his princes together.\n'),
	(15328, 21, 49, 4, 'Why do you boast in the valleys,\nyour flowing valley, backsliding daughter?\nYou trusted in her treasures,\nsaying, ‘Who will come to me?’\n'),
	(15329, 21, 49, 5, 'Behold, I will bring a terror on you,”\nsays the Lord, Yahweh of Armies,\n“from all who are around you.\nAll of you will be driven completely out,\nand there will be no one to gather together the fugitives.\n'),
	(15330, 21, 49, 6, '“But afterward I will reverse the captivity of the children of Ammon,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(15331, 21, 49, 7, 'Of Edom, Yahweh of Armies says:\n“Is wisdom no more in Teman?\nHas counsel perished from the prudent?\nHas their wisdom vanished?\n'),
	(15332, 21, 49, 8, 'Flee! Turn back!\nDwell in the depths, inhabitants of Dedan;\nfor I will bring the calamity of Esau on him when I visit him.\n'),
	(15333, 21, 49, 9, 'If grape gatherers came to you,\nwould they not leave some gleaning grapes?\nIf thieves came by night,\nwouldn’t they steal until they had enough?\n'),
	(15334, 21, 49, 10, 'But I have made Esau bare,\nI have uncovered his secret places,\nand he will not be able to hide himself.\nHis offspring is destroyed,\nwith his brothers and his neighbors;\nand he is no more.\n'),
	(15335, 21, 49, 11, 'Leave your fatherless children.\nI will preserve them alive.\nLet your widows trust in me.”\n'),
	(15336, 21, 49, 12, 'For Yahweh says: “Behold, they to whom it didn’t pertain to drink of the cup will certainly drink; and are you he who will altogether go unpunished? You won’t go unpunished, but you will surely drink.\n'),
	(15337, 21, 49, 13, 'For I have sworn by myself,” says Yahweh, “that Bozrah will become an astonishment, a reproach, a waste, and a curse. All its cities will be perpetual wastes.”\n'),
	(15338, 21, 49, 14, 'I have heard news from Yahweh,\nand an ambassador is sent among the nations,\nsaying, “Gather yourselves together!\nCome against her!\nRise up to the battle!”\n'),
	(15339, 21, 49, 15, '“For, behold, I have made you small among the nations,\nand despised among men.\n'),
	(15340, 21, 49, 16, 'As for your terror,\nthe pride of your heart has deceived you,\nO you who dwell in the clefts of the rock,\nwho hold the height of the hill,\nthough you should make your nest as high as the eagle,\nI will bring you down from there,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15341, 21, 49, 17, '“Edom will become an astonishment.\nEveryone who passes by it will be astonished,\nand will hiss at all its plagues.\n'),
	(15342, 21, 49, 18, 'As in the overthrow of Sodom and Gomorrah and its neighbor cities,” says Yahweh,\n“no man will dwell there,\nneither will any son of man live therein.\n'),
	(15343, 21, 49, 19, '“Behold, he will come up like a lion from the pride of the Jordan against the strong habitation:\nfor I will suddenly make them run away from it;\nand whoever is chosen,\nI will appoint him over it.\nFor who is like me?\nWho will appoint me a time?\nWho is the shepherd who will stand before me?”\n'),
	(15344, 21, 49, 20, 'Therefore hear the counsel of Yahweh, that he has taken against Edom;\nand his purposes, that he has purposed against the inhabitants of Teman:\nSurely they will drag them away,\nthe little ones of the flock.\nSurely he will make their habitation desolate over them.\n'),
	(15345, 21, 49, 21, 'The earth trembles at the noise of their fall;\nthere is a cry, the noise which is heard in the Red Sea.\n'),
	(15346, 21, 49, 22, 'Behold, he will come up and fly as the eagle,\nand spread out his wings against Bozrah.\nThe heart of the mighty men of Edom at that day will be as the heart of a woman in her pangs.\n'),
	(15347, 21, 49, 23, 'Of Damascus:\n“Hamath is confounded, and Arpad;\nfor they have heard evil news.\nThey have melted away.\nThere is sorrow on the sea.\nIt can’t be quiet.\n'),
	(15348, 21, 49, 24, 'Damascus has grown feeble,\nshe turns herself to flee,\nand trembling has seized her.\nAnguish and sorrows have taken hold of her,\nas of a woman in travail.\n'),
	(15349, 21, 49, 25, 'How is the city of praise not forsaken,\nthe city of my joy?\n'),
	(15350, 21, 49, 26, 'Therefore her young men will fall in her streets,\nand all the men of war will be brought to silence in that day,”\nsays Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(15351, 21, 49, 27, '“I will kindle a fire in the wall of Damascus,\nand it will devour the palaces of Ben Hadad.”\n'),
	(15352, 21, 49, 28, 'Of Kedar, and of the kingdoms of Hazor, which Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon struck. Yahweh says:\n“Arise, go up to Kedar,\nand destroy the children of the east.\n'),
	(15353, 21, 49, 29, 'They will take their tents and their flocks.\nthey will carry away for themselves their curtains,\nall their vessels, and their camels;\nand they will cry to them, ‘Terror on every side!’\n'),
	(15354, 21, 49, 30, 'Flee!\nWander far off!\nDwell in the depths, you inhabitants of Hazor,” says Yahweh;\n“for Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon has taken counsel against you,\nand has conceived a purpose against you.\n'),
	(15355, 21, 49, 31, 'Arise! Go up to a nation that is at ease,\nthat dwells without care,” says Yahweh;\n“that has neither gates nor bars,\nthat dwells alone.\n'),
	(15356, 21, 49, 32, 'Their camels will be a booty,\nand the multitude of their livestock a plunder.\nI will scatter to all winds those who have the corners of their beards cut off;\nand I will bring their calamity from every side of them,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(15357, 21, 49, 33, 'Hazor will be a dwelling place of jackals,\na desolation forever.\nNo man will dwell there,\nneither will any son of man live therein.”\n'),
	(15358, 21, 49, 34, 'Yahweh’s word that came to Jeremiah the prophet concerning Elam, in the beginning of the reign of Zedekiah king of Judah, saying,\n'),
	(15359, 21, 49, 35, '“Yahweh of Armies says:\n‘Behold, I will break the bow of Elam,\nthe chief of their might.\n'),
	(15360, 21, 49, 36, 'I will bring on Elam the four winds from the four quarters of the sky,\nand will scatter them toward all those winds.\nThere will be no nation where the outcasts of Elam will not come.\n'),
	(15361, 21, 49, 37, 'I will cause Elam to be dismayed before their enemies,\nand before those who seek their life.\nI will bring evil on them, even my fierce anger,’ says Yahweh;\n‘and I will send the sword after them,\nuntil I have consumed them.\n'),
	(15362, 21, 49, 38, 'I will set my throne in Elam,\nand will destroy from there king and princes,’ says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15363, 21, 49, 39, '‘But it will happen in the latter days\nthat I will reverse the captivity of Elam,’ says Yahweh.”\n'),
	(15364, 21, 50, 1, 'The word that Yahweh spoke concerning Babylon, concerning the land of the Chaldeans, by Jeremiah the prophet.\n'),
	(15365, 21, 50, 2, '“Declare among the nations and publish,\nand set up a standard;\npublish, and don’t conceal:\nsay, ‘Babylon has been taken,\nBel is disappointed,\nMerodach is dismayed!\nHer images are disappointed.\nHer idols are dismayed.’\n'),
	(15366, 21, 50, 3, 'For a nation comes up out of the north against her,\nwhich will make her land desolate,\nand no one will dwell in it.\nThey have fled.\nThey are gone,\nboth man and animal.\n'),
	(15367, 21, 50, 4, '“In those days, and in that time,” says Yahweh,\n“the children of Israel will come,\nthey and the children of Judah together;\nthey will go on their way weeping,\nand will seek Yahweh their God.\n'),
	(15368, 21, 50, 5, 'They will inquire concerning Zion with their faces turned toward it,\nsaying, ‘Come, and join yourselves to Yahweh in an everlasting covenant\nthat will not be forgotten.’\n'),
	(15369, 21, 50, 6, 'My people have been lost sheep.\nTheir shepherds have caused them to go astray.\nThey have turned them away on the mountains.\nThey have gone from mountain to hill.\nThey have forgotten their resting place.\n'),
	(15370, 21, 50, 7, 'All who found them have devoured them.\nTheir adversaries said, ‘We are not guilty,\nbecause they have sinned against Yahweh,\nthe habitation of righteousness,\neven Yahweh, the hope of their fathers.’\n'),
	(15371, 21, 50, 8, '“Flee out of the middle of Babylon!\nGo out of the land of the Chaldeans,\nand be as the male goats before the flocks.\n'),
	(15372, 21, 50, 9, 'For, behold, I will stir up\nand cause to come up against Babylon a company of great nations from the north country;\nand they will set themselves in array against her.\nShe will be taken from there.\nTheir arrows will be as of an expert mighty man.\nNone of them will return in vain.\n'),
	(15373, 21, 50, 10, 'Chaldea will be a prey.\nAll who prey on her will be satisfied,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15374, 21, 50, 11, '“Because you are glad,\nbecause you rejoice,\nO you who plunder my heritage,\nbecause you are wanton as a heifer that treads out the grain,\nand neigh as strong horses;\n'),
	(15375, 21, 50, 12, 'your mother will be utterly disappointed.\nShe who bore you will be confounded.\nBehold, she will be the least of the nations,\na wilderness, a dry land, and a desert.\n'),
	(15376, 21, 50, 13, 'Because of Yahweh’s wrath she won’t be inhabited,\nbut she will be wholly desolate.\nEveryone who goes by Babylon will be astonished,\nand hiss at all her plagues.\n'),
	(15377, 21, 50, 14, 'Set yourselves in array against Babylon all around,\nall you who bend the bow;\nshoot at her.\nSpare no arrows;\nfor she has sinned against Yahweh.\n'),
	(15378, 21, 50, 15, 'Shout against her all around.\nShe has submitted herself.\nHer bulwarks have fallen.\nHer walls have been thrown down,\nfor it is the vengeance of Yahweh.\nTake vengeance on her.\nAs she has done, do to her.\n'),
	(15379, 21, 50, 16, 'Cut off the sower from Babylon,\nand him who handles the sickle in the time of harvest.\nFor fear of the oppressing sword,\nthey will each return to their own people,\nand they will each flee to their own land.\n'),
	(15380, 21, 50, 17, '“Israel is a hunted sheep.\nThe lions have driven him away.\nFirst, the king of Assyria devoured him,\nand now at last Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon has broken his bones.”\n'),
	(15381, 21, 50, 18, 'Therefore Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, says:\n“Behold, I will punish the king of Babylon and his land,\nas I have punished the king of Assyria.\n'),
	(15382, 21, 50, 19, 'I will bring Israel again to his pasture,\nand he will feed on Carmel and Bashan.\nHis soul will be satisfied on the hills of Ephraim and in Gilead.\n'),
	(15383, 21, 50, 20, 'In those days, and in that time,” says Yahweh,\n“the iniquity of Israel will be sought for,\nand there will be none;\nalso the sins of Judah,\nand they won’t be found;\nfor I will pardon them whom I leave as a remnant.\n'),
	(15384, 21, 50, 21, '“Go up against the land of Merathaim,\neven against it, and against the inhabitants of Pekod.\nKill and utterly destroy after them,” says Yahweh,\n“and do according to all that I have commanded you.\n'),
	(15385, 21, 50, 22, 'A sound of battle is in the land,\nand of great destruction.\n'),
	(15386, 21, 50, 23, 'How the hammer of the whole earth is cut apart and broken!\nHow Babylon has become a desolation among the nations!\n'),
	(15387, 21, 50, 24, 'I have laid a snare for you,\nand you are also taken, Babylon,\nand you weren’t aware.\nYou are found,\nand also caught,\nbecause you have fought against Yahweh.\n'),
	(15388, 21, 50, 25, 'Yahweh has opened his armory,\nand has brought out the weapons of his indignation;\nfor the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, has a work to do in the land of the Chaldeans.\n'),
	(15389, 21, 50, 26, 'Come against her from the farthest border.\nOpen her storehouses.\nCast her up as heaps.\nDestroy her utterly.\nLet nothing of her be left.\n'),
	(15390, 21, 50, 27, 'Kill all her bulls.\nLet them go down to the slaughter.\nWoe to them! For their day has come,\nthe time of their visitation.\n'),
	(15391, 21, 50, 28, 'Listen to those who flee and escape out of the land of Babylon,\nto declare in Zion the vengeance of Yahweh our God,\nthe vengeance of his temple.\n'),
	(15392, 21, 50, 29, '“Call together the archers against Babylon,\nall those who bend the bow.\nEncamp against her all around.\nLet none of it escape.\nPay her back according to her work.\nAccording to all that she has done, do to her;\nfor she has been proud against Yahweh,\nagainst the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(15393, 21, 50, 30, 'Therefore her young men will fall in her streets.\nAll her men of war will be brought to silence in that day,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15394, 21, 50, 31, '“Behold, I am against you, you proud one,” says the Lord, Yahweh of Armies;\n“for your day has come,\nthe time that I will visit you.\n'),
	(15395, 21, 50, 32, 'The proud one will stumble and fall,\nand no one will raise him up.\nI will kindle a fire in his cities,\nand it will devour all who are around him.”\n'),
	(15396, 21, 50, 33, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “The children of Israel and the children of Judah are oppressed together.\nAll who took them captive hold them fast.\nThey refuse to let them go.\n'),
	(15397, 21, 50, 34, 'Their Redeemer is strong:\nYahweh of Armies is his name.\nHe will thoroughly plead their cause,\nthat he may give rest to the earth,\nand disquiet the inhabitants of Babylon.\n'),
	(15398, 21, 50, 35, '“A sword is on the Chaldeans,” says Yahweh,\n“and on the inhabitants of Babylon,\non her princes,\nand on her wise men.\n'),
	(15399, 21, 50, 36, 'A sword is on the boasters,\nand they will become fools.\nA sword is on her mighty men,\nand they will be dismayed.\n'),
	(15400, 21, 50, 37, 'A sword is on their horses,\non their chariots,\nand on all the mixed people who are in the middle of her;\nand they will become as women.\nA sword is on her treasures,\nand they will be robbed.\n'),
	(15401, 21, 50, 38, 'A drought is on her waters,\nand they will be dried up;\nfor it is a land of engraved images,\nand they are mad over idols.\n'),
	(15402, 21, 50, 39, 'Therefore the wild animals of the desert\nwith the wolves will dwell there.\nThe ostriches will dwell therein;\nand it will be inhabited no more forever;\nneither will it be lived in from generation to generation.\n'),
	(15403, 21, 50, 40, 'As when God overthrew Sodom and Gomorrah and its neighbor cities,” says Yahweh,\n“so no man will dwell there,\nneither will any son of man live therein.\n'),
	(15404, 21, 50, 41, '“Behold, a people comes from the north;\nand a great nation and many kings will be stirred up from the uttermost parts of the earth.\n'),
	(15405, 21, 50, 42, 'They take up bow and spear.\nThey are cruel, and have no mercy.\nTheir voice roars like the sea.\nThey ride on horses,\neveryone set in array,\nas a man to the battle,\nagainst you, daughter of Babylon.\n'),
	(15406, 21, 50, 43, 'The king of Babylon has heard the news of them,\nand his hands become feeble:\nanguish has taken hold of him,\npains as of a woman in labor.\n'),
	(15407, 21, 50, 44, 'Behold, the enemy will come up like a lion\nfrom the pride of the Jordan against the strong habitation;\nfor I will suddenly make them run away from it.\nWhoever is chosen,\nI will appoint him over it;\nfor who is like me?\nWho will appoint me a time?\nWho is the shepherd who can stand before me?”\n'),
	(15408, 21, 50, 45, 'Therefore hear the counsel of Yahweh,\nthat he has taken against Babylon;\nand his purposes,\nthat he has purposed against the land of the Chaldeans:\nSurely they will drag them away,\neven the little ones of the flock.\nSurely he will make their habitation desolate over them.\n'),
	(15409, 21, 50, 46, 'At the noise of the taking of Babylon the earth trembles;\nand the cry is heard among the nations.\n'),
	(15410, 21, 51, 1, 'Yahweh says:\n“Behold, I will raise up against Babylon,\nand against those who dwell in Lebkamai, a destroying wind.\n'),
	(15411, 21, 51, 2, 'I will send to Babylon strangers, who will winnow her.\nThey will empty her land;\nfor in the day of trouble they will be against her all around.\n'),
	(15412, 21, 51, 3, 'Against him who bends, let the archer bend his bow,\nalso against him who lifts himself up in his coat of mail.\nDon’t spare her young men!\nUtterly destroy all her army!\n'),
	(15413, 21, 51, 4, 'They will fall down slain in the land of the Chaldeans,\nand thrust through in her streets.\n'),
	(15414, 21, 51, 5, 'For Israel is not forsaken, nor Judah, by his God,\nby Yahweh of Armies;\nthough their land is full of guilt against the Holy One of Israel.\n'),
	(15415, 21, 51, 6, '“Flee out of the middle of Babylon!\nEveryone save his own life!\nDon’t be cut off in her iniquity;\nfor it is the time of Yahweh’s vengeance.\nHe will render to her a recompense.\n'),
	(15416, 21, 51, 7, 'Babylon has been a golden cup in Yahweh’s hand,\nwho made all the earth drunk.\nThe nations have drunk of her wine;\ntherefore the nations have gone mad.\n'),
	(15417, 21, 51, 8, 'Babylon has suddenly fallen and been destroyed!\nWail for her!\nTake balm for her pain.\nPerhaps she may be healed.\n'),
	(15418, 21, 51, 9, '“We would have healed Babylon,\nbut she is not healed.\nForsake her,\nand let us each go into his own country;\nfor her judgment reaches to heaven,\nand is lifted up even to the skies.\n'),
	(15419, 21, 51, 10, '‘Yahweh has produced our righteousness:\ncome, and let us declare in Zion the work of Yahweh our God.’\n'),
	(15420, 21, 51, 11, '“Make the arrows sharp!\nHold the shields firmly!\nYahweh has stirred up the spirit of the kings of the Medes,\nbecause his purpose is against Babylon, to destroy it;\nfor it is the vengeance of Yahweh,\nthe vengeance of his temple.\n'),
	(15421, 21, 51, 12, 'Set up a standard against the walls of Babylon!\nMake the watch strong!\nSet the watchmen,\nand prepare the ambushes;\nfor Yahweh has both purposed and done\nthat which he spoke concerning the inhabitants of Babylon.\n'),
	(15422, 21, 51, 13, 'You who dwell on many waters, abundant in treasures,\nyour end has come, the measure of your covetousness.\n'),
	(15423, 21, 51, 14, 'Yahweh of Armies has sworn by himself, saying,\n‘Surely I will fill you with men,\nas with the canker worm;\nand they will lift up a shout against you.’\n'),
	(15424, 21, 51, 15, '“He has made the earth by his power.\nHe has established the world by his wisdom.\nBy his understanding he has stretched out the heavens.\n'),
	(15425, 21, 51, 16, 'When he utters his voice,\nthere is a roar of waters in the heavens,\nand he causes the vapors to ascend from the ends of the earth.\nHe makes lightning for the rain,\nand brings the wind out of his treasuries.\n'),
	(15426, 21, 51, 17, '“Every man has become brutish without knowledge.\nEvery goldsmith is disappointed by his image;\nfor his molten image is falsehood,\nand there is no breath in them.\n'),
	(15427, 21, 51, 18, 'They are vanity,\na work of delusion.\nIn the time of their visitation, they will perish.\n'),
	(15428, 21, 51, 19, 'The portion of Jacob is not like these,\nfor he is the former of all things;\nincluding the tribe of his inheritance:\nYahweh of Armies is his name.\n'),
	(15429, 21, 51, 20, '“You are my battle ax and weapons of war.\nWith you I will break the nations into pieces.\nWith you I will destroy kingdoms.\n'),
	(15430, 21, 51, 21, 'With you I will break in pieces\nthe horse and his rider.\n'),
	(15431, 21, 51, 22, 'With you I will break in pieces\nthe chariot and him who rides therein.\nWith you I will break in pieces\nman and woman.\nWith you I will break in pieces\nthe old man and the youth.\nWith you I will break in pieces\nthe young man and the virgin.\n'),
	(15432, 21, 51, 23, 'With you I will break in pieces\nthe shepherd and his flock.\nWith you I will break in pieces\nthe farmer and his yoke.\nWith you will I break in pieces\ngovernors and deputies.\n'),
	(15433, 21, 51, 24, '“I will render to Babylon and to all the inhabitants of Chaldea all their evil that they have done in Zion in your sight,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15434, 21, 51, 25, '“Behold, I am against you, destroying mountain,” says Yahweh,\n“which destroys all the earth.\nI will stretch out my hand on you,\nroll you down from the rocks,\nand will make you a burned mountain.\n'),
	(15435, 21, 51, 26, 'They won’t take a cornerstone from you,\nnor a stone for foundations;\nbut you will be desolate for ever,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15436, 21, 51, 27, '“Set up a standard in the land!\nBlow the trumpet among the nations!\nPrepare the nations against her!\nCall together against her the kingdoms of Ararat, Minni, and Ashkenaz!\nAppoint a marshal against her!\nCause the horses to come up as the rough canker worm!\n'),
	(15437, 21, 51, 28, 'Prepare against her the nations,\nthe kings of the Medes, its governors, and all its deputies, and all the land of their dominion!\n'),
	(15438, 21, 51, 29, 'The land trembles and is in pain;\nfor the purposes of Yahweh against Babylon stand,\nto make the land of Babylon a desolation, without inhabitant.\n'),
	(15439, 21, 51, 30, 'The mighty men of Babylon have stopped fighting,\nthey remain in their strongholds.\nTheir might has failed.\nThey have become as women.\nHer dwelling places are set on fire.\nHer bars are broken.\n'),
	(15440, 21, 51, 31, 'One runner will run to meet another,\nand one messenger to meet another,\nto show the king of Babylon that his city is taken on every quarter.\n'),
	(15441, 21, 51, 32, 'So the passages are seized.\nThey have burned the reeds with fire.\nThe men of war are frightened.”\n'),
	(15442, 21, 51, 33, 'For Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel says:\n“The daughter of Babylon is like a threshing floor at the time when it is trodden.\nYet a little while, and the time of harvest comes for her.”\n'),
	(15443, 21, 51, 34, '“Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon has devoured me.\nHe has crushed me.\nHe has made me an empty vessel.\nHe has, like a monster, swallowed me up.\nHe has filled his mouth with my delicacies.\nHe has cast me out.\n'),
	(15444, 21, 51, 35, 'May the violence done to me and to my flesh be on Babylon!”\nthe inhabitant of Zion will say; and,\n“May my blood be on the inhabitants of Chaldea!”\nwill Jerusalem say.\n'),
	(15445, 21, 51, 36, 'Therefore Yahweh says:\n“Behold, I will plead your cause,\nand take vengeance for you.\nI will dry up her sea,\nand make her fountain dry.\n'),
	(15446, 21, 51, 37, 'Babylon will become heaps,\na dwelling place for jackals,\nan astonishment, and a hissing,\nwithout inhabitant.\n'),
	(15447, 21, 51, 38, 'They will roar together like young lions.\nThey will growl as lions’ cubs.\n'),
	(15448, 21, 51, 39, 'When they are heated, I will make their feast,\nand I will make them drunk,\nthat they may rejoice,\nand sleep a perpetual sleep,\nand not wake up,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15449, 21, 51, 40, '“I will bring them down like lambs to the slaughter,\nlike rams with male goats.\n'),
	(15450, 21, 51, 41, '“How Sheshach is taken!\nHow the praise of the whole earth seized!\nHow Babylon has become a desolation among the nations!\n'),
	(15451, 21, 51, 42, 'The sea has come up on Babylon.\nShe is covered with the multitude of its waves.\n'),
	(15452, 21, 51, 43, 'Her cities have become a desolation,\na dry land, and a desert,\na land in which no man dwells.\nNo son of man passes by it.\n'),
	(15453, 21, 51, 44, 'I will execute judgment on Bel in Babylon,\nand I will bring out of his mouth that which he has swallowed up.\nThe nations will not flow any more to him.\nYes, the wall of Babylon will fall.\n'),
	(15454, 21, 51, 45, '“My people, go away from the middle of her,\nand each of you save yourselves from Yahweh’s fierce anger.\n'),
	(15455, 21, 51, 46, 'Don’t let your heart faint.\nDon’t fear for the news that will be heard in the land.\nFor news will come one year,\nand after that in another year news will come,\nand violence in the land,\nruler against ruler.\n'),
	(15456, 21, 51, 47, 'Therefore behold, the days come that I will execute judgment on the engraved images of Babylon;\nand her whole land will be confounded.\nAll her slain will fall in the middle of her.\n'),
	(15457, 21, 51, 48, 'Then the heavens and the earth,\nand all that is therein,\nwill sing for joy over Babylon;\nfor the destroyers will come to her from the north,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15458, 21, 51, 49, '“As Babylon has caused the slain of Israel to fall,\nso the slain of all the land will fall at Babylon.\n'),
	(15459, 21, 51, 50, 'You who have escaped the sword, go!\nDon’t stand still!\nRemember Yahweh from afar,\nand let Jerusalem come into your mind.”\n'),
	(15460, 21, 51, 51, '“We are confounded,\nbecause we have heard reproach.\nConfusion has covered our faces,\nfor strangers have come into the sanctuaries of Yahweh’s house.”\n'),
	(15461, 21, 51, 52, '“Therefore behold, the days come,” says Yahweh,\n“that I will execute judgment on her engraved images;\nand through all her land the wounded will groan.\n'),
	(15462, 21, 51, 53, 'Though Babylon should mount up to the sky,\nand though she should fortify the height of her strength,\nyet destroyers will come to her from me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(15463, 21, 51, 54, '“The sound of a cry comes from Babylon,\nand of great destruction from the land of the Chaldeans!\n'),
	(15464, 21, 51, 55, 'For Yahweh lays Babylon waste,\nand destroys out of her the great voice!\nTheir waves roar like many waters.\nThe noise of their voice is uttered.\n'),
	(15465, 21, 51, 56, 'For the destroyer has come on her,\neven on Babylon.\nHer mighty men are taken.\nTheir bows are broken in pieces,\nfor Yahweh is a God of retribution.\nHe will surely repay.\n'),
	(15466, 21, 51, 57, 'I will make her princes, her wise men,\nher governors, her deputies, and her mighty men drunk.\nThey will sleep a perpetual sleep,\nand not wake up,”\nsays the King, whose name is Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(15467, 21, 51, 58, 'Yahweh of Armies says:\n“The wide walls of Babylon will be utterly overthrown.\nHer high gates will be burned with fire.\nThe peoples will labor for vanity,\nand the nations for the fire;\nand they will be weary.”\n'),
	(15468, 21, 51, 59, 'The word which Jeremiah the prophet commanded Seraiah the son of Neriah, the son of Mahseiah, when he went with Zedekiah the king of Judah to Babylon in the fourth year of his reign. Now Seraiah was chief quartermaster.\n'),
	(15469, 21, 51, 60, 'Jeremiah wrote in a book all the evil that should come on Babylon, even all these words that are written concerning Babylon.\n'),
	(15470, 21, 51, 61, 'Jeremiah said to Seraiah, “When you come to Babylon, then see that you read all these words,\n'),
	(15471, 21, 51, 62, 'and say, ‘Yahweh, you have spoken concerning this place, to cut it off, that no one will dwell in it, neither man nor animal, but that it will be desolate forever.’\n'),
	(15472, 21, 51, 63, 'It will be, when you have finished reading this book, that you shall bind a stone to it, and cast it into the middle of the Euphrates.\n'),
	(15473, 21, 51, 64, 'Then you shall say, ‘Thus will Babylon sink, and will not rise again because of the evil that I will bring on her; and they will be weary.’”\nThus far are the words of Jeremiah.\n'),
	(15474, 21, 52, 1, 'Zedekiah was twenty-one years old when he began to reign. He reigned eleven years in Jerusalem: and his mother’s name was Hamutal the daughter of Jeremiah of Libnah.\n'),
	(15475, 21, 52, 2, 'He did that which was evil in Yahweh’s sight, according to all that Jehoiakim had done.\n'),
	(15476, 21, 52, 3, 'For through Yahweh’s anger this happened in Jerusalem and Judah, until he had cast them out from his presence.\nZedekiah rebelled against the king of Babylon.\n'),
	(15477, 21, 52, 4, 'In the ninth year of his reign, in the tenth month, in the tenth day of the month, Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon came, he and all his army, against Jerusalem, and encamped against it; and they built forts against it round about.\n'),
	(15478, 21, 52, 5, 'So the city was besieged to the eleventh year of king Zedekiah.\n'),
	(15479, 21, 52, 6, 'In the fourth month, in the ninth day of the month, the famine was severe in the city, so that there was no bread for the people of the land.\n'),
	(15480, 21, 52, 7, 'Then a breach was made in the city, and all the men of war fled, and went out of the city by night by the way of the gate between the two walls, which was by the king’s garden. Now the Chaldeans were against the city all around. The men of war went toward the Arabah,\n'),
	(15481, 21, 52, 8, 'but the army of the Chaldeans pursued the king, and overtook Zedekiah in the plains of Jericho; and all his army was scattered from him.\n'),
	(15482, 21, 52, 9, 'Then they took the king, and carried him up to the king of Babylon to Riblah in the land of Hamath; and he pronounced judgment on him.\n'),
	(15483, 21, 52, 10, 'The king of Babylon killed the sons of Zedekiah before his eyes. He also killed all the princes of Judah in Riblah.\n'),
	(15484, 21, 52, 11, 'He put out the eyes of Zedekiah; and the king of Babylon bound him in fetters, and carried him to Babylon, and put him in prison until the day of his death.\n'),
	(15485, 21, 52, 12, 'Now in the fifth month, in the tenth day of the month, which was the nineteenth year of king Nebuchadnezzar, king of Babylon, Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard, who stood before the king of Babylon, came into Jerusalem.\n'),
	(15486, 21, 52, 13, 'He burned Yahweh’s house, and the king’s house; and all the houses of Jerusalem, even every great house, he burned with fire.\n'),
	(15487, 21, 52, 14, 'All the army of the Chaldeans, who were with the captain of the guard, broke down all the walls of Jerusalem all around.\n'),
	(15488, 21, 52, 15, 'Then Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard carried away captive of the poorest of the people, and the residue of the people who were left in the city, and those who fell away, who fell to the king of Babylon, and the residue of the multitude.\n'),
	(15489, 21, 52, 16, 'But Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard left of the poorest of the land to be vineyard keepers and farmers.\n'),
	(15490, 21, 52, 17, 'The Chaldeans broke the pillars of brass that were in Yahweh’s house, and the bases and the bronze sea that were in Yahweh’s house in pieces, and carried all of their brass to Babylon.\n'),
	(15491, 21, 52, 18, 'They also took away the pots, the shovels, the snuffers, the basins, the spoons, and all the vessels of brass with which they ministered.\n'),
	(15492, 21, 52, 19, 'The captain of the guard took away the cups, the fire pans, the basins, the pots, the lamp stands, the spoons, and the bowls; that which was of gold, in gold, and that which was of silver, in silver.\n'),
	(15493, 21, 52, 20, 'They took the two pillars, the one sea, and the twelve bronze bulls that were under the bases, which king Solomon had made for Yahweh’s house. The brass of all these vessels was without weight.\n'),
	(15494, 21, 52, 21, 'As for the pillars, the height of the one pillar was eighteen cubits; and a line of twelve cubits encircled it; and its thickness was four fingers. It was hollow.\n'),
	(15495, 21, 52, 22, 'A capital of brass was on it; and the height of the one capital was five cubits, with network and pomegranates on the capital all around, all of brass: and the second pillar also had like these, and pomegranates.\n'),
	(15496, 21, 52, 23, 'There were ninety-six pomegranates on the sides; all the pomegranates were one hundred on the network all around.\n'),
	(15497, 21, 52, 24, 'The captain of the guard took Seraiah the chief priest, and Zephaniah the second priest, and the three keepers of the threshold:\n'),
	(15498, 21, 52, 25, 'and out of the city he took an officer who was set over the men of war; and seven men of those who saw the king’s face, who were found in the city; and the scribe of the captain of the army, who mustered the people of the land; and sixty men of the people of the land, who were found in the middle of the city.\n'),
	(15499, 21, 52, 26, 'Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard took them, and brought them to the king of Babylon to Riblah.\n'),
	(15500, 21, 52, 27, 'The king of Babylon struck them, and put them to death at Riblah in the land of Hamath.\nSo Judah was carried away captive out of his land.\n'),
	(15501, 21, 52, 28, 'This is the number of the people whom Nebuchadnezzar carried away captive:\nin the seventh year, three thousand twenty-three Jews;\n'),
	(15502, 21, 52, 29, 'in the eighteenth year of Nebuchadnezzar, he carried away captive from Jerusalem eight hundred thirty-two persons;\n'),
	(15503, 21, 52, 30, 'in the twenty-third year of Nebuchadnezzar Nebuzaradan the captain of the guard carried away captive of the Jews seven hundred forty-five people:\nall the people were four thousand six hundred.\n'),
	(15504, 21, 52, 31, 'In the thirty-seventh year of the captivity of Jehoiachin king of Judah, in the twelfth month, in the twenty-fifth day of the month, Evilmerodach king of Babylon, in the first year of his reign, lifted up the head of Jehoiachin king of Judah, and released him from prison.\n'),
	(15505, 21, 52, 32, 'He spoke kindly to him, and set his throne above the throne of the kings who were with him in Babylon,\n'),
	(15506, 21, 52, 33, 'and changed his prison garments. Jehoiachin ate bread before him continually all the days of his life.\n'),
	(15507, 21, 52, 34, 'For his allowance, there was a continual allowance given him by the king of Babylon, every day a portion until the day of his death, all the days of his life.\n'),
	(15508, 22, 1, 1, 'How the city sits solitary,\nthat was full of people!\nShe has become as a widow,\nwho was great among the nations!\nShe who was a princess among the provinces\nhas become a slave!\n'),
	(15509, 22, 1, 2, 'She weeps bitterly in the night.\nHer tears are on her cheeks.\nAmong all her lovers\nshe has no one to comfort her.\nAll her friends have dealt treacherously with her.\nThey have become her enemies.\n'),
	(15510, 22, 1, 3, 'Judah has gone into captivity because of affliction,\nand because of great servitude.\nShe dwells among the nations.\nShe finds no rest.\nAll her persecutors overtook her within the straits.\n'),
	(15511, 22, 1, 4, 'The roads to Zion mourn,\nbecause no one comes to the solemn assembly.\nAll her gates are desolate.\nHer priests sigh.\nHer virgins are afflicted,\nand she herself is in bitterness.\n'),
	(15512, 22, 1, 5, 'Her adversaries have become the head.\nHer enemies prosper;\nfor Yahweh has afflicted her for the multitude of her transgressions.\nHer young children have gone into captivity before the adversary.\n'),
	(15513, 22, 1, 6, 'All majesty has departed from the daughter of Zion.\nHer princes have become like deer that find no pasture.\nThey have gone without strength before the pursuer.\n'),
	(15514, 22, 1, 7, 'Jerusalem remembers in the days of her affliction and of her miseries\nall her pleasant things that were from the days of old;\nwhen her people fell into the hand of the adversary,\nand no one helped her.\nThe adversaries saw her.\nThey mocked at her desolations.\n'),
	(15515, 22, 1, 8, 'Jerusalem has grievously sinned.\nTherefore she has become unclean.\nAll who honored her despise her,\nbecause they have seen her nakedness.\nYes, she sighs, and turns backward.\n'),
	(15516, 22, 1, 9, 'Her filthiness was in her skirts.\nShe didn’t remember her latter end.\nTherefore she has come down astoundingly.\nShe has no comforter.\n“See, Yahweh, my affliction;\nfor the enemy has magnified himself.”\n'),
	(15517, 22, 1, 10, 'The adversary has spread out his hand on all her pleasant things;\nfor she has seen that the nations have entered into her sanctuary,\nconcerning whom you commanded that they should not enter into your assembly.\n'),
	(15518, 22, 1, 11, 'All her people sigh.\nThey seek bread.\nThey have given their pleasant things for food to refresh their soul.\n“Look, Yahweh, and see;\nfor I have become despised.”\n'),
	(15519, 22, 1, 12, '“Is it nothing to you, all you who pass by?\nLook, and see if there is any sorrow like my sorrow,\nwhich is brought on me,\nwith which Yahweh has afflicted me in the day of his fierce anger.\n'),
	(15520, 22, 1, 13, '“From on high has he sent fire into my bones,\nand it prevails against them.\nHe has spread a net for my feet.\nHe has turned me back.\nHe has made me desolate and I faint all day long.\n'),
	(15521, 22, 1, 14, '“The yoke of my transgressions is bound by his hand.\nThey are knit together.\nThey have come up on my neck.\nHe made my strength fail.\nThe Lord has delivered me into their hands,\nagainst whom I am not able to stand.\n'),
	(15522, 22, 1, 15, '“The Lord has set at nothing all my mighty men within me.\nHe has called a solemn assembly against me to crush my young men.\nThe Lord has trodden the virgin daughter of Judah as in a wine press.\n'),
	(15523, 22, 1, 16, '“For these things I weep.\nMy eye, my eye runs down with water,\nbecause the comforter who should refresh my soul is far from me.\nMy children are desolate,\nbecause the enemy has prevailed.”\n'),
	(15524, 22, 1, 17, 'Zion spreads out her hands.\nThere is no one to comfort her.\nYahweh has commanded concerning Jacob,\nthat those who are around him should be his adversaries.\nJerusalem is among them as an unclean thing.\n'),
	(15525, 22, 1, 18, '“Yahweh is righteous;\nfor I have rebelled against his commandment.\nPlease hear all you peoples,\nand see my sorrow.\nMy virgins and my young men have gone into captivity.\n'),
	(15526, 22, 1, 19, '“I called for my lovers,\nbut they deceived me.\nMy priests and my elders gave up the spirit in the city,\nwhile they sought food for themselves to refresh their souls.\n'),
	(15527, 22, 1, 20, '“Look, Yahweh; for I am in distress.\nMy heart is troubled.\nMy heart turns over within me,\nfor I have grievously rebelled.\nAbroad, the sword bereaves.\nAt home, it is like death.\n'),
	(15528, 22, 1, 21, '“They have heard that I sigh.\nThere is no one to comfort me.\nAll my enemies have heard of my trouble.\nThey are glad that you have done it.\nYou will bring the day that you have proclaimed,\nand they will be like me.\n'),
	(15529, 22, 1, 22, '“Let all their wickedness come before you.\nDo to them as you have done to me for all my transgressions.\nFor my sighs are many,\nand my heart is faint.\n'),
	(15530, 22, 2, 1, 'How has the Lord covered the daughter of Zion with a cloud in his anger!\nHe has cast the beauty of Israel down from heaven to the earth,\nand hasn’t remembered his footstool in the day of his anger.\n'),
	(15531, 22, 2, 2, 'The Lord has swallowed up all the dwellings of Jacob\nwithout pity.\nHe has thrown down in his wrath the strongholds of the daughter of Judah.\nHe has brought them down to the ground.\nHe has profaned the kingdom and its princes.\n'),
	(15532, 22, 2, 3, 'He has cut off all the horn of Israel in fierce anger.\nHe has drawn back his right hand from before the enemy.\nHe has burned up Jacob like a flaming fire,\nwhich devours all around.\n'),
	(15533, 22, 2, 4, 'He has bent his bow like an enemy.\nHe has stood with his right hand as an adversary.\nHas killed all that were pleasant to the eye.\nIn the tent of the daughter of Zion, he has poured out his wrath like fire.\n'),
	(15534, 22, 2, 5, 'The Lord has become as an enemy.\nHe has swallowed up Israel.\nHe has swallowed up all her palaces.\nHe has destroyed his strongholds.\nHe has multiplied mourning and lamentation in the daughter of Judah.\n'),
	(15535, 22, 2, 6, 'He has violently taken away his tabernacle,\nas if it were of a garden.\nHe has destroyed his place of assembly.\nYahweh has caused solemn assembly and Sabbath to be forgotten in Zion.\nIn the indignation of his anger, he has despised the king and the priest.\n'),
	(15536, 22, 2, 7, 'The Lord has cast off his altar.\nHe has abhorred his sanctuary.\nHe has given the walls of her palaces into the hand of the enemy.\nThey have made a noise in Yahweh’s house,\nas in the day of a solemn assembly.\n'),
	(15537, 22, 2, 8, 'Yahweh has purposed to destroy the wall of the daughter of Zion.\nHe has stretched out the line.\nHe has not withdrawn his hand from destroying;\nHe has made the rampart and wall lament.\nThey languish together.\n'),
	(15538, 22, 2, 9, 'Her gates have sunk into the ground.\nHe has destroyed and broken her bars.\nHer king and her princes are among the nations where the law is not.\nYes, her prophets find no vision from Yahweh.\n'),
	(15539, 22, 2, 10, 'The elders of the daughter of Zion sit on the ground.\nThey keep silence.\nThey have cast up dust on their heads.\nThey have clothed themselves with sackcloth.\nThe virgins of Jerusalem hang down their heads to the ground.\n'),
	(15540, 22, 2, 11, 'My eyes fail with tears.\nMy heart is troubled.\nMy liver is poured on the earth,\nbecause of the destruction of the daughter of my people,\nbecause the young children and the infants swoon in the streets of the city.\n'),
	(15541, 22, 2, 12, 'They ask their mothers,\n“Where is grain and wine?”\nwhen they swoon as the wounded in the streets of the city,\nwhen their soul is poured out into their mothers’ bosom.\n'),
	(15542, 22, 2, 13, 'What shall I testify to you?\nWhat shall I liken to you, daughter of Jerusalem?\nWhat shall I compare to you,\nthat I may comfort you, virgin daughter of Zion?\nFor your breach is as big as the sea.\nWho can heal you?\n'),
	(15543, 22, 2, 14, 'Your prophets have seen false and foolish visions for you.\nThey have not uncovered your iniquity,\nto reverse your captivity,\nbut have seen for you false revelations and causes of banishment.\n'),
	(15544, 22, 2, 15, 'All that pass by clap their hands at you.\nThey hiss and wag their head at the daughter of Jerusalem, saying,\n“Is this the city that men called ‘The perfection of beauty,\nthe joy of the whole earth’?”\n'),
	(15545, 22, 2, 16, 'All your enemies have opened their mouth wide against you.\nThey hiss and gnash their teeth.\nThey say, “We have swallowed her up.\nCertainly this is the day that we looked for.\nWe have found it.\nWe have seen it.”\n'),
	(15546, 22, 2, 17, 'Yahweh has done that which he planned.\nHe has fulfilled his word that he commanded in the days of old.\nHe has thrown down,\nand has not pitied.\nHe has caused the enemy to rejoice over you.\nHe has exalted the horn of your adversaries.\n'),
	(15547, 22, 2, 18, 'Their heart cried to the Lord.\nO wall of the daughter of Zion,\nlet tears run down like a river day and night.\nGive yourself no relief.\nDon’t let the your eyes rest.\n'),
	(15548, 22, 2, 19, 'Arise, cry out in the night,\nat the beginning of the watches!\nPour out your heart like water before the face of the Lord.\nLift up your hands toward him for the life of your young children,\nwho faint for hunger at the head of every street.\n'),
	(15549, 22, 2, 20, '“Look, Yahweh, and see to whom you have done thus!\nShould the women eat their offspring,\nthe children that they held and bounced on their knees?\nShould the priest and the prophet be killed in the sanctuary of the Lord?\n'),
	(15550, 22, 2, 21, '“The youth and the old man lie on the ground in the streets.\nMy virgins and my young men have fallen by the sword.\nYou have killed them in the day of your anger.\nYou have slaughtered, and not pitied.\n'),
	(15551, 22, 2, 22, '“You have called, as in the day of a solemn assembly, my terrors on every side.\nThere was no one that escaped or remained in the day of Yahweh’s anger.\nMy enemy has consumed those whom I have cared for and brought up.\n'),
	(15552, 22, 3, 1, 'I am the man who has seen affliction\nby the rod of his wrath.\n'),
	(15553, 22, 3, 2, 'He has led me and caused me to walk in darkness,\nand not in light.\n'),
	(15554, 22, 3, 3, 'Surely he turns his hand against me\nagain and again all day long.\n'),
	(15555, 22, 3, 4, 'He has made my flesh and my skin old.\nHe has broken my bones.\n'),
	(15556, 22, 3, 5, 'He has built against me,\nand surrounded me with bitterness and hardship.\n'),
	(15557, 22, 3, 6, 'He has made me dwell in dark places,\nas those who have been long dead.\n'),
	(15558, 22, 3, 7, 'He has walled me about, so that I can’t go out.\nHe has made my chain heavy.\n'),
	(15559, 22, 3, 8, 'Yes, when I cry, and call for help,\nhe shuts out my prayer.\n'),
	(15560, 22, 3, 9, 'He has walled up my ways with cut stone.\nHe has made my paths crooked.\n'),
	(15561, 22, 3, 10, 'He is to me as a bear lying in wait,\nas a lion in secret places.\n'),
	(15562, 22, 3, 11, 'He has turned away my ways,\nand pulled me in pieces.\nHe has made me desolate.\n'),
	(15563, 22, 3, 12, 'He has bent his bow,\nand set me as a mark for the arrow.\n'),
	(15564, 22, 3, 13, 'He has caused the shafts of his quiver to enter into my kidneys.\n'),
	(15565, 22, 3, 14, 'I have become a derision to all my people,\nand their song all day long.\n'),
	(15566, 22, 3, 15, 'He has filled me with bitterness.\nHe has stuffed me with wormwood.\n'),
	(15567, 22, 3, 16, 'He has also broken my teeth with gravel.\nHe has covered me with ashes.\n'),
	(15568, 22, 3, 17, 'You have removed my soul far away from peace.\nI forgot prosperity.\n'),
	(15569, 22, 3, 18, 'I said, “My strength has perished,\nalong with my expectation from Yahweh.”\n'),
	(15570, 22, 3, 19, 'Remember my affliction and my misery,\nthe wormwood and the bitterness.\n'),
	(15571, 22, 3, 20, 'My soul still remembers them,\nand is bowed down within me.\n'),
	(15572, 22, 3, 21, 'This I recall to my mind;\ntherefore I have hope.\n'),
	(15573, 22, 3, 22, 'It is because of Yahweh’s loving kindnesses that we are not consumed,\nbecause his compassion doesn’t fail.\n'),
	(15574, 22, 3, 23, 'They are new every morning.\nGreat is your faithfulness.\n'),
	(15575, 22, 3, 24, '“Yahweh is my portion,” says my soul.\n“Therefore I will hope in him.”\n'),
	(15576, 22, 3, 25, 'Yahweh is good to those who wait for him,\nto the soul who seeks him.\n'),
	(15577, 22, 3, 26, 'It is good that a man should hope\nand quietly wait for the salvation of Yahweh.\n'),
	(15578, 22, 3, 27, 'It is good for a man that he bear the yoke in his youth.\n'),
	(15579, 22, 3, 28, 'Let him sit alone and keep silence,\nbecause he has laid it on him.\n'),
	(15580, 22, 3, 29, 'Let him put his mouth in the dust,\nif it is so that there may be hope.\n'),
	(15581, 22, 3, 30, 'Let him give his cheek to him who strikes him.\nLet him be filled full of reproach.\n'),
	(15582, 22, 3, 31, 'For the Lord will not cast off forever.\n'),
	(15583, 22, 3, 32, 'For though he causes grief,\nyet he will have compassion according to the multitude of his loving kindnesses.\n'),
	(15584, 22, 3, 33, 'For he does not afflict willingly,\nnor grieve the children of men.\n'),
	(15585, 22, 3, 34, 'To crush under foot all the prisoners of the earth,\n'),
	(15586, 22, 3, 35, 'to turn away the right of a man before the face of the Most High,\n'),
	(15587, 22, 3, 36, 'to subvert a man in his cause, the Lord doesn’t approve.\n'),
	(15588, 22, 3, 37, 'Who is he who says, and it comes to pass,\nwhen the Lord doesn’t command it?\n'),
	(15589, 22, 3, 38, 'Doesn’t evil and good come out of the mouth of the Most High?\n'),
	(15590, 22, 3, 39, 'Why does a living man complain,\na man for the punishment of his sins?\n'),
	(15591, 22, 3, 40, 'Let us search and try our ways,\nand turn again to Yahweh.\n'),
	(15592, 22, 3, 41, 'Let us lift up our heart with our hands to God in the heavens.\n'),
	(15593, 22, 3, 42, '“We have transgressed and have rebelled.\nYou have not pardoned.\n'),
	(15594, 22, 3, 43, '“You have covered us with anger and pursued us.\nYou have killed.\nYou have not pitied.\n'),
	(15595, 22, 3, 44, 'You have covered yourself with a cloud,\nso that no prayer can pass through.\n'),
	(15596, 22, 3, 45, 'You have made us an off-scouring and refuse\nin the middle of the peoples.\n'),
	(15597, 22, 3, 46, '“All our enemies have opened their mouth wide against us.\n'),
	(15598, 22, 3, 47, 'Terror and the pit have come on us,\ndevastation and destruction.”\n'),
	(15599, 22, 3, 48, 'My eye runs down with streams of water,\nfor the destruction of the daughter of my people.\n'),
	(15600, 22, 3, 49, 'My eye pours down\nand doesn’t cease,\nwithout any intermission,\n'),
	(15601, 22, 3, 50, 'until Yahweh looks down,\nand sees from heaven.\n'),
	(15602, 22, 3, 51, 'My eye affects my soul,\nbecause of all the daughters of my city.\n'),
	(15603, 22, 3, 52, 'They have chased me relentlessly like a bird,\nthose who are my enemies without cause.\n'),
	(15604, 22, 3, 53, 'They have cut off my life in the dungeon,\nand have cast a stone on me.\n'),
	(15605, 22, 3, 54, 'Waters flowed over my head.\nI said, “I am cut off.”\n'),
	(15606, 22, 3, 55, 'I called on your name, Yahweh,\nout of the lowest dungeon.\n'),
	(15607, 22, 3, 56, 'You heard my voice:\n“Don’t hide your ear from my sighing,\nand my cry.”\n'),
	(15608, 22, 3, 57, 'You came near in the day that I called on you.\nYou said, “Don’t be afraid.”\n'),
	(15609, 22, 3, 58, 'Lord, you have pleaded the causes of my soul.\nYou have redeemed my life.\n'),
	(15610, 22, 3, 59, 'Yahweh, you have seen my wrong.\nJudge my cause.\n'),
	(15611, 22, 3, 60, 'You have seen all their vengeance\nand all their plans against me.\n'),
	(15612, 22, 3, 61, 'You have heard their reproach, Yahweh,\nand all their plans against me,\n'),
	(15613, 22, 3, 62, 'the lips of those that rose up against me,\nand their plots against me all day long.\n'),
	(15614, 22, 3, 63, 'You see their sitting down and their rising up.\nI am their song.\n'),
	(15615, 22, 3, 64, 'You will pay them back, Yahweh,\naccording to the work of their hands.\n'),
	(15616, 22, 3, 65, 'You will give them hardness of heart,\nyour curse to them.\n'),
	(15617, 22, 3, 66, 'You will pursue them in anger,\nand destroy them from under the heavens of Yahweh.\n'),
	(15618, 22, 4, 1, 'How the gold has become dim!\nThe most pure gold has changed!\nThe stones of the sanctuary are poured out\nat the head of every street.\n'),
	(15619, 22, 4, 2, 'The precious sons of Zion,\ncomparable to fine gold,\nhow are they esteemed as earthen pitchers,\nthe work of the hands of the potter!\n'),
	(15620, 22, 4, 3, 'Even the jackals offer their breast.\nThey nurse their young ones.\nBut the daughter of my people has become cruel,\nlike the ostriches in the wilderness.\n'),
	(15621, 22, 4, 4, 'The tongue of the nursing child clings to the roof of his mouth for thirst.\nThe young children ask bread,\nand no one breaks it for them.\n'),
	(15622, 22, 4, 5, 'Those who ate delicacies are desolate in the streets.\nThose who were brought up in purple embrace dunghills.\n'),
	(15623, 22, 4, 6, 'For the iniquity of the daughter of my people is greater than the sin of Sodom,\nwhich was overthrown as in a moment.\nNo hands were laid on her.\n'),
	(15624, 22, 4, 7, 'Her nobles were purer than snow.\nThey were whiter than milk.\nThey were more ruddy in body than rubies.\nTheir polishing was like sapphire.\n'),
	(15625, 22, 4, 8, 'Their appearance is blacker than a coal.\nThey are not known in the streets.\nTheir skin clings to their bones.\nIt is withered.\nIt has become like a stick.\n'),
	(15626, 22, 4, 9, 'Those who are killed with the sword are better than those who are killed with hunger;\nFor these pine away, stricken through,\nfor lack of the fruits of the field.\n'),
	(15627, 22, 4, 10, 'The hands of the pitiful women have boiled their own children.\nThey were their food in the destruction of the daughter of my people.\n'),
	(15628, 22, 4, 11, 'Yahweh has accomplished his wrath.\nHe has poured out his fierce anger.\nHe has kindled a fire in Zion,\nwhich has devoured its foundations.\n'),
	(15629, 22, 4, 12, 'The kings of the earth didn’t believe,\nneither did all the inhabitants of the world,\nthat the adversary and the enemy would enter into the gates of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(15630, 22, 4, 13, 'It is because of the sins of her prophets\nand the iniquities of her priests,\nThat have shed the blood of the just in the middle of her.\n'),
	(15631, 22, 4, 14, 'They wander as blind men in the streets.\nThey are polluted with blood,\nSo that men can’t touch their garments.\n'),
	(15632, 22, 4, 15, '“Go away!” they cried to them.\n“Unclean! Go away! Go away! Don’t touch!\nWhen they fled away and wandered, men said among the nations,\n“They can’t live here any more.”\n'),
	(15633, 22, 4, 16, 'Yahweh’s anger has scattered them.\nHe will not pay attention to them any more.\nThey didn’t respect the persons of the priests.\nThey didn’t favor the elders.\n'),
	(15634, 22, 4, 17, 'Our eyes still fail,\nlooking in vain for our help.\nIn our watching we have watched for a nation that could not save.\n'),
	(15635, 22, 4, 18, 'They hunt our steps,\nso that we can’t go in our streets.\nOur end is near.\nOur days are fulfilled,\nfor our end has come.\n'),
	(15636, 22, 4, 19, 'Our pursuers were swifter than the eagles of the sky.\nThey chased us on the mountains.\nThey set an ambush for us in the wilderness.\n'),
	(15637, 22, 4, 20, 'The breath of our nostrils,\nthe anointed of Yahweh,\nwas taken in their pits;\nof whom we said,\nunder his shadow we will live among the nations.\n'),
	(15638, 22, 4, 21, 'Rejoice and be glad, daughter of Edom,\nthat dwells in the land of Uz.\nThe cup will pass through to you also.\nYou will be drunken,\nand will make yourself naked.\n'),
	(15639, 22, 4, 22, 'The punishment of your iniquity is accomplished, daughter of Zion.\nHe will no more carry you away into captivity.\nHe will visit your iniquity, daughter of Edom.\nHe will uncover your sins.\n'),
	(15640, 22, 5, 1, 'Remember, Yahweh, what has come on us.\nLook, and see our reproach.\n'),
	(15641, 22, 5, 2, 'Our inheritance has been turned over to strangers,\nour houses to aliens.\n'),
	(15642, 22, 5, 3, 'We are orphans and fatherless.\nOur mothers are as widows.\n'),
	(15643, 22, 5, 4, 'We have drunken our water for money.\nOur wood is sold to us.\n'),
	(15644, 22, 5, 5, 'Our pursuers are on our necks.\nWe are weary, and have no rest.\n'),
	(15645, 22, 5, 6, 'We have given our hands to the Egyptians,\nand to the Assyrians, to be satisfied with bread.\n'),
	(15646, 22, 5, 7, 'Our fathers sinned, and are no more.\nWe have borne their iniquities.\n'),
	(15647, 22, 5, 8, 'Servants rule over us.\nThere is no one to deliver us out of their hand.\n'),
	(15648, 22, 5, 9, 'We get our bread at the peril of our lives,\nbecause of the sword of the wilderness.\n'),
	(15649, 22, 5, 10, 'Our skin is black like an oven,\nbecause of the burning heat of famine.\n'),
	(15650, 22, 5, 11, 'They ravished the women in Zion,\nthe virgins in the cities of Judah.\n'),
	(15651, 22, 5, 12, 'Princes were hanged up by their hands.\nThe faces of elders were not honored.\n'),
	(15652, 22, 5, 13, 'The young men carry millstones.\nThe children stumbled under loads of wood.\n'),
	(15653, 22, 5, 14, 'The elders have ceased from the gate,\nand the young men from their music.\n'),
	(15654, 22, 5, 15, 'The joy of our heart has ceased.\nOur dance is turned into mourning.\n'),
	(15655, 22, 5, 16, 'The crown has fallen from our head.\nWoe to us, for we have sinned!\n'),
	(15656, 22, 5, 17, 'For this our heart is faint.\nFor these things our eyes are dim.\n'),
	(15657, 22, 5, 18, 'For the mountain of Zion, which is desolate.\nThe foxes walk on it.\n'),
	(15658, 22, 5, 19, 'You, Yahweh, remain forever.\nYour throne is from generation to generation.\n'),
	(15659, 22, 5, 20, 'Why do you forget us forever,\nand forsake us for so long a time?\n'),
	(15660, 22, 5, 21, 'Turn us to yourself, Yahweh, and we will be turned.\nRenew our days as of old.\n'),
	(15661, 22, 5, 22, 'But you have utterly rejected us.\nYou are very angry against us.\n'),
	(15662, 23, 1, 1, 'Now in the thirtieth year, in the fourth month, in the fifth of the month, as I was among the captives by the river Chebar, the heavens were opened, and I saw visions of God.\n'),
	(15663, 23, 1, 2, 'In the fifth of the month, which was the fifth year of king Jehoiachin’s captivity,\n'),
	(15664, 23, 1, 3, 'Yahweh’s word came to Ezekiel the priest, the son of Buzi, in the land of the Chaldeans by the river Chebar; and Yahweh’s hand was there on him.\n'),
	(15665, 23, 1, 4, 'I looked, and behold, a stormy wind came out of the north: a great cloud, with flashing lightning, and a brightness around it, and out of the middle of it as it were glowing metal, out of the middle of the fire.\n'),
	(15666, 23, 1, 5, 'Out of its center came the likeness of four living creatures. This was their appearance: They had the likeness of a man.\n'),
	(15667, 23, 1, 6, 'Everyone had four faces, and each one of them had four wings.\n'),
	(15668, 23, 1, 7, 'Their feet were straight feet. The sole of their feet was like the sole of a calf’s foot; and they sparkled like burnished brass.\n'),
	(15669, 23, 1, 8, 'They had the hands of a man under their wings on their four sides. The four of them had their faces and their wings like this:\n'),
	(15670, 23, 1, 9, 'Their wings were joined to one another. They didn’t turn when they went. Each one went straight forward.\n'),
	(15671, 23, 1, 10, 'As for the likeness of their faces, they had the face of a man. The four of them had the face of a lion on the right side. The four of them had the face of an ox on the left side. The four of them also had the face of an eagle.\n'),
	(15672, 23, 1, 11, 'Such were their faces. Their wings were spread out above. Two wings of each one touched another, and two covered their bodies.\n'),
	(15673, 23, 1, 12, 'Each one went straight forward: where the spirit was to go, they went. They didn’t turn when they went.\n'),
	(15674, 23, 1, 13, 'As for the likeness of the living creatures, their appearance was like burning coals of fire, like the appearance of torches. The fire went up and down among the living creatures. The fire was bright, and lightning went out of the fire.\n'),
	(15675, 23, 1, 14, 'The living creatures ran and returned as the appearance of a flash of lightning.\n'),
	(15676, 23, 1, 15, 'Now as I saw the living creatures, behold, there was one wheel on the earth beside the living creatures, for each of the four faces of it.\n'),
	(15677, 23, 1, 16, 'The appearance of the wheels and their work was like a beryl. The four of them had one likeness. Their appearance and their work was as it were a wheel within a wheel.\n'),
	(15678, 23, 1, 17, 'When they went, they went in their four directions. They didn’t turn when they went.\n'),
	(15679, 23, 1, 18, 'As for their rims, they were high and dreadful; and the four of them had their rims full of eyes all around.\n'),
	(15680, 23, 1, 19, 'When the living creatures went, the wheels went beside them. Then the living creatures were lifted up from the earth, the wheels were lifted up.\n'),
	(15681, 23, 1, 20, 'Wherever the spirit was to go, they went. The spirit was to go there. The wheels were lifted up beside them; for the spirit of the living creature was in the wheels.\n'),
	(15682, 23, 1, 21, 'When those went, these went. When those stood, these stood. When those were lifted up from the earth, the wheels were lifted up beside them; for the spirit of the living creature was in the wheels.\n'),
	(15683, 23, 1, 22, 'Over the head of the living creature there was the likeness of an expanse, like an awesome crystal to look at, stretched out over their heads above.\n'),
	(15684, 23, 1, 23, 'Under the expanse, their wings were straight, one toward the other. Each one had two which covered on this side, and each one had two which covered their bodies on that side.\n'),
	(15685, 23, 1, 24, 'When they went, I heard the noise of their wings like the noise of great waters, like the voice of the Almighty, a noise of tumult like the noise of an army. When they stood, they let down their wings.\n'),
	(15686, 23, 1, 25, 'There was a voice above the expanse that was over their heads. When they stood, they let down their wings.\n'),
	(15687, 23, 1, 26, 'Above the expanse that was over their heads was the likeness of a throne, as the appearance of a sapphire stone. On the likeness of the throne was a likeness as the appearance of a man on it above.\n'),
	(15688, 23, 1, 27, 'I saw as it were glowing metal, as the appearance of fire within it all around, from the appearance of his waist and upward; and from the appearance of his waist and downward I saw as it were the appearance of fire, and there was brightness around him.\n'),
	(15689, 23, 1, 28, 'As the appearance of the rainbow that is in the cloud in the day of rain, so was the appearance of the brightness all around.\nThis was the appearance of the likeness of Yahweh’s glory. When I saw it, I fell on my face, and I heard a voice of one that spoke.\n'),
	(15690, 23, 2, 1, 'He said to me, “Son of man, stand on your feet, and I will speak with you.”\n'),
	(15691, 23, 2, 2, 'The Spirit entered into me when he spoke to me, and set me on my feet; and I heard him who spoke to me.\n'),
	(15692, 23, 2, 3, 'He said to me, “Son of man, I send you to the children of Israel, to a nation of rebels who have rebelled against me. They and their fathers have transgressed against me even to this very day.\n'),
	(15693, 23, 2, 4, 'The children are impudent and stiff-hearted. I am sending you to them, and you shall tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh.’\n'),
	(15694, 23, 2, 5, 'They, whether they will hear, or whether they will refuse, for they are a rebellious house, yet they will know that there has been a prophet among them.\n'),
	(15695, 23, 2, 6, 'You, son of man, don’t be afraid of them, neither be afraid of their words, though briers and thorns are with you, and you do dwell among scorpions. Don’t be afraid of their words, nor be dismayed at their looks, though they are a rebellious house.\n'),
	(15696, 23, 2, 7, 'You shall speak my words to them, whether they will hear, or whether they will refuse; for they are most rebellious.\n'),
	(15697, 23, 2, 8, 'But you, son of man, hear what I tell you. Don’t be rebellious like that rebellious house. Open your mouth, and eat that which I give you.”\n'),
	(15698, 23, 2, 9, 'When I looked, behold, a hand was stretched out to me; and, behold, a scroll of a book was in it.\n'),
	(15699, 23, 2, 10, 'He spread it before me. It was written within and without; and lamentations, mourning, and woe were written in it.\n'),
	(15700, 23, 3, 1, 'He said to me, “Son of man, eat what you find. Eat this scroll, and go, speak to the house of Israel.”\n'),
	(15701, 23, 3, 2, 'So I opened my mouth, and he caused me to eat the scroll.\n'),
	(15702, 23, 3, 3, 'He said to me, “Son of man, cause your belly to eat, and fill your bowels with this scroll that I give you.”\nThen I ate it; and it was as sweet as honey in my mouth.\n'),
	(15703, 23, 3, 4, 'He said to me, “Son of man, go to the house of Israel, and speak my words to them.\n'),
	(15704, 23, 3, 5, 'For you are not sent to a people of a strange speech and of a hard language, but to the house of Israel;\n'),
	(15705, 23, 3, 6, 'not to many peoples of a strange speech and of a hard language, whose words you can’t understand. Surely, if I sent you to them, they would listen to you.\n'),
	(15706, 23, 3, 7, 'But the house of Israel will not listen to you, for they will not listen to me; for all the house of Israel are obstinate and hard-hearted.\n'),
	(15707, 23, 3, 8, 'Behold, I have made your face hard against their faces, and your forehead hard against their foreheads.\n'),
	(15708, 23, 3, 9, 'I have made your forehead as a diamond, harder than flint. Don’t be afraid of them, neither be dismayed at their looks, though they are a rebellious house.”\n'),
	(15709, 23, 3, 10, 'Moreover he said to me, “Son of man, receive in your heart and hear with your ears all my words that I speak to you.\n'),
	(15710, 23, 3, 11, 'Go to them of the captivity, to the children of your people, and speak to them, and tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh;’ whether they will hear, or whether they will refuse.\n'),
	(15711, 23, 3, 12, 'Then the Spirit lifted me up, and I heard behind me the voice of a great rushing, saying, “Blessed be Yahweh’s glory from his place.”\n'),
	(15712, 23, 3, 13, 'I heard the noise of the wings of the living creatures as they touched one another, and the noise of the wheels beside them, even the noise of a great rushing.\n'),
	(15713, 23, 3, 14, 'So the Spirit lifted me up, and took me away; and I went in bitterness, in the heat of my spirit; and Yahweh’s hand was strong on me.\n'),
	(15714, 23, 3, 15, 'Then I came to them of the captivity at Tel Aviv, that lived by the river Chebar, and to where they lived; and I sat there overwhelmed among them seven days.\n'),
	(15715, 23, 3, 16, 'At the end of seven days, Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15716, 23, 3, 17, '“Son of man, I have made you a watchman to the house of Israel. Therefore hear the word from my mouth, and warn them from me.\n'),
	(15717, 23, 3, 18, 'When I tell the wicked, ‘You will surely die;’ and you give him no warning, nor speak to warn the wicked from his wicked way, to save his life; the same wicked man will die in his iniquity; but I will require his blood at your hand.\n'),
	(15718, 23, 3, 19, 'Yet if you warn the wicked, and he doesn’t turn from his wickedness, nor from his wicked way, he will die in his iniquity; but you have delivered your soul.”\n'),
	(15719, 23, 3, 20, '“Again, when a righteous man turns from his righteousness, and commits iniquity, and I lay a stumbling block before him, he will die. Because you have not given him warning, he will die in his sin, and his righteous deeds which he has done will not be remembered; but I will require his blood at your hand.\n'),
	(15720, 23, 3, 21, 'Nevertheless if you warn the righteous man, that the righteous not sin, and he does not sin, he will surely live, because he took warning; and you have delivered your soul.”\n'),
	(15721, 23, 3, 22, 'Yahweh’s hand was there on me; and he said to me, “Arise, go out into the plain, and I will talk with you there.”\n'),
	(15722, 23, 3, 23, 'Then I arose, and went out into the plain, and behold, Yahweh’s glory stood there, like the glory which I saw by the river Chebar. Then I fell on my face.\n'),
	(15723, 23, 3, 24, 'Then the Spirit entered into me, and set me on my feet. He spoke with me, and said to me, “Go, shut yourself inside your house.\n'),
	(15724, 23, 3, 25, 'But you, son of man, behold, they will put ropes on you, and will bind you with them, and you will not go out among them.\n'),
	(15725, 23, 3, 26, 'I will make your tongue stick to the roof of your mouth, that you will be mute, and will not be able to correct them; for they are a rebellious house.\n'),
	(15726, 23, 3, 27, 'But when I speak with you, I will open your mouth, and you shall tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh.’ He who hears, let him hear; and he who refuses, let him refuse; for they are a rebellious house.”\n'),
	(15727, 23, 4, 1, '“You also, son of man, take a tile, and lay it before yourself, and portray on it a city, even Jerusalem.\n'),
	(15728, 23, 4, 2, 'Lay siege against it, build forts against it, and cast up a mound against it. Also set camps against it and plant battering rams against it all around.\n'),
	(15729, 23, 4, 3, 'Take for yourself an iron pan, and set it for a wall of iron between you and the city. Then set your face toward it. It will be besieged, and you shall lay siege against it. This shall be a sign to the house of Israel.\n'),
	(15730, 23, 4, 4, '“Moreover lie on your left side, and lay the iniquity of the house of Israel on it. According to the number of the days that you shall lie on it, you shall bear their iniquity.\n'),
	(15731, 23, 4, 5, 'For I have appointed the years of their iniquity to be to you a number of days, even three hundred ninety days. So you shall bear the iniquity of the house of Israel.\n'),
	(15732, 23, 4, 6, '“Again, when you have accomplished these, you shall lie on your right side, and shall bear the iniquity of the house of Judah. I have appointed forty days, each day for a year, to you.\n'),
	(15733, 23, 4, 7, 'You shall set your face toward the siege of Jerusalem, with your arm uncovered; and you shall prophesy against it.\n'),
	(15734, 23, 4, 8, 'Behold, I put ropes on you, and you shall not turn yourself from one side to the other, until you have accomplished the days of your siege.\n'),
	(15735, 23, 4, 9, '“Take for yourself also wheat, barley, beans, lentils, millet, and spelt, and put them in one vessel. Make bread of it. According to the number of the days that you will lie on your side, even three hundred ninety days, you shall eat of it.\n'),
	(15736, 23, 4, 10, 'Your food which you shall eat shall be by weight, twenty shekels a day. From time to time you shall eat it.\n'),
	(15737, 23, 4, 11, 'You shall drink water by measure, the sixth part of a hin. From time to time you shall drink.\n'),
	(15738, 23, 4, 12, 'You shall eat it as barley cakes, and you shall bake it in their sight with dung that comes out of man.”\n'),
	(15739, 23, 4, 13, 'Yahweh said, “Even thus will the children of Israel eat their bread unclean, among the nations where I will drive them.”\n'),
	(15740, 23, 4, 14, 'Then I said, “Ah Lord Yahweh! Behold, my soul has not been polluted; for from my youth up even until now I have not eaten of that which dies of itself, or is torn of animals. No abominable meat has come into my mouth!”\n'),
	(15741, 23, 4, 15, 'Then he said to me, “Behold, I have given you cow’s dung for man’s dung, and you shall prepare your bread on it.”\n'),
	(15742, 23, 4, 16, 'Moreover he said to me, “Son of man, behold, I will break the staff of bread in Jerusalem. They will eat bread by weight, and with fearfulness. They will drink water by measure, and in dismay;\n'),
	(15743, 23, 4, 17, 'that they may lack bread and water, be dismayed one with another, and pine away in their iniquity.\n'),
	(15744, 23, 5, 1, '“You, son of man, take a sharp sword. You shall take it as a barber’s razor to yourself, and shall cause it to pass over your head and over your beard. Then take balances to weigh and divide the hair.\n'),
	(15745, 23, 5, 2, 'A third part you shall burn in the fire in the middle of the city, when the days of the siege are fulfilled. You shall take a third part, and strike with the sword around it. A third part you shall scatter to the wind, and I will draw out a sword after them.\n'),
	(15746, 23, 5, 3, 'You shall take of it a few in number, and bind them in the folds of your robe.\n'),
	(15747, 23, 5, 4, 'Of these again you shall take, and cast them into the middle of the fire, and burn them in the fire. From it a fire will come out into all the house of Israel.\n'),
	(15748, 23, 5, 5, '“Thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘This is Jerusalem. I have set her in the middle of the nations, and countries are around her.\n'),
	(15749, 23, 5, 6, 'She has rebelled against my ordinances in doing wickedness more than the nations, and against my statutes more than the countries that are around her; for they have rejected my ordinances, and as for my statutes, they have not walked in them.’\n'),
	(15750, 23, 5, 7, '“Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Because you are more turbulent than the nations that are around you, and have not walked in my statutes, neither have kept my ordinances, neither have followed the ordinances of the nations that are around you;\n'),
	(15751, 23, 5, 8, 'therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Behold, I, even I, am against you; and I will execute judgments among you in the sight of the nations.\n'),
	(15752, 23, 5, 9, 'I will do in you that which I have not done, and which I will not do anything like it any more, because of all your abominations.\n'),
	(15753, 23, 5, 10, 'Therefore the fathers will eat the sons within you, and the sons will eat their fathers. I will execute judgments on you; and I will scatter the whole remnant of you to all the winds.\n'),
	(15754, 23, 5, 11, 'Therefore as I live,’ says the Lord Yahweh, ‘surely, because you have defiled my sanctuary with all your detestable things, and with all your abominations, therefore I will also diminish you. My eye won’t spare, and I will have no pity.\n'),
	(15755, 23, 5, 12, 'A third part of you will die with the pestilence, and they will be consumed with famine within you. A third part will fall by the sword around you. A third part I will scatter to all the winds, and will draw out a sword after them.\n'),
	(15756, 23, 5, 13, '“‘Thus my anger will be accomplished, and I will cause my wrath toward them to rest, and I will be comforted. They will know that I, Yahweh, have spoken in my zeal, when I have accomplished my wrath on them.\n'),
	(15757, 23, 5, 14, '“‘Moreover I will make you a desolation and a reproach among the nations that are around you, in the sight of all that pass by.\n'),
	(15758, 23, 5, 15, 'So it will be a reproach and a taunt, an instruction and an astonishment, to the nations that are around you, when I execute judgments on you in anger and in wrath, and in wrathful rebukes—I, Yahweh, have spoken it—\n'),
	(15759, 23, 5, 16, 'when I send on them the evil arrows of famine that are for destruction, which I will send to destroy you. I will increase the famine on you, and will break your staff of bread.\n'),
	(15760, 23, 5, 17, 'I will send on you famine and evil animals, and they will bereave you. Pestilence and blood will pass through you. I will bring the sword on you. I, Yahweh, have spoken it.’”\n'),
	(15761, 23, 6, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15762, 23, 6, 2, '“Son of man, set your face toward the mountains of Israel, and prophesy to them,\n'),
	(15763, 23, 6, 3, 'and say, ‘You mountains of Israel, hear the word of the Lord Yahweh! Thus says the Lord Yahweh to the mountains and to the hills, to the watercourses and to the valleys: “Behold, I, even I, will bring a sword on you, and I will destroy your high places.\n'),
	(15764, 23, 6, 4, 'Your altars will become desolate, and your incense altars will be broken. I will cast down your slain men before your idols.\n'),
	(15765, 23, 6, 5, 'I will lay the dead bodies of the children of Israel before their idols. I will scatter your bones around your altars.\n'),
	(15766, 23, 6, 6, 'In all your dwelling places, the cities will be laid waste and the high places will be desolate; that your altars may be laid waste and made desolate, and your idols may be broken and cease, and your incense altars may be cut down, and your works may be abolished.\n'),
	(15767, 23, 6, 7, 'The slain will fall among you, and you will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(15768, 23, 6, 8, '“‘“Yet I will leave a remnant, in that you will have some that escape the sword among the nations, when you are scattered through the countries.\n'),
	(15769, 23, 6, 9, 'Those of you that escape will remember me among the nations where they are carried captive, how I have been broken with their lewd heart, which has departed from me, and with their eyes, which play the prostitute after their idols. Then they will loathe themselves in their own sight for the evils which they have committed in all their abominations.\n'),
	(15770, 23, 6, 10, 'They will know that I am Yahweh. I have not said in vain that I would do this evil to them.”’\n'),
	(15771, 23, 6, 11, '“Thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Strike with your hand, and stamp with your foot, and say, “Alas!” Because of all the evil abominations of the house of Israel; for they will fall by the sword, by the famine, and by the pestilence.\n'),
	(15772, 23, 6, 12, 'He who is far off will die of the pestilence. He who is near will fall by the sword. He who remains and is besieged will die by the famine. Thus I will accomplish my wrath on them.\n'),
	(15773, 23, 6, 13, 'You will know that I am Yahweh, when their slain men are among their idols around their altars, on every high hill, on all the tops of the mountains, under every green tree, and under every thick oak, the places where they offered pleasant aroma to all their idols.\n'),
	(15774, 23, 6, 14, 'I will stretch out my hand on them, and make the land desolate and waste, from the wilderness toward Diblah, throughout all their habitations. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(15775, 23, 7, 1, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15776, 23, 7, 2, '“You, son of man, thus says the Lord Yahweh to the land of Israel, ‘An end! The end has come on the four corners of the land.\n'),
	(15777, 23, 7, 3, 'Now is the end on you, and I will send my anger on you, and will judge you according to your ways. I will bring on you all your abominations.\n'),
	(15778, 23, 7, 4, 'My eye will not spare you, neither will I have pity; but I will bring your ways on you, and your abominations will be among you. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.’\n'),
	(15779, 23, 7, 5, '“Thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘An evil! A unique evil! Behold, it comes.\n'),
	(15780, 23, 7, 6, 'An end has come. The end has come! It awakes against you. Behold, it comes.\n'),
	(15781, 23, 7, 7, 'Your doom has come to you, inhabitant of the land! The time has come! The day is near, a day of tumult, and not of joyful shouting, on the mountains.\n'),
	(15782, 23, 7, 8, 'Now I will shortly pour out my wrath on you, and accomplish my anger against you, and will judge you according to your ways. I will bring on you all your abominations.\n'),
	(15783, 23, 7, 9, 'My eye won’t spare, neither will I have pity. I will punish you according to your ways. Your abominations will be among you. Then you will know that I, Yahweh, strike.\n'),
	(15784, 23, 7, 10, '“‘Behold, the day! Behold, it comes! Your doom has gone out. The rod has blossomed. Pride has budded.\n'),
	(15785, 23, 7, 11, 'Violence has risen up into a rod of wickedness. None of them will remain, nor of their multitude, nor of their wealth. There will be nothing of value among them.\n'),
	(15786, 23, 7, 12, 'The time has come! The day draws near. Don’t let the buyer rejoice, nor the seller mourn; for wrath is on all its multitude.\n'),
	(15787, 23, 7, 13, 'For the seller won’t return to that which is sold, although they are still alive; for the vision concerns the whole multitude of it. None will return. None will strengthen himself in the iniquity of his life.\n'),
	(15788, 23, 7, 14, 'They have blown the trumpet, and have made all ready; but no one goes to the battle; for my wrath is on all its multitude.\n'),
	(15789, 23, 7, 15, '“‘The sword is outside, and the pestilence and the famine within. He who is in the field will die by the sword. He who is in the city will be devoured by famine and pestilence.\n'),
	(15790, 23, 7, 16, 'But those of those who escape, they will escape and will be on the mountains like doves of the valleys, all of them moaning, everyone in his iniquity.\n'),
	(15791, 23, 7, 17, 'All hands will be feeble, and all knees will be weak as water.\n'),
	(15792, 23, 7, 18, 'They will also clothe themselves with sackcloth, and horror will cover them. Shame will be on all faces, and baldness on all their heads.\n'),
	(15793, 23, 7, 19, 'They will cast their silver in the streets, and their gold will be as an unclean thing. Their silver and their gold won’t be able to deliver them in the day of Yahweh’s wrath. They won’t satisfy their souls or fill their bellies; because it has been the stumbling block of their iniquity.\n'),
	(15794, 23, 7, 20, 'As for the beauty of his ornament, he set it in majesty; but they made the images of their abominations and their detestable things therein. Therefore I have made it to them as an unclean thing.\n'),
	(15795, 23, 7, 21, 'I will give it into the hands of the strangers for a prey, and to the wicked of the earth for a plunder; and they will profane it.\n'),
	(15796, 23, 7, 22, 'I will also turn my face from them, and they will profane my secret place. Robbers will enter into it, and profane it.\n'),
	(15797, 23, 7, 23, '“‘Make chains; for the land is full of bloody crimes, and the city is full of violence.\n'),
	(15798, 23, 7, 24, 'Therefore I will bring the worst of the nations, and they will possess their houses. I will also make the pride of the strong to cease. Their holy places will be profaned.\n'),
	(15799, 23, 7, 25, 'Destruction comes! They will seek peace, and there will be none.\n'),
	(15800, 23, 7, 26, 'Mischief will come on mischief, and rumor will be on rumor. They will seek a vision of the prophet; but the law will perish from the priest, and counsel from the elders.\n'),
	(15801, 23, 7, 27, 'The king will mourn, and the prince will be clothed with desolation. The hands of the people of the land will be troubled. I will do to them after their way, and according to their own judgments I will judge them. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(15802, 23, 8, 1, 'In the sixth year, in the sixth month, in the fifth day of the month, as I sat in my house, and the elders of Judah sat before me, the Lord Yahweh’s hand fell on me there.\n'),
	(15803, 23, 8, 2, 'Then I saw, and behold, a likeness as the appearance of fire; from the appearance of his waist and downward, fire; and from his waist and upward, as the appearance of brightness, as it were glowing metal.\n'),
	(15804, 23, 8, 3, 'He stretched out the form of a hand, and took me by a lock of my head; and the Spirit lifted me up between earth and the sky, and brought me in the visions of God to Jerusalem, to the door of the gate of the inner court that looks toward the north; where there was the seat of the image of jealousy, which provokes to jealousy.\n'),
	(15805, 23, 8, 4, 'Behold, the glory of the God of Israel was there, according to the appearance that I saw in the plain.\n'),
	(15806, 23, 8, 5, 'Then he said to me, “Son of man, lift up your eyes now the way toward the north.”\nSo I lifted up my eyes the way toward the north, and saw, northward of the gate of the altar this image of jealousy in the entry.\n'),
	(15807, 23, 8, 6, 'He said to me, “Son of man, do you see what they do? Even the great abominations that the house of Israel commit here, that I should go far off from my sanctuary? But you will again see yet other great abominations.”\n'),
	(15808, 23, 8, 7, 'He brought me to the door of the court; and when I looked, behold, a hole in the wall.\n'),
	(15809, 23, 8, 8, 'Then he said to me, “Son of man, dig now in the wall.”\nWhen I had dug in the wall, I saw a door.\n'),
	(15810, 23, 8, 9, 'He said to me, “Go in, and see the wicked abominations that they do here.”\n'),
	(15811, 23, 8, 10, 'So I went in and looked, and saw every form of creeping things, abominable animals, and all the idols of the house of Israel, portrayed around on the wall.\n'),
	(15812, 23, 8, 11, 'Seventy men of the elders of the house of Israel stood before them. In the middle of them Jaazaniah the son of Shaphan stood, every man with his censer in his hand; and the smell of the cloud of incense went up.\n'),
	(15813, 23, 8, 12, 'Then he said to me, “Son of man, have you seen what the elders of the house of Israel do in the dark, every man in his rooms of imagery? For they say, ‘Yahweh doesn’t see us. Yahweh has forsaken the land.’”\n'),
	(15814, 23, 8, 13, 'He said also to me, “You will again see more of the great abominations which they do.”\n'),
	(15815, 23, 8, 14, 'Then he brought me to the door of the gate of Yahweh’s house which was toward the north; and I saw the women sit there weeping for Tammuz.\n'),
	(15816, 23, 8, 15, 'Then he said to me, “Have you seen this, son of man? You will again see yet greater abominations than these.”\n'),
	(15817, 23, 8, 16, 'He brought me into the inner court of Yahweh’s house; and I saw at the door of Yahweh’s temple, between the porch and the altar, there were about twenty-five men, with their backs toward Yahweh’s temple, and their faces toward the east. They were worshiping the sun toward the east.\n'),
	(15818, 23, 8, 17, 'Then he said to me, “Have you seen this, son of man? Is it a light thing to the house of Judah that they commit the abominations which they commit here? For they have filled the land with violence, and have turned again to provoke me to anger. Behold, they put the branch to their nose.\n'),
	(15819, 23, 8, 18, 'Therefore will I also deal in wrath. My eye won’t spare, neither will I have pity. Though they cry in my ears with a loud voice, yet I will not hear them.”\n'),
	(15820, 23, 9, 1, 'Then he cried in my ears with a loud voice, saying, “Cause those who are in charge of the city to draw near, each man with his destroying weapon in his hand.”\n'),
	(15821, 23, 9, 2, 'Behold, six men came from the way of the upper gate, which lies toward the north, every man with his slaughter weapon in his hand. One man in the middle of them was clothed in linen, with a writer’s inkhorn by his side. They went in, and stood beside the bronze altar.\n'),
	(15822, 23, 9, 3, 'The glory of the God of Israel went up from the cherub, whereupon it was, to the threshold of the house; and he called to the man clothed in linen, who had the writer’s inkhorn by his side.\n'),
	(15823, 23, 9, 4, 'Yahweh said to him, “Go through the middle of the city, through the middle of Jerusalem, and set a mark on the foreheads of the men that sigh and that cry over all the abominations that are done within it.”\n'),
	(15824, 23, 9, 5, 'To the others he said in my hearing, “Go through the city after him, and strike. Don’t let your eye spare, neither have pity.\n'),
	(15825, 23, 9, 6, 'Kill utterly the old man, the young man, the virgin, little children and women; but don’t come near any man on whom is the mark. Begin at my sanctuary.”\nThen they began at the old men who were before the house.\n'),
	(15826, 23, 9, 7, 'He said to them, “Defile the house, and fill the courts with the slain. Go out!”\nThey went out, and struck in the city.\n'),
	(15827, 23, 9, 8, 'While they were killing, and I was left, I fell on my face, and cried, and said, “Ah Lord Yahweh! Will you destroy all the residue of Israel in your pouring out of your wrath on Jerusalem?”\n'),
	(15828, 23, 9, 9, 'Then he said to me, “The iniquity of the house of Israel and Judah is exceedingly great, and the land is full of blood, and the city full of perversion; for they say, ‘Yahweh has forsaken the land, and Yahweh doesn’t see.’\n'),
	(15829, 23, 9, 10, 'As for me also, my eye won’t spare, neither will I have pity, but I will bring their way on their head.”\n'),
	(15830, 23, 9, 11, 'Behold, the man clothed in linen, who had the inkhorn by his side, reported the matter, saying, “I have done as you have commanded me.”\n'),
	(15831, 23, 10, 1, 'Then I looked, and see, in the expanse that was over the head of the cherubim there appeared above them as it were a sapphire stone, as the appearance of the likeness of a throne.\n'),
	(15832, 23, 10, 2, 'He spoke to the man clothed in linen, and said, “Go in between the whirling wheels, even under the cherub, and fill both your hands with coals of fire from between the cherubim, and scatter them over the city.”\nHe went in as I watched.\n'),
	(15833, 23, 10, 3, 'Now the cherubim stood on the right side of the house, when the man went in; and the cloud filled the inner court.\n'),
	(15834, 23, 10, 4, 'Yahweh’s glory mounted up from the cherub, and stood over the threshold of the house; and the house was filled with the cloud, and the court was full of the brightness of Yahweh’s glory.\n'),
	(15835, 23, 10, 5, 'The sound of the wings of the cherubim was heard even to the outer court, as the voice of God Almighty when he speaks.\n'),
	(15836, 23, 10, 6, 'It came to pass, when he commanded the man clothed in linen, saying, “Take fire from between the whirling wheels, from between the cherubim,” that he went in, and stood beside a wheel.\n'),
	(15837, 23, 10, 7, 'The cherub stretched out his hand from between the cherubim to the fire that was between the cherubim, and took some of it, and put it into the hands of him who was clothed in linen, who took it and went out.\n'),
	(15838, 23, 10, 8, 'The form of a man’s hand appeared here in the cherubim under their wings.\n'),
	(15839, 23, 10, 9, 'I looked, and behold, there were four wheels beside the cherubim, one wheel beside one cherub, and another wheel beside another cherub. The appearance of the wheels was like a beryl stone.\n'),
	(15840, 23, 10, 10, 'As for their appearance, the four of them had one likeness, like a wheel within a wheel.\n'),
	(15841, 23, 10, 11, 'When they went, they went in their four directions. They didn’t turn as they went, but to the place where the head looked they followed it. They didn’t turn as they went.\n'),
	(15842, 23, 10, 12, 'Their whole body, including their backs, their hands, their wings, and the wheels, were full of eyes all around, even the wheels that the four of them had.\n'),
	(15843, 23, 10, 13, 'As for the wheels, they were called in my hearing, “the whirling wheels”.\n'),
	(15844, 23, 10, 14, 'Every one them had four faces. The first face was the face of the cherub. The second face was the face of a man. The third face was the face of a lion. The fourth was the face of an eagle.\n'),
	(15845, 23, 10, 15, 'The cherubim mounted up. This is the living creature that I saw by the river Chebar.\n'),
	(15846, 23, 10, 16, 'When the cherubim went, the wheels went beside them; and when the cherubim lifted up their wings to mount up from the earth, the wheels also didn’t turn from beside them.\n'),
	(15847, 23, 10, 17, 'When they stood, these stood. When they mounted up, these mounted up with them; for the spirit of the living creature was in them.\n'),
	(15848, 23, 10, 18, 'Yahweh’s glory went out from over the threshold of the house, and stood over the cherubim.\n'),
	(15849, 23, 10, 19, 'The cherubim lifted up their wings, and mounted up from the earth in my sight when they went out, with the wheels beside them. Then they stood at the door of the east gate of Yahweh’s house; and the glory of the God of Israel was over them above.\n'),
	(15850, 23, 10, 20, 'This is the living creature that I saw under the God of Israel by the river Chebar; and I knew that they were cherubim.\n'),
	(15851, 23, 10, 21, 'Every one had four faces, and every one four wings. The likeness of the hands of a man was under their wings.\n'),
	(15852, 23, 10, 22, 'As for the likeness of their faces, they were the faces which I saw by the river Chebar, their appearances and themselves. They each went straight forward.\n'),
	(15853, 23, 11, 1, 'Moreover the Spirit lifted me up, and brought me to the east gate of Yahweh’s house, which looks eastward. Behold, twenty-five men were at the door of the gate; and I saw among them Jaazaniah the son of Azzur, and Pelatiah the son of Benaiah, princes of the people.\n'),
	(15854, 23, 11, 2, 'He said to me, “Son of man, these are the men who devise iniquity, and who give wicked counsel in this city;\n'),
	(15855, 23, 11, 3, 'who say, ‘The time is not near to build houses. This is the cauldron, and we are the meat.’\n'),
	(15856, 23, 11, 4, 'Therefore prophesy against them. Prophesy, son of man.”\n'),
	(15857, 23, 11, 5, 'Yahweh’s Spirit fell on me, and he said to me, “Speak, ‘Yahweh says: “Thus you have said, house of Israel; for I know the things that come into your mind.\n'),
	(15858, 23, 11, 6, 'You have multiplied your slain in this city, and you have filled its streets with the slain.\n'),
	(15859, 23, 11, 7, '“‘Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Your slain whom you have laid in the middle of it, they are the meat, and this is the cauldron; but you will be brought out of the middle of it.\n'),
	(15860, 23, 11, 8, 'You have feared the sword; and I will bring the sword on you,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(15861, 23, 11, 9, '“I will bring you out of the middle of it, and deliver you into the hands of strangers, and will execute judgments among you.\n'),
	(15862, 23, 11, 10, 'You will fall by the sword. I will judge you in the border of Israel. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(15863, 23, 11, 11, 'This will not be your cauldron, neither will you be the meat in the middle of it. I will judge you in the border of Israel.\n'),
	(15864, 23, 11, 12, 'You will know that I am Yahweh, for you have not walked in my statutes, You have not executed my ordinances, but have done after the ordinances of the nations that are around you.”’”\n'),
	(15865, 23, 11, 13, 'When I prophesied, Pelatiah the son of Benaiah died. Then fell I down on my face, and cried with a loud voice, and said, “Ah Lord Yahweh! will you make a full end of the remnant of Israel?”\n'),
	(15866, 23, 11, 14, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15867, 23, 11, 15, '“Son of man, your brothers, even your brothers, the men of your relatives, and all the house of Israel, all of them, are they to whom the inhabitants of Jerusalem have said, ‘Go far away from Yahweh. This land has been given to us for a possession.’”\n'),
	(15868, 23, 11, 16, '“Therefore say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Whereas I have removed them far off among the nations, and whereas I have scattered them among the countries, yet I will be to them a sanctuary for a little while in the countries where they have come.”’\n'),
	(15869, 23, 11, 17, '“Therefore say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “I will gather you from the peoples, and assemble you out of the countries where you have been scattered, and I will give you the land of Israel.”\n'),
	(15870, 23, 11, 18, '“‘They will come there, and they will take away all its detestable things and all its abominations from there.\n'),
	(15871, 23, 11, 19, 'I will give them one heart, and I will put a new spirit within you. I will take the stony heart out of their flesh, and will give them a heart of flesh;\n'),
	(15872, 23, 11, 20, 'that they may walk in my statutes, and keep my ordinances, and do them. They will be my people, and I will be their God.\n'),
	(15873, 23, 11, 21, 'But as for them whose heart walks after the heart of their detestable things and their abominations, I will bring their way on their own heads,’ says the Lord Yahweh.”\n'),
	(15874, 23, 11, 22, 'Then the cherubim lifted up their wings, and the wheels were beside them. The glory of the God of Israel was over them above.\n'),
	(15875, 23, 11, 23, 'Yahweh’s glory went up from the middle of the city, and stood on the mountain which is on the east side of the city.\n'),
	(15876, 23, 11, 24, 'The Spirit lifted me up, and brought me in the vision by the Spirit of God into Chaldea, to the captives.\nSo the vision that I had seen went up from me.\n'),
	(15877, 23, 11, 25, 'Then I spoke to the captives all the things that Yahweh had shown me.\n'),
	(15878, 23, 12, 1, 'Yahweh’s word also came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15879, 23, 12, 2, '“Son of man, you dwell in the middle of the rebellious house, who have eyes to see, and don’t see, who have ears to hear, and don’t hear; for they are a rebellious house.\n'),
	(15880, 23, 12, 3, '“Therefore, you son of man, prepare your stuff for moving, and move by day in their sight. You shall move from your place to another place in their sight. It may be they will consider, though they are a rebellious house.\n'),
	(15881, 23, 12, 4, 'You shall bring out your stuff by day in their sight, as stuff for moving. You shall go out yourself at evening in their sight, as when men go out into exile.\n'),
	(15882, 23, 12, 5, 'Dig through the wall in their sight, and carry your stuff out that way.\n'),
	(15883, 23, 12, 6, 'In their sight you shall bear it on your shoulder, and carry it out in the dark. You shall cover your face, so that you don’t see the land, for I have set you for a sign to the house of Israel.”\n'),
	(15884, 23, 12, 7, 'I did so as I was commanded. I brought out my stuff by day, as stuff for moving, and in the evening I dug through the wall with my hand. I brought it out in the dark, and bore it on my shoulder in their sight.\n'),
	(15885, 23, 12, 8, 'In the morning, Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15886, 23, 12, 9, '“Son of man, hasn’t the house of Israel, the rebellious house, said to you, ‘What are you doing?’\n'),
	(15887, 23, 12, 10, '“Say to them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “This burden concerns the prince in Jerusalem, and all the house of Israel among whom they are.”’\n'),
	(15888, 23, 12, 11, '“Say, ‘I am your sign. As I have done, so will it be done to them. They will go into exile, into captivity.\n'),
	(15889, 23, 12, 12, '“‘The prince who is among them will bear on his shoulder in the dark, and will go out. They will dig through the wall to carry things out that way. He will cover his face, because he will not see the land with his eyes.\n'),
	(15890, 23, 12, 13, 'I will also spread my net on him, and he will be taken in my snare. I will bring him to Babylon to the land of the Chaldeans; yet he will not see it, though he will die there.\n'),
	(15891, 23, 12, 14, 'I will scatter toward every wind all who are around him to help him, and all his bands. I will draw out the sword after them.\n'),
	(15892, 23, 12, 15, '“‘They will know that I am Yahweh when I disperse them among the nations, and scatter them through the countries.\n'),
	(15893, 23, 12, 16, 'But I will leave a few men of them from the sword, from the famine, and from the pestilence, that they may declare all their abominations among the nations where they come. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(15894, 23, 12, 17, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15895, 23, 12, 18, '“Son of man, eat your bread with quaking, and drink your water with trembling and with fearfulness.\n'),
	(15896, 23, 12, 19, 'Tell the people of the land, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh concerning the inhabitants of Jerusalem, and the land of Israel: “They will eat their bread with fearfulness, and drink their water in dismay, that her land may be desolate, and all that is therein, because of the violence of all those who dwell therein.\n'),
	(15897, 23, 12, 20, 'The cities that are inhabited will be laid waste, and the land will be a desolation. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.”’”\n'),
	(15898, 23, 12, 21, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15899, 23, 12, 22, '“Son of man, what is this proverb that you have in the land of Israel, saying, ‘The days are prolonged, and every vision fails?’\n'),
	(15900, 23, 12, 23, 'Tell them therefore, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “I will make this proverb to cease, and they will no more use it as a proverb in Israel;”’ but tell them, ‘“The days are at hand, and the fulfillment of every vision.\n'),
	(15901, 23, 12, 24, 'For there will be no more any false vision nor flattering divination within the house of Israel.\n'),
	(15902, 23, 12, 25, 'For I am Yahweh. I will speak, and the word that I speak will be performed. It will be no more deferred; for in your days, rebellious house, I will speak the word, and will perform it,” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(15903, 23, 12, 26, 'Again Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15904, 23, 12, 27, '“Son of man, behold, they of the house of Israel say, ‘The vision that he sees is for many day to come, and he prophesies of times that are far off.’\n'),
	(15905, 23, 12, 28, '“Therefore tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “None of my words will be deferred any more, but the word which I speak will be performed,” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(15906, 23, 13, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15907, 23, 13, 2, '“Son of man, prophesy against the prophets of Israel who prophesy, and say to those who prophesy out of their own heart, ‘Hear Yahweh’s word:\n'),
	(15908, 23, 13, 3, 'Thus says the Lord Yahweh, “Woe to the foolish prophets, who follow their own spirit, and have seen nothing!\n'),
	(15909, 23, 13, 4, 'Israel, your prophets have been like foxes in the waste places.\n'),
	(15910, 23, 13, 5, 'You have not gone up into the gaps or built up the wall for the house of Israel, to stand in the battle in Yahweh’s day.\n'),
	(15911, 23, 13, 6, 'They have seen falsehood and lying divination, who say, ‘Yahweh says;’ but Yahweh has not sent them. They have made men to hope that the word would be confirmed.\n'),
	(15912, 23, 13, 7, 'Haven’t you seen a false vision, and haven’t you spoken a lying divination, in that you say, ‘Yahweh says;’ but I have not spoken?”\n'),
	(15913, 23, 13, 8, '“‘Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Because you have spoken falsehood and seen lies, therefore, behold, I am against you,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(15914, 23, 13, 9, '“My hand will be against the prophets who see false visions and who utter lying divinations. They will not be in the council of my people, neither will they be written in the writing of the house of Israel, neither will they enter into the land of Israel. Then you will know that I am the Lord Yahweh”\n'),
	(15915, 23, 13, 10, '“‘Because, even because they have seduced my people, saying, “Peace;” and there is no peace. When one builds up a wall, behold, they plaster it with whitewash.\n'),
	(15916, 23, 13, 11, 'Tell those who plaster it with whitewash that it will fall. There will be an overflowing shower; and you, great hailstones, will fall. A stormy wind will tear it.\n'),
	(15917, 23, 13, 12, 'Behold, when the wall has fallen, won’t it be said to you, “Where is the plaster with which you have plastered it?”\n'),
	(15918, 23, 13, 13, '“‘Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: “I will even tear it with a stormy wind in my wrath. There will be an overflowing shower in my anger, and great hailstones in wrath to consume it.\n'),
	(15919, 23, 13, 14, 'So will I break down the wall that you have plastered with whitewash, and bring it down to the ground, so that its foundation will be uncovered. It will fall, and you will be consumed in the middle of it. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(15920, 23, 13, 15, 'Thus will I accomplish my wrath on the wall, and on those who have plastered it with whitewash. I will tell you, ‘The wall is no more, neither those who plastered it;\n'),
	(15921, 23, 13, 16, 'to wit, the prophets of Israel who prophesy concerning Jerusalem, and who see visions of peace for her, and there is no peace,’” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(15922, 23, 13, 17, 'You, son of man, set your face against the daughters of your people, who prophesy out of their own heart; and prophesy against them,\n'),
	(15923, 23, 13, 18, 'and say, “Thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Woe to the women who sew pillows on all elbows, and make kerchiefs for the head of persons of every stature to hunt souls! Will you hunt the souls of my people, and save souls alive for yourselves?\n'),
	(15924, 23, 13, 19, 'You have profaned me among my people for handfuls of barley and for pieces of bread, to kill the souls who should not die, and to save the souls alive who should not live, by your lying to my people who listen to lies.’\n'),
	(15925, 23, 13, 20, '“Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Behold, I am against your pillows, with which you hunt the souls to make them fly, and I will tear them from your arms. I will let the souls go, even the souls whom you hunt to make them fly.\n'),
	(15926, 23, 13, 21, 'I will also tear your kerchiefs, and deliver my people out of your hand, and they will be no more in your hand to be hunted. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(15927, 23, 13, 22, 'Because with lies you have grieved the heart of the righteous, whom I have not made sad; and strengthened the hands of the wicked, that he should not return from his wicked way, and be saved alive.\n'),
	(15928, 23, 13, 23, 'Therefore you shall no more see false visions, nor practice divination. I will deliver my people out of your hand. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(15929, 23, 14, 1, 'Then some of the elders of Israel came to me, and sat before me.\n'),
	(15930, 23, 14, 2, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15931, 23, 14, 3, '“Son of man, these men have taken their idols into their heart, and put the stumbling block of their iniquity before their face. Should I be inquired of at all by them?\n'),
	(15932, 23, 14, 4, 'Therefore speak to them, and tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Every man of the house of Israel who takes his idols into his heart, and puts the stumbling block of his iniquity before his face, and comes to the prophet; I Yahweh will answer him therein according to the multitude of his idols;\n'),
	(15933, 23, 14, 5, 'that I may take the house of Israel in their own heart, because they are all estranged from me through their idols.”’\n'),
	(15934, 23, 14, 6, '“Therefore tell the house of Israel, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Return, and turn yourselves from your idols! Turn away your faces from all your abominations.\n'),
	(15935, 23, 14, 7, '“‘“For everyone of the house of Israel, or of the strangers who live in Israel, who separates himself from me, and takes his idols into his heart, and puts the stumbling block of his iniquity before his face, and comes to the prophet to inquire for himself of me; I Yahweh will answer him by myself.\n'),
	(15936, 23, 14, 8, 'I will set my face against that man, and will make him an astonishment, for a sign and a proverb, and I will cut him off from among my people. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(15937, 23, 14, 9, '“‘“If the prophet is deceived and speaks a word, I, Yahweh, have deceived that prophet, and I will stretch out my hand on him, and will destroy him from among my people Israel.\n'),
	(15938, 23, 14, 10, 'They will bear their iniquity. The iniquity of the prophet will be even as the iniquity of him who seeks him;\n'),
	(15939, 23, 14, 11, 'that the house of Israel may no more go astray from me, neither defile themselves any more with all their transgressions; but that they may be my people, and I may be their God,” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(15940, 23, 14, 12, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15941, 23, 14, 13, '“Son of man, when a land sins against me by committing a trespass, and I stretch out my hand on it, and break the staff of its bread, and send famine on it, and cut off from it man and animal;\n'),
	(15942, 23, 14, 14, 'though these three men, Noah, Daniel, and Job, were in it, they would deliver only their own souls by their righteousness,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(15943, 23, 14, 15, '“If I cause evil animals to pass through the land, and they ravage it, and it is made desolate, so that no man may pass through because of the animals;\n'),
	(15944, 23, 14, 16, 'though these three men were in it, as I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “they would deliver neither sons nor daughters. They only would be delivered, but the land would be desolate.\n'),
	(15945, 23, 14, 17, '“Or if I bring a sword on that land, and say, ‘Sword, go through the land; so that I cut off from it man and animal;’\n'),
	(15946, 23, 14, 18, 'though these three men were in it, as I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “they would deliver neither sons nor daughters, but they only would be delivered themselves.\n'),
	(15947, 23, 14, 19, '“Or if I send a pestilence into that land, and pour out my wrath on it in blood, to cut off from it man and animal;\n'),
	(15948, 23, 14, 20, 'though Noah, Daniel, and Job, were in it, as I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “they would deliver neither son nor daughter; they would deliver only their own souls by their righteousness.”\n'),
	(15949, 23, 14, 21, 'For thus says the Lord Yahweh: “How much more when I send my four severe judgments on Jerusalem, the sword, the famine, the evil animals, and the pestilence, to cut off from it man and animal!\n'),
	(15950, 23, 14, 22, 'Yet, behold, there will be left a remnant in it that will be carried out, both sons and daughters. Behold, they will come out to you, and you will see their way and their doings. Then you will be comforted concerning the evil that I have brought on Jerusalem, even concerning all that I have brought on it.\n'),
	(15951, 23, 14, 23, 'They will comfort you, when you see their way and their doings; then you will know that I have not done all that I have done in it without cause,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(15952, 23, 15, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15953, 23, 15, 2, '“Son of man, what is the vine tree more than any tree, the vine-branch which is among the trees of the forest?\n'),
	(15954, 23, 15, 3, 'Will wood be taken of it to make anything? Will men take a pin of it to hang any vessel on it?\n'),
	(15955, 23, 15, 4, 'Behold, it is cast into the fire for fuel; the fire has devoured both its ends, and the middle of it is burned. Is it profitable for any work?\n'),
	(15956, 23, 15, 5, 'Behold, when it was whole, it was suitable for no work. How much less, when the fire has devoured it, and it has been burned, will it yet be suitable for any work?”\n'),
	(15957, 23, 15, 6, 'Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: “As the vine tree among the trees of the forest, which I have given to the fire for fuel, so I will give the inhabitants of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(15958, 23, 15, 7, 'I will set my face against them. They will go out from the fire, but the fire will devour them. Then you will know that I am Yahweh, when I set my face against them.\n'),
	(15959, 23, 15, 8, 'I will make the land desolate, because they have committed a trespass,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(15960, 23, 16, 1, 'Again Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(15961, 23, 16, 2, '“Son of man, cause Jerusalem to know her abominations;\n'),
	(15962, 23, 16, 3, 'and say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh to Jerusalem: “Your origin and your birth is of the land of the Canaanite. An Amorite was your father, and your mother was a Hittite.\n'),
	(15963, 23, 16, 4, 'As for your birth, in the day you were born your navel was not cut. You weren’t washed in water to cleanse you. You weren’t salted at all, nor swaddled at all.\n'),
	(15964, 23, 16, 5, 'No eye pitied you, to do any of these things to you, to have compassion on you; but you were cast out in the open field, because you were abhorred in the day that you were born.\n'),
	(15965, 23, 16, 6, '“‘“When I passed by you, and saw you wallowing in your blood, I said to you, ‘Though you are in your blood, live!’ Yes, I said to you, ‘Though you are in your blood, live!’\n'),
	(15966, 23, 16, 7, 'I caused you to multiply as that which grows in the field, and you increased and grew great, and you attained to excellent ornament. Your breasts were formed, and your hair grew; yet you were naked and bare.\n'),
	(15967, 23, 16, 8, '“‘“Now when I passed by you, and looked at you, behold, your time was the time of love; and I spread my skirt over you, and covered your nakedness. Yes, I swore to you, and entered into a covenant with you,” says the Lord Yahweh, “and you became mine.\n'),
	(15968, 23, 16, 9, '“‘“Then washed I you with water. Yes, I thoroughly washed away your blood from you, and I anointed you with oil.\n'),
	(15969, 23, 16, 10, 'I clothed you also with embroidered work, and put sealskin shoes on you. I dressed you with fine linen and covered you with silk.\n'),
	(15970, 23, 16, 11, 'I decked you with ornaments. put bracelets on your hands, and a chain on your neck.\n'),
	(15971, 23, 16, 12, 'I put a ring on your nose, and earrings in your ears, and a beautiful crown on your head.\n'),
	(15972, 23, 16, 13, 'Thus you were decked with gold and silver. Your clothing was of fine linen, silk, and embroidered work. You ate fine flour, honey, and oil. You were exceedingly beautiful, and you prospered to royal estate.\n'),
	(15973, 23, 16, 14, 'Your renown went out among the nations for your beauty; for it was perfect, through my majesty which I had put on you,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(15974, 23, 16, 15, '“‘“But you trusted in your beauty, and played the prostitute because of your renown, and poured out your prostitution on everyone who passed by. It was his.\n'),
	(15975, 23, 16, 16, 'You took some of your garments, and made for yourselves high places decked with various colors, and played the prostitute on them. This shall not happen, neither shall it be.\n'),
	(15976, 23, 16, 17, 'You also took your beautiful jewels of my gold and of my silver, which I had given you, and made for yourself images of men, and played the prostitute with them.\n'),
	(15977, 23, 16, 18, 'You took your embroidered garments, covered them, and set my oil and my incense before them.\n'),
	(15978, 23, 16, 19, 'My bread also which I gave you, fine flour, oil, and honey, with which I fed you, you even set it before them for a pleasant aroma; and so it was,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(15979, 23, 16, 20, '“‘“Moreover you have taken your sons and your daughters, whom you have borne to me, and you have sacrificed these to them to be devoured. Was your prostitution a small matter,\n'),
	(15980, 23, 16, 21, 'that you have slain my children, and delivered them up, in causing them to pass through the fire to them?\n'),
	(15981, 23, 16, 22, 'In all your abominations and your prostitution you have not remembered the days of your youth, when you were naked and bare, and were wallowing in your blood.\n'),
	(15982, 23, 16, 23, '“‘“It has happened after all your wickedness. Woe, woe to you!” says the Lord Yahweh,\n'),
	(15983, 23, 16, 24, '“that you have built for yourselves a vaulted place, and have made yourselves a lofty place in every street.\n'),
	(15984, 23, 16, 25, 'You have built your lofty place at the head of every way, and have made your beauty an abomination, and have opened your feet to everyone who passed by, and multiplied your prostitution.\n'),
	(15985, 23, 16, 26, 'You have also committed sexual immorality with the Egyptians, your neighbors, great of flesh; and have multiplied your prostitution, to provoke me to anger.\n'),
	(15986, 23, 16, 27, 'See therefore, I have stretched out my hand over you, and have diminished your portion, and delivered you to the will of those who hate you, the daughters of the Philistines, who are ashamed of your lewd way.\n'),
	(15987, 23, 16, 28, 'You have played the prostitute also with the Assyrians, because you were insatiable; yes, you have played the prostitute with them, and yet you weren’t satisfied.\n'),
	(15988, 23, 16, 29, 'You have moreover multiplied your prostitution to the land of merchants, to Chaldea; and yet you weren’t satisfied with this.\n'),
	(15989, 23, 16, 30, '“‘“How weak is your heart,” says the Lord Yahweh, “since you do all these things, the work of an impudent prostitute;\n'),
	(15990, 23, 16, 31, 'in that you build your vaulted place at the head of every way, and make your lofty place in every street, and have not been as a prostitute, in that you scorn pay.\n'),
	(15991, 23, 16, 32, '“‘“A wife who commits adultery! Who takes strangers instead of her husband!\n'),
	(15992, 23, 16, 33, 'People give gifts to all prostitutes; but you give your gifts to all your lovers, and bribe them, that they may come to you on every side for your prostitution.\n'),
	(15993, 23, 16, 34, 'You are different from other women in your prostitution, in that no one follows you to play the prostitute; and whereas you give hire, and no hire is given to you, therefore you are different.”’\n'),
	(15994, 23, 16, 35, '“Therefore, prostitute, hear Yahweh’s word:\n'),
	(15995, 23, 16, 36, '‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh, “Because your filthiness was poured out, and your nakedness uncovered through your prostitution with your lovers; and because of all the idols of your abominations, and for the blood of your children, that you gave to them;\n'),
	(15996, 23, 16, 37, 'therefore see, I will gather all your lovers, with whom you have taken pleasure, and all those who you have loved, with all those who you have hated. I will even gather them against you on every side, and will uncover your nakedness to them, that they may see all your nakedness.\n'),
	(15997, 23, 16, 38, 'I will judge you, as women who break wedlock and shed blood are judged; and I will bring on you the blood of wrath and jealousy.\n'),
	(15998, 23, 16, 39, 'I will also give you into their hand, and they will throw down your vaulted place, and break down your lofty places. They will strip you of your clothes, and take your beautiful jewels. They will leave you naked and bare.\n'),
	(15999, 23, 16, 40, 'They will also bring up a company against you, and they will stone you with stones, and thrust you through with their swords.\n'),
	(16000, 23, 16, 41, 'They will burn your houses with fire, and execute judgments on you in the sight of many women. I will cause you to cease from playing the prostitute, and you will also give no hire any more.\n'),
	(16001, 23, 16, 42, 'So will I cause my wrath toward you to rest, and my jealousy will depart from you. I will be quiet, and will not be angry any more.\n'),
	(16002, 23, 16, 43, '“‘“Because you have not remembered the days of your youth, but have raged against me in all these things; therefore, behold, I also will bring your way on your head,” says the Lord Yahweh: “and you shall not commit this lewdness with all your abominations.\n'),
	(16003, 23, 16, 44, '“‘“Behold, everyone who uses proverbs will use this proverb against you, saying, ‘As is the mother, so is her daughter.’\n'),
	(16004, 23, 16, 45, 'You are the daughter of your mother, who loathes her husband and her children; and you are the sister of your sisters, who loathed their husbands and their children. Your mother was a Hittite, and your father an Amorite.\n'),
	(16005, 23, 16, 46, 'Your elder sister is Samaria, who dwells at your left hand, she and her daughters; and your younger sister, who dwells at your right hand, is Sodom with her daughters.\n'),
	(16006, 23, 16, 47, 'Yet you have not walked in their ways, nor done their abominations; but soon you were more corrupt than they in all your ways.\n'),
	(16007, 23, 16, 48, 'As I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “Sodom your sister has not done, she nor her daughters, as you have done, you and your daughters.\n'),
	(16008, 23, 16, 49, '“‘“Behold, this was the iniquity of your sister Sodom: pride, fullness of bread, and prosperous ease was in her and in her daughters. She also didn’t strengthen the hand of the poor and needy.\n'),
	(16009, 23, 16, 50, 'They were haughty, and committed abomination before me. Therefore I took them away when I saw it.\n'),
	(16010, 23, 16, 51, 'Samaria hasn’t committed half of your sins; but you have multiplied your abominations more than they, and have justified your sisters by all your abominations which you have done.\n'),
	(16011, 23, 16, 52, 'You also bear your own shame yourself, in that you have given judgment for your sisters; through your sins that you have committed more abominable than they, they are more righteous than you. Yes, be also confounded, and bear your shame, in that you have justified your sisters.\n'),
	(16012, 23, 16, 53, '“‘“I will reverse their captivity, the captivity of Sodom and her daughters, and the captivity of Samaria and her daughters, and the captivity of your captives among them;\n'),
	(16013, 23, 16, 54, 'that you may bear your own shame, and may be ashamed because of all that you have done, in that you are a comfort to them.\n'),
	(16014, 23, 16, 55, 'Your sisters, Sodom and her daughters, will return to their former estate; and Samaria and her daughters will return to their former estate; and you and your daughters will return to your former estate.\n'),
	(16015, 23, 16, 56, 'For your sister Sodom was not mentioned by your mouth in the day of your pride,\n'),
	(16016, 23, 16, 57, 'before your wickedness was uncovered, as at the time of the reproach of the daughters of Syria, and of all who are around her, the daughters of the Philistines, who despise you all around.\n'),
	(16017, 23, 16, 58, 'You have borne your lewdness and your abominations,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(16018, 23, 16, 59, '“‘For thus says the Lord Yahweh: “I will also deal with you as you have done, who have despised the oath in breaking the covenant.\n'),
	(16019, 23, 16, 60, 'Nevertheless I will remember my covenant with you in the days of your youth, and I will establish to you an everlasting covenant.\n'),
	(16020, 23, 16, 61, 'Then you will remember your ways and be ashamed, when you receive your sisters, your elder sisters and your younger; and I will give them to you for daughters, but not by your covenant.\n'),
	(16021, 23, 16, 62, 'I will establish my covenant with you. Then you will know that I am Yahweh;\n'),
	(16022, 23, 16, 63, 'that you may remember, and be confounded, and never open your mouth any more, because of your shame, when I have forgiven you all that you have done,” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16023, 23, 17, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16024, 23, 17, 2, '“Son of man, tell a riddle, and speak a parable to the house of Israel;\n'),
	(16025, 23, 17, 3, 'and say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “A great eagle with great wings and long feathers, full of feathers, which had various colors, came to Lebanon, and took the top of the cedar.\n'),
	(16026, 23, 17, 4, 'He cropped off the topmost of its young twigs, and carried it to a land of traffic. He planted it in a city of merchants.\n'),
	(16027, 23, 17, 5, '“‘“He also took some of the seed of the land, and planted it in fruitful soil. He placed it beside many waters. He set it as a willow tree.\n'),
	(16028, 23, 17, 6, 'It grew, and became a spreading vine of low stature, whose branches turned toward him, and its roots were under him. So it became a vine, produced branches, and shot out sprigs.\n'),
	(16029, 23, 17, 7, '“‘“There was also another great eagle with great wings and many feathers. Behold, this vine bent its roots toward him, and shot out its branches toward him, from the beds of its plantation, that he might water it.\n'),
	(16030, 23, 17, 8, 'It was planted in a good soil by many waters, that it might produce branches, and that it might bear fruit, that it might be a good vine.”’\n'),
	(16031, 23, 17, 9, '“Say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Will it prosper? Won’t he pull up its roots, and cut off its fruit, that it may wither; that all its fresh springing leaves may wither? It can’t be raised from its roots by a strong arm or many people.\n'),
	(16032, 23, 17, 10, 'Yes, behold, being planted, will it prosper? Won’t it utterly wither when the east wind touches it? It will wither in the beds where it grew.”’”\n'),
	(16033, 23, 17, 11, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16034, 23, 17, 12, '“Say now to the rebellious house, ‘Don’t you know what these things mean?’ Tell them, ‘Behold, the king of Babylon came to Jerusalem, and took its king, and its princes, and brought them to him to Babylon.\n'),
	(16035, 23, 17, 13, 'He took some of the royal offspring, and made a covenant with him. He also brought him under an oath, and took away the mighty of the land;\n'),
	(16036, 23, 17, 14, 'that the kingdom might be brought low, that it might not lift itself up, but that by keeping his covenant it might stand.\n'),
	(16037, 23, 17, 15, 'But he rebelled against him in sending his ambassadors into Egypt, that they might give him horses and many people. Will he prosper? Will he who does such things escape? Will he break the covenant, and still escape?\n'),
	(16038, 23, 17, 16, '“‘As I live,’ says the Lord Yahweh, ‘surely in the place where the king dwells who made him king, whose oath he despised, and whose covenant he broke, even with him in the middle of Babylon he will die.\n'),
	(16039, 23, 17, 17, 'Pharaoh with his mighty army and great company won’t help him in the war, when they cast up mounds and build forts, to cut off many persons.\n'),
	(16040, 23, 17, 18, 'For he has despised the oath by breaking the covenant; and behold, he had given his hand, and yet has done all these things. He won’t escape.\n'),
	(16041, 23, 17, 19, '“Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘As I live, I will surely bring on his own head my oath that he has despised and my covenant that he has broken.\n'),
	(16042, 23, 17, 20, 'I will spread my net on him, and he will be taken in my snare. I will bring him to Babylon, and will enter into judgment with him there for his trespass that he has trespassed against me.\n'),
	(16043, 23, 17, 21, 'All his fugitives in all his bands will fall by the sword, and those who remain will be scattered toward every wind. Then you will know that I, Yahweh, have spoken it.’\n'),
	(16044, 23, 17, 22, '“Thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘I will also take some of the lofty top of the cedar, and will plant it. I will crop off from the topmost of its young twigs a tender one, and I will plant it on a high and lofty mountain.\n'),
	(16045, 23, 17, 23, 'I will plant it in the mountain of the height of Israel; and it will produce boughs, and bear fruit, and be a good cedar. Birds of every kind will dwell in the shade of its branches.\n'),
	(16046, 23, 17, 24, 'All the trees of the field will know that I, Yahweh, have brought down the high tree, have exalted the low tree, have dried up the green tree, and have made the dry tree flourish.\n“‘I, Yahweh, have spoken and have done it.’”\n'),
	(16047, 23, 18, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me again, saying,\n'),
	(16048, 23, 18, 2, '“What do you mean, that you use this proverb concerning the land of Israel, saying,\n‘The fathers have eaten sour grapes,\nand the children’s teeth are set on edge’?\n'),
	(16049, 23, 18, 3, '“As I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “you shall not use this proverb any more in Israel.\n'),
	(16050, 23, 18, 4, 'Behold, all souls are mine; as the soul of the father, so also the soul of the son is mine. The soul who sins, he shall die.\n'),
	(16051, 23, 18, 5, '“But if a man is just,\nand does that which is lawful and right,\n'),
	(16052, 23, 18, 6, 'and has not eaten on the mountains,\nhasn’t lifted up his eyes to the idols of the house of Israel,\nhasn’t defiled his neighbor’s wife,\nhasn’t come near a woman in her impurity,\n'),
	(16053, 23, 18, 7, 'and has not wronged any,\nbut has restored to the debtor his pledge,\nhas taken nothing by robbery,\nhas given his bread to the hungry,\nand has covered the naked with a garment;\n'),
	(16054, 23, 18, 8, 'he who hasn’t lent to them with interest,\nhasn’t taken any increase from them,\nwho has withdrawn his hand from iniquity,\nhas executed true justice between man and man,\n'),
	(16055, 23, 18, 9, 'has walked in my statutes,\nand has kept my ordinances,\nto deal truly;\nhe is just,\nhe shall surely live,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16056, 23, 18, 10, '“If he fathers a son who is a robber who sheds blood, and who does any one of these things,\n'),
	(16057, 23, 18, 11, 'or who does not do any of those things,\nbut even has eaten at the mountain shrines,\nand defiled his neighbor’s wife,\n'),
	(16058, 23, 18, 12, 'has wronged the poor and needy,\nhas taken by robbery,\nhas not restored the pledge,\nand has lifted up his eyes to the idols,\nhas committed abomination,\n'),
	(16059, 23, 18, 13, 'has lent with interest,\nand has taken increase from the poor;\nshall he then live? He shall not live. He has done all these abominations. He shall surely die. His blood will be on him.\n'),
	(16060, 23, 18, 14, '“Now, behold, if he fathers a son, who sees all his father’s sins, which he has done, and fears, and does not such like;\n'),
	(16061, 23, 18, 15, 'who hasn’t eaten on the mountains,\nhasn’t lifted up his eyes to the idols of the house of Israel,\nhasn’t defiled his neighbor’s wife,\n'),
	(16062, 23, 18, 16, 'hasn’t wronged any,\nhasn’t taken anything to pledge,\nhasn’t taken by robbery,\nbut has given his bread to the hungry,\nand has covered the naked with a garment;\n'),
	(16063, 23, 18, 17, 'who has withdrawn his hand from the poor,\nwho hasn’t received interest or increase,\nhas executed my ordinances,\nhas walked in my statutes;\nhe shall not die for the iniquity of his father. He shall surely live.\n'),
	(16064, 23, 18, 18, 'As for his father, because he cruelly oppressed, robbed his brother, and did that which is not good among his people, behold, he will die in his iniquity.\n'),
	(16065, 23, 18, 19, '“Yet you say, ‘Why doesn’t the son bear the iniquity of the father?’ When the son has done that which is lawful and right, and has kept all my statutes, and has done them, he will surely live.\n'),
	(16066, 23, 18, 20, 'The soul who sins, he shall die. The son shall not bear the iniquity of the father, neither shall the father bear the iniquity of the son. The righteousness of the righteous shall be on him, and the wickedness of the wicked shall be on him.\n'),
	(16067, 23, 18, 21, '“But if the wicked turns from all his sins that he has committed, and keeps all my statutes, and does that which is lawful and right, he shall surely live. He shall not die.\n'),
	(16068, 23, 18, 22, 'None of his transgressions that he has committed will be remembered against him. In his righteousness that he has done, he shall live.\n'),
	(16069, 23, 18, 23, 'Have I any pleasure in the death of the wicked?” says the Lord Yahweh; “and not rather that he should return from his way, and live?\n'),
	(16070, 23, 18, 24, '“But when the righteous turns away from his righteousness, and commits iniquity, and does according to all the abominations that the wicked man does, should he live? None of his righteous deeds that he has done will be remembered. In his trespass that he has trespassed, and in his sin that he has sinned, in them he shall die.\n'),
	(16071, 23, 18, 25, '“Yet you say, ‘The way of the Lord is not equal.’ Hear now, house of Israel: Is my way not equal? Aren’t your ways unequal?\n'),
	(16072, 23, 18, 26, 'When the righteous man turns away from his righteousness, and commits iniquity, and dies therein; in his iniquity that he has done he shall die.\n'),
	(16073, 23, 18, 27, 'Again, when the wicked man turns away from his wickedness that he has committed, and does that which is lawful and right, he will save his soul alive.\n'),
	(16074, 23, 18, 28, 'Because he considers, and turns away from all his transgressions that he has committed, he shall surely live. He shall not die.\n'),
	(16075, 23, 18, 29, 'Yet the house of Israel says, ‘The way of the Lord is not fair.’ House of Israel, aren’t my ways fair? Aren’t your ways unfair?\n'),
	(16076, 23, 18, 30, '“Therefore I will judge you, house of Israel, everyone according to his ways,” says the Lord Yahweh. “Return, and turn yourselves from all your transgressions; so iniquity will not be your ruin.\n'),
	(16077, 23, 18, 31, 'Cast away from you all your transgressions, in which you have transgressed; and make yourself a new heart and a new spirit: for why will you die, house of Israel?\n'),
	(16078, 23, 18, 32, 'For I have no pleasure in the death of him who dies,” says the Lord Yahweh. “Therefore turn yourselves, and live!\n'),
	(16079, 23, 19, 1, '“Moreover, take up a lamentation for the princes of Israel,\n'),
	(16080, 23, 19, 2, 'and say,\n‘What was your mother?\nA lioness.\nShe couched among lions,\nin the middle of the young lions she nourished her cubs.\n'),
	(16081, 23, 19, 3, 'She brought up one of her cubs.\nHe became a young lion.\nHe learned to catch the prey.\nHe devoured men.\n'),
	(16082, 23, 19, 4, 'The nations also heard of him.\nHe was taken in their pit;\nand they brought him with hooks to the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(16083, 23, 19, 5, '“‘Now when she saw that she had waited,\nand her hope was lost,\nthen she took another of her cubs,\nand made him a young lion.\n'),
	(16084, 23, 19, 6, 'He went up and down among the lions.\nHe became a young lion.\nHe learned to catch the prey.\nHe devoured men.\n'),
	(16085, 23, 19, 7, 'He knew their palaces,\nand laid waste their cities.\nThe land was desolate,\nwith its fullness,\nbecause of the noise of his roaring.\n'),
	(16086, 23, 19, 8, 'Then the nations attacked him on every side from the provinces.\nThey spread their net over him.\nHe was taken in their pit.\n'),
	(16087, 23, 19, 9, 'They put him in a cage with hooks,\nand brought him to the king of Babylon.\nThey brought him into strongholds,\nso that his voice should no more be heard on the mountains of Israel.\n'),
	(16088, 23, 19, 10, '“‘Your mother was like a vine\nin your blood,\nplanted by the waters.\nIt was fruitful and full of branches by reason of many waters.\n'),
	(16089, 23, 19, 11, 'It had strong branches for the scepters of those who ruled.\nTheir stature was exalted among the thick boughs.\nThey were seen in their height\nwith the multitude of their branches.\n'),
	(16090, 23, 19, 12, 'But it was plucked up in fury.\nIt was cast down to the ground,\nand the east wind dried up its fruit.\nIts strong branches were broken off and withered.\nThe fire consumed them.\n'),
	(16091, 23, 19, 13, 'Now it is planted in the wilderness,\nin a dry and thirsty land.\n'),
	(16092, 23, 19, 14, 'Fire has gone out of its branches.\nIt has devoured its fruit,\nso that there is in it no strong branch to be a scepter to rule.’\nThis is a lamentation, and shall be for a lamentation.”\n'),
	(16093, 23, 20, 1, 'In the seventh year, in the fifth month, the tenth day of the month, some of the elders of Israel came to inquire of Yahweh, and sat before me.\n'),
	(16094, 23, 20, 2, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16095, 23, 20, 3, '“Son of man, speak to the elders of Israel, and tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Is it to inquire of me that you have come? As I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “I will not be inquired of by you.”’\n'),
	(16096, 23, 20, 4, '“Will you judge them, son of man? Will you judge them? Cause them to know the abominations of their fathers.\n'),
	(16097, 23, 20, 5, 'Tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “In the day when I chose Israel, and swore to the offspring of the house of Jacob, and made myself known to them in the land of Egypt, when I swore to them, saying, ‘I am Yahweh your God;’\n'),
	(16098, 23, 20, 6, 'in that day I swore to them, to bring them out of the land of Egypt into a land that I had searched out for them, flowing with milk and honey, which is the glory of all lands.\n'),
	(16099, 23, 20, 7, 'I said to them, ‘Each of you throw away the abominations of his eyes. Don’t defile yourselves with the idols of Egypt. I am Yahweh your God.’\n'),
	(16100, 23, 20, 8, '“‘“But they rebelled against me, and would not listen to me. They didn’t all throw away the abominations of their eyes. They also didn’t forsake the idols of Egypt. Then I said I would pour out my wrath on them, to accomplish my anger against them in the middle of the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(16101, 23, 20, 9, 'But I worked for my name’s sake, that it should not be profaned in the sight of the nations, among which they were, in whose sight I made myself known to them, in bringing them out of the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(16102, 23, 20, 10, 'So I caused them to go out of the land of Egypt, and brought them into the wilderness.\n'),
	(16103, 23, 20, 11, 'I gave them my statutes, and showed them my ordinances, which if a man does, he will live in them.\n'),
	(16104, 23, 20, 12, 'Moreover also I gave them my Sabbaths, to be a sign between me and them, that they might know that I am Yahweh who sanctifies them.\n'),
	(16105, 23, 20, 13, '“‘“But the house of Israel rebelled against me in the wilderness. They didn’t walk in my statutes, and they rejected my ordinances, which if a man keeps, he shall live in them. They greatly profaned my Sabbaths. Then I said I would pour out my wrath on them in the wilderness, to consume them.\n'),
	(16106, 23, 20, 14, 'But I worked for my name’s sake, that it should not be profaned in the sight of the nations, in whose sight I brought them out.\n'),
	(16107, 23, 20, 15, 'Moreover also I swore to them in the wilderness, that I would not bring them into the land which I had given them, flowing with milk and honey, which is the glory of all lands;\n'),
	(16108, 23, 20, 16, 'because they rejected my ordinances, and didn’t walk in my statutes, and profaned my Sabbaths; for their heart went after their idols.\n'),
	(16109, 23, 20, 17, 'Nevertheless my eye spared them, and I didn’t destroy them. I didn’t make a full end of them in the wilderness.\n'),
	(16110, 23, 20, 18, 'I said to their children in the wilderness, ‘Don’t walk in the statutes of your fathers. Don’t observe their ordinances or defile yourselves with their idols.\n'),
	(16111, 23, 20, 19, 'I am Yahweh your God. Walk in my statutes, keep my ordinances, and do them.\n'),
	(16112, 23, 20, 20, 'Make my Sabbaths holy. They shall be a sign between me and you, that you may know that I am Yahweh your God.’\n'),
	(16113, 23, 20, 21, '“‘“But the children rebelled against me. They didn’t walk in my statutes, and didn’t keep my ordinances to do them, which if a man does, he shall live in them. They profaned my Sabbaths. Then I said I would pour out my wrath on them, to accomplish my anger against them in the wilderness.\n'),
	(16114, 23, 20, 22, 'Nevertheless I withdrew my hand, and worked for my name’s sake, that it should not be profaned in the sight of the nations, in whose sight I brought them out.\n'),
	(16115, 23, 20, 23, 'Moreover I swore to them in the wilderness, that I would scatter them among the nations, and disperse them through the countries;\n'),
	(16116, 23, 20, 24, 'because they had not executed my ordinances, but had rejected my statutes, and had profaned my Sabbaths, and their eyes were after their fathers’ idols.\n'),
	(16117, 23, 20, 25, 'Moreover also I gave them statutes that were not good, and ordinances in which they should not live.\n'),
	(16118, 23, 20, 26, 'I polluted them in their own gifts, in that they caused all that opens the womb to pass through the fire, that I might make them desolate, to the end that they might know that I am Yahweh.”’\n'),
	(16119, 23, 20, 27, '“Therefore, son of man, speak to the house of Israel, and tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Moreover, in this your fathers have blasphemed me, in that they have committed a trespass against me.\n'),
	(16120, 23, 20, 28, 'For when I had brought them into the land which I swore to give to them, then they saw every high hill, and every thick tree, and they offered there their sacrifices, and there they presented the provocation of their offering. There they also made their pleasant aroma, and there they poured out their drink offerings.\n'),
	(16121, 23, 20, 29, 'Then I said to them, ‘What does the high place where you go mean?’ So its name is called Bamah to this day.”’\n'),
	(16122, 23, 20, 30, '“Therefore tell the house of Israel, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Do you pollute yourselves in the way of your fathers? Do you play the prostitute after their abominations?\n'),
	(16123, 23, 20, 31, 'When you offer your gifts, when you make your sons pass through the fire, do you pollute yourselves with all your idols to this day? Should I be inquired of by you, house of Israel? As I live, says the Lord Yahweh, I will not be inquired of by you!\n'),
	(16124, 23, 20, 32, '“‘“That which comes into your mind will not be at all, in that you say, ‘We will be as the nations, as the families of the countries, to serve wood and stone.’\n'),
	(16125, 23, 20, 33, 'As I live, says the Lord Yahweh, surely with a mighty hand, with an outstretched arm, and with wrath poured out, I will be king over you.\n'),
	(16126, 23, 20, 34, 'I will bring you out from the peoples, and will gather you out of the countries in which you are scattered with a mighty hand, with an outstretched arm, and with wrath poured out.\n'),
	(16127, 23, 20, 35, 'I will bring you into the wilderness of the peoples, and there I will enter into judgment with you face to face.\n'),
	(16128, 23, 20, 36, 'Just as I entered into judgment with your fathers in the wilderness of the land of Egypt, so will I enter into judgment with you,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16129, 23, 20, 37, '“I will cause you to pass under the rod, and I will bring you into the bond of the covenant.\n'),
	(16130, 23, 20, 38, 'I will purge out from among you the rebels and those who disobey me. I will bring them out of the land where they live, but they shall not enter into the land of Israel. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16131, 23, 20, 39, '“‘As for you, house of Israel, thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Go, everyone serve his idols, and hereafter also, if you will not listen to me; but you shall no more profane my holy name with your gifts and with your idols.\n'),
	(16132, 23, 20, 40, 'For in my holy mountain, in the mountain of the height of Israel,” says the Lord Yahweh, “there all the house of Israel, all of them, shall serve me in the land. There I will accept them, and there I will require your offerings and the first fruits of your offerings, with all your holy things.\n'),
	(16133, 23, 20, 41, 'I will accept you as a pleasant aroma when I bring you out from the peoples and gather you out of the countries in which you have been scattered. I will be sanctified in you in the sight of the nations.\n'),
	(16134, 23, 20, 42, 'You will know that I am Yahweh when I bring you into the land of Israel, into the country which I swore to give to your fathers.\n'),
	(16135, 23, 20, 43, 'There you will remember your ways, and all your deeds in which you have polluted yourselves. Then you will loathe yourselves in your own sight for all your evils that you have committed.\n'),
	(16136, 23, 20, 44, 'You will know that I am Yahweh, when I have dealt with you for my name’s sake, not according to your evil ways, nor according to your corrupt doings, you house of Israel,” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16137, 23, 20, 45, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16138, 23, 20, 46, '“Son of man, set your face toward the south, and preach toward the south, and prophesy against the forest of the field in the South.\n'),
	(16139, 23, 20, 47, 'Tell the forest of the South, ‘Hear Yahweh’s word: Thus says the Lord Yahweh, “Behold, I will kindle a fire in you, and it will devour every green tree in you, and every dry tree. The burning flame will not be quenched, and all faces from the south to the north will be burned by it.\n'),
	(16140, 23, 20, 48, 'All flesh will see that I, Yahweh, have kindled it. It will not be quenched.”’”\n'),
	(16141, 23, 20, 49, 'Then I said, “Ah Lord Yahweh! They say of me, ‘Isn’t he a speaker of parables?’”\n'),
	(16142, 23, 21, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16143, 23, 21, 2, '“Son of man, set your face toward Jerusalem, and preach toward the sanctuaries, and prophesy against the land of Israel.\n'),
	(16144, 23, 21, 3, 'Tell the land of Israel, ‘Yahweh says: “Behold, I am against you, and will draw my sword out of its sheath, and will cut off from you the righteous and the wicked.\n'),
	(16145, 23, 21, 4, 'Seeing then that I will cut off from you the righteous and the wicked, therefore my sword will go out of its sheath against all flesh from the south to the north.\n'),
	(16146, 23, 21, 5, 'All flesh will know that I, Yahweh, have drawn my sword out of its sheath. It will not return any more.”’\n'),
	(16147, 23, 21, 6, '“Therefore sigh, you son of man. You shall sigh before their eyes with a broken heart and with bitterness.\n'),
	(16148, 23, 21, 7, 'It shall be, when they ask you, ‘Why do you sigh?’ that you shall say, ‘Because of the news, for it comes! Every heart will melt, all hands will be feeble, every spirit will faint, and all knees will be weak as water. Behold, it comes, and it shall be done, says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16149, 23, 21, 8, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16150, 23, 21, 9, '“Son of man, prophesy, and say, ‘Yahweh says:\n“A sword! A sword!\nIt is sharpened,\nand also polished.\n'),
	(16151, 23, 21, 10, 'It is sharpened that it may make a slaughter.\nIt is polished that it may be as lightning.\nShould we then make mirth?\nThe rod of my son condemns every tree.\n'),
	(16152, 23, 21, 11, 'It is given to be polished,\nthat it may be handled.\nThe sword is sharpened.\nYes, it is polished\nto give it into the hand of the killer.”’\n'),
	(16153, 23, 21, 12, 'Cry and wail, son of man;\nfor it is on my people.\nIt is on all the princes of Israel.\nThey are delivered over to the sword with my people.\nTherefore beat your thigh.\n'),
	(16154, 23, 21, 13, '“For there is a trial. What if even the rod that condemns will be no more?” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16155, 23, 21, 14, '“You therefore, son of man, prophesy,\nand strike your hands together.\nLet the sword be doubled the third time,\nthe sword of the fatally wounded.\nIt is the sword of the great one who is fatally wounded,\nwhich enters into their rooms.\n'),
	(16156, 23, 21, 15, 'I have set the threatening sword against all their gates,\nthat their heart may melt,\nand their stumblings be multiplied.\nAh! It is made as lightning.\nIt is pointed for slaughter.\n'),
	(16157, 23, 21, 16, 'Gather yourselves together.\nGo to the right.\nSet yourselves in array.\nGo to the left,\nwherever your face is set.\n'),
	(16158, 23, 21, 17, 'I will also strike my hands together,\nand I will cause my wrath to rest.\nI, Yahweh, have spoken it.”\n'),
	(16159, 23, 21, 18, 'Yahweh’s word came to me again, saying,\n'),
	(16160, 23, 21, 19, '“Also, you son of man, appoint two ways, that the sword of the king of Babylon may come. They both will come out of one land, and mark out a place. Mark it out at the head of the way to the city.\n'),
	(16161, 23, 21, 20, 'You shall appoint a way for the sword to come to Rabbah of the children of Ammon, and to Judah in Jerusalem the fortified.\n'),
	(16162, 23, 21, 21, 'For the king of Babylon stood at the parting of the way, at the head of the two ways, to use divination. He shook the arrows back and forth. He consulted the teraphim. He looked in the liver.\n'),
	(16163, 23, 21, 22, 'In his right hand was the lot for Jerusalem, to set battering rams, to open the mouth in the slaughter, to lift up the voice with shouting, to set battering rams against the gates, to cast up mounds, and to build forts.\n'),
	(16164, 23, 21, 23, 'It will be to them as a false divination in their sight, who have sworn oaths to them; but he brings iniquity to memory, that they may be taken.\n'),
	(16165, 23, 21, 24, '“Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Because you have caused your iniquity to be remembered, in that your transgressions are uncovered, so that in all your doings your sins appear; because you have come to memory, you will be taken with the hand.\n'),
	(16166, 23, 21, 25, '“‘You, deadly wounded wicked one, the prince of Israel, whose day has come, in the time of the iniquity of the end,\n'),
	(16167, 23, 21, 26, 'thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Remove the turban, and take off the crown. This will not be as it was. Exalt that which is low, and humble that which is high.\n'),
	(16168, 23, 21, 27, 'I will overturn, overturn, overturn it. This also will be no more, until he comes whose right it is; and I will give it.”’\n'),
	(16169, 23, 21, 28, '“You, son of man, prophesy, and say, ‘The Lord Yahweh says this concerning the children of Ammon, and concerning their reproach:\n“A sword! A sword is drawn!\nIt is polished for the slaughter,\nto cause it to devour,\nthat it may be as lightning;\n'),
	(16170, 23, 21, 29, 'while they see for you false visions,\nwhile they divine lies to you,\nto lay you on the necks of the wicked who are deadly wounded,\nwhose day has come in the time of the iniquity of the end.\n'),
	(16171, 23, 21, 30, 'Cause it to return into its sheath.\nIn the place where you were created,\nin the land of your birth, I will judge you.\n'),
	(16172, 23, 21, 31, 'I will pour out my indignation on you.\nI will blow on you with the fire of my wrath.\nI will deliver you into the hand of brutish men,\nskillful to destroy.\n'),
	(16173, 23, 21, 32, 'You will be for fuel to the fire.\nYour blood will be in the middle of the land.\nYou will be remembered no more;\nfor I, Yahweh, have spoken it.”’”\n'),
	(16174, 23, 22, 1, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16175, 23, 22, 2, '“You, son of man, will you judge? Will you judge the bloody city? Then cause her to know all her abominations.\n'),
	(16176, 23, 22, 3, 'You shall say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “A city that sheds blood within herself, that her time may come, and that makes idols against herself to defile her!\n'),
	(16177, 23, 22, 4, 'You have become guilty in your blood that you have shed, and are defiled in your idols which you have made! You have caused your days to draw near, and have come even to your years. Therefore I have made you a reproach to the nations, and a mocking to all the countries.\n'),
	(16178, 23, 22, 5, 'Those who are near, and those who are far from you, will mock you, you infamous one, full of tumult.\n'),
	(16179, 23, 22, 6, '“‘“Behold, the princes of Israel, everyone according to his power, have been in you to shed blood.\n'),
	(16180, 23, 22, 7, 'In you have they treated father and mother with contempt. Among you they have oppressed the foreigner. In you they have wronged the fatherless and the widow.\n'),
	(16181, 23, 22, 8, 'You have despised my holy things, and have profaned my Sabbaths.\n'),
	(16182, 23, 22, 9, 'Slanderous men have been in you to shed blood. In you they have eaten on the mountains. They have committed lewdness among you.\n'),
	(16183, 23, 22, 10, 'In you have they uncovered their fathers’ nakedness. In you have they humbled her who was unclean in her impurity.\n'),
	(16184, 23, 22, 11, 'One has committed abomination with his neighbor’s wife; and another has lewdly defiled his daughter-in-law. Another in you has humbled his sister, his father’s daughter.\n'),
	(16185, 23, 22, 12, 'In you have they taken bribes to shed blood. You have taken interest and increase, and you have greedily gained of your neighbors by oppression, and have forgotten me,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16186, 23, 22, 13, '“‘“Behold, therefore I have struck my hand at your dishonest gain which you have made, and at your blood which has been within you.\n'),
	(16187, 23, 22, 14, 'Can your heart endure, or can your hands be strong, in the days that I will deal with you? I, Yahweh, have spoken it, and will do it.\n'),
	(16188, 23, 22, 15, 'I will scatter you among the nations, and disperse you through the countries. I will consume your filthiness out of you.\n'),
	(16189, 23, 22, 16, 'You will be profaned in yourself, in the sight of the nations. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.”’”\n'),
	(16190, 23, 22, 17, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16191, 23, 22, 18, '“Son of man, the house of Israel has become dross to me. All of them are brass, tin, iron, and lead in the middle of the furnace. They are the dross of silver.\n'),
	(16192, 23, 22, 19, 'Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Because you have all become dross, therefore, behold, I will gather you into the middle of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(16193, 23, 22, 20, 'As they gather silver, brass, iron, lead, and tin into the middle of the furnace, to blow the fire on it, to melt it; so I will gather you in my anger and in my wrath, and I will lay you there, and melt you.\n'),
	(16194, 23, 22, 21, 'Yes, I will gather you, and blow on you with the fire of my wrath, and you will be melted in the middle of it.\n'),
	(16195, 23, 22, 22, 'As silver is melted in the middle of the furnace, so you will be melted in the middle of it; and you will know that I, Yahweh, have poured out my wrath on you.’”\n'),
	(16196, 23, 22, 23, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16197, 23, 22, 24, '“Son of man, tell her, ‘You are a land that is not cleansed, nor rained on in the day of indignation.’\n'),
	(16198, 23, 22, 25, 'There is a conspiracy of her prophets within it, like a roaring lion ravening the prey. They have devoured souls. They take treasure and precious things. They have made many widows within it.\n'),
	(16199, 23, 22, 26, 'Her priests have done violence to my law, and have profaned my holy things. They have made no distinction between the holy and the common, neither have they caused men to discern between the unclean and the clean, and have hidden their eyes from my Sabbaths. So I am profaned among them.\n'),
	(16200, 23, 22, 27, 'Her princes within it are like wolves ravening the prey, to shed blood, and to destroy souls, that they may get dishonest gain.\n'),
	(16201, 23, 22, 28, 'Her prophets have plastered for them with whitewash, seeing false visions, and divining lies to them, saying, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh,’ when Yahweh has not spoken.\n'),
	(16202, 23, 22, 29, 'The people of the land have used oppression and exercised robbery. Yes, they have troubled the poor and needy, and have oppressed the foreigner wrongfully.\n'),
	(16203, 23, 22, 30, '“I sought for a man among them who would build up the wall and stand in the gap before me for the land, that I would not destroy it; but I found no one.\n'),
	(16204, 23, 22, 31, 'Therefore I have poured out my indignation on them. I have consumed them with the fire of my wrath. I have brought their own way on their heads,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16205, 23, 23, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came again to me, saying,\n'),
	(16206, 23, 23, 2, '“Son of man, there were two women, the daughters of one mother.\n'),
	(16207, 23, 23, 3, 'They played the prostitute in Egypt. They played the prostitute in their youth. Their breasts were fondled there, and their youthful nipples were caressed there.\n'),
	(16208, 23, 23, 4, 'Their names were Oholah the elder, and Oholibah her sister. They became mine, and they bore sons and daughters. As for their names, Samaria is Oholah, and Jerusalem Oholibah.\n'),
	(16209, 23, 23, 5, '“Oholah played the prostitute when she was mine. She doted on her lovers, on the Assyrians her neighbors,\n'),
	(16210, 23, 23, 6, 'who were clothed with blue, governors and rulers, all of them desirable young men, horsemen riding on horses.\n'),
	(16211, 23, 23, 7, 'She gave herself as a prostitute to them, all of them the choicest men of Assyria. She defiled herself with the idols of whoever she lusted after.\n'),
	(16212, 23, 23, 8, 'She hasn’t left her prostitution since leaving Egypt; for in her youth they lay with her. They carressed her youthful nipples; and they poured out their prostitution on her.\n'),
	(16213, 23, 23, 9, '“Therefore I delivered her into the hand of her lovers, into the hand of the Assyrians, on whom she doted.\n'),
	(16214, 23, 23, 10, 'These uncovered her nakedness. They took her sons and her daughters; and they killed her with the sword. She became a byword among women; for they executed judgments on her.\n'),
	(16215, 23, 23, 11, '“Her sister Oholibah saw this, yet she was more corrupt in her lusting than she, and in her prostitution which was more depraved than the prostitution of her sister.\n'),
	(16216, 23, 23, 12, 'She lusted after the Assyrians, governors and rulers, her neighbors, clothed most gorgeously, horsemen riding on horses, all of them desirable young men.\n'),
	(16217, 23, 23, 13, 'I saw that she was defiled. They both went the same way.\n'),
	(16218, 23, 23, 14, '“She increased her prostitution; for she saw men portrayed on the wall, the images of the Chaldeans portrayed with red,\n'),
	(16219, 23, 23, 15, 'dressed with belts on their waists, with flowing turbans on their heads, all of them looking like princes, after the likeness of the Babylonians in Chaldea, the land of their birth.\n'),
	(16220, 23, 23, 16, 'As soon as she saw them, she lusted after them and sent messengers to them into Chaldea.\n'),
	(16221, 23, 23, 17, 'The Babylonians came to her into the bed of love, and they defiled her with their prostitution. She was polluted with them, and her soul was alienated from them.\n'),
	(16222, 23, 23, 18, 'So she uncovered her prostitution and uncovered her nakedness. Then my soul was alienated from her, just like my soul was alienated from her sister.\n'),
	(16223, 23, 23, 19, 'Yet she multiplied her prostitution, remembering the days of her youth, in which she had played the prostitute in the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(16224, 23, 23, 20, 'She lusted after their lovers, whose flesh is as the flesh of donkeys, and whose issue is like the issue of horses.\n'),
	(16225, 23, 23, 21, 'Thus you called to memory the lewdness of your youth, in the caressing of your nipples by the Egyptians because of your youthful breasts.\n'),
	(16226, 23, 23, 22, '“Therefore, Oholibah, thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Behold, I will raise up your lovers against you, from whom your soul is alienated, and I will bring them against you on every side:\n'),
	(16227, 23, 23, 23, 'the Babylonians and all the Chaldeans, Pekod, Shoa, Koa, and all the Assyrians with them; all of them desirable young men, governors and rulers, princes and men of renown, all of them riding on horses.\n'),
	(16228, 23, 23, 24, 'They will come against you with weapons, chariots, and wagons, and with a company of peoples. They will set themselves against you with buckler, shield, and helmet all around. I will commit the judgment to them, and they will judge you according to their judgments.\n'),
	(16229, 23, 23, 25, 'I will set my jealousy against you, and they will deal with you in fury. They will take away your nose and your ears. Your remnant will fall by the sword. They will take your sons and your daughters; and the rest of you will be devoured by the fire.\n'),
	(16230, 23, 23, 26, 'They will also strip you of your clothes, and take away your beautiful jewels.\n'),
	(16231, 23, 23, 27, 'Thus I will make your lewdness to cease from you, and remove your prostitution from the land of Egypt; so that you will not lift up your eyes to them, nor remember Egypt any more.’\n'),
	(16232, 23, 23, 28, '“For thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Behold, I will deliver you into the hand of them whom you hate, into the hand of them from whom your soul is alienated.\n'),
	(16233, 23, 23, 29, 'They will deal with you in hatred, and will take away all your labor, and will leave you naked and bare. The nakedness of your prostitution will be uncovered, both your lewdness and your prostitution.\n'),
	(16234, 23, 23, 30, 'These things will be done to you, because you have played the prostitute after the nations, and because you are polluted with their idols.\n'),
	(16235, 23, 23, 31, 'You have walked in the way of your sister; therefore will I give her cup into your hand.’\n'),
	(16236, 23, 23, 32, '“Thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n‘You will drink of your sister’s cup,\nwhich is deep and large.\nYou will be ridiculed and held in derision.\nIt contains much.\n'),
	(16237, 23, 23, 33, 'You will be filled with drunkenness and sorrow,\nwith the cup of astonishment and desolation,\nwith the cup of your sister Samaria.\n'),
	(16238, 23, 23, 34, 'You will even drink it and drain it out.\nYou will gnaw the broken pieces of it,\nand will tear your breasts;\nfor I have spoken it,’ says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16239, 23, 23, 35, '“Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Because you have forgotten me, and cast me behind your back, therefore you also bear your lewdness and your prostitution.’”\n'),
	(16240, 23, 23, 36, 'Yahweh said moreover to me: “Son of man, will you judge Oholah and Oholibah? Then declare to them their abominations.\n'),
	(16241, 23, 23, 37, 'For they have committed adultery, and blood is in their hands. They have committed adultery with their idols. They have also caused their sons, whom they bore to me, to pass through the fire to them to be devoured.\n'),
	(16242, 23, 23, 38, 'Moreover this they have done to me: they have defiled my sanctuary in the same day, and have profaned my Sabbaths.\n'),
	(16243, 23, 23, 39, 'For when they had slain their children to their idols, then they came the same day into my sanctuary to profane it; and behold, they have done this in the middle of my house.\n'),
	(16244, 23, 23, 40, '“Furthermore you sisters have sent for men who come from far away, to whom a messenger was sent, and behold, they came; for whom you washed yourself, painted your eyes, decorated yourself with ornaments,\n'),
	(16245, 23, 23, 41, 'and sat on a stately bed, with a table prepared before it, whereupon you set my incense and my oil.\n'),
	(16246, 23, 23, 42, '“The voice of a multitude being at ease was with her. With men of the common sort were brought drunkards from the wilderness; and they put bracelets on their hands, and beautiful crowns on their heads.\n'),
	(16247, 23, 23, 43, 'Then I said of her who was old in adulteries, ‘Now they will play the prostitute with her, and she with them.’\n'),
	(16248, 23, 23, 44, 'They went in to her, as they go in to a prostitute. So they went in to Oholah and to Oholibah, the lewd women.\n'),
	(16249, 23, 23, 45, 'Righteous men will judge them with the judgment of adulteresses and with the judgment of women who shed blood; because they are adulteresses, and blood is in their hands.\n'),
	(16250, 23, 23, 46, '“For thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘I will bring up a mob against them, and will give them to be tossed back and forth and robbed.\n'),
	(16251, 23, 23, 47, 'The company will stone them with stones, and dispatch them with their swords. They will kill their sons and their daughters, and burn up their houses with fire.\n'),
	(16252, 23, 23, 48, '“‘Thus I will cause lewdness to cease out of the land, that all women may be taught not to be lewd like you.\n'),
	(16253, 23, 23, 49, 'They will recompense your lewdness on you, and you will bear the sins of your idols. Then you will know that I am the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16254, 23, 24, 1, 'Again, in the ninth year, in the tenth month, in the tenth day of the month, Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16255, 23, 24, 2, '“Son of man, write the name of the day, this same day. The king of Babylon drew close to Jerusalem this same day.\n'),
	(16256, 23, 24, 3, 'Utter a parable to the rebellious house, and tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh,\n“Put the cauldron on the fire.\nPut it on,\nand also pour water into it.\n'),
	(16257, 23, 24, 4, 'Gather its pieces into it,\neven every good piece:\nthe thigh and the shoulder.\nFill it with the choice bones.\n'),
	(16258, 23, 24, 5, 'Take the choice of the flock,\nand also a pile of wood for the bones under the cauldron.\nMake it boil well.\nYes, let its bones be boiled within it.”\n'),
	(16259, 23, 24, 6, '“‘Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“Woe to the bloody city,\nto the cauldron whose rust is in it,\nand whose rust hasn’t gone out of it!\nTake out of it piece after piece.\nNo lot is fallen on it.\n'),
	(16260, 23, 24, 7, '“‘“For her blood is in the middle of her.\nShe set it on the bare rock.\nShe didn’t pour it on the ground,\nto cover it with dust.\n'),
	(16261, 23, 24, 8, 'That it may cause wrath to come up to take vengeance,\nI have set her blood on the bare rock,\nthat it should not be covered.”\n'),
	(16262, 23, 24, 9, '“‘Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“Woe to the bloody city!\nI also will make the pile great.\n'),
	(16263, 23, 24, 10, 'Heap on the wood.\nMake the fire hot.\nBoil the meat well.\nMake the broth thick,\nand let the bones be burned.\n'),
	(16264, 23, 24, 11, 'Then set it empty on its coals,\nthat it may be hot,\nand its brass may burn,\nand that its filthiness may be molten in it,\nthat its rust may be consumed.\n'),
	(16265, 23, 24, 12, 'She is weary with toil;\nyet her great rust,\nrust by fire, doesn’t leave her.\n'),
	(16266, 23, 24, 13, '“‘“In your filthiness is lewdness. Because I have cleansed you and you weren’t cleansed, you won’t be cleansed from your filthiness any more, until I have caused my wrath toward you to rest.\n'),
	(16267, 23, 24, 14, 'I, Yahweh, have spoken it. It will happen, and I will do it. I won’t go back. I won’t spare. I won’t repent. According to your ways, and according to your doings, they will judge you,” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16268, 23, 24, 15, 'Also Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16269, 23, 24, 16, '“Son of man, behold, I will take away from you the desire of your eyes with a stroke: yet you shall neither mourn nor weep, neither shall your tears run down.\n'),
	(16270, 23, 24, 17, 'Sigh, but not aloud. Make no mourning for the dead. Bind your headdress on you, and put your shoes on your feet. Don’t cover your lips, and don’t eat mourner’s bread.”\n'),
	(16271, 23, 24, 18, 'So I spoke to the people in the morning; and at evening my wife died. So I did in the morning as I was commanded.\n'),
	(16272, 23, 24, 19, 'The people asked me, “Won’t you tell us what these things are to us, that you do so?”\n'),
	(16273, 23, 24, 20, 'Then I said to them, “Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16274, 23, 24, 21, '‘Speak to the house of Israel, “Thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Behold, I will profane my sanctuary, the pride of your power, the desire of your eyes, and that which your soul pities; and your sons and your daughters whom you have left behind will fall by the sword.\n'),
	(16275, 23, 24, 22, 'You will do as I have done. You won’t cover your lips or eat mourner’s bread.\n'),
	(16276, 23, 24, 23, 'Your turbans will be on your heads, and your shoes on your feet. You won’t mourn or weep; but you will pine away in your iniquities, and moan one toward another.\n'),
	(16277, 23, 24, 24, 'Thus Ezekiel will be a sign to you; according to all that he has done, you will do. When this comes, then you will know that I am the Lord Yahweh.’”’”\n'),
	(16278, 23, 24, 25, '“You, son of man, shouldn’t it be in the day when I take from them their strength, the joy of their glory, the desire of their eyes, and that whereupon they set their heart, their sons and their daughters,\n'),
	(16279, 23, 24, 26, 'that in that day he who escapes will come to you, to cause you to hear it with your ears?\n'),
	(16280, 23, 24, 27, 'In that day your mouth will be opened to him who has escaped, and you shall speak, and be no more mute. So you will be a sign to them. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16281, 23, 25, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16282, 23, 25, 2, '“Son of man, set your face toward the children of Ammon, and prophesy against them.\n'),
	(16283, 23, 25, 3, 'Tell the children of Ammon, ‘Hear the word of the Lord Yahweh! Thus says the Lord Yahweh, “Because you said, ‘Aha!’ against my sanctuary, when it was profaned; and against the land of Israel, when it was made desolate; and against the house of Judah, when they went into captivity:\n'),
	(16284, 23, 25, 4, 'therefore, behold, I will deliver you to the children of the east for a possession. They will set their encampments in you, and make their dwellings in you. They will eat your fruit and they will drink your milk.\n'),
	(16285, 23, 25, 5, 'I will make Rabbah a stable for camels, and the children of Ammon a resting place for flocks. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16286, 23, 25, 6, 'For thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Because you have clapped your hands, stamped with the feet, and rejoiced with all the contempt of your soul against the land of Israel;\n'),
	(16287, 23, 25, 7, 'therefore, behold, I have stretched out my hand on you, and will deliver you for a plunder to the nations. I will cut you off from the peoples, and I will cause you to perish out of the countries. I will destroy you. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16288, 23, 25, 8, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Because Moab and Seir say, ‘Behold, the house of Judah is like all the nations;’\n'),
	(16289, 23, 25, 9, 'therefore, behold, I will open the side of Moab from the cities, from his cities which are on his frontiers, the glory of the country, Beth Jeshimoth, Baal Meon, and Kiriathaim,\n'),
	(16290, 23, 25, 10, 'to the children of the east, to go against the children of Ammon; and I will give them for a possession, that the children of Ammon may not be remembered among the nations.\n'),
	(16291, 23, 25, 11, 'I will execute judgments on Moab. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16292, 23, 25, 12, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Because Edom has dealt against the house of Judah by taking vengeance, and has greatly offended, and taken revenge on them;”\n'),
	(16293, 23, 25, 13, 'therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh, “I will stretch out my hand on Edom, and will cut off man and animal from it; and I will make it desolate from Teman. They will fall by the sword even to Dedan.\n'),
	(16294, 23, 25, 14, 'I will lay my vengeance on Edom by the hand of my people Israel. They will do in Edom according to my anger and according to my wrath. Then they will know my vengeance,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16295, 23, 25, 15, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Because the Philistines have taken revenge, and have taken vengeance with contempt of soul to destroy with perpetual hostility;”\n'),
	(16296, 23, 25, 16, 'therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh, “Behold, I will stretch out my hand on the Philistines, and I will cut off the Cherethites, and destroy the remnant of the sea coast.\n'),
	(16297, 23, 25, 17, 'I will execute great vengeance on them with wrathful rebukes. Then they will know that I am Yahweh, when I lay my vengeance on them.”’”\n'),
	(16298, 23, 26, 1, 'In the eleventh year, in the first of the month, Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16299, 23, 26, 2, '“Son of man, because Tyre has said against Jerusalem, ‘Aha! She is broken! She who was the gateway of the peoples has been returned to me. I will be replenished, now that she is laid waste;’\n'),
	(16300, 23, 26, 3, 'therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh, ‘Behold, I am against you, Tyre, and will cause many nations to come up against you, as the sea causes its waves to come up.\n'),
	(16301, 23, 26, 4, 'They will destroy the walls of Tyre, and break down her towers. I will also scrape her dust from her, and make her a bare rock.\n'),
	(16302, 23, 26, 5, 'She will be a place for the spreading of nets in the middle of the sea; for I have spoken it,’ says the Lord Yahweh. ‘She will become plunder for the nations.\n'),
	(16303, 23, 26, 6, 'Her daughters who are in the field will be slain with the sword. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.’\n'),
	(16304, 23, 26, 7, '“For thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Behold, I will bring on Tyre Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, king of kings, from the north, with horses, with chariots, with horsemen, and an army with many people.\n'),
	(16305, 23, 26, 8, 'He will kill your daughters in the field with the sword. He will make forts against you, cast up a mound against you, and raise up the buckler against you.\n'),
	(16306, 23, 26, 9, 'He will set his battering engines against your walls, and with his axes he will break down your towers.\n'),
	(16307, 23, 26, 10, 'By reason of the abundance of his horses, their dust will cover you. Your walls will shake at the noise of the horsemen, of the wagons, and of the chariots, when he enters into your gates, as men enter into a city which is broken open.\n'),
	(16308, 23, 26, 11, 'He will tread down all your streets with the hoofs of his horses. He will kill your people with the sword. The pillars of your strength will go down to the ground.\n'),
	(16309, 23, 26, 12, 'They will make a plunder of your riches, and make a prey of your merchandise. They will break down your walls, and destroy your pleasant houses. They will lay your stones, your timber, and your dust in the middle of the waters.\n'),
	(16310, 23, 26, 13, 'I will cause the noise of your songs to cease. The sound of your harps won’t be heard any more.\n'),
	(16311, 23, 26, 14, 'I will make you a bare rock. You will be a place for the spreading of nets. You will be built no more; for I Yahweh have spoken it,’ says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16312, 23, 26, 15, '“Thus says the Lord Yahweh to Tyre: ‘Won’t the islands shake at the sound of your fall, when the wounded groan, when the slaughter is made within you?\n'),
	(16313, 23, 26, 16, 'Then all the princes of the sea will come down from their thrones, and lay aside their robes, and strip off their embroidered garments. They will clothe themselves with trembling. They will sit on the ground, and will tremble every moment, and be astonished at you.\n'),
	(16314, 23, 26, 17, 'They will take up a lamentation over you, and tell you,\n“How you are destroyed,\nwho were inhabited by seafaring men,\nthe renowned city,\nwho was strong in the sea,\nshe and her inhabitants,\nwho caused their terror to be on all who lived there!”\n'),
	(16315, 23, 26, 18, 'Now the islands will tremble in the day of your fall.\nYes, the islands that are in the sea will be dismayed at your departure.’\n'),
	(16316, 23, 26, 19, '“For thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘When I make you a desolate city, like the cities that are not inhabited; when I bring up the deep on you, and the great waters cover you;\n'),
	(16317, 23, 26, 20, 'then I will bring you down with those who descend into the pit, to the people of old time, and will make you dwell in the lower parts of the earth, in the places that are desolate of old, with those who go down to the pit, that you be not inhabited; and I will set glory in the land of the living.\n'),
	(16318, 23, 26, 21, 'I will make you a terror, and you will no more have any being. Though you are sought for, yet you will never be found again,’ says the Lord Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16319, 23, 27, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came again to me, saying,\n'),
	(16320, 23, 27, 2, '“You, son of man, take up a lamentation over Tyre;\n'),
	(16321, 23, 27, 3, 'and tell Tyre, ‘You who dwell at the entry of the sea, who are the merchant of the peoples to many islands, thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“You, Tyre, have said,\n‘I am perfect in beauty.’\n'),
	(16322, 23, 27, 4, 'Your borders are in the heart of the seas.\nYour builders have perfected your beauty.\n'),
	(16323, 23, 27, 5, 'They have made all your planks of cypress trees from Senir.\nThey have taken a cedar from Lebanon to make a mast for you.\n'),
	(16324, 23, 27, 6, 'They have made your oars of the oaks of Bashan.\nThey have made your benches of ivory inlaid in boxwood from the islands of Kittim.\n'),
	(16325, 23, 27, 7, 'Your sail was of fine linen with embroidered work from Egypt,\nthat it might be to you for a banner.\nBlue and purple from the islands of Elishah was your awning.\n'),
	(16326, 23, 27, 8, 'The inhabitants of Sidon and Arvad were your rowers.\nYour wise men, Tyre, were in you.\nThey were your pilots.\n'),
	(16327, 23, 27, 9, 'The old men of Gebal\nand its wise men were your repairers of ship seams in you.\nAll the ships of the sea with their mariners were in you\nto deal in your merchandise.\n'),
	(16328, 23, 27, 10, '“‘“Persia, Lud, and Put were in your army,\nyour men of war.\nThey hung the shield and helmet in you.\nThey showed your beauty.\n'),
	(16329, 23, 27, 11, 'The men of Arvad with your army were on your walls all around,\nand valient men were in your towers.\nThey hung their shields on your walls all around.\nThey have perfected your beauty.\n'),
	(16330, 23, 27, 12, '“‘“Tarshish was your merchant by reason of the multitude of all kinds of riches. They traded for your wares with silver, iron, tin, and lead.\n'),
	(16331, 23, 27, 13, '“‘“Javan, Tubal, and Meshech were your traders. They traded the persons of men and vessels of brass for your merchandise.\n'),
	(16332, 23, 27, 14, '“‘“They of the house of Togarmah traded for your wares with horses, war horses, and mules.\n'),
	(16333, 23, 27, 15, '“‘“The men of Dedan traded with you. Many islands were the market of your hand. They brought you horns of ivory and ebony in exchange.\n'),
	(16334, 23, 27, 16, '“‘“Syria was your merchant by reason of the multitude of your handiworks. They traded for your wares with emeralds, purple, embroidered work, fine linen, coral, and rubies.\n'),
	(16335, 23, 27, 17, '“‘“Judah and the land of Israel were your traders. They traded wheat of Minnith, confections, honey, oil, and balm for your merchandise.\n'),
	(16336, 23, 27, 18, '“‘“Damascus was your merchant for the multitude of your handiworks, by reason of the multitude of all kinds of riches, with the wine of Helbon, and white wool.\n'),
	(16337, 23, 27, 19, '“‘“Vedan and Javan traded with yarn for your wares: bright iron, cassia, and calamus were among your merchandise.\n'),
	(16338, 23, 27, 20, '“‘“Dedan was your trafficker in precious cloths for riding.\n'),
	(16339, 23, 27, 21, '“‘“Arabia, and all the princes of Kedar were the merchants of your hand; in lambs, rams, and goats. In these, they were your merchants.\n'),
	(16340, 23, 27, 22, '“‘“The traders of Sheba and Raamah were your traders. They traded for your wares with the chief of all spices, and with all precious stones, and gold.\n'),
	(16341, 23, 27, 23, '“‘“Haran, Canneh, and Eden, the traders of Sheba, Asshur and Chilmad, were your traders.\n'),
	(16342, 23, 27, 24, 'These were your traders in choice wares, in wrappings of blue and embroidered work, and in chests of rich clothing, bound with cords and made of cedar, among your merchandise.\n'),
	(16343, 23, 27, 25, '“‘“The ships of Tarshish were your caravans for your merchandise.\nYou were replenished\nand made very glorious in the heart of the seas.\n'),
	(16344, 23, 27, 26, 'Your rowers have brought you into great waters.\nThe east wind has broken you in the heart of the seas.\n'),
	(16345, 23, 27, 27, 'Your riches,\nyour wares,\nyour merchandise,\nyour mariners,\nyour pilots,\nyour repairers of ship seams,\nthe dealers in your merchandise,\nand all your men of war, who are in you,\nwith all your company which is among you,\nwill fall into the heart of the seas in the day of your ruin.\n'),
	(16346, 23, 27, 28, 'At the sound of the cry of your pilots,\nthe suburbs will shake.\n'),
	(16347, 23, 27, 29, 'All who handle the oars,\nthe mariners and all the pilots of the sea,\nwill come down from their ships.\nThey will stand on the land,\n'),
	(16348, 23, 27, 30, 'and will cause their voice to be heard over you,\nand will cry bitterly.\nThey will cast up dust on their heads.\nThey will wallow in the ashes.\n'),
	(16349, 23, 27, 31, 'They will make themselves bald for you,\nand clothe themselves with sackcloth.\nThey will weep for you in bitterness of soul,\nwith bitter mourning.\n'),
	(16350, 23, 27, 32, 'In their wailing they will take up a lamentation for you,\nand lament over you, saying,\n‘Who is there like Tyre,\nlike her who is brought to silence in the middle of the sea?’\n'),
	(16351, 23, 27, 33, 'When your wares went out of the seas,\nyou filled many peoples.\nYou enriched the kings of the earth\nwith the multitude of your riches and of your merchandise.\n'),
	(16352, 23, 27, 34, 'In the time that you were broken by the seas,\nin the depths of the waters,\nyour merchandise\nand all your company fell within you.\n'),
	(16353, 23, 27, 35, 'All the inhabitants of the islands are astonished at you,\nand their kings are horribly afraid.\nThey are troubled in their face.\n'),
	(16354, 23, 27, 36, 'The merchants among the peoples hiss at you.\nYou have become a terror,\nand you will be no more.”’”\n'),
	(16355, 23, 28, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came again to me, saying,\n'),
	(16356, 23, 28, 2, '“Son of man, tell the prince of Tyre, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“Because your heart is lifted up,\nand you have said, ‘I am a god,\nI sit in the seat of God,\nin the middle of the seas;’\nyet you are man,\nand not God,\nthough you set your heart as the heart of God—\n'),
	(16357, 23, 28, 3, 'behold, you are wiser than Daniel;\nthere is no secret that is hidden from you;\n'),
	(16358, 23, 28, 4, 'by your wisdom and by your understanding you have gotten yourself riches,\nand have gotten gold and silver into your treasures;\n'),
	(16359, 23, 28, 5, 'by your great wisdom\nand by your trading you have increased your riches,\nand your heart is lifted up because of your riches—”\n'),
	(16360, 23, 28, 6, '“‘therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“Because you have set your heart as the heart of God,\n'),
	(16361, 23, 28, 7, 'therefore, behold, I will bring strangers on you,\nthe terrible of the nations.\nThey will draw their swords against the beauty of your wisdom.\nThey will defile your brightness.\n'),
	(16362, 23, 28, 8, 'They will bring you down to the pit.\nYou will die the death of those who are slain\nin the heart of the seas.\n'),
	(16363, 23, 28, 9, 'Will you yet say before him who kills you, ‘I am God’?\nBut you are man, and not God,\nin the hand of him who wounds you.\n'),
	(16364, 23, 28, 10, 'You will die the death of the uncircumcised\nby the hand of strangers;\nfor I have spoken it,” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16365, 23, 28, 11, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16366, 23, 28, 12, '“Son of man, take up a lamentation over the king of Tyre, and tell him, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“You were the seal of full measure,\nfull of wisdom,\nand perfect in beauty.\n'),
	(16367, 23, 28, 13, 'You were in Eden,\nthe garden of God.\nEvery precious stone adorned you:\nruby, topaz, emerald,\nchrysolite, onyx, jasper,\nsapphire, turquoise, and beryl.\nGold work of tambourines\nand of pipes was in you.\nThey were prepared in the day that you were created.\n'),
	(16368, 23, 28, 14, 'You were the anointed cherub who covers.\nThen I set you up on the holy mountain of God.\nYou have walked up and down in the middle of the stones of fire.\n'),
	(16369, 23, 28, 15, 'You were perfect in your ways from the day that you were created,\nuntil unrighteousness was found in you.\n'),
	(16370, 23, 28, 16, 'By the abundance of your commerce, your insides were filled with violence,\nand you have sinned.\nTherefore I have cast you as profane out of God’s mountain.\nI have destroyed you, covering cherub,\nfrom the middle of the stones of fire.\n'),
	(16371, 23, 28, 17, 'Your heart was lifted up because of your beauty.\nYou have corrupted your wisdom by reason of your splendor.\nI have cast you to the ground.\nI have laid you before kings,\nthat they may see you.\n'),
	(16372, 23, 28, 18, 'By the multitude of your iniquities,\nin the unrighteousness of your commerce,\nyou have profaned your sanctuaries.\nTherefore I have brought out a fire from the middle of you.\nIt has devoured you.\nI have turned you to ashes on the earth\nin the sight of all those who see you.\n'),
	(16373, 23, 28, 19, 'All those who know you among the peoples will be astonished at you.\nYou have become a terror,\nand you will exist no more.”’”\n'),
	(16374, 23, 28, 20, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16375, 23, 28, 21, '“Son of man, set your face toward Sidon, and prophesy against it,\n'),
	(16376, 23, 28, 22, 'and say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“Behold, I am against you, Sidon.\nI will be glorified among you.\nThen they will know that I am Yahweh,\nwhen I have executed judgments in her,\nand am sanctified in her.\n'),
	(16377, 23, 28, 23, 'For I will send pestilence into her,\nand blood into her streets.\nThe wounded will fall within her,\nwith the sword on her on every side.\nThen they will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(16378, 23, 28, 24, '“‘“There will be no more a pricking brier to the house of Israel, nor a hurting thorn of any that are around them that scorned them. Then they will know that I am the Lord Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16379, 23, 28, 25, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “When I have gathered the house of Israel from the peoples among whom they are scattered, and am sanctified in them in the sight of the nations, then they will dwell in their own land which I gave to my servant Jacob.\n'),
	(16380, 23, 28, 26, 'They will dwell in it securely. Yes, they will build houses, plant vineyards, and will dwell securely, when I have executed judgments on all those who scorn them all around. Then they will know that I am Yahweh their God.”’”\n'),
	(16381, 23, 29, 1, 'In the tenth year, in the tenth month, on the twelfth day of the month, Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16382, 23, 29, 2, '“Son of man, set your face against Pharaoh king of Egypt, and prophesy against him and against all Egypt.\n'),
	(16383, 23, 29, 3, 'Speak and say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“Behold, I am against you, Pharaoh king of Egypt,\nthe great monster that lies in the middle of his rivers,\nthat has said, ‘My river is my own,\nand I have made it for myself.’\n'),
	(16384, 23, 29, 4, 'I will put hooks in your jaws,\nand I will make the fish of your rivers stick to your scales.\nI will bring you up out of the middle of your rivers,\nwith all the fish of your rivers which stick to your scales.\n'),
	(16385, 23, 29, 5, 'I’ll cast you out into the wilderness,\nyou and all the fish of your rivers.\nYou’ll fall on the open field.\nYou won’t be brought together or gathered.\nI have given you for food to the animals of the earth\nand to the birds of the sky.\n'),
	(16386, 23, 29, 6, '“‘“All the inhabitants of Egypt will know that I am Yahweh, because they have been a staff of reed to the house of Israel.\n'),
	(16387, 23, 29, 7, 'When they took hold of you by your hand, you broke, and tore all their shoulders. When they leaned on you, you broke, and paralyzed all of their thighs.”\n'),
	(16388, 23, 29, 8, '“‘Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I will bring a sword on you, and will cut off man and animal from you.\n'),
	(16389, 23, 29, 9, 'The land of Egypt will be a desolation and a waste. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.\n“‘“Because he has said, ‘The river is mine, and I have made it;’\n'),
	(16390, 23, 29, 10, 'therefore, behold, I am against you, and against your rivers. I will make the land of Egypt an utter waste and desolation, from the tower of Seveneh even to the border of Ethiopia.\n'),
	(16391, 23, 29, 11, 'No foot of man will pass through it, nor will any animal foot pass through it. It won’t be inhabited for forty years.\n'),
	(16392, 23, 29, 12, 'I will make the land of Egypt a desolation in the middle of the countries that are desolate. Her cities among the cities that are laid waste will be a desolation forty years. I will scatter the Egyptians among the nations, and will disperse them through the countries.”\n'),
	(16393, 23, 29, 13, '“‘For thus says the Lord Yahweh: “At the end of forty years will I gather the Egyptians from the peoples where they were scattered.\n'),
	(16394, 23, 29, 14, 'I will reverse the captivity of Egypt, and will cause them to return into the land of Pathros, into the land of their birth. They will be a lowly kingdom, there.\n'),
	(16395, 23, 29, 15, 'It will be the lowest of the kingdoms. It won’t lift itself up above the nations any more. I will diminish them, so that they will no longer rule over the nations.\n'),
	(16396, 23, 29, 16, 'It will no longer be the confidence of the house of Israel, bringing iniquity to memory, when they turn to look after them. Then they will know that I am the Lord Yahweh.”’”\n'),
	(16397, 23, 29, 17, 'It came to pass in the twenty-seventh year, in the first month, in the first day of the month, Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16398, 23, 29, 18, '“Son of man, Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon caused his army to serve a great service against Tyre. Every head was made bald, and every shoulder was worn; yet he had no wages, nor did his army, from Tyre, for the service that he had served against it.\n'),
	(16399, 23, 29, 19, 'Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Behold, I will give the land of Egypt to Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon. He will carry off her multitude, take her plunder, and take her prey. That will be the wages for his army.\n'),
	(16400, 23, 29, 20, 'I have given him the land of Egypt as his payment for which he served, because they worked for me,’ says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16401, 23, 29, 21, '“In that day I will cause a horn to sprout for the house of Israel, and I will open your mouth among them. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16402, 23, 30, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came again to me, saying,\n'),
	(16403, 23, 30, 2, '“Son of man, prophesy, and say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“Wail, ‘Alas for the day!’\n'),
	(16404, 23, 30, 3, 'For the day is near,\neven Yahweh’s day is near.\nIt will be a day of clouds,\na time of the nations.\n'),
	(16405, 23, 30, 4, 'A sword will come on Egypt,\nand anguish will be in Ethiopia,\nwhen the slain fall in Egypt.\nThey take away her multitude,\nand her foundations are broken down.\n'),
	(16406, 23, 30, 5, '“‘“Ethiopia, Put, Lud, all the mixed people, Cub, and the children of the land that is allied with them, will fall with them by the sword.”\n'),
	(16407, 23, 30, 6, '“‘Yahweh says:\n“They also who uphold Egypt will fall.\nThe pride of her power will come down.\nThey will fall by the sword in it from the tower of Seveneh,”\nsays the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16408, 23, 30, 7, '“They will be desolate in the middle of the countries that are desolate.\nHer cities will be among the cities that are wasted.\n'),
	(16409, 23, 30, 8, 'They will know that I am Yahweh\nwhen I have set a fire in Egypt,\nand all her helpers are destroyed.\n'),
	(16410, 23, 30, 9, '“‘“In that day messengers will go out from before me in ships to make the careless Ethiopians afraid. There will be anguish on them, as in the day of Egypt; for, behold, it comes.”\n'),
	(16411, 23, 30, 10, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“I will also make the multitude of Egypt to cease,\nby the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon.\n'),
	(16412, 23, 30, 11, 'He and his people with him,\nthe terrible of the nations,\nwill be brought in to destroy the land.\nThey will draw their swords against Egypt,\nand fill the land with the slain.\n'),
	(16413, 23, 30, 12, 'I will make the rivers dry,\nand will sell the land into the hand of evil men.\nI will make the land desolate,\nand all that is therein,\nby the hand of strangers:\nI, Yahweh, have spoken it.”\n'),
	(16414, 23, 30, 13, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“I will also destroy the idols,\nand I will cause the images to cease from Memphis.\nThere will be no more a prince from the land of Egypt.\nI will put a fear in the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(16415, 23, 30, 14, 'I will make Pathros desolate,\nand will set a fire in Zoan,\nand will execute judgments on No.\n'),
	(16416, 23, 30, 15, 'I will pour my wrath on Sin,\nthe stronghold of Egypt.\nI will cut off the multitude of No.\n'),
	(16417, 23, 30, 16, 'I will set a fire in Egypt\nSin will be in great anguish.\nNo will be broken up.\nMemphis will have adversaries in the daytime.\n'),
	(16418, 23, 30, 17, 'The young men of Aven and of Pibeseth will fall by the sword.\nThey will go into captivity.\n'),
	(16419, 23, 30, 18, 'At Tehaphnehes also the day will withdraw itself,\nwhen I break the yokes of Egypt, there.\nThe pride of her power will cease in her.\nAs for her, a cloud will cover her,\nand her daughters will go into captivity.\n'),
	(16420, 23, 30, 19, 'Thus I will execute judgments on Egypt.\nThen they will know that I am Yahweh.”’”\n'),
	(16421, 23, 30, 20, 'In the eleventh year, in the first month, in the seventh day of the month, Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16422, 23, 30, 21, '“Son of man, I have broken the arm of Pharaoh king of Egypt. Behold, it has not been bound up, to apply medicines, to put a bandage to bind it, that it become strong to hold the sword.\n'),
	(16423, 23, 30, 22, 'Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Behold, I am against Pharaoh king of Egypt, and will break his arms, the strong arm, and that which was broken. I will cause the sword to fall out of his hand.\n'),
	(16424, 23, 30, 23, 'I will scatter the Egyptians among the nations, and will disperse them through the countries.\n'),
	(16425, 23, 30, 24, 'I will strengthen the arms of the king of Babylon, and put my sword in his hand; but I will break the arms of Pharaoh, and he will groan before the king of Babylon with the groaning of a mortally wounded man.\n'),
	(16426, 23, 30, 25, 'I will hold up the arms of the king of Babylon; and the arms of Pharaoh will fall down. Then they will know that I am Yahweh, when I put my sword into the hand of the king of Babylon, and he stretches it out on the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(16427, 23, 30, 26, 'I will scatter the Egyptians among the nations, and disperse them through the countries. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16428, 23, 31, 1, 'In the eleventh year, in the third month, in the first day of the month, Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16429, 23, 31, 2, '“Son of man, tell Pharaoh king of Egypt, and his multitude:\n‘Whom are you like in your greatness?\n'),
	(16430, 23, 31, 3, 'Behold, the Assyrian was a cedar in Lebanon\nwith beautiful branches,\nand with a forest-like shade,\nof high stature;\nand its top was among the thick boughs.\n'),
	(16431, 23, 31, 4, 'The waters nourished it.\nThe deep made it to grow.\nIts rivers ran all around its plantation;\nand it sent out its channels to all the trees of the field.\n'),
	(16432, 23, 31, 5, 'Therefore its stature was exalted above all the trees of the field;\nand its boughs were multiplied.\nIts branches became long by reason of many waters,\nwhen it spread them out.\n'),
	(16433, 23, 31, 6, 'All the birds of the sky made their nests in its boughs.\nUnder its branches, all the animals of the field gave birth to their young.\nAll great nations lived under its shadow.\n'),
	(16434, 23, 31, 7, 'Thus was it beautiful in its greatness,\nin the length of its branches;\nfor its root was by many waters.\n'),
	(16435, 23, 31, 8, 'The cedars in the garden of God could not hide it.\nThe cypress trees were not like its boughs.\nThe pine trees were not as its branches;\nnor was any tree in the garden of God like it in its beauty.\n'),
	(16436, 23, 31, 9, 'I made it beautiful by the multitude of its branches,\nso that all the trees of Eden,\nthat were in the garden of God, envied it.’\n'),
	(16437, 23, 31, 10, '“Therefore thus said the Lord Yahweh: ‘Because you are exalted in stature, and he has set his top among the thick boughs, and his heart is lifted up in his height;\n'),
	(16438, 23, 31, 11, 'I will even deliver him into the hand of the mighty one of the nations. He will surely deal with him. I have driven him out for his wickedness.\n'),
	(16439, 23, 31, 12, 'Strangers, the tyrants of the nations, have cut him off, and have left him. His branches have fallen on the mountains and in all the valleys and his boughs are broken by all the watercourses of the land. All the peoples of the earth have gone down from his shadow, and have left him.\n'),
	(16440, 23, 31, 13, 'All the birds of the sky will dwell on his ruin, and all the animals of the field will be on his branches;\n'),
	(16441, 23, 31, 14, 'to the end that none of all the trees by the waters exalt themselves in their stature, and don’t set their top among the thick boughs. Their mighty ones don’t stand up on their height, even all who drink water; for they are all delivered to death, to the lower parts of the earth, among the children of men, with those who go down to the pit.’\n'),
	(16442, 23, 31, 15, '“Thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘In the day when he went down to Sheol\n I caused a mourning. I covered the deep for him, and I restrained its rivers. The great waters were stopped. I caused Lebanon to mourn for him, and all the trees of the field fainted for him.\n'),
	(16443, 23, 31, 16, 'I made the nations to shake at the sound of his fall, when I cast him down to Sheol with those who descend into the pit. All the trees of Eden, the choice and best of Lebanon, all that drink water, were comforted in the lower parts of the earth.\n'),
	(16444, 23, 31, 17, 'They also went down into Sheol with him to those who are slain by the sword; yes, those who were his arm, who lived under his shadow in the middle of the nations.\n'),
	(16445, 23, 31, 18, '“‘To whom are you thus like in glory and in greatness among the trees of Eden? Yet you will be brought down with the trees of Eden to the lower parts of the earth. You will lie in the middle of the uncircumcised, with those who are slain by the sword.\n“‘This is Pharaoh and all his multitude,’ says the Lord Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16446, 23, 32, 1, 'In the twelfth year, in the twelfth month, in the first day of the month, “Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16447, 23, 32, 2, '‘Son of man, take up a lamentation over Pharaoh king of Egypt, and tell him,\n“You were likened to a young lion of the nations;\nyet you are as a monster in the seas.\nYou broke out with your rivers,\nand troubled the waters with your feet,\nand fouled their rivers.”\n'),
	(16448, 23, 32, 3, 'Thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“I will spread out my net on you with a company of many peoples;\nand they will bring you up in my net.\n'),
	(16449, 23, 32, 4, 'I will leave you on the land.\nI will cast you out on the open field,\nand will cause all the birds of the sky to settle on you.\nI will satisfy the animals of the whole earth with you.\n'),
	(16450, 23, 32, 5, 'I will lay your flesh on the mountains,\nand fill the valleys with your height.\n'),
	(16451, 23, 32, 6, 'I will also water the land in which you swim with your blood,\neven to the mountains.\nThe watercourses will be full of you.\n'),
	(16452, 23, 32, 7, 'When I extinguish you, I will cover the heavens\nand make its stars dark.\nI will cover the sun with a cloud,\nand the moon won’t give its light.\n'),
	(16453, 23, 32, 8, 'I will make all the bright lights of the sky dark over you,\nand set darkness on your land,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16454, 23, 32, 9, '“I will also trouble the hearts of many peoples,\nwhen I bring your destruction among the nations,\ninto the countries which you have not known.\n'),
	(16455, 23, 32, 10, 'Yes, I will make many peoples amazed at you,\nand their kings will be horribly afraid for you,\nwhen I brandish my sword before them.\nThey will tremble at every moment,\nevery man for his own life,\nin the day of your fall.”\n'),
	(16456, 23, 32, 11, 'For thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“The sword of the king of Babylon will come on you.\n'),
	(16457, 23, 32, 12, 'I will cause your multitude to fall by the swords of the mighty.\nThey are all the ruthless of the nations.\nThey will bring the pride of Egypt to nothing,\nand all its multitude will be destroyed.\n'),
	(16458, 23, 32, 13, 'I will destroy also all its animals from beside many waters.\nThe foot of man won’t trouble them any more,\nnor will the hoofs of animals trouble them.\n'),
	(16459, 23, 32, 14, 'Then I will make their waters clear,\nand cause their rivers to run like oil,”\nsays the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16460, 23, 32, 15, '“When I make the land of Egypt desolate and waste,\na land destitute of that of which it was full,\nwhen I strike all those who dwell therein,\nthen they will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(16461, 23, 32, 16, '“‘“This is the lamentation with which they will lament. The daughters of the nations will lament with this. They will lament with it over Egypt, and over all her multitude,” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16462, 23, 32, 17, 'Also in the twelfth year, in the fifteenth day of the month, Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16463, 23, 32, 18, '“Son of man, wail for the multitude of Egypt, and cast them down, even her and the daughters of the famous nations, to the lower parts of the earth, with those who go down into the pit.\n'),
	(16464, 23, 32, 19, 'Whom do you pass in beauty? Go down, and be laid with the uncircumcised.\n'),
	(16465, 23, 32, 20, 'They will fall among those who are slain by the sword. She is delivered to the sword. Draw her away with all her multitudes.\n'),
	(16466, 23, 32, 21, 'The strong among the mighty will speak to him out of the middle of Sheol\n with those who help him. They have gone down. The uncircumcised lie still, slain by the sword.\n'),
	(16467, 23, 32, 22, '“Asshur is there with all her company. Her graves are all around her. All of them slain, fallen by the sword;\n'),
	(16468, 23, 32, 23, 'whose graves are set in the uttermost parts of the pit, and her company is around her grave; all of them slain, fallen by the sword, who caused terror in the land of the living.\n'),
	(16469, 23, 32, 24, '“There is Elam and all her multitude around her grave; all of them slain, fallen by the sword, who have gone down uncircumcised into the lower parts of the earth, who caused their terror in the land of the living, and have borne their shame with those who go down to the pit.\n'),
	(16470, 23, 32, 25, 'They have set her a bed among the slain with all her multitude. Her graves are around her; all of them uncircumcised, slain by the sword; for their terror was caused in the land of the living, and they have borne their shame with those who go down to the pit. He is put among those who are slain.\n'),
	(16471, 23, 32, 26, '“There is Meshech, Tubal, and all their multitude. Their graves are around them, all of them uncircumcised, slain by the sword; for they caused their terror in the land of the living.\n'),
	(16472, 23, 32, 27, 'They will not lie with the mighty who are fallen of the uncircumcised, who have gone down to Sheol with their weapons of war, and have laid their swords under their heads, and their iniquities are on their bones; for they were the terror of the mighty in the land of the living.\n'),
	(16473, 23, 32, 28, '“But you will be broken among the uncircumcised, and will lie with those who are slain by the sword.\n'),
	(16474, 23, 32, 29, '“There is Edom, her kings, and all her princes, who in their might are laid with those who are slain by the sword. They will lie with the uncircumcised, and with those who go down to the pit.\n'),
	(16475, 23, 32, 30, '“There are the princes of the north, all of them, and all the Sidonians, who have gone down with the slain. They are put to shame in the terror which they caused by their might. They lie uncircumcised with those who are slain by the sword, and bear their shame with those who go down to the pit.\n'),
	(16476, 23, 32, 31, '“Pharaoh will see them, and will be comforted over all his multitude, even Pharaoh and all his army, slain by the sword,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16477, 23, 32, 32, '“For I have put his terror in the land of the living. He will be laid among the uncircumcised, with those who are slain by the sword, even Pharaoh and all his multitude,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16478, 23, 33, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16479, 23, 33, 2, '“Son of man, speak to the children of your people, and tell them, ‘When I bring the sword on a land, and the people of the land take a man from among them, and set him for their watchman;\n'),
	(16480, 23, 33, 3, 'if, when he sees the sword come on the land, he blows the trumpet, and warns the people;\n'),
	(16481, 23, 33, 4, 'then whoever hears the sound of the trumpet, and doesn’t heed the warning, if the sword comes, and takes him away, his blood will be on his own head.\n'),
	(16482, 23, 33, 5, 'He heard the sound of the trumpet, and didn’t take warning. His blood will be on him; whereas if he had heeded the warning, he would have delivered his soul.\n'),
	(16483, 23, 33, 6, 'But if the watchman sees the sword come, and doesn’t blow the trumpet, and the people aren’t warned, and the sword comes, and takes any person from among them; he is taken away in his iniquity, but his blood I will require at the watchman’s hand.’\n'),
	(16484, 23, 33, 7, '“So you, son of man: I have set you a watchman to the house of Israel. Therefore hear the word from my mouth, and give them warnings from me.\n'),
	(16485, 23, 33, 8, 'When I tell the wicked, ‘O wicked man, you will surely die,’ and you don’t speak to warn the wicked from his way; that wicked man will die in his iniquity, but I will require his blood at your hand.\n'),
	(16486, 23, 33, 9, 'Nevertheless, if you warn the wicked of his way to turn from it, and he doesn’t turn from his way; he will die in his iniquity, but you have delivered your soul.\n'),
	(16487, 23, 33, 10, '“You, son of man, tell the house of Israel: ‘You say this, “Our transgressions and our sins are on us, and we pine away in them. How then can we live?”’\n'),
	(16488, 23, 33, 11, 'Tell them, ‘“As I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “I have no pleasure in the death of the wicked; but that the wicked turn from his way and live. Turn, turn from your evil ways! For why will you die, house of Israel?”’\n'),
	(16489, 23, 33, 12, '“You, son of man, tell the children of your people, ‘The righteousness of the righteous will not deliver him in the day of his disobedience. And as for the wickedness of the wicked, he will not fall thereby in the day that he turns from his wickedness; neither will he who is righteous be able to live by it in the day that he sins.\n'),
	(16490, 23, 33, 13, 'When I tell the righteous that he will surely live; if he trusts in his righteousness, and commits iniquity, none of his righteous deeds will be remembered; but he will die in his iniquity that he has committed.\n'),
	(16491, 23, 33, 14, 'Again, when I say to the wicked, “You will surely die;” if he turns from his sin, and does that which is lawful and right;\n'),
	(16492, 23, 33, 15, 'if the wicked restore the pledge, give again that which he had taken by robbery, walk in the statutes of life, committing no iniquity; he will surely live. He will not die.\n'),
	(16493, 23, 33, 16, 'None of his sins that he has committed will be remembered against him. He has done that which is lawful and right. He will surely live.\n'),
	(16494, 23, 33, 17, '“‘Yet the children of your people say, “The way of the Lord is not fair;” but as for them, their way is not fair.\n'),
	(16495, 23, 33, 18, 'When the righteous turns from his righteousness, and commits iniquity, he will even die therein.\n'),
	(16496, 23, 33, 19, 'When the wicked turns from his wickedness, and does that which is lawful and right, he will live thereby.\n'),
	(16497, 23, 33, 20, 'Yet you say, “The way of the Lord is not fair.” House of Israel, I will judge every one of you after his ways.’”\n'),
	(16498, 23, 33, 21, 'In the twelfth year of our captivity, in the tenth month, in the fifth day of the month, one who had escaped out of Jerusalem came to me, saying, “The city has been defeated!”\n'),
	(16499, 23, 33, 22, 'Now Yahweh’s hand had been on me in the evening, before he who had escaped came; and he had opened my mouth, until he came to me in the morning; and my mouth was opened, and I was no longer mute.\n'),
	(16500, 23, 33, 23, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16501, 23, 33, 24, '“Son of man, those who inhabit the waste places in the land of Israel speak, saying, ‘Abraham was one, and he inherited the land; but we are many. The land is given us for inheritance.’\n'),
	(16502, 23, 33, 25, 'Therefore tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “You eat with the blood, and lift up your eyes to your idols, and shed blood. So should you possess the land?\n'),
	(16503, 23, 33, 26, 'You stand on your sword, you work abomination, and every one of you defiles his neighbor’s wife. So should you possess the land?”’\n'),
	(16504, 23, 33, 27, '“You shall tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “As I live, surely those who are in the waste places will fall by the sword. I will give he who is in the open field to the animals to be devoured; and those who are in the strongholds and in the caves will die of the pestilence.\n'),
	(16505, 23, 33, 28, 'I will make the land a desolation and an astonishment. The pride of her power will cease. The mountains of Israel will be desolate, so that no one will pass through.\n'),
	(16506, 23, 33, 29, 'Then they will know that I am Yahweh, when I have made the land a desolation and an astonishment, because of all their abominations which they have committed.”’\n'),
	(16507, 23, 33, 30, '“As for you, son of man, the children of your people talk about you by the walls and in the doors of the houses, and speak to one another, everyone to his brother, saying, ‘Please come and hear what the word is that comes out from Yahweh.’\n'),
	(16508, 23, 33, 31, 'They come to you as the people come, and they sit before you as my people, and they hear your words, but don’t do them; for with their mouth they show much love, but their heart goes after their gain.\n'),
	(16509, 23, 33, 32, 'Behold, you are to them as a very lovely song of one who has a pleasant voice, and can play well on an instrument; for they hear your words, but they don’t do them.\n'),
	(16510, 23, 33, 33, '“When this comes to pass—behold, it comes—then they will know that a prophet has been among them.”\n'),
	(16511, 23, 34, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16512, 23, 34, 2, '“Son of man, prophesy against the shepherds of Israel. Prophesy, and tell them, even the shepherds, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Woe to the shepherds of Israel who feed themselves! Shouldn’t the shepherds feed the sheep?\n'),
	(16513, 23, 34, 3, 'You eat the fat. You clothe yourself with the wool. You kill the fatlings, but you don’t feed the sheep.\n'),
	(16514, 23, 34, 4, 'You haven’t strengthened the diseased. You haven’t healed that which was sick. You haven’t bound up that which was broken. You haven’t brought back that which was driven away. You haven’t sought that which was lost, but you have ruled over them with force and with rigor.\n'),
	(16515, 23, 34, 5, 'They were scattered, because there was no shepherd. They became food to all the animals of the field, and were scattered.\n'),
	(16516, 23, 34, 6, 'My sheep wandered through all the mountains, and on every high hill. Yes, my sheep were scattered on all the surface of the earth. There was no one who searched or sought.”\n'),
	(16517, 23, 34, 7, '“‘Therefore, you shepherds, hear Yahweh’s word:\n'),
	(16518, 23, 34, 8, '“As I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “surely because my sheep became a prey, and my sheep became food to all the animals of the field, because there was no shepherd. My shepherds didn’t search for my sheep, but the shepherds fed themselves, and didn’t feed my sheep.”\n'),
	(16519, 23, 34, 9, 'Therefore, you shepherds, hear Yahweh’s word:\n'),
	(16520, 23, 34, 10, 'Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I am against the shepherds. I will require my sheep at their hand, and cause them to cease from feeding the sheep. The shepherds won’t feed themselves any more. I will deliver my sheep from their mouth, that they may not be food for them.”\n'),
	(16521, 23, 34, 11, '“‘For thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I myself, even I, will search for my sheep, and will seek them out.\n'),
	(16522, 23, 34, 12, 'As a shepherd seeks out his flock in the day that he is among his sheep that are scattered abroad, so will I seek out my sheep. I will deliver them out of all places where they have been scattered in the cloudy and dark day.\n'),
	(16523, 23, 34, 13, 'I will bring them out from the peoples, and gather them from the countries, and will bring them into their own land. I will feed them on the mountains of Israel, by the watercourses, and in all the inhabited places of the country.\n'),
	(16524, 23, 34, 14, 'I will feed them with good pasture; and their fold will be on the mountains of the height of Israel. There they will lie down in a good fold. They will feed on fat pasture on the mountains of Israel.\n'),
	(16525, 23, 34, 15, 'I myself will be the shepherd of my sheep, and I will cause them to lie down,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16526, 23, 34, 16, '“I will seek that which was lost, and will bring back that which was driven away, and will bind up that which was broken, and will strengthen that which was sick; but I will destroy the fat and the strong. I will feed them in justice.”’\n'),
	(16527, 23, 34, 17, '“As for you, O my flock, thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Behold, I judge between sheep and sheep, the rams and the male goats.\n'),
	(16528, 23, 34, 18, 'Does it seem a small thing to you to have fed on the good pasture, but you must tread down with your feet the residue of your pasture? And to have drunk of the clear waters, but must you foul the residue with your feet?\n'),
	(16529, 23, 34, 19, 'As for my sheep, they eat that which you have trodden with your feet, and they drink that which you have fouled with your feet.’\n'),
	(16530, 23, 34, 20, '“Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh to them: ‘Behold, I, even I, will judge between the fat sheep and the lean sheep.\n'),
	(16531, 23, 34, 21, 'Because you thrust with side and with shoulder, and push all the diseased with your horns, until you have scattered them abroad;\n'),
	(16532, 23, 34, 22, 'therefore will I save my flock, and they will no more be a prey. I will judge between sheep and sheep.\n'),
	(16533, 23, 34, 23, 'I will set up one shepherd over them, and he will feed them, even my servant David. He will feed them, and he will be their shepherd.\n'),
	(16534, 23, 34, 24, 'I, Yahweh, will be their God, and my servant David prince among them. I, Yahweh, have spoken it.\n'),
	(16535, 23, 34, 25, '“‘I will make with them a covenant of peace, and will cause evil animals to cease out of the land. They will dwell securely in the wilderness, and sleep in the woods.\n'),
	(16536, 23, 34, 26, 'I will make them and the places around my hill a blessing. I will cause the shower to come down in its season. There will be showers of blessing.\n'),
	(16537, 23, 34, 27, 'The tree of the field will yield its fruit, and the earth will yield its increase, and they will be secure in their land. Then they will know that I am Yahweh, when I have broken the bars of their yoke, and have delivered them out of the hand of those who made slaves of them.\n'),
	(16538, 23, 34, 28, 'They will no more be a prey to the nations, neither will the animals of the earth devour them; but they will dwell securely, and no one will make them afraid.\n'),
	(16539, 23, 34, 29, 'I will raise up to them a plantation for renown, and they will no more be consumed with famine in the land, and not bear the shame of the nations any more.\n'),
	(16540, 23, 34, 30, 'They will know that I, Yahweh, their God am with them, and that they, the house of Israel, are my people, says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16541, 23, 34, 31, 'You my sheep, the sheep of my pasture, are men, and I am your God,’ says the Lord Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16542, 23, 35, 1, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16543, 23, 35, 2, '“Son of man, set your face against Mount Seir, and prophesy against it,\n'),
	(16544, 23, 35, 3, 'and tell it, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I am against you, Mount Seir, and I will stretch out my hand against you. I will make you a desolation and an astonishment.\n'),
	(16545, 23, 35, 4, 'I will lay your cities waste, and you will be desolate. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(16546, 23, 35, 5, '“‘“Because you have had a perpetual hostility, and have given over the children of Israel to the power of the sword in the time of their calamity, in the time of the iniquity of the end;\n'),
	(16547, 23, 35, 6, 'therefore, as I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “I will prepare you for blood, and blood will pursue you. Since you have not hated blood, therefore blood will pursue you.\n'),
	(16548, 23, 35, 7, 'Thus will I make Mount Seir an astonishment and a desolation. I will cut off from it him who passes through and him who returns.\n'),
	(16549, 23, 35, 8, 'I will fill its mountains with its slain. The slain with the sword will fall in your hills and in your valleys and in all your watercourses.\n'),
	(16550, 23, 35, 9, 'I will make you a perpetual desolation, and your cities will not be inhabited. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(16551, 23, 35, 10, '“‘“Because you have said, ‘These two nations and these two countries will be mine, and we will possess it;’ whereas Yahweh was there:\n'),
	(16552, 23, 35, 11, 'therefore, as I live,” says the Lord Yahweh, “I will do according to your anger, and according to your envy which you have shown out of your hatred against them; and I will make myself known among them when I judge you.\n'),
	(16553, 23, 35, 12, 'You will know that I, Yahweh, have heard all your insults which you have spoken against the mountains of Israel, saying, ‘They have been laid desolate. They have been given us to devour.’\n'),
	(16554, 23, 35, 13, 'You have magnified yourselves against me with your mouth, and have multiplied your words against me. I have heard it.”\n'),
	(16555, 23, 35, 14, 'Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “When the whole earth rejoices, I will make you desolate.\n'),
	(16556, 23, 35, 15, 'As you rejoiced over the inheritance of the house of Israel because it was desolate, so will I do to you. You will be desolate, Mount Seir, and all Edom, even all of it. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16557, 23, 36, 1, 'You, son of man, prophesy to the mountains of Israel, and say, “You mountains of Israel, hear Yahweh’s word.\n'),
	(16558, 23, 36, 2, 'Thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Because the enemy has said against you, “Aha!” and, “The ancient high places are ours in possession!”’\n'),
	(16559, 23, 36, 3, 'therefore prophesy, and say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Because, even because they have made you desolate, and swallowed you up on every side, that you might be a possession to the residue of the nations, and you are taken up in the lips of talkers, and the evil report of the people;”\n'),
	(16560, 23, 36, 4, 'therefore, you mountains of Israel, hear the word of the Lord Yahweh: Thus says the Lord Yahweh to the mountains and to the hills, to the watercourses and to the valleys, to the desolate wastes and to the cities that are forsaken, which have become a prey and derision to the residue of the nations that are all around;\n'),
	(16561, 23, 36, 5, 'therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Surely in the fire of my jealousy I have spoken against the residue of the nations, and against all Edom, that have appointed my land to themselves for a possession with the joy of all their heart, with despite of soul, to cast it out for a prey.”’\n'),
	(16562, 23, 36, 6, 'Therefore prophesy concerning the land of Israel, and tell the mountains, the hills, the watercourses and the valleys, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I have spoken in my jealousy and in my wrath, because you have borne the shame of the nations.”\n'),
	(16563, 23, 36, 7, 'Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: “I have sworn, ‘Surely the nations that are around you will bear their shame.’\n'),
	(16564, 23, 36, 8, '“‘“But you, mountains of Israel, you shall shoot out your branches, and yield your fruit to my people Israel; for they are at hand to come.\n'),
	(16565, 23, 36, 9, 'For, behold, I am for you, and I will come to you, and you will be tilled and sown.\n'),
	(16566, 23, 36, 10, 'I will multiply men on you, all the house of Israel, even all of it. The cities will be inhabited, and the waste places will be built.\n'),
	(16567, 23, 36, 11, 'I will multiply man and animal on you. They will increase and be fruitful. I will cause you to be inhabited as you were before, and you will do better than at your beginnings. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(16568, 23, 36, 12, 'Yes, I will cause men to walk on you, even my people Israel. They will possess you, and you will be their inheritance, and you will never again bereave them of their children.”\n'),
	(16569, 23, 36, 13, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Because they say to you, ‘You are a devourer of men, and have been a bereaver of your nation;’\n'),
	(16570, 23, 36, 14, 'therefore you shall devour men no more, and not bereave your nation any more,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16571, 23, 36, 15, '“I won’t let you hear the shame of the nations any more. You won’t bear the reproach of the peoples any more, and you won’t cause your nation to stumble any more,” says the Lord Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16572, 23, 36, 16, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16573, 23, 36, 17, '“Son of man, when the house of Israel lived in their own land, they defiled it by their ways and by their deeds. Their way before me was as the uncleanness of a woman in her impurity.\n'),
	(16574, 23, 36, 18, 'Therefore I poured out my wrath on them for the blood which they had poured out on the land, and because they had defiled it with their idols.\n'),
	(16575, 23, 36, 19, 'I scattered them among the nations, and they were dispersed through the countries. I judged them according to their way and according to their deeds.\n'),
	(16576, 23, 36, 20, 'When they came to the nations where they went, they profaned my holy name; in that men said of them, ‘These are Yahweh’s people, and have left his land.’\n'),
	(16577, 23, 36, 21, 'But I had respect for my holy name, which the house of Israel had profaned among the nations where they went.\n'),
	(16578, 23, 36, 22, '“Therefore tell the house of Israel, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “I don’t do this for your sake, house of Israel, but for my holy name, which you have profaned among the nations where you went.\n'),
	(16579, 23, 36, 23, 'I will sanctify my great name, which has been profaned among the nations, which you have profaned among them. Then the nations will know that I am Yahweh,” says the Lord Yahweh, “when I am proven holy in you before their eyes.\n'),
	(16580, 23, 36, 24, '“‘“For I will take you from among the nations and gather you out of all the countries, and will bring you into your own land.\n'),
	(16581, 23, 36, 25, 'I will sprinkle clean water on you, and you will be clean. I will cleanse you from all your filthiness, and from all your idols.\n'),
	(16582, 23, 36, 26, 'I will also give you a new heart, and I will put a new spirit within you. I will take away the stony heart out of your flesh, and I will give you a heart of flesh.\n'),
	(16583, 23, 36, 27, 'I will put my Spirit within you, and cause you to walk in my statutes. You will keep my ordinances and do them.\n'),
	(16584, 23, 36, 28, 'You will dwell in the land that I gave to your fathers. You will be my people, and I will be your God.\n'),
	(16585, 23, 36, 29, 'I will save you from all your uncleanness. I will call for the grain, and will multiply it, and lay no famine on you.\n'),
	(16586, 23, 36, 30, 'I will multiply the fruit of the tree and the increase of the field, that you may receive no more the reproach of famine among the nations.\n'),
	(16587, 23, 36, 31, '“‘“Then you will remember your evil ways, and your deeds that were not good; and you will loathe yourselves in your own sight for your iniquities and for your abominations.\n'),
	(16588, 23, 36, 32, 'I don’t do this for your sake,” says the Lord Yahweh. “Let it be known to you: be ashamed and confounded for your ways, house of Israel.”\n'),
	(16589, 23, 36, 33, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “In the day that I cleanse you from all your iniquities, I will cause the cities to be inhabited and the waste places will be built.\n'),
	(16590, 23, 36, 34, 'The land that was desolate will be tilled instead of being a desolation in the sight of all who passed by.\n'),
	(16591, 23, 36, 35, 'They will say, ‘This land that was desolate has become like the garden of Eden. The waste, desolate, and ruined cities are fortified and inhabited.’\n'),
	(16592, 23, 36, 36, 'Then the nations that are left around you will know that I, Yahweh, have built the ruined places, and planted that which was desolate. I, Yahweh, have spoken it, and I will do it.”\n'),
	(16593, 23, 36, 37, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “For this, moreover, will I be inquired of by the house of Israel, to do it for them: I will increase them with men like a flock.\n'),
	(16594, 23, 36, 38, 'As the flock for sacrifice, as the flock of Jerusalem in her appointed feasts, so the waste cities will be filled with flocks of men. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16595, 23, 37, 1, 'Yahweh’s hand was on me, and he brought me out in Yahweh’s Spirit, and set me down in the middle of the valley; and it was full of bones.\n'),
	(16596, 23, 37, 2, 'He caused me to pass by them all around: and behold, there were very many in the open valley; and behold, they were very dry.\n'),
	(16597, 23, 37, 3, 'He said to me, “Son of man, can these bones live?”\nI answered, “Lord Yahweh, you know.”\n'),
	(16598, 23, 37, 4, 'Again he said to me, “Prophesy over these bones, and tell them, ‘You dry bones, hear Yahweh’s word.\n'),
	(16599, 23, 37, 5, 'Thus says the Lord Yahweh to these bones: “Behold, I will cause breath to enter into you, and you will live.\n'),
	(16600, 23, 37, 6, 'I will lay sinews on you, and will bring up flesh on you, and cover you with skin, and put breath in you, and you will live. Then you will know that I am Yahweh.”’”\n'),
	(16601, 23, 37, 7, 'So I prophesied as I was commanded. As I prophesied, there was a noise, and behold, there was an earthquake. Then the bones came together, bone to its bone.\n'),
	(16602, 23, 37, 8, 'I saw, and, behold, there were sinews on them, and flesh came up, and skin covered them above; but there was no breath in them.\n'),
	(16603, 23, 37, 9, 'Then he said to me, “Prophesy to the wind, prophesy, son of man, and tell the wind, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Come from the four winds, breath, and breathe on these slain, that they may live.”’”\n'),
	(16604, 23, 37, 10, 'So I prophesied as he commanded me, and the breath came into them, and they lived, and stood up on their feet, an exceedingly great army.\n'),
	(16605, 23, 37, 11, 'Then he said to me, “Son of man, these bones are the whole house of Israel. Behold, they say, ‘Our bones are dried up, and our hope is lost. We are completely cut off.’\n'),
	(16606, 23, 37, 12, 'Therefore prophesy, and tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I will open your graves, and cause you to come up out of your graves, my people; and I will bring you into the land of Israel.\n'),
	(16607, 23, 37, 13, 'You will know that I am Yahweh, when I have opened your graves, and caused you to come up out of your graves, my people.\n'),
	(16608, 23, 37, 14, 'I will put my Spirit in you, and you will live. Then I will place you in your own land; and you will know that I, Yahweh, have spoken it and performed it,” says Yahweh.’”\n'),
	(16609, 23, 37, 15, 'Yahweh’s word came again to me, saying,\n'),
	(16610, 23, 37, 16, '“You, son of man, take one stick, and write on it, ‘For Judah, and for the children of Israel his companions.’ Then take another stick, and write on it, ‘For Joseph, the stick of Ephraim, and for all the house of Israel his companions.’\n'),
	(16611, 23, 37, 17, 'Then join them for yourself to one another into one stick, that they may become one in your hand.\n'),
	(16612, 23, 37, 18, '“When the children of your people speak to you, saying, ‘Won’t you show us what you mean by these?’\n'),
	(16613, 23, 37, 19, 'tell them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I will take the stick of Joseph, which is in the hand of Ephraim, and the tribes of Israel his companions; and I will put them with it, with the stick of Judah, and make them one stick, and they will be one in my hand.\n'),
	(16614, 23, 37, 20, 'The sticks on which you write will be in your hand before their eyes.”’\n'),
	(16615, 23, 37, 21, 'Say to them, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I will take the children of Israel from among the nations, where they have gone, and will gather them on every side, and bring them into their own land.\n'),
	(16616, 23, 37, 22, 'I will make them one nation in the land, on the mountains of Israel. One king will be king to them all. They will no longer be two nations. They won’t be divided into two kingdoms any more at all.\n'),
	(16617, 23, 37, 23, 'They won’t defile themselves any more with their idols, nor with their detestable things, nor with any of their transgressions; but I will save them out of all their dwelling places, in which they have sinned, and will cleanse them. So they will be my people, and I will be their God.\n'),
	(16618, 23, 37, 24, '“‘“My servant David will be king over them. They all will have one shepherd. They will also walk in my ordinances, and observe my statutes, and do them.\n'),
	(16619, 23, 37, 25, 'They will dwell in the land that I have given to Jacob my servant, in which your fathers lived. They will dwell therein, they, and their children, and their children’s children, forever. David my servant will be their prince for ever.\n'),
	(16620, 23, 37, 26, 'Moreover I will make a covenant of peace with them. It will be an everlasting covenant with them. I will place them, multiply them, and will set my sanctuary among them forever more.\n'),
	(16621, 23, 37, 27, 'My tent also will be with them. I will be their God, and they will be my people.\n'),
	(16622, 23, 37, 28, 'The nations will know that I am Yahweh who sanctifies Israel, when my sanctuary is among them forever more.”’”\n'),
	(16623, 23, 38, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(16624, 23, 38, 2, '“Son of man, set your face toward Gog, of the land of Magog, the prince of Rosh, Meshech, and Tubal, and prophesy against him,\n'),
	(16625, 23, 38, 3, 'and say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I am against you, Gog, prince of Rosh, Meshech, and Tubal.\n'),
	(16626, 23, 38, 4, 'I will turn you around, and put hooks into your jaws, and I will bring you out, with all your army, horses and horsemen, all of them clothed in full armor, a great company with buckler and shield, all of them handling swords;\n'),
	(16627, 23, 38, 5, 'Persia, Cush, and Put with them, all of them with shield and helmet;\n'),
	(16628, 23, 38, 6, 'Gomer, and all his hordes; the house of Togarmah in the uttermost parts of the north, and all his hordes; even many peoples with you.\n'),
	(16629, 23, 38, 7, '“‘“Be prepared, yes, prepare yourself, you, and all your companies who are assembled to you, and be a guard to them.\n'),
	(16630, 23, 38, 8, 'After many days you will be visited. In the latter years you will come into the land that is brought back from the sword, that is gathered out of many peoples, on the mountains of Israel, which have been a continual waste; but it is brought out of the peoples, and they will dwell securely, all of them.\n'),
	(16631, 23, 38, 9, 'You will ascend. You will come like a storm. You will be like a cloud to cover the land, you, and all your hordes, and many peoples with you.”\n'),
	(16632, 23, 38, 10, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “It will happen in that day that things will come into your mind, and you will devise an evil plan.\n'),
	(16633, 23, 38, 11, 'You will say, ‘I will go up to the land of unwalled villages. I will go to those who are at rest, who dwell securely, all of them dwelling without walls, and having neither bars nor gates,\n'),
	(16634, 23, 38, 12, 'to take the plunder and to take prey; to turn your hand against the waste places that are inhabited, and against the people who are gathered out of the nations, who have gotten livestock and goods, who dwell in the middle of the earth.’\n'),
	(16635, 23, 38, 13, 'Sheba, and Dedan, and the merchants of Tarshish, with all the young lions of it, will ask you, ‘Have you come to take the plunder? Have you assembled your company to take the prey, to carry away silver and gold, to take away livestock and goods, to take great plunder?’”’\n'),
	(16636, 23, 38, 14, '“Therefore, son of man, prophesy, and tell Gog, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “In that day when my people Israel dwells securely, will you not know it?\n'),
	(16637, 23, 38, 15, 'You will come from your place out of the uttermost parts of the north, you, and many peoples with you, all of them riding on horses, a great company and a mighty army.\n'),
	(16638, 23, 38, 16, 'You will come up against my people Israel, as a cloud to cover the land. It will happen in the latter days, that I will bring you against my land, that the nations may know me, when I am sanctified in you, Gog, before their eyes.”\n'),
	(16639, 23, 38, 17, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Are you he of whom I spoke in old time by my servants the prophets of Israel, who prophesied in those days for years that I would bring you against them?\n'),
	(16640, 23, 38, 18, 'It will happen in that day, when Gog comes against the land of Israel,” says the Lord Yahweh, “that my wrath will come up into my nostrils.\n'),
	(16641, 23, 38, 19, 'For in my jealousy and in the fire of my wrath I have spoken. Surely in that day there will be a great shaking in the land of Israel;\n'),
	(16642, 23, 38, 20, 'so that the fish of the sea, the birds of the sky, the animals of the field, all creeping things who creep on the earth, and all the men who are on the surface of the earth will shake at my presence. Then the mountains will be thrown down, the steep places will fall, and every wall will fall to the ground.\n'),
	(16643, 23, 38, 21, 'I will call for a sword against him to all my mountains,” says the Lord Yahweh. “Every man’s sword will be against his brother.\n'),
	(16644, 23, 38, 22, 'I will enter into judgment with him with pestilence and with blood. I will rain on him, and on his hordes, and on the many peoples who are with him, an overflowing shower, with great hailstones, fire, and sulfur.\n'),
	(16645, 23, 38, 23, 'I will magnify myself, and sanctify myself, and I will make myself known in the eyes of many nations. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.”’\n'),
	(16646, 23, 39, 1, '“You, son of man, prophesy against Gog, and say, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Behold, I am against you, Gog, prince of Rosh, Meshech, and Tubal.\n'),
	(16647, 23, 39, 2, 'I will turn you around, and will lead you on, and will cause you to come up from the uttermost parts of the north; and I will bring you onto the mountains of Israel.\n'),
	(16648, 23, 39, 3, 'I will strike your bow out of your left hand, and will cause your arrows to fall out of your right hand.\n'),
	(16649, 23, 39, 4, 'You will fall on the mountains of Israel, you, and all your hordes, and the peoples who are with you. I will give you to the ravenous birds of every sort, and to the animals of the field to be devoured.\n'),
	(16650, 23, 39, 5, 'You will fall on the open field; for I have spoken it,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16651, 23, 39, 6, '“I will send a fire on Magog, and on those who dwell securely in the islands. Then they will know that I am Yahweh.\n'),
	(16652, 23, 39, 7, '“‘“I will make my holy name known among my people Israel. I won’t allow my holy name to be profaned any more. Then the nations will know that I am Yahweh, the Holy One in Israel.\n'),
	(16653, 23, 39, 8, 'Behold, it comes, and it will be done,” says the Lord Yahweh. “This is the day about which I have spoken.\n'),
	(16654, 23, 39, 9, '“‘“Those who dwell in the cities of Israel will go out, and will make fires of the weapons and burn them, both the shields and the bucklers, the bows and the arrows, and the war clubs and the spears, and they will make fires with them for seven years;\n'),
	(16655, 23, 39, 10, 'so that they will take no wood out of the field, and not cut down any out of the forests; for they will make fires with the weapons. They will plunder those who plundered them, and rob those who robbed them,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16656, 23, 39, 11, '“‘“It will happen in that day, that I will give to Gog a place for burial in Israel, the valley of those who pass through on the east of the sea; and it will stop those who pass through. They will bury Gog and all his multitude there; and they will call it ‘The valley of Hamon Gog’.\n'),
	(16657, 23, 39, 12, '“‘“The house of Israel will be burying them for seven months, that they may cleanse the land.\n'),
	(16658, 23, 39, 13, 'Yes, all the people of the land will bury them; and they will become famous in the day that I will be glorified,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16659, 23, 39, 14, '“‘“They will set apart men of continual employment, who will pass through the land. Those who pass through will go with those who bury those who remain on the surface of the land, to cleanse it. After the end of seven months they will search.\n'),
	(16660, 23, 39, 15, 'Those who pass through the land will pass through; and when anyone sees a man’s bone, then will he set up a sign by it, until the undertakers have buried it in the valley of Hamon Gog.\n'),
	(16661, 23, 39, 16, 'Hamonah will also be the name of a city. Thus will they cleanse the land.”’\n'),
	(16662, 23, 39, 17, '“You, son of man, thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Speak to the birds of every sort, and to every animal of the field, “Assemble yourselves, and come; gather yourselves on every side to my sacrifice that I sacrifice for you, even a great sacrifice on the mountains of Israel, that you may eat meat and drink blood.\n'),
	(16663, 23, 39, 18, 'You shall eat the flesh of the mighty, and drink the blood of the princes of the earth, of rams, of lambs, and of goats, of bulls, all of them fatlings of Bashan.\n'),
	(16664, 23, 39, 19, 'You shall eat fat until you are full, and drink blood until you are drunk, of my sacrifice which I have sacrificed for you.\n'),
	(16665, 23, 39, 20, 'You shall be filled at my table with horses and chariots, with mighty men, and with all men of war,” says the Lord Yahweh.’\n'),
	(16666, 23, 39, 21, '“I will set my glory among the nations. Then all the nations will see my judgment that I have executed, and my hand that I have laid on them.\n'),
	(16667, 23, 39, 22, 'So the house of Israel will know that I am Yahweh their God, from that day and forward.\n'),
	(16668, 23, 39, 23, 'The nations will know that the house of Israel went into captivity for their iniquity; because they trespassed against me, and I hid my face from them; so I gave them into the hand of their adversaries, and they all fell by the sword.\n'),
	(16669, 23, 39, 24, 'I did to them according to their uncleanness and according to their transgressions. I hid my face from them.\n'),
	(16670, 23, 39, 25, '“Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘Now I will reverse the captivity of Jacob, and have mercy on the whole house of Israel. I will be jealous for my holy name.\n'),
	(16671, 23, 39, 26, 'They will bear their shame, and all their trespasses by which they have trespassed against me, when they dwell securely in their land, and no one will make them afraid,\n'),
	(16672, 23, 39, 27, 'when I have brought them back from the peoples, and gathered them out of their enemies’ lands, and am sanctified in them in the sight of many nations.\n'),
	(16673, 23, 39, 28, 'They will know that I am Yahweh their God, in that I caused them to go into captivity among the nations, and have gathered them to their own land. Then I will leave none of them captive any more.\n'),
	(16674, 23, 39, 29, 'I won’t hide my face from them any more; for I have poured out my Spirit on the house of Israel,’ says the Lord Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16675, 23, 40, 1, 'In the twenty-fifth year of our captivity, in the beginning of the year, in the tenth day of the month, in the fourteenth year after that the city was struck, in the same day, Yahweh’s hand was on me, and he brought me there.\n'),
	(16676, 23, 40, 2, 'In the visions of God brought he me into the land of Israel, and set me down on a very high mountain, whereon was as it were the frame of a city on the south.\n'),
	(16677, 23, 40, 3, 'He brought me there; and, behold, there was a man, whose appearance was like the appearance of brass, with a line of flax in his hand, and a measuring reed; and he stood in the gate.\n'),
	(16678, 23, 40, 4, 'The man said to me, “Son of man, see with your eyes, and hear with your ears, and set your heart on all that I will show you; for you have been brought here so that I may show them to you. Declare all that you see to the house of Israel.”\n'),
	(16679, 23, 40, 5, 'Behold, there was a wall on the outside of the house all around, and in the man’s hand a measuring reed six cubits long, of a cubit and a hand width each. So he measured the thickness of the building, one reed; and the height, one reed.\n'),
	(16680, 23, 40, 6, 'Then he came to the gate which looks toward the east, and went up its steps. He measured the threshold of the gate, one reed wide; and the other threshold, one reed wide.\n'),
	(16681, 23, 40, 7, 'Every lodge was one reed long and one reed wide. Between the lodges was five cubits. The threshold of the gate by the porch of the gate toward the house was one reed.\n'),
	(16682, 23, 40, 8, 'He measured also the porch of the gate toward the house, one reed.\n'),
	(16683, 23, 40, 9, 'Then measured he the porch of the gate, eight cubits; and its posts, two cubits; and the porch of the gate was toward the house.\n'),
	(16684, 23, 40, 10, 'The lodges of the gate eastward were three on this side, and three on that side. The three of them were of one measure. The posts had one measure on this side and on that side.\n'),
	(16685, 23, 40, 11, 'He measured the width of the opening of the gate, ten cubits; and the length of the gate, thirteen cubits;\n'),
	(16686, 23, 40, 12, 'and a border before the lodges, one cubit on this side, and a border, one cubit on that side; and the lodges, six cubits on this side, and six cubits on that side.\n'),
	(16687, 23, 40, 13, 'He measured the gate from the roof of the one lodge to the roof of the other, a width of twenty-five cubit, door against door.\n'),
	(16688, 23, 40, 14, 'He also made posts, sixty cubits; and the court reached to the posts, around the gate.\n'),
	(16689, 23, 40, 15, 'From the forefront of the gate at the entrance to the forefront of the inner porch of the gate were fifty cubits.\n'),
	(16690, 23, 40, 16, 'There were closed windows to the lodges, and to their posts within the gate all around, and likewise to the arches. Windows were around inward. Palm trees were on each post.\n'),
	(16691, 23, 40, 17, 'Then brought he me into the outer court. Behold, there were rooms and a pavement made for the court all around. Thirty rooms were on the pavement.\n'),
	(16692, 23, 40, 18, 'The pavement was by the side of the gates, corresponding to the length of the gates, even the lower pavement.\n'),
	(16693, 23, 40, 19, 'Then he measured the width from the forefront of the lower gate to the forefront of the inner court outside, one hundred cubits, both on the east and on the north.\n'),
	(16694, 23, 40, 20, 'He measured the length and width of the gate of the outer court which faces toward the north.\n'),
	(16695, 23, 40, 21, 'The lodges of it were three on this side and three on that side. Its posts and its arches were the same as the measure of the first gate: its length was fifty cubits, and the width twenty-five cubits.\n'),
	(16696, 23, 40, 22, 'Its windows, its arches, and its palm trees were the same as the measure of the gate which faces toward the east. They went up to it by seven steps. Its arches were before them.\n'),
	(16697, 23, 40, 23, 'There was a gate to the inner court facing the other gate, on the north and on the east. He measured one hundred cubits from gate to gate.\n'),
	(16698, 23, 40, 24, 'He led me toward the south; and behold, there was a gate toward the south. He measured its posts and its arches according to these measurements.\n'),
	(16699, 23, 40, 25, 'There were windows in it and in its arches all around, like those windows: the length was fifty cubits, and the width twenty-five cubits.\n'),
	(16700, 23, 40, 26, 'There were seven steps to go up to it, and its arches were before them. It had palm trees, one on this side, and another on that side, on its posts.\n'),
	(16701, 23, 40, 27, 'There was a gate to the inner court toward the south. He measured one hundred cubits from gate to gate toward the south.\n'),
	(16702, 23, 40, 28, 'Then he brought me to the inner court by the south gate. He measured the south gate according to these measurements;\n'),
	(16703, 23, 40, 29, 'with its lodges, its posts, and its arches, according to these measurements. There were windows in it and in its arches all around. It was fifty cubits long, and twenty-five cubits wide.\n'),
	(16704, 23, 40, 30, 'There were arches all around, twenty-five cubits long, and five cubits wide.\n'),
	(16705, 23, 40, 31, 'Its arches were toward the outer court. Palm trees were on its posts. The ascent to it had eight steps.\n'),
	(16706, 23, 40, 32, 'He brought me into the inner court toward the east. He measured the gate according to these measurements;\n'),
	(16707, 23, 40, 33, 'with its lodges, its posts, and its arches, according to these measurements. There were windows in it and in its arches all around. It was fifty cubits long, and twenty-five cubits wide.\n'),
	(16708, 23, 40, 34, 'Its arches were toward the outer court. Palm trees were on its posts on this side and on that side. The ascent to it had eight steps.\n'),
	(16709, 23, 40, 35, 'He brought me to the north gate, and he measured it according to these measurements;\n'),
	(16710, 23, 40, 36, 'its lodges, its posts, and its arches. There were windows in it all around. The length was fifty cubits and the width twenty-five cubits.\n'),
	(16711, 23, 40, 37, 'Its posts were toward the outer court. Palm trees were on its posts on this side and on that side. The ascent to it had eight steps.\n'),
	(16712, 23, 40, 38, 'A room with its door was by the posts at the gates. They washed the burnt offering there.\n'),
	(16713, 23, 40, 39, 'In the porch of the gate were two tables on this side, and two tables on that side, on which to kill the burnt offering, the sin offering, and the trespass offering.\n'),
	(16714, 23, 40, 40, 'On the one side outside, as one goes up to the entry of the gate toward the north, were two tables; and on the other side, which belonged to the porch of the gate, were two tables.\n'),
	(16715, 23, 40, 41, 'Four tables were on this side, and four tables on that side, by the side of the gate: eight tables, on which they killed the sacrifices.\n'),
	(16716, 23, 40, 42, 'There were four tables for the burnt offering, of cut stone, a cubit and a half long, and a cubit and a half wide, and one cubit high. They laid the instruments with which they killed the burnt offering and the sacrifice on them.\n'),
	(16717, 23, 40, 43, 'The hooks, a hand width long, were fastened within all around. The meat of the offering was on the tables.\n'),
	(16718, 23, 40, 44, 'Outside of the inner gate were rooms for the singers in the inner court, which was at the side of the north gate. They faced toward the south. One at the side of the east gate faced toward the north.\n'),
	(16719, 23, 40, 45, 'He said to me, “This room, which faces toward the south, is for the priests, the keepers of the duty of the house.\n'),
	(16720, 23, 40, 46, 'The room which faces toward the north is for the priests, the keepers of the duty of the altar. These are the sons of Zadok, who from among the sons of Levi come near to Yahweh to minister to him.”\n'),
	(16721, 23, 40, 47, 'He measured the court, one hundred cubits long, and a hundred cubits wide, square. The altar was before the house.\n'),
	(16722, 23, 40, 48, 'Then he brought me to the porch of the house, and measured each post of the porch, five cubits on this side, and five cubits on that side. The width of the gate was three cubits on this side and three cubits on that side.\n'),
	(16723, 23, 40, 49, 'The length of the porch was twenty cubits, and the width eleven cubits; even by the steps by which they went up to it. There were pillars by the posts, one on this side, and another on that side.\n'),
	(16724, 23, 41, 1, 'He brought me to the temple, and measured the posts, six cubits wide on the one side, and six cubits wide on the other side, which was the width of the tent.\n'),
	(16725, 23, 41, 2, 'The width of the entrance was ten cubits; and the sides of the entrance were five cubits on the one side, and five cubits on the other side. He measured its length, forty cubits, and the width, twenty cubits.\n'),
	(16726, 23, 41, 3, 'Then he went inward and measured each post of the entrance, two cubits; and the entrance, six cubits; and the width of the entrance, seven cubits.\n'),
	(16727, 23, 41, 4, 'He measured its length, twenty cubits, and the width, twenty cubits, before the temple. He said to me, “This is the most holy place.”\n'),
	(16728, 23, 41, 5, 'Then he measured the wall of the house, six cubits; and the width of every side room, four cubits, all around the house on every side.\n'),
	(16729, 23, 41, 6, 'The side rooms were in three stories, one over another, and thirty in order. They entered into the wall which belonged to the house for the side rooms all around, that they might be supported, and not penetrate the wall of the house.\n'),
	(16730, 23, 41, 7, 'The side rooms were wider on the higher levels, because the walls were narrower at the higher levels. Therefore the width of the house increased upward; and so one went up from the lowest level to the highest through the middle level.\n'),
	(16731, 23, 41, 8, 'I saw also that the house had a raised base all around. The foundations of the side rooms were a full reed of six great cubits.\n'),
	(16732, 23, 41, 9, 'The thickness of the wall, which was for the side rooms, on the outside, was five cubits. That which was left was the place of the side rooms that belonged to the house.\n'),
	(16733, 23, 41, 10, 'Between the rooms was a width of twenty cubits around the house on every side.\n'),
	(16734, 23, 41, 11, 'The doors of the side rooms were toward an open area that was left, one door toward the north, and another door toward the south. The width of the open area was five cubits all around.\n'),
	(16735, 23, 41, 12, 'The building that was before the separate place at the side toward the west was seventy cubits wide; and the wall of the building was five cubits thick all around, and its length ninety cubits.\n'),
	(16736, 23, 41, 13, 'So he measured the house, one hundred cubits long; and the separate place, and the building, with its walls, one hundred cubits long;\n'),
	(16737, 23, 41, 14, 'also the width of the face of the house, and of the separate place toward the east, one hundred cubits.\n'),
	(16738, 23, 41, 15, 'He measured the length of the building before the separate place which was at its back, and its galleries on the one side and on the other side, one hundred cubits from the inner temple, and the porches of the court\n'),
	(16739, 23, 41, 16, 'the thresholds, and the closed windows, and the galleries around on their three stories, over against the threshold, with wood ceilings all around, and from the ground up to the windows, (now the windows were covered),\n'),
	(16740, 23, 41, 17, 'to the space above the door, even to the inner house, and outside, and by all the wall all around inside and outside, by measure.\n'),
	(16741, 23, 41, 18, 'It was made with cherubim and palm trees. A palm tree was between cherub and cherub, and every cherub had two faces;\n'),
	(16742, 23, 41, 19, 'so that there was the face of a man toward the palm tree on the one side, and the face of a young lion toward the palm tree on the other side. It was made like this through all the house all around.\n'),
	(16743, 23, 41, 20, 'Cherubim and palm trees were made from the ground to above the door. The wall of the temple was like this.\n'),
	(16744, 23, 41, 21, 'As for the temple, the door posts were squared. As for the face of the sanctuary, its appearance was as the appearance of the temple.\n'),
	(16745, 23, 41, 22, 'The altar was of wood, three cubits high, and its length two cubits. Its corners, its length, and its walls were of wood. He said to me, “This is the table that is before Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16746, 23, 41, 23, 'The temple and the sanctuary had two doors.\n'),
	(16747, 23, 41, 24, 'The doors had two leaves each, two turning leaves: two for the one door, and two leaves for the other.\n'),
	(16748, 23, 41, 25, 'There were made on them, on the doors of the temple, cherubim and palm trees, like those made on the walls. There was a threshold of wood on the face of the porch outside.\n'),
	(16749, 23, 41, 26, 'There were closed windows and palm trees on the one side and on the other side, on the sides of the porch. This is how the side rooms of the house and the thresholds were arranged.\n'),
	(16750, 23, 42, 1, 'Then he brought me out into the outer court, the way toward the north. Then he brought me into the room that was opposite the separate place, and which was opposite the building toward the north.\n'),
	(16751, 23, 42, 2, 'Before the length of one hundred cubits was the north door, and the width was fifty cubits.\n'),
	(16752, 23, 42, 3, 'Opposite the twenty cubits which belonged to the inner court, and opposite the pavement which belonged to the outer court, was gallery against gallery in the third floor.\n'),
	(16753, 23, 42, 4, 'Before the rooms was a walk of ten cubits’ width inward, a way of one cubit; and their doors were toward the north.\n'),
	(16754, 23, 42, 5, 'Now the upper rooms were shorter; for the galleries took away from these, more than from the lower and the middle, in the building.\n'),
	(16755, 23, 42, 6, 'For they were in three stories, and they didn’t have pillars as the pillars of the courts. Therefore the uppermost was set back more than the lowest and the middle from the ground.\n'),
	(16756, 23, 42, 7, 'The wall that was outside by the side of the rooms, toward the outer court before the rooms, its length was fifty cubits.\n'),
	(16757, 23, 42, 8, 'For the length of the rooms that were in the outer court was fifty cubits. Behold, before the temple were one hundred cubits.\n'),
	(16758, 23, 42, 9, 'From under these rooms was the entry on the east side, as one goes into them from the outer court.\n'),
	(16759, 23, 42, 10, 'In the thickness of the wall of the court toward the east, before the separate place, and before the building, there were rooms.\n'),
	(16760, 23, 42, 11, 'The way before them was like the appearance of the rooms which were toward the north; according to their length so was their width: and all their exits were both according to their fashions, and according to their doors.\n'),
	(16761, 23, 42, 12, 'According to the doors of the rooms that were toward the south was a door at the head of the way, even the way directly before the wall toward the east, as one enters into them.\n'),
	(16762, 23, 42, 13, 'Then he said to me, “The north rooms and the south rooms, which are before the separate place, are the holy rooms, where the priests who are near to Yahweh shall eat the most holy things. There they shall lay the most holy things, with the meal offering, the sin offering, and the trespass offering; for the place is holy.\n'),
	(16763, 23, 42, 14, 'When the priests enter in, then they shall not go out of the holy place into the outer court, but they shall lay their garments in which they minister there; for they are holy. Then they shall put on other garments, and shall approach to that which is for the people.”\n'),
	(16764, 23, 42, 15, 'Now when he had finished measuring the inner house, he brought me out by the way of the gate which faces toward the east, and measured it all around.\n'),
	(16765, 23, 42, 16, 'He measured on the east side with the measuring reed five hundred reeds, with the measuring reed all around.\n'),
	(16766, 23, 42, 17, 'He measured on the north side five hundred reeds with the measuring reed all around.\n'),
	(16767, 23, 42, 18, 'He measured on the south side five hundred reeds with the measuring reed.\n'),
	(16768, 23, 42, 19, 'He turned about to the west side, and measured five hundred reeds with the measuring reed.\n'),
	(16769, 23, 42, 20, 'He measured it on the four sides. It had a wall around it, the length five hundred, and the width five hundred, to make a separation between that which was holy and that which was common.\n'),
	(16770, 23, 43, 1, 'Afterward he brought me to the gate, even the gate that looks toward the east.\n'),
	(16771, 23, 43, 2, 'Behold, the glory of the God of Israel came from the way of the east. His voice was like the sound of many waters; and the earth was illuminated with his glory.\n'),
	(16772, 23, 43, 3, 'It was according to the appearance of the vision which I saw, even according to the vision that I saw when I came to destroy the city; and the visions were like the vision that I saw by the river Chebar; and I fell on my face.\n'),
	(16773, 23, 43, 4, 'Yahweh’s glory came into the house by the way of the gate which faces toward the east.\n'),
	(16774, 23, 43, 5, 'The Spirit took me up, and brought me into the inner court; and behold, Yahweh’s glory filled the house.\n'),
	(16775, 23, 43, 6, 'I heard one speaking to me out of the house; and a man stood by me.\n'),
	(16776, 23, 43, 7, 'He said to me, “Son of man, this is the place of my throne, and the place of the soles of my feet, where I will dwell among the children of Israel forever. The house of Israel will no more defile my holy name, neither they, nor their kings, by their prostitution, and by the dead bodies of their kings in their high places;\n'),
	(16777, 23, 43, 8, 'in their setting of their threshold by my threshold, and their door post beside my door post. There was a wall between me and them; and they have defiled my holy name by their abominations which they have committed. Ttherefore I have consumed them in my anger.\n'),
	(16778, 23, 43, 9, 'Now let them put away their prostitution, and the dead bodies of their kings, far from me. Then I will dwell among them forever.\n'),
	(16779, 23, 43, 10, '“You, son of man, show the house to the house of Israel, that they may be ashamed of their iniquities; and let them measure the pattern.\n'),
	(16780, 23, 43, 11, 'If they are ashamed of all that they have done, make known to them the form of the house, and its fashion, and its exits, and its entrances, and all its forms, and all its ordinances, and all its forms, and all its laws; and write it in their sight; that they may keep the whole form of it, and all its ordinances, and do them.\n'),
	(16781, 23, 43, 12, '“This is the law of the house. On the top of the mountain the whole limit around it shall be most holy. Behold, this is the law of the house.\n'),
	(16782, 23, 43, 13, '“These are the measurements of the altar by cubits (the cubit is a cubit and a hand width): the bottom shall be a cubit, and the width a cubit, and its border around its edge a span; and this shall be the base of the altar.\n'),
	(16783, 23, 43, 14, 'From the bottom on the ground to the lower ledge shall be two cubits, and the width one cubit; and from the lesser ledge to the greater ledge shall be four cubits, and the width a cubit.\n'),
	(16784, 23, 43, 15, 'The upper altar shall be four cubits; and from the altar hearth and upward there shall be four horns.\n'),
	(16785, 23, 43, 16, 'The altar hearth shall be twelve cubits long by twelve wide, square in its four sides.\n'),
	(16786, 23, 43, 17, 'The ledge shall be fourteen cubits long by fourteen wide in its four sides; and the border about it shall be half a cubit; and its bottom shall be a cubit around; and its steps shall look toward the east.”\n'),
	(16787, 23, 43, 18, 'He said to me, “Son of man, thus says the Lord Yahweh: ‘These are the ordinances of the altar in the day when they make it, to offer burnt offerings on it, and to sprinkle blood on it.\n'),
	(16788, 23, 43, 19, 'You shall give to the priests the Levites who are of the offspring of Zadok, who are near to me, to minister to me,’ says the Lord Yahweh, ‘a young bull for a sin offering.\n'),
	(16789, 23, 43, 20, 'You shall take of its blood, and put it on its four horns, and on the four corners of the ledge, and on the border all around. You shall cleanse it and make atonement for it that way.\n'),
	(16790, 23, 43, 21, 'You shall also take the bull of the sin offering, and it shall be burned in the appointed place of the house, outside of the sanctuary.\n'),
	(16791, 23, 43, 22, '“On the second day you shall offer a male goat without defect for a sin offering; and they shall cleanse the altar, as they cleansed it with the bull.\n'),
	(16792, 23, 43, 23, 'When you have finished cleansing it, you shall offer a young bull without defect, and a ram out of the flock without defect.\n'),
	(16793, 23, 43, 24, 'You shall bring them near to Yahweh, and the priests shall cast salt on them, and they shall offer them up for a burnt offering to Yahweh.\n'),
	(16794, 23, 43, 25, '“Seven days you shall prepare every day a goat for a sin offering. They shall also prepare a young bull, and a ram out of the flock, without defect.\n'),
	(16795, 23, 43, 26, 'Seven days shall they make atonement for the altar and purify it. So shall they consecrate it.\n'),
	(16796, 23, 43, 27, 'When they have accomplished the days, it shall be that on the eighth day, and forward, the priests shall make your burnt offerings on the altar, and your peace offerings. Then I will accept you,’ says the Lord Yahweh.”\n'),
	(16797, 23, 44, 1, 'Then he brought me back by the way of the outer gate of the sanctuary, which looks toward the east; and it was shut.\n'),
	(16798, 23, 44, 2, 'Yahweh said to me, “This gate shall be shut. It shall not be opened, no man shall enter in by it; for Yahweh, the God of Israel, has entered in by it. Therefore it shall be shut.\n'),
	(16799, 23, 44, 3, 'As for the prince, he shall sit in it as prince to eat bread before Yahweh. He shall enter by the way of the porch of the gate, and shall go out by the way of the same.”\n'),
	(16800, 23, 44, 4, 'Then he brought me by the way of the north gate before the house; and I looked, and behold, Yahweh’s glory filled Yahweh’s house; so I fell on my face.\n'),
	(16801, 23, 44, 5, 'Yahweh said to me, “Son of man, mark well, and see with your eyes, and hear with your ears all that I tell you concerning all the ordinances of Yahweh’s house, and all its laws; and mark well the entrance of the house, with every exit of the sanctuary.\n'),
	(16802, 23, 44, 6, 'You shall tell the rebellious, even the house of Israel, ‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “You house of Israel, let that be enough of all your abominations,\n'),
	(16803, 23, 44, 7, 'in that you have brought in foreigners, uncircumcised in heart and uncircumcised in flesh, to be in my sanctuary, to profane it, even my house, when you offer my bread, the fat and the blood, and they have broken my covenant, to add to all your abominations.\n'),
	(16804, 23, 44, 8, 'You have not performed the duty of my holy things; but you have set performers of my duty in my sanctuary for yourselves.”\n'),
	(16805, 23, 44, 9, 'Thus says the Lord Yahweh, “No foreigner, uncircumcised in heart and uncircumcised in flesh, shall enter into my sanctuary, of any foreigners who are among the children of Israel.\n'),
	(16806, 23, 44, 10, '“‘“But the Levites who went far from me, when Israel went astray, who went astray from me after their idols, they will bear their iniquity.\n'),
	(16807, 23, 44, 11, 'Yet they shall be ministers in my sanctuary, having oversight at the gates of the house, and ministering in the house. They shall kill the burnt offering and the sacrifice for the people, and they shall stand before them to minister to them.\n'),
	(16808, 23, 44, 12, 'Because they ministered to them before their idols, and became a stumbling block of iniquity to the house of Israel. Therefore I have lifted up my hand against them,” says the Lord Yahweh, “and they will bear their iniquity.\n'),
	(16809, 23, 44, 13, 'They shall not come near to me, to execute the office of priest to me, nor to come near to any of my holy things, to the things that are most holy; but they will bear their shame, and their abominations which they have committed.\n'),
	(16810, 23, 44, 14, 'Yet I will make them performers of the duty of the house, for all its service, and for all that will be done therein.\n'),
	(16811, 23, 44, 15, '“‘“But the priests the Levites, the sons of Zadok, who performed the duty of my sanctuary when the children of Israel went astray from me, shall come near to me to minister to me. They shall stand before me to offer to me the fat and the blood,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16812, 23, 44, 16, '“They shall enter into my sanctuary, and they shall come near to my table, to minister to me, and they shall keep my instruction.\n'),
	(16813, 23, 44, 17, '“‘“It will be that, when they enter in at the gates of the inner court, they shall be clothed with linen garments. No wool shall come on them while they minister in the gates of the inner court, and within.\n'),
	(16814, 23, 44, 18, 'They shall have linen turbans on their heads, and shall have linen breeches on their waists. They shall not clothe themselves with anything that makes them sweat.\n'),
	(16815, 23, 44, 19, 'When they go out into the outer court, even into the outer court to the people, they shall put off their garments in which they minister, and lay them in the holy rooms. They shall put on other garments, that they not sanctify the people with their garments.\n'),
	(16816, 23, 44, 20, '“‘“They shall not shave their heads, or allow their locks to grow long. They shall only cut off the hair of their heads.\n'),
	(16817, 23, 44, 21, 'None of the priests shall drink wine when they enter into the inner court.\n'),
	(16818, 23, 44, 22, 'They shall not take for their wives a widow, or her who is put away; but they shall take virgins of the offspring of the house of Israel, or a widow who is the widow of a priest.\n'),
	(16819, 23, 44, 23, 'They shall teach my people the difference between the holy and the common, and cause them to discern between the unclean and the clean.\n'),
	(16820, 23, 44, 24, '“‘“In a controversy they shall stand to judge. They shall judge it according to my ordinances. They shall keep my laws and my statutes in all my appointed feasts. They shall make my Sabbaths holy.\n'),
	(16821, 23, 44, 25, '“‘“They shall go in to no dead person to defile themselves; but for father, or for mother, or for son, or for daughter, for brother, or for sister who has had no husband, they may defile themselves.\n'),
	(16822, 23, 44, 26, 'After he is cleansed, they shall reckon to him seven days.\n'),
	(16823, 23, 44, 27, 'In the day that he goes into the sanctuary, into the inner court, to minister in the sanctuary, he shall offer his sin offering,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16824, 23, 44, 28, '“‘They shall have an inheritance. I am their inheritance; and you shall give them no possession in Israel. I am their possession.\n'),
	(16825, 23, 44, 29, 'They shall eat the meal offering, and the sin offering, and the trespass offering; and every devoted thing in Israel shall be theirs.\n'),
	(16826, 23, 44, 30, 'The first of all the first fruits of every thing, and every offering of everything, of all your offerings, shall be for the priest. You shall also give to the priests the first of your dough, to cause a blessing to rest on your house.\n'),
	(16827, 23, 44, 31, 'The priests shall not eat of anything that dies of itself, or is torn, whether it is bird or animal.\n'),
	(16828, 23, 45, 1, '“‘“Moreover, when you divide by lot the land for inheritance, you shall offer an offering to Yahweh, a holy portion of the land. The length shall be the length of twenty-five thousand reeds, and the width shall be ten thousand. It shall be holy in all its border all around.\n'),
	(16829, 23, 45, 2, 'Of this there shall be a five hundred by five hundred square for the holy place; and fifty cubits for its suburbs all around.\n'),
	(16830, 23, 45, 3, 'Of this measure you shall measure a length of twenty-five thousand, and a width of ten thousand. In it shall be the sanctuary, which is most holy.\n'),
	(16831, 23, 45, 4, 'It is a holy portion of the land; it shall be for the priests, the ministers of the sanctuary, who come near to minister to Yahweh. It shall be a place for their houses and a holy place for the sanctuary.\n'),
	(16832, 23, 45, 5, 'Twenty-five thousand in length, and ten thousand in width, shall be for the Levites, the ministers of the house, as a possession for themselves, for twenty rooms.\n'),
	(16833, 23, 45, 6, '“‘“You shall appoint the possession of the city five thousand wide, and twenty-five thousand long, side by side with the offering of the holy portion: it shall be for the whole house of Israel.\n'),
	(16834, 23, 45, 7, '“‘“What is for the prince shall be on the one side and on the other side of the holy offering and of the possession of the city, in front of the holy offering and in front of the possession of the city, on the west side westward, and on the east side eastward; and in length answerable to one of the portions, from the west border to the east border.\n'),
	(16835, 23, 45, 8, 'In the land it shall be to him for a possession in Israel. My princes shall no more oppress my people; but they shall give the land to the house of Israel according to their tribes.”\n'),
	(16836, 23, 45, 9, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “Let it suffice you, princes of Israel: remove violence and plunder, and execute justice and righteousness; dispossessing my people,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16837, 23, 45, 10, '“You shall have just balances, a just ephah, and a just bath.\n'),
	(16838, 23, 45, 11, 'The ephah and the bath shall be of one measure, that the bath may contain one tenth of a homer, and the ephah one tenth of a homer. Its measure shall be the same as the homer.\n'),
	(16839, 23, 45, 12, 'The shekel shall be twenty gerahs. Twenty shekels plus twenty-five shekels plus fifteen shekels shall be your mina.\n'),
	(16840, 23, 45, 13, '“‘“This is the offering that you shall offer: the sixth part of an ephah from a homer of wheat; and you shall give the sixth part of an ephah from a homer of barley;\n'),
	(16841, 23, 45, 14, 'and the set portion of oil, of the bath of oil, one tenth of a bath out of the cor, which is ten baths, even a homer; (for ten baths are a homer;)\n'),
	(16842, 23, 45, 15, 'and one lamb of the flock, out of two hundred, from the well-watered pastures of Israel—for a meal offering, and for a burnt offering, and for peace offerings, to make atonement for them,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16843, 23, 45, 16, '“All the people of the land shall give to this offering for the prince in Israel.\n'),
	(16844, 23, 45, 17, 'It shall be the prince’s part to give the burnt offerings, the meal offerings, and the drink offerings, in the feasts, and on the new moons, and on the Sabbaths, in all the appointed feasts of the house of Israel. He shall prepare the sin offering, the meal offering, the burnt offering, and the peace offerings, to make atonement for the house of Israel.”\n'),
	(16845, 23, 45, 18, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “In the first month, in the first day of the month, you shall take a young bull without defect; and you shall cleanse the sanctuary.\n'),
	(16846, 23, 45, 19, 'The priest shall take of the blood of the sin offering, and put it on the door posts of the house, and on the four corners of the ledge of the altar, and on the posts of the gate of the inner court.\n'),
	(16847, 23, 45, 20, 'So you shall do on the seventh day of the month for everyone who errs, and for him who is simple. So you shall make atonement for the house.\n'),
	(16848, 23, 45, 21, '“‘“In the first month, in the fourteenth day of the month, you shall have the Passover, a feast of seven days; unleavened bread shall be eaten.\n'),
	(16849, 23, 45, 22, 'On that day the prince shall prepare for himself and for all the people of the land a bull for a sin offering.\n'),
	(16850, 23, 45, 23, 'The seven days of the feast he shall prepare a burnt offering to Yahweh, seven bulls and seven rams without defect daily the seven days; and a male goat daily for a sin offering.\n'),
	(16851, 23, 45, 24, 'He shall prepare a meal offering, an ephah for a bull, and an ephah for a ram, and a hin of oil to an ephah.\n'),
	(16852, 23, 45, 25, '“‘“In the seventh month, in the fifteenth day of the month, in the feast, he shall do like like that for seven days; according to the sin offering, according to the burnt offering, and according to the meal offering, and according to the oil.”\n'),
	(16853, 23, 46, 1, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “The gate of the inner court that looks toward the east shall be shut the six working days; but on the Sabbath day it shall be opened, and on the day of the new moon it shall be opened.\n'),
	(16854, 23, 46, 2, 'The prince shall enter by the way of the porch of the gate outside, and shall stand by the post of the gate; and the priests shall prepare his burnt offering and his peace offerings, and he shall worship at the threshold of the gate. Then he shall go out; but the gate shall not be shut until the evening.\n'),
	(16855, 23, 46, 3, 'The people of the land shall worship at the door of that gate before Yahweh on the Sabbaths and on the new moons.\n'),
	(16856, 23, 46, 4, 'The burnt offering that the prince shall offer to Yahweh shall be on the Sabbath day six lambs without defect and a ram without defect;\n'),
	(16857, 23, 46, 5, 'and the meal offering shall be an ephah for the ram, and the meal offering for the lambs as he is able to give, and a hin of oil to an ephah.\n'),
	(16858, 23, 46, 6, 'On the day of the new moon it shall be a young bull without defect, and six lambs, and a ram. They shall be without defect.\n'),
	(16859, 23, 46, 7, 'He shall prepare a meal offering, an ephah for the bull, and an ephah for the ram, and for the lambs according as he is able, and a hin of oil to an ephah.\n'),
	(16860, 23, 46, 8, 'When the prince enters, he shall go in by the way of the porch of the gate, and he shall go out by its way.\n'),
	(16861, 23, 46, 9, '“‘“But when the people of the land come before Yahweh in the appointed feasts, he who enters by the way of the north gate to worship shall go out by the way of the south gate; and he who enters by the way of the south gate shall go out by the way of the north gate. He shall not return by the way of the gate by which he came in, but shall go out straight before him.\n'),
	(16862, 23, 46, 10, 'The prince shall go in with them when they go in. When they go out, he shall go out.\n'),
	(16863, 23, 46, 11, '“‘“In the feasts and in the solemnities the meal offering shall be an ephah\n for a bull, and an ephah for a ram, and for the lambs as he is able to give, and a hin of oil to an ephah.\n'),
	(16864, 23, 46, 12, 'When the prince prepares a freewill offering, a burnt offering or peace offerings as a freewill offering to Yahweh, one shall open for him the gate that looks toward the east; and he shall prepare his burnt offering and his peace offerings, as he does on the Sabbath day. Then he shall go out; and after his going out one shall shut the gate.\n'),
	(16865, 23, 46, 13, '“‘“You shall prepare a lamb a year old without defect for a burnt offering to Yahweh daily. Morning by morning you shall prepare it.\n'),
	(16866, 23, 46, 14, 'You shall prepare a meal offering with it morning by morning, the sixth part of an ephah, and the third part of a hin of oil, to moisten the fine flour; a meal offering to Yahweh continually by a perpetual ordinance.\n'),
	(16867, 23, 46, 15, 'Thus they shall prepare the lamb, the meal offering, and the oil, morning by morning, for a continual burnt offering.”\n'),
	(16868, 23, 46, 16, '“‘Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “If the prince gives a gift to any of his sons, it is his inheritance. It shall belong to his sons. It is their possession by inheritance.\n'),
	(16869, 23, 46, 17, 'But if he gives of his inheritance a gift to one of his servants, it shall be his to the year of liberty; then it shall return to the prince; but as for his inheritance, it shall be for his sons.\n'),
	(16870, 23, 46, 18, 'Moreover the prince shall not take of the people’s inheritance, to thrust them out of their possession. He shall give inheritance to his sons out of his own possession, that my people not each be scattered from his possession.”’”\n'),
	(16871, 23, 46, 19, 'Then he brought me through the entry, which was at the side of the gate, into the holy rooms for the priests, which looked toward the north. Behold, there was a place on the back part westward.\n'),
	(16872, 23, 46, 20, 'He said to me, “This is the place where the priests shall boil the trespass offering and the sin offering, and where they shall bake the meal offering; that they not bring them out into the outer court, to sanctify the people.”\n'),
	(16873, 23, 46, 21, 'Then he brought me out into the outer court, and caused me to pass by the four corners of the court; and behold, in every corner of the court there was a court.\n'),
	(16874, 23, 46, 22, 'In the four corners of the court there were courts enclosed, forty cubits long and thirty wide. These four in the corners were the same size.\n'),
	(16875, 23, 46, 23, 'There was a wall around in them, around the four, and boiling places were made under the walls all around.\n'),
	(16876, 23, 46, 24, 'Then he said to me, “These are the boiling houses, where the ministers of the house shall boil the sacrifice of the people.”\n'),
	(16877, 23, 47, 1, 'He brought me back to the door of the house; and behold, waters flowed out from under the threshold of the house eastward, for the front of the house faced toward the east. The waters came down from underneath, from the right side of the house, on the south of the altar.\n'),
	(16878, 23, 47, 2, 'Then he brought me out by the way of the gate northward, and led me around by the way outside to the outer gate, by the way of the gate that looks toward the east. Behold, waters ran out on the right side.\n'),
	(16879, 23, 47, 3, 'When the man went out eastward with the line in his hand, he measured one thousand cubits, and he caused me to pass through the waters, waters that were to the ankles.\n'),
	(16880, 23, 47, 4, 'Again he measured one thousand, and caused me to pass through the waters, waters that were to the knees. Again he measured one thousand, and caused me to pass through waters that were to the waist.\n'),
	(16881, 23, 47, 5, 'Afterward he measured one thousand; and it was a river that I could not pass through; for the waters had risen, waters to swim in, a river that could not be walked through.\n'),
	(16882, 23, 47, 6, 'He said to me, “Son of man, have you seen?”\nThen he brought me, and caused me to return to the bank of the river.\n'),
	(16883, 23, 47, 7, 'Now when I had returned, behold, on the bank of the river were very many trees on the one side and on the other.\n'),
	(16884, 23, 47, 8, 'Then he said to me, “These waters flow out toward the eastern region, and will go down into the Arabah. Then they will go toward the sea; and flow into the sea which will be made to flow out; and the waters will be healed.\n'),
	(16885, 23, 47, 9, 'It will happen, that every living creature which swarms, in every place where the rivers come, will live. Then there will be a very great multitude of fish; for these waters have come there, and the waters of the sea will be healed, and everything will live wherever the river comes.\n'),
	(16886, 23, 47, 10, 'It will happen, that fishermen will stand by it. From En Gedi even to En Eglaim will be a place for the spreading of nets. Their fish will be after their kinds, as the fish of the great sea, exceedingly many.\n'),
	(16887, 23, 47, 11, 'But the miry places of it, and its marshes, will not be healed. They will be given up to salt.\n'),
	(16888, 23, 47, 12, 'By the river on its bank, on this side and on that side, will grow every tree for food, whose leaf won’t wither, neither will its fruit fail. It will produce new fruit every month, because its waters issue out of the sanctuary. Its fruit will be for food, and its leaf for healing.”\n'),
	(16889, 23, 47, 13, 'Thus says the Lord Yahweh: “This shall be the border, by which you shall divide the land for inheritance according to the twelve tribes of Israel. Joseph shall have two portions.\n'),
	(16890, 23, 47, 14, 'You shall inherit it, one as well as another; for I swore to give it to your fathers. This land will fall to you for inheritance.\n'),
	(16891, 23, 47, 15, '“This shall be the border of the land:\n“On the north side, from the great sea, by the way of Hethlon, to the entrance of Zedad;\n'),
	(16892, 23, 47, 16, 'Hamath, Berothah, Sibraim, which is between the border of Damascus and the border of Hamath; Hazer Hatticon, which is by the border of Hauran.\n'),
	(16893, 23, 47, 17, 'The border from the sea, shall be Hazar Enon at the border of Damascus; and on the north northward is the border of Hamath. This is the north side.\n'),
	(16894, 23, 47, 18, '“The east side, between Hauran and Damascus and Gilead, and the land of Israel, shall be the Jordan; from the north border to the east sea you shall measure. This is the east side.\n'),
	(16895, 23, 47, 19, '“The south side southward shall be from Tamar as far as the waters of Meriboth Kadesh, to the brook, to the great sea. This is the south side southward.\n'),
	(16896, 23, 47, 20, '“The west side shall be the great sea, from the south border as far as over against the entrance of Hamath. This is the west side.\n'),
	(16897, 23, 47, 21, '“So you shall divide this land to yourselves according to the tribes of Israel.\n'),
	(16898, 23, 47, 22, 'It will happen, that you shall divide it by lot for an inheritance to you and to the aliens who live among you, who will father children among you. Then they shall be to you as the native-born among the children of Israel. They shall have inheritance with you among the tribes of Israel.\n'),
	(16899, 23, 47, 23, 'It shall happen, that in whatever tribe the stranger lives, there you shall give him his inheritance,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16900, 23, 48, 1, '“Now these are the names of the tribes: From the north end, beside the way of Hethlon to the entrance of Hamath, Hazar Enan at the border of Damascus, northward beside Hamath (and they shall have their sides east and west), Dan, one portion.\n'),
	(16901, 23, 48, 2, '“By the border of Dan, from the east side to the west side, Asher, one portion.\n'),
	(16902, 23, 48, 3, '“By the border of Asher, from the east side even to the west side, Naphtali, one portion.\n'),
	(16903, 23, 48, 4, '“By the border of Naphtali, from the east side to the west side, Manasseh, one portion.\n'),
	(16904, 23, 48, 5, '“By the border of Manasseh, from the east side to the west side, Ephraim, one portion.\n'),
	(16905, 23, 48, 6, '“By the border of Ephraim, from the east side even to the west side, Reuben, one portion.\n'),
	(16906, 23, 48, 7, '“By the border of Reuben, from the east side to the west side, Judah, one portion.\n'),
	(16907, 23, 48, 8, '“By the border of Judah, from the east side to the west side, shall be the offering which you shall offer, twenty-five thousand reeds in width, and in length as one of the portions, from the east side to the west side: and the sanctuary shall be in the middle of it.\n'),
	(16908, 23, 48, 9, '“The offering that you shall offer to Yahweh shall be twenty-five thousand reeds in length, and ten thousand in width.\n'),
	(16909, 23, 48, 10, 'For these, even for the priests, shall be the holy offering: toward the north twenty-five thousand in length, and toward the west ten thousand in width, and toward the east ten thousand in width, and toward the south twenty-five thousand in length: and the sanctuary of Yahweh shall be in the middle of it.\n'),
	(16910, 23, 48, 11, 'It shall be for the priests who are sanctified of the sons of Zadok, who have kept my instruction, who didn’t go astray when the children of Israel went astray, as the Levites went astray.\n'),
	(16911, 23, 48, 12, 'It shall be to them an offering from the offering of the land, a most holy thing, by the border of the Levites.\n'),
	(16912, 23, 48, 13, '“Answerable to the border of the priests, the Levites shall have twenty-five thousand in length, and ten thousand in width. All the length shall be twenty-five thousand, and the width ten thousand.\n'),
	(16913, 23, 48, 14, 'They shall sell none of it, nor exchange it, nor shall the first fruits of the land be alienated; for it is holy to Yahweh.\n'),
	(16914, 23, 48, 15, '“The five thousand that are left in the width, in front of the twenty-five thousand, shall be for common use, for the city, for dwelling and for suburbs; and the city shall be in the middle of it.\n'),
	(16915, 23, 48, 16, 'These shall be its measurements: the north side four thousand and five hundred, and the south side four thousand and five hundred, and on the east side four thousand and five hundred, and the west side four thousand and five hundred.\n'),
	(16916, 23, 48, 17, 'The city shall have suburbs: toward the north two hundred fifty, and toward the south two hundred fifty, and toward the east two hundred fifty, and toward the west two hundred fifty.\n'),
	(16917, 23, 48, 18, 'The remainder in the length, alongside the holy offering, shall be ten thousand eastward, and ten thousand westward; and it shall be alongside the holy offering. Its increase shall be for food to those who labor in the city.\n'),
	(16918, 23, 48, 19, 'Those who labor in the city, out of all the tribes of Israel, shall cultivate it.\n'),
	(16919, 23, 48, 20, 'All the offering shall be a square of twenty-five thousand by twenty-five thousand. You shall offer it as a holy offering, with the possession of the city.\n'),
	(16920, 23, 48, 21, '“The remainder shall be for the prince, on the one side and on the other of the holy offering and of the possession of the city; in front of the twenty-five thousand of the offering toward the east border, and westward in front of the twenty-five thousand toward the west border, alongside the portions, it shall be for the prince. The holy offering and the sanctuary of the house shall be in the middle of it.\n'),
	(16921, 23, 48, 22, 'Moreover from the possession of the Levites, and from the possession of the city, being in the middle of that which is the prince’s, between the border of Judah and the border of Benjamin, shall be for the prince.\n'),
	(16922, 23, 48, 23, '“As for the rest of the tribes: from the east side to the west side, Benjamin, one portion.\n'),
	(16923, 23, 48, 24, '“By the border of Benjamin, from the east side to the west side, Simeon, one portion.\n'),
	(16924, 23, 48, 25, '“By the border of Simeon, from the east side to the west side, Issachar, one portion.\n'),
	(16925, 23, 48, 26, '“By the border of Issachar, from the east side to the west side, Zebulun, one portion.\n'),
	(16926, 23, 48, 27, '“By the border of Zebulun, from the east side to the west side, Gad, one portion.\n'),
	(16927, 23, 48, 28, '“By the border of Gad, at the south side southward, the border shall be even from Tamar to the waters of Meribath Kadesh, to the brook, to the great sea.\n'),
	(16928, 23, 48, 29, '“This is the land which you shall divide by lot to the tribes of Israel for inheritance, and these are their several portions, says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(16929, 23, 48, 30, '“These are the exits of the city: On the north side four thousand and five hundred reeds by measure;\n'),
	(16930, 23, 48, 31, 'and the gates of the city shall be named after the tribes of Israel, three gates northward: the gate of Reuben, one; the gate of Judah, one; the gate of Levi, one.\n'),
	(16931, 23, 48, 32, '“At the east side four thousand and five hundred reeds, and three gates: even the gate of Joseph, one; the gate of Benjamin, one; the gate of Dan, one.\n'),
	(16932, 23, 48, 33, '“At the south side four thousand and five hundred reeds by measure, and three gates: the gate of Simeon, one; the gate of Issachar, one; the gate of Zebulun, one.\n'),
	(16933, 23, 48, 34, '“At the west side four thousand and five hundred reeds, with their three gates: the gate of Gad, one; the gate of Asher, one; the gate of Naphtali, one.\n'),
	(16934, 23, 48, 35, '“It shall be eighteen thousand reeds around: and the name of the city from that day shall be, ‘Yahweh is there.’\n'),
	(16935, 24, 1, 1, 'In the third year of the reign of Jehoiakim king of Judah Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon came to Jerusalem and besieged it.\n'),
	(16936, 24, 1, 2, 'The Lord gave Jehoiakim king of Judah into his hand, with part of the vessels of the house of God;\n and he carried them into the land of Shinar to the house of his god. He brought the vessels into the treasure house of his god.\n'),
	(16937, 24, 1, 3, 'The king spoke to Ashpenaz the master of his eunuchs, that he should bring in some of the children of Israel, even of the royal offspring and of the nobles;\n'),
	(16938, 24, 1, 4, 'youths in whom was no defect, but well-favored, and skillful in all wisdom, and endowed with knowledge, and understanding science, and who had the ability to stand in the king’s palace; and that he should teach them the learning and the language of the Chaldeans.\n'),
	(16939, 24, 1, 5, 'The king appointed for them a daily portion of the king’s dainties, and of the wine which he drank, and that they should be nourished three years; that at its end they should stand before the king.\n'),
	(16940, 24, 1, 6, 'Now among these were of the children of Judah: Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah.\n'),
	(16941, 24, 1, 7, 'The prince of the eunuchs gave names to them: to Daniel he gave the name Belteshazzar; to Hananiah, Shadrach; to Mishael, Meshach; and to Azariah, Abednego.\n'),
	(16942, 24, 1, 8, 'But Daniel purposed in his heart that he would not defile himself with the king’s dainties, nor with the wine which he drank. Therefore he requested of the prince of the eunuchs that he might not defile himself.\n'),
	(16943, 24, 1, 9, 'Now God made Daniel find kindness and compassion in the sight of the prince of the eunuchs.\n'),
	(16944, 24, 1, 10, 'The prince of the eunuchs said to Daniel, “I fear my lord the king, who has appointed your food and your drink. For why should he see your faces worse looking than the youths who are of your own age? So would you endanger my head with the king.”\n'),
	(16945, 24, 1, 11, 'Then Daniel said to the steward whom the prince of the eunuchs had appointed over Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah:\n'),
	(16946, 24, 1, 12, '“Test your servants, I beg you, ten days; and let them give us vegetables to eat, and water to drink.\n'),
	(16947, 24, 1, 13, 'Then let our faces be examined before you, and the face of the youths who eat of the king’s dainties; and as you see, deal with your servants.”\n'),
	(16948, 24, 1, 14, 'So he listened to them in this matter, and tested them for ten days.\n'),
	(16949, 24, 1, 15, 'At the end of ten days, their faces appeared fairer, and they were fatter in flesh, than all the youths who ate of the king’s dainties.\n'),
	(16950, 24, 1, 16, 'So the steward took away their dainties, and the wine that they would drink, and gave them vegetables.\n'),
	(16951, 24, 1, 17, 'Now as for these four youths, God gave them knowledge and skill in all learning and wisdom; and Daniel had understanding in all visions and dreams.\n'),
	(16952, 24, 1, 18, 'At the end of the days which the king had appointed for bringing them in, the prince of the eunuchs brought them in before Nebuchadnezzar.\n'),
	(16953, 24, 1, 19, 'The king talked with them; and among them all was found no one like Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah. Therefore stood they before the king.\n'),
	(16954, 24, 1, 20, 'In every matter of wisdom and understanding, concerning which the king inquired of them, he found them ten times better than all the magicians and enchanters who were in all his realm.\n'),
	(16955, 24, 1, 21, 'Daniel continued even to the first year of king Cyrus.\n'),
	(16956, 24, 2, 1, 'In the second year of the reign of Nebuchadnezzar, Nebuchadnezzar dreamed dreams; and his spirit was troubled, and his sleep went from him.\n'),
	(16957, 24, 2, 2, 'Then the king commanded to call the magicians, and the enchanters, and the sorcerers, and the Chaldeans, to tell the king his dreams. So they came in and stood before the king.\n'),
	(16958, 24, 2, 3, 'The king said to them, “I have dreamed a dream, and my spirit is troubled to know the dream.”\n'),
	(16959, 24, 2, 4, 'Then the Chaldeans spoke to the king in the Syrian language, “O king, live forever! Tell your servants the dream, and we will show the interpretation.”\n'),
	(16960, 24, 2, 5, 'The king answered the Chaldeans, “The thing has gone from me. If you don’t make known to me the dream and its interpretation, you will be cut in pieces, and your houses will be made a dunghill.\n'),
	(16961, 24, 2, 6, 'But if you show the dream and its interpretation, you will receive of me gifts and rewards and great honor. Therefore show me the dream and its interpretation.”\n'),
	(16962, 24, 2, 7, 'They answered the second time and said, “Let the king tell his servants the dream, and we will show the interpretation.”\n'),
	(16963, 24, 2, 8, 'The king answered, “I know of a certainty that you are trying to gain time, because you see the thing has gone from me.\n'),
	(16964, 24, 2, 9, 'But if you don’t make known to me the dream, there is but one law for you; for you have prepared lying and corrupt words to speak before me, until the situation changes. Therefore tell me the dream, and I will know that you can show me its interpretation.”\n'),
	(16965, 24, 2, 10, 'The Chaldeans answered before the king, and said, “There is not a man on the earth who can show the king’s matter, because no king, lord, or ruler, has asked such a thing of any magician, or enchanter, or Chaldean.\n'),
	(16966, 24, 2, 11, 'It is a rare thing that the king requires, and there is no other who can show it before the king, except the gods, whose dwelling is not with flesh.”\n'),
	(16967, 24, 2, 12, 'Because of this, the king was angry and very furious, and commanded that all the wise men of Babylon be destroyed.\n'),
	(16968, 24, 2, 13, 'So the decree went out, and the wise men were to be slain. They sought Daniel and his companions to be slain.\n'),
	(16969, 24, 2, 14, 'Then Daniel returned answer with counsel and prudence to Arioch the captain of the king’s guard, who had gone out to kill the wise men of Babylon.\n'),
	(16970, 24, 2, 15, 'He answered Arioch the king’s captain, “Why is the decree so urgent from the king?” Then Arioch made the thing known to Daniel.\n'),
	(16971, 24, 2, 16, 'Daniel went in, and desired of the king that he would appoint him a time, and he would show the king the interpretation.\n'),
	(16972, 24, 2, 17, 'Then Daniel went to his house and made the thing known to Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah, his companions:\n'),
	(16973, 24, 2, 18, 'that they would desire mercies of the God of heaven concerning this secret; that Daniel and his companions would not perish with the rest of the wise men of Babylon.\n'),
	(16974, 24, 2, 19, 'Then the secret was revealed to Daniel in a vision of the night. Then Daniel blessed the God of heaven.\n'),
	(16975, 24, 2, 20, 'Daniel answered,\n“Blessed be the name of God forever and ever;\nfor wisdom and might are his.\n'),
	(16976, 24, 2, 21, 'He changes the times and the seasons.\nHe removes kings, and sets up kings.\nHe gives wisdom to the wise,\nand knowledge to those who have understanding.\n'),
	(16977, 24, 2, 22, 'He reveals the deep and secret things.\nHe knows what is in the darkness,\nand the light dwells with him.\n'),
	(16978, 24, 2, 23, 'I thank you, and praise you,\nyou God of my fathers,\nwho have given me wisdom and might,\nand have now made known to me what we desired of you;\nfor you have made known to us the king’s matter.”\n'),
	(16979, 24, 2, 24, 'Therefore Daniel went in to Arioch, whom the king had appointed to destroy the wise men of Babylon. He went and said this to him: “Don’t destroy the wise men of Babylon. Bring me in before the king, and I will show to the king the interpretation.”\n'),
	(16980, 24, 2, 25, 'Then Arioch brought in Daniel before the king in haste, and said this to him: “I have found a man of the children of the captivity of Judah who will make known to the king the interpretation.”\n'),
	(16981, 24, 2, 26, 'The king answered Daniel, whose name was Belteshazzar, “Are you able to make known to me the dream which I have seen, and its interpretation?”\n'),
	(16982, 24, 2, 27, 'Daniel answered before the king, and said, “The secret which the king has demanded can’t be shown to the king by wise men, enchanters, magicians, or soothsayers;\n'),
	(16983, 24, 2, 28, 'but there is a God in heaven who reveals secrets, and he has made known to the king Nebuchadnezzar what will be in the latter days. Your dream, and the visions of your head on your bed, are these:\n'),
	(16984, 24, 2, 29, '“As for you, O king, your thoughts came on your bed, what should happen hereafter; and he who reveals secrets has made known to you what will happen.\n'),
	(16985, 24, 2, 30, 'But as for me, this secret is not revealed to me for any wisdom that I have more than any living, but to the intent that the interpretation may be made known to the king, and that you may know the thoughts of your heart.\n'),
	(16986, 24, 2, 31, '“You, O king, saw, and behold, a great image. This image, which was mighty, and whose brightness was excellent, stood before you; and its appearance was terrifying.\n'),
	(16987, 24, 2, 32, 'As for this image, its head was of fine gold, its breast and its arms of silver, its belly and its thighs of brass,\n'),
	(16988, 24, 2, 33, 'its legs of iron, its feet part of iron, and part of clay.\n'),
	(16989, 24, 2, 34, 'You saw until a stone was cut out without hands, which struck the image on its feet that were of iron and clay, and broke them in pieces.\n'),
	(16990, 24, 2, 35, 'Then the iron, the clay, the brass, the silver, and the gold were broken in pieces together, and became like the chaff of the summer threshing floors. The wind carried them away, so that no place was found for them. The stone that struck the image became a great mountain, and filled the whole earth.\n'),
	(16991, 24, 2, 36, '“This is the dream; and we will tell its interpretation before the king.\n'),
	(16992, 24, 2, 37, 'You, O king, are king of kings, to whom the God of heaven has given the kingdom, the power, the strength, and the glory.\n'),
	(16993, 24, 2, 38, 'Wherever the children of men dwell, he has given the animals of the field and the birds of the sky into your hand, and has made you rule over them all. You are the head of gold.\n'),
	(16994, 24, 2, 39, '“After you, another kingdom will arise that is inferior to you; and another third kingdom of brass, which will rule over all the earth.\n'),
	(16995, 24, 2, 40, 'The fourth kingdom will be strong as iron, because iron breaks in pieces and subdues all things; and as iron that crushes all these, it will break in pieces and crush.\n'),
	(16996, 24, 2, 41, 'Whereas you saw the feet and toes, part of potters’ clay, and part of iron, it will be a divided kingdom; but there will be in it of the strength of the iron, because you saw the iron mixed with miry clay.\n'),
	(16997, 24, 2, 42, 'As the toes of the feet were part of iron, and part of clay, so the kingdom will be partly strong, and partly broken.\n'),
	(16998, 24, 2, 43, 'Whereas you saw the iron mixed with miry clay, they will mingle themselves with the seed of men; but they won’t cling to one another, even as iron does not mix with clay.\n'),
	(16999, 24, 2, 44, '“In the days of those kings the God of heaven will set up a kingdom which will never be destroyed, nor will its sovereignty be left to another people; but it will break in pieces and consume all these kingdoms, and it will stand forever.\n'),
	(17000, 24, 2, 45, 'Because you saw that a stone was cut out of the mountain without hands, and that it broke in pieces the iron, the brass, the clay, the silver, and the gold; the great God has made known to the king what will happen hereafter. The dream is certain, and its interpretation sure.”\n'),
	(17001, 24, 2, 46, 'Then the king Nebuchadnezzar fell on his face, worshiped Daniel, and commanded that they should offer an offering and sweet odors to him.\n'),
	(17002, 24, 2, 47, 'The king answered to Daniel, and said, “Of a truth your God is the God of gods, and the Lord of kings, and a revealer of secrets, since you have been able to reveal this secret.”\n'),
	(17003, 24, 2, 48, 'Then the king made Daniel great, and gave him many great gifts, and made him rule over the whole province of Babylon, and to be chief governor over all the wise men of Babylon.\n'),
	(17004, 24, 2, 49, 'Daniel requested of the king, and he appointed Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego over the affairs of the province of Babylon; but Daniel was in the king’s gate.\n'),
	(17005, 24, 3, 1, 'Nebuchadnezzar the king made an image of gold, whose height was sixty cubits, and its width six cubits. He set it up in the plain of Dura, in the province of Babylon.\n'),
	(17006, 24, 3, 2, 'Then Nebuchadnezzar the king sent to gather together the satraps, the deputies, and the governors, the judges, the treasurers, the counselors, the sheriffs, and all the rulers of the provinces, to come to the dedication of the image which Nebuchadnezzar the king had set up.\n'),
	(17007, 24, 3, 3, 'Then the satraps, the deputies, and the governors, the judges, the treasurers, the counselors, the sheriffs, and all the rulers of the provinces, were gathered together to the dedication of the image that Nebuchadnezzar the king had set up; and they stood before the image that Nebuchadnezzar had set up.\n'),
	(17008, 24, 3, 4, 'Then the herald cried aloud, “To you it is commanded, peoples, nations, and languages,\n'),
	(17009, 24, 3, 5, 'that whenever you hear the sound of the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp, pipe, and all kinds of music, you fall down and worship the golden image that Nebuchadnezzar the king has set up.\n'),
	(17010, 24, 3, 6, 'Whoever doesn’t fall down and worship shall be cast into the middle of a burning fiery furnace the same hour.”\n'),
	(17011, 24, 3, 7, 'Therefore at that time, when all the peoples heard the sound of the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp, pipe, and all kinds of music, all the peoples, the nations, and the languages, fell down and worshiped the golden image that Nebuchadnezzar the king had set up.\n'),
	(17012, 24, 3, 8, 'Therefore at that time certain Chaldeans came near, and brought accusation against the Jews.\n'),
	(17013, 24, 3, 9, 'They answered Nebuchadnezzar the king, “O king, live for ever!\n'),
	(17014, 24, 3, 10, 'You, O king, have made a decree, that every man that hears the sound of the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp, pipe, and all kinds of music, shall fall down and worship the golden image;\n'),
	(17015, 24, 3, 11, 'and whoever doesn’t fall down and worship shall be cast into the middle of a burning fiery furnace.\n'),
	(17016, 24, 3, 12, 'There are certain Jews whom you have appointed over the affairs of the province of Babylon: Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego. These men, O king, have not respected you. They don’t serve your gods, and don’t worship the golden image which you have set up.”\n'),
	(17017, 24, 3, 13, 'Then Nebuchadnezzar in rage and fury commanded that Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego be brought. Then these men were brought before the king.\n'),
	(17018, 24, 3, 14, 'Nebuchadnezzar answered them, “Is it on purpose, Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, that you don’t serve my god, nor worship the golden image which I have set up?\n'),
	(17019, 24, 3, 15, 'Now if you are ready whenever you hear the sound of the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp, pipe, and all kinds of music to fall down and worship the image which I have made, good; but if you don’t worship, you shall be cast the same hour into the middle of a burning fiery furnace. Who is that god that will deliver you out of my hands?”\n'),
	(17020, 24, 3, 16, 'Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego answered the king, “Nebuchadnezzar, we have no need to answer you in this matter.\n'),
	(17021, 24, 3, 17, 'If it happens, our God whom we serve is able to deliver us from the burning fiery furnace; and he will deliver us out of your hand, O king.\n'),
	(17022, 24, 3, 18, 'But if not, let it be known to you, O king, that we will not serve your gods or worship the golden image which you have set up.”\n'),
	(17023, 24, 3, 19, 'Then Nebuchadnezzar was full of fury, and the form of his appearance was changed against Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego. He spoke, and commanded that they should heat the furnace seven times more than it was usually heated.\n'),
	(17024, 24, 3, 20, 'He commanded certain mighty men who were in his army to bind Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, and to cast them into the burning fiery furnace.\n'),
	(17025, 24, 3, 21, 'Then these men were bound in their pants, their tunics, and their mantles, and their other clothes, and were cast into the middle of the burning fiery furnace.\n'),
	(17026, 24, 3, 22, 'Therefore because the king’s commandment was urgent, and the furnace exceeding hot, the flame of the fire killed those men who took up Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego.\n'),
	(17027, 24, 3, 23, 'These three men, Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, fell down bound into the middle of the burning fiery furnace.\n'),
	(17028, 24, 3, 24, 'Then Nebuchadnezzar the king was astonished, and rose up in haste. He spoke and said to his counselors, “Didn’t we cast three men bound into the middle of the fire?”\nThey answered the king, “True, O king.”\n'),
	(17029, 24, 3, 25, 'He answered, “Look, I see four men loose, walking in the middle of the fire, and they are unharmed. The appearance of the fourth is like a son of the gods.”\n'),
	(17030, 24, 3, 26, 'Then Nebuchadnezzar came near to the mouth of the burning fiery furnace. He spoke and said, “Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, you servants of the Most High God, come out, and come here!”\nThen Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego came out of the middle of the fire.\n'),
	(17031, 24, 3, 27, 'The satraps, the deputies, and the governors, and the king’s counselors, being gathered together, saw these men, that the fire had no power on their bodies. The hair of their head wasn’t singed. Their pants weren’t changed, the smell of fire wasn’t even on them.\n'),
	(17032, 24, 3, 28, 'Nebuchadnezzar spoke and said, “Blessed be the God of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, who has sent his angel, and delivered his servants who trusted in him, and have changed the king’s word, and have yielded their bodies, that they might not serve nor worship any god, except their own God.\n'),
	(17033, 24, 3, 29, 'Therefore I make a decree, that every people, nation, and language, which speak anything evil against the God of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, shall be cut in pieces, and their houses shall be made a dunghill; because there is no other god who is able to deliver like this.”\n'),
	(17034, 24, 3, 30, 'Then the king promoted Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego in the province of Babylon.\n'),
	(17035, 24, 4, 1, 'Nebuchadnezzar the king,\nto all the peoples, nations, and languages, who dwell in all the earth:\nPeace be multiplied to you.\n'),
	(17036, 24, 4, 2, 'It has seemed good to me to show the signs and wonders that the Most High God has worked toward me.\n'),
	(17037, 24, 4, 3, 'How great are his signs!\nHow mighty are his wonders!\nHis kingdom is an everlasting kingdom.\nHis dominion is from generation to generation.\n'),
	(17038, 24, 4, 4, 'I, Nebuchadnezzar, was at rest in my house, and flourishing in my palace.\n'),
	(17039, 24, 4, 5, 'I saw a dream which made me afraid; and the thoughts on my bed and the visions of my head troubled me.\n'),
	(17040, 24, 4, 6, 'Therefore made I a decree to bring in all the wise men of Babylon before me, that they might make known to me the interpretation of the dream.\n'),
	(17041, 24, 4, 7, 'Then the magicians, the enchanters, the Chaldeans, and the soothsayers came in; and I told the dream before them; but they did not make known to me its interpretation.\n'),
	(17042, 24, 4, 8, 'But at the last Daniel came in before me, whose name was Belteshazzar, according to the name of my god, and in whom is the spirit of the holy gods. I told the dream before him, saying,\n'),
	(17043, 24, 4, 9, '“Belteshazzar, master of the magicians, because I know that the spirit of the holy gods is in you, and no secret troubles you, tell me the visions of my dream that I have seen, and its interpretation.\n'),
	(17044, 24, 4, 10, 'Thus were the visions of my head on my bed: I saw, and behold, a tree in the middle of the earth; and its height was great.\n'),
	(17045, 24, 4, 11, 'The tree grew, and was strong, and its height reached to the sky, and its sight to the end of all the earth.\n'),
	(17046, 24, 4, 12, 'The leaves of it were beautiful, and it had much fruit, and in it was food for all. The animals of the field had shade under it, and the birds of the sky lived in its branches, and all flesh was fed from it.\n'),
	(17047, 24, 4, 13, '“I saw in the visions of my head on my bed, and behold, a watcher and a holy one came down from the sky.\n'),
	(17048, 24, 4, 14, 'He cried aloud, and said thus, ‘Cut down the tree, and cut off its branches! Shake off its leaves, and scatter its fruit! Let the animals get away from under it, and the fowls from its branches.\n'),
	(17049, 24, 4, 15, 'Nevertheless leave the stump of its roots in the earth, even with a band of iron and brass, in the tender grass of the field; and let it be wet with the dew of the sky. Let his portion be with the animals in the grass of the earth.\n'),
	(17050, 24, 4, 16, 'Let his heart be changed from man’s, and let an animal’s heart be given to him. Then let seven times pass over him.\n'),
	(17051, 24, 4, 17, '“‘The sentence is by the decree of the watchers, and the demand by the word of the holy ones; to the intent that the living may know that the Most High rules in the kingdom of men, and gives it to whomever he will, and sets up over it the lowest of men.’\n'),
	(17052, 24, 4, 18, '“This dream I, king Nebuchadnezzar, have seen; and you, Belteshazzar, declare the interpretation, because all the wise men of my kingdom are not able to make known to me the interpretation; but you are able; for the spirit of the holy gods is in you.”\n'),
	(17053, 24, 4, 19, 'Then Daniel, whose name was Belteshazzar, was stricken mute for a while, and his thoughts troubled him. The king answered, “Belteshazzar, don’t let the dream, or the interpretation, trouble you.”\nBelteshazzar answered, “My lord, may the dream be for those who hate you, and its interpretation to your adversaries.\n'),
	(17054, 24, 4, 20, 'The tree that you saw, which grew, and was strong, whose height reached to the sky, and its sight to all the earth;\n'),
	(17055, 24, 4, 21, 'whose leaves were beautiful, and its fruit plentiful, and in it was food for all; under which the animals of the field lived, and on whose branches the birds of the sky had their habitation:\n'),
	(17056, 24, 4, 22, 'it is you, O king, that have grown and become strong; for your greatness has grown, and reaches to the sky, and your dominion to the end of the earth.\n'),
	(17057, 24, 4, 23, '“Whereas the king saw a watcher and a holy one coming down from the sky, and saying, ‘Cut down the tree, and destroy it; nevertheless leave the stump of its roots in the earth, even with a band of iron and brass, in the tender grass of the field, and let it be wet with the dew of the sky. Let his portion be with the animals of the field, until seven times pass over him.\n'),
	(17058, 24, 4, 24, '“This is the interpretation, O king, and it is the decree of the Most High, which has come on my lord the king:\n'),
	(17059, 24, 4, 25, 'that you shall be driven from men, and your dwelling shall be with the animals of the field. You shall be made to eat grass as oxen, and shall be wet with the dew of the sky, and seven times shall pass over you; until you know that the Most High rules in the kingdom of men, and gives it to whomever he will.\n'),
	(17060, 24, 4, 26, 'Whereas they commanded to leave the stump of the roots of the tree; your kingdom shall be sure to you, after that you will have known that the heavens do rule.\n'),
	(17061, 24, 4, 27, 'Therefore, O king, let my counsel be acceptable to you, and break off your sins by righteousness, and your iniquities by showing mercy to the poor; if there may be a lengthening of your tranquility.”\n'),
	(17062, 24, 4, 28, 'All this came on the king Nebuchadnezzar.\n'),
	(17063, 24, 4, 29, 'At the end of twelve months he was walking in the royal palace of Babylon.\n'),
	(17064, 24, 4, 30, 'The king spoke and said, “Is not this great Babylon, which I have built for the royal dwelling place, by the might of my power and for the glory of my majesty?”\n'),
	(17065, 24, 4, 31, 'While the word was in the king’s mouth, a voice came from the sky, saying, “O king Nebuchadnezzar, to you it is spoken: ‘The kingdom has departed from you.\n'),
	(17066, 24, 4, 32, 'You shall be driven from men; and your dwelling shall be with the animals of the field. You shall be made to eat grass as oxen. Seven times shall pass over you, until you know that the Most High rules in the kingdom of men, and gives it to whomever he will.’”\n'),
	(17067, 24, 4, 33, 'This was fulfilled the same hour on Nebuchadnezzar. He was driven from men, and ate grass as oxen, and his body was wet with the dew of the sky, until his hair had grown like eagles’ feathers, and his nails like birds’ claws.\n'),
	(17068, 24, 4, 34, 'At the end of the days I, Nebuchadnezzar, lifted up my eyes to heaven, and my understanding returned to me, and I blessed the Most High, and I praised and honored him who lives forever;\nfor his dominion is an everlasting dominion,\nand his kingdom from generation to generation.\n'),
	(17069, 24, 4, 35, 'All the inhabitants of the earth are reputed as nothing;\nand he does according to his will in the army of heaven,\nand among the inhabitants of the earth;\nand no one can stop his hand,\nor ask him, “What are you doing?”\n'),
	(17070, 24, 4, 36, 'At the same time my understanding returned to me; and for the glory of my kingdom, my majesty and brightness returned to me. My counselors and my lords sought me; and I was established in my kingdom, and excellent greatness was added to me.\n'),
	(17071, 24, 4, 37, 'Now I, Nebuchadnezzar, praise and extol and honor the King of heaven; for all his works are truth, and his ways justice; and those who walk in pride he is able to abase.\n'),
	(17072, 24, 5, 1, 'Belshazzar the king made a great feast to a thousand of his lords, and drank wine before the thousand.\n'),
	(17073, 24, 5, 2, 'Belshazzar, while he tasted the wine, commanded that the golden and silver vessels which Nebuchadnezzar his father had taken out of the temple which was in Jerusalem be brought to him; that the king and his lords, his wives and his concubines, might drink from them.\n'),
	(17074, 24, 5, 3, 'Then they brought the golden vessels that were taken out of the temple of God’s house which was at Jerusalem; and the king and his lords, his wives and his concubines, drank from them.\n'),
	(17075, 24, 5, 4, 'They drank wine, and praised the gods of gold, and of silver, of brass, of iron, of wood, and of stone.\n'),
	(17076, 24, 5, 5, 'In the same hour, the fingers of a man’s hand came out and wrote near the lamp stand on the plaster of the wall of the king’s palace. The king saw the part of the hand that wrote.\n'),
	(17077, 24, 5, 6, 'Then the king’s face was changed in him, and his thoughts troubled him; and the joints of his thighs were loosened, and his knees struck one against another.\n'),
	(17078, 24, 5, 7, 'The king cried aloud to bring in the enchanters, the Chaldeans, and the soothsayers. The king spoke and said to the wise men of Babylon, “Whoever reads this writing, and shows me its interpretation, shall be clothed with purple, and have a chain of gold about his neck, and shall be the third ruler in the kingdom.”\n'),
	(17079, 24, 5, 8, 'Then all the king’s wise men came in; but they could not read the writing, and couldn’t make known to the king the interpretation.\n'),
	(17080, 24, 5, 9, 'Then king Belshazzar was greatly troubled, and his face was changed in him, and his lords were perplexed.\n'),
	(17081, 24, 5, 10, 'The queen by reason of the words of the king and his lords came into the banquet house. The queen spoke and said, “O king, live forever; don’t let your thoughts trouble you, nor let your face be changed.\n'),
	(17082, 24, 5, 11, 'There is a man in your kingdom, in whom is the spirit of the holy gods; and in the days of your father light and understanding and wisdom, like the wisdom of the gods, were found in him. The king Nebuchadnezzar your father, yes, the king, your father, made him master of the magicians, enchanters, Chaldeans, and soothsayers;\n'),
	(17083, 24, 5, 12, 'because an excellent spirit, knowledge, understanding, interpreting of dreams, showing of dark sentences, and dissolving of doubts were found in the same Daniel, whom the king named Belteshazzar. Now let Daniel be called, and he will show the interpretation.”\n'),
	(17084, 24, 5, 13, 'Then Daniel was brought in before the king. The king spoke and said to Daniel, “Are you that Daniel of the children of the captivity of Judah, whom the king my father brought out of Judah?\n'),
	(17085, 24, 5, 14, 'I have heard of you, that the spirit of the gods is in you, and that light, understanding, and excellent wisdom are found in you.\n'),
	(17086, 24, 5, 15, 'Now the wise men, the enchanters, have been brought in before me, that they should read this writing, and make known to me its interpretation; but they could not show the interpretation of the thing.\n'),
	(17087, 24, 5, 16, 'But I have heard of you, that you can give interpretations, and dissolve doubts. Now if you can read the writing, and make known to me its interpretation, you shall be clothed with purple, and have a chain of gold around your neck, and shall be the third ruler in the kingdom.”\n'),
	(17088, 24, 5, 17, 'Then Daniel answered before the king, “Let your gifts be to yourself, and give your rewards to another. Nevertheless, I will read the writing to the king, and make known to him the interpretation.\n'),
	(17089, 24, 5, 18, '“You, king, the Most High God gave Nebuchadnezzar your father the kingdom, and greatness, and glory, and majesty.\n'),
	(17090, 24, 5, 19, 'Because of the greatness that he gave him, all the peoples, nations, and languages trembled and feared before him. He killed whom he wanted to, and he kept alive whom he wanted to. He raised up whom he wanted to, and he put down whom he wanted to.\n'),
	(17091, 24, 5, 20, 'But when his heart was lifted up, and his spirit was hardened so that he dealt proudly, he was deposed from his kingly throne, and they took his glory from him.\n'),
	(17092, 24, 5, 21, 'He was driven from the sons of men, and his heart was made like the animals’, and his dwelling was with the wild donkeys. He was fed with grass like oxen, and his body was wet with the dew of the sky; until he knew that the Most High God rules in the kingdom of men, and that he sets up over it whomever he will.\n'),
	(17093, 24, 5, 22, '“You, his son, Belshazzar, have not humbled your heart, though you knew all this,\n'),
	(17094, 24, 5, 23, 'but have lifted up yourself against the Lord of heaven; and they have brought the vessels of his house before you, and you and your lords, your wives, and your concubines, have drunk wine from them. You have praised the gods of silver and gold, of brass, iron, wood, and stone, which don’t see, or hear, or know; and you have not glorified the God in whose hand your breath is, and whose are all your ways.\n'),
	(17095, 24, 5, 24, 'Then the part of the hand was sent from before him, and this writing was inscribed.\n'),
	(17096, 24, 5, 25, '“This is the writing that was inscribed: ‘MENE, MENE, TEKEL, UPHARSIN.’\n'),
	(17097, 24, 5, 26, '“This is the interpretation of the thing:\nMENE: God has counted your kingdom, and brought it to an end.\n'),
	(17098, 24, 5, 27, 'TEKEL: you are weighed in the balances, and are found wanting.\n'),
	(17099, 24, 5, 28, 'PERES: your kingdom is divided, and given to the Medes and Persians.”\n'),
	(17100, 24, 5, 29, 'Then Belshazzar commanded, and they clothed Daniel with purple, and put a chain of gold about his neck, and made proclamation concerning him, that he should be the third ruler in the kingdom.\n'),
	(17101, 24, 5, 30, 'In that night Belshazzar the Chaldean King was slain.\n'),
	(17102, 24, 5, 31, 'Darius the Mede received the kingdom, being about sixty-two years old.\n'),
	(17103, 24, 6, 1, 'It pleased Darius to set over the kingdom one hundred twenty satraps, who should be throughout the whole kingdom;\n'),
	(17104, 24, 6, 2, 'and over them three presidents, of whom Daniel was one; that these satraps might give account to them, and that the king should suffer no loss.\n'),
	(17105, 24, 6, 3, 'Then this Daniel was distinguished above the presidents and the satraps, because an excellent spirit was in him; and the king thought to set him over the whole realm.\n'),
	(17106, 24, 6, 4, 'Then the presidents and the satraps sought to find occasion against Daniel as touching the kingdom; but they could find no occasion or fault, because he was faithful. There wasn’t any error or fault found in him.\n'),
	(17107, 24, 6, 5, 'Then these men said, “We won’t find any occasion against this Daniel, unless we find it against him concerning the law of his God.”\n'),
	(17108, 24, 6, 6, 'Then these presidents and satraps assembled together to the king, and said thus to him, “King Darius, live forever!\n'),
	(17109, 24, 6, 7, 'All the presidents of the kingdom, the deputies and the satraps, the counselors and the governors, have consulted together to establish a royal statute, and to make a strong decree, that whoever asks a petition of any god or man for thirty days, except of you, O king, he shall be cast into the den of lions.\n'),
	(17110, 24, 6, 8, 'Now, O king, establish the decree, and sign the writing, that it not be changed, according to the law of the Medes and Persians, which doesn’t alter.”\n'),
	(17111, 24, 6, 9, 'Therefore king Darius signed the writing and the decree.\n'),
	(17112, 24, 6, 10, 'When Daniel knew that the writing was signed, he went into his house (now his windows were open in his room toward Jerusalem) and he kneeled on his knees three times a day, and prayed, and gave thanks before his God, as he did before.\n'),
	(17113, 24, 6, 11, 'Then these men assembled together, and found Daniel making petition and supplication before his God.\n'),
	(17114, 24, 6, 12, 'Then they came near, and spoke before the king concerning the king’s decree: “Haven’t you signed a decree that every man who makes a petition to any god or man within thirty days, except to you, O king, shall be cast into the den of lions?”\nThe king answered, “This thing is true, according to the law of the Medes and Persians, which doesn’t alter.”\n'),
	(17115, 24, 6, 13, 'Then they answered and said before the king, “That Daniel, who is of the children of the captivity of Judah, doesn’t respect you, O king, nor the decree that you have signed, but makes his petition three times a day.”\n'),
	(17116, 24, 6, 14, 'Then the king, when he heard these words, was very displeased, and set his heart on Daniel to deliver him; and he labored until the going down of the sun to rescue him.\n'),
	(17117, 24, 6, 15, 'Then these men assembled together to the king, and said to the king, “Know, O king, that it is a law of the Medes and Persians, that no decree nor statute which the king establishes may be changed.”\n'),
	(17118, 24, 6, 16, 'Then the king commanded, and they brought Daniel, and cast him into the den of lions. The king spoke and said to Daniel, “Your God whom you serve continually, he will deliver you.”\n'),
	(17119, 24, 6, 17, 'A stone was brought, and laid on the mouth of the den; and the king sealed it with his own signet, and with the signet of his lords; that nothing might be changed concerning Daniel.\n'),
	(17120, 24, 6, 18, 'Then the king went to his palace, and passed the night fasting. No musical instruments were brought before him; and his sleep fled from him.\n'),
	(17121, 24, 6, 19, 'Then the king arose very early in the morning, and went in haste to the den of lions.\n'),
	(17122, 24, 6, 20, 'When he came near to the den to Daniel, he cried with a troubled voice. The king spoke and said to Daniel, “Daniel, servant of the living God, is your God, whom you serve continually, able to deliver you from the lions?”\n'),
	(17123, 24, 6, 21, 'Then Daniel said to the king, “O king, live forever!\n'),
	(17124, 24, 6, 22, 'My God has sent his angel, and has shut the lions’ mouths, and they have not hurt me; because as before him innocence was found in me; and also before you, O king, I have done no harm.”\n'),
	(17125, 24, 6, 23, 'Then the king was exceedingly glad, and commanded that they should take Daniel up out of the den. So Daniel was taken up out of the den, and no kind of harm was found on him, because he had trusted in his God.\n'),
	(17126, 24, 6, 24, 'The king commanded, and they brought those men who had accused Daniel, and they cast them into the den of lions, them, their children, and their wives; and the lions mauled them, and broke all their bones in pieces, before they came to the bottom of the den.\n'),
	(17127, 24, 6, 25, 'Then king Darius wrote to all the peoples, nations, and languages, who dwell in all the earth:\n“Peace be multiplied to you.\n'),
	(17128, 24, 6, 26, '“I make a decree that in all the dominion of my kingdom men tremble and fear before the God of Daniel;\n“for he is the living God,\nand steadfast forever.\nHis kingdom is that which will not be destroyed.\nHis dominion will be even to the end.\n'),
	(17129, 24, 6, 27, 'He delivers and rescues.\nHe works signs and wonders in heaven and in earth,\nwho has delivered Daniel from the power of the lions.”\n'),
	(17130, 24, 6, 28, 'So this Daniel prospered in the reign of Darius, and in the reign of Cyrus the Persian.\n'),
	(17131, 24, 7, 1, 'In the first year of Belshazzar king of Babylon Daniel had a dream and visions of his head on his bed. Then he wrote the dream and told the sum of the matters.\n'),
	(17132, 24, 7, 2, 'Daniel spoke and said, “I saw in my vision by night, and, behold, the four winds of the sky broke out on the great sea.\n'),
	(17133, 24, 7, 3, 'Four great animals came up from the sea, different from one another.\n'),
	(17134, 24, 7, 4, '“The first was like a lion, and had eagle’s wings. I watched until its wings were plucked, and it was lifted up from the earth, and made to stand on two feet as a man. A man’s heart was given to it.\n'),
	(17135, 24, 7, 5, '“Behold, there was another animal, a second, like a bear. It was raised up on one side, and three ribs were in its mouth between its teeth. They said this to it: ‘Arise! Devour much flesh!’\n'),
	(17136, 24, 7, 6, '“After this I saw, and behold, another, like a leopard, which had on its back four wings of a bird. The animal also had four heads; and dominion was given to it.\n'),
	(17137, 24, 7, 7, '“After this I saw in the night visions, and, behold, there was a fourth animal, awesome and powerful, and exceedingly strong. It had great iron teeth. It devoured and broke in pieces, and stamped the residue with its feet. It was different than all the animals that were before it. It had ten horns.\n'),
	(17138, 24, 7, 8, '“I considered the horns, and behold, there came up among them another horn, a little one, before which three of the first horns were plucked up by the roots: and behold, in this horn were eyes like the eyes of a man, and a mouth speaking great things.\n'),
	(17139, 24, 7, 9, '“I watched until thrones were placed,\nand one who was ancient of days sat.\nHis clothing was white as snow,\nand the hair of his head like pure wool.\nHis throne was fiery flames,\nand its wheels burning fire.\n'),
	(17140, 24, 7, 10, 'A fiery stream issued and came out from before him.\nThousands of thousands ministered to him.\nTen thousand times ten thousand stood before him.\nThe judgment was set.\nThe books were opened.\n'),
	(17141, 24, 7, 11, '“I watched at that time because of the voice of the great words which the horn spoke. I watched even until the animal was slain, and its body destroyed, and it was given to be burned with fire.\n'),
	(17142, 24, 7, 12, 'As for the rest of the animals, their dominion was taken away; yet their lives were prolonged for a season and a time.\n'),
	(17143, 24, 7, 13, '“I saw in the night visions, and behold, there came with the clouds of the sky one like a son of man, and he came even to the ancient of days, and they brought him near before him.\n'),
	(17144, 24, 7, 14, 'Dominion was given him, and glory, and a kingdom, that all the peoples, nations, and languages should serve him. His dominion is an everlasting dominion, which will not pass away, and his kingdom that which will not be destroyed.\n'),
	(17145, 24, 7, 15, '“As for me, Daniel, my spirit was grieved within my body, and the visions of my head troubled me.\n'),
	(17146, 24, 7, 16, 'I came near to one of those who stood by, and asked him the truth concerning all this.\n“So he told me, and made me know the interpretation of the things.\n'),
	(17147, 24, 7, 17, '‘These great animals, which are four, are four kings, who will arise out of the earth.\n'),
	(17148, 24, 7, 18, 'But the saints of the Most High will receive the kingdom, and possess the kingdom forever, even forever and ever.’\n'),
	(17149, 24, 7, 19, '“Then I desired to know the truth concerning the fourth animal, which was different than all of them, exceedingly terrible, whose teeth were of iron, and its nails of brass; which devoured, broke in pieces, and stamped the residue with its feet;\n'),
	(17150, 24, 7, 20, 'and concerning the ten horns that were on its head, and the other horn which came up, and before which three fell, even that horn that had eyes, and a mouth that spoke great things, whose look was more stout than its fellows.\n'),
	(17151, 24, 7, 21, 'I saw, and the same horn made war with the saints, and prevailed against them,\n'),
	(17152, 24, 7, 22, 'until the ancient of days came, and judgment was given to the saints of the Most High, and the time came that the saints possessed the kingdom.\n'),
	(17153, 24, 7, 23, '“Thus he said, ‘The fourth animal will be a fourth kingdom on earth, which will be different than all the kingdoms, and will devour the whole earth, and will tread it down, and break it in pieces.\n'),
	(17154, 24, 7, 24, 'As for the ten horns, ten kings will arise out of this kingdom. Another will arise after them; and he will be different than the former, and he will put down three kings.\n'),
	(17155, 24, 7, 25, 'He will speak words against the Most High, and will wear out the saints of the Most High. He will plan to change the times and the law; and they will be given into his hand until a time and times and half a time.\n'),
	(17156, 24, 7, 26, '“‘But the judgment will be set, and they will take away his dominion, to consume and to destroy it to the end.\n'),
	(17157, 24, 7, 27, 'The kingdom and the dominion, and the greatness of the kingdoms under the whole sky, will be given to the people of the saints of the Most High. His kingdom is an everlasting kingdom, and all dominions will serve and obey him.’\n'),
	(17158, 24, 7, 28, '“Here is the end of the matter. As for me, Daniel, my thoughts much troubled me, and my face was changed in me; but I kept the matter in my heart.”\n'),
	(17159, 24, 8, 1, 'In the third year of the reign of king Belshazzar a vision appeared to me, even to me, Daniel, after that which appeared to me at the first.\n'),
	(17160, 24, 8, 2, 'I saw the vision. Now it was so, that when I saw, I was in the citadel of Susa, which is in the province of Elam. I saw in the vision, and I was by the river Ulai.\n'),
	(17161, 24, 8, 3, 'Then I lifted up my eyes, and saw, and behold, there stood before the river a ram which had two horns. The two horns were high; but one was higher than the other, and the higher came up last.\n'),
	(17162, 24, 8, 4, 'I saw the ram pushing westward, northward, and southward. No animals could stand before him. There wasn’t any who could deliver out of his hand; but he did according to his will, and magnified himself.\n'),
	(17163, 24, 8, 5, 'As I was considering, behold, a male goat came from the west over the surface of the whole earth, and didn’t touch the ground. The goat had a notable horn between his eyes.\n'),
	(17164, 24, 8, 6, 'He came to the ram that had the two horns, which I saw standing before the river, and ran on him in the fury of his power.\n'),
	(17165, 24, 8, 7, 'I saw him come close to the ram, and he was moved with anger against him, and struck the ram, and broke his two horns. There was no power in the ram to stand before him; but he cast him down to the ground, and trampled on him. There was no one who could deliver the ram out of his hand.\n'),
	(17166, 24, 8, 8, 'The male goat magnified himself exceedingly. When he was strong, the great horn was broken; and instead of it there came up four notable horns toward the four winds of the sky.\n'),
	(17167, 24, 8, 9, 'Out of one of them came out a little horn, which grew exceeding great, toward the south, and toward the east, and toward the glorious land.\n'),
	(17168, 24, 8, 10, 'It grew great, even to the army of the sky; and it cast down some of the army and of the stars to the ground, and trampled on them.\n'),
	(17169, 24, 8, 11, 'Yes, it magnified itself, even to the prince of the army; and it took away from him the continual burnt offering, and the place of his sanctuary was cast down.\n'),
	(17170, 24, 8, 12, 'The army was given over to it together with the continual burnt offering through disobedience. It cast down truth to the ground, and it did its pleasure and prospered.\n'),
	(17171, 24, 8, 13, 'Then I heard a holy one speaking; and another holy one said to that certain one who spoke, “How long will the vision about the continual burnt offering, and the disobedience that makes desolate, to give both the sanctuary and the army to be trodden under foot be?”\n'),
	(17172, 24, 8, 14, 'He said to me, “To two thousand and three hundred evenings and mornings. Then the sanctuary will be cleansed.”\n'),
	(17173, 24, 8, 15, 'When I, even I Daniel, had seen the vision, I sought to understand it. Then behold, there stood before me something like the appearance of a man.\n'),
	(17174, 24, 8, 16, 'I heard a man’s voice between the banks of the Ulai, which called, and said, “Gabriel, make this man understand the vision.”\n'),
	(17175, 24, 8, 17, 'So he came near where I stood; and when he came, I was frightened, and fell on my face; but he said to me, “Understand, son of man; for the vision belongs to the time of the end.”\n'),
	(17176, 24, 8, 18, 'Now as he was speaking with me, I fell into a deep sleep with my face toward the ground; but he touched me, and set me upright.\n'),
	(17177, 24, 8, 19, 'He said, “Behold, I will make you know what will be in the latter time of the indignation; for it belongs to the appointed time of the end.\n'),
	(17178, 24, 8, 20, 'The ram which you saw, that had the two horns, they are the kings of Media and Persia.\n'),
	(17179, 24, 8, 21, 'The rough male goat is the king of Greece. The great horn that is between his eyes is the first king.\n'),
	(17180, 24, 8, 22, 'As for that which was broken, in the place where four stood up, four kingdoms will stand up out of the nation, but not with his power.\n'),
	(17181, 24, 8, 23, '“In the latter time of their kingdom, when the transgressors have come to the full, a king of fierce face, and understanding dark sentences, will stand up.\n'),
	(17182, 24, 8, 24, 'His power will be mighty, but not by his own power. He will destroy awesomely, and will prosper in what he does. He will destroy the mighty ones and the holy people.\n'),
	(17183, 24, 8, 25, 'Through his policy he will cause deceit to prosper in his hand. He will magnify himself in his heart, and he will destroy many in their security. He will also stand up against the prince of princes; but he will be broken without hand.\n'),
	(17184, 24, 8, 26, '“The vision of the evenings and mornings which has been told is true; but seal up the vision, for it belongs to many days to come.”\n'),
	(17185, 24, 8, 27, 'I, Daniel, fainted, and was sick for some days. Then I rose up, and did the king’s business. I wondered at the vision, but no one understood it.\n'),
	(17186, 24, 9, 1, 'In the first year of Darius the son of Ahasuerus, of the offspring of the Medes, who was made king over the realm of the Chaldeans,\n'),
	(17187, 24, 9, 2, 'in the first year of his reign I, Daniel, understood by the books the number of the years about which Yahweh’s word came to Jeremiah the prophet, for the accomplishing of the desolations of Jerusalem, even seventy years.\n'),
	(17188, 24, 9, 3, 'I set my face to the Lord God, to seek by prayer and petitions, with fasting and sackcloth and ashes.\n'),
	(17189, 24, 9, 4, 'I prayed to Yahweh my God, and made confession, and said,\n“Oh, Lord, the great and dreadful God, who keeps covenant and loving kindness with those who love him and keep his commandments,\n'),
	(17190, 24, 9, 5, 'we have sinned, and have dealt perversely, and have done wickedly, and have rebelled, even turning aside from your precepts and from your ordinances.\n'),
	(17191, 24, 9, 6, 'We haven’t listened to your servants the prophets, who spoke in your name to our kings, our princes, and our fathers, and to all the people of the land.\n'),
	(17192, 24, 9, 7, '“Lord, righteousness belongs to you, but to us confusion of face, as it is today; to the men of Judah, and to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, and to all Israel, who are near, and who are far off, through all the countries where you have driven them, because of their trespass that they have trespassed against you.\n'),
	(17193, 24, 9, 8, 'Lord, to us belongs confusion of face, to our kings, to our princes, and to our fathers, because we have sinned against you.\n'),
	(17194, 24, 9, 9, 'To the Lord our God belong mercies and forgiveness; for we have rebelled against him.\n'),
	(17195, 24, 9, 10, 'We haven’t obeyed Yahweh our God’s voice, to walk in his laws, which he set before us by his servants the prophets.\n'),
	(17196, 24, 9, 11, 'Yes, all Israel have transgressed your law, turning aside, that they should not obey your voice.\n“Therefore the curse and the oath written in the law of Moses the servant of God has been poured out on us; for we have sinned against him.\n'),
	(17197, 24, 9, 12, 'He has confirmed his words, which he spoke against us, and against our judges who judged us, by bringing on us a great evil; for under the whole sky, such has not been done as has been done to Jerusalem.\n'),
	(17198, 24, 9, 13, 'As it is written in the law of Moses, all this evil has come on us. Yet have we not entreated the favor of Yahweh our God, that we should turn from our iniquities, and have discernment in your truth.\n'),
	(17199, 24, 9, 14, 'Therefore Yahweh has watched over the evil, and brought it on us; for Yahweh our God is righteous in all his works which he does, and we have not obeyed his voice.\n'),
	(17200, 24, 9, 15, '“Now, Lord our God, who has brought your people out of the land of Egypt with a mighty hand, and have gotten yourself renown, as it is today; we have sinned. We have done wickedly.\n'),
	(17201, 24, 9, 16, 'Lord, according to all your righteousness, let your anger and please let your wrath be turned away from your city Jerusalem, your holy mountain; because for our sins, and for the iniquities of our fathers, Jerusalem and your people have become a reproach to all who are around us.\n'),
	(17202, 24, 9, 17, '“Now therefore, our God, listen to the prayer of your servant, and to his petitions, and cause your face to shine on your sanctuary that is desolate, for the Lord’s sake.\n'),
	(17203, 24, 9, 18, 'My God, turn your ear, and hear. Open your eyes, and see our desolations, and the city which is called by your name; for we do not present our petitions before you for our righteousness, but for your great mercies’ sake.\n'),
	(17204, 24, 9, 19, 'Lord, hear. Lord, forgive. Lord, listen and do. Don’t defer, for your own sake, my God, because your city and your people are called by your name.”\n'),
	(17205, 24, 9, 20, 'While I was speaking, and praying, and confessing my sin and the sin of my people Israel, and presenting my supplication before Yahweh my God for the holy mountain of my God;\n'),
	(17206, 24, 9, 21, 'yes, while I was speaking in prayer, the man Gabriel, whom I had seen in the vision at the beginning, being caused to fly swiftly, touched me about the time of the evening offering.\n'),
	(17207, 24, 9, 22, 'He instructed me, and talked with me, and said, Daniel, “I have now come to give you wisdom and understanding.\n'),
	(17208, 24, 9, 23, 'At the beginning of your petitions the commandment went out, and I have come to tell you; for you are greatly beloved. Therefore consider the matter, and understand the vision.\n'),
	(17209, 24, 9, 24, '“Seventy weeks are decreed on your people and on your holy city, to finish disobedience, and to make an end of sins, and to make reconciliation for iniquity, and to bring in everlasting righteousness, and to seal up vision and prophecy, and to anoint the most holy.\n'),
	(17210, 24, 9, 25, '“Know therefore and discern that from the going out of the commandment to restore and to build Jerusalem to the Anointed One, the prince, will be seven weeks and sixty-two weeks. It will be built again, with street and moat, even in troubled times.\n'),
	(17211, 24, 9, 26, 'After the sixty-two weeks the Anointed One will be cut off, and will have nothing. The people of the prince who come will destroy the city and the sanctuary. Its end will be with a flood, and war will be even to the end. Desolations are determined.\n'),
	(17212, 24, 9, 27, 'He will make a firm covenant with many for one week. In the middle of the week he will cause the sacrifice and the offering to cease. On the wing of abominations will come one who makes desolate; and even to the full end, and that determined, wrath will be poured out on the desolate.”\n'),
	(17213, 24, 10, 1, 'In the third year of Cyrus king of Persia a thing was revealed to Daniel, whose name was called Belteshazzar; and the thing was true, even a great warfare. He understood the thing, and had understanding of the vision.\n'),
	(17214, 24, 10, 2, 'In those days I, Daniel, was mourning three whole weeks.\n'),
	(17215, 24, 10, 3, 'I ate no pleasant bread. No meat or wine came into my mouth. I didn’t anoint myself at all, until three whole weeks were fulfilled.\n'),
	(17216, 24, 10, 4, 'In the twenty-fourth day of the first month, as I was by the side of the great river, which is Hiddekel,\n'),
	(17217, 24, 10, 5, 'I lifted up my eyes, and looked, and behold, there was a man clothed in linen, whose thighs were adorned with pure gold of Uphaz.\n'),
	(17218, 24, 10, 6, 'His body also was like the beryl, and his face as the appearance of lightning, and his eyes as flaming torches. His arms and his feet were like burnished brass. The voice of his words was like the voice of a multitude.\n'),
	(17219, 24, 10, 7, 'I, Daniel, alone saw the vision; for the men who were with me didn’t see the vision; but a great quaking fell on them, and they fled to hide themselves.\n'),
	(17220, 24, 10, 8, 'So I was left alone, and saw this great vision. No strength remained in me; for my comeliness was turned in me into corruption, and I retained no strength.\n'),
	(17221, 24, 10, 9, 'Yet I heard the voice of his words. When I heard the voice of his words, then I fell into a deep sleep on my face, with my face toward the ground.\n'),
	(17222, 24, 10, 10, 'Behold, a hand touched me, which set me on my knees and on the palms of my hands.\n'),
	(17223, 24, 10, 11, 'He said to me, Daniel, you greatly beloved man, understand the words that I speak to you, and stand upright; for I have been sent to you, now. When he had spoken this word to me, I stood trembling.\n'),
	(17224, 24, 10, 12, 'Then he said to me, “Don’t be afraid, Daniel; for from the first day that you set your heart to understand, and to humble yourself before your God, your words were heard. I have come for your words’ sake.\n'),
	(17225, 24, 10, 13, 'But the prince of the kingdom of Persia withstood me twenty-one days; but, behold, Michael, one of the chief princes, came to help me because I remained there with the kings of Persia.\n'),
	(17226, 24, 10, 14, 'Now I have come to make you understand what will happen to your people in the latter days; for the vision is yet for many days.”\n'),
	(17227, 24, 10, 15, 'When he had spoken these words to me, I set my face toward the ground, and was mute.\n'),
	(17228, 24, 10, 16, 'Behold, one in the likeness of the sons of men touched my lips. Then I opened my mouth, and spoke and said to him who stood before me, “My lord, by reason of the vision my sorrows have overtaken me, and I retain no strength.\n'),
	(17229, 24, 10, 17, 'For how can the servant of this my lord talk with this my lord? For as for me, immediately there remained no strength in me. There was no breath left in me.”\n'),
	(17230, 24, 10, 18, 'Then one like the appearance of a man touched me again, and he strengthened me.\n'),
	(17231, 24, 10, 19, 'He said, “Greatly beloved man, don’t be afraid. Peace be to you. Be strong. Yes, be strong.”\nWhen he spoke to me, I was strengthened, and said, “Let my lord speak; for you have strengthened me.”\n'),
	(17232, 24, 10, 20, 'Then he said, “Do you know why I have come to you? Now I will return to fight with the prince of Persia. When I go out, behold, the prince of Greece will come.\n'),
	(17233, 24, 10, 21, 'But I will tell you that which is inscribed in the writing of truth. There is no one who holds with me against these, but Michael your prince.\n'),
	(17234, 24, 11, 1, '“As for me, in the first year of Darius the Mede, I stood up to confirm and strengthen him.\n'),
	(17235, 24, 11, 2, '“Now will I show you the truth. Behold, three more kings will stand up in Persia; and the fourth will be far richer than all of them. When he has grown strong through his riches, he will stir up all against the realm of Greece.\n'),
	(17236, 24, 11, 3, 'A mighty king will stand up, who will rule with great dominion, and do according to his will.\n'),
	(17237, 24, 11, 4, 'When he stands up, his kingdom will be broken, and will be divided toward the four winds of the sky, but not to his posterity, nor according to his dominion with which he ruled; for his kingdom will be plucked up, even for others besides these.\n'),
	(17238, 24, 11, 5, '“The king of the south will be strong. One of his princes will become stronger than him, and have dominion. His dominion will be a great dominion.\n'),
	(17239, 24, 11, 6, 'At the end of years they will join themselves together; and the daughter of the king of the south will come to the king of the north to make an agreement; but she will not retain the strength of her arm. He will also not stand, nor will his arm; but she will be given up, with those who brought her, and he who became the father of her, and he who strengthened her in those times.\n'),
	(17240, 24, 11, 7, '“But out of a shoot from her roots one will stand up in his place, who will come to the army, and will enter into the fortress of the king of the north, and will deal against them, and will prevail.\n'),
	(17241, 24, 11, 8, 'He will also carry their gods, with their molten images, and with their goodly vessels of silver and of gold, captive into Egypt. He will refrain some years from the king of the north.\n'),
	(17242, 24, 11, 9, 'He will come into the realm of the king of the south, but he will return into his own land.\n'),
	(17243, 24, 11, 10, 'His sons will wage war, and will assemble a multitude of great forces, which will come on, and overflow, and pass through. They will return and wage war, even to his fortress.\n'),
	(17244, 24, 11, 11, '“The king of the south will be moved with anger, and will come out and fight with him, even with the king of the north. He will send out a great multitude, and the multitude will be given into his hand.\n'),
	(17245, 24, 11, 12, 'The multitude will be lifted up, and his heart will be exalted. He will cast down tens of thousands, but he won’t prevail.\n'),
	(17246, 24, 11, 13, 'The king of the north will return, and will send out a multitude greater than the former. He will come on at the end of the times, even of years, with a great army and with much substance.\n'),
	(17247, 24, 11, 14, '“In those times many will stand up against the king of the south. Also the children of the violent among your people will lift themselves up to establish the vision; but they will fall.\n'),
	(17248, 24, 11, 15, 'So the king of the north will come and cast up a mound, and take a well-fortified city. The forces of the south won’t stand, neither will his chosen people, neither will there be any strength to stand.\n'),
	(17249, 24, 11, 16, 'But he who comes against him will do according to his own will, and no one will stand before him. He will stand in the glorious land, and destruction will be in his hand.\n'),
	(17250, 24, 11, 17, 'He will set his face to come with the strength of his whole kingdom, and with him equitable conditions. He will perform them. He will give him the daughter of women, to corrupt her; but she will not stand, and won’t be for him.\n'),
	(17251, 24, 11, 18, 'After this he will turn his face to the islands, and will take many; but a prince will cause the reproach offered by him to cease. Yes, moreover, he will cause his reproach to turn on him.\n'),
	(17252, 24, 11, 19, 'Then he will turn his face toward the fortresses of his own land; but he will stumble and fall, and won’t be found.\n'),
	(17253, 24, 11, 20, '“Then one who will cause a tax collector to pass through the kingdom to maintain its glory will stand up in his place; but within few days he shall be destroyed, not in anger, and not in battle.\n'),
	(17254, 24, 11, 21, '“In his place a contemptible person will stand up, to whom they had not given the honor of the kingdom; but he will come in time of security, and will obtain the kingdom by flatteries.\n'),
	(17255, 24, 11, 22, 'The overwhelming forces will be overwhelmed from before him, and will be broken. Yes, also the prince of the covenant.\n'),
	(17256, 24, 11, 23, 'After the treaty made with him he will work deceitfully; for he will come up, and will become strong, with a small people.\n'),
	(17257, 24, 11, 24, 'In time of security he will come even on the fattest places of the province. He will do that which his fathers have not done, nor his fathers’ fathers. He will scatter among them prey, plunder, and substance. Yes, he will devise his plans against the strongholds, even for a time.\n'),
	(17258, 24, 11, 25, '“He will stir up his power and his courage against the king of the south with a great army; and the king of the south will wage war in battle with an exceedingly great and mighty army; but he won’t stand; for they will devise plans against him.\n'),
	(17259, 24, 11, 26, 'Yes, those who eat of his dainties will destroy him, and his army will be swept away. Many will fall down slain.\n'),
	(17260, 24, 11, 27, 'As for both these kings, their hearts will be to do mischief, and they will speak lies at one table; but it won’t prosper, for the end will still be at the appointed time.\n'),
	(17261, 24, 11, 28, 'Then he will return into his land with great wealth. His heart will be against the holy covenant. He will take action, and return to his own land.\n'),
	(17262, 24, 11, 29, '“He will return at the appointed time, and come into the south; but it won’t be in the latter time as it was in the former.\n'),
	(17263, 24, 11, 30, 'For ships of Kittim will come against him. Therefore he will be grieved, and will return, and have indignation against the holy covenant, and will take action. He will even return, and have regard to those who forsake the holy covenant.\n'),
	(17264, 24, 11, 31, '“Forces will stand on his part, and they will profane the sanctuary, even the fortress, and will take away the continual burnt offering. Then they will set up the abomination that makes desolate.\n'),
	(17265, 24, 11, 32, 'He will corrupt those who do wickedly against the covenant by flatteries; but the people who know their God will be strong, and take action.\n'),
	(17266, 24, 11, 33, '“Those who are wise among the people will instruct many; yet they will fall by the sword and by flame, by captivity and by plunder, many days.\n'),
	(17267, 24, 11, 34, 'Now when they fall, they will be helped with a little help; but many will join themselves to them with flatteries.\n'),
	(17268, 24, 11, 35, 'Some of those who are wise will fall, to refine them, and to purify, and to make them white, even to the time of the end; because it is yet for the time appointed.\n'),
	(17269, 24, 11, 36, '“The king will do according to his will. He will exalt himself, and magnify himself above every god, and will speak marvelous things against the God of gods. He will prosper until the indignation is accomplished; for that which is determined will be done.\n'),
	(17270, 24, 11, 37, 'He won’t regard the gods of his fathers, or the desire of women, or regard any god; for he will magnify himself above all.\n'),
	(17271, 24, 11, 38, 'But in his place he will honor the god of fortresses. He will honor a god whom his fathers didn’t know with gold, silver, and with precious stones and pleasant things.\n'),
	(17272, 24, 11, 39, 'He will deal with the strongest fortresses by the help of a foreign god. He will increase with glory whoever acknowledges him. He will cause them to rule over many, and will divide the land for a price.\n'),
	(17273, 24, 11, 40, '“At the time of the end the king of the south will contend with him; and the king of the north will come against him like a whirlwind, with chariots, with horsemen, and with many ships. He will enter into the countries, and will overflow and pass through.\n'),
	(17274, 24, 11, 41, 'He will enter also into the glorious land, and many countries will be overthrown; but these will be delivered out of his hand: Edom, Moab, and the chief of the children of Ammon.\n'),
	(17275, 24, 11, 42, 'He will also stretch out his hand on the countries. The land of Egypt won’t escape.\n'),
	(17276, 24, 11, 43, 'But he will have power over the treasures of gold and of silver, and over all the precious things of Egypt. The Libyans and the Ethiopians will be at his steps.\n'),
	(17277, 24, 11, 44, 'But news out of the east and out of the north will trouble him; and he will go out with great fury to destroy and utterly to sweep away many.\n'),
	(17278, 24, 11, 45, 'He will plant the tents of his palace between the sea and the glorious holy mountain; yet he will come to his end, and no one will help him.\n'),
	(17279, 24, 12, 1, '“At that time Michael will stand up, the great prince who stands for the children of your people; and there will be a time of trouble, such as never was since there was a nation even to that same time. At that time your people will be delivered, everyone who is found written in the book.\n'),
	(17280, 24, 12, 2, 'Many of those who sleep in the dust of the earth will awake, some to everlasting life, and some to shame and everlasting contempt.\n'),
	(17281, 24, 12, 3, 'Those who are wise will shine as the brightness of the expanse. Those who turn many to righteousness will shine as the stars forever and ever.\n'),
	(17282, 24, 12, 4, 'But you, Daniel, shut up the words, and seal the book, even to the time of the end. Many will run back and forth, and knowledge will be increased.”\n'),
	(17283, 24, 12, 5, 'Then I, Daniel, looked, and behold, two others stood, one on the river bank on this side, and the other on the river bank on that side.\n'),
	(17284, 24, 12, 6, 'One said to the man clothed in linen, who was above the waters of the river, “How long will it be to the end of these wonders?”\n'),
	(17285, 24, 12, 7, 'I heard the man clothed in linen, who was above the waters of the river, when he held up his right hand and his left hand to heaven, and swore by him who lives forever that it will be for a time, times, and a half; and when they have finished breaking in pieces the power of the holy people, all these things will be finished.\n'),
	(17286, 24, 12, 8, 'I heard, but I didn’t understand. Then I said, “My lord, what will be the outcome of these things?”\n'),
	(17287, 24, 12, 9, 'He said, “Go your way, Daniel; for the words are shut up and sealed until the time of the end.\n'),
	(17288, 24, 12, 10, 'Many will purify themselves, and make themselves white, and be refined; but the wicked will do wickedly; and none of the wicked will understand; but those who are wise will understand.\n'),
	(17289, 24, 12, 11, '“From the time that the continual burnt offering is taken away, and the abomination that makes desolate set up, there will be one thousand two hundred ninety days.\n'),
	(17290, 24, 12, 12, 'Blessed is he who waits, and comes to the one thousand three hundred thirty-five days.\n'),
	(17291, 24, 12, 13, '“But go you your way until the end; for you will rest, and will stand in your inheritance at the end of the days.”\n'),
	(17292, 25, 1, 1, 'Yahweh’s word that came to Hosea the son of Beeri, in the days of Uzziah, Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah, kings of Judah, and in the days of Jeroboam the son of Joash, king of Israel.\n'),
	(17293, 25, 1, 2, 'When Yahweh spoke at first by Hosea, Yahweh said to Hosea, “Go, take for yourself a wife of prostitution and children of unfaithfulness; for the land commits great adultery, forsaking Yahweh.”\n'),
	(17294, 25, 1, 3, 'So he went and took Gomer the daughter of Diblaim; and she conceived, and bore him a son.\n'),
	(17295, 25, 1, 4, 'Yahweh said to him, “Call his name Jezreel; for yet a little while, and I will avenge the blood of Jezreel on the house of Jehu, and will cause the kingdom of the house of Israel to cease.\n'),
	(17296, 25, 1, 5, 'It will happen in that day that I will break the bow of Israel in the valley of Jezreel.”\n'),
	(17297, 25, 1, 6, 'She conceived again, and bore a daughter.\nThen he said to him, “Call her name Lo-Ruhamah; for I will no longer have mercy on the house of Israel, that I should in any way pardon them.\n'),
	(17298, 25, 1, 7, 'But I will have mercy on the house of Judah, and will save them by Yahweh their God, and will not save them by bow, sword, battle, horses, or horsemen.”\n'),
	(17299, 25, 1, 8, 'Now when she had weaned Lo-Ruhamah, she conceived, and bore a son.\n'),
	(17300, 25, 1, 9, 'He said, “Call his name Lo-Ammi; for you are not my people, and I will not be yours.\n'),
	(17301, 25, 1, 10, 'Yet the number of the children of Israel will be as the sand of the sea, which can’t be measured or counted; and it will come to pass that, in the place where it was said to them, ‘You are not my people,’ they will be called ‘sons of the living God.’\n'),
	(17302, 25, 1, 11, 'The children of Judah and the children of Israel will be gathered together, and they will appoint themselves one head, and will go up from the land; for great will be the day of Jezreel.\n'),
	(17303, 25, 2, 1, '“Say to your brothers, ‘My people!’\nand to your sisters, ‘My loved one!’\n'),
	(17304, 25, 2, 2, 'Contend with your mother!\nContend, for she is not my wife,\nneither am I her husband;\nand let her put away her prostitution from her face,\nand her adulteries from between her breasts;\n'),
	(17305, 25, 2, 3, 'Lest I strip her naked,\nand make her bare as in the day that she was born,\nand make her like a wilderness,\nand set her like a dry land,\nand kill her with thirst.\n'),
	(17306, 25, 2, 4, 'Indeed, on her children I will have no mercy;\nfor they are children of unfaithfulness;\n'),
	(17307, 25, 2, 5, 'For their mother has played the prostitute.\nShe who conceived them has done shamefully;\nfor she said, ‘I will go after my lovers,\nwho give me my bread and my water,\nmy wool and my flax,\nmy oil and my drink.’\n'),
	(17308, 25, 2, 6, 'Therefore behold, I will hedge up your way with thorns,\nand I will build a wall against her,\nthat she can’t find her way.\n'),
	(17309, 25, 2, 7, 'She will follow after her lovers,\nbut she won’t overtake them;\nand she will seek them,\nbut won’t find them.\nThen she will say, ‘I will go and return to my first husband;\nfor then was it better with me than now.’\n'),
	(17310, 25, 2, 8, 'For she did not know that I gave her the grain, the new wine, and the oil,\nand multiplied to her silver and gold, which they used for Baal.\n'),
	(17311, 25, 2, 9, 'Therefore I will take back my grain in its time,\nand my new wine in its season,\nand will pluck away my wool and my flax which should have covered her nakedness.\n'),
	(17312, 25, 2, 10, 'Now I will uncover her lewdness in the sight of her lovers,\nand no one will deliver her out of my hand.\n'),
	(17313, 25, 2, 11, 'I will also cause all her celebrations to cease:\nher feasts, her new moons, her Sabbaths, and all her solemn assemblies.\n'),
	(17314, 25, 2, 12, 'I will lay waste her vines and her fig trees,\nabout which she has said, ‘These are my wages that my lovers have given me;\nand I will make them a forest,’\nand the animals of the field shall eat them.\n'),
	(17315, 25, 2, 13, 'I will visit on her the days of the Baals,\nto which she burned incense,\nwhen she decked herself with her earrings and her jewels,\nand went after her lovers,\nand forgot me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17316, 25, 2, 14, '“Therefore behold, I will allure her,\nand bring her into the wilderness,\nand speak tenderly to her.\n'),
	(17317, 25, 2, 15, 'I will give her vineyards from there,\nand the valley of Achor for a door of hope;\nand she will respond there,\nas in the days of her youth,\nand as in the day when she came up out of the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(17318, 25, 2, 16, 'It will be in that day,” says Yahweh,\n“that you will call me ‘my husband,’\nand no longer call me ‘my master.’\n'),
	(17319, 25, 2, 17, 'For I will take away the names of the Baals out of her mouth,\nand they will no longer be mentioned by name.\n'),
	(17320, 25, 2, 18, 'In that day I will make a covenant for them with the animals of the field,\nand with the birds of the sky,\nand with the creeping things of the ground.\nI will break the bow, the sword, and the battle out of the land,\nand will make them lie down safely.\n'),
	(17321, 25, 2, 19, 'I will betroth you to me forever.\nYes, I will betroth you to me in righteousness, in justice, in loving kindness, and in compassion.\n'),
	(17322, 25, 2, 20, 'I will even betroth you to me in faithfulness;\nand you shall know Yahweh.\n'),
	(17323, 25, 2, 21, 'It will happen in that day, I will respond,” says Yahweh,\n“I will respond to the heavens,\nand they will respond to the earth;\n'),
	(17324, 25, 2, 22, 'and the earth will respond to the grain, and the new wine, and the oil;\nand they will respond to Jezreel.\n'),
	(17325, 25, 2, 23, 'I will sow her to me in the earth;\nand I will have mercy on her who had not obtained mercy;\nand I will tell those who were not my people, ‘You are my people;’\nand they will say, ‘My God!’”\n'),
	(17326, 25, 3, 1, 'Yahweh said to me, “Go again, love a woman loved by another, and an adulteress, even as Yahweh loves the children of Israel, though they turn to other gods, and love cakes of raisins.”\n'),
	(17327, 25, 3, 2, 'So I bought her for myself for fifteen pieces of silver and a homer\n and a half of barley.\n'),
	(17328, 25, 3, 3, 'I said to her, “You shall stay with me many days. You shall not play the prostitute, and you shall not be with any other man. I will also be so toward you.”\n'),
	(17329, 25, 3, 4, 'For the children of Israel shall live many days without king, and without prince, and without sacrifice, and without sacred stone, and without ephod or idols.\n'),
	(17330, 25, 3, 5, 'Afterward the children of Israel shall return, and seek Yahweh their God, and David their king, and shall come with trembling to Yahweh and to his blessings in the last days.\n'),
	(17331, 25, 4, 1, 'Hear Yahweh’s word, you children of Israel;\nfor Yahweh has a charge against the inhabitants of the land:\n“Indeed there is no truth,\nnor goodness,\nnor knowledge of God in the land.\n'),
	(17332, 25, 4, 2, 'There is cursing, lying, murder, stealing, and committing adultery;\nthey break boundaries, and bloodshed causes bloodshed.\n'),
	(17333, 25, 4, 3, 'Therefore the land will mourn,\nand everyone who dwells therein will waste away.\nall living things in her,\neven the animals of the field and the birds of the sky;\nyes, the fish of the sea also die.\n'),
	(17334, 25, 4, 4, '“Yet let no man bring a charge, neither let any man accuse; For your people are like those who bring charges against a priest.\n'),
	(17335, 25, 4, 5, 'You will stumble in the day,\nand the prophet will also stumble with you in the night;\nand I will destroy your mother.\n'),
	(17336, 25, 4, 6, 'My people are destroyed for lack of knowledge.\nBecause you have rejected knowledge, I will also reject you,\nthat you may be no priest to me.\nBecause you have forgotten your God’s law,\nI will also forget your children.\n'),
	(17337, 25, 4, 7, 'As they were multiplied, so they sinned against me.\nI will change their glory into shame.\n'),
	(17338, 25, 4, 8, 'They feed on the sin of my people,\nand set their heart on their iniquity.\n'),
	(17339, 25, 4, 9, 'It will be, like people, like priest;\nand I will punish them for their ways,\nand will repay them for their deeds.\n'),
	(17340, 25, 4, 10, 'They will eat, and not have enough.\nThey will play the prostitute, and will not increase;\nbecause they have abandoned giving to Yahweh.\n'),
	(17341, 25, 4, 11, 'Prostitution, wine, and new wine take away understanding.\n'),
	(17342, 25, 4, 12, 'My people consult with their wooden idol,\nand answer to a stick of wood.\nIndeed the spirit of prostitution has led them astray,\nand they have been unfaithful to their God.\n'),
	(17343, 25, 4, 13, 'They sacrifice on the tops of the mountains,\nand burn incense on the hills, under oaks and poplars and terebinths,\nbecause its shade is good.\nTherefore your daughters play the prostitute,\nand your brides commit adultery.\n'),
	(17344, 25, 4, 14, 'I will not punish your daughters when they play the prostitute,\nnor your brides when they commit adultery;\nbecause the men consort with prostitutes,\nand they sacrifice with the shrine prostitutes;\nso the people without understanding will come to ruin.\n'),
	(17345, 25, 4, 15, '“Though you, Israel, play the prostitute,\nyet don’t let Judah offend;\nand don’t come to Gilgal,\nneither go up to Beth Aven,\nnor swear, ‘As Yahweh lives.’\n'),
	(17346, 25, 4, 16, 'For Israel has behaved extremely stubbornly, like a stubborn heifer.\nThen how will Yahweh feed them like a lamb in a meadow.\n'),
	(17347, 25, 4, 17, 'Ephraim is joined to idols.\nLeave him alone!\n'),
	(17348, 25, 4, 18, 'Their drink has become sour.\nThey play the prostitute continually.\nHer rulers dearly love their shameful way.\n'),
	(17349, 25, 4, 19, 'The wind has wrapped her up in its wings;\nand they shall be disappointed because of their sacrifices.\n'),
	(17350, 25, 5, 1, '“Listen to this, you priests!\nListen, house of Israel,\nand give ear, house of the king!\nFor the judgment is against you;\nfor you have been a snare at Mizpah,\nand a net spread on Tabor.\n'),
	(17351, 25, 5, 2, 'The rebels are deep in slaughter;\nbut I discipline all of them.\n'),
	(17352, 25, 5, 3, 'I know Ephraim,\nand Israel is not hidden from me;\nfor now, Ephraim, you have played the prostitute.\nIsrael is defiled.\n'),
	(17353, 25, 5, 4, 'Their deeds won’t allow them to turn to their God;\nfor the spirit of prostitution is within them,\nand they don’t know Yahweh.\n'),
	(17354, 25, 5, 5, 'The pride of Israel testifies to his face.\nTherefore Israel and Ephraim will stumble in their iniquity.\nJudah also will stumble with them.\n'),
	(17355, 25, 5, 6, 'They will go with their flocks and with their herds to seek Yahweh;\nbut they won’t find him.\nHe has withdrawn himself from them.\n'),
	(17356, 25, 5, 7, 'They are unfaithful to Yahweh;\nfor they have borne illegitimate children.\nNow the new moon will devour them with their fields.\n'),
	(17357, 25, 5, 8, '“Blow the cornet in Gibeah,\nand the trumpet in Ramah!\nSound a battle cry at Beth Aven, behind you, Benjamin!\n'),
	(17358, 25, 5, 9, 'Ephraim will become a desolation in the day of rebuke.\nAmong the tribes of Israel, I have made known that which will surely be.\n'),
	(17359, 25, 5, 10, 'The princes of Judah are like those who remove a landmark.\nI will pour out my wrath on them like water.\n'),
	(17360, 25, 5, 11, 'Ephraim is oppressed,\nhe is crushed in judgment;\nBecause he is intent in his pursuit of idols.\n'),
	(17361, 25, 5, 12, 'Therefore I am to Ephraim like a moth,\nand to the house of Judah like rottenness.\n'),
	(17362, 25, 5, 13, '“When Ephraim saw his sickness,\nand Judah his wound,\nThen Ephraim went to Assyria,\nand sent to king Jareb:\nbut he is not able to heal you,\nneither will he cure you of your wound.\n'),
	(17363, 25, 5, 14, 'For I will be to Ephraim like a lion,\nand like a young lion to the house of Judah.\nI myself will tear in pieces and go away.\nI will carry off, and there will be no one to deliver.\n'),
	(17364, 25, 5, 15, 'I will go and return to my place,\nuntil they acknowledge their offense,\nand seek my face.\nIn their affliction they will seek me earnestly.”\n'),
	(17365, 25, 6, 1, '“Come, and let us return to Yahweh;\nfor he has torn us to pieces,\nand he will heal us;\nhe has injured us,\nand he will bind up our wounds.\n'),
	(17366, 25, 6, 2, 'After two days he will revive us.\nOn the third day he will raise us up,\nand we will live before him.\n'),
	(17367, 25, 6, 3, 'Let us acknowledge Yahweh.\nLet us press on to know Yahweh.\nAs surely as the sun rises,\nYahweh will appear.\nHe will come to us like the rain,\nlike the spring rain that waters the earth.”\n'),
	(17368, 25, 6, 4, '“Ephraim, what shall I do to you?\nJudah, what shall I do to you?\nFor your love is like a morning cloud,\nand like the dew that disappears early.\n'),
	(17369, 25, 6, 5, 'Therefore I have cut them to pieces with the prophets;\nI killed them with the words of my mouth.\nYour judgments are like a flash of lightning.\n'),
	(17370, 25, 6, 6, 'For I desire mercy, and not sacrifice;\nand the knowledge of God more than burnt offerings.\n'),
	(17371, 25, 6, 7, 'But they, like Adam, have broken the covenant.\nThey were unfaithful to me, there.\n'),
	(17372, 25, 6, 8, 'Gilead is a city of those who work iniquity;\nit is stained with blood.\n'),
	(17373, 25, 6, 9, 'As gangs of robbers wait to ambush a man,\nso the company of priests murder on the path toward Shechem,\ncommitting shameful crimes.\n'),
	(17374, 25, 6, 10, 'In the house of Israel I have seen a horrible thing.\nThere is prostitution in Ephraim.\nIsrael is defiled.\n'),
	(17375, 25, 6, 11, '“Also, Judah, there is a harvest appointed for you,\nwhen I restore the fortunes of my people.\n'),
	(17376, 25, 7, 1, 'When I would heal Israel,\nthen the iniquity of Ephraim is uncovered,\nalso the wickedness of Samaria;\nfor they commit falsehood,\nand the thief enters in,\nand the gang of robbers ravages outside.\n'),
	(17377, 25, 7, 2, 'They don’t consider in their hearts that I remember all their wickedness.\nNow their own deeds have engulfed them.\nThey are before my face.\n'),
	(17378, 25, 7, 3, 'They make the king glad with their wickedness,\nand the princes with their lies.\n'),
	(17379, 25, 7, 4, 'They are all adulterers.\nThey are burning like an oven that the baker stops stirring,\nfrom the kneading of the dough, until it is leavened.\n'),
	(17380, 25, 7, 5, 'On the day of our king, the princes made themselves sick with the heat of wine.\nHe joined his hand with mockers.\n'),
	(17381, 25, 7, 6, 'For they have prepared their heart like an oven,\nwhile they lie in wait.\nTheir baker sleeps all the night.\nIn the morning it burns as a flaming fire.\n'),
	(17382, 25, 7, 7, 'They are all hot as an oven,\nand devour their judges.\nAll their kings have fallen.\nThere is no one among them who calls to me.\n'),
	(17383, 25, 7, 8, 'Ephraim, he mixes himself among the nations.\nEphraim is a pancake not turned over.\n'),
	(17384, 25, 7, 9, 'Strangers have devoured his strength,\nand he doesn’t realize it.\nIndeed, gray hairs are here and there on him,\nand he doesn’t realize it.\n'),
	(17385, 25, 7, 10, 'The pride of Israel testifies to his face;\nyet they haven’t returned to Yahweh their God,\nnor sought him, for all this.\n'),
	(17386, 25, 7, 11, '“Ephraim is like an easily deceived dove, without understanding.\nThey call to Egypt.\nThey go to Assyria.\n'),
	(17387, 25, 7, 12, 'When they go, I will spread my net on them.\nI will bring them down like the birds of the sky.\nI will chastise them, as their congregation has heard.\n'),
	(17388, 25, 7, 13, 'Woe to them!\nFor they have wandered from me.\nDestruction to them!\nFor they have trespassed against me.\nThough I would redeem them,\nyet they have spoken lies against me.\n'),
	(17389, 25, 7, 14, 'They haven’t cried to me with their heart,\nbut they howl on their beds.\nThey assemble themselves for grain and new wine.\nThey turn away from me.\n'),
	(17390, 25, 7, 15, 'Though I have taught and strengthened their arms,\nyet they plot evil against me.\n'),
	(17391, 25, 7, 16, 'They return, but not to the Most High.\nThey are like a faulty bow.\nTheir princes will fall by the sword for the rage of their tongue.\nThis will be their derision in the land of Egypt.\n'),
	(17392, 25, 8, 1, '“Put the trumpet to your lips!\nSomething like an eagle is over Yahweh’s house,\nbecause they have broken my covenant,\nand rebelled against my law.\n'),
	(17393, 25, 8, 2, 'They cry to me, ‘My God, we Israel acknowledge you!’\n'),
	(17394, 25, 8, 3, 'Israel has cast off that which is good.\nThe enemy will pursue him.\n'),
	(17395, 25, 8, 4, 'They have set up kings, but not by me.\nThey have made princes, and I didn’t approve.\nOf their silver and their gold they have made themselves idols,\nthat they may be cut off.\n'),
	(17396, 25, 8, 5, 'Let Samaria throw out his calf idol!\nMy anger burns against them!\nHow long will it be until they are capable of purity?\n'),
	(17397, 25, 8, 6, 'For this is even from Israel!\nThe workman made it, and it is no God;\nindeed, the calf of Samaria shall be broken in pieces.\n'),
	(17398, 25, 8, 7, 'For they sow the wind,\nand they will reap the whirlwind.\nHe has no standing grain.\nThe stalk will yield no head.\nIf it does yield, strangers will swallow it up.\n'),
	(17399, 25, 8, 8, 'Israel is swallowed up.\nNow they are among the nations like a worthless thing.\n'),
	(17400, 25, 8, 9, 'For they have gone up to Assyria,\nlike a wild donkey wandering alone.\nEphraim has hired lovers for himself.\n'),
	(17401, 25, 8, 10, 'But although they sold themselves among the nations,\nI will now gather them;\nand they begin to waste away because of the oppression of the king of mighty ones.\n'),
	(17402, 25, 8, 11, 'Because Ephraim has multiplied altars for sinning,\nthey became for him altars for sinning.\n'),
	(17403, 25, 8, 12, 'I wrote for him the many things of my law;\nbut they were regarded as a strange thing.\n'),
	(17404, 25, 8, 13, 'As for the sacrifices of my offerings,\nthey sacrifice meat and eat it;\nBut Yahweh doesn’t accept them.\nNow he will remember their iniquity,\nand punish their sins.\nThey will return to Egypt.\n'),
	(17405, 25, 8, 14, 'For Israel has forgotten his Maker and built palaces;\nand Judah has multiplied fortified cities;\nbut I will send a fire on his cities,\nand it will devour its fortresses.”\n'),
	(17406, 25, 9, 1, 'Don’t rejoice, Israel, to jubilation like the nations;\nfor you were unfaithful to your God.\nYou love the wages of a prostitute at every grain threshing floor.\n'),
	(17407, 25, 9, 2, 'The threshing floor and the wine press won’t feed them,\nand the new wine will fail her.\n'),
	(17408, 25, 9, 3, 'They won’t dwell in Yahweh’s land;\nbut Ephraim will return to Egypt,\nand they will eat unclean food in Assyria.\n'),
	(17409, 25, 9, 4, 'They won’t pour out wine offerings to Yahweh,\nneither will they be pleasing to him.\nTheir sacrifices will be to them like the bread of mourners;\nall who eat of it will be polluted;\nfor their bread will be for their appetite.\nIt will not come into Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(17410, 25, 9, 5, 'What will you do in the day of solemn assembly,\nand in the day of the feast of Yahweh?\n'),
	(17411, 25, 9, 6, 'For, behold, they have gone away from destruction.\nEgypt will gather them up.\nMemphis will bury them.\nNettles will possess their pleasant things of silver.\nThorns will be in their tents.\n'),
	(17412, 25, 9, 7, 'The days of visitation have come.\nThe days of reckoning have come.\nIsrael will consider the prophet to be a fool,\nand the man who is inspired to be insane,\nbecause of the abundance of your sins,\nand because your hostility is great.\n'),
	(17413, 25, 9, 8, 'A prophet watches over Ephraim with my God.\nA fowler’s snare is on all of his paths,\nand hostility in the house of his God.\n'),
	(17414, 25, 9, 9, 'They have deeply corrupted themselves,\nas in the days of Gibeah.\nHe will remember their iniquity.\nHe will punish them for their sins.\n'),
	(17415, 25, 9, 10, 'I found Israel like grapes in the wilderness.\nI saw your fathers as the first ripe in the fig tree at its first season;\nbut they came to Baal Peor, and consecrated themselves to the shameful thing,\nand became abominable like that which they loved.\n'),
	(17416, 25, 9, 11, 'As for Ephraim, their glory will fly away like a bird.\nThere will be no birth, no one with child, and no conception.\n'),
	(17417, 25, 9, 12, 'Though they bring up their children,\nyet I will bereave them, so that not a man shall be left.\nIndeed, woe also to them when I depart from them!\n'),
	(17418, 25, 9, 13, 'I have seen Ephraim, like Tyre, planted in a pleasant place;\nbut Ephraim will bring out his children to the murderer.\n'),
	(17419, 25, 9, 14, 'Give them—Yahweh what will you give?\nGive them a miscarrying womb and dry breasts.\n'),
	(17420, 25, 9, 15, '“All their wickedness is in Gilgal;\nfor there I hated them.\nBecause of the wickedness of their deeds I will drive them out of my house!\nI will love them no more.\nAll their princes are rebels.\n'),
	(17421, 25, 9, 16, 'Ephraim is struck.\nTheir root has dried up.\nThey will bear no fruit.\nEven though they give birth, yet I will kill the beloved ones of their womb.”\n'),
	(17422, 25, 9, 17, 'My God will cast them away, because they did not listen to him;\nand they will be wanderers among the nations.\n'),
	(17423, 25, 10, 1, 'Israel is a luxuriant vine that produces his fruit.\nAccording to the abundance of his fruit he has multiplied his altars.\nAs their land has prospered, they have adorned their sacred stones.\n'),
	(17424, 25, 10, 2, 'Their heart is divided.\nNow they will be found guilty.\nHe will demolish their altars.\nHe will destroy their sacred stones.\n'),
	(17425, 25, 10, 3, 'Surely now they will say, “We have no king; for we don’t fear Yahweh;\nand the king, what can he do for us?”\n'),
	(17426, 25, 10, 4, 'They make promises, swearing falsely in making covenants.\nTherefore judgment springs up like poisonous weeds in the furrows of the field.\n'),
	(17427, 25, 10, 5, 'The inhabitants of Samaria will be in terror for the calves of Beth Aven;\nfor its people will mourn over it,\nAlong with its priests who rejoiced over it,\nfor its glory, because it has departed from it.\n'),
	(17428, 25, 10, 6, 'It also will be carried to Assyria for a present to a great king.\nEphraim will receive shame,\nand Israel will be ashamed of his own counsel.\n'),
	(17429, 25, 10, 7, 'Samaria and her king float away,\nlike a twig on the water.\n'),
	(17430, 25, 10, 8, 'The high places also of Aven, the sin of Israel, will be destroyed.\nThe thorn and the thistle will come up on their altars.\nThey will tell the mountains, “Cover us!” and the hills, “Fall on us!”\n'),
	(17431, 25, 10, 9, '“Israel, you have sinned from the days of Gibeah.\nThere they remained.\nThe battle against the children of iniquity doesn’t overtake them in Gibeah.\n'),
	(17432, 25, 10, 10, 'When it is my desire, I will chastise them;\nand the nations will be gathered against them,\nwhen they are bound to their two transgressions.\n'),
	(17433, 25, 10, 11, 'Ephraim is a trained heifer that loves to thresh;\nso I will put a yoke on her beautiful neck.\nI will set a rider on Ephraim.\nJudah will plow.\nJacob will break his clods.\n'),
	(17434, 25, 10, 12, 'Sow to yourselves in righteousness,\nreap according to kindness.\nBreak up your fallow ground;\nfor it is time to seek Yahweh,\nuntil he comes and rains righteousness on you.\n'),
	(17435, 25, 10, 13, 'You have plowed wickedness.\nYou have reaped iniquity.\nYou have eaten the fruit of lies,\nfor you trusted in your way, in the multitude of your mighty men.\n'),
	(17436, 25, 10, 14, 'Therefore a battle roar will arise among your people,\nand all your fortresses will be destroyed,\nas Shalman destroyed Beth Arbel in the day of battle.\nThe mother was dashed in pieces with her children.\n'),
	(17437, 25, 10, 15, 'So Bethel will do to you because of your great wickedness.\nAt daybreak the king of Israel will be destroyed.\n'),
	(17438, 25, 11, 1, '“When Israel was a child, then I loved him,\nand called my son out of Egypt.\n'),
	(17439, 25, 11, 2, 'They called to them, so they went from them.\nThey sacrificed to the Baals,\nand burned incense to engraved images.\n'),
	(17440, 25, 11, 3, 'Yet I taught Ephraim to walk.\nI took them by his arms;\nbut they didn’t know that I healed them.\n'),
	(17441, 25, 11, 4, 'I drew them with cords of a man, with ties of love;\nand I was to them like those who lift up the yoke on their necks;\nand I bent down to him and I fed him.\n'),
	(17442, 25, 11, 5, '“They won’t return into the land of Egypt;\nbut the Assyrian will be their king,\nbecause they refused to repent.\n'),
	(17443, 25, 11, 6, 'The sword will fall on their cities,\nand will destroy the bars of their gates,\nand will put an end to their plans.\n'),
	(17444, 25, 11, 7, 'My people are determined to turn from me.\nThough they call to the Most High,\nhe certainly won’t exalt them.\n'),
	(17445, 25, 11, 8, '“How can I give you up, Ephraim?\nHow can I hand you over, Israel?\nHow can I make you like Admah?\nHow can I make you like Zeboiim?\nMy heart is turned within me,\nmy compassion is aroused.\n'),
	(17446, 25, 11, 9, 'I will not execute the fierceness of my anger.\nI will not return to destroy Ephraim:\nfor I am God, and not man; the Holy One among you;\nand I will not come in wrath.\n'),
	(17447, 25, 11, 10, 'They will walk after Yahweh,\nwho will roar like a lion;\nfor he will roar, and the children will come trembling from the west.\n'),
	(17448, 25, 11, 11, 'They will come trembling like a bird out of Egypt,\nand like a dove out of the land of Assyria;\nand I will settle them in their houses,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17449, 25, 11, 12, 'Ephraim surrounds me with falsehood,\nand the house of Israel with deceit.\nJudah still strays from God,\nand is unfaithful to the Holy One.\n'),
	(17450, 25, 12, 1, 'Ephraim feeds on wind,\nand chases the east wind.\nHe continually multiplies lies and desolation.\nThey make a covenant with Assyria,\nand oil is carried into Egypt.\n'),
	(17451, 25, 12, 2, 'Yahweh also has a controversy with Judah,\nand will punish Jacob according to his ways;\naccording to his deeds he will repay him.\n'),
	(17452, 25, 12, 3, 'In the womb he took his brother by the heel;\nand in his manhood he contended with God.\n'),
	(17453, 25, 12, 4, 'Indeed, he struggled with the angel, and prevailed;\nhe wept, and made supplication to him.\nHe found him at Bethel, and there he spoke with us,\n'),
	(17454, 25, 12, 5, 'even Yahweh, the God of Armies;\nYahweh is his name of renown!\n'),
	(17455, 25, 12, 6, 'Therefore turn to your God.\nKeep kindness and justice,\nand wait continually for your God.\n'),
	(17456, 25, 12, 7, 'A merchant has dishonest scales in his hand.\nHe loves to defraud.\n'),
	(17457, 25, 12, 8, 'Ephraim said, “Surely I have become rich,\nI have found myself wealth.\nIn all my wealth they won’t find in me any iniquity that is sin.”\n'),
	(17458, 25, 12, 9, '“But I am Yahweh your God from the land of Egypt.\nI will yet again make you dwell in tents,\nas in the days of the solemn feast.\n'),
	(17459, 25, 12, 10, 'I have also spoken to the prophets,\nand I have multiplied visions;\nand by the ministry of the prophets I have used parables.\n'),
	(17460, 25, 12, 11, 'If Gilead is wicked,\nsurely they are worthless.\nIn Gilgal they sacrifice bulls.\nIndeed, their altars are like heaps in the furrows of the field.\n'),
	(17461, 25, 12, 12, 'Jacob fled into the country of Aram,\nand Israel served to get a wife,\nand for a wife he tended flocks and herds.\n'),
	(17462, 25, 12, 13, 'By a prophet Yahweh brought Israel up out of Egypt,\nand by a prophet he was preserved.\n'),
	(17463, 25, 12, 14, 'Ephraim has bitterly provoked anger.\nTherefore his blood will be left on him,\nand his Lord will repay his contempt.\n'),
	(17464, 25, 13, 1, 'When Ephraim spoke, there was trembling.\nHe exalted himself in Israel,\nbut when he became guilty in Baal, he died.\n'),
	(17465, 25, 13, 2, 'Now they sin more and more,\nand have made themselves molten images of their silver,\neven idols according to their own understanding,\nall of them the work of the craftsmen.\nThey say of them, ‘They offer human sacrifice and kiss the calves.’\n'),
	(17466, 25, 13, 3, 'Therefore they will be like the morning mist,\nand like the dew that passes away early,\nlike the chaff that is driven with the whirlwind out of the threshing floor,\nand like the smoke out of the chimney.\n'),
	(17467, 25, 13, 4, '“Yet I am Yahweh your God from the land of Egypt;\nand you shall acknowledge no god but me,\nand besides me there is no savior.\n'),
	(17468, 25, 13, 5, 'I knew you in the wilderness,\nin the land of great drought.\n'),
	(17469, 25, 13, 6, 'According to their pasture, so were they filled;\nthey were filled, and their heart was exalted.\nTherefore they have forgotten me.\n'),
	(17470, 25, 13, 7, 'Therefore I am like a lion to them.\nLike a leopard, I will lurk by the path.\n'),
	(17471, 25, 13, 8, 'I will meet them like a bear that is bereaved of her cubs,\nand will tear the covering of their heart.\nThere I will devour them like a lioness.\nThe wild animal will tear them.\n'),
	(17472, 25, 13, 9, 'You are destroyed, Israel, because you are against me,\nagainst your help.\n'),
	(17473, 25, 13, 10, 'Where is your king now, that he may save you in all your cities?\nAnd your judges, of whom you said, ‘Give me a king and princes?’\n'),
	(17474, 25, 13, 11, 'I have given you a king in my anger,\nand have taken him away in my wrath.\n'),
	(17475, 25, 13, 12, 'The guilt of Ephraim is stored up.\nHis sin is stored up.\n'),
	(17476, 25, 13, 13, 'The sorrows of a travailing woman will come on him.\nHe is an unwise son;\nfor when it is time, he doesn’t come to the opening of the womb.\n'),
	(17477, 25, 13, 14, 'I will ransom them from the power of Sheol.\nI will redeem them from death!\nDeath, where are your plagues?\nSheol, where is your destruction?\n“Compassion will be hidden from my eyes.\n'),
	(17478, 25, 13, 15, 'Though he is fruitful among his brothers, an east wind will come,\nthe breath of Yahweh coming up from the wilderness;\nand his spring will become dry,\nand his fountain will be dried up.\nHe will plunder the storehouse of treasure.\n'),
	(17479, 25, 13, 16, 'Samaria will bear her guilt;\nfor she has rebelled against her God.\nThey will fall by the sword.\nTheir infants will be dashed in pieces,\nand their pregnant women will be ripped open.”\n'),
	(17480, 25, 14, 1, 'Israel, return to Yahweh your God;\nfor you have fallen because of your sin.\n'),
	(17481, 25, 14, 2, 'Take words with you, and return to Yahweh.\nTell him, “Forgive all our sins,\nand accept that which is good:\nso we offer our lips like bulls.\n'),
	(17482, 25, 14, 3, 'Assyria can’t save us.\nWe won’t ride on horses;\nneither will we say any more to the work of our hands, ‘Our gods!’\nfor in you the fatherless finds mercy.”\n'),
	(17483, 25, 14, 4, '“I will heal their waywardness.\nI will love them freely;\nfor my anger is turned away from him.\n'),
	(17484, 25, 14, 5, 'I will be like the dew to Israel.\nHe will blossom like the lily,\nand send down his roots like Lebanon.\n'),
	(17485, 25, 14, 6, 'His branches will spread,\nand his beauty will be like the olive tree,\nand his fragrance like Lebanon.\n'),
	(17486, 25, 14, 7, 'Men will dwell in his shade.\nThey will revive like the grain,\nand blossom like the vine.\nTheir fragrance will be like the wine of Lebanon.\n'),
	(17487, 25, 14, 8, 'Ephraim, what have I to do any more with idols?\nI answer, and will take care of him.\nI am like a green cypress tree;\nfrom me your fruit is found.”\n'),
	(17488, 25, 14, 9, 'Who is wise, that he may understand these things?\nWho is prudent, that he may know them?\nFor the ways of Yahweh are right,\nand the righteous walk in them;\nBut the rebellious stumble in them.\n'),
	(17489, 26, 1, 1, 'Yahweh’s word that came to Joel, the son of Pethuel.\n'),
	(17490, 26, 1, 2, 'Hear this, you elders,\nAnd listen, all you inhabitants of the land.\nHas this ever happened in your days,\nor in the days of your fathers?\n'),
	(17491, 26, 1, 3, 'Tell your children about it,\nand have your children tell their children,\nand their children, another generation.\n'),
	(17492, 26, 1, 4, 'What the swarming locust has left, the great locust has eaten.\nWhat the great locust has left, the grasshopper has eaten.\nWhat the grasshopper has left, the caterpillar has eaten.\n'),
	(17493, 26, 1, 5, 'Wake up, you drunkards, and weep!\nWail, all you drinkers of wine, because of the sweet wine;\nfor it is cut off from your mouth.\n'),
	(17494, 26, 1, 6, 'For a nation has come up on my land, strong, and without number.\nHis teeth are the teeth of a lion,\nand he has the fangs of a lioness.\n'),
	(17495, 26, 1, 7, 'He has laid my vine waste,\nand stripped my fig tree.\nHe has stripped its bark, and thrown it away.\nIts branches are made white.\n'),
	(17496, 26, 1, 8, 'Mourn like a virgin dressed in sackcloth for the husband of her youth!\n'),
	(17497, 26, 1, 9, 'The meal offering and the drink offering are cut off from Yahweh’s house.\nThe priests, Yahweh’s ministers, mourn.\n'),
	(17498, 26, 1, 10, 'The field is laid waste.\nThe land mourns, for the grain is destroyed,\nThe new wine has dried up,\nand the oil languishes.\n'),
	(17499, 26, 1, 11, 'Be confounded, you farmers!\nWail, you vineyard keepers;\nfor the wheat and for the barley;\nfor the harvest of the field has perished.\n'),
	(17500, 26, 1, 12, 'The vine has dried up, and the fig tree withered;\nthe pomegranate tree, the palm tree also, and the apple tree,\neven all of the trees of the field are withered;\nfor joy has withered away from the sons of men.\n'),
	(17501, 26, 1, 13, 'Put on sackcloth and mourn, you priests!\nWail, you ministers of the altar.\nCome, lie all night in sackcloth, you ministers of my God,\nfor the meal offering and the drink offering are withheld from your God’s house.\n'),
	(17502, 26, 1, 14, 'Sanctify a fast.\nCall a solemn assembly.\nGather the elders,\nand all the inhabitants of the land, to the house of Yahweh, your God,\nand cry to Yahweh.\n'),
	(17503, 26, 1, 15, 'Alas for the day!\nFor the day of Yahweh is at hand,\nand it will come as destruction from the Almighty.\n'),
	(17504, 26, 1, 16, 'Isn’t the food cut off before our eyes;\njoy and gladness from the house of our God?\n'),
	(17505, 26, 1, 17, 'The seeds rot under their clods.\nThe granaries are laid desolate.\nThe barns are broken down, for the grain has withered.\n'),
	(17506, 26, 1, 18, 'How the animals groan!\nThe herds of livestock are perplexed, because they have no pasture.\nYes, the flocks of sheep are made desolate.\n'),
	(17507, 26, 1, 19, 'Yahweh, I cry to you,\nFor the fire has devoured the pastures of the wilderness,\nand the flame has burned all the trees of the field.\n'),
	(17508, 26, 1, 20, 'Yes, the animals of the field pant to you,\nfor the water brooks have dried up,\nAnd the fire has devoured the pastures of the wilderness.\n'),
	(17509, 26, 2, 1, 'Blow the trumpet in Zion,\nand sound an alarm in my holy mountain!\nLet all the inhabitants of the land tremble,\nfor the day of Yahweh comes,\nfor it is close at hand:\n'),
	(17510, 26, 2, 2, 'A day of darkness and gloominess,\na day of clouds and thick darkness.\nAs the dawn spreading on the mountains,\na great and strong people;\nthere has never been the like,\nneither will there be any more after them,\neven to the years of many generations.\n'),
	(17511, 26, 2, 3, 'A fire devours before them,\nand behind them, a flame burns.\nThe land is as the garden of Eden before them,\nand behind them, a desolate wilderness.\nYes, and no one has escaped them.\n'),
	(17512, 26, 2, 4, 'Their appearance is as the appearance of horses,\nand as horsemen, so do they run.\n'),
	(17513, 26, 2, 5, 'Like the noise of chariots on the tops of the mountains do they leap,\nlike the noise of a flame of fire that devours the stubble,\nas a strong people set in battle array.\n'),
	(17514, 26, 2, 6, 'At their presence the peoples are in anguish.\nAll faces have grown pale.\n'),
	(17515, 26, 2, 7, 'They run like mighty men.\nThey climb the wall like warriors.\nThey each march in his line, and they don’t swerve off course.\n'),
	(17516, 26, 2, 8, 'Neither does one jostle another;\nthey march everyone in his path,\nand they burst through the defenses,\nand don’t break ranks.\n'),
	(17517, 26, 2, 9, 'They rush on the city.\nThey run on the wall.\nThey climb up into the houses.\nThey enter in at the windows like thieves.\n'),
	(17518, 26, 2, 10, 'The earth quakes before them.\nThe heavens tremble.\nThe sun and the moon are darkened,\nand the stars withdraw their shining.\n'),
	(17519, 26, 2, 11, 'Yahweh thunders his voice before his army;\nfor his forces are very great;\nfor he is strong who obeys his command;\nfor the day of Yahweh is great and very awesome,\nand who can endure it?\n'),
	(17520, 26, 2, 12, '“Yet even now,” says Yahweh, “turn to me with all your heart,\nand with fasting, and with weeping, and with mourning.”\n'),
	(17521, 26, 2, 13, 'Tear your heart, and not your garments,\nand turn to Yahweh, your God;\nfor he is gracious and merciful,\nslow to anger, and abundant in loving kindness,\nand relents from sending calamity.\n'),
	(17522, 26, 2, 14, 'Who knows? He may turn and relent,\nand leave a blessing behind him,\neven a meal offering and a drink offering to Yahweh, your God.\n'),
	(17523, 26, 2, 15, 'Blow the trumpet in Zion!\nSanctify a fast.\nCall a solemn assembly.\n'),
	(17524, 26, 2, 16, 'Gather the people.\nSanctify the assembly.\nAssemble the elders.\nGather the children, and those who nurse from breasts.\nLet the bridegroom go out of his room,\nand the bride out of her room.\n'),
	(17525, 26, 2, 17, 'Let the priests, the ministers of Yahweh, weep between the porch and the altar,\nand let them say, “Spare your people, Yahweh,\nand don’t give your heritage to reproach,\nthat the nations should rule over them.\nWhy should they say among the peoples,\n‘Where is their God?’”\n'),
	(17526, 26, 2, 18, 'Then Yahweh was jealous for his land,\nAnd had pity on his people.\n'),
	(17527, 26, 2, 19, 'Yahweh answered his people,\n“Behold, I will send you grain, new wine, and oil,\nand you will be satisfied with them;\nand I will no more make you a reproach among the nations.\n'),
	(17528, 26, 2, 20, 'But I will remove the northern army far away from you,\nand will drive it into a barren and desolate land,\nits front into the eastern sea,\nand its back into the western sea;\nand its stench will come up,\nand its bad smell will rise.”\nSurely he has done great things.\n'),
	(17529, 26, 2, 21, 'Land, don’t be afraid.\nBe glad and rejoice, for Yahweh has done great things.\n'),
	(17530, 26, 2, 22, 'Don’t be afraid, you animals of the field;\nfor the pastures of the wilderness spring up,\nfor the tree bears its fruit.\nThe fig tree and the vine yield their strength.\n'),
	(17531, 26, 2, 23, '“Be glad then, you children of Zion,\nand rejoice in Yahweh, your God;\nfor he gives you the former rain in just measure,\nand he causes the rain to come down for you,\nthe former rain and the latter rain,\nas before.\n'),
	(17532, 26, 2, 24, 'The threshing floors will be full of wheat,\nand the vats will overflow with new wine and oil.\n'),
	(17533, 26, 2, 25, 'I will restore to you the years that the swarming locust has eaten,\nthe great locust, the grasshopper, and the caterpillar,\nmy great army, which I sent among you.\n'),
	(17534, 26, 2, 26, 'You will have plenty to eat, and be satisfied,\nand will praise the name of Yahweh, your God,\nwho has dealt wondrously with you;\nand my people will never again be disappointed.\n'),
	(17535, 26, 2, 27, 'You will know that I am among Israel,\nand that I am Yahweh, your God, and there is no one else;\nand my people will never again be disappointed.\n'),
	(17536, 26, 2, 28, '“It will happen afterward, that I will pour out my Spirit on all flesh;\nand your sons and your daughters will prophesy.\nYour old men will dream dreams.\nYour young men will see visions.\n'),
	(17537, 26, 2, 29, 'And also on the servants and on the handmaids in those days,\nI will pour out my Spirit.\n'),
	(17538, 26, 2, 30, 'I will show wonders in the heavens and in the earth:\nblood, fire, and pillars of smoke.\n'),
	(17539, 26, 2, 31, 'The sun will be turned into darkness,\nand the moon into blood,\nbefore the great and terrible day of Yahweh comes.\n'),
	(17540, 26, 2, 32, 'It will happen that whoever will call on Yahweh’s name shall be saved;\nfor in Mount Zion and in Jerusalem there will be those who escape,\nas Yahweh has said,\nand among the remnant, those whom Yahweh calls.\n'),
	(17541, 26, 3, 1, '“For, behold, in those days,\nand in that time,\nwhen I restore the fortunes of Judah and Jerusalem,\n'),
	(17542, 26, 3, 2, 'I will gather all nations,\nand will bring them down into the valley of Jehoshaphat;\nand I will execute judgment on them there for my people,\nand for my heritage, Israel, whom they have scattered among the nations.\nThey have divided my land,\n'),
	(17543, 26, 3, 3, 'and have cast lots for my people,\nand have given a boy for a prostitute,\nand sold a girl for wine, that they may drink.\n'),
	(17544, 26, 3, 4, '“Yes, and what are you to me, Tyre, and Sidon,\nand all the regions of Philistia?\nWill you repay me?\nAnd if you repay me,\nI will swiftly and speedily return your repayment on your own head.\n'),
	(17545, 26, 3, 5, 'Because you have taken my silver and my gold,\nand have carried my finest treasures into your temples,\n'),
	(17546, 26, 3, 6, 'and have sold the children of Judah and the children of Jerusalem to the sons of the Greeks,\nthat you may remove them far from their border.\n'),
	(17547, 26, 3, 7, 'Behold, I will stir them up out of the place where you have sold them,\nand will return your repayment on your own head;\n'),
	(17548, 26, 3, 8, 'and I will sell your sons and your daughters into the hands of the children of Judah,\nand they will sell them to the men of Sheba,\nto a faraway nation,\nfor Yahweh has spoken it.”\n'),
	(17549, 26, 3, 9, 'Proclaim this among the nations:\n“Prepare for war!\nStir up the mighty men.\nLet all the warriors draw near.\nLet them come up.\n'),
	(17550, 26, 3, 10, 'Beat your plowshares into swords,\nand your pruning hooks into spears.\nLet the weak say, ‘I am strong.’\n'),
	(17551, 26, 3, 11, 'Hurry and come, all you surrounding nations,\nand gather yourselves together.”\nCause your mighty ones to come down there, Yahweh.\n'),
	(17552, 26, 3, 12, '“Let the nations arouse themselves,\nand come up to the valley of Jehoshaphat;\nfor there will I sit to judge all the surrounding nations.\n'),
	(17553, 26, 3, 13, 'Put in the sickle;\nfor the harvest is ripe.\nCome, tread, for the wine press is full,\nthe vats overflow, for their wickedness is great.”\n'),
	(17554, 26, 3, 14, 'Multitudes, multitudes in the valley of decision!\nFor the day of Yahweh is near, in the valley of decision.\n'),
	(17555, 26, 3, 15, 'The sun and the moon are darkened,\nand the stars withdraw their shining.\n'),
	(17556, 26, 3, 16, 'Yahweh will roar from Zion,\nand thunder from Jerusalem;\nand the heavens and the earth will shake;\nbut Yahweh will be a refuge to his people,\nand a stronghold to the children of Israel.\n'),
	(17557, 26, 3, 17, '“So you will know that I am Yahweh, your God,\ndwelling in Zion, my holy mountain.\nThen Jerusalem will be holy,\nand no strangers will pass through her any more.\n'),
	(17558, 26, 3, 18, 'It will happen in that day,\nthat the mountains will drop down sweet wine,\nthe hills will flow with milk,\nall the brooks of Judah will flow with waters,\nand a fountain will flow out from Yahweh’s house,\nand will water the valley of Shittim.\n'),
	(17559, 26, 3, 19, 'Egypt will be a desolation,\nand Edom will be a desolate wilderness,\nfor the violence done to the children of Judah,\nbecause they have shed innocent blood in their land.\n'),
	(17560, 26, 3, 20, 'But Judah will be inhabited forever,\nand Jerusalem from generation to generation.\n'),
	(17561, 26, 3, 21, 'I will cleanse their blood,\nthat I have not cleansed:\nfor Yahweh dwells in Zion.”\n'),
	(17562, 27, 1, 1, 'The words of Amos, who was among the herdsmen of Tekoa, which he saw concerning Israel in the days of Uzziah king of Judah, and in the days of Jeroboam the son of Joash king of Israel, two years before the earthquake.\n'),
	(17563, 27, 1, 2, 'He said:\n“Yahweh will roar from Zion,\nand utter his voice from Jerusalem;\nand the pastures of the shepherds will mourn,\nand the top of Carmel will wither.”\n'),
	(17564, 27, 1, 3, 'Yahweh says:\n“For three transgressions of Damascus, yes, for four,\nI will not turn away its punishment;\nbecause they have threshed Gilead with threshing instruments of iron;\n'),
	(17565, 27, 1, 4, 'but I will send a fire into the house of Hazael,\nand it will devour the palaces of Ben Hadad.\n'),
	(17566, 27, 1, 5, 'I will break the bar of Damascus,\nand cut off the inhabitant from the valley of Aven,\nand him who holds the scepter from the house of Eden;\nand the people of Syria shall go into captivity to Kir,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(17567, 27, 1, 6, 'Yahweh says:\n“For three transgressions of Gaza, yes, for four,\nI will not turn away its punishment;\nbecause they carried away captive the whole community,\nto deliver them up to Edom;\n'),
	(17568, 27, 1, 7, 'but I will send a fire on the wall of Gaza,\nand it will devour its palaces.\n'),
	(17569, 27, 1, 8, 'I will cut off the inhabitant from Ashdod,\nand him who holds the scepter from Ashkelon;\nand I will turn my hand against Ekron;\nand the remnant of the Philistines will perish,”\nsays the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(17570, 27, 1, 9, 'Yahweh says:\n“For three transgressions of Tyre, yes, for four,\nI will not turn away its punishment;\nbecause they delivered up the whole community to Edom,\nand didn’t remember the brotherly covenant;\n'),
	(17571, 27, 1, 10, 'but I will send a fire on the wall of Tyre,\nand it will devour its palaces.”\n'),
	(17572, 27, 1, 11, 'Yahweh says:\n“For three transgressions of Edom, yes, for four,\nI will not turn away its punishment;\nbecause he pursued his brother with the sword,\nand cast off all pity,\nand his anger raged continually,\nand he kept his wrath forever;\n'),
	(17573, 27, 1, 12, 'but I will send a fire on Teman,\nand it will devour the palaces of Bozrah.”\n'),
	(17574, 27, 1, 13, 'Yahweh says:\n“For three transgressions of the children of Ammon, yes, for four,\nI will not turn away its punishment;\nbecause they have ripped open the pregnant women of Gilead,\nthat they may enlarge their border.\n'),
	(17575, 27, 1, 14, 'But I will kindle a fire in the wall of Rabbah,\nand it will devour its palaces,\nwith shouting in the day of battle,\nwith a storm in the day of the whirlwind;\n'),
	(17576, 27, 1, 15, 'and their king will go into captivity,\nhe and his princes together,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(17577, 27, 2, 1, 'Yahweh says:\n“For three transgressions of Moab, yes, for four,\nI will not turn away its punishment;\nbecause he burned the bones of the king of Edom into lime;\n'),
	(17578, 27, 2, 2, 'but I will send a fire on Moab,\nand it will devour the palaces of Kerioth;\nand Moab will die with tumult, with shouting, and with the sound of the trumpet;\n'),
	(17579, 27, 2, 3, 'and I will cut off the judge from among them,\nand will kill all its princes with him,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(17580, 27, 2, 4, 'Yahweh says:\n“For three transgressions of Judah, yes, for four,\nI will not turn away its punishment;\nbecause they have rejected Yahweh’s law,\nand have not kept his statutes,\nand their lies have led them astray,\nafter which their fathers walked;\n'),
	(17581, 27, 2, 5, 'but I will send a fire on Judah,\nand it will devour the palaces of Jerusalem.”\n'),
	(17582, 27, 2, 6, 'Yahweh says:\n“For three transgressions of Israel, yes, for four,\nI will not turn away its punishment;\nbecause they have sold the righteous for silver,\nand the needy for a pair of shoes;\n'),
	(17583, 27, 2, 7, 'They trample on the dust of the earth on the head of the poor,\nand deny justice to the oppressed;\nand a man and his father use the same maiden, to profane my holy name;\n'),
	(17584, 27, 2, 8, 'and they lay themselves down beside every altar on clothes taken in pledge;\nand in the house of their God they drink the wine of those who have been fined.\n'),
	(17585, 27, 2, 9, 'Yet I destroyed the Amorite before them,\nwhose height was like the height of the cedars,\nand he was strong as the oaks;\nyet I destroyed his fruit from above,\nand his roots from beneath.\n'),
	(17586, 27, 2, 10, 'Also I brought you up out of the land of Egypt,\nand led you forty years in the wilderness,\nto possess the land of the Amorite.\n'),
	(17587, 27, 2, 11, 'I raised up some of your sons for prophets,\nand some of your young men for Nazirites.\nIsn’t this true,\nyou children of Israel?” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17588, 27, 2, 12, '“But you gave the Nazirites wine to drink,\nand commanded the prophets, saying, ‘Don’t prophesy!’\n'),
	(17589, 27, 2, 13, 'Behold, I will crush you in your place,\nas a cart crushes that is full of grain.\n'),
	(17590, 27, 2, 14, 'Flight will perish from the swift;\nand the strong won’t strengthen his force;\nneither shall the mighty deliver himself;\n'),
	(17591, 27, 2, 15, 'neither shall he stand who handles the bow;\nand he who is swift of foot won’t escape;\nneither shall he who rides the horse deliver himself;\n'),
	(17592, 27, 2, 16, 'and he who is courageous among the mighty will flee away naked on that day,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(17593, 27, 3, 1, 'Hear this word that Yahweh has spoken against you, children of Israel, against the whole family which I brought up out of the land of Egypt, saying:\n'),
	(17594, 27, 3, 2, '“I have only chosen you of all the families of the earth.\nTherefore I will punish you for all of your sins.”\n'),
	(17595, 27, 3, 3, 'Do two walk together,\nunless they have agreed?\n'),
	(17596, 27, 3, 4, 'Will a lion roar in the thicket,\nwhen he has no prey?\nDoes a young lion cry out of his den,\nif he has caught nothing?\n'),
	(17597, 27, 3, 5, 'Can a bird fall in a trap on the earth,\nwhere no snare is set for him?\nDoes a snare spring up from the ground,\nwhen there is nothing to catch?\n'),
	(17598, 27, 3, 6, 'Does the trumpet alarm sound in a city,\nwithout the people being afraid?\nDoes evil happen to a city,\nand Yahweh hasn’t done it?\n'),
	(17599, 27, 3, 7, 'Surely the Lord Yahweh will do nothing,\nunless he reveals his secret to his servants the prophets.\n'),
	(17600, 27, 3, 8, 'The lion has roared.\nWho will not fear?\nThe Lord Yahweh has spoken.\nWho can but prophesy?\n'),
	(17601, 27, 3, 9, 'Proclaim in the palaces at Ashdod,\nand in the palaces in the land of Egypt,\nand say, “Assemble yourselves on the mountains of Samaria,\nand see what unrest is in her,\nand what oppression is among them.”\n'),
	(17602, 27, 3, 10, '“Indeed they don’t know to do right,” says Yahweh,\n“Who hoard plunder and loot in their palaces.”\n'),
	(17603, 27, 3, 11, 'Therefore thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“An adversary will overrun the land;\nand he will pull down your strongholds,\nand your fortresses will be plundered.”\n'),
	(17604, 27, 3, 12, 'Yahweh says:\n“As the shepherd rescues out of the mouth of the lion two legs,\nor a piece of an ear,\nso shall the children of Israel be rescued who sit in Samaria on the corner of a couch,\nand on the silken cushions of a bed.”\n'),
	(17605, 27, 3, 13, '“Listen, and testify against the house of Jacob,” says the Lord Yahweh, the God of Armies.\n'),
	(17606, 27, 3, 14, '“For in the day that I visit the transgressions of Israel on him,\nI will also visit the altars of Bethel;\nand the horns of the altar will be cut off,\nand fall to the ground.\n'),
	(17607, 27, 3, 15, 'I will strike the winter house with the summer house;\nand the houses of ivory will perish,\nand the great houses will have an end,”\nsays Yahweh.\n'),
	(17608, 27, 4, 1, 'Listen to this word, you cows of Bashan, who are on the mountain of Samaria, who oppress the poor, who crush the needy, who tell their husbands, “Bring us drinks!”\n'),
	(17609, 27, 4, 2, 'The Lord Yahweh has sworn by his holiness that behold,\n“The days shall come on you that they will take you away with hooks,\nand the last of you with fish hooks.\n'),
	(17610, 27, 4, 3, 'You will go out at the breaks in the wall,\neveryone straight before her;\nand you will cast yourselves into Harmon,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17611, 27, 4, 4, '“Go to Bethel, and sin;\nto Gilgal, and sin more.\nBring your sacrifices every morning,\nyour tithes every three days,\n'),
	(17612, 27, 4, 5, 'offer a sacrifice of thanksgiving of that which is leavened,\nand proclaim free will offerings and brag about them:\nfor this pleases you, you children of Israel,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(17613, 27, 4, 6, '“I also have given you cleanness of teeth in all your cities,\nand lack of bread in every town;\nyet you haven’t returned to me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17614, 27, 4, 7, '“I also have withheld the rain from you,\nwhen there were yet three months to the harvest;\nand I caused it to rain on one city,\nand caused it not to rain on another city.\nOne place was rained on,\nand the piece where it didn’t rain withered.\n'),
	(17615, 27, 4, 8, 'So two or three cities staggered to one city to drink water,\nand were not satisfied:\nyet you haven’t returned to me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17616, 27, 4, 9, '“I struck you with blight and mildew many times in your gardens and your vineyards;\nand your fig trees and your olive trees have the swarming locust devoured:\nyet you haven’t returned to me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17617, 27, 4, 10, '“I sent plagues among you like I did Egypt.\nI have slain your young men with the sword,\nand have carried away your horses;\nand I filled your nostrils with the stench of your camp,\nyet you haven’t returned to me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17618, 27, 4, 11, '“I have overthrown some of you,\nas when God overthrew Sodom and Gomorrah,\nand you were like a burning stick plucked out of the fire;\nyet you haven’t returned to me,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17619, 27, 4, 12, '“Therefore thus will I do to you, Israel;\nbecause I will do this to you,\nprepare to meet your God, Israel.\n'),
	(17620, 27, 4, 13, 'For, behold, he who forms the mountains,\nand creates the wind,\nand declares to man what is his thought;\nwho makes the morning darkness,\nand treads on the high places of the earth:\nYahweh, the God of Armies, is his name.”\n'),
	(17621, 27, 5, 1, 'Listen to this word which I take up for a lamentation over you, O house of Israel.\n'),
	(17622, 27, 5, 2, '“The virgin of Israel has fallen;\nShe shall rise no more.\nShe is cast down on her land;\nthere is no one to raise her up.”\n'),
	(17623, 27, 5, 3, 'For thus says the Lord Yahweh:\n“The city that went out a thousand shall have a hundred left,\nand that which went out one hundred shall have ten left to the house of Israel.”\n'),
	(17624, 27, 5, 4, 'For Yahweh says to the house of Israel:\n“Seek me, and you will live;\n'),
	(17625, 27, 5, 5, 'but don’t seek Bethel,\nnor enter into Gilgal,\nand don’t pass to Beersheba:\nfor Gilgal shall surely go into captivity,\nand Bethel shall come to nothing.\n'),
	(17626, 27, 5, 6, 'Seek Yahweh, and you will live;\nlest he break out like fire in the house of Joseph,\nand it devour, and there be no one to quench it in Bethel.\n'),
	(17627, 27, 5, 7, 'You who turn justice to wormwood,\nand cast down righteousness to the earth:\n'),
	(17628, 27, 5, 8, 'seek him who made the Pleiades and Orion,\nand turns the shadow of death into the morning,\nand makes the day dark with night;\nwho calls for the waters of the sea,\nand pours them out on the surface of the earth, Yahweh is his name,\n'),
	(17629, 27, 5, 9, 'who brings sudden destruction on the strong,\nso that destruction comes on the fortress.\n'),
	(17630, 27, 5, 10, 'They hate him who reproves in the gate,\nand they abhor him who speaks blamelessly.\n'),
	(17631, 27, 5, 11, 'Therefore, because you trample on the poor,\nand take taxes from him of wheat:\nYou have built houses of cut stone,\nbut you will not dwell in them.\nYou have planted pleasant vineyards,\nbut you shall not drink their wine.\n'),
	(17632, 27, 5, 12, 'For I know how many your offenses,\nand how great are your sins—\nyou who afflict the just,\nwho take a bribe,\nand who turn away the needy in the courts.\n'),
	(17633, 27, 5, 13, 'Therefore a prudent person keeps silent in such a time,\nfor it is an evil time.\n'),
	(17634, 27, 5, 14, 'Seek good, and not evil,\nthat you may live;\nand so Yahweh, the God of Armies, will be with you,\nas you say.\n'),
	(17635, 27, 5, 15, 'Hate evil, love good,\nand establish justice in the courts.\nIt may be that Yahweh, the God of Armies, will be gracious to the remnant of Joseph.”\n'),
	(17636, 27, 5, 16, 'Therefore Yahweh, the God of Armies, the Lord, says:\n“Wailing will be in all the wide ways;\nand they will say in all the streets, ‘Alas! Alas!’\nand they will call the farmer to mourning,\nand those who are skillful in lamentation to wailing.\n'),
	(17637, 27, 5, 17, 'In all vineyards there will be wailing;\nfor I will pass through the middle of you,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17638, 27, 5, 18, '“Woe to you who desire the day of Yahweh!\nWhy do you long for the day of Yahweh?\nIt is darkness,\nand not light.\n'),
	(17639, 27, 5, 19, 'As if a man fled from a lion,\nand a bear met him;\nOr he went into the house and leaned his hand on the wall,\nand a snake bit him.\n'),
	(17640, 27, 5, 20, 'Won’t the day of Yahweh be darkness, and not light?\nEven very dark, and no brightness in it?\n'),
	(17641, 27, 5, 21, 'I hate, I despise your feasts,\nand I can’t stand your solemn assemblies.\n'),
	(17642, 27, 5, 22, 'Yes, though you offer me your burnt offerings and meal offerings,\nI will not accept them;\nneither will I regard the peace offerings of your fat animals.\n'),
	(17643, 27, 5, 23, 'Take away from me the noise of your songs!\nI will not listen to the music of your harps.\n'),
	(17644, 27, 5, 24, 'But let justice roll on like rivers,\nand righteousness like a mighty stream.\n'),
	(17645, 27, 5, 25, '“Did you bring to me sacrifices and offerings in the wilderness forty years, house of Israel?\n'),
	(17646, 27, 5, 26, 'You also carried the tent of your king and the shrine of your images, the star of your god, which you made for yourselves.\n'),
	(17647, 27, 5, 27, 'Therefore will I cause you to go into captivity beyond Damascus,” says Yahweh, whose name is the God of Armies.\n'),
	(17648, 27, 6, 1, 'Woe to those who are at ease in Zion,\nand to those who are secure on the mountain of Samaria,\nthe notable men of the chief of the nations,\nto whom the house of Israel come!\n'),
	(17649, 27, 6, 2, 'Go to Calneh, and see;\nand from there go to Hamath the great;\nthen go down to Gath of the Philistines.\nare they better than these kingdoms?\nor is their border greater than your border?\n'),
	(17650, 27, 6, 3, 'Those who put far away the evil day,\nand cause the seat of violence to come near;\n'),
	(17651, 27, 6, 4, 'Who lie on beds of ivory,\nand stretch themselves on their couches,\nand eat the lambs out of the flock,\nand the calves out of the middle of the stall;\n'),
	(17652, 27, 6, 5, 'who strum on the strings of a harp;\nwho invent for themselves instruments of music, like David;\n'),
	(17653, 27, 6, 6, 'who drink wine in bowls,\nand anoint themselves with the best oils;\nbut they are not grieved for the affliction of Joseph.\n'),
	(17654, 27, 6, 7, 'Therefore they will now go captive with the first who go captive;\nand the feasting and lounging will end.\n'),
	(17655, 27, 6, 8, '“The Lord Yahweh has sworn by himself,” says Yahweh, the God of Armies:\n“I abhor the pride of Jacob,\nand detest his fortresses.\nTherefore I will deliver up the city with all that is in it.\n'),
	(17656, 27, 6, 9, 'It will happen, if there remain ten men in one house,\nthat they shall die.\n'),
	(17657, 27, 6, 10, '“When a man’s relative carries him, even he who burns him, to bring bodies out of the house, and asks him who is in the innermost parts of the house, ‘Is there yet any with you?’ And he says, ‘No;’ then he will say, ‘Hush! Indeed we must not mention Yahweh’s name.’\n'),
	(17658, 27, 6, 11, '“For, behold, Yahweh commands, and the great house will be smashed to pieces,\nand the little house into bits.\n'),
	(17659, 27, 6, 12, 'Do horses run on the rocky crags?\nDoes one plow there with oxen?\nBut you have turned justice into poison,\nand the fruit of righteousness into bitterness;\n'),
	(17660, 27, 6, 13, 'you who rejoice in a thing of nothing, who say,\n‘Haven’t we taken for ourselves horns by our own strength?’\n'),
	(17661, 27, 6, 14, 'For, behold, I will raise up against you a nation, house of Israel,”\nsays Yahweh, the God of Armies;\n“and they will afflict you from the entrance of Hamath to the brook of the Arabah.”\n'),
	(17662, 27, 7, 1, 'Thus the Lord Yahweh showed me: and behold, he formed locusts in the beginning of the shooting up of the latter growth; and behold, it was the latter growth after the king’s harvest.\n'),
	(17663, 27, 7, 2, 'When they finished eating the grass of the land, then I said, “Lord Yahweh, forgive, I beg you! How could Jacob stand? For he is small.”\n'),
	(17664, 27, 7, 3, 'Yahweh relented concerning this. “It shall not be,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17665, 27, 7, 4, 'Thus the Lord Yahweh showed me and behold, the Lord Yahweh called for judgment by fire; and it dried up the great deep, and would have devoured the land.\n'),
	(17666, 27, 7, 5, 'Then I said, “Lord Yahweh, stop, I beg you! How could Jacob stand? For he is small.”\n'),
	(17667, 27, 7, 6, 'Yahweh relented concerning this. “This also shall not be,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n'),
	(17668, 27, 7, 7, 'Thus he showed me and behold, the Lord stood beside a wall made by a plumb line, with a plumb line in his hand.\n'),
	(17669, 27, 7, 8, 'Yahweh said to me, “Amos, what do you see?”\nI said, “A plumb line.”\nThen the Lord said, “Behold, I will set a plumb line in the middle of my people Israel. I will not again pass by them any more.\n'),
	(17670, 27, 7, 9, 'The high places of Isaac will be desolate, the sanctuaries of Israel will be laid waste; and I will rise against the house of Jeroboam with the sword.”\n'),
	(17671, 27, 7, 10, 'Then Amaziah the priest of Bethel sent to Jeroboam king of Israel, saying, “Amos has conspired against you in the middle of the house of Israel. The land is not able to bear all his words.\n'),
	(17672, 27, 7, 11, 'For Amos says, ‘Jeroboam will die by the sword, and Israel shall surely be led away captive out of his land.’”\n'),
	(17673, 27, 7, 12, 'Amaziah also said to Amos, “You seer, go, flee away into the land of Judah, and there eat bread, and prophesy there:\n'),
	(17674, 27, 7, 13, 'but don’t prophesy again any more at Bethel; for it is the king’s sanctuary, and it is a royal house!”\n'),
	(17675, 27, 7, 14, 'Then Amos answered Amaziah, “I was no prophet, neither was I a prophet’s son; but I was a herdsman, and a farmer of sycamore figs;\n'),
	(17676, 27, 7, 15, 'and Yahweh took me from following the flock, and Yahweh said to me, ‘Go, prophesy to my people Israel.’\n'),
	(17677, 27, 7, 16, 'Now therefore listen to Yahweh’s word: ‘You say, Don’t prophesy against Israel, and don’t preach against the house of Isaac.’\n'),
	(17678, 27, 7, 17, 'Therefore Yahweh says: ‘Your wife shall be a prostitute in the city, and your sons and your daughters shall fall by the sword, and your land shall be divided by line; and you yourself shall die in a land that is unclean, and Israel shall surely be led away captive out of his land.’”\n'),
	(17679, 27, 8, 1, 'Thus the Lord Yahweh showed me: behold, a basket of summer fruit.\n'),
	(17680, 27, 8, 2, 'He said, “Amos, what do you see?”\nI said, “A basket of summer fruit.”\nThen Yahweh said to me,\n“The end has come on my people Israel.\nI will not again pass by them any more.\n'),
	(17681, 27, 8, 3, 'The songs of the temple will be wailings in that day,” says the Lord Yahweh.\n“The dead bodies will be many. In every place they will throw them out with silence.\n'),
	(17682, 27, 8, 4, 'Hear this, you who desire to swallow up the needy,\nand cause the poor of the land to fail,\n'),
	(17683, 27, 8, 5, 'Saying, ‘When will the new moon be gone, that we may sell grain?\nAnd the Sabbath, that we may market wheat,\nmaking the ephah small, and the shekel large,\nand dealing falsely with balances of deceit;\n'),
	(17684, 27, 8, 6, 'that we may buy the poor for silver,\nand the needy for a pair of shoes,\nand sell the sweepings with the wheat?’”\n'),
	(17685, 27, 8, 7, 'Yahweh has sworn by the pride of Jacob,\n“Surely I will never forget any of their works.\n'),
	(17686, 27, 8, 8, 'Won’t the land tremble for this,\nand everyone mourn who dwells in it?\nYes, it will rise up wholly like the River;\nand it will be stirred up and sink again, like the River of Egypt.\n'),
	(17687, 27, 8, 9, 'It will happen in that day,” says the Lord Yahweh,\n“that I will cause the sun to go down at noon,\nand I will darken the earth in the clear day.\n'),
	(17688, 27, 8, 10, 'I will turn your feasts into mourning,\nand all your songs into lamentation;\nand I will make you wear sackcloth on all your bodies,\nand baldness on every head.\nI will make it like the mourning for an only son,\nand its end like a bitter day.\n'),
	(17689, 27, 8, 11, 'Behold, the days come,” says the Lord Yahweh,\n“that I will send a famine in the land,\nnot a famine of bread,\nnor a thirst for water,\nbut of hearing Yahweh’s words.\n'),
	(17690, 27, 8, 12, 'They will wander from sea to sea,\nand from the north even to the east;\nthey will run back and forth to seek Yahweh’s word,\nand will not find it.\n'),
	(17691, 27, 8, 13, 'In that day the beautiful virgins\nand the young men will faint for thirst.\n'),
	(17692, 27, 8, 14, 'Those who swear by the sin of Samaria,\nand say, ‘As your god, Dan, lives;’\nand, ‘As the way of Beersheba lives;’\nthey will fall, and never rise up again.”\n'),
	(17693, 27, 9, 1, 'I saw the Lord standing beside the altar, and he said, “Strike the tops of the pillars, that the thresholds may shake; and break them in pieces on the head of all of them; and I will kill the last of them with the sword: there shall not one of them flee away, and there shall not one of them escape.\n'),
	(17694, 27, 9, 2, 'Though they dig into Sheol, there my hand will take them; and though they climb up to heaven, there I will bring them down.\n'),
	(17695, 27, 9, 3, 'Though they hide themselves in the top of Carmel, I will search and take them out there; and though they be hidden from my sight in the bottom of the sea, there I will command the serpent, and it will bite them.\n'),
	(17696, 27, 9, 4, 'Though they go into captivity before their enemies, there I will command the sword, and it will kill them. I will set my eyes on them for evil, and not for good.\n'),
	(17697, 27, 9, 5, 'For the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, is he who touches the land and it melts, and all who dwell in it will mourn; and it will rise up wholly like the River, and will sink again, like the River of Egypt.\n'),
	(17698, 27, 9, 6, 'It is he who builds his rooms in the heavens, and has founded his vault on the earth; he who calls for the waters of the sea, and pours them out on the surface of the earth; Yahweh is his name.\n'),
	(17699, 27, 9, 7, 'Are you not like the children of the Ethiopians to me, children of Israel?” says Yahweh. “Haven’t I brought up Israel out of the land of Egypt, and the Philistines from Caphtor, and the Syrians from Kir?\n'),
	(17700, 27, 9, 8, 'Behold, the eyes of the Lord Yahweh are on the sinful kingdom, and I will destroy it from off the surface of the earth; except that I will not utterly destroy the house of Jacob,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17701, 27, 9, 9, '“For, behold, I will command, and I will sift the house of Israel among all the nations, as grain is sifted in a sieve, yet not the least kernel will fall on the earth.\n'),
	(17702, 27, 9, 10, 'All the sinners of my people will die by the sword, who say, ‘Evil won’t overtake nor meet us.’\n'),
	(17703, 27, 9, 11, 'In that day I will raise up the tent of David who is fallen, and close up its breaches, and I will raise up its ruins, and I will build it as in the days of old;\n'),
	(17704, 27, 9, 12, 'that they may possess the remnant of Edom, and all the nations who are called by my name,” says Yahweh who does this.\n'),
	(17705, 27, 9, 13, '“Behold, the days come,” says Yahweh,\n“that the plowman shall overtake the reaper,\nand the one treading grapes him who sows seed;\nand sweet wine will drip from the mountains,\nand flow from the hills.\n'),
	(17706, 27, 9, 14, 'I will bring my people Israel back from captivity,\nand they will rebuild the ruined cities, and inhabit them;\nand they will plant vineyards, and drink wine from them.\nThey shall also make gardens,\nand eat their fruit.\n'),
	(17707, 27, 9, 15, 'I will plant them on their land,\nand they will no more be plucked up out of their land which I have given them,”\nsays Yahweh your God.\n'),
	(17708, 28, 1, 1, 'The vision of Obadiah. This is what the Lord Yahweh says about Edom. We have heard news from Yahweh, and an ambassador is sent among the nations, saying, “Arise, and let’s rise up against her in battle.\n'),
	(17709, 28, 1, 2, 'Behold, I have made you small among the nations. You are greatly despised.\n'),
	(17710, 28, 1, 3, 'The pride of your heart has deceived you, you who dwell in the clefts of the rock, whose habitation is high, who says in his heart, ‘Who will bring me down to the ground?’\n'),
	(17711, 28, 1, 4, 'Though you mount on high as the eagle, and though your nest is set among the stars, I will bring you down from there,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17712, 28, 1, 5, '“If thieves came to you, if robbers by night—oh, what disaster awaits you—wouldn’t they only steal until they had enough? If grape pickers came to you, wouldn’t they leave some gleaning grapes?\n'),
	(17713, 28, 1, 6, 'How Esau will be ransacked! How his hidden treasures are sought out!\n'),
	(17714, 28, 1, 7, 'All the men of your alliance have brought you on your way, even to the border. The men who were at peace with you have deceived you, and prevailed against you. Friends who eat your bread lay a snare under you. There is no understanding in him.”\n'),
	(17715, 28, 1, 8, '“Won’t I in that day”, says Yahweh, “destroy the wise men out of Edom, and understanding out of the mountain of Esau?\n'),
	(17716, 28, 1, 9, 'Your mighty men, Teman, will be dismayed, to the end that everyone may be cut off from the mountain of Esau by slaughter.\n'),
	(17717, 28, 1, 10, 'For the violence done to your brother Jacob, shame will cover you, and you will be cut off forever.\n'),
	(17718, 28, 1, 11, 'In the day that you stood on the other side, in the day that strangers carried away his substance, and foreigners entered into his gates, and cast lots for Jerusalem, even you were like one of them.\n'),
	(17719, 28, 1, 12, 'But don’t look down on your brother in the day of his disaster, and don’t rejoice over the children of Judah in the day of their destruction. Don’t speak proudly in the day of distress.\n'),
	(17720, 28, 1, 13, 'Don’t enter into the gate of my people in the day of their calamity. Don’t look down on their affliction in the day of their calamity, neither seize their wealth on the day of their calamity.\n'),
	(17721, 28, 1, 14, 'Don’t stand in the crossroads to cut off those of his who escape. Don’t deliver up those of his who remain in the day of distress.\n'),
	(17722, 28, 1, 15, 'For the day of Yahweh is near all the nations! As you have done, it will be done to you. Your deeds will return upon your own head.\n'),
	(17723, 28, 1, 16, 'For as you have drunk on my holy mountain, so will all the nations drink continually. Yes, they will drink, swallow down, and will be as though they had not been.\n'),
	(17724, 28, 1, 17, 'But in Mount Zion, there will be those who escape, and it will be holy. The house of Jacob will possess their possessions.\n'),
	(17725, 28, 1, 18, 'The house of Jacob will be a fire, the house of Joseph a flame, and the house of Esau for stubble. They will burn among them, and devour them. There will not be any remaining to the house of Esau.” Indeed, Yahweh has spoken.\n'),
	(17726, 28, 1, 19, 'Those of the South will possess the mountain of Esau, and those of the lowland, the Philistines. They will possess the field of Ephraim, and the field of Samaria. Benjamin will possess Gilead.\n'),
	(17727, 28, 1, 20, 'The captives of this army of the children of Israel, who are among the Canaanites, will possess even to Zarephath; and the captives of Jerusalem, who are in Sepharad, will possess the cities of the Negev.\n'),
	(17728, 28, 1, 21, 'Saviors will go up on Mount Zion to judge the mountains of Esau, and the kingdom will be Yahweh’s.\n'),
	(17729, 29, 1, 1, 'Now Yahweh’s word came to Jonah the son of Amittai, saying,\n'),
	(17730, 29, 1, 2, '“Arise, go to Nineveh, that great city, and preach against it, for their wickedness has come up before me.”\n'),
	(17731, 29, 1, 3, 'But Jonah rose up to flee to Tarshish from the presence of Yahweh. He went down to Joppa, and found a ship going to Tarshish; so he paid its fare, and went down into it, to go with them to Tarshish from the presence of Yahweh.\n'),
	(17732, 29, 1, 4, 'But Yahweh sent out a great wind on the sea, and there was a mighty storm on the sea, so that the ship was likely to break up.\n'),
	(17733, 29, 1, 5, 'Then the mariners were afraid, and every man cried to his god. They threw the cargo that was in the ship into the sea to lighten the ship. But Jonah had gone down into the innermost parts of the ship, and he was laying down, and was fast asleep.\n'),
	(17734, 29, 1, 6, 'So the ship master came to him, and said to him, “What do you mean, sleeper? Arise, call on your God! Maybe your God will notice us, so that we won’t perish.”\n'),
	(17735, 29, 1, 7, 'They all said to each other, “Come, let us cast lots, that we may know who is responsible for this evil that is on us.” So they cast lots, and the lot fell on Jonah.\n'),
	(17736, 29, 1, 8, 'Then they asked him, “Tell us, please, for whose cause this evil is on us. What is your occupation? Where do you come from? What is your country? Of what people are you?”\n'),
	(17737, 29, 1, 9, 'He said to them, “I am a Hebrew, and I fear Yahweh, the God of heaven, who has made the sea and the dry land.”\n'),
	(17738, 29, 1, 10, 'Then the men were exceedingly afraid, and said to him, “What have you done?” For the men knew that he was fleeing from the presence of Yahweh, because he had told them.\n'),
	(17739, 29, 1, 11, 'Then they said to him, “What shall we do to you, that the sea may be calm to us?” For the sea grew more and more stormy.\n'),
	(17740, 29, 1, 12, 'He said to them, “Take me up, and throw me into the sea. Then the sea will be calm for you; for I know that because of me this great storm is on you.”\n'),
	(17741, 29, 1, 13, 'Nevertheless the men rowed hard to get them back to the land; but they could not, for the sea grew more and more stormy against them.\n'),
	(17742, 29, 1, 14, 'Therefore they cried to Yahweh, and said, “We beg you, Yahweh, we beg you, don’t let us die for this man’s life, and don’t lay on us innocent blood; for you, Yahweh, have done as it pleased you.”\n'),
	(17743, 29, 1, 15, 'So they took up Jonah, and threw him into the sea; and the sea ceased its raging.\n'),
	(17744, 29, 1, 16, 'Then the men feared Yahweh exceedingly; and they offered a sacrifice to Yahweh, and made vows.\n'),
	(17745, 29, 1, 17, 'Yahweh prepared a great fish to swallow up Jonah, and Jonah was in the belly of the fish three days and three nights.\n'),
	(17746, 29, 2, 1, 'Then Jonah prayed to Yahweh, his God, out of the fish’s belly.\n'),
	(17747, 29, 2, 2, 'He said,\n“I called because of my affliction to Yahweh.\nHe answered me.\nOut of the belly of Sheol I cried.\nYou heard my voice.\n'),
	(17748, 29, 2, 3, 'For you threw me into the depths,\nin the heart of the seas.\nThe flood was all around me.\nAll your waves and your billows passed over me.\n'),
	(17749, 29, 2, 4, 'I said, ‘I have been banished from your sight;\nyet I will look again toward your holy temple.’\n'),
	(17750, 29, 2, 5, 'The waters surrounded me,\neven to the soul.\nThe deep was around me.\nThe weeds were wrapped around my head.\n'),
	(17751, 29, 2, 6, 'I went down to the bottoms of the mountains.\nThe earth barred me in forever:\nyet have you brought up my life from the pit, Yahweh my God.\n'),
	(17752, 29, 2, 7, '“When my soul fainted within me, I remembered Yahweh.\nMy prayer came in to you, into your holy temple.\n'),
	(17753, 29, 2, 8, 'Those who regard lying vanities forsake their own mercy.\n'),
	(17754, 29, 2, 9, 'But I will sacrifice to you with the voice of thanksgiving.\nI will pay that which I have vowed.\nSalvation belongs to Yahweh.”\n'),
	(17755, 29, 2, 10, 'Then Yahweh spoke to the fish, and it vomited out Jonah on the dry land.\n'),
	(17756, 29, 3, 1, 'Yahweh’s word came to Jonah the second time, saying,\n'),
	(17757, 29, 3, 2, '“Arise, go to Nineveh, that great city, and preach to it the message that I give you.”\n'),
	(17758, 29, 3, 3, 'So Jonah arose, and went to Nineveh, according to Yahweh’s word. Now Nineveh was an exceedingly great city, three days’ journey across.\n'),
	(17759, 29, 3, 4, 'Jonah began to enter into the city a day’s journey, and he cried out, and said, “In forty days, Nineveh will be overthrown!”\n'),
	(17760, 29, 3, 5, 'The people of Nineveh believed God; and they proclaimed a fast, and put on sackcloth, from their greatest even to their least.\n'),
	(17761, 29, 3, 6, 'The news reached the king of Nineveh, and he arose from his throne, and took off his royal robe, covered himself with sackcloth, and sat in ashes.\n'),
	(17762, 29, 3, 7, 'He made a proclamation and published through Nineveh by the decree of the king and his nobles, saying, “Let neither man nor animal, herd nor flock, taste anything; let them not feed, nor drink water;\n'),
	(17763, 29, 3, 8, 'but let them be covered with sackcloth, both man and animal, and let them cry mightily to God. Yes, let them turn everyone from his evil way, and from the violence that is in his hands.\n'),
	(17764, 29, 3, 9, 'Who knows whether God will not turn and relent, and turn away from his fierce anger, so that we might not perish?”\n'),
	(17765, 29, 3, 10, 'God saw their works, that they turned from their evil way. God relented of the disaster which he said he would do to them, and he didn’t do it.\n'),
	(17766, 29, 4, 1, 'But it displeased Jonah exceedingly, and he was angry.\n'),
	(17767, 29, 4, 2, 'He prayed to Yahweh, and said, “Please, Yahweh, wasn’t this what I said when I was still in my own country? Therefore I hurried to flee to Tarshish, for I knew that you are a gracious God, and merciful, slow to anger, and abundant in loving kindness, and you relent of doing harm.\n'),
	(17768, 29, 4, 3, 'Therefore now, Yahweh, take, I beg you, my life from me; for it is better for me to die than to live.”\n'),
	(17769, 29, 4, 4, 'Yahweh said, “Is it right for you to be angry?”\n'),
	(17770, 29, 4, 5, 'Then Jonah went out of the city, and sat on the east side of the city, and there made himself a booth, and sat under it in the shade, until he might see what would become of the city.\n'),
	(17771, 29, 4, 6, 'Yahweh God prepared a vine, and made it to come up over Jonah, that it might be a shade over his head, to deliver him from his discomfort. So Jonah was exceedingly glad because of the vine.\n'),
	(17772, 29, 4, 7, 'But God prepared a worm at dawn the next day, and it chewed on the vine, so that it withered.\n'),
	(17773, 29, 4, 8, 'When the sun arose, God prepared a sultry east wind; and the sun beat on Jonah’s head, so that he fainted, and requested for himself that he might die, and said, “It is better for me to die than to live.”\n'),
	(17774, 29, 4, 9, 'God said to Jonah, “Is it right for you to be angry about the vine?”\nHe said, “I am right to be angry, even to death.”\n'),
	(17775, 29, 4, 10, 'Yahweh said, “You have been concerned for the vine, for which you have not labored, neither made it grow; which came up in a night, and perished in a night.\n'),
	(17776, 29, 4, 11, 'Shouldn’t I be concerned for Nineveh, that great city, in which are more than one hundred twenty thousand persons who can’t discern between their right hand and their left hand; and also much livestock?”\n'),
	(17777, 30, 1, 1, 'Yahweh’s word that came to Micah the Morashtite in the days of Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah, kings of Judah, which he saw concerning Samaria and Jerusalem.\n'),
	(17778, 30, 1, 2, 'Hear, you peoples, all of you.\nListen, O earth, and all that is therein:\nand let the Lord Yahweh be witness against you,\nthe Lord from his holy temple.\n'),
	(17779, 30, 1, 3, 'For, behold, Yahweh comes out of his place,\nand will come down and tread on the high places of the earth.\n'),
	(17780, 30, 1, 4, 'The mountains melt under him,\nand the valleys split apart,\nlike wax before the fire,\nlike waters that are poured down a steep place.\n'),
	(17781, 30, 1, 5, '“All this is for the disobedience of Jacob,\nand for the sins of the house of Israel.\nWhat is the disobedience of Jacob?\nIsn’t it Samaria?\nAnd what are the high places of Judah?\nAren’t they Jerusalem?\n'),
	(17782, 30, 1, 6, 'Therefore I will make Samaria like a rubble heap of the field,\nlike places for planting vineyards;\nand I will pour down its stones into the valley,\nand I will uncover its foundations.\n'),
	(17783, 30, 1, 7, 'All her idols will be beaten to pieces,\nand all her temple gifts will be burned with fire,\nand all her images I will destroy;\nfor of the hire of a prostitute has she gathered them,\nand to the hire of a prostitute shall they return.”\n'),
	(17784, 30, 1, 8, 'For this I will lament and wail;\nI will go stripped and naked;\nI will howl like the jackals,\nand moan like the daughters of owls.\n'),
	(17785, 30, 1, 9, 'For her wounds are incurable;\nfor it has come even to Judah.\nIt reaches to the gate of my people,\neven to Jerusalem.\n'),
	(17786, 30, 1, 10, 'Don’t tell it in Gath.\nDon’t weep at all.\nAt Beth Ophrah I have rolled myself in the dust.\n'),
	(17787, 30, 1, 11, 'Pass on, inhabitant of Shaphir, in nakedness and shame.\nThe inhabitant of Zaanan won’t come out.\nThe wailing of Beth Ezel will take from you his protection.\n'),
	(17788, 30, 1, 12, 'For the inhabitant of Maroth waits anxiously for good,\nbecause evil has come down from Yahweh to the gate of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(17789, 30, 1, 13, 'Harness the chariot to the swift steed, inhabitant of Lachish.\nShe was the beginning of sin to the daughter of Zion;\nFor the transgressions of Israel were found in you.\n'),
	(17790, 30, 1, 14, 'Therefore you will give a parting gift to Moresheth Gath.\nThe houses of Achzib will be a deceitful thing to the kings of Israel.\n'),
	(17791, 30, 1, 15, 'I will yet bring to you, inhabitant of Mareshah.\nHe who is the glory of Israel will come to Adullam.\n'),
	(17792, 30, 1, 16, 'Shave your heads,\nand cut off your hair for the children of your delight.\nEnlarge your baldness like the vulture;\nfor they have gone into captivity from you!\n'),
	(17793, 30, 2, 1, 'Woe to those who devise iniquity\nand work evil on their beds!\nWhen the morning is light, they practice it,\nbecause it is in the power of their hand.\n'),
	(17794, 30, 2, 2, 'They covet fields, and seize them;\nand houses, and take them away:\nand they oppress a man and his house,\neven a man and his heritage.\n'),
	(17795, 30, 2, 3, 'Therefore Yahweh says:\n“Behold, I am planning against these people a disaster,\nfrom which you will not remove your necks,\nneither will you walk haughtily;\nfor it is an evil time.\n'),
	(17796, 30, 2, 4, 'In that day they will take up a parable against you,\nand lament with a doleful lamentation, saying,\n‘We are utterly ruined!\nMy people’s possession is divided up.\nIndeed he takes it from me and assigns our fields to traitors!’”\n'),
	(17797, 30, 2, 5, 'Therefore you will have no one who divides the land by lot in Yahweh’s assembly.\n'),
	(17798, 30, 2, 6, '“Don’t prophesy!”\nThey prophesy.\n“Don’t prophesy about these things.\nDisgrace won’t overtake us.”\n'),
	(17799, 30, 2, 7, 'Shall it be said, O house of Jacob:\n“Is Yahweh’s Spirit angry?\nAre these his doings?\nDon’t my words do good to him who walks blamelessly?”\n'),
	(17800, 30, 2, 8, 'But lately my people have risen up as an enemy.\nYou strip the robe and clothing from those who pass by without a care, returning from battle.\n'),
	(17801, 30, 2, 9, 'You drive the women of my people out from their pleasant houses;\nfrom their young children you take away my blessing forever.\n'),
	(17802, 30, 2, 10, 'Arise, and depart!\nFor this is not your resting place,\nbecause of uncleanness that destroys,\neven with a grievous destruction.\n'),
	(17803, 30, 2, 11, 'If a man walking in a spirit of falsehood lies:\n“I will prophesy to you of wine and of strong drink”;\nhe would be the prophet of this people.\n'),
	(17804, 30, 2, 12, 'I will surely assemble, Jacob, all of you;\nI will surely gather the remnant of Israel;\nI will put them together as the sheep of Bozrah,\nas a flock in the middle of their pasture;\nthey will swarm with people.\n'),
	(17805, 30, 2, 13, 'He who breaks open the way goes up before them.\nThey break through the gate, and go out.\nAnd their king passes on before them,\nwith Yahweh at their head.\n'),
	(17806, 30, 3, 1, 'I said,\n“Please listen, you heads of Jacob,\nand rulers of the house of Israel:\nIsn’t it for you to know justice?\n'),
	(17807, 30, 3, 2, 'You who hate the good,\nand love the evil;\nwho tear off their skin,\nand their flesh from off their bones;\n'),
	(17808, 30, 3, 3, 'who also eat the flesh of my people,\nand flay their skin from off them,\nand break their bones,\nand chop them in pieces, as for the pot,\nand as meat within the cauldron.\n'),
	(17809, 30, 3, 4, 'Then they will cry to Yahweh,\nbut he will not answer them.\nYes, he will hide his face from them at that time,\nbecause they made their deeds evil.”\n'),
	(17810, 30, 3, 5, 'Yahweh says concerning the prophets who lead my people astray; for those who feed their teeth, they proclaim, “Peace!” and whoever doesn’t provide for their mouths, they prepare war against him:\n'),
	(17811, 30, 3, 6, '“Therefore night is over you, with no vision,\nand it is dark to you, that you may not divine;\nand the sun will go down on the prophets,\nand the day will be black over them.\n'),
	(17812, 30, 3, 7, 'The seers shall be disappointed,\nand the diviners confounded.\nYes, they shall all cover their lips;\nfor there is no answer from God.”\n'),
	(17813, 30, 3, 8, 'But as for me, I am full of power by Yahweh’s Spirit,\nand of judgment, and of might,\nto declare to Jacob his disobedience,\nand to Israel his sin.\n'),
	(17814, 30, 3, 9, 'Please listen to this, you heads of the house of Jacob,\nand rulers of the house of Israel,\nwho abhor justice,\nand pervert all equity.\n'),
	(17815, 30, 3, 10, 'They build up Zion with blood,\nand Jerusalem with iniquity.\n'),
	(17816, 30, 3, 11, 'Her leaders judge for bribes,\nand her priests teach for a price,\nand her prophets of it tell fortunes for money:\nyet they lean on Yahweh, and say,\n“Isn’t Yahweh among us?\nNo disaster will come on us.”\n'),
	(17817, 30, 3, 12, 'Therefore Zion for your sake will be plowed like a field,\nand Jerusalem will become heaps of rubble,\nand the mountain of the temple like the high places of a forest.\n'),
	(17818, 30, 4, 1, 'But in the latter days,\nit will happen that the mountain of Yahweh’s temple will be established on the top of the mountains,\nand it will be exalted above the hills;\nand peoples will stream to it.\n'),
	(17819, 30, 4, 2, 'Many nations will go and say,\n“Come, and let us go up to the mountain of Yahweh,\nand to the house of the God of Jacob;\nand he will teach us of his ways,\nand we will walk in his paths.”\nFor the law will go out of Zion,\nand Yahweh’s word from Jerusalem;\n'),
	(17820, 30, 4, 3, 'and he will judge between many peoples,\nand will decide concerning strong nations afar off.\nThey will beat their swords into plowshares,\nand their spears into pruning hooks.\nNation will not lift up sword against nation,\nneither will they learn war any more.\n'),
	(17821, 30, 4, 4, 'But they will sit every man under his vine and under his fig tree;\nand no one will make them afraid:\nFor the mouth of Yahweh of Armies has spoken.\n'),
	(17822, 30, 4, 5, 'Indeed all the nations may walk in the name of their gods;\nbut we will walk in the name of Yahweh our God forever and ever.\n'),
	(17823, 30, 4, 6, '“In that day,” says Yahweh,\n“I will assemble that which is lame,\nand I will gather that which is driven away,\nand that which I have afflicted;\n'),
	(17824, 30, 4, 7, 'and I will make that which was lame a remnant,\nand that which was cast far off a strong nation:\nand Yahweh will reign over them on Mount Zion from then on, even forever.”\n'),
	(17825, 30, 4, 8, 'You, tower of the flock, the hill of the daughter of Zion,\nto you it will come,\nyes, the former dominion will come,\nthe kingdom of the daughter of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(17826, 30, 4, 9, 'Now why do you cry out aloud?\nIs there no king in you?\nHas your counselor perished,\nthat pains have taken hold of you as of a woman in travail?\n'),
	(17827, 30, 4, 10, 'Be in pain, and labor to give birth, daughter of Zion,\nlike a woman in travail;\nfor now you will go out of the city,\nand will dwell in the field,\nand will come even to Babylon.\nThere you will be rescued.\nThere Yahweh will redeem you from the hand of your enemies.\n'),
	(17828, 30, 4, 11, 'Now many nations have assembled against you, that say,\n“Let her be defiled,\nand let our eye gloat over Zion.”\n'),
	(17829, 30, 4, 12, 'But they don’t know the thoughts of Yahweh,\nneither do they understand his counsel;\nfor he has gathered them like the sheaves to the threshing floor.\n'),
	(17830, 30, 4, 13, 'Arise and thresh, daughter of Zion;\nfor I will make your horn iron,\nand I will make your hoofs brass;\nand you will beat in pieces many peoples:\nand I will devote their gain to Yahweh,\nand their substance to the Lord of the whole earth.\n'),
	(17831, 30, 5, 1, 'Now you shall gather yourself in troops,\ndaughter of troops.\nHe has laid siege against us.\nThey will strike the judge of Israel with a rod on the cheek.\n'),
	(17832, 30, 5, 2, 'But you, Bethlehem Ephrathah,\nbeing small among the clans of Judah,\nout of you one will come out to me that is to be ruler in Israel;\nwhose goings out are from of old, from ancient times.\n'),
	(17833, 30, 5, 3, 'Therefore he will abandon them until the time that she who is in labor gives birth.\nThen the rest of his brothers will return to the children of Israel.\n'),
	(17834, 30, 5, 4, 'He shall stand, and shall shepherd in the strength of Yahweh,\nin the majesty of the name of Yahweh his God:\nand they will live, for then he will be great to the ends of the earth.\n'),
	(17835, 30, 5, 5, 'He will be our peace when Assyria invades our land,\nand when he marches through our fortresses,\nthen we will raise against him seven shepherds,\nand eight leaders of men.\n'),
	(17836, 30, 5, 6, 'They will rule the land of Assyria with the sword,\nand the land of Nimrod in its gates.\nHe will deliver us from the Assyrian,\nwhen he invades our land,\nand when he marches within our border.\n'),
	(17837, 30, 5, 7, 'The remnant of Jacob will be among many peoples,\nlike dew from Yahweh,\nlike showers on the grass,\nthat don’t wait for man,\nnor wait for the sons of men.\n'),
	(17838, 30, 5, 8, 'The remnant of Jacob will be among the nations,\namong many peoples,\nlike a lion among the animals of the forest,\nlike a young lion among the flocks of sheep;\nwho, if he goes through, treads down and tears in pieces,\nand there is no one to deliver.\n'),
	(17839, 30, 5, 9, 'Let your hand be lifted up above your adversaries,\nand let all of your enemies be cut off.\n'),
	(17840, 30, 5, 10, '“It will happen in that day”, says Yahweh,\n“that I will cut off your horses out from among you,\nand will destroy your chariots.\n'),
	(17841, 30, 5, 11, 'I will cut off the cities of your land,\nand will tear down all your strongholds.\n'),
	(17842, 30, 5, 12, 'I will destroy witchcraft from your hand;\nand you shall have no soothsayers.\n'),
	(17843, 30, 5, 13, 'I will cut off your engraved images and your pillars out from among you;\nand you shall no more worship the work of your hands.\n'),
	(17844, 30, 5, 14, 'I will uproot your Asherah poles out from among you;\nand I will destroy your cities.\n'),
	(17845, 30, 5, 15, 'I will execute vengeance in anger,\nand wrath on the nations that didn’t listen.”\n'),
	(17846, 30, 6, 1, 'Listen now to what Yahweh says:\n“Arise, plead your case before the mountains,\nand let the hills hear what you have to say.\n'),
	(17847, 30, 6, 2, 'Hear, you mountains, Yahweh’s controversy,\nand you enduring foundations of the earth;\nfor Yahweh has a controversy with his people,\nand he will contend with Israel.\n'),
	(17848, 30, 6, 3, 'My people, what have I done to you?\nHow have I burdened you?\nAnswer me!\n'),
	(17849, 30, 6, 4, 'For I brought you up out of the land of Egypt,\nand redeemed you out of the house of bondage.\nI sent before you Moses, Aaron, and Miriam.\n'),
	(17850, 30, 6, 5, 'My people, remember now what Balak king of Moab devised,\nand what Balaam the son of Beor answered him from Shittim to Gilgal,\nthat you may know the righteous acts of Yahweh.”\n'),
	(17851, 30, 6, 6, 'How shall I come before Yahweh,\nand bow myself before the exalted God?\nShall I come before him with burnt offerings,\nwith calves a year old?\n'),
	(17852, 30, 6, 7, 'Will Yahweh be pleased with thousands of rams?\nWith tens of thousands of rivers of oil?\nShall I give my firstborn for my disobedience?\nThe fruit of my body for the sin of my soul?\n'),
	(17853, 30, 6, 8, 'He has shown you, O man, what is good.\nWhat does Yahweh require of you, but to act justly,\nto love mercy, and to walk humbly with your God?\n'),
	(17854, 30, 6, 9, 'Yahweh’s voice calls to the city,\nand wisdom sees your name:\n“Listen to the rod,\nand he who appointed it.\n'),
	(17855, 30, 6, 10, 'Are there yet treasures of wickedness in the house of the wicked,\nand a short ephah that is accursed?\n'),
	(17856, 30, 6, 11, 'Shall I be pure with dishonest scales,\nand with a bag of deceitful weights?\n'),
	(17857, 30, 6, 12, 'Her rich men are full of violence,\nher inhabitants speak lies,\nand their tongue is deceitful in their speech.\n'),
	(17858, 30, 6, 13, 'Therefore I also have struck you with a grievous wound.\nI have made you desolate because of your sins.\n'),
	(17859, 30, 6, 14, 'You shall eat, but not be satisfied.\nYour humiliation will be within you.\nYou will store up, but not save;\nand that which you save I will give up to the sword.\n'),
	(17860, 30, 6, 15, 'You will sow, but won’t reap.\nYou will tread the olives, but won’t anoint yourself with oil;\nand crush grapes, but won’t drink the wine.\n'),
	(17861, 30, 6, 16, 'For the statutes of Omri are kept,\nand all the works of Ahab’s house.\nYou walk in their counsels,\nthat I may make you a ruin,\nand her inhabitants a hissing;\nAnd you will bear the reproach of my people.”\n'),
	(17862, 30, 7, 1, 'Misery is mine!\nIndeed, I am like one who gathers the summer fruits, as gleanings of the vineyard:\nThere is no cluster of grapes to eat.\nMy soul desires to eat the early fig.\n'),
	(17863, 30, 7, 2, 'The godly man has perished out of the earth,\nand there is no one upright among men.\nThey all lie in wait for blood;\nevery man hunts his brother with a net.\n'),
	(17864, 30, 7, 3, 'Their hands are on that which is evil to do it diligently.\nThe ruler and judge ask for a bribe;\nand the powerful man dictates the evil desire of his soul.\nThus they conspire together.\n'),
	(17865, 30, 7, 4, 'The best of them is like a brier.\nThe most upright is worse than a thorn hedge.\nThe day of your watchmen,\neven your visitation, has come;\nnow is the time of their confusion.\n'),
	(17866, 30, 7, 5, 'Don’t trust in a neighbor.\nDon’t put confidence in a friend.\nWith the woman lying in your embrace,\nbe careful of the words of your mouth!\n'),
	(17867, 30, 7, 6, 'For the son dishonors the father,\nthe daughter rises up against her mother,\nthe daughter-in-law against her mother-in-law;\na man’s enemies are the men of his own house.\n'),
	(17868, 30, 7, 7, 'But as for me, I will look to Yahweh.\nI will wait for the God of my salvation.\nMy God will hear me.\n'),
	(17869, 30, 7, 8, 'Don’t rejoice against me, my enemy.\nWhen I fall, I will arise.\nWhen I sit in darkness, Yahweh will be a light to me.\n'),
	(17870, 30, 7, 9, 'I will bear the indignation of Yahweh,\nbecause I have sinned against him,\nuntil he pleads my case, and executes judgment for me.\nHe will bring me out to the light.\nI will see his righteousness.\n'),
	(17871, 30, 7, 10, 'Then my enemy will see it,\nand shame will cover her who said to me,\nwhere is Yahweh your God?\nThen my enemy will see me and will cover her shame.\nNow she will be trodden down like the mire of the streets.\n'),
	(17872, 30, 7, 11, 'A day to build your walls—\nIn that day, he will extend your boundary.\n'),
	(17873, 30, 7, 12, 'In that day they will come to you from Assyria and the cities of Egypt,\nand from Egypt even to the River,\nand from sea to sea,\nand mountain to mountain.\n'),
	(17874, 30, 7, 13, 'Yet the land will be desolate because of those who dwell therein,\nfor the fruit of their doings.\n'),
	(17875, 30, 7, 14, 'Shepherd your people with your staff,\nthe flock of your heritage,\nwho dwell by themselves in a forest,\nin the middle of fertile pasture land, let them feed;\nin Bashan and Gilead, as in the days of old.\n'),
	(17876, 30, 7, 15, '“As in the days of your coming out of the land of Egypt,\nI will show them marvelous things.”\n'),
	(17877, 30, 7, 16, 'The nations will see and be ashamed of all their might.\nThey will lay their hand on their mouth.\nTheir ears will be deaf.\n'),
	(17878, 30, 7, 17, 'They will lick the dust like a serpent.\nLike crawling things of the earth they shall come trembling out of their dens.\nThey will come with fear to Yahweh our God,\nand will be afraid because of you.\n'),
	(17879, 30, 7, 18, 'Who is a God like you, who pardons iniquity,\nand passes over the disobedience of the remnant of his heritage?\nHe doesn’t retain his anger forever,\nbecause he delights in loving kindness.\n'),
	(17880, 30, 7, 19, 'He will again have compassion on us.\nHe will tread our iniquities under foot;\nand you will cast all their sins into the depths of the sea.\n'),
	(17881, 30, 7, 20, 'You will give truth to Jacob,\nand mercy to Abraham,\nas you have sworn to our fathers from the days of old.\n'),
	(17882, 31, 1, 1, 'A revelation about Nineveh. The book of the vision of Nahum the Elkoshite.\n'),
	(17883, 31, 1, 2, 'Yahweh is a jealous God and avenges. Yahweh avenges and is full of wrath. Yahweh takes vengeance on his adversaries, and he maintains wrath against his enemies.\n'),
	(17884, 31, 1, 3, 'Yahweh is slow to anger, and great in power, and will by no means leave the guilty unpunished. Yahweh has his way in the whirlwind and in the storm, and the clouds are the dust of his feet.\n'),
	(17885, 31, 1, 4, 'He rebukes the sea, and makes it dry, and dries up all the rivers. Bashan languishes, and Carmel; and the flower of Lebanon languishes.\n'),
	(17886, 31, 1, 5, 'The mountains quake before him, and the hills melt away. The earth trembles at his presence, yes, the world, and all who dwell in it.\n'),
	(17887, 31, 1, 6, 'Who can stand before his indignation? Who can endure the fierceness of his anger? His wrath is poured out like fire, and the rocks are broken apart by him.\n'),
	(17888, 31, 1, 7, 'Yahweh is good, a stronghold in the day of trouble; and he knows those who take refuge in him.\n'),
	(17889, 31, 1, 8, 'But with an overflowing flood, he will make a full end of her place, and will pursue his enemies into darkness.\n'),
	(17890, 31, 1, 9, 'What do you plot against Yahweh? He will make a full end. Affliction won’t rise up the second time.\n'),
	(17891, 31, 1, 10, 'For entangled like thorns, and drunken as with their drink, they are consumed utterly like dry stubble.\n'),
	(17892, 31, 1, 11, 'There is one gone out of you, who devises evil against Yahweh, who counsels wickedness.\n'),
	(17893, 31, 1, 12, 'Yahweh says: “Though they be in full strength, and likewise many, even so they will be cut down, and he shall pass away. Though I have afflicted you, I will afflict you no more.\n'),
	(17894, 31, 1, 13, 'Now will I break his yoke from off you, and will burst your bonds apart.”\n'),
	(17895, 31, 1, 14, 'Yahweh has commanded concerning you: “No more descendants will bear your name. Out of the house of your gods, will I cut off the engraved image and the molten image. I will make your grave, for you are vile.”\n'),
	(17896, 31, 1, 15, 'Behold, on the mountains the feet of him who brings good news, who publishes peace! Keep your feasts, Judah! Perform your vows, for the wicked one will no more pass through you. He is utterly cut off.\n'),
	(17897, 31, 2, 1, 'He who dashes in pieces has come up against you. Keep the fortress! Watch the way! Strengthen your waist! Fortify your power mightily!\n'),
	(17898, 31, 2, 2, 'For Yahweh restores the excellency of Jacob, as the excellency of Israel; for the destroyers have destroyed them, and ruined their vine branches.\n'),
	(17899, 31, 2, 3, 'The shield of his mighty men is made red. The valiant men are in scarlet. The chariots flash with steel in the day of his preparation, and the pine spears are brandished.\n'),
	(17900, 31, 2, 4, 'The chariots rage in the streets. They rush back and forth in the wide ways. Their appearance is like torches. They run like the lightnings.\n'),
	(17901, 31, 2, 5, 'He summons his picked troops. They stumble on their way. They dash to its wall, and the protective shield is put in place.\n'),
	(17902, 31, 2, 6, 'The gates of the rivers are opened, and the palace is dissolved.\n'),
	(17903, 31, 2, 7, 'It is decreed: she is uncovered, she is carried away; and her servants moan as with the voice of doves, beating on their breasts.\n'),
	(17904, 31, 2, 8, 'But Nineveh has been from of old like a pool of water, yet they flee away. “Stop! Stop!” they cry, but no one looks back.\n'),
	(17905, 31, 2, 9, 'Take the plunder of silver. Take the plunder of gold, for there is no end of the store, the glory of all goodly furniture.\n'),
	(17906, 31, 2, 10, 'She is empty, void, and waste. The heart melts, the knees knock together, their bodies and faces have grown pale.\n'),
	(17907, 31, 2, 11, 'Where is the den of the lions, and the feeding place of the young lions, where the lion and the lioness walked, the lion’s cubs, and no one made them afraid?\n'),
	(17908, 31, 2, 12, 'The lion tore in pieces enough for his cubs, and strangled for his lionesses, and filled his caves with the kill, and his dens with prey.\n'),
	(17909, 31, 2, 13, '“Behold, I am against you,” says Yahweh of Armies, “and I will burn her chariots in the smoke, and the sword will devour your young lions; and I will cut off your prey from the earth, and the voice of your messengers will no longer be heard.”\n'),
	(17910, 31, 3, 1, 'Woe to the bloody city! It is all full of lies and robbery. The prey doesn’t depart.\n'),
	(17911, 31, 3, 2, 'The noise of the whip, the noise of the rattling of wheels, prancing horses, and bounding chariots,\n'),
	(17912, 31, 3, 3, 'the horseman mounting, and the flashing sword, the glittering spear, and a multitude of slain, and a great heap of corpses, and there is no end of the bodies. They stumble on their bodies,\n'),
	(17913, 31, 3, 4, 'because of the multitude of the prostitution of the alluring prostitute, the mistress of witchcraft, who sells nations through her prostitution, and families through her witchcraft.\n'),
	(17914, 31, 3, 5, '“Behold, I am against you,” says Yahweh of Armies, “and I will lift your skirts over your face. I will show the nations your nakedness, and the kingdoms your shame.\n'),
	(17915, 31, 3, 6, 'I will throw abominable filth on you, and make you vile, and will set you a spectacle.\n'),
	(17916, 31, 3, 7, 'It will happen that all those who look at you will flee from you, and say, ‘Nineveh is laid waste! Who will mourn for her?’ Where will I seek comforters for you?”\n'),
	(17917, 31, 3, 8, 'Are you better than No-Amon, who was situated among the rivers, who had the waters around her; whose rampart was the sea, and her wall was of the sea?\n'),
	(17918, 31, 3, 9, 'Cush and Egypt were her boundless strength. Put and Libya were her helpers.\n'),
	(17919, 31, 3, 10, 'Yet was she carried away. She went into captivity. Her young children also were dashed in pieces at the head of all the streets, and they cast lots for her honorable men, and all her great men were bound in chains.\n'),
	(17920, 31, 3, 11, 'You also will be drunken. You will be hidden. You also will seek a stronghold because of the enemy.\n'),
	(17921, 31, 3, 12, 'All your fortresses will be like fig trees with the first-ripe figs: if they are shaken, they fall into the mouth of the eater.\n'),
	(17922, 31, 3, 13, 'Behold, your troops among you are women. The gates of your land are set wide open to your enemies. The fire has devoured your bars.\n'),
	(17923, 31, 3, 14, 'Draw water for the siege. Strengthen your fortresses. Go into the clay, and tread the mortar. Make the brick kiln strong.\n'),
	(17924, 31, 3, 15, 'There the fire will devour you. The sword will cut you off. It will devour you like the grasshopper. Multiply like grasshoppers. Multiply like the locust.\n'),
	(17925, 31, 3, 16, 'You have increased your merchants more than the stars of the skies. The grasshopper strips, and flees away.\n'),
	(17926, 31, 3, 17, 'Your guards are like the locusts, and your officials like the swarms of locusts, which settle on the walls on a cold day, but when the sun appears, they flee away, and their place is not known where they are.\n'),
	(17927, 31, 3, 18, 'Your shepherds slumber, king of Assyria. Your nobles lie down. Your people are scattered on the mountains, and there is no one to gather them.\n'),
	(17928, 31, 3, 19, 'There is no healing your wound, for your injury is fatal. All who hear the report of you clap their hands over you; for who hasn’t felt your endless cruelty?\n'),
	(17929, 32, 1, 1, 'The revelation which Habakkuk the prophet saw.\n'),
	(17930, 32, 1, 2, 'Yahweh, how long will I cry, and you will not hear? I cry out to you “Violence!” and will you not save?\n'),
	(17931, 32, 1, 3, 'Why do you show me iniquity, and look at perversity? For destruction and violence are before me. There is strife, and contention rises up.\n'),
	(17932, 32, 1, 4, 'Therefore the law is paralyzed, and justice never prevails; for the wicked surround the righteous; therefore justice comes out perverted.\n'),
	(17933, 32, 1, 5, '“Look among the nations, watch, and wonder marvelously; for I am working a work in your days, which you will not believe though it is told you.\n'),
	(17934, 32, 1, 6, 'For, behold, I raise up the Chaldeans, that bitter and hasty nation, that march through the width of the earth, to possess dwelling places that are not theirs.\n'),
	(17935, 32, 1, 7, 'They are feared and dreaded. Their judgment and their dignity proceed from themselves.\n'),
	(17936, 32, 1, 8, 'Their horses also are swifter than leopards, and are more fierce than the evening wolves. Their horsemen press proudly on. Yes, their horsemen come from afar. They fly as an eagle that hurries to devour.\n'),
	(17937, 32, 1, 9, 'All of them come for violence. Their hordes face the desert. He gathers prisoners like sand.\n'),
	(17938, 32, 1, 10, 'Yes, he scoffs at kings, and princes are a derision to him. He laughs at every stronghold, for he builds up an earthen ramp, and takes it.\n'),
	(17939, 32, 1, 11, 'Then he sweeps by like the wind, and goes on. He is indeed guilty, whose strength is his god.”\n'),
	(17940, 32, 1, 12, 'Aren’t you from everlasting, Yahweh my God, my Holy One? We will not die. Yahweh, you have appointed him for judgment. You, Rock, have established him to punish.\n'),
	(17941, 32, 1, 13, 'You who have purer eyes than to see evil, and who cannot look on perversity, why do you tolerate those who deal treacherously, and keep silent when the wicked swallows up the man who is more righteous than he,\n'),
	(17942, 32, 1, 14, 'and make men like the fish of the sea, like the creeping things, that have no ruler over them?\n'),
	(17943, 32, 1, 15, 'He takes up all of them with the hook. He catches them in his net, and gathers them in his dragnet. Therefore he rejoices and is glad.\n'),
	(17944, 32, 1, 16, 'Therefore he sacrifices to his net, and burns incense to his dragnet, because by them his life is luxurious, and his food is good.\n'),
	(17945, 32, 1, 17, 'Will he therefore continually empty his net, and kill the nations without mercy?\n'),
	(17946, 32, 2, 1, 'I will stand at my watch, and set myself on the ramparts, and will look out to see what he will say to me, and what I will answer concerning my complaint.\n'),
	(17947, 32, 2, 2, 'Yahweh answered me, “Write the vision, and make it plain on tablets, that he who runs may read it.\n'),
	(17948, 32, 2, 3, 'For the vision is yet for the appointed time, and it hurries toward the end, and won’t prove false. Though it takes time, wait for it; because it will surely come. It won’t delay.\n'),
	(17949, 32, 2, 4, 'Behold, his soul is puffed up. It is not upright in him, but the righteous will live by his faith.\n'),
	(17950, 32, 2, 5, 'Yes, moreover, wine is treacherous. A haughty man who doesn’t stay at home, who enlarges his desire as Sheol, and he is like death, and can’t be satisfied, but gathers to himself all nations, and heaps to himself all peoples.\n'),
	(17951, 32, 2, 6, 'Won’t all these take up a parable against him, and a taunting proverb against him, and say, ‘Woe to him who increases that which is not his, and who enriches himself by extortion! How long?’\n'),
	(17952, 32, 2, 7, 'Won’t your debtors rise up suddenly, and wake up those who make you tremble, and you will be their victim?\n'),
	(17953, 32, 2, 8, 'Because you have plundered many nations, all the remnant of the peoples will plunder you, because of men’s blood, and for the violence done to the land, to the city and to all who dwell in it.\n'),
	(17954, 32, 2, 9, 'Woe to him who gets an evil gain for his house, that he may set his nest on high, that he may be delivered from the hand of evil!\n'),
	(17955, 32, 2, 10, 'You have devised shame to your house, by cutting off many peoples, and have sinned against your soul.\n'),
	(17956, 32, 2, 11, 'For the stone will cry out of the wall, and the beam out of the woodwork will answer it.\n'),
	(17957, 32, 2, 12, 'Woe to him who builds a town with blood, and establishes a city by iniquity!\n'),
	(17958, 32, 2, 13, 'Behold, isn’t it of Yahweh of Armies that the peoples labor for the fire, and the nations weary themselves for vanity?\n'),
	(17959, 32, 2, 14, 'For the earth will be filled with the knowledge of Yahweh’s glory, as the waters cover the sea.\n'),
	(17960, 32, 2, 15, '“Woe to him who gives his neighbor drink, pouring your inflaming wine until they are drunk, so that you may gaze at their naked bodies!\n'),
	(17961, 32, 2, 16, 'You are filled with shame, and not glory. You will also drink, and be exposed! The cup of Yahweh’s right hand will come around to you, and disgrace will cover your glory.\n'),
	(17962, 32, 2, 17, 'For the violence done to Lebanon will overwhelm you, and the destruction of the animals, which made them afraid; because of men’s blood, and for the violence done to the land, to every city and to those who dwell in them.\n'),
	(17963, 32, 2, 18, '“What value does the engraved image have, that its maker has engraved it; the molten image, even the teacher of lies, that he who fashions its form trusts in it, to make mute idols?\n'),
	(17964, 32, 2, 19, 'Woe to him who says to the wood, ‘Awake!’ or to the mute stone, ‘Arise!’ Shall this teach? Behold, it is overlaid with gold and silver, and there is no breath at all within it.\n'),
	(17965, 32, 2, 20, 'But Yahweh is in his holy temple. Let all the earth be silent before him!”\n'),
	(17966, 32, 3, 1, 'A prayer of Habakkuk, the prophet, set to victorious music.\n'),
	(17967, 32, 3, 2, 'Yahweh, I have heard of your fame.\nI stand in awe of your deeds, Yahweh.\nRenew your work in the middle of the years.\nIn the middle of the years make it known.\nIn wrath, you remember mercy.\n'),
	(17968, 32, 3, 3, 'God came from Teman,\nthe Holy One from Mount Paran.\nSelah.\nHis glory covered the heavens,\nand his praise filled the earth.\n'),
	(17969, 32, 3, 4, 'His splendor is like the sunrise.\nRays shine from his hand, where his power is hidden.\n'),
	(17970, 32, 3, 5, 'Plague went before him,\nand pestilence followed his feet.\n'),
	(17971, 32, 3, 6, 'He stood, and shook the earth.\nHe looked, and made the nations tremble.\nThe ancient mountains were crumbled.\nThe age-old hills collapsed.\nHis ways are eternal.\n'),
	(17972, 32, 3, 7, 'I saw the tents of Cushan in affliction.\nThe dwellings of the land of Midian trembled.\n'),
	(17973, 32, 3, 8, 'Was Yahweh displeased with the rivers?\nWas your anger against the rivers,\nor your wrath against the sea,\nthat you rode on your horses,\non your chariots of salvation?\n'),
	(17974, 32, 3, 9, 'You uncovered your bow.\nYou called for your sworn arrows.\nSelah.\nYou split the earth with rivers.\n'),
	(17975, 32, 3, 10, 'The mountains saw you, and were afraid.\nThe storm of waters passed by.\nThe deep roared and lifted up its hands on high.\n'),
	(17976, 32, 3, 11, 'The sun and moon stood still in the sky,\nat the light of your arrows as they went,\nat the shining of your glittering spear.\n'),
	(17977, 32, 3, 12, 'You marched through the land in wrath.\nYou threshed the nations in anger.\n'),
	(17978, 32, 3, 13, 'You went out for the salvation of your people,\nfor the salvation of your anointed.\nYou crushed the head of the land of wickedness.\nYou stripped them head to foot.\nSelah.\n'),
	(17979, 32, 3, 14, 'You pierced the heads of his warriors with their own spears.\nThey came as a whirlwind to scatter me,\ngloating as if to devour the wretched in secret.\n'),
	(17980, 32, 3, 15, 'You trampled the sea with your horses,\nchurning mighty waters.\n'),
	(17981, 32, 3, 16, 'I heard, and my body trembled.\nMy lips quivered at the voice.\nRottenness enters into my bones, and I tremble in my place,\nbecause I must wait quietly for the day of trouble,\nfor the coming up of the people who invade us.\n'),
	(17982, 32, 3, 17, 'For though the fig tree doesn’t flourish,\nnor fruit be in the vines;\nthe labor of the olive fails,\nthe fields yield no food;\nthe flocks are cut off from the fold,\nand there is no herd in the stalls:\n'),
	(17983, 32, 3, 18, 'yet I will rejoice in Yahweh.\nI will be joyful in the God of my salvation!\n'),
	(17984, 32, 3, 19, 'Yahweh, the Lord, is my strength.\nHe makes my feet like deer’s feet,\nand enables me to go in high places.\nFor the music director, on my stringed instruments.\n'),
	(17985, 33, 1, 1, 'Yahweh’s word which came to Zephaniah, the son of Cushi, the son of Gedaliah, the son of Amariah, the son of Hezekiah, in the days of Josiah, the son of Amon, king of Judah.\n'),
	(17986, 33, 1, 2, 'I will utterly sweep away everything from the surface of the earth, says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17987, 33, 1, 3, 'I will sweep away man and animal. I will sweep away the birds of the sky, the fish of the sea, and the heaps of rubble with the wicked. I will cut off man from the surface of the earth, says Yahweh.\n'),
	(17988, 33, 1, 4, 'I will stretch out my hand against Judah, and against all the inhabitants of Jerusalem. I will cut off the remnant of Baal from this place: the name of the idolatrous and pagan priests,\n'),
	(17989, 33, 1, 5, 'those who worship the army of the sky on the housetops, those who worship and swear by Yahweh and also swear by Malcam,\n'),
	(17990, 33, 1, 6, 'those who have turned back from following Yahweh, and those who haven’t sought Yahweh nor inquired after him.\n'),
	(17991, 33, 1, 7, 'Be silent at the presence of the Lord Yahweh, for the day of Yahweh is at hand. For Yahweh has prepared a sacrifice. He has consecrated his guests.\n'),
	(17992, 33, 1, 8, 'It will happen in the day of Yahweh’s sacrifice, that I will punish the princes, the king’s sons, and all those who are clothed with foreign clothing.\n'),
	(17993, 33, 1, 9, 'In that day, I will punish all those who leap over the threshold, who fill their master’s house with violence and deceit.\n'),
	(17994, 33, 1, 10, 'In that day, says Yahweh, there will be the noise of a cry from the fish gate, a wailing from the second quarter, and a great crashing from the hills.\n'),
	(17995, 33, 1, 11, 'Wail, you inhabitants of Maktesh, for all the people of Canaan are undone! All those who were loaded with silver are cut off.\n'),
	(17996, 33, 1, 12, 'It will happen at that time, that I will search Jerusalem with lamps, and I will punish the men who are settled on their dregs, who say in their heart, “Yahweh will not do good, neither will he do evil.”\n'),
	(17997, 33, 1, 13, 'Their wealth will become a plunder, and their houses a desolation. Yes, they will build houses, but won’t inhabit them. They will plant vineyards, but won’t drink their wine.\n'),
	(17998, 33, 1, 14, 'The great day of Yahweh is near. It is near, and hurries greatly, the voice of the day of Yahweh. The mighty man cries there bitterly.\n'),
	(17999, 33, 1, 15, 'That day is a day of wrath, a day of distress and anguish, a day of trouble and ruin, a day of darkness and gloom, a day of clouds and blackness,\n'),
	(18000, 33, 1, 16, 'a day of the trumpet and alarm, against the fortified cities, and against the high battlements.\n'),
	(18001, 33, 1, 17, 'I will bring distress on men, that they will walk like blind men, because they have sinned against Yahweh, and their blood will be poured out like dust, and their flesh like dung.\n'),
	(18002, 33, 1, 18, 'Neither their silver nor their gold will be able to deliver them in the day of Yahweh’s wrath, but the whole land will be devoured by the fire of his jealousy; for he will make an end, yes, a terrible end, of all those who dwell in the land.\n'),
	(18003, 33, 2, 1, 'Gather yourselves together, yes, gather together, you nation that has no shame,\n'),
	(18004, 33, 2, 2, 'before the appointed time when the day passes as the chaff, before the fierce anger of Yahweh comes on you, before the day of Yahweh’s anger comes on you.\n'),
	(18005, 33, 2, 3, 'Seek Yahweh, all you humble of the land, who have kept his ordinances. Seek righteousness. Seek humility. It may be that you will be hidden in the day of Yahweh’s anger.\n'),
	(18006, 33, 2, 4, 'For Gaza will be forsaken, and Ashkelon a desolation. They will drive out Ashdod at noonday, and Ekron will be rooted up.\n'),
	(18007, 33, 2, 5, 'Woe to the inhabitants of the sea coast, the nation of the Cherethites! Yahweh’s word is against you, Canaan, the land of the Philistines. I will destroy you, that there will be no inhabitant.\n'),
	(18008, 33, 2, 6, 'The sea coast will be pastures, with cottages for shepherds and folds for flocks.\n'),
	(18009, 33, 2, 7, 'The coast will be for the remnant of the house of Judah. They will find pasture. In the houses of Ashkelon, they will lie down in the evening, for Yahweh, their God, will visit them, and restore them.\n'),
	(18010, 33, 2, 8, 'I have heard the reproach of Moab, and the insults of the children of Ammon, with which they have reproached my people, and magnified themselves against their border.\n'),
	(18011, 33, 2, 9, 'Therefore as I live, says Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, surely Moab will be as Sodom, and the children of Ammon as Gomorrah, a possession of nettles, and salt pits, and a perpetual desolation. The remnant of my people will plunder them, and the survivors of my nation will inherit them.\n'),
	(18012, 33, 2, 10, 'This they will have for their pride, because they have reproached and magnified themselves against the people of Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18013, 33, 2, 11, 'Yahweh will be awesome to them, for he will famish all the gods of the land. Men will worship him, everyone from his place, even all the shores of the nations.\n'),
	(18014, 33, 2, 12, 'You Cushites also, you will be killed by my sword.\n'),
	(18015, 33, 2, 13, 'He will stretch out his hand against the north, destroy Assyria, and will make Nineveh a desolation, as dry as the wilderness.\n'),
	(18016, 33, 2, 14, 'Herds will lie down in the middle of her, all the animals of the nations. Both the pelican and the porcupine will lodge in its capitals. Their calls will echo through the windows. Desolation will be in the thresholds, for he has laid bare the cedar beams.\n'),
	(18017, 33, 2, 15, 'This is the joyous city that lived carelessly, that said in her heart, “I am, and there is no one besides me.” How she has become a desolation, a place for animals to lie down in! Everyone who passes by her will hiss, and shake their fists.\n'),
	(18018, 33, 3, 1, 'Woe to her who is rebellious and polluted, the oppressing city!\n'),
	(18019, 33, 3, 2, 'She didn’t obey the voice. She didn’t receive correction. She didn’t trust in Yahweh. She didn’t draw near to her God.\n'),
	(18020, 33, 3, 3, 'Her princes within her are roaring lions. Her judges are evening wolves. They leave nothing until the next day.\n'),
	(18021, 33, 3, 4, 'Her prophets are arrogant and treacherous people. Her priests have profaned the sanctuary. They have done violence to the law.\n'),
	(18022, 33, 3, 5, 'Yahweh, within her, is righteous. He will do no wrong. Every morning he brings his justice to light. He doesn’t fail, but the unjust know no shame.\n'),
	(18023, 33, 3, 6, 'I have cut off nations. Their battlements are desolate. I have made their streets waste, so that no one passes by. Their cities are destroyed, so that there is no man, so that there is no inhabitant.\n'),
	(18024, 33, 3, 7, 'I said, “Just fear me. Receive correction, so that her dwelling won’t be cut off, according to all that I have appointed concerning her.” But they rose early and corrupted all their doings.\n'),
	(18025, 33, 3, 8, '“Therefore wait for me”, says Yahweh, “until the day that I rise up to the prey, for my determination is to gather the nations, that I may assemble the kingdoms, to pour on them my indignation, even all my fierce anger, for all the earth will be devoured with the fire of my jealousy.\n'),
	(18026, 33, 3, 9, 'For then I will purify the lips of the peoples, that they may all call on Yahweh’s name, to serve him shoulder to shoulder.\n'),
	(18027, 33, 3, 10, 'From beyond the rivers of Cush, my worshipers, even the daughter of my dispersed people, will bring my offering.\n'),
	(18028, 33, 3, 11, 'In that day you will not be disappointed for all your doings, in which you have transgressed against me; for then I will take away out from among you your proudly exulting ones, and you will no more be haughty in my holy mountain.\n'),
	(18029, 33, 3, 12, 'But I will leave among you an afflicted and poor people, and they will take refuge in Yahweh’s name.\n'),
	(18030, 33, 3, 13, 'The remnant of Israel will not do iniquity, nor speak lies, neither will a deceitful tongue be found in their mouth, for they will feed and lie down, and no one will make them afraid.”\n'),
	(18031, 33, 3, 14, 'Sing, daughter of Zion! Shout, Israel! Be glad and rejoice with all your heart, daughter of Jerusalem.\n'),
	(18032, 33, 3, 15, 'Yahweh has taken away your judgments. He has thrown out your enemy. The King of Israel, Yahweh, is among you. You will not be afraid of evil any more.\n'),
	(18033, 33, 3, 16, 'In that day, it will be said to Jerusalem, “Don’t be afraid, Zion. Don’t let your hands be weak.”\n'),
	(18034, 33, 3, 17, 'Yahweh, your God, is among you, a mighty one who will save. He will rejoice over you with joy. He will calm you in his love. He will rejoice over you with singing.\n'),
	(18035, 33, 3, 18, 'I will remove those who grieve about the appointed feasts from you. They are a burden and a reproach to you.\n'),
	(18036, 33, 3, 19, 'Behold, at that time I will deal with all those who afflict you, and I will save those who are lame, and gather those who were driven away. I will give them praise and honor, whose shame has been in all the earth.\n'),
	(18037, 33, 3, 20, 'At that time will I bring you in, and at that time will I gather you; for I will give you honor and praise among all the peoples of the earth, when I restore your fortunes before your eyes, says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18038, 34, 1, 1, 'In the second year of Darius the king, in the sixth month, in the first day of the month, Yahweh’s word came by Haggai, the prophet, to Zerubbabel, the son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, and to Joshua, the son of Jehozadak, the high priest, saying,\n'),
	(18039, 34, 1, 2, '“This is what Yahweh of Armies says: These people say, ‘The time hasn’t yet come, the time for Yahweh’s house to be built.’”\n'),
	(18040, 34, 1, 3, 'Then Yahweh’s word came by Haggai, the prophet, saying,\n'),
	(18041, 34, 1, 4, '“Is it a time for you yourselves to dwell in your paneled houses, while this house lies waste?\n'),
	(18042, 34, 1, 5, 'Now therefore this is what Yahweh of Armies says: Consider your ways.\n'),
	(18043, 34, 1, 6, 'You have sown much, and bring in little. You eat, but you don’t have enough. You drink, but you aren’t filled with drink. You clothe yourselves, but no one is warm, and he who earns wages earns wages to put them into a bag with holes in it.”\n'),
	(18044, 34, 1, 7, 'This is what Yahweh of Armies says: “Consider your ways.\n'),
	(18045, 34, 1, 8, 'Go up to the mountain, bring wood, and build the house. I will take pleasure in it, and I will be glorified,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18046, 34, 1, 9, '“You looked for much, and, behold, it came to little; and when you brought it home, I blew it away. Why?” says Yahweh of Armies, “Because of my house that lies waste, while each of you is busy with his own house.\n'),
	(18047, 34, 1, 10, 'Therefore for your sake the heavens withhold the dew, and the earth withholds its fruit.\n'),
	(18048, 34, 1, 11, 'I called for a drought on the land, on the mountains, on the grain, on the new wine, on the oil, on that which the ground produces, on men, on livestock, and on all the labor of the hands.”\n'),
	(18049, 34, 1, 12, 'Then Zerubbabel, the son of Shealtiel, and Joshua, the son of Jehozadak, the high priest, with all the remnant of the people, obeyed Yahweh, their God’s voice, and the words of Haggai, the prophet, as Yahweh, their God, had sent him; and the people feared Yahweh.\n'),
	(18050, 34, 1, 13, 'Then Haggai, Yahweh’s messenger, spoke Yahweh’s message to the people, saying, “I am with you,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18051, 34, 1, 14, 'Yahweh stirred up the spirit of Zerubbabel, the son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, and the spirit of Joshua, the son of Jehozadak, the high priest, and the spirit of all the remnant of the people; and they came and worked on the house of Yahweh of Armies, their God,\n'),
	(18052, 34, 1, 15, 'in the twenty-fourth day of the month, in the sixth month, in the second year of Darius the king.\n'),
	(18053, 34, 2, 1, 'In the seventh month, in the twenty-first day of the month, Yahweh’s word came by Haggai the prophet, saying,\n'),
	(18054, 34, 2, 2, '“Speak now to Zerubbabel, the son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, and to Joshua, the son of Jehozadak, the high priest, and to the remnant of the people, saying,\n'),
	(18055, 34, 2, 3, '‘Who is left among you who saw this house in its former glory? How do you see it now? Isn’t it in your eyes as nothing?\n'),
	(18056, 34, 2, 4, 'Yet now be strong, Zerubbabel,’ says Yahweh. ‘Be strong, Joshua, son of Jehozadak, the high priest. Be strong, all you people of the land,’ says Yahweh, ‘and work, for I am with you,’ says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18057, 34, 2, 5, 'This is the word that I covenanted with you when you came out of Egypt, and my Spirit lived among you. ‘Don’t be afraid.’\n'),
	(18058, 34, 2, 6, 'For this is what Yahweh of Armies says: ‘Yet once, it is a little while, and I will shake the heavens, the earth, the sea, and the dry land;\n'),
	(18059, 34, 2, 7, 'and I will shake all nations. The precious things of all nations will come, and I will fill this house with glory, says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18060, 34, 2, 8, 'The silver is mine, and the gold is mine,’ says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18061, 34, 2, 9, '‘The latter glory of this house will be greater than the former,’ says Yahweh of Armies; ‘and in this place will I give peace,’ says Yahweh of Armies.”\n'),
	(18062, 34, 2, 10, 'In the twenty-fourth day of the ninth month, in the second year of Darius, Yahweh’s word came by Haggai the prophet, saying,\n'),
	(18063, 34, 2, 11, '“Yahweh of Armies says: Ask now the priests concerning the law, saying,\n'),
	(18064, 34, 2, 12, '‘If someone carries holy meat in the fold of his garment, and with his fold touches bread, stew, wine, oil, or any food, will it become holy?’”\nThe priests answered, “No.”\n'),
	(18065, 34, 2, 13, 'Then Haggai said, “If one who is unclean by reason of a dead body touch any of these, will it be unclean?”\nThe priests answered, “It will be unclean.”\n'),
	(18066, 34, 2, 14, 'Then Haggai answered, “‘So is this people, and so is this nation before me,’ says Yahweh; ‘and so is every work of their hands. That which they offer there is unclean.\n'),
	(18067, 34, 2, 15, 'Now, please consider from this day and backward, before a stone was laid on a stone in Yahweh’s temple.\n'),
	(18068, 34, 2, 16, 'Through all that time, when one came to a heap of twenty measures, there were only ten. When one came to the wine vat to draw out fifty, there were only twenty.\n'),
	(18069, 34, 2, 17, 'I struck you with blight, mildew, and hail in all the work of your hands; yet you didn’t turn to me,’ says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18070, 34, 2, 18, '‘Consider, please, from this day and backward, from the twenty-fourth day of the ninth month, since the day that the foundation of Yahweh’s temple was laid, consider it.\n'),
	(18071, 34, 2, 19, 'Is the seed yet in the barn? Yes, the vine, the fig tree, the pomegranate, and the olive tree haven’t produced. From today I will bless you.’”\n'),
	(18072, 34, 2, 20, 'Yahweh’s word came the second time to Haggai in the twenty-fourth day of the month, saying,\n'),
	(18073, 34, 2, 21, '“Speak to Zerubbabel, governor of Judah, saying, ‘I will shake the heavens and the earth.\n'),
	(18074, 34, 2, 22, 'I will overthrow the throne of kingdoms. I will destroy the strength of the kingdoms of the nations. I will overthrow the chariots, and those who ride in them. The horses and their riders will come down, everyone by the sword of his brother.\n'),
	(18075, 34, 2, 23, 'In that day, says Yahweh of Armies, will I take you, Zerubbabel, my servant, the son of Shealtiel,’ says Yahweh, ‘and will make you as a signet, for I have chosen you,’ says Yahweh of Armies.”\n'),
	(18076, 35, 1, 1, 'In the eighth month, in the second year of Darius, Yahweh’s word came to Zechariah the son of Berechiah, the son of Iddo, the prophet, saying,\n'),
	(18077, 35, 1, 2, '“Yahweh was very displeased with your fathers.\n'),
	(18078, 35, 1, 3, 'Therefore tell them: Yahweh of Armies says: ‘Return to me,’ says Yahweh of Armies, ‘and I will return to you,’ says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18079, 35, 1, 4, 'Don’t you be like your fathers, to whom the former prophets proclaimed, saying: Yahweh of Armies says, ‘Return now from your evil ways, and from your evil doings;’ but they did not hear, nor listen to me, says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18080, 35, 1, 5, 'Your fathers, where are they? And the prophets, do they live forever?\n'),
	(18081, 35, 1, 6, 'But my words and my decrees, which I commanded my servants the prophets, didn’t they overtake your fathers?\n“Then they repented and said, ‘Just as Yahweh of Armies determined to do to us, according to our ways, and according to our practices, so he has dealt with us.’”\n'),
	(18082, 35, 1, 7, 'On the twenty-fourth day of the eleventh month, which is the month Shebat, in the second year of Darius, Yahweh’s word came to Zechariah the son of Berechiah, the son of Iddo, the prophet, saying,\n'),
	(18083, 35, 1, 8, '“I had a vision in the night, and behold, a man riding on a red horse, and he stood among the myrtle trees that were in a ravine; and behind him there were red, brown, and white horses.\n'),
	(18084, 35, 1, 9, 'Then I asked, ‘My lord, what are these?’”\nThe angel who talked with me said to me, “I will show you what these are.”\n'),
	(18085, 35, 1, 10, 'The man who stood among the myrtle trees answered, “They are the ones Yahweh has sent to go back and forth through the earth.”\n'),
	(18086, 35, 1, 11, 'They reported to Yahweh’s angel who stood among the myrtle trees, and said, “We have walked back and forth through the earth, and behold, all the earth is at rest and in peace.”\n'),
	(18087, 35, 1, 12, 'Then Yahweh’s angel replied, “O Yahweh of Armies, how long will you not have mercy on Jerusalem and on the cities of Judah, against which you have had indignation these seventy years?”\n'),
	(18088, 35, 1, 13, 'Yahweh answered the angel who talked with me with kind and comforting words.\n'),
	(18089, 35, 1, 14, 'So the angel who talked with me said to me, “Proclaim, saying, ‘Yahweh of Armies says: “I am jealous for Jerusalem and for Zion with a great jealousy.\n'),
	(18090, 35, 1, 15, 'I am very angry with the nations that are at ease; for I was but a little displeased, but they added to the calamity.”\n'),
	(18091, 35, 1, 16, 'Therefore Yahweh says: “I have returned to Jerusalem with mercy. My house shall be built in it,” says Yahweh of Armies, “and a line shall be stretched out over Jerusalem.”’\n'),
	(18092, 35, 1, 17, '“Proclaim further, saying, ‘Yahweh of Armies says: “My cities will again overflow with prosperity, and Yahweh will again comfort Zion, and will again choose Jerusalem.”’”\n'),
	(18093, 35, 1, 18, 'I lifted up my eyes, and saw, and behold, four horns.\n'),
	(18094, 35, 1, 19, 'I asked the angel who talked with me, “What are these?”\nHe answered me, “These are the horns which have scattered Judah, Israel, and Jerusalem.”\n'),
	(18095, 35, 1, 20, 'Yahweh showed me four craftsmen.\n'),
	(18096, 35, 1, 21, 'Then I asked, “What are these coming to do?”\nHe said, “These are the horns which scattered Judah, so that no man lifted up his head; but these have come to terrify them, to cast down the horns of the nations, which lifted up their horn against the land of Judah to scatter it.”\n'),
	(18097, 35, 2, 1, 'I lifted up my eyes, and saw, and behold, a man with a measuring line in his hand.\n'),
	(18098, 35, 2, 2, 'Then I asked, “Where are you going?”\nHe said to me, “To measure Jerusalem, to see what is its width and what is its length.”\n');
REPLACE INTO `verses` (`id`, `book_id`, `chapter_number`, `verse_number`, `text`) VALUES
	(18099, 35, 2, 3, 'Behold, the angel who talked with me went out, and another angel went out to meet him,\n'),
	(18100, 35, 2, 4, 'and said to him, “Run, speak to this young man, saying, ‘Jerusalem will be inhabited as villages without walls, because of the multitude of men and livestock in it.\n'),
	(18101, 35, 2, 5, 'For I,’ says Yahweh, ‘will be to her a wall of fire around it, and I will be the glory in the middle of her.\n'),
	(18102, 35, 2, 6, 'Come! Come! Flee from the land of the north,’ says Yahweh; ‘for I have spread you abroad as the four winds of the sky,’ says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18103, 35, 2, 7, '‘Come, Zion! Escape, you who dwell with the daughter of Babylon.’\n'),
	(18104, 35, 2, 8, 'For Yahweh of Armies says: ‘For honor he has sent me to the nations which plundered you; for he who touches you touches the apple of his eye.\n'),
	(18105, 35, 2, 9, 'For, behold, I will shake my hand over them, and they will be a plunder to those who served them; and you will know that Yahweh of Armies has sent me.\n'),
	(18106, 35, 2, 10, 'Sing and rejoice, daughter of Zion; for, behold, I come, and I will dwell within you,’ says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18107, 35, 2, 11, 'Many nations shall join themselves to Yahweh in that day, and shall be my people; and I will dwell among you, and you shall know that Yahweh of Armies has sent me to you.\n'),
	(18108, 35, 2, 12, 'Yahweh will inherit Judah as his portion in the holy land, and will again choose Jerusalem.\n'),
	(18109, 35, 2, 13, 'Be silent, all flesh, before Yahweh; for he has roused himself from his holy habitation!”\n'),
	(18110, 35, 3, 1, 'He showed me Joshua the high priest standing before Yahweh’s angel, and Satan standing at his right hand to be his adversary.\n'),
	(18111, 35, 3, 2, 'Yahweh said to Satan, “Yahweh rebuke you, Satan! Yes, Yahweh who has chosen Jerusalem rebuke you! Isn’t this a burning stick plucked out of the fire?”\n'),
	(18112, 35, 3, 3, 'Now Joshua was clothed with filthy garments, and was standing before the angel.\n'),
	(18113, 35, 3, 4, 'He answered and spoke to those who stood before him, saying, “Take the filthy garments off him.” To him he said, “Behold, I have caused your iniquity to pass from you, and I will clothe you with rich clothing.”\n'),
	(18114, 35, 3, 5, 'I said, “Let them set a clean turban on his head.”\nSo they set a clean turban on his head, and clothed him; and Yahweh’s angel was standing by.\n'),
	(18115, 35, 3, 6, 'Yahweh’s angel protested to Joshua, saying,\n'),
	(18116, 35, 3, 7, '“Yahweh of Armies says: ‘If you will walk in my ways, and if you will follow my instructions, then you also shall judge my house, and shall also keep my courts, and I will give you a place of access among these who stand by.\n'),
	(18117, 35, 3, 8, 'Hear now, Joshua the high priest, you and your fellows who sit before you; for they are men who are a sign: for, behold, I will bring out my servant, the Branch.\n'),
	(18118, 35, 3, 9, 'For, behold, the stone that I have set before Joshua; on one stone are seven eyes: behold, I will engrave its engraving,’ says Yahweh of Armies, ‘and I will remove the iniquity of that land in one day.\n'),
	(18119, 35, 3, 10, 'In that day,’ says Yahweh of Armies, ‘you will invite every man his neighbor under the vine and under the fig tree.’”\n'),
	(18120, 35, 4, 1, 'The angel who talked with me came again, and wakened me, as a man who is wakened out of his sleep.\n'),
	(18121, 35, 4, 2, 'He said to me, “What do you see?”\nI said, “I have seen, and behold, a lamp stand all of gold, with its bowl on the top of it, and its seven lamps on it; there are seven pipes to each of the lamps, which are on the top of it;\n'),
	(18122, 35, 4, 3, 'and two olive trees by it, one on the right side of the bowl, and the other on the left side of it.”\n'),
	(18123, 35, 4, 4, 'I answered and spoke to the angel who talked with me, saying, “What are these, my lord?”\n'),
	(18124, 35, 4, 5, 'Then the angel who talked with me answered me, “Don’t you know what these are?”\nI said, “No, my lord.”\n'),
	(18125, 35, 4, 6, 'Then he answered and spoke to me, saying, “This is Yahweh’s word to Zerubbabel, saying, ‘Not by might, nor by power, but by my Spirit,’ says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18126, 35, 4, 7, 'Who are you, great mountain? Before Zerubbabel you are a plain; and he will bring out the capstone with shouts of ‘Grace, grace, to it!’”\n'),
	(18127, 35, 4, 8, 'Moreover Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(18128, 35, 4, 9, '“The hands of Zerubbabel have laid the foundation of this house. His hands shall also finish it; and you will know that Yahweh of Armies has sent me to you.\n'),
	(18129, 35, 4, 10, 'Indeed, who despises the day of small things? For these seven shall rejoice, and shall see the plumb line in the hand of Zerubbabel. These are Yahweh’s eyes, which run back and forth through the whole earth.”\n'),
	(18130, 35, 4, 11, 'Then I asked him, “What are these two olive trees on the right side of the lamp stand and on the left side of it?”\n'),
	(18131, 35, 4, 12, 'I asked him the second time, “What are these two olive branches, which are beside the two golden spouts, that pour the golden oil out of themselves?”\n'),
	(18132, 35, 4, 13, 'He answered me, “Don’t you know what these are?”\nI said, “No, my lord.”\n'),
	(18133, 35, 4, 14, 'Then he said, “These are the two anointed ones who stand by the Lord\n of the whole earth.”\n'),
	(18134, 35, 5, 1, 'Then again I lifted up my eyes, and saw, and behold, a flying scroll.\n'),
	(18135, 35, 5, 2, 'He said to me, “What do you see?”\nI answered, “I see a flying scroll; its length is twenty cubits, and its width ten cubits.”\n'),
	(18136, 35, 5, 3, 'Then he said to me, “This is the curse that goes out over the surface of the whole land; for everyone who steals shall be cut off according to it on the one side; and everyone who swears falsely shall be cut off according to it on the other side.\n'),
	(18137, 35, 5, 4, 'I will cause it to go out,” says Yahweh of Armies, “and it will enter into the house of the thief, and into the house of him who swears falsely by my name; and it will remain in the middle of his house, and will destroy it with its timber and its stones.”\n'),
	(18138, 35, 5, 5, 'Then the angel who talked with me came forward, and said to me, “Lift up now your eyes, and see what is this that is appearing.”\n'),
	(18139, 35, 5, 6, 'I said, “What is it?”\nHe said, “This is the ephah basket that is appearing.” He said moreover, “This is their appearance in all the land\n'),
	(18140, 35, 5, 7, '(and behold, a talent of lead was lifted up); and this is a woman sitting in the middle of the ephah basket.”\n'),
	(18141, 35, 5, 8, 'He said, “This is Wickedness”; and he threw her down into the middle of the ephah basket; and he threw the weight of lead on its mouth.\n'),
	(18142, 35, 5, 9, 'Then lifted I up my eyes, and saw, and behold, there were two women, and the wind was in their wings. Now they had wings like the wings of a stork, and they lifted up the ephah basket between earth and the sky.\n'),
	(18143, 35, 5, 10, 'Then I said to the angel who talked with me, “Where are these carrying the ephah basket?”\n'),
	(18144, 35, 5, 11, 'He said to me, “To build her a house in the land of Shinar. When it is prepared, she will be set there in her own place.”\n'),
	(18145, 35, 6, 1, 'Again I lifted up my eyes, and saw, and behold, four chariots came out from between two mountains; and the mountains were mountains of brass.\n'),
	(18146, 35, 6, 2, 'In the first chariot were red horses; in the second chariot black horses;\n'),
	(18147, 35, 6, 3, 'in the third chariot white horses; and in the fourth chariot dappled horses, all of them powerful.\n'),
	(18148, 35, 6, 4, 'Then I asked the angel who talked with me, “What are these, my lord?”\n'),
	(18149, 35, 6, 5, 'The angel answered me, “These are the four winds of the sky, which go out from standing before the Lord of all the earth.\n'),
	(18150, 35, 6, 6, 'The one with the black horses goes out toward the north country; and the white went out after them; and the dappled went out toward the south country.”\n'),
	(18151, 35, 6, 7, 'The strong went out, and sought to go that they might walk back and forth through the earth: and he said, “Go around and through the earth!” So they walked back and forth through the earth.\n'),
	(18152, 35, 6, 8, 'Then he called to me, and spoke to me, saying, “Behold, those who go toward the north country have quieted my spirit in the north country.”\n'),
	(18153, 35, 6, 9, 'Yahweh’s word came to me, saying,\n'),
	(18154, 35, 6, 10, '“Take of them of the captivity, even of Heldai, of Tobijah, and of Jedaiah; and come the same day, and go into the house of Josiah the son of Zephaniah, where they have come from Babylon.\n'),
	(18155, 35, 6, 11, 'Yes, take silver and gold, and make crowns, and set them on the head of Joshua the son of Jehozadak, the high priest;\n'),
	(18156, 35, 6, 12, 'and speak to him, saying, ‘Yahweh of Armies says, “Behold, the man whose name is the Branch: and he shall grow up out of his place; and he shall build Yahweh’s temple;\n'),
	(18157, 35, 6, 13, 'even he shall build Yahweh’s temple; and he shall bear the glory, and shall sit and rule on his throne; and he shall be a priest on his throne; and the counsel of peace shall be between them both.\n'),
	(18158, 35, 6, 14, 'The crowns shall be to Helem, and to Tobijah, and to Jedaiah, and to Hen the son of Zephaniah, for a memorial in Yahweh’s temple.\n'),
	(18159, 35, 6, 15, 'Those who are far off shall come and build in Yahweh’s temple; and you shall know that Yahweh of Armies has sent me to you. This will happen, if you will diligently obey Yahweh your God’s voice.”’”\n'),
	(18160, 35, 7, 1, 'In the fourth year of king Darius, Yahweh’s word came to Zechariah in the fourth day of the ninth month, the month of Chislev.\n'),
	(18161, 35, 7, 2, 'The people of Bethel sent Sharezer and Regem Melech, and their men, to entreat Yahweh’s favor,\n'),
	(18162, 35, 7, 3, 'and to speak to the priests of the house of Yahweh of Armies, and to the prophets, saying, “Should I weep in the fifth month, separating myself, as I have done these so many years?”\n'),
	(18163, 35, 7, 4, 'Then the word of Yahweh of Armies came to me, saying,\n'),
	(18164, 35, 7, 5, '“Speak to all the people of the land, and to the priests, saying, ‘When you fasted and mourned in the fifth and in the seventh month for these seventy years, did you at all fast to me, really to me?\n'),
	(18165, 35, 7, 6, 'When you eat, and when you drink, don’t you eat for yourselves, and drink for yourselves?\n'),
	(18166, 35, 7, 7, 'Aren’t these the words which Yahweh proclaimed by the former prophets, when Jerusalem was inhabited and in prosperity, and its cities around her, and the South and the lowland were inhabited?’”\n'),
	(18167, 35, 7, 8, 'Yahweh’s word came to Zechariah, saying,\n'),
	(18168, 35, 7, 9, '“Thus has Yahweh of Armies spoken, saying, ‘Execute true judgment, and show kindness and compassion every man to his brother.\n'),
	(18169, 35, 7, 10, 'Don’t oppress the widow, nor the fatherless, the foreigner, nor the poor; and let none of you devise evil against his brother in your heart.’\n'),
	(18170, 35, 7, 11, 'But they refused to listen, and turned their backs, and stopped their ears, that they might not hear.\n'),
	(18171, 35, 7, 12, 'Yes, they made their hearts as hard as flint, lest they might hear the law, and the words which Yahweh of Armies had sent by his Spirit by the former prophets. Therefore great wrath came from Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18172, 35, 7, 13, 'It has come to pass that, as he called, and they refused to listen, so they will call, and I will not listen,” said Yahweh of Armies;\n'),
	(18173, 35, 7, 14, '“but I will scatter them with a whirlwind among all the nations which they have not known. Thus the land was desolate after them, so that no man passed through nor returned: for they made the pleasant land desolate.”\n'),
	(18174, 35, 8, 1, 'The word of Yahweh of Armies came to me.\n'),
	(18175, 35, 8, 2, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “I am jealous for Zion with great jealousy, and I am jealous for her with great wrath.”\n'),
	(18176, 35, 8, 3, 'Yahweh says: “I have returned to Zion, and will dwell in the middle of Jerusalem. Jerusalem shall be called ‘The City of Truth;’ and the mountain of Yahweh of Armies, ‘The Holy Mountain.’”\n'),
	(18177, 35, 8, 4, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “Old men and old women will again dwell in the streets of Jerusalem, every man with his staff in his hand for very age.\n'),
	(18178, 35, 8, 5, 'The streets of the city will be full of boys and girls playing in its streets.”\n'),
	(18179, 35, 8, 6, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “If it is marvelous in the eyes of the remnant of this people in those days, should it also be marvelous in my eyes?” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18180, 35, 8, 7, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “Behold, I will save my people from the east country, and from the west country;\n'),
	(18181, 35, 8, 8, 'and I will bring them, and they will dwell within Jerusalem; and they will be my people, and I will be their God, in truth and in righteousness.”\n'),
	(18182, 35, 8, 9, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “Let your hands be strong, you who hear in these days these words from the mouth of the prophets who were in the day that the foundation of the house of Yahweh of Armies was laid, even the temple, that it might be built.\n'),
	(18183, 35, 8, 10, 'For before those days there was no wages for man, nor any wages for an animal; neither was there any peace to him who went out or came in, because of the adversary. For I set all men everyone against his neighbor.\n'),
	(18184, 35, 8, 11, 'But now I will not be to the remnant of this people as in the former days,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18185, 35, 8, 12, '“For the seed of peace and the vine will yield its fruit, and the ground will give its increase, and the heavens will give their dew; and I will cause the remnant of this people to inherit all these things.\n'),
	(18186, 35, 8, 13, 'It shall come to pass that, as you were a curse among the nations, house of Judah and house of Israel, so will I save you, and you shall be a blessing. Don’t be afraid. Let your hands be strong.”\n'),
	(18187, 35, 8, 14, 'For Yahweh of Armies says: “As I thought to do evil to you, when your fathers provoked me to wrath,” says Yahweh of Armies, “and I didn’t repent;\n'),
	(18188, 35, 8, 15, 'so again I have thought in these days to do good to Jerusalem and to the house of Judah. Don’t be afraid.\n'),
	(18189, 35, 8, 16, 'These are the things that you shall do: speak every man the truth with his neighbor. Execute the judgment of truth and peace in your gates,\n'),
	(18190, 35, 8, 17, 'and let none of you devise evil in your hearts against his neighbor, and love no false oath: for all these are things that I hate,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18191, 35, 8, 18, 'The word of Yahweh of Armies came to me.\n'),
	(18192, 35, 8, 19, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “The fasts of the fourth, fifth, seventh, and tenth months shall be for the house of Judah joy and gladness, and cheerful feasts. Therefore love truth and peace.”\n'),
	(18193, 35, 8, 20, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “Many peoples, and the inhabitants of many cities will yet come;\n'),
	(18194, 35, 8, 21, 'and the inhabitants of one shall go to another, saying, ‘Let us go speedily to entreat the favor of Yahweh, and to seek Yahweh of Armies. I will go also.’\n'),
	(18195, 35, 8, 22, 'Yes, many peoples and strong nations will come to seek Yahweh of Armies in Jerusalem, and to entreat the favor of Yahweh.”\n'),
	(18196, 35, 8, 23, 'Yahweh of Armies says: “In those days, ten men will take hold, out of all the languages of the nations, they will take hold of the skirt of him who is a Jew, saying, ‘We will go with you, for we have heard that God is with you.’”\n'),
	(18197, 35, 9, 1, 'A revelation.\nYahweh’s word is against the land of Hadrach,\nand will rest upon Damascus;\nfor the eye of man\nand of all the tribes of Israel is toward Yahweh;\n'),
	(18198, 35, 9, 2, 'and Hamath, also, which borders on it;\nTyre and Sidon, because they are very wise.\n'),
	(18199, 35, 9, 3, 'Tyre built herself a stronghold,\nand heaped up silver like the dust,\nand fine gold like the mire of the streets.\n'),
	(18200, 35, 9, 4, 'Behold, the Lord will dispossess her,\nand he will strike her power in the sea;\nand she will be devoured with fire.\n'),
	(18201, 35, 9, 5, 'Ashkelon will see it, and fear;\nGaza also, and will writhe in agony;\nas will Ekron, for her expectation will be disappointed;\nand the king will perish from Gaza,\nand Ashkelon will not be inhabited.\n'),
	(18202, 35, 9, 6, 'Foreigners will dwell in Ashdod,\nand I will cut off the pride of the Philistines.\n'),
	(18203, 35, 9, 7, 'I will take away his blood out of his mouth,\nand his abominations from between his teeth;\nand he also will be a remnant for our God;\nand he will be as a chieftain in Judah,\nand Ekron as a Jebusite.\n'),
	(18204, 35, 9, 8, 'I will encamp around my house against the army,\nthat no one pass through or return;\nand no oppressor will pass through them any more:\nfor now I have seen with my eyes.\n'),
	(18205, 35, 9, 9, 'Rejoice greatly, daughter of Zion!\nShout, daughter of Jerusalem!\nBehold, your King comes to you!\nHe is righteous, and having salvation;\nlowly, and riding on a donkey,\neven on a colt, the foal of a donkey.\n'),
	(18206, 35, 9, 10, 'I will cut off the chariot from Ephraim,\nand the horse from Jerusalem;\nand the battle bow will be cut off;\nand he will speak peace to the nations:\nand his dominion will be from sea to sea,\nand from the River to the ends of the earth.\n'),
	(18207, 35, 9, 11, 'As for you also,\nbecause of the blood of your covenant,\nI have set free your prisoners from the pit in which is no water.\n'),
	(18208, 35, 9, 12, 'Turn to the stronghold, you prisoners of hope!\nEven today I declare that I will restore double to you.\n'),
	(18209, 35, 9, 13, 'For indeed I bend Judah as a bow for me.\nI have filled the bow with Ephraim;\nand I will stir up your sons, Zion,\nagainst your sons, Greece,\nand will make you like the sword of a mighty man.\n'),
	(18210, 35, 9, 14, 'Yahweh will be seen over them;\nand his arrow will go flash like lightning;\nand the Lord Yahweh will blow the trumpet,\nand will go with whirlwinds of the south.\n'),
	(18211, 35, 9, 15, 'Yahweh of Armies will defend them;\nand they will destroy and overcome with sling stones;\nand they will drink, and roar as through wine;\nand they will be filled like bowls,\nlike the corners of the altar.\n'),
	(18212, 35, 9, 16, 'Yahweh their God will save them in that day as the flock of his people;\nfor they are like the jewels of a crown,\nlifted on high over his land.\n'),
	(18213, 35, 9, 17, 'For how great is his goodness,\nand how great is his beauty!\nGrain will make the young men flourish,\nand new wine the virgins.\n'),
	(18214, 35, 10, 1, 'Ask of Yahweh rain in the spring time,\nYahweh who makes storm clouds,\nand he gives rain showers to everyone for the plants in the field.\n'),
	(18215, 35, 10, 2, 'For the teraphim have spoken vanity,\nand the diviners have seen a lie;\nand they have told false dreams.\nThey comfort in vain.\nTherefore they go their way like sheep.\nThey are oppressed, because there is no shepherd.\n'),
	(18216, 35, 10, 3, 'My anger is kindled against the shepherds,\nand I will punish the male goats;\nFor Yahweh of Armies has visited his flock, the house of Judah,\nand will make them as his majestic horse in the battle.\n'),
	(18217, 35, 10, 4, 'From him will come the cornerstone,\nfrom him the nail,\nfrom him the battle bow,\nfrom him every ruler together.\n'),
	(18218, 35, 10, 5, 'They shall be as mighty men,\ntreading down muddy streets in the battle;\nand they shall fight, because Yahweh is with them;\nand the riders on horses will be confounded.\n'),
	(18219, 35, 10, 6, '“I will strengthen the house of Judah,\nand I will save the house of Joseph,\nand I will bring them back;\nfor I have mercy on them;\nand they will be as though I had not cast them off:\nfor I am Yahweh their God, and I will hear them.\n'),
	(18220, 35, 10, 7, 'Ephraim will be like a mighty man,\nand their heart will rejoice as through wine;\nyes, their children will see it, and rejoice.\nTheir heart will be glad in Yahweh.\n'),
	(18221, 35, 10, 8, 'I will signal for them, and gather them;\nfor I have redeemed them;\nand they will increase as they have increased.\n'),
	(18222, 35, 10, 9, 'I will sow them among the peoples;\nand they will remember me in far countries;\nand they will live with their children, and will return.\n'),
	(18223, 35, 10, 10, 'I will bring them again also out of the land of Egypt,\nand gather them out of Assyria;\nand I will bring them into the land of Gilead and Lebanon;\nand there won’t be room enough for them.\n'),
	(18224, 35, 10, 11, 'He will pass through the sea of affliction,\nand will strike the waves in the sea,\nand all the depths of the Nile will dry up;\nand the pride of Assyria will be brought down,\nand the scepter of Egypt will depart.\n'),
	(18225, 35, 10, 12, 'I will strengthen them in Yahweh;\nand they will walk up and down in his name,” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18226, 35, 11, 1, 'Open your doors, Lebanon,\nthat the fire may devour your cedars.\n'),
	(18227, 35, 11, 2, 'Wail, cypress tree, for the cedar has fallen,\nbecause the stately ones are destroyed.\nWail, you oaks of Bashan,\nfor the strong forest has come down.\n'),
	(18228, 35, 11, 3, 'A voice of the wailing of the shepherds!\nFor their glory is destroyed: a voice of the roaring of young lions!\nFor the pride of the Jordan is ruined.\n'),
	(18229, 35, 11, 4, 'Yahweh my God says: “Feed the flock of slaughter.\n'),
	(18230, 35, 11, 5, 'Their buyers slaughter them, and go unpunished. Those who sell them say, ‘Blessed be Yahweh, for I am rich;’ and their own shepherds don’t pity them.\n'),
	(18231, 35, 11, 6, 'For I will no more pity the inhabitants of the land,” says Yahweh; “but, behold, I will deliver the men everyone into his neighbor’s hand, and into the hand of his king. They will strike the land, and out of their hand I will not deliver them.”\n'),
	(18232, 35, 11, 7, 'So I fed the flock of slaughter, especially the oppressed of the flock. I took for myself two staffs. The one I called “Favor”, and the other I called “Union”, and I fed the flock.\n'),
	(18233, 35, 11, 8, 'I cut off the three shepherds in one month; for my soul was weary of them, and their soul also loathed me.\n'),
	(18234, 35, 11, 9, 'Then I said, “I will not feed you. That which dies, let it die; and that which is to be cut off, let it be cut off; and let those who are left eat each other’s flesh.”\n'),
	(18235, 35, 11, 10, 'I took my staff Favor, and cut it apart, that I might break my covenant that I had made with all the peoples.\n'),
	(18236, 35, 11, 11, 'It was broken in that day; and thus the poor of the flock that listened to me knew that it was Yahweh’s word.\n'),
	(18237, 35, 11, 12, 'I said to them, “If you think it best, give me my wages; and if not, keep them.” So they weighed for my wages thirty pieces of silver.\n'),
	(18238, 35, 11, 13, 'Yahweh said to me, “Throw it to the potter, the handsome price that I was valued at by them!” I took the thirty pieces of silver, and threw them to the potter, in Yahweh’s house.\n'),
	(18239, 35, 11, 14, 'Then I cut apart my other staff, even Union, that I might break the brotherhood between Judah and Israel.\n'),
	(18240, 35, 11, 15, 'Yahweh said to me, “Take for yourself yet again the equipment of a foolish shepherd.\n'),
	(18241, 35, 11, 16, 'For, behold, I will raise up a shepherd in the land, who will not visit those who are cut off, neither will seek those who are scattered, nor heal that which is broken, nor feed that which is sound; but he will eat the meat of the fat sheep, and will tear their hoofs in pieces.\n'),
	(18242, 35, 11, 17, 'Woe to the worthless shepherd who leaves the flock! The sword will be on his arm, and on his right eye. His arm will be completely withered, and his right eye will be totally blinded!”\n'),
	(18243, 35, 12, 1, 'A revelation, Yahweh’s word concerning Israel. Yahweh, who stretches out the heavens, and lays the foundation of the earth, and forms the spirit of man within him says:\n'),
	(18244, 35, 12, 2, '“Behold, I will make Jerusalem a cup of reeling to all the surrounding peoples, and it will also be on Judah in the siege against Jerusalem.\n'),
	(18245, 35, 12, 3, 'It will happen in that day, that I will make Jerusalem a burdensome stone for all the peoples. All who burden themselves with it will be severely wounded, and all the nations of the earth will be gathered together against it.\n'),
	(18246, 35, 12, 4, 'In that day,” says Yahweh, “I will strike every horse with terror, and his rider with madness; and I will open my eyes on the house of Judah, and will strike every horse of the peoples with blindness.\n'),
	(18247, 35, 12, 5, 'The chieftains of Judah will say in their heart, ‘The inhabitants of Jerusalem are my strength in Yahweh of Armies their God.’\n'),
	(18248, 35, 12, 6, 'In that day I will make the chieftains of Judah like a pan of fire among wood, and like a flaming torch among sheaves; and they will devour all the surrounding peoples, on the right hand and on the left; and Jerusalem will yet again dwell in their own place, even in Jerusalem.\n'),
	(18249, 35, 12, 7, 'Yahweh also will save the tents of Judah first, that the glory of David’s house and the glory of the inhabitants of Jerusalem not be magnified above Judah.\n'),
	(18250, 35, 12, 8, 'In that day Yahweh will defend the inhabitants of Jerusalem. He who is feeble among them at that day will be like David, and David’s house will be like God, like Yahweh’s angel before them.\n'),
	(18251, 35, 12, 9, 'It will happen in that day, that I will seek to destroy all the nations that come against Jerusalem.\n'),
	(18252, 35, 12, 10, 'I will pour on David’s house, and on the inhabitants of Jerusalem, the spirit of grace and of supplication; and they will look to me whom they have pierced; and they shall mourn for him, as one mourns for his only son, and will grieve bitterly for him, as one grieves for his firstborn.\n'),
	(18253, 35, 12, 11, 'In that day there will be a great mourning in Jerusalem, like the mourning of Hadadrimmon in the valley of Megiddon.\n'),
	(18254, 35, 12, 12, 'The land will mourn, every family apart; the family of David’s house apart, and their wives apart; the family of the house of Nathan apart, and their wives apart;\n'),
	(18255, 35, 12, 13, 'the family of the house of Levi apart, and their wives apart; the family of the Shimeites apart, and their wives apart;\n'),
	(18256, 35, 12, 14, 'all the families who remain, every family apart, and their wives apart.\n'),
	(18257, 35, 13, 1, '“In that day there will be a spring opened to David’s house and to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, for sin and for uncleanness.\n'),
	(18258, 35, 13, 2, 'It will come to pass in that day, says Yahweh of Armies, that I will cut off the names of the idols out of the land, and they will be remembered no more. I will also cause the prophets and the spirit of impurity to pass out of the land.\n'),
	(18259, 35, 13, 3, 'It will happen that, when anyone still prophesies, then his father and his mother who bore him will tell him, ‘You must die, because you speak lies in Yahweh’s name;’ and his father and his mother who bore him will stab him when he prophesies.\n'),
	(18260, 35, 13, 4, 'It will happen in that day, that the prophets will each be ashamed of his vision, when he prophesies; neither will they wear a hairy mantle to deceive:\n'),
	(18261, 35, 13, 5, 'but he will say, ‘I am no prophet, I am a tiller of the ground; for I have been made a bondservant from my youth.’\n'),
	(18262, 35, 13, 6, 'One will say to him, ‘What are these wounds between your arms?’ Then he will answer, ‘Those with which I was wounded in the house of my friends.’\n'),
	(18263, 35, 13, 7, '“Awake, sword, against my shepherd,\nand against the man who is close to me,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n“Strike the shepherd, and the sheep will be scattered;\nand I will turn my hand against the little ones.\n'),
	(18264, 35, 13, 8, 'It shall happen that in all the land,” says Yahweh,\n“two parts in it will be cut off and die;\nbut the third will be left in it.\n'),
	(18265, 35, 13, 9, 'I will bring the third part into the fire,\nand will refine them as silver is refined,\nand will test them like gold is tested.\nThey will call on my name, and I will hear them.\nI will say, ‘It is my people;’\nand they will say, ‘Yahweh is my God.’”\n'),
	(18266, 35, 14, 1, 'Behold, a day of Yahweh comes, when your plunder will be divided within you.\n'),
	(18267, 35, 14, 2, 'For I will gather all nations against Jerusalem to battle; and the city will be taken, the houses rifled, and the women ravished. Half of the city will go out into captivity, and the rest of the people will not be cut off from the city.\n'),
	(18268, 35, 14, 3, 'Then Yahweh will go out and fight against those nations, as when he fought in the day of battle.\n'),
	(18269, 35, 14, 4, 'His feet will stand in that day on the Mount of Olives, which is before Jerusalem on the east; and the Mount of Olives will be split in two, from east to west, making a very great valley. Half of the mountain will move toward the north, and half of it toward the south.\n'),
	(18270, 35, 14, 5, 'You shall flee by the valley of my mountains; for the valley of the mountains shall reach to Azel; yes, you shall flee, just like you fled from before the earthquake in the days of Uzziah king of Judah. Yahweh my God will come, and all the holy ones with you.\n'),
	(18271, 35, 14, 6, 'It will happen in that day, that there will not be light, cold, or frost.\n'),
	(18272, 35, 14, 7, 'It will be a unique day which is known to Yahweh; not day, and not night; but it will come to pass, that at evening time there will be light.\n'),
	(18273, 35, 14, 8, 'It will happen in that day, that living waters will go out from Jerusalem; half of them toward the eastern sea, and half of them toward the western sea; in summer and in winter will it be.\n'),
	(18274, 35, 14, 9, 'Yahweh will be King over all the earth. In that day Yahweh will be one, and his name one.\n'),
	(18275, 35, 14, 10, 'All the land will be made like the Arabah, from Geba to Rimmon south of Jerusalem; and she will be lifted up, and will dwell in her place, from Benjamin’s gate to the place of the first gate, to the corner gate, and from the tower of Hananel to the king’s wine presses.\n'),
	(18276, 35, 14, 11, 'Men will dwell therein, and there will be no more curse; but Jerusalem will dwell safely.\n'),
	(18277, 35, 14, 12, 'This will be the plague with which Yahweh will strike all the peoples who have fought against Jerusalem: their flesh will consume away while they stand on their feet, and their eyes will consume away in their sockets, and their tongue will consume away in their mouth.\n'),
	(18278, 35, 14, 13, 'It will happen in that day, that a great panic from Yahweh will be among them; and they will lay hold everyone on the hand of his neighbor, and his hand will rise up against the hand of his neighbor.\n'),
	(18279, 35, 14, 14, 'Judah also will fight at Jerusalem; and the wealth of all the surrounding nations will be gathered together: gold, and silver, and clothing, in great abundance.\n'),
	(18280, 35, 14, 15, 'So will be the plague of the horse, of the mule, of the camel, and of the donkey, and of all the animals that will be in those camps, as that plague.\n'),
	(18281, 35, 14, 16, 'It will happen that everyone who is left of all the nations that came against Jerusalem will go up from year to year to worship the King, Yahweh of Armies, and to keep the feast of tents.\n'),
	(18282, 35, 14, 17, 'It will be, that whoever of all the families of the earth doesn’t go up to Jerusalem to worship the King, Yahweh of Armies, on them there will be no rain.\n'),
	(18283, 35, 14, 18, 'If the family of Egypt doesn’t go up, and doesn’t come, neither will it rain on them. This will be the plague with which Yahweh will strike the nations that don’t go up to keep the feast of tents.\n'),
	(18284, 35, 14, 19, 'This will be the punishment of Egypt, and the punishment of all the nations that don’t go up to keep the feast of tents.\n'),
	(18285, 35, 14, 20, 'In that day there will be on the bells of the horses, “HOLY TO YAHWEH”; and the pots in Yahweh’s house will be like the bowls before the altar.\n'),
	(18286, 35, 14, 21, 'Yes, every pot in Jerusalem and in Judah will be holy to Yahweh of Armies; and all those who sacrifice will come and take of them, and cook in them. In that day there will no longer be a Canaanite in the house of Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18287, 36, 1, 1, 'A revelation, Yahweh’s word to Israel by Malachi.\n'),
	(18288, 36, 1, 2, '“I have loved you,” says Yahweh.\nYet you say, “How have you loved us?”\n“Wasn’t Esau Jacob’s brother?” says Yahweh, “Yet I loved Jacob;\n'),
	(18289, 36, 1, 3, 'but Esau I hated, and made his mountains a desolation, and gave his heritage to the jackals of the wilderness.”\n'),
	(18290, 36, 1, 4, 'Whereas Edom says, “We are beaten down, but we will return and build the waste places”; Yahweh of Armies says, “They shall build, but I will throw down; and men will call them ‘The Wicked Land,’ even the people against whom Yahweh shows wrath forever.”\n'),
	(18291, 36, 1, 5, 'Your eyes will see, and you will say, “Yahweh is great—even beyond the border of Israel!”\n'),
	(18292, 36, 1, 6, '“A son honors his father, and a servant his master. If I am a father, then where is my honor? And if I am a master, where is the respect due me? Says Yahweh of Armies to you, priests, who despise my name. You say, ‘How have we despised your name?’\n'),
	(18293, 36, 1, 7, 'You offer polluted bread on my altar. You say, ‘How have we polluted you?’ In that you say, ‘Yahweh’s table is contemptible.’\n'),
	(18294, 36, 1, 8, 'When you offer the blind for sacrifice, isn’t that evil? And when you offer the lame and sick, isn’t that evil? Present it now to your governor! Will he be pleased with you? Or will he accept your person?” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18295, 36, 1, 9, '“Now, please entreat the favor of God, that he may be gracious to us. With this, will he accept any of you?” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18296, 36, 1, 10, '“Oh that there were one among you who would shut the doors, that you might not kindle fire on my altar in vain! I have no pleasure in you,” says Yahweh of Armies, “neither will I accept an offering at your hand.\n'),
	(18297, 36, 1, 11, 'For from the rising of the sun even to the going down of the same, my name is great among the nations, and in every place incense will be offered to my name, and a pure offering: for my name is great among the nations,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18298, 36, 1, 12, '“But you profane it, in that you say, ‘Yahweh’s table is polluted, and its fruit, even its food, is contemptible.’\n'),
	(18299, 36, 1, 13, 'You say also, ‘Behold, what a weariness it is!’ and you have sniffed at it”, says Yahweh of Armies; “and you have brought that which was taken by violence, the lame, and the sick; thus you bring the offering. Should I accept this at your hand?” says Yahweh.\n'),
	(18300, 36, 1, 14, '“But the deceiver is cursed, who has in his flock a male, and vows, and sacrifices to the Lord a defective thing; for I am a great King,” says Yahweh of Armies, “and my name is awesome among the nations.”\n'),
	(18301, 36, 2, 1, '“Now, you priests, this commandment is for you.\n'),
	(18302, 36, 2, 2, 'If you will not listen, and if you will not take it to heart, to give glory to my name,” says Yahweh of Armies, “then will I send the curse on you, and I will curse your blessings. Indeed, I have cursed them already, because you do not take it to heart.\n'),
	(18303, 36, 2, 3, 'Behold, I will rebuke your offspring, and will spread dung on your faces, even the dung of your feasts; and you will be taken away with it.\n'),
	(18304, 36, 2, 4, 'You will know that I have sent this commandment to you, that my covenant may be with Levi,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18305, 36, 2, 5, '“My covenant was with him of life and peace; and I gave them to him that he might be reverent toward me; and he was reverent toward me, and stood in awe of my name.\n'),
	(18306, 36, 2, 6, 'The law of truth was in his mouth, and unrighteousness was not found in his lips. He walked with me in peace and uprightness, and turned many away from iniquity.\n'),
	(18307, 36, 2, 7, 'For the priest’s lips should keep knowledge, and they should seek the law at his mouth; for he is the messenger of Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18308, 36, 2, 8, 'But you have turned away from the path. You have caused many to stumble in the law. You have corrupted the covenant of Levi,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18309, 36, 2, 9, '“Therefore I have also made you contemptible and wicked before all the people, according to the way you have not kept my ways, but have had respect for persons in the law.\n'),
	(18310, 36, 2, 10, 'Don’t we all have one father? Hasn’t one God created us? Why do we deal treacherously every man against his brother, profaning the covenant of our fathers?\n'),
	(18311, 36, 2, 11, 'Judah has dealt treacherously, and an abomination is committed in Israel and in Jerusalem; for Judah has profaned the holiness of Yahweh which he loves, and has married the daughter of a foreign god.\n'),
	(18312, 36, 2, 12, 'Yahweh will cut off, to the man who does this, him who wakes and him who answers, out of the tents of Jacob, and him who offers an offering to Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18313, 36, 2, 13, 'This again you do: you cover Yahweh’s altar with tears, with weeping, and with sighing, because he doesn’t regard the offering any more, neither receives it with good will at your hand.\n'),
	(18314, 36, 2, 14, 'Yet you say, ‘Why?’ Because Yahweh has been witness between you and the wife of your youth, against whom you have dealt treacherously, though she is your companion, and the wife of your covenant.\n'),
	(18315, 36, 2, 15, 'Did he not make you one, although he had the residue of the Spirit? Why one? He sought godly offspring. Therefore take heed to your spirit, and let no one deal treacherously against the wife of his youth.\n'),
	(18316, 36, 2, 16, 'For I hate divorce”, says Yahweh, the God of Israel, “and him who covers his garment with violence!” says Yahweh of Armies. “Therefore take heed to your spirit, that you don’t deal treacherously.\n'),
	(18317, 36, 2, 17, 'You have wearied Yahweh with your words. Yet you say, ‘How have we wearied him?’ In that you say, ‘Everyone who does evil is good in Yahweh’s sight, and he delights in them;’ or ‘Where is the God of justice?’\n'),
	(18318, 36, 3, 1, '“Behold, I send my messenger, and he will prepare the way before me; and the Lord, whom you seek, will suddenly come to his temple; and the messenger of the covenant, whom you desire, behold, he comes!” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18319, 36, 3, 2, '“But who can endure the day of his coming? And who will stand when he appears? For he is like a refiner’s fire, and like launderers’ soap;\n'),
	(18320, 36, 3, 3, 'and he will sit as a refiner and purifier of silver, and he will purify the sons of Levi, and refine them as gold and silver; and they shall offer to Yahweh offerings in righteousness.\n'),
	(18321, 36, 3, 4, 'Then the offering of Judah and Jerusalem will be pleasant to Yahweh, as in the days of old, and as in ancient years.\n'),
	(18322, 36, 3, 5, 'I will come near to you to judgment; and I will be a swift witness against the sorcerers, and against the adulterers, and against the perjurers, and against those who oppress the hireling in his wages, the widow, and the fatherless, and who deprive the foreigner of justice, and don’t fear me,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18323, 36, 3, 6, '“For I, Yahweh, don’t change; therefore you, sons of Jacob, are not consumed.\n'),
	(18324, 36, 3, 7, 'From the days of your fathers you have turned away from my ordinances, and have not kept them. Return to me, and I will return to you,” says Yahweh of Armies. “But you say, ‘How shall we return?’\n'),
	(18325, 36, 3, 8, 'Will a man rob God? Yet you rob me! But you say, ‘How have we robbed you?’ In tithes and offerings.\n'),
	(18326, 36, 3, 9, 'You are cursed with the curse; for you rob me, even this whole nation.\n'),
	(18327, 36, 3, 10, 'Bring the whole tithe into the storehouse, that there may be food in my house, and test me now in this,” says Yahweh of Armies, “if I will not open you the windows of heaven, and pour you out a blessing, that there will not be room enough for.\n'),
	(18328, 36, 3, 11, 'I will rebuke the devourer for your sakes, and he shall not destroy the fruits of your ground; neither shall your vine cast its fruit before its time in the field,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18329, 36, 3, 12, '“All nations shall call you blessed, for you will be a delightful land,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18330, 36, 3, 13, '“Your words have been stout against me,” says Yahweh. “Yet you say, ‘What have we spoken against you?’\n'),
	(18331, 36, 3, 14, 'You have said, ‘It is vain to serve God;’ and ‘What profit is it that we have followed his instructions, and that we have walked mournfully before Yahweh of Armies?\n'),
	(18332, 36, 3, 15, 'Now we call the proud happy; yes, those who work wickedness are built up; yes, they tempt God, and escape.’\n'),
	(18333, 36, 3, 16, 'Then those who feared Yahweh spoke one with another; and Yahweh listened, and heard, and a book of memory was written before him, for those who feared Yahweh, and who honored his name.\n'),
	(18334, 36, 3, 17, 'They shall be mine,” says Yahweh of Armies, “my own possession in the day that I make, and I will spare them, as a man spares his own son who serves him.\n'),
	(18335, 36, 3, 18, 'Then you shall return and discern between the righteous and the wicked, between him who serves God and him who doesn’t serve him.\n'),
	(18336, 36, 4, 1, '“For, behold, the day comes, it burns as a furnace; and all the proud, and all who work wickedness, will be stubble; and the day that comes will burn them up,” says Yahweh of Armies, “that it shall leave them neither root nor branch.\n'),
	(18337, 36, 4, 2, 'But to you who fear my name shall the sun of righteousness arise with healing in its wings. You will go out, and leap like calves of the stall.\n'),
	(18338, 36, 4, 3, 'You shall tread down the wicked; for they will be ashes under the soles of your feet in the day that I make,” says Yahweh of Armies.\n'),
	(18339, 36, 4, 4, '“Remember the law of Moses my servant, which I commanded to him in Horeb for all Israel, even statutes and ordinances.\n'),
	(18340, 36, 4, 5, 'Behold, I will send you Elijah the prophet before the great and terrible day of Yahweh comes.\n'),
	(18341, 36, 4, 6, 'He will turn the hearts of the fathers to the children, and the hearts of the children to their fathers, lest I come and strike the earth with a curse.”\n');
